<SLUG> BC--BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0933 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC--BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DUMB AND DUMBER BROKERS FROM THE D.A.'S LIST: SUSAN ANTILLA &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Susan Antilla &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- George Washington University
must have one heck of a math department. Consider what the
government describes as the much-sought-after talents of Robert
Daniel Idzi.
<p>
   Idzi, who graduated from GW in 1991, is one of two stock brokers
indicted Jan. 8 by the Manhattan District Attorney. Their alleged
crime: working as stand-ins for people who anticipated they were
too dumb to pass the Series 7 brokers' exam -- which tests
everything from securities law to basic math.
<p>
   The other indicted broker, Igor Sheckhtman, hails from the
University of California at Los Angeles -- another institute of
higher learning that may deserve a little credit for cranking out
an achievement test whiz-kid, should the case be solid.
<p>
   To get a good job, as your mother always told you, get a good
education.
<p>
   Not that there aren't noteworthy non-academic credentials on
their resumes, as listed in their regulatory records. Sheckhtman's
past includes a 10-year tenure working for Los Angeles Checkered
Cab Co., where he must have logged a lot of time calculating bond
yields at stop signs and red lights.
<p>
   Idzi also had an affinity for the transportation industry,
though he apparently was more inclined to desk jobs. Between 1985
and 1991 he worked at five different auto parts and distribution
companies. He also did a five-month stint at Korbean International
Investment Corp., shut down in February by the New York State
Attorney General's office.
<p>
   A compliance officer At Sunpoint Securities, Idzi's most recent
employer, said he hasn't known of Idzi's whereabouts since he set
Idzi up to two years ago to be stung by the National Association of
Securities Dealers. There was no telephone listing for Idzi in
Alexandria, Virginia, where his NASD records list him as living.
<p>
   There was no listing for Sheckhtman in Encino, Calif. M. Rimson
&AMP; Co., his most recent employer, was expelled from the NASD in
March.
<p>
   If it's true, as the district attorney says, that the
test-takers profited at the expense of less mentally gifted
broker-hopefuls, the two certainly picked their customers and
colleagues from a curious mailing list.
<p>
   John Corona, accused of being a middleman between impostors and
would-be-brokers, pleaded guilty in 1994 to a charge of
unauthorized use of an automobile -- a charge that was reduced from
attempted grand larceny, third degree, and possession of burglary
tools. A compliance officer for Toluca Pacific Securities, where
regulatory records list him as having worked, did not return a
telephone call. There was no telephone listing under Corona's name
in Howard Beach, New York, where records kept at the National
Association of Securities Dealers list him as living.
<p>
   Indeed, more often than not, there was no sign of the accused
brokers in the locales listed in their NASD records. ``In a lot of
cases, they move and don't tell us where they've gone,'' says
Michael Robinson, spokesman for NASD Regulation Inc.
<p>
   William Battista, accused of paying to have someone else take
his test, paid a fine in 1996 related to assault charges that were
dropped. Earlier, in 1992, he pleaded guilty to promotion of
gambling, a talent Wall Street may reward, but for which the Series
7 test apparently doesn't screen.
<p>
   You'll never guess. No telephone listed in his name at the New
York City address he filed with the NASD. A woman answering the
telephone at Euro-Atlantic Securities in New York said that
Battista worked at that office, but was not in on Jan. 17.
<p>
   Another alleged user of a stand-in, John D'Esposito, pleaded
guilty in 1991 to petty larceny after initial charges of criminal
possession of a loaded firearm, according to his regulatory
records. A man reached at the telephone number listed under the
same Staten Island, New York, address on D'Esposito's NASD records
said that while his name was John D'Esposito, he was not the John
D'Esposito who had been cited by the D.A.
<p>
   The criminal records go on and on. But enough of that. The gang
of 53 charged as part of a cheating ring weren't all on the dockets
of the Department of Justice. Some just had more than their share
of old-fashioned investor complaints. And big-ticket complaints, at
that.
<p>
   Darian Kelty of Fort Lauderdale, Florida, settled a $75,000
customer complaint for unauthorized trading and other allegations
for $24,500; Jack Biondolillo of Scottsdale, Arizona, was accused
of bilking a customer of $332,900 in a case that alleged
misrepresentation, among other things. He had no listing in
Scottsdale, where -- you guessed it -- NASD records list him as
living. A compliance officer for Russo Securities said she withdrew
his broker's registration application after learning of the
indictment.
<p>
   Paul Cilmi, who has an unpublished telephone number in Brooklyn,
lost an arbitration in which the complaining investor was awarded
$71,491.
<p>
   Michael Cilmi, whose phone in South Cairo, New York, went
unanswered, was co-defendant in that case against Paul Cilmi. His
regulatory records show that he filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy in
December of 1988, a period when he was working for the New York
City Department of Corrections.
<p>
   From there, he moved on to the Department of Sanitation before a
career switch to Wall Street, where he no doubt had a better shot
at making enough dough to pay off his debts. Stock brokers can be
groomed in the darnedest places.
</TEXT>
