<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-STOCKS-OPEN </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0503 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ARGENTINA-STOCKS-OPEN-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ARGENTINE STOCKS MAY RISE AS BOND SALE BUILDS CONFIDENCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Richard Jarvie &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Buenos Aires, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Argentine stocks may rise
as high demand for the country's biggest-ever bond sale reassures
investors the government will be able to cover this year's
financing needs.
<p>
   Demand for the $2 billion of 20-year bonds on sale today totaled
$6 billion ``ensuring that there should be plenty of interest in
future sales,'' said Hugo Dias Lourenco, an equity strategist at
consulting firm C&AMP;E Consultores.
<p>
   The high level of demand also shows that foreign investors are
confident Argentina's economy will continue to improve and they're
prepared to put money into the country in the search for higher
returns, added Dias Lourenco.
<p>
   ``There should be a big inflow of funds in coming months and a
good part of this should go into the stock market,'' said Dias
Lourenco.
<p>
   This could help lift the Merval index to 750 pesos by the end of
February, added Dias Lourenco. That would be 9 percent more than
the Merval's 686.1 close yesterday.
<p>
   Prospects of robust economic growth and rising corporate
earnings have helped boost the Merval by 40 percent since August.
<p>
   The increase was also helped by low U.S. bond yields which
caused foreign investors to seek higher returns in emerging equity
markets such as Argentina.
<p>
   The economy officially is forecast to expand by about 5 percent
this year following growth of between 3 percent and 4 percent in
1996.
<p>
   Dias Lourenco said he is recommending shares of companies that
are likely to increase sales as consumer spending grows over coming
months.
<p>
   These include steel companies, such as Acindar Industria
Argentina de Aceros SA, and auto manufacturers Ciadea SA and Sevel
Argentina SA.
<p>
   Yesterday, stocks rose after U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan allayed fears that the Fed could increase interest rates
next month in order to rein in inflation. Greenspan told the Senate
Budget Committee the U.S. economy ``retained considerable vigor,
with few signs of the imbalances and inflationary tensions that
have disrupted past expansions.''
<p>
   The Merval index of the 24 most-traded stocks closed unchanged
at 686.61 while the general index rose 0.16 percent to 19,796.24.
Of the 85 issues that were traded, 40 rose, 20 fell and 25 closed
unchanged. Turnover rose to 23.5 million pesos ($23.5 million) of
shares from Monday's 9.6 million pesos. Among stocks that are
widely traded abroad, telephone company Telefonica de Argentina SA
closed unchanged at 2.88 pesos while Telecom Argentina Stet-France
Telecom SA, another phone company, fell 0.43 percent to 4.54 pesos.
<p>
   Oil producer YPF SA closed unchanged at 28.1 pesos.
<p>
   The interest rate on seven-day interbank deposits rose to 5.7
percent from 5.6 percent on Monday while the peso traded at 0.9992
to the U.S. dollar compared with 0.9993 the previous day.
</TEXT>
