<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8544 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-APPLE-EARNINGS-57 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0958 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-APPLE-EARNINGS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; APPLE REPORTS A LOSS OF $120 MILLION FOR FIRST QUARTER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LAWRENCE M. FISHER &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SAN FRANCISCO  &MD;  Apple Computer Inc. posted a loss of $120
million for its first quarter Wednesday and said that it does not
expect to return to profitability as quickly as it had predicted,
with the first positive earnings not anticipated until the fourth
quarter in September.
<p>
   Separately, Sun Microsystems Inc., which a year ago entertained
the prospect of acquiring Apple, reported record revenues and
earnings for its second quarter, exceeding analyst estimates.
<p>
   Both companies released their results after the stock market had
closed. In Nasdaq trading, Apple shares fell 62.5 cents, to $17.25;
Sun shares also slipped 62.5 cents, to $28.25. In after-hours
trading, though, Sun traded as high as $28.75, while Apple shares
were unchanged.
<p>
   Earlier this month, Apple said it expected a loss of between
$100 million and $150 million in the quarter, far higher than
analysts had estimated. Wednesday's reported loss of $120 million
was equivalent to 96 cents a share, much more than the average
analyst estimate of 75 cents, according to First Call, though still
within the range of 48 cents to $1.20 among the 19 analysts
surveyed.
<p>
   Apple attributed the loss to weak Christmas-season sales of its
Performa line of consumer-oriented Macintosh computers, and the
price cuts and rebates needed to move these machines.
<p>
   In addition, Apple was unable to make enough of its new
Powerbook 1400 notebook computers to meet demand, resulting in a
backlog of $200 million. Though Apple had posted a surprise profit
in its fourth quarter, much of that came from an adjustment of
restructuring charges taken in the previous quarter.
<p>
   In reaction to the earnings and Apple's continued poor
performance, Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. Wednesday lowered Apple's
corporate credit rating and senior debt rating to B from B+, and
its subordinated debt rating to CCC+ from B-.
<p>
   S&AMP;P said that the new ratings reflected Apple's operating
losses, slipping market share and the need to revamp the company.
Apple officials have said they will cut costs so that the company
can break even on annual revenue of $8 billion, down from an
earlier target of $9 billion.
<p>
   But Apple officials said Wednesday that despite the challenges,
the company remained on track to a recovery. ``While we were very
disappointed by the Performa sales results and the associated loss,
our financial position remains sound,'' Fred Anderson, Apple's
executive vice president and chief financial officer, said in a
telephone conference call.
<p>
   ``We exited the quarter with $1.8 billion in cash and continued
to show improvements in our inventory management,'' he said.
<p>
   For the quarter, Apple reported a loss of $120 million, compared
with a loss of $69 million in the comparable period a year ago.
Revenues of $2.13 billion were down 32 percent from the $3.15
billion reported in the first quarter of the 1996 fiscal year.
<p>
   ``The quarter wasn't as bad as I though it would be,'' said
Charles R. Wolf, an analyst with CS First Boston, noting that
holiday sales were disappointing for nearly all consumer computer
makers.
<p>
   Apple primarily spoke of weakness in the Performa line, but
strong sales of Macintosh clones may have come at the expense of
the company's high-end models, Wolf said.
<p>
   ``My guess is they took at least $100 million off revenues, and
possibly $150 million, which is not insignificant vis-a-vis the
shortfall,'' he said.
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   Apple's financial woes have diverted attention from the
company's surprise acquisition of Next Software Inc. and the return
of a co-founder, Steven Jobs.
<p>
   But Ellen Hancock, Apple's chief technology officer, said in a
conference call that she was confident Apple would deliver new
operating system software incorporating Next's technology this
year. She said that an advance release for software developers
would be available midyear, with a customer release by the end of
the year.
<p>
   In contrast to Apple, which is suffering partly from a lack of
exciting new technology and partly from an inability to execute,
Sun is riding high on hot new products and delivering them
flawlessly. Sun's mainstay products, work stations and servers, are
still in the growth phase that began with the introduction of the
Ultrasparc line last year, while its new network computer, the
Javastation, has just begun to ship.
<p>
   ``The team is psyched; they're pretty focused,'' Scott McNealy,
Sun's chairman, president and chief executive, said in a conference
call. ``Our servers and power desktop systems are hot; customers
need the superior scalability, reliability and performance of our
products.''
<p>
   For the quarter, Sun had earnings of $178.3 million, or 46 cents
a share, up 41 percent from $126 million, or 32 cents a share, in
the period a year earlier. That exceeded the average analyst
estimate, according to First Call, of 42 cents a share. Per-share
figures reflect a recent 2-for-1 stock split. Sales of $2.08
billion were up nearly 19 percent.
<p>
   ``This was a really great quarter,'' said Doug van Dorsten, an
analyst at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, who noted that Sun was able to meet
its operating profit goals early and effectively deferred some
sales into its third quarter.
<p>
   He said that Sun had gained market share at the expense of
rivals like Silicon Graphics Inc. and Hewlett-Packard Co. ``More
and more, you're seeing applications that historically ran on
Silicon Graphics going to Sun,'' he said.
<p>
