<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tia-z> A8546 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-AOL-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0852 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-AOL-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AMERICA ONLINE FACES MORE QUESTIONS ABOUT PRICING PLAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Anne Marie Squeo and Greg Stohr &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg Business News &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 15 (Bloomberg) -- America Online Inc. is facing
questions from a group of state consumer-protection agencies over
the delays and mechanical problems caused by the online provider's
new flat-rate pricing plan.
<p>
   Attorneys general in Wisconsin, New York and other states are
looking into subscriber complaints of access problems since AOL
began offering unlimited service for a flat rate of $19.95 a month.
Previously, users paid $9.95 for the first five hours and $2.95 for
each additional hour.
<p>
   ``New York is looking into this because there have been lots of
complaints,'' said Margot Pagan, a spokeswoman for New York
Attorney General Dennis Vacco. ``It's very hard to take real world
law and apply it and enforce it in a virtual world.''
<p>
   Some states have begun discussions with AOL over complaints that
the new policy, which took effect Dec. 1, is causing traffic jams,
according to Jim Haney, a spokesman for the Wisconsin attorney
general's office. He said that Wisconsin was among those states.
<p>
   Haney said Wisconsin officials have received about 20 written
complaints in the last week.
<p>
   Private Lawsuits
<p>
   America Online also is facing several private lawsuits by
disgruntled customers who say the company reneged on its promise to
provide them with efficient on-line service. Complaints filed in
Chicago, Los Angeles, and New York say that customers have had
trouble connecting with AOL since the company switched to the new
pricing plan.
<p>
   Suits and probes have become almost routine for the nation's
largest and fastest-growing online provider, which now has more
than 7 million subscribers.
<p>
   In December, it reached a 19-state settlement over its plan to
automatically switch subscribers to the new pricing plan. And in
July, it agreed to pay $22 million to settle 11 private
class-action suits about billing and business practices. The
Federal Trade Commission, the nation's top consumer-protection
agency, also has been examining the company's practices as part of
an industry-wide probe.
<p>
   People ``are taking advantage of the situation,'' said Abhishek
Gami, a Nesbitt Burns analyst. ``I can't believe they are being
hurt by waiting in line. AOL is doing a good job of building out
the network and keeping individuals informed.''
<p>
   AOL shares fell 1 1/2 today to close at 38. Delays Reported
<p>
   Since the new pricing plan took effect, subscribers have
suffered delays and technical problems when trying to log onto AOL.
The problem was compounded when the company began offering 50 free
online hours to lure new users.
<p>
   America Online officials had warned users that the new pricing
plan could cause delays for a few months during its busiest hours,
from 8 p.m. to midnight and on weekends. The new pricing plan
charges subscribers $19.95 a month whether or not they can get into
it, leading users annoyed with the delays to seek refunds.
<p>
   The private suits charge AOL with breach of contract, negligence
and consumer fraud. Each seeks class-action status, so the company
might be able to resolve the claims in one setting, rather than in
several different courts.
<p>
   AOL says it expects to win the suits, though it understands the
frustrations of its customers. ``We had a fall surge that ate up a
lot of our capacity,'' said America Online spokeswoman Tricia
Primrose. She said AOL subscribers have almost tripled their online
time in the last three months -- from 1.6 million hours per day in
October to as much as 4.3 million hours per day now.
<p>
   That increase has strained the network's capacity, even as AOL
embarks on a $250 million project to expand the system. That
expansion, Primrose said, should solve the access problems when
it's completed in June.
<p>
   From the time it was announced in October, the pricing plan came
under fire. Attorneys general from 17 states sent the company a
letter saying that switching users without giving them a choice may
violate deceptive trade practice laws.
<p>
   To settle these concerns, America Online agreed to flash a
message on users' computer screens letting them choose between the
new and old plans. This quelled concerns that those who normally
spend $9.95 for five hours or less online would see their bills
more than double even if usage stayed the same.
<p>
   The Dulles, Virginia-based company also agreed to give refunds
to all AOL users who ask to get switched back to the old pricing
plan by April 10.
<p>
   America Online also had problems with its previous billing plan.
Last July, it agreed to pay as much as $22 million in free online
time to settle 11 private class-action lawsuits about its billing
and business practices. Those suits charged the online service with
misleading consumers by rounding off time spent online to the next
full minute and sometimes billing subscribers for time spent
browsing in so-called ``free'' areas.
<p>
NYT-01-15-97 1745EST
</TEXT>
