<SLUG> BC-CPT-SOFTBANK-ZDNET-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0408 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-SOFTBANK-ZDNET-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SOFTBANK'S ZIFF-DAVIS TO LAUNCH 10 ZDNET INTERNATIONAL EDITIONS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Karen Fessler &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg Business News &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 15 (Bloomberg) -- Softbank Corp.'s Ziff-Davis
Publishing Co. said it will expand ZDNet, its Internet service that
supplies information about computing and technology, by launching
10 local-language international editions.
<p>
   ZDNet debuted a site for Chinese computer users today, and plans
to launch additional sites in Australia, Hong Kong, Italy, Korea,
Malaysia/Singapore, Russia, Spain and Taiwan in March; and Japan in
April.
<p>
   The expansion comes as ZD Net increasingly attracts computer
users from overseas, enabling them to access news, features,
reviews and information directories. The new sites will be in the
local language and provide localized content.
<p>
   ``There is a tremendous amount of demand for international
content in the local language and with local content that isn't
being served yet,'' J.B. Holston, president of Ziff-Davis'
international division, said in an interview.
<p>
   About 35 percent of ZDNet's 8.89 million visits in November came
from computer users outside of the U.S., according to market
researcher I/Pro.
<p>
   Holston said the markets ZDNet will cover represent about 80
percent of all computer sales around the world. That will make ZD
Net attractive to advertisers, who ``like to able to talk
globally,'' he said.
<p>
   Each local edition will feature Ziff-Davis' ZDNet software
library, which contains 10,000 title that users can download onto
their own computers. The sites will also have information on buying
computing equipment.
<p>
   Ziff-Davis is teaming up with local content partners who ``will
put up the bulk of the investment'' to launch the sites, Holston
said. The editions will be operated both by the local partners and
by workers at ZDNet's Cambridge, Massachusetts headquarters.
<p>
   The Chinese ZDNet site will be linked to another site in China
being launched by a venture between Australia's News Corp. and
People's Daily newspaper. News Corp. today said it introduced the
Chinese-language news and information site, called ChinaByte.
<p>
   Users of ChinaByte seeking Internet-related information and news
will be linked to ZDNet under a licensing agreement between the
News Corp. venture and Ziff-Davis, Holston said.
<p>
NYT-01-15-97 1507EST
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 0956EST
</TRAILER>
