<DOCID> nyt970122.0008 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tia-z> A8548 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-EARNS-DIGITAL-EQU </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0589 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-EARNS-DIGITAL-EQUIPMENT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DIGITAL EQUIPMENT'S PROFIT FALLS LESS THAN EXPECTED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Gerard Meuchner &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg Business News &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Maynard, Massachusetts, Jan. 16 (Bloomberg) -- Digital Equipment
Corp. reported a smaller-than-expected drop in fiscal
second-quarter profit, providing shareholders some measure of hope
after the company lost money in five of the past six years.
<p>
   Maynard, Massachusetts-based Digital had fiscal second-quarter
net income of $31.9 million, or 15 cents a share, compared with net
income of $148.8 million, or 91 cents, a year ago.
<p>
   Revenue in the quarter ended Dec. 28 fell 15 percent to $3.36
billion from $3.95 billion in the year-ago quarter. In the fiscal
first quarter, revenue totaled $2.91 billion.
<p>
   The profit was driven by lower costs, a rebound in revenue, and
an end to losses in its personal computer business. All that isn't
enough for analysts and investors to conclude that Digital has
turned the corner in an industry becoming ever more competitive.
<p>
   ``One of the issues here is consistency,'' said Morgan Stanley
analyst Steven Milunovich. ``I'm not inclined to do anything on one
quarter's numbers. It's a good first step.''
<p>
   Wall Street expected Digital to earn 10 cents a share, according
to the average estimate of 15 analysts surveyed by First Call. The
estimates ranged from a loss of 4 cents to a profit of 37 cents.
Sales were expected to fall to about $3.3 billion.
<p>
   The smaller-than-expected decline in profit may not do much to
mollify investors in the nation's third largest computer company.
<p>
   ``The company should be doing so much better than that,'' said
John Rutledge, an analyst at Loomis, Sayles &AMP; Co., a Boston money
management firm that owns just more than 1 million Digital shares.
``That's not evidence of a turnaround.''
<p>
   Some are more optimistic.
<p>
   ``The results looked encouraging,'' said Salomon Brothers
analyst John Jones. ``The fact that they made some money in PCs is
a positive.''
<p>
   Digital Chairman Robert Palmer ``has got some challenges on his
hands, but he's making progress,'' said Jones, who has a ``buy''
recommendation on the stock.
<p>
   Digital's stock, down 43 percent last year, fell 3/4 yesterday
to 34 1/4.
<p>
   The company's gross margin widened to 32.9 percent in the
quarter, from 32.6 percent a year ago and 31.3 percent in the prior
quarter. Expenses totaled $1.07 billion in the quarter, a 6 percent
decline from a year ago.
<p>
   Digital didn't specify how much money its PC business made, or
divulge the sales related to its flagship Alpha chip, one of the
world's fastest microprocessors.
<p>
   The company's revenue tumbled in the fiscal first quarter after
Digital chose to sell more of its machines through its own sales
force, relying less on distributors. Digital blamed the change for
the 11 percent revenue plunge in the first quarter.
<p>
   The company's sales haven't returned to where they were before
the change.
<p>
   Product revenue in the second quarter was $1.84 billion, down 22
percent from a year ago. The gross margin on product sales widened
to 34.5 percent from 32.5 percent a year ago.
<p>
   Service revenue fell 6 percent to $1.51 billion from $1.6
billion, while the gross margin narrowed to 30.9 percent from 32.7
percent.
<p>
   Digital also cut 1,100 jobs in the quarter, reducing its payroll
to 55,900, less than half the 125,000 employees the company had in
the late 1980s.
<p>
NYT-01-16-97 0922EST
</TEXT>
