<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=ttd-z> A8549 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-AOL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1079 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-AOL-SFCHRON &QL; 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; America Online Asks Customers to Curtail Their Use &QL; 
By Jon Swartz and Julia Angwin &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   America Online, the nation's largest online service company,
yesterday acknowledged it is unable to provide reliable service to
its 8 million customers and pleaded with them to scale back their
use until it can fix the problem.
<p>
   The unusual request by AOL chief executive Steve Case came as
AOL grappled with system outages, a flood of customer complaints
and lawsuits by disgruntled users who have experienced difficulty
logging onto the overloaded system.
<p>
   In an apologetic letter to customers, Case wrote: `I know that
you may have had great difficulty connecting to AOL in recent
weeks, so I wanted to let you know what we're doing to address the
problem.''
<p>
   AOL said it will spend up to $350 million on new equipment and
personnel to ease the crunch caused by a surge in use since
December 1, when the company began charging $19.95 a month for
unlimited online time.
<p>
   ``There's also something you can do to help,'' Case wrote, ``and
that is to moderate your own use of AOL a bit during our peak
evening periods. During this transitional period, it would be
helpful if you were sensitive to the needs and frustrations of your
fellow members.
<p>
   ``Just as you would be sensitive about using a public phone
booth if others were waiting in line to use it, it would be helpful
if you could be considerate of the needs of other members of the
AOL community.''
<p>
   Dulles, Va.-based AOL said it has added 1 million members in the
past six weeks. Since September, customers of the fast-growing
service have more than doubled their average daily use, e-mail
messages have doubled to 18 million pieces a day, and total online
time for all users has nearly tripled to 125 million hours.
<p>
   The surge in use has overtaxed AOL's computer system, which can
handle only up to 260,000 users simultaneously. A hardware glitch
on Wednesday caused AOL to partially shut down from 12:15 p.m. to 4
p.m.
<p>
   ``It's an all-you-can-eat online system, but too many people are
lining up at the table,'' said Paul Saunders, an analyst at Van
Kasper &AMP; Co. in San Francisco and an occasional AOL user. ``(AOL)
didn't anticipate this spike in increased use.''
<p>
   Yesterday, AOL said it is scrambling to expand its system
capacity. The company will break ground next month on an
180,000-square-foot data center in Reston, Va.
<p>
   In addition, 600 new customer support employees will be added
over the next six months.
<p>
   The company also is jettisoning its ``Jetsons'' television
commercials and will sharply reduce mailings of free computer
diskettes loaded with AOL software.
<p>
   Case said he expects AOL's upgraded system to be fully in place
by the spring. But that isn't likely to placate irate customers  &MD; 
many of whom say it takes more than five attempts to successfully
log on to AOL.
<p>
   ``It's beginning to become ridiculously impractical for people
to do business,'' said Larry Shapiro, publisher of California
Employer Advisor, a newsletter in Tiburon. ``Reporters are having
trouble filing stories and graphic designers can't transfer files
via AOL.''
<p>
   Shapiro said the online logjam becomes acute in the late
afternoon  &MD;  about the same time that AOL subscribers on the East
Coast arrive home from work and attempt to log on.
<p>
   ``What bothers me is that while they have this problem, they're
advertising like crazy on TV and constantly sending out free
diskettes to get more subscribers,'' said Wayne Seden, an AOL
customer in Mountain View. ``I've used AOL for a couple of
years,and I'm ready to quit.''
<p>
   That's no easy chore, either.
<p>
   Consumers grouse that canceling their subscriptions is as
ticklish a task as getting online.
<p>
   ``It was really surprising that it was so easy to sign up and so
hard to get off,'' said Russell Handy, a San Diego resident who
said he tried for months last year to cancel his subscription to
the service.
<p>
   Although he kept calling to cancel, he said AOL kept deducting
monthly charges from his checking account. Finally, he asked the
bank to stop allowing the charges.
<p>
   The same thing happened to Farouk Algosaibi, a Berkeley
resident. Algosaibi said AOL continues to deduct charges from his
account more than one year after he stopped service.
<p>
   ``It's like they were going in and stealing my money,'' he said.
<p>
   A representative at one credit card company said they were
deluged with complaints from consumers trying to cancel AOL
payments. ``We get calls constantly,'' she said. ``We're about
ready to shoot AOL.''
<p>
   An AOL spokeswoman said AOL customers can cancel their accounts
only by calling the company at (800) 827-6364.
<p>
   Meanwhile, the company this week was hit with a raft of
class-action suits from disgruntled subscribers.
<p>
   At last count, six suits allege that the online service offered
its subscribers unlimited usage but did not have enough equipment
in place to meet the surge in demand. The suits seek either
punitive or exemplary damages.
<p>
   ``It's simply an outrage that consumers are being asked to cut
back on usage, but there is no offer by AOL to compensate them,''
said Joseph Tabacco, a San Francisco attorney representing one
group of plaintiffs.
<p>
   An AOL official declined to say whether customers will be
compensated for the lack of access this month. However, one
customer said she was told by an AOL representative that she could
appeal the charges in writing since she has not been able to log on
to the system.
<p>
   In addition, at least three state attorneys general  &MD;  Richard
Blumenthal of Connecticut, Dennis Vacco of New York and Jim Doyle
of Wisconsin  &MD;  confirmed they are in discussions with AOL seeking
some resolution to rampant customer complaints.
<p>
   ``Thousands of Connecticut consumers have paid for a service
that, very simply, they are not receiving,'' Blumenthal said in a
statement.
<p>
   The Illinois attorney general's office said it has received more
than two dozen complaints about AOL's billing practices,
cancellation policies and other issues. Industry observers argue
that competitive moves by companies such as AOL, Microsoft and AT&AMP;T
toward flat-rate pricing will only further clog the increasingly
congested Internet. Some suggest the industry would be better off
charging users on a pay-as-you-go basis.
<p>
NYT-01-16-97 2147EST
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 0957EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0010 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8551 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-AMERICA-ONLINE-NY </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0924 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-AMERICA-ONLINE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AMERICA ONLINE MOVES TO PLACATE ANGRY USERS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   With its network and the patience of its customers strained to
the breaking point, America Online announced a series of new
initiatives Thursday to try to relieve the congestion that has led
to at least four class-action lawsuits and thousands of complaints
from frustrated consumers.
<p>
   The on-line service has been flooded with complaints from people
around the country who have been unable to dial into the service
since it began offering unlimited use for $19.95 a month in
December.
<p>
   To help ease the strain, the company announced that it would
suspend its television advertising campaign, spend an additional
$100 million to expand the capacity of its network, and add more
telephone representatives to field calls from angry customers.
<p>
   But even these measures will not relieve the company's clogged
modems until the spring at the earliest, said Bob Pittman, the
president and chief executive of AOL Networks, the America Online
unit that runs the on-line service.
<p>
   ``It will be the end of spring before we are where we want to
be,'' he added. ``Some cities will feel it sooner because this is
about going from town to town putting more modems in.''
<p>
   The company has even resorted to a novel approach to solving the
capacity constraints: asking customers not to use the service. In a
letter posted to subscribers Thursday, Steve Case, the chairman and
chief executive of America Online Inc., said that many users were
so worried about not being able to get on the network that they
were simply staying on all the time.
<p>
   ``While that's understandable at one level,'' Case wrote. ``It
is obviously problematic at another.''
<p>
   Pittman said the company had anticipated some increased use
after the new pricing plan was introduced, but the jump has been
greater than expected. In December, American Online customers
logged a record 102 million hours on line, up from 45 million hours
in September. The average American Online member now spends 32
minutes a day on line, up from 14 minutes in September.
<p>
   But judging from the number of complaints, one might conclude
the average American Online subscriber spends more time trying
unsuccessfully to dial on.
<p>
   Since the beginning of the year, a petition has been passed by
e-mail collecting scores of names. Its plea is simple: ``We the
users of AOL demand a dependable service.''
<p>
   ``For the last month, it has been almost impossible to get
connected after about 3 or 4 o'clock in the afternoon,'' said
Judith Handelman, a freelance writer and editor in Scarsdale, N.Y.
``I wrote to them and I got this long letter full of claptrap.''
<p>
   Many customers use the service as part of their businesses,
making the difficulty of gaining access to e-mail even more
critical, but also making it harder to quit the service.
<p>
   ``I'd like to switch but I've got my AOL address on my business
card,'' said Jean Wyman, an entrepreneur who lives in Los Angeles.
<p>
   The company said Thursday that it was aware of four class-action
suits that have been filed against the service in California,
Illinois, New Jersey and New York. The New York suit accuses
America Online of breach of contract, deceptive practices,
deceptive advertising and unjust enrichment.
<p>
   ``If they didn't think that with 8 million subscribers they
didn't feel that they would have a tremendous burst of usage, then
they are incredibly naive  &MD;  and I don't think they are that,'' said
Edward Labaton, a partner with Goodkind Labaton Rudoff &AMP; Sucharow
in Manhattan, which filed a class-action suit on behalf of four
America Online members.
<p>
   Attorneys general in several states, including New York and
Wisconsin, are also alarmed by the complaints. Last month, America
Online reached an agreement with 19 states promising to clarify its
new pricing plan and offer refunds to consumers who ask to switch
back to their old plan before April.
<p>
   ``We're taking very close look at it,'' said Marc Carey, a
spokesman for New York state Attorney General Dennis Vacco.
<p>
   Despite the many complaints, America Online said that it was
still growing. The company had a net gain of 1.2 million
subscribers in the quarter ending Dec. 31, for a total of more than
8 million. December was the service's best month ever, with 500,000
new subscribers. A spokesman said that the company would not say
how many customers it has been losing in recent weeks.
<p>
   Under its new plan, American Online will increase its spending
on system capacity to $350 million from $250 million. Next month,
it said it would break ground on a 180,000-square-foot data center
in Reston, Va.
<p>
   The service currently has more than 200,000 modems in cities
around the country for subscribers to dial up. It promised to
increase that number by 75 percent, allowing an additional 6
million sessions a day.
<p>
   In addition, the company said it would hire 600 more customer
support representatives, for a total of more than 4,500. It will
also suspend its television advertisements and stop distributing
its ubiquitous floppy disks offering a free trial in areas where
access has been a problem.
<p>
   The management, which has been denying the problem for weeks,
has also become more humble.
<p>
   ``Am I bloody?'' Pittman, the company executive, asked. ``Yes.
Do my eyes have circles under them? Yes.''
<p>
NYT-01-16-97 2044EST
</TEXT>
