<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8552 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DIGITAL-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0561 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-DIGITAL-EARNS-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DIGITAL EARNINGS RETURN TO THE PLUS SIDE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By HIAWATHA BRAY &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Black ink has made a welcome return to the balance sheet of
Digital Equipment Corp. After nearly $500 million in losses over
the previous two quarters, Digital announced net income of $31.9
million or 15 cents per share for its second quarter, which ended
Dec. 28, 1996. Revenue grew by 15 percent over the first-quarter
level, but Digital officials warned that they expected little
additional revenue growth in the present quarter.
<p>
   Profits declined 79 percent from the same period a year earlier,
but Digital still managed to outperform the expectations of
industry analysts by about 4 cents a share. The performance boosted
Digital's stock, which opened Thursday at 34 1/4 on the New York
Stock Exchange and rose as high as 38 3/4 before closing at 36 3/4
up 2 1/2 for the day.
<p>
   Digital chairman Robert Palmer said the Maynard-based company
would have performed even better if it had been able to meet a late
surge in demand for its high-end Alpha server computers. Palmer
also said that Digital's troubled personal computer division did
better than expected, turning a profit while posting a 33 percent
increase in unit sales during the quarter.
<p>
   Bruce Claflin, general manager of Digital's PC operations,
declined to reveal how profitable the unit was. But he noted that
PC revenue actually fell compared to the year-earlier period. This
is partly because Digital has abandoned retail sales to consumers
to concentrate on its traditional business customers. In addition,
the company used to inflate its sales figures by saddling
distributors with too many computers. Claflin said that inventories
are now tightly managed to make sure that distributors get only as
many machines as they can sell.
<p>
   ``Our business is under control,'' Claflin said. ``It's solidly
profitable, and now it's going to resume a focused controlled
growth.''
<p>
   Meanwhile, Digital announced that unit sales of systems based on
its Alpha microprocessor grew just 1 percent from the same period
last year. Still, Alpha sales were up 33 percent over the previous
quarter and could have gone higher, because of a year-end increase
in orders for Alpha servers. Palmer said that revenue for these
late orders will show up in Digital's third-quarter results.
<p>
   Digital recently announced steep price cuts on Alpha
microprocessors, as well as servers and workstations using the
Alpha chips. Meanwhile, Motorola and IBM announced that they would
abandon efforts to support the popular Windows NT operating system
on their PowerPC microprocessor, one of Alpha's key rivals. As a
result, Alpha-based machines are the fastest computers that can run
Windows NT. ``In our view that provides us a clear opening to
underscore Alpha's advantages,'' Palmer said.
<p>
   Richard Chu, managing director of Cowen &AMP; Co. in Boston, said
it's too early to proclaim a turnaround at Digital. But he said the
latest report reflects solid improvement.
<p>
   ``Three months ago, you're looking at a lot of bad news. They
lost money, there was uncertainty about the sales organization,
uncertainty about the PC business,'' said Chu. ``This quarter ..
there definitely has been progress.''
<p>
NYT-01-16-97 1954EST
</TEXT>
