<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8553 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DIGITAL-EARNINGS- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0580 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-DIGITAL-EARNINGS-330&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DIGITAL RETURNS TO PROFITABILITY IN SECOND QUARTER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Digital Equipment Corp. said Thursday that it regained
profitability in its fiscal second quarter, but it is still
suffering from slow sales of its flagship high-performance computer
systems.
<p>
   Digital, which is based in Maynard, Mass., reported net income
of $31.9 million, or 15 cents a share, compared with profits of
$148.8 million, or 91 cents a share, in the corresponding period a
year earlier. Revenue also declined, to $3.36 billion, or 15
percent, from $3.95 billion a year ago.
<p>
   The earnings exceeded the average Wall Street estimate, which
was 10 cents a share, according to First Call. But expectations had
been relatively low after Digital stunned investors in October by
posting a loss of $66 million, or 48 cents a share, for its first
quarter.
<p>
   That news had sent Digital's stock price plunging 23 percent to
a five-year low of $29 a share. It subsequently recovered, and
Thursday the shares closed at $36.75, up $2.50.
<p>
   Much of the good news included in Thursday's announcement came
from Digital's troubled personal computer unit, which was
profitable again after suffering heavy losses most of last year. In
the second quarter, which ended Dec. 28, PC sales declined 20
percent compared with a year earlier, but they rose sharply from
the first quarter.
<p>
   The company also seemed to recover from the disruption caused by
changes in the organization of its sales force, which the company
said had cut into revenue. In addition, it reduced costs, lowering
its head count by 1,100, to 55,900 employees.
<p>
   Digital chairman and chief executive Robert Palmer called the
company's performance a ``significant turnaround'' and expressed
confidence that business would continue to improve over the next
two quarters. But he added that the company would be hard pressed
to maintain the same revenues in the third quarter, which is
generally weak.
<p>
   ``We believe a responsible goal would be to maintain flat
revenues, but historical precedent wouldn't support that,'' he
said.
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   Some Wall Street analysts were concerned about Digital's
prospects, especially because of the relatively weak sales of
high-performance systems built around its Alpha microprocessor.
<p>
   ``The issue is that this company has to generate more top-line
growth, and Alpha is the best shot,'' said Shao Wang, an analyst
with Smith Barney in New York.
<p>
   Sales of Alpha-based systems recovered somewhat in the second
quarter after a sharp decline in the previous period. Nevertheless,
Alpha-system revenues still grew only 1 percent at an annual rate.
<p>
   The Alpha microprocessor is one of the fastest in the industry.
But even though it has significantly better performance than Intel
Corp.'s Pentium Pro chip, Intel sold about 3 million Pentium Pro
chips last year, while Digital sold about 238,000 Alpha chips,
according to Dataquest, a market research firm in San Jose, Calif.
<p>
   Palmer said that Digital was unable to fill $50 million worth of
orders for high-end Alpha systems last quarter because orders
flooded in at the end of December. With those sales, which he said
would be booked this quarter, Alpha revenues would have shown
double-digit growth.
<p>
