<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=ttj-z> A8555 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-$ </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0811 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-$ADV19-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BUSY SIGNALS CAUSING ANGUISH AMONG AMERICA ONLINE USERS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DWIGHT SILVERMAN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Ssshhh. If you listen quietly, you can hear them. Those distant,
mournful cries are the anguished voices of America Online users
trying to connect.
<p>
   There are millions of them, and they all want one thing  &MD;  to
link up with the world's biggest online service to get e-mail, surf
the Internet, chat with friends or do some online shopping. The
problem is, they all want to get on at the same time.
<p>
   This is the direct result of America Online's decision to go
from per-hour to flat-fee pricing. Since the service now charges
$19.95 a month for unlimited access, users are staying on longer.
Some are even camping onto the system to receive e-mail or monitor
favorite chat rooms.
<p>
   It's worse in large cities, though subscribers in smaller towns
and rural areas are also finding it harder to get on.
<p>
   Not a day goes by that I don't receive at least three or four
pieces of e-mail from outraged America Online subscribers anxious
just to get their e-mail. Most of them never mention the other
features of the service; they just want to see what's in their
mailboxes, a testament to how important e-mail has become. The
problem is particularly vexing for businesses that have chosen
America Online as their e-mail source. Here, e-mail is more than
just a social thing  &MD;  it's an electronic lifeline.
<p>
   At this writing, it's been more than six weeks since the service
made its switch, and the busy signals have been almost continuous.
America Online executives say they are feverishly adding more
modems and phone lines, but so far it's been like handing an
eyedropper of water to refugees in the Sahara.
<p>
   If America Online can't solve this problem, market forces will
cause the situation to take care of itself. Frustrated subscribers
will cancel their accounts, moving on to Internet service providers
or other online services. There will be fewer subscribers trying to
connect to the service, freeing up the modems. That's bad for
America Online, which requires a constant source of new subscribers
to fuel its growth.
<p>
   There are a few things America Online subscribers can do to help
the situation:
<p>
    &MD;  If you can, avoid signing on during prime-time evening hours.
This is when most folks try connecting to the service and when the
logjam gets serious. Although you'll still get busy signals, there
will be fewer of them.
<p>
    &MD;  Don't be a part of the problem. When you get on, get what you
need and sign off the system so others can use it.
<p>
    &MD;  America Online's software won't repeatedly auto-dial a number,
but there are third-party programs that will. For example, Windows
users can try Gritty Redialer (keyword Gritty News) which will call
the service's local numbers until the system connects. Then you
don't have to sit there, repeatedly pressing the sign-on button.
<p>
    &MD;  If you already have an account with an Internet service
provider, you can bypass America Online's modems altogether and
connect to the service over the Net. Sign on to your provider, then
fire up the America Online software. Click on Setup from the
sign-on box; choose Edit Location; then change the type of
connection to TCP/IP. Save the settings, then back out and sign on
as you normally would.
<p>
   In fact, if you choose to use only this method to connect,
America Online will charge you less per month, partly making up for
the fact that you also must pay fees to an Internet provider.
<p>
    &MD;  Finally, the ultimate fix would be to flee America Online and
sign on with another provider. I've said this before, and it bears
repeating: If you go in search of an Internet provider, avoid those
whose fees are far below the mainstream. They usually cannot
generate enough cash to keep up with equipment demands. You're apt
to be back where you started, listening to the harsh sound of busy
signals.
<p>
   In a previous column, I said that if America Online can fix its
capacity problems  &MD;  and if you are using the Windows 95 version of
America Online  &MD;  it's probably the best value for Internet access.
For $20 a month, you get the Net plus all of the service's
proprietary content. That's a great deal.
<p>
   But it's moot if you can't get on to play with all these cool
features, or if the system is so bogged down that it's like wading
through electronic quicksand. If America Online is to survive as an
online service, it must put more emphasis on the word ``service''
and drag itself out of this morass  &MD;  quickly.
<p>
    &UR; -------- &LR; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com. Or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &HT;    
<p>
