<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8556 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-LAZARD-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0504 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-LAZARD-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; LAZARD RANKS AS TOP EUROPEAN CROSS-BORDER ADVISER IN 1996 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By David Callaway &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   London, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Lazard houses were the most
successful advisers on cross-border takeovers in Europe last year
in a business increasingly dominated by U.S. investment banks,
according to Acquisitions Monthly magazine.
<p>
   The three Lazard businesses in London, Paris and New York
collectively topped the magazine's rankings, advising on 46
transactions with a total value of 12 billion pounds ($19.8
billion). Those included the 3.3 billion-pound takeover of France's
CarnaudMetalbox by Crown Cork &AMP; Seal Co. of the U.S., the biggest
cross-border takeover last year.
<p>
   Lazard was followed Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co. and Goldman Sachs &AMP;
Co., which led a group of six U.S. investment banks within the top
10 advisers.
<p>
   ``The U.S. effectively has a stranglehold on European
cross-border mergers and acquisitions advisory work,'' Philip
Healey, editor of Acquisitions Monthly, said in a prepared
statement. ``This is at the expense of the U.K. banks and
integrated European investment banks.''
<p>
   U.S. investment banks have led a surge in mergers throughout
Europe in the last two years as industries such as phamaceuticals
and telecommunications prepare for monetary union at the end of the
decade. Bankers said their clients increasingly demand advisors
with global reach to help them make decisions on how to grow their
own businesses globally.
<p>
   Other U.S. investment banks in the top 10 were J.P. Morgan &AMP;
Co., Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., Lehman Brothers Inc., and Credit Suisse
First Boston, which Acquisitions Monthly counts as a U.S. bank.
<p>
   SBC Warburg, the investment banking arm of Swiss Bank Corp., the
Rothschild Group and Societe Generale rounded out the list of the
top 10 advisers.
<p>
   The largest merger in Europe last year, the $30 billion
combination of Swiss pharmaceutical companies Sandoz AG and
Ciba-Geigy AG, was advised on by J.P. Morgan and Morgan Stanley. It
wasn't counted as a cross-border transaction. Lazard, which ranked
sixth last year, benefited from an increasing amount of takeovers
in France and the U.K. Lazard has three businesses, Lazard Freres &AMP;
Cie. in Paris, Lazard Brothers in London and Lazard Freres &AMP; Co. in
New York. They work together on cross-border transactions, giving
the company the same benefits of international expertise on two
continents that the U.S. banks have. Healey said he expects the
pace of mergers in Europe to continue, which will benefit the U.S.
banks again.
<p>
   Acquisitions Monthly's Top 10 Advisers in Europe for 1996
Adviser Transactions Value in Pounds
Lazard Houses 46 12 billion Morgan Stanley 26 11 billion Goldman
Sachs 23 10.2 billion Credit Suisse First Boston 22 9.9 billion
J.P. Morgan 29 9.4 billion Merrill Lynch 13 8.2 billion SBC Warburg
41 5.9 billion Lehman Brothers 23 4.3 billion Rothschild Group 25
3.9 billion Societe Generale 15 3.7 billion
