<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=ttj-z> A8560 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-AUTODESK-PROGRAM- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0757 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-AUTODESK-PROGRAM-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ARCHITECTURAL SOFTWARE FIRM OFFERS HOME REMODELING PROGRAM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By TOM ABATE &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SAN FRANCISCO  &MD;  The company that made its name selling drafting
software to professional architects has come out with a new program
designed to help do-it-yourselfers remove the guesswork  &MD;  and
lessen the arguments  &MD;  inherent in home remodeling.
<p>
   Autodesk Inc. of San Rafael, Calif. started shipping its
``Picture This Home'' software Wednesday, after spending 18 months
developing a program that's supposed to be so easy to use, it won
the Good Housekeeping seal of approval.
<p>
   The $50 software runs on fast PCs with 16 megabytes of memory
and a four-speed CD-ROM drive. Autodesk Chief Executive Carol Bartz
said Picture This Home will let consumers design their kitchens,
for instance, then plug in specific cabinets, wall papers or
appliances to see exactly how the room would appear.
<p>
   ``It gives you a great way to visualize your ideas and design
the space,'' Bartz said. ``As we've shown the product to the media
and analysts, people have literally ripped the mouse out of our
hands.''
<p>
   Now Bartz is hoping Picture This Home will propel Autodesk  &MD; 
which has become a $500 million company on the strength of
engineering, architectural and multimedia tool sales  &MD;  into the
consumer arena.
<p>
   If the foray succeeds, it won't come a moment too soon. Autodesk
struggled in 1996. Engineers and architects delayed purchasing
Autodesk's professional-strength design software to await a revised
version that should be released soon.
<p>
   In the meantime, Autodesk's sales fell 6.4 percent to $381.6
million in the first nine months of fiscal 1997, down from $407.9
million in the same period the previous fiscal year.
<p>
   Its stock fell as well, dropping from a high of roughly 44 in
April to a low near 18 in August. Autodesk has begun to recover
some ground, and four Wall Street analysts recently recommended the
stock as a ``buy'' as the release date for its new professional
software grows near.
<p>
   Kate Delhagen, software analyst for Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass., said Autodesk is taking a risk by entering the
consumer market, where it is unknown and where two dozen home
design programs already exist.
<p>
   But Delhagen said Autodesk is hoping to distinguish Picture This
Home from other products by making its professional-strength tools
easy enough for consumers to use. For instance, the new software
contains a library of images that represent real products, from
cabinets to stoves, so the remodeler can see not just how
wall-to-wall cabinets would look, but how the ones with the glass
doors would differ from the cherry maple variety.
<p>
   ``That could hook a lot of people,'' Delhagen said.
<p>
   Chris LeTocq, who follows software for the Dataquest market
research firm in San Jose, said Autodesk had tried to prepare
itself for the consumer marketplace by testing the software on
focus groups and asking the Good Housekeeping Institute in New York
to certify Picture This Home as easy to use.
<p>
   ``This will be quite a challenge for Autodesk because it's a new
market, but they seemed to have done a lot of things right,'' he
said.
<p>
   To bridge the gap between selling to professionals and selling
to consumers, Autodesk hired Linda Henderson, who had directed
marketing for San Francisco-based food maker Specialty Brands and
for the St.-Louis-based Ralston Purina Co.
<p>
   Henderson said Autodesk tested the software to see whether it
appealed more to men or women. She said the tests showed both
genders found the software useful, men because it allowed them to
see how one style of wallpaper would look as opposed to another,
and women because it helped them sketch out room layouts which they
weren't comfortable doing with pen and paper.
<p>
   She said Autodesk had also conceived a print advertising
campaign that would play on the fact that remodeling projects
create family friction. One ad will show a man and woman lying at
opposite sides of the bed, with thought bubbles over his head
decrying the woman as a spendthrift, while the woman derides the
man's lack of taste.
<p>
   ``Our inside joke is that it's either Picture This Home or
Picture This Divorce,'' Henderson said.
<p>
   Indeed, to preserve family peace, the new software also contains
a built-in spreadsheet so do-it-yourselfers can see how this or
that change would affect the overall budget.
<p>
