<DOCID> nyt970122.0019 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8562 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0856 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BATTLING FOR THE OFFICE SUITE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By HIAWATHA BRAY &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   A few months ago, I sat in a large conference room at Microsoft
headquarters as Bill Gates and his lieutenants sang the praises of
the Microsoft Network on-line service. Dozens of journalists sat at
long, curved tables, pecking at laptop computers. No need to waste
our batteries, either; there was an electrical outlet at each seat.
<p>
   But there were no telephone lines for logging onto the Internet.
A few years earlier, when the complex was built, working on-line
wasn't much of an issue.
<p>
   It still wasn't in 1994, as Microsoft redesigned its Office
software suite for the Windows 95 operating system. Then, as now,
Office was the world's most popular bundle of basic business
software. Its Microsoft Word word processing program, the
spreadsheet program Excel, and PowerPoint, for producing
computerized slide shows, are the most popular products in their
categories.
<p>
   Maybe the company didn't want to mess with success. So their
upgraded version of the Office suite still couldn't work well with
the Internet or corporate intranets. Even the suite's built-in
address book didn't have a place for writing in electronic mail
addresses.
<p>
   But just over a year ago, Microsoft saw the light, and has
launched a ferocious campaign to add network capabilities to every
product it makes, including its Office suite. The newest version
hits stores today, and it'll land with a thump. Office 97 ($499
suggested retail price; $209 upgrade price for current Office
users) is a monster that will devour about 120 megabytes of your
hard drive and all the memory chips you can toss at it. But in
exchange, you get a batch of high-quality office software that
integrates nicely with internal corporate networks or the Internet.
<p>
   Don't give Microsoft too much credit; many of the new features
were pioneered months ago by Corel Corp. in its excellent Office 7
suite. Corel's WordPerfect word processing program offers a
built-in editor for creating World Wide Web pages. Office 7 lets
you add Internet-like hyperlinks to text documents, spreadsheets or
slide shows, and open your favorite Web browser from inside the
Corel suite. At last, Microsoft Office has caught up.
<p>
   But with Outlook, its new personal information manager,
Microsoft has stepped into the lead. Outlook, which will also be
sold as a separate product for around $100, is a desktop command
center that lets you manage your work, communicate easily with
colleagues, and access nearly every other function on your
computer. From inside Outlook, you can dispatch e-mail messages,
punch up favorite Web sites, launch a spreadsheet, scribble
electronic ``sticky notes'' or track the week's appointments.
<p>
   I lusted after this remarkable program since I saw a
demonstration of it last autumn. Now that I've used it for a few
weeks, I'm impressed, delighted  &MD;  and disappointed, too.
<p>
   Outlook is too big and too slow to run well on most desktop
machines. My Pentium with 16 megabytes of RAM memory began throwing
up ``out of memory'' errors for the first time since I switched to
Windows 95. No surprise. Outlook snatches 14 megabytes of RAM as
soon as you load it. It's a good thing Windows 95 lets you use a
chunk of your hard drive as a substitute for RAM chips. Otherwise,
I wouldn't have been able to run Outlook at all.
<p>
   Microsoft recommends 8 megs of memory to run any one of the
Office apps, except the Access database, which wants 12 megs. More
memory is needed to run several apps at once, the company says. No
foolin'.
<p>
   This is, of course, absurd. I was running Access alone, on a 16
meg machine, and it was crashing it for lack of memory.
<p>
   As it is, Outlook doesn't run so much as it limps. I'll have to
add at least another 16 megabytes of memory for proper performance.
If you plan to buy it, be sure to budget for more memory  &MD;  32
megabytes or bust.
<p>
   Office 97 has a number of other noteworthy flaws. Remember the
idiotic cartoon help screens from Microsoft's Bob? They're back,
and they ruin an otherwise excellent help feature. And documents
written in Word 97 cannot be read by someone with an earlier
version of Word. What was Microsoft thinking? Word documents are a
de facto standard in the business world. But users of Word 97 can
no longer casually e-mail their documents; the person on the other
end may not be able to read them.
<p>
   These weaknesses should give Corel a chance to recoup in its
next office suite, due out this year. Corel has allied with
Netscape Communications Corp. to add top-quality Internet and
intranet features. Based on my experience with Netscape's new
Communicator program, the next Corel-Netscape office suite will
probably leave Microsoft in the dust once again. WordPerfect users
should wait and see. But Office 97 is a sound investment for loyal
Microsoft users with a little spare cash and a lot of extra memory.
<p>
   (You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(AT)globe.com)
<p>
NYT-01-16-97 1342EST
</TEXT>
