<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8564 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-WEB-TAL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0768 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-WEB-TALES-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; A HAPPY ENDING TO A WRITER'S WEB TALES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MICHAEL SAUNDERS &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Xander Mellish is a name not easily forgotten, especially after
seeing it above an emerging collection of short stories. They are
available only on the web and only because Mellish discovered
herself elbowed away from the usual paths to publication.
<p>
   She launched her web site, which is at
www.users.interport.net/tildexmel, in September 1995. ``I started
it out of frustration with this closed little literary world, the
writing-school mafia who run all the literary publications in the
country,'' she said. ``I didn't want to be one of those people, but
I wanted people to read my stories.''
<p>
   Her characters are the kinds of beautiful losers walking New
York streets, people with lives and loves perpetually in flux. In
one story, Mellish, 28, effectively conveys the passion of a bike
messenger-musician whose life is divided between his two loves:
music and an ambitious girlfriend.
<p>
   Another tale lays bare the sad, complex bond of an ill young man
and the noble woman who cares for him, leading readers to wonder
what each one derives from the interaction.
<p>
   In ``Extraordinary,'' a 19-year-old summer fashion intern from
the Midwest reacts to Manhattan with a mix of excitement and quiet
terror:
<p>
   ``I can remember everything about that first flight, everything
I saw or felt. Right after one o'clock, I was drowsy and did go to
bed, and as I was drifting off I thought about the bus ride from
the airport, and about New York City. I thought about all the
glamorous night spots, and how I could just get into a taxi and ask
to be taken to them, and who I would meet there. But I was also
afraid the taxis might drive me around and around, between the
sirens, and not let me out and never bring me home.''
<p>
   The emotional depth of her stories and their whimsical cartoons
offer a creative respite from her real-life work, writing about
municipal bonds. ``Not that municipal bonds aren't exciting,'' she
says with a chuckle.
<p>
   Some of the stories have been revised several times over the
past year, occasionally prompted by readers' suggestions sent via
e-mail. ``It's like an evolving book. It's no different than an
old-fashioned literary community where people bounce things off
each other.''
<p>
   Thanks to the slow spiral of 'Net attention, she now has an
agent and is working on a compilation of short stories to be
published in the customary book form. When the first bound copies
move off the presses, Mellish will have passed a career milestone.
<p>
   ``But it could never be as good as the Internet,'' she said,
voice rising slightly. ``Somebody who is nobody having access to
all those readers. This is something that writers have wanted since
Gutenberg.''
<p>
--------- &QC;   &UR; Chippier chip:  &LR; At the Consumer Electronics Show, the
massive annual gadget-and-gewgaw exposition held last week in Las
Vegas, chip giant Intel tried to command the early buzz by
unveiling its multimedia-mauling MMX microprocessor chip.
<p>
   Intel says it will speed the simultaneous handling of sound and
video found in most new PC-platform entertainment applications that
can make even a fast Pentium chip into a poky hunk of silicon.
Hard-core gamers are happy, of course, but the MMX will likely have
little effect for most people, except for a possible pocketbook
bonus for anyone who delays buying a Pentium until later this year.
<p>
------- &QC;   &UR; Wired without wires:  &LR; There's likely to be more of an
immediate bump from last Thursday's Federal Communications
Commission announcement of new radio frequencies for cordless data
transmissions. This will enable networked computers, monitors,
printers, scanners and other peripherals to be controlled without
being linked by cables and phone lines that make the floor of a
small office seem like a vine-covered jungle.
<p>
   The push to wire schools to the Internet may proceed faster now
that most can avoid drilling through walls and floors that might
contain asbestos. One machine with a dedicated 'Net connection can
be linked to all others in the school by radio waves.
<p>
---------- &QC;   &UR; Free Slate:  &LR; The free on-line magazine Slate,
 &UR; www.slate.com &LR; , will stay free for the indefinite future,
according to editor Michael Kinsley. The web mag debuted last year
as a freebie but planned to charge $20 yearly once it was
established. Healthy advertising income is enabling it to exist
without resorting to paid subscriptions.
<p>
NYT-01-16-97 1324EST
</TEXT>
