<DOCID> nyt970122.0021 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tia-z> A8565 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-OFFICE- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0725 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-OFFICE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MICROSOFT UNVEILS UPDATED OFFICE AS KEY TO INTERNET &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By HEATHER GREEN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 16 (Bloomberg) -- Microsoft Corp. Chief Executive
Bill Gates unveiled the company's Office 97 software, calling it
the ``centerpiece of Microsoft's Internet strategy.''
<p>
   The package of spreadsheet, database and word-processing
software went on sale in stores today. It's expected to put more
pressure on competing software from Corel Corp. and International
Business Machines Corp. Office products, Microsoft's largest
moneymaker, already command an 85 percent market share.
<p>
   The new version includes such new programs as Internet browsing,
E-mail and collaboration software that let employees in distant
locations share and work on documents together. Office also makes
it easier to link documents and files to the Internet and to other
documents stored on a network.
<p>
   ``Office 97 will position Microsoft to have more power over how
we relate to the total network,'' said Bob Finch, investment
officer at Aeltus Investment Management, a Microsoft shareholder.
<p>
   The new Office is the company's most significant new product
sincec Windows 95, said Richard Fade, Microsoft's vice president of
desktop applications. Fade, Gates and other executives introduced
the product at New York City's Lincoln Center.
<p>
   Microsoft's shares rose 1 3/8 to 86.
<p>
   Microsoft said 500,000 units of Office 97 have been preordered
by distributors and resellers. It said 3 million copies were sold
to companies over the past month, and that 80 companies already
have installed the software on 1 million desktops.
<p>
   Office 97 sales are projected to reach $4 billion in fiscal
1997. The company reported fiscal 1996 revenue of $8.67 billion.
About half of that revenue was from applications sales, of which
zOffice makes up the bulk.
<p>
   Fade said the company expects 30 percent to 45 percent of
Office's users to switch to Office 97. He said the company expects
to expand its market share, in part by appealing to small
businesses and consumers. There are 55 million users of Office
products, with about 25 million users of the Office suite, or
package of products.
<p>
   The software also is expected to benefit from wider use of the
Windows 95 operating system, with which it's designed to work. Only
about 25 percent of the people using older Office products switched
to Office 95, introduced with the August 1995 release of Windows
95.
<p>
   In spite of the success Office is expected to have, analysts
said it is unlikely Microsoft will be able to offer an updated
package of software like Office 97 again.
<p>
   Increasingly, companies are creating computer networks based on
Internet software, with E-mail and collaboration as the focal
point, not word-processing software. Within those networks,
software can be updated piecemeal over time, instead of through one
large piece of software like Office.
<p>
   ``This is the last version of Office as we know it,'' said Eric
Brown, an analyst at Forrester Research Inc., a market researcher.
<p>
   The Internet software included in Office are the beginnings of a
switch toward that new network-centric model, Brown said.
<p>
   Microsoft, which spent $200 million developing the updated
product, said it planned to spend about the same amount to on
research and development for Office updates.
<p>
   It said future plans include putting more of the software on the
central computer servers in a corporate network, so there will be a
lighter load of software on each desktop.
<p>
   The company also will periodically update parts of the software,
making them available over the Internet and computer networks,
though it said it still plans a future overall upgrade like Office
1997.
<p>
   Microsoft is offering four versions of the software to appeal to
large and small customers. Prices range from $209 to $499 for
customers who already have Office, and from $499 to $799 for new
users.
<p>
   The basic Office package is made up of Microsoft Word, Microsoft
Excel spreadsheet, PowerPoint presentation software, Microsoft
Access database software and Outlook E-mail and calendar software.
The different components can be bought separately.
<p>
   (The Bloomberg web site is at http://www.bloomberg.com )
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1005EST
</TRAILER>
