<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=ttx-z> A8566 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0575 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEED THE NEW CHIP? MORE THAN LIFE! &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: What's so special about the new Pentium MMX
chip? Should I think about getting a new computer with one?  &MD;  Chip
Chucker.
<p>
   DEAR CHUCK: What's so special? WHAT'S SO SPECIAL?!?! Why, it's
new and improved! What more does any consumer need to know?!?! And
it even has an exotic-sounding new secret miracle ingredient, MMX.
<p>
   Intel has optimized the old Pentium so it will deliver better
graphics, video and sound. If you can believe everything in the
glowing press release, your old programs will run a tad faster. New
software written to take advantage of the chip's capability is
supposed to scream.
<p>
   Should you buy one? If you're in the market anyway, why not?
Otherwise, you can safely hold off unless you're one of those
anal-retentive gadget freaks who gets all wild-eyed and short of
breath at the mere thought of not owning the most advanced
technology on the planet.
<p>
   Incidentally, in a refreshing display of honest marketing (or it
could have just been a slip of the tongue), Intel says ``MMX''
doesn't stand for anything. It's just a trademark. Oh, sure, and
next you'll be telling me that Retsyn, Techron and Scrubbing
Bubbles are just made-up names for a few common chemicals and not
wonder-ingredients at all. I'll never fall for that.
<p>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Is it possible to get the E-mail address of
anyone in the world? I know my friend is working in Singapore and
has Internet access.  &MD;  Mail Call.
<p>
   DEAR MAIL: Unfortunately, the most reliable way to find an
E-mail address is to use one of those outmoded, hard-wired
telephonic communication devices found in almost every home to
contact your friend personally, for which service you will be
overcharged by a monopolistic megacorporation that hasn't figured
out exactly how to start overcharging people for using the
Internet. Or you can make it a collect call.
<p>
   Alternatively, you could try one of the ``white pages'' services
on the Web: InfoSpace (http://www.infospace.com), Four11
(http://www.four11.com), Bigfoot (http://www.bigfoot.com) or
WhoWhere (http://www.whowhere.com), to name a few.
<p>
   But be warned that these listings are not necessarily
up-to-date, complete or even accurate. For instance, a search for
``Bombay'' turned up dozens of faux-Dr. Bombays, none of whom was
me. And remember, for the best in computing advice, accept no
substitute, unless one of those other guys wants to take over for a
couple of weeks while I jet down to the Caribbean at company
expense so a platoon of obsequious poolside waiters can bring me a
constant supply of powerful native beverages. I think my editors
should know that this would really improve my attitude, therefore
the content of this column. Just a thought.
<p>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay, also known as Fort
Worth Star-Telegram systems manager Mike Gerst, offers occasionally
accurate advice about most matters electronic. He can be reached
via E-mail at drbombay(at sign)startext.net; via snail-mail in care
of the newspaper at Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101-1870; or via
facsimile machine at (817) 390-7257.)
<p>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.startext.net; www.arlington.net; and www.netarrant.net)
<p>
