<SLUG> BC-CPT-BROWN-COMPUTER-CO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0631 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EDMARK'S NEW COLLECTION OF KID'S PROGRAMS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LONNIE BROWN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Children can learn six new games and develop problem-solving
skills using two programs in Edmark Corp.'s Strategy Series.
Designed for ages eight and up, Strategy Challenges Collection 1:
Around the World and Strategy Challenges Collection 2: In the Wild
(CD-ROM; Windows/Mac; about $20) have classic games from various
countries.
<p>
   While the programs are geared toward children, some of the games
can be challenging for adults, particularly when played on the
highest skill levels. And parents, siblings or playmates can play
against a computer opponent or against another player.
<p>
   Collection 1 has been reviewed here previously when it was
released last year, but under another name (Strategy Games of the
World). It has three games: mancala (played with stones placed in
pits in a game board), nine men's morris (played with pieces on a
game board), and go-moku (the object of which is to place five
pieces in a row on a grid before an opponent does).
<p>
   Like Collection 1, the new Collection 2 has three games, and
features interactive strategy coaches who help the children learn
the basic rules of the game and suggest moves to help develop
strategies. Each game has a choice of six opponents who are
designed to show children defensive and offensive strategy.
<p>
   The three games are:
<p>
    &MD;  Jungle chess: A centuries-old game that began in China, this
game uses pieces shaped like animals. Each has a different power
rating indicated on its top. Pieces move one square at a time.
Players try to move into the opponent's den while trying to avoid
capture or falling into a trap on the way.
<p>
    &MD;  Surakarta: A game from the Indonesian island of Java. Instead
of playing with shells on a board drawn in the sand, children play
on the computer screen. Marble-like pieces are used on a board
which had two sets of loops. Players move their pieces along the
loops to capture the opponent's pieces while trying to avoid
capture.
<p>
    &MD;  Tablut: A game of Lapland, the region including parts of
Norway, Sweden, Finland and Russia. The board resembles a
checkerboard without checkered squares. One player has 16 dark
pieces; the other, nine light pieces including a king who starts in
the center of the board. The player with the light pieces tries to
move the king to an outside-edge square while the player with the
dark pieces tries to surround the king on four sides.
<p>
   As children learn the basics of the game, the skill levels
increase, and new backgrounds appear. The friendly strategy coaches
will sometimes appear, and if clicked on, will provide suggestions
for plays. As the skill level becomes more difficult, coaches will
appear more often.
<p>
   To show how the strategy of game play is applied in the real
world, Challenges 2 uses animal and insect videos show children how
animals react offensively and defensively to situations.
<p>
   The program also has a video for parents to learn how the
program teaches strategies, how to build a personal strategy, and
how to use strategies in the games.
<p>
   A two-player sample of Jungle Chess is available at the Edmark
Web site: www.edmark.com. Both Collection 1 and Collection 2
CD-ROMs can be purchased at the Web site for $19.95. For
information call: (800) 691-2985.
<p>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. An
archive of his recent computer columns is on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/data.htm. His column is distributed by The
N.Y. Times News Service.)
<p>
