<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-EARNING </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0547 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-EARNINGS-SPI &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MICROSOFT QUARTERLY PROFITS UP  &MD;  AGAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JIM ERICKSON &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Seattle Post-Intelligencer &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SEATTLE  &MD;  Microsoft Corp. Friday handily beat Wall Street
estimates by reporting a 45 percent increase in quarterly profits,
but the Redmond software company once again warned that its
fast-paced revenue growth is due to decline several quarters hence.
<p>
   For its fiscal second quarter ended Dec. 31, Microsoft said its
profit was $741 million compared to $575 million in the same period
a year ago. Revenues increased 22 percent to $2.68 billion.
<p>
   Strength across all lines of Microsoft's businesses, including
Windows operating systems and desktop applications, drove per-share
earnings to 57 cents, solidly above the consensus 51-cents-a-share
estimate by stock analysts who follow the company.
<p>
   The quarterly performance  &MD;  which was particularly positive
because Microsoft had recorded a 54 percent profit jump in the same
period last year, following the launch of the Windows 95 operating
system  &MD;  had been anticipated by investors following upbeat
earnings announcements earlier in the week by Intel Corp. and other
computer companies.
<p>
   Microsoft stock closed Friday at $87.125, up $1.125 in Nasdaq
trading. The earnings announcement came after markets closed.
<p>
   In a conference call with analysts, Microsoft Chief Financial
Officer Mike Brown said he was ``uncharacteristically optimistic
about the next two quarters'' following this week's release of
Office 97, one of the company's biggest revenue generators. Brown
said he expected earnings per share to increase 5 cents to 10 cents
in the current quarter, and another penny in Microsoft's fiscal
fourth quarter ending June 30.
<p>
   But Brown, who has typically tried to rein in overly optimistic
projections, warned that fiscal 1998 results will be ``solid'' but
growth would slow to ``the low double-digits.''
<p>
   Sales growth of important desktop applications sales will
decline because most corporations already own word processors and
other programs, he said. The company makes less money selling
software ``upgrades'' than it does on new sales.
<p>
   Overall PC sales are slowing, too, to about 15 percent a year,
which has an impact on Microsoft's highly-profitable operating
systems sales.
<p>
   Meanwhile, Microsoft's huge ongoing expenditures on research and
development will continue to balloon from $1 billion a year to $2
billion, Brown said, but returns on that investment won't be felt
until after 1998.
<p>
   Sales during the upcoming fiscal year will get a boost from new
versions of the Windows 95 and Windows NT operating systems, and
the company's sales of PC networking and Internet software are
quickly expanding.
<p>
   But the company's ``Backoffice'' business, which includes
fast-growing sales of the Windows NT server network operating
system, contributes a relatively small portion to overall revenue,
Brown said  &MD;  $750 million in fiscal 1996, when the company took in
$8.7 billion.
<p>
   Signs of a slowdown already are evident, Brown said. In the last
three quarters, year-over-year revenue growth rates have slipped
from 46 percent to 33 percent to 22 percent.
<p>
NYT-01-17-97 2120EST
