<SLUG> BC-US-STOCKS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0521 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-STOCKS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. STOCKS FALL ON IBM EARNINGS DISAPPOINTMENT (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Philip Boroff &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Add dropped first name and affiliation of Peter Cardillo of
Westfalia Investments. Updates prices.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. stocks fell from records
as International Business Machines Corp.'s lower-than-expected
profit damped optimism that earnings can live up to expectations.
<p>
   IBM, one of the 30 stocks in the Dow Jones Industrial Average,
tumbled 13 to 155, or 7.7 percent, sending the average down 75.82
to 6808.08.
<p>
   The drop triggered the New York Stock Exchange's ``uptick'' rule
at 9:50 a.m. Eastern time. The rule is triggered when the Dow
average drops 50 points, in an attempt to stabilize the market by
curbing some computer-guided trades.
<p>
   In the broader market, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index lost 2.34
to 780.38 and the Nasdaq Composite Index fell 2.73 to 1374.24.
<p>
   IBM said fourth-quarter profit rose 18 percent, slightly less
than expected, as a stronger dollar and weak demand in Europe hurt
results. Net income for the computer maker rose to $3.93 a share, 3
cents below analysts' expectations.
<p>
   ``They had some trouble in Europe,'' said analyst Bruce Raabe of
Collins &AMP; Co. ``And hardware sales were the weakest story.''
<p>
   The impact of IBM's disappointment was offset by
better-than-expected profits at Compaq Computer Corp. The
Houston-based computer maker said earnings gained 43 percent, to
$1.64 a share, surpassing expectations by 11 cents.
<p>
   Compaq rose 3 3/8 to 81 7/8.
<p>
   ``With the exception of IBM, so far the earnings look pretty
good,'' said Peter Cardillo, a market strategist at Westfalia
Investments.
<p>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.'s earnings rose 11 percent to $1.43 a
share, 2 cents above analysts' expectations, according to IBES
International Inc. The shares dropped 1/2 to 121 1/8.
<p>
   Dean Witter Discover &AMP; Co., the brokerage and credit card
issuer, said profit rose 28 percent, also topping forecasts.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T Corp. said its profits rose to 76 cents a share from 68
cents a year earlier. Analysts expected 80 cents a share, according
to IBES International Inc. Its shares lost 1/2 to 38 7/8.
<p>
   Shares rose 1/2 to 37 5/8.
<p>
   Stocks received no help from bonds, which declined as the
Treasury prepared to sell debt and a Federal Reserve governor
revived concern that the central bank may raise interest rates
soon. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond, used as a benchmark
for corporate borrowing costs, rose 2 basis points to 6.80 percent.
<p>
   Yesterday, the Dow industrials set their fourth consecutive
record, the 10th this year, rising 40.03 to 6883.90. Reports of
strong profits fueled the rise.
<p>
   Still, with the Dow industrials up 6.36 percent already this
year, ``investors are more sensitive to news that's unfavorable
than news that's favorable,'' said Philip Roth, chief technical
analyst at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
<p>
   Overseas markets were higher. In Japan, stocks jumped 3.78
percent to 18013.88 In London, the FTSE-100 gained 0.20 percent.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1007EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
