<DOCID> nyt970122.0026 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tia-z> A8570 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-EARNS-MICROSOFT-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0996 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-EARNS-MICROSOFT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MICROSOFT 2ND-QTR PROFIT RISES 29%; WARNS ABOUT FUTURE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Heather Green &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Redmond, Washington, Jan. 17 (Bloomberg) -- Microsoft Corp.
reported a 29 percent increase in second-quarter profit that beat
analysts' estimates, although the software maker warned of slower
earnings growth beginning with its next fiscal year in July.
<p>
   Net income rose to $740 million, or 57 cents a share, from $575
million, or 45 cents, in the year-earlier quarter. Revenue for the
quarter ended Dec. 31 rose 22 percent to $2.68 billion from $2.20
billion.
<p>
   Wall Street was looking for earnings of 51 cents, based on the
average estimate of 22 analysts from IBES International Inc.
<p>
   Microsoft said it expects profit growth to ebb as revenue growth
slows in products such as its Windows operating systems and Office
desktop software. The company also is investing hundreds of
millions of dollars on the Internet, where it got a late start, and
on products for the burgeoning business of computer networks.
<p>
   ``The numbers are good, but you have to look beyond that,'' said
Richard Scocozza, an analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman.
``Microsoft is out here saying growth is slowing, and that's what
we need to take away from this.''
<p>
   Microsoft's shares, which rose 1 1/8 to 87 1/8 on the Nasdaq
Stock Market, fell to as low as 85 1/4 when the company released
results after the close of trading.
<p>
   Signs of a slower growth are already are emerging. The
second-quarter's earnings growth didn't match the 54 percent
increase notched in the year-earlier quarter, when the August 1995
release of Windows 95 spurred a consumer buying binge.
<p>
   Microsoft said its software products, including business and
consumer operating systems and desktop programs, sold well across
the board during the quarter. Still, operating system sales growth
is expected to wane because of market saturation and less rapid
growth in personal-computer sales, Microsoft said.
<p>
   ``We worry a lot about desktop saturation,'' said Greg Maffei,
treasurer. ``We're bullish for the long-term, but we're trying to
put expectations in place to show growth isn't straight up.''
<p>
   The company said part of its concern was prompted by how well it
did in the second-quarter and whether those results would lead
investors to believe the growth could continue to increase.
<p>
   ``Our current EPS multiple is a cause for curiosity for me,''
said Michael Brown, Microsoft's chief financial officer, referring
to the ratio of the company's earnings per share to its stock
price. ``Our trailing multiple in the past was 35 when we grew at
46 percent a few quarters ago, but now we're growing 27 percent and
it (the trailing multiple) is 46.''
<p>
   Microsoft's operating system software is used to control the
basic operations of more than 80 percent of the world's computers,
which doesn't give Microsoft much room for growth, Scocozza said.
Growth in the desktop system will converge on PC growth rates,
which are about 15 percent, the company said.
<p>
   The growth of PC sales is expected to rise slightly to 17
percent in 1997 from 16 percent in 1996, although that is still
lower than the 24 percent the industry saw in 1995, according to
International Data Corp., a market researcher.
<p>
   The sales growth of the company's updated Office software, its
biggest moneymaker, is also expected to taper off in fiscal 1998
after rapid growth during the last two quarters of 1997. Office has
more than 85 percent of the market and has to rely more on
convincing companies to switch to the new product than on
increasing its share of the market.
<p>
   In the long-run, Office sales growth should be ``single-digit,''
the company said.
<p>
   Margins could narrow as well. Microsoft plans to spend about
$2.1 billion on research and development during fiscal 1997.
Although Microsoft declined to say how much it plans to spend in
fiscal 1998, the company said research and development will
increase sequentially through fiscal 1997 and into fiscal 1998.
<p>
   Microsoft is investing in Internet services and business and
network software, especially software designed to make it less
expensive to own a computer. Products, including the Windows NT
workstation, SQL Server and Exchange software, are expected to be
the main revenue gainers during the next few years.
<p>
   Microsoft is also investing heavily in Internet and news
services, and has said it expects to spend more than $1 billion
during the next three years before the services become profitable
in fiscal 1999. Investments include the MSN online network,
financial and travel services and a television channel and Internet
joint-venture with General Electric Co.'s NBC network.
<p>
   Revenue rose during the quarter on increasing demand for the
updated version of the company's Windows NT software and Windows
95, boosted by demand for Intel Corp.'s high-powered chips that are
included in most new computers, the company said.
<p>
   During the quarter, Microsoft also sold 3 million copies of its
updated Office programs to corporate users. Office, a package of
database, word-processing and spreadsheet software, went on sale
yesterday in stores.
<p>
   Microsoft said sales of previous Office products tapered off as
customers waited for the update to reach stores, but it expects
Office sales to jump, based on the orders it already received. The
company plans to defer about 25 percent of the revenue from Office
during the next 12 months.
<p>
   ``I'm optimistic about the next two quarters,'' Brown said.
Third quarter earnings should be up 5 or 10 cents sequentially,
with fourth-quarter earnings up another penny, he said.
<p>
   For the six months, Microsoft's net income rose to $1.35
billion, or $1.04 a share, from $1.07 billion, or 84 cents. Revenue
rose to $4.98 billion from $4.21 billion in the year-earlier
period.
<p>
NYT-01-17-97 2115EST
</TEXT>
