<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8571 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-EARNING </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0791 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-EARNINGS-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MICROSOFT'S EARNINGS TOP WALL STREET EXPECTATIONS &LR;  &QL; 
(ART ADV: Graphic of a stock chart is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) &QL; 
 &UR; By LAWRENCE M. FISHER &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   On Friday, Microsoft Corp. reported second quarter earnings that
far exceeded Wall Street analysts' expectations. But the software
giant also said that its growth could slow in fiscal 1998.
<p>
   Investors have grown accustomed to such cautionary remarks from
Microsoft, which often seem calculated to allow the company to
maintain its record of underpromising so that it can overdeliver.
Microsoft reported its results after the market's close, but in
after-hours trading, Microsoft shares rose $1.875 each, to $89,
after gaining $1.125, to $87.125, in on Nasdaq trading.
<p>
   ``We don't want overexuberance to reign,'' Greg Maffei,
Microsoft's treasurer, said in a telephone interview. ``We exceeded
Wall Street estimates very soundly this quarter. It's a recipe for
disaster to beat Street estimates by a wide margin, watch them
raise their estimates and lose your ability to beat them in the
future. We don't want 1998 to become a bar in the minds of analysts
that we can't meet.''
<p>
   For the quarter ended Dec. 31, Microsoft  &MD;  which is based in
Redmond, Wash.  &MD;  reported earnings of $741 million, or 57 cents a
share, up 29 percent from $575 million, or 45 cents a share, in the
comparable period a year earlier. Revenue totaled $2.68 billion, a
22 percent increase over the $2.20 billion reported a year earlier.
<p>
   Analysts had expected the company to earn 51 cents a share,
according to First Call.
<p>
   Maffei said the company had strong performances across all of
its businesses, with particularly robust sales of its Windows 95
operating systems for desktop computers and Back Office
applications for large enterprises. He said the company
intentionally tapered off sales of its Office 95 suite of
applications in anticipation of the launch of Office 97 earlier
this week.
<p>
   ``We are pleased with the current financial results and growth
prospects for the next two quarters, particularly with the outlook
for sales of Office 97,'' Mike Brown, Microsoft's chief financial
officer, said in a statement. ``However, I do anticipate lower
revenue increases in our maturing businesses and margin pressure
from continuing aggressive spending on research and development and
new business ventures,'' he said.
<p>
   ``I'm optimistic about the next two quarters,
uncharacteristically optimistic,'' Brown said in a telephone
conference call. But he noted that Microsoft had been on a downward
revenue growth trend, from 46 percent in fiscal 1995 to 33 percent
in 1996 and 22 percent in 1997  &MD;  and said that this trend would
continue in 1998.
<p>
   Wall Street analysts had already estimated that revenue growth
would drop to 20 percent.
<p>
   ``That was before the fiscal 1997 hurdle bar went up with our
strong results,'' Brown said. ``I will not attempt to second-guess
the market. However our current earnings per share multiple is
cause for curiosity for me,'' he said, noting that Microsoft shares
traded at a lower multiple of earnings two years ago when the
company had a higher growth rate.
<p>
   Brown said there were five factors that could slow growth and
squeeze profit margins: Microsoft's core business, desktop
applications is growing at less than 10 percent; its second-largest
business, desktop operating systems, may be hurt by slowing
computer sales; its fastest growing product, Back Office, remains
small; research and development costs continue to rise, and the
personal computer software business remains inherently risky.
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   ``It is very easy to move from the morning headlines to the
afternoon obituaries,'' Brown said, mentioning the Internet and the
network PC as particular challenges to Microsoft. ``Each year will
bring a new challenge, a new threat, a new competition,'' he said.
<p>
   Maffei said research and development costs continued to grow
more rapidly than revenues, totaling $485 million in the quarter,
up 55 percent from $313 billion in the comparable period a year
earlier.
<p>
   In August, Microsoft began shipping the updated version of
Windows NT, its network operating system software for businesses.
Maffei said that sales of Windows NT and business applications,
like Microsoft SQL Server, a data base management program, had
doubled in the last year. ``By fiscal year end, we expect NT market
share to exceed 40 percent,'' he said.
<p>
NYT-01-17-97 2015EST
</TEXT>
