<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tia-z> A8572 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-BRODERBUND-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0203 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-BRODERBUND-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BRODERBUND TO BUY BACK REMAINING 50% STAKE IN LIVING BOOKS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Karen Fessler &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 17 (Bloomberg) -- Broderbund Software Inc. said
it plans to buy back the other 50 percent of Living Books, which it
sold to Advanced Publications Inc.'s Random House Inc. unit in
1994.
<p>
   Financial terms of the preliminary agreement weren't disclosed.
<p>
   Random House said it will continue to work with Broderbund and
Living Books to develop children's software products.
<p>
   Broderbund formed Living Books as a studio to produce and market
multimedia software for children, then sold half of it Random
House.
<p>
   ``The future of Living Books and our partnership is best served
by making Living Books once again an integral part of the
Broderbund organization,'' said Albert Vitale, chairman and chief
executive of Random House.
<p>
   Novato, California-based Broderbund publishes consumer software.
Its shares fell 3/4 to 33 3/4. Closely held Advanced Publications'
New York-based Random House unit publishes Parade magazine, Vanity
Fair, Vogue and other magazines.
<p>
NYT-01-17-97 1804EST
</TEXT>
