<SLUG> BC-CPT-MUTFUND-WEB-ART-$ </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0467 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-MUTFUND-WEB-ART-$ADV19-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NO RUSH, YET, TO THE WEB &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ART ADV: Graphic showing mutual fund web sites will be sent to
NYT &LR;  graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) &QL; 
 &UR; By CAROLE GOULD &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   What if you threw a party, say, a Super Bowl bash, and nobody
came?
<p>
   That is the situation of the mutual fund industry as it tries to
do business with investors over the Internet.
<p>
   Home pages for fund families are popping up like mushrooms after
a heavy rain, and new on-line features are being marketed every
day. Some fund groups now let investors buy and sell shares using
their home computers. But the beer is getting flat: investors are
staying away in droves.
<p>
   So found the Investor Internet Adoption Study, conducted last
fall to measure fund investors' on-line habits. The study,
commissioned by Twentieth Century Mutual Funds and the Benham
Group, tried to gauge these investors' access to the Internet and
to understand their knowledge, needs and worries about Internet
services and investing on line.
<p>
   Elrick &AMP; Lavidge, a national research firm, conducted the
telephone interviews. It called 1,385 mutual fund investors at
random and found 250 who had personal access to the Internet.
<p>
   Over all, the research suggests that fund investors have been
slow to embrace the Internet, leading Twentieth Century and Benham
(now known together as American Century Investments) to conclude
that ``mutual fund Web site proliferation may be slightly ahead of
shareholder demand for on-line services.''
<p>
   The study concluded that 18 percent of fund investors, about 13
million people, have Internet access. Of these investors, 32
percent have visited Web sites of financial service companies; 28
percent have checked a fund site.
<p>
   The most popular Internet activity for fund investors is to
check fund share prices, the study found. Other activities, in
order of popularity, are reading or downloading prospectuses,
checking account balances and buying or selling fund shares.
<p>
   Still, the company remains optimistic that investors will catch
up to the industry as they become more familiar with new
technology.
<p>
   ``Investor visits to mutual fund Web sites are at a level where
you would expect them to be, considering the fact that most sites
have been in place less than two years and fund companies are just
beginning to understand investors' on-line service needs,'' said
Mary Witwer, director of electronic commerce for Twentieth Century
Mutual Funds and the Benham Group. ``As sites get better and
investors begin to realize the convenience offered by the Web,
usage should increase.''
<p>
NYT-01-17-97 1619EST
</TEXT>
