<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8574 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETNEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0561 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-NETNEWS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE GOOD OL' BOYS OF AVIATION GATHER IN THE INTERNET &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By CHARLES STOUGH &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Granted that things have changed in the international air
warfare business since the end of the Cold War, such as Russia's
offer to sell a few MiG-29 jets to the Pentagon, still there must
be some secrets worth keeping.
<p>
   Whatever those are, there's a chance that someone will blurt
them eventually in a Usenet newsgroup called rec.aviation.military,
the Internet equivalent of a pilots' ready room full of the
chattiest flyboys of all the world's nations.
<p>
   For example, in answer to a posting asking how one would re-work
an F-16 warplane to make it more radar-repellent  &MD;  in a word,
stealthy  &MD;  the helpful advice flowed in from fans everywhere.
<p>
   ``They'd have to completely redesign the engine-intake and ditch
the vertical tail to make any real improvement,'' one contributor
said.
<p>
   Bragging of successes against Arab air forces' MiGs, an Israeli
admitted that there already is a delta-wing, tailless version of
the F-16.
<p>
   Then there would still be the problem of the right-angle panel
joints, ``patches'' and rivet lines on the fuselage, said another
contributor. ``An F-16 is a virtual radar reflector,'' he said.
``Couple this with the fact that an F-16 isn't worth any more than
a lawn dart if it isn't carrying ordnance. Throw two Sidewinders,
six bombs, a couple fuel tanks, and a pod, and you've added quite a
bit of reflectivity  &MD;  you'll see him for many, many miles.''
<p>
   Yeah, well, OK then, never mind hiding the fully-armed F-16 for
now, but thanks for the tips.
<p>
   Meanwhile another thread of conversation asked what nicknames
are applied to pilots, particularly rookies, in the various air
forces. In the Canadian Air Force and U.S. Navy, for example,
newcomers are sometimes called Nuggets.
<p>
   Rookie is popular for CH-124 Sea King helicopter trainees, a
contributor responded, or FNG for Fairly New Guy, except military
crews seldom say ``fairly'' when any other ``F'' word will do.
<p>
   On the C-130 Hercules yard, newcomers are TWITs, for Transport
Weenies in Training. Then there are the ever so much more important
Fighter/Attack Guys, or FAGs. F-16 pilots call F- 15 pilots
Coneheads, but that could be because the F-15 drivers refer to
F-16s as Lawn Darts (see above).
<p>
   Tanker crews are TOADs because so many are Temporarily on Active
Duty. Bomber crews are Pukes. New naval aviators sometimes are
called Butterbars because of their ensign's gold collar insignia.
In the P-3 Orion community, trainees are No-Ps until they work up
to the seat of 3-P, or Third Pilot.
<p>
   All of this is kindly and gentle hazing, of course, and no one
takes offense, at least on the Internet. For unlike a genuine ready
room full of rival pilots, a computer keyboard connected to a
Usenet forum is hardly the place where an offended flyboy would
take a swing at anybody.
<p>
   (EDS.; PLS USE THE PROPER SYMBOL IN PLACE OF `(AT)' IN THIS PGF.
<p>
   Usenet newsgroups are accessible with modem-equipped computers;
consult local Internet service providers for instructions and
groups available. Charles Stough is an editor for the Dayton (Ohio)
Daily News. His electronic address is copyboy(at)dma.org.
<p>
