<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8575 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-SHARES-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0393 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-IBM-SHARES-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IBM STOCK SLIDES AFTER DISAPPOINTING 4TH-QTR EARNINGS REPORT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Margaret D. Williams &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Armonk, New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- International Business
Machines Corp.'s stock dropped as much as 7.7 percent after the
world's largest computer maker reported lower-than-expected sales
and earnings for the fourth quarter.
<p>
   IBM's stock fell 11 1/2 to 156 1/2 in early trading of 3.22
million shares, making it the second-most active U.S. stock.
Earlier, shares fell as low as 155. The stock had been trading at
ten-year highs in the past few weeks as investors were optimistic
about the earnings.
<p>
   ``IBM's been a major outperformer the past three or four
months,'' said John Rutledge, an analyst at Boston's Independence
Investment Associates, which owned 2.2 million IBM shares at the
end of September. Now, ``it takes a rest for a while.''
<p>
   IBM yesterday said fourth-quarter profit rose 18 percent,
slightly less than expected, as a stronger dollar and weak demand
in Europe hurt results.
<p>
   IBM said net income rose to $2.02 billion, or $3.93 a share,
from $1.71 billion, or $3.09 a share, in the year-earlier quarter.
Sales climbed 5.6 percent to $23.14 billion from $21.92 billion.
<p>
   Earnings were below the most recent estimate of $3.96 a share
from 15 analysts polled by IBES International Inc. Several analysts
had said they expected earnings of more than $4.00.
<p>
   At least four analysts cut their earnings estimates for 1997.
<p>
   ``Given that the stock has run up, we're probably going to see
the beginning'' of a decline, said Morgan Stanley analyst Steven
Milunovich. The drop could be as much as 15 percent in the next
three to five months, he said.
<p>
   IBM, like some other companies, was hurt by weak economies in
some European countries. Additionally, mainframe and workstation
sales were slow and falling memory-chip prices continued to hurt
results.
<p>
   Hardware sales edged up 2 percent to $11.7 billion, with
personal computer sales rising from the year-ago quarter in both
corporate products and home machines. System 390 mainframe sales
declined and RS/6000 workstation sales were unchanged from
year-earlier levels.
<p>
   ``The revenue growth story is not real strong at IBM,'' Rutledge
said. ``The bloom is off the rose.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1010EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0032 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8577 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-FINLAND-COMPUTE-2 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0605 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-FINLAND-COMPUTE-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HELSINKI: Heinonen said. &LR; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   At the moment, nearly 30 percent of Finnish homes have portable
computers, and about 60 percent of the population has access to the
Internet either at home, at work, or through a local institution
like a library, according to Johan Helsingus, chief executive of
Eunet Finland Oy, one of Europe's largest Internet service
providers.
<p>
   Merita, Finland's largest bank, already provides more than three
million account holders with highly secure electronic access by
computers.
<p>
   Telecom Finland, which is government-owned and the country's
largest phone company, is beginning a limited Internet telephone
service  &MD;  allowing customers to talk to each other through their
computer terminals. Since most such calls would be made through
local telephone numbers, the procedure promises in the long run to
become the cheapest way to call anyone.
<p>
   Laboring with a mood as dark as a Finnish December afternoon,
Dotty, 32, a recovering alcoholic who requested that his last name
not be used, surfed the Internet for an hour one day last month.
Ever since he learned how to get on the Internet barely three
months ago, he has come to the stately Rikhardinkadun public
library three hours a week to chat with other recovering alcoholics
halfway around the globe.
<p>
   Why not do his chatting locally, at Alcoholics Anonymous? ``Oh,
I do that, too, but the Net is different,'' he answered, barely
shifting his eyes off the computer screen. ``On the Net, feelings
are true. For me, it is more about self-help: a different kind of
therapy.''
<p>
   That same evening on a recent Thursday in another public library
at the Helsinki suburb of Vantaa, a woman was glued to a computer
in the airy atrium downstairs as she searched the Internet.
Upstairs on the second floor, Jean-Erik Ekberg, 27, was about to
start a class on how to use the Internet, in a room filled with
computers donated by industry and the municipality. Scattered
around were a freelance translator, a grandfather accompanied by
his granddaughter and grandson, and a banker on the verge of
retirement who had decided that Internet surfing would be an
amusing thing to do in his free time.
<p>
   Jarno Subanto, 26, who is studying educational sciences, has
access to a computer at home and at the university. He said: ``My
parents keep their portable computer in the bedroom. Some of my
friends move it to the breakfast table to read newspapers.'' He
does not actually have his own PC, but goes on line at Tampere
University, where Internet access is free. ``I am at a point where
I feel positively weird if I turn on my PC to find no e-mail,'' he
said. ``It means the connection is broken.''
<p>
   According to various estimates corroborated by universities,
Internet providers and telephone companies, 11 percent of the
population, or more than 570,000 Finns between the ages of 14 and
74, have used the Internet in the last three months  &MD;  a 21 percent
increase in the last three months.
<p>
   ``It's a snowball reaction that is fast changing people's
lives,'' said Petri Vuorimaa, the director of the Digital Media
Institute at Tampere University.
<p>
   Helsingus, chief executive of Eunet Finland Oy, said: ``In my
company, staff is wired 24 hours a day. When people get up they
start chatting. Two weeks ago, I asked my secretary to get someone
on the phone and her answer was, `Oh, he just stepped into the
shower,' '' he chuckled. ``But this is no joke. Being wired all the
time is the shape of the future.''
<p>
NYT-01-19-97 2029EST
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1010EST
</TRAILER>
