<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8580 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-JONBENET-WEBSITE- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0432 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-JONBENET-WEBSITE-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FIRM POSTS WEB SITE IN JONBENET RAMSEY DEATH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By HIAWATHA BRAY &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   When 6-year-old JonBenet Ramsey was slain last month, the case
drew the attention of newspapers and television networks worldwide.
It's not rare for a spectacular crime to draw so much media
attention.
<p>
   It is unusual for a victim's family to retain an elite crisis
management firm to help them cope with the publicity spawned by the
crime, and even more surprising that the crisis managers are using
the Internet to tell the Ramseys' side of the story.
<p>
   The firm is Rowan &AMP; Blewitt, founded in 1984 by former NBC News
White House correspondent Ford Rowan. Hank Boerner, a senior vice
president, said last week that the Ramseys' lawyers contacted the
firm shortly after JonBenet's body was found Dec. 26 in the
basement of their Boulder, Colo., home.
<p>
   ``They recognized what could happen with press coverage and they
wanted people who could communicate with the media,'' he said.
<p>
   The company sent two people to Boulder to coordinate media
coverage. At the firm's New York headquarters, other experts
analyzed coverage by TV networks, newspapers and on the Internet,
he said.
<p>
   The firm set up a site on the Internet's World Wide Web so that
media outlets could obtain information from the Ramseys. The site
was never intended for use by the general public, Boerner said, but
when CNN reporters learned of it, they posted a link to it on CNN's
site.
<p>
   Since then the site has received thousands of visitors from
around the world, though Boerner admitted that it contains little
information.
<p>
   This is the first time Rowan &AMP; Blewitt has created a web site in
connection with a murder investigation, but the company has used
the web on behalf of its more traditional corporate clients. For
instance, when citizens of a New Jersey town worried about toxic
chemicals in a Superfund cleanup site, the firm worked with the
cleanup company to create a web site packed with information.
<p>
   But another crisis management specialist questions Rowan &AMP;
Blewitt's high-profile approach in the Ramsey case.
<p>
   ``To keep people from jumping to the wrong conclusions, we just
operate in the background most of the time,'' said Larry Smith,
senior consultant for the Institute for Crisis Management in
Louisville, Ky. ``The very fact that they made it public that
they'd hired a public relation person ... that sent the wrong
message to a lot of people.''
<p>
NYT-01-20-97 1128EST
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1011EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0036 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=v pri=u sel=taf-z> A8581 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-LITE-CLIENTS-NY </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0445 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PHOTO-LITE-CLIENTS-NYT &LR; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
