<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0652 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY-COX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TECHNOBUDDY: TRY THIS AT HOME  &MD;  AFTER READING VERY CAREFULLY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BILL HUSTED &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   I've had plenty of tips in my time. Once, at a racetrack in
Arkansas, a nun told me to put all I could afford on the gray
horse. That's when I discovered that divine intervention does not
extend to racehorses.
<p>
   Computer tips are just as risky. For one thing, if you don't
completely understand the instructions, you can end up messing up
your computer. For another, there are plenty of tricks and tips
that work just fine but are more trouble than the problem they
solve.
<p>
   But a good computer tip  &MD;  like one at the racetrack  &MD;  can be
rewarding. Today I'm sharing some tips submitted by readers. I've
tested the ones mentioned, and they seem useful and worked fine for
me.
<p>
   The first tip comes from Mary Ellen Bacon. Like a lot of folks,
she enjoys sharing Web sites she's found with friends. Here's an
easy way to do it, in her own words:
<p>
   ``E-mail a favorite Web site to a friend. To send a Web page by
e-mail, while at the page, choose Mail Document from Netscape
Navigator's File menu. The e-mail window that appears will
automatically contain the site's URL, just a click away. If the
person receiving the message has Netscape Navigator, the page will
appear as an attachment in the message, and links in the page can
be accessed right from the mail message.''
<p>
   The next tip from Garry Daniell treads ground I've avoided: the
Windows 95 Registry. The Registry is a library of files that keeps
track of the configuration of your computer. I've avoided writing
about editing the Registry for two reasons: One, if you mess up
here you can cause enough damage to require installing Windows 95
from scratch. Two, I don't understand the Registry.
<p>
   But this tip is a pretty safe one, and it worked fine for me. If
you decide to try it, however, make sure you follow the
instructions exactly and don't try to make other changes unless
you're a certified wizard.
<p>
   ``When you open the Add/Remove Programs icon in Control Panel,
you get a listing of all the programs Windows 95 can automatically
remove. Occasionally, you may encounter an item Windows 95 will not
remove. Some programs will leave duplicate listings as repeated
installations or upgrades are installed.
<p>
   ``These items may be removed from the list by using the Registry
Editor, a utility program which comes with Windows 95. To do so,
follow these steps:
<p>
   ``1. Open the Registry Editor (choose Run in the Start Menu),
type `regedit' (without the quotes), and click OK.
<p>
   ``2. Navigate your way to: HKEY(underscore)LOCAL MACHINE 
(backslash)Software(backslash)Microsoft(backslash)Windows(backslash)
 CurrentVersion(backslash)Uninstall by clicking, with the left
mouse button, each folder named above.
<p>
   ``3. In the left window, with the right mouse button, click the
folder (under Uninstall) that represents the item you want to get
rid of and choose Delete.
<p>
   ``4. Close the Registry Editor.
<p>
   ``If you now reopen the Add/Remove Programs Properties dialog
box, the item will no longer be listed. A word of warning. This is
not a substitute for Windows 95 Uninstall Program as it only
removes the listing from the Registry. It does not delete files.
Any program removed from the Registry listing will no longer
function, so if you should happen to remove the wrong item, your
only recourse is to reinstall the program.''
<p>
   The two tips printed today are good examples of the clear
explanations that make it easy for novices to understand what to do
and why. If you'd like to submit a tip of your own, please e-mail
me at the address that appears with this column.
<p>
   (Reach Bill Husted by e-mail at tecbud(at)ajc.com.)
</TEXT>
