<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0682 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE-COX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSCENE: SHOP AROUND FOR FREE HOME PAGE SERVICES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BILL HUSTED &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Once upon a time, it was enough to have an e-mail address. But
nowadays, folks want their own home page in cyberspace.
<p>
   Personal Web pages are good places to store pictures of your
family, or links to your favorite sites on the Web. They're easy to
create and require very little attention once they're up and
running.
<p>
   But many Internet service providers charge extra for subscribers
who want a Web page of their own. That makes sense, because the
company has to provide space on its own computers to store the
documents and electronic images necessary for a Web page. That's
called ``hosting'' a page.
<p>
   Luckily there are several companies that offer to host personal
pages  &MD;  and, in some cases, pages for nonprofit organizations and
even small businesses  &MD;  for free. But make sure you understand that
you'll still need an Internet account to take advantage of these
offers. The companies give you an address on the Web and storage
for free, but not free Internet access. It's still a terrific deal,
though.
<p>
   In most cases, you won't be pressured to subscribe to a
commercial account, or to move your Internet access subscription to
the company that hosts the account. However, the usual consumer
rules for caution apply. And folks need to be extra careful with
any ``free'' offer. Remember, the Web is constantly in flux, so
make sure the offer hasn't changed and there are no charges before
you move your files to one of these free sites.
<p>
   A really good site  &MD;  if you can stand wading through all the
trendy talk of cybercommunities and such  &MD;  is at GeoCities, located
at http://www.geocities.com/homestead/.
<p>
   The notion is to create a virtual community, with cities and
suburbs. That's a neat idea, but you have to learn a whole new
vocabulary to figure out how this place works. All the information
to help you is there, but some folks would rather just skip the
trendy talk and get a free page on the Web.
<p>
   Things are a bit more straightforward at Achievement
International. The number and size of files you can store in your
free Web site are limited, but the directions for using the site
are clear. You'll find all the details at
http://www.achiever.com/design/freehmpg.html.
<p>
   Another place offering free Web page hosting and straight talk
is the Angelfire Home Pages at
http://www.angelfire.com/freepages/index.html. You click on one
button to create your page, another to edit it. The catch here is
that you pretty much have to follow a set format, so your home page
won't be as fancy as you might like.
<p>
   Truth is, a lot of newcomers will appreciate the ease of a site
like Angelfire and a lot of veterans will chafe at the
restrictions. To find out what kind of home page you'd like to
build and how much help you'll need, my best advice is to check
around at several of these sites and find the one that suits your
needs best.
<p>
   A good place to find a long list of sites offering free Web page
hosting is a page called, aptly enough, Sites Offering Free Web
Space at http://www.webbuild.com/(tilde)elkinsp/webspace.html.
<p>
   Still another page filled with hot links to several free
services is located at http://150.216
<p>
   .20.36/WebFree.html.
<p>
   Visit several sites that offer free pages before going to the
trouble of transferring the files needed to get your page up and
running.
<p>
   Check out each site carefully. Most really are free, but you'll
find that some places use an offer of free Web space as a come-on,
or make the process so complicated that it's too much trouble to
mess with. So cruise several of the sites and visit home pages that
are already located there before you sign up. It's no different
than house-hunting: You can tell a lot about a neighborhood by the
folks who hang out there.
<p>
   (Bill Husted can be reached at tecbud(AT)ajc.com.)
</TEXT>
