<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-TOOLS-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0647 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-TECH-TOOLS-COX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TECH TOOLS: ART PROGRAMS WORTHY DESPITE SHORTCOMINGS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JACK WARNER &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The wealth of art available for the computer continues to
expand, and today we examine a CD-ROM devoted to the work of Pablo
Picasso and another concerned with a great collection of American
art.
<p>
   Picasso, published by Grolier, presents about 600 works of the
Spanish-born artist. I suspect the program was made in France; it
has some of the earmarks of other French art discs I have seen  &MD; 
mainly a degree of disorganization and a manic tendency.
<p>
   The interface is odd but manageable. The primary means of
navigation are going straight through, in chronological order, or
by selecting a period of the artist's life and work.
<p>
   The art is presented well, but the information behind it is
shallow; the makers of the disc seemed more concerned with fancy
visual effects than enlightenment.
<p>
   We find that ``Demoiselles d'Avignon'' shocked the world of art,
but we are never really told why. We come upon a screen that shows
Henri Matisse lounging in his studio with a legend that says
``Picasso resumed his dialogue with Matisse.'' There is no
indication whatever of the dialogue itself or what it may have
meant to either painter.
<p>
   The program gets extremely noisy in the intervals between
periods in Picasso's life  &MD;  wrenching the viewer briefly from a
museum stroll into an MTV video.
<p>
   The National Museum of American Art, an arm of the Smithsonian
Institution in Washington, contains an incredible wealth of
American art, not limited merely to paintings but encompassing
sculpture and fine crafts as well, and ranging from obscure artists
to the most famous.
<p>
   A MacMillan Digital CD-ROM called National Museum of American
Art documents more than 750 of the museum's holdings in a most
thorough manner.
<p>
   The interface is a good deal clumsier than in ought to be; it
has trouble shifting between the various ways of examining the art.
However, it can be dealt with, and the different tours and
organizations of the art are quite good.
<p>
   I especially enjoyed the tour of personal favorites presented by
Elizabeth Broun, director of the museum. She discusses these
paintings in a cheery, engaging and often whimsical monologue,
descending only occasionally into that solemn tolling of the bells
of symbolism that makes one's teeth itch.
<p>
   I wish the pictures were presented somewhat larger; in an
800x600 resolution they are just barely large enough when enlarged.
Some very fascinating paintings are so murky it is still difficult
to see what's going on in them.
<p>
   Each object is presented along with discussions, sometimes
several of them, taken from show or museum catalogs. Some of these
are most illuminating; others are hilarious.
<p>
   I wonder if Frederic Remington would have understood the
commentary about his wonderful painting ``Fired On.'' Would he have
agreed that the white horse at the focus of the picture is not
spooked by being shot at, but ``it sees itself vaporized,
abstracted, bodiless  &MD;  as the `mere paint' that it is.''
<p>
   In addition to ample commentary, there is a picture and a brief
biography of each artist. There is also a multimedia gallery with
short film clips of some of the artists discussing their work, a
most delightful addition. Not one of them, as far as I could see,
appeared to be interested in painting things like horses that
suffer angst attacks in the midst of gunfights.
<p>
   National Museum of American Art is a welcome addition to any
library of CD-ROMs on art; so is Picasso, even with its paucity of
information. Both programs sell for about $40.
<p>
   (Jack Warner writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
<p>
   .
</TEXT>
