<SLUG> BC-CPT-SUN-MICROSYSTEMS- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0293 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-SUN-MICROSYSTEMS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW SUN COMPUTERS TO COMPETE WITH OLD MAINFRAMES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Margaret D. Williams &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Mountain View, California, Jan. 20 (Bloomberg) -- Sun
Microsystems Inc. introduced a new line of network computers aimed
at replacing traditional mainframes made by companies including
International Business Machines Corp.
<p>
   Sun introduced the new line along with a data storage system,
software and services. The systems will help Sun compete in the
market for machines that cost $500,000 to $2 million.
<p>
   ``It is a huge business opportunity for Sun,'' said Anil Gadre,
vice president of corporate marketing for Sun.
<p>
   The machines are designed to replace the traditional mainframes
that have become the center of many corporate networks. Mainframes
weren't initially designed to be used that way, although they've
been adapted to be linked with lots of smaller personal computers
or workstations to share data, files and applications.
<p>
   Sun, which specializes in workstations, servers system software
and other elements of the network that use and distribute data, now
wants to sell the most expensive piece of the network.
<p>
   Mainframes were designed to manage and centralize applications
and processing, and provide nonstop computing capability, although
they're not easy to upgrade or expand. Sun said its systems are
easier to integrate into a network because they have more
flexibility.
<p>
   The Sun Ultra Enterprise 10000 system, with 16 processors,
starts at $870,000, and will be shipped in volume starting in
March.
<p>
   Sun expects to start recording revenue from these systems in its
March quarter.
<p>
NYT-01-20-97 0925EST
