<SLUG> BC-CPT-PLAYSTATION-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0456 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-PLAYSTATION-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SONY CORP.'S PLAYSTATION GAME MACHINE SELLING OUT WORLDWIDE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Todd Zaun &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Tokyo, Jan. 20 (Bloomberg) -- Sony Corp.'s PlayStation video
game machine has sold out in Japan and supplies are dwindling
rapidly in U.S. and Europe, Sony Computer Entertainment Inc. said.
<p>
   ``Although we're producing quite a large number, demand is still
surpassing supply,'' said Konosuke Shimizu, vice-president of
corporate communications for Sony Computer Entertainment Inc., the
subsidiary of Sony Corp. that sells the PlayStation.
<p>
   Sony increased production of Playstation consoles to 1 million
units a month in November from about 650,000 a month.
<p>
   Renewed demand for the machine more than two years after its
introduction shows that Sony's strategy of paying more to lure game
developers to the PlayStation format is paying off, analysts said.
<p>
   In Japan, for example, stores such as Laox Co. are rushing to
secure more of the machines before Square Co. releases a
PlayStation game this month that's expected to be a hit.
<p>
   Sony has attracted many of Japan's best game makers by offering
higher royalties. And Sony buys more of the games in advance,
reducing the risk to game makers of a flop.
<p>
   PlayStation sales had reached 5 million in Japan and 11 million
worldwide as of Jan. 8, according to Sony Computer Entertainment.
<p>
   About 600 hundred games are available for Sony's PlayStation,
compared with 10 for the newer and more powerful Nintendo64, made
by Nintendo Corp.
<p>
   Enix Corp., an independent game maker best known in Japan for
the role-playing game Dragon Quest, said last week it will stop
making games exclusively for Nintendo. The company will make its
next version of Dragon Quest for Sony's PlayStation.
<p>
   Square, which makes the popular Final Fantasy game series,
decided late-last year to develop its games in the Sony PlayStation
format. The next version of Final Fantasy will go on sale Jan. 30.
<p>
   Japanese electronics retailer Laox said most of its stores sell
their stock of PlayStation consoles soon after they receive
shipments. The company increased its order for PlayStations,
anticipating demand will grow even stronger after the release of
the Final Fantasy game, a company official said.
<p>
   The game machine was also sold out at all Tokyo stores of
Sofmap, the computer and software retailer owned by Softbank Corp.
<p>
   Sony's stock fell 80 yen, or 1 percent, to 7,580, less than the
4.3 percent decline in the benchmark Nikkei 225 stock average.
Square Co. stock rose 120 yen, or 1.97 percent, to 6,200. Enix
Corp. fell 30 yen to 2,690.
<p>
NYT-01-20-97 0102EST
</TEXT>
