<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FRANKLIN-QUEST-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FRANKLIN QUEST TO BUY COVEY LEADERSHIP FOR $160 MLN IN STOCK &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Karen Fessler &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Salt Lake City, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Franklin Quest Co., a
time-management seminar provider, said it agreed to pay $160
million in stock for closely held Covey Leadership Center, which
sells productivity training books and other products.
<p>
   Salt Lake City-based Franklin, which sells products through its
catalog and retail stores, said it plans to name the combined
company Franklin Covey Co. It will have annual revenue of more than
$445 million and more than 100 retail stores.
<p>
   ``The opportunity to distribute Covey Leadership Center products
and services through the Franklin distribution channels will
accelerate our ability to reach more customers,'' said Stephen
Covey, chairman of Covey, which has printed more than 12 million
copies of books on leadership training and productivity.
<p>
   Franklin Quest shares rose 3/8 to 23 in early trading.
<p>
   The transaction, which will be accounted for as a pooling of
interests, has been approved by the board of directors of each
company and is pending approval from shareholders.
<p>
   The companies expect to complete the transaction by the end of
May.
</TEXT>
