<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8590 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MGM-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0414 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-MGM-INTERNET-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MGM SETS UP SITE TO HELP FIGHT CRIME &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By PETER TRUELL &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Inc. is showcasing an interactive Internet
service at the presidential inauguration that may, oddly enough,
help law-enforcement officials to catch up with the studio's former
boss.
<p>
   MGM Interactive introduced True Crime Stories, a new interactive
Web show, on the National Mall in Washington at the weekend, as
part of the Technology Playground section of festivities for
President Clinton's inauguration.
<p>
   The MGM subsidiary is developing True Crime Stories with the
justice department, the treasury department and 17 government
agencies charged with fighting crime.
<p>
   The Web show, produced for the Internet, is to feature
multimedia files, including video, audio, graphics and text on a
wide range of unsolved criminal cases 24 hours a day, seven days a
week, and users will be able to post messages and take part in
on-line exchanges with guest experts.
<p>
   The new show could help the justice department catch up with
Giancarlo Parretti, who bought MGM in 1990 for $1.3 billion, before
losing control of the studio a year later when bankers called in
his loans.
<p>
   Parretti is now a fugitive from U.S. justice after failing to
appear at a sentencing hearing on Jan. 6 in state court in
Wilmington, Del. He faces as much as 10 years in jail after a
conviction on charges of evidence tampering and perjury related to
his acquisition of MGM.
<p>
   Parretti, who is now believed to be in Orvieto, Italy, a town
some 60 miles north of Rome, is also wanted by the French
authorities on charges of bank fraud related to the hundreds of
millions of dollars he borrowed from Credit Lyonnais to acquire
MGM.
<p>
   Ron Frankel, executive vice president and general manager of MGM
Interactive, said on Friday that he did not know if Parretti would
be featured on the Web show, which has yet to have an official
starting date beyond the introduction at the inaugural festivities.
<p>
   But, he said, ``the Internet has such a powerful ability to
present information to people,'' and he expects that True Crime
Stories will help keep people informed about fugitives and may aid
government efforts to recapture them. If the Web show did help lead
to Parretti's recapture, Frankel said his reaction would be that
``the system worked.''
<p>
NYT-01-19-97 2205EST
</TEXT>
