<SLUG> BC-UNO-FTC-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0324 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-UNO-FTC-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNO RESTAURANTS SETTLES FTC CHARGE ON LOW-FAT PIZZA AD CLAIMS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Bob Drummond &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Uno Restaurant Corp., the
operator of Pizzeria Uno restaurants, today agreed to stop touting
some thin-crust pizzas as low-fat food, settling a false
advertising complaint by the Federal Trade Commission.
<p>
   The FTC charged that Pizzeria Uno's television and print ads
falsely promoted the restaurant chain's ``Thinzettas'' line of
thin-crust pizzas as low fat when at least six of the line's eight
pizzas exceeded acceptable limits for low-fat foods.
<p>
   The case marks the first time the federal consumer-protection
agency has brought charges involving nutrition claims by a
restaurant chain.
<p>
   To resolve the allegations, West Roxbury, Massachusetts-based
Uno signed an agreement pledging that it will not misrepresent fat
content or other nutritional information about its pizzas. The
settlement didn't call for a fine or other monetary penalty.
<p>
   The FTC, which polices federal false-advertising laws, has
recently stepped up oversight of diet-related promotional efforts.
<p>
   Last year, the agency took no action after probing menu claims
by PepsiCo Inc.'s Taco Bell chain, Brinker International Inc.'s
Chili's restaurants, Elias Brothers Restaurants Inc.'s Big Boy
chain, and Carlson Cos.' T.G.I. Friday's.
<p>
   In the last several years, however, food retailers such as Mrs.
Fields Cookies Inc., Dannon Co., and Grand Metropolitan Plc's
Haagen-Dazs Co. have settled FTC charges that they made false
low-fat claims for some food items.
<p>
   Uno officials couldn't be reached for comment. Uno shares rose
1/8 to 6 7/8 in morning trading.
<p>
   Under its agreement with the FTC, Uno is permitted to make
low-fat claims for food items as long as they meet federal Food and
Drug Administration guidelines for low-fat foods.
</TEXT>
