<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERACTIVE-ADS-M </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0742 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-INTERACTIVE-ADS-MEDIA-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AN INTERACTIVE ADVERTISING NETWORK OFFERS TUTORIALS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By STUART ELLIOTT &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Are you ready for classes in interactive advertising from A for
Apple to Z for Ziff-Davis?
<p>
   Those lessons for marketers and agencies, which began last week,
are not being taught by a beloved pedagogue like Mr. Microchips.
Nor are they to be found on a Web site like
http://www.welcomebackkotter.edu.
<p>
   Rather, the tutorials are in the form of a campaign for Double
Click, an interactive advertising network based in New York with
sales offices in cities including Boston, Chicago, Los Angeles and
Toronto.
<p>
   The effort to promote the perceived potential of cyberpitches is
being created by Digital Pulp, a small agency in New York, and
carries the theme ``Building one-to-one relationships millions at a
time.''
<p>
   Double Click plans to spend slightly more than $2 million
through 1997 on the campaign, which will include print
advertisements, direct mail and of course appeals on its own Web
site (http://www.doubleclick.com).
<p>
   ``We want to be a catalyst, if you will, for the industry to
grow and realize its potential,'' said Lee Nadler, marketing
director at Double Click.
<p>
   ``We recognize the need to bring in the big advertisers and the
big money,'' he added, ``and that's going to take some time. Yes,
we're selling now, but we're also educating for tomorrow's
dollars.''
<p>
   Recent setbacks in the interactive realm are ``getting everyone
terribly confused,'' Nadler said, like the abrupt shutdowns of what
had been promising electronic publishing ventures and disputes over
measuring Web site traffic.
<p>
   ``The promise of the Internet has led to a rush to put up
sites,'' he added, ``perhaps before they had a purpose. People need
to know how to harness this.''
<p>
   Nadler, who has also worked for Kirshenbaum Bond &AMP; Partners in
New York and the on-line service Prodigy, said: ``Door-to-door
sales was the most effective marketing tool because you got to know
the customer. You built a relationship, a dialogue. Now the Web has
that same power and same efficiency, but some people feel they're
coming in halfway through.''
<p>
   The first ad in the Double Click series makes that same
comparison to how Fuller brushes and vacuum cleaners were peddled:
``An introduction is made, interaction begins, questions are asked
and answered, products are sold.''
<p>
   The ad goes on to present tips on how to get the proverbial foot
in the door, suggesting for instance that the creative content of
interactive advertising ``be tested before you spend big money on
placements.''
<p>
   The campaign deliberately eschews explanations of how
interactive technology works, said Steven Sacks, president and
creative director at Digital Pulp, because it was more important to
``educate people on how this medium works and give them tools to
take advantage of it.''
<p>
   Double Click was formed in March by the merger of a unit of
Poppe Tyson, owned by Bozell, Jacobs, Kenyon &AMP; Eckhardt, with what
was the Internet Advertising Network.
<p>
   Double Click offers advertisers the ability to buy space on
almost 70 sites in content categories like business, entertainment,
news, search engines and sports, offering ``affinity groups'' of
consumers interested in those areas.
<p>
   Among the sites Double Click represents are one devoted to the
comic strip ``Dilbert'' (http://www.united
media.com/comics/dilbert/), USA Today Online
(http://www.usatoday.com) and the Internet Address Finder
(http://www.iaf.net).
<p>
   Double Click had hoped to have 100 sites in its network by the
end of 1996, but Nadler said that goal would now be met ``in the
next few months.'' He attributed the delay to ``strict criteria''
that required sites be ``well backed.''
<p>
   Double Click also customizes banners and other interactive ads
through a technology named Dart, for Dynamic Advertising Reporting
and Targeting.
<p>
   ``Dart allows us to recognize users when they come to a site on
our network,'' Nadler said. ``The advertiser tells us who the
target audience is; for example, college students in California. We
recognize those individuals and show them the message, within 15
milliseconds.''
<p>
   Perhaps a sequel to the hit film ``Jerry Maguire'' will feature
a zealous advertising agent who shouts, ``Show me the message!''
<p>
NYT-01-19-97 1903EST
</TEXT>
