<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8593 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0985 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-TECH-COLUMN-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TECHNOLOGY: `PUSH' TECHNOLOGY THAT MAKES THE INTERNET COME TO YOU &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   I have seen the future. It may work but it is very pushy.
<p>
   Using catchers, whackers, finders, savers and casters  &MD;  software
that has a slightly different attitude from passively casual
browsers  &MD;  a nascent industry is trying to create a new model for
the use of the Internet, one that will have almost nothing to do
with hyperlinks, cyberspace or the electronic frontier. The goal is
to make the Internet come to you, not the other way around.
<p>
   This is being called ``push'' technology and is one of the
hottest areas of Internet development. Microsoft and Netscape are
planning to incorporate it into future software releases. Apple
plans to use it to automatically update software.
<p>
   And right now, custom-designed news reports are being pushed
into PCs, most famously via Pointcast with 1.7 million users of its
free software (http://www.pointcast.com) automatically getting
reports from CNN, Wired and other publications.
<p>
   There are even commercial programs like WebEx and WebWhacker
that offer virtually a utopian promise: The software bears the
burden of waiting on line; sites are downloaded for quick viewing,
free of crashes and pauses. Off-line dipping replaces on-line
surfing.
<p>
   The startling thing about the interest in this technology are
the built-in contradictions. It promises freedom from the very
aspects of the Internet that have been so highly praised  &MD;  the
spur-of-the-moment discoveries, the libertarian freedom from
predetermined form and content. Each advantage of the Net has
become a disadvantage when seen through the prism of push.
<p>
   During the usual ``pull'' usage of the Net, we grope about,
grasping sites with laborious dedication. The idea behind push
technology is that the viewer becomes more passive; the material is
thrust out of cyberspace, following a custom-built series of
requests. It is more like home delivery than browsing, more like TV
than PC.
<p>
   Push technology is more appealing for making money on the
Internet. Sites are guaranteed more visitors, which means that they
can offer advertisers more attractive audiences. Advertisers'
banners and images are inserted on the home PC, and may have
greater impact because they are part of requested material.
<p>
   Gradually there may come to be a kind of junk mail that will
fill Web browsers along with e-mail boxes. If the Web is to have
any economic future, it may be founded on the basis of pushing
rather than pulling.
<p>
   The promise of push, the value it adds, is its delivery of
organized, edited information  &MD;  information that has been
requested, things often hard to come by on the Net. And a wide
variety of experiments testing how much such a service should be
employed are in progress.
<p>
   The New Century Network (http://www.newcentury.net) calls itself
``the best of America's newspapers'' and includes, in rather
haphazard form, an anthology of news and information. (New Century
is partly owned by New York Times Co.)
<p>
   New Century's contents are designed by its editors and delivered
wholesale. A custom-designed result can be created on the Newspage
site (http://www.newspage.com), where an individual profile will
create a ``daily custom newspaper,'' compiling sources ranging from
industry trade magazines to wire services.
<p>
   Pointcast is almost completely a matter of push. Theoretically
it is like having a personalized ticker tape and news service: all
news, all the time, all over the PC.
<p>
   Imitators have been spawned, like Intermind Communicator
(http://www.intermind.com). One new pushmeister, Marimba
(http://www.marimba.com), promises to do for software updates what
Pointcast has done for news (Apple will be using its technology for
self-updating software).
<p>
   Push technology may ultimately be pushing the Net into a form of
computer radio, and indeed, one of the most conveniently pushy
objects I have recently tried has been the $149 Newscatcher from
Global Village Communication, which regularly delivers news
headlines and information to the PC via a radio network; its main
problem is the brevity of the information.
<p>
   Newscatcher was so appealing, though, partly because it managed
to avoid many of the problems of push technology in its infancy:
awkwardness, messiness, slowness. Automatic downloads can cause
system crashes, eat up memory, clutter the PC with as much junk as
accumulated magazines waiting to be read.
<p>
   It was great to be able to read the lead news articles in The
Boston Globe and The Los Angeles Times courtesy of Pointcast, but
downloads were more time-consuming than just leaping to those
newspapers' Web sites via the traditional, now crusty browsers.
<p>
   Not even commercial packages were completely satisfying. This
kind of software requires a user with very specific desires, with a
clear notion of which sites and which information need to be
regularly accumulated. But sometimes that can only be discovered
through browsing.
<p>
   Ultimately, the best form of push technology may be a sort that
makes the Net almost irrelevant except as a vast sea to be explored
at will by smart agents that fish at our request.
<p>
   The ultimate push will be the creation of custom-built channels,
an individualized on-line service that is built when a user is off
line. The numbers of channels is potentially infinite, with each
one bearing the stamp of the user's desires.
<p>
   By the time that happens, the Internet will have evolved into a
utility more than a technological novelty, a convenience rather
than a mode of consciousness. And as we channel-surf through these
programs, delivered for our entertainment and enlightenment, push
will have really come to pull.
<p>
NYT-01-19-97 1826EST
</TEXT>
