<SLUG> BC-EURO-DISNEY-UPDATE4-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0545 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EURO-DISNEY-UPDATE4-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EURO DISNEY 1ST-QTR SALES RISE 12.7%, SHARES JUMP (UPDATE4) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jacqueline Simmons and Raymond Frenken &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates with share price gains in the sixth paragraph; analyst
quote in the fifth paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Paris, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Euro Disney SCA, operator of the
Disneyland Paris theme park, said first-quarter sales jumped 12.7
percent as attendance rose and visitors spent more money at its
hotels and attractions.
<p>
   Europe's largest theme park operator, whose amusements include
the Space Mountain roller coaster, said sales rose to 1.13 billion
francs ($205 million) in the three months ended Dec. 31 from 1.01
billion in the year-earlier period.
<p>
   Operating revenue from the park and related hotels rose 11.4
percent to 1.12 billion francs.
<p>
   Analysts said sales were better than expected, suggesting the
company is making strides in attracting more visitors and
generating higher revenue as it faces rising interest costs and
fees in the years ahead.
<p>
   ``A sales increase of that balance was above my expectations,''
said Jeff Summers, analyst at Klesch &AMP; Co. in London. ``That
suggests they are on line for park attendance of between 12.5
million and 13 million this year, which means they should be able
to offset increased finance charges that kick in this year.''
Attendance last year was 11.7 million.
<p>
   Shares rose 6.3 percent, or 0.75 franc, to 11.1 francs. Euro
Disney was the second-most active stock in Paris with 2.2 million
shares traded compared with a daily average of 406,739 shares in
the past six months.
<p>
   Some analysts remained skeptical, saying revenue must grow
substantially in the years ahead as interest costs and fees
gradually rise.
<p>
   ``Sales can go up but we don't know if they're making any
profit,'' said Nigel Reed, an analyst at Paribas Capital Markets in
London, who said the results were 5 percent above his estimate.
``We don't know the costs. They could have spent 100 million francs
on marketing and had a huge loss.''
<p>
   Euro Disney didn't release profit figures and declined to
disclose the number of park visitors or what they spent in the
period. It usually reports such figures in half-year statements.
<p>
   The company, 39.2 percent owned by Walt Disney Co. of the U.S.,
faces rising interest payments on its 15.1 billion francs in debt
in fiscal 1997 under a 1994 debt accord that helped avert a
bankruptcy. It also must pay royalty and management fees in 1998 to
Walt Disney.
<p>
   The company said lease and financial charges are set to rise by
200 million francs in 1997 from 103 million francs in fiscal 1996.
It said it won't raise prices this year, even though that would
have a ``temporary detrimental impact on margins.''
<p>
   ``This is a satisfying performance demonstrating our ability to
better exploit the potential of our low season,'' said Philippe
Bourguignon, chairman and chief executive. ``However, 1997 remains
a challenging year with no price increases and higher financial
charges.''
<p>
   Euro Disney said in November net income jumped 77 percent in its
fiscal year ended Sept. 30 to 202 million francs as more people
visited Disneyland Paris and stayed in its hotels.
</TEXT>
