<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8595 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CONGRESS-INTERNET </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0799 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-CONGRESS-INTERNET-ECON-ART-2TAKES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CONGRESSMEN, SENATORS STRIVE TO PROMOTE TECHNOLOGY IN AMERICA'S &LR; 
RURAL AREAS &QL; 
(ART ADV: Photos of Sen. Conrad Burns and Rep. Byron Dorgan are
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) &QL; 
 &UR; By DAN CARNEY &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Sen. Conrad Burns, a Montana Republican, does not have the
polish or erudition of most senators. He has no college degree, no
expensive suits, and few pretensions. On most days when the Senate
is in session, he can be found telling stories about his ranching
and farming constituents, people he once described as ``awful good
folks.''
<p>
   His legislative interests include Western land policies, farm
price supports  &MD;  and federal policy on encryption software. Like
many of his colleagues who represent rural areas, Burns maintains a
keen interest in technology and telecommunications issues.
<p>
   The interest of legislators like Burns  &MD;  not to mention two
House members from the Appalachian part of Virginia, Robert
Goodlatte, a Republican, Rick Boucher, a Democrat; Sens. Patrick
Leahy, R-Vt.; Byron Dorgan, D-N.D.; Olympia Snowe, R-Maine; and
John D. Rockefeller IV, D-W.V.  &MD;  is based largely on the theory
that the information revolution is the best hope for economic
development of their remote districts.
<p>
   Their theory is that people and whole companies will migrate to
places with lower labor costs and a higher quality of life once
they are freed of the need to live and work in close proximity to
customers and fellow employees.
<p>
   ``Rural America will gain enormously from advances in
telecommunications,'' Boucher argues. ``We have a low-cost business
environment, an excellent work force, a superb quality of life.
What we're lacking is telecommunications services.''
<p>
   With a determination that evokes earlier decades of the 20th
century, when rural legislators pushed to get electricity and
telephone service to their districts, the lawmakers are active on
two technological fronts. The first is local telecommunications
issues, particularly making sure high-speed transmission lines come
to small towns. These lawmakers helped write ``universal service''
language into the 1996 telecommunications bill; some have gone even
further.
<p>
   Boucher, for instance, helped four towns in his district with
populations of less than 10,000 bypass the local phone company and
install their own fiber optic networks, which can handle far
greater amounts of information than traditional copper telephone
wires.
<p>
   On the other front, they are devising broad operating principles
for the Internet. These include such things as a new copyright law
that will allow publishers, film makers, songwriters, and others to
sell their products on the Internet without fear they will be
illegally copied and circulated. These issues also include
encryption policies that let companies and individuals protect
confidential communications from hackers or competitors.
<p>
   Rural legislators would like to see the Internet become a medium
where employer, employee, producer, and consumer can interact
efficiently and securely. When that happens, they believe, physical
proximity will be less important to commerce and employment and
more people will move to small towns.
<p>
   To this end, Goodlatte and Boucher are trying to write a new
copyright law that will function in a medium in which copying is
extremely easy. On a parallel track, the 65-nation World
Intellectual Property Organization approved two copyright treaties
in December that will be up for ratification in the Senate this
year. The issue of copyright law and digital technologies is
complex, and understood by only a few members of Congress  &MD;  many of
them representing rural areas.
<p>
   Encryption is critical to rural lawmakers because it is used to
encode and decode electronic communications. Software producers
believe encryption programs will be as fundamental to security in
the information age as the lock and key are now.
<p>
   The issue pits business groups and self-described
cyberlibertarians against federal law enforcement and security
agencies, which fear their ability to conduct surveillance will be
greatly curtailed. The rural lawmakers come down on the side of
business and the libertarians. Burns, Leahy, and Goodlatte all have
bills to ease restrictions on the use of encryption programs.
<p>
   Neither of these issues has come to a vote. They are complicated
and have not been give priority by the Republican leadership in
either house. But they both could see some action this year. For
now, their biggest champions are rural lawmakers.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (MORE)
<p>
   nn
<p>
NYT-01-19-97 1817EST
