<DOCID> nyt970122.0049 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8596 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CONGRESS-INTERNET </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0713 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-CONGRESS-INTERNET-ECON-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: rural lawmakers. &LR; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   All of this interest in the Internet and technology raises the
question: are these lawmakers onto something or is this just the
latest economic development fad that will go the way of business
incubators and lavish tax concessions for foreign auto plants?
<p>
   While the answer is still unclear, there is some evidence this
may be more than a fad. After decades of almost unbroken decline,
rural America has reached parity with metropolitan America in
population growth. The average growth rate in rural counties
started approaching that of metropolitan counties in the early
1990s and caught up in 1995, according to an Agriculture Department
demographer, Calvin Beale.
<p>
   And while communications technology is not solely responsible
for this reversal of fortune, it certainly has played a role.
William Beyers, a professor of geography at the University of
Washington has studied a number of economically growing rural
counties and found them full of independent consultants,
contractors, brokers, and other types of professionals that use
modern telecommunications (along with some leg work) to serve
customers around the country and around the world.
<p>
   ``It's not just the Internet, though that gets all the hype,''
Beyers said. ``It's good old-fashioned file transfer and even
telephones.'' File transfer refers to a direct link from one
computer to another without the Internet.
<p>
   In one of his studies, he found that 40 percent of the new
companies in rural areas were primarily serving customers outside
of their regions.
<p>
   Many of them are small professional companies, sometimes just a
single person, that are commonly called lone eagles. They might be
a graphic arts studio in New Mexico that does most of its business
in Texas, or a stockbroker who has fled Los Angeles for the more
pristine environment of Washington state. Though not primarily
telecommunications companies, they rely on Internet technology to
gather information and talk with customers.
<p>
   In addition to these tiny companies, some major corporations
have made telecommunications-related shifts that have benefited a
few communities. Availing themselves of the lower labor costs,
banks, credit card companies, airlines, telephone companies, and a
host of other businesses have put big switchboard operations and
information centers in small towns. A call to directory assistance
in the Washington, D.C., area, for instance, is routed to a bank of
operators in Boucher's district in the southwest corner of
Virginia.
<p>
   But there is still no guarantee that rural America will benefit
any more from the approaching technological era than from previous
ones.
<p>
   ``It's not a silver bullet, but it's not a fad either,'' said
Bob Rowe, public service commissioner of Montana. Rowe said that
rural areas could benefit from the new technologies, but only if
people formed local networks and learned how to use them to their
own benefit.
<p>
   In this sense, information is no different from other
technologies. Those who learn how to exploit it most effectively
will prosper.
<p>
   Some critics point out that rural America already has an
up-to-date system capable of carrying vast amounts of information
around the world. It's called a telephone, and it did not stop the
exodus out of small towns this century.
<p>
   Others argue that while changes in telecommunications may hurt
big American cities, there is no guarantee that the beneficiaries
of this will be small American towns.
<p>
   ``There's no reason it stops in Fargo, N.D., or wherever,'' said
Andrew Blau of the telecommunications-oriented Benton Foundation.
``Maybe it goes on to Malaysia or Mexico. It goes right past our
borders, goes over our fence into the Southern Hemisphere.''
<p>
   But none of this damps the enthusiasm of those members of
Congress from rural areas who have latched onto the issue. The
emerging information age, Burns believes, will make his state far
less remote. ``We can't move Montana any closer to Denver or
Seattle or Minneapolis, nor do we want to,'' he said.
<p>
   ``This is our window, our door. It is our access to the world.''
<p>
NYT-01-19-97 1817EST
</TEXT>
