<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=ttx-z> A8597 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-FBC-ONLINE-TEX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1226 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-FBC-ONLINE-TEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; X'S, O'S AND E'S: RECRUITING ENTERS COMPUTER AGE OF E-MAILS,
INTERNET &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By CLARENCE E. HILL Jr. &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   In the crystal ball of Grapevine (Texas) High School football
coach Mike Sneed, the constant barrage of phone calls from college
recruiters dies down.
<p>
   His desktop no longer is filled with dozens upon dozens of
mailings from college recruiters. No more his hasty trips to
overnight delivery outlets to send off tapes for last-minute player
evaluations.
<p>
   Sneed is not a computer expert. He has never surfed the World
Wide Web or even sent electronic mail.
<p>
   But Sneed knows the future when he sees it. He believes that the
possibilities presented by the recruitment of blue chips via
microchips are endless.
<p>
   ``It would make things a whole lot easier,'' said Sneed, who
like most high school head coaches finds himself saddled with the
responsibilities of supplying footage of prospective recruits on
conventional videotapes.
<p>
   ``Maybe one day all they would have to do is punch up a kid on
the computer to view him in action. It would also save recruiters
time and cut down on travel costs. If there is a kid they are
marginally interested in, they can look him up on the computer. It
might save them a trip.''
<p>
   Today, Sneed's computer world is just a dream. College
recruiters still do their jobs the old-fashioned way  &MD;  featuring
long drives down dusty highways, stopping from town to town in
hopes of finding the next Heisman Trophy winner.
<p>
   But, considering that high schools and nearly every university
have access to the Internet, and that it is estimated that 15
percent of U.S. households use an online service, the vision of
online recruiting comes closer and closer to reality with every
passing day.
<p>
   Whether it's an athlete trading e-mails with coaches, or
recruiting experts holding ``chat'' sessions with fans, or boosters
setting up home pages to offer the latest information on their
respective schools, the computer and the array of services
available on the Internet are beginning to take recruiting into the
next millennium.
<p>
   ``This `is' the computer age,'' TCU coach Pat Sullivan said.
``With the Internet and the way it is, it's the wave of the future.
More and more kids are having access to computers. We don't use it
(for recruiting purposes). But it's something we are looking into
for the near future.''
<p>
   And for those who scoff at the notion of big-time recruits
having access to a computer to correspond with coaches, Texas A&AMP;M
coach R.C. Slocum has evidence to the contrary.
<p>
   ``There have been some big ones (recruits with whom he has
traded e-mails),'' said Slocum, who has communicated with potential
recruits using the Internet for several years now. ``Kids have
classes at school and get to fooling around. One kid got into the
Texas A&AMP;M home page and sent me one just to see if I would respond.
I did and we've corresponded several times. It's a big tool. I see
a tremendous escalation of this.''
<p>
   The online recruiting phenomenon has not yet engulfed the
majority of college football recruiters. Many, says Texas Tech
director of football operations Jack Tayrien, don't have the time
or have yet to become computer savvy.
<p>
   The use of computers to reach out and touch recruits, however,
has such future implications that online recruiting has been the
subject of legislation at the past two NCAA conventions.
<p>
   Computer-generated e-mail is regarded the same as mail sent
through the U.S. Postal Service. That means there is no limit to
how many times or when a school or coach can contact an athlete.
<p>
   ``You are limited right now by the number of kids that do use
it,'' TCU director of football operations Rick Villarreal said.
``But more and more have access. Right now e-mail is treated as a
letter, but it's better because you can have an immediate response.
And now when you can't call, you can e-mail.''
<p>
   Villarreal said ``schools that can hook into the Internet and
train coaches to use the computer have a definite advantage.''
<p>
   Texas A&AMP;M director of football operations Tim Cassidy, who said
all the Aggies coaches have their e-mail address on their business
cards, agrees.
<p>
   ``It's a great tool,'' Cassidy said. ``If a coach gets beeped
(e-mailed) from a prospect, he can respond immediately. We are
fortunate to have a football coach that's into computers. For guys
like R.C. that are willing to adapt, its a great tool.''
<p>
   While communicating via the Internet is still in its infancy as
far as coaches and recruits are concerned, it's fast becoming a way
of life for recruiting experts, fans and boosters, who use the
Internet to discover, trade and disseminate information about
recruits and schools.
<p>
   A scan through the National Recruiting Center, one of many sites
on the Internet set up specifically for recruiting information,
offers a glimpse of the mania.
<p>
   In the past three months, there have been roughly 59,429 hits
(the term for an Internet visit) on the NRC site. Surfers have
viewed home pages set up by newspapers, conferences (including the
Big 12 and Southeastern conferences), universities and recruiting
services like David Garvin's Heartland Recruiting and The Ultimate
Southern California High School Football Recruiting Site.
<p>
   Several companies, whose purpose is find scholarships for the
marginal athlete, also have home pages, where coaches can search
for players by sport, by position and by size and also view actual
game footage.
<p>
   Mostly, however, the NRC site is a haven for home pages set up
by fans, including Arlene's Husker Home Page, Husker Football
Freak's Home Page, Willie Wonka's Sooner Home Page, the Unofficial
Texas A&AMP;M Recruiting Page and Louisiana State's Recruiting and
Rumor Mill Home Page.
<p>
   The LSU page  &MD;  which is set up by Tigers fan Mike Scarborough
and features daily recruiting updates, commitments and the latest
gossip about prospective LSU recruits  &MD;  has had more than 7,200
hits in the past week alone.
<p>
   Bobby Burton of National Recruiting Advisor, whose 4-year-old
Austin, Texas-based recruiting news service went online this year
for the first time, said there is no doubt that the online
recruiting market is currently a fan-driven market.
<p>
   ``Last year, we were hearing what was going on the Internet and
were dumbfounded,'' Burton said. ``People were on there talking
about what we said. So decided to get into it. But it's definitely
more of fan thing than a player/coach thing. I got on there to do a
chat session and there were 108 people in the chatroom. It's
unbelievable.''
<p>
   Burton warns, however, that the fans' involvement has also
created concerns regarding the validity of information found on the
Internet. Tayrien agrees. He said his office has had to refute
information gathered on the Internet by boosters on several
occasions.
<p>
   The concerns aside, all involved believe the computer is
developing as a permanent tool in recruiting.
<p>
   Today, it's e-mail correspondence and fan home pages. Tomorrow,
it could be detailed player evaluations using digital photo imagery
and advanced scouting. Beyond that, no one knows what the future
holds for online recruiting, but the possibilities are seemingly as
wide as the imagination.
</TEXT>
