<SLUG> BC-CPT-MALAYSIA-COMPUTE- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0647 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-MALAYSIA-COMPUTE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MALAYSIA WOOS U.S. COMPUTER FIRMS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN MARKOFF &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif.  &MD;  Malaysia's prime minister, Mahathir
Mohamad, made a pilgrimage to Silicon Valley last week, calling on
the area's companies to join in an ambitious effort to build a
replica of the region in his nation.
<p>
   Speaking here before a group of Silicon Valley executives,
Mahathir sketched out a vision of a 25-year plan to build a
``multimedia supercorridor'' that would stretch south from Kuala
Lumpur, the capital, to the city's new international airport, which
is under construction.
<p>
   The 9-mile-by-30-mile area, which would include two new cities
and a computer network designed to exceed those in the world's most
advanced technology centers, would be created in part with generous
tax and financial incentives by which the Malaysians are hoping to
attract hundreds of corporations to build research and development
as well as manufacturing operations.
<p>
   ``Fantastic changes are taking place which make what was
impossible in the old economy of the Industrial Age suddenly
possible in the new world of the Information Age,'' Mahathir said.
<p>
   Mahathir met on Wednesday with William Gates, chairman of the
Microsoft Corp., and on Thursday with a group of Silicon Valley
leaders including Jim Barksdale, president of the Netscape
Communications Corp.; Larry Ellison, chairman of the Oracle Corp.;
Scott McNealy, chairman of Sun Microsystems Inc., and Lew Platt,
chairman of the Hewlett-Packard Co.
<p>
   A number of industry leaders have agreed to serve on an advisory
group for the Malaysian project, and at least one of the companies,
Sun Microsystems, has already agreed to locate a software
development group in the region.
<p>
   While American companies for years have been making
high-technology products in Asia for the United States market,
Silicon Valley executives are growing more interested in
opportunities to sell in the region, where economies are growing
more rapidly than in other parts of the world. To develop products
for these markets, many executives believe that the companies need
to base development staffs closer to them.
<p>
   Malaysia's plan is an effort to move beyond manufacturing to
high-technology development, and the prime minister pledged that in
addition to the financial incentives the project holds out, his
government was in the process of passing laws that would be
attractive to high-technology companies. He said these would
include new legal structures to accommodate electronic commerce,
intellectual property protection and a promise not to censor the
Internet.
<p>
   Several Silicon Valley leaders said they believed that in the
economic wars of the future, regions like the planned Malaysian
corridor would provide America with some of its fiercest
competition.
<p>
   ``This will be the new challenge,'' said John Morgridge,
chairman of Cisco Systems, a computer networking firm based in San
Jose, Calif. ``It won't be missiles that they are sending over
here.''
<p>
   This competition could even extend to sensitive issues like
computer encryption technology. In response to a reporter's
question, Mahathir said that because the United States, for
security reasons, had placed strict export controls on
data-scrambling technology it would be necessary for his country to
develop similar hardware and software independently.
<p>
   The government plans to begin construction on the two cities
before the end of the century, according to the prime minister. One
is to be the new seat of the government, and it is expected to have
a population of 250,000. The second city, to be named Cyberjava, is
to be an education and research and development center, and it is
projected to have 100,000 residents.
<p>
NYT-01-19-97 2026EST
</TEXT>
