<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8600 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-FUN-SCI- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0709 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-COMPUTER-FUN-SCI-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE LATEST FAILURE TO COMMUNICATE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By L.R. SHANNON &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Hyperterminal is the anemic communications program that comes
with Windows 95 and Windows NT 4.0. It is an improvement over
Terminal, the Windows 3.1 ``applet,'' in that it handles more file
settings and terminal emulations, but it is strictly text-based in
a graphical world. If your computer came with a modem,
Hyperterminal is a way to dip into on-line communications without
spending extra money at the outset, but it will not do for long.
<p>
   Hyperterminal was produced by Hilgraeve, a company in Monroe,
Mich., which has now introduced an upgrade, Hyperaccess, a
full-featured communications program, though still text-based,
along the lines of Procomm Plus. It is, Hilgraeve says, a
completely rewritten 32-bit program taking full advantage of
Windows 95 features like drag and drop; its phone book looks like
Windows Explorer, it works along with Internet Explorer or Netscape
Navigator, and it has the familiar menu bar and row of icons. So
far, so good.
<p>
   I installed Hyperaccess from a CD-ROM in a few minutes (it also
comes on diskettes) without fuss and, as the company suggests,
called its own bulletin board. That way, you can register on line,
as well as download software and look at product information. A
couple of mouse clicks later, I heard: ``We're sorry. Your call
cannot be completed as dialed ...'' I tried again. Same result.
Then I looked at the Confirm Phone Numbers window that appears when
you try to make a connection. The number for the long-distance call
was displayed not as 1 (313) 243-5915 but as 1 1 (313) 243-5915.
<p>
   Well, there must be a way to change the number. A box labeled
``modify'' appeared next to the number. The area code and the phone
number in the next box were correct, but the number in the ``will
dial as'' section had the erroneous double 1's. A lot of tabs were
attached  &MD;  description, ASCII sending and receiving, file transfer,
file usage, preferences, runtime values, colors, terminal emulator
 &MD;  that did not look helpful.
<p>
   I went back to the initial window. Where in the eight menus was
the place to add a new number. Properties? Nope. Transfer? Uh-uh.
Window? Naah. File, then New, of course. I made a new entry,
selected an icon for it and named it Try1, entering the company's
number carefully. But there was the extra 1. I made Try2, entering
this newspaper's 800 number. The extra 1 appeared; I tried to call
anyway. ``We're sorry. Your call ...'' Try3 was my own other line,
not long distance, and the call was successful.
<p>
   It was last resort time: the manual. I had skimmed Chapter 2,
with the instructions for installing the program and making the
first call. This time I read it carefully, without edification.
Chapter 3? That started with ``drag and drop,'' a neat feature, as
described, but not much use if I can call only within my own area
code.
<p>
   After several unsuccessful checks of the table of contents, I
dialed the phone number that Hilgraeve suggests for those who
``need answers quickly, or simply prefer talking to humans.'' It
was a Saturday, and nobody was home, though the recorded voice was
definitely a human's.
<p>
   I tried the Web site www.hilgraeve.com without finding any
information. I filled out a long form and left a message explaining
my problem. Five days later, an E-mail answer arrived: ``You need
to go into the dialing properties of the session and make sure that
you have the settings correct. These are the settings that are
being accessed to make the connection. The dialing properties are
not part of our program, but we access them as part of the dialing
procedures.''
<p>
   I went into the dialing properties box, which I had visited
before, and checked the settings, which looked fine. Then
inspiration hit. I typed the entire phone number, 1 313 243-5915,
into the section for local numbers, as if it were not a toll call.
It was a kludge, as we say, but it worked.
<p>
   Hyperaccess for Windows 95 and NT is $129 and can be ordered
from Hilgraeve by calling (800) 826-2760; it should also be widely
available.
<p>
