<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8601 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-S </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0969 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-SCI-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; APPLIANCE OR COMPUTER? YOU MAKE THE CALL! &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By STEPHEN MANES &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The Winter Consumer Electronics Show is always a glimpse of
things to come, but the 1997 edition this month in Las Vegas seemed
more like a masquerade ball. Computers dressed like television
sets, TV sets donned Web browsers, phones were accessorized with
screens and keyboards for sending e-mail, and intimate connections
with mysterious outsiders were the norm. In the so-called digital
convergence, do appliances or computers have more fun? Only your
programmer knows for sure.
<p>
   Screen phones were everywhere. Depending on the screen, the
keyboard and the internal electronics, they can display everything
from Caller ID to specialized information services, e-mail and even
the World Wide Web. Like many other items on display, most are not
quite ready for public consumption but should be available soon.
<p>
   Some include surprises. A touch of the redial button on a phone
in the press room instantly displayed the last eight numbers dialed
by unsuspecting journalists, along with credit card information
that would have been dynamite in less scrupulous hands.
<p>
   After using my own phone card, the only way I could purge the
information was to dial eight different local numbers before
relinquishing the handset. Look for a telephone to be named a
co-conspirator in a theft-of-services case someday.
<p>
   Phones that can send users' images were not in abundance,
perhaps because cheap systems are widely available for PCs. But 8x8
Inc., a recently renamed company specializing until now in chips,
demonstrated its first consumer product, the ViaTV System, a box
that promises to turn a TV set and standard phone line into a
picturephone.
<p>
   The pre-release demonstration did not bely the company's
admission in its recent initial public offering filings that given
the data speed of plain telephone lines, ``the human eye can detect
degradation of video quality.''
<p>
   At least the unit should be easy to install, which is more than
you can say about computer-based products. It should work with the
many products that adhere to the new videoconferencing standard
called H.324. But will Grandma and Grandpa pay $500 per box plus
phone tolls to see Junior babble in fuzzy, jerky glory?
<p>
   TV screens can double as decent Web terminals, as the estimable
WebTV set-top boxes from Sony and Philips Magnavox have shown. Now
many other big-name companies will offer competing systems,
including some built into TV sets. Like WebTV, some new systems
will tie customers to a single Internet service provider; others
will allow more freedom of choice, but connecting printers and
upgrading modems may remain problematic.
<p>
   Not taking this threat lightly, computers will be designed to
replace and even outdo mere TV sets. The Microsoft Corp. and dozens
of corporate partners announced plans for Entertainment PC 97
products with screens and a special interface big enough to be
watched at living-room distances.
<p>
   Along with receiving standard TV programming, the machines will
be able to decode and display special information broadcast in
tandem with some shows. The Cajun chef may invite you to download
his recipe for alligator andouille; the TV fisherman might provide
printable diagrams to help tell a sockeye salmon from a chinook.
<p>
   These machines should also be able to receive other data sent in
new ways. Special channels will broadcast information like stock
quotes, newspapers and popular web sites 24 hours a day; the
slumbering machine will awaken to grab whatever you have
specifically requested. Tucked away on your hard drive, even
bandwidth hogs like video clips should be quickly accessible.
DirecTV Inc. will offer bandwith capable of broadcasting up to 30
megabits (a lot) per second to users who have the company's
satellite dishes; cable customers may get data-only channels that
can deliver roughly a third of that (still a lot). The broadcasts
are, of course, one-way; e-Mail and the rest of the Web will be
available through conventional dial-up services.
<p>
   Machines like this are not expected before Christmas, but dates
do have a way of slipping. Last year's most eagerly awaited holiday
promise, the high-capacity, high-quality video and data disk system
that goes by the name of DVD, was sidetracked by copy-protection
worries and other thorny problems. DVD players for television sets
are already available in Japan and scheduled to begin appearing
here within the next two months at prices ranging from $500 to
$1,000.
<p>
   Computers with built-in DVD-ROM drives should show up by May.
Programming for them, particularly computer software, may be in
short supply for a while, and early DVD-ROM units may be
incompatible with certain current and future formats.
<p>
   Digital still cameras that link directly to computers continue
to improve, but no one would begin to confuse the picture quality
of a $500 or even $1,000 model with what you get from the cheapest
point-and-shoot film cameras. But tiny digital video cameras now
deliver stunning video quality that can be transferred with
relative ease to computer-based editing systems and can double in a
pinch to produce still photos. The over-$2,000 price of these
attractive units can be expected to drop over time.
<p>
   Weary and footsore, I tried the Great Escape, a Shiatsu massage
chair for which, according to the brochure, ``Panasonic used modern
electronic technology to analyze the finger movement of
professional masseurs in order to develop a way to duplicate it.''
Its aggressive pummeling did not come with a screen or a data
connection, but I bet next year's model will.
<p>
NYT-01-20-97 1509EST
</TEXT>
