<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=kan-z> A8602 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ENCYCLOPEDIA-COMP </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0585 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-ENCYCLOPEDIA-COMPUTER-2ndTAKE-KAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR; 
   (Kansas City, Mo.: he estimates that he sold 3,900 sets of
books.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   He is sad that Britannica's personal link with its customers
through its salespeople has been severed.
<p>
   ``We never dreamed in our 200-year history that the home field
sales force would be eliminated,'' said Tamburello, who retired in
1994. ``When they shut it down, I was in total shock.''
<p>
   Ever a company man, however, Tamburello praises Britannica's new
products.
<p>
   ``They have the greatest CD-ROM the good Lord has ever put on
this earth,'' he said. Catching himself, he adds, ``I never thought
I would say that.''
<p>
   Tamburello is already nostalgic for a simpler age, when families
spread their volumes of Britannicas before the fireplace and
swapped arcane facts.
<p>
   ``You can't cuddle up with a computer,'' Tamburello said.
<p>
   But the question remains, can you learn more from a computer?
<p>
   Few want to sit and see a novel scroll by on a luminous computer
screen.
<p>
   But Walter said computers are ideal for quickly searching
through encyclopedias.
<p>
   University librarians agree, and they now are among Britannica's
top customers. Already, 3 million students attend colleges that
have Britannica available electronically.
<p>
   The electronic encyclopedias are a powerful educational tool.
<p>
   Say a student is asked to write a paper on why the sky is blue.
In a small window on his computer, the student types the question.
<p>
   Among the articles offered up by Britannica is one on John
Tyndall, the scientist who first explained the color of the sky.
<p>
   Using a traditional print encyclopedia, the student would not be
automatically directed to Tyndall.
<p>
   The on-line version of Britannica directs readers to sites on
the Internet as well.
<p>
   Gary Sampson, systems librarian at Portland State University in
Oregon, said, ``Britannica has hundreds of people working all the
time to create Internet links.
<p>
   ``The computer is so fast it allows you to scan enormous amounts
of material. Previously, you had to go through `author, title,
subject.' Now, it's a lot easier.''
<p>
   Still, there are concerns.
<p>
   Jim Neeley, electronic information librarian at the University
of Kansas, said navigating Britannica's compact disc is not easy.
<p>
   ``Information on any one topic is scattered sometimes under a
bewildering number of entries.''
<p>
   The electronic service may be easier to use than the CD but it
is costly. The electronic Britannica will cost KU about $14,000 a
year based on the school's enrollment, Neeley said.
<p>
   ``There is no question that students much prefer electronic
resources to print resources,'' Neeley said. ``For some period, we
have been having increasing difficulty getting people to look at
printed resources.''
<p>
   Goulka said Britannica is exploring new technology that would
allow a 17-fold increase on a disc's data storage by stacking
layers of information.
<p>
   Britannica is betting that computer users will soon grow
frustrated with navigating the ever-expanding Internet.
<p>
   Searching a compact disc is faster and more precise, Goulka
said.
<p>
   But in the long-run, Britannica believes the main avenue of
delivering information to users will be on-line, he said.
<p>
   ``For those of us in the content business ... this is a wondrous
opportunity to redefine information,'' said Goulka.
<p>
NYT-01-20-97 1858EST
</TEXT>
