<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0055 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=kan-z> A8603 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ENCYCLOPEDIA-COMP </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0839 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-ENCYCLOPEDIA-COMPUTER-TWOTAKES-KAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE ENCYCLOPAEDIA BRITANNICA ADAPTS TO THE COMPUTER AGE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MARTIN ROSENBERG &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1996 Kansas City Star &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Embedded in millions of adults' memories is
the ``crack'' heard when opening a seldom-used Encyclopaedia
Britannica volume.
<p>
   We remember the heft of the tome, the feel of the pages rippling
through our fingers. We hunted obscure entries  &MD;  from ``Androcles''
to ``Zanzibar.''
<p>
   But the Encyclopaedia Britannica as we knew it is no more.
<p>
   Gone, too, is the traveling salesman who peddled its rich
offerings.
<p>
   Instead, the 32-volume citadel of Western knowledge, launched by
a pair of Scots in 1768, is quietly fading before the onslaught of
computer technology.
<p>
   It, like many of its encyclopedia competitors, is being reborn
(look up ``phoenix'') on compact disks and on the Internet.
<p>
   James E. Goulka, Britannica's chief operating officer, freely
admits that Britannica was slow to adapt to the new age. As a
result, it watched its revenues slip by more than one-third from
$658 million in 1991 to $423 million in 1995.
<p>
   A Swiss investor, Jacob Safra, bought Britannica a year ago and
is pushing its rebound.
<p>
   ``We were asleep at the switch when computers entered the market
beginning in the 1990s,'' Goulka said. ``At times I think of
ourselves as the world's largest monastery when Gutenberg showed up
with type.'' Before Johannes Gutenberg invented type in the 15th
century, most books were handwritten in monasteries.
<p>
   This year, Britannica expects 60 percent of its revenues will
come from sales of compact disc and an on-line version of the
encyclopedia. That is remarkable, considering that Chicago-based
Britannica did not get into the CD and on-line business until 1994.
<p>
   Britannica's far-flung sales force of 500 independent agents was
quietly dismantled last spring.
<p>
   Print volumes are still for sale  &MD;  at a bargain $995 per set,
down from $1,500 just a few years ago.
<p>
   But Britannica executives are convinced that the company's
products will increasingly pop up on computers, not bookshelves.
<p>
   Britannica CDs, which cost $299, are about the thickness of a
credit card and smaller than a coffee saucer. They run on
multimedia computers that have flooded the consumer market.
<p>
   Other companies have been faster to develop CD versions of their
encyclopedias. Microsoft's Encarta, Grolier's Interactive and
Compton's Interactive CD encyclopedias have been in the market for
several years and are far cheaper than Britannica. In fact, they
often are loaded into new computers along with other ``free''
software as an added incentive to buyers.
<p>
   But Britannica's CD is much more extensive, replicating the 44
million words contained in its print volumes. (It also is not as
visually appealing as competitors' CDs, which are full of
animations and video clips.)
<p>
   Furthermore, Britannica remains unique in that it presents
essays by leading authorities. Past contributors have included
Albert Einstein, Marie Curie and Sigmund Freud.
<p>
   ``In terms of the depth of the essays, they (Britannica)
absolutely have more than the others,'' said Mark Walter, editor of
the Seybold Report on Internet Publishing.
<p>
   Britannica is also available on-line for $150 a year or $14.95 a
month. Users can tap into the on-line service with a computer,
modem and Internet access provider that connects their computer to
the Internet over phone lines. The Internet address:
{http://www.eb.com}.
<p>
   The advantage of the on-line service is that it is always being
updated, and it contains electronic links to 5,000 other sites on
the Internet, the vast worldwide network of computers.
<p>
   ``By increasing access, (Britannica) has reinvented the mission
of an encyclopedia, expanding it from a circumscribed set of books
to the authoritative interface to reference information on the
Internet,'' according to an article in the monthly Seybold
publication.
<p>
   This cybertrend is not without its pain.
<p>
   For 42 of his 69 years, Carl Tamburello of North Kansas City
pitched Encyclopaedia Britannicas to would-be buyers as they licked
cotton candy at state fairs and slumped in family room easy chairs
across the Midwest.
<p>
   It was a polished presentation made to a carefully developed
list of prospects. Customers were invited to read along as the
salesman orated his printed script.
<p>
   They were shown sample volumes and glossy pictures of the
multivolume set. Parents eager to give their children the best
educational tools signed up in droves. They were given a choice of
bindings that matched their budgets.
<p>
   ``We had a product whose name was so powerful,'' Tamburello
said.
<p>
   Tamburello rose through the ranks of Britannica to become
division manager, and for many years he worked from the company's
former Country Club Plaza store. In his career, he estimates that
he sold 3,900 sets of books.
<p>
   MORE...MORE
<p>
