<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8604 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETSCAPE-475&AMP;ADD- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0723 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-NETSCAPE-475&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NETSCAPE TAKES ON RIVALS IN KPMG DEAL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   In its effort to prove itself a viable competitor in the
corporate computer-networking market, Netscape Communications Corp.
is expected to announce Tuesday that the accounting firm KPMG Peat
Marwick LLP has selected the newest version of Netscape's
business-communications software as the standard for 17,000 workers
in its 120 offices in the United States.
<p>
   The deal is an important endorsement for Netscape, which made
its name with software for browsing the World Wide Web but is
trying to challenge both Microsoft Corp. and the Lotus Development
unit of IBM as the leading supplier of messaging software to
businesses and institutions.
<p>
   No terms of the deal were disclosed.
<p>
   It remains unclear how many other big corporate customers may
follow KPMG's endorsement of Netscape's software package, which
combines a Web browser with work-group collaboration and electronic
mail. The package, called Communicator, is still in a test version
and will not be generally available for several months.
<p>
   Still, KPMG's adoption of the software will broaden Netscape's
sales effort because the deal also calls for the accounting firm to
become a prime reseller of the software to the clients of KPMG's
information-technology consulting business.
<p>
   Microsoft has put considerable pressure on Netscape over the
last year by giving away its competing Web-browsing software, and
Netscape has countered by broadening the reach of its products to
challenge both Microsoft and Lotus in the corporate computing
market.
<p>
   Both Microsoft, with a product called Exchange, and Lotus, with
its Notes product, have many customers who have bought e-mail
software based on proprietary technical standards developed before
the Internet became the computer industry's de facto standard.
<p>
   While Microsoft and Lotus are rushing to overhaul their existing
software for use with the Internet, Netscape is hoping to leap
ahead of them with Communicator, which is based on the Internet's
so-called open standards.
<p>
   KPMG is a large user of an older Lotus e-mail software product
called cc:mail, which it will phase out over the next year as it
installs an internal network built around the World Wide Web and
Netscape products.
<p>
   Allan Frank, KPMG's chief technology officer, said that he was
attracted to Netscape because KPMG believes in embracing Internet
standards. But he stressed in an interview that he had chosen
Communicator primarily for its capability as a Web browser, not for
its e-mail and work-group features.
<p>
   KPMG is building an internal Internet network, or Intranet,
called KWEB, which the firm hopes will allow its employees to share
information about customers, products and strategies.
<p>
   ``We are using the Netscape browser as a window into that,''
Frank said. ``E-mail is just one part of the whole thing for us.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE  &MD;  OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   Others in the industry believe that Netscape may have difficulty
turning its market lead in Web browsers into a business that can
compete in the broader field of corporate computer communications.
<p>
   ``It will be interesting to see when it actually ships,'' said
Sheldon Laube, chief technology officer and executive vice
president of USWeb Corp., a large developer of corporate Web sites,
referring to Communicator. ``I've used it, and its off-line
abilities are not as rich as Notes and Exchange,'' he said.
<p>
   But David Smith, an analyst with the Gartner Group, a technology
consulting firm based in Stamford, Conn., disagreed. ``E-mail is
going to be the battleground for the Internet over the next 12
months,'' he said, ``And I think those products that are close to
Internet standards are going to be the leaders.''
<p>
   KPMG will also become a systems integration partner of Netscape,
though Frank said that did not mean that KPMG would not install
software from Lotus, Microsoft or other companies if it served the
best needs of its clients.
<p>
   ``We don't own stock in any company,'' Frank said. ``We have
relationships with Netscape and we have relationships with other
companies.''
<p>
