<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-SUPERBOWL-SFCHRON &QL; 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Super Web Sites for Bowl XXXI Watchers &QL; 
By Jon Swartz &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Football couch potatoes who can't get enough of the week-long
hype leading up to Super Bowl XXXI, take heart.
<p>
   Like almost everything else in Western civilization, sport's
ultimate spectacle has found its way onto the World Wide Web.
<p>
   In fact, there are more Super Bowl-related sites (at least 10)
than Super Bowls won by the San Francisco 49ers (five) and
Pittsburgh Steelers (four) combined.
<p>
   By clicking on www.sportsline.com, for example, consumers can
check out the latest news stories, analyses, statistics, chat rooms
and video and audio clips about Sunday's clash between the Green
Bay Packers and New England Patriots.
<p>
   And that's not all.
<p>
   Fox TV's edition (www.tvguide.com/ sports/football/superb31/)
serves up a splashy page of photos, a virtual online tailgate party
and video clips of past Super Bowl heroes Marcus Allen and William
Floyd.
<p>
   The official Super Bowl site (www.superbowl.com), sponsored by
IBM, offers a potpourri on all things Super  &MD;  from the Bart
Starr-led Packers who won the first two Super Bowls to Brett Favre
and the current edition of the Pack, which is heavily favored to
win.
<p>
   There's even a Super Bowl site for kids at, are you ready for
this? http://pathfinder.com /htQxjAQAXEkpwK/SIFK
/superbowl97/central.html
<p>
   There's even a Super Bowl site for kids at, are you ready for
this? http:/ /pathfinder.com /htQxjAQAXEkpwK/SIFK
/superbowl97/central.html
<p>
   If those sites don't whet your appetite, then there's more to
choose from. Among your best bets are:
<p>
    &MD; www.espnet.sportszone.com
<p>
    &MD; www.cnn.com/SPORTS /FOOTBALL/pro/superbowl31
<p>
    &MD; www.nando.net/newsroom
/sports/fbo/1997/nfl/nfl/stat/superbowl31
<p>
   Who knows? Browsing the Super Bowl Web might be more
entertaining than watching the game.
<p>
