<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8610 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-SHARES-CORRECT-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0402 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-IBM-SHARES-CORRECT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IBM STOCK DROPS AFTER DISAPPOINTING 4TH-QTR EARNINGS (CORRECT) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Margaret D. Williams &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Corrects affiliation of investor in third paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Armonk, New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- International Business
Machines Corp.'s stock dropped as much as 7.7 percent after the
world's largest computer maker reported lower-than-expected sales
and earnings for the fourth quarter.
<p>
   IBM's stock fell 11 1/2 to 156 1/2 in early trading of 3.22
million shares, making it the second-most active U.S. stock.
Earlier, shares fell as low as 155. The stock had been trading at
ten-year highs in the past few weeks as investors were optimistic
about the earnings.
<p>
   ``IBM's been a major outperformer the past three or four
months,'' said John Rutledge, an analyst at Boston's Loomis, Sayles
&AMP; Co., which owned 1.1 million IBM shares at the end of September.
Now, ``it takes a rest for a while.''
<p>
   IBM yesterday said fourth-quarter profit rose 18 percent,
slightly less than expected, as a stronger dollar and weak demand
in Europe hurt results.
<p>
   IBM said net income rose to $2.02 billion, or $3.93 a share,
from $1.71 billion, or $3.09 a share, in the year-earlier quarter.
Sales climbed 5.6 percent to $23.14 billion from $21.92 billion.
<p>
   Earnings were below the most recent estimate of $3.96 a share
from 15 analysts polled by IBES International Inc. Several analysts
had said they expected earnings of more than $4.00.
<p>
   At least four analysts cut their earnings estimates for 1997.
<p>
   ``Given that the stock has run up, we're probably going to see
the beginning'' of a decline, said Morgan Stanley analyst Steven
Milunovich. The drop could be as much as 15 percent in the next
three to five months, he said.
<p>
   IBM, like some other companies, was hurt by weak economies in
some European countries. Additionally, mainframe and workstation
sales were slow and falling memory-chip prices continued to hurt
results.
<p>
   Hardware sales edged up 2 percent to $11.7 billion, with
personal computer sales rising from the year-ago quarter in both
corporate products and home machines. System 390 mainframe sales
declined and RS/6000 workstation sales were unchanged from
year-earlier levels.
<p>
   ``The revenue growth story is not real strong at IBM,'' Rutledge
said. ``The bloom is off the rose.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1025EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0061 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=ttd-z> A8612 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-BIZINSIDER-SFCHRO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0612 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-BIZINSIDER-SFCHRON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Does Aussie Media Mogul Have Eyes on Data Broadcasting? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Herb Greenberg &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   While Data Broadcasting is officially headquartered in Jackson
Hole, Wyo., most of its operations are in San Mateo.
<p>
   But it really doesn't matter where the company is based, because
nobody seems to care about what it does.
<p>
   For the record, its Internet site, DBC.com, is believed to be
the busiest site providing financial news and information, with
more than 4 million hits a day.
<p>
   ``We're making as much as anyone from advertising on the
Internet,'' says CEO Alan Tessler.
<p>
   And its QuoTrek unit delivers real-time quotes to investors over
a handheld device.
<p>
   Data Broadcasting currently trades at $7.13  &MD;  around half its
earnings before taxes, interest and depreciation  &MD;  making it ``very
undervalued'' relative to its peers, says analyst Joel Krasner of
Southcoast Capital in New York.
<p>
   Even when information services and Internet companies were on
fire last year, Data Broadcasting was lukewarm. ``We're cursed with
the fact that we've had earnings and cash flow from the get-go,''
jokes Tessler, alluding to investor infatuation with Internet
companies that aren't making any money.
<p>
   What about those earnings, which tumbled last year by more than
half? Tessler attributes that to a decision to plow money back into
the business. ``There will be a big payoff in the future from these
efforts,'' he says.
<p>
   Kerry Packer, Australia's richest man, apparently agrees. I hear
that in recent months he has bought a Data Broadcasting stake of
just under 5 percent. Packer's Consolidated Press includes
newspapers, magazines and television stations.
<p>
   Tessler wouldn't confirm whether Packer is an investor, and
Packer couldn't be reached.
<p>
   However, a recent story in the Sydney Morning Herald said that
``gaining a strong foothold in the new-media industry is an
important part of Packer's strategy to reshape his business into a
multimedia, leisure and entertainment conglomerate.''
<p>
   Data Broadcasting would clearly fit the bill. But any
acquisition would have to be friendly. Tessler and his partner,
Alan Hirschfield, control roughly 20 percent of Data Broadcasting's
stock.
<p>
   The duo has a history of buying and building business, and then
selling them.
<p>
   They got into Data Broadcasting in the early 1990s by purchasing
the non-bankrupt part of Financial News Network.
<p>
   ``This is the longest time I've been with a business,'' Tessler
says.
<p>
   And he makes it clear, that at the right price, the company
could be sold. ``And it will get sold to a strategic-type of buyer
to whom it makes some sense,'' Tessler says.
<p>
   He says that in recent months Data Broadcasting has had numerous
conversations with large U.S. media entities about taking a stake
in Data Broadcasting  &MD;  with an option to eventually buy the entire
company. ``We'd do such a deal in a minute, because we believe it
would be a major validation of what we're doing,'' he says.
<p>
   However, he adds, the media companies tend to be ``nervous''
about how Data Broadcasting can fit into their overall strategy.
<p>
   Meanwhile, Tessler complains that the stock is undervalued. What
would it be worth in a takeover?
<p>
   Krasner, the analyst, figures $15 per share ``if the deal were
done today.'' If the company's strategy works out, it could be
worth a heck of a lot more a year from now.
<p>
   Herb Greenberg can be reached online at bizinsider(at
sign)sfgate.com, and can be read on The Gate at
www.sfgate.com/finance/.
<p>
NYT-01-20-97 2254EST
