<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=ttd-z> A8614 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-REEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0543 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-REEL-SFCHRON &QL; 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Web Site Helps You Cut Time at the Video Store &QL; 
By Georgeanne Dennison &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   If you've ever stood in front of the racks of movies at a video
store trying to figure out what to rent, do I have a Web site for
you.
<p>
   It's www.reel.com, and it opened for Internet users on January
8. Run by 8-month-old San Francisco-based Reel Inc., the site has
information on more than 12,000 movies.
<p>
   The purpose of the site, according to Reel's founder and chief
executive, Stuart Skorman, is to play movie matchmaker. It does
that by guiding you to films you may not have seen, based on movies
you've already seen and liked.
<p>
   When you first go to the site you're asked to become a
registered user. The reason, according to Skorman, is so the
database will remember you on subsequent visits to the site.
Registration is free, and Skorman said the company will not sell
your personal information or send you junk mail.
<p>
   Once you've registered, you can have the site tailor suggestions
for you by clicking on Reel Genius. You'll be asked to pick a type
of film, such as a mystery or musical. Then you'll get five popular
films to rate. (You can rate more films after that if you want, and
the more you rate, the better the site can pick flicks.)
<p>
   When you finish rating, Reel will provide you with a list of up
to 25 films customized to your tastes. The system uses an
artificial intelligence program developed by Entertainment
Decisions of Evanston, Ill., which works by recognizing patterns in
your preferences.
<p>
   I tried the site and immediately discovered a glitch. As a
mystery buff, I clicked on Reel Genius. Five movies to rate popped
up: ``Braveheart,'' ``Faust,'' ``Silence of the Lambs,'' ``The
Sting'' and ``The Godfather.''
<p>
   The trouble is that ``Braveheart'' isn't a mystery. Skorman said
the flaw of offering films in the wrong genre is being corrected.
<p>
   Anyway, I ranked those films, then decided to rank another five.
The resulting recommendations were surprisingly on target. The
site's top pick for me was ``The Usual Suspects,'' which I had seen
and enjoyed.
<p>
   Reel also offers a quick synopsis of new movies in theaters and
video stores, as well as summaries of reviews by critics from the
New York Times, Los Angeles Times and USA Today, as well as TV's
Roger Ebert.
<p>
   Skorman said it's an interpretation of the review that's done by
his staff. ``It's our opinion of their opinion,'' he said.
<p>
   Skorman has been a movie matchmaker since his days at the helm
of Empire Video Superstores, which he founded 12 years ago in
Vermont. He sold his stake in the chain to Blockbuster Video three
years ago, and used the $4 million from the deal to start Reel.
<p>
   Reel currently has eight full-time employees and 50 part-time
workers doing everything from graphic design to writing to being
movie experts. Many of the employees once worked at video stores.
<p>
   There is no advertising on the site. Reel plans to make money by
starting a virtual video store, where you'll be able to rent or buy
videos by mail. Users eventually may even be able to download
movies via the Internet.
<p>
NYT-01-20-97 2255EST
</TEXT>
