NYT-01-22-97 1026EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0064 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8615 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTEL-ADS-MEDIA-6 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0927 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-INTEL-ADS-MEDIA-665&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; INTEL TO ENTICE SUPER BOWL VIEWERS TO NEW KIND OF CHIP &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By STUART ELLIOTT &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Consumers are used to watching commercials for snack chips
during the Super Bowl. As they watch Super Bowl XXXI on Sunday,
they will see  &MD;  for the first time  &MD;  a commercial for computer
chips, too.
<p>
   Intel Corp., the world's largest maker of microprocessors, will
become a Super Bowl advertiser with a spot promoting the MMX, the
version of its popular Pentium chip that was introduced on Jan. 8.
<p>
   The commercial, which depicts dirty dancing in a ``clean room''
inside an Intel chip-fabrication factory, is one of four pitching
the MMX, which features technology to improve multimedia
performance.
<p>
   The four spots are part of a worldwide television, print and
interactive campaign that begins Wednesday night in North America
and expands in February and March into Asia and Europe. The
campaign is by the longtime Intel agency, Euro RSCG Dahlin Smith
White in Salt Lake City, a unit of Havas Advertising.
<p>
   Although Intel offered no figure for the campaign's total budget
as the ads continue around the world through May, the company plans
to spend $25 million to $30 million just in North America. That
market accounts for about 40 percent of its worldwide sales.
<p>
   Anyone surprised that a microchip is being hawked on the Super
Bowl ought to read the next two paragraphs sitting down. For Intel
and Dahlin Smith are pushing the envelope for marketing
high-technology products even further by using, in two of the four
MMX commercials, a celebrity: the actor Jason Alexander, who plays
the whiny nebbish George on the hit NBC sitcom ``Seinfeld.'' That
star turn is also a first for Intel.
<p>
   And the campaign is infused with the kind of offbeat humor
rarely found in computer advertising. That's typified by the song
on the soundtrack of the two commercials without Alexander: the
disco tune ``Play That Funky Music (White Boy)'' by Wild Cherry,
which set platform shoes a-tapping in 1976.
<p>
   The MMX effort is indicative of the significant shift in the
marketing of computers and related products as agencies
increasingly adopt the methods used to sell consumer packaged
goods. After all, about the only ploy left unexploited when
Microsoft Corp. introduced the Windows 95 operating system was
matchbook-cover advertising.
<p>
   In fact, Intel and Dahlin Smith are pioneers in such efforts.
They teamed up to transform the computer chip from a commodity to a
branded product with the ubiquitous campaign that carries the
``Intel inside'' theme.
<p>
   ``The computer has been moving from being a business product in
the late '80s to being a business and consumer product,'' Dennis
Carter, vice president and marketing director at Intel in Santa
Clara, Calif., said Tuesday.
<p>
   ``We believe advertising is an incredibly effective medium for
communicating with consumers and educating them about new
products,'' said Carter, who offered a preview of the campaign in
an interview. ``The fact it's a technology product is tangential.''
<p>
   The initial spot peddling the MMX, appearing Wednesday night on
prime-time, sports and news programs, is one of the two in which
Alexander figures; the other will run on Sunday before or after the
Super Bowl.
<p>
   In both spots, Alexander demonstrates the potential  &MD;  and
pitfalls  &MD;  of using a personal computer powered with the MMX chip
for video conferences. He tries to impress blind dates and, in the
quintessential George manner, fails miserably.
<p>
   ``We did not start out with a goal to use a celebrity,'' Jon
White, executive vice president and executive creative director at
Dahlin Smith, said in a telephone interview from Salt Lake City.
``Jason is a personality who's playing a character we felt he could
play better than anybody.''
<p>
   As for the disco tune in the spots not featuring Alexander, said
Ann Lewnes, worldwide advertising director at Intel, ``music is a
great way to relate to an audience.''
<p>
   ``And a song like that,'' she added, ``appeals to Generation X
and the younger boomers, who are among the most avid computer
users.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE  &MD;  OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   That appeal may be even broader, as White suggested.
<p>
   ``My 13-year-old daughter, Rachel, was at a Utah Jazz game last
night,'' he said, ``and she told me they played `Play That Funky
Music' during one of the timeouts. As she was dancing, all her
friends asked, `How do you know that song?'''
<p>
   The two funky-music spots take place in an Intel clean room,
where ``highly trained professionals are engaged,'' a voice-over
announcer says, ``in the extremely precise process of adding fun to
the Pentium processor.'' As the disco beat intensifies, he asserts
that the MMX ``will make your multimedia dance.''
<p>
   To underscore that assertion, the technicians are wearing
``bunny suits''  &MD;  the garments meant to ensure sterility  &MD;  that are
shiny gold, silver, red and blue rather than the standard-issue
dull white.
<p>
   The Intel campaign is not Alexander's first foray onto Madison
Avenue. He also portrays a character nicknamed Pretzel Boy in
advertising for the Rold Gold brand sold by Frito-Lay, the
snack-chip unit of Pepsico Inc.
<p>
   Coincidentally, Pretzel Boy has appeared in Super Bowl spots,
though Rold Gold will be absent from the game on Sunday; Frito-Lay
will instead advertise brands like Baked Lay's and Tostitos.
<p>
NYT-01-21-97 2156EST
