<SLUG> BC-CPT-EARNS-COMPUTER-AS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0705 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-EARNS-COMPUTER-ASSOCIATES-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMPUTER ASSOCIATES'S 3RD-QTR RESULTS BEAT ESTIMATES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Heather Green &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Islandia, New York, Jan. 21 (Bloomberg)-- Computer Associates
International Inc. said third-quarter operating earnings rose 25
percent, slightly beating analysts' estimates.
<p>
   Profit from operations rose to $284.7 million, or 75 cents a
share, from net income of $227.2 million, or 60 cents, in the
year-earlier quarter. Including a charge of $598 million, or $1.57
a share, for the acquisition of Cheyenne Software Inc., the company
had a loss was $313.3 million, or 86 cents a share.
<p>
   Revenue for the quarter ended Dec. 31 rose 5 percent to $1.05
billion from $1 billion.
<p>
   Wall Street expected the software maker to post earnings of 74
cents a share, excluding the charges, based on the average estimate
of 13 analysts surveyed by IBES International Inc.
<p>
   Computer Associates shares rose 1 5/8 to 46. It released the
earnings statement after the close of U.S. stock-market trading.
<p>
   The Islandia, New York-based company warned last month of
disappointing sales as it switches to new products in Europe.
Analysts had expected revenue of $1.2 billion before the company's
warning.
<p>
   Computer Associates said it would take one or two quarters to
bring the European business up to speed. The company has been
shifting its focus to selling client-server software that manages
computer networks and scaling back products for large mainframe
computers.
<p>
   The company's software is used to monitor information sent over
computer networks.
<p>
   Computer Associates said its European sales force hasn't been
aggressive enough in building the new business, resulting in
lower-than-expected revenue.
<p>
   ``In Europe, it's a question of making the transition and
executing,'' said Sanjay Kumar, Computer Associates's president.
``We made some costly mistakes.''
<p>
   Computer Associates faces stiff competition, especially from
International Business Machines Corp.'s Tivoli unit, which had
strong sales during the quarter. Computer Associates said it isn't
losing contracts to IBM.
<p>
   Still, investors and analysts were cautious on a conference call
after earnings were released, questioning whether mainframe growth
was slowing and how Computer Associates could turn its fortunes
around in Europe, analysts said.
<p>
   ``The bottom line is they did what they said they would do for
the quarter,'' said Chris Mortenson, an analyst at Alex. Brown &AMP;
Sons. The company said it is focusing on improving the sales
training of its salespeople in Europe. Computer Associates said it
began selling client-server systems in Europe about nine months
ago, versus about two years ago in the U.S.
<p>
   The company said Europeans have been slower to change from
mainframe systems to client-servers and that its sales people
hadn't been persuasive enough it encouraging customers to make the
switch.
<p>
   Client-server systems overall are selling at a faster pace than
mainframes, as more companies use networks of high-powered computer
servers linked to personal computers. The company said it expects
that by the middle of 1998 half of its revenue will come from
client-server software and half from mainframe sales.
<p>
   That's compared to the 61 percent of revenue mainframe sales
accounted for in the third quarter and 63 percent in the
second-quarter.
<p>
   Mainframe sales for the quarter were $640 million, while
client-server sales were $371 million. International sales were
$409 million, while U.S. sales accounted for $644 million.
<p>
   The company said it expected to benefit from strong sales of
client-server software from Microsoft Corp., with which Computer
Associates products work.
<p>
   Computer Associates bought Cheyenne in December for about $1.19
billion.
<p>
   For the nine months, profit from operations rose to $627.9
million, or $1.65 a share, from $486.6 million, or $1.28, a year
earlier.
<p>
   Nine-month net income after the charge was $29.9 million, or 8
cents a share, compared with a loss of $321.5 million, or 89 cents.
Revenue rose to $2.84 billion from $2.39 billion.
<p>
