<SLUG> BC-EARNS-US-BANCORP-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0350 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-US-BANCORP-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. BANCORP 4TH-QTR EARNINGS RISE 9% ON MORE LOANS AND FEES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Michael Smith &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Portland, Oregon, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. Bancorp's
fourth-quarter earnings rose 9 percent, as the Oregon bank raked in
higher fees from loans, checking accounts and other services.
<p>
   U.S. Bancorp said net income rose to $120 million, or 79 cents
per share, from profit from operations of $110.5 million, or 71
cents, a year earlier. After acquisition-related charges, net
income in the last three months of 1995 was $21.38 million, or 13
cents.
<p>
   The earnings met Wall Street's expectations of 79 cents a share,
according to a survey of 17 analysts by IBES International Inc.
U.S. Bancorp shares rose 3/16 to 45 5/16 in morning trading.
<p>
   Chairman Gerry Cameron, in a statement, said the bank plans to
focus on boosting revenue and buying back stock in 1997, after
absorbing West One Bancorp, which it acquired in December 1995.
<p>
   In the quarter, total revenue 8.5 percent to $515.6 million, as
the bank raised more fees from customers and paid less for funds.
<p>
   Net interest income rose 8.5 percent to $394.1 million from
higher lending income. The net interest margin, or difference
between what a bank earns on loans and investments and pays for
deposits and borrowings, widened to 5.42 percentage points from
5.32 points in the third quarter.
<p>
   Noninterest income rose 6.9 percent to $132.6 million, led by a
jump in service charges on consumer deposit accounts. Fees from
trust services also rose, while credit card fees fell.
<p>
   Noninterest expenses fell 2.5 percent to $289.9 million, as
employees salaries and benefits were little changed. Before merger
costs, expenses were down 10 percent.
<p>
   U.S. Bancorp slashed costs as it absorbed West One, eliminating
1,100 jobs and closing 52 branches. In 1996, the bank achieved its
goal of slashing annual costs by $84 million.
<p>
   For the year, net income rose to $478.9 million, or $3.08 a
share, from $329.0 million, or $2.09, in 1995.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1029EST
</TRAILER>
