<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=ttd-z> A8624 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-BANDWIDTH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0821 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-BANDWIDTH-SFCHRON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Race Is On for Fast Net Access &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Jonathan Marshall &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   In the digital age, the race for profits will go to the swift  &MD; 
those companies that can deliver data to and from your computer the
fastest.
<p>
   Pacific Bell's announcement Monday that it plans to start
rolling out a powerful new data service later this year is a direct
challenge to cable television companies that already offer
high-speed Internet access to some homes.
<p>
   Early evidence suggests customers will love the speed and
convenience of Asymmetric Digital Subscriber Line (ADSL), which
lets customers download Web pages as much as 50 times faster than
normal telephone modems, over existing phone lines.
<p>
   But consumers may balk at the price. Pac Bell says it's likely
to charge about $165 a month for ADSL Internet access, on top of a
$600 set-up fee.
<p>
   Steve Chiapetto of San Ramon signed up in October as a guinea
pig for Pac Bell's ADSL experiment. Until then he was using a 14.4
kilobits-per-second modem to browse the Internet through AOL, which
he found hopelessly slow. His life  &MD;  or at least his online
existence  &MD;  has changed now that he downloads data at 1.5 million
bits (megabits) per second.
<p>
   ``Instead of pushing a button and going off to cook dinner
before a page comes up, it takes seconds,'' he said. ``I find it
easier to turn on the computer and get sports information than
going out to the driveway to get my newspaper.''
<p>
   Because Internet access is so fast, he uses the computer almost
daily now to look up Caltrans road information, check airplane
arrival times or help his daughter learn about building bridges for
a school project.
<p>
   But would he pay $165 a month for all that convenience? ``I'd
probably shy away,'' he admitted. ``I'd hope the price would come
down and become more reasonable.''
<p>
   Ron Raab, a molecular biologist and member of the San Ramon City
Council, also finds Pac Bell's ADSL service invaluable, whether
looking up a biotechnology database or checking weather reports.
But he figures he could buy a new computer each year for the fees
it would take to pay for ADSL. ``My wife would kill me,'' he said.
<p>
   Paula Reinman, product manager for ADSL at Pac Bell, conceded
that most residential customers will stick with traditional modems
or ISDN (Integrated Services Digital Network), which pumps data at
128 kilobits per second and costs roughly $49 per month. But ADSL
will be cheaper for many businesses than some heavyweight data
solutions, like T1 lines.
<p>
   ``Given the current pricing structure, ADSL needs to be targeted
to small business and to consumers who are using the Internet as a
critical piece of their life,'' Reinman said. ``Over time ADSL
modem prices will fall and it will become more of a mass market.''
<p>
   Super-fast Internet service is already available in a few
communities from cable companies at prices ranging from $35 to $60
a month  &MD;  a much more attractive deal for casual customers. In the
Bay Area, Home has launched service in Fremont and Sunnyvale.
<p>
   But most cable TV systems aren't yet capable of sending data in
two directions, so cable and telephone companies are still
neck-and-neck at this early stage of their race.
<p>
   Analysts are sharply divided over who will win. A recent study
by Lawrence Gasman of Communications Industry Researchers in
Charlottesville, Va., concluded that cable will ultimately have the
edge because its delivery medium, coaxial cable, has more data
carrying capacity than copper telephone wires used for ADSL.
<p>
   Emily Green of Forrester Research in Boston says cable modems
have the price edge if you can use them, but small business may opt
for ADSL because cable lines don't run through most business
districts.
<p>
   And Randy Carlson of the Yankee Group, also in Boston, sees the
cable companies retrenching to focus on their core business of
delivering video. Burdened by enormous debt, they can't afford a
huge investment in new data services.
<p>
   ``The telephone companies will win, definitely,'' he said.
``They have superior experience in two-way interactive
communication.''
<p>
   Both technologies will take years to deploy. By 2001,
Communications Industry Researchers projects, there will be 73.5
million connections to the Internet through ordinary telephone
modems, 40 million through ISDN, and only 20 million using ADSL or
cable modems.
<p>
   Many consumers will end up getting a choice of one or the other
but not both of the advanced services, depending on which company
has the resources to get to their neighborhood first.
<p>
   ``It's not a religious matter,'' said Jerry Bennington, a
spokesman for Cable Labs in Louisville, Colo. ``If ADSL showed up
and I didn't have a cable modem, I'd buy ADSL. Either way, it's a
victory for the consumer.''
<p>
