<p>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers.)
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice  &MD;  into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR; 
 &UR; By MEG LUKENS NOONAN
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   Killington, widely known for having the longest ski season and
wildest party scene in the East, is taking steps this year to
become better recognized as a family resort.
<p>
   The central Vermont ski area, New England's largest, was bought
last summer by the American Skiing Co., which immediately began
upgrading its facilities and creating new programs.
<p>
   Just last month, Killington acquired its neighbor, Pico
Mountain, giving the resort its seventh peak and its guests access
to even more family-friendly terrain.
<p>
   That may not matter to the rowdy young singles who drive up from
New York and New Jersey to thrash themselves on steep trails like
Outer Limits, Killington's signature mogul run, but it matters a
great deal to parents who may have found the sprawling resort's
boisterous crowds daunting enough to ski elsewhere.
<p>
   At Killington, the Rams Head area has been designated a family
ski mountain.
<p>
   Anchored by a greatly expanded and redesigned base lodge, which
houses all children's instruction programs, rental operations and
day care, Rams Head's novice and intermediate trails are set off
from the rest of the resort.
<p>
   There are two new novice trails and three new lifts, including a
high-speed quad chair that cuts in half travel time to the top of
Rams Head.
<p>
   A new ski-through underpass connecting Rams Head to Snowshed
eliminates the need to cross the Killington access road.
<p>
   Elsewhere at the resort, the Needle's Eye area on Skye Peak has
been reconfigured to eliminate crossover trails and allow for more
continuous top-to-bottom skiing.
<p>
   Two high-speed quad chairs, the Needle's Eye Express and the
Northbrook Quad, have also been installed to serve that area.
<p>
   New Yorkers, who make up the majority of Killington visitors,
can now take Amtrak's new 240-passenger Ethan Allen Express from
Penn Station to Rutland, Vt., about 15 miles west of Killington.
<p>
   The trip takes about five hours and costs $100 round trip, $50
for children. Through Feb. 9, children 15 and younger ride free.
<p>
   A transfer service to lodging in and near Killington costs $10
round trip. Call Killington Lodging and Travel Service, (800)
621-6867. Vans meet the trains.
<p>
   Limited service from Newark and La Guardia Airports is available
to Rutland Airport. Continental Airlines serves Burlington, Vt.,
which is about 90 minutes to the north.
 &UR; EVENTS &LR; 
<p>
   On Jan. 31, the public can test products free of cost from
several major manufacturers at Consumer Snowboard and Ski Demo Day,
which will be held at the base of Killington Mountain. Call (800)
621-6867.
<p>
   The Billings Farm and Museum, less than a half hour's drive in
Woodstock, will offer sleigh rides on Feb. 15, 16 and 17.
<p>
   Visitors pay $6.50 to tour the restored 1890 farmhouse, see
working dairy barns and blacksmith exhibits and ride on horse-drawn
sleighs. Information: (802) 457-2355.
<p>
   The free Killington Boardercross on March 1 pits some of the
best snowboarders in the East against one another in races through
bumps, banks, turns, drops and racing gates on Killington's
half-pipe and in the snowboard park. Information: (802) 422-6735.
<p>
   On March 30, for Easter, plans call for a sunrise service on top
of Killington Mountain and an egg hunt at the ski area.
Information: (800) 621-6867.
<p>
   April 12 and 13 is the 17th annual Bear Mountain Mogul
Challenge, featuring head-to-head ski competition on Outer Limits,
New England's steepest bump run.
<p>
   The popular event costs participants $35. Spectators can either
watch free from the deck at the base lodge or buy a lift ticket.
Information: (802) 422-6200.
<p>
   A couple of events focus on improving skiing and snowboarding.
Snowboard clinics for women  &MD;  they are also taught by women  &MD;  are
available Feb. 1 and 2 and March 8 and 9. Call (800) 621-6867 to
register.
<p>
   From March 31 to April 4, Killington's School for Professionals
will help advanced skiers and snowboarders, age 16 and older, who
want to teach or to improve their technique.
<p>
   To register for the program, which costs $325, call (800)
621-6867; for information, (802) 422-6727.
 &UR; WHAT TO DO &LR; 
<p>
   Killington's 95 miles of terrain (including Pico's) receive an
average snowfall of 250 inches a year, augmented by a snowmaking
system.
<p>
   To help visitors get a handle on Killington's sometimes
bewildering trail network, resort ambassadors guide Meet the
Mountain tours several times daily.
<p>
   The 90-minute tours, which leave from the Snowshed base area,
are conducted entirely on trails suitable for beginners.
<p>
   Demonstration skis are available for a fee at Snowshed and
Killington Base Lodge.
<p>
   Killington full-day tickets run $48 for weekdays and weekends,
and $49 for holidays.
<p>
   Killington lift tickets will be honored at Pico. Tickets good
only for Pico cost $35 on weekdays and weekends, and $39 on
holidays.
<p>
   To save money on full-day lift tickets, skiers can buy the
Magnificent Seven card for $273, good for seven full-day passes at
any of the American Skiing Co. resorts, bringing the cost to $39 a
day.
<p>
   Cross-country skiers will find several touring centers in the
area.
<p>
   The Mountain Top Inn cross country ski resort, Mountain Top
Road, Chittenden, (800) 445-2100 or (802) 483-2311, is a 15-minute
drive from Killington.
<p>
   Spread over 1,300 forested acres, the center has more than 100
kilometers of trails, snowmaking, a log cabin warming hut,
horse-drawn sleigh rides, ice skating and sledding, all at an
altitude of 2,000 feet.
<p>
   The lakeside Mountain Meadows Lodge ski touring center,
Thundering Brook Road, Killington, (802) 775-1010, has 60
kilometers of trails, snowshoeing, rentals and instruction. The
trail fee is $13 a day.
<p>
   From late February through mid-April, visitors can participate
in a working maple sugaring operation at Sugarbush Farm in
Woodstock, (802) 457-1757 or (800) 281-1757. Call first to see if
the sap is running.
 &UR; WHERE TO STAY &LR; 
<p>
   Most lodgings in a 30-mile radius have reduced-rate
lifts-and-lodging packages.
<p>
   Closest to the slopes are several resort-operated Killington
Village condominiums and hotels, all served by a free bus.
<p>
   Killington Lodging and Travel Service can book for most
lodgings.
<p>
   The timber and stone Red Rob Inn, Killington Road, Killington,
(802) 422-3303, fax (802) 422-3971, one mile from the Snowshed base
area, has 33 country style rooms, an indoor pool, massage
therapist, sauna, outdoor hot tub, game room and lounge with
entertainment.
<p>
   Slopeside shuttle, dinner and full breakfast are included. Rates
start at $160 for two.
<p>
   The Cortina Inn, Route 4, Killington, (802) 773-3331 or (800)
451-6108, fax (802) 775-6948, is a sprawling full-service
mini-resort with 97 rooms; some suites have fireplaces.
<p>
   Guests have access to an exercise room, indoor pool and outdoor
ice skating. Zola's Grille serves rack of lamb, grilled venison and
a buffet brunch on Sundays.
<p>
   Rates are $129 to $189 for two, including breakfast, through
Easter.
<p>
   Budget: The Mountain Meadows Lodge, Thundering Brook Road,
Killington, (800) 370-4567 or (802) 775-1010, is a comfortable
rambling farmhouse with 18 rooms, all with private baths.
<p>
   Some family rooms sleep as many as five. Rates start at $115 for
two, breakfast included. There is a cross-country ski center on the
premises.
<p>
   The Comfort Inn-Killington Center has 40 rooms and 20
efficiencies in five townhouse-style buildings three miles from the
Snowshed lifts, (802) 422-4222, fax (802) 422-4226.
<p>
   Continental breakfast is included. Children younger than 18 stay
free in their parents' rooms. Double rates range from $85 to $120.
<p>
   Luxury: Sixteen miles from the ski slopes is the intimate Tulip
Tree Inn, Chittenden Dam Road, Chittenden, (802) 483-6213, (800)
707-0017 a secluded eight-room country inn in the Green Mountain
National Forest. Each tastefully decorated room has a luxurious
bath, and five have whirlpools.
<p>
   The minimum stay is two nights on weekends, three nights during
holidays. Rates for two per night range from $150 to $199 , which
includes dinner and breakfast. Continental cuisine is served in the
dining room.
<p>
   The Woods at Killington, about three miles from Snowshoe, is on
100 wooded acres just off Killington Mountain Road. Individually
owned condominiums, with one, two and three bedrooms, from $175 to
$540 have master baths, two-person whirlpools, full kitchens and
fireplaces.
<p>
   The health club has an indoor pool, sauna, exercise room, spa
treatments, massages and salon services. Information: (802)
422-3100 or (800) 633-0127; fax (802) 422-4544.
 &UR; WHERE TO EAT &LR; 
<p>
   Panache, the Woods Resort, Killington Road, Killington (802)
422- 8622, specializes in African game. The menu, which changes
daily, might include wild boar, ostrich, even giraffe. The game is
all farm-raised. Some traditional fare is also available.
<p>
   In the pastel-colored dining room, the tables have as
centerpieces Japanese fighting fish in glass tanks. Children are
entertained and eat free pizza in an adjacent high-technology game
room called Pizzazz. Dinner for two with wine is about $85.
<p>
   Hemingway's, Route 4, Sherburne Flats, (802) 422-3886, is in the
restored 1860 Asa Briggs house, a former stagecoach stop now filled
with art and antiques.
<p>
   Diners can sit in either the formal peach-colored main room, a
more casual garden room or downstairs in the cozy brick-walled wine
cellar.
<p>
   A four-course tasting menu includes small portions of several
entrees and four wines ($60 with wines, $45 without). A vegetarian
version is $36 without wines.
<p>
   Specialties include risotto with Maine lobster, grilled duck,
venison and locally raised pheasant. Open for dinner Wednesday
through Sunday. Dinner for two with wine is $125.
<p>
   Powderhounds, Killington Road, Killington, (802) 422-4141, has a
casual dining room serving vegetarian dishes and homemade pastas
like pappardelle with pancetta and wild mushrooms. A children's
menu is available. Open daily for dinner; lunch served weekends and
holidays. Dinner for two with wine: $30 to $60.
<p>
   Choices, Glazebrook Center, Killington Road, Killington, (802)
422-4030, is one of two restaurants owned by a chef, Claude Blais.
The other is Claude's, next door.
<p>
   This bright and lively bistro serves hand-cut pastas, jambalaya,
smoked pork loin and knockwurst, in addition to sandwiches and
burgers in a softly-lit dining room and at a handsome cherry-wood
bar, popular with people dining alone. Open nightly for dinner and
Sunday for brunch. Dinner for two with wine: $40 to $50.
<p>
   Mother Shapiro's, Killington Road, Killington, (802) 422-9933,
is one of the resort's oldest places, serving pastas, burgers,
pulled-pork sandwiches, smoked barbecue ribs and steaks. Discounts
are offered Sunday through Friday.
<p>
   The Bobby Darling Band does a comedy-music show on Friday from
10 p.m. to 2 a.m., and Saturday from 4 to 7:30 p.m. Open all day.
Dinner for two with wine: $30 to $50.
