<DOCID> nyt970122.0074 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8634 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-IBM-EARNINGS-325&AMP; </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0949 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-IBM-EARNINGS-325&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IBM EARNINGS TOP FORECASTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   IBM reported fourth-quarter earnings Tuesday that were better
than expected, but some analysts feared that the results were not
strong enough to maintain the momentum that has seen shares of the
company soar more than 30 percent in the last three months.
<p>
   While IBM's growth in services continued, its hardware sales
were up only 2 percent in the quarter compared with the 1995
period, and sales in Europe were flat.
<p>
   Earnings for the quarter rose 18.2 percent, to $2 billion, or
$3.93 a share, compared with $1.7 billion, or $3.09 a share, a year
earlier. Revenue increased 5.6 percent, to $23.1 billion.
<p>
   The results surpassed the average forecast of Wall Street
analysts, of $3.88 a share, according to First Call. Still, a
number of analysts and some big investors were expecting IBM to
earn more than $4 a share and to register a double-digit revenue
increase.
<p>
   ``It's a disappointment,'' said Daniel Mandresh of Merrill Lynch
in New York, whose earnings estimate was one of the highest at
$4.32 a share. ``They had to be at $4 to justify where the stock
has come from. It's going to lose momentum tomorrow. How much I
don't know.''
<p>
   IBM announced the results after the stock market closed.
Earlier, shares reached a 52-week high in anticipation of a strong
earnings report, closing at $168, up $1. Traders said that
better-than-expected results earlier in the day from NCR and Tandem
Computer had encouraged belief that IBM, too, might deliver a
surprise.
<p>
   The shares of IBM are now a few dollars shy of their all-time
high of $175.875 set in August 1987. They have more than doubled in
the last year, after falling as low as $40.625 in 1993.
<p>
   Louis Gerstner Jr., IBM's chairman, said in a statement that
``we showed good growth in the fourth quarter despite a difficult
year-over-year comparison, continued weakness in Europe and a
greater-then-expected currency impact.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   IBM's services business continued to be the company's
strongest-performing unit as revenue increased 22 percent, the 16th
consecutive quarter of more than 20 percent growth. Some on Wall
Street have been suspicious of that performance, whispering that
IBM is sacrificing profit so that it can make low bids in order to
win contracts.
<p>
   But G. Richard Thoman, the chief financial officer, rejected
such notions in a meeting with analysts Tuesday. ``I will tell you
categorically that that is not the case,'' he said. ``We are not
buying the business.''
<p>
   Hardware sales were led by the personal computer division, which
continued a turnaround that has seen it gain market share against
its rival Compaq Computer in recent quarters. IBM did not disclose
growth figures, but Mandresh of Merrill Lynch estimated that the
division grew 25 percent during the quarter.
<p>
   Thoman also said the storage division had a strong quarter, led
by sales of hard disk drives, though its high-end storage systems
continued to be weak sellers.
<p>
   Since PCs and disk drives carry relatively low profit margins,
IBM's overall margins ebbed, to 40.3 percent in the quarter
compared with 41.7 percent a year earlier.
<p>
   Mainframe computers have relatively high margins, but sales
declined during the quarter compared with a year earlier. That was
largely because the fourth quarter of 1995 saw an 80 percent
increase in the amount of mainframe computing power IBM shipped
compared with a 35 percent increase in the most recent quarter.
<p>
   Thoman said that mainframe demand remained strong and that IBM
was continuing to find new customers for the machines that many
analysts had predicted were dinosaurs a few years ago.
<p>
   The AS/400 minicomputer had a strong quarter, but sales of the
RS6000 line of work stations and servers were flat.
<p>
   Software revenue grew 4 percent in the quarter, and Thoman cited
the performances of Lotus Development and Tivoli, IBM's two largest
recent acquisitions. Lotus sold 1.5 million copies of its Notes
software in the quarter, bringing its total installed to 9.5
million, twice what it was at the beginning of 1996.
<p>
   Sales of Tivoli's system-management software tripled in the
quarter, and the unit's overall revenue was larger than the first
three quarters combined, Thoman said.
<p>
   But the two units are a relatively small part of IBM's $13
billion in software sales, which are dominated by slower-growing
products for mainframes and minicomputers.
<p>
   Thoman said unfavorable exchange rates cut overall revenue 3
percent in the quarter and reduced earnings 18 cents a share. A
plunge in memory-chip prices also had a negative impact.
<p>
   But IBM was able to reduce expenses 2 percent compared with last
year and cut its tax rate to 29.9 percent compared with 33.4
percent in the fourth quarter of 1995. The company has said it will
continue to pursue that strategy as overall margins decline in the
years ahead.
<p>
   Thoman expressed optimism about 1997, but warned that the first
quarter would be a particularly tough comparison because of the
decline in memory-chip prices in 1996.
<p>
   Nevertheless, analysts said that the recent spectacular gain in
IBM's stock may have gotten ahead of its financial performance.
<p>
   Referring to Thoman, Mandresh said: ``He ended on a very
positive note, but this is a business that acts on disappointment.
The stock was $83 last January. Clearly, next January, the stock
will be higher than it is now, but it won't be higher tomorrow.''
<p>
NYT-01-21-97 2047EST
