<STORYID cat=l pri=r sel=tab-z> A8629 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-A-VILLAGE-REMEMBERS-N </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 2338 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-A-VILLAGE-REMEMBERS-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE VILLAGE THAT HASN'T FORGOTTEN &LR;  &QL; 
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package  &MD;  the rate
is not prohibitive  &MD;  contact one of the following sales
representatives:
   ( &MD;  U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
   ( &MD;  Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR; 
   ( &MD;  Latin America: PAUL FINCH in Los Angeles at (310) 996-0075;
fax: 310-996-0089.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; (-----They also have information on how to subscribe to ``WAY
TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers.-----) &LR; 
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice  &MD;  into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR; 
 &UR; By GILLIAN TINDALL
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   Few landscapes are as undramatically beautiful as the Limousin,
the rolling countryside around Limoges in the heart of France.
<p>
   South of the hot vineyards of the Loire and west of the central
mountains, it is a country of high green meadows and streams, of
chestnut and oak plantations, of small red dairy cows that match
the soil, and of compact, 1,000-year-old towns and villages.
<p>
   Until the present century, it had known no serious assault since
the ending of the war with the English 500 years ago.
<p>
   Far from Paris and from the traditional killing fields of
northern France, the citizens of central France had seen no invader
and indeed few strangers of any kind  &MD;  until 1940.
<p>
   Even then, with the occupation of half the country by the German
Army, the Limousin was at first untouched. It was in the
theoretically ``free'' zone of Vichy France.
<p>
   There was not even, in that fertile land with its peasant
economy of small, mixed farms, a shortage of food.
<p>
   And even after the end of 1942, when the increasingly tense
German Army took over the whole country, life well away from the
German command in the main cities was still much the same.
<p>
   Oradour-sur-Glane was, and is again today, a substantial village
about a dozen miles outside Limoges.
<p>
   The old village, however, is preserved in ruins, a historic
monument and a memorial to a mindless atrocity of World War II.
<p>
   In the fine early June of 1944, when the Normandy landings were
taking place, the 1,500 inhabitants of Oradour and its outlying
farms, plus refugees, were going about their daily affairs.
<p>
   They were tending their animals and their fields, sitting in the
schools, popping into the grocers or the pharmacy, stamping forms
in the mairie, or town hall, banging metal in the smithy, sitting
in one or another of the half dozen cafes.
<p>
   June 10 was a Saturday, the day when the tobacco ration was
distributed, so there were more men than usual about in the single
main street and the shaded, irregularly shaped square by the church
from where the road sloped down to the small river Glane.
<p>
   There were also, as it was the weekend, visitors from the town,
up for a day in the country and a meal at the inn, the Hotel
Milord. They arrived on the little tramway from Limoges that
terminated at the top of the street.
<p>
   A few people from Oradour had gone down to Limoges that morning
to shop by the same tram.
<p>
   At 2 in the afternoon a large detachment of SS troops came fast
up the road from Limoges (the N141 toward Angouleme and the
Atlantic coast) and forked right onto the D9. They drove straight
up into the center of Oradour.
<p>
   Five hours later, 642 people were dead. Almost 300 of these were
women and 205 were children.
<p>
   The men, including a party of teen-age cyclists who just
happened to be passing, had been assembled on the cattle-fair
ground, herded in various barns and then shot. Some men had managed
to run.
<p>
   The women and children had all been marched into the church,
which was then set on fire. All but one woman perished.
<p>
   The whole village, 328 houses and other buildings with all their
contents, was then set on fire and reduced to a smoldering ruin.
<p>
   It is unnecessary to go into greater detail here. Those who
visit the remains of the village can buy complete accounts.
<p>
   Twenty years ago, when I first visited the place, the official
booklet had a German eagle enblazoned in red across its cover.
<p>
   Today the covers are different, suggestive less of one specific
outrage than of a more general commemoration of the fragility of
human decencies and the need to remember the past in order to erect
safeguards in the future.
<p>
   As General de Gaulle said in 1945 when the war ended:
``Oradour-sur-Glane is the symbol of what our country had suffered.
We must conserve it, for never again must a comparable evil
occur.''
<p>
   Although there are gates with an information kiosk at each end
of the ruined village now, and thus an unobtrusive security
presence, you can wander in at any daylight hour and there is no
question of payment.
<p>
   This is not a place for crowds of tourists or conducted tours,
but rather for French families, with a sprinkling of English,
Belgian and Dutch, to bring their children on an informative
pilgrimage.
<p>
   By one of those strange ironies of time and chance the name
Oradour, which is centuries old, actually means a shrine or place
of prayer.
<p>
   A notice posted soon after the massacre suggests that a
respectful demeanor and ``correct dress'' are appropriate.
<p>
   Now people stroll thoughtfully in the sunshine taking a few
photos, and if the shorts and T-shirts of present day
holiday-makers would once have caused affront then that is simply
an outward sign that the world beyond the gates is very different
now.
<p>
   Today, in spite of everything one may know or read about the
horror of that June day over 50 years ago, the dominant impression
of Oradour is of peace.
<p>
   The carefully stabilized ruins of houses, shops, workshops and
barns, long cleansed of blackened debris, lapped in neatly cut
grass, form an oasis of tranquillity.
<p>
   Shady trees once again spread their branches where the cafe
tables used to be.
<p>
   In the words of George Meredith:
<p>
   Green earth forgets,
<p>
   The gay young generations mask her grief
<p>
   Here, one knows, hundreds were brutally wiped out, yet the
feeling today is less of death than of life arrested  &MD;  the life of
a prosperous corner of rural France on the eve of the present era.
<p>
   ``Le temps est reste fige pour que tu te souviennes''  &MD;  ``time
has remained fixed here to make us remember''  &MD;  says the notice at
the gate.
<p>
   However, more is preserved here, almost incidentally but
gathering meaning with every decade that passes, than a memory of
an atrocity.
<p>
   The street, up which you walk from what's left of the church,
following the tramline all the way up to the Art Deco post office
building and the large houses of the doctor and the lawyer, is a
street of the 1930's, traffic-free, white with dust.
<p>
   The remains of the very few cars then owned in Oradour stand
where the fire found and devoured them.
<p>
   Covered in protective brown paint, these antique Citroens and
Simcas, along with the twisted skeletons of push-bikes and sewing
machines, have acquired the air of metal sculptures, eloquent of
the busy and ``modern'' life in which they were once valued
possessions.
<p>
   Most of the roofless, windowless houses on the street carry a
small plaque telling one that here bread was baked, or groceries
sold or wheels fixed or shoes repaired or dressmaking undertaken: a
complete roll-call of the self-sufficient commerce and skills of a
community long before the era of the supermarket.
<p>
   Water pumps still stand by garden gates, desirable 20th-century
improvements on the traditional well.
<p>
   In the small, underground memorial museum by the cemetery, odds
and ends of daily life that survived the inferno have become
sanctified relics: decorative liqueur glasses, spectacles,
penknives, dental implements, watches with cracked faces showing
mid-afternoon times.
<p>
   Until that day in June 1944 when time was stopped forever,
Oradour seemed to have been one of the better places in which to be
born, to grow up, live and die.
<p>
   Up to that zero moment it had a history like anywhere else,
neither glorious nor ignoble.
<p>
   It was not even a focus of particular French Resistance
activity. To this day it is not clear why the SS chose it.
<p>
   It may even have been targeted by mistake for a more remote,
mountainous Limousin village  &MD;  Oradour-sur-Vayres. It had merely
participated, as ever, in the events of its time.
<p>
   One becomes aware that the church that is now a shell was once a
fine 15th-century building and that the remains of several other
houses nearby show massive, ancient stonework.
<p>
   Inside the church the First World War memorial is intact: The
citizens who erected it may reasonably have felt that, with all
those young names, Oradour had paid its dues to fate.
<p>
   In a side chapel wall plaques offer thanks to Mary for specific
favors.
<p>
   Today a new Oradour stands on a slope above the old one. Built
in the early 1950s, it is architecturally banal, but pleasant
enough with its flowery central square, new mairie, post office,
church and shops.
<p>
   There is even a Hotel Milord again, its tables laid for lunch
under a leaf-shaded terrace.
<p>
   There is a store selling Limoges porcelain, and both the fancy
cake shop and the tobacconist stock souvenir plates.
<p>
   You can buy one painted with assorted ruins, but I was not
surprised to hear that the most popular line depicts traditional
scenes from life in Oradour before its destiny struck.
<p>
   -----
 &UR; SIDEBAR: THE OLD AND NEW VILLAGES &LR; 
 &UR; GETTING THERE &LR; 
<p>
   Oradour-sur-Glane is 12 1/2 miles from Limoges. If you are
driving, leave Limoges on the N141, in the direction of Angouleme,
fork right onto the D9.
<p>
   Or take a bus from Limoges at the bus station  &MD;  Gare Routiere  &MD; 
at the train station or at several other points in the city center.
It is the bus to St.-Junien, which extends its route at least once
a day both going and coming to make a detour via Oradour.
<p>
   The Tourist Office has timetables.
 &UR; WHAT TO SEE &LR; 
<p>
   The Limoges Tourist Office (the Syndicat d'Initiative) is on the
Boulevard de Fleurus, between the Place Jourdain and the Place
Wilson, open every day except Sunday from 9 a.m. to noon and 2 to
6:30 (to 8 p.m. in summer); telephone (33-5) 55.34.46.87.
<p>
   Some English is spoken. The office can advise on buses and also
on getting a local guide at Oradour.
<p>
   There are no organized tours of the village, but you can arrange
with one of the guides at the church to give you an account of what
happened, there and elsewhere.
<p>
   Request this in advance if you are taking a whole group or if
you want an English speaker.
<p>
   Otherwise, you can just turn up at Oradour and make your request
on the spot.
<p>
   The village normally opens soon after sunrise and does not shut
till dusk  &MD;  pedestrians only. Informative booklets are for sale in
several languages.
<p>
   The official history costs $7. A shortened, up-to-date version
is $4.
<p>
   Alternatively, you can go through the Syndicat d'Initiative in
the new village of Oradour  &MD;  apply to the mairie there; (33-5) 55
03 13 73.
<p>
   The small, semi-underground museum at Oradour is near the
cemetery gate. As befits the subject, it is more of a memorial than
a true museum, and has the atmosphere of a chapel crypt.
<p>
   Laid out in it are surviving small personal possessions of some
villagers and a little fire-tempered china and glass. Open usually
from 9 to noon and 2 to 6; closes earlier in winter.
 &UR; WHERE TO STAY AND EAT &LR; 
<p>
   Nothing is available in the ruins of Oradour, and you should not
bring food or drink.
<p>
   In the new village, a few hundred yards up the road, there are
several very reasonably priced hotels and cafes.
<p>
   These include Au Bon Accueil, 2 Place Charles de Gaulle,
telephone and fax (33-5) 55 03 26 56, in a secluded spot behind the
mairie, with rooms from $30 to $43.75, calculated at 5.03 francs to
$1, and a modestly priced restaurant.
<p>
   The Hotel Milord, 10 Avenue du 10 Juin 1944, (33-5) 55 03 10 35,
fax (33-5) 55 03 21 76, is on the road but has a delightful terrace
to one side. A double room with shower and telephone is $28. Meals
$19.50 to $37.75, plus a lunch special for $12.
<p>
   Or you can stay in Limoges or one of the other little towns in
the area. Several have small, family-run hotels that are part of
the highly recommendable Logis de France chain such as the Au
Rendez-vous des Chasseurs in St.-Junien at Le Pont a la Planche,
(33-5) 55 02 19 73, fax (33-5) 55 02 06 98, in a delightful setting
on the Vienne River. Double room with shower: $50.
<p>
   Not far from Oradour, Le Relais, 1 Place Royale, telephone and
fax (33-5) 55 68 12 09, has its own garden in a tiny village called
Mortemart; a double with shower is $40.
<p>
    &UR; (Gillian Tindall's ``Celestine: Voices From a French Village''
will be published in paperback in March by Owl Books.) &LR; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Gillian Tindall &LR;  &QC; 
