<STORYID cat=t pri=r sel=tab-z> A8630 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-KING-ARTHUR-MEETS-NEW </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1631 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-KING-ARTHUR-MEETS-NEW-AGE-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; KING ARTHUR MEETS THE NEW AGE &LR;  &QL; 
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package  &MD;  the rate
is not prohibitive  &MD;  contact one of the following sales
representatives:
   ( &MD;  U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
   ( &MD;  Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR; 
   ( &MD;  Latin America: PAUL FINCH in Los Angeles at (310) 996-0075;
fax: 310-996-0089.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; (-----They also have information on how to subscribe to ``WAY
TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers.-----) &LR; 
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice  &MD;  into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR; 
 &UR; By GEORGIANA HAVILL
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   At a pub in Exmouth, an English Channel town in West Devon, my
husband and I got into a debate with the local lads over whether
King Arthur was real or legendary.
<p>
   ``Arthur's real, mate,'' a college student said over Stilton
cheese and dark stout. ``Most of his Tintagel castle still stands
in Cornwall, and you can visit his grave at Glastonbury Abbey. He's
buried there alongside Guinevere.''
<p>
   For nearly a week last October Adrian and I had been aimlessly
touring the southwest coastal villages of England in a rented Ford
Fiesta.
<p>
   The night before, we'd been in Lyme Regis  &MD;  John Fowles country
 &MD;  where we had walked the famous stone Cobb to its end, the white
waves pounding spray against us as we re-created Meryl Streep's
vigil for her man in the movie version of Fowles's ``French
Lieutenant's Woman.''
<p>
   The wind was so high it was impossible to hold my camera steady.
A visit to Camelot in Cornwall seemed like a good idea until our
B&AMP;B proprietor warned us away.
<p>
   ``They've Disneyized Cornwall,'' he warned. ``They have model
villages that charge fees to walk the streets. And you should see
what they've done to Lands End. It's a shame. Head for Glastonbury.
That will be a revelation for you.''
<p>
   And so we did.
<p>
   The next day we pointed our little Ford north on the M-5 highway
and headed toward Glastonbury, a town of 9,000 people in Somerset
currently being heralded as the ``British Jerusalem,'' a mecca for
various religious persuasions.
<p>
   As soon as we entered the narrow main streets of Glastonbury we
began to suspect that we had happened on a place where hashish
might actually be easier to find than a cream tea.
<p>
   As we opened our car doors, we could smell cannabis in the air
just a few feet from the Tourist Information Center, wafting out of
a large knot of dreadlocked men and women and the type of youths we
used to call ``Yippies'' that I hadn't seen in such numbers since
the 1968 Democratic Convention.
<p>
   ``Now this is beginning to look interesting,'' my husband
murmured, peering into a shop named Majik and Cult that offered a
one-hour special involving lying under a pyramid on a magnetic bed
while being massaged with ``mystical crystals.''
<p>
   Glastonbury already was offering us a dizzying juxtaposition of
effects, especially after our drive through quaint British villages
with their hedge-shouldered roads, orderly pubs and tea shops
presided over by tweedy gray-haired ladies.
<p>
   The small inn near the tourist center was called the Hangman B &AMP;
B. The tourist center itself is in a grim 15th-century structure
called the Tribunal.
<p>
   There we learned what thousands of New Age pilgrims to
Glastonbury believe, to one degree or another:
<p>
    &MD;  Glastonbury Abbey, the first church to be built in the British
Isles (construction began in A.D. 63, legend has it) not only
contains the grave sites of King Arthur and Queen Guinevere, but
also, some assert, the remains of St. Patrick.
<p>
    &MD;  Glastonbury Abbey hired an architect, Bligh Bond, in 1908 to
excavate and find ``lost chapels.'' Bond not only found the chapels
but also said that a friend received messages in Latin from dead
monks through psychic communication.
<p>
    &MD;  According to plaques placed about the abbey, Joseph of
Arimathea arrived at Glastonbury in A.D. 37 and founded the abbey.
It is said that he brought with him vials containing the blood and
sweat of Jesus. Some Glastonbury pilgrims maintain that the Chalice
Well near the Abbey, where the water indeed appears red, has
healing properties.
<p>
   Near the Chalice Well, also called the Blood Spring, is the
mysterious Tor, a steep and treeless 540-foot tiered hill with its
eerie 14th-century St. Michael's tower at the top.
<p>
   After climbing the stone steps to the summit, some visitors,
according to a pamphlet at the visitors center, say they are able
to jump into the air and experience weightlessness. Others simply
lie on the top of the Tor and claim to levitate.
<p>
   I myself attempted a small leap when up on the Tor and indeed
felt slightly more buoyant  &MD;  but perhaps I was just getting the
drift of the ``holy weed'' being consumed to the left and right of
me. UFO sightings over the Tor are frequent.
<p>
   While these sights are the chief attractions, there is more at
Glastonbury. Since Druids used to worship oak trees and because
there are two oak trees named Gog and Magog on the way to the Tor,
it is not unusual to see a young Druid prostrate at the base of an
old oak.
<p>
   And at the Glastonbury Zodiac, a series of zodiac signs that are
supposedly delineated by streams, paths or streets, believers come
to ``walk their sign.''
<p>
   Other, even stranger attractions are totally unfathomable.
<p>
   Suffice to say, that in a small British town where Christians,
Hare Krishnas, Druids and Rastafarians walk side by side through
the narrow streets, we began to believe the barman who told us that
``living in Glastonbury is like being inside a pack of Tarot
cards.''
<p>
   Not knowing whether we'd encounter zealots or scoffers, we
entered the 35 acres of Glastonbury Abbey with some trepidation.
<p>
   We found both  &MD;  those who were willing to believe the wildest
legends and skeptics who jokingly asked ``Where is Elvis buried?''
<p>
   The abbey is an independent charitable trust. The trustees hedge
wherever they can, at one point referring to the occupant of its
most famous grave site as ``the semi-legendary King Arthur.''
<p>
   The tomb of Arthur is said to have been found by the monks in
1191, shortly after a fire and at a time when the brothers were
nearly destitute.
<p>
   Historians today suggest that the ``discovery'' of Arthur may
have been a way to promote pilgrimages, a sort of medieval tourism.
(``Poor Arthur,'' a local told us over lager and cheese, ``they've
moved his body in the night all over England, depending on who
needs visitors the most.'')
<p>
   The actual site is marked simply by a stone outline with a sign
explaining that King Edward I and Queen Eleanor witnessed the
moving of Arthur and Guinevere's bodies in April 1278 to a black
marble tomb in Glastonbury. That tomb survived until the
dissolution of the abbey in 1539.
<p>
   Whether their remains were near our feet or not, the ruins of
the old abbey were inspiring  &MD;  the graceful interior arches solid
against the sky.
<p>
   In one corner, next to a still-used St. Patrick's Chapel was a
large thorn tree, one of three in Glastonbury supposedly grown from
the original that sprang from the staff of Joseph of Arimathea.
<p>
   Believed to be native to Syria, it is said to have the type of
thorns with which Jesus was crowned. It flowers twice a year  &MD; 
during Christmas and Easter week  &MD;  and blossoms are promptly
delivered to the reigning British monarch and the Queen Mother.
<p>
   We walked from the abbey to the Chalice Well, a distance of
about half a mile. There is a scientific explanation for the color
and therapeutic value of the spring.
<p>
   The water has a high iron content, which accounts for its
apparent color and perhaps the reputed fertility for women.
<p>
   According to the Chalice Well Trust, the Celtics and Druids
likely looked upon the spring as a holy well, since the reddish hue
of the water suggests the blood of childbirth.
<p>
   As we left the Chalice Well grounds and headed up the steep hill
of the Tor, we noticed a series of tents in a fenced-off pasture
with about 50 people milling around.
<p>
   A surreal happening, the group included a fair-haired lass in a
sari, a kilted bagpiper, children with gaily painted faces prancing
about smoldering bonfires and a dog with pastel ashes on its feet
and muzzle.
<p>
   As we tried to understand what was going on, a jubilant
``crusader'' invited us to join in.
<p>
   It was, we were told, a Hindu wedding, and who could refuse an
invitation to the nuptials on what was turning out to be a most
extraordinary day.
<p>
    &UR; (Georgiana Havill, a free-lance writer, recently visited
England for the first time.) &LR; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Georgiana Havill &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
    -  -  -  -  -  -  -  &QC; 
