<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0078 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=t pri=r sel=tab-z> A8632 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SAVE-YOUR-BACK!-NYTSF </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1274 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SAVE-YOUR-BACK!-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BACK-SAVERS: HOW TO ENJOY A PAIN-FREE TRIP &LR;  &QL; 
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package  &MD;  the rate
is not prohibitive  &MD;  contact one of the following sales
representatives:
   ( &MD;  U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
   ( &MD;  Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR; 
   ( &MD;  Latin America: PAUL FINCH in Los Angeles at (310) 996-0075;
fax: 310-996-0089.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; -----FREE ART ... One color slide is available by mail (or
overnight delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number)
AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to purchasers of this article. Please specify
that you want the art when you order the article. ----- &LR; 
<p>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers.)
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice  &MD;  into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR; 
 &UR; By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   ``Man was never meant to walk upright,'' an orthopedist once
told us. ``When he stood up, that's when his back problems began.''
<p>
   We think when man began to travel, his back problems got even
worse. That certainly became true when he began flying around in a
one-size-fits-all airplane seat.
<p>
   We say ``man,'' because, statistically, far more men than women
develop lower-back pain  &MD;  problems ranging from arthritis to an
uppity disk.
<p>
   And more than half of us will develop some kind of back problem
by the time we're 60.
<p>
   Flying in an airplane is one of the worst things you can do to
your back. Airplane seats give such poor back support that you
might as well be sitting against a board.
<p>
   At least modern autos and first-class railroad seats have some
kind of lumbar support built in.
<p>
   TIP: When you walk onto the plane, reach up and get one of those
little white pillows. But don't use it for a headrest. Instead,
stuff it behind the small of your back before you strap yourself
in. Leave it there for the whole flight, whether you're sitting up
and eating or reclining and napping.
<p>
   At first, it may feel unnatural, even uncomfortable. But by the
time the plane has left the airport, the pillow will have fitted to
the shape of your back, and you'll forget it's there.
<p>
   Incidentally, those little inflatable horseshoe-shaped pillows
offer the best support for a restful snooze while your in flight.
 &UR; OTHER IN-FLIGHT BACK-SAVERS &LR; 
<p>
   Here are some ideas to help save your back during air travel:
<p>
    &UR;  &MD;  Get an aisle seat. &LR;  That gives you a few extra inches to do
shoulder shrugs, ankle twists, neck rolls and other range-of-motion
exercises. And do them every hour or so.
<p>
    &UR;  &MD;  Get up and walk around the airplane. &LR;  This works especially
well on one of the big planes with double aisles that they use for
overseas flights.
<p>
   You can loop the whole fuselage  &MD;  all four or five cabins  &MD; 
several times (maybe a quarter-mile walk) before the flight
attendant catches on. Take the stroll every couple of hours.
<p>
   Those bold individuals flying on a B-747 can get extra exercise
by rushing up and down the stairway.
<p>
   Dr. Susan Zahalsky, who works at the Midway Hospital Medical
Center in Los Angeles, has some other ideas to help your back when
you're high in the sky:
<p>
    &MD;  Elevating your feet so your knees are higher than your hips
relieves the strain on your lower back. If your seat doesn't have
an elevated footrest, ask the flight attendant for a stack of
magazines to put under your feet. Or prop your feet up by using a
carry-on bag.
<p>
    &MD;  While you're walking around the cabin, flex backward at the
waist several times. This straightens out your spine.
<p>
   And men should take their wallets out of their back pockets.
Prolonged sitting on such a lump can put pressure on the sciatic
nerve, causing back pain and sharp pains down your leg.
 &UR; DOWN-TO-EARTH BACK-SAVERS &LR; 
<p>
   Here are some other ideas that will prevent you from hurting
your back while you're on the road:
<p>
    &MD;  If you're on a train or bus, the same advice applies as for
travelers on planes: Keep the joints loose, and get up and walk
around whenever you can.
<p>
    &MD;  If you're driving a recreational vehicle or an auto, that's
even more important. Stop every two hours.
<p>
   Don't just start looking for a coffee shop  &MD;  every two hours,
pull off the side of the road and STOP.
<p>
   Get out, spend a few minutes walking around the car. Stretch
your arms, legs and back. Do whatever it takes to loosen up.
<p>
   This will not only keep your back in fairly good shape, it will
help keep you awake as well.
<p>
    &MD;  Pack lightly. Women, especially, have a hard time realizing
that the same people won't be seeing you at dinner night after
night. You can wear the same clothes.
<p>
   More importantly, don't pack more luggage than you can carry by
yourself  &MD;  even if ``porterage'' is included in your package trip,
never count on it. Invariably there will be a strike, a mix-up or
some other calamity, and you'll end up carting your own bags, as we
did once, almost a half-mile from the Venice railroad station to
the Grand Canal.
<p>
   And it's better to pack in two small bags rather than one large
one  &MD;  that way you can balance the load.
<p>
    &MD;  Wear a fannypack instead of carrying a purse.
<p>
   A purse, whether slung or hauled over one shoulder, will have
you leaning to one side before a long walking tour is over.
<p>
   On the other hand, a fannypack distributes the weight evenly
around your waist  &MD;  and it's better protection for your valuables.
<p>
   If you carry lots of heavy things in your purse, carrying them
in your fannypack may make you just as tired. But it won't make
your neck and back sore.
<p>
   And while you're on the road, baby your back just as you do at
home: Lift things from the knees, avoid soft chairs and deep
couches, don't lean across wide bathroom counters to shave and
don't bend over sinks to wash your hair.
<p>
   Whenever you travel, ask your doctor for a muscle relaxant to
take along. An aspirin is a good substitute, but don't use it like
candy.
<p>
   If back pain begins, take one instantly. Spend about 30 minutes
in the hottest tub you can stand to relieve any spasms. Then go to
bed and rest  &MD;  it may take a day or more in bed, but do it without
a whimper.
<p>
   After all, spending one day of your vacation to get your back
well can pay off if you can travel pain-free for the rest of your
life.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
 &UR; -----
<p>
    &UR; (The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.) &LR; 
