<DOCID> nyt970122.0079 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=ttx-z> A8643 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ONLINE-CHRISTIANS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0927 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-ONLINE-CHRISTIANS-TEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONLINE SERVICE AIMED AT CHRISTIAN USERS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LESLIE GORNSTEIN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   FORT WORTH, Texas  &MD;  Photos on the Planet Out Web page include
two men kissing and a pair of women embracing.
<p>
   The organization that runs the site is linked with some of the
most prominent gay and lesbian activist groups in the country,
including Queer Nation and the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force.
<p>
   But at the Kingdom, a new online service based in Fort Worth,
the site is banned. Owner Jerry Woods says www.planetout.com
attracts children and should be blocked from customers' view, along
with pornographic pages and foul chat language.
<p>
   ``If they took the picture off of two guys kissing, then shucks,
someone can read it to their heart's content,'' Woods says.
``Kissing isn't pornography, but we step into a different value
system when it is two people of the same sex.''
<p>
   The Kingdom's online service is aimed at Christian users and
people whom Woods describes as having family values. At barely more
than a year old, the tiny company of six employees has fewer than
250 subscribers, and some experts say it has picked a hard market
to reach. But Woods, who is an electrical engineer, and his wife,
Angela, who handles sales, say the business can weather the
increasing competition in cyberspace.
<p>
   It won't be easy, says Quentin Schultze, a communications
professor at Calvin College in Grand Rapids, Mich., and the author
of the book ``Internet for Christians.''
<p>
   ``Attempts have, in general, failed miserably,'' Schultze says.
``They have not been able to provide enough perceived value for
religious users compared with what is out there on the Net.''
<p>
   Woods came up with the idea for a family-oriented online system
after ``we prayed about it,'' he says. He also wanted a way to
spend time with Angela, whom he had married about two years
earlier.
<p>
   ``Look at her,'' Woods said, gesturing to a blushing Angela at a
recent lunch. ``She is beautiful. I wanted her around me all the
time.''
<p>
   He raised about $250,000, 90 percent of which came from
relatives and friends, and the rest of which came from the sale of
Coherent Light Services, a Fort Worth peripherals business he had
owned, Woods says.
<p>
   When he started the Kingdom, Woods had his hands full raising
three young daughters, including an infant, all by his first wife,
who died three years ago. Still, he set up the business in his busy
home, installing 50 phone lines and a high-speed access cable.
<p>
   Angela, whom he had met through the Calvary Cathedral in Fort
Worth, kept the girls quiet during conferences (''Sssh! Daddy's on
the phone!'') and marketing duties. She speaks mostly to women's
professional groups, whose members have been made anxious by news
reports about pornography and stalking online.
<p>
   ``Moms really make a lot of the buying decisions,'' Woods says.
<p>
   The company, which has since moved to an office in North
Richland Hills, offers not only original content, but also Internet
access. The Kingdom tracks and blocks more than 30,000 sites that
it classifies as obscene or conflicting with family values.
<p>
   The Kingdom also offers chat rooms and news groups on different
topics, including Christians in business and home schooling. It has
a children's area, which it calls Little Blessings, and a social
gathering place called the Hallelujah Cafe. Employees end phone
conversations with ``Bless you, goodbye!''
<p>
   A subscription, which includes unlimited access, costs $24.95 a
month. Prepaid, the service costs $12.50 a month.
<p>
   ``Cuss words'' are not allowed. Rival Internet providers often
discontinue the accounts of customers who broadcast pornography.
But users trying to access porn or funnel a four-letter word
through the Kingdom are sent a message saying such behavior is
prohibited.
<p>
   ``We are going to help you by making sure you are taken care
of,'' Woods says. ``We are not going to drive you out.''
<p>
   But Schultze says many Christian or family-oriented consumers
don't need a service like the Kingdom because of an existing
abundance of parental monitoring software. People who want to
protect their children can do it themselves and still get a choice
in online services, he says.
<p>
   ``They may be able to swing a great price,'' he says.
<p>
   The service is also withholding crucial information to a large
community by blocking such sites as Planet Out, says Mary Gray,
producer of the Planet Out chat area.
<p>
   Gray says she knows of no other services that block Planet Out,
which has received investment capital from America Online and is
promoted on the Microsoft Network.
<p>
   But she says, ``It is always a shame to hear about a service
that blocks vital information to people who otherwise can't get
that information.
<p>
   ``It is so hard for me to understand how, in their minds, it
crosses a boundary when you have two people in love kissing. It is
kind of beyond me.''
<p>
   Still, Woods says, the Kingdom provides a valuable service to
families who don't have the time or expertise to configure their
own monitoring software or constantly screen online content.
<p>
   The business also helps raise money for schools by letting
students sell Kingdom subscriptions, earning $20 per sign-up.
<p>
   ``We are blazing a trail,'' he says.
<p>
    &MD; 
<p>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.startext.net; www.arlington.net; and www.netarrant.net)
<p>
NYT-01-21-97 1841EST
</TEXT>
