<SLUG> BC-CPT-EARNS-IBM-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0450 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-EARNS-IBM-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IBM'S 4TH-QTR PROFIT UP 18% AS SALES RISE 5.6% &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Margaret D. Williams &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Armonk, New York, Jan. 21 (Bloomberg) -- International Business
Machines Corp.'s fourth-quarter profit rose a less-than-expected 18
percent as a stronger dollar and weak demand in Europe hurt
results.
<p>
   IBM said net income rose to $2.02 billion, or $3.93 a share,
from $1.71 billion, or $3.09 a share, in the year-earlier quarter.
Sales climbed 5.6 percent to $23.14 billion from $21.92 billion.
<p>
   Results were below the most recent estimate of $3.96 a share
from 15 analysts polled by IBES International Inc. Several analysts
had said they expected earnings of more than $4.00.
<p>
   ``We showed good growth in the fourth quarter despite a
difficult year-over-year comparison, continued weakness in Europe
and a greater-than-expected currency impact,'' Chairman and Chief
Executive Louis Gerstner said in a statement.
<p>
   IBM's stock rose 1 to 168. Results were released after the close
of trading. The stock has climbed to its highest levels in almost
10 years and is just shy of its all-time high of 174 3/4 reached in
August 1987.
<p>
   IBM said revenue was slightly lower than expected because of
slack demand in Europe and a bigger-than-expected impact from a
stronger dollar.
<p>
   Currency cost the company 3 percentage points of revenue growth,
or 18 cents a share in earnings, in the fourth quarter, IBM said. A
year ago, currency had a 2 percentage point positive impact.
<p>
   On a constant currency basis, Gerstner said IBM's revenue rose 9
percent, its best showing since 1985.
<p>
   IBM's gross profit margin narrowed to 40.3 percent from 41.7
percent in the year-earlier period. Gross margin is the percentage
of sales remaining after the costs of manufacturing are subtracted.
<p>
   Services was a bright spot, with sales up 22 percent to $5.0
billion.
<p>
   Hardware sales edged up 2 percent to $11.7 billion, with
personal computer sales rising from the year-ago quarter in both
corporate products and home machines. System 390 sales declined and
RS/6000 workstation sales were unchanged from year-earlier levels.
<p>
   Software revenue increased 4 percent to $3.7 billion.
<p>
   IBM Microelectronic revenue declined, and the company said price
drops and weak demand in dynamic random-access memory hurt those
results. Still, the company said it remains optimistic about its
prospects for this year.
<p>
   ``I feel pretty good about 1997. We face strong product demand
for all product lines,'' said Chief Financial Officer Richard
Thoman in a conference with analysts.
<p>
