<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A8646 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETNEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0764 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-NETNEWS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ON THE INTERNET, THEY TALK OF BAD COMMERCIALS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Charles Stough is an editor at the Dayton (Ohio) Daily News) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By CHARLES STOUGH &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Sorry, Munchkins, as annual TV events go, the array of
commercials in the Super Bowl broadcast are quickly coming to rival
even The Wizard of Oz as audience draws. Plus, oh yeah, the
football.
<p>
   And why not? For establishing Apple as the anti-establishment
multinational computer company, or making frogs the spokesmodels of
Budweiser, there is no venue like the Bowl. If the true football
fans are draining municipal water systems during the timeouts,
it'll be the ad professionals making hurried toilet stops during
the third-and-short plays.
<p>
   Madison Avenue airs its best stuff for the Super Bowl. But
enough of that. This is about the bad commercials.
<p>
   For advertising professionals gather in a little-known corner of
the Internet's discussion forums, the Usenet newsgroup
alt.tv.commercials. And there recently they, plus students and
members of the consuming public, shared dishonors for what they
consider the worst commercials on TV.
<p>
   For example, Calvin Klein's spots. What is he trying to tell us
with those hollow-eyed, anorexic models and their letter-bomb
hairstyles? Are potential buyers supposed to identify with runaways
and flee to the upscale boutiques where all the runaways buy their
$50 colognes? ``These are scary commercials, any way you look at
it,'' a Usenet contributor said. ``I sure hope Calvin Klein doesn't
write a book.''
<p>
   And another laureate was the Bagel Bites ads with the basic
pitch, ``Now the kids can have pizza whenever they want, when they
eat our product ... delicious pizzas on wholesome little bagels!''
<p>
   As a contributor said, ``English translation: `Look! We've found
a new way to palm our processed meat/cheese by-products on the
public by slapping it on some toast, and telling the people that
they can eat it whenever they want because ... IT'S WHOLESOME!'''
<p>
   ``I think the irritating implication here is that `when pizza's
on a bagel, you can eat pizza anytime!' replied another user. `If I
put chocolate mousse on a bagel, can I eat it anytime?''
<p>
   Then there was the mini-waffle product with the syrup and butter
baked right in, the farmer's friend because he doesn't have time to
adorn proper waffles with the right amount of fat and sugar. So why
doesn't he get up with his wife, who apparently beat him to the
kitchen by hours, or his son, who's out in the barn doing the
milking already?
<p>
   Oh dear, next is General Motors. Well, let the critics tell it:
<p>
   ``The commercial that really irritates me is the Saturn
commercial in which Julie gets her first car,` one participant
said. `It makes it look like Saturn is helping Julie move out of
public housing. Wait'll Julie gets her first insurance bill or,
here in Virginia, pays her first personal property tax.''
<p>
   ``Yeah,'' chimed in another critic. ``You would think her new
Saturn had just been built by a special branch of Habitat for
Humanity that builds cars for people who can't afford one.''
<p>
   ``To me, its the music that I find most irritating about this
commercial,'' said another. ``Kind of a `sorry, your wife died in
childbirth delivering this beautiful baby' feel to it, if you ask
me.''
<p>
   The latest dead-star ad, using Fred Astair with a Dirt Devil
vacuum cleaner morphed into the action, is getting loud hoots on
the commercialism-vs.-morality front. ``I can understand John Wayne
for beer, but Fred Astaire with a VACUUM CLEANER?'' they wonder.
<p>
   But then there are the favorites, too, and in
alt.tv.commercials. they like the latest series of Snickers candy
bar spots. One has the groundskeeper painstakingly painting the end
zone until a player says, ``Nice work, but who are the Chefs?'' And
the injured and benched player who thinks he's Batman. And of
course everyone's favorite, the long line of clergymen pronouncing
the pregame prayers (``Thanks, Bagwan, that was very touching.
Next,'' says the coach).
<p>
   The lineup for the Super Bowl ads will be as prayerful as that
patient team's, and the ad critics will be lined up patiently too
-for the station breaks.
<p>
   Usenet newsgroups are accessible with modem-equipped computers;
consult local Internet service providers for instructions and
groups available. Charles Stough is an editor for the Dayton (Ohio)
Daily News. His electronic address is copyboy(at)dma.org.
<p>
