<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=ttj-z> A8647 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-TALES-H </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0800 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-TALES-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOLKTALES, SCRAPBOOKS, FOLK TALES GO GOES HIGH-TECH WITH LAPTOP &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By TOM ABATE &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SAN FRANCISCO  &MD;  The San Francisco Digital Media Center has put a
new spin on the age-old practice of telling stories around the
campfire.
<p>
   Run by artists Dana Atchley, Joe Lambert and Nina Mullen, the
center teaches people how to use computer software to turn their
family pictures and mementos into multimedia stories.
<p>
   ``We teach people how to use new computer tools to do things
people have been doing since the dawn of time, which is to tell
stories,'' Atchley said.
<p>
   As a printer, performer and broadcast producer, Atchley has been
telling stories for more than 25 years. The Digital Media Center,
which he runs with Lambert and Mullen, holds weekend classes to
impart some of what he has learned about the computer tools and
techniques of editing pictures, film clips and audio recordings.
<p>
   The objective of the $325 classes is to teach novices how to
meld narratives and photographs with sound and video. Participants
leave the workshop with a three- to five-minute story that is
dubbed onto a videotape so they can share it with family and
friends.
<p>
   ``About 75 percent of the students are women,'' said Mullen.
``That's because women tend to be the people who collect the
scrapbooks and the photos and are the keepers of the family
history.''
<p>
   In addition to weekend classes, the center holds $20 dinners
that show off multimedia art. Thursday, for instance, the center
will present Mauve Desert, a CD-ROM created by Los Angeles artist
Adriene Jenik. It revolves around a teenage girl's rebellious
psyche.
<p>
   The Digital Media Center is only one of several places in the
Bay Area where people can get intensive training in how to use new
computer tools to create multimedia.
<p>
   A partial list of such training centers would include the Bay
Area Video Coalition, the Media Alliance, San Francisco State
University's Multimedia Studies Program, the Kala Institute in
Berkeley, the Digiquest Learning Center in Marin County, United
Digital Artists in Burlingame and the extension program at Cal
State Hayward.
<p>
   But Lambert, of the S.F. Digital Media Center, said the most
important aspect of any training program was not the technology but
the technique of telling a story.
<p>
   ``What we have to overcome is everybody's fear of the vacation
slide show that goes on forever,'' Lambert said. ``Part of what we
do is make you comfortable with the technology, but the important
thing is choose a story line. That becomes the way you select what
gets in and what gets left out.''
<p>
   The center, which was founded in 1993 and has struggled along
ever since, has recently branched out into using the Internet as a
way to share personal stories. As such, it has become part of a
growing artistic and journalistic movement in The City that seeks
to counter the commercialization of the World Wide Web with stories
of personal or political significance.
<p>
   One example of this is the home page that San Francisco artist
Abbe Don created to tell the stories of her mother, grandmother and
great-grandmother (see www.bubbe.com). The page opens with a visit
to Bubbe's ``back porch,'' where her family's stories are told. The
site also contains tips for creating a family Web page and links to
other family history pages as a source of inspiration and ideas.
<p>
   On a more political bent, San Francisco photojournalist Tripp
Mikich has been putting documentary photography and audio
recordings on the FocalPoint f/8 Web site (www.f8.com). One of his
collaborators, Gary Matoso, recently pushed the concept of
Web-based stories further in a project called ``Roads to Refuge.''
<p>
   Supported in part by the United Nations High Commission on
Refugees, Matoso has created three-dimensional views of refugee
camps in Bosnia and Mali that can be viewed over the Web (see
www.worldmedialive.com).
<p>
   But all the practitioners of these new digital arts share a
common concern: that the technology not become more important than
the story.
<p>
   ``What exciting is that computer tools now let us do what only
professional video editors could do five or six years ago,''
Atchley said.
<p>
   Just as copy machines and desktop publishing made it easier for
people to get their words into print, Atchley said the new
multimedia tools would enable people to blend sounds and pictures.
<p>
   ``That's what I've been working for all these years, to find
ways for people to tell their own stories instead of waiting for
the networks to tell them for us,'' he said.
<p>
   For more information about the San Francisco Digital Media
Center call (415) 824-9394.
<p>
