<SLUG> BC-CPT-DIGITAL-EQUIPMENT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0264 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CPT-DIGITAL-EQUIPMENT-SUIT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DEC WINS A CHANCE TO SHRINK $5.93 MLN KEYBOARD-INJURY VERDICT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Betsy Jelisavcic &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 21 (Bloomberg) -- Digital Equipment Corp. will
get a chance to reduce a $5.93 million jury award to three women
claiming injuries from repeated use of Digital's keyboards.
<p>
   U.S. District Judge Jack Weinstein today granted the Maynard,
Massachusetts-based computer maker's request for a hearing to
reduce the award. The hearing is expected later this month or in
early February.
<p>
   A federal jury on Dec. 4 ordered Digital to pay $5.35 million to
Patricia Geressy, $306,000 to Jill M. Jackson, and $278,000 to
Jeanette Rotolo. The Brooklyn jury found that Digital failed to
warn them of injuries they could suffer from repeated use of
Digital's LK 201 keyboards.
<p>
   It was the first jury award for people claiming injuries from
repeated keyboard use. Before the verdict against Digital, computer
makers had won 21 of 22 repetitive-stress suits from jury verdicts
and other rulings on the evidence.
<p>
   The one previous loss for the industry was an $85,000 award to a
woman who had worked with a bar-code scanner.
<p>
   More than 2,000 keyboard-injury suits are pending against
computer makers.
<p>
   When Digital argues to reduce the $5.93 million award, it should
have product-liability lawyers compare jury awards against
manufacturers for similar injuries, Judge Weinstein said during a
hearing today in Brooklyn.
<p>
