<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tad-z> A8665 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS-2ndtak </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0919 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS-2ndtake-COX &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: flavored product. &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Q: I'm reminded of the old ``rat pack,'' that Frank Sinatra used
to lead. Who were its members? Didn't they make some movies?
<p>
   A: In addition to Sinatra, the bon-vivant group of Hollwood
actors in the ``pack'' included Joey Bishop, Tony Curtis, Sammy
Davis Jr., Peter Lawford, Dean Martin and Henry Silva. Various
members appeared in several movies together, including ``Oceans
Eleven`` (Warner, 1960), ``Sergeants Three'' (United Artists,
1962), ``Johnny Cool'' (United Artists, 1963), ``Robin and the
Seven Hoods'' (Warner, 1964), ``Salt and Pepper'' (United Artists,
1968) and ``One More Time'' (United Artists, 1970). Actress Shirley
MacLaine also has been mentioned as an occasional rat packer, but
she wasn't in the core group.
<p>
   Q: Will you refresh my memory about the ethics charges against
former House Speaker Jim Wright that resulted in his resignation?
<p>
   A: Wright (D-Texas), who was elected to the House in 1954,
became majority leader in 1976 and served as speaker from 1987 to
1989, resigned as speaker and as a member of Congress after the
House Committee on Standards of Official Conduct accused him of
breaking a number of House ethics rules. One charge was that he had
accepted about $145,000 worth of gifts from a Texas real estate
developer who was in a position to benefit directly from
legislation over which Wright had influence. The committee also
accused Wright of earning more income from outside sources than
House rules permitted by disguising it as earnings from the sale of
Wright's book, ``Reflections of a Public Man.'' Other improprieties
included Wright's reported use of a Dallas businessman's jet for a
three-day campaign trip in Texas in 1985; his insertion into the
Congressional Record of remarks promoting a videotape program being
sold by Pacific Institute, a Seattle company that was paying his
wife a $36,000 annual salary; and the payment by 10 special
interest groups of as much as $30,000 each to a longtime Wright
associate to fund opinion polls. On June 30, 1989, little more than
six weeks after the committee had charged him with 69 violations,
Wright announced his decision to step down.
<p>
   Q: What is the Navy's policy about burial at sea for someone who
once served in the Navy? Where is such burial done?
<p>
   A: The Burial at Sea program is open to active duty personnel,
retirees and honorably discharged members of the uniformed services
and their bona fide dependents. The Navy uses six major ports of
embarkation for the Burial at Sea program: Norfolk, Va.; Newport,
R.I., Jacksonville, Fla.; San Diego, Calif.; Bremerton, Wash.; and
Hawaii. For an information packet, call the Office of
Medical/Dental Affairs, Mortuary Affairs Branch, at 800-876-1131,
Ext. 603, 644 or 629.
<p>
   Q: At the sound of the closing bell of the New York Stock
Exchange, people in the balcony can be seen hammering the gavel.
Who are they?
<p>
   A: Most are trading floor managers, said Ray Pellecchia of the
NYSE, who hammer the gavel on a rotating system. They also open the
stock exchange. Heads of newly listed companies, retiring members
of the NYSE and visiting heads of state also get the honor,
Pellecchia said.
<p>
   Q: Has anyone been executed for the 1973 Alday family murders in
South Georgia?
<p>
   A: No. Carl Isaacs, one of three men convicted and sentenced to
death for the murders of six members of the Ned Alday family in
Seminole County, Ga., remains on death row where he continues to
appeal his sentence. The other two convicted killers, Wayne Carl
Coleman and George Dungee, had their death penalties overthrown in
1985 when the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals granted all three men a
new trial. They are currently serving multiple life sentences in
prison.
<p>
   Q: What is the origin of the expression ``caught red-handed''?
<p>
   A: In ancient times, ``to be taken with red hand'' was to be
caught in the act, like a murderer whose hands were dripping with
the victim's blood. The use of red hand in this sense dates to
15th- century Scotland and Scottish law. Sir Walter Scott's
``Ivanhoe'' contained an early print reference of ``taken
red-handed,'' meaning someone apprehended in the act of committing
a crime. It evolved into ``caught red-handed.''
<p>
   Q: Since Newt Gingrich's telephone conversation was apparently
intercepted illegally, are newspapers that publish the information
leaving themselves open for a lawsuit?
<p>
   A: Atlanta Journal-Constitution editors say the newspaper
violated no law in coming into possession of a copy of the cellular
conversation. An attorney for The New York Times, which also
obtained a copy of the tape, was asked much the same question.
George Freeman, an assistant general counsel for the Times, said:
``It has been a longstanding journalistic tradition, as well as
Supreme Court law, that the press may publish truthful and
newsworthy information it lawfully obtains.''
<p>
   Q: When will the knighting ceremonies for Paul McCartney be held
in London? Will they be open to the public? Where can fans write
him?
<p>
   A: No date has been announced. The Buckingham Palace ceremonies
will be at a mutually agreeable time to McCartney and the palace,
and they will be private, according to the British Embassy in
Washington. Such ceremonies often aren't even announced until after
the fact. Write to Paul McCartney, c/o MPL Communication Ltd., 1
Soho Square, London, England, W1V 6BQ. .
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
    &UR; MORE &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
