<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tad-z> A8667 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS-3rdtak </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0973 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS-3rdtake-COX &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: England, W1V 6BQ. &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Q: When one TV station goes to commercials and I switch
channels, I find commercials on the next one, too. Is that dictated
locally, or by the Federal Communications Commission?
<p>
   A: There's no law or rule governing when commercials are shown,
and they don't always run at the same time. You're probably
switching channels at the bottom of the hour, when programs end and
commercials begin. But programs on other channels end then, too,
and those stations also are going to commercials. It's not as
likely to happen within the shows, but most 30- minute situation
comedies are written for two commercial breaks, and it's possible
that they could occur at the same time as you switch from one
station to the next.
<p>
   Q: How did the Social Security's ``notch baby'' situation come
about, resulting in lowered Social Security payments for people
born in certain years? What administration did this to us?
<p>
   A: The notch baby issue is widely misunderstood, according to
the Social Security Administration. The agency insists it was not a
plan to give some people less money in benefits than they are
entitled to. To the contrary, the purpose of the 1977 legislation
correcting the benefit formula was to pay people benefits that are
``fair and appropriate.'' While it's true that some people receive
benefits smaller than others who had similar earnings but who were
born a year or two earlier, the alleged ``victim'' is receiving the
proper benefits, while the person receiving more is getting an
unintendended windfall, according to Social Security.
<p>
   The ``notch''  &MD;  the difference in payment rates to people born
between 1917 and 1921, and those paid to people born before then  &MD; 
was created by an act of Congress in 1977. The corrected formula
applies to people born in 1917 and afterward. Benefits for everyone
born from 1922 on are calculated using only the correct 1977
formula, the Social Security Administration says.
<p>
   Q: I'd like to write to members of the Oakland, Calif., school
board to express my opinion on the Ebonics issue. Do you have an
address?
<p>
   A: Oakland Unified School District, Board of Education, 1025
Second Ave., Room 320, Oakland, Calif. 94606.
<p>
   Q: In a recent radio broadcast, Paul Harvey referred to
hydrazine sulfate as a promising cancer-fighting medication. It
didn't sound like a commercial. How can I get more information?
<p>
   A: A spokeswoman for Paul Harvey News in Chicago said you need
to send a stamped, self-addressed envelope along with your request
for information to Dr. Joseph Gold, Syracuse Cancer Research
Institute, 600 E. Genesee St., Syracuse, N.Y. 13202. There's also a
web site on the Internet with extensive information:
www.ngen.com/hf-cancer .
<p>
   Q: I've heard that 40 percent of all Social Security payments go
to people whose average age is 30. Is this true?
<p>
   A: No way, says the Social Security Administration, although no
breakdown by ``average age'' is available. Last year, 45 million
people received benefits, said Patti Patterson, agency spokeswoman.
Of those, 32.3 million were 65 or older. So 12.7 million recipients
were younger than 65, and that entire group would constitute less
than 40 percent. Of the 7 million survivors of eligible
wage-earners who received benefits, 3.1 million were children,
Patterson said.
<p>
   Q: How can I write the Florida couple who taped Newt Gingrich's
cell phone conversation?
<p>
   A: Mail for Alice and John Martin can be sent to their attorney,
Larry Turner, 204 W. University Ave., Suite 6, Gainesville, Fla.
32601.
<p>
   Q: I once read an article about pet insurance, but the
veterinarians I have contacted don't have any information. Have
you?
<p>
   A: You're talking about Veterinary Pet Insurance of Anaheim,
Calif., which describes itself as the leading U.S. insurer of pets.
Founded in 1980, the company underwrites about 75,000 dogs and cats
and is licensed in 45 states (including Georgia). VPI has five
accident and illness plans with varying deductibles and premiums.
Major Medical Plan 40, for example, with a $40 deductible, has
annual premiums of $49 for puppies and kittens, $59 for pets 1 to 4
years old, and $79 for those 5 to 8. Subject to policy terms, the
insurance covers office calls, injections, prescriptions,
treatments, lab fees, X-rays, surgery and hospitalization.
Information: 800-872-7387.
<p>
   Q: What is the status of Loretta Sanchez, who won a hotly
contested race in California for the House seat held by Bob Dornan?
What was the vote recount?
<p>
   A: Sanchez was sworn into office when the 105th Congress
convened Jan. 8, but her election to represent California's 46th
Congressional District is still being challenged. The fight over
the results of the Nov. 6 election probably will continue through
January, and maybe beyond. After a recount requested by Dornan
showed Sanchez won by 979 votes, Dornan said he plans to contest
the election before a state court judge. Dornan's lawyer, Michael
Schroeder, said the figures don't add up. A review of voter sign-in
rosters, the machine count of ballots and a computer tape of the
election prepared later by registration clerks shows 1,985 more
ballots cast than reflected on sign-in sheets, Schroeder said. In
addition, he said, Dornan researchers identified 100 people who
voted twice, 200 people who had someone other than immediate family
turn in absentee ballots to voting places, and about 75 voters who
registered at business addresses, which is improper. Official vote
totals after the recount: Sanchez, Democrat, 48,056; Dornan,
Republican, 47,077; Lawrence Stafford, Reform, 3,232; Thomas
Reimer, Libertarian, 2,337; J. Carlos Aguirre, Natural Law, 1,972.
.
</TEXT>
