<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=tad-z> A8670 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MINI-REVIEWS-(5takes) </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0859 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MINI-REVIEWS-(5takes)-COX &QL; 
 &UR; CAPSULE REVIEWS OF CURRENT FILMS &QC; 
 &UR; c.1996 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   These brief reviews of current movies are written, unless
otherwise noted, by Cox News Service movie critic Eleanor Ringel.
They move weekly to clients of the New York Times News Service.
<p>
   G: General audiences. Nothing that would offend parents if
viewed by children.
<p>
   PG: Parental guidance suggested. May contain some material
parents consider inappropriate for young children.
<p>
   PG-13: Parents strongly cautioned. Some material may be
inappropriate for preteens.
<p>
   R: Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian.
Parents are urged to learn more about the film before taking
children.
<p>
   NC-17: No one under 17 admitted. Replaces the X rating.
<p>
   NR: Not rated.
<p>
   The Associate PG-13
<p>
   Cute but rarely flat-out funny, this Whoopi Goldberg vehicle
boasts one giddy gimmick: Its star is made up to look like a white
man. Goldberg plays a gifted New York financial analyst who creates
a fictitious male partner in order to gain admittance into Wall
Street's big money boys' club. The movie suffers from several
logical leaps, and Goldberg's performance at times seems phoned in.
But the sight of her as a man  &MD;  she's like a rubberized Marlon
Brando  &MD;  is almost worth the ticket price. Rated PG-13 for language
and suggestive scenes. 1 hour, 54 minutes.
<p>
   Beavis and Butt-head Do America PG-13
<p>
   MTV's Beavis and Butt-head became a successful media franchise
by embodying and satirizing rock video's saturation of America's
suburban adolescent imagination; it's a cartoon that celebrates
anti-social mayhem and slackerdom and smart-mouthing. Blown up for
the big screen, none of this seems unique. The funniest bits in
``Beavis and Butt-head Do America'' are only that. Bits. The
road-movie concept, which has the clueless duo wreaking havoc from
coast to coast, is running on fumes within an hour. Rated PG-13 for
suggestive humor. 1 hour, 22 minutes.
<p>
   The Crucible PG-13
<p>
   Casts a powerful spell. Daniel Day-Lewis, Winona Ryder, Joan
Allen and Paul Scofield star in this tour-de-force adaptation of
Arthur Miller's play about the Salem, Mass., witch trials in 1692.
Directed by Nicholas Hytner, this is ferocious, impassioned
filmmaking at its finest, as well as a timely reminder that
scoundrel times can happen any time. Rated PG- 13 for brief nudity
and adult themes. 2 hours, 3 minutes.
<p>
   Daylight PG- 13
<p>
   Now age 50 and knowing his days of playing beefcake brawlers a
la Rambo are numbered, Sylvester Stallone invests the hero of his
latest action- adventure movie with a touch of humanity. As
disgraced paramedic Kit Latura, who stages a daring rescue attempt
in a collapsed New York tunnel, Stallone wrestles with self-doubt
and old demons. He cries and compromises. He wears chinos, for
crying out loud. Alas, the silly, slam-bang movie around him is
still wearing ammo belts and communicating in grunts. Rated PG-13
for violence and language. 1 hour, 50 minutes.
<p>
   The English Patient R
<p>
   An elusive, eloquent and sweepingly romantic epic that mixes the
old-fashioned grandeur of a David Lean film with the sort of
fragmented narrative that presumes an audience well-versed in MTV.
Based on the Michael Ondaatje prize- winning novel, the movie
shifts between an abandoned monastery in Tuscany and the Tunisian
desert. In the present, i.e., the waning days of World War II, a
mysterious and hideously scarred burn patient (Ralph Fiennes) is
tended to by an Allied nurse (a radiant Juliette Binoche).
Meanwhile, morphine-induced oases of memory take us back to his
buried past  &MD;  as a mapmaker in prewar North Africa who falls for a
married woman (Kristin Scott Thomas). Deftly interweaving several
stories into a poetic, elliptical mosaic of love, war, passion and
tragedy, Minghella's movie touches us as all great movies must  &MD; 
truly, madly, deeply. Rated R for sex, violence and nudity. 2
hours, 40 minutes.
<p>
   The Evening Star PG-13
<p>
   About half as good as ``Terms of Endearment''. . . which isn't
such a bad thing when you think about it. For those who care to
catch up with Aurora Greenway 15 years later, it'll feel like old
home week. But if you thought James L. Brooks' Oscar-sweeping
laugh-and-cry fest was a unique, complete experience, you can skip
the sequel. 2 hours, 9 minutes.
<p>
   Evita PG
<p>
   It keeps its promise. Don't keep your distance. Director Alan
Parker has shrewdly turned Andrew Lloyd Webber and Tim Rice's
all-singing rock opera about Eva Peron into a music-video epic.
Madonna gives a charismatic performance as a small-town woman of
dubious reputation who became the most powerful woman in '40s
Argentina. Jonathan Pryce, as dictator/President Juan Peron, and
Antonio Banderas, as a kind of Argentinian Everyman, provide
excellent support. 2 hours, 13 minutes.
<p>
   Fierce Creatures PG-13
<p>
   The stars of the comedy classic ``A Fish Called Wanda''  &MD; 
including Jamie Lee Curtis, Kevin Kline and John Cleese  &MD;  reunite
as all new characters in this farce about efforts to save a failing
London zoo. 
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
