<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MINI-REVIEWS-(2ndtake)-COX &QL; 
 &UR; undated &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The First Wives Club PG
<p>
   An eager-to-please farce starring Goldie Hawn, Diane Keaton and
Bette Midler as middle-aged Manhattanites who've been discarded by
their husbands for younger models (Elizabeth Berkley and a
hilarious Sarah Jessica Parker). Brought together by the suicide of
a fourth friend (an unbilled Stockard Channing), the trio plots
revenge  &MD;  or justice, as they insist  &MD;  on their erring exes. Much
like the 1980 hit ``9 to 5,'' this make-nice movie starts sharp,
smart and nasty, then turns broad and unthreatening. Yes, it's
often very funny, but it's also frightened of its own shadow.
Still, it gives you your money's worth in wonderful comic acting.
These women are irrepressible and irreplaceable.
<p>
   Fly Away Home PG
<p>
   A first-class flight. To help a flock of orphaned Canada geese
migrate south, a sculptor-inventor (Jeff Daniels) teaches his
adolescent daughter (Oscar winner Anna Paquin) how to pilot a small
aircraft, then encourages her to fly solo. Yes, the premise veers
dangerously close to the real-life tragedy of Jessica Dubroff, the
7-year-old who crashed and died in April during a cross-country
solo flight. But in the sure hands of director Carroll Ballard
(``The Black Stallion''), this ``crazy idea'' becomes an uplifting
symbol of father-daughter bonding and environmental activism. Rated
PG for mild language and adult themes.
<p>
   The Garden of the Finzi-Continis R
<p>
   Hauntingly powerful. Spruced up with a new print and improved
sound in honor of its 25th anniversary, Vittorio De Sica's
late-in-life masterpiece won an Oscar in 1971 for best
foreign-language film. A wealthy, aristocratic Jewish family living
in Italy in the '30s refuses to hear  &MD;  or perhaps, cannot hear  &MD; 
the ominous approach of Hitler's Holocaust. Dominique Sanda plays
their lovely, imperious daughter. Rated R for nudity and adult
themes. In Italian with English subtitles. 1 hour, 35 minutes. 
<p>
   Get on the Bus R
<p>
   Issue-conscious director Spike Lee returns with his best movie
in years. Contrary to its billing, this film about a group of black
men riding into history is less about the destination  &MD;  the Million
Man March  &MD;  than the journeys each man made before he got on the
bus to Washington. Until this movie, Lee had not been successful at
tackling a variety of issues without leaving the audiences with
just as many questions. That's not the case here. The actors in the
ensemble cast brilliantly depict the fathers, former gang members
and homosexuals who join for the historic trip.
<p>
   Ghosts of Mississippi PG-13
<p>
   A true story that needs to be told. Rob Reiner's social drama
stars Alec Baldwin as the Mississippi prosecutor who, despite
considerable opposition, re-opened the case of slain civil-rights
activist Medgar Evers 30 years after his murder. James Woods has a
fine time as the Mean Ol' Boy killer, but Reiner encourages Whoopi
Goldberg, as Evers' determined widow, to act like a solemn cypher.
Rated PG-13 for violence, language and adult themes. 2 hours, 3
minutes.
<p>
   Hamlet PG-13
<p>
   Kenneth Branagh directed and stars in the first film version of
Shakespeare's immortal tragedy in its entirety (the movie's four
hours long). The wildly diverse cast ranges from the obvious (Kate
Winslet as Ophelia) to the eccentric (Jack Lemmon as Marcellus). 
<p>
   Jackie Chan's First Strike PG-13
<p>
   In a Jackie Chan flick, the last thing you worry about is the
plot. Our amiable cop hero Jackie (Chan) goes from Hong Kong to the
snowy Ukraine and from there to sunny Australia (via Moscow, no
less), propelled by mumbo jumbo about the CIA, the KGB, a stolen
tank of uranium. But what really matters is when he picks up a pair
of stilts, a couple of brooms or a folding aluminum ladder to fight
the bad dudes. Mixing the little-guy persona of Chaplin, the
courteous grace of Astaire and the high kicks of Lee (Bruce, that
is), Chan's athletic feats gain extra power from our knowing that
he does the stunts himself. His new film doesn't top any of the
stunts from his earlier Hong Kong films, but it's an
adrenalin-laced bonbon. 1 hour, 28 minutes.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
    &UR; MORE &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
