<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=tad-z> A8673 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MINI-REVIEWS-(3rdtake </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0930 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MINI-REVIEWS-(3rdtake)-COX &QL; 
 &UR; undated &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Jerry Maguire R
<p>
   Hollywood's top gun Tom Cruise plays a slick sports agent who
loses everything he thinks is important  &MD;  his job, his
prestigiously beautiful fiancee, the respect of his colleagues  &MD; 
only to find what really matters  &MD;  human connection and the love of
a good woman. Writer-director Cameron Crowe dealt with the theme of
redemption through love more succinctly in his acclaimed film ``Say
Anything . . . '' and Cruise's gutsy performance has one too many
big, actor-ly moments. Still, there is plenty about the movie that
is moving and entertaining, chiefly Renee Zellweger's portrayal of
Cruise's loyal, loving assistant. Rated R for sex, language and
adult themes. 2 hours, 15 minutes.
<p>
   Jingle All the Way PG
<p>
   Sugar-coated crud. Arnold Schwarzenegger stars as a workaholic
dad whose last chance to redeem himself with his little boy
(adorable Jake Lloyd) is to get the kid the Holy Grail of Christmas
gifts  &MD;  a Turbo Man action figure. But since the stores have been
sold out since Labor Day, it becomes a Herculean effort. Alas,
``Jingle'' is pure junk  &MD;  a loud, crass miscalculation that
squanders its star's considerable charm and obliterates a promising
supporting cast (Sinbad, Phil Hartman, Rita Wilson). It makes the
star's previous misstep, ``The Last Action Hero,'' look like
``Schindler's List.'' Rated PG for mi ld violence. 1 hour, 30
minutes.
<p>
   Mars Attacks! PG-13
<p>
   Close encounters of the Tim Burton kind. In this spacey sci-fi
spoof, little green guys from the angry red planet attack an
all-star cast ranging from Jack Nicholson as the president of the
United States to Tom Jones as, well, Tom Jones. You'll never look
at ``Independence Day'' in quite the same way. Rated PG-13 for
violence. 1 hour, 43 minutes.
<p>
   Marvin's Room PG-13
<p>
   Meryl Streep and Diane Keaton make sisterhood powerful in this
adaptation of Scott McPherson's humorous and poignant play about
terminal disease and dysfunctional families. Director Jerry Zaks
brings a too-heavy hand to the proceedings, but the powerhouse cast
(add Robert De Niro, Gwen Verdon, Leonardo DiCaprio) takes over.
Streep and Keaton are especially fine; their scenes together are a
study in contrasting yet complementary acting styles. Rated PG-13
for language and adult themes. 1 hour, 38 minutes.
<p>
   Michael PG
<p>
   An uneven winged victory. In Nora Ephron's appealing fantasy
romance, John Travolta plays an unusual angel who changes the lives
of two journalists (William Hurt and Andie MacDowell). It's a
wildly uneven film and gooey as all get-out. But it's good goo, the
kind that puts you in a goodwill-toward- everyone mood. 1 hour, 45
minutes.
<p>
   Mother PG-13
<p>
   Talk of an Oscar nomination may fuel a comeback for Debbie
Reynolds, who plays a quietly controlling mom in this latest comedy
from the usually hilarious Albert Brooks (``Lost in America,''
``Defending Your Life'').
<p>
   My Fellow Americans PG-13
<p>
   The obvious blueprint for this adorable comedy is ``Grumpy Old
Men,'' the 1993 hit that gave new life to the careers of Jack
Lemmon and Walter Matthau. Here, Lemmon's foil is James Garner  &MD; 
the pair play former U.S. presidents who must put aside their
longstanding rivalry when one is implicated in a scandal. The movie
has some mawkish moments and corny dialogue, but the political
jokes have real bite and Lemmon and Garner make a great, grumpy
team. Rated PG-13 for language and mild violence. 1 hour, 42
minutes.
<p>
   One Fine Day PG-13
<p>
   During this very long and complicated day, so much happens that
you begin to hate little Maggie (Mae Whitman) and Sammy (Alex D.
Linz) for not making their class field trip. But then single mom
Mel (Michelle Pfeiffer) and dad Jack (George Clooney) wouldn't have
been pitted together so they could trade off the kids, accidentally
swap cell phones and otherwise wreak havoc on all of Manhattan.
Still, not even the considerable good looks of the actors or the
use of every screwball gag imaginable can make this ``Pillow Talk''
update anything more than the predictable piece of work that it is.
Rated PG-13 for mild profanity. 1 hour, 48 minutes.
<p>
   101 Dalmatians G
<p>
   Somebody call PETA. This live-action remake of the 1961 Disney
animated feature is a frenetic mess. Glenn Close stars as Cruella
De Vil, a fur-mad fashion plate who wants to turn Dalmatian pups
into a coat. The doggies are adorable, but you've probably seen
Alpo commercials that are more entertaining. 1 hour, 43 minutes.
<p>
   The People vs. Larry Flynt R
<p>
   Milos Forman's riveting sideshow/biopic reminds us that the
First Amendment may well be the single most important thing that
makes our country great  &MD;  and that the right to self-expression
belongs to everybody, not just the polite. Larry Flynt is not
polite. Larry (Woody Harrelson) combines a bottom-line business
sense with a nose for the lowest common denominator. Thus is
Hustler magazine born, a publication that doesn't pretend to be
something people pick up for the articles. This is an audacious
film that's as smart as it is funny, equal parts political satire,
Rabelaisian romp and love story. 2 hours, 10 minutes. 
<p>
   The Preacher's Wife PG
<p>
   Makes a joyful noise. In this update of the 1947 movie ``The
Bishop's Wife,'' Denzel Washington plays an angel sent to Earth to
help a troubled couple (Whitney Houston and Courtney B. Vance).
Director Penny Marshall and her cast transform trite material into
a sweet-natured, PG-rated (parents, please note) crowd pleaser. 2
hours, 5 minutes.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
    &UR; MORE &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
