<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=tad-z> A8675 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MINI-REVIEWS-(4thtake </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0839 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MINI-REVIEWS-(4thtake)-COX &QL; 
 &UR; undated &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Ransom R
<p>
   In this slickly gripping thriller, Mel Gibson plays a self-made
millionaire who takes matters into his own hands when his son is
kidnapped. Rene Russo is his gorgeous, worried wife; Delroy Lindo
is the FBI agent on the case; and Gary Sinise and Lili Taylor are
the masterminds of the kidnapping plot. Though the movie is loosely
based on an old Glenn Ford film, director Ron Howard posits an
interesting subtext. In many ways what ``Ransom'' is really about
is the paranoia of the powerful  &MD;  how all the privilege and
connections in the world can't protect you when life goes awry. On
a pure action-movie level, though ``Ransom'' is often improbable,
it delivers the goods. But on another weirder level, it's a
subversive glimpse into the Nightmares of the Rich and Famous.
Rated R for violence, language and adult situations. 2 hours, 1
minute.
<p>
   The Relic R
<p>
   An exuberant study in B-movie cheesiness, this old-style
drive-in monster flick makes up in charm and verve what it lacks in
smarts. An unsightly reptile-mutant with an insatiable hankerin'
for human brains is terrorizing a Chicago museum. Tom Sizemore
(``Heat'') is terrific as a crusty police detective out to stop the
beast's skull-sucking spree. Rated R for extreme violence and
language. 1 hour, 50 minutes.
<p>
   Ridicule R
<p>
   Knowing, nasty and wonderful to watch. In 1783, a compassionate
but poor nobleman (Charles Berling) travels to Versailles to plead
with King Louis XVI for funds to drain his plague-ridden swamps. He
encounters a world where ``vices are without consequence but
ridicule can kill.'' A sardonic, elegant, scathingly adept film
from Patrice Leconte (``Monsieur Hire''). Rated R for sex, nudity
and adult themes. 1 hour, 42 minutes.
<p>
   Romeo and Juliet PG- 13 
<p>
   It's almost too bad about those nicely handled love scenes
between Leonardo DiCaprio and Claire Danes: They spoil ``Romeo and
Juliet's'' bid to be one of the most spectacularly awful movies of
all time. With its garish 1990s beachfront setting and its jerky,
dizzying, instant-headache camera work, Baz Luhrmann's ``Miami
Vice''``Romeo'' grovels so hard for a Generation X audience that
it's sure to turn off Shakespeare devotees. Rated PG-13 for
violence and adult themes. 2 hours.
<p>
   Star Wars PG
<p>
   ``A long time ago . . . '' or 20 years, to be exact, the world
first fell in love with George Lucas' space cowboy saga. Relive the
adventures of Luke Skywalker, Princess Leia and Han Solo on the big
screen in this anniversary re-release. The second and third
installments of the ``Star Wars'' trilogy  &MD;  ``The Empire Strikes
Back'' and ``Return of the Jedi''  &MD;  will follow in February.
<p>
   Some Mother's Son R
<p>
   The consistently brilliant Helen Mirren of ``Prime Suspect''
fame stars as Kathleen Quigley, an Irish teacher whose son is
jailed for IRA terrorism. Directed by Terry George, who co-wrote
the 1993 Daniel Day-Lewis drama, ``In the Name of the Father.''
<p>
   Scream R
<p>
   Horror maven Wes Craven (``Nightmare on Elm Street'') camps it
up in this self-aware sendup of scary movies. Someone is stalking
and killing a group of jaded teens who live for horror flicks
(played by a who's who of Hollywood's young elite, including Drew
Barrymore and Neve Campbell). ``Scream'' suffers from too many
inside jokes and not enough scares, but it does serve up a few
frightfully funny characters (Courteney Cox is right-on as a
tabloid-TV journalist). Rated R for violence, language and sex. 1
hour, 50 minutes.
<p>
   Secrets &AMP; Lies R
<p>
   A prize winner at Cannes, Mike Leigh's tender human comedy is a
sometimes hilarious, sometimes excruciating look at family. The
narrative meanders through the lives of a half-dozen characters
living in London, but the central pair are Hortense (Marianne
Jean-Baptiste), a bright professional woman in her 20s, and Cynthia
(Brenda Blethyn), a messed-up working-class woman in her 40s. When
Hortense, who was adopted, seeks out her birth mother, she turns
out to be Cynthia. One more thing: Hortense is black and Cynthia is
white. But race isn't the central issue here; Leigh is after more
fundamental bonds, the ones that ask if blood is thicker than
tears. At almost 2 hours, the loose-ends plot can be tiring, but
the acting is wonderful and the movie's insistent, subtly humorous
humanism seeps into your bones.
<p>
   Set It Off R
<p>
   While inner-city living's effect on young black women is a story
told too little on the big screen, ``Set It Off'' is as
unforgettable as it is necessary. The second film from video-movie
director F. Gary Gray (``Friday'') finds its engaging co-stars Jada
Pinkett, Queen Latifah, Vivica Fox and Kimberly Elise beaten down
by ``the system,'' and they are ready to start swinging back. But
their Los Angeles bank heists are only part of a whole and riveting
story about the ends some desperate people will go to in the name
of friendship and the actions even the moral-minded will take for
the sake of survival.
</TEXT>
