<STORYID cat=k pri=r sel=tad-z> A8677 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0691 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN-COX &QL; 
 &UR; COMMENTARY: CELLULAR GENIE OUT OF THE BOTTLE &QL; 
 &UR; By ROWLAND NETHAWAY &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Readers ripped me for a recent column prompted by the
controversy stirred up after a Florida couple taped a cellular
telephone conversation of House Speaker Newt Gingrich and several
top Republicans.
<p>
   Calls from Nebraska, letters from California and e-mail from
everywhere condemned me for the column. I was wished ill in a
variety of ways ranging from creative to crude. That's fine, but it
has little to do with the point I was trying to make.
<p>
   In case you've forgotten, the issue involved the demand by
congressional Republicans to prosecute everyone involved in
reporting a GOP strategy session overheard on a police scanner.
<p>
   Listening to their police scanner while driving to the mall, a
Florida couple overheard Gingrich and his colleagues discuss how to
put the best face on Gingrich's ethics problems.
<p>
   The Florida couple said they taped the conversation because they
wanted to give their grandchildren a piece of history, as though
grandchildren everywhere can't wait to exchange their Tickle Me
Elmo dolls for tapes of GOP strategy sessions.
<p>
   The grandparents, a school maintenance worker and a teacher's
aide, are active Democrats. Copies of the tape ended up in the
hands of congressional Democrats and soon thereafter in print.
<p>
   Democrats wanted to use the tape to show Gingrich did something
wrong. The Republicans wanted to use the tape to prosecute all the
Democrats responsible for making the tape public.
<p>
   I wanted to add a personal perspective to the issue. Overlooked,
I thought, was the fact that cellular phone conversations have
always been broadcast clear and unscrambled on radio frequencies
that can be picked up legally and listened to legally on legal
receivers, such as police scanners.
<p>
   I've known for years that a favorite pastime for many people,
especially rural citizens, is listening to police scanners. When
cellular phones came along, people discovered that many police
scanners pick up these broadcasts. The Florida couple say they have
listened to police scanners as a hobby for 20 years, which is not
unusual.
<p>
   Over the years, police officials have occasionally attempted to
get laws passed to make it illegal for citizens to listen to police
scanners. These efforts become problematic in a free society. They
raise the specter of repressive regimes that attempt to control
what their citizens hear or view on the airwaves, read in print or
say in public. Citizens in some countries must be registered and
licensed before they can own radio or television receivers.
<p>
   Rather than invest in better technology to solve its privacy
problem, in 1993 the cellular industry successfully lobbied
Congress to pass a law that makes it illegal to manufacture
scanners that can pick up the clear broadcasts of cell phones. That
left millions of legal scanners still out there, plus a confusing
legal mess.
<p>
   Two years ago I bought a scanner for a car trip. I wanted the
emergency road reports and the NOAA weather radio broadcasts. To my
surprise, I discovered it also received cell phone transmissions. I
also discovered that listening to cell phone broadcasts is a
widespread hobby in the western states.
<p>
   The answer to cell phone privacy, I wrote, should come from
better technology, such as digital cell phones, rather than more
criminal laws. When it comes to analog cell phone transmissions,
the genie is out of the bottle.
<p>
   In conclusion, I warned that people should not say anything over
a cellular phone that they don't want others to know.
<p>
   The angry reaction to my column makes me believe that lots of
Americans have been misled about the privacy of their cellular
phone conversations. Congress should have required the cellular
industry to fully reveal this fact to its customers.
<p>
   I now know that to say the emperor has no clothes on can upset
everyone, not just the emperor.
<p>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail:RNeth(at)aol.com
</TEXT>
