<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=tad-z> A8680 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0486 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS-COX &QL; 
 &UR; BOOKS COMMENTARY: FRANKLY, SCARLETT, `TARA' SHINES WITH FILM'S SET
DESIGNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By SCOTT EYMAN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Personally, I've grown weary of reading about ``Gone With the
Wind'' in either its literary or film forms.
<p>
   At any rate, for those who feel they can't get enough of what
Variety recently concluded is still by far the most successful
movie ever made (adjusting for inflation, ``GWTW'' has grossed $1.2
billion, compared to $698 million for ``ET''), there is ``On the
Road to Tara'' (Abrams, $39.95).
<p>
   The text doesn't offer much beyond what has already been printed
in previous books by Ron Haver, Gavin Lambert, and two or three
other writers, but what the large format volume does offer is
voluminous amounts of set and costume designs drawn from the
Selznick archives at the University of Texas. Since the film was
designed by the great William Cameron Menzies, and costumed by
Walter Plunkett, the artwork is often beautiful in and of itself.
<p>
   Menzies was the great, largely unsung architect of ``GWTW,''
indeed, of a good deal of classic Hollywood. He designed the look
of ``GWTW,'' and then storyboarded most of the sequences on a shot
by shot basis, which is why the film has such a unified style, in
spite of the fact that a half-dozen directors were sticking their
oars in at one time or another.
<p>
   If you're a completist, a reasonable addition to the library.
<p>
   Get 'em while they're hot ... If you want to sell books, you
really have to get on Oprah. Back in October, Winfrey's mention of
``Deep End of the Ocean'' helped move the literary novel to No. 1
on the fiction list. A little while later, Winfrey mentioned that
the next book her Reading Group would tackle would be Toni
Morrison's ``Song of Solomon.''
<p>
   ``Song of Solomon'' was published in 1977; in 1995, total sales
for the book amounted to 3,300 copies; 1996 sales were on the same
level. After Oprah's announcement, Plume promptly printed 500,000
new copies, and before you could say ``royalty check'' the book was
No. 1 on the paperback bestseller list.
<p>
   Aside from the fact that Winfrey, or her producers, have pretty
good taste, this illustrates how hidebound is the book industry's
own promotional apparatus, and how open people are to literary
experience.
<p>
   Good news and bad news ... Scribner's will publish the new Don
DeLillo novel, ``Underworld.'' The book, about the Cold War, will
be published in October. Although DeLillo's last book, ``Mao II,''
sold about 40,000 copies, not bad for a literary novel, but nothing
special commercially, Scribner's is said to have paid nearly $1
million for ``Underworld.'' Either it's very hungry for prestige,
or ``Underworld'' has elements that will appeal to a larger
audience than DeLillo's usual fans.
<p>
   (Scott Eyman is books editor of The Palm Beach Post.)
</TEXT>
