<STORYID cat=l pri=r sel=tad-z> A8682 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0600 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-REAL-LIFE-COX &QL; 
 &UR; PASS JUDGMENT ON JONBENET'S PARENTS? NOT YET &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By EMILY J. MINOR &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   On a cool winter evening some weeks ago, my 5-year-old son took
the stage. It was quite by accident, this performance at a local
arts center. The man on stage asked for children from the audience,
my kid's arm shot up and, voila, there he was, standing before a
couple thousand people.
<p>
   The small boy who still makes Mom order his cookie at the bakery
counter stood tall and talked loud and clear. He hammed it up. The
crowd laughed, then applauded. ``You stole the show,'' a nice lady
told us on the way out. I beamed.
<p>
   ``That was fun,'' said the 5-year-old.
<p>
   This, of course, has nothing to do with that tiny girl found
strangled in Boulder, Colo. Yet it has everything to do with her.
Because, quite suddenly, we have all decided that parents who put
their children in beauty pageants are selfish and irresponsible
people. Suddenly we've decided these mothers with cherry-red lips
and teased hair are a class below us.
<p>
   Suddenly, we've decided we're better than them because our kids
play with Barbie dolls and their kids dress like one.
<p>
   Yet, on that winter evening not so long ago, I was proud when my
kid stood on that stage and made a crowd of strangers smile.
<p>
   This little matter of looking at people and deciding right off
the bat that they're bad - and we're good - is the very thing we
hope our children will never do. We judge. All of us. The pretty
lady driving the Lexus and wearing a tennis outfit. I hate her. The
blue-collar guy who yells at his kid at Kmart. He makes me sick.
<p>
   But what do I know of these people? Nothing. I wouldn't pierce
my daughter's ears, carry a cell phone to the mall or let a nanny
raise my child. Yet lots of loving parents choose to do those very
things.
<p>
   It's difficult, I know, to relate to the mother with
Clairol-colored hair who sits before Katie Couric and explains,
quite politely, that there's nothing wrong with her daughter
competing in pageants. We poke fun, point out her fake nails,
polyester dress and hick accent. But shouldn't we give her a
chance? After all, it is possible that her little girl loves the
competition. And there's already money in the bank for the child's
college. I must say - perfect little me - I don't have all that
arranged quite yet.
<p>
   Despite what you and I think, JonBenet Ramsey's parents were not
bad parents simply because they let their daughter take the stage.
Thankfully, it takes more than that to ruin a child. They pushed
her, and we all wonder if they didn't push her a little too much.
The little girl had dyed hair and wore backless gowns. She knew how
to coyly shrug her shoulder and swing her behind.
<p>
   But, when the competition was finished, it's said that JonBenet
put on her jeans, tied her shoes and headed out to get dirty in a
mud puddle. And that seems pretty darn normal.
<p>
   If the Ramseys had anything to do with their little girl's
murder, they are, needless to say, very, very sick human beings.
<p>
   That won't be decided by pretty outfits and pageant judges,
though. And until we know more - more than just Mrs. Ramsey was a
former beauty queen and Mr. Ramsey is a wealthy businessman - it
certainly shouldn't be decided by the judgmental likes of you and
me.
<p>
   After all, have you read anything about Paula Jones lately?
Turns out there's more to her than big hair and gaudy makeup. Turns
out she could be telling the truth.
<p>
   (Emily J. Minor writes for The Palm Beach Post.)
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
    &UR; For use by clients of the New York Times News Service &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
