<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0099 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=tad-z> A8684 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EVA-LE-GALLIENNE-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1018 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EVA-LE-GALLIENNE-COX &QL; 
 &UR; BOOKS: LE GALLIENNE ACTED ROYALLY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By EYMAN SCOTT &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   EVA LE GALLIENNE, by Helen Sheehy. Knopf; 529 pages; $37.50.
<p>
   She was alone on stage. She was standing up, then, suddenly, she
stopped, swayed a tiny bit, then catapulted backward into a rocking
chair, as if her spine had been ripped from her body. The rocking
chair moved gently back and forth, her hand drifting across the
floor.
<p>
   It was the greatest death scene I've ever seen. The year was
1977, the play was ``The Royal Family,'' a middling George S.
Kaufman satire of the Barrymores, and the actress was Eva Le
Gallienne, playing the family matriarch.
<p>
   On the technical level, it would have been an impressive moment
for a young actor; for a woman pushing 80, it was astonishing. I
saw the play five times in a week, and she was never less than
dead-on in creating a moment of total loss that could only be
communicated by total control.
<p>
   In the early and middle years of this century, there were, by
common consent, three great actresses on the American stage: Helen
Hayes, Katherine Cornell, and Eva Le Gallienne. Of them, Le
Gallienne was the most serious artist. Her favorite writer was
Kierkegaard, she created the role of Julie in Molnar's ``Liliom,''
she excelled in Ibsen and Chekhov, she was playing Hecuba in ``The
Trojan Women'' in the mid-'60s.
<p>
   Le Gallienne was short, slight, not particularly beautiful, but
she had unbreakable will, charm, a warm cello voice, and that inner
light without which an actor is doomed to character parts. Her role
models were Bernhardt and, later, the supreme Duse. She despised
Hayes as a sell-out and seems to have given Cornell no serious
consideration whatever.
<p>
   Her absolute integrity is why Le Gallienne isn't better known
today. She was completely without that touch of whorish showbiz
neediness that can be counted upon to elicit an audience's empathy.
<p>
   ``Le Gallienne composed a part,'' writes Helen Sheehy in this,
the first comprehensive biography of the actress, ``thinking of her
role as a continuous piece of music, orchestrating the silence of
thoughts, so that each moment, each word, each gesture flowed
inevitably and spontaneously forward.''
<p>
   In addition to acting, Le Gallienne often directed and produced
as well; her greatest triumph was the six-year run of the Civic
Repertory Company, a brave attempt to create in America what other
countries have always taken for granted - a national repertory
theater, presenting the finest plays at the lowest possible prices.
<p>
   The tickets for the Civic Rep started at 35 cents and topped out
at $1.50, this at a time when Broadway tickets usually ran $1.50 to
$5. Because of the price structure, the Civic was of necessity
formulated around the European model of subsidies.
<p>
   For a time, the Civic thrived, but the Depression put paid to
the dream, and a later, post-war attempt to revive the concept fell
victim to increasingly impossible economics.
<p>
   One closes this valuable but occasionally frustrating book
wondering at Le Gallienne's refusal to go to Europe and match her
gifts against the people who do serious theater really well.
<p>
   Perhaps she was too austere and single-minded to really work
effectively with other people for very long. An actor/manager in
the tradition of Henry Irving or Olivier, she had to be left alone
to work her magic, but her uncommercial taste in material and
luxurious, thoroughly commercial taste in physical production
doomed her to the margins.
<p>
   Yet, she was right about a great deal. Her insistence on an
alternative to Broadway has borne fruit, not in a geniune national
repertory company, but in the regional theater movement.
<p>
   In addition, she had a wonderful eye for talent. Burgess
Meredith, May Sarton, John Garfield, Howard da Silva, Norman Lloyd
and Robert Lewis were all trained at the Civic, and their idealism
was further illuminated by the shining light of her integrity. They
all adored her and had lengthy careers marked by the Civic's
tradition of self-effacement, of serving the writer, of an actor
disappearing into a part.
<p>
   Personally, Le Gallienne was a lesbian - a big one, as Diane
Keaton's daughter proclaims in ``The First Wives Club.'' Most of
her lovers were subsidiary talents, although she did live for a
while with Mercedes de Acosta, the lesbian Errol Flynn.
<p>
   The only man she took as a lover was, of all people, Basil
Rathbone, in his young leading man period in the '20s, and they
were serious enough for her to contemplate marriage and children.
<p>
   Her powerful creative force was easily transmuted into erotic
energy; during the production of ``The Royal Family,'' she seduced
George S. Kaufman's daughter, a married woman 25 years her junior.
Whoever shared her life had to deal with her tendency toward the
imperious and arrogant; Le Gallienne had a tendency to reduce
lovers and coworkers alike to the status of helpmates at best,
servants at worst.
<p>
   Helen Sheehy quotes people who attest to Le Gallienne's
delightful humor, but if they're right Sheehy has flattened out her
subject. Le Gallienne comes across as petulant and almost comically
self-absorbed. The fault may be Sheehy's. Le Gallienne seems to
have been a gardener of genius - her estate in Connecticut sounds
comparable to Monet's - and very few gardeners lack (you should
pardon the expression) earthy humor.
<p>
   The primary problem of Eva Le Gallienne is that Sheehy tells the
story almost completely through Le Gallienne's eyes, relying too
much on her own words, as set down in her diaries and two volumes
of autobiography.
<p>
   If the book lacks objectivity, it also lacks flair. Sheehy's
stolidity makes it difficult for her to give a sense of Le
Gallienne's flair, her incandescence on stage.
<p>
   Since any theatrical talent is writing on water, it is left to
the chroniclers to preserve their art for posterity, and this is
something Sheehy has done only spasmodically.
<p>
   (Scott Eyman is books editor of The Palm Beach Post.)
</TEXT>
