<SLUG> BC-MAIL-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0342 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MAIL-COX &QL; 
 &UR; JUNK MAIL COULD WIPE OUT STAINED IMAGE &QL; 
 &UR; By CHARLES SEABROOK &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ATLANTA  &MD;  The Post Office has its own junk mail headache  &MD;  tons
of undeliverable newsletters, political fliers and department store
advertisers. Postal officials said Tuesday they're going to do
something about it.
<p>
   The Postal Service, they said, has awarded a five-year contract
to Southeast Paper Recycling of Atlanta to collect and recycle
undeliverable junk mail from nearly 200 post offices and two mail
processing plants in North Georgia, including metro Atlanta.
<p>
   Together, the postal facilities are expected to produce about
500 tons of paper for recycling per month, said Carol Larson,
spokeswoman for the Postal Service Atlanta District.
<p>
   Recycling, she said, will divert the wastepaper from landfills
and turn it into new products, such as newsprint and paper towels
and napkins. It will also save more than 100,000 trees and generate
more than $150,000 per year in revenue for the Postal Service, she
noted.
<p>
   ``The bulk of the paper that will be recycled is undeliverable
advertising mail,'' she said. That's what most homeowners call junk
mail, although Larson said the Post Office doesn't like to use that
term.
<p>
   Unlike First-Class Mail, this type of mail is rarely forwarded
when people change addresses. It ends up back at the post office,
marked undeliverable.
<p>
   Postal officials say a lot of the problems with junk mail  &MD; 
assuming people want it in the first place  &MD;  could be avoided if
residents left a correct or up-to-date forwarding address when
moving.
<p>
   The Postal Service delivered 183 billion pieces of mail
nationwide in 1996. Of that, about 39 percent, or 71 billion
pieces, was advertising mail.
<p>
   Nationwide, the Postal Service in 1996 recycled one million tons
of wastepaper, cardboard, plastics, cans and other material. The
recycling generated about $6.6 million in revenue for the agency
and earned kudos from the White House.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
    &UR; For use by clients of the New York Times News Service &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1048EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0102 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tad-z> A8688 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0552 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BOMB-COX &QL; 
 &UR; FIRST ABORTION CLINIC BOMB MEANT TO LEVEL BUILDING &QL; 
 &UR; By KATHY SCRUGGS and SCOTT MARSHALL &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ATLANTA  &MD;  The bomb that blasted through a window of a Sandy
Springs abortion clinic was meant to level the three-story,
concrete office building, authorities said Tuesday.
<p>
   The second bomb, which exploded 67 minutes later Thursday, was
different. It was packed with shrapnel and aimed at people.
<p>
   ``The magnitude of the (first) explosion was designed to bring
that building down,'' Fulton County Police Chief Louis Graham said
Tuesday. ``And the magnitude of the second thing was designed to
kill. These were not M- 80s.''
<p>
   A federal, state and local task force of about 100 law
enforcement officers, including FBI and ATF agents from across the
country, were ``very optimistic'' and ``following good leads,''
Graham said. More than 400 tips have been called in to the hotline
 &MD;  888-ATF-BOMB, FBI spokesman Jay Spadafore said Tuesday.
<p>
   Federal authorities Tuesday also said they were investigating
four pipe bombs found in a vacant office building in suburban
Lithonia.
<p>
   The devices  &MD;  four metal pipes with shotgun shells taped to them
and wires sticking out of them  &MD;  were discovered in a metal box
Saturday by a man cleaning out the small office on Old Covington
Road, police said. Owners of the building, which has been rented to
a taxi company, contacted police Monday.
<p>
   ATF spokesman Bobby Browning said other bomb components were
found in the building. Browning would not say if the explosives
were similar to those used in Sandy Springs.
<p>
   ``My first thought was that it was a practical joke,'' said
Henry Sosa, who owns a nearby towing business and runs the
building. ``But these things looked like they were ready to go.''
<p>
   In Sandy Springs, investigators Tuesday finished scouring the
area around the office building for clues and released the
Carpenter Drive property to its owner.
<p>
   ``We are going to stay there until the owner makes arrangements
for security on the property,'' Graham said. ``We don't want to
just walk away and leave those people.''
<p>
   The first blast at 9:30 a.m. Thursday did extensive damage,
knocking out ceiling tiles on all floors and leaving dangling
electrical wires. It left a 41/2- to 6-inch-deep crater in an area
that was on top of reinforced concrete, said Fulton County police
Capt. Terry Mulkey.
<p>
   The second explosion at 10:37 a.m. blew a 5-
foot-by-6-foot-by-41/2-foot hole next to a dumpster on the
northwest side. Law enforcement officials told reporters Tuesday
that it contained 3-inch concrete nails.
<p>
   Officials said it's still too early to rule out any connection
to the July 27 pipe bomb that killed one and injured 111 during
Olympic festivities. That bomb also contained nails.
<p>
   ``We're proceeding with an open mind,'' Graham said.
<p>
   Investigators were also trying to determine the real target of
the bombs. The clinic was not open for abortions on Thursday.
<p>
   ``We feel it probably was the abortion clinic, but again we
can't say that absolutely,'' Graham said. ``What other reason would
a second bomb have been planted at the building except to kill
somebody  &MD;  public safety, news reporters or innocent bystanders?''
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
    &UR; For use by clients of the New York Times News Service &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1049EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0103 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tad-z> A8690 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1003 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-LOTTERY-COX &QL; 
 &UR; TOP TEXAS LOTTERY MANAGER'S RECORDS SUBPOENAED &QL; 
 &UR; By KEN HERMAN &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   AUSTIN, Texas  &MD;  Federal prosecutors who allege Texas consultants
for GTECH paid kickbacks to a company official are reviewing
records concerning GTECH's top Texas employee.
<p>
   In a subpoena sent to Kentucky officials, prosecutors in New
Jersey asked for employment records of James Hosker, who was hired
away from his post as head of the Kentucky Lottery to run GTECH's
Texas operations from Austin.
<p>
   Hosker, who took the Kentucky Lottery job in November 1990, left
in June 1992 to join GTECH, which operates the Texas Lottery.
<p>
   The subpoena was issued last month by federal prosecutors in New
Jersey, ordering Kentucky lottery officials to submit all of
Hosker's employment records ``including but not limited to
personnel records, recommendations, job performance reviews and
exit records.''
<p>
   A spokeswoman for Hosker referred all questions Tuesday to the
company's Rhode Island headquarters. Company spokesman Bob Rendine
said speculation would be improper on why federal prosecutors in
New Jersey are interested in Hosker's Kentucky employment records.
<p>
   ``For anybody to make any kind of assumption is not only
inappropriate, but flat-out outrageous,'' Rendine said.
<p>
   A state audit report in Kentucky critical of changes Hosker made
to GTECH's contract there  &MD;  before he joined GTECH in Texas  &MD;  had
been referred to the Kentucky attorney general. The attorney
general declined criminal prosecution.
<p>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Kimberly Guadagno of Newark has declined
to discuss the subpoena or confirm that a GTECH-related
investigation is continuing. In October, jurors in Newark convicted
J. David Smith, GTECH's former national sales manager, and one of
the company's New Jersey consultant on charges that Smith took
kickbacks.
<p>
   A presentencing report issued last week said Smith also took
kickbacks  &MD;  topping $500,000  &MD;  from former Texas Lt. Gov. Ben
Barnes, GTECH's top Texas consultant. Barnes, who says he hired
Smith to do consulting, has denied the allegations.
<p>
   In April 1994, after Hosker was in Austin, Kentucky State
Auditor Ben Chandler issued a report claiming Kentucky had given
GTECH too good of a deal. The report pointed a finger at Hosker and
Brian Potter, who also had served as president of the Kentucky
Lottery.
<p>
   At the time, Illinois accountant John Filan, who helped review
the Kentucky Lottery, said problems with the contract began with
changes Hosker and Potter made. All changes were ratified by the
lottery board. All members of that panel resigned after the audit
report.
<p>
   Chandler's report said Kentucky paid GTECH $2.7 million more per
year than other states paid for similar services. The original 1989
contract was amended in 1991 and 1992. The second change came four
months before Hosker's departure for GTECH and Texas.
<p>
   Rendine on Tuesday characterized the Kentucky audit as ``amateur
hour.''
<p>
   ``When they tried to compare prices paid in large states with
prices paid in small states, we knew it was not a very good
analysis,'' he said. Changes that added to the state's cost were
changes that also provided additional services and products,
Rendine said.
<p>
   The audit report was forwarded to the Kentucky attorney general,
who said no criminal charges were warranted.
<p>
   Just as Rendine cautioned against jumping to conclusions about
what prosecutors want to see from the Kentucky employment records,
he warned against drawing implications about Hosker's move from
negotiating with GTECH to working for it. He said any overlap of
payments from the two sides was an innocent, inevitable outcome.
<p>
   ``When you leave a place of employment ... and go to work
somewhere else inevitably you will find you are owned comp or
vacation time and you will receive a check weeks later at your
other place of employment,'' Rendine said. ``That's precisely what
happened in Mr. Hosker's case.''
<p>
   He added that Hosker notified Kentucky officials, in a public
meeting, that he planned to talk to GTECH about a job.
<p>
   GTECH has operated the Kentucky Lottery's on-line games since
they began in 1989. But last year Automated Wagering Inc. underbid
GTECH by $25 million and was awarded a five-year contract to
provide a computer system and operate the on-line lotto games. The
two firms submitted the only bids.
<p>
   The Automated Wagering deal went sour last year when the company
could not guarantee it could install and operate the new system.
The company was in the midst of potential ownership restructuring.
<p>
   In September, the Kentucky Lottery Board gave up on Automated
Wagering and instructed lottery officials to negotiate an extension
of the GTECH contract, now scheduled to expire in October 1997.
<p>
   Hosker honed his political skills within the Democratic Party in
Massachusetts. He became lottery director after a long stint in the
state treasurer's office, the agency that oversees the
Massachusetts Lottery.
<p>
   In November 1990, Hosker was hired for the Kentucky job by
then-Gov. Wallace Wilkinson, who a year later would become a key
player in the career of another GTECH official. In 1991, on his
last day in office, Wilkinson pardoned Smith, who had pleaded
guilty on a misdemeanor charge of possessing gambling devices.
<p>
   The charge, reduced from a felony, stemmed from the early 1980s
when Smith's Kentucky company placed video poker machines in bars.
<p>
   Wilkinson's lottery ties also included L. Rogers Wells, a former
top aide who was acquitted of kickback charges with Smith in
Kentucky.
<p>
   Wells served as Wilkinson's finance secretary.
<p>
   At the time, Wells was president of Interlott, an Ohio-based
firm that sells lottery ticket-vending machines to several states,
including Texas.
<p>
   The Wells-Smith trial ended in January 1995 when U.S. District
Judge John Heyburn II ordered Smith and Wells acquitted before the
case went to the jury.
</TEXT>
