<DOCID> nyt970122.0104 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tad-z> A8692 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FREEZE-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0801 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FREEZE-COX &QL; 
 &UR; FLORIDA OFFICIALS ASK FOR FEDERAL FREEZE AID &QL; 
 &UR; By MARY ELLEN KLAS and LISA SHUCHMAN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla.  &MD;  An unexpected freeze ravaged fruit and
vegetable plants in pockets of South Florida this weekend and
caused at least $100 million in crop damage. State officials on
Tuesday decided to seek federal disaster relief.
<p>
   Florida Agriculture Commissioner Bob Crawford said the Saturday
night freeze was the most damaging since 1989 and came without
warning. The cold sent temperatures below freezing along a trough
from Clewiston through the southwest corridor and into Homestead in
Dade County. Clewiston reported a low of 19 degrees.
<p>
   The icy weather lingered for up to 8 hours  &MD;  killing tomatoes,
zucchini, cucumbers and bell pepper plants, turning the juice of
young oranges to slush and withering young sugar cane plants.
<p>
   Consumers will feel the impact immediately, Crawford said.
<p>
   ``Expect prices to skyrocket,'' he said. Mexico, which supplies
half of the nation's winter vegetable crop, also was hit by the
freeze.
<p>
   The cold snap caught weather forecasters and farmers by
surprise.
<p>
   Crawford blamed the lack of warning on the absence of the
National Weather Service agriculture forecasts this year. The
federal government ended its agriculture forecasts last spring to
save $3.3 million and left the job for private forecasters.
<p>
   Crawford also blamed the private forecasters. They miscalculated
the cold snap, failing to predict that temperatures in the southern
half of the state would drop lower than the cloud-covered regions
farther north.
<p>
   ``There's pretty much unanimous agreement by anyone using a
weather service that they missed this one pretty badly,'' said
Dallas Townsend, Hendry County extension director.
<p>
   The cold temperatures inflicted the heaviest damage on vegetable
crops in Southwest Florida and in Homestead, where farmers produce
the other half of the nation's winter vegetable crop. They lost
between 50 percent and 75 percent of their harvest, Crawford said.
<p>
   In Collier and Hendry counties, where farmers grow tomatoes,
green peppers and cucumbers, the outlook was also grim.
<p>
   ``The vegetable industry really got clobbered,'' said Townsend.
He spent the last three days assessing the damage and concluded:
``It's going to be devastating losses industry-wide in this area.''
<p>
   In western Palm Beach County, farmers fared better. The cold
damaged sweet corn, radishes and leafy greens, but losses were
considered light to moderate.
<p>
   ``Palm Beach County seems to have done better than most areas,''
said Gary Smiegel of Lantana-based Mecca Farms. ``We may have lost
10 percent of our crop, but some farmers in Immokalee, Naples and
Homestead lost 100 percent.''
<p>
   Mecca Farms grows tomatoes, peppers and squash in Palm Beach and
Martin counties.
<p>
   Crawford called his $100 million damage estimate
``conservative'' and said the freeze was most damaging cold snap in
Florida since the 1989 freeze that inflicted $1 billion in damages
on Florida's fruit and vegetable industry.
<p>
   The crop damage forced growers to send crews into overtime
Sunday to salvage their losses and speed up their harvesting.
<p>
   The cold is not expected to affect the harvest of the state's
sugar cane crop. The cane was hit by frost, but that should not
affect raw sugar yields, said Bob Buker, senior vice president of
Clewiston-based U.S. Sugar Corp.
<p>
   The cold might have hurt young plant cane, however, which would
affect next year's crop. It will be two or three months before the
full impact of the cold on the young cane can be measured, Buker
said.
<p>
   In the Gulf citrus-growing area of Hendry, Collier and Lee
counties, growers expect the freeze damage will reduce their juice
yields, said Ron Hamel, executive vice president of the Gulf Citrus
Growers Association.
<p>
   The freeze was not all bad news for citrus growers, however.
Those who still have fruit to sell will now be able to get more
money. The expectation that the state's growers would this year
produce a record-sized crop had driven down prices.
<p>
   But on Monday, orange juice for March delivery rose 5.95 cents
to 85.85 cents a pound on the New York Cotton Exchange. That was
the biggest one-day change since August. Prices for March delivery
rose again on Tuesday, closing at 86.65 cents a pound.
<p>
   Meanwhile, Crawford's office continues to collect damage
estimates. Gov. Lawton Chiles is expected to formally ask federal
authorities this week to declare the affected regions federal
disasters areas. Growers, who are not covered by crop insurance,
could then be eligible for low-interest loans.
<p>
   (Mary Ellen Klas and Lisa Shuchman write for The Palm Beach
Post.)
</TEXT>
