<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tad-z> A8694 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0908 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BOHLS-COLUMN-COX &QL; 
 &UR; SPORTS COMMENTARY: COACHING CAROUSEL CAN BE A CRUEL RIDE &QL; 
 &UR; By KIRK BOHLS &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  Bill Parcells used to be a chain smoker. He's
still a self- described compulsive eater. In fact, he said if he
didn't work out at 5:30 every morning, ``I'd be dead.''
<p>
   Mike Holmgren said his stomach's been bothering him the past two
months and he can't sleep.
<p>
   And these are the two NFL coaches who won.
<p>
   Just think of those 28 other poor schmucks whose seasons ended
short of the Super Bowl. For 10 of them, more than that ended. They
were canned, three of them after only two seasons on the job. How's
THEIR health these days? Health hell, how's that mortgage payment
coming?
<p>
   The tenure of those 10 pink-slipped head coaches averaged only
five years, thanks to bulletproof Wayne Fontes' nine seasons and
offense-less Jim Mora's 11{. Take them out of the equation, and the
other eight averaged just 3.7 years on the sideline.
<p>
   ``I hope it's an aberration,'' Green Bay's Holmgren said. ``In
two or three instances, I felt it shouldn't have happened. A couple
didn't get enough time.''
<p>
   Bobby Ross was pressured into resigning at San Diego, just two
years removed from a Super Bowl. George Seifert was shown the door
because he hadn't been to the big game since the 1994 season.
<p>
   Al Groh, New England's excellent but well-traveled defensive
coordinator, has made seven college and four NFL stops.
<p>
   ``My wife and I designed our dream house in South Carolina and
we were in it four months,'' Groh said. ``We've built four houses,
and the first three we lived in 'em a year. When we moved to
Massachusetts, my son, Mike, said, `Dad, if you want to stay, don't
build a house.'''
<p>
   If they build it, they still will come and go. That's why nearly
a third of the NFL's head-coaching work force was left to fill out
questionnaires from some idiot named Tom Benson. Nice gig if you
can get it, huh?
<p>
   It's a wonder anybody wants to. And it'll get worse before it
gets better. When a pair of 2-year-old expansion teams like
Carolina and Jacksonville reach the NFC and AFC championship games,
that sound you hear is the heads of head coaches being lopped off.
<p>
   Of the 20 survivors this season, three were first-year head
coaches, five were in their second year and three more in their
third. In this decade alone, the 29 NFL teams already will have had
75 head coaches by next fall. That counts Cleveland but not the
expansion teams, although the future of Carolina's Tom Coughlin was
in doubt at midseason. The college casualties were even higher this
fall.
<p>
   The profession is becoming more and more precarious, which
explains why more and more coaches, a la Parcells and new Falcons
hire Dan Reeves, are seeking more and more control of their own
destiny. That's why they try to sit in the general manager's chair
or sit on their GM and make most of the personnel decisions in the
draft and free agency.
<p>
   You can't blame them, but you can't necessarily fault management
because coaches can up and leave as easily as they are fired. If it
were left up to Parcells, New England would have drafted a
defensive player in the first round, not wideout Terry Glenn, and
might not be here now.
<p>
   The coaching carousel is a vicious cycle but no longer a
recycle. Of the 27 current head coaches in place, only four of
their predecessors have top jobs in the league: Reeves (Atlanta),
Lindy Infante (Indianapolis), Jimmy Johnson (Miami) and Ross
(Detroit).
<p>
   ``Management of an NFL franchise is different than it's ever
been with the salary cap and a fixed budget,'' said Patriots owner
Robert Kraft, who refuses to give Parcells total autonomy and will
probably lose him to the Jets. ``The skills to manage a football
team and do it well are not the same it takes to manage an office.
Unless you're a great financial person, I'm not sure you can do
that job well.''
<p>
   Holmgren almost quit to become a high school teacher after two
years as a high school assistant on a team that lost every game. He
considered his father's career in real estate. Parcells picked
coaching over law school out of Wichita State.
<p>
   ``Any time 33 percent of your industry is changing, it is
surprising,'' Parcells said. ``The game has changed. There's a lot
of volatility. Players change (more quickly), owners change. I
don't think it's for the better.
<p>
   ``But I like the game, and I don't care what goes with it. I was
probably a 9 for putting pressure on myself. Now I'm at
mid-range.''
<p>
   Holmgren said we've seen the last of the Don Shulas and Tom
Landrys and Chuck Nolls and Dick Ver ... how's that? You said Dick
Vermeil wants back in the rat race after sitting on the sidelines
for 15 years? Neither Parcells nor Holmgren suggested Vermeil
should get a group rate on Dennis Rodman's NBA psychologist, but if
the couch fits.
<p>
   Vermeil, who accepted the St. Louis Rams coaching job Tuesday,
was in Holmgren's office three years ago when Vermeil was
contemplating a return to the Philadelphia Eagles position he
abruptly vacated in 1981.
<p>
   ``I told him things have really changed,'' Holmgren said. ``What
do you think made you get out the last time? You're a perfectionist
in an imperfect game.''
<p>
   But at the current rate of exchange for coaches, not for very
long.
<p>
   (Kirk Bohls writes for The Austin American-Statesman.)
</TEXT>
