<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0215 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PENTHOUSE-MILITARY-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PENTHOUSE WINS COURT ORDER TO SELL MAGAZINES ON MILITARY BASES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Seena Simon &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Penthouse magazine won a court
order allowing it to sell sexually explicit magazines and videos in
military-run stores on U.S. bases and ships worldwide.
<p>
   U.S. District Judge Shira Scheindlin in New York granted
Penthouse owner General Media Communications Inc. and several
publishing and entertainment trade groups a preliminary injunction
that lifts a recent ban on the sales.
<p>
   The judge found that the ban on ``indecent'' material in the
stores violates the First Amendment right of publishers and video
producers to distribute material that some people find offensive.
She also found the ban unconstitutionally vague.
<p>
   ``Sexually explicit material cannot be banned from sale or
rental at military exchanges merely because it is offensive,''
Scheindlin wrote in a ruling issued today.
<p>
   She rejected the U.S. Defense Department's argument that the ban
would erode the military's core values of honor, courage and
commitment.
<p>
   The preliminary injunction replaces a temporary restraining
order Scheindlin had imposed against the military on Dec. 20.
</TEXT>
