<DOCID> nyt970122.0107 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tad-z> A8696 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-REEVES-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0493 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FALCONS-REEVES-COX &QL; 
 &UR; REEVES TAKES OVER FALCONS &QL; 
 &UR; By LEN PASQUARELLI &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ATLANTA  &MD;  Charged officially with reversing the fortunes of one
of the league's worst franchises, Dan Reeves conceded during his
first day on the Atlanta Falcons payroll that the task might be a
daunting one.
<p>
   But Reeves took a giant step Tuesday toward assuring the city's
long-suffering fans he's game for the challenge.
<p>
   ``Probably the greatest motivator that I know of is fear,''
Reeves, 53, said after a Georgia Dome press conference. ``It's
driven me my entire life, and it will drive me now. The past four
years (with the New York Giants), I worked harder than in any of
the previous 12 seasons at Denver. I want to succeed, and I know
I'll work even harder here to try and make sure we do.''
<p>
   Reeves' record (149-113-1) in 16 years on the sidelines makes
him the 10th-winningest coach in NFL history. His resume is
highlighted by seven playoff appearances, five division titles and
three conference crowns.
<p>
   Reeves has participated as a player or coach in eight of the 30
Super Bowl games.
<p>
   ``For 16 years, I've thought about Dan and the possibilities of
him being here with us,'' Taylor Smith said. ``For various reasons,
timing and whatever else, it never worked until now. But now is the
time for him. The instant respect he brings our franchise around
the league is something special.''
<p>
   Unlike New York, where Reeves was hamstrung by the structural
constraints of the organization, Reeves will have no one to blame
but himself if he fails to deliver in Suwanee, the Falcons'
training camp.
<p>
   The titles of coach and executive vice president/football
operations afford him more ``authority''  &MD;  a word he said he
preferred over ``control''  &MD;  to undertake whatever moves are
necessary to make the team a playoff contender.
<p>
   Beyond his short-term goal of assembling a staff by the end of
the week, Reeves' aim is to create the kind of stability Atlanta
has lacked for three decades. With only a cursory knowledge of the
Falcons' roster, Reeves reiterated the need to surround himself
with strong assistants who share his mindset.
<p>
   ``The long-range plan,'' Reeves said, ``is for the Falcons to be
successful year in and year out.''
<p>
   Although he exhibited more excitement than emotion, the Rome,
Ga., native and former Americus resident left little doubt the
opportunity to return to his roots played a big role in accepting a
position he sought 20 years ago.
<p>
   ``This is home,'' said Reeves. ``It's not often you get the
opportunity to try to succeed at something in the place you want to
spend the rest of your life.''
<p>
   In 1977, as a Dallas assistant coach, Reeves pursued the
Falcons' vacancy subsequently filled by Leeman Bennett.
<p>
   Owner Rankin Smith and team president Taylor Smith allowed that
they weren't going to let Reeves escape this time. .
</TEXT>
