<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NETWATCH-COX &QL; 
 &UR; AOL SUBSCRIBERS CAN BYPASS TRAFFIC TROUBLES &QL; 
 &UR; By ART KRAMER &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Despite busy signals, slowdowns, e-mail outages and message
board miseries in the seven weeks since America Online unshackled
most of its users from hourly charges, the majority of the
service's 8 million subscribers are not suing, petitioning,
withholding monthly fees or canceling their subscriptions  &MD;  yet.
For the AOLoyal, there are a few ways to cope while the service
works to ease access.
<p>
   A feature called flash sessions allows subscribers to log onto
AOL automatically during off-peak hours to send and retrieve
e-mail. A button titled ``walk me through'' gives you step-by-step
instructions.
<p>
   Members who have accounts with an Internet service provider at
home or work can use them to get into AOL through a ``pipe'' that
is hundreds of times wider than a standard telephone connection.
<p>
   From the AOL welcome screen, choose the ``setup'' and ``create
location'' buttons to set up a new ``locality.'' A locality is a
script that AOL uses to connect you to their computers, and you can
create and save as many localities as you like with whatever names
you choose.
<p>
   By opting for TCP/IP instead of AOLnet in the ``network''
window, you'll bypass the phone lines altogether and hook up to AOL
through your Internet connection.
<p>
   You can also set up localities to dial, two per session, any of
AOL's local telephone numbers. Be aware that you'll lose
performance if you connect using a line rated for a modem slower
than the one in your computer.
<p>
   The three recommended Atlanta-area numbers listed in the AOL
Insider section are generally the least-used lines. But usage on
the other 11 lines varies with the time of day and other factors.
<p>
   Tips and Updates: Keyword: Insider
<p>
   List of Access Numbers: Keyword: Access
<p>
   Flash Session Set Up: Keyword: Flash Sessions
<p>
   Rolling Stone writer Fred Goodman says the online serialization
of his new rock history, ``Mansion on the Hill: Dylan, Young,
Geffen and the Head-On Collision of Rock and Commerce'' (Times
Books, $25) is more than just a magazine article on a computer
screen.
<p>
   But despite the addition of a few audio clips, the biggest
difference between the online production and a magazine article is
the absence of glossy paper and liquor ads.
<p>
   That's not a bad thing, though, especially if you're interested
in rock icons like Bob Dylan and the managers, agents and producers
behind their careers.
<p>
   The first weekly installment, online through Thursday, examines
how Dylan and manager Albert Grossman carved out an unprecedented
degree of independence from the dictates of record companies.
<p>
   Music Central: http://musiccentral.msn.com or on MSN under
Essentials.
<p>
   (Art Kramer writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) .
</TEXT>
