<DOCID> nyt970122.0109 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tad-z> A8699 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0466 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TRAIN-COX &QL; 
 &UR; BOY'S PLAYFUL TRAIN RIDE ENDS IN TRAGEDY ALONGSIDE TRACKS &QL; 
 &UR; By JINGLE DAVIS &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Searchers who found the body of 7-year-old Carlos Wilson on
Tuesday said the boy made a valiant effort to survive after being
trapped in the cold night air on the outside of a moving freight
train.
<p>
   ``He held on for at least an hour to a ladder on one of the
freight cars, three or four cars back from the engine'' said
Jenkins County, Ga., Sheriff Bobby Womack. ``Poor little thing must
have been terrified, with all the noise and the cold.''
<p>
   The child, dressed only in jeans, sneakers and a short-sleeved
shirt, clung limpet-like to a grain car's ladder through the South
Georgia countryside for 43 miles, from his hometown of Millen to
rural Effingham County, the sheriff said.
<p>
   Carlos was ``probably'' alive when he jumped or fell from the
freight car just east of the tiny town of Oliver, Womack said.
<p>
   He said the body was found Tuesday in low-growing weeds about 20
feet from the tracks by searchers using a dog.
<p>
   ``It looked like he tried to scratch a little nest in the broom
straw to keep warm,'' Womack said, commenting that overnight
temperatures Sunday and Monday dipped into the high 30s. ``He'd
taken his shoes off and his heels looked like he'd scratched down
into the dirt. I think he must have died of shock or exposure,
because he just had one little cut on his head.''
<p>
   The Norfolk Southern Railroad freight train left Millen around
4:30 p.m. Sunday on a non-stop run from the small town to Savannah,
some 75 miles away, according to company spokesman Rick Harris, who
said the train's top speed was under 45 mph.
<p>
   Sheriff Womack said the episode began when Wilson and three
older boys were climbing freight car ladders while the train was
stopped at a switching area in Millen.
<p>
   When the train pulled out, the other boys jumped off.
<p>
   ``They were yelling at Carlos to jump, but he was probably
scared,'' Womack said.
<p>
   One of the friends said Carlos yelled from the train, telling
them to meet him at the next railroad station.
<p>
   The search for the child was delayed until 7 p.m. Sunday when
Carlos' mother, Louise Evans, a single parent, questioned her son's
playmates and learned what had happened.
<p>
   Carlos' cousin, Dorothea Young, who lives across the street,
said he was a happy youngster in a family of four boys, two younger
and one older.
<p>
   ``Carlos loved to play with the other children,'' Young said.
``But I know his mother didn't know he was climbing on the
trains.''
<p>
   Womack said an autopsy will be performed. Railroad investigators
are looking into the incident, Harris said.
<p>
   (Jingle Davis writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) .
</TEXT>
