<DOCID> nyt970122.0110 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8701 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-SHARES-UPDATE1-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0461 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-IBM-SHARES-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IBM STOCK DROPS AFTER DISAPPOINTING 4TH-QTR EARNINGS (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Margaret D. Williams &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds investor, analyst comments. Updates share price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Armonk, New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- International Business
Machines Corp.'s stock dropped as much as 7.7 percent after the
world's largest computer maker reported lower-than-expected
fourth-quarter sales and earnings.
<p>
   IBM shares fell 9 to 159 in midmorning trading of 6.32 million.
The stock accounted for 32 points of the 51.57-point drop in the
Dow Jones Industrial Average. Earlier, shares fell as low as 155,
after trading at ten-year highs in the past few weeks on investor
optimism about the earnings.
<p>
   ``The stock had run up in expectation that the numbers would be
higher,'' said Phil Sheeted, managing partner at Looms Sails &AMP; Co.,
which owns IBM stock.
<p>
   IBM yesterday said fourth-quarter profit rose 18 percent,
slightly less than expected, as a stronger dollar and weak demand
in Europe hurt results.
<p>
   IBM said net income rose to $2.02 billion, or $3.93 a share,
from $1.71 billion, or $3.09 a share, in the year-earlier quarter.
Sales climbed 5.6 percent to $23.14 billion from $21.92 billion.
<p>
   Earnings were below the most recent estimate of $3.96 a share
from 15 analysts polled by IBES International Inc. Several analysts
had said they expected earnings of more than $4.00.
<p>
   ``Given that the stock has run up, we're probably going to see
the beginning'' of a decline, said Morgan Stanley analyst Steven
Milunovich. The drop could be as much as 15 percent in the next
three to five months, he said.
<p>
   At least four analysts cut their earnings estimates for 1997.
IBM's Chief Financial Officer Richard Thoman said yesterday
continued weakness in memory chip prices and uncertainty about
currency could further hamper results.
<p>
   ``They are going to have a hard time doing an encore,'' said
industry analyst Bob Djurdjevic of Annex Research in Phoenix. On a
constant-currency basis, IBM said revenue rose 9 percent, its best
performance since 1985.
<p>
   IBM, like some other companies, was hurt by weak economies in
some European countries. Additionally, mainframe and workstation
sales were slow and falling memory-chip prices continued to hurt
results.
<p>
   Hardware sales edged up 2 percent to $11.7 billion, with
personal computer sales rising from the year-ago quarter in both
corporate products and home machines. System 390 mainframe sales
declined and RS/6000 workstation sales were unchanged from
year-earlier levels.
<p>
   ``The revenue growth story is not real strong at IBM,'' John
Rutledge, an analyst at Loomis, Sayles. ``The bloom is off the
rose.''
</TEXT>
