<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MONSANTO-RUSSIA-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MONSANTO'S PHARMACEUTICAL UNIT FORMS $32 MLN VENTURE IN RUSSIA &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Toni Clarke &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   St. Louis, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Monsanto Co. said its Searle
pharmaceutical unit formed a $32 million joint venture with a
Russian research center to make medical products in a new plant
outside Moscow.
<p>
   Under an agreement between Skokie, Illinois-based Searle and the
Biopreparaty/Russian Research Center for Molecular Diagnostics and
Therapy, Searle will provide cash, equipment and construction
services to build the 65,000-square-foot plant. It will make 40 to
50 medications, including cardiovascular and anti-infection drugs,
Searle said.
<p>
   The facility should be completed by the second quarter of 1999.
<p>
   ``Searle is convinced that this market has significant potential
to become a sizable marketplace for high-quality, cost-effective
pharmaceutical products,'' said Searle chief executive Richard De
Schutter.
<p>
   St. Louis-based Monsanto is in the process of transforming
itself from a chemicals company into one focusing on agricultural
biotechnology, food ingredients and pharmaceuticals.
</TEXT>
