<SLUG> BC-EARNS-UST-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0295 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-UST-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UST 4TH-QUARTER EARNINGS RISE 3.4% AS COMPETITION HURTS SALES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Leslie Hillman &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Greenwich, Connecticut, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- UST Inc. said its
fourth-quarter earnings rose 3.4 percent as competition in the
moist snuff industry cut into sales.
<p>
   UST, which makes Skoal and Copenhagen brand snuff, said net
income rose to $114.5 million, or 61 cents a share, from $110.7
million, or 56 cents, in the year-ago quarter. Revenue after excise
taxes rose 2.2 percent to $352.5 million from $344.9 million.
<p>
   The Greenwich, Connecticut-based company, which also makes
Washington state's Chateau Ste. Michelle and Columbia Crest wines,
said its non-tobacco sales rose in the fourth quarter.
<p>
   The results matched a forecast the company released two weeks
ago when it said its fourth-quarter earnings would fall short of
analysts' expectations because of lower-than-expected sales. UST
shares fell 1/8 to 30 7/8 in midmorning trading.
<p>
   UST, the nation's largest maker of moist snuff with about 80
percent of the market, said its unit sales fell 3 percent for the
fourth quarter. Competition from discounted brands, a pricing
policy change at military commissaries and sales of new products
caused the drop, the company said.
<p>
   UST, which has some of the highest-priced brands, has seen its
market share eroded by lower-priced brands.
<p>
   In response, UST has said it won't raise prices as much as in
the past or may even discount some brands, which it said may affect
earnings growth.
<p>
   For the year, net income rose 8 percent to $464 million, or
$2.42 a share, from $429.8 million, or $2.16. Revenue rose 5.4
percent to $1.40 billion from $1.33 billion.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1059EST
</TRAILER>
