<DOCID> nyt970122.0115 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8737 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-SHARES-UPDATE1-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0470 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-IBM-SHARES-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IBM STOCK DROPS AFTER DISAPPOINTING 4TH-QTR EARNINGS (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Margaret D. Williams &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds investor, analyst comments. Updates share price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Armonk, New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- International Business
Machines Corp.'s stock dropped as much as 7.7 percent after the
world's largest computer maker reported lower-than-expected sales
and earnings for the fourth quarter.
<p>
   IBM's stock fell 9 to 159 in midmorning trading of 5.96 million
shares. The stock accounted for 32 points of the 51.57 point drop
in the Dow Jones Industrial Average. Earlier, shares fell as low as
155. The stock had been trading at ten-year highs in the past few
weeks as investors were optimistic about the earnings.
<p>
   ``The stock had run up in expectation that the numbers would be
higher,'' said Phil Shettewi, portfolio manager at Loomis Sayles &AMP;
Co., which owns IBM stock.
<p>
   IBM yesterday said fourth-quarter profit rose 18 percent,
slightly less than expected, as a stronger dollar and weak demand
in Europe hurt results.
<p>
   IBM said net income rose to $2.02 billion, or $3.93 a share,
from $1.71 billion, or $3.09 a share, in the year-earlier quarter.
Sales climbed 5.6 percent to $23.14 billion from $21.92 billion.
<p>
   Earnings were below the most recent estimate of $3.96 a share
from 15 analysts polled by IBES International Inc. Several analysts
had said they expected earnings of more than $4.00.
<p>
   ``Given that the stock has run up, we're probably going to see
the beginning'' of a decline, said Morgan Stanley analyst Steven
Milunovich. The drop could be as much as 15 percent in the next
three to five months, he said.
<p>
   At least four analysts cut their earnings estimates for 1997.
IBM's Chief Financial Officer Richard Thoman said yesterday
continued weakness in memory chip prices and uncertainty about
currency could further hamper results.
<p>
   `` They are going to have a hard time doing an encore,'' said
industry analyst Bob Djurdjevic of Annex Research in Phoenix. On a
constant currency basis, IBM said revenue rose 9 percent, its best
performance since 1985.
<p>
   IBM, like some other companies, was hurt by weak economies in
some European countries. Additionally, mainframe and workstation
sales were slow and falling memory-chip prices continued to hurt
results.
<p>
   Hardware sales edged up 2 percent to $11.7 billion, with
personal computer sales rising from the year-ago quarter in both
corporate products and home machines. System 390 mainframe sales
declined and RS/6000 workstation sales were unchanged from
year-earlier levels.
<p>
   ``The revenue growth story is not real strong at IBM,'' John
Rutledge, analyst at Boston's Loomis, Sayles &AMP; Co. said. ``The
bloom is off the rose.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1106EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0116 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8748 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FASTENAL-COMPANY-SPOT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0980 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FASTENAL-COMPANY-SPOTLIGHT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FASTENAL TRIPS SHORT-SELLERS BETTING ON FALL: COMPANY SPOTLIGHT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Daniel Fisher &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Winona, Minnesota, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Fastenal Co.
shareholders aren't the only ones nervous about the company's
fourth-quarter earnings report due Friday.
<p>
   Short-sellers -- speculators who sold borrowed shares in the
hope of buying them back at a lower price -- may have more at
stake.
<p>
   They've sold short almost 4 million shares in a gamble that the
fast-growing distributor of nuts, bolts and other industrial
supplies, which has come up short of Wall Street earnings estimates
in the last two quarters, will again miss forecasts. That, they
hope, might finally deflate Fastenal's sky-high stock price of more
than 50 times estimated 1997 earnings.
<p>
   On the other side of the bet is the big mutual fund company
Janus Capital Corp., which stuffed its funds with $187 million in
Fastenal stock last summer.
<p>
   Janus officials wouldn't discuss Fastenal. But analyst Judith
Scott of Robert Baird &AMP; Co. thinks Janus will win this chapter of a
long-running battle between Fastenal's bulls and bears.
<p>
   ``Every year of its history there's been somebody who really
liked the stock and was willing to buy it at any price and made a
ton of money doing it,'' she said.
<p>
   The Winona, Minnesota, company has done plenty to confound its
critics. Earnings increased at a 35 percent annual rate in the five
years ended Dec. 30, 1995. Even with last year's earnings
disappointments, Scott said she thinks the company will end the
year with earnings of about 88 cents a share, more than 20 percent
above 1995.
<p>
   Adjusted for splits, Fastenal shares have soared more than
60-fold since the initial offering in 1987. The stock recently
traded at about 47. And while Fastenal is expensive compared with
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index, which has a price-to-earnings
ratio of 22, that's nothing new: The company's shares have traded
at an average of more than 50 times per-share earnings since 1993.
<p>
   Fastenal's performance is driven by a furious increase in sales
as it opens stores and adds new products. While it resembles a
wholesale distributor -- its stores tend to be in dingy industrial
areas, and a $10 minimum purchase discourages retail customers --
Fastenal's gross margins resemble Tiffany &AMP; Co. at more than 50
percent.
<p>
   Revenue soared to an estimated $300 million in 1996 from $20.3
million in 1987. Fastenal founder and Chief Executive Robert
Kierlin thinks growth will accelerate as the company starts
offering everything from janitorial supplies to cutting tools.
<p>
   ``We're hoping the economy stays reasonably strong and we'll be
able to put out 40 percent revenue growth in 1997,'' he said. ``It
should get better after that.''
<p>
   Such projections enrage short-sellers, who faced with
embarrassing losses decline to be quoted by name. They say the
company's vaunted growth rate is slowing, not accelerating. Indeed,
net income, which rose 57 percent in 1994 is expected to be up just
22 percent for 1996.
<p>
   And while revenue rose 28 percent to $210 million in the nine
months ended Sept. 30, revenue at stores open two years or more
rose only 20 percent, half the rate reported in 1995.
<p>
   Signs of slowing growth has short sellers speculating that
sooner or later, Fastenal shares will plunge. Short interest in the
stock has hung at about 4 million shares since August, representing
more than 14 percent of the float, or 27 million shares available
for trading. So many shares are sold short that it would take more
than 30 days of average trading in the stock for bearish
speculators to buy back all the shares they need to return to
brokers.
<p>
   Some short-sellers even say Janus propped up Fastenal shares
last year, when it reported disappointing earnings. The fund bought
3.88 million shares between March 30 and Sept. 30, according to
Securities and Exchange Commission filings, making Fastenal the
largest single holding in the $728 million Janus Enterprise Fund at
8.4 percent of assets.
<p>
   During that period, short-sellers say, some 30 million Fastenal
shares changed hands. Cutting the total in half to eliminate the
double-counting that analysts say is common in transactions on the
Nasdaq exchange, Janus represented a quarter of the trading in that
period.
<p>
   Janus just took advantage of the earnings disappointments to
assemble its stake, said analyst Scott of Baird &AMP; Co. Fastenal's
earnings were constrained last year, she said, because the company
boosted its work force by 40 percent to more than 3,000 to staff
promising new businesses.
<p>
   ``The reason they've missed numbers is the expenses of these
personnel,'' Scott said. ``They will get the payoff next year.''
<p>
   Kierlin certainly thinks so. He sees more growth potential in
businesses like janitorial services than in sticking with nuts and
bolts.
<p>
   ``The fastener business is $6 billion at wholesale, and we could
aspire to maybe 20 percent of the market,'' he said. ``Industrial
maintenance represents a $60 billion market.''
<p>
   So far, Kierlin has been right, watching an investment that
began with a single store in 1968 balloon to a market value of $219
million.
<p>
   Scott said many of the people who've bet against Fastenal over
the years -- commentator Dan Dorfman twice suggested in 1994 that
its shares would tumble, when in fact they more than doubled -- did
so on the misperception that the company competes with retail
hardware chains such as Home Depot Inc.
<p>
   In fact, Fastenal sells almost exclusively to commercial
customers. That hasn't stopped critics who look at the company's
expensive stock and conclude it's ready for a fall.
<p>
   These hopeful pessimists have waited a long time, but at some
point they may no choice but to say uncle.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1109EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0117 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8750 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EARNS-STRATUS-COMPUTE </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0311 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-STRATUS-COMPUTER-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; STRATUS 4TH-QTR PROFIT JUMPS 26%; CEO FOSTER SEEKS REPLACEMENT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Gerard Meuchner &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Marlboro, Massachusetts, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Stratus Computer
Inc. said fourth-quarter profit jumped a higher-than-expected 26
percent, boosted by lower costs and rising revenue at the maker of
computer systems.
<p>
   The company also said that founder and Chief Executive Bill
Foster plans to hire a new CEO by the end of the year. Foster said
in a statement that after almost 17 years running Stratus, ``the
timing is good for a new CEO.'' Foster will remain chairman of the
Marlboro, Massachusetts-based company.
<p>
   Stratus said fourth-quarter net income rose to $17.7 million, or
74 cents a share, from $14.1 million, or 60 cents, in the
year-earlier period. Revenue in the quarter ended Dec. 29 rose 4.6
percent to $176.1 million from $168.4 million.
<p>
   Results were higher than the most recent estimate of 63 cents a
share from 10 analysts polled by IBES International Inc.
<p>
   Stratus makes fault-tolerant systems that are used for bank
machines, telephone systems, gasoline pumps and other machines
where availability is crucial. Its shares were unchanged at 29 3/4
in late morning trading.
<p>
   The company's expenses for research and development,
compensation and other administrative functions fell 11.2 percent
to $57.3 million from $64.5 million.
<p>
   In August, Stratus announced that Foster would resume as CEO
after Gary Haroian resigned. Foster said at the time that he and
Haroian had a difference of opinion about the company's direction.
<p>
   The fourth-quarter sales increase at Stratus comes after two
quarters in which revenue growth stalled. In both the third and
second quarters of 1996, revenue was unchanged from the year-ago
period.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1110EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0118 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8759 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-US-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0787 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ECONOMY-US-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. ECONOMY: 1996 HOUSING STARTS STRONGEST IN EIGHT YEARS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Vincent Del Giudice and Marthe Fourcade &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- House construction enjoyed a
banner year in 1996, posting the strongest annual gain in eight
years, though snow, flooding and mud slides in the West depressed
December building activity, new figures showed today.
<p>
   Starts of new houses last year rose 8.8 percent to 1.474
million, the highest level since 1988. The increase was fueled by a
dip in 30-year fixed mortgage interest rates below 7 percent early
in the year and a pickup in economic activity in the fourth
quarter.
<p>
   Builders and analysts said the unexpectedly large 12.2 percent
decline in December starts, following a revised 9.3 percent
increase in November, doesn't mean the bottom has fallen out of the
housing market.
<p>
   ``We have relatively stable interest rates, and the highest
housing affordability in a long time,'' said Joel Rassman, chief
financial officer for Toll Brothers Inc., a Huntington Valley,
Pennsylvania, company that builds houses in 13 Eastern states.
<p>
   High levels of consumer confidence and job creation, plus rising
incomes and still-low mortgage rates, lead builders to expect a
strong year, though few expect this year's level of starts to top
1996.
<p>
   ``I'm rather optimistic about 1997 now that it's arrived --much
more optimistic than I was six or seven months ago,'' said Robert
Strudler, chief executive officer of U.S. Home Corp. in Houston.
Added Leonard Miller, chairman of Miami-based Lennar Corp.: ``You
see no major buildup of inventories in the industry.''
<p>
   In financial markets, U.S. government bond prices were little
changed after the report, leaving the yield on the Treasury's
benchmark 30-year bond at 6.78 percent. Stocks were mixed in New
York trading and the dollar was higher against other major
currencies.
<p>
   In December, alone, all regions of the country reported a drop
in new starts as the monthly rate fell to 1.329 million, adjusted
for seasonal variations -- the lowest since June 1995, according to
the Commerce Department. The flood-ravaged West was especially hard
hit. Analysts had expected a 2.8 percent decline for December
instead of the 12.2 percent drop reported.
<p>
   Meanwhile, permits for new housing construction fell 0.6 percent
nationwide in December to an annual rate of 1.410 million, rate
after increasing 4.1 percent in November, the Commerce Department
said.
<p>
   By category, single-family housing construction dropped 11.8
percent during December while multi-family projects declined 13.6
percent from a month earlier.
<p>
   By region last month, housing starts plunged 29.2 percent in the
West to a rate of 257,000; dropped 7.9 percent in the Midwest to
302,000; fell 7.2 percent in the South to 645,000; and declined 2.3
percent in the Northeast to 125,000.
<p>
   Though bad weather played a role in December's showing, that's
not entirely unexpected since home building usually ``winds down in
the winter months'' said Scott Brown, an economist at Raymond James
&AMP; Associates in St. Petersburg, Florida. ``We're going to see a
pickup in housing starts when the weather clears,'' said Carl
Palash, chief economist at MCM MoneyWatch in New York.
<p>
   And with mortgage rates still at historically low levels, starts
``should be relatively robust'' in 1997, perhaps reaching a total
of 1.38 million, Brown said.
<p>
   At Dallas-based Centex Corp., one of the nation's largest home
builders and mortgage originators, spokeswoman Sheila Gallagher
said by the end of the company's fiscal year in March, Centex will
have built and delivered about 12,500 new homes, but that the total
will likely drop to 12,000 for the fiscal year ending March 1998.
After marching higher over several months, the average rate on a
30-year fixed loan fell to 7.60 percent in December from 7.62
percent in November, according to Bloomberg analytics.
<p>
   That put the average principal and interest payment on a
$100,000 loan at $706.07 last month, down from $707.45 a month
before. Those figures don't include tax, fire insurance or escrow
costs.
<p>
   In the most recent week, the average 30-year mortgage rate rose
2 basis points to 7.87 percent.
<p>
   The next move in home construction -- and sales -- will be
plainly evident when the weather turns milder in a few months.
<p>
   ``The real question is when does the consumer decide that the
time (to buy) is now,'' said Ira Norris, president of INCO Homes in
Upland, California. `I think people need to believe that housing
prices are on the rise before they buy, and right now the urgency
is not there.''
</TEXT>
