<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-SIGNET-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SIGNET 4TH-QTR EARNINGS RISE 6% ON INCREASED LENDING, FEES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Joseph A. Giannone &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Richmond, Virginia, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Signet Banking Corp.
said fourth-quarter profit from operations rose 6 percent on
increased lending and service charges.
<p>
   The Richmond, Virginia-based bank said fourth-quarter earnings
rose to $33.6 million, or 55 cents a share, from $9 million, or 15
cents, in the same period in 1995.
<p>
   Not counting a $35 million charge for losses from commercial
loan fraud and earnings from Capital One Corp. before its spin-off
to shareholders in February, 1995, the company said its net income
for the fourth quarter of 1995 was $31.8 million, or 53 cents a
share.
<p>
   Fourth-quarter 1996 earnings were a penny over the average
forecast of 54 cents a share, according to a Zacks Investment
Research survey of 13 analysts. Signet shares were unchanged at 30
1/4.
<p>
   ``Targeted commercial and consumer businesses were very well
received in the marketplace,'' said Malcolm McDonald, Signet
chairman and chief executive, in a statement.
<p>
   Net interest income rose 1 percent to $116.7 million. Total
loans rose 12.7 percent to $6.32 billion, however net interest
margin, or the difference between what a bank pays for deposits and
earns on loans, narrowed to 4.56 percent from 4.78 percent.
<p>
   Noninterest income, excluding securities gains, rose 25 percent
to $84.7 million, driven by fees for loan service charges and other
fees.
<p>
   Noninterest expense, excluding the $35 million charge for loan
fraud in 1995, rose 6.9 percent to $125.3 million, as salaries and
benefits increased.
<p>
   The bank increased the amount it sets aside for future loan
losses 60 percent to $29.8 million, though non-performing assets
fell 29 percent to $38.8 million.
</TEXT>
