<SLUG> BC-EU-BA-AMERICAN-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0449 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EU-BA-AMERICAN-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EU'S VAN MIERT SEES RISK OF NATIONAL COURT FIGHTS OVER BA-AA &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By James G. Neuger &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Brussels, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The European Commission raised
the specter of court fights across Europe if the U.K. government
waves through the planned alliance of British Airways Plc and
American Airlines over European antitrust objections.
<p>
   Opening a new front in the battle over the U.S.-U.K. airline
linkup, European Union Competition Commissioner Karel Van Miert
said any court challenge by the commission would prompt a slew of
suits by rival air carriers.
<p>
   Van Miert held out hope that the U.K. government will tie its
approval to further concessions by the two airlines, preventing
them from gaining a stranglehold on routes between the U.K. and
U.S., the biggest transatlantic air travel market.
<p>
   ``I hope it has come across that our desire is not one of
looking for a conflict,'' Van Miert told a press conference. ``It's
a long flight, a difficult flight with a lot of turbulence.''
<p>
   The feud over the claim by the commission, the EU's executive
agency, that it has jurisdiction over the air alliance has gone to
the highest reaches of the U.K. government, with Prime Minister
John Major calling it a wholly British matter.
<p>
   Van Miert last week threatened to take the U.K. government to
court if it okayed the alliance, which the commission says would
curtail competition on routes between the U.K. and U.S.
<p>
   In December, the U.K. government called on BA and American,
owned by AMR Corp., to give up 168 of their 3,352 weekly
takeoff-and-landing slots at London's Heathrow Airport, equivalent
to 12 daily round-trip flights and far few than rival U.S. airlines
had demanded.
<p>
   BA and American plan to unite their transatlantic flights, fares
and marketing, creating a BA-AA brand similar to partnerships
between U.S. and European carriers, such as KLM Royal Dutch
Airlines and Northwest Airlines Corp.
<p>
   BA and American already control 60 percent of U.S.-U.K. air
traffic and 24 percent of U.S.-Europe traffic. The two operate
every flight on some routes, such as Heathrow-Dallas and
Heathrow-Boston.
<p>
   Under EU law, the commission could appeal to the European Court
of Justice if it determines the alliance is illegal. In turn,
airlines like Lufthansa AG and Air France would be free to file
suit in their national courts.
<p>
   ``That gives the opportunity to competitors to go to court, not
just the European Court, but to take it to national court,'' Van
Miert said. He underlined that the commission is looking at all air
alliances, not only the U.K.-U.S. pact.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1124EST
</TRAILER>
