<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-CORESTATES-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CORESTATES FINANCIAL 4TH-QTR NET RISES 1.8% ON SLOW LOAN GROWTH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Marjorie Shaffer &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Philadelphia, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- CoreStates Financial Corp.
said its fourth-quarter net income rose 1.8 percent as cost savings
and strong gains internationally couldn't offset slow loan growth.
<p>
   The nation's 21st-largest bank company reported net income rose
to $195.5 million, or 91 cents a share, from $192.1 million or 87
cents a share. The earnings were slightly below Wall Street's
expectations of 94 cents a share, according to a survey of 19
analysts by IBES International Inc.
<p>
   The fourth-quarter figures include the costs of CoreStates'
merger with Meridian Bancorp. last year. Without those costs,
earnings rose 2.8 percent to $201.6 million, or 93 cents a share,
from $196.1 million, or 89 cents.
<p>
   Revenue fell 1.3 percent to $761.5 million from $771.9 million.
Net interest income fell 2.0 percent as net interest margin
declined to 5.51 percent form 5.56 percent.
<p>
   For the full year, net income fell 0.9 percent to $649.1
million, or $2.97 a share, from $655.2 million or $2.95, a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
