<SLUG> BC-EARNS-BEAR-STEARNS-UP </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0509 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-BEAR-STEARNS-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BEAR STEARNS COS. FISCAL 2ND-QTR NET UP 68% (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Scott W. Martin &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds additional background and comment from Chief Executive
Officer James Cayne.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Bear Stearns Cos. said earnings
in its fiscal second quarter rose 68 percent to a record $176.5
million, led by trading and investment banking.
<p>
   The sixth-biggest U.S. securities firm's net income for the
three months ended Dec. 31 rose to $1.27 a share, from $105.2
million, or 72 cents, in the same period a year earlier.
<p>
   That exceeded the average forecast of 89 cents a share from six
analysts surveyed by IBES International Inc. The estimates ranged
from 82 cents a share to 95 cents. Bear Stearns shares rose 1/2 to
30 3/8.
<p>
   ``Bear Stearns had a strong underwriting business and a good
trading environment in all markets,'' said John Keefe, an
independent securities analyst.
<p>
   Bear Stearns' results come amid a surge in securities firms'
profits as low interest rates and record highs in the stock market
boost trading, underwriting and mergers and acquisitions. Yesterday
Salomon Inc., the world's biggest bond trader, said fourth quarter
earnings rose 36 percent, while Smith Barney Inc., the
second-biggest broker, posted a 21 percent gain in profits.
<p>
   ``These are the best quarterly results Bear Stearns has ever
had, representing the sixth consecutive quarter in which our return
on common equity has topped 20 percent,'' said Bear Stearns Chief
Executive Officer James Cayne. The firm's return on shareholders
equity, a key measure of profitability, was 33 percent in the
second quarter.
<p>
   Bear Stearns, one of Wall Street's biggest traders of stocks and
bonds, said revenue for the quarter after interest expense rose 37
percent to $940.1 million from $688 million in the year-earlier
period.
<p>
   Trading revenue rose 65 percent to a record $429.2 million.
Trading contributed 46 percent of the firm's net revenue in the
second quarter, versus 43 percent in the same period a year
earlier.
<p>
   Investment banking revenue rose 22 percent to $183 million. Bear
Stearns was the eighth-biggest underwriter of U.S. stocks and bonds
during the quarter, according to Securities Data Co., a Newark, New
Jersey-based firm that tracks the securities industry. Bear Stearns
was the fifth-largest arranger of high-yield debt sales, the most
profitable bond underwriting for Wall Street firms.
<p>
   Brokerage commissions rose 12 percent to $184 million in the
second quarter.
<p>
   Bear Stearns' non-interest expense increased 27 percent in the
second quarter to $650 million. Compensation as a percentage of net
revenue in the quarter was 49 percent versus 50 percent in the same
period a year earlier.
<p>
   For sixth months ending December 31, 1996, Bear Stearns earned
$285.0 million, or $2.02 a share, up 43 percent from $199 million,
or $1.36, a year earlier. The firm's return on shareholders' equity
was 27 percent.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1131EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0125 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8792 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LION-ABC-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0187 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FOOD-LION-ABC-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DISNEY'S ABC ORDERED TO PAY FOOD LION $5.5 MLN IN DAMAGES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Joseph Menn &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Greensboro, North Carolina, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Walt Disney
Co.'s ABC television network must pay Food Lion Inc. $5.5 million
in punitive damages for having two news producers lie to get jobs
at the supermarket chain, a federal jury decided.
<p>
   After more than five days of hard-fought deliberations, the
12-member jury decided that ABC and its ``PrimeTime Live'' program
consciously broke fraud laws to get undercover footage for a 1992
expose on food handling at the supermarket chain.
<p>
   Food Lion claimed the report cost it more than $2 billion in
lost profit and stock value.
<p>
   The jury spared the two producers but directed two ABC
executives to pay a total of $45,750.
<p>
   The Greensboro, North Carolina, jury last month awarded Food
Lion $1,402 in compensatory damages, mostly for the salaries earned
by the producers at the stores.
<p>
   Belgian grocery chain Delhaize-Le Lion SA owns about half Food
Lion's voting stock.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1132EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0126 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8794 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EARNS-AT&AMP;T-UPDATE2-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0950 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-AT&AMP;T-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AT&AMP;T'S 4TH-QTR PROFIT FALLS SHORT OF EXPECTATIONS (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Colleen McElroy &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates with analysts comment, details on uncollectible bills,
number of employees at year end. Adds stock price)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- AT&AMP;T Corp.'s fourth-quarter
earnings fell short of expectations as a slight improvement in
long-distance operations was offset by higher costs related to
unpaid bills.
<p>
   Profit from continuing operations rose 14 percent to $1.24
billion, or 76 cents a share, from $1.09 billion, or 68 cents, in
the year-earlier period. Wall Street was expecting 80 cents, the
average estimate of 25 analysts from IBES International Inc.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T's results show the company is beginning to stem customer
defections in its long-distance operations. However, the turnaround
is in its early stages and could take several quarters to complete,
analysts said.
<p>
   ``There is movement in the right direction,'' said Barry Sine,
an analyst at SBC Warburg Inc. ``The problem is the rate of
improvement is not substantial enough to meet expectations.''
<p>
   AT&AMP;T's sales rose 2.7 percent to $13.24 from $12.89 billion.
Continuing operations include AT&AMP;T's long-distance, wireless,
Internet and credit-card businesses.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T shares fell 3/4 to 38 5/8 at late morning.
<p>
   Volume, or the amount of traffic the company carried on its
long-distance network, rose six percent -- up from 5 percent in the
third quarter. AT&AMP;T said it began to see ``early-stage benefits''
from efforts to stem market-share loss such as its flat-rate
calling plan.
<p>
   The AT&AMP;T One Rate plan has 3 million customers that have come
from other AT&AMP;T calling plans as well as from competitors. It lets
users make long-distance calls for 15 cents a minute anywhere in
the U.S. and at any time.
<p>
   The plan ``is meeting AT&AMP;T's expectations for reducing customer
churn,'' AT&AMP;T said. Churn is the rate at which customers leave AT&AMP;T
for another long-distance carrier.
<p>
   ``They may have turned the corner, ending the decreasing growth
rates in volume,'' said Robert Wilkes, an analyst at Brown Brothers
Harriman.
<p>
   Still, AT&AMP;T's volume growth is expected to be the lowest among
the top three U.S. long-distance carriers. Analysts expect No. 2
MCI Communications Corp. to boost volume nine percent, while No. 3
Sprint Corp. is seen increasing volume 10 percent or more.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T said sales from communications services -- which includes
long-distance and wireless -- rose 4.3 percent to $12.86 billion.
<p>
   Operating profit for communications services rose more than 14
percent to $1.91 billion, while operating margin widened to 14.8
percent from 13.5 percent.
<p>
   Uncollectibles
<p>
   AT&AMP;T for the first time cited ``uncollectible'' expenses in its
long-distance business resulting from unpaid phone bills related to
fraud, delinquencies and bankruptcies among its business customers.
The problem bills increased AT&AMP;T's expenses by $200 million in the
quarter.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T expects the uncollectible items to cost the company $100
million, or 4 cents a share per quarter, for the next few quarters.
<p>
   ``We don't think that's a one-time event,'' said Eileen
Connolly, an AT&AMP;T spokeswoman.
<p>
   Analysts said other phone companies may report similar trends.
``It's something to put on the radar screen,'' Wilkes said.
<p>
   Wireless revenue rose 18 percent to $937 million, while the
company boosted its number of cellular customers 32 percent to 5.2
million. AT&AMP;T said that number includes more than 900,000 digital
wireless customers.
<p>
   Sales from communications products and other services, including
consulting and online services, rose 17 percent to $386 million.
Less than a year after it was unveiled, AT&AMP;T's WorldNet
Internet-access service has 568,000 customers.
<p>
   Financial services revenue fell 32 percent to $374 million
because of the company's 1995 program to diversify funding sources
for its AT&AMP;T Universal Card services, AT&AMP;T said.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T's financial services business had an operating loss of $4
million, compared with an operating profit of $109 million a year
earlier. However, that's narrower than the $35 million loss in the
third quarter.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T's total operating expenses from continuing operations rose
2 percent. The company said ``significant'' increases in network
expenses was offset by a decrease in access fees to connect to the
Bells's networks, and selling expenses.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T said it had 130,400 employees as of Dec. 31, up 1.5
percent. The increase bucks AT&AMP;T's plan, unveiled last January, to
slash 17,000 jobs from its long-distance, wireless and credit-card
businesses. AT&AMP;T has cut 5,700 jobs under that plan.
<p>
   Those cuts have been offset by an increase in jobs at its
wireless and customer care positions for offering a package of
services.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T also said it plans this year to buy stock in the open
market for shareowner and employee-benefit plans, rather than issue
new shares, to try to decrease dilution from such plans. In the
1995 fourth quarter, AT&AMP;T said restructuring and other charges
reduced profit by $2.04 billion, or $1.27 a share, resulting in a
bottom-line loss of $948 million, or 59 cents.
<p>
   During the 1996 quarter, New York-based AT&AMP;T completed its
massive restructuring that spun off NCR Corp. and Lucent
Technologies Inc. It also tapped R.R. Donnelley &AMP; Sons Co. Chief
Executive John Walter to succeed Chairman Robert Allen in 1998.
<p>
   For 1996, AT&AMP;T said income from continuing operations rose to
$5.61 billion, or $3.47 a share, from $5.24 billion, or $3.29 a
year earlier.
<p>
   Sales for 1996 rose to $52.18 billion from $50.66 billion.
</TEXT>
