<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-STOCKS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. STOCKS MIXED AS RETREAT IN IBM SHAVES DOW INDUSTRIALS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Roger Madoff and Philip Boroff &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. stocks were mixed as
International Business Machines Corp.'s weaker-than-expected profit
dragged the Dow Jones Industrial Average lower.
<p>
   Compaq Computer Corp. and Bristol-Myers Squibb Co. added
surprisingly strong earnings announcements to this week's pile of
profit reports, helping broader averages set records for a fifth
straight session.
<p>
   IBM, the world's largest computer maker, sank 9 5/8 to 158 3/8,
trimming 34 points from the Dow industrials. The 30-stock Dow
average slid 59.27 to 6824.63, after dropping as much as 75.82
points.
<p>
   The benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index, which comprises 75
percent of the market capitalization of U.S. stocks -- rose 0.15 to
782.87. The computer-industry weighted Nasdaq Composite Index
gained 7.67 to 1384.64, paced by Microsoft Corp. for a third day.
``The market right now just wants to go up,'' said Kenneth Corba,
chief investment officer at Eagle Asset Management, which oversees
$2.7 billion. ``We're in a hospitable environment.''
<p>
   Outside of IBM, ``there's been no series of earnings
disappointments,'' Corba said.
IBM
<p>
   IBM said fourth-quarter profit rose 18 percent, slightly less
than expected, as a stronger dollar and weak demand in Europe hurt
results. Net income for the computer maker rose to $3.93 a share, 3
cents below analysts' expectations.
<p>
   ``They had some trouble in Europe,'' said analyst Bruce Raabe of
Collins &AMP; Co. ``And hardware sales were the weakest story.''
<p>
   The impact of IBM's disappointment was offset by
better-than-expected profits at Compaq. The Houston-based computer
maker said earnings gained 43 percent, to $1.64 a share, surpassing
expectations by 11 cents. Compaq rose 3 3/4 to 82 1/4.
<p>
   ``I don't think IBM is the bellwether for technology, any more
than General Motors is the bellwether for the U.S. economy,'' said
Sally Anderson, senior money manager at Kopp Investment Advisors,
which oversees $3.4 billion and holds about $8 million of IBM
stock.
<p>
   ``The economy has become much more diverse,'' Anderson said.
``There have been so many new companies, and they've diluted the
impact of the big ones.''
Bristol-Myers
<p>
   Bristol-Myers earnings rose 11 percent to $1.43 a share, 2 cents
above analysts' expectations, according to IBES International Inc.
The shares dropped 1/4 to 121 3/8.
<p>
   Dean Witter Discover &AMP; Co., the brokerage and credit card
issuer, said profit rose 28 percent, also topping forecasts. Its
shares rose 3/4 to 37 7/8.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T Corp. said its profit rose to 76 cents a share from 68
cents a year earlier. Analysts expected 80 cents a share, according
to IBES International Inc. The long-distance company's shares lost
3/4 to 38 5/8.
<p>
   Stocks received no help from bonds, which declined as the
Treasury prepared to sell debt and a Federal Reserve governor
revived concern that the central bank may raise interest rates
soon. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond, used as a benchmark
for corporate borrowing costs, was little changed at 6.79 percent.
<p>
   Still, with the Dow industrials up 6.36 percent already this
year, ``investors are more sensitive to news that's unfavorable
than news that's favorable,'' said Philip Roth, chief technical
analyst at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1136EST
</TRAILER>
