<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-DOLLAR-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0297 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-AUSTRALIA-DOLLAR-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AUSTRALIA DOLLAR LITTLE CHANGED AS REPORTS POINT TO LOWER RATES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Tom Giles &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Australian dollar was
little changed as a series of reports highlighting the country's
sluggish economy bolstered the expectation that the central bank
will cut interest rates.
<p>
   ``The Australian dollar is under pressure from the fact that
they are still talking about lower rates over there,'' said Mike
Norton, a trader at ING Baring Capital Markets. ``The economy is
still a little struggling, and they need to do something to jump
start it.''
<p>
   The Australian dollar was recently quoted at 77.59 cents, little
changed from yesterday's 77.77 cents.
<p>
   Weak retail sales and a high jobless rate will continue to
restrain the economy until the middle of the year and keep alive
chances the central bank will cut rates, said Access Economics, an
Australian forecasting group.
<p>
   ``We expect output growth to accelerate from mid 1997 as world
activity picks up, housing recovers, public-sector cuts slow and
the stock cycle turns,'' Access said in a 1997 outlook report
prepared for clients.
<p>
   In other economic news, while the Westpac-Melbourne Institute's
index of economic activity rose 0.6 percent in November, most of
that came from new building activity related to the 2000 Olympics
in Sydney.
<p>
   Further, weekly wages for workers in the centralized wage system
were unchanged in November, alleviating concern that wages could
fuel inflation.
<p>
   That, in turn, did little to damp expectation that the central
bank will cut rates soon. Lower rates hurt the Australian dollar by
making holdings denominated in it less attractive to investors.
</TEXT>
