<SLUG> BC-MCCONAL-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0556 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-MCCONAL-TEXAS-TEX &QL; 
NORWEGIAN HERITAGE ALIVE IN TINY TOWN &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
By JON McCONAL &QC; 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NORSE, Texas  &MD;  Pernell Aars' voice is deep and commanding.
<p>
   You look at this man with sheet-white chin whiskers and huge
fingers crooked from years of work and immediately want to sit and
listen to him tell a story or two.
<p>
   So here I sat with Aars and his wife Rosalie in the majestic Our
Savior's Lutheran Church, organized in 1869, and listened to
stories of the early Norwegians who came here in 1854.
<p>
   ``They said Bosque County was like Norway, so eight families
came here from East Texas,'' he said. ``By 1880 about 1,000
Norwegians lived here.''
<p>
   That included Cleng Peerson, known as the Father of Norwegian
Immigration to America.
<p>
   ``He is buried in the cemetery,'' said Rosalie Aars.
<p>
   That helped to bring the King of Norway in 1982 to this tiny
settlement about six miles west of Clifton and 70 miles
south-southwest of Fort Worth.
<p>
   ``I've been going to church here 83 years. Was baptized here,''
Pernell Aars said.
<p>
   Sunlight flashed though the beautiful stained-glass windows as
he talked.
<p>
   ``The interior is much the same as the original,'' Rosalie Aars
said. ``And they have had church here every Sunday since 1876.''
<p>
   Then we walked to the cemetery to look at Peerson's grave. We
stopped at the marker of the Rev. John K. Rystad, the pastor from
1878 to 1925.
<p>
   ``That was 47 years. Can you imagine a man staying that long
anywhere?'' he said.
<p>
   We came to Peerson's marker, a towering stone edifice. One side
reads: ``The pioneer of Norse immigration to America. Born in
Norway May 17, 1782. Landed in America in 1821 and died in Texas
Dec. 16, 1865.''
<p>
   The other side is written in Norwegian.
<p>
   We wandered past graves of Colwicks, Branhagens, Amundsons and
Wegners. Rosalie Aars pointed to an old marker with the fading
letters of August, 1862.
<p>
   The man's name was Evan Questad. His father was Carl Questad,
one of the original settlers who gave land for this cemetery and
later sold land for the church site.
<p>
   ``The story was that he (Evan) was standing watch for Indians.
He developed pneumonia and died,'' she said. ``The strange thing
was that it happened in August, when getting pneumonia seems
unusual.''
<p>
   There are other unusual stories about people buried here. One
concerns Gustav Wilhelm Belfroge.
<p>
   He was a world-renowned Norwegian naturalist and lived in this
community from 1870 to 1879.
<p>
   History says that he accumulated a great collection of insects
by setting his traps at night under two great live oaks that once
stood in front of a blacksmith shop.
<p>
   He sent many of his specimens back to Norway, where they were
placed in the national museum.
<p>
   The story goes that Belfroge's fondness for nature was matched
by his fondness for drink.
<p>
   Sometimes, he had no money to buy liquor. He solved the problem
by drinking the alcohol ]in which his specimens were preserved.
<p>
   He died Dec. 7, 1882. He had an insect collection that numbered
36,881 and was valued then at $368.
<p>
   He is buried in Norse in an unmarked grave. Some people say that
the spot once could be found because no insect would crawl over
that ground.
<p>
   (Jon McConal is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.)
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1150EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0131 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8808 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ROCHE-EUROPE-TODAY-UP </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1360 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ROCHE-EUROPE-TODAY-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ROCHE ACQUISITION WATCH INTENSIFIES: EUROPE TODAY (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Dane Hamilton &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds closing share prices in 6th paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   London, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Roche Holding AG was in the
spotlight again today as shares in the Swiss drugmaker surged on
speculation it is planning a major acquisition.
<p>
   In an industry where the companies keep getting bigger as their
numbers shrink, the cash-rich Roche is almost sure to make a major
acquisition soon, analysts say.
<p>
   Such speculation is not new. For several years, shares in
possible targets like Britain's Zeneca Group Plc, Warner-Lambert
Co. in the U.S. and Sweden's Astra AB have jumped with the view
that Roche could be looking to buy them.
<p>
   While the company insists it is well placed without an
acquisition, shares rose today as much as 11 percent on what
analysts said was speculation it could be poised to sell its
under-performing Givaudan-Roure fragrances and flavorings division.
The proceeds could be used to further build its $10 billion war
chest for a major purchase, they say.
<p>
   ``If Roche wanted to shed a unit before strengthening its
pharmaceuticals portfolio, Givaudan would be a prime candidate,''
said Claudio Werder, an analyst at Bank J. Vontobel AG. ``It's the
one unit that fits least into the company's strategy.''
<p>
   Roche's widely traded non-voting shares jumped as high as 12,500
Swiss francs ($8,729), an intraday record, ending the day up 7
percent at 11,935 francs. Its closely held bearer shares ended
trading up 3 percent to 16,235.
<p>
   Speculation about a major Roche acquisition was heightened last
year when Sandoz AG and Ciba-Geigy AG joined to form Novartis AG.
The creation of Novartis, which received U.S. approval in December,
pushed Roche off of first place in the Swiss drugmaker league
table.
<p>
   ``Last summer, everybody was only talking about Novartis,'' said
Patrick Carisch, head of equities at Credit Suisse Asset Management
and a Roche shareholder. ``Now, Roche is back en vogue, and people
obviously expect something from the company sooner or later.''
<p>
   While Roche faces patent expirations of major drugs in several
years, the company that built itself on the success of the
antidepressant Valium has possible blockbuster drugs close to
market that could push growth, along with a big foothold in the
booming biotechnology market.
<p>
   The nagging question in investors' minds is whether the
Ciba-Sandoz union will prompt Roche to spend some of its $10
billion cash pile on an acquisition. The Ciba-Sandoz union merger,
which received final U.S. approval in December, booted Roche from
first to second place in the Swiss drugmaker league table and
eighth place worldwide.
<p>
   Dresdner Kleinwort Benson analyst Stuart Harris estimates Roche
could put together financing of $20 billion more. ``They could fund
a deal pretty easily,'' he said.
<p>
   The market has moved fast to drive up share prices of potential
takeover targets, betting that Roche would soon jump back on the
takeover bandwagon after its successful $5.3 billion takeover of
the Syntex Corp. in the U.S. in 1994.
<p>
   Two years ago, Zeneca, viewed as Roche's dream target for its
portfolio of new cardiovascular and cancer drugs, could have been
bought for half the $30 billion it would take today.
<p>
   Or, if Roche wanted to expand in the flourishing
over-the-counter healthcare products market like rival SmithKline
Beecham Plc, it could have bought Warner-Lambert Co., a U.S. market
leader with brands like Schick razors and Halls cough drops, for
around $15 billion in 1994. Now it would take twice that, analysts
said.
<p>
   Recently, even SmithKline was considered a Roche takeover
target. The blockbuster acquisition could easily cost $35 billion
or more, and would vault Roche beyond Britain's Glaxo Wellcome Plc
and Novartis, the two largest drug companies in market share.
<p>
   In an industry that has seen a record of nearly $100 billion
worth of mergers and acquisitions since 1994, such a bid could be
justified. No drugmaker now has more than 5 percent of the world
market. Analysts and industry executives say a 10 percent market
share is a good base for survival in a rapidly changing
marketplace. A Roche-SmithKline merger would put it closer to that,
though not all the way.
<p>
   Combating newly powerful group buyers of drugs and struggling to
cut costs to fund expensive research and development operations,
the worldwide drug industry has seen dozens of agreed or forced
marriages in recent years.
<p>
   The largest include Glaxo's $14.7 billion Wellcome takeover,
American Home Products Corp. purchase of American Cyanamid for $9.7
billion and Hoechst AG's purchase of Marion Merrill Dow for $7.1
billion.
<p>
   Roche says it's in no hurry to make an acquisition, which
analysts say may be partly because three founding families of the
company still control more than 50 percent of the voting stock.
They reportedly don't want their holdings diluted, as they would be
in a stock swap merger like that of Novartis.
<p>
   That leaves debt financing, a more expensive route, though one
which Roche hasn't been afraid to use. In addition to Syntex, Roche
paid cash in 1990 when it bought a controlling stake in
California-based Genentech Inc., one of the world's oldest and most
successful biotechnology companies, for $2.1 billion.
<p>
   Max Gurtner, spokesman for Roche, scoffs at the notion the
company is under pressure to buy anything.
<p>
   ``We will always remain subject to all these rumors because we
have this cash pile,'' said Gurtner. ``That will continue.''
<p>
   To counterbalance the argument that it must acquire something,
Gurtner points to Roche's unblemished record earnings growth in the
last nine years and strong pipeline of promising products.
<p>
   Last week, the company said 1996 sales had grown 11 percent to
15.9 billion Swiss francs ($11.6 billion) and that it expects
another rise in net profit in 1996, which it reports later in the
year.
<p>
   Like all drugmakers, Roche wants to expand its product base.
While it faces a patent expiration to one of its largest products,
the anesthetic Dormicum, also called Versed, in the U.S. in three
years, other products are in a stronger patent position.
<p>
   Its biggest seller, the widely used antibiotic Rocephin, which
generated 1.2 billion Swiss francs in 1995, won't face generic
competitors until 2002, analysts say, well after other products
will have reached the market.
<p>
   ``They are not in the situation of an Astra or a Glaxo, where
they have a huge product going off patent,'' said Genghis
Lloyd-Harris, a Credit Suisse First Boston analyst who rates the
stock a ``buy.''
<p>
   Among the products that are expected to drive strong growth are
the anti-obesity drug Xenical, which was filed for approval in the
U.S. last month; Posicor, a next generation calcium channel blocker
heart medication, and Invirase, a new AIDS medication that adds to
a stable of two other drugs to treat the deadly disease, Hivid and
Cytovene.
<p>
   Still, analysts think the company will make an acquisition soon.
<p>
   Lloyd-Harris said that while Roche has made a healthy, 14
percent return on its cash resources in recent years, the funds
could become too large in comparison to its drug operations in
coming years. This may be an enviable position for some but one
which raises questions about appropriate use of shareholders'
wealth, he said.
<p>
   ``There comes a point that your cash pool gets too big,'' said
Lloyd-Harris, which could be ``a compelling reason'' for an
acquisition.
<p>
   Speculation that disagreements on the need for an acquisition
may arise among Roche shareholders was evident this month when
Martin Ebner, the Swiss financier behind BZ Group, a Roche
shareholder, acknowledged that he had recently sold part of voting,
``bearer'' shares in the company.
<p>
   Ebner, at a press conference, denied it had to do with
disagreements. He didn't elaborate further.
<p>
   ``That's not because we're unhappy with the management, but
because we wanted to broaden our holdings,'' said Ebner.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1155EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0132 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8810 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EARNS-SGS-THOMSON-UPD </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1166 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-SGS-THOMSON-UPDATE5-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SGS-THOMSON SHARES PLUNGE 12% AFTER WARNING ON SALES (UPDATE5) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Melissa Pozsgay &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Closes out prices for shares traded in Paris.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Paris, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Shares of SGS-Thomson
Microelectronics NV plunged 12 percent after Europe's biggest
semiconductor maker said fourth-quarter profit fell 15.5 percent
and warned revenue could fall in the first quarter. Fourth-quarter
net fell to $142 million, or $1.02 a share, on sales of $1.06
billion. A year earlier, the company earned $168 million, or $1.24
a share, on sales of $974.7 million. While the decline in net was
expected, the company unnerved the market by saying first-quarter
sales will fall to about $988.4 million, hurt by weak prices caused
by oversupply in its lower-margin memory products. It expects
renewed growth throughout the rest of the year.
<p>
   ``SGS-Thomson's only problem is its share price has run ahead of
itself, in tandem with Intel, going too far too fast,'' said
Kenneth Anderson, a portfolio manager at Edinburgh-based Scottish
Widows Investment Management Ltd., which has some 20 billion pounds
($33 billion) in assets. ``The earnings and outlook in themselves
were broadly in keeping with expectations,'' he added.
<p>
   SGS-Thomson's warning comes a week after Intel Corp., the
world's biggest chipmaker, said rising expenses, price cuts and a
seasonal dip in demand will hamper its earnings too. SGS-Thomson's
shares took an extra hit when International Business Machines
Corp.'s stock began dropping in New York on lower-than-expected
fourth-quarter earnings.
<p>
   Shares of SGS-Thomson had more than doubled over the past 12
months. They rose 14 percent over the past week after Salomon
Brothers and Lehman Brothers increased their 12-month target for
the company's American depository receipts to $100. Lehman Brothers
reiterated that target price in a note today.
<p>
   SGS shares closed at 379 French francs ($68.5), down 12 percent
-- their biggest one-day drop ever. The ADR's fell 13.25 percent,
or $10 5/8, at 68 5/8 in early trading.
<p>
   ``What they said on the outlook for the first quarter can be
construed as a very slight profit warning,'' said John Fordyce, a
trader at Paris-based brokerage Ferri.
<p>
   Still, analysts and investors said SGS-Thomson's emphasis on
making high-margin specialty chips for the exploding market of
more-sophisticated digital consumer electronics products should
allow it to see strong growth once the semiconductor market has
overcome its latest slump.
<p>
   ``In spite of its comments on this quarter, SGS is still a
growth story within the semiconductor industry,'' said Patricia
d'Ille, who manages a $20 million fund at Monte Paschi Banque.
<p>
   D'Ille said she was taking advantage of the dip in SGS-Thomson
shares to add them to her portfolio.
<p>
   SGS-Thomson has bucked the trend of falling semiconductor sales
at companies including Motorola Inc. of the U.S. by concentrating
on high-margin chips used in cellular telephones, computer disc
drives and digital-television signal decoders.
<p>
   Fourth-quarter sales at SGS-Thomson, a French-Italian company,
were up 9 percent from a year earlier. Sales for the year rose 16
percent from a year earlier to $4.12 billion, with the biggest
growth coming from high-margin ``differentiated'' chips.
<p>
   Orders for such chips represented 58.6 percent of net revenues
in 1996, up from 51.5 percent in 1995. They were 61.3 percent of
sales in the fourth quarter.
<p>
   As part of its strategy, SGS-Thomson forms alliances with other
companies, including Alcatel Alsthom SA, Northern Telecom Inc.,
Hewlett-Packard Co. and disk drive maker Seagate Technology Inc.,
to develop the sophisticated chips they need. Those and other
companies accounted for 31 percent of SGS- Thomson's 1996 sales.
<p>
   Analysts said that strategy should pay off in 1997, as demand
for mobile phones and digital decoders takes off.
<p>
   ``I'm quite optimistic for SGS-Thomson, especially when I look
at the new technologies they've developed and the advances they
have,'' said Jim Tully, a technology analyst at Dataquest.
<p>
   As part of this strategy, SGS-Thomson recently agreed to work
with Microsoft Corp., the world's biggest maker of software for
personal computers, to design a new product to make it easier to
play digital video discs, or DVDs, on personal computers. DVDs are
expected to eventually replace video cassette recorders and CD-ROMs
used in multimedia computers.
<p>
   SGS-Thomson has largely steered clear of the competitive
dynamic-random-access memory chip market, where average prices were
slashed 75 percent last year as a surplus of chips flooded the
market. These chips are primarily used in personal computers and
basic consumer-electronics goods.
<p>
   Full-year net income rose 19 percent to $625.5 million, or $4.50
a share, compared with $526.5 million, or $4.03 a share, in 1995.
Analysts had predicted full-year earnings of $4.46 a share.
Full-year operating income rose 23 percent to $799.4 million.
<p>
   Per-share earnings were based on average shares outstanding of
138.7 million compared with 130.6 million in 1995.
<p>
   Research and development costs rose 21 percent to $532.3 million
in 1996, representing 12.9 percent of revenue. Capital investments
totaled $1.12 billion for the year, up from $1.0 billion in 1995.
<p>
   The company said it expects capital spending in the first half
of 1997 to equal the $660 million it spent in the first half of
1996.
<p>
   As of Dec. 31, total debt was $623.1 million, including $194.9
million of long-term debt. Shareholders equity stood at $3.26
billion.
<p>
   Pasquale Pistorio, SGS-Thomson's president and chief executive,
said the company's low debt level gave it the agility it needed to
make new investments or even acquisitions if the opportunity
arises.
<p>
   ``There is no good (acquisition) opportunity in sight,'' for
now, he added.
<p>
   Pistorio declined to comment on speculation SGS-Thomson's
shareholder structure could change in the near future.
<p>
   SGS-Thomson is controlled by a group of Italian and French
state-owned companies, with only 30.6 percent of its shares
publicly traded.
<p>
   But as the French government moves to sell defense electronics
company Thomson-CSF and float a stake in France Telecom SA, those
companies might look to sell their stake in SGS-Thomson.
<p>
   Pistorio denied a press report that French Industry Minster
Franck Borotra had approached him about bringing in new
shareholders into the company's capital if state- controlled sell
their stake in the company.
<p>
   ``The job we have as managers is to make the company perform,''
Pistorio said. ``We don't see anything that could impact the
company's performance.''
<p>
   SGS-Thomson has factories in Phoenix, Arizona, and Crolles,
France, and is building new factories in Singapore; Catania, Italy,
and Rousset, France. It's U.S. headquarters are in Carrollton,
Texas.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
