<STORYID cat=k pri=r sel=ttx-z> A8811 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0714 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX &QL; 
CLINTON'S SPEECH WAS SHORT AND . . . DID I SAY IT WAS SHORT? &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
By BILL THOMPSON &QC; 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   If you were looking for soaring rhetoric, for inspirational
themes, for memorable images and quotable turns of phrase  &MD;  if you
were looking for a great speech, in other words  &MD;  President
Clinton's second inaugural address was surely not your cup of tea.
<p>
   Well, then, if Clinton's speech was not deeply inspirational or
searingly memorable or eminently quotable, what was it?
<p>
   Two words come to mind, one of which, ``pedestrian,'' is not a
compliment. But the other word, a word that is too rarely applied
to a speech by William Jefferson Clinton, is meant as high
flattery.
<p>
   The speech was ``short.''
<p>
   Short by Clinton standards, anyway. He spoke for 21 or 22
minutes, depending on whose clock you trust. He's been known to
spend 22 minutes clearing his throat.
<p>
   He must have been in a hurry to get to those 14 inaugural balls.
He didn't want to show up late and miss Al Gore doing the Macarena.
<p>
   If he'd been so inclined, Clinton could have pushed the
afternoon soap operas into the realm of late-night television.
<p>
   It hardly seems fair to criticize the president's speech after
he mercifully opted to practice oratorical self-control. But then
nobody said life was fair, as another smooth-talking Democrat once
noted.
<p>
   Clinton is vastly overrated as an orator, perhaps because he had
the good fortune to be compared to George Bush in 1992 and to Bob
Dole in the most recent presidential election. Bush and Dole are
great Americans, but neither man's resume begins with the phrase
``scintillating public speaker.''
<p>
   There's no denying that Clinton can reel off a pretty good
speech from time to time. On occasion, he's been known to rise to
the, uh, occasion.
<p>
   Unfortunately, Inauguration Day 1997 was not one of those
occasions.
<p>
   It wasn't that Clinton failed to touch on significant issues. He
talked about racial harmony, personal responsibility, the
importance of American leadership in a changing world. The problem
was that he didn't address those issues with any conviction or
passion.
<p>
   The speech seemed to have been written by a committee, and he
delivered it with all the intensity of a bureaucrat reading a
committee report.
<p>
   For many of those 21, or 22, minutes that Clinton spoke, he
seemed to be arguing with himself. For example:
<p>
   ``Government is not the problem, and government is not the
solution. We, the American people, we are the solution....
<p>
   ``As times change, so government must change. We need a new
government for a new century  &MD;  humble enough not to try to solve
all our problems for us, but strong enough to give us the tools to
solve our problems for ourselves.''
<p>
   Let's go over that again: Government shouldn't try to solve our
problems but it should ``give us the tools to solve our problems.''
<p>
   That's double talk, folks: Government should be weaker but
should also be stronger.
<p>
   It's a reflection of the ambiguity that defines Bill Clinton.
<p>
   Clinton knows full well that most Americans want less
government, and he wants to comply with their wishes. But he can't
shake his lifelong liberal's compulsion to look first toward
government whenever a solution is needed.
<p>
   Personally, I'd rather have seen the president yield to his
natural inclination to prescribe a government remedy for every ill.
I'd have liked his speech better if he'd chosen one side or the
other  &MD;  even the wrong side  &MD;  and embraced it with every fiber of
his being. That would have been leadership, whether you agreed with
him or not.
<p>
   Instead, he did what he always does. He tried to have it both
ways.
<p>
   The fundamental flaw in Clinton's inaugural address was the
fundamental flaw in his character and his presidency: He has, as
someone said of his predecessor, no principles strong enough to
break.
<p>
   On the first day of his second term as our 42nd president,
Clinton decided to straddle the bridge to the 21st century, instead
of leading us across it.
<p>
   But it's hard to rip him for that. It's what he's always done.
<p>
   And at least the speech was short.
<p>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.)
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1157EST
</TRAILER>
