<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BRAZIL-FORUM-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BRAZIL RE-ELECTION DEBATE TO LAST THROUGH MAY: BLOOMBERG FORUM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Simon Romero &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Brasilia, Brazil, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) - Brazilian lawmakers are
expected to discuss for another three to four months a
constitutional amendment allowing the nation's president, governors
and mayors to run for re-election.
<p>
   ``The debate will last through April or May. There are numerous
committee and floor votes that need to be held before voting is
finished,'' Murillo de Aragao, head of the Brasilia-based
consulting firm Arko Advice, told the Bloomberg Forum.
<p>
   President Fernando Henrique Cardoso's four-year term as
president ends in 1998. Investors view a successful re-election bid
by Cardoso as an assurance that his government's economic policies
will continue for the next six years, said de Aragao.
<p>
   Members of Cardoso's Social Democrat party and their allies in
the lower house of Congress hope to hold the first of two floor
votes on the re-election amendment by Jan. 29. The measure needs
three-fifths approval to become law.
<p>
   Still, before two floor votes in the lower house, the amendment
must pass through two committees. Then, after leaving the lower
house, the amendment goes before a committee in the Senate,
followed by two Senate floor votes, said de Aragao.
<p>
   While lawmakers start the voting process, supporters of
Cardoso's re-election are stoking the fires of his government's
growing public support. Cardoso's Social Democrats and allies from
a leading right-of-center party have spent about $2 million on a
10-day advertising blitz for re-election.
<p>
   At the end of 1996, Cardoso was considered ``excellent'' or
``good'' by 47 percent of Brazil's population, according to the
Datafolha polling service. That's up from 36 percent when he took
office in January, 1995.
<p>
   Many Brazilians are happy with the job Cardoso and his economic
team are doing. When he was still Brazil's finance minister,
Cardoso implemented in 1994 a program that slashed inflation to 10
percent last year, down from roaring four-digit price increases.
<p>
   Even with Cardoso's popularity rising, opposition to his
re-election still exists. The clauses of the re-election amendment
allowing mayors and governors to run for a consecutive term are a
possible source of dissent among congressmen, said Arko's de
Aragao.
<p>
   ``If the amendment is not passed, we might see a period of
confusion, more political than economical,'' said de Aragao. ``But
after three to four weeks, things will get back to normal
considering the popular support for the `Real Plan.'''
<p>
   In the meantime, Cardoso's rivals are eagerly awaiting the
outcome of the re-election debate. Former Sao Paulo mayor Paulo
Maluf, Workers Party leader Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva and Jaime
Lerner, the governor of the prosperous southern state of Parana,
are among those that are considering mounting their own
presidential bid, said de Aragao.
</TEXT>
