<SLUG> BC-EARNS-COMPAQ-UPDATE2- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0689 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-COMPAQ-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMPAQ 4TH-QTR NET SOARS 43% ON MORE CORPORATE SALES (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Daniel Fisher &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
(Adds analyst comment in fifth paragraph, updates stock price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Houston, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Compaq Computer Corp.'s
fourth-quarter earnings rose 43 percent, far exceeding estimates,
on increased sales of computers to corporate customers and
improvements in operating efficiency.
<p>
   The No. 1 personal computer maker said net income rose to $462
million, or $1.64 a share, up from year-earlier profit from
operations of $323 million, or $1.17. Acquisition-related charges
of $241 million, or 87 cents, in the 1995 quarter resulted in net
income of $82 million, or 30 cents.
<p>
   Revenue rose 15 percent to $5.42 billion from $4.7 billion.
<p>
   Compaq's results exceeded all but the most-optimistic estimates.
Wall Street was expecting earnings of $1.53 a share, based on the
average estimate of 34 analysts from First Call. Many analysts had
increased their unofficial forecasts to about $1.60 in recent
weeks.
<p>
   ``They're gaining market share, profit margins are increasing,
cash is growing, what else do you want?'' said Stephen Dube, an
analyst with Wasserstein Perella Securities.
<p>
   Compaq shares jumped 4 1/8, or 5.3 percent, to 82 5/8 on trading
of 4.4 million, more than the three-month daily average of 3
million. Compaq led some other computer makers' shares higher, with
Dell Computer Corp.'s stock rising 1 7/8 to 66.
<p>
   Houston-based Compaq said its closely watched gross margin ---
revenue minus the cost of manufacturing computers -- rose to 24.4
percent, its highest level in almost two years. Compaq cited a
shift toward corporate computers and servers, which carry higher
profit margins, as well as aggressive moves to cut inventory and
speed up collection of payments.
<p>
   Compaq slashed inventory almost in half to $1.15 billion from
$2.16 billion a year ago, said Compaq's chief financial officer,
Earl Mason. Days sales outstanding, a measure of how long Compaq
takes to collect its bills, fell to 53 from 60. Those moves helped
Compaq reduce the amount of money tied up in inventory and
receivables and boost cash to $4 billion from $745 million in the
year-earlier period.
<p>
   ``What you see happening is, our people got to some of the
inventory goals about a year ahead of schedule,'' said Mason, who
joined Compaq from Inland Steel Industries Inc. in May.
<p>
   Mason said Compaq will continue to report higher earnings and
profit margins this year than in 1996, although he declined to say
whether the company will exceed its fourth-quarter gross margin of
24.4 percent.
<p>
   Compaq won't be able to trim inventory as much this year as it
did in 1996, Mason acknowledged. He said the bulk of gains in
profitability will come from a shift toward so-called enterprise,
or large corporate computer, systems.
<p>
   ``As the enterprise business becomes more of a lion's share of
our overall revenue stream, then the mix alone brings up gross
margins,'' Mason said.
<p>
   Compaq's profitability has been bolstered by new products,
including a line of workstations aimed at engineers and financial
professionals. Compaq also has acquired several companies that make
systems to link computers in networks, so it can sell entire
computer systems and not just desktop PCs.
<p>
   Selling, general and administrative expense rose to 10.6 percent
of revenue in the fourth quarter from about 10 percent in the
year-earlier period.
<p>
   Research and development expense increased to about 1.9 percent
from 1.7 percent, Compaq said. The company made up for those
increases by trimming inventory and better managing the flow of
products through the manufacturing and selling process.
<p>
   For the year, Houston-based Compaq reported net income of $1.31
billion, or $4.66 a share, compared with profit from operations of
$1.03 billion, or $3.74 a share. Compaq reported 1995 net income of
$789 million, or $2.88 a share, after the acquisition-related
charges.
<p>
   Revenue increased 23 percent to $18.11 billion from $14.76
billion.
</TEXT>
