<DOCID> nyt970122.0137 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8817 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-RATING-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0318 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PANAMA-RATING-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PANAMA'S DEBT RECEIVES `BA1' FROM MOODY'S IN DEBUT RATING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jill Hamburg &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Panama received a ``junk'' bond
rating for its outstanding publicly-traded debt from Moody's
Investors Service and Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp., its first rating for
the country.
<p>
   Moody's rated the bonds ``Ba1,'' the top level for high risk
debt, which is considered below investment-grade.
<p>
   The rating applies to a note sold by the government as well as
its $3.5 billion in outstanding Brady bonds, created last year as
part of a restructuring accord, from old bank loans on which Panama
defaulted in the past decade.
<p>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's assigned Panama a `BB+' rating.
<p>
   Panama's bonds surged 4.175 points or 5.6 percent on the news.
Panamanian interest-reduction bonds soared in morning trading to 76
5/8 bid and 77 1/8 offered.
<p>
   A ``manageable'' debt burden and progress toward an open economy
prompted the ratings, Moody's Managing Director for sovereign risk
Vincent Trugliea and Steven Hess, a senior analyst, said in a
report.
<p>
   ``The outlook for the Panamanian economy is for gradual
improvement.'' The rating wasn't higher because of ``the poor
record of repayment by the government during the past decade.''
<p>
   ``Economic reforms that are being implemented by the current
government should provide a basis for improved economic performance
over the next several years,'' the report said.
<p>
   The changes include selling state firms, repealing labor
protection laws, removing import tariffs and beefing up regulation
of the financial industry, the credit rating company said.
<p>
   The rating report highlighted Panama's growing maritime
transport and tourism industries, which are using land and
facilities the U.S. expects to hand over to Panamanian authorities
in 1999.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1204EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0138 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=l pri=r sel=tab-z> A8830 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-HEALTH-ORGANIZA </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1466 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-WORLD-HEALTH-ORGANIZATION-CRISIS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE WHO STRIKES A MID-LIFE-CRISIS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this ``separate buy'' article from the London-based
science and technology weekly NEW SCIENTIST it must be purchased --
the rate is not prohibitive -- from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: &LR; 
 &UR; (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City,
816-822-8448 or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &UR; (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR; 
 &UR; (--Mexico, Central America, South America: PAUL FINCH in Los
Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax, 310-996-0089. &LR; 
 &UR; By PHYLLIDA BROWN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Copyright 1997 New Scientist &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   When the World Health Organization (WHO) declared that its goal
was to achieve ``health for all by the year 2000,'' nobody seemed
to think the idea was ridiculous.
<p>
   After all, it was 1978: AIDS was unknown; the WHO had played a
major role in fighting smallpox, which was eradicated in 1977, and
it helped poorer countries produce essential drugs cheaply. The WHO
was taken seriously.
<p>
   Today things are different. The WHO, 50 years old next year, is
in crisis. It has become a bit-player on the international stage
and is increasingly under fire for its lack of leadership and
failure to modernize.
<p>
   The events of the next 12 months are likely to decide its
future. The executive board  &MD;  the governing body drawn from the
WHO's member states  &MD;  gathered this month in Geneva in a tense
meeting. Earlier, the United States had threatened to reduce its
contribution, which would leave the organization $20 million short
this year.
<p>
   During the meeting, the WHO drew up its new global policy for
the 21st century. Next January, the board must elect a
director-general for the next five years.
 &UR; QUESTIONABLE LEADERSHIP &LR; 
<p>
   Both the policy and the leadership candidates are being closely
scrutinized by the WHO's members. Industrialized countries largely
pay for the WHO. Most of them have been critical of the its
management for the past five years and their patience is running
out. Some developing countries are also voicing concern.
<p>
   The current director-general, Hiroshi Nakajima, is expected to
stand for a third term. His election for a second term, back in
1993, was opposed by most Western industrialized countries, which
blame him for the WHO's decline since he took over in 1988.
<p>
   Their views have not changed.
<p>
   ``Our position is the same as in 1993,'' says one Western
diplomatic source. ``We do not wish Nakajima to run again.''
<p>
   Who they would prefer to lead is less clear. The current
unofficial shortlist includes several internal candidates, two of
the WHO's six regional directors, a deputy health minister from
Zambia and the director of the U.N. Population Fund, Nafis Sadik.
There is also excitement, but little evidence, that Norway's former
prime minister, Gro Harlem Brundtland, might be persuaded to stand.
 &UR; UPDATING POLICY &LR; 
<p>
   But leadership is not the only concern of the WHO's critics.
They want to modernize the WHO. Four years ago, the executive board
recommended 47 changes in the organization, many of them minor. But
the board also asked the WHO to set new, practical targets for the
future and to clarify what it does that other organizations cannot.
All eyes are now on the WHO's response.
<p>
   The WHO was once on its own in promoting health around the
world. Now it has gradually been joined by UNICEF, the U.N.
Development Program, the U.N. Population Fund and the World Bank,
which argues that a healthy workforce helps a country's economy to
grow faster.
<p>
   The World Bank's health budget alone is $2.5 billion this year  &MD; 
dwarfing the WHO's annual budget of $900 million  &MD;  making it the
largest external source of financing for health in developing
countries.
<p>
   Recently, the WHO has also begun to lose intellectual initiative
to the World Bank, says Kelley Lee, a health policy researcher at
the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, who has
analyzed the WHO's work.
<p>
   ``The bank is setting the terms of the debate and the WHO is
catching up. They should be taking the lead.''
<p>
   The WHO's mandate, made when it was founded in 1948, was
ambitious: ``The attainment by all peoples of the highest possible
level of health.'' Today, critics argue, the organization should
define its aims more realistically and concentrate on priorities,
such as the health of the poorest 1 billion people.
<p>
   But the WHO's senior management has decided that ``health for
all'' should remain its key goal. Details of the policy have yet to
be filled out, because the organization is still consulting its
members. But the broad aims include reducing poverty and ensuring
that everyone has equal access to health care.
<p>
   Critics think the policy is too broad and lacks specific
targets. In documents circulated by the Dag Hammarskjold
Foundation, an influential Swedish think-tank, for a meeting in
Uppsala, Sweden, last April, the policy was described as
``unreachable'' and ``vague.''
 &UR; MISSING TARGETS &LR; 
<p>
   The clamor for a more tightly focused policy is growing. The
WHO's core job has always been to provide information and technical
backup. It makes epidemiological forecasts and gives guidelines on
the treatment of diseases. It also sets standards, such as the safe
limits of chemicals in air or water.
<p>
   Because no one else has a mandate to do these jobs, argue the
critics, the WHO should concentrate on them, and stop trying to be
all things to all people.
<p>
   Apart from these tasks, they say, the WHO should concentrate on
major challenges such as smoking, which will kill 8.4 million
people a year by 2020.
<p>
   One of the WHO's traditional tasks  &MD;  and one of its least
glamorous  &MD;  is to strengthen basic health care in developing
countries. If the WHO withdraws from such open-ended tasks to
concentrate on providing information, poorer countries fear they
will be left with even less help, Lee says.
<p>
   Because the WHO has spread its resources so thinly, its
technical staff lack the time to analyze data thoroughly, say
health researchers. Almost everyone agrees that one of the WHO's
most important tasks is to provide clear and accurate figures on
the causes of death in all countries.
<p>
   Last year, the WHO published conflicting versions of its own
numbers. The World Health Report estimated that 3 million people
died from tuberculosis (TB) and 2 million from malaria. Two other
1996 reports carrying the WHO's logo  &MD;  The Global Burden of Disease
and Investing in Health Research and Development  &MD;  said that there
were 2 million deaths from TB and fewer than 1 million deaths from
malaria.
<p>
   Both sets of numbers came from the same technical staff. But the
lower numbers  &MD;  produced in a joint effort between the WHO and
Harvard University  &MD;  were subject to rigorous checks to ensure that
nobody was counted twice.
<p>
   The WHO loses credibility if it cannot perform its core
functions properly, such as getting its numbers right, argues one
American scientist.
<p>
   ``You don't provide moral leadership if you don't pay attention
to the facts.''
 &UR; A NEW FOCUS? &LR; 
<p>
   For all the criticism, almost no one doubts the need for the
WHO. They just want it to do its job better. Passionate defenders
of the WHO are also some of the strongest advocates of change.
<p>
   Dean Jamison, professor of public health at the University of
California at Los Angeles, says the WHO's egalitarian commitment to
health for all must be safeguarded at a time when market principles
are changing healthcare.
<p>
   ``It's extremely important (for the WHO) to be exercising moral
leadership and mobilizing communities for the highest ethical
standards possible,'' Jamison says. But, he adds, ``it had better
get itself energetic leadership,'' and concentrate on its greatest
strengths.
<p>
   Or as Richard Peto, a leading epidemiologist at the University
of Oxford, puts it, the WHO's job should be ``to count the dead by
the year 2000.''
<p>
   ------------------ &QC; 
