<STORYID cat=d pri=r sel=ttx-z> A8837 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BUNDY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0694 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-FOOD-BUNDY-COLUMN-TEX &QL; 
YOU'RE ON PAR WITH THIS GOLF-COURSE CHILI &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
By BEVERLY BUNDY &QC; 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Sometimes, we get gifts in the Food section. Last week, we got
one from Tom Mays of Fort Worth, Texas.
<p>
   Here's the history that came along with the recipe.
<p>
   In 1968, Ridglea Country Club opened a second 18-hole golf
course, for men only. Mrs. Willie Williams was the head chef for
the course. A craze developed over Mrs. Williams' chili recipe; the
takeout business often equaled the dine-in orders, Mays writes.
<p>
   Mrs. Williams retired in 1989, leaving chili lovers bemoaning
their loss. But Mays was one of the lucky ones because he received
a copy of the recipe. Following is Mrs. Williams' recipe.
<p>
   And in a real departure for Texans, I'm also running a recipe
for chili made with chicken, and yes, fellow cowboys, beans. If the
beans and chicken really offend you, call it a stew and move on.
It's a nice combination for a family dinner or when you've got to
feed a crowd. This recipe is from ``365 More Ways to Cook Chicken''
by Melanie Barnard (HarperCollins, $12.95). 
<p>
   RIDGLEA COUNTRY CLUB'S BLUE RIBBON CHILI
<p>
   Serves 4
<p>
   1 pound extra-lean chili-ground beef
<p>
   1 1/2 cups chopped yellow onion
<p>
   1 1/2 cups water
<p>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
<p>
   2 teaspoons salt
<p>
   2 tablespoons chili powder
<p>
   2 tablespoons paprika
<p>
   1/2 teaspoon oregano
<p>
   1/4 teaspoon garlic powder
<p>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne
<p>
   2 tablespoons masa harina
<p>
   1/2 cup water
<p>
   Saute beef until brown. Add onions and saute until onions are
transparent. Add all additional ingredients, except masa and 1/2
cup water. Bring to a boil. Reduce heat and simmer for 30 minutes.
Stir masa harina into 1/2 cup water. Stir into chili and simmer for
an additional 30 minutes.
<p>
   Note: Add more masa harina to water if a thicker chili is
desired.
<p>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 286 calories, 15 grams fat, 13
grams carbohydrates, 25 grams protein, 80 milligrams cholesterol,
1,297 milligrams sodium, 48 percent of calories from fat. 
<p>
   CHICKEN AND THREE-BEAN CHILI
<p>
   Serves 8-10
<p>
   2 large onions, chopped
<p>
   1 large green bell pepper, chopped
<p>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
<p>
   1 cup chicken broth, preferably reduced-sodium
<p>
   4 large garlic coves, crushed through a press
<p>
   1 1/2 pounds skinless, boneless chicken thighs, cut into
3/4-inch chunks
<p>
   1/4 cup chopped smoked ham
<p>
   2 tablespoons chili powder
<p>
   1 1/2 teaspoons ground cumin
<p>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano
<p>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne
<p>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
<p>
   2 (14 1/2-ounce) cans stewed tomatoes, preferably
Southwestern-style
<p>
   15-ounce can black beans, drained
<p>
   15-ounce can red kidney beans, drained
<p>
   15-ounce can white or cannellini beans, drained
<p>
   1/2 cup chopped cilantro or parsley
<p>
   Salt
<p>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In large Dutch oven, cook onion and
bell pepper in olive oil and 2 tablespoons of broth, covered, over
medium-low heat, stirring often, until onion is softened, about 5
minutes. Add garlic and cook, uncovered, 1 minute. Add chicken,
ham, chili powder, cumin, oregano and cayenne. Cook, stirring, 1
minute. Add remaining broth, stewed tomatoes, all 3 types of beans
and half the cilantro.
<p>
   Cover chili and bake 50 minutes. Uncover and bake until slightly
thickened, about 10 minutes.
<p>
   Stir in remaining cilantro. Season with salt to taste before
serving.
<p>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 287 calories, 8 grams fat, 33
grams carbohydrates, 23 grams protein, 47 milligrams cholesterol,
478 milligrams sodium, 46 percent of calories from fat. 
<p>
   REQUESTS
<p>
    &MD;  Happy Carver, Fort Worth, has misplaced an old recipe for
mincemeat mayonnaise cake.
<p>
    &MD;  A Fort Worth reader would like a recipe for fried rice and
sweet-and-sour chicken.
<p>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor at the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to her via snail mail in care of the
newspaper at Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101-1870; or via E-mail at
bbundy(at sign)startext.net Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column.)
</TEXT>
