<NWORDS> 0409 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-PIPER-JAFFRAY-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PIPER JAFFRAY 1ST-QTR NET FALLS 73% AS LEGAL FEES RISE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Monique Wise &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Minneapolis, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Piper Jaffray Cos. said its
fiscal first-quarter net income fell 73 percent as legal fees
stemming from lawsuits against its Piper Capital Management unit
rose.
<p>
   The parent of Minneapolis-based securities firm Piper Jaffray
Inc. said net income for the quarter ended Dec. 31 rose to $1.8
million, or 10 cents a share, from $6.7 million, or 37 cents, a
year earlier.
<p>
   Piper Jaffray stock fell as much as 3/4 to 18 1/2 in morning
trading.
<p>
   ``It's disappointing that litigation-related expenses continue
to have a negative impact on our net income,'' Chairman and Chief
Executive Addison L. Piper said in a statement.
<p>
   Total revenue at the firm rose 4.7 percent to $138.8 million
from $132.5 million a year ago.
<p>
   Revenue from brokerage commissions rose 9 percent to $46.4
million. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index rose 7.7 percent, while
the Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 9.6 percent during the
quarter. That helped boost the average number of shares that
changed hands daily on the New York Stock Exchange almost 17
percent to 430 million.
<p>
   Trading revenue rose 7.6 percent to $44 million from $40.9
million a year earlier. Investment banking revenue slipped 16
percent to $20.9 million from $25 million in the same period in
1995, as the firm's equity unit posted lower revenue, said
spokeswoman Marie Uhrich.
<p>
   Revenue from asset management was also lower, falling 7 percent
to $8.9 million.
<p>
   Expenses climbed 11.7 percent to $135.8 million, led by a 21
percent gain in the ``other expenses'' category to $22.2 million.
The category includes legal costs related to lawsuits involving the
firm's asset management unit.
<p>
   The majority of the other expenses costs, however, do not derive
from legal or settlement costs, Uhrich said.
<p>
   Piper Jaffray faces lawsuits and claims involving 13 funds at
its Piper Capital Management unit, Uhrich said. Its Institutional
Government Income Portfolio mutual fund was ravaged by
derivative-related losses in 1994 in mid-1994, and lost about a
quarter of its value. Investors filed lawsuits, alleging they had
been misled about the fund's risks.
<p>
   Payroll expenses rose 12 percent to $86 million, as the firm
hired 68 people in its capital markets division.
</TEXT>
