<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COLOMBIA-STOCKS-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COLOMBIAN STOCKS FALL AMID FEARS OF U.S. SANCTIONS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By David Scanlan &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Bogota, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Colombian stocks fell for a sixth
day amid concern the U.S. could impose trade sanctions because of
unhappiness over the Colombia drug trade.
<p>
   ``The tendency is still for prices to fall, and this may
continue a bit more (in coming days),'' said Guillermo Espinosa,
trader at Correval SA brokerage.
<p>
   The Bogota IBB index fell 23.6 points, or 2.4 percent, to
963.01, according to a preliminary estimate. Trading volume was
1.79 billion pesos ($1.8 million), down from the 1996 trading
average of 2.3 billion pesos.
<p>
   Among movers, Bavaria SA fell 8.5 percent to 5,200 pesos.
Bancoquia fell 7.9 percent to 2,423 pesos. Cadenalco SA fell 5.6
percent to 850 pesos. Coltabaco fell 8.4 percent to 3,500 pesos.
<p>
   Washington is angry at Colombia for imposing light sentences on
two top leaders of the Cali drug cartel. This could lead to trade
sanctions when Washington issues its annual report on the global
drug trade March 1.
<p>
   The six-day slump follows 18 straight days in increases, in
which the Bogota index soared 26 percent in peso terms.
<p>
   In New York, Banco Ganadero fell 1/2 to 29 5/8, after the bank
reported net income rose 6 percent in 1996 over 1995, below
expectations.
</TEXT>
