<SLUG> BC-EARNS-MCDONALD'S-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0384 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-MCDONALD'S-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MCDONALD'S 4TH-QTR EARNINGS EXPECTED TO RISE AMID SLOW SALES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Shannon Stevens &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Oak Brook, Illinois, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- McDonald's Corp. is
expected to report a modest increase in fourth-quarter earnings as
its sales growth slows worldwide.
<p>
   The world's largest fast-food chain is expected to earn 57 cents
a share, the average estimate of 22 analysts surveyed by First Call
Corp., up from 51 cents a year earlier. The company is expected to
report earnings later this week.
<p>
   Sales at McDonald's U.S. restaurants open at least a year fell
an estimated 2 percent to 2.5 percent in the quarter, said Dean
Witter analyst David Adelman. That's partly because a confusing
marketing campaign has left people unsure about what McDonald's has
to offer, he said.
<p>
   ``They've been talking about price, new products, kids meals,
movie promotional tie-ins, Olympics,'' Adelman said. ``There hasn't
been one overlying consistency to their message.''
<p>
   McDonald's doesn't give a specific figure for its same-store
sales, though it does say whether they rose or fell. Same-store
sales are considered a good indicator of a company's business
because they don't include newly opened or expanded stores.
<p>
   The sales lost from that lack of focus is compounded by
successful marketing campaigns by Burger King and Wendy's
International Inc., which take some customers away from McDonald's.
<p>
   Additionally, profit margins are expected to slip because of the
combination of lower same-store sales and higher labor costs from
efforts to improve the quality of service.
<p>
   Outside the U.S., results are expected to be mixed, with the
sluggish economies in France, Germany and Canada leading to slower
sales growth there. Also, the dollar is so much stronger than the
Japanese yen that currency translation could hurt McDonald's even
though sales are strong in Japan.
<p>
   Earnings still could get a boost from international profits
because of easier comparisons than earlier in the year. While the
20 percent gain in international sales a year ago is no small
amount to match, it's smaller than the 38 percent and 44 percent
increases in the first and second quarter of last year,
respectively.
</TEXT>
