<DOCID> nyt970122.0147 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=ttj-z> A8846 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-DEATHS-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1028 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ELDERLY-DEATHS-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TIME RUNNING OUT IN FRAUD PROBE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JIM HERRON ZAMORA &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SAN FRANCISCO  &MD;  As the clock winds down on the statute of
limitations, San Francisco police are feverishly probing five
mysterious deaths that may involve a murder-for-profit scheme  &MD;  and
new details are emerging on alleged errors by officers formerly on
the case.
<p>
   For nearly four years, police have been investigating
allegations that five elderly San Francisco men were slowly
poisoned to death while their assets and estates were plundered  &MD; 
just as slowly  &MD;  by a family of con artists.
<p>
   The probe, code-named Foxglove, has long been marred by
accusations of misconduct against the original two investigators.
<p>
   In documents newly obtained by The Examiner, the Police
Department has accused the pair  &MD;  pulled off the case in 1994  &MD;  of
jeopardizing the safety of a witness, failing to warn potential
victims of danger and leaking a sealed request for a search warrant
to private investigators who were allegedly planning to shop the
story to Hollywood producers.
<p>
   In the overall case, the four-year statute of limitations on
alleged fraud, theft and financial elder abuse expires in February.
<p>
   If prosecutors do not file charges on the alleged lesser crimes
next month, then the only possible case left will be homicide, the
hardest charge to prove. That deadline may force the department and
prosecutors to either file the lesser charges or drop the costly,
complex investigation.
<p>
   Neither district attorney's spokesman John Shanley nor Deputy
Police Chief John Willett would say whether they planned to file
charges.
<p>
   ``I anticipate that there will be a decision whether or not we
proceed with the case in February,'' Willett said. ``It's not going
to be quietly given up. ... We've done too much to just hope that
it goes out into the sunset.''
<p>
   The five alleged victims were all befriended not long before
their deaths by members of a group that included Angela Tene; her
mother, Mary Tene Steiner; her brother, Danny Tene, and Angela's
boyfriend, George Lama.
<p>
   Law enforcement officials say all three Tenes are members of the
Tene Bimbo clan, which gained notoriety in Peter Maas' best-selling
1974 book, ``King of the Gypsies,'' and in a film of the same name.
<p>
   Since fall 1994, Inspector Phil Tummarello has been
investigating allegations that the four may have slowly poisoned
the men, using the drug digitalis in a plot to acquire their
estates. Digitalis, a heart drug that can be fatal in higher doses,
is derived from the foxglove plant.
<p>
   The bodies of four men  &MD;  Philip H. Steiner Jr., 93; Konstantin
K. Liotweizen, 92; Nicholas C. Bufford, 87; and Stephen Storvick,
91  &MD;  were exhumed in 1994 for autopsies.
<p>
   An autopsy also was conducted on a fifth person, Harry Glover
Hughes, 94, when he died in March 1994. Police have not released
the autopsy results.
<p>
   The subjects of the investigation have not been accused of any
crimes. They could not be reached for comment but have denied any
wrongdoing through their legal counsel.
<p>
   Tummarello was assigned to Foxglove after the first two
inspectors came under investigation for alleged misconduct.
<p>
   The inspectors, Gregory Ovanessian and Daniel Yawczak, are
accused of ``engaging in conduct which subverts the good order,
efficiency and discipline of the department'' in connection with
their handling of the early part of the investigation in 1993.
<p>
   Both have denied wrongdoing, are fighting the administrative
charges and are still working on non-Foxglove investigations.
<p>
   Among the most serious accusations: They ``permitted the
disclosure of confidential information from a witness who has
requested confidentiality. After the disclosure, the victim's life
was threatened, and she had to move from her home to safety,''
according to police documents.
<p>
   They are also accused of waiting from February 1993 until
September 1993 to inform some possible victims of the alleged
scheme, potentially jeopardizing their lives.
<p>
   Ovanessian and Yawczak ``permitted the scheme to continue,''
police documents say, and ``took no steps to notify the alleged
victims or their families of the danger to their lives.''
<p>
   During that same period in 1993, Ovanessian and Yawczak
allegedly told a private investigator ``that the case was taking
too much of their time and that once the people die, they can check
the bodies for poison,'' according to a police document outlining
the misconduct charges.
<p>
   Yawczak also allegedly told a city attorney's investigator he
was ``too busy to do the case'' and that they would ``wait until
the men die, and then they would have a murder case,'' police
documents state.
<p>
   Tummarello, who helped create a special unit to investigate
financial abuse of the elderly in 1993, has declined to comment on
details of the case.
<p>
   ``The seriousness of the allegations (of murder) warrant
scrutiny,'' Tummarello said Tuesday. ``Investigations like this
take on a life of their own. I'm sure all the parties involved
would like to see the investigation concluded, but the complicated
nature of the allegations dictates that a very thorough
investigation is going to take a substantial amount of time.''
<p>
   For more than a year, Tummarello worked on the case at a desk in
the Police Department's homicide detail at the Hall of Justice. In
1996, he was moved to a state Department of Justice office
building, allowing him more privacy.
<p>
   Inspector Michael Stasko, who has a background of investigating
fraud and police misconduct, joined him there. They are being
assisted by state officials and are working on no other cases,
Willett said.
<p>
   Police Chief Fred Lau stressed that Ovanessian and Yawczak were
considered innocent until proved otherwise.
<p>
   He conceded that the department was hampered by leaks about the
case in 1994 and said the department had learned from its mistakes
in the investigation.
<p>
   ``Because of this case, we've learned a lot of lessons about
crimes against the elderly,'' Lau said. ``It's a very complicated
case.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1233EST
</TRAILER>
