<DOCID> nyt970122.0148 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=ttj-z> A8849 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYER-PENALTY-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0463 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-LAWYER-PENALTY-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JUDGE BARS FROM CASE LAWYER WHO TRIED TO SELL OUT CLIENTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ERIC BRAZIL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SAN FRANCISCO  &MD;  A San Francisco lawyer who committed the
``colossal misdeed'' of offering to sell out his clients for $8
million to $10 million cannot re-enter the case from which he was
disqualified, an appellate court has ruled.
<p>
   Michael Khourie's disqualification from the class-action lawsuit
was exceptional for ``the magnitude of the ethical lapse,''
presiding Justice Anthony Kline wrote in his opinion for the state
1st District Court of Appeals.
<p>
   Khourie's misconduct ``shakes the foundations of (the judicial)
process'' and is ``a betrayal of his clients'' and public trust,
Kline wrote.
<p>
   Khourie, 74, a Mill Valley resident and an attorney in San
Francisco for more than 40 years, recently retired, keeping a
single client, the firm Cal Pak Delivery Inc. of Hayward.
<p>
   In 1993 Cal Pak sued United Parcel Service in a class action on
behalf of 150,000 intra-state shippers, alleging overcharges of $40
million and seeking exemplary damages.
<p>
   In January 1995, according to uncontested testimony, Khourie
contacted UPS vice president Edwin Reitman and at a face-to-face
meeting offered to dismiss the lawsuit in exchange for an
``up-front'' payment to him of a ``fee'' of $8 million to $10
million.
<p>
   Reitman rejected the proposal, which was accompanied by a threat
of more litigation. In April, 1995, UPS moved to disqualify Khourie
from the case, and a month later Superior Court Judge William
Cahill disqualified him.
<p>
   In brushing aside Khourie's objections to his disqualification,
Kline noted that ``had Khourie's scheme succeeded, his clients
would have been not just tactically disadvantaged but completely
undone.''
<p>
   Khourie's continued presence in the case ``after his colossal
misdeed would cast a shadow on future attempts'' to bring it to
trial, Kline wrote in the opinion, issued last week.
<p>
   In the court's opinion, Judge Cahill had no choice other than
disqualification because he faced ``a direct, acknowledged,
undisputed and indefensible betrayal by counsel of the interests of
his clients and the ... class.''
<p>
   Khourie's attorney, Michael Trayner, said Tuesday his client's
action was ``aberrational'' for a man who, throughout a long,
distinguished legal career, had been ``highly ethical.'' No
decision has been made whether to appeal, he said.
<p>
   In papers filed with the court, Khourie acknowledged making the
proposal to UPS and called it ``improper'' and ``a tragic
misadventure.'' Ill health, marital problems and loss of the annual
retainer from his old law firm probably contributed to his faulty
judgment, he said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1238EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0149 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8850 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAV-DEBT-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0703 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-YUGOSLAV-DEBT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CARGILL OPPOSES PROPOSED RESCHEDULING OF FORMER YUGOSLAV DEBT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jane Baird &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   London, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Cargill Financial Services
advised investors to reject a proposal to reschedule $80.4 million
of defaulted debt of the former Yugoslavia by the republics of
Slovenia, Croatia and Macedonia.
<p>
   All three of these countries already have rescheduled the bulk
of their share of the defaulted debt inherited from Yugoslavia,
known as New Financing Agreement debt.
<p>
   Swiss Bank is now attempting to negotiate a settlement between
investors and the three republics for another type of former
Yugoslav debt known as Alternative Participation Instruments.
<p>
   The rescheduling would settle 53 percent of the debt.
<p>
   ``We feel that 53 percent of principal and accrued interest is
not a fair value for bondholders, particularly given that
bondholders would be releasing the most creditworthy republics from
further obligations,'' said Cargill spokesperson Laurie Johnson, in
Minneapolis.
<p>
   Cargill Financial Services is the brokerage arm of
Minneapolis-based trading company Cargill Inc.
<p>
   In an announcement published in the Financial Times, Cargill
asked holders of the debt to meet in New York on Feb. 7 or in
London on Feb. 10. ``Before agreeing to pursue the Swiss Bank
proposal, we believe API holders should meet to discuss what other
alternatives may exist,'' the announcement stated.
<p>
   Officials of Swiss Bank declined to comment for now, other than
to say that the debt being discussed amounts to about $80.4
million.
<p>
   Even while this debt remains in default, Slovenia and Croatia
have received investment-grade ratings from the credit companies.
Slovenia is rated ``A'' by Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. and ``A3'' by
Moody's Investors Service, while Croatia last week received ratings
of ``BBB-'' from S&AMP;P and ``Baa3'' from Moody's.
<p>
   Slovenia and Croatia have rescheduled most of their shares of
former Yugoslav debt, and ``it is a question of time before
agreements with other creditors follow,'' said Helena Hassell, a
director with Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. in New York. ``This is
something that we are not concerned will affect the rating.''
<p>
   Slovenia re-entered international capital markets last June with
the sale of $325 million of five-year Eurobonds. Croatia is now
holding investor presentations for its first Eurobond sale
involving as much as $250 million of five-year bonds.
<p>
   ``Sure it's unusual'' for an investment-grade borrower to have
outstanding claims on defaulted debt, ``but the circumstances are
unusual as well,'' said Andrew Kenningham, a senior economist at
Merrill Lynch. ``There is no question about the willingness of
Slovenia and Croatia to pay their share, although there may be some
haggling to do over the amount.''
<p>
   In 1988, Yugoslavia reached an agreement to reschedule bank debt
into NFA debt. Creditor banks could choose not to take NFA debt and
instead receive 10-year bonds that paid a below-market interest
rate of 5.75 percent. Because it was structured as bonds rather
than loans, this debt was expected to be less vulnerable to another
default and rescheduling.
<p>
   Yugoslavia then splintered and civil war broke out. The country
stopped payments on all of its debt in April 1992.
<p>
   Last year, Slovenia rescheduled an 18 percent share of the NFA
debt, exchanging it for $820 million worth of floating-rate notes
maturing in 2006. Croatia settled its 29.5 percent share,
exchanging it for $1.46 billion of floating-rate notes. Macedonia
agreed to reschedule 5.4 percent, although the banks gave it some
concession on past-due interest.
<p>
   The remaining two successor republics of Yugoslavia --Bosnia and
the Republic of Yugoslavia, which includes Serbia, Montenegro --
are still in default on their portions of the NFA debt.
<p>
   Swiss Bank's proposed rescheduling would settle about 53 percent
of principal and accrued interest for the three republics on about
the same terms that the NFA debt was settled, Cargill stated.
<p>
   ``We do not believe that this proposal represents an equitable
settlement,'' Cargill said in its announcement.
</TEXT>
