<SLUG> BC-EARNS-GREAT-WESTERN-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0422 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-GREAT-WESTERN-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GREAT WESTERN 4TH-QTR EARNINGS FALL 14% ON LOWER LOAN INCOME &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Michael Smith &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Chatsworth, California, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Great Western
Financial Corp. fourth-quarter earnings fell 14 percent, as income
from mortgage loans plummeted and the bank boosted reserves for
lending losses.
<p>
   The nation's second-largest savings bank said earnings before
charges and gains fell to $85 million, or 58 cents a share, from
$98.6 million, or 66 cents, in the last three months of 1995. After
the charges and gains, the Chatsworth, California-based thrift
reported earnings of $5.13 million, or 1 cent a share.
<p>
   The results exceeded analysts' expectations of 56 cents a share,
according of a survey of 13 analysts by IBES International Inc.
Great Western shares rose 5/16 to 31 13/16 in midday trading.
<p>
   Net interest income fell 4.5 percent to $335.0 million, as
revenue from mortgage-backed securities fell. The thrift boosted
its provision for future lending losses by 71 percent to $85.9
million, cutting into profit.
<p>
   Noninterest income rose 7.2 percent to $114.1 million, as fees
from retail banking surged. Great Western had a pretax gain of
$23.0 million for the sale of its student lending business.
<p>
   Noninterest expenses rose 41 percent to $357.7 million, mainly
because of a $68.3 million pretax charge for a plan to cut 800 jobs
in a bid to reduce costs in the mortgage lending business.
<p>
   The thrift said it had a long way to go to revamp the mortgage
business, after real estate loans grew by $1.6 billion in the
quarter, about the same rate as in the fourth quarter of 1995.
<p>
   ``This level of mortgage originations is not satisfactory,''
said Chief Executive John Maher in a statement.
<p>
   Great Western, in a plan announced last month, is trying to
recover from a long slide in its mortgage business, that took the
thrift from being the fifth-largest U.S. mortgage bank to below No.
20.
<p>
   The company plans to cut 800 jobs, reduce the size of its
headquarters and replace antiquated systems this year. It already
has sold $300 million in non-performing home mortgages.
<p>
   The goal, a spokesman said, is to reduce the cost of making a
mortgage to $3,000 from $4,000. That, he said, should allow Great
Western to boost lending, regaining some of its lost market share.
<p>
   Great Western has $43.5 billion in assets and 1,150 mortgage and
consumer banking offices in California and Florida.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1249EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
