<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8864 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-FED-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0421 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ECONOMY-FED-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FED'S REGIONAL SURVEY SEES `SCATTERED EVIDENCE' OF HIGHER WAGES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Vincent Del Giudice &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The U.S. economy continues to
grow with low unemployment nudging labor costs higher, the Federal
Reserve said today.
<p>
   While the Fed found ``scattered evidence'' of pressures for
higher wages in its latest regional economic survey, the central
still found no evidence of accelerating consumer prices outside of
energy.
<p>
   The Fed's regional outlook, commonly known as the beige book, is
based on reports from the Fed's 12 district banks and is published
eight times each year. The report will help form the basis for
discussion on interest rate targets at the Feb. 4-5 meeting of the
Fed's policy-setting Federal Open Market Committee.
<p>
   While release of the report had been set for 2 p.m. Washington
time, the report was inadvertently released ahead on schedule on
the Internet.
<p>
   In testimony yesterday to a Senate panel, Fed Chairman Alan
Greenspan said the U.S. economy remains strong with few signs of
immediate inflationary pressures even as an era of low wage gains
may be ending.
<p>
   ``The economy has retained considerable vigor, with few signs of
the imbalances and inflationary tensions that have disrupted past
expansions,'' Greenspan said. ``By some important measures of price
trends, inflation actually slowed a bit in 1996.''
<p>
   Economists interpreted Greenspan's comments as suggesting the
FOMC won't raise interest rates next month. Still, Greenspan left
the door ajar for action later if inflation accelerates because of
rising wage levels.
<p>
   The overall consumer price index rose 3.3 percent last year, the
largest increase since 1990. However, much of that came from an 8.6
percent rise in energy prices. Not counting food and energy, prices
rose only 2.6 percent, tying the 1994 rate for the lowest core
inflation rate in 30 years.
<p>
   In its last regional outlook Dec. 4, the Fed said the economy
growthing at a subdued pace with no sign of rising consumer prices.
That lack of an inflation threat allowed the central bank to
refrain from increasing interest rates at their last policy meeting
Dec. 17.
<p>
   Central bankers last cut the federal funds rate by a quarter
point at the Jan. 31 FOMC meeting, when many analysts were
predicting the U.S. economy was heading into a recession. That
followed identical quarter-point reductions in December and July
1995.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1300EST
</TRAILER>
