<DOCID> nyt970122.0156 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=l pri=r sel=ttj-z> A8865 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BEAUTY-QUEEN-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0800 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BEAUTY-QUEEN-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FORMER MISS UNIVERSE GLAD LIFE AS BEAUTY QUEEN IS OVER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By CLIFFORD PUGH &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   HOUSTON  &MD;  Mention the word ``crown'' to Chelsi Smith, and you're
likely to hear a loud groan.
<p>
   ``It was so heavy, it made a dent right here,'' the 23-year-old
says with a laugh, as she rubs the front of her head.
<p>
   By winning a triple crown of beauty pageants  &MD;  Miss Texas USA,
Miss USA and Miss Universe  &MD;  within a 10-month period two years
ago, Smith got used to wearing a tiara and glittery gowns.
<p>
   Now, though, the crown she wore as Miss Universe is packed away
in the back of a closet in her North Hollywood apartment along with
the memories of her life as a beauty queen.
<p>
   There are some who think that winning a beauty pageant is the
pinnacle of a person's life. Smith, who was selected over 81
contestants from around the world in Namibia, South Africa, in the
spring of 1995, is not one of those people.
<p>
   ``Miss Universe certainly wasn't a peak,'' she says. ``It was a
steppingstone.''
<p>
   Newly married to her longtime boyfriend, fitness trainer Kelly
Blair, she has left the beauty business behind and is pursuing a
career as a singer in Los Angeles.
<p>
   During a recent interview at her in-laws' home in the Houston
area, she expressed mixed feelings about pageant life. She said she
felt so relieved that her reign was over last spring that she did a
little dance in a corner of the stage after she crowned her
successor in Las Vegas.
<p>
   ``I was excited, because I wanted my life back,'' she says.
<p>
   Though she has some beefs about the pageant system, she admits
that ``I played the game to get where I needed to go.''
<p>
   As a child raised in the Houston suburb of Deer Park by her
grandmother, Smith seldom watched beauty pageants.
<p>
   After graduating from high school in 1991, she aspired to be a
singer and performed with a lounge band. She quit after several
months because she didn't like the travel and the smoky bars. She
enrolled at San Jacinto College with plans to become an elementary
school teacher.
<p>
   She entered her first real beauty pageant  &MD;  Miss Houston USA  &MD; 
in 1992 in hopes of earning money for college and to buy a car,
since her 1981 Toyota was on its last legs. She placed as first
runner-up and was hooked.
<p>
   Smith remembers a lot of good things about her reign as Miss
Universe.
<p>
   She traveled to 18 countries, met such luminaries as Hillary
Rodham Clinton and the princess of Thailand, and appeared on such
shows as the People's Choice Awards and Soul Train Awards.
<p>
   She sat next to Jack Nicholson at a movie screening and helped
build a house with former President Jimmy Carter and the Habitat
for Humanity group. She liked the perks of flying first class and
being met at airports with flowers and a limousine.
<p>
   But she became increasingly disenchanted with the life of a
beauty pageant winner.
<p>
   ``You're taken advantage of in a way, almost like a doll that
someone shapes and moves and tells to do this and that,'' she says.
``It gives you an identity crisis. You forget who you really are
and where you came from and why you are there.''
<p>
   Her year as Miss Universe was a lonely time, she says. She ran
up huge phone bills calling her fiance in Texas.
<p>
   She also missed having time to herself. She was chaperoned on
official duties and lived with pageant personnel in a Los Angeles
apartment. On her rare day off, she would escape up the California
coast and stay by herself in a hotel. In some foreign countries,
she found she was expected to be all-knowing.
<p>
   ``They would ask me how to solve the problems of overpopulation
and I'd think, `You've got to be kidding. I don't even own a house
yet.''' Her prize package, which is touted as more than a
half-million dollars, was an illusion, she says. The cash wasn't
enough to pay the taxes on the gifts, many of which she never used.
<p>
   Even the exposure that came from winning the crown has been, in
some ways, double-edged.
<p>
   When she embarked on an acting career after relinquishing the
crown, her agent told her to prepare two resumes  &MD;  one listing her
titles and one omitting them, because some Hollywood producers
assume that a former beauty queen can't think or act.
<p>
   When her acting career stalled, largely because of her
inexperience, she met a record producer because of her celebrity
status. Smith has signed with the Clockwork record label and hopes
to launch an easy-listening R&AMP;B singing career in the mold of Toni
Braxton and Vanessa Williams.
<p>
   She acknowledges it's an opportunity she never would have had if
she had remained in Deer Park. ``Even if it's just a pinky toe, I'd
rather have something in the door than absolutely nothing,'' she
says.
</TEXT>
