<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PARCELLS-HOLMGREN-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PARCELLS AND HOLMGREN HAVE DIFFERENT RECIPES FOR SUCCESS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Scott Soshnick &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New Orleans, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Green Bay Packers coach Mike
Holmgren is taking a page from the manual of Phil Jackson, who
frequently uses Zen Buddhist teachings to motivate his NBA champion
Chicago Bulls.
<p>
   Holmgren, who 10 years ago made a living as a high school
teacher, spoke philosophically about when his Super Bowl joyride
will end.
<p>
   ``I've been on a big wave and you can't get off the board
because you're going to hold on for dear life,'' Holmgren said.
<p>
   The game presents a sharp contrast in coaching styles. The New
England Patriots' Bill Parcells, the battle-tested veteran,
commands respect because of his two Super Bowl rings during his
eight-year tenure with the New York Giants.
<p>
   Holmgren, a Californian who is a former San Francisco 49ers
offensive coordinator, is an affable, easy-going leader.
<p>
   ``Those West Coast coaches tend to be labeled as more laid back
and player friendly,'' said Patriots tackle Bruce Armstrong.
``Parcells is considered more strict.''
<p>
   Yet there seems to have been a role reversal this week, when
Holmgren uncharacteristically imposed a 1:30 a.m. curfew on his
players. Parcells, meanwhile, set no curfew for his players until
later in the week.
<p>
   ``I think everyone in the organization is feeling very good
about what we've done,'' Holmgren said. ``But at the same time, we
want to finish the job.''
<p>
   Although his team is listed as a 14-point favorite, Holmgren
said Parcells gives the Patriots an advantage in coaching.
<p>
   ``I don't know about that,'' Parcells said. ``I know whose team
is the underdog. Ninety percent of the people don't think we have a
chance.''
<p>
   And those who do are banking on Parcells, widely considered the
best coach in the NFL. Not far behind is Holmgren, though, and
Parcells agrees with that.
<p>
   ``I think he's established himself as one of the premier coaches
in the league,'' Parcells said.
<p>
   While their styles and attitudes differ, the coaches share some
similarities. Both own two Super Bowl rings. Holmgren won his as an
assistant with the San Francisco 49ers. Parcells won his as head
coach of the New York Giants.
<p>
   Parcells refuses to wear his rings around his team, and he won't
say why. Holmgren displays his proudly, hoping it inspires his
players to win their own.
<p>
   ``The key thing with Mike is his ability to relate to people,''
said Packers General Manager Ron Wolf. ``He's an excellent teacher
and most importantly, he's a fine human being.''
<p>
   Wolf will get no argument from tight end Mark Chmura, who was
pondering retirement while on injured reserve last season because
of a back injury.
<p>
   ``He cared about me as a person, not only as a football
player,'' he said. ``He gave me the opportunity to let the back
heal and I'm thankful for that.''
<p>
   Had Holmgren turned his back on him, what would Chmura be doing
on Sunday?
<p>
   ``Rooting for the Patriots.''
</TEXT>
