<STORYID cat=l pri=r sel=ttj-z> A8871 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CHANNEL-ONE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0648 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CHANNEL-ONE-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SCHOOLS' CHANNEL ONE AGAIN ASSAILED AS ADVERTISING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JULIAN GUTHRIE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SAN FRANCISCO  &MD;  After finally gaining credibility among
educators and garnering prestigious awards for its news
programming, Channel One television  &MD;  which beams news and
commercials into 12,000 of the nation's secondary schools  &MD;  is back
to being assailed as an ``advertising vehicle for a captive
audience.''
<p>
   Only 20 percent of Channel One's 12-minute air time is spent
covering recent political, economic, social and cultural stories,
according to a three-part study funded by the media watchdog group
Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting. The other 80 percent is devoted
to advertising, sports, weather and natural disasters, according to
the study, which looked at 36 Channel One programs in 1995 and
1996.
<p>
   ``Channel One's `news' is no more than filler,'' Mark Crispin
Miller, a Johns Hopkins University professor, wrote in the study.
``Its real function is not journalistic but commercial, for it is
meant primarily to get us ready for the ads.''
<p>
   Channel One, which debuted in 1990 and drew immediate fire for
bringing commercials into the classroom, reaches about 8 million
American teenagers. In California, the telecast is delivered to 180
public, private and parochial schools.
<p>
   In return for broadcasting the Channel One program  &MD;  broken up
into 10 minutes of news briefs and 2 minutes of flashy, MTV-style
ads underwritten by companies such as Pepsi and Reebok  &MD; 
participating schools get free TV monitors for each classroom,
VCRs, satellite dishes and wiring. The hookup cost to Channel One
costs about $50,000. Ads run roughly $200,000 per 30-second spot.
<p>
   To executives at Channel One, the latest criticism is old and
inaccurate.
<p>
   ``The study is clearly not based on fact,'' bristled Claudia
Peters, executive vice president of network affairs for Channel One
Network, based in New York. Peters said Channel One spends $10
million a year on ``intensive news coverage,'' sending reporters to
hot spots such as Bosnia, Northern Ireland and Israel.
<p>
   ``Educators are clearly happy with what they're getting,''
Peters said. ``They are renewing Channel One in their classrooms at
a rate of 99 percent. Channel One programming has won over 100
educational and journalistic awards, including the George Foster
Peabody Award for our AIDS coverage.''
<p>
   A co-author of the study, Vassar College sociology Professor
William Hoynes, concluded the brightest aspect of Channel One is
its occasional in-depth look at teen issues such as drinking,
violence, pregnancy and relationships. He cautioned, however, that
the broadcaster tries to be a ``moral educator'' rather than an
objective news presence.
<p>
   The ads are a small price to pay compared to the benefits to
students, according to Elias Chamorro, principal of Overfelt High
School in San Jose, the first school in California to air Channel
One.
<p>
   ``Get by the commercials and look at the news content and it's a
very good thing,'' said Chamorro, who now works for the East Side
Union High School District. ``A lot of high school students don't
read the newspaper, so this was their news. It really helped to
keep them up on current events.''
<p>
   Under pressure from district officials, Chamorro said, Channel
One was discontinued at Overfelt last June. ``The kids liked it,
but no one was listening to the kids,'' said Chamorro, who is still
upset over the decision. ``It turned into a political issue.''
<p>
   But educators should never make a ``Faustian bargain'' with the
business community, argued Marianne Manilov, executive director of
the Center for Commercial-Free Public Education in Oakland.
<p>
   ``You can't just say, `I'll sell out a little,''' Manilov said.
``Selling school time is wrong. Period.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1313EST
</TRAILER>
