<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8872 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-RATING-UPDATE1 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0639 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PANAMA-RATING-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PANAMA'S DEBT GETS `JUNK' GRADE FROM MOODY'S, S&AMP;P (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jill Hamburg &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds background in second paragraph, quotes from Standard &AMP;
Poor's Corp. in 11th paragraph, and rewrites throughout.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Panama received a ``junk'' bond
rating for its outstanding publicly-traded debt from Moody's
Investors Service and Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp., the country's first
rating.
<p>
   Moody's rated the bonds ``Ba1,'' the top level for high risk
debt, which is considered below investment-grade. Standard &AMP; Poor's
assigned Panama's debt a `BB+' rating.
<p>
   Panama's bonds surged 4.175 points or 5.6 percent on the news.
Panamanian interest-reduction bonds soared in morning trading to 76
5/8 bid and 77 1/8 offered.
<p>
   The ratings come a year after Panama and its creditors
restructured defaulted bank debt, restoring the nation's standing
as a potential international borrower. Panama now vaults to the top
tier of Latin American credits, a signal of investors' growing
confidence in the region. That trend helped emerging market bonds
to surge 36 percent in the past year.
<p>
   The ratings apply to a note sold by the government as well as
its $3.5 billion in outstanding Brady bonds created last year as
part of a restructuring accord, from old bank loans on which Panama
defaulted in the past decade.
<p>
   A ``manageable'' debt burden and progress toward an open economy
prompted Moody's rating, Managing Director for sovereign risk
Vincent Trugliea and Steven Hess, a senior analyst, said in a
report.
<p>
   ``The outlook for the Panamanian economy is for gradual
improvement.'' The rating wasn't higher because of ``the poor
record of repayment by the government during the past decade.''
<p>
   ``Economic reforms that are being implemented by the current
government should provide a basis for improved economic performance
over the next several years,'' Moody's report said.
<p>
   The changes include selling state firms, repealing labor
protection laws, removing import tariffs and beefing up regulation
of the financial industry, the credit rating company said.
<p>
   Moody's also highlighted Panama's growing maritime transport and
tourism industries, which are using land and facilities the U.S.
expects to hand over to Panamanian authorities in 1999. S&AMP;P said
its rating was constrained by Panama's high level of public debt,
low level of savings, ``high'' 14 percent unemployment and poor
federal tax collection system.
<p>
   The high-level junk rating, while lower than the
investment-grade rating some investors expected, is likely to lead
Panamanian bonds to appreciate from their present level, said
Stuart Parkinson, analyst at Deutsche Bank AG in London.
<p>
   Moody's today also limited all future Panamanian bond issues,
public and private, to ratings no higher than a so-called
``ceiling'' of ``Baa1,'' which is three notches higher.
<p>
   The decision was uncommon, since a nation's foreign debt rating
and the national rating ceiling are usually the same. Moody's said
the use by private industry of the U.S. dollar, and the absence of
foreign exchange controls accounted for the difference.
<p>
   When Panama and its creditors agreed to restructure the past-due
debt principle and interest into Brady bonds -- named after a
former U.S. Treasury Secretary -- Panama regained its standing as a
potential borrower on the international bond market.
<p>
   Panama's Minister of Planning and Economic Policy, Guillermo
Chapman, said in a speech in New York recently that Pananma was
interested in seeking project financing to improve its
infrastructure.
<p>
   That's a change from last July, when Chapman told a gathering of
investors that the country had no reason to come to market
immediately.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1314EST
</TRAILER>
