<STORYID cat=d pri=r sel=ttx-z> A8873 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0796 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX &QL; 
A CHUCK-WAGON TASTE WITH LESS FAT AND SUGAR &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
By ART CHAPMAN &QC; 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Every year, when chuck wagon cook Dennis Dodson came to the Fort
Worth Stock Show from his home in Poolville, Texas, it was like
walking down the aisles of a grocery store: a fat cow over there, a
juicy pig here, a little cabrito in the goat herd.
<p>
   But this year, Dodson's shopping list is a little leaner.
<p>
   At nearly 42, he has come up against a few health problems that
require a change in diet. It's nothing serious, he says, but he
intends to keep it that way.
<p>
   It is a difficult task for Dodson. His Rafter L Chuck Wagon
business is a booming one, with several large corporations as
clients. When they have their company parties, they expect Dodson
to show up with this steaks, potatoes, biscuits, gravy and cobbler.
<p>
   They don't want to know about heavy fat in the meat, or too much
sugar in the sweets. They want to kick back and have a good time
without worrying about a lecture in nutrition.
<p>
   Dodson is trying to balance their needs with his.
<p>
   ``I've got three kids,'' he said, ``and I'd kind of like to see
them graduate from high school, and then college. That's why I am
changing things.''
<p>
   Since October, Dodson and his wife, Jan, have been working on
their chuck-wagon menu, trying to duplicate their trademark taste,
without some of the fats and sugars.
<p>
   ``We used to do a horseradish sauce that was pure sour cream,''
said Dodson, citing an example. ``Now I use about two-thirds
low-fat yogurt and one-third low-fat sour cream. It still makes a
good steak sauce.''
<p>
   One of Dodson's signature dishes is his potatoes. In the past,
he boiled new potatoes, rolled them in butter, then stirred in sour
cream, ranch dressing, and topped them with bacon bits.
<p>
   ``It was straight cholesterol,'' he said with a laugh. ``We
wanted to change that, but we were really worried because the
potatoes were a dish that everybody liked and expected.''
<p>
   But he said he might have found a better way. He uses one part
sour cream mixed with three parts yogurt. He throws chopped parsley
in with the mixture and lets it all set overnight.
<p>
   Instead of butter, he uses a lower-fat margarine, and punches
the taste up just a little with a bit of lemon juice.
<p>
   ``We did have one lady tell us the taste was a little different,
but she liked it. When we told her what we had done, she wanted
seconds,'' he said.
<p>
   Most everyone asks for seconds on his cobblers, but those too
have been altered.
<p>
   Dodson has found the wonders of fresh fruit. The canned fruits,
he found, are usually coated with a sugary syrup that adds calories
to the cobbler, but not much taste.
<p>
   ``I use fresh fruit with very little sugar,'' he said. ``Where I
used to use 3 cups of sugar in a recipe, I now use maybe a
half-cup.''
<p>
   He has also cut back the sugar in his bread puddings. Dodson
makes his own bread, usually half-wheat flour and half-white. That
bread also goes into his pudding. Instead of using whole eggs, he
now mixes egg whites with EggBeaters. Instead of cream, he uses 1
percent milk.
<p>
   ``We use more raisins and fruits and less sugar,'' he said.
<p>
   Even the beans have been altered to fit Dodson's healthier
cooking style.
<p>
   ``I used to cook them with bacon fat or ham hocks,'' he said.
``I have found you can get better results by using the ham center
cuts. If someone gets a piece of that ham, it's just something
extra.
<p>
   ``They don't get the rind or the fat, but they do get the
flavor. I don't have grease sitting on top of my beans anymore.''
<p>
   The meats that Dodson uses are all hand-selected. He makes sure
the steaks, the roasts and the prime ribs are all trimmed of any
excess fats.
<p>
   All the changes, he said, have been accepted by his clients.
They might not always know they are eating healthier chuck-wagon
fare, but they do know they are getting a good meal in a friendly,
western setting.
<p>
   The menu alterations have been successful enough that Dodson is
now planning a new cookbook. Perhaps even a video.
<p>
   ``I'm really enjoying doing it,'' said Dodson, twirling his
waxed mustache. ``And I look at it this way: If I get to stay
around long enough to cook one more meal, then it's worth it.''
<p>
   (Staff writer Art Chapman contributes a column on low-fat
cooking and eating to the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Write him via
snail mail in care of the newspaper at Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101-1870; or via E-mail at artc(at sign)startext.net. His site on
the World Wide Web is startext.net/interact/chapman.htm.)
<p>
   -
<p>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.startext.net; www.arlington.net; and www.netarrant.net)
</TEXT>
