<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8876 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-BIZ-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0805 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SPORTS-BIZ-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE REAL SUPER BOWL BEGINS BEFORE GAME: SPORTS BUSINESS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By W.D. Murray filed through the Princeton newsroom &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New Orleans, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Forget about the Green Bay
Packers and the New England Patriots. The real Super Bowl begins
about 15 minutes into the pregame show with the first television
commercial.
<p>
   For the next several hours, viewers will be bombarded with
million-dollar pitches for snack foods, vacuum cleaners, credit
cards, pork and a new car called the Boxster.
<p>
   The Super Bowl has grown into one of the most expensive pieces
of marketing real estate in the U.S. The 29 minutes of ads during
the game will generate nearly $70 million for News Corp.'s Fox
Broadcasting Co. with another $10 million or so coming from the
pre- and postgame shows.
<p>
   Advertisers have lined up an impressive roster of pitchmen: Bob
Dole, Cindy Crawford, the late Fred Astaire, and numerous animated
characters.
<p>
   ``Super Bowl Sunday is the most eagerly anticipated day of
television advertising each year,'' said Carl Pascarella, president
and chief executive of Visa U.S.A.
<p>
   It wasn't always that way. The big change came when Apple
Computer Inc. aired its famous ``1984'' advertisement to show that
its Macintosh home computer would change the thinking of the world.
In the ad, which aired during the third quarter of the 1984 game, a
young woman burst into an auditorium of ashen-faced people staring
at someone talking on a giant screen and threw a battle hammer at
it, causing it to explode.
<p>
   When the computer was launched two days after the Super Bowl,
the inventory was sold out in just six hours.
<p>
   A marketing beast had been born. In the 1990s, according to
Competitive Media Reporting, some $425.2 million has been spent on
Super Bowl advertising time.
<p>
   Last year, NBC pulled in $86.8 million, with the San Francisco
49ers-San Diego Chargers showdown the season before generating
$90.7 million for ABC Sports.
<p>
   The firm found that from 1991 to 1996 PepsiCo Inc. spent $69.7
million -- about the equivalent of all of this year's game time
advertising -- pitching its products during Super Bowl contests.
Anheuser-Busch Cos. was a distant second at $49.6 million; Nike
Inc. was third at $19.3 million; McDonald's Corp. fourth at $16.6
million; and Chrysler Corp. fifth at $13.9 million.
<p>
   The basis for such spending is simple -- the Super Bowl delivers
an audience. This year, Fox is predicting some 43 million homes
will be tuned in.
<p>
   Rich Silverstein, of the San Francisco-based Goodby, Silverstein
&AMP; Partners, creators of this year's spots introducing Porsche AG's
Boxster, says it's more than numbers. The real value is ``the
husband and wife are watching together.''
<p>
   Visa is relying on the wit and humor of Dole, who unsuccessfully
ran for the presidency.
<p>
   ``To continue building Visa brand visibility...we needed to find
a captivating image,'' Pascarella said. ``Bob Dole is one of the
most intriguing and admired personalities in the world.''
<p>
   The 60-second commercial, created by BBDO New York, will
lightheartedly show Dole leading a parade in his Kansas hometown
and then running into some problems.
<p>
   Coca-Cola Co. jumps into the Super Bowl fray with a
geographically split television campaign -- a strategy several
advertisers are using.
<p>
   One part of the country will see two ads pitching a new citrus
drink called Surge while other regions will see spots for Diet
Coke. The company said the reason for the split is that Surge is
being launched only in some markets.
<p>
   The National Pork Producers, meanwhile, have spent almost its
entire 1997 ad budget for five spots -- four during the pre-game
show and one in the second quarter. The campaign shows a royal food
taster keeling over after eating pork. When everyone leaves the
room, the taster gets up and eats the remaining pork with a smile
on his face.
<p>
   Nike, the Beaverton, Oregon-based athletic shoe and apparel
maker, will air ``Li'l Penny's Super Bowl Party.'' In the spot, the
puppet version of NBA star Penny Hardaway throws a bash attended by
golfer Tiger Woods and supermodel Tyra Banks.
<p>
   Meanwhile, Cleveland-based Royal Appliance Manufacturing Co. is
relying on the game's becoming part of Americana to sell its Dirt
Devil vacuum cleaners.
<p>
   ``It has less to do with football than being a part of American
culture,'' said Deborah Holtkamp, Royal's advertising director.
``We feel it's worth this amount of money to launch a campaign on a
grand scale.''
<p>
   Royal also isn't relying on the sports star of the moment to
sell vacuum cleaners. It bought rights to dance sequences in two of
Astaire's films, then used computer graphics wizardry to put its
vacuum cleaners in his arms.
</TEXT>
