<NWORDS> 0450 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BRAZIL-STOCKS-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BRAZIL STOCKS FALL AMID CONCERN STATE COMPANIES ARE EXPENSIVE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Herbert Lash &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Sao Paulo, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Brazilian stocks fell, led by
state-controlled companies, amid concern that leading stocks
including Telecomunicacoes Brasilieras SA, Petroleo Brasileiro SA
and Centrais Eletricas Brasileiras SA are more expensive than
justified by prospects for corporate earnings.
<p>
   ``I'm surprised the fall isn't harder. I wouldn't buy these
stocks at these prices,'' said Sergio Blatyta, chief trader at
Banco Votorantim SA.
<p>
   The Bovespa index for the Sao Paulo stock exchange declined
250.75 points, or 0.3 percent, to 78,798.32, only the third decline
so far this year. In Rio de Janeiro, the IBV index fell 168 points,
or 0.6 percent, to 29,581.
<p>
   The federally controlled telephone company known as Telebras and
the federal utility called Eletrobras rose to all-time highs
yesterday, which oil company Petrobras reached on Tuesday.
<p>
   The companies have led an 11.5 percent rise this year in the
benchmark Bovespa index. The three stocks account for 69 percent of
the weight exchange officials assign to the Bovespa index.
<p>
   Telebras, Petrobras and Eletrobras rose on government plans to
sell state assets this year and to open the oil and
telecommunications industries to private investment.
<p>
   Shares also rose on expectations President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso will gain the right to seek re-election in 1998 and keep
his anti-inflation program on track. The government is trying to
amend the constitution so Cardoso can serve consecutive terms.
<p>
   Non-voting preferred shares in Telebras fell 30 centavos to 90.4
reais, Petrobras preferred fell 4.5 reais to 189 and Eletrobras
preferred fell 3 reais to 434.
<p>
   Petrochemical company Copene Petroquimica do Nordeste SA was one
of the day's biggest decliners, falling 4.2 percent to 345 reais.
Copene posted a fourth-quarter loss of 6.4 million reais after
production costs cut gross margin to 13 percent from 17 percent in
the third quarter, Votorantim said in a report.
<p>
   Among other decliners, Banco Bradesco SA fell 3.1 percent to
8.48 reais, white goods manufacturer Brasmotor SA fell 2.1 percent
to 278 reais and Telecomunicacoes de Parana SA fell 4.3 percent to
670.
<p>
   Santander Investment Securities initiated coverage on Bradesco
with a ``market perform'' recommendation, saying the bank is fairly
valued. Expectations the stock will climb 19 percent to 9.74 reais
in the next 12 months to 18 months is in line with expectations the
Bovespa index will rise 22 percent during the period, the bank
said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1327EST
</TRAILER>
