<NWORDS> 0259 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-VENEZUELA-STOCKS-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; VENEZUELAN STOCKS FALL ON VALUATIONS AND UNSETTLED STRIKES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Peter Wilson &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Caracas, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Venezuelan shares fell for a
second straight session as investors sold shares on concern that
future corporate earnings don't justify current stock valuations.
<p>
   Investors are also concerned about a possible strike at Cia.
Anonima Nacional Telefonos de Venezuela, the national phone
company.
<p>
   ''Most of the sellers are locals, taking profits,'' said William
Boulton, a trader with Bancaracas Casa de Bolsa. ''There is also
some concern about the strikes but I think they will be settled.''
<p>
   The Caracas Stock Exchange's general index fell 48.21 points, or
0.8 percent, to 6317.16.
<p>
   Domestic investors continue to sell shares on concerns that a
December rally of more than 20 percent pushed prices of some shares
to a level that isn't warranted by their potential future earnings.
<p>
   At CANTV, the national phone company, workers are scheduled to
take a strike vote this afternoon. Workers are demanding a 140
percent raise, while the company is offering 20 percent.
<p>
   Benchmark CANTV fell 5 bolivars, or 0.3 percent, to 1,925
bolivars (US$4.04).
<p>
   Banco Provincial fell 13 bolivars, or 1.6 percent, to 807
bolivars, CA Electricidad de Caracas rose 4.50 bolivars, or 0.9
percent, to 485.50 bolivars, and Vencemos Type 1 shares fell 20
bolivars, or 1.6 percent, to 1,230 bolivars.
<p>
   All figures were preliminary.
</TEXT>
