<SLUG> BC-LEVI-STRAUSS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0204 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-LEVI-STRAUSS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; LEVI STRAUSS TO SELL BRITTANIA UNIT TO FOCUS ON PREMIUM BRANDS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Christine L. Overholt &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   San Francisco, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. said it
plans to sell its Brittania Sportswear Ltd. discount clothing unit
to focus on its premium brands, Levi jeans, Dockers pants and
Slates dress pants.
<p>
   Brittania's casual wear is largely sold through discount chains,
such as Kmart Corp. and Dayton-Hudson Corp.'s Target stores. About
71 percent of Brittania's 1995 revenue was generated by its two
biggest customers, Levi's has said.
<p>
   ``Our core competency is premium apparel brands distributed
through premium channels. It's what we do best,'' said company
spokesman Brad Williams. He declined to value the unit.
<p>
   Based in Renton, Washington, Brittania employs about 120 people
to make jeans, leather goods and underwear. Levi bought the company
from Asian Pacific Industries in 1987.
<p>
   Closely held Levi Strauss, the world's largest maker of
brand-name clothing and the second-biggest maker of jeans in the
U.S., said it had $6.7 billion in sales in 1995. The company
employs about 37,500 people.
</TEXT>
