<DOCID> nyt970122.0169 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=ttx-z> A8890 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PREFONTAI </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0476 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-FILM-REVIEW-PREFONTAINE-TEX &QL; 
`PREFONTAINE' IS A RACE BETWEEN THE QUICK AND THE DEADLY DULL &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
By MICHAEL H. PRICE &QC; 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Film: ``Prefontaine.''
<p>
   Writer/director: Steve James.
<p>
   Featuring: Jared Leto, Amy Locane, R. Lee Ermey, Ed O'Neill.
<p>
   Motion-picture rating: PG-13 (profanity and worse; portrayal of
drunkenness; mature themes; occasional violence).
<p>
   Grade: 2 on a scale of 5, on condition that this film does a
quick fade to home video. 
<p>
   ``Prefontaine'' may have wowed the opening-nighters at the
Sundance Film Festival, but when you take it out of movie-nut
territory and plunk it down at the shopping-mall multiplex, it's
just another ``inspiring'' and ``uplifting'' pseudo-documentary
about a gifted grandstander who cashed in too early.
<p>
   Coming from Steve James, the filmmaker responsible for that
excellent basketball documentary ``Hoop Dreams'' (1994),
``Prefontaine'' is a singular disappointment. It drags for the most
part and is hobbled by a lead actor (Jared Leto) whose glum
inexpressiveness is somehow supposed to pass for charismatic
arrogance.
<p>
   The running time approaches 2 hours but feels longer. Also, its
waste of such striking talents as Amy Locane and R. Lee Ermey is
near-criminal.
<p>
   Maybe it would work better as a TV program, but then they would
have to get rid of all that ugly language that is supposed to give
the film an ``edge'' of ``gritty realism.''
<p>
   Obviously, James finds fascination in everything that has to do
with Steve Prefontaine, the Oregon runner who wound up at the 1972
Munich Olympics. Prefontaine is introduced as an irritating kid, a
shrieking daredevil who grows up with a chip on his shoulder.
Simply put (per the movie version), Prefontaine wants to become a
track-and-field champ simply because he's NOT built for such events
but intends to beat the odds.
<p>
   He develops a confrontational friendship with a legendary coach
(Ermey), who will go on to invent a famous brand of running shoe.
He betrays a hometown girlfriend (Laurel Holloman) to gain a more
fashionable sweetheart (Locane). He is so disturbed by an outbreak
of terrorism at the Olympics that he loses his desire to run.
<p>
   Leto, of the late ABC series ``My So-Called Life,'' is pretty
much a one-note actor, so he doesn't register much more than a
blank stare. But we hear all about these developments via
dramatizations and in bogus interviews with actors playing the
``real'' people to whom all this stuff happened.
<p>
   There is already a Prefontaine documentary in circulation
(''Fire on the Track,'' a CBS network production) and it's an
impressive account. This feature-film retread might have been less
superfluous had James &AMP; Co. undertaken a true dramatization, rather
than cranking out this sentimentalized mock-documentary.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1330EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0170 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8891 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-LYNCH-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0466 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MERRILL-LYNCH-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MERRILL STARTS OFFERING INVESTMENT SERVICES FOR ONE ANNUAL FEE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Scott W. Martin &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. said it
started offering U.S. clients securities trading, mutual funds and
financial planning for one annual fee.
<p>
   Merrill introduced the new program, called Merrill Lynch
Financial Advantage Service, to some clients on a trial basis three
months ago.
<p>
   Clients who use the program won't pay brokerage commissions for
a limited number of trades and will get financial advice and price
reductions on other services such as margin loans and mortgages.
<p>
   ``The concept of Merrill Lynch Financial Advantage has caught
the attention of Wall Street and Main Street alike,'' said John L.
Steffens, head of Merrill's brokerage unit. ``Our pilot has been
the most successful introduction of a new service we've ever had.''
<p>
   Smith Barney, the nation's second-largest brokerage firm, began
offering a service similar to Financial Advantage this month. The
moves by Merrill and Smith Barney are designed to expand their
clients' investment choices and come as investors flock to
so-called fund supermarkets, which offer the choice of a variety of
mutual funds.
<p>
   Charles Schwab Corp. offered the first fund supermarket in 1992,
called OneSource, which now handles some $39 billion. OneSource's
success has spawned several imitations, including products from
Quick &AMP; Reilly Inc., Smith Barney and Fidelity Investments.
<p>
   Financial Advantage will boost Merrill's fee income at a time
when it and many of its Wall Street rivals want to decrease
reliance on volatile trading commissions and underwriting fees,
which rise and fall with swings in the stock and bond markets.
<p>
   Merrill now covers about 70 percent of its fixed expenses with
fees from asset management, investment banking and other services.,
and the firm wants to increase that percentage as much as possible,
Merrill executives say.
<p>
   Financial Advantage is designed for investors who may not trade
stock and bonds frequently, but have several brokerage or mutual
fund accounts and are interested in financial planning.
<p>
   Clients with between $100,000 and $250,000 in Merrill accounts
get 12 commission-free trades a year, a Merrill Visa card, an
analysis of retirement and college investments and access to the
firm's stock and bond research for a fee equal to 1.5 percent of
assets.
<p>
   As clients keep more money with Merrill, their fees go down and
commission-free trades and financial planning services increase.
Clients with more than $1 million in their Merrill account pay a
fee of 1 percent or lower, receive between 50 and 75 free trades
and expanded financial planning.
</TEXT>
