<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-SUSPENSIONS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0394 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BKC-UCONN-SUSPENSIONS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CONNECTICUT PLAYERS MOORE, KING TO MISS AT LEAST ONE MORE GAME &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Pete Coates &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Storrs, Connecticut, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The suspension of
University of Connecticut basketball players Ricky Moore and Kirk
King will extend at least through tonight's game against Miami.
<p>
   School officials continue to await the NCAA's final report on an
investigation into allegations that the players accepted airline
tickets from an agent.
<p>
   The school declared Moore and King ineligible last Thursday and
said it was conducting an internal investigation into the
allegations. School officials then forwarded their findings to the
NCAA for review.
<p>
   NCAA spokesman Bill Saum said the eligibility committee has
already reviewed the school's report and reached a decision on when
and under what conditions Moore and King could return.
<p>
   He said the NCAA report will be forwarded to UConn officials
``today or tomorrow.'' The school will then have a chance to review
the decision, then make a public announcement.
<p>
   The school wouldn't comment if it had received the report and no
press conference has been scheduled.
<p>
   Saum wouldn't disclose details of the decision, saying only that
the two players wouldn't be allowed to play tonight when the
Huskies travel to Miami.
<p>
   Without two of their most experienced players, the Huskies were
beaten by top-ranked Kansas 73-65 on Sunday.
<p>
   The 6-foot-8, 240-pound King, a senior captain, is the team's
starting center. He is averaging 7.6 rebounds a game. The 6-foot-2
Moore, a sophomore, averages 6.5 assists, second-best in the Big
East.
<p>
   UConn has become one of the nation's most prominent basketball
programs the past 11 years under coach Jim Calhoun. Since his
arrival in 1986, the Huskies have gone 226-101 and won the past
three regular-season Big East championships.
<p>
   The team rose to its first-ever No. 1 ranking in 1995, as did
the women's team, then lost in the round of 16 of the NCAA
tournament.
<p>
   This year's team is unranked and stands 11-4 overall, including
a 4-2 mark in the conference.
<p>
   Connecticut has produced several NBA players, including Ray
Allen of the Milwaukee Bucks, Cliff Robinson of the Portland Trail
Blazers and Donyell Marshall of the Golden State Warriors.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1338EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0174 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8902 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-BROWN-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0764 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PACKERS-BROWN-BOS &QL; 
PACKERS' BROWN HAS BEEN A HUGE FACTOR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By PETER MAY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  You may not hear much about Gilbert Brown, but you
can't ignore him. He's simply too big. One of the many problems the
Patriots will have Sunday is how do you move a human grand piano?
<p>
   ``You can't,'' said Green Bay guard Adam Timmerman. ``I know. I
play against him every day. Not only is he as big as a piano, he's
as hard to move as one. And as much fun, too.''
<p>
   Brown, a defensive tackle, got the ultimate honor Tuesday at
media day: his own podium. He was right there next to receiver Don
Beebe on the floor of the Superdome, handling questions the same
way he shucks offensive linemen.
<p>
   Brown is Thomas Hamilton big, tipping the scales at well over
300 pounds (he wouldn't say how much Tuesday, but he's listed at
325). His girth was believed to be a big reason for injuries that
hindered his development and led to his release by the Minnesota
Vikings.
<p>
   ``Things happened. They were probably my fault,'' he said.
``I've moved on. Let's leave it at that. I'm happy.''
<p>
   In 1996, he was still large but he also was healthy. The result
was 16 starts, 52 tackles (most on the defensive line) and a
well-earned reputation as an immovable force in the trenches.
<p>
   The Patriots know this. Teams frequently have had to put two men
on Brown simply to contain him, leaving single coverage on pass
rushers Reggie White and Sean Jones. But sometimes even that
doesn't work. Not only is Brown big and strong, he's also, for his
size, athletic. He was, after all, a sprinter in high school,
something that today seems implausible.
<p>
   ``There are few and far between like Gilbert,'' said Patriots
center Dave Wohlabaugh. ``He may be overshadowed along that front
line by other guys, but he's a big part of their success. He takes
on double-teams. He's a run-stopper. He sheds blocks. And he has
amazing lateral quickness. That's what impresses me the most.''
<p>
   So, in the words of Sidney Greenstreet, how did the Packers
manage to land such a leviathan? Simple. They had Brown on their
draft board when he came out of the University of Kansas in 1993
and claimed him on waivers prior to the start of the '93 season
after the Vikings, who drafted him in the third round, let him go.
<p>
   Maybe coach Mike Holmgren and general manager Ron Wolf knew what
they were getting. If they did, it has been delayed gratification,
for Brown was hurt his first two seasons in Green Bay before
finally taking over a starting role last season. Then came this
season and the Packers' pigskin pooh-bahs again look like geniuses.
<p>
   ``The Minnesota style of defense is different from ours and is
more pass-rush oriented,'' Holmgren said. ``Gilbert is good, but
he's not that kind of a player. When he became available, we felt
we had to look at him. I think we hit on one.''
<p>
   The only downside, Holmgren admitted, has been the weight. ``I
try not to let him go home (to Detroit) because his mom is such a
good cook,'' the coach said. ``But this year, he has done a nice
job of managing his weight. I mean, he's never going to be thin.''
<p>
   Said Brown, ``My mom feeds all of us (five children) well.
That's why I am the way I am today. People are amazed at how big I
am. I tell them, that may be, but you don't know what you're
missing. My mom cooks just about everything. Peppery steaks, fried
chicken. What she cooks is so good that I just have to taste it.''
<p>
   But beneath all the ectoplasm is someone who helped make the
Packers' defense No. 1 in the NFL, particularly against the run. In
Green Bay's two playoff games, Brown was, well, big. He had four
tackles and deflected a pass against the 49ers. Against the
Panthers, he had two tackles and forced a fumble. San Francisco's
Terry Kirby and Carolina's Anthony Johnson combined for 45 rushing
yards in those games.
<p>
   ``Down there, in the trenches, that's where the men play,''
Brown said. ``That's the man's game. You've got everyone coming at
you. I like playing nose tackle. It's my home.''
<p>
   And so is Green Bay, for now. By sheer coincidence, Brown's
breakthrough season also came on the last year of his contract. His
agent is seeking a deal in the range of $2-2.5 million a year, but
Brown says Patriots, not greenbacks, are on his mind this week,
even moreso than food.
<p>
   ``I'll worry about that down the road,'' Brown said of his
contract. ``Right now, all I'm concerned about is the game at hand.
Everything else can wait.''
</TEXT>
