<SLUG> BC-NY-TIMES-TRUSTEE-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0273 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-TIMES-TRUSTEE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW YORK TIMES CO. TRUST HELD BY SULZBERGERS ADDS TRUSTEE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Lynne Marek &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- A trust for the controlling
family of the New York Times Co. added a trustee, bringing a new
generation into the group of septuagenarians who oversee the trust
and guide the family's media empire.
<p>
   Lynn Dolnick, 45, was chosen in December from among a crowd of
young heirs to serve on the board of trustees. A filing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission today said the family's 1986
trust agreement was changed last month so Dolnick could be added to
a group that includes the company's chairman and chief executive,
the 70-year-old Arthur `Punch' Sulzberger Sr., and his three older
sisters. Dolnick is a niece of Sulzberger.
<p>
   ``It's just to start getting the next generation involved in
matters,'' said the trust's lawyer in explaining the change.
<p>
   The choice places on the board a person outside the media
business as Dolnick works for the National Zoo in Washington, D.C.,
where she is chief of the Exhibition Interpretation division,
according to the SEC filing.
<p>
   Nonetheless, Dolnick may know something about the industry by
proxy as her mother, Ruth Holmberg, publishes the family's
Chattanooga Times newspaper in Tennessee. Holmberg, one of
Sulzberger's three sisters, also serves as a trustee.
<p>
   Marian Heiskell and Dr. Judith Sulzberger are also trustees, and
the Sulzberger family exercises almost full control over the
company by virtue of its non-trading Class B share holdings.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1344EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0177 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8907 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-PERKINS- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0468 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-PERKINS-BOS &QL; 
PERKINS PERKS UP A BIT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MARK BLAUDSCHUN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  And on the third day, they talked. That would be
the Patriot assistant coaches, of course, who were allowed by NFL
mandate to speak to the media Tuesday. It took four years of
silence and a Super Bowl appearance to lift Bill Parcells' gag
order.
<p>
   Foremost among the speakers at Super Bowl Media Day was
offensive coordinator Ray Perkins.
<p>
   Now, depending on your loyalties  &MD;  as well as the number of
points scored by the Patriot offense  &MD;  Perkins is either very good
or very bad at his job.
<p>
   The critics suggested that Perkins was at fault early in the
season when the Patriots were struggling offensively, and that
either quarterbacks coach Chris Palmer or Parcells himself deserved
the credit when the team started scoring almost at will.
<p>
   So, naturally, some reporters, with four years of questions
stored in their memory banks, began Tuesday's chat by asking him
whether he was a genius or clueless.
<p>
   ``Probably neither,'' said Perkins, with a laugh.
<p>
   He said he didn't mind the code of silence imposed by Parcells.
<p>
   ``It's probably better that way,'' said Perkins, who as head
coach of the New York Giants from 1979-82 hired a couple of
assistants named Bill Parcells and Bill Belichick. ``You want to
have one voice on your club, and that should be the head coach.''
<p>
   Perkins, who may be out of a job if Parcells does decide to quit
the Patriots after the Super Bowl, would like to be a head coach
again.
<p>
   ``But nobody has called,'' he said, ``and I'm not the type of
person who goes around and applies for jobs. Football has been a
big part of my life. I'd still like to stay in it. It's been a good
run.''
<p>
   Perkins, who also was head coach at Tampa Bay from 1987-90, said
his relationship with Parcells is more professional than personal,
although they have known each other for almost 20 years.
<p>
   ``It's more like a head coach/assistant coach (relationship)
than anything else,'' he said.
<p>
   The offense the Patriots are running is a derivative of the one
used by the Baltimore Colts when Perkins was a wide receiver for
them from 1967-72.
<p>
   ``The key to success for an offense,'' he said, ``is to fit it
to what the players do best and take advantage of their
abilities.''
<p>
   For almost an hour, Perkins sat in the stands and answered
questions about the past, present and future.
<p>
   He was asked how it felt to be vilified when the Patriots were
struggling.
<p>
   ``I don't feel I have to defend myself to anyone,'' he said. ``I
know what my responsibilities are.''
<p>
   And then it was time to go. Time to move back into the shadow
world where Parcells keeps his assistant coaches.
</TEXT>
