<DOCID> nyt970122.0179 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8911 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BELICHICK-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1057 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-BELICHICK-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BELICHICK KEEPS HIS DEFENSES UP &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MICHAEL MADDEN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  It was the 99th time the hook was tossed over the
yellow police tape (``Caution,'' read the tape, most aptly) that
separated Bill Belichick from the rear flank of the media hordes
Tuesday at the Superdome.
<p>
   ``Do you know Al?'' was the bait this time. ``Do you know Al
Davis personally?''
<p>
   Belichick would not bite. A little bob and a slight feint toward
the bait, but the Patriot assistant head coach merely swam right on
by.
<p>
   ``Well, I know he's not with the Packers, and I know he's not
with the Patriots,'' replied Belichick, ``so right now all I'm
concerned with is who's on the Packers and who's on the Patriots.''
<p>
   Belichick is expected to have an interview with Davis, owner of
the Oakland Raiders, early next week for the vacant coaching job.
Indeed, Belichick is considered one of the leading candidates for
Oakland.
<p>
   ``Of course I know Al,'' Belichick finally relented. ``I've been
in the league 21 years and there's probably not too many people in
the league that I don't know.''
<p>
   But, until Tuesday, New England fans knew next to nothing about
Belichick, even though he has been with the Patriots 11 months and
once was head coach of the Cleveland Browns. On the first day the
Patriot assistants were allowed to talk to the media, Belichick
showed that he has changed little from Cleveland, where he used few
words, and used them cautiously.
<p>
   Writers from Cleveland drew straws to determine who would have
to do the obligatory story about the coach who sent Bernie Kosar
packing from Cleveland and started the untested Todd Philcox at
quarterback. Belichick gave them little.
<p>
   ``Right now I'm here to focus on the Green Bay Packers and the
Super Bowl,'' replied Belichick, when asked his emotional take on
his  &MD;  and the Browns'  &MD;  demise in Cleveland. ``That's what I'm here
to talk about, not last year, not next year and not 1983.''
<p>
   Writers from Oakland and San Francisco did their duty and asked
question after question about Belichick's plans. Other writers were
intrigued to see whether they could learn how the move from head
coach to assistant coach had affected Belichick, a longtime friend
of Bill Parcells.
<p>
   ``You take what you learn and you try to be better prepared for
the next situation if it comes up,'' replied Belichick. ``That's my
agenda now  &MD;  not to deal with what happened last year (in
Cleveland) or what's going to happen next year. I'm sure there's
going to be a time and a place for that.''
<p>
   But not here and not now, not on the floor of the Superdome days
before the Super Bowl. His one and only concern now, said
Belichick, is the Patriots vs. the Packers. But questioners
questioned. What did he learn from the Cleveland experience?
<p>
   ``You always learn things, but my attitude now is to try and
contribute as much as I could to the Patriots' football team,'' he
replied, still escaping the lure. ``That's been my goal and I've
tried to benefit the team as much as I possibly could.''
<p>
   Which Belichick certainly has done. The New England defense  &MD; 
especially the secondary that Belichick coaches  &MD;  has suddenly
meshed and, as Belichick himself put it, ``is playing with a lot of
confidence.'' That crew will be facing the NFL's top offense and,
as Belichick put it, ``We know we're the big underdogs, so I guess
we'll try to slap something together and see if we can be
competitive.''
<p>
   So it went for nearly an hour, Belichick shedding little light
on any subject. Even to New England writers, who at this late date
wanted to know the most basic of answers  &MD;  just who does call the
team's defensive signals, Belichick or Al Groh?  &MD;  the information
was bare-boned.
<p>
   Belichick sits in the press box and sends his input down to Groh
on the field. Groh, in turn, sends the defensive signals onto the
field. But, as both Belichick and Groh put it, the two are so
similar in their philosophies and know each other's minds so well
that rarely is there a disagreement. In those rare cases when
``there is an either-or call,'' as Groh put it, Groh makes the
call.
<p>
   ``It's probably much the same way it was when we were all
coaching in New York (with the Giants),'' explained Belichick.
``Romeo (Crennel) is the defensive line coach, Al coaches the
linebackers and I coach the secondary. We all work together and we
know what we have to do.''
<p>
   And Groh makes the calls?
<p>
   ``We work together as a staff on that,'' replied Belichick. ``We
know what we're going to do in certain situations. Al's down on the
field signaling the defense and I'm upstairs. I pick up tendencies
(of the opposing offense) up in the press box and make sure we're
doing the right thing defensively. Al and I give feedback to each
other on what's happening.''
<p>
   In most football cities, all these details of structure and
communication are known by the fifth day of training camp. With the
Patriots and their silent coaching staff, however, such details
remain vague to the team's fans, even a scant few days from the
Super Bowl.
<p>
   Even more vague to the fans, though, are the personalities and
styles of these hitherto-anonymous assistants. Belichick, for
instance, deflects all praise for the vast improvement in the
Patriots' defense, saying only, ``Most of it is due to the players
being more comfortable with the system, and understanding their
role and what they need to do, and gaining the confidence of when
they do it the way it's designed, it's going to work.''
<p>
   So it went: many questions, much bait tossed toward Belichick
and few nibbles. Typical was the question about Parcells' uncertain
status being a topic of conversation in the coaches' locker room,
since it will affect all the assistants' jobs next week, too. How
much of a topic is it?
<p>
   ``I'd say it's been minor,'' he replied. ``I'd say much of our
talk has been about Keith Jackson, Mark Chmura, Antonio Freeman,
Brett Favre, Dorsey Levens, guys like that.''
<p>
   So the media came from Belichick's past homes in Cleveland and
New York, from his present home in New England and possibly his
future home in Oakland, and the conclusions of most seemed similar
after listening to Belichick. Still a stranger in our midst.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
