<DOCID> nyt970122.0180 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8912 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-FED-UPDATE1-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0804 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ECONOMY-FED-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FED'S SURVEY SEES `SCATTERED EVIDENCE' OF HIGHER WAGES (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Vincent Del Giudice and Laura Cohn &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds analyst comment, market reaction and details from regional
reports.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The U.S. economy continues to
grow with low unemployment nudging labor costs higher, the Federal
Reserve said today.
<p>
   While the Fed found ``scattered evidence'' of pressures for
higher wages in its latest regional economic survey, the central
bank still found no evidence of accelerating consumer prices
outside of energy.
<p>
   The Fed's regional outlook, commonly known as the beige book, is
based on reports from the Fed's 12 district banks and is published
eight times each year. The report will help form the basis for
discussion on interest rate targets at the Feb. 4-5 meeting of the
Fed's policy-setting Federal Open Market Committee.
<p>
   ``Economic growth in December and early January was moderate in
most parts of the country,'' the Fed said in its report. ``Holiday
sales were in line with retailers' expectations of moderate growth.
Manufacturing activity continued to grow, with significant strength
coming from capital equipment and materials manufacturers.''
<p>
   The report is likely to be ``comforting'' for investors, said
James Padinha, an economist at MMS International in San Francisco,
because it doesn't point to wage pressures or other worrisome signs
of inflation. Still, he said, ``if anything, the report is
understating the potential for accelerated growth.''
<p>
   In financial markets, the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond was
little changed after release of the survey. The bond rose 1/16,
pushing down the yield less than a basis point to 6.78 percent.
<p>
   The latest Fed regional survey is in line with recent comments
from Fed officials. In testimony yesterday to a Senate panel, Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan said the U.S. economy remains strong with
few signs of immediate inflationary pressures even as an era of low
wage gains may be ending.
<p>
   The survey was prepared by the San Francisco Federal Reserve
Bank, based on information gathered in December and early January.
<p>
   In the Fed's New York district, the economy had a ``slightly
firmer tone than in the last report, while price pressures remain
subdued,'' the Fed said. Major retailers in the New York area said
holiday-season and post-holiday sales were ``on or above plan.''
<p>
   In the Boston area, meanwhile, the economy ``continues to expand
at a moderate pace,'' the Fed said. Retailers in that area said
holiday sales were ``modestly higher than a year earlier and mostly
in line with their expectations.''
<p>
   In the Kansas City area, rising job creation is beginning to put
upward pressure on wat &QC; 5Q!%9 &QC; % %1M!Y 9warning about as a risk to
the nation's inflation outlook.
``Labor markets remained tight in much of the district, leading
some firms to increase wages,'' the Fed said. In Kansas City, the
economy ``continued to grow moderately the past month, while
showing a few signs of slowing,'' the Fed said. ``Manufacturing
activity remained fairly strong.'' Also in the area, retail sales
during the holidays were ``somewhat less than expected,'' while
construction activity ``edged downward.'' &HT;    While release of the report had been set for 2 p.m. Washington
time, the report was inadvertently released at 12:10 p.m.
Washington time on the Internet.
<p>
   In his testimony yesterday, Greenspan said, ``the economy has
retained considerable vigor, with few signs of the imbalances and
inflationary tensions that have disrupted past expansions.'' He
added: ``By some important measures of price trends, inflation
actually slowed a bit in 1996.''
<p>
   Economists interpreted Greenspan's comments as suggesting the
FOMC won't raise interest rates next month. Still, Greenspan left
the door ajar for action later if inflation accelerates because of
rising wage levels.
<p>
   The overall consumer price index rose 3.3 percent last year, the
largest increase since 1990. However, much of that came from an 8.6
percent rise in energy prices. Not counting food and energy, prices
rose only 2.6 percent, tying the 1994 rate for the lowest core
inflation rate in 30 years.
<p>
   In its last regional outlook Dec. 4, the Fed said the economy
growing at a subdued pace with no sign of rising consumer prices.
That lack of an inflation threat allowed the central bank to
refrain from increasing interest rates at their last policy meeting
Dec. 17.
<p>
   Central bankers last cut the federal funds rate by a quarter
point at the Jan. 31 FOMC meeting, when many analysts were
predicting the U.S. economy was heading into a recession. That
followed identical quarter-point reductions in December and July
1995.
</TEXT>
