<DOCID> nyt970122.0181 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8913 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-DIPLOMAT-QUITS-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0855 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DIPLOMAT-QUITS-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (w and i coding) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TOP &LR;   &UR; U.S. &LR;   &UR; AIDE IN TAIWAN QUITS AMID INQUIRY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BRIAN MCGRORY &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  The highest-ranking U.S. diplomatic official in
Taiwan abruptly resigned his post last week, as federal
investigators investigated a possible role in soliciting Democratic
campaign contributions from Taiwanese businessmen, officials said
Tuesday.
<p>
   James Wood, a former Arkansas lawyer and Clinton appointee, left
his post shortly after federal agents searched his offices in
Virginia and Taipei, reviewing documents and other paperwork, a
source familiar with the investigation told the Globe.
<p>
   Wood had virtually no foreign policy experience when President
Clinton named him to the post in 1995. Since then, he has been
derided by followers of the U.S. diplomatic corps for his handling
of Taiwan-U.S. relations, and criticized further amid more recent
allegations that he played an important role in raising Asian money
for Clinton's reelection campaign.
<p>
   The State Department spokesman, Nicholas Burns, confirmed
Tuesday that Wood had resigned as of last Friday. ``His resignation
has been accepted,'' Burns said.
<p>
   Wood officially served as the chairman of the American Institute
in Taiwan. The U.S. United States does not officially recognize
Taiwan, and thus does not have an embassy or ambassador in Taipei.
The American Institute, a federally funded, nonprofit corporation
that operates under the authority of the U.S. secretary of state,
serves as the primary diplomatic channel to Taipei and functions
like embassies in other capitals, with its chairman serving as an
unofficial U.S. ambassador. Wood split his time between the
institute's offices in Virginia and Taiwan.
<p>
   A woman who answered the telephone at the institute's suburban
Virginia office said, ``I'll transfer you to his former
secretary.'' When the person answered, she said, ``I don't know how
to reach him.''
<p>
   The FBI began investigating Wood last fall, according to the
source knowledgeable about the inquiry. In October, Newsweek
magazine reported that senior Taiwanese officials had complained
that Wood was pressuring Taiwanese businessmen for contributions to
Clinton's reelection campaign.
<p>
   The magazine reported that Wood had told business executives
that Clinton deserved to be ``rewarded'' for granting a U.S.
visitor's visa to President Lee Teng-hui of Taiwan, then steered
potential contributors to John Huang, who traveled to Taiwan
periodically while raising funds for the Democratic National
Committee.
<p>
   Huang's activities on behalf of the DNC have stirred intense
controversy over Democratic fund-raising last year. The entire
issue is under review by Justice Department and congressional
investigators.
<p>
   In his only public comments to date, Wood, asked if he urged
Taiwanese businessmen to give money to Huang, told Newsweek, ``That
could have happened.'' But, he added, he ``couldn't recall.''
<p>
   Tuesday, analysts welcomed Wood's resignation as a boon to U.S.
policy in Asia. Many followers of U.S. Asian policy noted that Wood
was the first appointment to that post who had no ability to speak
the language. Those who came before him, analysts said, were senior
members of the U.S. diplomatic corps schooled in Asian policy.
<p>
   Other critics maintained that Wood had lied to members of
Congress after his appointment by saying he had helped create the
Taiwan Relations Act of 1979. Wood's critics said U.S. officials
involved in the measure had never heard of him.
<p>
   Harvey Feldman, a Heritage Foundation analyst and a former State
Department official under Jimmy Carter who helped shape the Taiwan
Relations Act, said Wood had misled senators in 1995 when he told
them he was one of the authors of the Taiwan law.
<p>
   ``I and others pointed out that he was making claims for which
he was not entitled,'' Feldman said. ``As far as anyone was aware
in senior positions at the time, until he surfaced ... we had never
heard of him.''
<p>
   ``There is very little good to say,'' added Steve Yates, another
Heritage Foundation analyst. ``He was one of the most clearly
political appointments made in the foreign realm. He had extremely
little background.''
<p>
   The position of chairman of the American Institute does not
require Senate confirmation, officials said. The Senate is
consulted on the nominee, and individual senators are free to raise
objections. Apparently, no senator raised significant objections.
<p>
   But soon after Wood took his post, members of the diplomatic
corps expressed displeasure, particularly in light of the
sometimes-strained relations between the United States and China.
<p>
   ``There was a lot of doubt among people who are familiar with
U.S.-Taiwan-People's Republic of China relations,'' said Ralph
Klough of the School for Advanced International Studies at Johns
Hopkins in Washington. ``He hadn't had a lot of experience to deal
with this situation. His predecessors had been foreign service
officers with a lot of experience. They were very senior people.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1347EST
</TRAILER>
