<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0182 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=l pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8915 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-ABIOLA-2TAKES </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1164 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PROFILE-ABIOLA-2 TAKES-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (l and i coding) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HARSH LESSONS FOR A DAUGHTER OF NIGERIA &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID L. MARCUS &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ARLINGTON, Va.  &MD;  During her sophomore year at Harvard, Hafsat
Abiola designed her own major. She wanted to combine her interests
in economics, politics and history so she could study her homeland,
Nigeria, from a distance.
<p>
   The more she researched, she knew, the more she would learn
about Nigeria's horrors, including military coups, human rights
abuses and political assassinations.
<p>
   But she had no inkling that the most devastating lessons would
soon involve her own family.
<p>
   In 1993, just before Abiola started her junior year, her father,
Moshood K.O. Abiola, was elected president of Nigeria. Six months
later, when he tried to assume power, the military annulled the
election and jailed him. He was thrown into solitary confinement,
unable to see a lawyer, send letters or read a newspaper. He
remains in prison, and his family has no idea how he's doing.
<p>
   And last summer, as Abiola's mother, Kudirat, campaigned for his
release, she was gunned down on a street in Lagos, Nigeria's
capital.
<p>
   In the fall, Abiola, 22, didn't just come back for her last
semester of college, she came back with a gusto that surprised even
her friends. She has handed in her 122-page thesis, and this month
she'll take her final exams. Her adviser predicts Abiola will
graduate with honors  &MD;  a special distinction because her mother and
her grandmothers never got beyond high school.
<p>
   In between studying and keeping tabs on five younger brothers
and sisters, Abiola is setting up a foundation to honor her mother.
She might go to graduate school. But first she will go on a West
Coast tour for Amnesty International to speak out about repression
in Nigeria, Africa's most populous country.
<p>
   This isn't what Abiola pictured when she arrived at college as
an 18-year-old freshman who consulted her father about every big
decision. Abiola laughs easily, and she breaks into a laugh as she
remembers how naive and carefree she was back in the fall of 1992.
``I figured I would get my degree, go home, get married to a
Nigerian who was a friend of the family and live five minutes from
my parents.''
<p>
   A privileged life
<p>
   Sitting in the apartment of her older brother, Lekar, during
winter break in Virginia, Abiola describes her family's estate in
Lagos. She mentions the gate in front, the sprawling house, the
tennis court and soccer field, the two pools, the three shifts of
security guards ...
<p>
   Just how many rooms does the house have?
<p>
   Abiola, who has spent two hours talking effortlessly about her
theories of development and democracy, is stumped. Her hair is tied
in tight braids. She thinks for a few seconds.
<p>
   ``Fifty rooms?'' she says, as if she's never considered the
question. ``Plus the guest house.''
<p>
   Abiola's father  &MD;  known as ``Chief Abiola''  &MD;  started as an
accountant at a hospital in Lagos, then served as the top executive
for IT&AMP;T in Africa and the Mideast. He also published newspapers,
ran agribusinesses and, according to Randy Echols, his lobbyist in
Washington, became Nigeria's leading distributor of both the Bible
and the Koran.
<p>
   The family expanded as Abiola took a total of four wives and
moved into the estate in Lagos. His daughter says money, real
estate and possessions mean little. Asked about memories of growing
up, she rhapsodizes about traveling with her father, talking
politics with up-and-coming leaders across Africa.
<p>
   ``It was a lot of fun to see my father interact with leaders,
but the best for me was when he would tell me about his childhood,
about how he had to carry firewood home and walk a long way to
school where he had to copy down everything because his family
didn't have money for books,'' Abiola said.
<p>
   ``Hafsat is quite remarkable, considering the stress she must be
under with her father in detention and her mother just killed,''
says Owens Saro-Wiwa, brother of Ken Saro-Wiwa, a writer who was
executed by the government in 1995. ``And it's wonderful that
someone with that background, a rich father and all the trappings
of wealth, is so committed to human rights and democracy.''
<p>
   When Abiola was 14, her family sent her to Phillips Academy in
Andover. She became president of a black students association and
ran track. To the horror of her schoolmates back in Nigeria, she
also joined a gay student group. She wasn't gay and she probably
was the only Muslim member. No matter. She believed passionately in
freedom.
<p>
   ``I didn't understand my country until I came to the United
States and started questioning so many things about Nigeria,''
Abiola says. ``You step away and say, `This doesn't seem right,
this doesn't seem fair.'''
<p>
   During her senior year at prep school, she was admitted to four
top colleges. She wanted to go to Georgetown University, but she
asked her father's advice.
<p>
   ``Let me think about it,'' he said. He called a day later and
said, ``Harvard.'' She smiles as she remembers that conversation.
The family likes to joke about the way her father makes a decision,
then pretends he needs time to think about it and eventually
announces his original decision.
<p>
   At dinner at the Charles Hotel in Cambridge, Abiola asked her
father what major he would recommend. He asked for time to think
that over.
<p>
   A few days later, a postcard arrived. ``Finance and computer
science,'' it said. She tried to follow his advice, but after a
couple of economics courses, she was frustrated. They were too
quantitative and theoretical. She wanted to mix in real-world
experiences, so she added politics and history and created her own
major.
<p>
   At Harvard, she didn't take long to make a mark.
<p>
   History professor Leroy Vail was teaching an honors course on
South Africa when he was struck by the maturity of Abiola, then a
freshman. A year later, Vail hosted a garden party at his house. He
looked out to see half the people transfixed, clustered around
Abiola as she gave an impromptu seminar on Nigeria.
<p>
   ``She's perhaps the most remarkable student I've known in 30
years of teaching,'' says Vail, now Abiola's thesis adviser. ``I
told her if she lived in a decent country, I could see her as the
first woman president.''
<p>
   Told of that, Abiola reacts the way she does to many
compliments: with an airy laugh. ``Professor Vail amuses me,'' she
says.
<p>
   A free election
<p>
   When Nigeria's dictator, Gen. Sani Abacha, promised a free
election in 1993, Chief Abiola saw his chance to be elected
president. Dozens of relatives joined the campaign, so Hafsat
Abiola decided to stay at Harvard. She spent hundreds of dollars
calling back to Nigeria every month. The news was heartening. In
Nigeria, where regional and ethnic differences are sharp, polls
showed her father winning support from all groups  &MD;  even soldiers.
<p>
    &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC; 
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1348EST
</TRAILER>
