<STORYID cat=i pri=s sel=tad-z> A8919 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MONARCHY-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0810 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BRITAIN-MONARCHY-COX  &QL; 
 &UR; ROYAL FAMILY WORKS TO RESTORE PUBLIC CONFIDENCE IN MONARCHY
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; For release weekend of Jan. 25-26
<p>
    &UR; By LOUIS J. SALOME
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR; 
<p>
   LONDON  &MD;  After years of scandals, the British royal family has
embarked on a quiet but determined public relations effort to
restore its image and stem a fatal plunge in popularity.
<p>
   Representatives of Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Charles, her
son and heir, deny that a carefully plotted restoration scheme is
etched on royal stationery and sealed in Buckingham Palace vaults.
<p>
   But they acknowledge that, in an attempt to restore public
confidence in the monarchy, the palace will call more attention to
its charitable work and seek ways to cast Charles, 48, as a serious
heir who is fit to rule.
<p>
   It hopes to complete its work in advance of the 50th anniversary
of Queen Elizabeth's reign in 2002.
<p>
   Staring the royal family in the face is a respected national
poll that this month said 48 percent of the queen's subjects
believed the royal family would be abolished in 50 years.
Fifty-eight percent predicted that Britain will be a republic in
100 years.
<p>
   More than a third of those questioned said they believed Charles
would make a bad king.
<p>
   Only seven years ago the same poll reported that only 11 percent
of the people questioned believed the monarchy would be history
within 50 years.
<p>
   ``The monarchy is doomed. I think they should agree to go,''
said Paul Flynn, a member of the opposition Labor Party and the
most vocal parliamentary advocate of a republican government. ``I'd
give it 10 years. I don't think it will survive the death of the
queen.''
<p>
   The royal family's supporters aren't convinced.
<p>
   Lord Blake, a Conservative member of parliament and defender of
the monarchy and the aristocratic system it supports, believes the
royal family's problems have been ``very much exaggerated in the
media.''
<p>
   The queen, who turns 71 in April, is ``admired and respected''
by the public, Lord Blake said, and Charles' prospects of being
king ``haven't been damaged'' by his divorce from Diana, the
princess of Wales and mother of his two sons. Charles ``wouldn't be
the first king who has had a previous divorce,'' Lord Blake said.
<p>
   David Starkey of the London School of Economics, a historian and
expert on the British monarchy, believes the royal family has
``reasonably serious problems, but I don't think they're anything
like terminal.''
<p>
   He said Charles is ``not irretrievably lost even now. But there
are more question marks over him than are comfortable.''
<p>
   Even so, Starkey said, ``More likely than not there will be a
monarchy in 50 years.''
<p>
   A new seven-person steering committee of advisers will help
Charles decide what speeches to give, trips to make and duties to
share with the queen. As part of the rehabilitation effort, Charles
will make serious speeches on the environment, education,
architecture and jobs for young people and make major public
appearances in Britain and abroad.
<p>
   To improve his kingly standing with the public as his mother
ages, Charles will share more of the monarch's duties.
<p>
    &UR; (Story can end here. Optional add follows.) &LR; 
<p>
   In what some commentators have called the beginning of the end
to the ``War of The Waleses,'' Charles and Diana may in time even
attend some official engagements together. The prince and princess
will try to avoid scheduling separate engagements on the same days
so public attention isn't shared, which inevitably leaves Charles
in the shadows.
<p>
   Royal strategy is also being crafted by the family's Way Ahead
Group, which is headed by the queen and includes all senior family
members and Elizabeth's senior advisers.
<p>
   The queen and her husband Prince Philip will celebrate their
50th wedding anniversary this year by inviting 4,000 other couples
who were married in 1947 to a garden party at Buckingham Palace.
<p>
   Elizabeth and Philip were married on Nov. 20, 1947, but the
garden party will be held on July 15 to take advantage of the
weather.
<p>
   Diana still attracts armies of photographers, an admiring public
and intense political scrutiny wherever she goes in her drive to
capture the title of Britain's ``Queen of Hearts.''
<p>
   Her recent trip to war-ruined Angola on behalf of the Red Cross
campaign to ban land mines brought Diana into conflict with
government policy. She drew some criticism, a great deal more
praise and attention that few if any other British public figure
could match.
<p>
   Diana's appearances at balls, banquets and movie premiers won't
dry up. But her work for the International Red Cross, and for
charities that combat AIDS, cancer, leprosy and provide medical
care for children will enhance her status without harming the royal
family.
</TEXT>
