<SLUG> BC-MOYNIHAN-STADIUM-BILL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0218 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MOYNIHAN-STADIUM-BILL-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SEN. MOYNIHAN REINTRODUCES BILL TO BAN TAX-EXEMPT STADIUM BONDS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Zimri Smith &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan
reintroduced legislation that would ban the sale of tax-exempt
bonds to finance professional sports stadiums.
<p>
   The New York Democrat presented the bill to the Senate last
night, said a spokeswoman for the senator.
<p>
   Moynihan sponsored similar legislation last year, drawing
objections from states and local governments that had stadium
projects planned or underway.
<p>
   The main difference between this year's bill and last year's is
the effective date of the ban would be delayed, according to the
Bond Buyer newspaper. Under the new bill, the ban would take effect
when the legislation is approved by a congressional committee, the
newspaper said. Last year's bill, which would have put the ban into
effect as of the day it was introduced, didn't pass.
<p>
   State and local government groups last year objected to the
effective date of the ban, saying it was retroactive and put many
bond sales at risk.
<p>
   Moynihan said last year that he wanted to stop the unwarranted
loss of federal funds that benefits wealthy sports teams and their
owners.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1351EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0187 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8921 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GISLER-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0849 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GISLER-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; INTRODUCTING THE NEW MR. IRRELEVANT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By GORDON EDES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  If his name were Bledsoe or Meggett or Slade, and
he had his own podium at Super Bowl Media Day, you would already
know about Uncle Sonny, the emu farmer.
<p>
   You would know about the ``Go, Patriots'' sign in the window of
the R &AMP; R Barbecue, the only restaurant in Runge, Tex. (pop. 1,200)
where the R and R Special  &MD;  hamburger, fries and a Coke  &MD;  can be
had for just $3.45.
<p>
   You would know that his high school graduating class had just 26
students, that his first car was an old farm truck, and that his
mother, Kathy, the fourth-grade teacher, is amazed at her son's
transformation into a ``neat freak.''
<p>
   And you would know, from Uncle Sonny, that ``the boy's daddy,
Jerry, is thrilled to death,'' and will make the nine-hour drive
from Runge to New Orleans to see his son play for the Patriots in
the Super Bowl.
<p>
   But on Media Day, Mike Gisler was an uncharted island in a sea
of minicams and microphones. No elevated podium, no pack of
interrogators hanging on his every word.
<p>
   No one asked if he had any of Uncle Sonny's healing emu oil in
his locker.
<p>
   No one asked about the ``Gisler, 67'' sign in the R &AMP; R, in the
middle of Dallas Cowboys country.
<p>
   No one asked the size of his daddy's cattle ranch (a modest 115
acres, which is why he also has an oil business in town) or about
the signs and banners hanging in his mama's schoolhouse.
<p>
   Everyone, even Mike Gisler, a backup center/guard and special
teams regular, gets asked something on Media Day. One life form
attached to the end of a microphone accosted just about everybody
in a uniform to ask who was their favorite member of the Three
Stooges.
<p>
   ``I didn't get asked that one,'' Gisler said. ``I did have a
couple of people asking me some shady things, stuff that had no
connection to football.''
<p>
   His opinion of Bourbon Street? ``Yeah, stuff like that,'' he
said.
<p>
   But for the better part of the hour in which the Patriots took
the Superdome field to face a horde more fearsome than the Green
Bay Packers  &MD;  a thousand reporters with pens dripping and tongues
wagging  &MD;  Gisler found his was mostly an unexamined life.
<p>
   Like metal filings to a magnet, the mobs amassed around Bledsoe
and Meggett and Slade, Parcells, McGinest and Coates.
<p>
   Gisler, the 303d player chosen in the 1992 draft who passed
through the Saints and Oilers before becoming a Patriot, talked to
a solitary reporter from San Antonio, the big city about an hour
away from Runge. ``Last week, I talked to a reporter from Victoria,
which is also an hour from Runge,'' said Gisler, whose name is
pronounced like the fowl. ``And a lot of people have come up and
said, `Hi, I'm so-and-so from such-and-such,' and I say, `OK.'''
<p>
   Gisler said he was content to be among the overlooked.
<p>
   ``I kind of like this,'' he said. ``I wouldn't want to be up
there (on a podium). They've been up there talking a solid hour. I
could field questions for an hour, but talking for an hour? That's
a different story.''
<p>
   As a national story, Gisler figures he's no story at all. He was
doubtful that he was creating much of a ripple even in Runge.
``I've been gone so long,'' he said, ``a lot of people there
probably don't even know who I am.''
<p>
   It took Uncle Sonny Hall, and Kathy Gisler, and Julia Reyes,
proprietor of the R &AMP; R, to set the record straight on that one.
<p>
   ``Wow,'' said Uncle Sonny. ``Mike Gisler was born and raised
here. This is something big and great. Call back the wife in an
hour, she'll tell you.''
<p>
   Uncle Sonny used to work the oil fields as a welder, then
retired and invested in emus, the ostrich-like birds. ``I had to go
back to work so I could raise the emus,'' he said. ``I bought them
boogers, then the bottom dropped out, and now I can't even give 'em
away. But their oil is wonderful, for burns, hurts, fair skin. I
think Mike has some, and some of the Cowboys, too.
<p>
   Kathy Gisler no longer has use for the Cowboys, not after their
arrest record drew more attention than their wins and losses. ``I
root for whoever Mike plays for,'' she said, ``and anyone who's
playing against the Cowboys.''
<p>
   She won't be in New Orleans Sunday; she opted to babysit in
Houston for Gisler's 11-month-old daughter, Jordan McKee. ``I tried
to watch the AFC (Championship) game, and nearly had a heart
attack,'' she said. ``I told Mike, and he understands.''
<p>
   Julia Reyes' son, Ramiro, played high school ball with Gisler.
Every Friday, she and her husband, Raymond, turn their 11-table
restaurant over to the high school team for their game-day meal.
``No, we don't have a TV in here,'' she said, ``but we're
supporting Mike. We're a small town, but we're all excited and
we're following them all the way. Go, Patriots!''
<p>
   A little story for a big day. Maybe it'll be told just once, but
for big Mike Gisler and little Runge, Tex., it doesn't have to be
told at all. They're the ones living it, after all.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
