<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8922 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JEFFERSO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1583 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JEFFERSON-BOS &QL; 
PATRIOTS JEFFERSON RECEIVER FACES TOUGH COVERAGE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MICHAEL HOLLEY &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla.  &MD;  No one at Raines High bothered the skinny
kid from the north side of town. His classmates might have made a
crack about his spindly legs, and he might have responded with a
joke about the size of someone's head. But that was it.
<p>
   You knew not to make things too personal with Shawn Jefferson,
the 140-pounder from the projects. He didn't have to tell you that.
You just had to watch him walk. Freddie Stephens, the football
coach, sensed it every day in the late 1980s when he would see the
well-dressed Jefferson on the Raines campus, walking with
playfulness in one step and business in the other.
<p>
   Jefferson could use his speed to run by you on a football field.
He was so fast that soon after watching him run, Stephens insisted
that he ``go talk to Coach Adams.'' Yes, James Adams. The track
coach. But as quickly as he could make a defender miss on the
field, he could become a territorial defender off it when he sensed
that someone was disrespecting his family.
<p>
   He's still like that.
<p>
   Patriots fans know the man is fast. He was fast enough to catch
50 Drew Bledsoe passes this season; fast enough to open the middle
of the field so rookie Terry Glenn could catch 90; fast enough that
Bill Parcells told him last summer that he would be a starter until
he showed he couldn't handle it.
<p>
   ``And I believed him,'' Jefferson said, ``because Bill is a man
of his word.''
<p>
   People like Parcells would have been accepted in Jefferson's
high school neighborhood. That it is predominantly black is not the
point. This is: word is bond. And if your words and actions do not
connect, Jefferson would rather not speak to you. If you happen to
disrespect the family? That's not good.
<p>
   ``I don't like people playing around with my family, man,'' said
Jefferson, the 11th of 12 children. ``I get real serious when it
comes to them.''
<p>
   The subject has become more tense for Shawn and his mother, Jean
Daniels, in the last six years. Those who use pens, notepads,
recorders and cameras for a living have come to this northern
Florida city saying they want to speak with Jean about the son she
reluctantly allowed to play football at Raines. But they often
leave with reports rife with psychoanalysis.
<p>
   On the same day in 1991 that Jefferson was drafted by the
Houston Oilers, his brother, Kenneth Hartley, was arrested and
charged with murder. He had been released from prison less than a
year earlier for a 1987 crime in which he shot and killed a
15-year-old girl (he was given a seven-year sentence because the
evidence against him was weak; he was released early).
<p>
   In '91, authorities said, Hartley abducted a young man named
Gino Mayhew, forced him to drive his Chevy Blazer to Jacksonville's
Sherwood Elementary School and then oh-so-coldly shot him once in
the face and three times in the back of the head. The prosecutor on
the case, George Bateh, said Hartley left the man dead in the
schoolyard as night fell. It was a ghastly sight for schoolchildren
the next morning.
<p>
   For that, Hartley sits on death row about 60 miles from here in
a place called Union Correctional Institution. His little brother,
the one he often protected, is in New Orleans getting ready to
participate in his second Super Bowl.
<p>
   Hence, the analysis.
<p>
   People want to know why. People build contrasts. They see that
Jefferson and Hartley grew up in the same house. Both heard Jean
Daniels insist on Bible readings, homework, respect. Both knew
streets where men and women were gunned down. But these were also
streets where the majority of people worked often and hard for
small pay. Work was the rule, killing the exception. So why this?
<p>
   ``I understand that Shawn Jefferson is a fine young man and
there are other fine people in his family,'' Bateh said. ``But
Kenneth Hartley is a robber and a killer. He has killed twice. He
is an urban terrorist. He is a clear and present danger to anyone
around him. When given the liberty, he kills.''
<p>
   Bateh did not pause when saying this. He spoke directly,
quickly. This is part of his job. Jefferson's official job is to
catch passes for the Patriots. But he has another: looking out for
his family.
<p>
   The man Bateh describes as a mean-spirited killer still is
Jefferson's big brother, nicknamed ``Kip.'' That brother sat in a
Raines gym and listened as Coach Stephens asked him to let his
little brother develop into a football player, rather than a
teen-ager who ran the streets. Hartley agreed and, despite his
criminal record, Stephens says to this day, ``Kip was never a bully
at school. Surprisingly, he was real quiet. Real respectful in
public.''
<p>
   Jefferson still loves this brother. He still is family. So as
the state systematically plows toward the execution of one of its
nearly 400 people on death row, Hartley's little brother is trying
to prevent it. He pays his brother's legal fees.
<p>
   Right? Wrong? This is inconsequential to Jefferson. It is his
brother, which means it is his family. And, he repeats, ``No one is
going to mess with my family.''
<p>
   Jefferson is right. No earthly one has messed with his family.
But fate has tested his parents' faith (Curtis Jefferson no longer
lives with the family). Hartley was given his death sentence in
'93. His time is due to come in about 2003. Another son died of
asthma. Another was the victim of crib death. Another daughter has
been paralyzed for several years because of an accident she had as
a teen.
<p>
   The family didn't want to talk about any of that last week.
Jefferson was seething over an article that came out of Providence.
He believes that a writer came here and misled his mother, saying
that a story would be written about him. But the story mentioned
his brother as much as him. Hartley elected not to comment, as did
Daniels.
<p>
   ``She is tired of talking about the differences between her
sons,'' Stephens said. ``There is always that mention of Kip: one
son on death row, another in the NFL. Well, you know, sometimes
that is the way life goes.''
<p>
   Maybe it could have tilted another way for Jefferson. People
here tell you that this city's streets can swallow up young black
men. There are nearly a million people in Greater Jacksonville and
the city has developed some shops along the St. John's River. But
for all its people, this area has the pace of a much smaller
region. Some choose to combat their boredom and scarce job
opportunities by sinking into crime. That is evidenced by
statistics that now include Kenneth Hartley. Dade County, in the
much larger Miami area, has more people on death row than Duval.
The difference, though, is less than 10.
<p>
   Stephens knew that if Jefferson worked with him, he could get to
college on a football scholarship. Stephens and Adams, the track
coach, stayed on Jefferson.
<p>
   ``Those two coaches are the reason I'm here today,'' Jefferson
said. ``Especially Coach Stephens. When I was out there being a
knucklehead, he sat me down and told me about it. I'm telling you,
I owe everything to those guys.''
<p>
   Stephens will take some credit. He will also volley some back to
Jefferson for being a steady and businesslike teen-ager. The coach
likes to tell the recruiting story in which Jefferson ignored the
University of Georgia and leaned toward tiny Liberty University.
The reason had little to do with football: Liberty is a Christian
school run by Jerry Falwell.
<p>
   ``That has to tell you a lot about that kid right there,''
Stephens said. ``There he is turning down Georgia  &MD;  Georgia!  &MD;  for
Liberty.''
<p>
   He eventually settled on Central Florida, which changed to
Division 1AA (from Division 2) while Jefferson was there. The folks
in Orlando won't forget him. When the Knights made it to the
national semifinals before losing to eventual champion Georgia
Southern, Jefferson decided that the team should have rings. He
delivered them when he got to the NFL.
<p>
   Speaking of the NFL, he was angry at every team in the league
for going eight rounds before picking him. He thought he was much
better than that and told his college teammates, ``I'm going to
make them pay.''
<p>
   That was always Jefferson, fiercely competitive when a challenge
was presented to him and those he loves. He hears the whispers,
people saying that his brother is guilty despite consistent
innocent pleas.
<p>
   ``There are hundreds of people on death row,'' Bateh said.
``Talk to most of them and they'll tell you that they're
innocent.''
<p>
   The attorney Jefferson hired, Robert Willis, responded to that
by noting that Hartley could have pleaded guilty and avoided death
row ``but he refused because he maintained his innocence.''
<p>
   Away from all the legal arguments and social questions,
Jefferson prepares for the Packers. He says he is anxious to face
Jacksonville natives LeRoy Butler and Edgar Bennett of the Packers.
He says he will be representing Raines High because ``you have to
know about winning at that school. You have to have heart. If you
walk in there, you see trophies in the classrooms because they
don't have enough room in the trophy cases.''
<p>
   Jefferson smiled and talked about the days when no one bothered
him because they could sense he had heart. It takes heart to be a
little guy in a big man's game. It takes heart to stay with your
family, no matter what they do.
</TEXT>
