<SLUG> BC-EARNS-AT&AMP;T-UPDATE3-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0973 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-AT&AMP;T-UPDATE3-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AT&AMP;T'S 4TH-QTR PROFIT FALLS SHORT OF EXPECTATIONS (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Colleen McElroy &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
(Adds comments from AT&AMP;T CFO, full-year net income results. Updates
stock price)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- AT&AMP;T Corp.'s fourth-quarter
earnings fell short of expectations as a slight improvement in
long-distance operations was offset by higher costs related to
unpaid bills.
<p>
   Profit from continuing operations rose 14 percent to $1.24
billion, or 76 cents a share, from $1.09 billion, or 68 cents, in
the year-earlier period. Wall Street was expecting 80 cents,
according to the average estimate of 25 analysts from IBES
International Inc.
<p>
   While AT&AMP;T's results show the company is beginning to stem
defections by long-distance customers, President John Walter's
turnaround effort is still at an early stage and could take several
quarters to complete, analysts said.
<p>
   ``There is movement in the right direction,'' said Barry Sine,
an analyst at SBC Warburg Inc. ``The problem is the rate of
improvement is not substantial enough to meet expectations.''
<p>
   AT&AMP;T's sales rose 2.7 percent to $13.24 from $12.89 billion.
Continuing operations include AT&AMP;T's long-distance, wireless,
Internet and credit-card businesses.
<p>
   During the 1996 fourth quarter, New York-based AT&AMP;T completed a
three-way split that spun off NCR Corp. and Lucent Technologies
Inc. Income and a gain from the discontinued operations resulted in
net income of $1.62 billion, or $1 a share.
<p>
   In the 1995 period, restructuring charges and income from
discontinued operations resulted in a loss of $2.68 billion, or
$1.67 a share. Income from discontinued operations in that period
was $417 million, or 26 cents a share.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T shares fell 3/4 to 38 5/8 in midafternoon trading.
<p>
   Volume, or the amount of traffic AT&AMP;T carried on its phone
network, rose six percent -- up from 5 percent in the third
quarter. AT&AMP;T said its flat-rate calling plan is beginning to stem
market-share losses.
<p>
   The AT&AMP;T One Rate plan has 3 million customers that have come
from other AT&AMP;T calling plans as well as from competitors. It lets
users make long-distance calls for 15 cents a minute anywhere in
the U.S. and at any time.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T said the plan is reducing churn, or the rate at which
customers leave AT&AMP;T for another long-distance carrier.
<p>
   ``They may have turned the corner, ending the decreasing growth
rates in volume,'' said Robert Wilkes, an analyst at Brown Brothers
Harriman.
<p>
   Still, AT&AMP;T's volume growth is expected to be the lowest among
the top three U.S. long-distance carriers. Analysts expect No. 2
MCI Communications Corp. to boost volume nine percent, while No. 3
Sprint Corp. is seen increasing volume 10 percent or more.
<p>
   Operating profit for communications services -- long-distance
and wireless -- rose more than 14 percent to $1.91 billion, while
operating margin widened to 14.8 percent from 13.5 percent.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T for the first time noted uncollectible expenses in its
long-distance business resulting from unpaid phone bills due to
fraud, delinquencies and bankruptcies among its business customers.
The problem bills increased AT&AMP;T's expenses by $200 million in the
quarter.
<p>
   ``The competition is so intense now that someone who doesn't pay
his bill, they can always just move to another carrier,'' Chief
Financial Officer Richard Miller said.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T expects the uncollectible items to cost the company $100
million, or 4 cents a share per quarter, for the next few quarters.
<p>
   Analysts said other phone companies may report similar trends.
``It's something to put on the radar screen,'' Wilkes said.
<p>
   Wireless revenue rose 18 percent to $937 million, while the
company boosted its number of cellular customers 32 percent to 5.2
million. AT&AMP;T said that number includes more than 900,000 digital
wireless customers.
<p>
   Sales from communications products, including consulting and
online services, rose 17 percent to $386 million. Less than a year
after it was unveiled, AT&AMP;T's WorldNet Internet-access service has
568,000 customers.
<p>
   Financial services revenue fell 32 percent to $374 million
because of the company's 1995 program to diversify funding sources
for its AT&AMP;T Universal Card services, AT&AMP;T said.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T's financial services business had an operating loss of $4
million, compared with an operating profit of $109 million in the
year-earlier period. However, that's narrower than the $35 million
loss in the third quarter.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T's total operating expenses from continuing operations rose
2 percent. The company said ``significant'' increases in network
expenses were offset by a decrease in access fees to connect to the
Bells' networks, and selling expenses.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T said it had 130,400 employees as of Dec. 31, up 1.5
percent. The increase runs counter to AT&AMP;T's plan, unveiled last
January, to slash 17,000 jobs from its long-distance, wireless and
credit-card businesses. AT&AMP;T has cut 5,700 jobs under that plan.
<p>
   Those cuts have been offset by an increase in jobs at its
wireless and customer-care positions, part of a plan to offer a
package of services.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T also said it plans this year to buy stock in the open
market for shareholder and employee-benefit plans, rather than
issue new shares, to try to decrease dilution from such plans.
<p>
   For 1996, AT&AMP;T said income from continuing operations rose to
$5.61 billion, or $3.47 a share, from $5.24 billion, or $3.29 a
year earlier.
<p>
   Income and a gain from discontinued operations resulted in net
income of $5.91 billion, or $3.66 a share. A year earlier, income
from discontinued operations and charges resulted in net income to
$139 million, or 9 cents a share.
<p>
   Sales for 1996 rose to $52.18 billion from $50.66 billion.
</TEXT>
