<SLUG> BC-EARNS-SEARS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0349 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-SEARS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SEARS EXPECTED TO REPORT STRONG 4TH-QTR INCREASE IN EARNINGS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Heather Pauly &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Hoffman Estates, Illinois, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Sears, Roebuck
&AMP; Co.'s fourth-quarter earnings are expected to rise on strong
sales growth, particularly for goods such as clothing that carry
higher profits.
<p>
   Analysts said the results, which are expected this week, should
also show an increase in credit-card delinquencies, mostly because
of the rise in personal bankruptcies. The unit's profit, though, is
expected to rise because of higher rates on the cards and higher
fees.
<p>
   ``The quarter will be characterized with excellent retailing
results and another large reserve for bad debt on credit cards,''
said Joseph Ronning, an analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman.
<p>
   Sears is expected to earn $1.37 a share, the average estimate of
23 analysts surveyed by IBES International Inc., up from $1.13 in
the year-earlier quarter.
<p>
   The nation's second-largest retailer had strong sales increases
during the holiday season in most of its business, from computers
to jewelry. Clothing sold particularly well.
<p>
   Sales at stores open at least a year rose 9.5 percent in
December and 6.1 percent for the 48 weeks ended Jan. 4, bigger
gains than those turned in by many of Sears' competitors.
<p>
   Clothing sales also made up a greater percentage of total sales,
analysts said, which helped boost margins since Sears makes more
money on apparel than most other goods.
<p>
   ``Strong gross margin performance will favorably impact year-end
results,'' Chairman Arthur Martinez said in a statement earlier
this month.
<p>
   The expectation of higher earnings comes as other retailers --
including Kmart Corp., Toys ``R'' Us Inc., Limited Inc. and
Wal-Mart Stores Inc. -- are expected to report less-than-robust
fourth-quarter earnings following a disappointing holiday shopping
season.
<p>
   Sears' increase also comes against a robust quarter last year,
when earnings rose 28 percent on a 7 percent jump in sales.
</TEXT>
