<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8926 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-FUND-RAISING-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0764 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DEMS-FUND-RAISING-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CLINTON URGES LIMITS ON LARGE DONATIONS TO PARTY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By WALTER V. ROBINSON &LR;   &UR; AND BOB HOHLER &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  The lofty rhetoric of inauguration day behind him,
President Clinton turned Tuesday to the fund-raising scandal that
bedeviled his reelection, endorsing unilateral limits on large
donations to the Democratic Party and bipartisan campaign finance
reform that would prohibit large party donations altogether.
<p>
   Seeking to improve its image, the Democratic National Committee
also ordered an immediate ban on contributions from permament
residents who are noncitizens and from U.S. subsidiaries of foreign
companies, even though such donations are legally permissible.
<p>
   Moreover, after a campaign in which Clinton met a Chinese arms
dealer at the White House, and Vice President Al Gore raised
$20,000 from a convicted tax evader who was later imprisoned for
drug smuggling, the DNC promised closer scrutiny of people invited
to the White House. It also promised a rigorous background check on
anyone who gives more than $5,000.
<p>
   Clinton has endorsed campaign finance reform before. And his
assertion in a speech to the DNC that Republican abuses are worse,
together with the Democratic Party's enormous success in raising
campaign funds, provoked skepticism that the White House really
supports reform.
<p>
   ``If you are going to support this legislation and then beat the
crap out of the other side, it is pretty hard to get bipartisan
consensus,'' complained Sen. John McCain, Republican of Arizona,
and the principal author of campaign finance reform legislation in
the Senate.
<p>
   What angered McCain was Clinton's comment that Republicans have
had a ``free ride'' during disclosures of Democratic fund-raising
excesses. Republicans, Clinton said, ``raise more money; they raise
more foreign money; they raise more money in big contributions. And
we take all the heat.''
<p>
   While the GOP outraises the Democrats, McCain said he knows of
no evidence that the GOP raised foreign money illegally.
<p>
   Clinton, in his remarks, did not acknowledge any irregularities
in Democratic fund-raising. And his spokesman, Michael McCurry,
said Clinton would not stop his practice of inviting major donors
to spend the night in the Lincoln bedroom at the White House.
<p>
   But Vice President Al Gore, who spoke before Clinton, said the
Democrats want to ``put our house in order'' in the wake of
allegations of illegal fund-raising. And Clinton offered in his
address to the national committee to support an immediate ban on
all major donations to the party  &MD;  so-called ``soft money''  &MD;  if
the Republicans would follow suit.
<p>
   But McCain said Republicans would agree only if Democrats
stopped utilizing huge expenditures from labor unions, a suggestion
Democrats have rejected.
<p>
   Even without GOP agreement, the Democrats said they would
institute reforms of their own.
<p>
   In addition to turning away donations from resident aliens, the
DNC said it would also limit annual donations from individuals,
corporations and unions to $100,000. Some donors have given much
more. Former Stride-Rite Chairman Arnold Hiatt, for example, gave a
single donation to the party of $500,000.
<p>
   The bipartisan legislation, filed Tuesday in the Senate by
McCain and Sen. Russell D. Feingold, Democrat of Wisconsin; and in
the House by Reps. Christopher Shays, Republican of Connecticut,
and Martin T. Meehan, Democrat of Massachusetts, would revamp the
way parties and candidates raise and spend campaign funds.
<p>
   It would ban soft money, the so-called ``party building''
donations with no limits which both parties have used to indirectly
promote their presidential candidates; sharply reduce or eliminate
contributions from political action committees and encourage
candidates to abide by voluntary spending limits by providing free
or discounted radio and television time.
<p>
   But similar measures died in the Senate in 1988, 1994 and 1996.
President Bush vetoed campaign finance legislation in 1992.
<p>
   Clinton spoke to the DNC as it changed its leadership. Sen.
Christopher J. Dodd, Democrat of Connecticut, handed over the title
of general chairman to former Colorado Gov. Roy Romer. The
day-to-day national chairman will be Steven Grossman, a former
Massachusetts state party chairman who has been serving as chairman
of the American Israel Public Affairs Committee. Another
Massachusetts fund-raiser, Alan Solomont, will become the party's
national finance chairman.
</TEXT>
