<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0194 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=k pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8932 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0786 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; RIGHTS COLLIDE ON A MASSACHUSETTS STREET &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By EILEEN McNAMARA &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Go house hunting with a full wallet in Milton, Mass. and your
real estate agent is likely to take you to Highland Street.
<p>
   She will point out the view toward Boston through the ancient
elms on the magnificent estates on either side of the hill.
<p>
   She will note the convenience for children of the public library
down the street and the playing fields of Milton Academy around the
corner.
<p>
   What she won't mention are the admitted and suspected child
molesters in the elegant brick mansion at the crest of the hill.
<p>
   She won't tell you because she doesn't know. She doesn't know
because the Catholic Church didn't tell her or anyone else. Not the
police chief. Not the Board of Selectmen. Not the headmaster of
Milton Academy. Not the children's librarian.
<p>
   The Archdiocese of Boston did not have to tell. Whether it
should have is a more difficult question, encapsulating the
inherent tension between civil liberties and public safety.
<p>
   There was no legal obligation to reveal the quietly expanded
mission of Our Lady's Hall, a retreat house that calls itself an
outpatient counseling center for alcoholic priests  &MD;  many of whom
now shun the place for fear of being branded among their colleagues
as child molesters themselves.
<p>
   The resident priests in the revolving cadre, removed from their
parishes because of allegations of sexual abuse, have been
convicted of no crimes. That, of course, does not mean they did not
commit any. Such convictions are rare among the clergy because
abuse allegations often surface years after the statute of
limitations has expired or they are resolved through civil rather
than criminal proceedings.
<p>
   ``If they are here, it really would be none of your business,''
is the view of Rev. Robert Beale, the director of the alcohol
recovery program at Our Lady's Hall.
<p>
   He has a point, a point that underscores the false security
represented by the Sex Offender Registry adopted with such fanfare
in Massachusetts last year.
<p>
   A Highland Street resident can ask the police department  &MD; 
located, as it happens, at the foot of Highland Street  &MD;  for the
names of sex offenders in the neighborhood and never learn of the
presence of the troubled, but never prosecuted, priests.
<p>
   John Walsh, spokesman for the archdiocese, has their privacy in
mind when he acknowledges only that Our Lady's Hall is used as
``transitional housing'' for priests under fire for sexual abuse.
He declines to say for how many priests the residence has served
that purpose, and for how long.
<p>
   None are in residence this week, he says, but declines to
confirm or deny that as many as eight have been there recently, and
that the mansion has been used in this way for years.
<p>
   ``For years?'' says an incredulous police chief, Kevin Mearn.
Until Tuesday, he thought Our Lady's Hall was ``just a retreat
house. Maybe they haven't been convicted but, at a minimum, the
police department should have been made aware of this, and there is
the question of the neighborhood's right to know who's living
here.''
<p>
   A classic clash of competing interests.
<p>
   Walsh says that the movements of the priests are ``strictly
monitored'' and ``carefully supervised,'' but others describe Our
Lady's Hall as ``a bed-and-breakfast'' that does not prohibit the
priests from leaving the grounds unaccompanied.
<p>
   As a practical matter, the Catholic Church has no real authority
to restrict the movements of its priests. And there are those who
contend it is only ``the hysteria'' about child abuse that makes
the priests' presence in a neighborhood of swing sets and tree
houses an issue at all.
<p>
   ``A lot of people would say, `Send them to Outer Mongolia,' but
there are children there, too,'' says Rev. Stephen Rossetti, a
psychiatrist at St. Luke's Institute, a Maryland treatment facility
for priests who molest children. ``In most cases these men are not
an immediate threat to minors. Will sending them to Antarctica make
children safer? No. Treatment will.''
<p>
   Priests at Our Lady's Hall get counseling, Walsh says, but he is
unsure of the extent of it, or whether it occurs on site. ``It
probably depends on the case, and because of their privacy rights,
I couldn't talk about that anyway,'' he says.
<p>
   Silence and denial have been the two greatest obstacles to
combating child abuse, especially among the clergy. The Catholic
Church insists it is no longer in denial, but  &MD;  for reasons it can
legally defend  &MD;  the silence continues.
<p>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist for the Boston Globe.)
</TEXT>
