<p>
   Bloomberg News plans to move the following stories for use by
N.Y. Times News Service clients, AMs and PMs of Jan. 23 and
thereafter. For overall questions about Bloomberg News stories,
please contact Beth Karlin in the New York bureau, (212)-318-2300.
For questions about market news stories, contact Ken Kohn in the
New York bureau, (212)-318-2300. For questions about company news
stories, contact Larry Levinson in the Princeton, N.J., bureau,
(609)-279-4000. For questions about Washington stories, contact
Chuck Hawkins, (202)-434-1830. For repeats and transmission issues,
please contact Roberto Dias at (212)-318-2121.)
<p>
   Name Change Advisory
<p>
   Editors, desks: Effective immediately, we have changed our name
to Bloomberg News from Bloomberg Business News, reflecting the
varied and evolving nature of news coverage throughout Bloomberg.
Bylines on our stories should now be attributed to BLOOMBERG NEWS.
Please call Beth Karlin or Brian Rooney at 212-318-2300 with
questions or comments.
<p>
   Ways of Wall Street
<p>
   WAYS (New York) -- The computer industry is great -- or is it?
Compaq Computer Corp. shares soared today while those of
International Business Machines Corp. got pasted. Commentary by
Bloomberg Editor-at-Large David Pauly.
<p>
   Inside Washington
<p>
   CLINTON-LEGACY (Washington) -- So it wasn't a great inaugural
speech. So historians don't believe Bill Clinton will rank as a
great president. So what? As his second term begins, Clinton stands
a good chance of presiding over eight years of peace and
prosperity. What president wouldn't covet that record for his place
in history? By Monroe W. Karmin.
<p>
   Top Stories
<p>
   ECONOMY-US (Washington) -- Starts of new U.S. housing
construction posted the strongest annual gain in eight years in
1996, though snow, flooding, and mud slides in the West depressed
December building activity. The story may be re-lead with
ECONOMY-FED. By Vincent Del Giudice.
<p>
   COMERICA (Detroit) -- Comerica Inc. will cut 1,890 jobs as the
Detroit-based bank tries to slash costs and increase earnings to
fend off potential acquirers. Michigan's largest bank also will
take steps to increase revenues by $110 million annually starting
in the first half of 1998, and said it will take a $90 million
pre-tax restructuring charge in the fourth quarter g. By Joseph A.
Giannone.
<p>
   FOOD-LION-ABC (Greensboro, North Carolina) -- Food Lion Inc.
wins $5.5 million in punitive damages from Walt Disney Co.'s ABC in
a surprising verdict that could reduce the number of hidden-camera
exposes. By Joseph Menn.
<p>
   TRAVELERS-BUYBACK (New York) -- Travelers Group Inc.'s board
said it would buy back as much as $1 billion of stock and pay an
additional 33 percent on its quarterly dividend, sending the
insurance and financial services company's shares to an all-time
high. By Ted Hampton/
<p>
   ARGENTINA-BONDS (Buenos Aires) -- Argentina took advantage of
euphoric global bond markets, financing $2 billion of its debt load
at low interest rates. By Richard Jarvie and Mike Streeto.
<p>
   MEDICARE-HMOS (Washington) -- The Clinton administration
proposal to reduce future Medicare spending relies on a $46 billion
cut in payments to health maintenance organizations over six years
for one third of its savings. By Paul Heldman.
<p>
   Market News and Features
<p>
   US-BONDS (New York) -- U.S. bonds were little changed as the
Treasury prepared to sell $17.5 billion in notes and Argentina
readied a $2 billion bond issue. By Dave Liedtka.
<p>
   DOLLAR (New York) -- The dollar jumped to a 47-month high versus
the yen and a 31-month peak against the German mark amid
expectations the Group of Seven leading industrial nations won't
stand in the way of its rise. By Dan Weil.
<p>
   US-STOCKS (New York) -- U.S. stocks were mixed as International
Business Machines Corp.'s weaker-than-expected profit dragged the
Dow Jones Industrial Average lower. By Roger Madoff.
<p>
   COMMODITIES (New York) -- Coffee jumped to a four-month high
amid concern that a Colombian dockworkers' strike and a
disappointing Brazilian crop would reduce global supplies.
<p>
   Earnings and their Aftermath
<p>
   IBM-SHARES (Armonk, New York) -- International Business Machines
Corp.'s shares fall after the world's largest computer maker
reported lower-than-expected sales and earnings for the fourth
quarter. By Margaret D. Williams.
<p>
   EARNS-COMPAQ (Houston) -- Compaq Computer Corp.'s fourth-quarter
earnings rose 43 percent, far exceeding estimates, on increased
sales of computers to corporate customers and improvements in
operating efficiency.
<p>
   EARNS-AT&AMP;T (New York) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. fourth-quarter earnings fall
short of expectations as a slight improvement in its long-distance
operations was offset by higher costs related to unpaid bills. By
Colleen McElroy.  &QR;  CN)
<p>
   EARNS-BEAR-STEARNS (New York) -- Bear Stearns Cos., the
sixth-biggest U.S. securities firm, said earnings in its fiscal
second quarter rose 68 percent to a record $176.5 million, led by
trading and investment banking. By Scott W. Martin.
<p>
   EARNS-DEAN-WITTER (New York) -- Dean Witter, Discover &AMP; Co. said
fourth-quarter earnings rose 28 percent as rising income from
managing clients' money and from penalties charged to credit card
customers overcame credit card losses. By Monique Wise.
<p>
   ETRADE-SHARES (Palo Alto, California) -- ETrade Group Inc.
shares rise after the online securities trader said its fiscal
first-quarter earnings more than doubled, exceeding Wall Street
forecasts. By David Simons.
<p>
   Company News
<p>
   CYPRUS-AMAX-GOLD (Englewood, Colorado) -- Cyprus Amax Minerals
Co. to cut its 53 percent stake in Amax Gold Inc. and seek a merger
partner for the gold company. By Jeanie Stokes.)
<p>
   EUROCOPTER-INDICTMENT (Alexandria, Virginia) -- The president of
Eurocopter's U.S. division was indicted on charges of defrauding
the U.S. government on the sale of five helicopters to the Israeli
Navy. By Loren Steffy.
<p>
   NEW-YORK-TIMES (Washington)--A trust that controls New York
Times Co. stock for the company's founding Sulzberger family says
it added a fifth trustee to represent a new generation of the clan
that reigns over the media empire. By Lynne Marek
<p>
   UNO-FTC (Washington) -- Uno Restaurant Corp., the operator of
Pizzeria Uno restaurants, agrees to stop touting some thin-crust
pizzas as low-fat food, settling a false advertising complaint by
the FTC. By Bob Drummond.
<p>
   EARNS-SGS-THOMSON (Paris) -- Shares of SGS-Thomson
Microelectronics NV, Europe's biggest semiconductor maker traded as
American depositary receipts in the U.S., fell as much as 6.7
percent after it spoke about an ``uncertain'' first-quarter. By
Melissa Pozsgay.
<p>
   EURO-DISNEY (Paris) -- Euro Disney SCA, Europe's largest theme
park operator, said sales in its fiscal first quarter, which ended
Dec. 31, rose 13 percent. By Jacqueline Simmons.
<p>
   ROCHE-EUROPE-TODAY (London) -- Roche Holding AG, a cash-rich
Swiss drug company, is set to join the growing number of drugmakers
that get bigger by swallowing a rival, with one possible target
being U.S.-based Warner-Lambert Co. By Dane Hamilton. May be
updated as WARNER-LAMBERT.
<p>
   COKE-EU (Brussels) -- The European Commission approved Coca-Cola
Enterprises Inc.'s $1.85 billion purchase Britain's largest
bottler, dismissing complaints by Virgin Group that it would stifle
competition. By Raphael Minder and James G. Neuger.
<p>
   Washington Report
<p>
   ECONOMY-HOUSING (Washington) -- Starts of news U.S. housing
dropped a larger-than-expected 12.2 percent in December, a weak
ending to the strongest annual performance in eight years, Commerce
Department figures show. By Vincent Del Giudice.
<p>
   ECONOMY-FED (Washington) -- Federal Reserve releases its latest
regional economic outlook -- also known as the Beige Book. By
Vincent Del Giudice.
<p>
   US-LABOR-COSTS (Washington) -- The long unblemished inflation
outlook in the U.S. is likely to take a hit next week when the
government releases its quarterly report on employment costs. By
Laura Cohn.
<p>
   CONGRESS-CONFIRMATION (Washington) -- President Bill Clinton's
new cabinet choices seem to be meeting Congressional standards as
the Senate prepares to vote on confirming Madeleine Albright as
Secretary of State. And Senate committee hearings continue to
consider Andrew Cuomo to be Secretary of HUD, William Cohen to be
Defense Secretary and Bill Daley as Commerce Secretary. By Mark
Willen.
<p>
   CONGRESS-ALBRIGHT (Washington) -- Madeleine Albright faces
minimal opposition to her nomination to be Secretary of State as
the Senate are set to vote later this afternoon. By Jenny Tomkins.
<p>
   CONGRESS-DALEY (Washington) -- Chicago lawyer and Democratic
strategist Bill Daley, President Bill Clinton's nominee for
Commerce Secretary, faces tough Senate questions during his
confirmation hearing. By Jenny Tomkins.
<p>
   CONGRESS-COHEN (Washington) -- Senate Armed Services Committee
holds a hearing on the nomination of William S. Cohen to be Defense
Secretary. By Dave Ahearn.
<p>
   CONGRESS-CUOMO (Washington) -- Senate Banking Committee holds a
hearing to review the nomination of Andrew Cuomo to be HUD
Secretary. By Gerald Burstyn.
<p>
   Latin America
<p>
   COLOMBIA-LONG-DISTANCE (Bogota) -- Bowing to labor union
pressure, Colombia agreed to delay the planned opening of the
nation's long-distance telephone service market to foreign
competition. By David Scanlan.
<p>
   BRAZIL-BANCO-CREFISUL (Sao Paulo) -- Brazilian businessman
Ricardo Mansur hopes use a name change, new corporate headquarters
and a foray into international bond markets to fuel growth at Banco
Crefisul. By Herbert Lash.
<p>
   More Columns and Commentary
<p>
   PERSONAL-WEALTH (New York) -- Tightwads take note. Starting next
week, individual investors in the U.S. can buy stock in Merck &AMP;
Co., the nation's biggest drugmaker, directly from the Whitehouse
Station, New Jersey-based headquarters. Merck is one of about 200
American corporations that invite investors to buy their shares
directly from the companies themselves or their bank
representatives. By Scott Schnipper.
<p>
   LEGAL-AFFAIRS (New York) -- Martha Stewart may be the
high-priestess of swanky suburban style to her fans, but to her
former gardener she's a wage cheat. He says she owes him more than
$30,000 in overtime for washing cars, grooming dogs and performing
other work at the Westport estate that serves as the set for the
``Martha Stewart Living'' shows on CBS and the Lifetime cable
channel. Stewart says no way, claiming he was an agricultural
worker and by law isn't entitled to overtime. By Seena Simon.
<p>
   SPORTS-BIZ (New Orleans) -- The Super Bowl has grown into one of
the most expensive pieces of marketing real estate in the U.S. The
29 minutes of ads during the game will generate almost $70 million
for News Corp.'s Fox Broadcasting Co. with another $10 million or
so coming from the pre- and postgame shows. By W.D. Murray.
<p>
   Features &AMP; Forums
<p>
   BRINKER-COMPANY-SPOTLIGHT (Dallas) -- To thrive, a so-called
concept restaurant chain such as Brinker International Inc. must do
two things: Jazz up its old restaurants and come up with ideas for
new ones. Brinker is trying to patch up its 500 Chili Bar &AMP; Grill
stores, but also is trying the new -- in this case, a takeout store
it calls Eatzi's, which caters to upscale customers whose tastes
range from exotic fare to comfort food. By Shannon Stevens.
<p>
   FASTENAL-COMPANY-SPOTLIGHT (Winona, Minnesota) -- Fastenal Co.
shareholders aren't the only ones nervous about the company's
fourth-quarter earnings report due Friday. Short-sellers are
betting that the fast-growing distributor of nuts, bolts and other
industrial supplies, which has come up short of Wall Street
earnings estimates in the last two quarters, will again miss
forecasts. By Daniel Fisher.
<p>
   (END BLOOMBERG NYTNS BUDGET)
