<SLUG> BC-IBM-SHARES-UPDATE2-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0443 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-IBM-SHARES-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IBM STOCK DROPS AFTER DISAPPOINTING 4TH-QTR EARNINGS (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Margaret D. Williams &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Rewrites. Updates share price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Armonk, New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- International Business
Machines Corp.'s stock dropped as much as 7.7 percent as investors
worried that lagging sales of its mainframes and computer chips
will hurt profits in coming quarters.
<p>
   IBM's stock fell 8 7/8 to 159 1/8 at early afternoon after the
company reported fourth-quarter earnings and sales that trailed
expectations. Shares earlier touched 155 and accounted for 29
points of the Dow Jones Industrial Average's 40.03 point drop.
<p>
   IBM stock had surged to nine-year highs on optimism for strong
growth in all its businesses. IBM said late yesterday that sales of
computer hardware edged up just 2 percent as corporations bought
networks of personal computers rather than IBM's hallmark
mainframes. IBM also joined Computer Associates International Inc.
and Oracle Corp. in blaming dismal sales in Europe for
disappointing results.
<p>
   ``The revenue growth story is not real strong at IBM,'' said
John Rutledge, an analyst at Boston's Loomis, Sayles &AMP; Co. ``The
bloom is off the rose.''
<p>
   IBM's net income rose to $2.02 billion, or $3.93 a share, from
$1.71 billion, or $3.09 a share, in the year-earlier quarter. The
results were slightly below the $3.96 a share average estimate from
15 analysts surveyed by IBES International Inc. Several analysts
expected earnings of more than $4.00.
<p>
   At least four analysts cut their earnings estimates for IBM's
1997 earnings.
<p>
   Others expressed concern about IBM's stock.
<p>
   ``Given that the stock has run up, we're probably going to see
the beginning'' of a decline, said Morgan Stanley analyst Steven
Milunovich. The drop could be as much as 15 percent in the next
three to five months, he said.
<p>
   European companies are spending less than half the amount that
U.S. and Asian firms spend on technology. That, coupled with weak
economies in some countries, will continue to hurt computer and
software companies, analysts said.
<p>
   Oracle said last month that weakness in Europe hurt its results,
and Computer Associates said yesterday that European sales fell 21
percent. IBM's sales in Europe were unchanged from a year ago at
$8.1 billion.
<p>
   IBM's hardware sales rose to $11.7 billion, with personal
computer sales rising from the year-ago quarter in both corporate
products and home machines. System 390 mainframe sales declined and
RS/6000 workstation sales were unchanged from year-earlier levels.
</TEXT>
