<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8942 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0882 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (k and w coding.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE EVIDENCE AGAINST GINGRICH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By THOMAS OLIPHANT &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON -- In one of the hundreds of documents made public
over the inaugural weekend in Newt Gingrich's ethics case, one
stands out for both its probative and personal value.
<p>
   In the speaker's own hand, it shows a stick figure in the
middle. On the left, arrows show all things flowing to him; on the
right, arrows show all things flowing from him.
<p>
   At the bottom, Gingrich has written: ``A pattern rather than a
single point.''
<p>
   For the Dennis Rodman of Congress, the evidentiary value is
obvious. There was no compartmentalization of any of Gingrich's
various legislative, political and personal activities. Because
there wasn't, rules and possibly laws that nearly everyone in
politics obeys routinely were not so much broken as shattered.
<p>
   The diagram of Gingrich Inc. does not require a psychologist for
further analysis, moreover. To say that the speaker has a bit of an
ego problem  &MD;  other documents also show him in the center of
various universes  &MD;  is classic understatement and a continual
precursor to the attitude that rules are for other, lesser souls.
<p>
   That Gingrich behaved with impunity is now established fact. The
fact that the perpetrator turned out to be the pol who made such a
big deal two years ago about applying laws to Congress that apply
to real people is at least ironic.
<p>
   Ever since special counsel James Cole's summary of the evidence
in this case was made public, discerning readers of the national
press will have noted words and phrases like ``surprising'' or
``surprisingly strong'' in the descriptions of it.
<p>
   In journalism, these are usually code words for previous
ignorance. In this case, they are also code for information that
went completely against the factually challenged conventional
wisdom that had previously prevailed.
<p>
   For roughly two years, the ethics case has supposedly been about
a college course and its financing, and then (after last September)
also about whether Gingrich had misled the House's ethics committee
during its investigation.
<p>
   Up until Friday afternoon this case was supposed to be
hopelessly partisan, possibly hopelessly snagged and likely to
result in an ugly fight this week on the House floor.
<p>
   Then Jim Cole opened his mouth and his files for the first time,
whereupon the atmosphere was completely transformed. For a change,
the evidence spoke instead of the spin doctors. For a change,
evidence produced a bipartisan result that was both mature,
justified and, for the moment (at least until the next case or
until the Internal Revenue Service rules on this one), dispositive.
<p>
   Cole's summary of the facts  &MD;  written, spoken and documentary  &MD; 
made three things clear above all:
<p>
    &MD; This was not about a college course as such, but about the
funding of Gingrich's ambitious national political operation. Short
of cash, he himself hit upon the idea of getting more money by
attracting donors with the prospect of giving tax-deductible
contributions.
<p>
   About $1.5 million that the committee could identify was raised
in this fashion, employing dormant foundations similar to the way
financial scams use ``shell'' corporations. Several checks, made
out to the foundations which in turn wrote checks back to
Gingrich's major political committee, were identified, and donors
confirmed that they were solicited for politics, not charity.
<p>
    &MD; Gingrich told the ethics subcommittee and Cole at least three
directly conflicting things about his activities.
<p>
   At the outset, when he was seeking quick dismissal of all
charges, he acknowledged some commingling of his political and
educational lives. During the investigation itself, he denied using
tax-deductive money for political purposes. And then, confronted
with the evidence that he did, he confessed.
<p>
    &MD; The case was plea-bargained. The investigating subcommittee,
its documents show, was prepared to say it had reason to believe
that Gingrich flouted the tax laws and either knew or should have
known he was giving false information to the ethics unit.
<p>
   But to avoid months of evidentiary hearings, Gingrich agreed to
admit to softened charges of what amounts to recklessness in his
political fund-raising and the provision of false and misleading
evidence, fudging the issue of intent.
<p>
   On the $300,000 penalty, Cole blew away another morsel of GOP
spin. It had nothing to do with reimbursing the ethics committee;
instead, it reflected his and the subcommittee's judgment that
Gingrich's offenses fell between those requiring a formal reprimand
(for ``serious'' rules violations) and those calling for censure
(``more serious'' violations).
<p>
   As such, the idea was to make the point by adding something to
the reprimand. At the same time (Democrats finally noted), the
purpose was to leave Gingrich's future to his own judgment and that
of his Republican colleagues.
<p>
   What formally unfolded yesterday displayed the power of evidence
over politics, of rigorous investigation over sound bites.
<p>
   Whitewater fanatics might want to take note, but they probably
won't.
<p>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</TEXT>
