<p>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
<p>
   ANTI-ABORTION-RALLY (Washington)  &MD;  Thousands of anti-abortion
activists gather in Washington on the anniversary of the Supreme
Court's 1973 Roe v. Wade decision, which made abortion legal. They
applaud plans by congressional leaders to ban some types of
late-term abortions. By HOLLY YEAGER.
<p>
   HUD-CUOMO (Washington)  &MD;  HUD nominee Andrew Cuomo's confirmation
hearing was a virtual love-in Wednesday with even some of the
housing agency's severest GOP critics on the Senate Banking
Committee singing his praises. Chairman Sen. Alfonse D'Amato,
R-N.Y., said that although the agency improved itself under
departing HUD Secretary Henry Cisneros, it still has far to go. By
DAN FREEDMAN.
<p>
   VICTIMS-RIGHTS (Washington)  &MD;  Sens. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
and Jon L. Kyl, R-Ariz., have introduced a Victims' Rights
Constitutional Amendment that would grant victims certain rights.
By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
<p>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
<p>
   KOHL-FOOD (Paris)  &MD;  Hannalore Kohl, the wife of Germany's
grossly overweight chancellor, has just published a calorifically
challenging cookbook of her husband's favorite fare with dishes
like cholesterol-laden sauerbraten. It's become a best-seller. By
BERNARD D. KAPLAN.
<p>
   FOR SUNDAY, JAN. 26
<p>
   HOLOCAUST-ORIGIN (Paris)  &MD;  Fifty-five years ago last week,
high-ranking Nazi officials met in the leafy Berlin suburb of
Wannsee to plan the mass murder of six million European Jews. The
so-called Wannsee conference, convened on Adolf Hitler's orders,
was where Nazi big-wigs plotted to exterminate Europe's Jews. By
BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (``i'' category.)
<p>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington)  &MD;  If Bill Clinton were a painter,
his rendering of the 21st century would be a massive mural in which
ancient adversaries have tasted the milk of human compassion and
become addicted to it. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (``k'' category)
</TEXT>
