<SLUG> BC-NATIONSBANK-SPLIT-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0285 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NATIONSBANK-SPLIT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NATIONSBANK SETS 2-FOR-1 STOCK SPLIT, FORECASTS STRONG GROWTH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Duncan Martell &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Charlotte, North Carolina, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) --NationsBank
Corp. set a 2-for-1 stock split and said it expects to continue to
post strong financial results.
<p>
   The Charlotte, North Carolina-based bank said the stock split
will be paid Feb. 27 to shareholders of record Feb. 7.
<p>
   ``The stock split underscores the board's confidence that our
strong performance will continue,'' said Chief Executive Hugh
McColl in a statement.
<p>
   The shares rose 2 1/8 to 108 7/8 in early afternoon trading of
952,700, compared with the three-month daily average of 1.02
million. Earlier, shares touched a record high of 109.
<p>
   Last week, NationsBank said fourth-quarter net income rose 24
percent to $632 million, or $2.19 a share. Earnings exceeded
expectations of $2.13 a share, based on a survey of 27 analysts by
Zacks Investment Research.
<p>
   Companies generally split their stock when it rises to more than
$100 a share, analysts have said. The move makes it easier for
small investors to buy and sell shares.
<p>
   ``It also makes it more attractive for individual investors to
purchase shares and thus broaden the ownership base of the
company.'' said McColl.
<p>
   On Jan. 7, NationsBank bought St. Louis-based Boatmen's
Bancshares Inc. for $9.76 billion in stock and cash, to create the
nation's fourth-largest bank. It now operates 2,500 branches across
16 states from Maryland to New Mexico and has $225 billion in
assets.
<p>
   NationsBank shares have risen 28 percent since the acquisition
was announced Aug. 30.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1402EST
</TRAILER>
