<DOCID> nyt970122.0204 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=tth-z> A8945 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CABLE-SHOWS-SPI </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1077 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TV-CABLE-SHOWS-SPI &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CABLE CHANNELS EMBRACING NETWORKS TACTIC: ORIGINAL SERIES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN LEVESUQE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Seattle Post-Intelligencer &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Shows that run on cable channels don't attract nearly the same
size audiences as programs on the major networks. While the
mainstream networks reach just about every home that has a
television set, fledgling cable channels like Animal Planet, a
spinoff of Discovery Channel, are launched with only a few million
subscribers.
<p>
   Building viewer loyalty is a challenge, especially with
programming that relies on reruns of specials, movies and
documentaries. Many cable channels have decided that one of the
best ways to keep viewers coming back is to borrow a page from the
network playbook: original series programming.
<p>
   So, in these weeks and months of TV's midseason, a couple dozen
new series are coming to cable (or have already arrived), from a
reincarnated ``Lassie'' to a reincarnated ``Robin Hood.'' Here's a
rundown on some of them.
<p>
   Animal Planet
<p>
    &MD;  ``Lassie: Best Friends Are Forever.'' One of the biggest icons
in TV history returns in a brand new series, complete with a new
Timmy. Premieres March 1.
<p>
   Bravo
<p>
    &MD;  ``Profiles.'' This is a series consisting of acquired and
original documentaries about artists at work. Among those to be
featured: Welsh baritone Bryn Terfel, the hottest star in opera
today; American musical legends like Tony Bennett and the late
Billie Holiday; and British dramatist Dennis Potter, in the last
interview before his death. Premieres in April.
<p>
   Comedy Central
<p>
    &MD;  ``Comics on Delivery.'' Got a problem? Call a comedian to help
you out of it. Seriously. Well, not so seriously, but this is
really the premise. It's a sort of help line for people who need
assistance going to the dentist, buying a car, breaking up with a
lover, etc. Already premiered. Check local listings.
<p>
    &MD;  ``Viva Variety.'' Basically a European-style variety show with
novelty acts, celebrity guests, live music  &MD;  the sort of stuff Ed
Sullivan used to present. Premiere TBA.
<p>
   Court TV
<p>
    &MD;  ``Cochran &AMP; Grace.'' Johnnie Cochran, O.J. Simpson's former
defense attorney, teams with Nancy Grace, a former prosecutor in
Atlanta, for a nightly debate on legal issues. Already premiered.
Check local listings.
<p>
   Discovery Channel
<p>
    &MD;  ``Discovery News.'' In this weekly science newscast, Discovery
Channel teams with ABC News to investigate and report on the
scientific angles behind the headlines. An anchor hasn't been
chosen yet; ABC News correspondents will contribute segments to the
broadcast. Premieres April 4.
<p>
    &MD;  ``New Detectives.'' This series will examine the science and
forensics involved in criminal investigations. Each one-hour
episode will focus on a particular procedure, such as using DNA
evidence found at the crime scene. Premieres April 1.
<p>
   HBO
<p>
    &MD;  ``The Chris Rock Show.'' The former ``Saturday Night Live''
cast member, whose HBO special last summer won rave reviews, tries
his hand at a weekly, half-hour, late-night show, featuring a
topical monologue, guests from entertainment, news, sports,
publishing and other fields, and a musical performance. Premieres
Feb. 7.
<p>
   E! Entertainment TV
<p>
    &MD;  ``Model.'' A documentary-style series chronicling the personal
and professional lives of the world's top fashion models, it will
have its first broadcast Sunday during a nine-hour ``Supermodel
Sunday'' marathon. The first model profiled: Naomi Campbell.
Premieres Sunday.
<p>
   The Learning Channel
<p>
    &MD;  ``Danger Zone.'' What possesses firefighters and stunt workers
to go to work every day? This documentary series takes a look at
people who have dangerous, often life-threatening jobs. Premieres
April 1.
<p>
    &MD;  ``Legends of the Isles.'' Was Robin Hood a draft-dodger? Was
Richard the Lionheart really French, not English? This weekly
series uses historical documents, expert analysis and recreations
to separate history from myth. Premieres April 4.
<p>
   Lifetime
<p>
    &MD;  ``The Dish.'' Tracee Ross, daughter of Diana Ross, hosts this
weekly review of pop culture, zeroing in on the hottest movies, TV
shows, fashions, books, magazines, CDs and videos. Premieres
Friday.
<p>
    &MD;  ``Pandora.'' Think of this as the TV version of the back page
of a women's magazine, where you can find a horoscope or maybe a
numerology column. Toss in information on tarot cards, herbs and
crystals, and you've got ``Pandora.'' Premieres Friday.
<p>
    &MD;  ``The Wire.'' Where ``Pandora'' gives you the back of the
magazine, ``The Wire'' presents the rest of it. Hosted by a group
of young experts, ``The Wire'' offers up information on lifestyle
and travel, hairstyle trends, makeup, careers and fashion.
Premieres Friday.
<p>
    &MD;  ``Three Blind Dates.'' Three couples set out on blind dates,
and the camera follows along, capturing the anxiety, the despair
and the occasional match made in heaven. Premieres Friday.
<p>
   Showtime
<p>
    &MD;  ``The Hunger.'' An anthology series that focuses on the
erotic, the unusual, the slightly horrific. Acclaimed directors
Tony and Ridley Scott are the executive producers. Premiere TBA.
<p>
   TNN
<p>
    &MD;  ``Yesterday and Today.'' Larry Gatlin will host this weekly
one-hour show that reflects on the history of country artists and
their influence on contemporary country music. Premieres in April.
<p>
   TNT
<p>
    &MD;  ``The New Adventures of Robin Hood.'' This isn't your father's
``Robin Hood.'' Matthew Porretta plays the legendary hero in a
heightened-reality sort of presentation, with evildoers possessing
all sorts of supernatural powers. Already premiered; Mondays.
<p>
   Travel Channel
<p>
   ``Historic Traveler.'' Half-hour series combines history and
travel to take a look into America's past. Premiere TBA.
<p>
   USA
<p>
    &MD;  ``Claude's Crib.'' Claude Brooks plays a college student
trying to make ends meet in this multiracial sitcom. Already
premiered; Sundays.
<p>
   ` &MD;  `La Femme Nikita.'' Peta Wilson plays the prisoner who
becomes a spy/assassin to avoid her own execution in this weekly
series based on the movie. Already premiered; Mondays.
<p>
    &MD;  ``Lost on Earth.'' A TV reporter is demoted to hosting a kids'
show with a bunch of puppets who actually are aliens. Already
premiered; Saturdays.
<p>
   John Levesque is the Seattle Post-Intelligencer's TV critic.
Call him at 206-448-8330 or send e-mail to: tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</TEXT>
