<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-WHITE-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0707 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PACKERS-WHITE-BOS &QL; 
PACKERS' WHITE IS ON A MISSION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MARK BLAUDSCHUN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  Speeches. Meetings. So many that it would be easy
for some players to roll their eyes when No. 92 says it might be a
good idea to get together and ``talk about a few things.''
<p>
   But, then again, consider the source. No. 92 might be talking
the talk as much as anyone down here. But oh, Lordy, has the man
walked the walk.
<p>
   Yes, he has. For 12 seasons. Perhaps better than anyone ever has
at his position. Oh, you can argue the point and trot out any Hall
of Famer you want to measure up with Reginald Howard White, and you
will be hard-pressed to find a better defensive lineman. Not now.
Maybe not ever.
<p>
   Which is why so much attention has been focused on White this
week as the Green Bay Packers count down their game-preparation
checklist for Sunday's Super Bowl against the Patriots.
<p>
   Call him what you want. The Minister of Defense. Rev. White
(which is accurate, since White is indeed an ordained, practicing
pastor). Or the biggest impact player to hit the Packers in a
generation, which coincidentally is how long it has been (29 years)
since they were in a Super Bowl.
<p>
   Or call him what teammate Don Beebe calls the 6-foot-5-inch,
300-pound, 35-year-old defensive end. ``This guy,'' said Beebe,
``is like God in pads. He's the most revered athlete I've ever been
around.''
<p>
   The Patriots will have to contend with the 11-time Pro Bowl
player Sunday.
<p>
   ``A lot of players fold their tent and can't react in big
games,'' said Patriots defensive end Willie McGinest, ``but he's
one of those players who has stepped up in the big games. He's one
of those impact players who has turned games around.''
<p>
   And teams. Four years ago, the Packers were one of those ``if
only'' teams when White decided that eight seasons in Philadelphia
without sniffing a Super Bowl were enough.
<p>
   He shopped himself around on what was only half-jokingly called
the Reggie White Traveling Ministry Tour before settling on a
four-year deal with Green Bay, feeling that the Packers had the
best chance to reach the ultimate prize.
<p>
   White's religious fervor has been well-documented, and although
he sometimes seems to push the boundary between belief and crusade
by saying things such as the Packers were meant to win the NFC
championship because that was the role God had cast for them, there
is nothing phony about him.
<p>
   Skepticism toward the Packers and toward White's beliefs has
been part of the package since he arrived in Green Bay. But he
rapidly converts the doubters.
<p>
   ``We still have a way to go,'' he said in Tuesday's dog and pony
show known as Super Bowl Media Day. ``I see a lot of guys on the
media jumping on the bandwagon now, when four years ago I somewhat
foresaw this and a lot of guys giggled and wrote certain type
stories. But my question is, what do you have to say now?''
<p>
   What can you say, except that White has helped will the Packers
past the roadblocks that kept them out the championship game since
1968?
<p>
   He is certainly not the only reason the Packers have emerged as
the best team in the NFC  &MD;  and, if you believe the oddsmakers, the
best team in football  &MD;  but he probably is the main one.
<p>
   Mike Holmgren, who has willingly accepted White's role as
surrogate coach, does not dispute the suggestion.
<p>
   ``Reggie is one of our best recruiters,'' said Holmgren,
explaining that when White chose the Packers as a free agent, it
legitimized Green Bay as a place where others might want to
continue their careers. ``They want him as a teammate. In this day
and age, I can assure you that he is the real thing. What he says,
he means.''
<p>
   White knows that, at 35, even with another Pro Bowl season under
his belt, one in which he led the Packers in sacks, he might not
get this far again. This might be his once chance to get the team
achievement to match the individual awards he has garnered.
<p>
   ``One thing we talked about my first year here,'' said White,
``is that if you go to the Super Bowl and win one as a Green Bay
Packer, it would be unlike any other thing that you've ever
experienced.''
</TEXT>
