<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0208 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8949 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COACHES- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1005 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COACHES-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PATRIOTS ASSISTANT COACHES BREAK THE SILENCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By RON BORGES &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  Dante Scarnecchia put to rest any concerns his
boss might have had about his suddenly restored constitutional
right to free speech with the first public utterance from his mouth
this season.
<p>
   ``Green Bay's got a great team,'' the Patriots' assistant coach
said Tuesday, tongue firmly planted in cheek. ``They got a great
quarterback. They got great running backs. They got great
receivers. They got a great defense. Great to see ya. See ya
later.''
<p>
   This is what the New England media has waited all year to hear?
<p>
   Since the arrival of Bill Parcells as head coach four years ago,
assistants have been treated like children in New England. On the
best of days, they were to be seen and not heard. If they needed an
opinion on anything, Parcells would gladly let them know what it
was.
<p>
   But once your team makes the Super Bowl, the wraps are off. Or,
in the case of the assistant coaches of the New England Patriots,
the duct tape comes off. The National Football League set them
free, free to put their foot in their mouth at will. America! What
a country!
<p>
   NFL rules mandate that all players and coaches at the Super Bowl
must endure three days of unparalleled media grilling. They must
field questions about their childhood transgressions and their
childhood triumphs. They are asked about their team, their players
and their boss.
<p>
   Upon occasion, they might even be asked to talk about the game.
<p>
   Could Parcells' silent majority stand up to the heat?
<p>
   Fear not, your Tunaship.
<p>
   ``I'd like to knock that one right out of the water,''
quarterbacks coach Chris Palmer deftly said when asked about a
swirling rumor that he will head to San Diego after the Super Bowl
to become Kevin Gilbride's offensive coordinator. ``That will have
to wait until after the Super Bowl.''
<p>
   In other words, maybe I is and maybe I isn't, but even if you
force bamboo shoots under my fingernails, I ain't talkin'. Parcells
would have been proud. So would the head of the KGB.
<p>
   Over in the corner stood special teams coach Mike Sweatman, who
seemed to be trying to maintain the code of omerta (silence or
death) as best he could by standing so far from the fray that he
easily could have been mistaken for someone in charge of team
security rather than special teams play.
<p>
   Small knots of knotheads with pen, paper and minicam encircled
offensive coordinator Ray Perkins, defensive coordinator Al Groh
and always affable assistant head coach Bill Belichick, who showed
immediately that a year of silence had done nothing to alter the
personality that reminded people in Cleveland of a porcupine in
earmuffs during his brief tenure there as head coach.
<p>
   Belichick has been rumored to be under consideration as the next
sacrificial lamb for Al Davis (which is known in some circles as
head coach of the Oakland Raiders); also, writers who knew him in
Cleveland have been trying for a year to find out what life is like
when you go from being the boss to working for the boss. With his
tongue now untied by NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue, Belichick
cleared the air.
<p>
   ``Cleveland guys and Oakland guys have been here for 30 minutes
with their bait out and I haven't bitten for it yet,'' Belichick
said.
<p>
   Is that any way for a gentleman from Wesleyan to talk?
<p>
   As the questions persisted about his comings (from Cleveland) or
his goings (to Oakland), Belichick chose to use another
constitutional amendment not cited lately in Foxborough  &MD;  the Fifth
Amendment. It's just called ``taking the Fifth'' when a Mafia Don
does it before a Congressional subcommittee. Suffice it to say,
it's not often combined with the First Amendment (free speech), but
these are unusual times in New England. The way things were going
Tuesday, civics teachers in the New Orleans school system should
have brought their students to the Superdome to watch the
Constitution in action right there on the 50-yard line.
<p>
   But halfway up in the stands, high above it all, sat Groh, a
quiet, intelligent man who took the line of least resistance. He
just listened to the questions fired at him and answered them
thoughtfully. He was not there to entertain or obfuscate. He was
there to do the best he could to help, answering questions about
his defense and how it has come to be one of the best in football
over the past seven weeks, and what it was like to work for
Parcells and with Belichick, who had once been his boss.
<p>
   He even told an anecdote or two about the peripatetic life of an
NFL assistant coach and what it can do to families and mortgages.
He was rather pleasant to listen to, quite frankly.
<p>
   What Groh could not answer he did not answer. What he could he
did. As Groh's performance made clear, this talking thing is really
not that difficult for an adult, as long as you don't view it as
the Spanish Inquisition.
<p>
   All it really is, is people asking people about football. It's
not people asking people about the nation's nuclear arsenal.
<p>
   At one point, when Groh was asked about scrappy reserve
linebacker Marty Moore, he even went so far as to engage his
questioner in conversation.
<p>
   ``You from Montana or Kentucky?'' Groh asked, assuming the
questioner had to be from one of those places to be interested in
Moore. ``Neither? Oh. It's just interesting at this point that I
get a Marty Moore question.''
<p>
   Groh went on to explain how tough a kid Moore is and how there
were more than a few NFL teams he could play for, and that there's
just no opportunity here for full-time work right now, even though
Moore is so well-prepared and does everything he's asked to do. In
other words, he put in a few good words for a good kid.
<p>
   Was this something that had to be banned in Boston for four
years? Considering what came out of the mouths of the 12 men who
work for Bill Parcells, it hardly seemed so.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1407EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0209 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tth-z> A8950 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-RURAL-COLUMN-RAMSEY-S </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0821 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-RURAL-COLUMN-RAMSEY-SPI &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BUSINESS `LONG EAGLES' WHO NEST IN THE WEST &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BRUCE RAMSEY &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Seattle Post-Intelligencer &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Philip Burgess, president of a Denver think tank, Center for the
New West, remembers the discovery a few years ago.
<p>
   He kept stumbling across people in rural areas doing their
business by telephone, fax and air express for clients far away.
When he ran across the New York stockbroker in rural Colorado, he
decided he was on to something.
<p>
   The broker explained that he moved out of New York after his
boy's bicycle was stolen for the third time and some miscreant
snatched his wife's purse. Life was a lot different in Colorado: a
lot better. Work was the same, though. He just did it over the
phone.
<p>
   Burgess dubbed such folks ``lone eagles.''
<p>
   Dick Larsen is a lone eagle. Originally a corporate guy who
worked at U.S. Steel and Ford Motor Co., he went to work as a
finance consultant. He helps draw up business plans to present to
lenders and financiers, and in sales and acquisitions of companies.
He could have done this work from San Francisco, where he was
living, but he decided he could also do it from Bend, Ore.
<p>
   ``It's not a business you're going to start from Bend,'' says
Larsen, 62. He couldn't have built up the knowledge and contacts
without years first in San Francisco and New York. But once he was
set up, there was no need to live in a big city.
<p>
   He moved to central Oregon 22 years ago. Real estate was cheap,
the air clean, ski slopes and fishing streams uncrowded. He lives
seven minutes from his office. He still spends a lot of time flying
off to see clients, but he'd have to do that wherever he lived.
<p>
   More and more Dick Larsens are living where they want. They are
brokers, engineers, consultants, sales reps, writers, artists and
even cottage manufacturers. And they are helping to transform the
West.
<p>
   ``Rural areas in the West have gone from decline in the '80s to
growing faster than the national average in the '90s,'' says
William Beyers, professor of geography at the University of
Washington. Beyers reports mini-booms in places such as Griggs,
Idaho, where Paul Allen has a ranch, and Montrose, Colo., just up
the road from the ``starter mansions'' of Telluride.
<p>
   On Beyers' map, the boom counties extend in a web of dark
splotches from the Canadian border to Mexico.
<p>
   In Washington state, the hot spots are in a swath from Port
Angeles east and north to Canada; Kittitas and Okanogan counties;
the areas around Pullman and Long Beach. But the growth is
everywhere. In the 1980s, only half the 27 rural counties had net
in-migration. In the first half of the 1990s, all of them did.
<p>
   The reason is not all lone eagles. Retirees are a big group, as
are manufacturers seeking cheap land. The lone eagles are of
particular interest because, in the geographer's taxonomy, they're
a new species.
<p>
   How many are there? Washington State University professors Don
Dillman and Priscilla Salant and graduate student Lisa Carley
surveyed driver's license applicants, and estimate that 2,600 lone
eagles move to Washington each year. How many move within the state
they don't know. They tend to be older, better educated and more
affluent than the average migrant. Most are self-employed. Sixty
percent earn more than $50,000 a year.
<p>
   These are ``very significant movements of high-quality wealth
creators,'' says Burgess of the Center for the New West.
<p>
   Why Washington? Almost all cited the natural environment,
including the climate and outdoor recreation. Next, cited by 65
percent, was personal safety. Third, 59 percent, mentioned lack of
a state income tax.
<p>
   About half the lone eagles moved to urban counties, where they
are lost in the aggregate of humanity. The half that moved to rural
counties are more significant.
<p>
   They bring urban incomes and urban tastes. They will not put up
with bad coffee, underfinanced libraries and Chinese restaurants
that offer up chop suey and egg foo yung. Though older, they are
early adopters of technology. Seventy-nine percent use fax
machines; 59 percent, modems; 66 percent, overnight mail; 31
percent, cell phones.
<p>
   ``Their entrance can help a whole community wire up'' to the
Internet, says Tim Sweeney, consumer policy specialist at the
Washington Utilities and Transportation Commission.
<p>
   Sweeney recently took a car trip across the West, and was amazed
at all the new houses. He thought, ``How do all these people make a
living?'' Not from mining, logging or sheep ranching.
<p>
   Salant, who helped run the WSU study, grapples with that
question, too. ``There are more ways than you might think,'' she
says. ``Lone eagles are only the most dramatic examples. People
say, `This is where I want to raise my child,' and they make it
work.''
<p>
   Bruce Ramsey is a P-I business reporter and columnist.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
