<DOCID> nyt970122.0210 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=i pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8951 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-ABIOLA-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADER> T     01-22 1125 </HEADER>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PROFILE-ABIOLA-2ND &LR;   &UR; TAKE-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (l and i coding) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ARLINGTON, Va.: ... even soldiers. &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The election was held on June 12 of that year. Nigerians and
foreign observers alike agree that her father won a fair, two-way
race with 54 percent of the vote.
<p>
   Abacha never made the vote count public. He quickly annulled the
election.
<p>
   Chief Abiola went on a tour of Europe and the United States to
rally government support. At a three-hour dinner with the Abiolas
in Cambridge, Vail watched father and daughter exchange ideas.
Chief Abiola was smart, tough and passionate about Nigeria  &MD;  just
like his daughter.
<p>
   In June 1994, as Abiola claimed the office, the Nigerian
government arrested him for ``misrepresenting'' himself as the
president of the country. When students protested, they were beaten
and jailed. Abiola, who suffers hypertension, was confined to a
cell in an army base, denied visitors and not allowed his medicine.
<p>
   His oldest wife, Hafsat's mother, made the rounds of officials
and foreign embassies. In December 1994, Abiola's oldest children
were allowed to meet him in a warden's office. The visit lasted
only a few minutes. Hafsat and her brothers and sisters hugged
their father and said, ``We're proud of you.'' But they were
worried. They noticed that he looked disoriented and he limped  &MD; 
because he had been beaten by a guard, Hafsat says.
<p>
   Abiola's carefully phrased answers often make her sound older
than a 22-year-old. When she talks about her father, whom she calls
``Daddy,'' she sounds younger.
<p>
   ``My father is sweet and naive and nice,'' she says. ``That's
the reason why Abacha has chosen the right person. My father says,
`What has caused these people do do this? What can be done for
them?'''
<p>
   That 1994 visit was the last time any family members saw Chief
Abiola. Hafsat returned to Harvard and, to the amazement of her
friends, burrowed back into her studies.
<p>
   In November 1995, the regime executed Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight
others from the Movement for the Survival of the Ogoni people, who
had challenged oil companies. Saro-Wiwa had been a family friend,
and Hafsat Abiola was outraged. A few weeks later, she rented an
apartment near campus and took off the spring semester to campaign
for democracy in Nigeria. She got a taste of politics when she
testified before the New York City Council. As she had requested,
the council passed a resolution condemning Nigeria's regime.
<p>
   Last March, Abiola's mother was arrested for distributing
material critical of the regime. She was released after a day.
<p>
   At 4 a.m. on June 4, Abiola answered the phone.
<p>
   ``Did I wake you?'' a family friend in Washington said, adding,
``Go back to sleep. We'll talk later.''
<p>
   Abiola couldn't sleep. The friend told her to fly to Washington
immediately so they could talk face to face. Abiola had a
premonition that something had happened to her father. When she got
to Washington, she learned that her mother, Kudirat, had been shot
dead by three men in a passing car as she drove to a meeting at the
Canadian embassy in Lagos.
<p>
   Abiola and her siblings gathered at her older brother's
apartment in Virgina. They quickly agreed on their priorities.
First they would get their two youngest brothers out of the family
compound in Lagos and into the United States. Then they would
continue their studies, as their mother had wanted.
<p>
   Hafsat Abiola made an announcement: ``I'm going to take up
Mommy's work.''
<p>
   In Nigeria, the regime had rounded up about 20 of her cousins,
uncles and half-brothers, saying they were under investigation for
homicide. The Abiolas figured the government was trying to divide
the family. (The relatives were released without being charged.)
<p>
   A day after the killing, Hafsat Abiola spoke to CNN
International, the Voice of America and opposition radio in
Nigeria. ``If the military is really looking for the killer of my
mom, they should start by looking in the mirror,'' Abiola recalls
telling the network.
<p>
   During several conversations, Abiola is at a loss for words only
once, when remembering her mother. She talks about how loving her
mother was. About how she gave birth to nine children (two died in
infancy), educated herself and became a spokeswoman for justice in
Nigeria.
<p>
   Abiola pauses, brushes her eyes and then gets her composure
back. 
<p>
   Channeling her anger
<p>
   How does she do it? How does Abiola write a thesis about oil and
politics, keep up with her friends, watch over her younger siblings
and speak to community groups  &MD;  while grieving for her mother and
worrying about her father? That's the question Vail and others who
know Abiola have asked themselves.
<p>
   ``Even though I've known her for four years, I don't know her,''
Vail says. Romney Resney, Abiola's adviser during her freshman
year, puts it this way: ``Sure, she had frustrations about what was
going on in Nigeria and frustrations about being here, where people
don't have a clue about Nigeria. It would be easy to become angry
or shut down or withdraw. Instead, she has channeled it into trying
to raise awareness of what's going on.''
<p>
   Last November, on the one-year anniversary of the execution of
Saro-Wiwa, Abiola led a service for her mother in Memorial Chapel
in Harvard Yard. Hundreds of friends and Nigerian exiles showed up.
Abiola gave a stirring speech about her memories of her mother and
her hopes for Nigeria.
<p>
   Resney, who had studied leadership at the Kennedy School of
Government, watched Abiola in awe. ``I thought, my God, she has
everything that her father has, plus the poise of her mother. It
was just amazing.''
<p>
   Abiola says she draws strength from her large family. But
sometimes, she says, she feels pulled between two worlds, between
the traditions of West Africa and the freedom of the West.
<p>
   She no longer assumes she'll marry a family friend, or even a
Nigerian. Marriage isn't in her immediate plans, anyway. There's
work to be done and she has to watch over her siblings (the two
youngest brothers live with her older brother in Virginia, and the
other brothers and sisters are studying in several states).
<p>
   Would she let her husband have several wives?
<p>
   ``I think that it's fine for my husband to have several wives so
long as he allows me to have several husbands,'' she quips. Then
she explains that polygamy dates back to the days when people lived
in the countryside of Nigeria. With urbanization, the practice is
dying out.
<p>
   Several relatives have warned Abiola that she is courting
trouble by being so outspoken. They advise her to be more demure.
<p>
   ``I tell them, `I'm going to think about that, and I'm going to
let you know,''' she says. ``Of course, I've already made up my
mind.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1408EST
</TRAILER>
