<STORYID cat=k pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8952 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0681 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; OAKLAND STADIUM WOES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MARTIN F. NOLAN &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   OAKLAND, Calif. -- When Super Bowl fever sweeps a city, the
party is grand, but the hangover can be massive.
<p>
   In 1995, this city embraced its prodigal pro football team,
which had abandoned Oakland for the glitzier pastures of Los
Angeles. Al Davis, guiding genius and chief travel agent of the
Oakland Raiders, has struck gold twice here. After 13 seasons in
LA, he returned to open arms and open wallets.
<p>
   Could they expand the stadium, build luxury boxes and spiff up
the infrastructure without taxpayer funds? ``No problem!'' chorused
the politicians of Oakland and Alameda County. Fans will grab the
tab.
<p>
   Every Raiders rooter would eagerly purchase a ``Personal Seat
License,'' costing between $250 and $4,000 for a 10-year lease on a
stadium seat. Politicians pictured a waiting list longer than the
Bay Bridge.
<p>
   At first, PSLs sold quickly, but sales soon became as sluggish
as the Raider offense stalled at 35,000 in a 62,500-seat stadium.
In Oakland, PSL came to mean Pretty Serious Losses.
<p>
   Last week, while its school board was admitting Oakland's
failure to teach its students English, the departing city manager
forecast a budget deficit of $16 million. By grim coincidence, the
city's tab for the PSL, including cost overruns on rebuilding
Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum, is $15 million so far.
<p>
   ``Could we put the $15 million into the budget?'' asked the
chairman of the City Council's budget committee. ``Yes, but that
wouldn't solve the Coliseum problem.''
<p>
   A key ingredient in hangovers is denial. While the city holds
the bag, the city's establishment suffers from amnesia. In the
summer of 1995, The Oakland Tribune called itself ``The Official
Newspaper of Oakland Raiders Fans.'' The slogan was either printed
in disappearing ink or spiked because of the paper's other slogan,
``Friend of the People It Serves.'' Today, the Tribune's most
visible link with the Raiders is not boosterism but a flood of
classified ads from fans trying to dump their ducats, average price
$51.
<p>
   Davis himself is a sloganeer, coining ``Commitment to
Excellence'' and ``Just Win, Baby,'' phrases that once intimidated
opponents. But it has been XIV Super Sundays since the Raiders
reached the big bowl. In today's NFL, free agency helps Carolina
and Jacksonville prevail over silver-and-black tradition. The
Raiders scare only lonely PSL tailgaters.
<p>
   In a downward spiral, a so-so team means few sellouts, which
means no televised home games, an eroding fan base and well-soaked
taxpayers. Corporate sponsorship is skimpy. Bay Area businesses
neither fill the skyboxes nor pony up to baptize the place Clorox
Coliseum or Levi Strauss Stadium.
<p>
   Davis heeded his own slogans before making the deal, skimming
excellent returns off the top: $22 million from PSL sales and $32
million from city and county bonds. When the city and county
started to choke on the shortfall, Davis was serene. ``They asked
me to come back and I did,'' he said. ``I didn't do anything
wrong.''
<p>
   In Boston, there's nothing wrong with a stadium that won't harm
vital neighborhoods, damage the quality of life or drain valuable
resources. In Boston, the most precious of these is land. Alameda
County is 738 square miles; Boston's Suffolk County is 59 square
miles. The stadium here is five miles from downtown, analogous in
Boston to the old state hospital grounds in Mattapan, OK for most
fans but dicey for the skybox crowd.
<p>
   A stadium launched by Super Bowl fever can mean empty seats and
full remorse, as Gail Steele, head of Alameda County's Board of
Supervisors, has admitted:
<p>
   ``There is no question we overestimated the potential for
success of this whole agreement.... We were listening to the fans
who wanted the Raiders back in town. We were listening to the
marketing consultants who told us it would be an easy sellout.
Maybe we made a big mistake.''
<p>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1410EST
</TRAILER>
