<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOOTBALL'S GRADUATION GAP &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DERRICK Z. JACKSON &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   My recent column on the dismal graduation rates of
African-American players on many college football teams brought
requests for a detailed comparison from readers, including those
who were shocked that Florida and Ohio State, the first- and
second-ranked teams in the country, were so bad.
<p>
   The following lists are from the National Collegiate Athletic
Association Division 1 graduation rates report for 1996. The rates
cover athletes who received some form of athletic aid who entered
school during the 1986-87, 1987-88, 1988-89 and 1989-90 school
years, giving the schools at least six years to graduate them and
four straight classes by which to judge a school's consistency.
<p>
   One lawyer from Florida said that I singled out Florida coach
Steve Spurrier unfairly as a prime academic offender. Of the 36
teams that participated in the bowls, Florida was in the bottom 10
of overall team graduations and African-American graduations. It
was in the top 10 for graduation gaps between African-American and
white players and between African-American players and the general
student body.
<p>
   Spurrier became coach in 1990. The reader said Spurrier could
not be held responsible for Florida's rates because they cover only
athletes recruited before he was hired.
<p>
   Because of the way the NCAA compiles reports, it will take until
2000 before there are rates for which Spurrier is completely
responsible. But he remains at least mathematically 75 percent
responsible for the players he had for three of their possible four
years of eligibility (1989-90 entering class), 50 percent
responsible for those he had for two seasons and 25 percent
responsible for those he knew only in their final year of
eligibility.
<p>
   That takes us back to the 1987-88 season, which covers most of
the current report and makes Spurrier significantly responsible for
the graduation of his players.
<p>
   If graduation rates under Spurrier, who makes $1.1 million a
year in salary, shoot up, fine. But there are few signs that the
worst schools, including Florida, put books before the weight room.
<p>
   The lists (Army and Navy do not give athletic scholarships but
are included in some of the lists based on their overall graduation
rates):
<p>
   The Associated Press final Top 25 team rankings:
<p>
   1. Florida
<p>
