<STORYID cat=l pri=r sel=ttj-z> A8955 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LESS-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0512 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CAR-LESS-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOOTLOOSE AND FANCY FREE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By AL McKEE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SAN FRANCISCO  &MD;  My friend Dennis is about to give up the car he
has driven for 21 years, a 1967 Volvo. Although he has a new
Oldsmobile lined up to take its place, he is having some difficulty
saying goodbye to his shapely first love  &MD;  shapely, anyway, in
Dennis' eyes.
<p>
   Where I see a sluggish engine, worn upholstery, a body like a
Husqvarna sewing machine, Dennis sees  &MD;  what? Twenty-one years of
Swedish massage?
<p>
   I find this emotional attachment to a vehicle mystifying, but
then, I have never owned a car. Indeed, at age 44, I have never had
a driver's license. Nor has my wife.
<p>
   We have spent our lives on foot  &MD;  or on buses, in taxis, in the
back seat of other people's cars.
<p>
   Thus have we bypassed whole segments of the American experience:
the family drive, the traffic jam, the used car lot, the
treasure-filled garage. Our friends think us deprived, but since
these things have never been a part of our lives, we are like those
people born deaf who don't miss music.
<p>
   I'll admit not having a car probably impeded my romantic
development. It's true, I didn't see a lot of action in that regard
until I left my small hometown and began living in big cities where
one's sexual identity was not so closely linked to the size of
one's transportation.
<p>
   (I did date a girl in high school for awhile. We walked most
places and occasionally she drove, a situation so perverse in its
social dynamics  &MD;  at that time, in that place  &MD;  that it doomed our
relationship. She couldn't bear the strain of automotive role
reversal. It was as if I had asked to borrow her underwear.)
<p>
   Once I got out of Missouri, however, my luck improved.
Fortunately, I was not attracted to girls who salivated over chrome
and steel, but to oddballs like myself who enjoyed, for example,
striking out on foot in a lashing rain. I remember the thrill of
kinship when, on my first date with the oddball I would marry, I
suggested we grab a taxi and she replied, ``Why don't we walk?''
<p>
   No doubt a practical case may be made for not owning a car.
Certainly, we have saved a fortune on monthly payments, insurance,
gas and oil, parking, mechanic's fees, traffic tickets, bridge
tolls and those little dogs with bobbing heads.
<p>
   On the other hand, we have put a lot of money into shoes. You
can argue it from a health standpoint, from an environmental
standpoint and from the standpoint of resistance to America's
corporate culture. But to be truthful, I am a walker not for any
enlightened motive, but because I missed out on the vehicular gene.
<p>
   I walk for the same reason gibbons traverse the treetops hand to
hand  &MD;  it's the way I have always gotten around. Which is why, in
the years ahead, I expect I'll continue down this road less
traveled  &MD;  in my case, not a road at all, but a footpath.
<p>
    &UR; ----- &LR; Examiner contributor Al McKee, a free-lance writer in
San Francisco, works in a university book store. &LR; 
</TEXT>
