<SLUG> BC-HOCKEY-FAMILY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1515 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HOCKEY-FAMILY-ART-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WITH FIVE CHILDREN PLAYING, THE COURTNEYS LIVE LIFE ON THE RINK &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DICK LEHR &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   BELMONT, Mass. Right now many of you might be nursing a second
cup of coffee or tea, huddled cozily at your kitchen table, the
newspaper spread out before you. But let this serve as a reminder
that the youth hockey world, unlike any other in youth sports, is
already rockin' and rollin', and for one particular suburban family
that means five pairs of arms and legs intersecting, a crazy
patchwork of hockey mania moving frenetically from beds to the
breakfast table to that gangly climb into hockey pants and other
paraphernalia hanging down there in the basement.
<p>
   It's the Courtney Five  &MD;  count 'em.
<p>
   Five skaters in search of a rink.
<p>
     ``I've got healthy lungs,'' jokes Dotty Courtney, mother of
this brood, the time-keeper and cheerleader who keeps the three
girls and two boys moving from their sleep time to their ice time,
an undertaking that in the next 48 hours will take all or parts of
this family's hockey enterprise to six different rinks in greater
Boston.
<p>
   The lifestyle of the stick and skate crowd is a maddening load
of expenses, equipment, logistics and cold weather that makes the
youth baseball and soccer scene seem lightweight.
<p>
   In fact, by the close of the weekend, Hockey Five-O will log
about 11 hours of ice time, a figure that does not include
commuting and dressing time. It opens this morning with
recreational hockey for the three girls at the Belmont rink, while
9-year-old Ricky peels off to West Roxbury for a Mite's game at
7:30 a.m., followed by practice at 12:30 in Concord for 14-year-old
Sarah, a 2:30 p.m. game in Acton for 11-year-old Kathryn and
15-year-old Elizabeth, a second practice for Sarah in Concord at
6:20 p.m. and then 12-year-old Mikey's Pee Wee game at 7:30 p.m. at
Cleveland Circle. (Piano lessons for the girls somehow occur during
mid-afternoon.) Tomorrow opens with recreational hockey in town, a
game at 1:50 p.m in Watertown for Kathryn and Elizabeth and then,
in the weekend's finale, Sarah's bantam game in Concord at 2:50
p.m.
<p>
   Whew. There are hockey families, and then there are hockey
families. ``It keeps the kids busy,'' deadpans ``Big Mike,'' their
dad, a dentist, standing now in the kitchen with ``Little Mike''
dressing up for an afternoon game, and the other kids attired in
all or part of their own hockey gear. ``It can get a little bit
difficult, all the time involved.''
<p>
   Elizabeth makes a face. These hockey mornings are madcap, kids
grabbing bagels or granola bars on the run. ``We haven't had
breakfast together for like three years,'' she smiles.
<p>
   Hockey runs in the family. The kids' grandfather, Tom Courtney,
who grew up in Cambridge, played for that city's high school team.
Their father played in Belmont, as did their uncle. (Their dad,
Mike Courtney, adds modestly, ``I wasn't very good; my older
brother, he was the one.'') Their four cousins also play, and one
of them  &MD;  yet another Mike in the family  &MD;  is the captain and a
high-scoring forward, nicknamed ``Sniper,'' on this year's high
school squad.
<p>
   ``I used to take the kids skating,'' explains Mike Courtney,
about how his own kids got started. They'd also go to see their
older cousins play in games, and, recalls Dotty Courtney, ``Grampa
would always say, Mikey, when are you going to start.
<p>
   ``I always got the feeling that it was kind of expected of the
boys in the family to play,'' says Dotty. Mikey, now 12, was indeed
the one who broke the ice, joining Belmont Rangers Hockey as a
kindergartner eight years ago. But he was soon followed by sister
Sarah, and then, says their mother, ``One by one they all became
interested and joined a team.''
<p>
   Elizabeth, the oldest, was the last, and she decided to play  &MD; 
gulp  &MD;  goalie. Mentioning that position causes Dotty Courtney to
pause. In baseball or soccer, you outfit the kids in cleats, a bat,
a glove and a ball, then toss in between $30 and $50 in
registration fees. Hockey means rink time, which has to be paid
for, and the programs need to charge big money to cover that. This
season alone the Courtneys have paid out about $2,500 in hockey
fees. It's an investment that does not include the cost of
equipment  &MD;  $200 for a good pair of skates, the shoulder pads, the
pants, the shinguards and elbow pads. The priciest position is
goalie, and to equip Elizabeth this year in new netminder gear cost
about $1,200  &MD;  gulp.
<p>
   ``I don't want to even think about it,'' says Dotty. There is no
shortage of ideas for birthday and holiday presents, with helmets
and hockey gloves under this year's Christmas tree.
<p>
   The kids belong to a town program that has about 200 kids
skating for it, from mites to midgets (kindergarteners to
teen-agers), and the Belmont squads play other teams in either the
Greater Boston League or the Yankee Conference League, involving
about 3,800 skaters in all. The family's ties to hockey encompass
Mike Courtney's working the bench as assistant coach on one of the
kids' team, and Dotty Courtney's serving on the boards of both
Belmont Ranger Hockey and The Friends of Belmont Hockey, which
supports the high school teams.
<p>
   The season? ``It never ends, actually,'' says Dotty, describing
a hockey life that starts in September and runs into March and
includes a couple weeks toward the end of the summer for hockey
camp, which all the kids attend.
<p>
   ``This is our life,'' she jokes, pulling down a poster-sized
calendar hanging on the door from the kitchen to the cellar, each
day noting one hockey commitment or another. ``My famous saying is,
if it's not on the calendar then it doesn't exist.
<p>
   During the winter, a typical week involves, for each kid-player,
at least two practices and one or two games, or a family total of
about 30 hours of ice time. But there's actually even more.
Elizabeth, as goalie for the girls varsity team, practices daily
and also logs another six hours as one of the on-ice guards at the
town rink during the public skating sessions.
<p>
   The holidays are another matter, a time of tournaments and extra
practices, so that during late December Ricky Courtney's team was
playing three consecutive days in the Belmont Hockey Classic, with
Ricky, little number 7, scooting around the ice, his name
emblazoned on the back of his Mite's jersey, looking to pass the
puck to teammates like Drew Davidson, who scored late in the game
on a breakaway, and Zach Croy, another of the team's quick-skating
forwards. ``We were scared at the beginning of the game,'' Ricky
recalled after his team had won the opening contest, ``because our
goalie wasn't there. But he showed up at the last minute and we
were OK.''
<p>
   Meanwhile, older brother Mikey skated on the right wing during
his Pee Wee team's quest in an eight-team holiday tournament,
culminating in a championship game on New Year's Day. The family
zigs and zags around the region, piling into their shiny new white
Suburban, five kids and five hockey bags.
<p>
   How do they make ends meet, timewise?
<p>
   ``The list,'' says Dotty. Then with added emphasis, she repeats,
``The list!'' Each Friday, she explains, she studies the upcoming
jam of weekend hockey, makes a list of all the games and practices,
and then divides the duty with her husband: ``We write it all down
and split it in half.''
<p>
   Even with all the running around, she notes importantly, ``We
both make most of the games.''
<p>
   To be sure, the hockey crowd can have its rough edges  &MD;  the
bellowing from hyperactive parents and fans who stalk the sidelines
of any kid sport, but especially in hockey. (In fact, a Belmont
high school hockey contest against visiting Danvers, played one
night following one of Ricky Courtney's games, was marred by a
brawl that required a Belmont police response.)
<p>
   Then there are the parents of the '90s who complain about the
scheduling demands of any of the youth sports, never mind hockey
and never mind having five kids who play. But the Courtneys are
clearly devoted, all aboard for Ricky's game, the girls roaming the
rink and Mikey hanging out with his friends, parents Mike and Dotty
standing up in the bleachers, dressed carefully for the occasion in
their insulated boots, gloves, sweaters and heavy coats, because
they know  &MD;  oh, do they know  &MD;  that Belmont's is one of the coldest
ice rinks around.
<p>
   ``It's not like I think they'll ever play professional,'' says
Mike. ``They have fun.'' And of course there's plenty more to come,
as Dotty flips ahead through the calendar for the winter months,
already marked up with times and places for games and tournaments
that will take the family to the Cape and beyond, including Sarah's
team trip to Montreal at Easter.
<p>
   ``We'll make it a family event,'' says Dotty, adding the
obvious: ``The only traveling or vacation we get is hockey.''
</TEXT>
