<DOCID> nyt970122.0216 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8958 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1130 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ALLEGRA LIKE A BREATH OF FRESH AIR FOR SEPRACOR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Sepracor Inc. stockholders are breathing easy these days.
<p>
   Shares of the Marlborough, Mass. drug company are up 34 percent
in a little over a week and reached an all-time high of 22 3/4
Tuesday. They have been soaring since federal regulators made news
with a rare decision to push the long-established antihistamine
Seldane used by allergy sufferers and others off the market.
<p>
   The U.S. Food and Drug administration decision Jan. 14
effectively turned that shelf space over to Sepracor's Allegra, a
near-twin drug unincumbered by Seldane's rare but potentially
lethal side effects. Challenges to the decision are likely to only
delay Seldane's departure.
<p>
   It is unclear whether Sepracor will actually make more money
from its drug thanks to the FDA decision, and no financial benefit
at all will fall to its bottom line before 1999. But regulators
have given another important boost to Sepracor's core strategy that
will likely benefit the company's crowded pipeline of other drugs.
<p>
   Sepracor is heading into the home stretch in the development of
an improved version of Albuterol, a drug commonly used to treat
asthma patients, who spend $1.4 billion on the medication each
year. And another antihistamine that would replace a near-twin
hampered with serious side effects is on the way and could be much
more lucrative for Sepracor. In all, 14 drugs that improve on
existing products are in the works.
<p>
   ``Most people develop drugs based on a new chemical entity,''
said Sepracor president Timothy Barberich. ``Our approach is to
view the existing portfolio of approved products as Sepracor's
pipeline.''
<p>
   Advances in chemistry and manufacturing technology are pushing
many drugs, new and old, toward a higher level of safety and
effectiveness. Sepracor has spent most of the 1990s developing
better versions of existing drugs and has lost more than $135
million along the way. The company is still three years away from
any profit by most accounts, but earnings could quickly jump to
more than $4 per share on a fully taxed basis by 2001, according to
Barbara Dau Hoffman of Vector Securities and other analysts.
<p>
   ``My feeling is that this is the way the world is going and
they're out front,'' said mutual fund manager Warren Isabelle of
Pioneer Group, the company's second-largest stockholder with about
1.2 million shares. ``The fact that you've seen the FDA take this
action sets a precedent.''
<p>
   Sepracor has typically targeted popular drugs whose 17-year
patent protections were nearing expiration. The original
manufacturer was thought to be a willing partner for marketing the
improved drug, which would start the patent clock anew and diminish
impending competition from inexpensive generics.
<p>
   ``In addition to this (Sepracor drug line) becoming a good
defensive strategy, it may become a regulatory necessity'' as a
result of the FDA's removal of Seldane, said Hoffman.
<p>
   This is not the first time the market has taken a shine to
Sepracor. Its shares soared from 4 to nearly 22 in about nine
months in 1995 thanks to the same kind of promise. But a decline in
biotech stock prices, a secondary stock offering and a round of
debt financing, plus a six-month delay in an important clinical
trial, knocked the stock's peak price in half by last summer.
<p>
   Now, analysts note, Sepracor has one product on the market,
another months away from a new drug application and a third close
behind. Just as important, the FDA seems to have gone out of its
way to give Sepracor a boost. But they warn the stock is still
subject to the market's prevailing opinion of developing companies
and could get hammered if the investment mood changes.
<p>
   This is the guts of Sepracor's chemistry: most man-made
compounds consists of two mirror-image molecules, often referred to
the right- and left-hand molecules. Sometimes, the benefits of a
compound are contained in one ``hand,'' and side effects are in the
other. Only within the last few years, chemists have been able to
split the compound and produce the desired half in industrial
quantities.
<p>
   Sepracor is not alone in its ability to do the chemistry, but it
has a huge lead and key patents on over 40 drugs. Many of the
improved drugs are believed to reduce or eliminate side effects.
Some just improve the effectiveness of the existing drug. Others
create new uses, like Sepracor's split version of the well-known
anti-depressant Prozac that is being developed for its apparent
benefit in warding off migraine headaches.
<p>
   Though Allegra is Sepracor's first drug to market, the company's
other antihistamine could become the superior cash cow.
<p>
   Sepracor, then in need of funding, negotiated away a good chunk
of its potential Allegra royalties years ago to manufacturer
Hoechst Marion Russell, which also owns the to-be-shelved Seldane.
Those royalties, at best 8 percent, will probably not generate more
than $40 million annually for Sepracor in years ahead.
<p>
   A near-twin for the antihistamine Hismanal, another drug with
potentially dire side effects, is under development by Separacor
and possibly is within three years of reaching the market. The
improved version of Hisminal could prove superior to its
competitors and provide Sepracor a much bigger slice of the sales
pie.
<p>
   Improved Albuterol, the drug for asthma patients, is in the
midst of final Phase III clinical trials, and Sepracor is expected
to apply for FDA approval later this year.
<p>
   The side effects of existing Albuterol products are not nearly
as clear cut as the antihistamines targeted by Sepracor. Key to its
strategy is a hoped-for indication from the FDA that Sepracor's
asthma drug is a preferred treatment for children, an advantage
none of its competitors would enjoy.
<p>
   Revenues from the sale of improved Albuterol are forecast by
analysts to start trickling in by 1998 and ramp up to nearly $150
million within two years. Sales of the Hismanal antihistamine
alternative are targeted to start in the year 2000.
<p>
   Meanwhile, Sepracor is still burning through $45 million a year
in development expenses. Barberich insists that is no problem,
pointing to Sepracor's $100 million in cash and another $100
million in securities.
<p>
   Investors who remember Sepracor's slump last year don't want to
see another stock offering to raise cash and dilute the value of
their stock. ``We would not be terribly thrilled,'' said Pioneer's
Isabelle. ``There really is no compelling reason to go to the well
right now.''
<p>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
