<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A8960 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EARNS-NORTHERN-STATE- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0471 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-NORTHERN-STATE-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NORTHERN STATES POWER 4TH-QUARTER NET RISES 35% (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Karen Padley &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
(Rewrites. Adds annual earnings. Updates stock price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Minneapolis, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Northern States Power Co.
said fourth-quarter profit rose 35 percent because of lower costs,
higher earnings from its non-regulated businesses and
colder-than-usual weather.
<p>
   Net income at the Minneapolis-based utility increased to $79.7
million, or $1.11 a share, from $59 million, or 82 cents, in the
year-earlier period. Per-share amounts reflect the payment of
preferred stock dividends.
<p>
   Revenue increased 8.7 percent to $710 million from $652.8
million, said Northern States, which provides natural gas and
electricity to customers in Minnesota, North and South Dakota,
Wisconsin and Michigan.
<p>
   While per-share results beat the 98-cent average estimate of six
analysts surveyed by IBES International, Northern States shares
fell 1/2 to 47 1/4 in early afternoon trading. Dain Bosworth
analyst David Thickens said the decline could be due to yesterday's
decision by the Wisconsin Public Service Commission to delay a vote
on the merger of Northern States and Wisconsin Energy Corp.
<p>
   The company said it reduced costs from the 1995 quarter, when it
converted two plants from intermediate to peak-load operation. It
also didn't have any major power plant outages due to maintenance
during the most-recent quarter.
<p>
   Higher usage by customers because of cold weather added 8 cents
a share to its fourth-quarter earnings, compared with 4 cents in
the year-earlier period, the company said.
<p>
   As a result, earnings at its regulated utility business
accounted for $1.01 of its per-share earnings, up from 81 cents a
year ago.
<p>
   Northern States Power said its non-regulated businesses, which
had start-up costs in the year-earlier period, improved. Such units
accounted for 10 cents of per-share earnings, up from 1 cent.
<p>
   The non-regulated businesses include the Schkopau power plant in
Germany, several power plants in Latin America and NRG Generating
(U.S.) Inc., the former O'Brien Environmental Energy Inc. which
Northern States helped bring out of bankruptcy reorganization.
<p>
   For the year, Northern States said net income rose 5.1 percent
to $274.5 million, or $3.82 a share, from year-earlier profit from
operations of $261.1 million, or $3.69.
<p>
   After a non-recurring gain of $14.7 million, or 22 cents, from
buying out a purchased power contract, 1995 net income was $275.8
million, or $3.91 a share.
<p>
   Revenue rose 3.3 percent to $2.65 billion from $2.57 billion.
<p>
   Northern States Power said weather-related usage added 16 cents
a share to 1996 earnings, down from 20 cents the previous year.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1414EST
</TRAILER>
