<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0218 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=d pri=u sel=tdt-z> A8961 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0829 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW ORLEANS OFFERS SUPER RESTAURANTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ALISON ARNETT &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Food and New Orleans are a twin set. No matter why one is
traveling to the Crescent City, restaurant dining has to be part of
the quest.
<p>
   And what restaurants! New Orleans is one of the biggest tourist
and convention cities in the country, so the Super Bowl influx is
just another blip on the calendar. While January and February may
be the doldrums for restaurants in the rest of the country, New
Orleans will slide from the Sugar Bowl crowds to the Super Bowl
right into Madri Gras with several big conventions thrown in for
good measure. (itals)Laissez les bons temps rouler!(unitals)
<p>
   Emeril Lagasse, who owns Emeril's and NOLA, two of the most
popular restaurants in the city, is a native of Fall River, Mass.,
so this Super Bowl is something special. ``I'm so excited,''
Lagasse says. ``And my dad, who came down here to live a couple of
years ago and works with me in the restaurant, is ecstatic. He's
been a Patriots fan since forever.''
<p>
   Emeril's is ``going to do a first-time-ever Sunday brunch, a
four-course prix fixe menu.''
<p>
   Lagasse, a season ticket-holder for the Saints, didn't get
tickets in the team's lottery but says he's trying to buy a few.
``The owner of the Patriots is coming in next week,'' he says.
<p>
   New Orleans is the best place in the country for a Super Bowl,
Lagasse says. Everything  &MD;  great restaurants, hotels, the French
Quarter shops  &MD;  is within walking distance of the Superdome.
Besides, the city has a great ``party feeling.''
<p>
   Susan Spicer, chef-owner of Bayona in the French Quarter, says
the hoopla surrounding this Super Bowl is bigger than she remembers
from the last time New Orleans was host, in 1990.
<p>
   Bayona, another popular and highly acclaimed restaurant, is
already almost booked around Super Bowl time, but Spicer suggests
calling her restaurant or any of the other popular restaurants to
check. Since many business groups book reservations for the same
time in several places and travelers to the city sometimes find
that their plans change, no-shows are common. Often a table will
open up at the last minute, she says.
<p>
   The Gumbo Shop on St. Peter Street in the Quarter serves about
1,000 bowls of traditional gumbo a week, but Richard Taylor,
president of Roberts' Gumbo Shop Inc., figures the number will soar
beginning the Thursday before the game and continuing through Super
Bowl Sunday. The small restaurant, known for its beautiful
historical wall mural and its reasonable prices, serves seafood
gumbo, chicken and andouille sausage gumbo and smoked duck and
oyster gumbo as well as other soups and Creole and Cajun dishes.
The line to get in for lunch or dinner often stretches through the
courtyard.
<p>
    &UR; Emeril's  &LR; (800 Tchoupitoulas St., 504-528-9393),  &UR; NOLA  &LR; (534
St. Louis St., 504-522-6652) and  &UR; Bayona  &LR; (430 Dauphine St.,
504-525-4455) are in the vanguard, along with spots featuring the
new New Orleans cuisine, such as  &UR; Mike's on the Avenue  &LR; (628 St.
Charles Ave., 504-523-1709). But there's so much more to the fabric
of New Orleans food life. One heartening note is that the city is a
lively restaurant culture and the locals eat out a lot, not just at
the new places, but the classics like  &UR; Brennan's  &LR; and  &UR; Arnaud  &LR; in
the French Quarter.
<p>
   Here are a few suggestions from Lagasse, Spicer and others:
<p>
    &UR; Galatoire's &LR; , 209 Bourbon St., 504-525-2021. You don't need,
in fact you can't get, a reservation; just stand in line on Bourbon
Street. Once inside, though, you can easily imagine you've fallen
back into the last century as you taste the benchmark for such
classic Creole dishes as crabmeat etouffe.
<p>
    &UR; Camellia Grill &LR; , 626 S. Carrollton Ave., 504-866-9573.
Everyone eats breakfast at the counter  &MD;  that's all the seating
there is. Ceiling fans revolve slowly, throwing lazy shadows on
black-and-white tile floors as mountains of pecan waffles and huge
cheese omelets are created rapid-fire.
<p>
    &UR; Peristyle &LR; , 1041 Dumaine St., 504-593-9535. Recommended by both
Spicer and Lagasse, this French Quarter restaurant is known for new
twists on French and Louisiana dishes.
<p>
    &UR; Acme Oyster House &LR; , 724 Iberville St., 504-522-5973. There
are several oyster houses in the Quarter, but this one, plain and
reasonable, is the most atmospheric, many think.
<p>
    &UR; Brigtsen's &LR; , 723 Dante St., 504-861-7610. Another favorite of
many, this restaurant in the Carrollton section features Frank
Brigtsen's Cajun fantasies.
<p>
    &UR; Uglesich &LR; , 1238 Baronne St., 504-523-8571. Great oyster loaves,
soft-shell crabs and po-boys are strong draws to this modest lunch
spot.
<p>
    &UR; Taqueria Corona &LR; , 5932 Magazine St., 504-897-3974. This funky
Mexican cafe is a wonderful respite when Cajun and Creole start to
pale. As Spicer, in the middle of Super Bowl preparations, says,
``Boy, would I love a fish taco right now.''
