<SLUG> BC-FBN-SWITCHED-SIDES-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0387 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-SWITCHED-SIDES-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EX-PACKER, EX-PATRIOT FACING FORMER TEAMS SUPER BOWL SUNDAY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Scott Soshnick &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New Orleans, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Two players in the Super
Bowl know about life on the other side.
<p>
   Mike Bartrum and Jeff Dellenbach played for both the Green Bay
Packers and the New England Patriots this season, and will be on
opposite sidelines on Sunday.
<p>
   Bartrum, a tight end and long snapper, began the year with
Packers, and was traded to the Patriots after he tore ligaments in
his ankle during the preseason. Dellenbach started 1996 with the
Patriots, and was cut after he struggled with his short-snapping
duties in the first two games of the year.
<p>
   While both are happy for a chance to win the Super Bowl, neither
thought it would happen like this.
<p>
   ``It's very ironic,'' said Bartrum, who signed a two-year
contract with the Packers in March of last year after playing for
them in 1995. ``I thought there was a place for me in Green Bay.
<p>
   The Packers thought otherwise after Bartrum's injury, which
would have kept him out of action for at least three weeks. So on
Aug. 25 he was sent to New England, who because of Dellenbach's
struggles needed a snapper.
<p>
   ``All of a sudden I'm in New England,'' Bartrum said. ``Coach
Parcells gave me a chance.''
<p>
   At the time, the 6-foot-5, 245-pound Bartrum was leaving a
leading Super Bowl contender and joining a team that likely would
have been happy just to make the playoffs.
<p>
   ``It's going to be fun playing against Green Bay,'' said
Bartrum, who harbors no ill will towards the Packers. ``I know it's
a business, but I really want to prove to them they made a mistake
by trading me.''
<p>
   The same is true for Dellenbach, whose signing with the Packers
was a homecoming. A native of Wausau, Wisconsin, and a University
of Wisconsin product, the 6-foot-6, 300-pounder said he couldn't be
happier after spending 10 seasons with the Miami Dolphins.
<p>
   The odd scenario sets up a spy vs. spy situation, where each
player might provide his current team with information about the
opposition.
<p>
   While Bartrum said he would love to give the coaches an edge in
their preparation, he doesn't think he'd be much help. ``I don't
remember a lot,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
