<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BOWL-CHOICES-2TA </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1186 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FOOD-BOWL-CHOICES-2 TAKES-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SUPER BOWL ROOTERS, PUT YOUR MOUTH WHERE YOUR MONEY IS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ALISON ARNETT AND SHERYL JULIAN &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   If football fans were foodies, they'd throw the chips away, pull
that pot of chili right off the stove, put the hot dogs back in the
refrigerator. Everything that isn't regionally relevant to an
afternoon when the home team is in the Super Bowl would be
banished.
<p>
   This is a prideful moment here in New England Patriots country
and it calls for culinary patriotism. Of course, team
identification is thicker than geography, so even in the Pats'
heartland, there will be those cheering for the other side. Pick
your team and root with your fork.
<p>
   Barbara Haber of Lexington, Mass. stoutly declares her
loyalties: ``Packers  &MD;  and it goes way back.'' And according to the
Madison, Wis., native, football automatically means ``brats,''
short for bratwurst and pronounced with a Wisconsin ``a'' that's a
dead regional giveaway.
<p>
   ``Bratwurst with cold or warm potato salad,'' says Maison Robert
restaurateur Ann Robert, raised in Lafayette County in the
southwestern end of Wisconsin. ``And cheese. Everyone knows a
factory where the owner has put away a Cheddar for five years.''
<p>
   ``Bratwurst and beer,'' echoes Roger Bieri, who lives in
Swampscott, Mass. and works at the New England Life Insurance Co.
Bieri's father comes from the Door Peninsula, where Green Bay is
located. Cheese, says Bieri, is the universal food, and
Wisconsinites are proud to be called ``cheeseheads.''
<p>
   Sounds fairly straightforward. Sounds as if everyone from Lake
Superior to Milwaukee will be watching the Super Bowl and eating
cheese, bratwurst and potato salad, washed down with beer.
<p>
   Unless of course you happen to live near Racine and you've put
in an order at Danny's Meats and Catering, which is offering a
``Packer pig roast'' for 15 to 20 people. (This makes sense; the
name ``Packers'' comes from the meatpacking house in Green Bay that
originally sponsored the team.)
<p>
   We're not sure how much people eat in Racine, but we'd bet it's
quite a lot. Danny's Packer pig roast consists of a hindquarter of
smoked pig (about 18 pounds), 5 pounds of potato salad, 5 pounds of
pasta salad, 5 pounds of baked beans, rolls and sauces. Mike Doepke
of Danny's, reached by phone, was happy to explain the special,
which costs $80 and is offered every Sunday the Packers are
playing. He wanted to know why a reporter from The Boston Globe was
interested in Super Bowl Sunday.
<p>
   You can't expect those guys from Wisconsin, busy chowing down
hindquarters of pig, to keep track of details. Anyway, it's 12
degrees out there, and that doesn't count the wind chill factor.
They've got to eat brats and pig just to fortify themselves for
walking outside and starting the car.
<p>
   Where does that leave us? We can't look like culinary slouches.
We had hardy forebears. They managed to stick out that first rough
winter and pull enough fish from the sea to sustain themselves. We
should be doing what they did  &MD;  eating chowder. It was good enough
to feed them for a few centuries, it can certainly feed a few
hungry football fans.
<p>
   There's a third category of fans who'll be watching the Super
Bowl on Sunday  &MD;  the ones who made it down to New Orleans.
``They'll all gain about 10 pounds,'' says Anne Foley of Arlington,
raised in the Carrollton section of New Orleans and about to hop on
a plane and head back home with her husband, Michael. ``We love the
food,'' says Anne Foley. ``There's nothing like it anywhere else.''
<p>
   Foley's mother, Marie Clerc Higgins, was raised by a French
mother. Reached at her home in New Orleans, she was asked what
would be on her Super Bowl menu. She says that sometimes she makes
a ham and serves it with sweet potatoes. She likes jambalaya, too,
the rice and seafood dish. Gumbo, she says, ``is a nice warm soup
and it can be done ahead of time. I make okra and seafood gumbo. I
put sausage in with the seafood. After Christmas I make gumbo with
the turkey carcass.''
<p>
   Jambalaya is a typical home-style New Orleans dish, says John
Silberman, owner of Magnolias Southern Cuisine in Cambridge, Mass.,
the restaurant once known as the Cajun Yankee. Silberman, a New
Yorker, lived in New Orleans for seven years, and did several
restaurant stints, including one working for Paul Prudhomme at
K-Paul's Louisiana Kitchen.
<p>
   Silberman's jambalaya contains andouille sausage, chicken and
shrimp. Because he makes it to order at the restaurant, he cooks
the rice separately and tosses it with the meat and seafood just
before it goes into the dining room. That method prevents serving
gluey rice  &MD;  especially if half time is later than you planned.
<p>
   Jambalaya, says Silberman, is one of those dishes that New
Orleanians insist define a cook's ability. Because it's so good at
home, he says, locals usually don't dine out on it. ``Everybody's
mother does it better,'' he says.
<p>
   So even if your mother never made fish chowder, it's your
patriotic duty to fashion a pot for the family this weekend. For
those who can't bear to leave the chips behind, try sprinkling them
on top. After all, New Englanders are nothing if not innovative.
Remember the American Revolution? We started it.
<p>
NEW ENGLAND FISH CHOWDER &HT;    
<p>
   Adapted from ``Jasper White's Cooking from New England'' (Harper
&AMP; Row).
<p>
   3 1/2 pounds skinless, boneless fish
<p>
   1/4 pound meaty salt pork, cut into 1/4- to 1/2-inch dice
<p>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter
<p>
   2 large onions, cut into 3/4-inch dice
<p>
   3 bay leaves
<p>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme
<p>
   3 or 4 large Maine or other boiling potatoes, peeled and halved
lengthwise, then cut into 1/4-inch slices
<p>
   3 cups strong fish stock or 2 cups of bottled clam juice diluted
with 1 cup cold water
<p>
   2 cups heavy cream
<p>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
<p>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
<p>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh chervil (optional)
<p>
   8 tablespoons (1 stick) unsalted butter
<p>
   Leave the fish in as large pieces as possible, since it tends to
flake when the chowder is stirred.
<p>
   In a large flameproof casserole, render the salt pork until it
begins to turn crisp. Add the 4 tablespoons of butter with the
onions, bay leaves and thyme.
<p>
   Cook the mixture for 5 minutes or until the onions are soft but
not brown. Add potatoes and fish stock and bring the mixture to a
boil. Lower the heat and simmer the potatoes for 20 minutes or
until they are tender.
<p>
   Remove the bay leaves from the stock. Add the fish and heavy
cream. Bring the soup to a boil, lower the heat, and simmer for 8
to 10 minutes or until fish is cooked through and beginning to
flake. Add salt and pepper, stir in the parsley and chervil, if
using, and remove the soup from the heat.
<p>
   With a slotted spoon, transfer the chunks of fish, onions and
potatoes to soup plates. Ladle the piping broth into the bowls. Add
a dollop of butter to each soup plate and serve with crackers or
biscuits.
<p>
   Serves 8.
<p>
    &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC; 
