<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0696 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; LOVE GETS COMFY IN HOLLYWOOD; RODMAN CHANGES HIS GAME PLAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MATTHEW GILBERT &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Anyone who watched the Golden Globes on Sunday couldn't miss the
countless camera pans of an ever-smiling new actress with a polite
blond hairdo and rubbery Hollywood lips. Her name is Courtney Love,
and, just in time to survive the media's Death of Grunge
pronouncements, she is riding a massive career makeover, suddenly a
distant cousin to the reckless bigmouth known for her blood-red
lipstick and sloppy kinder-whore stylings. She's become Blanche to
her former Baby Jane.
<p>
   Is Love's transformation from addict-widow to movie star the
decade's greatest story of triumph? Or is her Hollywood conversion
a sellout of major proportions? The answer may depend on whether
you view the star of ``The People Vs. Larry Flynt'' from a rock
perspective, which would require Love always to have pock-marked
skin and at least one temper tantrum per interview, or a Hollywood
perspective, which would prefer the actress to be well-behaved and
recovered, or at least pretending to be. The cover story in
February's  &UR; Premiere &LR;  is a good snapshot of Love at the crossroads,
smitten with her newfound acceptance and yet very self-conscious
about it. ``I know a lot of it's fake,'' she says. ``But I don't
care! The welcome that I get from the grown-ups in the film
industry is so nice. ... I'm used to going to a mall and having a
kid with black lipstick scream at me, `I love you! I didn't kill
myself because of you!' Or `You suck!' But a grown-up in his 50s,
in a suit, being nice? I melt.''
<p>
   Love seems to take particular pleasure in hanging out with Young
Hollywood folks like Christian Slater and Winona Ryder and playing
that Young Hollywood game, Six Degrees of Kevin Bacon. ``I really
felt like a Brat Packer for about five seconds,'' she says. Mind
you, she still has some rock 'n' roll conscience, which guided her
choice of BMW: ``To get a new one would have been really un-punk
rock. I couldn't live with myself.''
<p>
   Meanwhile,  &UR; Rolling Stone  &LR; for Feb. 6 has a good piece on the
drug struggles of Scott Weiland, the Stone Temple Pilot who has
been in and out of rehab 13 times in three years, and their effect
on his fellow band members. Most of the interviewing was done
before Weiland's most recent relapse, in December, after six months
of court-ordered inpatient treatment. ``It got to the point,''
Weiland told writer David Fricke, ``where I didn't feel like I got
a good enough rush unless I had one hand on the needle and one hand
dialing 911.'' Maybe Courtney Love can introduce him to her movie
agent.
<p>
--------- &QC; 
<p>
 &UR; ufdots &LR; 
<p>
   February's  &UR; GQ &LR;  has a Dennis Rodman article that doesn't turn
the self-promoting basketball player into a cute, true-colors icon
of individuality. At a Taco Bell at a mall food court, not
surprisingly, Rodman is hounded by a fan. ``You can't go
anywhere,'' he complains. ``You're trying to do normal things  &MD;  sit
in this (expletive) mall without (expletive) people coming up who
want your (expletive) autograph.'' Anyway, Rodman has a plan. ``I
know people are getting sick and tired of Dennis Rodman. You have
yor time, and then you move on. I want people to look at me not
just as an athelete; I want them to think of me as a universal
person. ... I think my next forte will be doing movies.''
<p>
   February's  &UR; Esquire &LR;  has a fascinating piece about the writer
Jesse Hill Ford, who killed himself last June. In 1965, Ford
published ``The Liberation of Lord Byron Jones,'' a novel
condemning racial injustice that was celebrated by the critics. In
1970, shortly after the movie version was released, a paranoid Ford
fired his gun at a strange car that had entered his rural Tennessee
driveway, killing a 21-year-old black man named George Doaks Jr. He
was acquitted, but spent the rest of his life dealing with
hostility and accusations of racism, and he never bounced back,
both as a writer and as a man. The story, filled with irony and
tragedy, reads like an elaborate movie treatment. Someone should
write a screenplay.
</TEXT>
