<STORYID cat=i pri=u sel=ttj-z> A8966 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-ORIGIN-$ADV </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0959 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HOLOCAUST-ORIGIN-$ADV26-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For release Sunday Jan. 26)
 &UR; ON JANUARY 20, 1942, THE NAZIS SET IN MOTION `THE FINAL SOLUTION' &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BERNARD D. KAPLAN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Hearst Newspapers &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   PARIS  &MD;  Fifty-five years ago this month, high-ranking Nazi
officials met in the leafy Berlin suburb of Wannsee to plan the
mass murder of six million European Jews.
<p>
   The so-called Wannsee conference, convened Jan. 20, 1942, on
Adolf Hitler's orders, was conducted in secret and only the
scantiest records have survived.
<p>
   More than a half-century later, the circumstances surrounding
the decision to launch the systematic extermination of European
Jewry in German death camps remain a subject of heated controversy.
<p>
   At the heart of the dispute is whether such a mind-boggling
crime could have been carried out even by Hitler and his fanatical
lieutenants without at least the tacit support and knowledge of
ordinary Germans.
<p>
   Fresh fuel was recently added to the debate by Harvard historian
Daniel Goldhagen who in his best-seller, ``Hitler's Willing
Executioners'' accused the whole German nation of readily
collaborating in genocide.
<p>
   The Germans, according to Goldhagen, suffered few qualms because
they had been indoctrinated by more than a century of vicious
anti-Jewish propaganda which had turned them into the most
anti-semitic society in Europe.
<p>
   The American historian, whose own father was a refugee from
Nazism, has sparked a fierce polemic on both sides of the Atlantic,
although some experts have pointed out his thesis is hardly new.
<p>
   Not surprisingly, Goldhagen has raised hackles among modern-day
Germans, many of whom have attacked his book as an unfair attempt
to pin perpetual guilt on them and their descendants.
<p>
   Critics don't contest the central theme of his book: that
special police battalions which hunted down and slaughtered Jews
throughout Nazi-occupied Europe were recruited among non-Nazis and
were not compelled to perform their murderous task. Nor would they
have been punished if they had refused, as official documents of
the time make clear.
<p>
   The units, numbering more than 100,000, were made up of
volunteers and, as contemporary records show, were a cross-section
of the German population. Goldhagen contends that this demonstrates
it wasn't only the Nazis who favored exterminating the Jews.
<p>
   But several historians argue that he has over-stated his case.
<p>
   In particular, the critics insist he is on shaky ground in
claiming that pre-Hitlerite Germany was the most anti-semitic
country in Europe, preparing the way for what was to come.
<p>
   ``No one in the year 1900 or even in 1930 would have named
Germany as the country where Jews had the worst of it  &MD;  far from
it,'' said French historian Alain Sinsheimer.
<p>
   While Germany had its share of outspoken anti-semites such as
composer Richard Wagner and the English-born ``philosopher,''
Houston Stewart Chamberlain, he noted that the German Jews in the
19th and early 20th centuries enjoyed greater freedom and
prosperity than their co-religionists in most other societies.
<p>
   ``Hatred of the Jews was far more pronounced in Czarist Russia
and in France  &MD;  remember the case of Captain Alfred Dreyfus  &MD;  than
in Germany,'' Sinsheimer explained. ``At the turn-of-the-century
and even later, few observers would have rated the Germans as
notably anti-semitic.''
<p>
   That is why Goldhagen's claim that Hitler's ``final solution''  &MD; 
the decision taken at Wannsee to wipe out the Jewish people  &MD;  was a
product of the Germans' uniquely violent and bloodthirsty
anti-semitism is dubious, he said.
<p>
   Mass-killing techniques and extermination camps existed before
the Wannsee meeting. But it was there that the sinister SS chief,
Reinhard Heydrich, presented for the first time a detailed plan for
the Jews' destruction.
<p>
   At Wannsee, it was decided to use the deadly nerve gas Zyklon B
 &MD;  previously experimented with  &MD;  as the quickest way to kill the
intended victims.
<p>
   Some historians argue that the intense secrecy surrounding the
grisly three-day conference reflected Hitler's deep doubts over how
the German population would react. Allied investigators learned of
the conference when they debriefed Nazi officials right after the
war.
<p>
   No document linking Hitler personally to what transpired there
has ever come to light.
<p>
   In his recent book on the German resistance to the Nazis,
``Plotting to Kill Hitler,'' German historian Joachim Fest argues
that strong disapproval of the Nazis's treatment of the Jews was
widespread among the professional army officers, aristocrats and
officials who formed the core of the opposition movement.
<p>
   Fest observes that at the show trials of those linked to the
conspiracy to assassinate Hitler in July 1944, nearly
three-quarters of the defendants denounced anti-semitism, although
this only assured them a death sentence.
<p>
   ``Hitler almost certainly summoned the Wannsee conference
because he recognized time had begun to run out for him  &MD;  it was
just after the United States had entered the war and things had
started going badly for the Germans on the Russian front,'' British
historian Bernard Langton noted.
<p>
   In Langton's view, Hitler's obsessed anti-semitism had grown to
the point where he regarded extermination of the Jews as the single
all-consuming ideological object of his life and his paramount war
aim.
<p>
   ``Wannsee was where the Nazi high command organized their
killing machine on a continental scale and to be as efficient as
possible,'' he said. ``The objective was to make sure the maximum
number of Jews would die in whatever length of time the Nazi regime
had left. In this, Hitler was only too successful.''
</TEXT>
