<STORYID cat=k pri=r sel=ttj-z> A8970 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0677 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDER A SIN, PERSONAL ARCHAEOLOGY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By STEPHANIE SALTER &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SAN FRANCISCO  &MD;  It all began when I bought 300 cotton puffs for
79 cents at Woolworth's. Little did I know it would end with my
life passing before my very eyes. And nose.
<p>
   Three hundred cotton puffs for six bits is such a good bargain,
it mattered not that I might still have some old puffs stashed
under my bathroom sink. I figured it was probably time I got into
the small cabinet anyway and took inventory. Toss a few things out.
Tidy up.
<p>
   Ha. Three hours and two full wastebaskets after I went in, I
emerged exhausted, embarrassed, bewildered and feeling very old.
<p>
   You pick up a scrapbook, an old photo album or a packet of
dusty, yellowing letters, and you expect to time-travel through
your past and maybe through a few social eras. You don't expect it
when you go under your bathroom sink to put away cotton puffs.
<p>
   The dozens of empty prescription drug vials alone were
mind-bending. The oldest: a silver tube of ointment, prescribed in
1973 when I was living in New York. The doctor and the pharmacy
have been dead for at least a decade.
<p>
   The partially used physicians' samples were the most perplexing.
When did I need the tiny orange anti-itch/anti-anxiety pills? What
doctor gave them to me? Why did I take only one? (Did I take it or
give it to somebody else as you should never do with prescription
drugs?)
<p>
   Ah, the Vicodin from '89 when I got mugged and knifed on the
street, had surgery and was in a cast for a month.
<p>
   The Vicodin from two years ago when I tore my anterior cruciate
ligament, had surgery and was on a cane for two months.
<p>
   The Percocet from when the Vicodin stopped working.
<p>
   The antibiotics  &MD;  ``Take all of these pills even if you begin to
feel better''  &MD;  for a host of bugs caught over the past 15 years.
Unused Bonine for a killer boat ride out to the Farallones in '88.
Packets of weird, fizzy decongestant prescribed by a doctor I
fairly crawled to in Paris in '92.
<p>
   Then there was the, uh, birth control. I'll skip the details,
but suffice to say, I found some museum pieces. What variety. What
a stockpile. Obviously, I once took the Boy Scout motto very much
to heart.
<p>
   Equally copious  &MD;  and dated  &MD;  was the makeup. Although I rarely
wear it, I seem never to have thrown out a tube, bottle, pencil or
compact of cosmetic paint that I acquired. Lipstick the color of
dried blood (or maybe refritos). Nail polish the color of Bazooka
bubble gum. Slime green eye shadow. Electric blue liner. Fake
suntan. Foundation for a street mime.
<p>
   The trip through perfume land, however, was sweet, full of the
kind of immediate recall that only the olfactory senses can
deliver. Love's Musky Jasmine from the early '70s; Figi from the
late. My '80s Halston phase. The Chloe that a former beau tried to
foist upon me during my Halston phase. The super-expensive
Valentino I bought 10 years ago and use for only the most special
evenings.
<p>
   (It's a quarter-of-an ounce bottle, still two-thirds full; a
testament to my glamorous social life.)
<p>
   Millions of hair pins and bobby pins. Stray barrettes and
ponytail holders. Two of those expandable, pointy headbands that I
keep hoping will work in my hair but won't. Straight pins, safety
pins, needles. Pocket sewing kits with only pink thread left. Jars
of cheap moisturizers  &MD;  what was I thinking?  &MD;  nearly empty bottles
of sun block and mosquito repellent.
<p>
   And one door key. A big, heavy, brass hotel job. Room 827.
Where? When? Did I have a good time?
<p>
   Oh, yes, there were cotton puffs. Maybe 100. But they were
ruined from some long-ago (I hope) leak in the pipes, so I threw
them out with all the other sorry stuff. At the rate I seem to use
cotton puffs, 300 probably will last me until I am eligible for
Social Security.
<p>
   I should be just about ready then to go back under my bathroom
sink.
<p>
    &UR; ------- &LR; Stephanie Salter is an Examiner columnist.
</TEXT>
