representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR; 
 &UR; By RICHARD ROEPER &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Chicago Sun-Times &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   The problem is, Chicago wants Dennis Rodman to be cuddly.
<p>
   Dennis Rodman ain't cuddly.
<p>
   He is not Tickle Me Dennis. He is tick...tick...ticking Dennis,
and he exploded once again last week.
<p>
   You know what happened. You've seen ``the kick'' a hundred times
on TV by now. You've heard that the NBA has suspended Rodman for at
least 11 games and ordered him to undergo counseling.
<p>
   Rodman's troubles don't end there. There may be criminal and
civil charges. There's also a rumor that his charge card at
Victoria's Secret may be revoked.
<p>
   This is the funniest part of the whole sad saga: According to
police who are following the letter of the law, Rodman at this
point is only a ``suspect'' in the ``alleged'' assault on that
cameraman last week in Minneapolis.
<p>
   Does that mean they're going to have to find a bunch of other
6-foot-8 guys with rainbow-colored hair, multiple tattoos and body
piercings to fill out a police lineup? Good luck.
<p>
   Too many kids want to believe Dennis is this neato video game
character. Heck, too many parents want to believe that. Not to
mention the guys who worship him as the great rebounding god and
the women who think of him as the ultimate anti-hero sex symbol.
<p>
   Other than the rebounding, it's all a crock.
<p>
   (And even as a basketball player, Rodman is overvalued. He's one
of the worst offensive players in the league, and too often he
sacrifices team defense in favor of padding his rebounding stats.
He's the Dave Kingman of basketball.)
<p>
   Dennis Rodman is not a misunderstood rebel, he's a manipulative,
money-hungry, one-man corporation trying to make as much money as
possible as quickly as possible. When Charles Barkley compared
Rodman to a prostitute, he was insulting prostitutes.
<p>
   For one thing, they have better makeup.
<p>
   For the last year and a half, Chicago has smothered Rodman with
love. When it comes to dealing with Dennis the Menace, the City of
the Big Shoulders has become the City of the Group Hug. We're like
the self-indulgent parents who think that everything the disturbed
child does is a healthy sign of expression.
<p>
   This is the first time ever that the cities of San Antonio and
Detroit can feel more sophisticated than Chicago. They've got to be
laughing at us for continuing to put up with this goofball who used
to blight their towns.
<p>
   Dennis Rodman is a jerk and a clown and a coward, and he's
getting paid more to wear Converse gym shoes than you'll make for
getting up every morning for the rest of your life and going to
work. Feel free to resent him, folks.
<p>
   You'd think people would be sick of Rodman's tired act by now -
the cross-dressing and the publicity stunts and the outbursts of
profanity and the lame show on MTV and the pay-per-gawk public
appearances. We got over our brief collective fascination with Boy
George and Anna Nicole Smith and Hulk Hogan, why can't we get past
this freakazoid?
<p>
   If you're a parent who thinks it's cute for your child to dress
up like Dennis or hold up signs in a sports arena pining for the
return of Rodman, you're stupid.
<p>
   If you're a hardcore Bulls fan who thinks Rodman is the victim
of persecution by the NBA, you're an idiot.
<p>
   If you greet Rodman's eventual return to the Bulls with a
standing ovation, you're a dupe.
<p>
   Michael Jordan is the greatest athlete in the history of team
sports and he is in the stretch run of his career, and Rodman is
soiling the memories. Jordan and Pippen sharing the court with
Rodman is tantamount to the three surviving Beatles reuniting but
having to share the stage with RuPaul.
<p>
   Rodman's greatest punishment isn't the suspension or the fine or
any of that. Five years from now, he'll be 40 and he'll be out of
the game, and no one will care about his antics, and Dennis Rodman
will have to live with himself.
<p>
   His greatest punishment is his future.
<p>
    &UR; (Richard Roeper  &MD;  email:rroeper(at)suntimes.com  &MD;  is a
columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, a radio host and a commentator
for Fox News in Chicago. He has written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy,
Chicago magazine and many other publications, and has appeared as a
guest on ``Nightline'' and ``Oprah.'') &LR; 
<p>
   ----------- &QC; 
