<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tab-z> A8978 </STORYID>
<SLUG> STEPHANOPOULOS-NEWSMAN-N </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1326 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; STEPHANOPOULOS-NEWSMAN-NOW-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE (UNHOLY) TRANSFORMATION OF GEORGE STEPHANOPOULOS &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased  &MD;  the
rate is not prohibitive  &MD;  from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: &LR; 
<p>
   (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. &LR; 
<p>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR; 
<p>
   (--Latin America: PAUL FINCH in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax,
310-996-0089. &LR; 
 &UR; By MAX FRANKEL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   The overnight transformation of George Stephanopoulos from
partisan pitchman to TV journalist highlights a disturbing
phenomenon: the progressive collapse of the walls that
traditionally separated news from propaganda.
<p>
   Self-respecting news organizations used to pride themselves on
the sturdy barriers they maintained to guard against all kinds of
partisan contamination.
<p>
   Inside the office, they built a high wall between those who
reported and analyzed events and those who offered opinions about
them  &MD;  between the newsroom and the editorial page. A second wall
separated both the news and editorial departments from the
commercial ambitions of the business office.
<p>
   And an especially thick wall was erected around the entire
enterprise to keep out the pollution generated by politicians and
advertisers.
<p>
   But now, particularly in television, America's primary source of
news, the walls are buckling. Stephanopoulos is hardly the first
politician to breach them.
<p>
   David Gergen changes identity faster than Clark Kent. Pete
Williams leapt from the Pentagon to NBC without stopping for lunch.
No one even bothers any longer to decontaminate a convert  &MD;  such
as, say, Bill Moyers  &MD;  by stretching out his passage from politics
to reporting over a cleansing period of time.
<p>
   Nor does anyone feel the need to put distance between an active
politician  &MD;  for instance, Pat Buchanan  &MD;  and the news team. On the
contrary, the commerce of television welcomes celebrity and
contentiousness.
<p>
   When ABC News first announced the hiring of Stephanopoulos, it
said he would be both a ``political analyst'' and a
``correspondent,'' with appearances on ``Good Morning America'' and
``This Week.''
<p>
   That gilding of an amateur must have caused a ripple of
resentment among reporters who take pride in the title
``correspondent.''
<p>
   So a second announcement quickly emphasized that the new recruit
would not be reporting news or questioning guests. And that, it was
said, would avoid any ``appearance of conflict.''
<p>
   Oh, sure.
<p>
   Who could possibly find conflict in an ``analysis'' of the
words, deeds and motives of Bill Clinton and his administration by
one of the architects of his presidency who just happens to owe his
celebrity and new job entirely to that president? How could anyone
discern even the appearance of a conflict between Stephanopoulos'
four-year career of media manipulation for the White House and
whatever he will now say or neglect to say as an ABC commentator?
<p>
   If our senses are so dulled to journalistic conflicts of
interest, it cannot be because of any redeeming features of the
Stephanopoulos appointment.
<p>
   It must be because news organizations, particularly TV-talk
shows, so routinely confuse dispassionate news analysis with the
expression of partisan opinion. At most, they compensate for one
prejudiced commentator by employing another, which further
conditions us to getting heat where there should be light.
<p>
   As ABC argued in self-justification, why should it not put
Stephanopoulos on a Sunday program that frequently features William
Kristol, a former aide to Vice President Dan Quayle?
<p>
   But then why be squeamish about Kristol and Stephanopoulos
questioning guests, like real reporters? A professional
opinion-monger such as George Will routinely does that on the same
program and thereby baits reporters, such as Sam Donaldson and
Cokie Roberts, into expressing their contrary opinions.
<p>
   The trouble with news programs that lapse into bouts of opinion
is that the panelists end up scoring points instead of illuminating
events. The ultimate perversion occurs on ``The McLaughlin Group,''
whose members are encouraged to rudely shout out ill-argued
conclusions, often three or four at the same time.
<p>
   And some TV ``news'' shows abandon all pretense of
nonpartisanship by staging cockfights among unemployed politicians
 &MD;  pitting John Sununu against Geraldine Ferraro or Mary Matalin
against Dee Dee Myers.
<p>
   The paradox in all this is that the principal network anchors,
who used to be scorned for coloring the news with the curl of a lip
or the arch of an eyebrow, now stand out as the most impartial and
polite voices in TV news.
<p>
   Although the experiences and independence of Tom Brokaw, Peter
Jennings, Dan Rather and Ted Koppel would give their opinions a lot
more weight than those of any politician, they still observe the
disciplines of their craft. Their on-air analyses plumb the views
and prejudices of others without parading their own.
<p>
   To be sure, none of us in the news business are perfectly
disinterested. We are not entirely above commercial motive or
always successful in suppressing a personal view. And yes, The New
York Times once felt a need to balance the opinions on its op-Ed
page by hiring William Safire direct from President Nixon's staff
of speech writers.
<p>
   And so long as Nixon remained in the White House with Watergate
bursting all around, Safire showed himself understandably
conflicted in some of the columns he wrote. But they were plainly
carried as columns of opinion, strictly segregated from the news.
<p>
   In my experience, The Times was insufficiently fastidious only
once, two decades ago, when it hired Leslie Gelb, an arms-control
expert, to write knowingly about diplomacy soon after he had
practiced it inside the State Department. It even let him shuttle
to and from government, making an exception that reinforced our
rule against such slackness.
<p>
   Why is television increasingly lax about the old standards?
<p>
   Obviously, a Stephanopoulos has star qualities. He comes as a
ready-made celebrity expert, telegenic, charming, articulate. He
brings promise of an immediate lift in the ratings and in profits.
The same qualities and promise must explain why, contrary to
custom, the highest officials of Columbia University escorted him
before the cameras to announce Stephanopoulos' other new job  &MD;  as
teacher and scholar.
<p>
   If he is serious about academia and journalism, Stephanopoulos
will in time outgrow his youthful ardors and escapades, recover his
chastity and qualify as a professional student and observer of
public affairs.
<p>
   But if TV news is serious about its reputation for disinterested
analysis, it had better cement those walls.
<p>
    &UR; (Max Frankel is the former Washington Bureau chief, editorial
page editor and executive editor of The New York Times. He won a
Pulitzer Prize in 1973 and has been a correspondent in Eastern
Europe, Moscow and the Caribbean. Frankel now writes this ``Word &AMP;
Image'' column for The New York Times Magazine.) &LR; 
<p>
   -----------------  &QC; 
