<STORYID cat=l pri=r sel=tab-z> A8984 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-POT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 2789 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DOCTOR-POT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MAKE WAY FOR THE MEDICAL-MARIJUANA MOVEMENT &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased  &MD;  the
rate is not prohibitive  &MD;  from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: &LR; 
<p>
   (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. &LR; 
<p>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR; 
<p>
   (--Latin America: PAUL FINCH in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax,
310-996-0089. &LR; 
 &UR; By NICK GILLESPIE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Reason Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; NOTE: Full-length article (3,500 words) available on request &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   Opponents of California's Proposition 215 and Arizona's
Proposition 200  &MD;  both of which allow doctors to recommend or
prescribe currently illegal drugs  &MD;  managed to drive home one basic
point.
<p>
   These ballot initiatives were, in the words of Clinton drug czar
Barry McCaffrey, ``a stalking horse for legalization.''
<p>
   The California measure, Orange County Sheriff Brad Gates warned,
``wouldn't just legalize marijuana for medical use  &MD;  it would
legalize marijuana, period, with absolutely no controls on quality,
or dosage, or who can get it.''
<p>
   Arizona Republican Congressman Paul Mortenson told the Arizona
Republic, ``The message from Proposition 200 is: `Do drugs, so
what?'''
<p>
   ``What we have here,'' pronounced Dan Lungren, California's
attorney general, ``is a law flying under false colors.''
<p>
   But in the end, voters in both states who oppose drug
legalization remained unpersuaded.
<p>
   Indeed, the final tallies in November weren't even close: 56
percent of Californians favored Proposition 215, with 44 percent
opposed. Arizona's Proposition 200 scored an even more lopsided
win, 65 percent vs. 35 percent.
<p>
   The medical-use initiatives carried the day  &MD;  not because of any
new strong push for widescale legalization of marijuana but because
of the huge reservoir of sympathy people have for desperately ill
terminal patients and chronic-pain sufferers.
<p>
   Pre-election polls commissioned by Arizonans for Drug Policy
Reform, the group pushing Proposition 200, found fewer than
one-quarter of state residents favored legalization. But election
exit polls showed overwhelming support for medical use of marijuana
in every demographic group, including Republicans, conservatives
and Dole voters.
<p>
   In the wake of such success  &MD;  and national polls suggesting
receptiveness to the idea  &MD;  the medical-use movement is sure to
spread across the country.
<p>
   California for Medical Rights, one of the main proponents of
Proposition 215, has renamed itself Americans for Medical Rights
and plans to lobby for similar measures in other states.
<p>
   And Democratic Rep. Barney Frank of Massachusetts, who in 1995
introduced a medical marijuana law in Congress, says he will
introduce new legislation similar to the California initiative.
<p>
   These new propositions represent the most significant shift in
drug policy in recent years because they ``make the debate on
legalization possible for the first time,''in the words of the
chief organizer of the Arizona measure. They do so by challenging
the drug war's axiomatic assumption that ``illicit'' or ``illegal''
drugs are demonic substances that offer no possible benefits to
society.
<p>
   And as one tenet of the drug war's underlying philosophy is
opened to debate, it seems likely a more expansive reconsideration
of the whole enterprise may be in the offing.
<p>
   Although significant, that is a far cry from Gates' assertion
that California's Proposition 215 would ``legalize marijuana,
period.''
<p>
   Other opponents have raised the specter of ``pot doctors'' and
``Dr. Feelgoods'' who will indiscriminately provide fraudulent
medical certification for recreational users, effectively
legalizing drugs.
<p>
   In such a fractious debate it's important to appreciate what the
two initiatives  &MD;  deemed ``tremendous tragedies'' and ``dangerous
developments'' by drug czar McCaffrey  &MD;  write into law.
<p>
   California's Compassionate Use Act of 1996 grew largely out of
the experience of illegal but semi-tolerated ``buyers' clubs'' that
provide marijuana to chemotherapy, AIDS, glaucoma and chronic-pain
patients. One of the guiding forces behind the measure was Dennis
Peron, director of San Francisco's Cannabis Buyers Club, which has
more than 6,000 registered members.
<p>
   Peron, a co-author of the proposition, also heads Californians
for Compassionate Use, which, along with Californians for Medical
Rights, coordinated the campaign.
<p>
   In stumping for the measure, advocates stressed medical and
personal angles. Television spots featured oncologists, cancer
patients and widowed spouses discussing the ways in which medical
marijuana helped ease pain and suffering.
<p>
   Support for the initiative was strongest in and around urban
centers such as San Francisco, Los Angeles and San Diego.
Demographically, Proposition 215 polled well among most groups
other than Republicans and, interestingly, voters 65 and older.
<p>
   The pro-215 campaign spent about $2 million, much of it supplied
by out-of-state contributors including billionaire George Soros and
insurance magnate Peter Lewis. The measure closely resembles laws
twice passed by the California legislature but vetoed by Gov. Pete
Wilson.
<p>
   It allows patients to possess, grow and consume pot on a
doctor's ``recommendation'' that ``the person's health would
benefit from the use of marijuana'' in treating terminal illnesses
such as cancer, chronic pain or  &MD;  and this is what gave opponents
fits  &MD;  ``any other illness for which marijuana provides relief.''
<p>
   Proposition 215 also stipulates that a patient's ``primary
caregiver''  &MD;  defined as ``the individual designated by the person
... who has consistently assumed responsibility for the housing,
health or safety of that person''  &MD;  is not subject to criminal
sanctions.
<p>
   Doctors recommending use would similarly be exempt from
punishment or other sorts of retribution, such as the lifting of
state medical licenses.
<p>
   The point man behind Arizona's Drug Medicalization, Prevention
and Control Act of 1996 was Phoenix-area millionaire John Sperling.
The head of the Apollo Group, a consortium of for-profit
educational institutions, Sperling says his interest in the issue
is ``purely public policy. I spent 10 years reading about drug
policy and never read a positive article.''
<p>
   He is emphatic: ``We have to medicalize drug use. We have to get
it out of the hands of the criminal-justice community and put it
into the hands of the public-health and medical community.''
<p>
   Toward that end, Sperling created Arizonans for Drug Policy
Reform and pulled together a high-profile board. Former Reagan
administration official John Norton served as chairman of a group
that included former Civil Aeronautics Board head Marvin S. Cohen,
State Court of Appeals Judge Rudolph S. Gerber and more than a
dozen prominent Arizona physicians.
<p>
   Sperling also convinced former Sens. Barry Goldwater and Dennis
DeConcini to publicly back the measure.
<p>
   As in California, advocates focussed on the inviolability of the
doctor-patient relationship, the nausea that accompanies cancer
chemotherapy and radiation treatments, and the loss of appetite and
weight (wasting syndrome) in AIDS patients.
<p>
   Arizona's proposition enables doctors to prescribe any
``Schedule I'' drug  &MD;  a category that includes marijuana, heroin,
LSD, methamphetamine and other illegal substances  &MD;  if they can
cite research that ``supports'' a medical application and they
obtain a concurring written opinion from another doctor.
<p>
   Those prescriptions would provide a valid, legal defense against
drug possession or use charges.
<p>
   The act also includes a number of criminal-justice provisions
designed to ``medicalize'' the drug war: People without valid
prescriptions who are convicted of possession or use fewer than
three times can't get jail time; state prisoners serving time for
non-violent use or possession  &MD;  conceivably as many as 1,800 people
 &MD;  are immediately eligible for a parole hearing and possible
release.
<p>
   Parolees and newly convicted people must accept court-ordered
drug treatment and education and do community service. A
truth-in-sentencing provision holds that anyone convicted of
committing a violent crime while ``high'' must serve 100 percent of
his sentence.
<p>
   Organizers of both efforts remain emphatic that the acts cover
only legitimate, defensible medical use  &MD;  a position somewhat
undercut when Peron recently told The New York Times that ``all
marijuana use is medical  &MD;  except for kids.''
<p>
   Many difficult questions revolve around the interaction of the
new statutes with federal drug laws.
<p>
   For example, under federal law it remains illegal to
manufacture, use, possess or distribute any Schedule I drugs,
including marijuana. So even patients following doctors' orders  &MD; 
and complying with state laws  &MD;  are violating federal law.
<p>
   While doctors are already prohibited from prescribing Schedule I
drugs, the U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency (DEA) does license
physicians to prescribe Schedule II drugs such as morphine. The DEA
carefully tracks the use of Schedule II drugs and exercises
powerful oversight in that area.
<p>
   It is not clear if the feds will respond to doctors who
prescribe or recommend Schedule I drugs by pulling their ability to
prescribe Schedule II drugs.
<p>
   Indeed, it is not even clear how the DEA will learn that doctors
are prescribing marijuana or other Schedule I drugs, because those
prescriptions will not be filled by pharmacists or other health
officials who report to the government.
<p>
   The DEA's official position hardly clarifies the issue: ``The
passage of these propositions in no way alters the DEA's
fundamental mission: to enforce the federal drug laws of the United
States. The DEA intends to continue targeting the most significant
drug traffickers at home and abroad.''
<p>
   Because of limited resources, the DEA traditionally has ignored
individual users and small-time dealers, focusing on drug kingpins
and large commercial operations. The feds have largely left buyers'
clubs alone.
<p>
   But the California Medical Association has expressed fears that
doctors prescribing marijuana to more than a few patients will be
categorized as ``significant drug traffickers'' and either lose
their Schedule II privileges or be arrested.
<p>
   Given the overwhelming victories and the negative publicity
associated with hauling legitimate practitioners into court,
however, it is ``very unlikely'' that federal agents will go after
doctors, Frank says.
<p>
   At least in the short run, the DEA seems to be adopting a
wait-and-see posture.
<p>
   McCaffrey's office has announced plans to ``actively collect
data  &MD;  i.e., drug-related accident rates, teen pregnancy, work
absences, hospital emergency cases and the like  &MD;  which will
indicate the consequences of the referenda.''
<p>
   In fact, in the wake of the propositions, no one  &MD;  opponent or
proponent  &MD;  knows for sure what will happen.
<p>
   In California thousands of ``registered'' marijuana users
already receive their pot from buyers' clubs. And, says Dale
Gieringer, head of the California chapter of the National
Organization to Reform Marijuana Laws  &MD;  NORML  &MD;  ``scores'' of
doctors are already publicly ``recommending'' pot to patients.
<p>
   How much will medical-use rates fluctuate in the face of
Proposition 215? Will more doctors get with the program?
<p>
   ``There's no way to know,'' Gieringer says.
<p>
   Following the passage of both initiatives, perhaps only this
much is certain: A new conversation about drug policy is taking
place, one that actually requires state and federal governments to
enter into dialogue with citizens.
<p>
   ``Just say no'' has been answered with ``Tell us why.'' It is
not clear that the government will be able to hold up its end of
the discussion.
<p>
   McCaffrey, in his official statement lamenting the new state
laws, sputtered: ``We had support from former Presidents Ford,
Carter and Bush''  &MD;  as if a trinity of one-term former chief
executives would somehow provide a boost to any cause.
<p>
   However, as Americans for Medical Rights and other groups push
initiatives in other states, the conversation about the medical use
of currently illegal drugs is bound to continue.
<p>
   The California and Arizona initiatives ``give some real oomph''
to the medical-use debate, Frank says. ``They are another argument
for changing federal law.'' Although he concedes such a change is
unlikely to unfold quickly, he suggests that Congress will take
note of public opinion.
<p>
   Nor, despite what opponents claim, is there any reason to assume
that medical-use laws have any absolute link to legalization. While
people may be willing to expand the current pharmacopoeia, they are
not necessarily signing onto the idea that individuals should have
the right to decide what drugs they can take. Just as drug warriors
must explain themselves to a skeptical public, so too must
legalizers.
<p>
   The potential connection between medical use and legalization
is, in fact, a fairly subtle one.
<p>
   McCaffrey has suggested: ``There could not be a worse message to
young people than the provisions of these referenda. Just when the
nation is trying its hardest to educate teen-agers not to use
psychoactive drugs, now they are being told that marijuana and
other drugs are good, they are medicine.''
<p>
   On one level, such an equation is absurd. People  &MD;  including
teen-agers  &MD;  don't take drugs recreationally because they are
certified as ``good'' medicine. If they did, we could expect a run
on any number of drugs, ranging from Kaopectate to penicillin.
<p>
   At the same time, redefining marijuana as medicine makes people
less likely to automatically agree that it is an unmitigated evil.
<p>
   The real contribution of medical marijuana to the larger debate
on legalization is that it may well put the lie to official claims
about drugs. Lungren, for instance, has said that smoking or eating
marijuana has no beneficial medical effect  &MD;  even though he allows
that Marinol, a prescription version of THC, the active ingredient
in marijuana, has some value.
<p>
   At the very least, recent events will focus more critical
scrutiny on government statements. When McCaffrey presents his
evidence of the ``inevitable result of the referenda,'' he will
have to work to convince his audience.
<p>
   Yale Law School Professor Steven B. Duke suggests that if the
public sees more and more people using marijuana medically and
testifying to its value, they may rethink their position on it.
<p>
   ``There might be a recognition as well that the government is
lying in other areas of drug policy too,'' says Duke, co-author of
``America's Longest War: Rethinking Our Tragic Crusade Against
Drugs.'' He adds: ``Among prohibitionists, there's a sense that if
you give an inch, you lose everything. That's certainly the case
with opponents of medical marijuana.''
<p>
   Ironically, the failure to compromise on a relatively
non-controversial topic such as medical marijuana could open the
door to a much broader rejection of the drug war.
<p>
   It is in this sense that the initiatives have, as Sperling puts
it, made the ``debate on legalization'' possible. What shape it
will take and what ends it will achieve are far from certain.
<p>
   Judging from poll data, there is currently little support for
legalization.
<p>
   But as the passage of Propositions 200 and 215 forces
prohibitionists to justify their policies, and the country's
experience with medical use of illegal substances gets under way,
that debate should prove to be one full of possibilities.
<p>
    &UR; (Nick Gillespie  &MD;  ngilles123(at)aol.com  &MD;  is a senior editor of
Reason Magazine, where a longer version of this article first
appeared.) &LR; 
