<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DOCTOR-POT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MAKE WAY FOR THE MEDICAL-MARIJUANA MOVEMENT &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased  &MD;  the
rate is not prohibitive  &MD;  from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: &LR; 
<p>
   (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. &LR; 
<p>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR; 
<p>
   (--Latin America: PAUL FINCH in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax,
310-996-0089. &LR; 
 &UR; By NICK GILLESPIE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Reason Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; NOTE: Full-length article (3,500 words) available on request &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   Opponents of California's Proposition 215 and Arizona's
Proposition 200  &MD;  both of which allow doctors to recommend or
prescribe currently illegal drugs  &MD;  managed to drive home one basic
point.
<p>
   These ballot initiatives were, in the words of Clinton drug czar
Barry McCaffrey, ``a stalking horse for legalization.''
<p>
   The California measure, Orange County Sheriff Brad Gates warned,
``wouldn't just legalize marijuana for medical use  &MD;  it would
legalize marijuana, period, with absolutely no controls on quality,
or dosage, or who can get it.''
<p>
   Arizona Republican Congressman Paul Mortenson told the Arizona
Republic, ``The message from Proposition 200 is: `Do drugs, so
what?'''
<p>
   ``What we have here,'' pronounced Dan Lungren, California's
attorney general, ``is a law flying under false colors.''
<p>
   But in the end, voters in both states who oppose drug
legalization remained unpersuaded.
<p>
   Indeed, the final tallies in November weren't even close: 56
percent of Californians favored Proposition 215, with 44 percent
opposed. Arizona's Proposition 200 scored an even more lopsided
win, 65 percent vs. 35 percent.
<p>
   The medical-use initiatives carried the day  &MD;  not because of any
new strong push for widescale legalization of marijuana but because
of the huge reservoir of sympathy people have for desperately ill
terminal patients and chronic-pain sufferers.
<p>
   Pre-election polls commissioned by Arizonans for Drug Policy
Reform, the group pushing Proposition 200, found fewer than
one-quarter of state residents favored legalization. But election
exit polls showed overwhelming support for medical use of marijuana
in every demographic group, including Republicans, conservatives
and Dole voters.
<p>
   In the wake of such success  &MD;  and national polls suggesting
receptiveness to the idea  &MD;  the medical-use movement is sure to
spread across the country.
<p>
   California for Medical Rights, one of the main proponents of
Proposition 215, has renamed itself Americans for Medical Rights
and plans to lobby for similar measures in other states.
<p>
   And Democratic Rep. Barney Frank of Massachusetts, who in 1995
introduced a medical marijuana law in Congress, says he will
introduce new legislation similar to the California initiative.
<p>
   These new propositions represent the most significant shift in
drug policy in recent years because they ``make the debate on
legalization possible for the first time,''in the words of the
chief organizer of the Arizona measure. They do so by challenging
the drug war's axiomatic assumption that ``illicit'' or ``illegal''
drugs are demonic substances that offer no possible benefits to
society.
<p>
   And as one tenet of the drug war's underlying philosophy is
opened to debate, it seems likely a more expansive reconsideration
of the whole enterprise may be in the offing.
<p>
   Although significant, that is a far cry from Gates' assertion
that California's Proposition 215 would ``legalize marijuana,
period.''
<p>
   Other opponents have raised the specter of ``pot doctors'' and
``Dr. Feelgoods'' who will indiscriminately provide fraudulent
medical certification for recreational users, effectively
legalizing drugs.
<p>
   In such a fractious debate it's important to appreciate what the
two initiatives  &MD;  deemed ``tremendous tragedies'' and ``dangerous
developments'' by drug czar McCaffrey  &MD;  write into law.
<p>
   California's Compassionate Use Act of 1996 grew largely out of
the experience of illegal but semi-tolerated ``buyers' clubs'' that
provide marijuana to chemotherapy, AIDS, glaucoma and chronic-pain
patients. One of the guiding forces behind the measure was Dennis
Peron, director of San Francisco's Cannabis Buyers Club, which has
more than 6,000 registered members.
<p>
   Peron, a co-author of the proposition, also heads Californians
for Compassionate Use, which, along with Californians for Medical
Rights, coordinated the campaign.
<p>
   In stumping for the measure, advocates stressed medical and
personal angles. Television spots featured oncologists, cancer
patients and widowed spouses discussing the ways in which medical
