<p>
   Given the overwhelming victories and the negative publicity
associated with hauling legitimate practitioners into court,
however, it is ``very unlikely'' that federal agents will go after
doctors, Frank says.
<p>
   At least in the short run, the DEA seems to be adopting a
wait-and-see posture.
<p>
   McCaffrey's office has announced plans to ``actively collect
data  &MD;  i.e., drug-related accident rates, teen pregnancy, work
absences, hospital emergency cases and the like  &MD;  which will
indicate the consequences of the referenda.''
<p>
   In fact, in the wake of the propositions, no one  &MD;  opponent or
proponent  &MD;  knows for sure what will happen.
<p>
   In California thousands of ``registered'' marijuana users
already receive their pot from buyers' clubs. And, says Dale
Gieringer, head of the California chapter of the National
Organization to Reform Marijuana Laws  &MD;  NORML  &MD;  ``scores'' of
doctors are already publicly ``recommending'' pot to patients.
<p>
   How much will medical-use rates fluctuate in the face of
Proposition 215? Will more doctors get with the program?
<p>
   ``There's no way to know,'' Gieringer says.
<p>
   Following the passage of both initiatives, perhaps only this
much is certain: A new conversation about drug policy is taking
place, one that actually requires state and federal governments to
enter into dialogue with citizens.
<p>
   ``Just say no'' has been answered with ``Tell us why.'' It is
not clear that the government will be able to hold up its end of
the discussion.
<p>
   McCaffrey, in his official statement lamenting the new state
laws, sputtered: ``We had support from former Presidents Ford,
Carter and Bush''  &MD;  as if a trinity of one-term former chief
executives would somehow provide a boost to any cause.
<p>
   However, as Americans for Medical Rights and other groups push
initiatives in other states, the conversation about the medical use
of currently illegal drugs is bound to continue.
<p>
   The California and Arizona initiatives ``give some real oomph''
to the medical-use debate, Frank says. ``They are another argument
for changing federal law.'' Although he concedes such a change is
unlikely to unfold quickly, he suggests that Congress will take
note of public opinion.
<p>
   Nor, despite what opponents claim, is there any reason to assume
that medical-use laws have any absolute link to legalization. While
people may be willing to expand the current pharmacopoeia, they are
not necessarily signing onto the idea that individuals should have
the right to decide what drugs they can take. Just as drug warriors
must explain themselves to a skeptical public, so too must
legalizers.
<p>
   The potential connection between medical use and legalization
is, in fact, a fairly subtle one.
<p>
   McCaffrey has suggested: ``There could not be a worse message to
young people than the provisions of these referenda. Just when the
nation is trying its hardest to educate teen-agers not to use
psychoactive drugs, now they are being told that marijuana and
other drugs are good, they are medicine.''
<p>
   On one level, such an equation is absurd. People  &MD;  including
teen-agers  &MD;  don't take drugs recreationally because they are
certified as ``good'' medicine. If they did, we could expect a run
on any number of drugs, ranging from Kaopectate to penicillin.
