 &UR; RWANDA'S INNOCENT OUTCASTS &LR; 
 &UR; By ELIZABETH ROYTE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   Two years ago, while Rwanda's Hutu militias were murdering half
a million Tutsis, most of them men, Hutu soldiers and civilians
also raped more than 250,000 women. Never having enjoyed a
particularly high status even in the best of times, these women now
are in the most dire straits. Elizabeth Royte is a contributing
writer for The New York Times Magazine. (slugged:
BC-RWANDAN-RAPED-WOMEN-NYTSF, priority code r, category codes a,i)
 &UR; MAKE WAY FOR THE MEDICAL-MARIJUANA MOVEMENT &LR; 
 &UR; By NICK GILLESPIE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Reason Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   The success of California's Proposition 215 and Arizona's
Proposition 200  &MD;  both of which allow doctors to recommend or
prescribe currently illegal drugs  &MD;  is opening a fractious debate
on drug use  &MD;  and legalization  &MD;  that is sure to spread throughout
the United States. Nick Gillespie is a senior editor at Reason
Magazine. (slugged: BC-DOCTOR-POT-NYTSF, priority code r, category
codes a,l)
 &UR; CLANCY'S GAME &LR; 
 &UR; By DICK VICTORY
 &UR; c.1997 Washingtonian Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   According to Forbes magazine, novelist Tom Clancy made $15
million in 1995 and $16 million in 1996. A recent article in GQ by
Peter Bart suggested that super-popular writers such as Clancy and
John Grisham have such powerful brand names that ``no publisher can
afford to pay them what they demand.'' Now Clancy's released a
CD-ROM war game, ``SSN.'' What's the secret of this guy's wild
success? Dick Victory is senior editor at Washingtonian Magazine.
(slugged: BC-TOM-CLANCY-SSNGAME-NYTSF, category code r, priority
code a,e)
 &UR; THE (UNHOLY) TRANSFORMATION OF GEORGE STEPHANOPOULOS &LR; 
 &UR; By MAX FRANKEL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   The overnight transformation of George Stephanopoulos from
partisan pitchman to TV journalist highlights a disturbing
phenomenon: the progressive collapse of the walls that
traditionally separated news from propaganda.
<p>
   Max Frankel is the former Washington Bureau chief, editorial
page editor and executive editor of The New York Times. He won a
Pulitzer Prize in 1973 and has been a correspondent in Eastern
Europe, Moscow and the Caribbean. (slugged:
BC-STEPHANOPOULOS-NEWSMAN-NOW-NYTSF, priority code r, category code
k,a)
