 &UR; NEWS &AMP; COMMENTARY &LR; 
 &UR; WILL CLINTON GOVERN FROM A `NEW VITAL CENTER?' &LR; 
 &UR; By ALAN BRINKLEY &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   President Clinton spent 1996 embracing the political center so
fervently that his Republican opponents were hard-pressed to find
an issue on which they disagreed with him. He has been talking ever
since of governing from a new ``vital center.''
<p>
   ``The public wants us to work together,'' Clinton said recently.
``I stand ready to forge a coalition of the center. ...''
<p>
   Alan Brinkley is a professor of American history at Columbia
University and the author most recently of ``The End of Reform: New
Deal Liberalism in Recession and War.'' (slugged:
BC-CLINTON-VITAL-CENTER-NYTSF, priority code r, category codes k,a)
 &UR; THE BRAVE NEW WORLD OF WEB ADVERTISING &LR; 
 &UR; By JOAN VOIGHT &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Wired &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; World rights excluding Japan and the UK &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   The advertising world is scrambling for new ways to pull dollars
out of Web sites. No longer are they content to simply paste their
ads on a cracker-sized piece of Web real estate. And forget about
trying to Instead, advertisers want to work hand in hand with
publishers to co-produce the material that packs Web pages. It may
abolish the Web as we know it. Joan Voight is San Francisco bureau
chief for Adweek. (slugged: BC-WIRED-ADS-ON-INTERNET-NYTSF,
priority code r, category codes a,l)
 &UR; EXPANDING NATO WON'T BRING MORE PEACE ON EARTH &LR; 
 &UR; By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Copyright 1997 La Stampa &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   To expand NATO  &MD;  as is currently being proposed  &MD;  would violate
Russia's vital security and geopolitical interests. It would
threaten the way the Cold War was concluded with the voluntary
assent of Russia. Yet some say that Russia has no right to veto the
will of others in the West.
<p>
   Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow. (slugged:
BC-GORBACHEV-REBUKES-WEST-ART-NYTSF, priority code r, category
codes k,i)
<p>
    &MD;  (This timely article has already moved to clients of the
monthly Gorbachev column.)  &MD; 
 &UR; PROBLEMS AT THE WAR-CRIMES TRIBUNAL &LR; 
 &UR; By THEODOR MERON &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Foreign Affairs Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   In the fall of 1997 the judges of the International Criminal
Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia will complete their four-year
terms. By now, their frustration underscores the need for a careful
evaluation of the tribunal's record and prospects. Theodor Meron is
Charles L. Denison Professor of Law at the New York University
School of Law. He assisted Richard Goldstone in the prosecution of
indicted war criminal Dusan Tadic in 1995. (slugged:
BC-ATROCITIES-UNPUNISHED-NYTSF, priority code r, category codes
k,i)
 &UR; LIFESTYLE: &LR; 
 &UR; PORTRAIT OF A TEEN SUICIDE  &MD;  MINE &LR; 
 &UR; (1,200 words)
 &UR; World rights.
This is free-lance writer Frank Crow's gripping and important
first-person account of how at age 19 he shot himself in the chest
while despondent over his love for another boy. Miraculously, he
survived. Now, 55 years later, Crow tells his story and pleads with
today's troubled teens not to ``pull the trigger'' on themselves.
(slugged: BC-MY-SUICIDE-ATTEMPT-NYTSF, priority code r, category
codes k and l)
 &UR; ENTERTAINMENT: &LR; 
 &UR; FILMMAKING IN NEW ORLEANS: HOLLYWOOD'S BIG ON THE BIG EASY &LR; 
 &UR; (1,200 words)
 &UR; World rights except Boston, Great Britain and Australia.
 &UR; Color slides and B&AMP;W photos of the casts of the TV shows
``Orleans'' (including Larry Hagman) and ``The Big Easy''
available.
 &UR; By IVOR DAVIS &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   Not all the crowds in New Orleans are there for Super Bowl
Sunday (Jan. 29) or Mardi Gras (Feb. 11). Hollywood-based
journalist Ivor Davis reports on the myriad directors, producers,
actors and actress who have descended on the city in the hopes of
capturing some of The Big Easy's legendary mystique. Includes
interviews with actor Larry Hagman, director Alan Parker and New
Orleans native, news anchor Cokie Roberts. (slugged:
BC-IVOR-HOLLYWOOD'S-NEW-ORLEANS-FEVER-ART-NYTSF, priority code r,
category code e)
<p>
   Thank you very much,
<p>
   The New York Times Syndicate
<p>
    &UR; (New York headquarters: 212-499-3300 or 1-800-972-3550; fax,
212-499-3382.) &LR; 
