<DOCID> nyt970122.0248 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9000 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-US-STOCKS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0326 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-STOCKS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. STOCKS FALL AS WEAK PROFITS DRAG IBM, DJIA LOWER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Roger Madoff and Philip Boroff &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. stocks retreated as
International Business Machines Corp.'s weaker-than-expected profit
dragged the Dow Jones Industrial Average lower.
<p>
   Weak demand for a $17.5 billion sale of two-year government
notes boosted yields, contributing to stocks' retreat.
<p>
   The Dow industrials fell 68.50 to 6815.40, with some 31 points
of the decline attributable to IBM. The world's largest computer
maker sank 10 to 159 3/8.
<p>
   ``We'll have some earnings disappointments,'' and those
companies' shares will suffer, said Kenneth Corba, chief investment
officer at Eagle Asset Management, which oversees $2.7 billion.
Still, ``I don't the market's overvalued in the context of all of
the positives,'' he said. ``You have declining interest rates;
corporate America's become more profitable and more competitive.
We're in an hospitable environment.''
<p>
   Compaq Computer Corp. and Dean Witter Discover Co. added
surprisingly strong earnings announcements to this week's pile of
profit reports, helping broader averages set records for a fifth
straight session.
<p>
   The benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index, which comprises 75
percent of the market capitalization of U.S. stocks, gained 0.30 to
783.02, losing a 2.54-point gain after bonds retreated. Johnson &AMP;
Johnson, General Electric Co. and Intel Corp. offset IBM's decline.
<p>
   The Nasdaq Composite Index, which includes many computer stocks,
gained 5.87 to 1382.84, after rising as much as 10.30 points.
Microsoft Corp. led the advance for a third day.
<p>
   Stocks fell back after the yield on the 30-year U.S. Treasury
bond rose 3 basis points to 6.81 percent. The yield is used as a
benchmark for corporate borrowing costs, so when it rises it can
hurt companies' bottom lines.
</TEXT>
