<DOCID> nyt970122.0249 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tab-z> A9006 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EVITA-FEMINIST-HERO-N </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1514 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EVITA-FEMINIST-HERO-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EVITA: THE UNLIKELY FEMINIST &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
 &MD;  the rate is not prohibitive  &MD;  from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: &LR; 
<p>
   (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. &LR; 
<p>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR; 
<p>
   (--Latin America: PAUL FINCH in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax,
310-996-0089. &LR; 
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice  &MD;  into the
``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.
 &UR; By MARIO SZICHMAN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   The era in which the heroine we call Evita forged her career was
an exciting one for actresses.
<p>
   In the late 1930s, in Buenos Aires  &MD;  performing as Eva Durante  &MD; 
she landed a few small parts in a weekly radio series.
<p>
   By 1943, as Eva Duarte, she had a few minor film roles and then
became a star in a radio soap opera called ``My Kingdom for Love.''
There she began to enact roles of famous women  &MD;  public figures
whose lives might have given the future first lady a few ideas on
how to achieve immortality.
<p>
   Among those roles were Queen Elizabeth I; Empress Josephine, who
was Napoleon's wife; Madame Chiang Kai-shek; and Tsarina Alexandra
of Russia, who was killed with her entire family by the Bolsheviks.
Their lives might have carried a vital lesson: to neither be a
widow nor to die simultaneously with one's husband.
<p>
   By 1943 in Argentina, members of the ruling military junta were
in strong sympathy with the Axis nations  &MD;  Japan, Italy and
Germany. Taking a political cue from such unsavory role models as
Adolf Hitler and Benito Mussolini, they also imitated the Nazi and
fascist predilection for choosing mistresses who were chorus girls
and actresses.
<p>
   By 1944, when Evita caught the eye of Col. Juan Peron, she was
having a passing affair with another colonel, Anibal Imbert, who
was considerably down from Peron on the scale of power, as the
minister of communications.
<p>
   But when the owner of the radio station where Evita was the star
learned about her relationship with Imbert, he immediately raised
her salary from 150 pesos to 5,000 per month.
<p>
   It was an intelligent decision taking into account that one of
the tasks of the Ministry of Communications was to control the
radio stations.
<p>
   At the time, competition among actresses to win the minds and
hearts of colonels was a ferocious game. Politicians and
journalists were able to detect which colonels were rapidly
ascending the power ladder just by taking a look at which actresses
they were escorting. It seemed that the more prominent the actress,
the more promising the colonel's career.
<p>
   Evita was one of those leading ladies who fought strenuously to
stay in the race.
<p>
   One story that circulated during this time was that she met
Peron during a fund-raising effort for victims of an earthquake
that destroyed the northern city of San Juan. Evita was escorted to
the event by Imbert.
<p>
   But when she saw Libertad Lamarque, the famous actress and tango
singer, talking to Peron  &MD;  the driving force in the ruling military
 &MD;  Evita asked to be introduced. It was the last time she and
Lamarque were on friendly terms. From then on, there was a
relentless feud between them, which ended on the set of the movie
``The Circus Cavalcade,'' which they were both filming.
<p>
   One day Evita, trying to show that circumstances had changed
after her engagement to Peron, decided to sit in the chair with
Libertad Lamarque's name on it. The star reacted by making the
worst mistake of her life: She slapped Evita's face.
<p>
   In 1946, after Peron became president, Lamarque was forced into
exile in Mexico City and her films were banned in Argentina.
<p>
   (``There is no more freedom in Argentina after Libertad left the
country,'' complained the opposition, making a word play with
Lamarque's first name.)
<p>
   It is difficult to imagine what could have happened in
Argentina, though, if Lamarque had married Peron instead of Evita.
As difficult, perhaps, as trying to imagine what could have
happened if the prim actress Ann Archer had landed Evita's role in
the blockbuster movie instead of Golden Globe-winner Madonna.
<p>
   But knowing the personalities of Lamarque and Evita, it is safe
to assume that the former, who had a basically demure personality,
would not have become immortal in Argentinean politics. Evita,
however, was all fire.
<p>
   In spite of the age difference between Evita  &MD;  who was 24  &MD;  and
Peron  &MD;  who was 48 when they first met  &MD;  she was an equal partner
in the marriage.
<p>
   Nothing in common with the other Eva, the mistress of Hitler,
who followed the Fuehrer, in eating a piece of wedding cake and
then swallowing a cyanide pill  &MD;  going along with him submissively
to consummate a suicide pact.
<p>
   And it was precisely this equality of a former actress and a
military president that infuriated those very military men who used
to relish  &MD;  and brag about  &MD;  keeping the company of actresses.
<p>
   And whereas Peron never felt comfortable in the midst of people,
Evita loved to be surrounded by crowds, and hear for hours on end
the plight of the humble ones. Moreover, if kissing the sores of
the lepers is commonly associated with sainthood, Evita certainly
had claims to the title of saint because on several occasions she
did exactly that.
<p>
   But she was remembered most not for her theatrical gestures, or
her scorching-earth personality or her jewels, clothes and hairdos,
but for the political accomplishments which, in her own time, made
her the butt of jokes as well as the most hatred woman in
Argentinean oligarchy.
<p>
   An unlikely feminist hero, she was during the Peronist era the
main promoter of the women's right to vote. An unlikely champion of
leftist causes, in her designer dresses, she fought nonetheless for
the rights and dignity of workers, children and old people. And
this was in a country where the ruling class did not even try to
hide its visible contempt for people who did not run a household
full of servants.
<p>
   And the imprint of Evita's personality marked Peron's life after
she died, in July, 1952, at the tragically young age of 33, from
uterine cancer, even as he looked vainly for emulators.
<p>
   First it was Josephine Baker, the famous nightclub singer, who
in November, 1952, went to Buenos Aires from Paris, as part of an
international tour. So impressed with Baker was the widowed Peron
that he created the World Cultural Association, with her as its
president. Its goal was to fight racial and religious
discrimination.
<p>
   But brief was to be her attention to those scourges of mankind
because some days later, Peron gave Baker a new task. He appointed
her an inspector in the Ministry of Health. Baker took that job to
heart, discovering so many irregularities that after countless
spats with Ramon Carrillo, the minister of health, she decided to
leave the country.
<p>
   Later Carrillo sent a letter to Peron complaining about Baker's
browbeatings, and what seemed to be her penchant for ``imitating in
her acts and social views the most reverend Senora Eva Peron.''
<p>
   After his overthrow, in 1955, Peron started his long exile,
first in Paraguay, then in Venezuela and, after that, in Panama,
where he met a chorus girl, Isabel Martinez. She would become
Evita's worst understudy  &MD;  and her most successful  &MD;  as Peron's
running mate, in 1973.
<p>
   Although ``Isabelita'' wore her hair combed straight back and
tied in a chignon  &MD;  as many women today are doing in imitation of
Madonna's Evita style  &MD;  and imitated some of Evita's mannerisms,
she lacked both the glamour that Madonna wisely infuses into her
role and the conviction to carry out her ideas.
<p>
   Besides, the two women were at opposite poles. Whereas Evita
tried always to exact revenge from the evil dogs who tried to
humiliate her, Isabelita wanted only the approval of her enemies.
<p>
   Indeed, Evita had understudies and emulators  &MD;  but she was a
hard act to follow.
<p>
    &UR; (Mario Szichman, an Argentinean novelist and essayist who now
lives in New York, is the author of ``At 8:25 Evita Became
Immortal'' and three other books in a series on a Jewish family's
travails during the Peronist era.) &LR; 
<p>
   --------------- &QC; 
