<DOCID> nyt970122.0255 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=k pri=r sel=tab-z> A9014 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ATROCITIES-UNPUNISHED </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1542 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ATROCITIES-UNPUNISHED-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PROBLEMS AT THE WAR-CRIMES TRIBUNAL &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; (For purchase information  &MD;  the rates are not prohibitive --
contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives: &LR; 
<p>
   (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. &LR; 
<p>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR; 
<p>
   (--Latin America: PAUL FINCH in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax,
310-996-0089. &LR; 
 &UR; By THEODOR MERON &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Foreign Affairs Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice, into the
``i'' international and ``k'' commentary files.
<p>
   In the fall of 1997 the judges of the International Criminal
Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia will complete their four-year
terms.
<p>
   If top and mid-level leaders indicted by the tribunal have not
been arrested and delivered to The Hague by then, Antonio Cassese,
the tribunal's president, has threatened to propose that the
Security Council terminate the tribunal's mandate.
<p>
   Cassese's warning echoes similar calls for top-level arrests
from former chief prosecutor Richard Goldstone, justice of the
South African Constitutional Court, and Louise Arbour, his
successor from the Ontario Court of Appeals.
<p>
   Their frustration underscores the need for a careful evaluation
of the tribunal's record and prospects.
<p>
   The U.N. Security Council established the tribunal on May 25,
1993, in response to the deliberate, systematic and outrageous
violations of human rights and humanitarian norms during the
Balkans war.
<p>
   Atrocities committed include summary executions, torture, rape,
arbitrary mass internment, deportation and displacement,
hostage-taking, inhuman treatment of prisoners, indiscriminate
shelling of cities and unwarranted destruction of private property.
<p>
   Of the 74 persons indicted for such atrocities, one has pleaded
guilty and been sentenced to 10 years imprisonment, five are
currently in custody awaiting trial and one  &MD;  Dusan Tadic, a
Bosnian Serb accused of committing abuses against Muslims in the
Omarska concentration camp in Bosnia  &MD;  is on trial.
<p>
   None of the seven, however, are top political or military
leaders who gave the key orders. The absence of such leaders among
those in custody has led Cassese to assert that the General
Framework Agreement for Peace in Bosnia and Herzegovina reached at
Dayton in November 1995 ``is becoming an exercise in hypocrisy.''
<p>
   Initially the tribunal's founders hoped the trials would defuse
ethnic tensions and assist in peacemaking.
<p>
   They also hoped that enforcing accountability would deter
violations of global humanitarian law in Yugoslavia and elsewhere.
And because the Hague tribunal was established while the war was
still raging  &MD;  in contrast to the Nuremberg war-crimes trials,
which began only after World War II had been fought and won  &MD;  there
was even a chance it might stop the war sooner.
<p>
   Conversely, failure to establish the tribunal would have made it
appear that even the most egregious crimes against humanity could
go unpunished.
<p>
   In the former Yugoslavia, the prospects for reunification and
reconciliation were poor from the beginning  &MD;  given the tremendous
scale of atrocities, the hatred and suspicion between ethnic groups
and the irresponsible leaders thriving on extreme nationalism and
violence.
<p>
   From its inception, the tribunal has been plagued by the lack of
cooperation from Serbian leaders in Belgrade, Bosnian-Serb leaders
in Pale and Croatian leaders in Zagreb.
<p>
   In contrast to Nuremberg, where the Allies had unlimited police
power on the ground, the tribunal has had to depend on the
readiness of the Security Council and the international community
to exert pressure for full compliance on reluctant parties.
<p>
   But it has rarely worked. Suspects have been sheltered and
protected. Access to sites where atrocities were committed has been
obstructed, hindering the collection of perishable evidence.
Witnesses, even victims, have withheld their testimony.
<p>
   That no witness for the prosecution in the Dusan Tadic case
still lives in an area under the control of Pale or Belgrade speaks
to the ever-present fear of reprisal among those who might testify.
<p>
   At the governmental level, Republika Srpska, the Serb-majority
entity in Bosnia, has failed to execute any of the scores of arrest
warrants it has been sent. The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia has
not arrested any of the indictees on its territory. Croatia has
detained one, but has so far failed to deliver him up to The Hague.
<p>
   Zagreb's limited cooperation with the tribunal, to which it
committed in the Dayton agreements, has been a small price to pay
for Croatia's growing international legitimacy. Indeed, it was
recently admitted to the Council of Europe, often seen as a way
station en route to the European Union.
<p>
   The international community has given the tribunal strong
rhetorical support, but little aid in enforcement.
<p>
   In addition, the tribunal has faced budgetary difficulties. Were
it not for favorable public opinion, government and U.N. backing
for both the tribunal and its budget would be even weaker.
<p>
   Cassese and Goldstone opted to devote much of their time to
mobilizing public opinion behind the tribunal and its mission.
Goldstone's successor, chief prosecutor Arbour, will probably find
it necessary to do the same.
<p>
   The fact that the tribunal's list of indictees was for a long
time composed solely of Serbs exacerbated the Serbs' siege
mentality and fueled their complaint that they were the only
target.
<p>
   If IFOR could not carry out arrests with the tremendous
firepower of its 60,000 troops in Bosnia, surely no arrests will be
attempted as the NATO force dwindles and ultimately withdraws.
<p>
   The great hope of tribunal advocates was that the
individualization and decollectivization of guilt  &MD;  placing
responsibility on the leaders and the perpetrators of atrocities,
rather than on whole communities  &MD;  would help bring about peace and
reconciliation.
<p>
   The tribunal's critics argued that it would obstruct peace
negotiations. How, they protested, could those who make decisions
at the negotiating table be expected to agree to provisions that
might endanger their leadership and bring them to justice?
<p>
   The irony is that both sides were proved wrong.
<p>
   Because of the international community's reluctance or inability
to enforce indictments, the tribunal has had no major impact,
positive or negative, on national reconciliation.
<p>
   Perhaps the realization that the tribunal's days may be numbered
unless indicted leaders and perpetrators are arrested and delivered
up to The Hague may yet shock the international community into
action.
<p>
   Folding the tribunal before it has tried a substantial number of
major culprits would be immensely embarrassing to both the global
community and to the United States, which has given the tribunal
more political, budgetary and logistical support than any other
nation.
<p>
   Recently, nations worldwide have been more ready to prosecute
human rights and humanitarian atrocities, including Korea, where
even ex-presidents have been convicted, Ethiopia and Honduras.
<p>
   In South Africa, prosecutions are under way against persons who
did not cooperate fully with its Truth Commission by coming
forward, reporting on injustices during apartheid and seeking
amnesty.
<p>
   It is not absurd to suggest that in a few years Belgrade, Zagreb
or even Pale might have more responsible leaders and more credible
criminal-justice systems, and might be ready to prosecute before
their courts some of those indicted by the tribunal.
<p>
   But from now on, international criminal tribunals must be more
effectively supported by police power. Just as there can be no
national justice without a police force, there can be no effective
international justice without arrests, subpoenas, investigations
and a reliable enforcement method.
<p>
   The international community's inability to create such a
mechanism threatens all efforts to create a system of international
criminal justice.
<p>
   But we must not give up in despair.
<p>
    &UR; (Theodor Meron is Charles L. Denison Professor of Law at the
New York University School of Law. He assisted Richard Goldstone in
the prosecution of indicted war criminal Dusan Tadic in 1995. This
article is adapted from a longer version in Foreign Affairs.) &LR; 
<p>
   --------------
