<DOCID> nyt970122.0259 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=i pri=s sel=tad-z> A9020 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TRINIDAD-RACE-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1302 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TRINIDAD-RACE-COX  &QL; 
 &UR; ON TINY WEST INDIAN ISLAND, RACE RELATIONS DOMINATE DEBATE, LIFE
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; Eds: This story was budgeted as TRINIDAD-POLITICS-COX
<p>
    &UR; With TRINIDAD-WEALTH and TRINIDAD-GLANCE; COX Photos to move
<p>
    &UR; For release weekend of Jan. 25-26
<p>
    &UR; By SHELLEY EMLING
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR; 
<p>
   PORT OF SPAIN, Trinidad  &MD;  On this West Indian island of
blood-red bougainvillea and towering palm trees, a floundering
economy has brought a rise in homelessness and vagrancy.
<p>
   As a transit point for South American cocaine destined for the
U.S. mainland  &MD;  about 1,000 kilos pass through here each month  &MD;  it
has seen an increase in drug use as well.
<p>
   But when asked about his country's most pressing problems, Prime
Minister Basdeo Panday unexpectedly reveals a flaming commitment to
racial harmony, not reducing crime or inflation rates.
<p>
   ``Because of suspicions and underlying antagonisms, we have
never been able to do all we are capable of doing,'' said Panday
who, in November 1995, was sworn in as Trinidad's first prime
minister of East Indian descent. ``Since coming to office, I've
tried to assure people that all will be treated fairly and they
will.''
<p>
   Panday's response underscores the importance of an issue that's
shaped debates here for decades.
<p>
   Race is is deliberated in taxi cabs, at fruit stands, on talk
shows, even as Trinidad struggles to recover from a severe 15-year
recession brought on by the global oil price collapse that pummeled
its oil and natural gas industry. It's discussed even as it tries
to stem a wave of violent crimes, 70 percent of which are drug
related.
<p>
   It's not hard to see why.
<p>
   This most southern of all Caribbean islands seems to draw its
population from every conceivable social and ethnic group. It is a
place where it's just as easy to buy pig's feet as it is to eat
chung pow pork.
<p>
   More than 80 percent of the country's 1.5 million people can
trace their ancestry to Africa or India, and today the two groups
are of equal size. The rest of the people are mixed race, Chinese
and Syrian.
<p>
   ``Race is the only issue when it comes to Trinidad,'' said Ken
Boodhoo, a Trinidadian professor of international relations at
Florida International University in Miami. ``It's an issue that's
been around for 200 years.''
<p>
   And it's an issue that's only picked up steam with the election
of Panday, the grandson of indentured Hindu laborers brought to
work on British-owned sugar plantations in Trinidad in 1908.
<p>
   Panday, the leader of the United National Congress party, was
elected by the slimmest of margins. He holds a two-seat majority in
parliament.
<p>
   But the results represented a dramatic shift of power in
Trinidad and its sister island, Tobago, where blacks had been in
charge since independence from Britain in 1962. The shift followed
a long history of racial friction, including ``black power''
protests in the 1970s that twice led to the declaration of a state
of emergency.
<p>
   Panday, 64, campaigned on a platform of ``national unity'' and
has spent his first year in office trying to reassure blacks that
he won't hurt their interests.
<p>
   He established a public holiday to honor Spiritual Baptists, who
blend African and Christian beliefs. He granted a Christmas bonus
to mostly black street cleaners, trash collectors and other
government workers.
<p>
   ``There was trepidation among Africans when I first came to
office,'' said Panday in an interview. ``So I've had to stabilize
society, assuring everyone that I wouldn't upset the apple cart.''
<p>
   But Panday's overtures have prompted Indians to accuse him of
inverse discrimination, exacerbating racial discord.
<p>
   ``In the past, most state scholarships were given to blacks and
there was discrimination against Indians,'' said Sat Maharaj,
secretary general of the Sanatan Dharma Maha Sabha, one of
Trinidad's largest Hindu organizations. ``And now the danger is
that Panday will bend over backwards to please the Africans to such
an extent that Indians will still be discriminated against.''
<p>
   Blacks don't see it that way, and fear domination by a people
that already holds sway over the economy.
<p>
   ``Blacks always felt that as long as they controlled the
government, it was o.k. if Indians controlled commerce,'' said
Selwyn Ryan, the black director of the Center for Ethnic Studies at
the University of the West Indies.``But now with the election of
Panday, many blacks feel that the balance of power has been tipped
too much.''
<p>
    &UR; (Story can end here. Optional adds follow.) &LR; 
<p>
   In the years after British rule began in 1797, Africans were
brought over as slaves to work sugar and cocoa plantations. After
emancipation in 1838, labor became scarce and Indians were brought
over to work the farms.
<p>
   Since independence from Britain in 1962, each group has
prospered in its own way. Blacks have controlled government and
thereby largely dominated civil service and government jobs. At the
same time, many Indians succeeded in family-controlled businesses
and in professions, especially medicine.
<p>
   Each group believes the other has prospered more than it has.
Members of both races use racial slurs casually, and both have
formed well-defined perceptions about the other.
<p>
   Blacks call Indians ostentatious and materialistic, often
pointing out that the most-decorated homes at Christmastime are the
ones owned by Indians. For their part, Indians call blacks lazy and
easygoing, adding that they prefer partying and spending to working
and saving.
<p>
   ``Indians often use the word nigger when referring to blacks,
and blacks often use the word coolie when referring to Indians,''
said Rhona Baptiste, who owns a bookstore here. ``But this is a
small country, and people of different races are friends, and
everyone is intimately involved with each other.''
<p>
   Coolie is a derogatory term for a person of Indian descent.
<p>
   While it's true that Indians and blacks dine together, work
together, visit each other's homes and even inter-marry, this
social civility has never translated into harmony at the political
level.
<p>
   Recently, for example, nightclub owners started holding separate
events for blacks, whites and Indians, calling it ``niche
marketing.'' But representatives of all races have accused the
clubs of discrimination, and Attorney General Ramesh Maharaj has
introduced legislation to revoke the licenses of clubs that
segregate patrons.
<p>
    &UR; (Story can end here. Optional add follows.) &LR; 
<p>
   Many residents are hoping that as people grow accustomed to the
change in leadership, the country will be able to move beyond the
race issue and get on with the business of economic development.
<p>
   A new $1 billion liquefied natural gas plant is in the works,
and stands to become the country's largest single investment.
<p>
   And to attract U.S. investors and tourists, Trinidad and Tobago
plans to open its first consulate in Miami later this year.
<p>
   Panday has worked hard to develop a close relationship with the
United States.
<p>
   Trinidad was the first country in the Caribbean to sign a ``hot
pursuit'' pact allowing U.S. ships and planes to pursue suspected
illegal drug carriers into territorial waters and airspace. It was
the only Caribbean country visited by Secretary of State Warren
Christopher last March during a trip to Latin America. Over the
next two years, U.S. firms plan to invest more than $3 billion,
mostly in the petrochemical, oil and gas, and iron and steel
industries.
<p>
   ``I think things will get better once people realize that an
Indian prime minister can serve people of all races,'' Baptiste
said. ``People will realize that the sun still shines, and that it
still rains, and that the sky isn't going to fall.''
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
    &UR; For use by clients of the New York Times News Service &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
