<DOCID> nyt970122.0262 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tia-z> A9027 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRIER-SUPER-BOWL- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0308 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HKN-GRIER-SUPER-BOWL-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EDMONTON OILERS' MIKE GRIER HAS SPECIAL INTEREST IN SUPER BOWL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Michael Buteau &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Edmonton, Alberta, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Like most of his
teammates, Edmonton Oilers rookie right wing Mike Grier will be
watching the Super Bowl on Sunday.
<p>
   Unlike his teammates, Grier has a personal interest in the game
between the New England Patriots and Green Bay Packers. His father,
Bobby Grier, is the Patriots' director of player personnel.
<p>
   ``It's kind of an emotional game for me,'' said Grier, who grew
up in Holliston, Massachusetts, and has been a Patriots fan his
whole life. ``Hopefully they can win.''
<p>
   Before he can turn his mind to football though, Grier will have
to focus on his team's hockey game against the Capitals in
Washington.
<p>
   ``Luckily our game is in the afternoon (noon Washington time),''
Grier said, ``so I'll have plenty of time to watch the Super
Bowl.''
<p>
   The Super Bowl starts about six hours later in New Orleans.
<p>
   The 22-year-old Grier, who at 6-foot-1, 235 pounds could almost
pass for an NFL linebacker. Grier said his choice of hockey over
football was geographically influenced.
<p>
   ``I basically grew up my whole life in Massachusetts and it's a
pretty big hockey area,'' he said. ``Once I got into it and started
playing, I really fell in love with it.''
<p>
   Grier's father was the Patriots running backs coach in 1985 when
the Chicago Bears trounced New England 46-10 in Super Bowl XX.
<p>
   His son, who won a national championship with Boston University
in 1995, hopes Dad has better luck the second time around.
<p>
   ``In '85 things didn't go so well,'' said Grier, who has five
goals and nine assists in 45 games with Edmonton this season. ``I'm
just glad he has another shot at it.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1437EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0263 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=k pri=u sel=ttj-z> A9028 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0846 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV26-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For Release Sunday, Jan. 26) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IS CLINTON'S UNITY CALL FANTASY OR REALITY? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT E. THOMPSON &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Hearst Newspapers &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  If Bill Clinton were a painter, his rendering of
the 21st century would be a massive mural in which America would be
depicted as a land radiating ``a new spirit of community for a new
century.''
<p>
   In bold strokes and vivid colors, the president would people his
landscape with ancient adversaries  &MD;  Democrats and Republicans,
liberals and conservatives, blacks and whites, rich and poor,
Christians and Jews, old and young  &MD;  who have tasted the milk of
human compassion and become addicted to it.
<p>
   Cynicism, acrimony and prejudice would have no place in the
tranquil scene sketched by the man from Hope.
<p>
   ``Our rich texture of racial, religious and political diversity
will be a godsend in the 21st Century, '' proclaimed the president
at the beginning of his second term. ``Great rewards will come to
those who can live together, learn together, work together, forge
new ties that bind together.''
<p>
   When in November the American people elected a Democratic
president and a Republican Congress, Clinton contended, they did
not do so to advance ``the politics of petty bickering and extreme
partisanship.''
<p>
   Instead, he said, they called on us to ``be repairers of the
breach and to move on with America's mission.''
<p>
   Thus did the 42nd president chart a course in which people will
work and serve together in a common endeavor to enrich a land of
new promise.
<p>
   But were the eloquent words just a fantasy, an unreal belief
that a president can cement such a bond with his adversaries and
then move in tandem with them toward a glorious future?
<p>
   Other presidents have promised to work with the opposition in a
bipartisan effort. But eventually they have had to recognize the
reality that politicians and political parties are in stiff
competition with each other and, therefore, must oppose each other.
<p>
   Yet Clinton is determined to give it a try. Rarely if ever has a
president filled his inaugural address with such grandiloquent
overtures to his political foes.
<p>
   The day after his inaugural, Clinton said he intended to meet
the Republicans ``halfway'' on several major issues, including
Medicare. In the budget that he will submit to Congress on Feb. 6,
Clinton will include $138 billion in proposed spending cuts over a
six-year period.
<p>
   What he foresees in the 21st Century, said Clinton, is a nation
that ``balances its budget but never loses the balance of its
values; a nation where our grandparents have secure retirement and
health care, and their grandchildren know we have made the reforms
necessary to sustain those benefits for their time.''
<p>
   Although the times and the circumstances are vastly changed,
Clinton sees himself as a president in the mold of Thomas
Jefferson, who at the beginning of the 19th Century doubled the
size of the United States with the Louisiana Purchase, and Theodore
Roosevelt, who helped America ``harness the Industrial Revolution
to our values of free enterprise, conservation and human decency''
at the dawn of this century.
<p>
   Presidents carefully select the predecessor they wish to
emulate.
<p>
   In 1992, when he was hanging on the ropes, George Bush tried
desperately to make it appear that he was about to score a
startling upset just as Harry Truman did in 1948.
<p>
   But Clinton was even more adept at drawing a comparison between
himself and the plain-spoken Missourian. Receiving the support of
Truman's daughter, Margaret, he journeyed to Independence, Mo., to
identify himself with Truman.
<p>
   That comparison no longer is necessary to Clinton. Where Truman
won votes and scored political points by giving the Republicans
hell, Clinton has decided he can achieve the same objective by
locking arms with them.
<p>
   Having declared the era of big government to be over, it isn't
wise for him to try to don the mantle of Franklin D. Roosevelt.
<p>
   It is far better for him to try to carve a career molded after
that of Teddy Roosevelt, an energetic and enlightened leader who
forced social and economic reform upon the Republican Party and
decreed that America was a world power.
<p>
   At the start of his second term, Clinton obviously is seeking a
prominent niche in the pantheon of presidents. He is determined to
do and say those things that will at last make his presidency an
historic one.
<p>
   His objective, he said, is to help a free people ``shape the
forces of the information age and the global society, to unleash
the limitless potential of all our people and, yes, to form a more
perfect union.''
<p>
   The meaning of the canvas he has painted is best found in the
words of the dying Cardinal Joseph Bernardin that he quoted: ``It
is wrong to waste the precious gift of time on acrimony and
division.''
<p>
   The great test of Clinton's last four years in the White House
will be to further endow and preserve the glowing panorama he has
painted.
</TEXT>
