<STORYID cat=i pri=u sel=ttj-z> A9035 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-KOHL-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0533 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-KOHL-FOOD-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; KOHL'S SECRET OF SUCCESS: DON'T JOG, DON'T DIET AND BE YOURSELF &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; A News Analysis &LR;  &QL;  (For use by New York Times News Service
clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BERNARD D. KAPLAN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Hearst Newspapers &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   PARIS  &MD;  Hannalore Kohl, the wife of Germany's grossly overweight
chancellor, has just published a calorifically challenging cookbook
of her husband's favorite fare: dishes like cholesterol-laden
sauerbraten, fatty sausages and pork and red cabbage drowning in
lard.
<p>
   It's become a best-seller.
<p>
   Gastronomic correctness clearly has no place in the Kohl family
kitchen. Thereby hangs a political tale.
<p>
   To borrow the jargon of the diet gurus, Helmut Kohl is what he
eats.
<p>
   He's a supremely unself-conscious figure who pays no attention
to his heroic girth and hasn't the slightest urge to look trim.
<p>
   His confident disdain for being other than he is has helped to
make him an astonishingly successful politician.
<p>
   The voters don't seem to care what he looks like, either. They
just keep putting him in office.
<p>
   He may be the only major political figure of our time who is
genuinely comfortable with himself  &MD;  and that goes also for his
ample waistline.
<p>
   Somehow, this has gotten through to the German public. It has
made him unassailable in their eyes.
<p>
   The German economy is floundering and unemployment has hit a
record high, but, remarkably, none of the political fallout has
rubbed off on Kohl personally.
<p>
   ``Kohl never pretends, never fakes it,'' according to German
political writer Anne-Marie Kroller. ``Of how many other
politicians can this be said?''
<p>
   His 15-year stint as chancellor has broken the postwar longevity
record of his mentor, Konrad Adenauer. Most analysts consider it
all but certain he will surpass the all-time German record of 18
years set by Otto von Bismarck in the 19th century.
<p>
   Kohl towers over the 15-nation European Union and will probably
fulfill his ambition to enter history as the father of European
political integration.
<p>
   He is a fat man in a political world otherwise dominated by thin
men or, at least, as in Bill Clinton's case, by leaders
demonstrating through the media their obsession with fitness. Even
Boris Yeltsin, before illness laid him low, made sure the TV
cameras were rolling whenever he played tennis.
<p>
   Kohl scorns all this. In his lone concession to his tailor, he
retreats every summer to an Austrian lake for two weeks where his
intake is said to consist of nothing but sauerkraut juice.
<p>
   But journalists are never invited to witness the ordeal. There
are no photo opportunities to show the chancellor guzzling his
liquid diet or, God forbid, exercising.
<p>
   When he returns to Bonn, observers invariably note that his suit
jackets still stretch tautly over his ample front.
<p>
   To describe Kohl as out-of-shape is like saying Al Gore may
occasionally weigh the possibility of running for president.
<p>
   Yet he is proof that, contrary to what most modern politicians
and their spin doctors believe, image is not everything.
<p>
   Contentedly shoveling down Frau Kohl's dumplings, the rotund
chancellor has emerged as a political pin-up who is the envy of
svelter but lesser men.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1439EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
