<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-AIRLINES-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0262 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-VENEZUELA-AIRLINES-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; VENEZUELA SAYS ONLY FOUR JETS MEET U.S. NOISE REGULATIONS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Peter Wilson and Carlos Camacho &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Caracas, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Venezuela's government said only
four of the country's commercial jets meet U.S. noise regulations,
which could result in reduced service to that country.
<p>
   Transportation Minister Moises Graterol Orozco said all four
belong to Aerovias Venezolanas SA, the country's largest domestic
airline.
<p>
   ``Only four aircraft are fit to enter the U.S.,'' said Graterol
Orozco.
<p>
   Many of Venezuela's jets, mostly older Boeing 727's, 737's and
DC-9s, don't meet U.S. sound regulations adopted in 1990. The jets
have to be fitted with so-called hush kits that reduce their engine
noise. Kits cost about US$1.4 million to $2 million a plane, which
many Venezuelan carriers can't afford, officials said.
<p>
   Yesterday, Aerovias Venezolanas said its Servivensa unit
temporarily suspended daily service to New York and reduced its
flights to Miami because some of its aircraft don't meet U.S. noise
regulations.
<p>
   Servivensa's service to Miami and New York were suspended last
year after the U.S. said its jets didn't meet safety regulations,
leading the Federal Aviation Administration to threaten to revoke
the landing rights of all Venezuelan carriers, including
Servivensa.
<p>
   Avensa, as the airline is known, and Servivensa are partially
owned by H.L. Boulton &AMP; Co., a Caracas-based holding company, and
the Venezuelan government.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1439EST
</TRAILER>
