<DOCID> nyt970122.0270 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9039 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LION-ABC-UPDATE2 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0811 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FOOD-LION-ABC-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DISNEY'S ABC MUST PAY FOOD LION $5.5 MLN IN DAMAGES (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Joseph Menn &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Rewrites. Adds comments from ABC, Food Lion, jurors and
analyst. Adds details. Updates stock activity.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Greensboro, North Carolina, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Walt Disney
Co.'s ABC television network must pay Food Lion Inc. $5.5 million
in punitive damages for having two news producers lie to get jobs
at the supermarket chain, a federal jury decided.
<p>
   The verdict stunned media lawyers, who said the successful
attack on a program that didn't libel anyone would spur similar
suits and reduce the number of investigations that use hidden
cameras.
<p>
   ``People are going to think three or four times before they do
something like this,'' said Robert Sack, a libel defense lawyer for
Time Inc., the Wall Street Journal and Newsday. ``There are going
to be stories about health, safety and other possible misdeeds that
will never get out.''
<p>
   Food Lion's Class A shares rose 1/8 to 9 1/8 in midafternoon
trading of 536,900, more than its three-month daily average of
479,000. Disney's stock rose 1/8 to 69 7/8.
<p>
   After more than five days of hard-fought deliberations, the
12-member jury decided that ABC and its ``PrimeTime Live'' program
consciously broke fraud laws to get undercover footage for a 1992
expose on food handling at the supermarket chain.
<p>
   The producers faked resumes to get low-level Food Lion jobs
where they could report on and film the company's practices. One of
the producers hid a small camera in her wig. The program then
showed Food Lion employees rewrapping and displaying meat after the
``sell-by'' dates had expired.
<p>
   Salisbury, North Carolina-based Food Lion claimed the report
cost it more than $2 billion in lost profit and stock value. U.S.
District Judge Carlton Tilley barred Food Lion from using the
content of the broadcast as evidence.
<p>
   The jury, which last week said it was deadlocked 11-1, spared
the two producers, directing two higher-ranking ABC executives to
pay a combined $45,750. Former ``PrimeTime'' executive producer
Richard Kaplan, now elsewhere at ABC, was told to pay $35,000 and
Senior Producer Ira Rosen was ordered to pay $10,750.
<p>
   ``We're very satisfied with the verdict,'' said Food Lion
attorney Richard Wyatt.
<p>
   ABC said it would appeal ``through all available channels'' if
Tilley doesn't set the verdict aside.
<p>
   The judgment ``should trouble every American,'' the network said
in a statement. ``Food Lion has succeeded in convincing a jury to
punish ABC for using undercover investigating techniques that
exposed its unsanitary practices.''
<p>
   Jurors said the verdict was intended only to warn the media that
they have to obey the law and not make false statements.
<p>
   ``No one wants to handcuff the media,'' said jury foreman Greg
Mack. ``The real problem came (because) ABC had no guidelines.''
<p>
   Tony Kinton, a brewery worker in Reidsville, North Carolina,
said that he was the lone juror that hadn't wanted to award any
punitive damages. Others wanted to award billions of dollars and
some expressed their opinions before hearing any evidence, he said.
<p>
   ``We had no choice,'' Kinton said. ``We were going to send a
message to the press that there are limitations.''
<p>
   The verdict is the latest in a series of court decisions aimed
not at the content of news reports but at newsgathering techniques.
Rulings in the past year have allowed juries to consider whether
reporters invaded the privacy of accident victims and barred a
camera crew from following the son of an executive at U.S.
Healthcare Inc.
<p>
   ``People are angry at people who gather the news and the way
they gather the news, even when it is in the public interest,''
said libel lawyer Sack.
<p>
   In the Food Lion case, the Greensboro, North Carolina, jury last
month awarded $1,402 in compensatory damages, mostly for the
salaries earned by the producers at the stores.
<p>
   Sack predicted that the gap between the small compensatory
damages and the multimillion-dollar punitive award would prompt the
judge or the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to reduce the amount
of punitive damages.
<p>
   The slight rise in Food Lion's shares indicates that investors
realize that the chain must do more to win back customers, analysts
said. Food Lion has revamped its stores and preparation methods to
restore customer confidence.
<p>
   ``It's probably the safest place to buy perishables now,'' said
Salomon Brothers analyst Jonathon Ziegler.
<p>
   Sales, however, are not increasing as quickly as they had before
the show, when Food Lion was the fastest-growing grocer in the
country. And its net income hasn't recovered since 1992.
<p>
   Belgian grocery chain Delhaize-Le Lion SA owns about half Food
Lion's voting stock.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1440EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0271 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9040 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ALBRIGHT-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0341 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CONGRESS-ALBRIGHT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SENATE CONFIRMS MADELINE ALBRIGHT AS U.S. SECRETARY OF STATE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jenny Tomkins and Tom Ferraro &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Without dissent, the U.S. Senate
confirmed Madeline Albright as the first woman to be U.S. secretary
of state. Albright, who served as U.S. ambassador to the United
Nation's in the first Clinton administration, is the first
appointee to Clinton's second term cabinet to be approved by the
Senate. Today's 99-0 vote, the first Senate floor vote this year,
came two days after the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
unanimously recommended that she be confirmed. Albright was praised
by Democrats and Republicans alike, along with much of the U.S.
corporate community, which likes her pro-business positions. She
particularly pleased business leaders at her Jan. 8 confirmation
hearing when she told the Foreign Relations Committee that the
United States must seek to engage, not isolate China -- the world's
most populous nation. Albright testified that U.S. trade with Asia,
particularly China, is high on the Clinton administration's agenda.
``In Asia,'' she said, ``China is rapidly emerging as the next
great power in our era.'' Mattel Inc., and Boeing Co., are among
the major U.S. companies with financial interests in China.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   There have been repeated efforts in recent years to strip China
of the U.S.'s most-favored nation trading status because of human
rights violations. Those attempts have been thwarted, though, by
both Democratic and Republican administrations, which saw trade as
a key to relations with China. Albright also promised, as secretary
of state, to protect U.S. companies and workers in international
trade disputes.
<p>
   ``A principle responsibility of the Department of State is to
see that American companies and workers receive fair treatment and
that inequitable barriers to competition are overcome,'' she told
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee at its Jan. 8 hearing.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1441EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0272 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9041 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-US-STOCKS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0888 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-STOCKS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. STOCKS MIXED AS WEAK PROFITS DRAG IBM, DJIA LOWER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Roger Madoff and Philip Boroff &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. stocks were mixed as
International Business Machines Corp.'s weaker-than-expected profit
dragged the Dow Jones Industrial Average lower.
<p>
   The Dow industrials fell 60.81 to 6823.09, with some 32 points
of the decline attributable to IBM. The world's largest computer
maker sank 10 1/2 to 158 7/8.
<p>
   ``We'll have some earnings disappointments,'' and those
companies' shares will suffer, said Kenneth Corba, chief investment
officer at Eagle Asset Management, which oversees $2.7 billion.
Still, ``I don't the market's overvalued in the context of all of
the positives,'' he said. ``You have declining interest rates;
corporate America's become more profitable and more competitive.
We're in an hospitable environment.''
<p>
   Compaq Computer Corp. and Dean Witter Discover Co. added
surprisingly strong earnings announcements to this week's pile of
profit reports, helping broader averages set records for a fifth
straight session.
<p>
   The benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index, which comprises 75
percent of the market capitalization of U.S. stocks, gained 0.79 to
783.51. The index retreated, then bounced back after weak demand
for a $17.5 billion sale of two-year government notes sent bond
yields higher. Johnson &AMP; Johnson, General Electric Co. and Intel
Corp. offset IBM's decline.
<p>
   The Nasdaq Composite Index, which includes many computer stocks,
gained 5.87 to 1382.84, after rising as much as 10.30 points.
Microsoft Corp. led the advance for a third day.
<p>
   Mutual fund inflows continued to help shares. Mutual Fund Trim
Tabs, a newsletter that tracks money going to mutual funds, said
assets are pouring in at a $28.4 billion monthly pace, $500 million
short of the record set last January.
<p>
   ``You're having tremendous demand for stocks,'' said Philip
Brown, president of Meridian Investment Co., with $3.7 billion in
equities. ``You have an economy that isn't doing that bad.
Corporate profits aren't declining -- they just aren't going to be
up as much.''
<p>
   Fourth-quarter profit growth of 18 percent couldn't support IBM
shares, which had risen 66 percent in the year up to the report
released after the market's close yesterday. A stronger dollar and
weak demand in Europe hurt the bottom line. Net income for the
computer maker rose to $3.93 a share, 3 cents below analysts'
expectations.
<p>
   On the heels of surprisingly good numbers from Intel and
Microsoft, other computer-industry shares held up amid IBM's
retreat.
<p>
   Computer maker Dell Computer Corp. rose 1 3/4 to 65 7/8. Gateway
2000 Inc., a computer retailer, rose 2 1/8 to 61 3/8. Electronic
Data Systems Inc., a primary competitor for IBM's lucrative
computer services business, gained 1/4 to 47 3/4. Microsoft rose 2
to a record 97 and Intel jumped 3 5/16 to 151 3/8, a peak as well.
<p>
   ``I don't think IBM is the bellwether for technology, any more
than General Motors is the bellwether for the U.S. economy,'' said
Sally Anderson, a senior money manager at Kopp Investment Advisors,
which oversees $3.4 billion and holds about $8 million of IBM
stock.
<p>
   ``The economy has become much more diverse,'' Anderson said.
``There have been so many new companies, and they've diluted the
impact of the big ones.''
<p>
   The impact of IBM's disappointment was offset by
better-than-expected profits at the No. 1 maker of personal
computers, Compaq. The Houston-based computer maker said earnings
gained 43 percent, to $1.64 a share, surpassing expectations by 11
cents. Compaq jumped 5 1/8 to 83 5/8.
<p>
   Dean Witter Discover &AMP; Co., the brokerage and credit card
issuer, said profit rose 28 percent, topping forecasts. Its shares
gained 7/8 to 38.
<p>
   Bristol-Myers earnings rose 11 percent to $1.43 a share, 2 cents
above analysts' expectations, according to IBES International Inc.
The shares fell 1/8 to 121 1/2, after rising 12 percent from the
start of the year to yesterday, almost double the DJIA's gain in
the same period.
<p>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson jumped 3 3/8 to a record 56 7/8 after gaining
2 1/2 yesterday. The health-care product company said earnings rose
20 percent before trading began yesterday. Its shares have risen 31
percent in the past year.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T Corp. said its profit rose to 76 cents a share from 68
cents a year earlier. Analysts expected 80 cents a share, according
to IBES International Inc. The long-distance company's fell 7/8 to
38 1/2.
<p>
   Steris Corp. sank 8 1/8 to 29 7/8 after Bill Sanford, the
company's chairman and chief executive, told Dow Jones he expects
the medical device company to earn 38 cents a share in the fiscal
third quarter, below analysts' average expectation of 53 cents,
according to IBES.
<p>
   Norand Corp., a maker of mobile computers, surged 13 1/2 to 32
7/8 after Western Atlas Inc. said it would pay $261.3 million, or
$33.50 a share in cash, for all of Norand's 7.8 million shares.
Western Atlas fell 2 1/8 to 70.
<p>
   Gains in stocks were muted as the yield on the 30-year U.S.
Treasury bond rose 3 basis points to 6.81 percent. The yield is
used as a benchmark for corporate borrowing costs, so when it rises
it can hurt companies' bottom lines.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
