<SLUG> BC-EARNS-ALLEGHENY-TELED </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0587 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-ALLEGHENY-TELEDYNE-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ALLEGHENY TELEDYNE REPORTS HIGHER 4TH-QTR PROFIT (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Matthew J. Doherty &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
(Adds full-year results in 14th to 16th paragraphs.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Pittsburgh, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Allegheny Teledyne Inc.'s
fourth-quarter earnings exceeded expectations as profits at its
specialty metals, aerospace and electronics units more than offset
lower stainless steel prices.
<p>
   Profit from operations rose 31 percent to $68.2 million, or 40
cents a share, from pro forma profit from operations of $52.1
million, or 30 cents, in the year-earlier quarter. Revenue rose
less than 1 percent to $920.3 million from $914.7 million.
<p>
   The Pittsburgh-based company's profit from operations surpassed
the average estimate of 29 cents a share from five analysts polled
by First Call Corp.
<p>
   Allegheny's earnings were helped by the August acquisition of
Teledyne Inc. for $2.25 billion in stock, which transformed
stainless steel producer Allegheny Ludlum Corp. into the largest
U.S. producer of specialty metals.
<p>
   ``The year ended with upward earnings momentum,'' said William
Rutledge, Allegheny Teledyne's chief executive officer and
president, in a statement. ``Many of the synergies from our
business combination were put in place in the fourth quarter. These
moves should add to earnings in 1997.''
<p>
   Allegheny Teledyne shares rose 1/4 to 21 3/4 in midday trading
of 623,800, almost double the three-month daily average.
<p>
   Charges amounting to $16.8 million, or 10 cents a share,
resulted in net income of $51.4 million, or 30 cents. The charges
are for debt redemption, merger and restructuring costs and
litigation settlements, an include a gain from the sale of real
estate. In the year-earlier quarter, charges of $3.1 million, or 2
cents a share, resulted in pro forma net income $49 million, or 28
cents, the company said. The 1995 results were restated to reflect
the Teledyne purchase. Strong demand from the aerospace industry
for specialty metals, avionics, engines and other products helped
boost earnings, the company said. Operating profit in the specialty
metals unit rose 23 percent to $70.6 million from $57.6 million.
Revenue fell 7.2 percent to $482.9 million from $520.3 million,
dragged down by lower prices for flat-rolled stainless steel. The
company expects the Teledyne acquisition to make it less vulnerable
to downturns in the steel industry. The specialty metals unit
generates half of Allegheny Teledyne's revenue. Operating profit
from aerospace and electronics increased 62 percent to $34.8
million as revenue rose 9.2 percent to $252.8 million, Allegheny
Teledyne said. For the full year, Allegheny Teledyne said profit
from operations fell 5.6 percent to $236.5 million, or $1.34 a
share, from $250.4 million, or $1.41, in 1995. In 1996, a
combination of gains and charges reduced earnings by $23.5 million,
or 14 cents a share, making net income $213 million, or $1.20. In
1995, a gain of $23.5 million, or 13 cents a share, resulted in net
income of $273.9 million, or $1.54, the company said. Revenue from
continuing operations was little changed, inching up to $3.77
billion from $3.76 billion Allegheny Teledyne has said it expects
pre-tax cost savings of at least $85 million a year after the
acquisition. The company is using Teledyne's pension fund surplus
of $850 million to fund pension liabilities and retiree medical
expenses at Allegheny Ludlum operations.
</TEXT>
