 &UR; BC-MARVEL-ENTERTAINMENT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MARVEL/CHASE CREDIT AGREEMENT REJECTED BY BANKRUPTCY COURT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Bob Bauers &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Wilmington, Delaware, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Marvel
Entertainment Group Inc.'s $100 million credit agreement with Chase
Manhattan Bank was rejected by a U.S. Bankruptcy Court judge.
<p>
   Judge Helen S. Balick extended a $20 million interim credit
facility and said she wouldn't approve the final, $100 million
facility until two provisions were removed.
<p>
   Balick said she rejected the agreement on the basis of the
provision that Ronald Perelman must retain at least 51 percent
control or a loan default would be triggered. She also opposed a
provision that said the loan would be in default if anyone filed a
motion challenging the licensing agreement under which Toy Biz Inc.
can manufacture Marvel Entertainment-copyrighted products for free.
<p>
   Balick, in her ruling, was responding to objections filed by
holders of Marvel Holdings Inc. bonds, whose collateral would be
greatly reduced under Marvel Entertainment's proposed
reorganization plan.
</TEXT>
