<STORYID cat=k pri=r sel=ttj-z> A9079 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0819 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BOXING PROMOTER KING HAS MADE MILLIONS, NEARLY RUINED BOXING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DAN LYNCH &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Albany Times Union &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ALBANY, N.Y.  &MD;  A few months back, during boxing trainer Kevin
Rooney's multimillion-dollar breach-of-contract suit against Mike
Tyson, I was standing with a mob outside the federal courthouse on
Broadway when the parties involved in the case swarmed down the
steps on a lunch break.
<p>
   A guy near me had brought his kids to catch a glimpse of Tyson.
Striding out behind the fighter was a big, bulky, bespectacled man
whose silvery hair stood straight on end, like the hair on those
little plastic troll dolls.
<p>
   ``Who's that, Dad?` one of the kids asked.
<p>
   ``The biggest crook in boxing,'' his father explained.
<p>
   A widely held opinion. The thickset man with the electrified
hair was Don King, con man supreme, the modern Rasputin of
professional boxing. A former numbers writer in Cleveland, King
served a 10-year prison term for manslaughter after stomping a
business competitor to death. While in the slammer, he devised a
new career for himself  &MD;  boxing manager and promoter.
<p>
   Preying on the racial fears of the young, poorly educated
minority guys who labor in this rugged sport, King has made untold
millions in a 25-year career. He's stiffed countless fighters who
are better at mayhem than math, and  &MD;  along the way  &MD;  he's nearly
ruined boxing.
<p>
   Who cares, you might say? It's a scummy, violent sport peopled
by thugs and lowlifes. Always has been. And there's truth in that,
too. Boxing's participants traditionally have been ghetto guys
without schooling who, for one reason or another, had no real
chance to develop marketable skills in more respectable sports like
football, basketball and baseball.
<p>
   But for all its brutality, boxing is the essential human
competition  &MD;  one on one, man to man, heart to heart. I like it and
I won't apologize for it, any more than I'll apologize for liking
opera. Properly officiated and managed, boxing is less dangerous
than football. You can ask Bo Jackson about that. And it has been a
pathway to decent lives for thousands of guys who would otherwise
have been ground under by the cruel conditions of the world into
which they were born.
<p>
   Floyd Patterson, the former heavyweight champion who now serves
as New York's boxing czar, is one of those guys. Boxing saved him
from a life of Brooklyn street thuggery and made him rich. The
celebrity it gave him motivated him to become a thoroughly
admirable man. He told me that when he was fighting in the 1950s
and 1960s almost everybody in the world knew who the 12 champions
in various weight classes were.
<p>
   King fixed that, though. Using his personal influence with
various minority fighters, he conferred respectability on the
alphabet-soup collection of sanctioning bodies that now dominate
the sport. He created so many champions in so many expanded weight
classes that not even Floyd Patterson can name all the champions
recognized by this or that phony sanctioning body.
<p>
   That's more. It's been King who's given us so many fake fights  &MD; 
mismatches like the one-round Mike Tyson KOs of Bruce Seldon and
Peter McNeeley. It's King who's given us so many shady decisions  &MD; 
fights in which one or more judges seem to have made their way to
ringside with the aid of seeing-eye dogs.
<p>
   Sure, he's staged great fights. But great fights happen because
great fighters exist to fight them. They happen because of destiny
and market forces, not because Don King has cast his magic spell
over some poor ghetto kid who worries that white promoters will rob
him.
<p>
   Overall, King has been a profoundly destructive force in boxing.
None of that, however, will keep him out of the International
Boxing Hall of Fame in Canastota, N.Y. The hall recently announced
that King and 12 other guys are to join the 160 fighters and
``non-participants` enshrined on plaques on the museum's wall.
<p>
   The hall is a marvelous institution, the brainchild of former
welterweight champion Carmen Basilio, who lives in Canastota.
Basilio wanted boxing to have its own shrine. He wanted Canestota
to be to boxing what Cooperstown is to baseball. He got the thing
up and running eight years ago with a small museum just off the New
York Thruway east of Syracuse. The museum has room to grow, and
Carmen Basilio wants to grow it. He wants to see true
respectability conferred on the sport he loves.
<p>
   But the admission of Don King to the company of gallant fighters
and honorable non-participants like the late Cus D'Amato, who built
the sport rather than debasing it, is a blunder of monumental
proportions.
<p>
   Boxing has long needed a shrine like Canastota. But why tarnish
that shrine with false idols like Don King?
<p>
    &UR; ------- &LR; Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union,
Box 15000, Albany, N.Y. 12212.
</TEXT>
