<SLUG> BC-US-FEATURE-BUDGET-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1128 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-FEATURE-BUDGET-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FEATURE BUDGET FOR THE WEEKEND OF JAN. 25 - JAN. 26. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Editors: Features suggested for weekend use will follow this
budget. Stories are slugged BC-FEA-SLUG &QR; . For resends, call Beth
Karlin at (212) 318-2944, Chuck Stevens (212) 318-2166 or Jim
Greiff (609) 279-4056.
<p>
   ECONOMY-US (Washington) -- While the economy's strong
performance over the past four years brought President Bill Clinton
back to the White House, few business leaders and economists think
it will last through his second term. By Michael McKee. 800.
<p>
   ECONOMY-FOOD (Washington) -- Consumer food prices in 1997 will
hold steady or even retreat after surging last year at their
highest rate since 1990, analysts say. That could remove one of the
inflation concerns that has been troubling policymakers at the
Federal Reserve. By Roger Runningen. 800.
<p>
   LEGAL-AFFAIRS (New York) -- Martha Stewart may be the
high-priestess of swanky suburban style to her fans, but to her
former gardener she's a wage cheat. He says she owes him more than
$30,000 in overtime for washing cars, grooming dogs and performing
other work at the Westport estate that serves as the set for the
``Martha Stewart Living'' shows on CBS and the Lifetime cable
channel. Stewart says no way, claiming he was an agricultural
worker who by law aren't entitled to overtime. By --Seena Simon.
950.
<p>
   MONEY-ON-NET (New York) -- Companies like Touch-It Inc., which
makes paper that changes color at different temperatures, was
unlikely to snare a big-name underwriter such as Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co. to help it go public. So it turned to Direct Stock Market Inc.
for help. Direct Stock Market and others like it offer services
ranging from an online shopping mall, where investors can peruse
company information, to the hand-holding and assistance more
typical of an investment bank. By Duncan Martell. 1,000.
<p>
   AIRBUS-ADS (Atlanta) -- The television commercial touts the
virtues of a fast new model: Lots of leg room, great mileage --with
room for 300 and the ability to fly from New York to Paris nonstop.
Airbus Industrie is betting that out of millions of viewers a
select few will want its A330 jetliner. And at $110 million each, a
few buyers is all the European planemaker needs. By Anthony
Effinger and Adam Levy. 750.
<p>
   DISCLOSURE (Boston) -- General Motors Corp. gave a welcome
warning last month to a few close friends. One by one, the
automaker called analysts at top brokerage firms on Dec. 18 to say
that fourth-quarter costs would be higher than expected. GM stock
promptly plunged. Almost daily, companies big and small tell a
select group of investors and analysts that bad news is coming,
giving them a chance to bail out before everyone else. By Gerard
Meuchner. 1,000.
<p>
   PERSONAL-WEALTH (New York) -- Tightwads take note. Starting next
week, individual investors in the U.S. can buy stock in Merck &AMP;
Co., the nation's biggest drugmaker, directly from the Whitehouse
Station, New Jersey-based headquarters. Merck is one of about 200
American corporations that invite investors to buy their shares
directly from the companies themselves or their bank
representatives. Scott Schnipper. 600 words.
<p>
   TRADER (Chicago) -- It's 7:00 a.m. Central Time and for Mercury
Trading options dealers, the next seven and a half hours will
determine whether the firm's $121,000 investment is lost or becomes
millions. By Dylan Ratigan. 1,100.
<p>
   TAKING-STOCK -- (New York) Corporate profits don't have a prayer
of meeting expectations, interest rates are rising and the Dow
Jones Industrial Average is overpriced. Yet fear not, demand for
stock outpaces supply, and could lift the Dow Jones Industrial
Average another 25 percent. By Roger Madoff. 900.
<p>
   MINDING-MONEY (New York): Rich people, and the folks who manage
cash for them, are betting that they'll have to be a bit more
original this year to make money. Last year, U.S. stocks made lots
of money, but in 1997, investors are choosing managers who
specialize in specific sectors, who can put money overseas, or who
can sell stocks short. By Katherine Burton. 800.
<p>
   MUTUAL-FUNDS (Kansas City, Missouri) -- American Century
Investments has a new mutual fund that penalizes investors who
think short-term. American Century's Twentieth Century New
Opportunities Fund will charge extra fees to any investor who pulls
money within five years of buying shares
<p>
   PERSONAL-FUNDS (Boston) -- The concerns of many stock fund
investors is that the young hot-shots who run billions in
high-flying mutual fund assets these days have never been tested by
a real bear market. Not Massachusetts Investors Trust. With a
history that dates to 1924, it survived the Crash of 1929, the
Great Depression, not to mention the bear market of the 1970s. By
Tim Quinson and David A. Andelman. 1,000
<p>
   SELLING-HOMES (New York) -- Selling a home in the dead of winter
need not be a futile attempt thanks to some useful tips offered by
brokers from around the country. By Robert Burgess. 775.
<p>
   FASTENAL (Winona, Minnesota) -- Fastenal Co. shareholders aren't
the only ones nervous about the company's fourth-quarter earnings
report due Friday. Short-sellers --speculators who sold borrowed
shares in the hope of buying them back at a lower price -- may have
more at stake. They're betting that the fast-growing distributor of
nuts, bolts and other industrial supplies, which has come up short
of Wall Street earnings estimates in the last two quarters, will
again miss forecasts. By Daniel Fisher. 900.
<p>
   BRINKER (Dallas) -- To thrive, a so-called concept restaurant
chain like Brinker International Inc. must do two things: Jazz up
its old restaurants and come up with ideas for new ones. Brinker is
trying to patch up its 500 Chili Bar &AMP; Grill stores, but also is
trying the new -- in this case, a takeout store it calls Eatzi's,
which caters to upscale customers whose tastes range from exotic
fare to comfort food. By Shannon Stevens. 850.
<p>
   SPORTS-BIZ (New Orleans) -- Squads of National Football League
undercover agents will be prowling the streets of New Orleans
during Super Bowl week, looking for people selling merchandise with
unauthorized team logos. Just as licensed merchandise has become a
money machine for professional sports, bootleggers are making big
money by selling T-shirts, caps and other team paraphernalia
without paying for the right to use their logos. By W.D. Murray.
700
<p>
   FOOTBALL-LEAGUE (New York) -- Investors are forming the All
America Football League in a long-shot attempt to rival the
powerful National Football League, beginning in March 1998. By Jon
Friedman. 500.
-0- (BBN) Jan/22/97 15:05 EOS (BBN) Jan/22/97 15:05 86
