<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-TAXES-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0245 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-VENEZUELA-TAXES-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; VENEZUELA'S CALDERA ADMINISTRATION DELAYS TAX EXEMPTION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jake Keaveny and Carlos Camacho &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Caracas, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Venezuela's government said an
long-awaited five-year tax exemption for new investment projects
will be delayed longer for revision.
<p>
   The tax, being created to spur oil and other export geared
investments, was completed last week by Venezuela's tax authority
and finance ministry.
<p>
   It will be revised following complaints from state oil company
Petroleos de Venezuela SA, said Finance Minister Luis Raul Matos
Azocar following the weekly cabinet meeting.
<p>
   Matos Azocar did not specify what the shortcomings were or when
a new draft would be completed.
<p>
   Last week several oil companies complained the exemption was not
transparent and, in particular instances, involved reimbursements
in the form of tax coupons.
<p>
   The exemption is to apply during pre-operative stages of
investments for oil, mining and other export geared industries.
Congress approved the framework last July. Foreign oil companies,
waiting to spend billions of dollars on exploration projects, are
waiting for the government to complete the details.
<p>
   Venezuela reopened its oil industry to private investment last
year for the first time in 20 years. PDVSA, as the state oil
company is known, plans to double daily oil production capacity by
2006.
</TEXT>
