<DOCID> nyt970122.0290 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9086 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-COMERICA-CUTS-UPDATE1 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0574 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COMERICA-CUTS-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMERICA TO CUT 14% OF JOBS, CLOSE BRANCHES (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Joseph A. Giannone &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds detail throughout; updates stock price; adds comments from
analyst and investor.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Detroit, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Comerica Inc. said it will cut
1,890 jobs, or 14 percent of its payroll, and close about 15
branches to slash costs and boost profits.
<p>
   The Detroit-based bank took a $90 million charge against
fourth-quarter earnings to reflect the costs of the job cuts and
other restructuring moves. Comerica doesn't know how many people
will be fired and how many unfilled positions will be eliminated,
said bank spokesman Wayne Mielke.
<p>
   The bank said the steps, such as using computers to help make
loans and streamline financial reporting, will boost revenue $110
million a year, starting in the first half of 1998. Comerica is
taking these steps to convince investors that the bank --often
cited by analysts as a likely takeover target -- should remain
independent.
<p>
   ``Sounds like they heard footsteps,'' said James Schmidt, a
portfolio manager at John Hancock Funds, which owns 552,800 shares.
``They're nervous about being taken over, and this is a move to
forestall that.''
<p>
   Comerica announced the steps as it reported fourth-quarter
profit from operations rose 14 percent to $121 million, or $1.06 a
share -- a penny shy of Wall Street expectations.
<p>
   Comerica shares fell 3/8 to 55 7/8 in afternoon trading.
<p>
   Comerica joins Keycorp, First of America Corp. and Signet
Banking Corp., among other companies which are under pressure from
investors to boost profits by cutting costs.
<p>
   The moves also makes the bank less attractive to acquirers,
analysts said, because there's less waste to trim. Often banks
justify the price of a takeover by finding costs savings.
<p>
   The bank began its restructuring program, Direction 2000, in
February 1995, setting up consumer, business and investment banking
units, and consolidating back office operations. Last September
Comerica employees were asked to come up with suggestions to reduce
costs at the bank.
<p>
   The bank was advised by Chandrika Tandon's Tandon Capital
Associates, a New York-based consultant that built a reputation for
slashing payrolls at other banks. Fleet Financial Corp., Chase
Manhattan Corp., Michigan National Bank, and Midlantic Bancorp all
used Tandon to devise ways to boost profits at least in part by
firing workers.
<p>
   In its earnings report, Comerica said net interest income rose
3.6 percent to $353.3 million as loans outstanding increased 4.7
percent to an average of $25.5 billion in the quarter. The net
interest margin widened to 4.61 percent from 4.31 percent.
<p>
   Overall credit quality improved, as the bank reduced by 3
percent to $32 million the amount it set aside for future loan
losses while net write-offs fell 38 percent to $22.3 million.
<p>
   Total noninterest income fell 5.8 percent to $132.4 million,
amid declines in broker fees and revolving credit fees.
<p>
   Noninterest expense rose 24 percent to $356.2 million. Excluding
the restructuring charge, expenses fell 7.7 percent.
<p>
   For full year 1996, net income rose 0.9 percent to $417.2
million, or $3.55 a share, from $413.4 million, or $3.54, in 1995.
Comerica, which has $34 billion in assets, operates about 265
branches in Michigan, California, Texas and Florida.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1511EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0291 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9087 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EARNS-DEAN-WITTER-UPD </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0645 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-DEAN-WITTER-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DEAN WITTER 4TH-QTR NET RISES 28% ON ASSET MANAGEMENT (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Monique Wise &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates stock price. Adds details on expenses.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Dean Witter, Discover &AMP; Co.
said fourth-quarter earnings rose 28 percent as rising income from
managing clients' money and from penalties charged to credit card
customers overcame credit card losses.
<p>
   The company, which owns broker Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. and
issues the Discover credit card, said net income rose to $227.8
million, or 68 cents a share, from $178.1 million, or 51 cents, a
year earlier.
<p>
   The earnings beat the average estimate of 65 cents a share of
eight analysts surveyed by Zacks Investment Research Inc. Dean
Witter rose 7/8 to 38 in late afternoon trading of 781,400 shares,
more than the three-month daily average of 692,300.
<p>
   ``The earnings were very strong,'' said analyst Michael
Freudenstein, who follows financial companies for J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.
``Each of their lines of business performed well.''
<p>
   Net income at Dean Witter Reynolds, the third-largest U.S.
securities firm in terms of brokers, rose 8.8 percent to $126
million from $115.8 million a year earlier, an increase of 5.9
percent from the third quarter.
<p>
   Asset management and administration fees, which increased 16
percent to $299.3 million, led the securities unit's performance.
Investment banking revenue jumped 60 percent to $78.1 million amid
a rally in the stock and bond markets.
<p>
   ``We continued to achieve rapid growth in assets under
management,'' Chairman and Chief Executive Philip J. Purcell said
in a statement.
<p>
   Assets under management and administration rose 13 percent to
$90 billion from the year-ago period. Trading revenue declined 1.9
percent to $108.9 million.
<p>
   Net operating revenue at the securities unit rose 11 percent to
$879 million.
<p>
   In December, Dean Witter announced an agreement to buy Lombard
Securities, an on-line brokerage based in San Francisco.
<p>
   Discover card earnings rose 63 percent to $101.8 million from
$62.3 million a year earlier. The rise came even as the company
increased its provisions for loan losses by 53 percent to $636
million.
<p>
   ``Revenues from their credit card services were very high,''
said analyst Mark Alpert at Alex. Brown &AMP; Sons Inc. ``They priced a
lot of their accounts in terms of annual percentage rates and late
fees, which more than offset the rise in write-offs.''
<p>
   Merchant and cardmember fees, on a managed loan basis, rose 48
percent to a record $563.8 million from a year earlier, boosted by
higher transaction volume.
<p>
   The firm increased the penalties it charges for late payments
and spending over credit limits, a spokeswoman said.
<p>
   The loss, or net charge-off, rate for managed loans in credit
services rose to 6 percent from 4.4 percent in the year-earlier
period.
<p>
   ``Our fourth-quarter results were exceptionally strong given the
industry-wide trend of higher credit card write-offs,'' said
Purcell.
<p>
   Discover net operating revenue rose 14 percent to $735.9
million.
<p>
   For the full year, Dean Witter Discover net income rose 11
percent to $951.4 million, or $2.79 a share, from $856.4 million,
or $2.44 in 1995.
<p>
   Total expenses, excluding interest, increased 9.8 percent to
$1.25 billion, led by a 13 percent rise in payroll costs.
<p>
   Compensation expenses rose 13 percent to $427.1 million at Dean
Witter Reynolds and rose 11 percent to $132.1 million at the credit
card unit.
<p>
   Marketing and business development expenses also contributed to
increased costs, advancing 13 percent to $253.6 million for the
company as a whole. They rose 89 percent to $43 million at the
brokerage unit and rose 5 percent to $210.8 million at the credit
card division.
</TEXT>
