<SLUG> BC-NEW-ZEALAND-DOLLAR-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0323 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NEW-ZEALAND-DOLLAR-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DOLLAR-NEW ZEALAND: DECLINES AHEAD OF CENTRAL BANKER'S SPEECH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jenny Ruth &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Wellington, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- The New Zealand dollar
declined amid concern that Reserve Bank of New Zealand Gov. Don
Brash may say interest rates and the currency are too high.
<p>
   Brash is scheduled to speak later today to the Canterbury
Chamber of Commerce on the central bank's inflation target of zero
to 3 percent.
<p>
   ``It's more than likely he will say that,'' said Tania Pye, a
dealer at Bankers Trust New Zealand, adding that her firm's index
of monetary conditions, which measures the inter-relationship
between the currency and interest rates, is at 127.5 points, above
the central bank's optimum level of 123 points.
<p>
   ``They certainly must be thinking monetary conditions are a
little tight at the moment,'' Pye said.
<p>
   The New Zealand dollar was quoted recently at 70.39 U.S. cents,
compared with 70.55 cents in late domestic trading yesterday. The
currency gained 8.1 percent against its U.S. counterpart last year.
New Zealand 90-day bank bills, the benchmark from which other
interest rates are set were at 7.34 percent, down from 7.36 percent
yesterday.
<p>
   Still, ``any kind of selling (of New Zealand dollars) will be an
opportunity to buy,'' said Richard Koss, economist at New
York-based MFR Inc. whose US$30 million Lexington Ramirez Global
Income Fund invests in New Zealand.
<p>
   Prime Minister Jim Bolger's comments earlier this week that the
government won't intervene to try to push the currency lower were
encouraging, Koss said. ``If he's not going to do anything, it's
hard to see the central bank being somehow more accommodative.''
<p>
   Figures released last week showed inflation at 2.4 percent 4in
1996.
<p>
   The government is under pressure from exporters complaining
about the strength of the currency.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1514EST
</TRAILER>
