<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9091 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PECO-DEBT-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0672 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PECO-DEBT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PECO SEEKS TO REFINANCE $3.6 BLN DEBT WITH PENNSYLVANIA'S HELP &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Kerry Dooley &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Philadelphia, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Peco Energy Co. asked
Pennsylvania's permission to refinance $3.6 billion in long-term
obligations with a new type of bond.
<p>
   The bonds would be backed by fees the utility will collect from
consumers for transmitting electricity after state power sales are
deregulated in 1999.
<p>
   Philadelphia-based Peco says its nuclear plant debt and other
long-term obligations would hinder it in a competitive market, and
Pennsylvania has agreed to let utilities prepare for deregulation
by backing the new, lower-cost bonds.
<p>
   Although U.S. utilities are expected to ask for issuance of $50
billion in these asset-backed securities, Peco's request to state
regulators for a specific amount is the nation's first.
<p>
   ``I don't think it will roll smoothly for that reason. There's
no precedent,'' said Daniel Scotto, an analyst with Bear Stearns.
<p>
   Peco filed this morning with the Pennsylvania Public Utilities
Commission for $3.6 billion in bonds. If the commission approves,
Peco said it may apply for $3.5 billion more. Whether the state or
Peco would issue the bonds has yet to be determined.
<p>
   What Pennsylvania does with Peco's request could set a model for
similar negotiations across the U.S. California plans to issue $5
billion in bonds this year for its three largest electric
companies. Ohio and New York are considering legislation that would
let their state utility commissions help power companies in the
same way.
<p>
   In deciding how much of Peco's long-term obligations can be
refinanced using the bonds, regulators can reject debt or contracts
that it decides were undertaken because of bad business decisions.
<p>
   California already has decided three companies are entitled to
full recovery of their investments in power sources. These include
nuclear plant debt, as well as power supply contracts that
utilities had to sign with other generators because of federal law.
<p>
   California's Infrastructure and Economic Development Bank will
issue $5 billion of the bonds this year. State law lets the bank
have as much as $10 billion in these bonds outstanding.
<p>
   San Francisco-based Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co. and Southern
California Edison Co. each estimate borrowing about $2 billion from
this issue. San Diego Gas &AMP; Electric Co. expects to borrow about
$500 million.
<p>
   In California and Pennsylvania, the new debt will be backed with
the guarantee of money from what consumers will pay for electricity
delivery.
<p>
   In a deregulated power market, consumers will be able to choose
power suppliers other than their tradition utility. However,
electricity will still be moved using utilities' existing power
lines and transmission equipment, and consumers will pay delivery
fees to their local utility, regardless of who supplies their
power. The new bonds will be backed by those delivery fees.
California says the new bonds will help it cut consumers' electric
bills 10 percent by next year. Peco said its customers would see
rates drop 2.9 percent if it gets approval to issue the $3.6
billion in bonds.
<p>
   The state plans to help utilities refinance their debt have
eased some investors' concerns about deregulation, said Gregory
Phelps, portfolio manager for John Hancock Advisers' Patriot Fund,
which holds 100,000 Peco shares.
<p>
   Utilities and investors once feared companies would be left with
billions in debt that would leave them unable to compete with new
suppliers. California and Pennsylvania, among the leading states in
deregulation, have agreed to let utilities refinance much, if not
all, of these obligations.
<p>
   Still, Peco's ability to compete in a competitive power market
isn't assured, Phelps said. Peco's rates are double the U.S.
average. ``There are a lot of disgruntled customers,'' he said.
``It's too early to tell how many will switch'' to a new supplier.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1519EST
</TRAILER>
