<DOCID> nyt970122.0295 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=l pri=u sel=taf-z> A9095 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1006 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ELECTRICAL CODES AND REGULATIONS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (kd) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ART ADV: How-to diagram will be sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Electricity is essential to our daily existence. We use it to
light homes, run motors and power our communication devices. It is
a powerful source of energy, but it can be dangerous unless it is
properly controlled.
<p>
   Control goes beyond power generation and transmission.
Electrical components must be designed and manufactured to handle
current loads without overheating or shorting out, but even the
best components can malfunction if not installed properly. 
<p>
   The government does not regulate manufacturing specifications;
instead manufacturers submit samples of their products to the
Underwriters Laboratories for quality control. The Underwriters
Laboratories are a group of independent laboratories sponsored
jointly by manufacturers, insurance companies and other interested
parties.
<p>
   Products tested must meet minimum standards to be approved by
the Underwriters. All approved products are registered on the
approved list and may carry the Underwriters seal.
<p>
   All items must be clearly marked with a seal or initials and a
code so that field inspectors may identify the manufacturer by
referring to the Underwriters list. If there is any question about
a device that you intend to buy or install, you can write to the
Underwriters Laboratories at 333 Pfingsten Road, Northbrook, Ill.
60062-2096, to see if the item has been tested by them.
<p>
   It is worth noting that the approval rating simply means that an
item has been tested and meets the Underwriters minimum safety
requirements. Similar components may not be of the same quality
even though they both carry the Underwriters seal.
<p>
   Also the Underwriters seal guarantees that the product is safe
only when used for the purpose for which it was designed. A length
of lamp cord is adequate for wiring lamps and extension cords, but
not for permanent wiring in a circuit. Neither the Underwriters
seals not the approved list can be used as an adequate guide to the
proper installation of a product.
<p>
   Comprehensive installation procedures are spelled out in the
National Electrical Code. The code is not intended as a manual of
instruction for untrained people, but it does outline safe wiring
methods with the proper materials to use to safeguard people and
property from hazards. The code is updated every three years to
keep up with new materials and standards.
<p>
   Copies are available from the National Fire Protection
Association, 1 Battery March Park, Quincy, Mass. 02269-9101. (Most
libraries also carry a copy of the code, but not necessarily the
most current version.) Do-it-yourselfers may find the code
technical and difficult to read, but fortunately some home centers
sell booklets containing the basics of the code written in more
accessible terminology. In Canada, the Canadian Electrical Code
serves the same purpose as the American National Electrical Code.
<p>
   Neither the Underwriters specifications nor the code carry the
weight of law, but most states and municipalities enact legislation
that requires all electrical wiring to be in accordance with the
code's guidelines, using products approved by the Underwriters
Laboratories. In addition, these local codes or ordinances often
supplement the National Electrical Code with additions or
restrictions that are applicable to the area. The code, for
example, sanctions the use of armored cable in most electrical
circuits, but it may be prohibited by local code.
<p>
   Local codes are usually quite specific about who may or may not
install or repair electrical wiring. Some codes, particularly in
large urban areas, require that all electrical work be done by a
licensed electrician. Other codes allow do-it-yourselfers to wire
circuits as long as a licensed electrician inspects the job and
makes the final hookup to the service panel. It's important for the
homeowner to consult with the local building department before
attempting to install new wiring or add to existing circuits.
<p>
   Strict application of the codes will result in electrical work
that is safe, but it may not be the most efficient or economical
wiring. Do-it-yourselfers should also consult other sources (e.g.
books on the principles of electrical wiring) when designing
circuits.
<p>
   Local authorities are able to monitor modifications in home
construction and wiring by requiring the homeowner to get a permit
before starting a job. As part of the application process, the
homeowner may have to submit a written description with sketches of
the project; and in some communities, he may be required to take a
simple electrical proficiency test to demonstrate his knowledge of
basic electrical circuits.
<p>
   In addition, he will also have to schedule a visit by the local
electrical inspector. With simple jobs, the inspector will usually
examine the circuit after the work is completed. For larger
projects, the inspector may want to visit the site periodically and
check on the work as it progresses.
<p>
   In general, most electrical inspectors are also available to
answer questions about materials and hookup procedures. They would
prefer to suggest the correct materials to use, rather than reject
a job that was installed with inferior products.The
do-it-yourselfer can avoid making costly mistakes by consulting
with the electrical inspector before beginning an installation.
<p>
   Even if you're not planning to install new wiring or add to
existing circuits, there are still valid reasons for knowing the
safety standards outlined in the electrical codes. You will be in a
better position to evaluate the quality of the wiring in your home
and spot potential hazards. If you are planning to buy another
home, you can inspect the wiring yourself and identify possible
code violations or substandard materials.
</TEXT>
