<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9097 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EATON-VANCE-FORUM-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0535 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EATON-VANCE-FORUM-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EATON VANCE LOOKS TO MAKE ACQUISITION: BLOOMBERG FORUM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Tim Quinson &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Boston, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Eaton Vance Corp. wants to buy
another fund management company, said James Hawkes, the company's
chief executive.
<p>
   ``We would look for a firm as an acquisition that might
complement Eaton Vance's investment management capabilities,''
Hawkes told the Bloomberg Forum.
<p>
   Eaton Vance has the financial resources to make a purchase. The
Boston-based company has more than $115 million in cash and
short-term investments, plus a credit facility of $75 million, that
could be used to make an acquisition.
<p>
   ``In the last 12 to 18 months, we have been looking for a firm
and we've not yet found the right one,'' Hawkes said.
<p>
   All signs are pointing to Eaton Vance buying a fund manager that
specializes in stocks. It's an area of the business where Eaton
Vance wants to get stronger.
<p>
   Eaton Vance is best known as a manager of municipal bond funds,
which account for about 46 percent of the company's $17.6 billion
in assets under management.
<p>
   The company has taken steps in recent years to broaden its
equity fund lineup. Eaton Vance's equity fund assets increased 30
percent in the 12-month period ended Oct. 31 to $3.1 billion.
<p>
   Eaton Vance now offers 13 stock fund portfolios, up from nine in
the past 12 months. Eaton Vance would like to market more small
company stock funds, as well as funds that use computer-generated
quantitative models to pick stocks, Hawkes said.
<p>
   ``If we found a manager that had a strong record (in one of
these areas), we would consider adding that to the Eaton Vance
stable,'' he said.
<p>
   An obstacle to making an acquisition is the relative high price
that money managers can demand in this heady market, Hawkes said.
``One of the reasons we've been at this for 18 months and haven't
found the right company to acquire is simply issues of what you get
relative to what you pay,'' he said.
<p>
   An unsolicited offer for Eaton Vance would likely be rejected. A
group of five senior managers, including Hawkes and Chairman Landon
T. Clay, control Eaton Vance's voting stock in a trust, making an
unfriendly acquisition of the company almost impossible.
<p>
   Eaton Vance has no plans of selling itself. The company ranks
No. 30 of about 550 companies in terms of mutual fund assets,
Hawkes said. ``We can effectively compete,'' he said.
<p>
   Eaton Vance's stock was a high flier over the past 12 months,
rising almost 75 percent on a total return basis. That's more than
double what the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index gained.
<p>
   Still, Eaton Vance's stock is inexpensive relative to other fund
managers, Hawkes said. The stock trades at about 11 times what the
company earning in the 12-month period ended Oct. 31.
<p>
   That ratio is about half of where the benchmark S&AMP;P 500 is
trading, Hawkes said. Eaton Vance's stock was down 3/8 at 45 5/8 in
recent trading.
<p>
   Eaton Vance is one of the oldest investment firms. It dates to
1924 when Charles F. Eaton and John G. Howard founded a firm called
Eaton &AMP; Howard in Boston. It's been here ever since.
</TEXT>
