<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9099 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EARNS-COMPAQ-UPDATE3- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0708 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-COMPAQ-UPDATE3-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMPAQ 4TH-QTR NET SOARS 43% ON MORE CORPORATE SALES (UPDATE3) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Daniel Fisher &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Rewrites. Updates stock activity.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Houston, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Compaq Computer Corp.'s
fourth-quarter earnings rose 43 percent, far exceeding estimates,
on increased sales of computers to corporate customers and
improvements in operating efficiency.
<p>
   The No. 1 personal computer and server maker said net income
rose to $462 million, or $1.64 a share, from year-earlier profit
from operations of $323 million, or $1.17. Revenue rose 15 percent
to $5.42 billion from $4.7 billion.
<p>
   Compaq's results exceeded all but the most-optimistic forecasts,
demonstrating the increasing strength of personal computer makers
as companies shift from mainframe computers to networks of PCs.
Compaq shares jumped 4 3/4, or 6 percent, to 83 1/4 on trading of
8.2 million, more than twice the three-month daily average of 3
million.
<p>
   ``They're gaining market share, profit margins are increasing,
cash is growing, what else do you want?'' said Stephen Dube, an
analyst with Wasserstein Perella Securities.
<p>
   Wall Street was expecting earnings of $1.53 a share, based on
the average estimate of 34 analysts from First Call. Many analysts
had increased their unofficial forecasts to about $1.60 in recent
weeks.
<p>
   Compaq led some other computer makers' shares higher, with Dell
Computer Corp.'s stock rising 2 to 66 1/8.
<p>
   However, shares of International Business Machines Corp., whose
earnings were hurt by lagging mainframe sales, fell 10 1/8 to 157
7/8.
<p>
   Houston-based Compaq said its closely watched gross margin ---
revenue minus the cost of manufacturing computers -- rose to 24.4
percent, its highest level in almost two years.
<p>
   Compaq cited a shift toward corporate computers and servers,
which carry higher profit margins, as well as aggressive moves to
cut inventory and speed up collection of payments.
<p>
   The company slashed inventory almost in half to $1.15 billion
from $2.16 billion in the year-earlier period, said Compaq Chief
Financial Officer Earl Mason.
<p>
   Days sales outstanding, a measure of how long Compaq takes to
collect its bills, fell to 53 from 60. Those moves helped Compaq
reduce the amount of money tied up in inventory and receivables and
boost cash to $4 billion from $745 million in the year-earlier
period.
<p>
   ``Our people got to some of the inventory goals about a year
ahead of schedule,'' said Mason, who joined Compaq from Inland
Steel Industries Inc. in May.
<p>
   Mason said Compaq will continue to report higher earnings and
profit margins this year than in 1996, although he declined to say
whether the company will exceed its fourth-quarter gross margin of
24.4 percent.
<p>
   Compaq won't be able to trim inventory as much this year as it
did in 1996, Mason acknowledged. He said the bulk of gains in
profitability will come from a shift toward so-called enterprise,
or large corporate computer, systems.
<p>
   ``As the enterprise business becomes more of our overall revenue
stream, the mix alone brings up gross margins,'' Mason said.
<p>
   Compaq's profitability has been bolstered by new products,
including a line of workstations aimed at engineers and financial
professionals. Compaq also has acquired several companies that make
systems to link computers in networks, so it can sell entire
computer systems and not just desktop PCs.
<p>
   Selling, general and administrative expense rose to 10.6 percent
of revenue in the fourth quarter from about 10 percent in the
year-earlier period.
<p>
   Research and development expense increased to about 1.9 percent
from 1.7 percent, Compaq said. The company made up for those
increases by trimming inventory and better managing the flow of
products through the manufacturing and selling process.
<p>
   For the year, Houston-based Compaq reported net income of $1.31
billion, or $4.66 a share, compared with profit from operations of
$1.03 billion, or $3.74 a share.
<p>
   Compaq reported 1995 net income of $789 million, or $2.88 a
jI2sSrlblshare, after acquisition-related charges.  &LR; , h Revenue
increased 23 percent to $18.11 billion from $14.76 billion.
</TEXT>
