<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9100 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-PHONE-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0457 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COLOMBIA-PHONE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COLOMBIA SEEN AS LIKELY TO DELAY OPENING OF TELEPHONE MARKET &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By David Scanlan &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Bogota, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- International phone companies in
Colombia said the country will probably delay the opening of the
long-distance phone market at least until next year, a year later
than originally planned.
<p>
   Phone companies blame the delay on concerns expressed by workers
at the state-owned phone company, which would have to cut jobs to
compete with the foreign competitors.
<p>
   Colombia initially planned to offer foreign companies the right
to offer phone service beginning in March. The date was then pushed
back to August. Next year is more likely now, the phone companies
said.
<p>
   ``We have the impression it won't happen this year,'' said
Sergio Martinez, executive president of the Colombian Information
and Telecommunications Association, an industry group of 31 foreign
telecommunications companies.
<p>
   ``There is strong suspicion it won't happen during this
administration,'' which ends in August 1998, Martinez said.
<p>
   Colombian officials say they will hire a group of experts this
month to conduct a study on the impact of the opening of the phone
market. This is to be followed by a conference on the matter this
year, though no date has been set. The official plan is still to
open the market to two foreign operators this year, a spokeswoman
for the Communications Ministry said.
<p>
   The government postponed the opening of the market in part
because of demands from the unions at Telecom, the state phone
company. Telecom has a monopoly on long-distance phone service. The
plan calls for two foreign operators to compete with Telecom.
<p>
   The Telecom workers want the company to have more time to get
ready for competition.
<p>
   The phone concessions will be for 10 years, exclusive for seven
years. The minimum price is $150 million, though Colombia is hoping
an auction among various bidders will push the price to $200
million to $250 million.
<p>
   At least two groups appear firm in their plans to bid on the
service, government officials have said.
<p>
   The groups include Sprint Corp., Deutsche Telecom and France
Telecom with Colombian industrial group Santo Domingo and local
phone companies in Medellin and Cali.
<p>
   The other group consists of MCI Corp., Bell Canada
International, El Tiempo newspaper, the Bogota phone company and
the Sarmiento Angulo industrial group.
<p>
   Telefonica of Spain, Korea Telecom and STET of Italy have also
expressed interest.
<p>
   The long-distance phone market, worth about $900 million in
1995, is expected to grow at a rate of 8.5 percent a year for the
rest of the decade.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1524EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0300 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9101 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-FED-UPDATE2-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0910 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ECONOMY-FED-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FED'S SURVEY SEES `SCATTERED EVIDENCE' OF HIGHER WAGES (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Vincent Del Giudice and Laura Cohn &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Edits to tighten. Adds region-by-region summary, latest
financial markets.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The U.S. economy continues to
grow with low unemployment nudging labor costs higher, the Federal
Reserve said today.
<p>
   While the Fed found ``scattered evidence'' of pressures for
higher wages in its latest regional economic survey, the central
bank still found no evidence of accelerating consumer prices
outside of energy in December or early January.
<p>
   The Fed's regional outlook, commonly known as the beige book, is
based on reports from the Fed's 12 district banks and is published
eight times each year. The report will help form the basis for
discussion on interest rate targets at the Feb. 4-5 meeting of the
Fed's policy-setting Federal Open Market Committee.
<p>
   ``Economic growth in December and early January was moderate in
most parts of the country,'' the Fed said in its report. ``Holiday
sales were in line with retailers' expectations of moderate growth.
Manufacturing activity continued to grow, with significant strength
coming from capital equipment and materials manufacturers.''
<p>
   The report is likely to be ``comforting'' for investors, said
James Padinha, an economist at MMS International in San Francisco,
because it doesn't point to wage pressures or other worrisome signs
of inflation.
<p>
   In financial markets, though, the benchmark 30-year Treasury
bond fell after the government's auction of about $17 billion in
two-year notes. The bond fell 1/2, pushing up the yield more than 4
basis points to 6.82 percent, as dealers tried to sell their
holdings of the new government securities.
<p>
   While release of the report had been set for 2 p.m. Washington
time, it was inadvertently released at 12:10 p.m. on the Internet
by the Fed. ``Everybody has broken an embargo, including me,''
joked the Fed's chief spokesman, Joseph Coyne. News agencies
occasionally release stories about government reports before their
scheduled release times because of unintentional computer glitches.
<p>
   The latest Fed regional survey, compiled by the Federal Reserve
Bank of San Francisco, is in line with comments yesterday by Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan, who said the U.S. economy remains strong
with few signs of immediate inflationary pressures even as an era
of low wage gains may be ending.
<p>
   In the Fed's New York district, for example, the economy had a
``slightly firmer tone than in the last report, while price
pressures remain subdued,'' the Fed said.
<p>
   In the country's mid-section, the Kansas City Fed said rising
job creation is beginning to put upward pressure on wages,
something Fed officials have been warning about as a risk to the
nation's inflation outlook.
<p>
   Along the Pacific coast, the San Francisco Fed reported
retailers enjoyed a ``good'' holiday selling season, though adverse
weather in late December and early January ``held down
post-Christmas retail activity.''
<p>
   In his testimony yesterday, Greenspan said, ``the economy has
retained considerable vigor, with few signs of the imbalances and
inflationary tensions that have disrupted past expansions.'' He
added: ``By some important measures of price trends, inflation
actually slowed a bit in 1996.''
<p>
   Economists interpreted Greenspan's comments as suggesting the
FOMC won't raise interest rates next month. Still, Greenspan left
the door ajar for action later if inflation accelerates because of
rising wage levels.
<p>
   The overall consumer price index rose 3.3 percent last year, the
largest increase since 1990. However, much of that came from an 8.6
percent rise in energy prices. Not counting food and energy, prices
rose only 2.6 percent, tying the 1994 rate for the lowest core
inflation rate in 30 years.
<p>
   AJbI6''w)% &QC; 91 &QC; UQ1 &QC;  &QC; -Q!M%Q!economy growing at a subdued pace with
