<DOCID> nyt970122.0303 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9106 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-RATES-OF-RETURN-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0798 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-RATES-OF-RETURN-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ARGENTINA FINDS INVESTORS HUNGRY FOR YIELD: RATES OF RETURN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Richard Jarvie &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Buenos Aires, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Bond investors around the
world lined up to lend Argentina $2 billion today at
lower-than-expected interest rates, helping the nation finance its
growing national debt.
<p>
   The country sold 20-year global bonds at a yield of 11.375
percent, or 462.5 basis points more than U.S. government debt.
That's better than the 500 basis point difference underwriter
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. expected less than a week ago.
<p>
   Brisk demand for the country's debt suggests investors are
confident that Argentina, a nation that suffered from economic
stagnation and hyperinflation during much of the 1970s and 1980s,
will be able to pay lenders 20 years from now.
<p>
   Bond investors, faced with low yields and high prices in many
other parts of the world, ``have got to buy high-yield and emerging
markets debt,'' said Carl Ericson, head of $6 billion in taxable
fixed income at Colonial Advisory Services in Boston. Argentina has
``to make hay while the sun shines.''
<p>
   Underwriters said they'd received $8 billion in bids for the new
securities by the end of yesterday, three times as much as they
needed to sell. Argentina plans to raise the bulk of the $8.5
billion it needs to borrow in foreign markets this year by the end
of the first quarter.
<p>
   ``The government is being very shrewd in bringing forward its
funding, raising as much as possible,'' said Norberto Rosas, an
economist at Argentine consulting firm Proeco. ``It's covering
itself against a possible change in world financial market
conditions later in the year.''
<p>
   The global securities are sold simultaneously around the world
and traded around the clock. Demand for the bonds was so brisk that
the government scrapped its original plan to split the sale between
five-year debt and 20-year debt.
<p>
   Argentina was able to persuade investors to accept a lower yield
in part because they have little choice. Yields of many other bonds
have declined and investors are scouring the globe for high-yield
securities.
<p>
   Argentina's new debt still offers more yield than some of the
alternatives. The new debt yields more than the high-yield,
high-risk ``junk'' debt of some U.S. companies. The 8.25 percent
bonds of Kmart Corp., the U.S. retailer, recently yielded 313 basis
points more than Treasuries. The bonds, which mature in 2022, carry
a rating similar to Argentina.
<p>
   The country's 10-year debt yields about 370 basis points more
than U.S. government debt. The higher borrowing rate on the 20-year
securities gives investors an extra cushion, and ``takes into
account some chance that things will go badly,'' said Luis Luis, a
principal at Scudder Stevens &AMP; Clark that manages $1.75 billion in
Latin America debt.
<p>
   Still, Argentina's Par Brady bonds also offer investors the
chance to buy into the country, and they're backed in part by U.S.
Treasury securities. The Brady bonds yield 549 basis points more
than U.S. government debt.
<p>
   Yet Argentina was able to garner a lower yield at today's sale,
taking advantage of current low interest rates and growing investor
confidence in the country. In March, it plans to sell another $1
billion of bonds.
<p>
   This year, $10.2 billion of Argentina's debt comes due. Another
$10 billion matures in 1998, while in 1999 the sum rises to $11.6
billion, according to Fundacion Capital, an economic research firm.
<p>
   At the moment, the signs for Argentina's economy and the
nation's ability to manage its $100 billion debt, seem good.
<p>
   The economy is set to expand by about 5 percent this year
following 4 percent growth in 1996, according to government
officials and private economists.
<p>
   Inflation, once the nemesis of the economy, has been tamed. In
1996, retail prices rose by just 0.05 percent. Its inflation rate
was among the lowest in the world.
<p>
   Yet all is not rosy. The unemployment rate is 17 percent, and
the government hasn't been able to balance its budget.
<p>
   What's more, the chances for political change after President
Carlos Menem steps down in 1999 may also raise the risk that his
economic program will be scrapped. Concerns that Argentina will
fall into another period of high inflation and slow growth stopped
some investors from making a long-term commitment to the country.
<p>
   ''It was a far different country 20-years ago than it is today,
and I can't predict what the country will look like 20-years from
now,'' said Edwin Ferrell, who helps manage $3.2 billion for the
Principal Financial Group in Des Moines, Iowa. ``It's a leap of
faith.''
<p>
   Still, it appears that's a leap many investors are willing to
make.
</TEXT>
