<SLUG> BC-PENTHOUSE-MILITARY-UP </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0353 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PENTHOUSE-MILITARY-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PENTHOUSE MAY SELL MAGAZINE IN U.S. MILITARY STORES (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Seena Simon &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Rewrites third paragraph. Adds comment from Penthouse
publisher, Pentagon spokesman.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Penthouse magazine won a court
order allowing it to sell sexually explicit magazines and videos in
military-run stores at bases and on ships worldwide.
<p>
   U.S. District Judge Shira Scheindlin in New York granted
Penthouse owner General Media Communications Inc. and several
publishing and entertainment trade groups a preliminary injunction
that lifts a recent ban on the sales.
<p>
   The judge said the ban violates the First Amendment rights of
the publisher and others, and was unconstitutionally vague. Sales
of ``lascivious'' material that elicit a sexual response were
banned by the Military Honor and Decency Act of 1996.
<p>
   The judge ``has just given the First Amendment a new spitshine
by rejecting the bloated Military Honor and Decency Act as
unconstitutional,'' Penthouse publisher Bob Guccione said in a
statement.
<p>
   Pentagon spokesman Michael Doubleday said the military is
considering whether to appeal.
<p>
   The preliminary injunction replaces a temporary restraining
order Scheindlin had imposed against the military on Dec. 20.
``Sexually explicit material cannot be banned from sale or rental
at military exchanges merely because it is offensive,'' Scheindlin
wrote in a ruling issued today.
<p>
   She rejected the U.S. Defense Department's argument that the ban
would erode the military's core values of honor, courage and
commitment.
<p>
   The ban was to take effect last Dec. 22 after President Clinton
signed the decency act, which was included in the fiscal year 1997
military spending bill. Backed by several conservative Congressmen,
the law was passed in Congress without debate.
<p>
   Penthouse says it is the third-most popular magazine sold on
military exchanges. The decency act didn't ban the sale of sexually
explicit material in private stores in military bases.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1531EST
</TRAILER>
