<SLUG> BC-BBA-MATTINGLY-CHRONOL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0565 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BBA-MATTINGLY-CHRONOLOGY-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; YEAR-BY-YEAR CHRONOLOGY OF DON MATTINGLY'S MAJOR LEAGUE CAREER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Bob Bensch &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- A year-by-year look at the
major league career of Don Mattingly, who announced his retirement
today:
1982 - Made major league debut on Sept. 8 vs Baltimore, replacing
Dave Winfield in left field. Gets first career hit on Oct. 1
against Boston.
1983 - Begins season with Yankees and sent to Triple-A Columbus
April 14. Recalled June 20 when Bobby Murcer retires. Hits first
major league home run on June 24 at Boston.
1984 - Becomes first Yankee to win American League batting title
since Mickey Mantle in 1956 with .343 average, beating out teammate
Dave Winfield on last day of season. Named to All-Star game. Led
A.L. with 207 hits and 44 doubles.
1985 - Named A.L. Most Valuable Player after hitting .324 with 35
home runs and 145 runs batted in. Led major leagues in RBI, doubles
(48) and sacrifice flies (15). Led A.L. with 370 total bases and 86
extra-base hits. Won first Gold Glove Award. Named to All-Star
Game.
1986 - Finished second in A.L. MVP voting to Roger Clemens after
hitting .352 with 31 HR and 113 RBI. Led majors with 238 hits, .578
slugging percentage, 388 total bases, 86 extra-base hits and 53
doubles. Set team record for hits in a season. Wins second Gold
Glove Award. Named to All-Star Game.
1987 - Set new major league record by hitting six grand slams in a
season. Tied major league record by hitting home runs in eight
straight games. Hit 30 home runs to become first Yankee since
Mickey Mantle and Roger Maris in 1962 to hit 30 HR in three
straight seasons. Tied major league record with 22 putouts in a
game on July 20. Won third Gold Glove Award. Named to All-Star
Game.
1988 - Became first Yankee in 30 years to hit .300 for five
straight seasons after batting .303. Won fourth Gold Glove award.
Named to All-Star Game.
1989 - Played in 1,000th career game, going 4-for-4 with home run
and four RBI at California. Won fifth Gold Glove award. Named to
All-Star Game.
1990 - Missed 54 games with back injuries. Hit .256 to finish below
.300 for first time in seven seasons.
1991 - Named the 10th team captain in Yankees history. Won sixth
Gold Glove Award.
1992 - Led team in RBI (86) for sixth time, first player to do so
since Yogi Berra in 1955. Won seventh Gold Glove Award.
1993 - Set team record for fielding percentage by first baseman
(.998) and committed only three errors all season. Won eighth Gold
Glove Award.
1994 - Collected 1,000th career RBI against Texas on April 7.
Became sixth player to get 2,000 career hits as a Yankee. Hit first
career pinch-hit home run at California on July 24. Played in only
97 games, lowest total since becoming everyday player. Tied own
team fielding record for lowest percentage (.998), committing only
two errors in 989 chances. Set A.L. record by leading league in
fielding for seventh time. Won ninth and final Gold Glove Award.
1995 - Hit .288 with seven HR and 49 RBI. Appeared in postseason
for first time in career as Yankees earn Wild Card berth. Hit .417
in five-game series with Seattle with one HR and tied for team lead
with six RBI. Became free agent after season and didn't sign with
any team.
1996 - Sat out season.
1997 - Announced official retirement on Jan. 22.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1533EST
</TRAILER>
