<DOCID> nyt970122.0310 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9117 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0832 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FEA-MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MUTUAL FUNDS: AMERICAN CENTURY CHARGES SHORT-TERM INVESTORS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Tim Quinson &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Repeating for all needing.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Kansas City, Missouri, Jan. 20 (Bloomberg) -- American Century
Investments has a new mutual fund that penalizes investors who
think short-term.
<p>
   American Century's Twentieth Century New Opportunities Fund will
charge extra fees to any investor who pulls money within five years
of buying shares of the fund. That's a concrete incentive for
customers to become the kind of long-term investors the mutual fund
industry has long coveted.
<p>
   The fees equal 2 percent, or $20 per $1,000 withdrawn.
<p>
   ``It's a marketing gimmick designed to get people to invest for
the long term,'' said William Dougherty, president of Kanon Bloch
Carre, a Boston-based industry consulting firm. ``But, is it fair
or is it extortion?''
<p>
   Officials at Kansas City-based American Century, which used to
be called Twentieth Century Mutual Funds, said the ``2-percent
redemption fee emphasizes our position that investors should have
at least a five-year time horizon,'' said Christopher Doyle, an
American Century spokesman.
<p>
   The Twentieth Century New Opportunities Fund also is designed
for the more wealthy investor.
<p>
   The fund, which opened Jan. 1, is limited to investors who
already have at least $90,000 in assets with the company, Doyle
said. The fund also requires a minimum initial investment of
$10,000, which is above average for U.S. stock funds. The maximum
an investor can put in the fund is $500,000, and the management fee
is 1.5 percent, or $15 per $1,000 invested, he said. The average
management fee for a U.S. stock fund is closer to 1.4 percent.
<p>
   The extra fees will protect existing investors from untimely
redemptions, which could hurt the performance of the fund by
forcing the managers to sell securities they many not want to sell,
Doyle said. All redemptions fees charged would go to the fund
rather than the management company, he said.
<p>
   Investors will also hope to benefit from American Century's fund
management record for its long-term funds. Its Giftrust Investors
Fund, designed for people who want to make a gift in trust, usually
to a child, though it also can be to a charity, requires
investments be held for 10 years.
<p>
   Giftrust, started in late 1983, has assets of about $900
million.
<p>
   Giftrust has a stellar long-term record, even after suffering a
subpar 1996 when the fund gained 5.78 percent, according to
Bloomberg Fund Performance, compared with the 16-percent gain of
the Russell 2000 Index.
<p>
   Giftrust reported annual gains averaging almost 21.78 percent
over the past 10 years, ranking No. 1 of 33 ``small cap growth''
funds tracked by Morningstar Inc.
<p>
   American Century saw ``negligible'' shareholder fund withdrawals
during the summer when shares of small-sized companies were
especially volatile, Doyle said. Many of American Century's biggest
funds, including the $20 billion Ultra fund and the $2.2 billion
Vista fund, specialize in investing in these types of companies.
Neither fund charges redemption fees.
<p>
   American Century said it plans to close the New Opportunities
fund to new investors when it reaches $400 million, Doyle said.
Today, the fund has about $19 million in assets.
<p>
   Still, the 2-percent redemption fee and five-year limit are
unique for the fund industry, analysts said. The research group
Morningstar Inc. counts just one other U.S. stock fund that charges
a 2 percent redemption fee.
<p>
   Shareholders who pull assets from Oakmark Small Cap Fund within
six months of having purchased shares must pay a fee equal to 2
percent of assets. The fees are charged to prevent investors from
trying to time swings in the market by buying and selling fund
shares.
<p>
   Thirteen other funds available in the U.S. charge
similarly-sized fees, Morningstar reported. Ten are international
funds and three are ``tax-managed'' funds marketed by Vanguard
Group, according to the research group.
<p>
   ``These fees are designed to make sure people keep their money
invested,'' said Geoff Bobroff, an independent industry consultant
in East Greenwich, Rhode Island. ``If the markets crater, however,
people will run for cover no matter what the fees are.''
<p>
   That's what investors did -- at least for one week -- during
this past summer. Investors pulled about $5 billion from equity
funds in a mid-July week when the U.S. stock market suffered one of
its biggest declines in a decade, according to research groups that
track mutual fund money flows.
<p>
   ``Redemption fees will reduce this friction,'' Bobroff said.
<p>
   Still, it seems odd that someone would want to give his or her
money to American Century and let it sit there for five or 10 years
no matter what happens to the stock market. That takes a lot of
trust. And, now, American Century is rolling out another fund to
test investors' trust.
</TEXT>
