<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9121 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-SPORTS-BIZ-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0680 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FEA-SPORTS-BIZ-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMBING NEW ORLEANS FOR BRAND PIRATES: SPORTS BUSINESS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By W.D. Murray filed through the Princeton newsroom. &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Repeating for all needing.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New Orleans, Jan. 15 (Bloomberg) -- Pirates, beware.
<p>
   Squads of National Football League undercover agents will be
prowling the streets of New Orleans during Super Bowl week, looking
for people selling merchandise with unauthorized team logos, the
NFL said.
<p>
   Just as licensed merchandise has become a money machine for
professional sports, bootleggers make big money by selling
T-shirts, caps and other team paraphernalia without paying for the
right to use their logos.
<p>
   ``Counterfeit merchandise is still a big, big problem,'' said
Brian McCarthy, head of corporate communications for NFL Properties
Inc., the league's marketing arm. ``We take protecting our
licensees very seriously. Every product they (the illegal
merchants) sell not only rips off the licensee but also takes money
out of the league's pockets.''
<p>
   Some $10 billion of licensed sports products ranging from
trading cards to toilet seat covers was sold in the U.S. last year.
The NFL accounted for about $3 billion of that with $60 million to
$70 million coming from Super Bowl products. Bootleggers will sell
$1 million of Super Bowl merchandise alone, McCarthy said.
<p>
   Generally, the leagues keep anywhere from 8 to 15 percent of
total wholesale -- $1.5 billion in the NFL's case -- with the rest
going to the licensee.
<p>
   ``Companies spend a great deal of money to become an official
licensee,'' said Mike Nichols, editor and publisher of Team
Licensing Report, a Phoenix-based newsletter. ``If their rights are
not protected, then the license loses its value.''
<p>
   To help protect that value, the NFL, National Basketball
Association, National Hockey League, Major League Baseball, apparel
maker Starter Corp. and others have joined in a coalition called
CAPS -- the Coalition to Advance and Protect Sports Licenses -- to
police the business.
<p>
   The effort to crackdown on bootleg merchandise, pioneered by
such companies as Gucci Group, has worked for professional sports,
Nichols said.
<p>
   ``We are seeing less and less counterfeit merchandise being sold
on the streets of host cities,'' he said.
<p>
   To thwart counterfeiters, the league has designed a special
holograph that must be attached to all officially licensed
products. There are also special tags which are sewn onto the
garments or attached to the other items.
<p>
   ``We prosecute anyone we catch,'' McCarthy said. ``But the major
problem is that the laws aren't really tough enough. Many of these
illegal vendors are back on the streets selling knockoffs as soon
as they are released. And we see the same people at events across
the country. It's a lucrative underground business.''
<p>
   One company that is thankful for such policing efforts is Pro
Player, a division of Fruit of the Loom Inc. The Hudson, New
Hampshire, company owns the rights to produce T-shirts, jackets,
hats and fleece apparel bearing the Green Bay Packers and New
England Patriots logos. Super Sunday has become just that for the
company. ``This is huge, just huge,'' said a company spokesman.
``We came out with our `Squeeze the Cheese' T-shirts at the end of
Sunday's game and the orders have been flooding in.'' The company
said it expect $1 million in revenue from the ``Squeeze'' T-shirts.
Company president Doug Kelly had predicted before last weekend's
league championship games that a Packers Super Bowl victory could
mean additional sales of $6 million to $8 million. A Pats triumph
could bring an additional $5 million in revenue.
<p>
   Back in New Orleans, NFL Properties will be patrolling the
sidelines as well as the streets. The league has agreements with
several companies regarding what apparel and logos can be displayed
on the sidelines during a game. ``We know the attraction to such a
large television audience,'' McCarthy said. ``We want to stop any
attempt at ambush marketing.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1538EST
</TRAILER>
