<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9127 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-NEW-LEAGUE-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0600 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FOOTBALL-NEW-LEAGUE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; INVESTORS FORM ORGANIZATION TO START NEW PRO FOOTBALL LEAGUE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jon Friedman (212) 318-2337 &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Repeating for all needing.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 15 (Bloomberg) -- An investor group said it is
forming a new professional football league to challenge the
National Football League, beginning play in 1998. Wall Street
powerhouse Credit Suisse First Boston is assisting the new All
America Football League as its financial advisor.
<p>
   The AAFL expects to begin play in 12 of the nation's 25 largest
cities. The investor group's leader, Detroit real estate developer
Bernard Glieberman, said he couldn't name the cities or the
stadiums where the teams will play next year.
<p>
   Credit Suisse First Boston, based in New York, declined comment
on the financial details. It's the seventh-largest securities firm
in the U.S. and a unit of Zurich, Switzerland-based Credit Suisse
Group.
<p>
   Glieberman said the league will benefit by itself signing
players who would then be drafted the league's teams. He said this
arrangement will minimize the possibility that the teams will
encounter bloated payrolls, a financial hardship that has ruined
other professional sports leagues.
<p>
   Aside from that notion, Glieberman was skimpy on details about
important details. The league expects to begin play with
investments totaling $80 million, but Glieberman declined to
identify the investors or offer details on which networks will
broadcast the games. He didn't say what days the teams would play,
leaving a range of Friday through Monday.
<p>
   Then there is the matter of competing in prestige with the
established and booming National Football League. By holding its
games in the spring, the league will also bump up against the
baseball, basketball and ice hockey seasons in North America.
<p>
   Football analysts said the venture shapes up as a long shot
because the NFL is going through a prosperous period. It has no
labor unrest or strikes. NFL revenues have grown to more than $2.3
billion from $900 million in 1989. The average players' salary has
risen to more than $700,000 from $365,000 in 1990.
<p>
   ``It's hard to challenge the NFL because it's huge, established,
wealthy and it has got everything going for it,'' said Dick Schaap,
a commentator for ESPN and the author of several books about
football.
<p>
   The new league is bullish on its chances of success. Glieberman
said prospective sponsors are ``extremely excited about the way we
are handling this.'' He didn't name any of the sponsors.
<p>
   ``We're very confident that there is a tremendous amount of
football talent,'' said Randy Vataha, a consultant to the new
league and a former NFL player.
<p>
   ``If not for expansion, Mark Brunell would still be a backup
quarterback in the NFL,'' Vataha said, referring to the player who
emerged as a star of the Jacksonville Jaguars this year in the
team's second season in the NFL.
<p>
   Last May, the AAFL hired Game Plan Inc., a firm specializing in
consulting to sports leagues and teams. Game Plan found that almost
two-thirds of American adults describe themselves as avid or casual
football fans and that 54 percent of all U.S. adults will qualify
as potential AAFL fans.
<p>
   Still, ESPN's Schaap said: ``I don't think it's terrific timing
for a new league.''
<p>
   In fact, it was exactly 30 years ago today that the Kansas City
Chiefs of the upstart American Football League got drubbed by the
Green Bay Packers of the National Football League in the first
Super Bowl by a score of 35-10.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1539EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0313 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9132 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGACY-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1058 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CLINTON-LEGACY-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HISTORY MAY RECORD PRESIDENT CLINTON AS ANOTHER IKE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Monroe W. Karmin &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- So it wasn't a great
inaugural speech. So historians don't believe Bill Clinton will
rank as a great president. So what? Clinton, as his second term
begins, stands a good chance of presiding over eight years of peace
and prosperity. What president wouldn't covet that record for his
place in history?
<p>
   ``A lot of presidents would say, 'May God bless me with that
record,''' said Norman Ornstein, a political science scholar at The
American Enterprise Institute, a Washington think tank.
<p>
   Clinton, in interviews, likened himself to Thomas Jefferson and
Theodore Roosevelt, presidents who led the country as it entered
previous millenniums. The United States will enter its third
millennium in 2000, the final year of Clinton's presidency.
<p>
   However, Clinton's stewardship more closely resembles that of
Dwight Eisenhower. He, too, served two terms. He, too, steered the
country down the middle of the road. He, too, presided over peace
and relative prosperity. He, too, was much maligned during his time
in the White House.
<p>
   Yet Eisenhower's reputation is much higher today. If not
regarded as a ``great'' president, he's now rated as well above
average. His ranking has jumped from 22nd in the 1962 poll of
historians conducted by Arthur Schlesinger, the Harvard professor,
to among the top 10 more recently. ``Eisenhower is now seen as
having been a very useful president,'' said Stephen Hess, a
presidential scholar at The Brookings Institution, a Washington
think tank.
<p>
   Clinton could end up with a similar destiny, if the next four
years and history are kind. With luck as well as skill, the
president will have neither an international or domestic crisis to
deal with. There are no war clouds abroad and no recession, or
worse, immediately in sight at home.
<p>
   That benign outlook, strange as it may seem, is enough to
deprive Clinton of greatness. As he, himself, has said in
interviews, greatness tends to be bestowed on those presidents who
are faced with crises; be they George Washington who presided over
the founding of the country, or Abraham Lincoln who was confronted
by the slavery issue and the Civil War, or Franklin Roosevelt, who
had to cope with the Great Depression and World War II.
<p>
   Clinton's place in history, rather, will be determined by his
success, or lack of it, in attaining the goals he has set for his
second term. At the top of the president's agenda is reaching
agreement with congressional Republicans on a plan to balance the
budget by the year 2002.
<p>
   That may not seem to be such a big deal when compared with
winning wars and ending depressions. Yet, it could earn for Clinton
a place in the record books.
<p>
   The current economic expansion will be six years old this
spring. If it endures through Clinton's second term, it will
surpass the expansions of the 1980s and 1960s as the longest of the
post-World War II era. No small achievement.
<p>
   It's true most economists don't see that happening, with the
consensus predicting a recession in 1998 or 1999. Yet many
economists also agree that expansions don't inevitably die of old
age; rather, they come about because of unforeseen foreign crises
or policy mistakes by Clinton or others.
<p>
   In the current situation, most economists agree, one policy
mistake would be for Clinton to abandon his balanced budget goal,
which he so far shows no signs of doing. Abandoning the goal would
increase the pressure on the Federal Reserve to raise interest
rates to contain the inflationary effect of widening deficits.
<p>
   Another policy mistake, obviously, would be for the Fed to wait
too long to move against inflation even if the budget continues on
the road to balance. Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan shows no
inclination toward making that error. He told a congressional
committee this week that there are signs that the nation's tight
labor markets may be beginning to boost workers' pay increases
enough to cause inflation to pick up down the road. If that
happens, he indicated, the central bank will respond by raising
interest rates.
<p>
   Raising rates this year to head off an acceleration in
inflation, of course, would reduce the need to raise rates even
higher later on once inflation builds a head of steam. Early
action, moreover, would give the Fed flexibility to lower rates if
the economy slows too much going into 1998 and thus avert a
recession. If the Fed is skillful, ``we could see the economy
remain strong for quite a while,'' said AEI's Ornstein.
<p>
   For Clinton to make his contribution to the expansion's
longevity, he'll have to ignore the advice of the Schlesinger
historians, now presided over by Arthur Jr. ``Middle-roading may be
fine for campaigning, but it is a sure road to mediocrity in
governing,'' he wrote in a December ranking of presidents in the
New York Times. ``The middle of the road is not the vital center:
it is the dead center. Clinton would be wise to eschew it if he
wants to improve his ratings.''
<p>
   Clinton, however, has no choice but to travel down the middle of
the road; Congress is in Republican hands, after all. The
Republicans failed attempt at confrontation politics a year ago
certainly didn't advance the national agenda. Since his reelection,
the president has talked of the need for political cooperation and
giving voice to America's vital center.
<p>
   He did so again in his inaugural address. Noting that voters had
elected a Republican Congress and a Democratic president, Clinton
said: ``Surely they did not do this to advance the politics of
petty bickering and extreme partisanship they plainly deplore.''
<p>
   This week the president also played his opening card -- a
proposed $138 billion cut in Medicare expenditures over six years
-- in this year's battle of the budget. His formal budget will be
sent to Congress early next month, which will begin the political
painful process of trying to reduce the soaring costs of programs
that distribute benefits to people directly. If the
middle-of-the-road is Eisenhower terrain, then Clinton may find the
journey into history to have a rewarding destination -- a ``peace
and prosperity'' president, like Ike.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1541EST
</TRAILER>
