<SLUG> BC-IBM-SHARES-UPDATE3-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0722 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-IBM-SHARES-UPDATE3-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IBM STOCK DROPS AFTER DISAPPOINTING 4TH-QTR EARNINGS (UPDATE3) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Margaret D. Williams &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds details on businesses, updates share price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Armonk, New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- International Business
Machines Corp.'s stock dropped as much as 7.7 percent as investors
worried that lagging sales of its mainframes and related products
will hurt profits in coming quarters.
<p>
   IBM's stock fell 10 to 158 in late trading after the company
reported fourth-quarter earnings and sales that trailed
expectations. Shares earlier touched 155 and accounted for 35
points of the Dow Jones Industrial Average's 62.35-point drop.
<p>
   IBM shares had surged to nine-year highs on optimism for strong
growth in all its businesses. The company said late yesterday that
sales of computer hardware edged up just 2 percent as corporations
bought networks of personal computers rather than IBM's hallmark
mainframes.
<p>
   IBM also joined Computer Associates International Inc. and
Oracle Corp. in blaming dismal sales in Europe for disappointing
results.
<p>
   ``The revenue growth story is not real strong at IBM,'' said
John Rutledge, an analyst at Boston's Loomis, Sayles &AMP; Co. ``The
bloom is off the rose.''
<p>
   IBM's earnings were slightly below the average estimate of $3.96
a share from 15 analysts surveyed by IBES International Inc.
Several analysts expected earnings of more than $4.00.
<p>
   Net income rose to $2.02 billion, or $3.93 a share, from $1.71
billion, or $3.09, in the year-earlier quarter.
<p>
   At least four analysts cut their estimates for IBM's 1997
earnings and at least two cut 1998 estimates. John Jones at Salomon
Brothers downgraded his recommendation on the stock to ``buy'' from
``strong buy'' and Donald Young at Prudential Securities downgraded
the rating to ``hold'' from ``buy.''
<p>
   Others expressed concern that IBM's stock price will decline
substantially over the next few months. IBM's shares reached 168
yesterday, shy of the all-time high of 174 3/4 set in August 1987.
<p>
   ``Given that the stock has run up, we're probably going to see
the beginning'' of a decline, said Morgan Stanley analyst Steven
Milunovich. The drop could be as much as 15 percent in the next
three to five months, he said.
<p>
   IBM's not alone in reporting disappointing sales in Europe.
<p>
   European companies are spending less than half the amount that
U.S. and Asian firms spend on technology. That, coupled with weak
economies in some countries, will continue to hurt computer and
software companies, analysts said.
<p>
   Oracle said last month that weakness in Europe hurt its results,
and Computer Associates said yesterday that European sales fell 21
percent. IBM's sales in Europe were unchanged from a year ago at
$8.1 billion.
<p>
   Hardware is IBM's biggest business, accounting for 48 percent of
total sales last year and about two-thirds of profits.
<p>
   IBM unveiled new mainframes this fall. Even so, its hardware
sales edged up just 2 percent to $11.7 billion. System 390
mainframe sales declined and RS/6000 workstation sales were
unchanged from year-earlier levels.
<p>
   Software sales, nearly three-quarters of which are related to
mainframe sales, rose only 4 percent. And maintenance revenue from
contracts to service and maintain the big computers fell 6 percent
as more companies turn to cheaper and easier-to-operate PCs and
powerful servers to deliver information over networks.
<p>
   IBM's PC sales rose from the year-earlier quarter in both
corporate products and home machines.
<p>
   Sales at IBM Microelectronics, the company's chip business,
dropped from the year-earlier period, largely because of falling
prices for dynamic random-access memory chips.
<p>
   IBM's gross margin fell to 40.3 percent from 41.7 percent in the
year-earlier quarter, and IBM expects it to fall another percentage
point in 1997 as prices decline and the mix of more profitable
products is lower.
<p>
   Also, the stronger dollar cost the company 18 cents in per-share
earnings during the quarter. When the dollar is stronger, it is
more expensive to buy dollars with foreign currencies.
<p>
   IBM said yesterday that currency will continue to be a ``wild
card.'' IBM gets more than 60 percent of its sales from outside the
U.S.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1542EST
</TRAILER>
