<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9140 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-US-GRAINS-CLOSE-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0453 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-GRAINS-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SOYBEANS FALL AS RAIN SOAKS BRAZIL CROP (UPDATE1): U.S. GRAINS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Tim Coulter &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds final prices.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Chicago, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Soybean futures fell amid
expectations that recent rain in Brazil replenished soil moisture,
promising a bumper harvest.
<p>
   As much as 3 inches of rain fell last weekend on the world's
second-largest soybean crop, with the heaviest amount in key
growing areas of southern Brazil, and more moisture is on the way.
Weather Services Corp. said scattered rain is likely in southern
Brazil through this weekend and chances are increasing for showers
or thundershowers early next week.
<p>
   The rains could end concern that dry weather during the past
month would stunt development of the crop.
<p>
   ``People don't believe we have a weather problem in South
America,'' said analyst Don Roose at U.S. Commodities Inc. in West
Des Moines, Iowa. ``We think it's almost back to ideal, and that
has set the market back.''
<p>
   Soybeans for March delivery on the Chicago Board of Trade, after
opening higher, fell to $7.405 a bushel, down 6.25 cents.
<p>
   Lower prices for processed soybean products contributed to the
drop. March soybean meal lost $1.80 to $236.30 a short ton, and
March soybean oil fell 0.09 cent to 24.00 cents a pound.
<p>
   To be sure, some traders say additional moisture is needed for
Brazilian plants to reach full production potential. Since U.S.
supplies are headed for their lowest level in 20 years, a bumper
harvest in South America is essential to meet rising world oilseed
demand.
<p>
   ``You have a bullish situation in beans, and all the rain did is
delay the rally,'' said Fred Soneson, analyst at LFG L.L.C. in
Chicago, a commodities brokerage.
<p>
   Strong global demand has led to tight U.S. soybean reserves,
which by September are expected to drop to 155 million bushels, the
lowest since 1977, according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
<p>
   Traders on Friday will receive two key indicators of demand. The
Census Bureau will estimate December soybean crushings, and the
USDA will report export sales for the week ended Jan. 16.
<p>
   Wheat futures fell amid signs that increased world trade was
occurring outside the U.S.
<p>
   Iraq probably bought 300,000 metric tons of wheat and Egypt
secured 200,000 tons, traders said, though both orders were filled
outside of the U.S. India tomorrow tenders for 50,000 tons of wheat
but could buy substantially more, traders said, supplies that also
are likely to come from elsewhere.
<p>
   Wheat for March delivery fell 3 cents on the CBOT to $3.7925 a
bushel. March corn slid 0.5 cent to $2.705 a bushel.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1543EST
</TRAILER>
