<DOCID> nyt970122.0317 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=l pri=u sel=taf-z> A9141 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ANTIQUES-SHOW-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1272 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-ANTIQUES-SHOW-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; STALKING ANTIQUES WITH MONA &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (kd) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MITCHELL OWENS &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Muses have gone out of fashion, but given the largely
unsurprising wares at the 43rd Winter Antiques Show, the exposition
could have used a deity like Mona Strader Schlesinger Bush Williams
von Bismarck de Martini.
<p>
   This socialite, who died in 1983 at 86, would be the customer of
any dealer's dreams. During her heyday in the 1930s, a $700 million
fortune insured that whatever Mona wanted, Mona got. Too bad this
avaricious sylph, best known as Mona Bismarck, is not around,
checkbook ajar. Flaunt-happy plutocrats like her would spice up the
antiques show, a once-bright exhibition that appears to be sliding
into a blancmange. For the benefit of the East Side House
Settlement, the show opened at the Seventh Regiment Armory on Park
Avenue and 67th Street on Jan. 16 and closes Sunday.
<p>
   Perhaps the decline is due to timidity. Today's millionaires are
simply not keeping up appearances, which might explain the show's
emphasis on brown furniture. Camelback sofas can be dandy, but they
are rarely what make shoppers hyperventilate. What antiques shows
need are customers whose willingness to spend boldly inspires
dealers to flush out rare fantasias.
<p>
   Or dealers who are willing to take a gamble, to stock something
bizarre and pray for an adventuresome client to drop in. Like
beacons of hope in a sea of French-polished veneer, a few of this
show's 70 dealers understand that nothing exceeds like excess, but
for the most part the eye-popping items are few and far between.
Not to mention examples of solid scholarship.
<p>
   Barry Friedman, a dealer in decorative arts of the mid-20th
century, called Mona ``the wife of the architect of Rockefeller
Center.'' Hanging in his booth is a 1933 gold-frame pencil study of
Mona by Bernard Boutet de Monvel. The price is $6,500.
<p>
   Actually, Mona  &MD;  whose eyes of Caribbean blue and cropped silver
hair led her to be dubbed the ``rock-crystal goddess''  &MD;  had five
husbands. And not one was an architect. Her biggest catch was the
third, Harrison H. Williams, a utilities magnate, whose money was
the engine of opportunity for Mona, a Kentucky beauty with a
do-it-yourself English accent who became his second wife.
<p>
   She liked the rare, the exotic, the costly. Her shopping list
would have included something Chinese, to coordinate with the
Oriental wallpaper in her house at Fifth Avenue and 94th Street
(now the International Center of Photography) or to remind her of
the red-lacquer fence on her estate (now a housing development) in
Bayville, N.Y.
<p>
   Three mazelike windows for sale by Michael Goedhuis, a London
dealer, certainly would have caught Mona's Orientalist fancy.
Sternly elegant and constructed of age-ambered cedar, the windows,
which are basically square trelliswork screens, are relics of a
Ming dynasty villa. Each is priced at around $7,000.
<p>
   Mona would have craved, too, an 18th-century tile plaque cut
into the shape of a pagoda at Aronson of Amsterdam. It is priced at
$160,000. Glazed in orange, blue, yellow and red  &MD;  and looking like
a chinoiserie cookie by Martha Stewart  &MD;  the plaque depicts two
mandarins taking tea in a seaside gazebo trimmed with tiny bells.
<p>
   ``You hung it on a wall from a ribbon, like a picture,'' said
Irene Aronson, who added that the plaque's dominant color, yellow,
made for troublesome production: ``It's hard to bake properly. If
the kiln temperature is too high, the yellow pops off.''
<p>
   Mona might have chosen for her husband Harrison's dressing room
a pair of 7{-inch-by-6-inch black-and-white English ceramic
portraits of Tom Spring and Jack Langan, leading British boxers of
the 1820s. Priced at $3,000 for the pair, they are sold by the
Manhattan shop of Earle D. Vandekar of Knightsbridge. Harrison
Williams died in 1953, but his marital successor, a German count
who had been his secretary, would have appreciated the boxer
portraits, too: Edward von Bismarck took a keen personal interest
in male musculature.
<p>
   Forearms flexed and fists raised, Spring and Langan, who are
stripped to the waist in the pictures, fought a bloody 75-round
match in 1824  &MD;  both men bare-knuckled. As John Richardson, the
Picasso biographer, and Mercedes Bass, the socialite, mulled over a
Wedgwood platter, Paul R. Vandekar, said: ``Boxing was done without
gloves then, so you can imagine the damage inflicted.''
<p>
   Mona had a mania for all-white rooms  &MD;  Syrie Maugham, England's
white queen, decorated the Fifth Avenue Williams house and the
couple's place in Palm Beach, Fla.  &MD;  so she would have snapped up a
miniature silver-mounted Indian bureau bookcase in the booth of
Matz &AMP; Pribell. The 36-inch-tall tabletop folly is reassuringly
costly ($35,000) and happily rare (its only known siblings are in
museums). The 1770 bookcase is veneered in elephant ivory, etched
like scrimshaw with inky images of Dr. Seuss-surreal topiary trees
and oddly proportioned Georgian buildings.
<p>
   ``The Indians interpreted drawings provided by their British
colonial clients,'' said Marc J. Matz, ``so sometimes they ended up
a little quirky.''
<p>
   Also strange shaped is a gilt-bronze and blue-enamel Russian
mantel clock offered by Mory Linz-Einstein, the owner of a Paris
shop, Galeria Epoca. The style of the tubby timepiece, which is
encased in writhing tendril-like supports, can only be described as
Antoni Gaudi by way of Walt Disney. ``It was inspired by the
peasant art of ancient Russia,'' said Ms. Linz-Einstein, who added
that she bought the clock from a noble Russian family. She
described it as dating from ``before Pierre le Grand,'' referring
to the 18th-century Czar Peter the Great. One observer, however,
disagreed, labeling it Russian Art Nouveau. Whatever the era, it is
priced at $29,000, which includes a matching pair of four-branch
candelabra.
<p>
   Less expensive, at $25,000, but more certain in epoch is an 1872
third edition of ``The Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam.'' Offered by
Bauman Rare Books, its splendor is protected by the original
velvet-lined black leather presentation case. It is the binding,
not the contents, that would have enthralled Mona, who had a
passion for jewels but reportedly never read a book in her life.
<p>
   Designed and made by Sangorski &AMP; Sutcliffe, premier English
bookbinders, the Victorian volume is clad in midnight-blue morocco,
its cover emblazoned with a luscious gold peacock, whose sweeping
tail feathers incorporate 15 garnets, each the size of a nailhead.
The bird's eye is a cabochon ruby; the comb on his head is made of
seven natural seed pearls. And the back cover is paved with Ceylon
sapphires. Though its flowery prose is secondary to the byzantine
binding, the book was intended to be read, if at all, during ``a
very careful pensive moment,'' Natalie Bauman said.
<p>
   Mona's last husband, an Italian doctor, would not have
appreciated an 1870s sketch Peter Nahum is selling for $2,250. But
its sentiment and subject would be appropriate: when Umberto
Martini died in a suspicious automobile accident, he was on the
brink of exposure as a bigamist-embezzler.
<p>
   The sketch is the work of Sir Edward Burne-Jones, the
Pre-Raphaelite painter, and measures 5{ inches by 3~ inches. It
depicts a smirking, potbellied sprite beside the words ``Bent on No
Good.'' There is a secret image on the reverse: a white-clad
maiden, hand tinted and simpering.
<p>
   ``Burne-Jones loved vulnerable women but couldn't stand their
power over his emotions,'' Nahum said. ``This is like the devil
within and the devil without.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1544EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0318 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9142 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-US-BONDS-CLOSE-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0876 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-BONDS-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. BONDS FALL AS TRADERS SEEK BUYERS FOR TWO-YEAR NOTES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Dave Liedtk &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. bonds fell as Wall Street
firms struggled to sell the $17.5 billion of two-year notes they
bought from the Treasury and prepared for another auction tomorrow.
<p>
   The Treasury sold its notes at a yield of 5.984 percent, less
than the 6 percent yield traders anticipated just before the sale.
The issue recently yielded 6.01 percent.
<p>
   The lower-than-expected yield at the sale ``doesn't mean auction
went well,'' because securities firms can't sell the bonds for as
mexQ!eA%Q! &QC; YI959Q &QC; IQ!5M%5I-Sauvigne, a trader at Chase Securities
Inc. Making the sale more
difficult is the Treasury's sale of $12.5 billion of fivnotes
tomorrow. &HT;    The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond, little changed prior to the
1 p.m. Eastern time sale, slumped 1/2 point, or $5 per $1,000 bond,
pushing its yield up 3 basis points to 6.81 percent.
<p>
   Securities firms had an easier time finding buyers for the $2
billion of 20-year global bonds Argentina sold today, as investors
hungry for higher yields snapped up the securities.
<p>
   The country sold the bonds at a yield of 11.375 percent, or
462.5 basis points more than U.S. government debt. That's better
than the 500 basis point difference underwriters expected less than
a week ago. Global bonds are sold simultaneously around the world
and trade 24-hours a day.
<p>
   Bond investors, faced with low yields and high prices in many
other parts of the world, ``have got to buy high-yield and emerging
markets debt,'' said Carl Ericson, head of $6 billion in taxable
fixed income at Colonial Advisory Services in Boston. Argentina has
``to make hay while the sun shines.''
<p>
   Investors looked past government reports showing a drop in new
home starts and moderate economic growth as they fretted about
demand for all the new Treasury debt.
<p>
   With all the supply, ``people have got a pretty bearish
viewpoint right now,'' said David Hoffman, who manages $300 million
in bonds at Brandywine Asset Management in Wilmington, Delaware.
<p>
   Wall Street firms often push yields higher before the Treasury
sells debt to try to stir up demand from investors.
<p>
   ``The reaction to the two-year is burdened by the prospect of
more supply coming in the pipeline,'' said Tony Crescenzi, a trader
at Miller Tabak Hirsch &AMP; Co. ``Even with good results, the market
is not trading well off them,'' he said.
<p>
   Traders said comments from Federal Reserve Governor Susan
Phillips in a Market News interview also weighed on bonds earlier
in the day. Phillips suggested that the Fed might not wait for a
rise in the core consumer price index before boosting rates.
<p>
   ``Phillips' comments were extremely bearish. They lend support
to the believers who think that the Fed will still have to
tighten,'' or raise rates, said Todd Speiser, a trader at Aubrey G.
Lanston &AMP; Co.
<p>
   The Fed hasn't changed bank lending rates since January 1996,
when it cut the so-called federal funds target by a quarter of a
percentage point to 5.25 percent. The Fed's policy-making Federal
Open Market Committee next meets on Feb. 4-5.
<p>
   Earlier, bonds got a brief fillip after the government reported
a bigger-than-expected drop in December housing starts.
<p>
   The Commerce Department said housing starts fell by 12.2 percent
in December, after climbing a revised 9.3 percent the month before.
Analysts surveyed by Bloomberg News on average expected a decline
of 2.8 percent.
<p>
   Today's housing number adds to a body of evidence suggesting the
economy is growing with little inflation.
<p>
   ``By and large the numbers tell me the economy is not going
gangbusters and not falling off a cliff and that's what (Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan) said in his testimony,'' to the Senate
Budget Committee yesterday, said Robert Alley, who manages about
$2.5 billion at AIM Advisors Inc. in Houston.
<p>
   That should help temper concern that the Fed will soon raise
borrowing rates, some investors said.
<p>
   ``The Fed's likely to be on hold,'' said Alley, who's been
buying bonds lately as he receives cash in his fund. ``We're adding
bonds.''
<p>
   Investors got further evidence that the economy is growing and
jobs are being added at a non-inflationary pace from the Federal
Reserve's report on regional economic activity.
<p>
   While the Fed found ``scattered evidence'' that wages are rising
in its latest survey, the central bank found no evidence of
accelerating inflation, outside of energy prices.
<p>
   ``It more or less confirms the general impression that the
economy has picked up steam and that things are chugging along with
little threat of inflation,'' said Robert McGee, chief economist at
Tokai Bank.
<p>
   The Fed's regional outlook, commonly known as the beige book, is
based on anecdotal evidence of business conditions compiled by the
Fed's 12 district banks, and is published eight times each year.
The report will help form the basis for discussion on interest rate
targets at Fed's meeting next month.
<p>
   While release of the report had been set for 2 p.m. Eastern
time, it was inadvertently released ahead of schedule on the
Internet.
</TEXT>
