<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tia-z> A9145 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MATTINGLY-RETIRES </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0208 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BBA-MATTINGLY-RETIRES-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FORMER YANKEE DON MATTINGLY OFFICIALLY RETIRES FROM BASEBALL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Bob Bensch &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Don Mattingly, the greatest New
York Yankee never to appear in a World Series, officially retired
from baseball.
<p>
   Mattingly, 35, has not played since 1995 and was plagued by back
problems during his final few seasons, cutting his production.
<p>
   A free-agent after his last season, Mattingly elected not to
re-sign with the Yankees and sat out the 1996 season as New York
won its first World Series in 18 years.
<p>
   He never formally retired, leaving open the possibility to a
return to New York or another major league team. Last season,
Mattingly received contract offers from three or four teams, but
didn't accept any, saying the situations weren't right for him.
<p>
   A six-time All-Star, Mattingly hit .307 with 222 home runs and
1,099 runs batted in during his 13-year career. He won the 1984
American League batting title with a .343 average, edging out
teammate Dave Winfield on the final day of the season, and was
named the 1985 American League Most Valuable Player after hitting
.324 with 35 HR and 145 RBI.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1546EST
</TRAILER>
