<SLUG> BC-LEGAL-AFFAIRS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0941 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-LEGAL-AFFAIRS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JOB TITLES ARE MORE THAN JUST NAMES TO EMPLOYERS: LEGAL AFFAIRS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Seena Simon &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Martha Stewart may be the high
priestess of posh living to her fans, but to her former gardener
she's a wage cheat.
<p>
   Renaldo Abreu is suing Stewart in Connecticut state court,
saying she owes him more than $30,000 in overtime for washing cars,
grooming dogs and performing other work at the Westport estate that
serves as the set for the ``Martha Stewart Living'' shows on CBS
and the Lifetime cable channel.
<p>
   Stewart said he's not entitled to the extra pay, turning to a
tactic often used by companies trying to gain a legal edge in
disputes with employees: Describe their jobs in such a way that the
employee isn't entitled to receive overtime pay, to join a union or
to collect the minimum wage.
<p>
   ``Any law that protects workers can be evaded by
misclassification,'' said Laurence Gold, associate general counsel
for the AFL-CIO. ``It's happening more and more.''
<p>
   In Stewart's case, the dean of domesticity says Abreu has no
right to more than the $54,000 she paid him in 1994 because he's an
agricultural worker -- a job status exempt from overtime. The suit
is pending.
<p>
   The plight of Stewart's gardener isn't unique. Some of the
country's biggest companies routinely give workers job titles that
in no way depict what they do for a living. When challenged,
however, the name games often fail.
<p>
   Take the case of United Parcel Service Inc., which in August
lost a bid to call itself an ``airline'' and thus classify its
workers as airline employees. That designation would have helped
protect the company from strikes by its 165,000 drivers, package
sorters and mechanics represented by the International Brotherhood
of Teamsters.
<p>
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington found that since
90 percent of UPS packages never leave the ground, the company
wasn't an airline that would be governed by the Railway Labor Act,
which regulates railroads and airlines.
<p>
   The law was designed, among other things, to prevent crippling
strikes that idle the nation's transportation network and hurt the
economy. A strike can be barred for months or even years until the
National Mediation Board, a federal agency, declares negotiations
at an impasse. Only then can workers walk off the job.
<p>
   UPS said it wanted to come under the Railway Act to compete
better with largely non-union Federal Express Corp. Even FedEx
workers who are unionized, including 3,000 pilots, must go through
protracted mediation before they strike.
<p>
   ``It puts us at a competitive disadvantage,'' said UPS
spokeswoman Gina Ellrich. ``We provide the exact same services as
Federal Express.''
<p>
   The appeals court didn't buy that argument, noting that unlike
UPS, Federal Express's main business is air freight, with a
trucking operation as an add-on. The three-judge panel also pointed
out that FedEx started as an airline, while UPS has been regulated
as a trucking company for decades.
<p>
   Agriculture may be the biggest hotbed of job classification
disputes, because the industry is immune from federal laws that let
workers in other fields unionize and enjoy other rights.
<p>
   ``Agricultural workers are exempted from most of the protections
of federal labor law,'' said Georgetown University law professor
Michael Gottesman. ``There is a huge advantage to employers.''
<p>
   Of course, changing a job title without changing the work
doesn't always fly.
<p>
   Tyson Foods Inc., the big poultry processor, learned that lesson
last April, when the U.S. Supreme struck down its bid to lump
together 157 truckers, chicken catchers and forklift operators at a
Wilkesboro, North Carolina, plant as agricultural workers. Tyson's
goal was to block the workers from joining the Teamsters union, a
right not guaranteed to agricultural laborers.
<p>
   The ruling forced Tyson to let those workers and employees with
similar jobs at other Tyson plants unionize.
<p>
   While companies have tried to use creative job classifications
to deny extra pay and other benefits to workers, the federal
government may soon borrow the tactic in a move to impose reforms
on the poultry-processing industry.
<p>
   Later this year, the U.S. Labor Department is expected to try
using laws that protect migrant farm workers to make the industry
provide better housing and change how it recruits workers.
<p>
   The plan comes as the industry relies increasingly on workers
recruited from near the Mexican border for processing work in
Arkansas, Georgia and other states.
<p>
   ``This would place some basic requirement that the living
conditions be basically habitable and that the transportation be
habitable,'' said Laurence Norton, an attorney with Texas Rural
Legal Aid. ``Employers don't want to be covered by this because it
places restrictions on them.''
<p>
   The industry maintains that its workers are employed throughout
the year, not transients who follow crop harvests. For that reason,
said Rogers, Arkansas-based Hudson Foods Inc., migrant labor laws
don't apply.
<p>
   ``They are permanent employees,'' said Hudson Foods spokeswoman
Terri Mallioux. ``We don't hire seasonal workers.''
<p>
   If the industry challenges the Labor Department, courts likely
will be asked to examine what workers do on the job and decide
whether Congress wanted migrant labor laws to be broadly
interpreted.
<p>
   So don't be surprised if the debate over whether a job
classification fits the job grows as complicated as a Thanksgiving
dinner at Martha Stewart's house.
</TEXT>
