<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tia-z> A9151 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-INTRODUCT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0383 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PACKERS-INTRODUCTION-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PACKERS ELECT TO INTRODUCE DEFENSIVE UNIT AT SUPER BOWL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Scott Soshnick &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New Orleans, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Green Bay Packers coach Mike
Holmgren said his defense will be introduced at the Super Bowl,
preventing what could have been a divisive problem four days before
the game.
<p>
   The Packers used a rotation system this season, meaning it would
be the defense's turn this week. There was speculation, however,
that Holmgren would introduce his offense, which is led by
quarterback Brett Favre.
<p>
   The Super Bowl is a homecoming for Favre, the league's two-time
Most Valuable Player, who grew up about an hour away in Kiln,
Mississippi.
<p>
   ``There was a lot of lobbying from both sides,'' Holmgren said.
<p>
   Several defensive players, including veterans LeRoy Butler and
Sean Jones, said a switch would have disrupted the team.
<p>
   ``We thought we were going to get a raw deal because it's
Brett's home town,'' Butler said. ``I'm juiced for that
introduction.''
<p>
   So is second-year cornerback Craig Newsome, who Butler said is
working with his six-year-old son on some sort of routine when he
enters the field.
<p>
   While the Packers' high-octane offense got most of the attention
during the season, their defense ranked first overall in the
league.
<p>
   The unit's leaders are Reggie White and Jones, Green Bay's
defensive ends. White, the NFL's all-time sacks leader, like Jones,
is making his first appearance in the Super Bowl.
<p>
   ``I would have been upset,'' White said. ``But it wouldn't have
caused a problem.''
<p>
   Not true, Jones said.
<p>
   ``He's lying,'' he said. The defense would have been very
angry.''
<p>
   Perhaps recognizing that, Holmgren said he wouldn't fiddle with
the rotation, which he said has worked pretty well so far. At least
one member of the offensive unit said he's happy for the guys on
the other side of the ball.
<p>
   ``It was the right thing to do,'' said running back Edgar
Bennett. ``They deserve it.''
<p>
   Bennett is particularly happy for Butler, a teammate at Robert
E. Lee High School in Jacksonville, Florida, then at Florida State
and now in Green Bay.
<p>
   ``We're like brothers he said. ``It's like I'm out there with
him.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1548EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0322 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9155 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-COPPER-UPDATE1-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0670 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COPPER-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; N.Y. COPPER RISES ON SIGNS OF STEADY CONSTRUCTION (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Samantha Zee &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates with closing prices)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Copper prices rose after a U.S.
government report on December building permits, a gauge of future
demand for copper, showed little change.
<p>
   Permits for new U.S. housing construction were issued last month
at an annual rate of 1.410 million, down 0.6 percent from November,
when permits rose 4.1 percent, the Commerce Department said today.
<p>
   The permit figure -- a sign of steady future demand for copper,
a key material used by the construction industry --offset the
Commerce Department's report that U.S. housing starts fell 12.2
percent in December to a seasonally adjusted rate of 1.329 million.
Analysts had forecast a 2.8 percent decline last month.
<p>
   ``Look at the permit data, there's almost no change and it's a
better indication of demand for the construction industry,'' said
Dean Crist, an economist at the National Association of Home
Builders in Washington. The December declines in housing starts
were mostly weather-related, he said.
<p>
   Copper for March delivery rose 1.05 cent to $1.073 a pound on
the New York Mercantile Exchange's Comex division.
<p>
   Last month's drop in housing starts followed a revised 9.3
percent rise in November.
<p>
   Weather was ``a factor last month, with all the rain storms and
floods along the Californian coast and all the way up to the
Canadian boarder,'' Crist said. ``You can't even lay the
foundations of a house in weather like that.''
<p>
   Copper demand, particularly in the construction industry, can't
be assessed from `` a one-month perspective, but (from) the year
overall,'' said Joe Drosdick, a copper manager at American Iron and
Metal Co. in Verona, New Jersey.
<p>
   In an average 1,000-square feet apartment, about 280 pounds of
copper is used with the number rising to about 440 pounds of copper
in an average single-family home of 21,000 square feet, according
to the New York-based Copper Development Association Inc.
<p>
   In 1994, the building and construction industry used about 3.126
billion pounds of copper -- about 41 percent of total U.S. annual
production, the association said.
<p>
   Even with the drop-off in December, housing construction posted
the strongest annual gain in eight years during 1996.
<p>
   The lull during December may not last as demand from the
building industry is expected to grow this year, though not as
robustly as in 1996, according to the National Association of Home
Builders.
<p>
   ``The figures show growth, they're not going negative,'' Crist
said. ``Still, we expect a slowdown in overall economic demand
because we don't see the same level of employment this year as last
year.''
<p>
   Housing starts are estimated at 1.382 million this year, Crist
said, down 6.2 percent from 1.474 million last year when starts
rose 8.8 percent, the highest level since 1988, fueled by a dip in
30-year fixed mortgage interest rates below 7 percent.
<p>
   ``I'm rather optimistic about 1997 now that it's arrived, much
more optimistic than I was six or seven months ago.'' said Robert
Strudler, chief executive officer of U.S. Home Corp. in Houston.
<p>
   Still, the weakness in December construction demand comes at a
time of rising exchange-held supplies. London Metal Exchange
stockpiles rose 4,725 metric tons yesterday to 143,225 tons. The
jump bolstered expectations that copper supplies held in exchanges
will grow in the coming months, easing concern of spot shortages.
<p>
   ``The trend for LME stockpiles is higher, although some of the
Comex stockpiles are going to LME warehouses,'' Drosdick said.
<p>
   While Comex copper supplies fell 1,389 short tons (1,260 metric
tons) since Friday, U.S. copper warehouses operated by the LME
registered increases. The largest gains were in Baltimore, up 375
tons and in Long Beach, California, up 2,250 tons, the LME said
yesterday.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1550EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
