<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HKN-FLAMES-MOVES-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CALGARY FLAMES RECALL DEFENSEMAN CHRIS O'SULLIVAN FROM MINORS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Dan Bollerman &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Calgary, Alberta, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Calgary Flames
recalled defenseman Chris O'Sullivan from their American Hockey
League affiliate in Saint John, New Brunswick.
<p>
   O'Sullivan, 22, had two goals and eight assists in 23 games for
the Flames earlier this season.
<p>
   At St. John, the 6-foot-2, 185-pounder tallied two goals and
four assists in 16 games.
<p>
   O'Sullivan played the last four years at Boston University after
the Flames made him the 30th overall selection in the 1992 NHL
Entry Draft.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1554EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0326 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9168 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-MINDING-MONEY-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0779 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FEA-MINDING-MONEY-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NIMBLE MANAGERS WILL BE KING IN 1997: MINDING MONEY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Katherine Burton &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Repeating for all needing.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 20 (Bloomberg) -- Rich people, and the folks who
manage cash for them, are betting that they'll have to be a bit
more original this year to make money.
<p>
   ``I've restructured my portfolio to be nimble,'' said George
Hambrecht, president of Barlow Partners, who manages $110 million
by farming out cash to outside managers who invest primarily in
U.S. stocks. ``That way we'll only lose an arm and a leg rather
than the whole body.''
<p>
   With analysts expecting meager returns on U.S. stocks, investors
are looking for managers who can make money even if U.S. shares
tumble. That's why they're placing money with global managers of
stocks, bonds, commodities and currencies, or with managers who
specialize in parts of the U.S. market they think will make money,
such as gold or technology shares.
<p>
   They also want managers who sell stocks short, by borrowing
shares and selling them immediately hoping to later buy them back
at lower prices.
<p>
   Last year, managers profited from being one-trick ponies. Julian
Robertson, who runs the $8.5 billion Tiger Management funds,
returned 38 percent after fees in 1996. Even though he can invest
in stocks, bond and commodities around the globe, he concentrated
on the U.S., betting that such shares as Citicorp, Intel Corp. and
USAir Inc. would jump.
<p>
   Leon Cooperman, who runs the $3 billion Omega Advisors global
fund, also made a bundle from U.S. stocks. His fund returned about
36 percent after fees in 1996.
<p>
   Neither were available to talk about 1997 strategies.
<p>
   Hedge fund managers don't expect U.S. earnings to climb more
than 5 percent this year, meaning stocks prices will probably climb
less than 10 percent, said Charles Gradante, co-principal of
WPG-Hennessee Hedge Fund Advisory Group, a New York consultant that
matches wealthy investors with money managers.
<p>
   Gradante is telling his clients to put two-thirds of their money
overseas or in investments that don't move in tandem with U.S.
stocks. Last year, he told clients that two-thirds of their money
should be in the U.S.
<p>
   Evaluation Associates in Norwalk, Connecticut is putting a
``large percentage'' of its $500 million in hedge funds with
managers who invest in stocks, bonds, commodities and currencies
around the world, said Patrick Moriarty, a senior vice president.
``They can take both sides of a bet.''
<p>
   Last year, some of the biggest managers who bet on macroeconomic
trends by, say, buying the dollar or shorting oil, didn't do well
in part because they weren't heavily invested in U.S. shares.
<p>
   Mark Strome's Offshore Fund ended the year down 16.9 percent,
and George Soros' $7 billion flagship Quantum Fund dropped 1.49
percent, its worst year since 1981.
<p>
   Strome, who runs Strome, Susskind Investment Management in Santa
Monica, California, is preparing to short the U.S. stock market
this year, said a person familiar with the fund.
<p>
   Other global managers are pouring money into European, Latin
American and Asian markets, said Gradante of WPG-Hennessee.
<p>
   European stocks and bonds should do better that their U.S.
counterparts, Gradante said. That's because interest rates are
expected to remain unchanged or fall as inflation remains under
control.
<p>
   Global managers are also bullish on Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index,
which has already jumped about 17 percent in the past three months,
and in stocks in Thailand, South Korea and India, which all got
trampled last year but are poised for a rebound.
<p>
   In Latin America stock markets, Mexico, Venezuela and Argentina
are all getting new money from these managers, Gradante said.
<p>
   In the U.S., Hambrecht's betting on technology managers who buy
and hold shares as well as sell them short. He also has money with
energy managers, who should do well because low inventories in
heating oil, gasoline and crude should push energy prices higher.
<p>
   Jim Hedges, who runs LJH Alternative Investment Advisors in
Naples, Florida, a consultant to wealthy individuals and
institutions, agrees that Thailand, South Korea and India stocks
should be winners this year.
<p>
   He also likes the debt of companies in or near bankruptcy, which
he said could return around 20 percent for the second year in a
row; real estate investment trusts, which generally don't move in
the same direction as other U.S. stocks and gold stocks, which
could benefit from declining production costs and which are selling
cheaply because of low gold prices.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1556EST
</TRAILER>
