<STORYID cat=w pri=s sel=tad-z> A9171 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-LABS-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1441 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EPA-LABS-COX  &QL; 
 &UR; DID EPA UNLEASH A WITCH HUNT AMONG ITS OWN SCIENTISTS?
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; For release Saturday, Jan. 25.
<p>
    &UR; By JEFF NESMITH &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  More than three years after the U.S. government
accused Jesse MacArthur ``Mac'' Long of defrauding taxpayers out of
the cost of obtaining a Ph.D. degree, the complaint against the
Environmental Protection Agency scientist has been dropped.
<p>
   In return for a U.S. attorney's agreement to take no further
action against him, Long agreed to pay $24,000 in ``reimbursement''
for taxpayers' money that paid for tuition and other expenses
associated with the doctorate.
<p>
   Before closing the case, government lawyers said they never
intended to accuse him of wrongdoing, violating any law or
breaching any contract. But, they said, in receiving the degree
from Montana State University in 1993 he may have benefited from
``wrongful conduct'' on the part of someone else.
<p>
   Long, a 53-year-old chemist at EPA's research laboratory in
Athens, Ga., says that in order to pay legal costs and the
agreed-to settlement, he and his wife have exhausted their life
savings and been forced to take out a second mortgage on their
home. His attorney estimates the settlement and defense costs will
total well over $100,000.
<p>
   Some career EPA scientists see Long's ordeal as much more than
one man's fight to save his reputation. The charges against him
grew out of a wide-ranging investigation of several EPA research
laboratories by the EPA Office of Inspector General (IG), the
agency's internal ``watchdog'' organization.
<p>
   The case and others growing out of the IG probe raised a raft of
thorny public policy issues, including the direction of the
agency's scientific programs and the level of expertise expected
and encouraged at EPA.
<p>
   ``EPA scientists and their front-line managers received brutal
treatment during IG investigations that federal hearing examiners
subsequently ruled were carried out in bad faith,'' said EPA
microbiologist David Lewis, also of Athens.
<p>
   During the IG's investigations of EPA labs, dozens of scientists
were interrogated, and some were threatened with criminal charges.
Several were fired, suspended or demoted  &MD;  only to be reinstated
when actions against them were appealed. In some cases, the
government was ordered to pay their attorney fees.
<p>
   A relatively new federal agency, EPA has failed to establish a
reputation as an outstanding scientific organization. A chorus of
complaints about the agency's science has been led primarily by
regulated industry, especially chemical manufacturers. However,
university researchers, environmentalists and even some EPA
managers have charged that scientific achievement at the agency is
stagnant.
<p>
   Five years ago, an independent panel convened by
then-Administrator William K. Reilly concluded that EPA had
provided ``insufficient incentives to reward the production of
high-quality science.''
<p>
   Its report stated, ``The panel strongly recommends that the
agency expand opportunities for rotations that allow scientists
from other organizations to work in EPA's science programs and EPA
scientists to participate in the scientific efforts of other
organizations.''
<p>
   Long's co-workers, who have raised $3,300 in a legal defense
fund for him, say he is an honest and dedicated government worker,
whose career and savings were laid waste by a ruthless effort to
find examples of ``fraud, waste and abuse'' in government.
<p>
   Ironically, it was his attempt to broaden his expertise that
caused him to run afoul of the controversial investigation by
Inspector General John Martin, who launched probes of the Athens
lab and several others while under stinging criticism in Congress
for allegedly failing to more vigorously expose examples of fraud,
waste and abuse at EPA.
<p>
   To allay criticism from a House subcommittee, Martin rewrote the
criteria under which his top investigators received their annual
federal employee job performance evaluations. The new standards
pressured them to produce indictments, administrative action or
civil lawsuits in at least 25 percent of the cases they supervised.
<p>
   They were awarded extra ``points'' when one of their cases
attracted the interest of a member of Congress or got publicity for
Martin's office.
<p>
   IG investigators charged that beginning in 1989, Long
manipulated bureaucratic processes to obtain benefits to which he
was not entitled  &MD;  the Ph.D. degree  &MD;  at taxpayers' expense.
<p>
   Long, who joined the Athens laboratory in 1975, applied in 1988
for a training program under which EPA sponsors a limited number of
employees for postgraduate studies. He was turned down.
<p>
   He said that Rose Marie Russo, director of the Athens
laboratory, then directed him to prepare the paperwork to have
himself temporarily detailed to Montana State to do the research he
had proposed in the detection of extremely low levels of
pollutants.
<p>
   Court records show that Martin's office recommended that Long be
indicted over the Ph.D. degree, but that a U.S. attorney in Macon,
Ga., declined to take the case because it did not involve ``drugs
or guns and a bunch of peanut farmers'' on a Georgia grand jury
would not understand it.
<p>
   The failure to get an indictment did not end the IG's interest
in Mac Long, however.
<p>
   On the night of Nov. 9, 1994, two IG investigators knocked on
the front door of Long's home in Athens. They handed him a letter
advising him that the U.S. attorney in Billings, Mont., intended to
file a civil lawsuit against him for $117,317.83, the amount the
investigators had concluded the government paid in salary, tuition
and other expenses involved in the degree.
<p>
   Investigator Lorraine Fairchild later recalled in a court
deposition that as Long stared at the letter, she asked him to
engage laboratory director Russo in a secretly recorded telephone
conversation aimed at implicating the lab director in the case.
<p>
   Long refused. The Montana U.S. attorney filed the lawsuit on
Dec. 13, 1994, charging that Long had manipulated the EPA grant
process to set up his own Ph.D. program at government expense. That
amounted to ``unjust enrichment'' and fraud against the government,
the suit declared.
<p>
   Martin retired this month, coincidentally on almost the exact
day the lawsuit against Long was being closed. A few weeks before
leaving the job, he said in an interview that the probe by his
office of agency research laboratories, and of scientists such as
Mac Long, had identified numerous management problems that needed
to be corrected.
<p>
   He said the effort by his investigators to get people such as
Long to surreptitiously tape-record staged conversations with their
superiors was a respected and commonly used law enforcement
technique.
<p>
   For his part, Martin refused a request that the interview be
tape-recorded.
<p>
   He said the pressure placed on his supervising investigators to
produce ``criminal and/or administrative action'' against the
people they investigate was ``a sort of incentive program.''
<p>
   He said extra points are awarded for cases that attract
publicity because of the importance of letting EPA employees
``realize that we do find wrongdoing and that when we do we
aggressively pursue it.''
<p>
   But the series of audits and investigations of the EPA
laboratories has sent a different message, some scientists say.
<p>
   ``These labs bore the brunt of the IG thing,'' said Sam
Karickhoff, a research chemist at the Athens lab, adding that the
investigations provoked ``a lot of paranoia'' among scientists.
<p>
   ``It appeared to me that the IG people came, at least to our
lab, with a preconceived idea of guilt and an agenda to prove their
preconceived notions,'' said Robert Swank, director of research at
the 70-employee laboratory. ``I think the results have been a major
negative impact on morale and productivity.''
<p>
   Late last year, the government offered to drop all charges if
Long would pay the reduced sum of $24,000.
<p>
   Stanley Kaleczyc, Long's Montana lawyer, said the expense of
going to trial would probably add more than that to Long's legal
bills. Kaleczyc advised his client to accept the settlement offer.
<p>
   Long said he decided he and his wife could fight no longer, so
he agreed to the settlement.
<p>
   ``Prior to this, the only black marks on my record were two
speeding tickets,'' he said. ``We have both suffered an enormous
physical, emotional, financial disaster. It was a terrible
injustice that decent, honest, hard-working people should not have
had to endure.''
</TEXT>
