<STORYID cat=d pri=r sel=ttx-z> A9172 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ULTRACAFFEINE-DRINKS- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0632 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-ULTRACAFFEINE-DRINKS-TEX &QL; 
FIZZ BIZ: HERE'S THE BUZZ ON COKE'S AND PEPSI'S NEW
EXTRA-CAFFEINATED DRINKS &QL; 
EDS: Accompanied by ULTRACAFFEINE-TASTE TEST and
ULTRACAFFEINE-BOX. &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
By BEVERLY BUNDY &QC; 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The average American drinks a gallon of soft drinks a week.
Coca-Cola and Pepsico are out to see that she drinks even more.
<p>
   Both companies are rolling out new drinks. Coke is taking aim
with Surge, a Mountain Dew/PowerAde-type drink. Pepsi has Josta, a
mahogany-hued fizzer made with the Brazilian guarana berry.
<p>
   Both are new flavors for newish soft drink consumers.
<p>
   ``Consumers tend to be interested in trying new products and
wanting variety now and then,'' says Gary Hemphill, vice president
of Beverage Marketing Corp., a consulting and information group for
suppliers and manufacturers of soft drinks. ``That's the reason
we've seen soft drink companies getting involved in partnerships
for bottled and canned teas, drinks like Fruitopia and Pepsi
pairing with Ocean Spray.''
<p>
   Too, there's a whole new group of consumers coming up every
couple of years. Teen-agers drink more soda than other Americans,
and they develop brand loyalty early.
<p>
   ``Young people drink large quantities of soft drinks,'' says
John Sicher, editor and publisher of ``Beverage Digest,'' a
newsletter for the nonalcoholic beverage industry. ``When a young
person forms an allegiance to a brand, it is largely carried
through as the person gets older.''
<p>
   In Coke's case, it's not just teen-agers that it wants for its
new Surge; it's 12- to 24-year-old males. Street buzz is that Surge
is Coke's entry to go up against heavily caffeinated Mountain Dew,
Pepsi's $3 billion-a-year heavy citrus soda, which is popular with
young men.
<p>
   But Surge is an animal unto itself. In addition to high fructose
corn syrup, the drink also contains maltodextrin, the carbohydrate
used in PowerAde, Coke's sports drink.
<p>
   This yields a neon-green soda that has about the same amount of
caffeine as Mountain Dew (slightly more than Coke or Pepsi) but
still far less than coffee. (A 12-ounce serving of Pepsi contains
38 milligrams of caffeine, Mountain Dew has 52 milligrams and
coffee has about 300 milligrams.)
<p>
   The sugars in Surge are a whopping 42 grams, about par with soft
drinks but nearly double that of sports drinks.
<p>
   Sicher says the Surge formula follows the trend in the soft
drink beverage industry of having ``value-added products that add a
nutritive element,'' much like the orange juice industry is adding
calcium to its formula.
<p>
   Josta, Pepsi's new soft drink, also has an added element, but
the company is pussyfooting around the issue.
<p>
   Josta is made with the caffeine-laden guarana, a Brazilian berry
that word of mouth compares to Asia's ginseng, used for centuries
as a folkloric sexual and physical stimulant. Several mammoth
companies were pushing to get guarana beverages on the shelves;
Pepsi won the race.
<p>
   Pepsi makes no claims, but the legend on the panther-emblazoned,
jungle-themed cans reads: ``Guarana grows deep within the jungle.
For centuries, ancient tribes believed that guarana released raw,
primal power. Now the legend of guarana has been captured in the
potent flavor of Josta. Unleash it.''
<p>
   Whatever else it does, Josta unleashes a jolt of energy. It
weighs in with 59 milligrams of caffeine and 44 grams of sugars in
a 12-ounce can.
<p>
   Don't expect the soft drink category to stop with these entries.
Pepsi recently went into a developmental deal with Starbucks to
come up with coffee-based soft drinks. Talk about your primal
power.
<p>
   -
<p>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.startext.net; www.arlington.net; and www.netarrant.net)
</TEXT>
