<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9173 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-COOPER-LYBRAND-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0651 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COOPER-LYBRAND-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SEC UPHOLDS SUSPENSION OF TWO EX-COOPERS &AMP; LYBRAND EXECUTIVES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Neil Roland &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Washington) -- The Securities and Exchange
Commission upheld the suspension of two former Coopers &AMP; Lybrand
executives for failing to recognize red flags about the financial
condition of Savin Corp. in the early 1980s.
<p>
   The executives, David Checkosky and Norman Aldrich, both
accountants, recklessly agreed to defer costs that Savin incurred
in developing a new photocopier, the SEC said. The company later
filed for bankruptcy protection. The accountants ignored numerous
signs ``that should have caused them to question Savin's accounting
treatment,'' the SEC ruled in a 2-1 vote. Instead of showing
``heightened vigilance,'' the Coopers partners demonstrated ``lack
of independent judgment,'' the SEC said. Checkosky's and Aldrich's
attorneys declined comment. The two former Coopers partners had
argued in an earlier administrative filing that they ``consistently
used substantial care'' during the audits while trying to comply
with an ``ambiguous'' accounting standard.
<p>
   The 27-page SEC decision said that Savin's improper cost
deferrals allowed it to narrow operating losses. The Coopers
accountants should have reacted to red flags that included company
financial losses, employee lay-offs, and unsuccessful attempts to
develop copier designs, the decision said.
<p>
   SEC Commissioner Norman Johnson was the lone dissenter, arguing
that Checkosky and Aldrich were ``merely negligent'' and acted
without willful intent.
<p>
   ``The majority's position will impair the relationships between
professionals and their clients,'' wrote Johnson, a Republican.
``Difficult ethical and professional responsibility concerns are
generally matters most appropriately dealt with by professional
organizations or, in certain cases, malpractice litigation.''
<p>
   Johnson also argued that the Coopers audits at issue were too
old to rule on. Voting for the majority were SEC Chairman Arthur
Levitt and Commissioner Isaac Hunt, both Democrats.
<p>
   ``Recklessness'' has been defined by the courts as ``an extreme
departure from the standards of ordinary care.'' ``Negligence'' is
considered an inadvertent or insignificant deviation from
accounting standards.
<p>
   The SEC decision yesterday ended a lengthy case first ruled on
by the SEC in 1992. Checkosky and Aldrich appealed the decision to
the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit,
which sent it back to the SEC in 1994 ``for a more adequate
explanation.''
<p>
   The SEC decision upheld the two-year suspension of Checkosky and
Aldrich from working as accountants for a publicly traded company.
The penalty was academic, as the two finished serving their
suspensions in 1994.
<p>
   Checkosky, who was lead partner on the 1981-1984 audits, and
Aldrich, who was an audit manager and concurring partner, have both
left the firm, a Coopers spokeswoman said. Coopers, the nation's
fifth largest accounting firm, declined comment on the matter.
<p>
   An academic said today that the SEC decision ``is important in
underscoring the idea of professional responsibilities.
<p>
   ``If a company's in financial trouble and there are enough red
flags, it doesn't take a genius to figure out that they may try to
play accounting games,'' said J. Edward Ketz, a Penn State
University accounting professor. ``The auditor has to be more
A0vigilant.''
<p>
   Stamford, Connecticut-based Savin, which emerged from year-long
Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in 1993, declined comment. The
company settled SEC charges in 1985 by agreeing not to commit
future violations, to restate 1983 and 1984 annual reports, and to
write off some deferred costs related to development of the
copiers. Savin neither admitted nor denied wrongdoing under the
settlement.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1559EST
</TRAILER>
