<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9175 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-STOCKS-CLOSE-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0397 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CHILE-STOCKS-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CHILE STOCKS TUMBLE AS STRONGER PESO DETERS FOREIGN INVESTORS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Philip Sanders &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Santiago, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Chilean stocks fell as a
stronger peso made it more expensive for foreign investors to buy
shares, deterring new investment.
<p>
   The peso rose 1.5 percent during the last two days after the
central bank widened the band within which the currency can trade.
<p>
   ``You can buy less stocks with the same dollars today than
yesterday,'' said Axel Christensen, head of research at Citicorp in
Chile.
<p>
   Moreover, the stronger peso hit exporters including Cia. de
Petroleos de Chile SA, or Copec, whose shares fell as their goods
became more expensive overseas.
<p>
   The selective stock index tumbled 2.32 points, or 2.08 percent,
to 108.94, according to results taken immediately after the market
closed. The general stock index fell 64.59 points, or 1.23 percent,
to 5196.97.
<p>
   ``Logic says exporters are going to be hit by the stronger
peso,'' said David Chon, a strategist at Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. in New
York.
<p>
   Among exporters, shares in Copec fell 2.06 percent to 1660.00,
while Cia. Manufacturera de Papeles y Cartones SA, or CMPC, dropped
2.63 percent to 4625.00.
<p>
   Other stocks fell as foreign investment dried up because of the
stronger peso, Christensen said.
<p>
   Moreover, ``there is no local support for stocks at these
prices,'' he said. ``The pension funds aren't buying any more.''
<p>
   After rallying 15 percent over two weeks, stocks slumped 5.5
percent in the last two days amid concern they're overvalued.
<p>
   Shares in Empresa Nacional de Electricidad SA, or Endesa,
slumped 5.86 percent to 241.0, partly on concern profits will fall
this year.
<p>
   ``Our view on Endesa is negative,'' said Juan Sommer, head of
research at Celfin SA. ``There is a lot of short-term bad news for
the company,'' which is Chile's largest hydroelectricity generator.
<p>
   The recent drought is forcing Endesa to buy more expensive
electricity from thermal power producers in order to meet its sales
commitments.
<p>
   Shares in Enersis SA, which owns 26 percent of Endesa, fell 1.81
percent to 244.01. Trading totaled 14.04 billion pesos ($33.3
million) today. The number of issues that advanced, declined or
closed unchanged wasn't immediately available.
</TEXT>
