<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=ttj-z> A9191 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SELENA-PERMIER-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0830 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SELENA-PERMIER-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHERE IN THE WORLD WILL `SELENA' OPEN? HERE, HOPES SAN ANTONIO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JIM BEAL JR. &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Antonio Express-News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SAN ANTONIO  &MD;  Where in the world is the ``Selena'' movie world
premiere to be? Will there even be a star-studded world premiere?
<p>
   Movie representatives frantically dodged those questions this
week, denying reports that the film would premiere not in Texas,
where the late Tejano music superstar lived, but in Miami.
<p>
   The prospect outraged Selena's many fans here.
<p>
   Selena Quintanilla Perez, a musical icon for Latin Americans and
Spanish speakers in the United States, rose to fame in San Antonio
and other parts of South Texas. Her brief career ended tragically
when she was shot to death by a disgruntled ex-employee in Corpus
Christi, Texas in 1995.
<p>
   ``Selena,'' a major motion picture about her life, is slated to
open nationwide March 21.
<p>
   The controversy started Saturday when the San Antonio
Express-News reported that the movie would premiere in 14 cities,
with a world premiere featuring the movie's major stars in Miami
March 18.
<p>
   The story was based on information provided by Bert Quintanilla,
marketing director of Q Productions, the Corpus Christi-based
talent and booking agency run by Selena's father, Abraham
Quintanilla.
<p>
   The story quoted a representative from Esparza-Katz Productions,
makers of the movie, who said plans were ``still evolving; anything
could change.''
<p>
   The news touched off criticism from disappointed Selena fans in
South Texas who were surprised by the Miami choice.
<p>
   It also triggered angry phone calls to the newspaper from the
movie's producers and representatives of Q Productions.
<p>
   Moctesuma Esparza, producer of ``Selena,'' said there are no
firm premiere dates, ``nor have we finalized the selection of
cities or what we're going to do in any of the cities.
<p>
   ``Our intention is to have a fabulous celebration there in South
Texas, as well as in all of the United States. Our intention is to
take the celebration of this beautiful movie of Selena's life to
all of her fans and to share this with everyone. But we will
definitely have a gala celebration in South Texas,'' Esparza said.
<p>
   Esparza called the list ``an internal document'' and didn't seem
too keen about the word ``premiere.''
<p>
   ``This will be a movie with multiple premieres,'' he said. ``I
don't know that we'll even call them that, because it's becoming a
misunderstanding over nothing.''
<p>
   But fans didn't seem to misunderstand the possibility that Miami
could be the site of the film's biggest opening event.
<p>
   ``People thought they should show the movie here or in Corpus
first,'' said Richard Pena of pioneering Tejano radio station KEDA.
<p>
   A ``Selena'' press junket to which movie critics are invited
also is slated for early March in Miami.
<p>
   ``We're going to be doing a press junket throughout the United
States,'' Esparza said. ``Miami is one of the towns we'll hit, yes.
We hope to visit Miami. There are many national shows that are
based out of Miami, just like there are national shows based out of
New York. We'll visit New York. We'll obviously do a press junket
in L.A., as well as in San Antonio. Our intention is to celebrate
this movie everywhere that we can.''
<p>
   A representative of Warner Bros., the film's distributor, who
declined to give her name for publication, was firm about plans
still being in development.
<p>
   ``There are no concrete plans,'' she said.
<p>
   Esparza says dates will be finalized ``in a matter of days, we
hope,'' he said Monday. ``There are many different people's
schedules that we have to take into consideration, many different
normal logistical issues. It's the sort of thing that's not news.
You just announce when you're ready for it.''
<p>
   When the list was provided to the Express-News by Bert
Quintanilla, he said the information about premiere showings was
provided by Warner Bros.
<p>
   Quintanilla has since said he didn't give the newspaper
permission to release the information.
<p>
   ``To be honest with you, I didn't read the story, so I can't
really comment on it,'' Quintanilla said Monday. ``I just know that
I was telling (the reporter) not to run with it until it's
official. Everything is up in the air. What you guys are talking
about is just discussion pieces that may or could have or could
have not come out. We didn't know. We still don't know.''
<p>
   Separately, Esparza expressed dismay about a quote in the
original story from Howard Cohen, a music critic from the Miami
Herald.
<p>
   ``The story stated that we were going to have the world premiere
in Miami,'' Esparza said. ``And it went on to quote a local Miami
music person saying he didn't understand why it should be done
there because Selena was not anywhere near the stature of Gloria
Estefan, which I thought was real mean-spirited that such a quote
would even be included in the story.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1602EST
</TRAILER>
