<SLUG> BC-HKN-CANADIENS-LING-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0166 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HKN-CANADIENS-LING-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MONTREAL CANADIENS RECALL RIGHT WING DAVID LING FROM AHL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Dan Bollerman &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Montreal, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Montreal Canadiens recalled
wing David Ling from their American Hockey League affiliate in
Fredericton, New Brunswick, two days after Benoit Brunet broke his
hand.
<p>
   Ling, 22, was Fredericton's second-leading scorer with 16 goals,
25 assists and 154 penalty minutes in 33 games this season. He had
also played in two games with the Canadiens earlier this season
before being sent to Fredericton on Jan. 15.
<p>
   The 5-foot-9, 185-pound Ling was acquired in a trade with the
Calgary Flames in exchange for center Scott Fraser on Oct. 25. He
had two assists and 19 penalty minutes in five games with the
Flames' AHL affiliate in Saint John, New Brunswick, before the
trade.
<p>
   Brunet, a left wing, broke his left hand in Monday's game
against the Detroit Red Wings.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1602EST
</TRAILER>
