<DOCID> nyt970122.0337 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9194 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TOSCO-SHARES-UPDATE-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0560 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TOSCO-SHARES-UPDATE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TOSCO SHARES DROP ON EXPLOSION, RISE ON EARNINGS (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By George Stein &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Rewrites to include details and effect of explosion, update
stock price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Stamford, Connecticut, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Tosco Corp. stock
sank on the report of an explosion at one of its refineries last
night, then recovered on better-than-expected fourth-quarter
earnings, analysts said.
<p>
   Trading was halted briefly on the New York Stock Exchange, and
Tosco shares fell as much as 2 to 89 1/8 after trading resumed
early this morning. By late afternoon, shares were up 3/8 at 91
1/2. Though poor refining and marketing results pulled down
fourth-quarter earnings by 11 percent from a year ago, analysts had
expected worse. Earnings were 67 cents a share, and a consensus of
17 analysts polled by First Call Corp. had predicted 63 cents.
<p>
   ``Earnings were clearly secondary to the situation on the West
Coast with respect to performance of the stock'' early in the day,
said Morgan Stanley analyst Douglas T. Terreson. ``There were some
concerns they would have capacity off the market for some time.''
<p>
   Tosco, the largest operator of convenience stores in the nation,
will be the sixth-largest U.S. refiner after it completes the $1.8
billion purchase of Unocal Corp.'s refineries and gas stations it
announced in November. The company will sell fuel through 5,300 gas
stations and convenience stores nationwide, and be the
third-largest refiner on the West Coast.
<p>
   The explosion took place yesterday at Tosco's 150,000 barrel a
day Avon refinery in Martinez, California, in the San Francisco Bay
area. The company said one worker was killed and 25 injured.
Traders said Tosco had to shut down a hydrocracking unit that makes
gasoline and diesel fuel. West Coast wholesale gasoline prices rose
as a result.
<p>
   Still, Terreson said the portion of the refinery affected by the
explosion represents 3-4 percent of Tosco earnings.
<p>
   ``The worst case is not so bad, and the company is fully
insured,'' he said. ``As that information began being fed into the
market, investors became more comfortable with the stock and began
to buy it.''
<p>
   The company reported that fourth-quarter net income fell to
$30.2 million, or 67 cents, from $33.8 million, or 90 cents. The
per-share drop reflects both the drop in profit and an increase in
Tosco's outstanding shares.
<p>
   Tosco issued shares as part of its $750 million acquisition of
the Circle K Corp. convenience store chain in May. Tosco had 44.9
million shares outstanding in the fourth quarter compared with 37.6
million last year.
<p>
   ``The earnings were fine,'' said Terreson. ``Our estimate was 65
cents a share so it was slightly better than expectations.
Operating results were strong.''
<p>
   Thomas D. O'Malley, Tosco's Chairman and Chief Executive
Officer, said in a statement that ``refining and marketing margins
were weak throughout the quarter due to the industry's inability to
pass higher crude oil costs on to the consumer. Cold weather in the
East helped Tosco's Bayway Refinery to a certain degree, but
conditions on the West Coast were weak.''
<p>
   Terreson said Morgan Stanley thinks Tosco's stock has continued
room for growth. ``We have a 110 price target for Tosco by 1997,''
he said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1604EST
</TRAILER>
