<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0345 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=ttc-z> A9203 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHTECH-PRINTS-2ndta </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0348 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HIGHTECH-PRINTS-2ndtake-LADN &QL; 
LOS ANGELES: of the image. &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
c.1997 Los Angeles Daily News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   He opted for this approach in ``Dutch Occupation Green,'' a
blurred shot of a woman walking away from the photographer.
<p>
   Alone, the picture elicits a sense of melancholy. But with the
fusion of a colored border, the image provokes conflicting feelings
of warm passion and distant coolness.
<p>
   ``It's like the first time you hear a Joy Division song. You're
surprised that anything can be highly emotional and mechanical at
the same time,'' Hanley said. ``I've always used digital gear to
create these feelings in my visual art.''
<p>
   While the end product  &MD;  a limited edition of prints  &MD;  remains
the same, the electronic publishing tools let Muse X trim its
production costs. Traditional print shops often use silk-screening,
lithography or etching as a means of reproducing a work, said
Leavitt. When an artist agrees to release a limited edition of a
particular piece, these houses make all of the prints at once. The
artist then examines each copy and signs off those meeting
approval.
<p>
   If the ink smudges or a color is slightly off, the flawed print
is tossed. And copies that have not been sold in advance must be
stored.
<p>
   ``The cost is usually prohibitive. I know of one-time editions
running up to $50,000, what with the time and labor and cost of
supplies,'' Leavitt said. ``Because all of our projects are stored
digitally, we don't have to devote the same resources to a single
run.''
<p>
   Instead, Muse X prints a single copy of the work. Once the
artist approves it, the staff stores the image on a disk. Then, the
company prints only as many copies as the artist sells or needs for
exhibitions.
<p>
   ``We can do multiple prints at multiple times and the quality of
the prints will always remain the same,'' said Jane Hart, director
of the company's publications. ``We don't have to worry about
whether the inks will match. That's the beauty of working with
digital tools. They're always consistent.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1608EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0346 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=ttd-z> A9204 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PRE-FILM-2NDTAKE-SFCH </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0398 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PRE-FILM-2NDTAKE-SFCHRON &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; UNDATED: with interviews. &LR;  &HT;     &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Characters are identified with subtitles, and it is hard to tell
who are the real Oregonians and who are actors. But when the
subtitle introduces coach Bill Dellinger, and he is Ed O'Neill from
television's ``Married ... With Children,'' that's when you know
it's Hollywood.
<p>
   ``The use of archival footage, home movies, all of these allowed
us to tell a bigger story without having to re-create every
element,'' James says.
<p>
   Some of the most inspiring moments in ``Prefontaine'' are the
old washed-out film clips of Pre himself pounding the track like a
stallion.
<p>
   ``It's a constant reminder that this is a real story,'' says
James, who was not afraid to show Pre's face for all to see that he
was more ruggedly handsome than Jared Leto, the actor who portrays
him. Although the resemblance is uncanny, Leto's baby face is too
smooth to be messed up with a floppy mustache and mutton chops. But
he wears plastic-cloth '70s styles very well, and unlike most
actors who attempt sports, he can actually run and not look clumsy.
His stride is amazingly similar to Pre's, and Leto can turn a
quarter-mile in a minute flat.
<p>
   In ``Pre,'' the runner will be played by Billy Crudup, who is a
little slower than Leto but exactly Pre's height, at 5 foot 9.
Cruise considered taking the role himself, but he's shorter than
Crudup.
<p>
   The secondary role is Bill Bowerman, the salty Oregon and
Olympic track coach. Originally a consultant on ``Prefontaine,''
Bowerman switched to ``Pre,'' then threatened to sue Disney if it
featured him in its film. In ``Pre,'' he will be portrayed by
Donald Sutherland. In ``Prefontaine,'' he is R. Lee Ermey, who was
in ``Full Metal Jacket'' and ``Dead Man Walking.''
<p>
   A subplot is that Bowerman was always using his wife's waffle
iron to design a more durable shoe. Bowerman's invention turns out
to be a prototype Nike. One of Pre's many theatrical gestures is
his tearing off the gimmicky Nike swoosh before wearing the shoes.
<p>
   That was just like Pre. Even his fourth-place finish at the
Olympics was dramatic, when he sprinted for the glory and fell
short. Strategically, he could have positioned himself for a silver
or bronze. But Pre would never have stood on a lower step.
<p>
   He was golden all the way.
</TEXT>
