<DOCID> nyt970122.0347 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9205 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-TAKING-STOCK-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0943 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FEA-TAKING-STOCK-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE DJIA'S EXPENSIVE; BUY BEFORE IT RISES AGAIN: TAKING STOCK &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Roger Madoff &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Repeating for all needing.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 21 (Bloomberg) -- The bad news about the market
is all true.
<p>
   Corporate profits don't have a prayer of meeting expectations,
interest rates are rising and stocks, especially those in the Dow
Jones Industrial Average, are overpriced. These concerns have
stalked the market along its record run of the past two years --
and for all the menace, few stocks have turned tail. Traditional
measures of market value aren't what's driving stocks these days,
investors say.
<p>
   ``Step back and take a look at the big picture: The demand for
stocks outpaces supply, and we don't see any real competition out
there,'' said Robert Turner, president of Turner Investment
Partners, which oversees $2.4 billion.
<p>
   More people want to buy than sell stocks because they see them
as the only place to beat the low-single-digit returns offered in
savings accounts.
<p>
   Bonds might lure investors if benchmark 30-year Treasury yields
rose above 8 percent and stayed there. From Oct. 19 to Nov. 23,
1994, stocks fell 6.5 percent as yields rose to 8.16 percent.
That's a far cry from the current 6.78 percent, though.
<p>
   The lack of alternatives to stocks goes a long way toward
explaining how the Dow Jones Industrial Average has risen 32
percent in the past year without a similar improvement in the
earnings of member companies such as DuPont Co.
<p>
   It's why $223 billion poured into mutual funds last year,
topping 1995's pace by more than $93 billion.
<p>
   It's why non-U.S. money is entering the country at a rapid clip,
helping drive the U.S. dollar to three-year highs against the
German mark and Japanese yen.
<p>
   Predicting a shift in sentiment isn't easy. Few are willing to
say when the good times could end. The returns of investing are so
great -- the best since the mid-1950s, measured by the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 Index -- that few are willing to bet on an eventual
reversal.
<p>
   Jeremy Siegel, a professor of finance at the Wharton School and
a staunch proponent of stock investing, calls the market ``slightly
overvalued'' based on companies' likely earnings during the past
six months and the next six months.
<p>
   Still, that's no reason to sell, he said. ``At the top of bull
markets, it's usually much more overvalued than at current times.''
<p>
   By Siegel's estimate, the Dow can rise as high as 8500 -- a 25
percent gain.
<p>
   For market strategists who expect stock prices to fall when
price-earnings ratios get high, it's like looking at a football box
score to see who won the Yankee game.
<p>
   ``I don't think valuation enters into it,'' said David Shulman,
a stock analyst at Salomon Brothers Inc.
<p>
   Daily stock market reports attribute the rise in the Dow to
events such as strong profits in member companies such as Eastman
Kodak and General Electric Co. Yet that doesn't explain why DuPont
is the best-performing stock in the Dow industrials this year.
<p>
   In 1996, DuPont's stock climbed 35 percent while earnings rose
18 percent. The shares have tacked on 18 percent this year, even
though 1997 earnings growth is forecast at 7.9 percent.
<p>
   ``I don't think this has much to do with earnings,'' said
Kenneth L. Fisher, president of Fisher Investments, with $1.3
billion under management. ``This has to do with the flow of
funds.''
<p>
   By Fisher's account, investors chase the largest, most liquid
companies because that's where the foreign money goes. DuPont is
rising because its $62.3 billion market capitalization, more than
twice that of the average company in the S&AMP;P 500, makes it easy to
put money in and take money out.
<p>
   Fisher runs a portfolio that buys stocks with market
capitalization at least double that of the average S&AMP;P 500 company.
It has beat the S&AMP;P 500 for three years. ``The only problem with
our style is that it looks dumb,'' he said.
<p>
   Of the perils to stocks, unrealistic expectations for corporate
profits could pose the greatest danger. Analysts expect earnings of
companies in the S&AMP;P 500 Index to expand 14.1 percent in 1997, 81
percent better than 1996's results.
<p>
   That's almost impossible, because earnings growth fell during
the past couple years and the economy is unlikely to grow much
faster than at present.
<p>
   Fortunately for the market, analysts trim their expectations as
the end of each quarter approaches. Expectations for fourth-quarter
profits among S&AMP;P 500 companies in a First Call survey, for
example, initially were for growth of between 13 percent and 14
percent. By quarter's end, analysts whittled those estimates to 8.2
percent, said Charles Hill, director of research at First Call.
<p>
   That enabled most companies to beat estimates, so far. Interest
rates at current levels aren't much to worry about, either. In
theory, they cut the value of stocks as they rise because higher
rates slow borrowing and expansion.
<p>
   By that rationale, stocks should be below where they were in
September 1993. That's when the yield on the benchmark 30-year
Treasury bond was at 5.78 percent, a full percentage point below
its current level.
<p>
   The Dow industrials have almost doubled since then.
<p>
   Even though rates are higher now, they are still low enough so
that all but the most indebted corporations and people can borrow
cheaply, said Gil Knight, director of research at Allied Investment
Advisors.
<p>
   If stocks retreat, slower profit growth or higher interest rates
will take the heat. Just don't give them credit for taking stocks
higher.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1609EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0348 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=u sel=ttc-z> A9206 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHTECH-PRINTS-2Take </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
