<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BRAZIL-STOCKS-CLOSE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BRAZIL STOCKS FALL AMID CONCERN SHARES ARE EXPENSIVE (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Herbert Lash &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates with closing market figures; adds details on Cardoso's
re-election bid, Copene and Bradesco.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Sao Paulo, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Brazilian stocks fell because
of concern that state-controlled companies like Telecomunicacoes
Brasilieras SA, Petroleo Brasileiro SA and Centrais Eletricas
Brasileiras SA are more expensive than earnings prospects justify.
<p>
   ``I'm surprised the fall isn't harder,'' said Sergio Blatyta,
chief trader at Banco Votorantim SA. ``I wouldn't buy these stocks
at these prices.''
<p>
   The Bovespa index for the Sao Paulo stock exchange fell 874.06
points, or 1.1 percent, to 78,175.01, only the third decline so far
this year. In Rio de Janeiro, the IBV index fell 203 points, or 0.7
percent, to 29,546. Shares worth 490.8 million reais ($470.8
million) were traded in Sao Paulo.
<p>
   The government-controlled telephone company known as Telebras
and the federal utility called Eletrobras rose to all-time highs
yesterday. Petrobras hit an all-time high on Monday.
<p>
   The companies led a rally that pushed the Bovespa index 12.3
percent higher year-to-date before today's decline. The
state-controlled companies account for 69 percent of the weight
exchange officials assign to the index.
<p>
   Telebras, Petrobras and Eletrobras rose on government plans to
sell state assets this year and to open the oil and
telecommunications industries to private investment.
<p>
   Shares also rose on expectations President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso would gain the right to seek re-election next year and keep
his anti-inflation program on track. The government is trying to
amend the constitution so Cardoso can serve consecutive terms,
which is currently banned.
<p>
   Non-voting preferred shares in Telebras fell 1.1 reais to 89.6
reais, Petrobras preferred fell 5.5 reais to 188 and Eletrobras
preferred fell 1.01 reais to 435.99.
<p>
   Petrochemical company Copene Petroquimica do Nordeste SA was one
of the day's biggest decliners, falling 4.2 percent to 345 reais.
Copene posted a fourth-quarter loss of 6.4 million reais after
production costs cut gross margin to 13 percent from 17 percent in
the third quarter, Votorantim said in a report.
<p>
   Among other decliners, Banco Bradesco SA fell 3.4 percent to
8.45 reais, home appliance manufacturer Brasmotor SA fell 1.4
percent to 279.99 reais and Telecomunicacoes de Parana SA fell 1.4
percent to 690.
<p>
   Santander Investment Securities initiated coverage on Bradesco
with a ``market perform'' recommendation, saying the bank is fairly
valued. The stock should climb 19 percent to 9.74 reais in the next
12 months to 18 months if, as Santander expects, the Bovespa index
rises 22 percent over the same period, the bank said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1610EST
</TRAILER>
