<DOCID> nyt970122.0353 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=ttd-z> A9211 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PRE-FILM-2TAKES-SFCHR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0893 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PRE-FILM-2TAKES-SFCHRON &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; AFTER 22 YEARS, HOLLYWOOD CATCHES UP WITH STEVE PREFONTAINE &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``s'' sports news file) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By SAM WHITING &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.1997, San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The legend of distance runner Steve Prefontaine is big enough
for two movies, and that's how many are coming.
<p>
   Twenty-two years after the death of the maverick Olympian with
the shaggy golden hair and the only suntan in Eugene, Ore.,
Disney's Hollywood Pictures will release ``Prefontaine'' on January
24, followed later this year by ``Pre,'' produced by Tom Cruise for
Warner Bros.
<p>
   Two features, on top of an existing documentary, might seem
excessive for a three-miler who is now little remembered, but
Prefontaine was an American original whose life story rivals James
Dean's.
<p>
   Dean was an actor who looked great playing other people, then
crashed his silver Porsche and died at age 24, on Sept. 30, 1955.
Prefontaine was a swashbuckler who starred in his own movie every
day and looked great doing it right up until the night he flipped
his gold MG and died at age 24, on May 30, 1975. Tests revealed
that he had been legally drunk.
<p>
   Prefontaine had just been named ``the most popular track athlete
in the world'' by Track &AMP; Field News. Hours before his death, he
had won an international race at Hayward Field, his home stadium at
the University of Oregon, with fans chanting, ``Go, Pre.'' He next
appeared as a corpse in a black hearse that slowly circled Hayward
Field while mourners in the stands chanted, ``Go, Pre.''
<p>
   ``They cheered a ghost going around the track,'' says
``Prefontaine'' writer and director Steve James. ``This is one of
those stories that's hard to believe unless you know it to be
true.''
<p>
   James and his partner, co-producer and photography director
Peter Gilbert, have some experience with fact being more compelling
than fiction. They made ``Hoop Dreams,'' the hit high school
basketball documentary.
<p>
   ``I'm a firm believer that with real stories the truth is way
more interesting than whatever poetic license the film might
take,'' James says.
<p>
   With Prefontaine, not much license was necessary. He wasn't just
an athlete who died young; he became a cult figure while still
alive. The Coos Bay kid, who began running when he discovered that
he was too small for team sports, left behind American records in
every race from two miles to six and 2,000 meters to 10,000 meters.
<p>
   His nickname was Pre and it fit. He did things before anyone
else dared, like fighting hypocrisy in the American Olympic
program, which expected U.S. athletes to win without adequate
financial support.
<p>
   The first athlete to wear and endorse Nike, he brought panache
to a sport that previously had captured little public attention,
and helped start the jogging craze that spread from the Northwest
across the country in the early 1970s.
<p>
   ``I don't just go out there and run,'' Prefontaine said. ``I
like to give people watching something exciting.''
<p>
   With the gutsy charm and charisma of Joe Namath, Pre delivered
on his promises until he finished a disastrous fourth in the 5,000
meters in the 1972 Olympics in Munich, after the life had been
snuffed out of the Games by murderous terrorists.
<p>
   ``Dreams don't work out the way you wanted. In that respect,
`Hoop Dreams' and `Prefontaine' have something in common,'' James
says. ``Unless you already know these things about Pre, this film
holds some surprises.''
<p>
   One surprise is that to protect his amateur status, Pre had to
lower his standard of living. His European competitors received
jobs as policemen without having to swing a baton or walk a beat.
Pre had to sling pitchers in a bawdy beer joint in Eugene and live
in a trailer by the railroad tracks.
<p>
   James was unable to portray all this discomfort. When a train
rumbled by, Pre's tin-can home shook, but James didn't have the
money for those kinds of effects. He also had to rewrite his script
when Disney hacked his budget to $8.5 million. He had expected to
spend three times that, which is almost exactly the Cruise-Warner
budget of $25 million.
<p>
   Originally, there was to be just one Pre feature, which sprouted
from a 1995 television documentary called ``Fire on the Track.''
<p>
   Its producers, Jon Lutz and Mark Doonan, wanted to follow that
with a full-length film. But one of the writers  &MD;  Kenny Moore, a
Sports Illustrated reporter who had run at Oregon and been a
teammate of Pre's at the Munich Olympics  &MD;  split off with Robert
Towne, who had written and directed the track movie ``Personal
Best.'' Moore and Towne followed the money to Cruise and Warner
Bros. Lutz and Doonan sold their story to Disney, which hired James
and Gilbert for their feature debut. The race was on.
<p>
   ``What you had were two groups passionate about a story,'' James
says.
<p>
   Warner Bros. had the money and the better title. Disney had the
story rights and exclusive cooperation of Pre's family, teammates
and friends.
<p>
   ``If we believed that money was the final arbiter of quality,
then `Hoop Dreams' would have been a disaster,'' says James, who
made ``Prefontaine'' in more of a docudrama style than he intended.
<p>
   ``Steve is very vivid in these people's minds and he's been dead
over 20 years,'' says James, who decided to tell the story with
interviews.
</TEXT>
