<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9212 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-WAYS-OF-WALL-STREET-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0593 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-WAYS-OF-WALL-STREET-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DIFFERENT PERCEPTIONS ON IBM AND COMPAQ: WAYS OF WALL STREET &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By David Pauly &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The computer industry is great
-- or is it?
<p>
   Compaq Computer Corp. shares climbed about 7 percent today.
International Business Machines Corp. stock dropped about 6
percent. Same industry. Same day.
<p>
   Both stocks moved in response to their fourth-quarter results,
good in each case. IBM's profit in the quarter rose 18 percent to
$2.02 billion, or $3.93 a share. But Compaq's earnings increased by
a much bigger amount, jumping 43 percent to $462 million, or $1.64
a share.
<p>
   You're beginning to see why the stocks moved as they did.
Investors also perceived that Compaq would continue to increase its
profits at a good clip while IBM might be slowing down.
<p>
   Stephen Dube, an analyst with Wasserstein Perella Securities,
said this about Compaq: ``They're gaining market share, profit
margins are increasing, cash is growing; what else to you want?''
<p>
   Of IBM, Larry Woods, an independent analyst, said: ``These are
not good numbers.''
<p>
   Whether all the figures justified the divergent moves in IBM and
Compaq shares was questionable, however.
<p>
   There's no reason for IBM and Compaq to move in lock-step, of
course. Same industry but different companies. Compaq's strong suit
is personal computers and it has moved into servers, which connect
networks of PCs.
<p>
   IBM has several businesses and remains a giant in all of them.
It competes with Compaq in PCs but it also makes mainframe
computers, workstations, semiconductors and software. IBM Chairman
Louis Gerstner has made a big push into the services business --
running and maintaining computer systems for other companies.
<p>
   Right now, Compaq's business is paying off. Sales of PCs to
companies, more profitable than sales to individuals, are strong.
In the fourth quarter, Houston-based Compaq got the most out of
those sales by cutting its costs. It slashed its inventories to
$1.15 billion from $2.16 billion a year earlier, for instance, and
collected its bills faster. Both moves freed up cash.
<p>
   With its spread of businesses, IBM reported both good and bad
for the final three months of 1996. Revenue from services jumped 22
percent to $5 billion and now account for 22 percent of IBM's total
sales.
<p>
   During 1996, according to a report by Lehman Brothers Holdings
Inc. today, IBM's services business signed $22.1 billion in new
contracts. That was more than the estimated $10.5 billion in
services contracts picked up by rival Computer Sciences Corp. and
the $7.5 billion in new contracts won by Electronic Data Systems
Corp.
<p>
   IBM's software sales were up too, by 4 percent. But total sales
of computers rose just 2 percent and falling prices of memory chips
caused a decline in semiconductor sales. Weak sales in Europe and a
strong dollar, which reduced the value of sales made abroad,
further muddied IBM's picture.
<p>
   There's a case for breaking up IBM into several companies that
might compete better on their own -- but Gerstner will have none of
that.
<p>
   One of these quarters, all of IBM's businesses may hit at once
and, for a day or so at least, leave more focused companies like
Compaq behind.
<p>
   Actually, for investors who hold their stocks for more than a
week, today's moves in Compaq and IBM were meaningless. In the past
three months, including today, IBM shares are up about 25 percent
while Compaq's rose about 20 percent.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1611EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0355 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9213 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-PERSONAL-WEALTH-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0987 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FEA-PERSONAL-WEALTH-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BUYING STOCKS WITHOUT BROKERS OR COMMISSIONS: PERSONAL WEALTH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Scott Schnipper &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Repeating for all needing.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Tightwads take note. Starting
next week, individual investors in the U.S. can buy stock in Merck
&AMP; Co., the nation's biggest drugmaker, directly from the company.
<p>
   Just send Merck an enrollment form and a check for at least
$350, plus a $10 enrollment fee. At Merck's current price of about
$88 a share, investors would receive approximately four shares.
<p>
   ``It's no muss, no fuss investing,'' said Charles Carlson, a
certified financial analyst and editor of the No-Load Stock Insider
newsletter. ``It doesn't get much easier.''
<p>
   Or cheaper. Merck is one of about 200 American corporations that
invite investors to buy their shares directly from the companies or
their bank representatives, by passing brokers and brokers'
commissions. Some companies charge between $10 and $15 to set up an
account, a dollar or two for each transaction, or a fee only when
an investor sells their stock. Other companies charge nothing at
all.
<p>
   In the end, it still represents a big savings from what brokers
charge. The brokerage fee for buying 100 shares or less of Merck
ranges from $29.95 to $55 at discount broker Charles Schwab &AMP; Co.,
depending on whether an investor uses a broker, the Internet or
other services. Full-service brokers such as Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
charge more.
<p>
   As with most plans, investors can buy more shares with all or
part of Merck's 40 cents-a-share quarterly dividend, make weekly
purchases of between $50 and $50,000, or can have monthly
investments of at least $50 wired out of their bank checking
accounts. If when these services come with fees attached they
remain much less costly than using a broker.
<p>
   Spurred by favorable Securities and Exchange Commission rulings
in late 1994, the number of companies that sell their shares
directly to investors has exploded. Each month a dozen or more
companies are starting direct-purchase programs. Carlson estimates
that within two years, between 500 and 1,000 companies will offer
the option.
<p>
   The list of companies already includes such blue chips as
Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., McDonald's Corp., Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co.,
Chevron Corp., Exxon Corp., and Texaco Inc. -- all part of the Dow
Jones Industrial Average, along with Merck.
<p>
   J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. runs a program allowing individual investors
in the U.S. to buy American depository receipts of more than 40
foreign companies.
<p>
   A couple of years ago, there were only about 50 companies
offering direct stock sales, and the list was dominated by
slow-growing electric utilities.
<p>
   Now, the roster has grown more exciting. It includes First USA
Inc., the nation's third-largest credit-card issuer, which Banc One
Corp. of Columbus, Ohio offered to buy earlier this week for stock
valued at about $7 billion. First USA has made its stock available
to investors who call a toll-free number to request an application
and prospectus, and then mail back a check for purchases of as
little as $1,000.
<p>
   The lag between when an order is placed and when it is executed
draws attention to one of direct investing's drawbacks: speed. The
process generally two weeks or more. And the stock's price can
change significantly in either direction during the that period.
<p>
   There's only one fixed price for a stock on any given day using
direct investment, so there's no way of knowing what exact price
will be paid or received. On Jan. 2, for instance, First USA shares
on the New York Stock Exchange traded between $32.75 and $34.625
before ending at $33.
<p>
   If an investor plans on holding a stock for several years, minor
price changes will matter little, however. And many companies are
getting faster, executing trades daily, once a week or every two
weeks instead of once a month or, in some instances, every three
months. Others are offering shareholders an 800 number if they want
to sell. But most companies stick to the slow lane.
<p>
   ``The speed on the buy and sell side is improving,'' Carlson
said, and telephone services are superior to old rules that forced
investors to send written instructions of a sell order.
<p>
   Still, direct investing clearly isn't designed for active
traders.
<p>
   Indeed, one appeal of selling stock directly to investors is
that those investors are more likely to become loyal, long-term
shareholders who support management, says Robert O'Hara, marketing
director for the National Association of Investors Corp. The
non-profit NAIC runs a service that assists investors in buying
stock from about 150 companies for $7 plus the cost of one share.
The group says more than 400,000 investors have used the service in
the past 10 years.
<p>
   A spokesman for First USA said selling stock directly to
shareholders has helped the company broaden its shareholder base a
bit beyond institutional investors.
<p>
   Investors interested in direct purchases have a few options.
<p>
   One is to write or call the ``No-Load Stock Insider'' for a
sample of that newsletter free of charge, at 7412 Calumet Ave.,
Hammond, Indiana 46324; (219) 852-3230. A six-times-a-year
subscription is $33. The newsletter is published by NorthStar
Financial Inc.
<p>
   Investors can obtain an application and prospectus from any one
of about 100 companies that have direct-purchase plans by calling
the Direct Stock Purchase Plan Clearinghouse -- a joint venture
between NorthStar Financial and New York-based Shareholder
Communications Corp. -- at (800) 744-4117. (Companies pay to have
their stocks listed.)
<p>
   Membership in the NAIC costs $39, though there's no obligation
to remain a member after the investment plan has been used.
Contact: NAIC, 711 W. Thirteen Mile Road, Madison Heights, Michigan
48071, or (810) 583-6242.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1613EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
