<SLUG> BC-CORPORATE-WELFARE-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0875 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CORPORATE-WELFARE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. HOUSE GROUP TO TARGET $2 BLN A YEAR IN `CORPORATE WELFARE' &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By David Ward &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- An eclectic coalition led by
U.S. House Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich of Ohio plans to
release a list next week of government spending programs for
corporations that it wants eliminated or reduced to save
Kvs~~goysUtaxpayers more than $2 billion a year.
<p>
   The list, which is still being finalized, calls for elimination
of the Agriculture Department's Market Access Program, which helps
U.S. food exporters market overseas; closing the Overseas Private
Investment Corp., which provides insurance to companies investing
overseas; elimination of the Rural Utility Service, which provides
subsidized electricity for rural areas; and a reduction in U.S.
dues paid to the International Monetary Fund.
<p>
   The manifesto will come from an unusual policy coalition that
includes Ralph Nader and Friends of the Earth on the left and the
Cato and Heritage institutes on the right. It targets about a dozen
so-called ``corporate welfare'' provisions they say R[RB/+V ki 9A!
``!eXP ggx`9W( nci s ``Thisut direction,'' said Gnt oTax Reform,
which n twith the focus on bais ibe doable.''
<p>
   Still, all of the programs on the list have strong backers in
Congress and many have survived repeated attacks in years past.
``These are easier said than done,'' Norquist said.
<p>
   Nothing was included unless all of the coalition members agreed
-- and that kept some often-criticized projects off the list.
<p>
   Among the escapees is the U.S. Department of Agriculture's
peanut and sugar subsidies, which together cost taxpayers more than
$1.5 billion in higher food costs, according to General Accounting
Office estimates.
<p>
   The U.S. sets a minimum price for U.S. sugar and limits the
import of cheaper foreign sugar. It also limits permits for peanut
growers, and then sets minimum prices for the peanuts they grow,
raising the costs for processors.
<p>
   ``We tried, but we couldn't get enough support to include these
on the list,'' said Stephen Moore, a fiscal policy analyst at the
Cato Institute. Participants said some environmental and public
interest groups opposed removing the limits because of the impact
on family farmers.
<p>
   The coalition also decided to leave tax breaks off the list,
allowing the tax subsidy for corn-based ethanol fuel to escape the
group's targeting. That tax break, which was worth about $3.6
billion during the last five years, benefits a handful of
corporations, led by Archer-Daniels-Midland Co., which accounts for
almost 40 percent of the ethanol produced, and High Plains Corp.,
whose sole business is ethanol production.
<p>
   Lawmakers have repeatedly attempted to kill the program, only to
see it survive. ADM remains committed to the program, and still
wields enormous power in Washington. The company, its chairman,
Dwayne Andreas, and executives, gave $495,000 to candidates and
lawmakers in the last election cycle, according to the Center for
Responsive Politics.
<p>
   Still, Kasich's group is taking on a host of popular programs,
including the Rural Utility Service, formerly known as the Rural
Electrification Administration. Started in 1936, it had the noble
goal of providing electricity to rural America.
<p>
   That subsidy, now $89 million a year, benefits government-owned
municipal utilities and the holders of their tax-free bonds at the
expense of the more than 200 investor-owned utilities, according to
the Edison Electric Institute.
<p>
   Killing the program won't be an easy task. ``Rural utility
services have a pretty large constituency,'' Cato's Moore said.
``That will be tough work for western and rural senators and
congressmen.''
<p>
   Kasich will also take another swing at OPIC, which provides
insurance for U.S. companies operating outside the U.S. Efforts to
kill the program last year were unsuccessful. Its' opponents argue
that providing corporate insurance is a job for business, even
though the program is profitable. It returned $209 million last
year. ``That's all the more reason it should be privatized,''
Norquist said.
<p>
   The USDA's Market Access Program, among the most often-cited
example of unneeded government largesse, also made Kasich's list
this year, Moore and other participants said.
<p>
   Formerly known as the Market Promotion Program, it provides $70
million a year for companies to advertise overseas. Firms from
Grand Metropolitan Plc's Pillsbury Co. to McDonald's Corp. have
received funds, although lawmakers have limited access to the funds
in recent years.
<p>
   ``It ended up subsidizing advertising and marketing for large
agribusiness efforts,'' said Friends of the Earth's Gawain Kripke.
``It doesn't in any way help American agriculture.''
<p>
   The group also wants the U.S. to reduce its agreement to provide
funds in the Treasury to be used by the IMF to bail out emerging
economies if they were on the verge of loan defaults.
<p>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin argues, however, that by
contributing to the fund, the U.S. insures that it won't have to
unilaterally bail out a failing economy's such as we did with
Mexico in 1995.
</TEXT>
