<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9224 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-FED-UPDATE3-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0990 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ECONOMY-FED-UPDATE3-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FED'S SURVEY SEES `SCATTERED EVIDENCE' OF HIGHER WAGES (UPDATE3) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Vincent Del Giudice and Laura Cohn &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Edits third paragraph to clarify FOMC meeting expectations;
adds closing financial markets.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The U.S. economy continues to
grow with low unemployment nudging labor costs higher, the Federal
Reserve said today.
<p>
   While the Fed found ``scattered evidence'' of pressures for
higher wages in its latest regional economic survey, the central
bank still found no evidence of accelerating consumer prices
outside of energy in December or early January.
<p>
   The Fed's regional outlook, commonly known as the beige book, is
based on reports from the Fed's 12 district banks and is published
eight times each year. Their report will help form the basis for
discussion at the Feb. 4-5 meeting of the Federal Open Market
Committee, where analysts expect Fed policymakers to leave the
overnight borrowing rate for banks unchanged at 5.25 percent. The
federal funds rate target has held at that level since Jan. 31,
1996.
<p>
   ``Economic growth in December and early January was moderate in
most parts of the country,'' the Fed said in its report. ``Holiday
sales were in line with retailers' expectations of moderate growth.
Manufacturing activity continued to grow, with significant strength
coming from capital equipment and materials manufacturers.''
<p>
   The report is likely to be ``comforting'' for investors, said
James Padinha, an economist at MMS International in San Francisco,
because it doesn't point to wage pressures or other worrisome signs
of inflation.
<p>
   In financial markets, though, the benchmark 30-year Treasury
bond fell after the government's auction of about $17 billion in
two-year notes. The bond fell 1/2, pushing up the yield more than 4
basis points to 6.82 percent, as dealers tried to sell their
holdings of the new government securities.
<p>
   The latest Fed regional survey, compiled by the Federal Reserve
Bank of San Francisco, is in line with comments yesterday by Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan, who said the U.S. economy remains strong
with few signs of immediate inflationary pressures even as an era
of low wage gains may be ending.
<p>
   In the Fed's New York district, for example, the economy had a
``slightly firmer tone than in the last report, while price
pressures remain subdued,'' the Fed said.
<p>
   In the country's mid-section, the Kansas City Fed said rising
job creation is beginning to put upward pressure on wages,
something Fed officials have been warning about as a risk to the
nation's inflation outlook.
<p>
   Along the Pacific coast, the San Francisco Fed reported
retailers enjoyed a ``good'' holiday selling season, though adverse
weather in late December and early January ``held down
post-Christmas retail activity.''
<p>
   Release of the report had been set for 2 p.m. Washington time,
however it was inadvertently released at 12:10 p.m. on the Internet
by the Fed. ``Everybody has broken an embargo, including me,''
joked the Fed's chief spokesman, Joseph Coyne. News agencies
occasionally release stories about government reports before their
scheduled release times because of unintentional computer glitches.
<p>
   In his testimony yesterday, Greenspan said, ``the economy has
retained considerable vigor, with few signs of the imbalances and
inflationary tensions that have disrupted past expansions.'' He
added: ``By some important measures of price trends, inflation
actually slowed a bit in 1996.''
<p>
   Economists interpreted Greenspan's comments as suggesting the
FOMC won't raise interest rates next month. Still, Greenspan left
the door ajar for action later if inflation accelerates because of
rising wage levels.
<p>
   The overall consumer price index rose 3.3 percent last year, the
largest increase since 1990. However, much of that came from an 8.6
percent rise in energy prices. Not counting food and energy, prices
rose only 2.6 percent, tying the 1994 rate for the lowest core
inflation rate in 30 years.
<p>
   In its last regional outlook Dec. 4, the Fed said the economy
growing at a subdued pace with no sign of rising consumer prices.
That lack of an inflation threat allowed the central bank to
refrain from increasing interest rates at their last policy meeting
Dec. 17.
<p>
   Central bankers last cut the federal funds rate by a quarter
point at the Jan. 31, 1996, FOMC meeting, when many analysts were
predicting the U.S. economy was heading into a recession. That
followed identical quarter-point reductions in July and December
1995.
<p>
   Following are summaries of regional economic activity as
reported by the Fed's district banks:
<p>
   Boston: Economy continues to expand at moderate pace. Holiday
sales higher at retailers.
<p>
   New York: Slightly firmer tone to regional economy. Price
pressures subdued.
<p>
   Philadelphia: Economic activity moving up slowly. No signs of
acceleration in the rate of general wage increases.
<p>
   Cleveland: Regional economy held steady at a good level.
Unemployment near or below national average.
<p>
   Richmond: Economic activity at high levels. Retail sales up
sharply. Commercial real estate strong.
<p>
   Atlanta: Retail sales mixed. Wages ``generally appear to be
holding steady.''
<p>
   Chicago: Signs of increasing wage pressures. Holiday sales fell
short of expectations.
<p>
   St. Louis: Economy picked up since last report. Retail sales met
expectations. Tight labor markets prevail.
<p>
   Minneapolis: Even in bitter winter, regional economy continue to
grow. Oil development is ``pumping cash.''
<p>
   Kansas City: Economy shows few signs of slowing. Consumer and
producer prices both stable.
<p>
   Dallas: Growth ``slightly stronger'' than in October and
November. Oil drilling on the rise.
<p>
   San Francisco: Strong expansion reported. Storm repair helping
construction spending.
</TEXT>
