<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ARGENTINA-CORN-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ARGENTINA SELLS 100,000 TONS OF CORN TO KOREA, TRADERS SAY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Rona Cohen &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Buenos Aires, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Argentina sold 100,000
metric tons of the current corn crop to Korea for shipment in June
and July for about $106 a ton, traders said.
<p>
   The exact price wasn't available from traders. The price doesn't
include shipping costs.
<p>
   Korea also bought another 50,000 tons of corn that will most
likely come from Argentina, traders said. The purchase was made
through exporters on an optional origin basis, meaning the
exporters can choose the country of origin.
<p>
   The Agriculture Secretariat estimated Argentina will produce a
record 14.6 million tons of corn in the current 1996-97 crop year,
up from 10.5 million in 1995-96. After local demand, estimated at 4
million to 4.5 million tons, is met, about 10 million tons would be
left for export.
<p>
   Traders said Argentina has already sold about 2.5 million tons
of corn for export from the 1996-97 crop.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1620EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0363 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9227 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-CARDOSO-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0203 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BRAZIL-CARDOSO-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BRAZIL'S CARDOSO TO VISIT BRITAIN, ITALY DURING CARNIVAL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Simon Romero &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Brasilia, Brazil, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Brazilian President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso will travel to the United Kingdom and
Italy in February, instead of taking part in his country's Carnival
celebrations.
<p>
   Cardoso will visit the U.K. on Feb. 10, and be received by Prime
Minister John Major at 10 Downing St. During his stay in London,
Cardoso, a sociologist, will take part in a conference on Latin
America, Brazil's Foreign Affairs Ministry said.
<p>
   On Feb. 11, Cardoso is scheduled to go to Italy, where he will
meet with lawmakers from the Italian lower house and senate, as
well as government leaders. Both Feb. 10 and 11 are national
holidays in Brazil. February 11, known in other countries as Mardi
Gras or Shrove Tuesday, is the day before Ash Wednesday.
<p>
   During his scheduled four-day stay in Italy, Cardoso is slated
to meet with Pope John Paul II at the Vatican. In addition, Cardoso
plans to speak at a U.N. conference on agriculture and will visit
the University of Bologna, the ministry said in a statement.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1620EST
</TRAILER>
