<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0365 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=l pri=u sel=taf-z> A9230 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-ELECTRONICS- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0411 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CONSUMER-ELECTRONICS-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; LAS VEGAS: the screen. &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Internet in a Dish
<p>
   A big complaint about the Internet is that it takes too long to
download anything that is fun. Hughes Network Systems demonstrated
a 36-inch satellite dish called the Convergence Antenna that makes
the process 15 times faster than with a standard modem.
<p>
   Instead of getting the Internet through telephone lines, users
subscribe to Hughes's satellite Internet service, called Direc PC.
In a demonstration, a 90-second animation clip that normally takes
an hour to download arrived in less than two minutes.
<p>
   But speed costs: Direc PC costs about $150 a month for unlimited
access; the Convergence Antenna is about $650. The dish also picks
up 175 channels on television.
<p>
   Souped-Up Telephones
<p>
   The Cidco iPhone display at the show was mobbed by
conventioneers watching demonstrations of a phone with a
4-by-7-inch touch screen that allows users to surf the Internet.
Like other telephones that can connect to the Internet, the iPhone
has a small pull-out keyboard that also lets the user tap out
e-mail messages. But its liquid-crystal display screen is double
the size of that on other Internet telephones and allows you to see
graphics as well as text. It's due in stores by fall, at $500 or
so.
<p>
   The Philips P200 also attracted plenty of attention, but mostly
for its looks. It is a standard screen phone that can send and
receive e-mail and do banking on line. But it is more sculptured
than the usual screen phones, with a fluid design. It will be
released in May, with a list price of $499. 
<p>
   Movies to Come and Go
<p>
   Want to rent a video but are too wedded to the sofa to stir
outside? Soon, one company promises, you will be able to call up
your cable company, order a movie from a catalogue of thousands and
have it beamed in to your VCR. After two plays, the movie
disappears. That's the concept behind Emc3, an Amsterdam company
that aims to revolutionize video rentals.
<p>
   Two things have to happen before movies can be delivered this
way: you will have to buy a D-VHS VCR, due in stores later this
year from several companies for around $750. These VCR's can record
digital information delivered by satellite or cable. And Emc3 has
to sell its technology to cable companies and satellite television
providers.
<p>
   The company says it can provide music and computer software the
same way. As soon as somebody signs a deal.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1621EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0366 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=d pri=r sel=ttx-z> A9231 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ULTRACAFFEINE-BOX-TEX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0581 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-ULTRACAFFEINE-BOX-TEX &QL; 
SOME LORE ABOUT THE DUELING COLA COMPANIES &QL; 
EDS: Accompanied by ULTRA CAFFEINE-DRINKS and ULTRA CAFFEINE-TASTE
TEST. &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Following is some cola lore. 
<p>
   CURES THAT REFRESH
<p>
    &MD;  The original soft drink entrepreneurs were looking for cures,
not the pause that refreshes. Coca-Cola came about in 1886 when an
Atlanta pharmacist mixed up a cola syrup and promoted it as a cure
for hangovers and headaches. The syrup got mixed with carbonated
water at Jacob's Pharmacy to become a cola drink.
<p>
    &MD;  ``Brad's drink'' came along in the same year when North
Carolina pharmacist Caleb Bradham whipped up a similar concoction.
The drink's name changed to Pepsi-Cola in 1903.
<p>
    &MD;  Waco pharmacist Charles C. Alderton came up with Dr Pepper at
the Old Corner Drugstore in 1885, and, as the story goes, named it
for yet another pharmacist, Dr. Charles K. Pepper. 
<p>
   LIKE, IT'S BETTER THAN POT, MAN
<p>
   Because of its original formula of cocaine and caffeine, many
old-time Southerners called Cokes ``dopes.'' 
<p>
   GOES GREAT WITH BURGERS
<p>
   According to Elisabeth Rozin, author of ``The Primal
Cheeseburger,'' colas are the drink of choice with a cheeseburger
platter because the spicy medicinal flavor and heavy carbonation
cleanse and refresh the palate after the load of fat delivered by
the burger and fries. 
<p>
   THE VAMPIRIC CHOICE
<p>
   Gothic author Anne Rice, signing books recently in Lewisville,
Texas, toted along a cooler packed with a six-pack of her favorite
beverage. No, it wasn't blood; it was Tab. 
<p>
   WHY ISN'T IS MOM?
<p>
   ``Pop'' entered the vocabulary in the early 1800s; the term came
from the sound made when the corks were pulled from the bottles of
then-natural soda waters. 
<p>
   DR PEPPER
<p>
   Corporate Dr Pepper left its Waco, Texas, birthplace in 1922 to
move to Dallas. The defection made little difference to the
residents of Jerusalem on the Brazos; Waco is still the No. 1
market for the drink.
<p>
   Dr Pepper lost its period in the 1950s, when the script type of
the logo was changed to a more ``modern'' bold italic type.
<p>
   The Dr Pepper bottling plant in Dublin, Texas, is the only one
that still uses pure cane sugar as its sweetener. The plant
distributes its product in a 40-mile radius of Dublin but will (and
does) ship the product around the country to consumers. To order,
phone (817) 445-3466. 
<p>
   7UP
<p>
   7UP got its name from the marketer's fascination with cattle
brands, according to ``I'm a Spam Fan: The Stories Behind America's
Favorite Foods.'' It certainly beats the original name for the
soda: Bib-Label Lithiated Lemon-Lime Soda. 
<p>
   PASSOVER COKE
<p>
   Around the Jewish observance of Passover, some bottlers in the
United States occasionally put out ``Passover'' Coke. Because some
Jews aren't allowed to consume corn products at this time, Coke
uses sucrose as its sweetener in specially marked bottles of Coke.
Look for the Coke in delis and the supermarkets. Coke, by the way,
is always kosher. 
<p>
   INDUSTRY SHARE
<p>
   The top 10 soft drink brands' industry share for 1995 are:
Coca-Cola Classic, 20 percent; Pepsi, 15.4 percent; Diet Coke, 9.5
percent; Dr Pepper, 6 percent; Mountain Dew, 5.6 percent; Diet
Pepsi, 5.4 percent; Sprite, 4.9 percent; Seven-Up, 2.7 percent;
Caffeine Free Diet Coke, 1.9 percent; Caffeine Free Diet Pepsi, 1.1
percent; others, 27.4 percent. Source: Beverage Marketing
Corporation of New York.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1621EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0367 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9232 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FED-PARRY-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0662 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FED-PARRY-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FED'S PARRY SAYS INFLATION MAY RISE AS ECONOMY STRENGTHENS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Tom Bemis &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   San Francisco, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. inflation may rise in
1997 because employment is high and the economy is showing new
signs of strength, Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco President
Robert Parry said today.
<p>
   ``Inflation could be set to rise in the future,'' Parry said in
the text of a speech to the National Association of Business
Economists in San Francisco. ``Available data on the fourth quarter
have shown considerable strength,'' he said.
<p>
   Yesterday Parry told reporters he expects the 1997 core rate of
inflation, which excludes volatile energy and food prices, to rise
``a couple of tenths'' to 2.8 percent from 2.6 percent in 1996.
<p>
   Parry's comments today came as newly released figures showed
U.S. housing starts last year rose 8.8 percent to 1.474 million,
the highest level since 1988.
<p>
   The Fed's `beige book'' survey of regional economic data
released today also found ``scattered evidence'' of pressure for
higher wages.
<p>
   U.S. bonds were lower after the U.S. Treasury sold $17.5 billion
of two-year notes today. The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell
1/2, pushing its yield up more than 4 basis points to 6.82 percent.
<p>
   Traders said comments late yesterday from Federal Reserve
Governor Susan Phillips revived concern the Fed may raise interest
rates soon.
<p>
   Phillips suggested in a Market News interview that the Fed might
not wait for a rise in the core consumer price index before
boosting rates.
<p>
   The Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC), the interest
rate-setting body of the central bank, is next scheduled to meet
Feb. 4-5. Parry, who is widely viewed as an inflation hawk, is a
voting member of the FOMC.
<p>
   Yesterday Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told a Senate
hearing that there are few signs of inflation in the economy.
<p>
   ``The economy has retained considerable vigor, with few signs of
the imbalances and inflationary tensions that have disrupted past
expansions,'' Greenspan said. ``By some important measures of price
trends, inflation actually slowed a bit in 1996.''
<p>
   His remarks yesterday helped boost the Dow Jones Industrial
average to a record close of 6877.35. Today, the Dow closed down
33.9 points at 6850. Broader market indices were higher.
<p>
   Fed officials have said tightening job markets are the most
likely threat to price stability in 1997. That's partly because
average hourly earnings rose 6 cents last month, or 0.5 percent,
according to the Labor Department. For all of last year, hourly
earnings climbed 3.8 percent, the biggest gain since a similar 3.8
percent increase in 1990.
<p>
   Last Thursday, Federal Reserve Gov. Laurence Meyer, widely
viewed as an inflation dove, warned the Fed would have to raise
interest rates if unemployment falls much below the current 5.3
percent rate.
<p>
   Greenspan also left open the possibility of an interest rate
increase if the economy grows faster than the 3.0 percent rate he
forecast for 1996. ``Indeed, the recent pickup in some measures of
wages suggests that the transition may already be running its
course,'' the Fed chairman said.
<p>
   Parry reiterated comments he made in a speech yesterday to the
Financial Women's Association that workers who have been more
concerned with keeping their jobs than getting pay raises will
likely begin seeking wage increases this year.
<p>
   ``Even if some workers continue to feel insecure, they still
won't be willing to pass up wage increases forever,'' Parry said
yesterday.
<p>
   He also said a stronger dollar, which makes foreign goods
cheaper by comparison with American products, is unlikely to help
keep inflation down. ``Our inflation rate ultimately depends on our
monetary policy, and not on the existence of foreign competitors,''
Parry said in the text of his speech to the business economists.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1622EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0368 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=s sel=taf-z> A9233 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-IANNIS-XENAKIS-MUSIC- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0986 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-IANNIS-XENAKIS-MUSIC-$ADV26-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HE COMPOSES DIFFERENTLY, THEREFORE HE EXISTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 26) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (af) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL GRIFFITHS &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   At a time when so many composers have given up on radical
innovation, the Greek composer Iannis Xenakis, who turns 75 this
year, has become a heartening figure. His music, as represented in
new recordings, is hardly less uncompromising than it was in the
1950s, though it is certainly richer and more adept, probably
because he has been able to build on his successes while retaining
an extraordinary imperviousness to his mistakes.
<p>
   In more than four decades of working with orchestras he has
developed a keen imagination for sound, generated by new playing
techniques or, more usually these days, by assembling chords that
work as single colors.
<p>
   But harmony and voice-leading still mean very little to him,
insistent pulsation and scatter shots remain his most
characteristic kinds of rhythm, and his musical forms are chains of
events: chains sustained by the excitement of each moment and the
timing of each jump.
<p>
   The expressive result is aggressive, or not so much aggressive
as defiant. Xenakis's music is not trying to hurt but rather to
protect itself: to stake out its territory and fence off any
possibility that it might be heard in traditional ways. Only by
being emphatically different, according to Xenakis, can his music
answer the call he makes on it, which is to demonstrate that he
exists.
<p>
   ``Composition, action are nothing but a struggle for
existence,'' he tells Balint Andras Varga in Varga's recently
published ``Conversations With Iannis Xenakis.'' ``If I imitate the
past, I do nothing, and consequently I am not. I am sure that I
exist only if I do something different.''
<p>
   By no means is this just some sort of exhibitionism.
Exhibitionists need an audience; Xenakis, one senses from this
book, is alone with himself, and his triumphs, in terms of public
acclaim and colleagues' imitation, are an embarrassment. For to
achieve complete victory in his ``struggle for existence'' he would
have to create something so different that to anybody else it would
be totally meaningless.
<p>
   Even he has not gone that far, though he has regularly traveled
a long way into the desert of incoherence, often by calculating his
music so as to maximize disorder. This is the main thrust of his
mathematical techniques: his spinning numbers, like John Cage's
coin tossings, insure that notes are chosen and ordered by blind
chance, or according to processes of change that have little to do
with conventional musical perception.
<p>
   What meaning remains will usually be crude, and it is striking
that in his conversations with Varga, Xenakis so often equates
beauty with savagery: in his fascination with weapons and armor,
for instance, with the sea or with the bulls of the Camargue.
<p>
   In his music virtually the whole elaborate machinery of Western
composition is set aside, and we are left with a brute vocabulary
of signals. As sometimes in the work of other modernists  &MD; 
Stravinsky, Varese, Harrison Birtwistle  &MD;  avoidance of the
immediate past leads to imagined contact with the archaic.
<p>
   In the conversation book Xenakis recalls how, as a boy in
Greece, he ``went to the museum and tried to imagine how the
statues would move if they suddenly came to life.''
<p>
   ``With what gestures?'' he wondered. ``How would they speak?
What would the music of their language be like?'' These are the
questions his compositions have been answering.
<p>
   Their answers, being removed from ordinary ways of doing things
musically, require particular efforts of virtuosity and imagination
from performers if the music's strength  &MD;  its intense particularity
 &MD;  is not to seem mere incapacity.
<p>
   Happily there are musicians up to this challenge, and none more
so than Charles Zachary Bornstein and his ST-X Ensemble, who gave
us ``Kraanerg'' at Cooper Union in New York City in the fall and
have now released two selections of smaller pieces on Mode CDs.
Each includes a 60's classic  &MD;  ``Eonta'' for piano and brass in one
case, ``Akrata'' for symphonic winds in the other  &MD;  along with more
recent works.
<p>
   Both recordings convince by their own conviction; all the
performances are hot. But the disk including ``Eonta'' (Mode 53) is
a clear front-runner.
<p>
   It offers the stark, urgent ritual ``N'shima,'' for two
amplified ``peasant voices'' with trombones, horns and cello; the
percussion solo ``Rebonds,'' brilliantly played by Robert McEwan,
and best of all, ``Akanthos,'' a 10-minute drama of sibylline
utterance in a context of clouds, brayings and scrubbings of sound,
all contrived, astonishingly, by an ensemble close to that of
Ravel's supersophisticated Mallarme settings.
<p>
   The soprano Susan May is superb in producing the imprecations,
formalized laughter, stunning octave leaps and final scanning of
the horizon before wild yelps.
<p>
   The other record (Mode 56), though, has the immense and strange
attractions of ``Echange,'' a concerto for bass clarinet and
ensemble, whose behemothian sounds glisten with harmonics.
<p>
   It is remarkable how, in discussing some of these and other
violently poetic works with Varga, Xenakis is unwilling to describe
them as anything more than interesting sequences of interesting
sounds. If the music is to assert his existence, perhaps it can do
so only by being itself, and not by being about its composer, who
must stand aside and let it happen.
<p>
   ``Eonta,'' he recalls, came into his mind while he was at
Tanglewood in Lenox, Mass., sitting in a boat with a pretty young
woman. ``We were surrounded by a forest, and I stroked the water
with my hand,'' he says. In the eventual eruptive work, though,
listeners are left, as Bornstein's note puts it, with ``radiated
light and cascading water'': a bucolic interlude has become fierce
physics.
</TEXT>
