<SLUG> BC-THE-BIRTH-OF-THE-BRA- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1581 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-THE-BIRTH-OF-THE-BRA-(BOOK EXCERPT/PART 1)-ART-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; THE BIRTH OF THE BRASSIERE: FROM WOODEN SLATS TO PADDED SATIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; North American print rights. &QL; 
 &UR; (Available art: B&AMP;W illustrations of an early 19th-century woman
being laced into a long corset; a 1897 Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co.
catalogue ad for the Princess Bust Developer; and an 1899 for the
first patented ``soutien-gorge'' brassiere.) &QL; 
   (To publish one or more parts of this book excerpt, they must be
purchased -- the rate is not prohibitive -- from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative Connie White in Kansas City. For a
price quote for your publication, call 800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax 816-822-1444.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; EDITOR'S NOTE: This is the first in a two-part excerpt of ``A
History of the Breast'' (Knopf) by Marilyn Yalom.
 &UR; By MARILYN YALOM &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
<p>
   Christian Dior's oft-quoted statement that ``without foundations
there can be no fashion'' has been meaningful for the past 700
years.
 &UR; STAYING PUT WITH CORSETS OF WOOD AND WHALEBONE &LR; 
<p>
   In the early 14th century, when women abandoned the loose tunics
that had previously been worn by both sexes in favor of
tighter-fitting clothes, undergarments began their fashionable
ascent.
<p>
   The stiff, clinging underbodice known as a ``cotte'' defined the
new thin ideal. Large-busted women bound strips of cloth around
their chests to acquire the small-breasted look then in favor.
<p>
   Some kind of breast support was now considered essential to the
wardrobe of any self-respecting lady, and from that time until the
beginning of our own century, breasts were supported mainly by
corsets.
<p>
   Corsets became truly formidable in the 15th century with the
invention of the ``body'' or ``pair of bodys'' in Spain. This
armorlike structure, consisting of two pieces hinged together at
the sides, made its way from the trendsetting Spanish court into
French and English high society during the 16th century.
<p>
   Strengthened with slats of wood and whalebone, and sometimes
made of leather or even metal, the ``body'' was worn as an
undergarment or, in some versions, as an outer garment.
<p>
   It is possible that the metal versions (which have survived in a
few museums) were used only for orthopedic cases, but there is no
doubt that upper-class women subjected themselves to the agony of
being encased in ``bodys'' stiffened by paste, leather, wood and
whalebone.
<p>
   The French version, alternately called a ``corset'' or a
``corps'' (body), was a kind of girdle that fit tightly across the
chest from beneath the breasts to beneath the ribs and ended in a
point on the stomach.
<p>
   In most French and English versions, a single bone, wood, ivory,
horn or metal busk was placed in the middle of the corset to
maintain its rigidity. This was the origin of all the boning and
similar devices designed to support the figure that developed in
corsetry over the next 400 years.
<p>
   Made by specialist craftsmen and often engraved with amorous
verses, the busk itself became an erotic object, the subject of
boudoir poems and public gestures. It was considered daring to pull
the central busk out from the bodice and to gesture with it as a
form of flirtation.
<p>
   The cultivation of the breast as a fashion icon took on new
commercial dimensions around 1670, when staymaking became a
distinct branch of tailoring.
<p>
   Corsets were a must for bourgeois and noble ladies, marking
their distinction from the popular classes. Some even wore their
lightly boned ``corps de nuit'' or ``corsets de nuit'' in bed.
<p>
   From the mid-18th century, a campaign against the corset raged
through much of Europe. Under the banners of science and reason,
and in step with the campaign against wet nursing, doctors in every
country militated against the corset on the grounds that it
deformed women's bodies.
<p>
   One of the first fashion changes of the French Revolution was
the exile of the corset. But before long, the corset reappeared in
both long and short models.
<p>
   The ``Empire waist,'' fashionable throughout Europe during the
reign of Napoleon (1804-1815), broke with all previous conventions
by raising the waist to the area immediately under the breasts. In
this manner the breasts became the undisputed center of attention.
<p>
   With the Restoration of the French monarchy in 18l5 and the
triumph of political conservatism throughout Europe, the waist
descended back to its natural level.
 &UR; FROM `DIVORCE CORSETS' TO FRENCH FALSIES &LR; 
<p>
   Around 1816, it was fashionable for breasts to be far apart from
one another. The ``Divorce Corset'' separated the breasts by means
of a padded triangle of iron or steel which was inserted into the
center front of the corset with its point upward.
<p>
   It became the rage in both France and England, although the
English quickly reverted to the unified, shelflike bust.
<p>
   At this time, in both France and England, corsets were still
beyond the reach of the working class. When the Swiss industrialist
Jean Werly installed the first corset factory at Bar-le-Duc in
France, cheaper mass-produced models became available.
<p>
   The mid-19th century was a time of major innovation in
undergarment production. Eyelet holes began to be strengthened with
metal rings. India rubber and elastic began to vie with whalebone
to produce the desired compression and support.
<p>
   Waistlines moved up and down, dropping below the normal waist
around 1840 and rising again in the late 1850s with the advent of
the crinoline (a stiffened petticoat or ``hoop'').
<p>
   The exaggerated hourglass figure required that waists be laced
in so tightly that some women reputedly died from the strain. A
waist measurement of 17 to 21 inches represented the ideal.
<p>
   Stays with front fastenings were introduced in England in the
1850s, and gradually all but replaced the backlaced model. The
French produced an astonishing variety of specialized corsets in a
wide array of materials and colors.
<p>
   To judge from the ads, which by now were appearing in fashion
magazines, a Frenchwoman had nothing better to do than spend her
time changing between leisure corsets, sleeping corsets, pregnancy
corsets, nursing corsets and corsets for horseback riding, bathing
and bicycling.
<p>
   By the end of the century, French corsetry was at the pinnacle
of its commercial heights.
<p>
   Falsies or ``bust improvers'' were commonly used throughout this
period. Made from cup-shaped wire structures or flexible celluloid,
or pieces of material with circular pockets into which a pad could
be inserted, English models promised to ``give roundness to those
that are too slim.''
<p>
   French falsies were fashioned out of ``peau de chamois,'' padded
satin, or, most frequently, rubber. American ``bust pads'' could be
bought in exclusive foundation stores or ordered cheaply through
the Sears, Roebuck catalogue.
<p>
   Surely one of the weirdest breast-augmenting gimmicks was ``The
Bust Developer''  &MD;  a three-part program including a jar of cream, a
bottle of lotion and a metal object resembling a bathroom plunger.
The bust developer was made of nickel and aluminum, and came in two
sizes, either a 4- or 5-inch diameter.
<p>
   The transition from the corset to the brassiere that took place
in the first decades of the 20th century represented a major
breakthrough for women. For the first time, a separate garment was
designed exclusively for the breasts.
<p>
   A French department store advertising its 1899-1890 corset
collection introduced the ``soutien-gorge'' (literally, ``throat
support''), in which the breasts were supported from above, by
shoulder straps, rather than from below. The soutien-gorge was the
mother of the modern brassiere.
<p>
   (Marilyn Yalom is a senior scholar at the Institute for Women
and Gender at Stanford University. ``A History of the Breast'' is
her fourth book.)
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 by Marilyn Yalom &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; Excerpted from the book ``A History of the Breast,'' published
by Knopf.
<p>
    &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</TEXT>
