<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; EDITOR'S NOTE: This is the first in a two-part excerpt of ``A
History of the Breast'' (Knopf) by Marilyn Yalom.
 &UR; By MARILYN YALOM &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
<p>
   Christian Dior's oft-quoted statement that ``without foundations
there can be no fashion'' has been meaningful for the past 700
years.
 &UR; STAYING PUT WITH CORSETS OF WOOD AND WHALEBONE &LR; 
<p>
   In the early 14th century, when women abandoned the loose tunics
that had previously been worn by both sexes in favor of
tighter-fitting clothes, undergarments began their fashionable
ascent.
<p>
   The stiff, clinging underbodice known as a ``cotte'' defined the
