   At this time, in both France and England, corsets were still
beyond the reach of the working class. When the Swiss industrialist
Jean Werly installed the first corset factory at Bar-le-Duc in
France, cheaper mass-produced models became available.
<p>
   The mid-19th century was a time of major innovation in
undergarment production. Eyelet holes began to be strengthened with
metal rings. India rubber and elastic began to vie with whalebone
to produce the desired compression and support.
<p>
   Waistlines moved up and down, dropping below the normal waist
around 1840 and rising again in the late 1850s with the advent of
the crinoline (a stiffened petticoat or ``hoop'').
<p>
   The exaggerated hourglass figure required that waists be laced
in so tightly that some women reputedly died from the strain. A
waist measurement of 17 to 21 inches represented the ideal.
<p>
   Stays with front fastenings were introduced in England in the
1850s, and gradually all but replaced the backlaced model. The
French produced an astonishing variety of specialized corsets in a
wide array of materials and colors.
<p>
   To judge from the ads, which by now were appearing in fashion
magazines, a Frenchwoman had nothing better to do than spend her
time changing between leisure corsets, sleeping corsets, pregnancy
corsets, nursing corsets and corsets for horseback riding, bathing
and bicycling.
<p>
   By the end of the century, French corsetry was at the pinnacle
of its commercial heights.
<p>
   Falsies or ``bust improvers'' were commonly used throughout this
period. Made from cup-shaped wire structures or flexible celluloid,
or pieces of material with circular pockets into which a pad could
be inserted, English models promised to ``give roundness to those
that are too slim.''
<p>
   French falsies were fashioned out of ``peau de chamois,'' padded
satin, or, most frequently, rubber. American ``bust pads'' could be
bought in exclusive foundation stores or ordered cheaply through
the Sears, Roebuck catalogue.
<p>
   Surely one of the weirdest breast-augmenting gimmicks was ``The
Bust Developer''  &MD;  a three-part program including a jar of cream, a
bottle of lotion and a metal object resembling a bathroom plunger.
The bust developer was made of nickel and aluminum, and came in two
sizes, either a 4- or 5-inch diameter.
<p>
   The transition from the corset to the brassiere that took place
in the first decades of the 20th century represented a major
breakthrough for women. For the first time, a separate garment was
designed exclusively for the breasts.
<p>
   A French department store advertising its 1899-1890 corset
collection introduced the ``soutien-gorge'' (literally, ``throat
support''), in which the breasts were supported from above, by
shoulder straps, rather than from below. The soutien-gorge was the
mother of the modern brassiere.
<p>
   (Marilyn Yalom is a senior scholar at the Institute for Women
and Gender at Stanford University. ``A History of the Breast'' is
her fourth book.)
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 by Marilyn Yalom &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; Excerpted from the book ``A History of the Breast,'' published
by Knopf.
<p>
    &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</TEXT>
