<DOCID> nyt970122.0385 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=v pri=u sel=tab-z> A9251 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-THE-BIRTH-OF-THE-BRA- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0525 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-THE-BIRTH-OF-THE-BRA-BOOK-EXCERPT-ADVISORY-ART-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; 700 YEARS OF LINGERIE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; North American print rights. &QL; 
 &UR; Art available. &QL; 
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This advisory has been transmitted three times  &MD;  into
the ``v,'' ``l'' and ``a'' files.)
 &UR; By MARILYN YALOM &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Imagine wearing a corset strengthened with wood, whalebone  &MD; 
even metal. Or an undergarment that cinches your waist into a
17-inch ``hourglass'' shape. These are just some of the indignities
 &MD;  and dangers  &MD;  women have endured in their centuries-long quest to
live up to an ever-changing ideal of feminine beauty.
<p>
   This fascinating two-part series about the evolution of lingerie
is excerpted from ``A History of the Breast'' (Knopf) by Marilyn
Yalom, a senior scholar at the Institute for Women and Gender at
Stanford University.
 &UR; PART ONE: THE BIRTH OF THE BRASSIERE  &MD;  FROM WOODEN SLATS TO PADDED
SATIN &LR; 
 &UR; (Available art: B&AMP;W illustrations of an early 19th-century woman
being laced into a long corset; a 1897 Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co.
catalogue ad for the Princess Bust Developer; and an 1899 for the
first patented ``soutien-gorge'' brassiere.)
<p>
   The evolution of lingerie begins in the early 14th century, when
women abandon loose tunics in favor of tighter-fitting clothes.
Corsets are crafted of wood, whalebone, leather  &MD;  even metal. By
the mid-1800s there are corsets for sleeping, horseback riding,
bathing and bicycling, and by end of the century, plungerlike
``bust developers'' are being marketed in women's magazines. Not
long after, the first modern-day brassiere  &MD;  one in which the
breasts are supported from above by shoulder straps  &MD;  makes its
debut. By Marilyn Yalom. Excerpted from ``A History of the Breast''
(Knopf). 1,100 words. (slugged: BC-THE-BIRTH-OF-THE-BRA-(BOOK
EXCERPT/PART 1)-ART-NYTSF)
 &UR; PART TWO: 20TH-CENTURY BRASSIERES  &MD;  FROM HANDKERCHIEFS AND RIBBON
TO BULLET BRAS, JOGBRAS AND WONDERBRAS &LR; 
 &UR; (Available art: color slides and B&AMP;W prints of a 1962 Maiden Form
bra ad; B&AMP;W prints of a 1927 Maiden Form bra ad; B&AMP;W illustration
of a Scanties advertisement, 1928.)
<p>
   In 1914 the first patented U.S. brassiere is invented by New
York debutante Mary Phelps Jacobs, who, while dressing for a dance,
abandons the heavy evening corset laid out by her maid and instead
fits herself with two handkerchiefs and a pink ribbon. During the
decades that follow large breasts go in and out of style several
times. Rayon, Lastex and nylon make bras more comfortable than
ever, and manufacturers respond to social trends and fashion whims
with such innovations the ``invisible'' bra, the Jogbra and the
Wonderbra. By Marilyn Yalom. Excerpted from ``A History of the
Breast'' (Knopf). 1,200 words. (slugged:
BC-100-YEARS-OF-BRASSIERES-(BOOK EXCERPT/PART 2)-ART-NYTSF)
<p>
   ----------- &QC; 
<p>
   (To publish one or more parts of this book excerpt, they must be
purchased -- the rate is not prohibitive -- from one of New York
Times Syndicate sales representative Connie White in Kansas City.
Call 800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax 816-822-1444.
<p>
    &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</TEXT>
