<DOCID> nyt970122.0390 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=k pri=r sel=tad-z> A9257 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0575 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MURRAY-COLUMN-COX  &QL; 
 &UR; TALL TALES &AMP; SHORT STORIES: A DEGREE OF DIFFERENCE
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; By JOE MURRAY &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas  &MD;  I was standing in line at the
department store checkout counter. The nice lady clerk was fanning
herself with a sales slip.
<p>
   ``Whoo-ee,'' she intoned. ``Is it just me, or is it hot in
here?''
<p>
   I said it was hot. The customer next to me said he thought it
was just right. Right away I knew he was a Yankee.
<p>
   Not just from the way he was dressed, wearing a fresh polo shirt
with the label on the pocket and hardly faded at all, and pleated
britches starchy crisp.
<p>
   East Texans tend to wear wilted blue jeans and checkered shirts
with button-down collars that, on less formal occasions, are left
loose and curled at the tips.
<p>
   Neither was it his accent that branded him an outsider, though
from the way he spoke you could tell he was from somewhere way off
 &MD;  either that, or he was on TV.
<p>
   East Texans have a slow way of talking. Not only do we say what
we think, we talk like we think. We tend to drop certain letters
and, in the process, pick up others.
<p>
   Concrete, for example, is likely to come out concreek. Saturday
turns into Satiddy. Even our Southern accent has an accent. You-all
is yawl.
<p>
   Personally, I'm hoping this idea that black English is a
language unto itself will catch on, what they're calling Ebonics  &MD; 
a combination of ebony and phonics.
<p>
   If so, maybe they'll cut East Texans a little slack, too, on the
way we talk  &MD;  Redneconics, if you will.
<p>
   But I digress.
<p>
   Getting back to the Yankee fellow who was standing back of me in
the line, a nice-looking older gent with white hair and matching
beard, neatly trimmed.
<p>
   I asked him what I already knew.
<p>
   ``That's not an East Texas accent, is it?''
<p>
   He looked at me for a long moment, as if I were accusing him of
something he didn't want to admit to.
<p>
   ``Actually,'' he said, trying to talk slower, ``it's a mixture
that comes from many places.''
<p>
   This got the lady clerk's attention. ``Like whar?'' she asked,
narrowing her eyes.
<p>
   Minnesota, for one place. Vermont for another. Even the
Caribbean Islands, he said.
<p>
   ``But I like it here best,'' he said, ``especially the
weather.''
<p>
   That, of course, is how I knew him for what he was, an outsider,
when the lady clerk had asked us if it felt too hot in the store.
No East Texan will ever admit to the temperature being just right.
<p>
   I tried to explain as much to him, but there's just so much
other people can understand, even if they live among us.
<p>
   ``Where I originally came from it's 20 degrees below zero,'' he
said. ``Your weather is wonderful. How can you fault it?''
<p>
   ``It's the humidity,'' the lady clerk said, lowering her voice
as if it were a secret.
<p>
   He shook his head. ``It reminds me of the Caribbean,'' he
allowed. ``I love it here.''
<p>
   Well, so do we. People who have lived here all their lives and
have never been anywhere are quick to tell you East Texas is the
best place in the world, forever and ever, amen.
<p>
   Just so long as you don't ask us about the weather at the wrong
time of the year.
<p>
   Those times being spring and summer, fall and winter.
<p>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. The e-mail address
is awew18a(at)prodigy.com.)
</TEXT>
