NYT-01-22-97 1630EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0393 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tth-z> A9261 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0868 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CURT FLOOD'S BATTLES WEREN'T FOUGHT FOR FREE LUNACY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ED NOTE: RESENDING TO FIX SPELLING OF LAST NAME OF JULIUS ERVING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURA VECSEY &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Seattle Post-Intelligencer &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SEATTLE  &MD;  In his time, Curt Flood was an original. A Gold Glove
center fielder with the St. Louis Cardinals, he was also a brooder
and a painter and an iconoclast whose active and nervous
intelligence drove him not only to question authority, but to blow
it up.
<p>
   Curt Flood took baseball to the wall.
<p>
   He took unfavorable and costly action against the people who
made up the rules.
<p>
   In 1969, Flood refused to report for duty after the Cardinals
traded him to the Phillies. Instead of accepting his fate, Flood
took his sense of outrage and injustice all the way to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
<p>
   He would not be treated like meat.
<p>
   As a 12-year veteran, he should have some say in what happened
to him.
<p>
   He fought a system that bound Mickey Mantle to the Yankees, Bob
Gibson to the Cardinals and Jackie Robinson to the Dodgers.
<p>
   Flood lost his case. But it is his undying legacy that his fight
enabled others after him to win.
<p>
   But what about this winning?
<p>
   What about the new world order in sports that Curt Flood
invented by calling himself a ``free agent?''
<p>
   We don't have Curt Floods in sports these days. Mostly because
we don't need them, or so it would seem.
<p>
   Today's battles are about the bottom line.
<p>
   Everyone's a star. Everyone's a corporation. Too many players
think they are as big if not bigger than the game, which is a
notion affirmed by their sneaker makers.
<p>
   Gary Payton and Ken Griffey Jr. and Andre Agassi are not only
bound to the NBA, Major League Baseball or the ATP, they are bound
to each other, as ``part of the Nike family.''
<p>
   These guys say these things. And mean it.
<p>
   Twenty-five years ago, Flood did all the dirty work for freedom
and the rights of an individual player to make their own deals,
their best deals.
<p>
   But now, it's 180 degrees wrong the other way.
<p>
   The time line from Curt Flood's righteous and right-on protest
down to Dennis Rodman's latest NBA suspension is filled with other
eruptions and episodes that have radically changed the climate in
which athletes labor.
<p>
   But certainly, a quarter century later, free agency has turned
into free lunacy.
<p>
   Now it's bad as you wanna be.
<p>
   Now it's rich rewards not for substance and convictions, but for
House of Style cameos and fishnet pants and tie-dyed hair that is
only half as mixed up as the stuff inside a Dennis Rodman cranium.
<p>
   Instead of Curt Flood, we get Dennis Rodman as the most
flamboyant symbol of our sporting era  &MD;  with Nike and Converse and
MTV willing to bank their profit margins on a guy who is mistakenly
marketed as the brave one, willing to live out his fantasies in
public.
<p>
   I have a fantasy, too. It's that Nike, Converse and MTV would
cut Rodman loose. Rodman unplugged. For his sake. For ours. So we
can concentrate on other players who are trying to do the right
thing, even though it's hard to figure that out.
<p>
   Sports can give us heroes and role models. Sports can give us
real revolutionaries, not just rebels without a clue.
<p>
   On NBC last Sunday, as the Rodman-less Bulls were getting
hammered by the Rockets, commentator and former NBA great Julius
Erving made a personal plea to Rodman, who was missing game No. 2
of an 11-game (maybe longer) suspension.
<p>
   Erving said one day, when Rodman is done with his career, either
through retirement or exile, he will regret that he never gave
anything back to the game.
<p>
   Erving's plea seemed just as naive as it was earnest.
<p>
   The very idea that Rodman should recognize his responsibility to
give something back to the game seems as far-fetched as his wedding
dress publicity stunts.
<p>
   Rodman, whose free agency landed him a one-year, $10 million
deal with the Bulls this season, is making the Forbes big money
list because he refuses to accept the larger responsibility that
most NBA players, and most athletes, eventually come to accept.
<p>
   Rodman is living proof that humans, unfortunately, need a few
checks and balances to keep things from exploding.
<p>
   ``We all have times of frustration when we want to retaliate,
but we know we can't,'' Michael Jordan said when asked for his take
on Rodman's groin-kicking of a courtside cameraman.
<p>
   Well, this week, when Curt Flood died of cancer, the world lost
a man who fought the good fight for a cause that was worthy of his
anger and frustration and worthy of retaliation.
<p>
   For that, Flood never got the chance to finish what he started.
His .296 career batting average, seven Gold Gloves and three
All-Star appearances had all the makings of a Hall of Fame career.
<p>
   But he traded it to make a stand.
<p>
   Rodman, a gifted athlete who has re-created the art of defense
and rebounding with his tireless effort, is about to trade his for
nothing except the right to be as bad as he wants to be, just
because he thinks he's the boldest sign of our times.
<p>
   Here's hoping history is not as kind to Dennis Rodman as it has
been and will be to Curt Flood.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1632EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0394 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9262 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LION-ABC-UPDATE4 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0892 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FOOD-LION-ABC-UPDATE4-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DISNEY'S ABC MUST PAY FOOD LION $5.5 MLN IN DAMAGES (UPDATE4) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Joseph Menn &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Rewrites top. Adds closing stock price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Greensboro, North Carolina, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- A federal
jury told Walt Disney Co.'s ABC television network to pay Food Lion
Inc. $5.5 million in punitive damages for having two news producers
lie to get jobs at the supermarket chain.
<p>
   The verdict stunned media lawyers, since Food Lion never
challenged the truth of the resulting 1992 ``PrimeTime Live''
expose, which showed workers disguising and selling out-of-date
meat.
<p>
   Lawyers said the verdict, if it holds up on appeal, will spur
similar suits and reduce the number of investigations that use
hidden cameras. The award comes after several lesser-known rulings
aimed at how the media gathers news.
<p>
   ``People are going to think three or four times before they do
something like this,'' said Robert Sack, a libel defense lawyer for
Time Inc., the Wall Street Journal and Newsday. ``There are going
to be stories about health, safety and other possible misdeeds that
will never get out.''
<p>
   ABC said it would appeal ``through all available channels'' if
U.S. District Judge Carlton Tilley doesn't set the verdict aside.
<p>
   Other lawyers said the award is likely to be reduced, since it
is several thousand times the $1,402 in actual damages that the
jury awarded Food Lion last month.
<p>
   Food Lion's Class A shares rose 1/16 to 9 1/8 in trading of
602,400, more than its three-month daily average of 479,000.
Disney's stock rose 1 to 70 3/4.
<p>
   ``We're very satisfied with the verdict,'' said Food Lion
attorney Richard Wyatt.
<p>
   After more than five days of hard-fought deliberations, the
12-member jury decided that ABC and PrimeTime executives
consciously broke fraud laws to get undercover footage.
<p>
   Two lower-level producers faked resumes to get Food Lion jobs
where they could report on and film the company's practices through
small cameras hidden in wigs and clothing.
<p>
   Salisbury, North Carolina-based Food Lion claimed the report
cost it more than $2 billion in lost profit and stock value. Judge
Tilley barred Food Lion from using the content of the broadcast as
evidence.
<p>
   The jury, which last week said it was deadlocked 11-1, spared
the two producers, directing two higher-ranking ABC executives to
pay a combined $45,750. Former ``PrimeTime'' executive producer
Richard Kaplan, now elsewhere at ABC, was told to pay $35,000 and
Senior Producer Ira Rosen was ordered to pay $10,750.
<p>
   ABC said it would pay as much as legally possible of the
individual awards.
<p>
   The judgment ``should trouble every American,'' the network said
in a statement. ``Food Lion has succeeded in convincing a jury to
punish ABC for using undercover investigating techniques that
exposed its unsanitary practices.''
<p>
   Jurors said the verdict was intended only to warn the media that
they have to obey the law and not make false statements.
<p>
   ``No one wants to handcuff the media,'' said jury foreman Greg
Mack. ``The real problem came (because) ABC had no guidelines.''
<p>
   Tony Kinton, a brewery worker in Reidsville, North Carolina, was
the lone juror that hadn't wanted to award any punitive damages.
Others wanted to award billions of dollars and some expressed their
opinions before hearing any evidence, he said.
<p>
   ``We had no choice,'' Kinton said. ``We were going to send a
message to the press that there are limitations.''
<p>
   The media said it got the message loud and clear.
<p>
   ``The real loser is the public,'' said Bruce Sanford, a libel
attorney in Washington, D.C. ``All we will get are more stories on
Dennis Rodman.''
<p>
   The verdict is the latest in a series of court decisions aimed
not at the content of news reports but at newsgathering techniques.
<p>
   Rulings in the past year have allowed juries to consider whether
reporters invaded the privacy of accident victims and barred a
camera crew from following the son of an executive at U.S.
Healthcare Inc.
<p>
   ``People are angry at people who gather the news and the way
they gather the news, even when it is in the public interest,''
said libel lawyer Sack, of the New York firm Gibson, Dunn &AMP;
Crutcher.
<p>
   In the Food Lion case, the Greensboro, North Carolina, jury last
month awarded $1,402 in compensatory damages, mostly for the
salaries earned by the producers at the stores.
<p>
   Sack and other legal experts predicted that the gap between the
small compensatory damages and the multimillion-dollar punitive
award would prompt the judge or the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals to reduce the amount of punitive damages.
<p>
   The slight rise in Food Lion's shares indicates that investors
realize that the chain must do more to win back customers, analysts
said. Food Lion has already revamped its stores and preparation
methods to restore customer confidence.
<p>
   ``It's probably the safest place to buy perishables now,'' said
Salomon Brothers analyst Jonathon Ziegler.
<p>
   Sales, however, are not increasing as quickly as they had before
the show, when Food Lion was the fastest-growing grocer in the
country. And its net income hasn't recovered since 1992.
<p>
   Belgian grocery chain Delhaize-Le Lion SA owns about half Food
Lion's voting stock.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1632EST
</TRAILER>
