<DOCID> nyt970122.0402 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9278 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-WEDNESDAY'S-US-MARKET </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0560 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-WEDNESDAY'S-US-MARKETS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WEDNESDAY'S U.S. MARKETS: STOCKS ARE MIXED AS DOLLAR JUMPS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Scott Schnipper &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. stocks were mixed as
International Business Machines Corp. reported disappointing
earnings, straying from this month's trend of higher-than-forecast
profits, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index and Nasdaq Composite
indexes reached records. The dollar surged against major
currencies, while Treasury bonds sank.
<p>
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average slumped 33.87 to 6850.03. The
S&AMP;P 500, representing three-quarters of the value of all U.S.
stocks, rose 3.5 to a record 786.22, while the Nasdaq Composite
Index vaulted 11.07 to 1388.04, both reaching their fifth straight
all-time high.
<p>
   ``We'll have some earnings disappointments,'' and those
companies' shares will suffer, said Kenneth Corba, chief investment
officer at Eagle Asset Management, which oversees $2.7 billion.
Still, ``I don't think the market's overvalued in the context of
all of the positives,'' he said. ``You have declining interest
rates; corporate America's become more profitable and more
competitive. We're in a hospitable environment.''
<p>
   Compaq Computer Corp. and Dean Witter Discover Co. added
surprisingly strong earnings announcements to this week's pile of
profit reports.
<p>
   The dollar jumped to its highest point in almost four years
against the Japanese yen and its highest since June 1994 versus the
German mark, bolstered by U.S. economic strength and expectations
that major nations won't stand in the way of its rise.
<p>
   It reached 1.6445 marks and 119.18 yen, while climbing to a
32-month peak of 1.4358 Swiss francs. It was recently at 1.6415
marks, from 1.6298 marks late yesterday in New York, and at 118.98
yen, up from 117.99 yen.
<p>
   ``The beat goes on for the dollar,'' said James McGroarty, chief
currency manager of Potomac Babson Inc., a money management firm
whose parent, David L. Babson Inc., has $13 billion of assets.
Potomac Babson bought dollars today. ``We think this move has
further to go.''
<p>
   In the past month, the dollar rose 6 percent against the
deutsche mark and 4 percent against the yen.
<p>
   The U.S. currency also got a boost as Russia's parliament
debated whether to demand that President Boris Yeltsin resign
because of his poor health. The State Duma voted to continue
discussing a resolution calling for Yeltsin's departure.
<p>
   Signs of political turmoil in Russia often hurt the mark because
Germany is Russia's largest trading partner and creditor.
<p>
   Treasury bonds fell as Wall Street firms struggled to sell the
$17.5 billion of two-year notes they bought from the Treasury and
prepared for the Treasury's sale of $12.5 billion of five-year
notes tomorrow.
<p>
   The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond, little changed prior to the
1 p.m. Eastern time sale, slumped about 1/2 point, or $5 per $1,000
bond, pushing its yield up 4 basis points to 6.82 percent.
<p>
   In other markets:
<p>
   -- Gold for delivery in February dropped $2.1 an ounce to
$351.70.
<p>
   -- Crude oil for delivery in March rose 2 cents a barrel to
$24.24 on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
<p>
   -- Britain's FT-SE 100 stock index gained 23.6 to a record
4219.1.
<p>
   -- Japan's Nikkei 225 Index surged 655.72 to 18,013.88.
</TEXT>
