<DOCID> nyt970122.0403 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=ttj-z> A9284 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-DREW-BARRYMORE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1174 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DREW-BARRYMORE-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DREW BARRYMORE FALLS FOR LONE STAR STATE AND A TEXAS ACTOR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BRUCE WESTBROOK &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   McDADE, Texas  &MD;  Drew Barrymore fell in love with Texas. In fact,
she sounds as if she fell in love IN Texas, too  &MD;  and with a Texas
boy.
<p>
   He's Luke Wilson, 25, the handsome star of last year's quirky
``Bottle Rocket,'' which was written by his brother, Owen, and
directed by Wes Anderson.
<p>
   Now the Dallas-born Wilson and Hollywood brat Barrymore are
toiling together in ``Home Fries,'' a comedy being shot in Bastrop,
Coupland and other Austin-area towns.
<p>
   Their characters fall in love  &MD;  and the actors don't seem far
behind.
<p>
   This is their second film together, after shooting
``Independence,'' as yet unreleased, last summer.
<p>
   ``I feel like it's sheer luck,'' Barrymore, 21, said as she
waited to film a scene while sitting in a van on a country road 35
miles east of Austin.
<p>
   ``But obviously it was very fated, because before I'd met Mr.
Wilson, I'd already been assigned to do two movies with him.''
<p>
   Mr. Wilson? That doesn't sound chummy. It turns out discretion
is a newfound virtue for Barrymore, who brandishes it like a child
with a new puppy.
<p>
   That's a big change for a woman who had preteen bouts with drugs
and a monthlong marriage  &MD;  not to mention notoriety for posing in
Playboy and flashing her breasts for David Letterman on ``The Late
Show.''
<p>
   ``Well, I HAVE learned to be discreet,'' Barrymore insisted.
``I've learned it's the best way.
<p>
   ``I'm a very open and honest person. But where I draw the line
is, there are certain times where it's not just me  &MD;  when it
involves someone else.''
<p>
   Fine, but back to ``Mr. Wilson'' ... ``Well, it was so strange
meeting someone and knowing that, like, someone up above or around
the universe had chosen for us to work together,'' she said,
running a hand through the short, curly, red-dyed hair she's
wearing for this shoot.
<p>
   ``It was funny because I was, like, `Who is this person who's SO
in my life and I'm in theirs?' And thank God he's, like, the most
incredible person I have ever met.''
<p>
   Barrymore tends to pepper her talk with absolutes. In Texas, she
has experienced ``the most beautiful sunset I've ever seen.'' But
the most incredible person? ``Well ... no comment,'' she said  &MD; 
then immediately recanted.
<p>
   ``I'll give you some details, but I'll also leave out a few.
I'll make it a puzzle. I think it's important to respect who you're
with and to be discreet, but to remain yourself, too. That goes for
love. Be who you are, but respect that person, too.''
<p>
   As for Mr. Wilson, he's even more discreet, avoiding the subject
while munching lunch in a drafty tent near a horse stall. An
amiable, soft-spoken guy with a quick but natural smile, he grew up
in Dallas, the son of an ad-man dad and a photographer mom. For the
past three years, he's lived in Los Angeles, hustling acting gigs.
<p>
   ``Working with Drew in this and `Independence' is quite a
coincidence,'' he said in his lazy drawl.
<p>
   The Warner Bros. movie is modestly budgeted, though the buzz
around the set is that the bankable Barrymore is getting several
million bucks.
<p>
   Shelley Duvall plays Barrymore's mom in ``Home Fries,'' due in
theaters by fall. It will probably be rated PG-13. ``X-Files''
co-producer Vince Gilligan wrote the screenplay. Directing is Dean
Parisot, who has helmed TV's ``Northern Exposure'' and ``E.R.''
<p>
   (FOLLOWING 5 PARAGRAPHS ARE OPTIONAL.)
<p>
   In ``Home Fries,'' Wilson and Jake Busey (``The Frighteners'')
play brothers whose father has philandered with Sally (Barrymore)
in a small town, leaving her 8 1/2 months pregnant.
<p>
   The boys, who are military nuts, use an Army helicopter to
terrorize their dad and head him back home. But the man has a fatal
heart attack.
<p>
   They then learn that some incriminating radio messages from
their chopper were picked up on the drive-through speaker at a
burger joint where Sally happens to work. Wilson's character gets a
job there to find out how much Sally knows, then falls in love with
her. Mayhem ensues.
<p>
   ``I'm just a nice guy from this nutty family where things go
haywire,'' Wilson said.
<p>
   Barrymore can relate from personal experience.
<p>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
<p>
   Though America came to know Barrymore as the wide-eyed innocent
of ``E.T.  &MD;  The Extra-Terrestrial'' when she was just 6, being the
offspring of the Barrymore acting clan has meant a life in the fast
lanes of Hollywood and New York.
<p>
   ``The people there are extraordinary,'' she said, ``but they
have an attitude that can knock you over. I believe in kindness,
and it's hard to find people who are warm in cities.
<p>
   ``I want to be where people are nice  &MD;  where they value the
power of a smile and how it takes nothing but gives everything.
That's where I want to raise my children.''
<p>
   If anything, kids are more on her mind than boyfriends. Playing
a pregnant woman has put Barrymore in a fiercely maternal state.
<p>
   ``I am very ready for motherhood,'' she said, gently cradling a
rubbery prosthetic beneath her dress.
<p>
   Barrymore raised the dress  &MD;  she wore leggings underneath  &MD;  to
reveal her fake rounded belly.
<p>
   ``It smells like pancake mix  &MD;  like a Bisquick nightmare,'' she
said. ``Go on  &MD;  smell it!'' She settled back into her seat.
<p>
   ``I don't know when it will be,'' she said of motherhood. ``I
choose to wait until the perfect time in the cosmos. I'll probably
be so thrilled, I'll be in a rainbow all day. I'll be playing music
and talking to him or her and trying to stay away from starches.''
<p>
   Barrymore says Texas touches her. She recalls another Texas stay
in 1994, when filming ``Bad Girls,'' a production plagued by
infighting and the firing of a director.
<p>
   ``I didn't have a lover, and I was very alone then,'' she said.
``But one day I walked outside and was covered in butterflies. That
was, like, perfect  &MD;  my first great Texas experience. It was one of
the most incredible days of my life.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
<p>
   Austin has been a bit more mundane than that West Texas shoot.
During her time off, Barrymore delights in bohemian slovenliness.
<p>
   ``I don't do massage or manny-peddies (manicure-pedicures). I
don't grab a Fendi bag and trot out to my BMW to go catch some
sushi. I put on my boxers, go downstairs, read a book and pick my
toenails.
<p>
   ``I DO clean them. I'm very clean. Don't think just because I
don't manny-peddy that I'm a dirty birdie, because my feet are
clean.''
<p>
   With that  &MD;  and a bubbly laugh  &MD;  she whisks into the winter
winds, ready to jump into a pickup with Mr. Wilson for the next
scene.
<p>
   ``Just remember,'' Barrymore said, pausing at the window, ``this
is what movies are all about for me. It's not about the reception
or the numbers. It's about what's happening while you're filming.
This experience has been the best. It has gone by so quickly. ... I
love Texas. It's meant so much to me.''
</TEXT>
