<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9290 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-HO-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0533 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-AIDS-HO-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ABBOTT, GLAXO DRUGS SEEN CLEARING HIV IN LYMPH TISSUE, SEMEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Kristin Jensen &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Treating newly-infected HIV
patients with a combination of Abbott Laboratories' Norvir and
Glaxo Wellcome Plc's AZT and 3TC appears to stop the reproduction
of HIV within lymphoid tissue and seminal fluid, AIDS researcher
David Ho said today.
<p>
   Ho and his fellow researchers did find some evidence of
``residual particles'' of HIV in the lymphoid tissue of patients
treated with the combination for 10 to 16 months, though he said
there was no evidence the virus was reproducing. Ho and his team
also found that the patients' immune systems were holding up well,
showing no signs of increased viral activity.
<p>
   The finding is important because the lymphoid tissue is one of
the places researchers believe HIV could hide in patients who have
no sign of the virus in their blood using the most sensitive tests.
Still, Ho cautioned that the finding is preliminary and no one
knows for sure if this means a cure for the disease is near.
<p>
   ``Can HIV be eradicated from an infected person? The answer is
clearly we don't know,'' Ho told reporters. ``And if you ask has
HIV been eradicated from any of our patients, the answer is
unequivocally no.''
<p>
   Ho said he now believes that it will take between two and
two-and-a-half years before HIV decays enough in the body to
consider stopping treatment. Originally, he and his team planned to
consider taking patients off treatment after 12 months when the
patients showed no detectable signs of virus in the blood and
lymphoid tissue.
<p>
   ``We're definitely reversing what we had put down on paper
initially,'' Ho said. ``We clearly said this is premature.''
<p>
   The team revised the estimate using results of clinical studies
and a mathematical model, Ho said. He said the team will test more
tissue samples and wait at least two years for any one patient
before considering stopping therapy. Several patients may reach
that point in the next six to eight months, he said.
<p>
   Ho and his team began with 12 newly-infected patients, treating
them with the Norvir/AZT/3TC combination. Seven of those patients
remain in the study after drop-outs due to side effects and failure
to comply with the necessary regimen.
<p>
   Since then, the group has added 11 more newly-infected patients
who are being treated with Merck &AMP; Co.'s Crixivan along with AZT
and 3TC, a regimen that has fewer side effects. Those patients have
only been in the study between four and nine months, though they
too show no signs of HIV in the blood with the most sensitive
tests, Ho said.
<p>
   Ho stressed that there is a long way to go before the virus is
understood and said it's too soon to predict when or if a cure will
be found. The recent news about HIV treatments may have been
over-optimistic.
<p>
   ``The situation is neither black nor white,'' Ho said. ``It is
some shade of gray.''
<p>
   The ongoing studies previewed today by Ho will be presented in
full later this week at the Fourth Conference on Retroviruses and
Opportunistic Infections in Washington.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1640EST
</TRAILER>
