<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9304 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-DISCLOSURE-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1078 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FEA-DISCLOSURE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SMALL INVESTORS AT A LOSS WHEN IT COMES TO TIMELY INFORMATION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Gerard Meuchner &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Repeating for all needing.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Boston, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- General Motors Corp. gave a
welcome warning last month to a few close friends.
<p>
   One by one, the automaker called analysts at top brokerage firms
on Dec. 18 to say that fourth-quarter costs would be higher than
expected. Word was quickly passed to those firm's big clients,
whose sales of GM stock sent the shares tumbling 1 3/8 on a day
when the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 38 points. Other
investors had to wait until the next day -- when nine analysts cut
fourth-quarter earnings estimates -- to find out what GM said in
private.
<p>
   Almost daily, companies ranging in size from GM and Pharmacia &AMP;
Upjohn Co. to little-known Pioneer-Standard Electronics Inc. and
Vantive Corp. tell certain investors and analysts that bad news is
coming, giving them a chance to bail out before everyone else.
<p>
   ``The game is rigged,'' said Michael Lorberblatt, a New York
artist who owns 126 GM shares. ``I'm getting screwed.''
<p>
   GM says it did nothing wrong and that its phone calls to
analysts didn't give an advantage to anyone. And the automaker saw
no need to issue a news release, a spokesman said, because the
information wasn't important enough.
<p>
   Lorberblatt doesn't buy it. ``Why would they be calling anybody
in the first place?'' he asked. ``They have little sweetheart deals
with big financial institutions.''
<p>
   Investors looking for help when this happens will be
disappointed. The Securities and Exchange Commission and the stock
exchanges have no power to stop what one regulator calls ``uneven
disclosure.''
<p>
   The SEC's main job, for example, is to look for signs that
someone wrongly obtained important information that could affect a
company's stock price and used it to trade. ``The SEC sees its job
as being a cop,'' said Edward Fleischman, a former SEC
commissioner.
<p>
   The stock exchanges, meanwhile, simply push companies to
publicly disclose news in some uniform manner, usually in the form
of press releases or news conferences.
<p>
   In fact, doling out timely news to a few investors and analysts
is perfectly legal, experts say. ``A conference call is the
functional equivalent of a press release,'' said Boris Feldman, a
Palo Alto, California, securities lawyer.
<p>
   Uneven disclosure happens so often it passes with little notice,
particularly at smaller companies.
<p>
   Consider software developer Vantive. On Oct. 17, the company
reported third-quarter earnings that exceeded forecasts by 50
percent. The stock closed at 40 3/4, its second-highest ever.
<p>
   The next day, the shares plunged 23 percent, all in the first
hour of trading. That's because the night before -- after the
positive earnings were disseminated to everyone -- Vantive told a
small group of analysts in a conference call that revenue growth
would slow. Those on the call passed on the warning to their
clients, many of whom had their sell orders ready to go when the
market opened.
<p>
   Vantive Chief Financial Officer Kathleen Murphy says she doesn't
understand the stock's plunge because the company only repeated
what it disclosed earlier in securities filings.
<p>
   While U.S. regulators shrug their shoulders at this kind of poor
disclosure, officials in other countries are getting impatient with
it. Some Swedish regulators, for instance, got fed up with this
practice after Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn on Oct. 31 first publicly issued
an uneventful earnings report and then told a small group of
analysts and investors by phone something that was left out of that
report: Wall Street's 1997 profit estimates were 10 cents too high.
On the heels of that call, the drugmaker's shares fell 1 3/4 to 36.
<p>
   The Stockholm Stock Exchange on Dec. 4 said it wouldn't take
action against the company, but Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn promised that
from now on it will include news that could affect the stock in its
press releases.
<p>
   Sometimes, loose lips in a one-on-one conversation starts the
chain of tips that lead to trading advantages for just a few.
<p>
   Take electronics parts distributor Pioneer-Standard. On Sept.
10, the company's stock fell 17 percent in the first half hour of
trading after McDonald &AMP; Co. analyst Robert Damron told the
brokerage's sales force he cut his rating on Pioneer-Standard to
``hold'' from ``aggressive buy'' because of slower sales.
<p>
   Damron, now with Cleary Gull Reiland &AMP; McDevitt, was on target
with his rating cut because he happened to have a great source for
his projection. The day before he put out his bearish report,
Damron learned that the company was going to have a disappointing
quarter in a phone call with Chief Executive James Bayman.
<p>
   That call was a surprise to even Pioneer-Standard's Chief
Financial Officer John Goodger. Minutes after arriving at his
office in the morning, with the market already open, the National
Association of Securities Dealer's surveillance department called
Goodger to ask why the stock was dropping.
<p>
   Goodger checked and found out about the phone call between
Bayman and Damron. More than four hours later, at 1:22 p.m.,
Pioneer publicly announced that fiscal second-quarter sales and
earnings would be less than a year earlier.
<p>
   ``We tried to get that out as soon as possible,'' Goodger said.
<p>
   There is a potential solution to the uneven disclosure problem,
said John Markese, president of the 180,000-member American
Association of Individual Investors: broadcast conference calls
over the Internet. Individuals could listen in, although only
analysts could ask questions, he said.
<p>
   Congress, too, has tried to tackle the problem and in 1995
passed a law giving companies a legal ``safe harbor'' when they
make ``forward-looking statements.''
<p>
   Critics of the bill, though, say it may give well-connected
analysts and investors even more of an edge, as some companies use
the law as a legal shield when discussing forecasts.
<p>
   ``Companies are not as careful about what they say and to
whom,'' said former SEC commissioner Rick Roberts.
<p>
   Federal Reserve statistics show that people are pulling money
out of stocks and shifting cash to mutual funds. While there are
many reasons for selling individual stocks, one might just be that
small investors know companies don't give them the news when they
need it.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1645EST
</TRAILER>
