<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MEXICO-STOCKS-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MEXICO SHARES FALL FOR 2ND DAY AMID HIGHER U.S. INTEREST RATES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Mexico City, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Mexican stocks fell for a
second day as higher U.S. interest rates fueled concerns that local
rates would follow, hurting corporate earnings, investors said.
<p>
   The yield on the benchmark U.S. 30-year Treasury bond rose 5
basis points to 6.83 percent. Higher U.S. interest rates sometimes
prompt the Mexican central bank to push local rates higher in order
to discourage investors from taking their money out of the country.
<p>
   Still, optimism that higher employment rates will boost consumer
demand in coming months helped Mexican shares recover from a drop
of 28 points in early trading.
<p>
   ``Retail companies are telling us that in December and during
the fourth quarter they registered higher sales,'' said Gerardo
Copca, an analyst at Valores Finamex SA in Mexico city.
<p>
   The Mexican government said Monday that the nation's
unemployment rate fell to 4.1 percent in December, the lowest level
in two years.
<p>
   The bolsa index fell 9.59 points, or 0.26 percent, to 3707.75.
Shares of financial group Grupo Financiero Serfin SA and hotel
operator Grupo Posadas SA led the declines.
<p>
   At the same time, shares of textile and petrochemical producer
Cydsa SA and bus maker Consorcio G Grupo Dina SA rose today.
<p>
   Cydsa's shares increased 0.98 to 21 pesos after the
Monterrey-based company said yesterday that it plans to invest $36
million in 1997 to upgrade its operations.
<p>
   Dina's shares rose 0.3 to 5.8 pesos on indications that truck
and bus sales may be picking up steam. In December, bus sales
almost tripled, while truck sales rose 91 percent.
--Eduardo Garcia in Mexico City, (525) 514 3042 through the New
York newsroom (212) 318 2300/cp
