<STORYID cat=l pri=u sel=taf-z> A9308 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-U.S.-DESIGN-STU </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0902 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PARIS-U.S.-DESIGN-STUDENTS-850(2TAKES)-ART-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; YOUNG AMERICANS TRIUMPH IN PARIS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (kd) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Philippe Starck, watch your back. American design students
stormed Paris two weeks ago.
<p>
   This year, for the first time, 17 American design students from
four schools exhibited their work at the Paris furniture show, the
Salon du Meuble. And by all accounts they created une sensation.
<p>
   Most walked off with commissions in their pockets or contract
talks with manufacturers under their belts. Several turned down
on-the-spot sales of their models. Fairgoers jumped the ropes to
get a good look at the unexpectedly sleek concepts and
craftsmanship. Though there were some standard design-student takes
on view  &MD;  angry young chairs and a don't-call-me-a-table or two  &MD; 
there were also furniture prototypes that showed prescience about
where homes are headed as the generation born in the late 60's and
the early 70's comes of age as professionals.
<p>
   In a big clue to who's looking forward, Frederic de Bernard, the
fair's North American agent, observed that the American students
were the only group that showed computer desks for home offices
among the 1,000 exhibitors in seven halls.
<p>
   ``As we pulled pieces out of the crates, the French were like,
`Wow, what is that?' '' said David Mocarski, a faculty member from
the Art Center College of Design in Pasadena, Calif., four of whose
students were exhibiting.
<p>
   Mocarski's students showed a coffee table made of carbon fiber,
a material that originated in the aerospace industry; two
home-office computer desks, and a bar stool called Lenny, based on
an anatomical sketch by Leonardo da Vinci, with a seat that rested
on a spine instead of legs.
<p>
   ``Students are rethinking the home in terms of their own life
style,'' said Richard Prisco, the chairman of the furniture
department at the Savannah (Ga.) College of Art and Design, another
participating school. ``Generation X, the new professionals, just
out of college, changing jobs every couple of years, people who are
on the move. They're addressing furniture to their peers  &MD; 
collapsible, lightweight, high-end design with inexpensive,
recycled materials. These students are making smaller work, not
large things like sofas that would be impossible to move.''
<p>
   The idea of inviting the Americans originated with Beth
Dickstein in New York, a design consultant to manufacturers. Ms.
Dickstein suggested it at last year's Paris fair, which featured a
section of French design students' work. The organizers donated
space for the Americans to exhibit alongside the French students,
and they approached 25 American schools, four of which were finally
invited. The Pasadena and Savannah schools were joined by the Rhode
Island School of Design in Providence and Pratt Institute in
Brooklyn.
<p>
   What no one predicted was that the students, both American and
French, would walk away with the show.
<p>
   ``We had fairgoers tell us that the student portion of the show
was the whole reason for coming, that it was the only place where
something fresh was happening,'' said Patricia Oliver, the
chairwoman of the environmental design department at the Art Center
College of Design.
<p>
   What do students know that professionals don't? In particular,
what can Americans teach the French about design?
<p>
   The students and their teachers agreed that the picture of life
at home is changing in the late 20th century, but that home
furnishings are not  &MD;  or at least not fast enough. Though
television sets are becoming computers that are becoming chat
rooms, for example, armoires continue to hide television sets in
living rooms. But this generation of design students seems
determined to redefine living spaces and to reorganize the rooms of
the average house. America lives on the edge of these life-style
changes: where it leads, the world will follow.
<p>
   ``We're still holding on to the ceremonial home  &MD;  the living
room, the dining room,'' said Peter Benarcik, a master's candidate
in environmental design at the Art Center and the creator of the
Lenny stool. ``Do we need these rooms?''
<p>
   Like many of the students, Benarcik cited the computer and its
integration with home entertainment systems as the key element in
finally forcing the home to change physically. ``You can give it a
face lift  &MD;  the typical Eurodesign approach, when you paint the
appliance out with matte black and put some metal on it  &MD;  or you
can give it a new esthetic so it's no longer this thing against the
wall,'' Benarcik said. ``Maybe instead of working at home on the
dining room table, the computer is the dining room table, and
everything is housed underneath it, and you're fed information the
way you're fed off of a plate.''
<p>
   The biggest cross-cultural shock at the fair was that the
American students were concerned with substance, not style  &MD;  not
reinventing the wheel but building new vehicles.
<p>
   Speaking of the French students' work, Thomas Goldstein, a
recent Pratt graduate, said: ``It was things I've seen before. I
think that's the state of French design  &MD;  it's very beautiful, very
stylish, but maybe a bit conservative.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (MORE)
