NYT-01-22-97 1646EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0412 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=l pri=u sel=taf-z> A9309 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-U.S.-DESIGN-STU </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0590 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PARIS-U.S.-DESIGN-STUDENTS-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: bit conservative.'' &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Bruce Tharp, a recent graduate of the Pratt master's program,
showed a genre-bending item titled Precious Box, a bubinga wood
cube on polished aluminum legs that is a reliquary for the home. It
contained velvet pouches for what Tharp calls ``ordinary
treasures''  &MD;  ticket stubs, love letters, seashells.
<p>
   Tomoko Hayakawa, a master's candidate in industrial design at
Pratt, showed a towering room partition, more totem than screen.
Composed of paper stretched on aluminum frames, it is meant to be
the focus of a room rather than a divider. Each diamond-shaped
opening with its sculptural display is conceived as a window for
contemplation, something that will furnish the room with a unique
meaning for each member of a family. She calls her designs
``something-furniture'' and cites as inspiration a comment by Issey
Miyake, that clothes are ``tools for the wearer's creativity.''
<p>
   Julie Moringello, a graduate student at the Rhode Island School
of Design, showed her Emoticon Screen, a room divider with a
different kind of interface: its blue plastic panels suggest a
computer screen and are decorated with emoticons, faces composed of
keyboard letters and punctuation marks.
<p>
   Some of the American students showed multifunctional furniture,
a design trend that the industry is only beginning to acknowledge.
<p>
   ``The pressures of space are increasing,'' said Ms. Oliver, the
Art Center faculty member. ``Objects need to have storage potential
or the ability to define an open living space so that you can
section yourself off when you're using it from the rest of what's
going on in the room.''
<p>
   New technology was also front and center in the American
students' work. Joseph Perilla, a master's candidate in industrial
design at Pratt and a professional architectural model builder,
showed a plywood chair executed with current model-making
technology. The chair was designed with computer-aided design
software: Perilla's computer disk then guided a tooling machine's
laser in making the exacting decorative cuts in the thin surface of
the chair's plywood veneer.
<p>
   With dreams firmly in place, the American students are also
strongly interested in getting them to market: they may have
learned how in France. Ms. Moringello toured the Ligne Roset
factory near Paris and realized there that her unique designs were
not necessarily commercially improbable.
<p>
   ``European manufacturers can change their tooling; they can do
small runs of things,'' Ms. Moringello said. ``There's still work
that's done by hand, in combination with automatization.''
<p>
   Benarcik, the Art Center student, also admires the European
manufacturing system's ability to respond quickly to new design.
``We exhibited in Atlanta as students  &MD;  we had Herman Miller and
Knoll there, and these guys are talking about tens of thousands of
pieces in their run,'' he said. ``They can't afford to just try
something.''
<p>
   ``Each of us got offers in France,'' he added. ``Now we can say
to companies at home, `Are you willing to do this and match costs?'
''
<p>
   Mocarski said his students and their colleagues at other design
schools were poised for success. ``Manufacturers are looking for
new ideas right now, especially when you're dealing with something
like home offices, multifunctional furniture, markets that are
developing in a creative way,'' he said. ``These students are
stepping into this. So, much of what they do will be what you next
own.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1646EST
</TRAILER>
