<DOCID> nyt970122.0413 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=ttx-z> A9311 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-CAPSULE-REVIEWS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0675 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-VIDEO-CAPSULE-REVIEWS-TEX &QL; 
QUICK LOOKS AT `MANNY &AMP; LO,' `SPECIMEN,' `THE POMPATUS OF LOVE,'
OTHERS &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
By MICHAEL H. PRICE and TODD CAMP &QC; 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Following are mini-reviews of films newly released on videotape.
The ratings are on a 1-to-5 scale. 
<p>
   ``Manny &AMP; Lo''  &MD;  This is an artsy, disjointed but consistently
interesting comedy/drama about abandoned, adolescent sisters who
become fugitives from an abusive ``juvenile welfare'' system. The
kid actors (Scarlett Johansson and Aleksa Palladino) are very good,
and Mary Kay Place (as a helpful grown-up) is excellent.
Writer-director Lisa Krueger, however, has a difficult time keeping
her ambitious storytelling intentions in sharp perspective. R
(profanity, adult situations and themes). 2 1/2.
<p>
   ``Specimen:'' This by-the-numbers science-fiction thriller has
``Saved by the Bell'' star Mark Paul Goesselaar playing the
offspring of an alien impregnation experiment. It borrows heavily
from pictures like ``The Terminator'' and ``Firestarter,'' but some
decent effects and a professional look overall rescue it from
schlock status. R (profanity, adult situations, nudity,
particularly the behinds of naked alien guys). 3.
<p>
   ``The Pompatus of Love''  &MD;  This engaging romantic comedy should
have played theatrically. Funnier than ``The Brothers McMullen''
and also a little more reality-based, ``Pompatus'' takes its name
from an obscure Steve Miller Band lyric and stars Jon Cryer, Adrian
Pasdar, Tim Guinee and Adam Oliensis as 1990s guys trying to
survive in the world of relationships. R (harsh language, nudity,
sexual activity). 3.
<p>
   ``Absolutely Fabulous: The Last Shout''  &MD;  Just when you thought
it was safe to go shopping again, Patsy and Edina are back and
they're more fabulous than ever. The Brit bad girls return for one
last whirlwind adventure before Edina's daughter Sapphron gets
hitched. The gals travel from the slopes of Switzerland to the
shops on Savile Row. Series regulars Jennifer Saunders and Joanna
Lumley are joined by special guests Marianne Faithfull (as God) and
Christian LaCroix (as himself). PG-13 (rude language, depictions of
drinking and drug use). 4.
<p>
   ``John Carpenter's Escape From L.A.''  &MD;  This witty,
action-filled and essentially serious sequel to the 1982 hit
``Escape From New York'' finds Kurt Russell returning to play
heroic bad guy Snake Plisskin, at large in a hostile, ruined Los
Angeles of the near future. R (violence, harsh language, mature
themes) 3.
<p>
   ``Alaska''  &MD;  This superior wilderness adventure stars Thora
Birch and Vincent Kartheiser as heroic youngsters who run afoul of
a dangerous game-poacher (Charlton Heston). PG (mature themes,
violent action, scattered uncivil language). 3 1/2.
<p>
   ``Broken Arrow''  &MD;  John Travolta is in top form as a deranged
military officer who conspires to steal two nuclear warheads.
Samantha Mathis and Christian Slater are the heroic types who must
halt the menace. John Woo directs. R (violence, harsh language). 3.
<p>
   ``Chungking Express''  &MD;  Asian filmmaker Wong Kar Wei scores with
a bizarre fantasy about drug rip-offs and doomed romance. R (adult
situations, violence, language, drug references). 3.
<p>
   ``D3: The Mighty Ducks''  &MD;  In this third part of the Mighty Duck
series, Emilio Estevez returns as coach of the coolest ice-hockey
team ever, as the Mighty Ducks land in an intimidating new school.
PG (language, slapstick violence, mature themes). 2.
<p>
   ``Eddie''  &MD;  Whoopi Goldberg is better than the material in this
hackneyed tale of an unlikely person chosen to coach a big-time
basketball team. PG-13 (rude humor, language, mature themes). 2
1/2.
<p>
   ``Maybe ... Maybe Not''  &MD;  From Germany, this comedy of sexual
absurdities stars Til Schweiger as an incorrigible womanizer who,
when thrown out by his long-suffering girlfriend, accepts lodging
in the apartment of a gay acquaintance (Joachim Krol). Richly
observed satire, it is in German with English subtitles. R (sexual
activity, language, nudity). 3 1/2.
</TEXT>
