<SLUG> BC-BRADY-BOND-CLOSE-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0433 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BRADY-BOND-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EMERGING MARKET DEBT: PANAMA SOARS ON TOP SUB-INVESTMENT RATING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jill Hamburg &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Panamanian Brady bonds surged
almost 5 percent after Moody's Investors Service and Standard &AMP;
Poor's Corp. gave the bonds their highest sub-investment grade
ratings.
<p>
   Other Brady bonds ended the day little changed. The sale of $2
billion 20-year Argentine government bonds failed to lift Argentine
Brady securities. Benchmark floating-rate bonds ended the day 1/8
point lower at 89 5/8 bid and 89 7/8 offered.
<p>
   Slumping U.S. bonds weighed on the Brady market, as securities
firms struggled to sell $17.5 billion of two-year notes they bought
from the Treasury. U.S. 30-year, zero-coupon bonds back many Brady
bonds and account for much of their market value.
<p>
   Rating Panama's creditworthiness for the first time, Moody's
gave Panamanian international bonds ``Ba1,'' the top level for high
risk debt, while Standard &AMP; Poor's assigned Panama's debt a
parallel ``BB+'' rating.
<p>
   The companies cited a ``manageable'' debt burden and the
country's progress toward an open economy. The ratings come a year
after Panama and its creditors restructured defaulted bank debt,
restoring the nation's standing as a potential international
borrower.
<p>
   The ratings led investors to bet the bonds will appreciate, and
sparked a surge of buying, bringing the bonds' yield premium above
comparable U.S. bonds down to 250 basis points, from 296 basis
points last night.
<p>
   That will probably shrink further, to 175 basis points, said
Franklin Chalmers, a portfolio manager at Private Asset Management
in Panama City. ``We expects spreads to tighten, if the government
continues with the privatization program and structural and fiscal
reforms,'' he said.
<p>
   Panamanian interest-reduction Brady bonds rose 3.7 percent or
2.675 points to 75 1/8 bid and 75 5/8 offered. The past-due
interest bonds gained 4.8 percent, closing 4 points higher at 86.5
bid and 87 offered.
<p>
   ``There's still upside,'' said Stuart Parkinson, analyst at
Deutsche Bank AG in London.
<p>
   Brady bonds, named after former-U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady, were created as part of a debt relief and restructuring plan
for developing countries which defaulted on bank loans.
<p>
   Argentina, Brazil, Costa Rica, Dominican Republic, Ecuador,
Mexico, Panama, Uruguay, Venezuela, Bulgaria, Poland, Slovenia,
Jordan, Nigeria and the Philippines have all converted past-due
debts into Brady-type bonds.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
