<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-CONNECTICUT-UPDA </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0416 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-AT&AMP;T-CONNECTICUT-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AT&AMP;T TO OFFER LOCAL SERVICE IN CONNECTICUT NEXT MONTH (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Colleen McElroy &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds comment from SNET. Adds closing stock prices)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. said it will provide
local phone service in Connecticut starting in the second week of
February, challenging Southern New England Telephone Co.'s virtual
monopoly in the state.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T also said it will offer local calling in Illinois and
Michigan as well, by the end of March.
<p>
   Connecticut is the third local market that AT&AMP;T is entering,
after Rochester, New York, and Sacramento, California. AT&AMP;T buys
cdtime from local carriers in those markets at a discount and
resells it under its brand name.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T, the nation's largest long-distance carrier, hopes that
offering local calling will deter its customers from defecting to
competitors. The more services customers can get from a single
phone company, the less likely they are to switch, analysts say.
<p>
   ``We will be offering local and long-distance on one bill,''
said John Heath, a spokesman for New York-based AT&AMP;T. ``Customers
can pay with one check.''
<p>
   AT&AMP;T shares fell 1/2 to 38 7/8, while Southern New England
Telephone shares fell 3/4 to 37.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T said it initially will offer service to a small number of
customers Connecticut, as it tests billing and customer-service
operations, then expand statewide.
<p>
   Southern New England Telephone said AT&AMP;T is one of 17 companies
that have received Connecticut regulators' approval to offer local
service.
<p>
   ``Our aim is to continue to be the hometown phone company of
choice for Connecticut customers,'' said Ron Serrano, president of
SNET's communications, information and entertainment group.
<p>
   In Connecticut, AT&AMP;T gets a 25 percent discount for residential
telephone calls from Southern New England Telephone, and a 40
percent discount for business calls.
<p>
   In California, where it plans to expand statewide, AT&AMP;T gets
discounts of 17 percent for both business and residential calls.
Discounts are determined through state government regulators under
a new federal law that opens up local telephone markets.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T jumped into the local phone market in Rochester in January
1995. Several months later it stopped marketing the service, saying
it couldn't make a profit from the 5 percent discount it received
from Frontier Corp.'s Rochester Telephone unit.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1649EST
</TRAILER>
