<STORYID cat=l pri=u sel=taf-z> A9320 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ECART-FURNITURE-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0308 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ECART-FURNITURE-NYT &LR;  &QR; 
 &UR; PUTMAN TO LEAVE HER PARIS COMPANY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (kd) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ELAINE LOUIE &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Andree Putman, the French interior designer, is leaving Ecart
International, the company she founded in 1978 to reissue classics
of early 20th-century furniture design, said Michel Taurel,
development manager of Ecopar, the parent company of Ecart, which
is in Paris.
<p>
   ``It's an agreement between her and Ecopar,'' Taurel said by
telephone from Paris, ``because, you know, she is 70-and-something
old, and she is actually retiring from her activities at Ecart.''
<p>
   In New York, Ralph Pucci, whose company, Pucci International,
represents Ecart International in the United States, said, ``I
think she has gone off to explore other avenues.'' At Mrs. Putman's
office in Paris Wednesday, an assistant said she was out for the
evening and not reachable.
<p>
   During her reign as artistic director of Ecart, Mrs. Putman
produced an intensely personal collection of reproduction
furniture, nearly all of it elegant, timeless and overlooked in its
own era.
<p>
   She is widely credited with being one of the first to revive the
Art Deco style. She rediscovered and reproduced the sleek,
modernistic furniture designs of the architect Eileen Gray and
reissued a 1903 lamp by Mariano Fortuny, more famous for his
pleated fabrics, that she had seen at the Fortuny Museum in Venice.
<p>
   In Spain, she negotiated the rights to the voluptuous furniture
designs by Antonio Gaudi, the Spanish architect. In Manhattan, she
designed the interior of Morgans Hotel on Madison Avenue and
oversaw its lobby renovation last year.
<p>
   Ecart will continue to reissue designs and produce furniture
designed by Christophe Pillet, Taurel said, and will expand into
large-scale projects like the Deutsche Bank headquarters in
Berlin.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1649EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0419 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=ttj-z> A9321 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-ABORTION-RALLY-H </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0692 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ANTI-ABORTION-RALLY-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ANTI-ABORTION ACTIVISTS GATHER TO MARK ROE V. WADE ANNIVERSARY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By HOLLY YEAGER &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Hearst Newspapers &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  Tens of thousands of anti-abortion activists
gathered in Washington Wednesday, marching to the Supreme Court to
mark the anniversary of its landmark 1973 Roe v. Wade decision,
which made abortion legal.
<p>
   ``Our purpose today is to tell official Washington that they
must understand the humanity of each pre-born child at
fertilization,'' said Nellie J. Gray, president of the March for
Life Education and Defense Fund, which organized the annual event.
<p>
   Before their march to the high court, protesters rallied on a
muddy lawn between the White House and the Washington Monument.
Gray told them that 24 years after the Roe v. Wade decision,
``pro-life America is here to stay.''
<p>
   Tensions were high earlier in the day when police thought a
small explosion in downtown Washington had been directed at a
nearby Planned Parenthood clinic. Law enforcement officials said
later they did not believe the incident was linked to the clinic.
<p>
   Ann M. Adams of Burke, Va., who attended the rally with her
daughter and twin 2-1/2-year-old grandsons, said she was relieved
to learn that anti-abortion activists were not involved in the
explosion.
<p>
   Anti-abortion protests should be peaceful and legal, she said,
because, ``It's a violent thing that we're trying to combat.''
<p>
   A bombing at an Atlanta abortion clinic last Thursday that
injured six has drawn new attention to violence against abortion
providers.
<p>
   Vice President Al Gore, speaking Wednesday at a luncheon
sponsored by the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action
League, said the country would not tolerate those who carry out
such attacks.
<p>
   ``We will punish you to the full extent of the law,'' Gore said.
``We will not let you terrorize America's women or their doctors.
We will not let you deface our Constitution.''
<p>
   Speaking at the anti-abortion rally, Rep. Kenny Hulshof, R-Mo.,
disagreed with Gore's view of abortion rights, but agreed that
violence at clinics should not be tolerated. ``Just as we must
continue to pray for an end to violence outside those clinics, let
us continue to pray for an end to violence inside those clinics,''
he said.
<p>
   Vincent A. Ciappetta, a police officer from Cutchogue, N.Y.,
came to the rally with about 35 members of his Knights of Columbus
chapter.
<p>
   ``We have to make a statement for life,'' said Ciappetta, who
has started a group of anti-abortion law enforcement officials
called Cops for Life.
<p>
   Recalling that he attended a similar rally last year, Ciappetta
said, ``It's frustrating that things haven't changed, but things
will change.''
<p>
   Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, drew loud cheers when he told the
crowd that Congress would again approve a ban on so-called
``partial-birth'' abortions, a controversial type of late-term
abortion.
<p>
   Congress approved the ban last year, but President Clinton
vetoed the measure because it did not make exceptions in cases
where a mother's life was in danger.
<p>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi included the
measure Tuesday when he unveiled his list of top 10 legislative
goals, calling Clinton's veto of the ban ``a shameless act that we
must deal with.
<p>
   ``We are determined to do this, and we will do it earlier rather
than later in this first session,'' Lott said.
<p>
   DeWine said if lawmakers and anti-abortion activists ``do a good
enough job explaining to the American people what partial-birth
abortion really is ... public opinion will sweep this country and
even Bill Clinton will have to say `Yes, I will sign it.'''
<p>
   Eileen M. Salisbury, a 14-year-old from Shepherd, Mich.,
attended Clinton's second inaugural Monday, which she called ``a
really good experience, historically.''
<p>
   But she said she was more comfortable at Wednesday's event,
where she held a wood post supporting a banner that read,
``Michigan Loves Life. Protect the Unborn.''
<p>
   ``We know these people are fighting for our cause,'' Salisbury
said.
</TEXT>
