<DOCID> nyt970122.0420 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=w pri=s sel=tad-z> A9322 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-POLMONEY-HEARINGS-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0987 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-POLMONEY-HEARINGS-COX &QL; 
 &UR; SENATE HOPES TO AVOID PARTISANSHIP IN HEARINGS ON DNC FUND-RAISING
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; For release Saturday, Jan. 25.
<p>
    &UR; By KEN FOSKETT &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &QC;  &LR; 
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  With House Speaker Newt Gingrich's ethics saga now
over, Senate leaders are preparing public hearings into Democratic
fund-raising practices that could eclipse the intense publicity
surrounding the speaker's case.
<p>
   Hearings themselves are still a month or more away, but Senate
Republicans and Democrats have already begun jostling to define the
scope of the inquiry and set the tone for the politically charged
proceedings.
<p>
   Republicans are eager to keep them narrowly focused on how the
Democratic National Committee collected millions of dollars in
potentially illegal contributions from foreign interests, much of
it under the direction of former Commerce Department official and
DNC fund-raiser John Huang.
<p>
   Republican leaders are keen to know if the White House may have
provided any special favors in return for the donations, about $1.5
million of which the DNC has voluntarily returned.
<p>
   Democratic leaders want to keep the scope of the Senate
Governmental Affairs Committee hearings as broad as possible,
exhuming examples of improper donations among Republican
contributors as well.
<p>
   In letters made public Wednesday, Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., urged the committee chairman, Sen. Fred Thompson,
R-Tenn., to examine reports that top Republicans recently told
Business Roundtable members, composed of leading corporate
executives, to stop giving to Democrats or be denied access to
Republican congressional leaders.
<p>
   ``This ... provides compelling testimony for reform of a system
in which money appears to buy influence and access,'' Daschle
wrote.
<p>
   Both parties say they are anxious to avoid the intensely
partisan tone that dominated the Senate Banking Committee hearings
in the previous Congress into the Clintons' Whitewater dealings.
<p>
   The Senate fund-raising hearings will be scripted by Thompson,
the minority counsel for the Watergate hearings 20 years ago and a
politician often touted as a potential presidential candidate in
2000.
<p>
   Thompson has hired a half-dozen new committee staff members to
begin interviewing witnesses, collecting documents and issuing
subpoenas.
<p>
   He pledged Wednesday that the hearings would be ``balanced'' and
``broad in scope,'' but he made no promises that Democrats would be
given equal time to take the hearings in a direction of their
choosing.
<p>
   ``If you've got a problem area it ought to be looked at
regardless of which party,'' Thompson said. ``But there's no
affirmative action that will be applied in terms of percentages.''
<p>
   Paul Clark, Thompson's spokesman on the committee, said the
senator doesn't plan ``an aggressive, partisan investigation.''
<p>
   But such a feat in a town that thrives on scandal and in a
Congress riven with partisan divisions will require ``an almost
superhuman'' effort from Thompson, says Larry Makinson, deputy
director at the Center For Responsive Politics, a non-partisan
advocacy group for campaign finance reform.
<p>
   ``If this were truly a disinterested, bipartisan look, the
Republicans would begin to get slathered with a little bit of mud
themselves,'' says Makinson. ``No one is blameless in this
situation of fund-raising.
<p>
   ``The potential for embarrassment for both the Republican and
Democratic Party right now is sky-high. The temptation for people
on both sides to take off is probably going to be irresistible, so
I don't think it's going to sound like something put on by the
League of Women Voters, that's for sure.''
<p>
   Hearings that degenerate into ``partisan conflict'' will quickly
lose credibility among voters, said Whit Ayres, a Republican
pollster in Atlanta.
<p>
   ``Congressional hearings into the actions of a president from
the other party ... not only have to be fair, they have to be
perceived as fair,'' says Ayres. ``The demeanor and decisions and
tone of the chair are critically important.''
<p>
   One way Republicans are seeking to minimize the chances that the
hearings will backfire is to follow what Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., described in a recent news conference as a
``two-track'' approach.
<p>
   While Thompson's committee gathers evidence and lines up
witnesses out of the spotlight, Senate Republican leaders will be
pushing their legislative agenda on the Senate floor, Lott said.
<p>
   ``We have responsibilities that we have to face on behalf of the
people that elected us, and we're going to do that,'' Lott said.
<p>
   Republican leaders say they also plan to avoid long, drawn-out
hearings similar to the Whitewater hearings conducted by Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., which ended with no clear result and left
the impression that the sole purpose was to embarrass the
president.
<p>
   While there is still no timetable set for when the hearings will
begin or how long they will last, ``Thompson does not plan to have
this thing stretch out for the duration of the 105th Congress,''
Clark said. ``It's not going to happen.''
<p>
   Democrats, meanwhile, are preparing to ensure that whatever
unsavory details emerge from the hearings, they include Republican
wrongdoing as well.
<p>
   Daschle and other Democrats frequently cite the case of Simon
Fireman, a Boston businessman who paid a $6 million fine last year
for illegally channeling contributions to Bob Dole's failed
presidential campaign through a Hong Kong bank.
<p>
   ``I certainly hope that in the spirit with which you have heard
so many of us discuss these matters over the past several weeks
that Sen. Thompson will not limit the scope simply to Democratic
activities,'' Daschle said Wednesday. ``I expect Senator Thompson
to be much more fair-minded, much more open to other issues.''
</TEXT>
