<SLUG> BC-EARNS-STRATUS-COMPUTE </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0589 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-STRATUS-COMPUTER-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; STRATUS 4TH-QTR PROFIT RISES; CEO SEEKS REPLACEMENT (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Gerard Meuchner &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds investor comment and full-year earnings details.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Marlboro, Massachusetts, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Stratus Computer
Inc. said fourth-quarter profit jumped 26 percent on lower costs
and rising revenue, and that Chairman and founder Bill Foster plans
to step aside as chief executive.
<p>
   Net income rose to $17.7 million, or 74 cents a share, from
$14.1 million, or 60 cents, in the year-earlier period. Earnings
exceeded forecasts of 63 cents a share, the average estimate of 10
analysts polled by IBES International Inc.
<p>
   The earnings gain is a reassurance that Stratus is back on track
after two quarters of stalled revenue growth, investors said. The
company makes breakdown-resistant computers for banks and other
companies that need systems that don't crash.
<p>
   ``Those are a signs of acceleration, and acceptance in the
marketplace,'' said Alan Tingey, a money manager at Smoot, Miller,
Cheney &AMP; Co., a Salt Late City-based firm that owned almost 25,000
Stratus shares at the end of September.
<p>
   Stratus shares rose 2 1/8 to close at 31 7/8 with 452,300
changing hands, almost five times the three month daily average.
The shares are near the 52-week high of 32 1/8 reached June 12.
Revenue for the Marlboro, Massachusetts-based company rose 4.6
percent to $176.1 million from $168.4 million, after two quarters
in which revenue growth was unchanged from year-earlier levels.
<p>
   Results were improved by lower expenses for research and
development, compensation and other administrative functions. Those
expenses fell 11 percent in the fourth quarter to $57.3 million
from $64.5 million.
<p>
   Expenses relating to cutting back its sales operations in
certain markets reduced fourth-quarter earnings by 10 cents a
share, the company said. Stratus chose to pay for the cutback out
of expenses instead of taking a separate charge, said spokesman
Peter Christiana.
<p>
   The fourth-quarter results don't put to rest concern about the
company, Tingey said. ``I don't think the future of Stratus is
without its clouds,'' he said. ``The premium people are willing to
pay for (continuously available computers) has contracted over
time.''
<p>
   That will put pressure on profits if revenue growth doesn't keep
pace, Tingey said.
<p>
   In August, Stratus announced that Foster would resume the duties
of CEO after Gary Haroian resigned. Foster said at the time that he
and Haroian had a difference of opinion about the company's
direction.
<p>
   Now, Foster plans to step aside and hire a new CEO by the end of
the year. Foster said in a statement that after almost 17 years
running Stratus, ``the timing is good for a new CEO.''
<p>
   Foster's announcement of a CEO search isn't troublesome because
he will stay on as chairman, money manager Tingey said.
<p>
   For the year, Stratus said profit from operations rose to $47.1
million, or $1.98 a share, from 1995's profit from operations of
$36.8 million, or $1.55.
<p>
   Net income in 1996 more than doubled to $43.5 million, or $1.83
a share, including a pretax $4.6 million charge in the second
quarter for restructuring its software business.
<p>
   In 1995, Stratus had net income of $17.3 million, or 73 cents,
including a pretax $24.5 million charge for cutting cuts and
consolidating facilities.
<p>
   Sales rose 3.6 percent last year to $609.3 million from $587.9
million.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1652EST
</TRAILER>
