<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9326 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-FOOD-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0900 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FEA-FOOD-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; '97 FOOD PRICES COULD HOLD STEADY AFTER '96 RISE: U.S. OUTLOOK &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Roger Runningen &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 16 (Bloomberg) -- Consumer food prices in 1997
will hold steady or even retreat after surging last year at their
highest rate since 1990, analysts said.
<p>
   That could remove one of the inflation concerns that has been
troubling policymakers at the Federal Reserve. ``A slowing of the
increase in food prices'' this year could help offset a likely
increase in the underlying rate of inflation, Fed Gov. Laurence H.
Meyer said today in a speech to the Charlotte, North Carolina,
Economics Club.
<p>
   Grain prices have retreated from a surge last year that pushed
up retail prices for bread, milk, pork and other foods. With 1996
harvests refilling grain bins, there is enough corn, wheat and
soybeans to satisfy the strong worldwide demand that fed last
year's price increases.
<p>
   Moderate food price inflation is likely because the new farm
bill, ending 60 years of government controls on how much farmers
plant, increases the chances that the bumper 1996 harvest will be
repeated this year. ``We think the edge is off food price
inflation,'' said Vincent J. Malanga, who manages a $175 million
commodity fund as president of LaSalle Economics Inc., New York. He
figures food prices will climb 3 percent in 1997, after rising 3.3
percent in 1996.
<p>
   Bigger crops would help drive food prices lower, compared with
1996, on such consumer staples as milk, bread, cereals and chicken.
Pork and beef prices could rise from a year earlier on smaller
supplies. Food processors such as CPC International Inc., makers of
Mazola corn oil, could get a lift in profits as corn refining costs
ease.
<p>
   Of course, bad weather or rising energy or labor costs could
still force food prices higher in 1997. For now, though, analysts
see the chances improving for steady food prices.
<p>
   Officially, retail food prices are forecast to increase between
3 percent and 3.5 percent in 1997, according to the U.S.
Agriculture Department. That compares with a 3.3 percent increase
for all of 1996, calculated on a January-to-December basis.
<p>
   Last year's grain-price surge, the biggest since the early
1970s, caused U.S. food prices to exceed the overall inflation rate
for the first time since 1990. The cost of food makes up 16 percent
of the CPI. Not counting food and energy, the so-called core rate
of inflation last year was at 2.6 percent, tying the 1994 rate as
the lowest in three decades.
<p>
   ``We're not projecting any major price increases for 1997,''
said Annette Clauson, the USDA's food-inflation analyst, whose
projections are fed to the Federal Reserve Board before each
meeting on interest-rate policy.
<p>
   One big contributor to the benign food-price outlook is the new
farm bill, passed in April 1996, which makes 1997 the first year
since the Depression that farmers are free to plant any crop they
choose.
<p>
   ``It significantly changes programs in ways that will give
farmers more flexibility to respond to market conditions, and on
more acres,'' Malanga said.
<p>
   Grain prices soared in 1996 because of record numbers of
livestock at home and a boom in exports, triggered in part by
growing wealth in Asian economies and a corresponding demand for
improved diets of meat, milk and other staples.
<p>
   Now, farmers, lured by the high prices of 1996, are likely to
plant fence-to-fence this spring, resulting in greater supplies of
wheat, corn, and soybeans, says food and agribusiness consultant
John Urbanchuk. Traders in commodity markets have pushed corn
prices down 25 percent from a year ago, to about $2.74 a bushel.
<p>
   Larger supplies at lower prices will help moderate the price
outlook for everything from breads, cereals and bakery goods to
meat, milk and eggs. For example, milk prices, which rose 7 percent
in 1996, are forecast to rise a more moderate 2 percent to 2.5
percent increase this year, according to USDA. Poultry producers,
who can increase production by hatching more chicks faster than
beef producers can breed new calves, are forecast to boost turkey
and broiler production by 5 percent to take advantage of cheaper
feed.
<p>
   ``You're looking at relatively benign food-price inflation in
1997,'' said Urbanchuk, of AUS Consultants, Moorestown, New Jersey.
He figures food prices in 1997 will rise 2.5 percent to 3.0
percent. Beef prices could rise 1 to 2 percent in 1997, after
posting a 1.6 percent price decline in 1996. Prices fell last year
because ranchers, facing high feed costs, sold off herds and
created an artificial beef glut. Now, with grain prices weaker,
farmers are likely to concentrate on rebuilding herds, and beef
won't be as plentiful in the supermarket.
<p>
   ``When you rebuild the herd, this reduces supplies for
slaughter,'' said Donald Ratacjzak, head of the economic
forecasting center at Georgia State University in Atlanta.
<p>
   Of course, all bets are off if bad weather dogs farmers during
the spring planting season, or if drought, floods or an early frost
slash harvests this fall.
<p>
   USDA's food-price forecasts, and those of private economists,
are based on assumptions of ``normal'' weather. It wouldn't take
much of a swing in weather conditions ``to gyrate those food
prices,'' said Sung Won Sohn, chief economist at Norwest Corp.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1653EST
</TRAILER>
