<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9329 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-US-UPDATE2-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1036 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ECONOMY-US-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. ECONOMY: '96 HOUSING STARTS STRONGEST IN 8 YEARS (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Vincent Del Giudice and Marthe Fourcade &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Rewrites lead; moves Toll Brothers Inc. reaction to third
paragraph; adds closing markets to eighth and ninth paragraphs.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Home construction in the U.S.
enjoyed a banner year in 1996, posting the strongest gain in eight
years, while the overall economy was running at a healthy pace as
the new year dawned, new reports showed today.
<p>
   Starts of new houses last year rose 8.8 percent to 1.474
million, the highest level since 1988, the Commerce Department
said. The increase was fueled by a dip in 30-year fixed mortgage
interest rates below 7 percent early in the year and a pickup in
economic activity in the fourth quarter.
<p>
   ``We have relatively stable interest rates, and the highest
housing affordability in a long time,'' said Joel Rassman, chief
financial officer for Toll Brothers Inc., a Huntington Valley,
Pennsylvania, company that builds houses in 13 Eastern states.
Still, snow, floods and mudslides in the West depressed housing
construction in December.
<p>
   As 1997 begins, the housing market -- and the overall economy --
seem poised to remain vigorous, even if housing construction
doesn't match last year's pace. ``Economic growth in December and
early January was moderate in most parts of the country,''
according to a regional economic survey released today by the
Federal Reserve.
<p>
   Though the Fed, always on guard for inflation, found ``scattered
evidence'' of pressure building for higher wages, the central bank
still found no evidence of accelerating consumer prices except for
energy costs.
<p>
   Analysts and investors viewed the reports as further signs the
Fed can leave interest rates unchanged at the next meeting of the
policymaking Federal Open Market Committee Feb. 4-5.
<p>
   The Fed report is likely to be ``comforting'' for investors,
said James Padinha, an economist at MMS International in San
Francisco, because it doesn't point to wage pressures or other
worrisome signs of inflation.
<p>
   In financial markets, though, the benchmark 30-year Treasury
bond slumped after the government's auction of about $17 billion in
two-year notes. The bond fell 1/2 point in late New York trading,
pushing up the yield more than 4 basis points to 6.82 percent.
<p>
   Stocks, meantime, were mixed. The Dow Jones Industrial Average
fell 33.87 points on weak earnings reports to close at 6850.03. The
Nasdaq Composite Index, though, rose 11 points to close at a record
1388.04. The dollar, meantime, was higher against other major
currencies.
<p>
   Builders and analysts said the unexpectedly large 12.2 percent
decline in December starts, following a revised 9.3 percent
increase in November, doesn't mean the bottom has fallen out of the
housing market.
<p>
   High levels of consumer confidence and job creation, plus rising
incomes and still-low mortgage rates, lead builders to expect a
strong year, though few expect this year's level of starts to top
1996.
<p>
   ``I'm rather optimistic about 1997 now that it's arrived --much
more optimistic than I was six or seven months ago,'' said Robert
Strudler, chief executive officer of U.S. Home Corp. in Houston.
Added Leonard Miller, chairman of Miami-based Lennar Corp.: ``You
see no major buildup of inventories in the industry.''
<p>
   In December, alone, all regions of the country reported a drop
in new starts as the monthly rate fell to 1.329 million, adjusted
for seasonal variations -- the lowest since June 1995, according to
the Commerce Department. The flood-ravaged West was especially hard
hit. Analysts had expected a 2.8 percent decline for December
instead of the 12.2 percent drop reported.
<p>
   Meanwhile, permits for new housing construction fell 0.6 percent
nationwide in December to an annual rate of 1.410 million, rate
after increasing 4.1 percent in November, the Commerce Department
said.
<p>
   By category, single-family housing construction dropped 11.8
percent during December while multi-family projects declined 13.6
percent from a month earlier.
<p>
   By region last month, housing starts plunged 29.2 percent in the
West to a rate of 257,000; dropped 7.9 percent in the Midwest to
302,000; fell 7.2 percent in the South to 645,000; and declined 2.3
percent in the Northeast to 125,000.
<p>
   Though bad weather played a role in December's showing, that's
not entirely unexpected since home building usually ``winds down in
the winter months'' said Scott Brown, an economist at Raymond James
&AMP; Associates in St. Petersburg, Florida. ``We're going to see a
pickup in housing starts when the weather clears,'' said Carl
Palash, chief economist at MCM MoneyWatch in New York.
<p>
   And with mortgage rates still at historically low levels, starts
``should be relatively robust'' in 1997, perhaps reaching a total
of 1.38 million, Brown said.
<p>
   At Dallas-based Centex Corp., one of the nation's largest home
builders and mortgage originators, spokeswoman Sheila Gallagher
said by the end of the company's fiscal year in March, Centex will
have built and delivered about 12,500 new homes, but that the total
will likely drop to 12,000 for the fiscal year ending March 1998.
<p>
   After marching higher over several months, the average rate on a
30-year fixed loan fell to 7.60 percent in December from 7.62
percent in November, according to Bloomberg analytics.
<p>
   That put the average principal and interest payment on a
$100,000 loan at $706.07 last month, down from $707.45 a month
before. Those figures don't include tax, fire insurance or escrow
costs.
<p>
   In the most recent week, the average 30-year mortgage rate rose
2 basis points to 7.87 percent.
<p>
   The next move in home construction -- and sales -- will be
plainly evident when the weather turns milder in a few months.
<p>
   ``The real question is when does the consumer decide that the
time (to buy) is now,'' said Ira Norris, president of INCO Homes in
Upland, California. `I think people need to believe that housing
prices are on the rise before they buy, and right now the urgency
is not there.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1655EST
</TRAILER>
