<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-REPUBLIC-INDUSTRIES-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; REPUBLIC INDUSTRIES TO BUY FLORIDA DEALER FOR $35 MLN (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Adam Levy &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds closing stock price. Adds Merrill Lynch recommendation and
price targets)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Fort Lauderdale, Florida, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Republic
Industries Inc. said it acquired Carlisle Motors in Florida for $35
million in stock, the latest in a flurry of car dealership
acquisitions by billionaire H. Wayne Huizenga's holding company.
<p>
   Carlisle operates three new and used automobile dealerships,
including the nation's fourth-largest Lincoln-Mercury dealer. Based
in St. Petersburg, Florida, Carlisle owns Lincoln-Mercury, Ford and
Hyundai dealerships in St. Petersburg and Clearwater, Florida.
<p>
   For Republic, Carlisle is the 15th such acquisition announced
since last summer, part of the company's aggressive plan to
complement and support its fledgling chain of haggle-free,
high-service dealerships, AutoNation USA.
<p>
   Republic has also agreed to buy two of the nation's five biggest
car rental agencies -- National Car rental System and Alamo
Rent-A-Car -- for a total of $3 billion in stock and debt.
<p>
   More acquisitions are certain, the company said.
<p>
   ``Our new association with Republic and AutoNation USA provides
us with opportunities to expand our business in the new and used
car marketplace,'' said Scott Wilkerson, president of Carlisle, who
will head Republic's efforts to grow in the Tampa Bay area.
<p>
   Shares of Republic closed at 41 1/8, up 1, a record high. The
stock has more than tripled since February.
<p>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. today rated Republic stock ``accumulate''
for the near-term and ``buy'' for the long-term. Analysts forecast
the stock to increase to a range between 43 and 47 a share in the
next 12 months.
<p>
   Republic has opened seven AutoNation superstores in Florida,
Arizona, Michigan, Texas and California, and plans to have 90 by
2000.
<p>
   New car dealers provide AutoNation with yet another source of
vehicles through trade-ins, the company said, adding that it
further rounds out the company's ambitious plan to grab a slice of
the giant automobile business.
<p>
   Republic is Huizenga's latest venture. He twice made himself a
billionaire, co-founding Waste Management Inc., now called WMX
Technologies Inc., and later founding Blockbuster Entertainment
Corp., which is now a unit of Viacom Inc.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1656EST
</TRAILER>
