<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0425 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9331 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-COMERICA-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0639 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COMERICA-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMERICA TO CUT 14% OF JOBS, CLOSE BRANCHES (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Joseph A. Giannone and Michael Smith &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds comments from chairman, adds closing stock price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Detroit, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Comerica Inc. said it will cut
1,890 jobs, or 14 percent of its workforce, and close branches to
cut costs, boost profits and avoid a potential takeover.
<p>
   The Detroit-based bank took a $90 million charge against
fourth-quarter earnings to pay for the job cuts and other
restructuring moves. Comerica doesn't know how exactly how many
people will be fired, said bank spokesman Wayne Mielke.
<p>
   The bank said it's taking other measures to boost revenue by
$110 million a year. It's part of a strategy to convince investors
that the bank -- often cited by analysts as a likely takeover
target -- should remain independent.
<p>
   If Comerica doesn't cut costs, ``someone else will (cut) them
for us,'' said Chairman and Chief Executive Eugene Miller. ``And I
mean being taken over.''
<p>
   Comerica joins Keycorp, First of America Corp. and Signet
Banking Corp. among banks that are restructuring under pressure
from investors to boost profits by cutting costs. The moves makes
the bank less attractive to acquirers, analysts said, because
there's less waste to trim.
<p>
   ``Sounds like they heard footsteps,'' said James Schmidt, a
portfolio manager at John Hancock Funds, which owns 552,800 shares.
<p>
   The bank plans to cut jobs across all its businesses, as it
implements 1,800 suggestions culled from employees since September
on how to save money and operate more efficiently. Changes range
from reducing the number of people needed to approve a loan, to
saving $1 million a year by using fewer kinds of envelopes.
<p>
   The bank was advised by Chandrika Tandon's New York-based
consulting firm Tandon Capital Associates, which built a reputation
for slashing payrolls at other banks.
<p>
   Fleet Financial Corp., Chase Manhattan Corp., Michigan National
Bank, and Midlantic Bancorp all hired Tandon to devise ways to
boost profits at least in part by firing workers.
<p>
   Tandon organized four months of meetings, getting suggestions on
how to save money from 5,000 Comerica employees, ranging from
tellers to Miller. The bank's senior executives then decided which
ideas to implement.
<p>
   Miller said it wasn't difficult convincing his employees to come
up with ideas that may cost them their job in the end. ``We tried
to explain the rationale, that if we're going to grow the company
we have to do these things.''
<p>
   Comerica announced the steps as it reported fourth-quarter
profit from operations rose 14 percent to $121 million, or $1.06 a
share -- a penny shy of Wall Street expectations.
<p>
   Comerica shares were unchanged at 56 1/4 in trading of 452,000
shares, not quite twice its daily average volume.
<p>
   In its earnings report, Comerica said net interest income rose
3.6 percent to $353.3 million as loans outstanding increased 4.7
percent to an average of $25.5 billion in the quarter. The net
interest margin widened to 4.61 percent from 4.31 percent.
<p>
   Overall credit quality improved, as the bank reduced by 3
percent to $32 million the amount it set aside for future loan
losses while net write-offs fell 38 percent to $22.3 million.
<p>
   Total noninterest income fell 5.8 percent to $132.4 million,
amid declines in broker fees and revolving credit fees.
<p>
   Noninterest expense rose 24 percent to $356.2 million. Excluding
the restructuring charge, expenses fell 7.7 percent.
<p>
   For full year 1996, net income rose 0.9 percent to $417.2
million, or $3.55 a share, from $413.4 million, or $3.54, in 1995.
Comerica, which has $34 billion in assets, operates about 365
branches in Michigan, California, Texas and Florida.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1658EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0426 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9333 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-US-BONDS-CLOSE-REPEAT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0895 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-BONDS-CLOSE-REPEAT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. BONDS FALL AS TRADERS SEEK BUYERS FOR 2-YR NOTES (REPEAT) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Dave Liedtk &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds dropped word ``the'' in quote in third paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. bonds fell as Wall Street
firms struggled to sell the $17.5 billion of two-year notes they
bought from the Treasury and prepared for another auction tomorrow.
<p>
   The Treasury sold its notes at a yield of 5.984 percent, less
than the 6 percent yield traders anticipated just before the sale.
The issue recently yielded 6.01 percent.
<p>
   The lower-than-expected yield at the sale ``doesn't mean the
auction went well,'' because securities firms can't sell the bonds
for as much as they paid the government for them, said Mark
Sauvigne, a trader at Chase Securities Inc. Making the sale more
difficult is the Treasury's sale of $12.5 billion of five-year
notes tomorrow.
<p>
   The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond, little changed prior to the
1 p.m. Eastern time sale, slumped 1/2 point, or $5 per $1,000 bond,
pushing its yield up 3 basis points to 6.81 percent.
<p>
   Securities firms had an easier time finding buyers for the $2
billion of 20-year global bonds Argentina sold today, as investors
hungry for higher yields snapped up the securities.
<p>
   The country sold the bonds at a yield of 11.375 percent, or
462.5 basis points more than U.S. government debt. That's better
than the 500 basis point difference underwriters expected less than
a week ago. Global bonds are sold simultaneously around the world
and trade 24-hours a day.
<p>
   Bond investors, faced with low yields and high prices in many
other parts of the world, ``have got to buy high-yield and emerging
markets debt,'' said Carl Ericson, head of $6 billion in taxable
fixed income at Colonial Advisory Services in Boston. Argentina has
``to make hay while the sun shines.''
<p>
   Investors looked past government reports showing a drop in new
home starts and moderate economic growth as they fretted about
demand for all the new Treasury debt.
<p>
   With all the supply, ``people have got a pretty bearish
viewpoint right now,'' said David Hoffman, who manages $300 million
in bonds at Brandywine Asset Management in Wilmington, Delaware.
<p>
   Wall Street firms often push yields higher before the Treasury
sells debt to try to stir up demand from investors.
<p>
   ``The reaction to the two-year is burdened by the prospect of
more supply coming in the pipeline,'' said Tony Crescenzi, a trader
at Miller Tabak Hirsch &AMP; Co. ``Even with good results, the market
is not trading well off them,'' he said.
<p>
   Traders said comments from Federal Reserve Governor Susan
Phillips in a Market News interview also weighed on bonds earlier
in the day. Phillips suggested that the Fed might not wait for a
rise in the core consumer price index before boosting rates.
<p>
   ``Phillips' comments were extremely bearish. They lend support
to the believers who think that the Fed will still have to
tighten,'' or raise rates, said Todd Speiser, a trader at Aubrey G.
Lanston &AMP; Co.
<p>
   The Fed hasn't changed bank lending rates since January 1996,
when it cut the so-called federal funds target by a quarter of a
percentage point to 5.25 percent. The Fed's policy-making Federal
Open Market Committee next meets on Feb. 4-5.
<p>
   Earlier, bonds got a brief fillip after the government reported
a bigger-than-expected drop in December housing starts.
<p>
   The Commerce Department said housing starts fell by 12.2 percent
in December, after climbing a revised 9.3 percent the month before.
Analysts surveyed by Bloomberg News on average expected a decline
of 2.8 percent.
<p>
   Today's housing number adds to a body of evidence suggesting the
economy is growing with little inflation.
<p>
   ``By and large the numbers tell me the economy is not going
gangbusters and not falling off a cliff and that's what (Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan) said in his testimony,'' to the Senate
Budget Committee yesterday, said Robert Alley, who manages about
$2.5 billion at AIM Advisors Inc. in Houston.
<p>
   That should help temper concern that the Fed will soon raise
borrowing rates, some investors said.
<p>
   ``The Fed's likely to be on hold,'' said Alley, who's been
buying bonds lately as he receives cash in his fund. ``We're adding
bonds.''
<p>
   Investors got further evidence that the economy is growing and
jobs are being added at a non-inflationary pace from the Federal
Reserve's report on regional economic activity.
<p>
   While the Fed found ``scattered evidence'' that wages are rising
in its latest survey, the central bank found no evidence of
accelerating inflation, outside of energy prices.
<p>
   ``It more or less confirms the general impression that the
economy has picked up steam and that things are chugging along with
little threat of inflation,'' said Robert McGee, chief economist at
Tokai Bank.
<p>
   The Fed's regional outlook, commonly known as the beige book, is
based on anecdotal evidence of business conditions compiled by the
Fed's 12 district banks, and is published eight times each year.
The report will help form the basis for discussion on interest rate
targets at Fed's meeting next month.
<p>
   While release of the report had been set for 2 p.m. Eastern
time, it was inadvertently released ahead of schedule on the
Internet.
</TEXT>
