<SLUG> BC-CANADA-STOCKS-CLOSE-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1050 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CANADA-STOCKS-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CANADA STOCKS FALL, LED BY BARRICK, AS GOLD DROPS, YIELDS RISE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Toronto, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Canadian stocks fell, led by
gold issues, on declining bullion prices. Rising bond yields damped
demand for interest-sensitive stocks like BCE Inc. The Toronto
Stock Exchange Composite 300 index fell 17.28 points to 6058.70. It
has declined 1.5 percent since rising to a record 6138.80 on
Friday.
<p>
   Barrick Gold Corp. fell on concern that an accord won't be
reached with the Indonesian government on developing Bre-X Minerals
Ltd.'s gold-rich Busang property before a new 30-day deadline set
by Jakarta expires. ``The uncertainty about Busang is keeping a lid
on (gold) stocks,'' said Tony Popowich, a trader for Altamira
Investment Services Inc., which manages C$15 billion.
<p>
   Barrick fell C$0.60 to C$35.55, and Placer Dome declined C$0.70
to C$27.60. Bre-X rose C$0.05 to C$22.65 in late trading after
falling as much as C$1.
<p>
   The Indonesian government has ordered Barrick to make an
agreement with Bre-X and local interests to develop the Bre-X
discovery, said to be the richest gold find of the century. Placer
Dome has made a takeover bid of more than C$6 billion for Bre-X in
an effort to shut out Barrick.
<p>
   Placer was pushed lower after it said it will lay off 100
employees in Venezuela, or half its workforce there, because of
delays in reaching an accord with Corporacion Venezolana de Guayana
to develop the promising Las Cristinas gold mine.
<p>
   Rising bond yields, which raised concern that interest rates may
climb soon, also hurt utility and phone stocks, such as Teleglobe
Inc. and BCE Inc. Teleglobe fell C$1.70(US$1.27)to C$38.25, while
BCE declined C$0.35 to C$67.20.
<p>
   ``The market's had a nice run and when that happens at the same
time there's concern about interest rates, it's quite normal to
expect the market to correct,'' said Gerry Brockelsby, a partner at
Marquest Investment Counsel Inc. who manages assets of C$850
million.
<p>
   ``People think the interest-rate bogeyman is right around the
corner.''
<p>
   Higher interest rates raise corporate borrowing costs and lower
profits. The yield on Canada's 30-year bond, which is used as a
benchmark for corporate borrowers, jumped 4 basis points to 7.32
percent. Bullion Lower
Weaker bullion prices also hurt gold stocks as the producers'
profit outlook dimmed. Gold for next month delivery fell US$2.10 to
US$351.20 an ounce in New York amid lower demand from investors
because a surging U.S. dollar is making bullion more expensive to
buyers using other currencies. Gold is priced in U.S. dollars.
``You can't be comfortable with gold shares at US$350 prices,''
said Jim Muir, portfolio manager at AGF Trust Co., who manages
assets of C$100 million. Muir sold most of his gold-stock portfolio
just before shares began declining. The gold and precious minerals
group has fallen 11 percent since hitting a three-month high in
mid-November. TVX Gold Inc. fell C$0.15 to C$9.90, Euro-Nevada
Mining Corp. dropped C$0.65 to C$35.20 and Kinross Gold Corp.
slipped C$0.25 to C$9.20. Analysts surveyed by IBES International
expect TVX Gold to post a fourth-quarter profit of US$0.02 a share,
22.7 percent lower than they anticipated a month ago.
<p>
   Weaker crude prices sent the oil and gas group 1.39 percent
lower. Spot crude has fallen 3.5 percent this week because of
milder weather in the northeast U.S. and Canada.
<p>
   Talisman Energy Inc. fell C$1.30 to C$45.95, Petro-Canada
slipped C$0.70 to C$20.80, Renaissance Energy Ltd. declined C$0.95
to C$46.30, and Canadian Natural Resources Ltd. fell C$1.30 to
C$37.80.
<p>
   ``They're responding to the weaker commodity prices we've had
over the last few days,'' said Donald Whatley, an oil and gas
analyst at Bunting Warburg Inc.
<p>
   Decliners outpaced advancers 559 to 451, while 270 were
unchanged. On the broader TSE, 120.9 million shares traded above
the three-month daily average of 97.4 million.
<p>
   Air Canada was the most actively traded stock. It jumped C$0.70
to C$8 on 11.92 million shares after it slashed fares by up to 70
percent to more than 100 destinations worldwide. Its offer lasts
until Jan. 30 for travel until May 15.
<p>
   Its Class A shares rose C$0.75 to C$7.50 on 3.43 million shares.
<p>
   The Toronto 35 Index Participation Fund units fell C$0.10 to
C$31.95 on 7 million shares.
<p>
   Golden Rule Resources Ltd. rose C$1.20 to C$12.10 on 2.83
million shares after the company met with Bay St. analysts
yesterday to bring them update on their Stenpad gold concession in
western Ghana.
<p>
   CIBC Wood Gundy Securities Inc. rated the company a
``speculative buy'' at C$10.90, commenting that while the company's
work to date is preliminary, the results ``are quite spectacular.''
<p>
   Northern Telecom Ltd., which accounts for 2.7 percent of the TSE
300, tempered declines by rising C$1.70 to C$95.50.
<p>
   The company said it has signed a US$200-million contract to
supply equipment to Washington-based MCI Communications Corp., one
of the world's largest long-distance carriers.
<p>
   CNR rose C$1 to C$53, lifting the transport and environment
group 1.31 percent, after it posted better-than-expected
fourth-quarter results. CNR posted a profit of C$1.22 a share,
above the C$1.09 expected by seven analysts at IBES International
Inc.
<p>
   Analyst Fred Larkin at Bunting Warburg Inc. raised his 12-month
price target to C$60 from C$58. Analyst Joseph Leinwand at RBC
Dominion Securities Inc. set a one-year target of C$62.
<p>
   --Caroline Van Hasselt in Toronto (416) 364-7300/kd
