<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9337 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-MONEY-ON-NET-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1144 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FEA-MONEY-ON-NET-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; INTERNET MAY BE BOON TO COMPANIES GOING PUBLIC: MONEY ON THE NET &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Duncan Martell &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Repeating for those needing.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 16 (Bloomberg) -- Touch-It Inc. and its founder
Paul Wakefield are looking to Direct Stock Market Inc.'s Internet
service to help the company go public.
<p>
   Touch-It developed paper that changes color at different
temperatures, ideal for cups that reveal a message when filled with
coffee or soda. The company, born in Wakefield's Ogden, Utah,
garage, is ``just about profitable'' and had about half a million
dollars in revenue last year. While accomplishments for tiny
Touch-It, those results aren't likely to set Wall Street on fire or
snare a big-name underwriter like Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co. that's more
attuned to managing Lucent Technologies Inc.'s $3 billion IPO.
<p>
   That's where Direct Stock Market, Direct IPO Inc. and others
come in. These companies offer services ranging from an online
shopping mall, where investors can peruse information on startups
like Touch-It, to the hand-holding and assistance more typical of
an investment bank. Direct IPO, for example, will unveil its first
Internet direct public offering, or DPO, this month, after scouring
300 business plans.
<p>
   ``You can reach a lot more people on the Internet,'' Wakefield
said.
<p>
   Wakefield plans to start selling Touch-It shares next week
through what's known as a SCOR, or small corporate offering
registration, relying on a network of small brokers to push the
stock. A SCOR allows companies to raise as much as $1 million
within a 12-month period.
<p>
   He also plans to sign on with Direct Stock Market, which will
charge $500 a quarter to air Touch-It's prospectus on its Web site
and provide a link to Touch-It's own Internet site. The cost is a
fraction of the $400,000 a traditional underwriter might charge for
a $5 million IPO.
<p>
   ``The price is extremely reasonable,'' Wakefield said. ``The
Internet will fill a void in the offering. It expands the scope of
who you're actually talking to.''
<p>
   The visibility of companies like Direct Stock Market that assist
Internet DPOs follows Spring Street Brewing Co.'s highly publicized
offering last March. About a quarter of the brewer's shares were
sold to investors who saw information about it on the Internet.
<p>
   Andrew Klein, the company's founder, subsequently formed Wit
Capital Corp., which is seeking to let investors buy and sell
Nasdaq stocks on the Internet.
<p>
   Others, like Marina del Rey, California-based Direct IPO,
actually screen potential DPO candidates and take a 5 percent
equity stake in the ones they select. In return, the companies get
a Web-based public relations campaign, guidance and access to a
group of high-tech advisers Direct IPO has assembled.
<p>
   Direct IPO then hopes to hand off the company to a traditional
underwriter three years down the road for another stock sale and a
debut on the Nasdaq Stock Market or regional exchanges.
<p>
   So far, only about 25 to 30 companies have used the Internet
intensively as part of their offerings, raising less than $100
million, estimates John Perkins, chairman of the Small Business
Capital Access Association and former commissioner of securities in
Missouri.
<p>
   That's a speck compared with the record $49 billion initial
public offerings raised last year.
<p>
   Still, DPOs conducted in large part over the Internet are
raising new questions of regulatory oversight -- even though the
Securities and Exchange Commission gives its blessing to the
concept.
<p>
   ``If there is fraudulent trading activity on the World Wide Web
affecting U.S. investors, just like anywhere else, the SEC will
have jurisdiction,'' said Paula Jenson, deputy chief counsel of the
SEC's division of market regulation. ``With the new technology,
it's creating a lot of questions that have to be answered
quickly.''
<p>
   Also troubling to some is the lack of analyst coverage and the
ease with which investors can buy or sell an infrequently traded
stock -- known as liquidity.
<p>
   ``The issue of sponsorship, liquidity, follow-on research, all
of the things that are perceived to be givens in the normal
investment banking activities are potentially absent here,'' said
Dick Smith, equity syndicate manager for San Francisco investment
bank Montgomery Securities.
<p>
   Another company, InterBourse Ltd. is looking to alleviate the
liquidity problem by setting up a trading system for the stocks of
tiny companies that have gone public.
<p>
   Daniel Weaver, a finance professor at Marquette University and
one of InterBourse's founders, plans to charge companies about
$1,000 a month to list shares on the trading site.
<p>
   ``Anybody that wants to help a company go public and doesn't
have a good secondary market is doomed to failure,'' Weaver said,
because investors could be stuck with shares they can't sell.
<p>
   Direct Stock Market, based in Santa Monica, California, features
a handful of companies on its Web site that have been cleared by
regulatory agencies for selling stock.
<p>
   There's Interactive Products &AMP; Services Inc., which is seeking
to develop a hand-held cordless Internet appliance and a wireless
keyboard and mouse for the personal computer. It's aiming to raise
up to $5 million through what's known as a Regulation A filing,
another way companies can sell stock without using an underwriter.
<p>
   Adeptus Corp., of Tacoma, Washington, is selling 2,500 units of
400 shares each to raise $1 million to help finance the development
of a device that will analyze body fluids taken directly from a
patient.
<p>
   ``The only companies that would be using something like this are
the teeny-tiny companies that wouldn't be underwritten by anybody
you'd ever heard of,'' said Montgomery Securities' Smith.
<p>
   Still others view their efforts as a sort of public venture
capital, allowing individual investors to buy shares in young
companies that may be years away from producing earnings.
<p>
   ``We want to be the Kleiner Perkins of Internet offerings,''
said Michael Turpin, chairman of Direct IPO, referring to one of
the best-known venture capital firms in the U.S. that typically
makes its investments available only to wealthy investors.
<p>
   Direct IPO concedes that won't be easy.
<p>
   ``Our first deal is very, very important because it'll set our
reputation with the public, investors and in the media,'' said
President Mark Perlmutter.
<p>
   Though they're off to an ambitious start, DPOs on the Internet
aren't likely to garner interest and credibility until a couple of
the companies hit home runs and earn fat returns for the investors.
<p>
   ``None of us have quit our day jobs,'' said InterBourse's
Weaver.
Check 'em out:
http://www.directipo.com http://www.direct-stock-market.com
http://www.interbourse.com
</TEXT>
