<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-ASSOCIATES-U </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0661 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COMPUTER-ASSOCIATES-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMPUTER ASSOCIATES SHARES FALL ON EUROPEAN OUTLOOK (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Heather Green &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds closing stock price)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Islandia, New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Computer Associates
International Inc. shares fell 5.9 percent amid concern about
European sales.
<p>
   The third-largest software maker yesterday reported
third-quarter earnings slightly higher than analysts' estimates and
revenue in line with company forecasts. Computer Associates'
European sales, though, fell 21 percent, more than expected,
analysts said.
<p>
   Computer Associates shares fell 2 1/2 to 43 1/2 in trading of
11.9 million, making the stock among the most active in U.S.
trading. Earlier shares touched 42 1/2. The company released
yesterday the earnings statement after the close of U.S. markets.
<p>
   ``The European market was worse than expected,'' said Andrew
Roskill, an analyst at Smith Barney Inc.
<p>
   The Islandia, New York-based company warned last month of
disappointing sales as it switches to new products in Europe. It
will take one or two quarters to bring the European business up to
speed, Computer Associates said.
<p>
   The company, which makes software used to monitor computer
systems, has been shifting its focus to selling client-server
software that manages networks of computers and away from products
for large mainframe computers.
<p>
   Computer Associates said its European sales force hasn't been
aggressive enough in building the new business, resulting in
lower-than-expected revenue.
<p>
   The company also told analysts and investors in a conference
call last night that European sales were reduced by poor growth in
upgrading mainframe processing power, Roskill said. When companies
upgrade their mainframe processing power, they typically buy more
software from Computer Associates, he said.
<p>
   International Business Machines Corp. said last night its
fourth-quarter earnings failed to meet analysts' estimates, in
part, because of weak economies in Europe and slow sales of
workstations and mainframes.
<p>
   Computer Associates recorded profit from operations rose to
$284.7 million, or 75 cents a share, from net income of $227.2
million, or 60 cents, in the year-earlier quarter. Including a
charge of $598 million, or $1.57 a share, for the acquisition of
Cheyenne Software Inc., the company had a loss was $313.3 million,
or 86 cents a share.
<p>
   Revenue for the quarter ended Dec. 31 rose 5 percent to $1.05
billion from $1 billion.
<p>
   Wall Street expected the software maker to earn 74 cents a
share, excluding the charges, based on the average estimate of 13
analysts surveyed by IBES International Inc.
<p>
   Computer Associates said it's focusing on improving the training
of its salespeople in Europe. European customers have been slow in
changing from mainframe systems to client-servers, and its sales
people hadn't been persuasive enough in encouraging the switch, the
company said.
<p>
   Client-server systems overall are selling at a faster pace than
mainframes, as more companies use networks of high-powered computer
servers linked to personal computers.
<p>
   ``We see this as an opportunity to buy the stock,'' said Bruce
Raabe, an analyst at Collins &AMP; Co. The stock was reiterated a
``buy'' by analyst Sanjiv Hingorani at Furman Selz Inc. and
``outperform'' by Smith Barney's Roskill.
<p>
   The company said it expects that its revenue will be equally
split between client-server software and mainframe sales by the
middle of 1998.
<p>
   That's compared with 61 percent of revenue that came from
mainframe sales in the third quarter and 63 percent in the second
quarter.
<p>
   Mainframe sales for the quarter were $640 million, while
client-server sales were $371 million. International sales were
$409 million, down from $519 million in the year-earlier period,
Roskill said. U.S. sales in the third quarter accounted for $644
million.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1716EST
</TRAILER>
