<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=ttj-z> A9351 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0732 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BELICHICK AIN'T MUCH FUN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By RAY RATTO &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  If Bill Belichick really is hired to become the
next coach of the Raiders, we are all in for some rollicking good
times. This guy is a riot.
<p>
   Ask him about the Oakland rumor, and he says, ``All my focus
right now is on the Green Bay Packers.''
<p>
   Ask him about spending his five years as the head coach of the
Cleveland Browns and being the last man Art Modell abandoned on his
way to Baltimore, and he says, ``I'm only concentrating on beating
the Packers.''
<p>
   Ask him about whether he would like to be a head coach anywhere,
and he says ... well, you know.
<p>
   ``That's not what I'm here to talk about,'' the defensive
backfield coach of the New England Patriots said Tuesday. ``Not
last year, or next year, or 1983. I'm focusing all my energies on
beating the Packers.''
<p>
   See? You can't get this stuff on ``Evening At The Improv,'' or
``Def Comedy Jam.'' Only from Bill Belichick.
<p>
   The Belichick-Raider rumors have been floating for about a week
and have picked up intensity the last few days. Now it may well be
that he would not be a very good fit for Al Davis (and let's face
it, there aren't many of those anyway). But still it's out there,
and the world's media must be entertained while Bill Parcells
pretends he's not on his way to New York to resuscitate the Jets.
<p>
   So where better to go than the source?
<p>
   ``So Bill, did your last year in Cleveland teach you ...''
<p>
   ``Are you a different coach now after your experience in ... ''
<p>
   ``Did you ever think you'd get another opportunity to ... ''
<p>
   No matter. ``Right now what we're talking about is trying to
beat Green Bay.''
<p>
   Yeah, but ...
<p>
   ``You can throw out that hook, change bait and keep casting, but
it's not going to change,'' he said with a smile. ``Trust me on
this one ... Packers.''
<p>
   It is this kind of monomaniacal eye-on-the-prize behavior that
made him a successful aide to Parcells when the New York Giants
were vying with the 49ers for dominance. It is the same trait that
helped make his time in Cleveland so unpleasant, capped by the
graceless dismissal of quarterback and local icon Bernie Kosar.
<p>
   By the end, he ended up one of the scapegoats Modell was looking
for as he prepared to abandon Ohio for Maryland. Belichick was
fired over the phone, and had it not been for Parcells he might
still be out of the game. The Patriots' coaching staff is made up
almost entirely of men who either coached or played for Parcells in
New York, and Belichick was considered the brightest on the staff.
<p>
   One theory has it that Parcells, who brought back Belichick in
part to try to get him another head coaching spot, expected owner
Bob Kraft to hire Belichick as the new head coach when Parcells
leaves and is unhappy that is now regarded as unlikely.
<p>
   Parcells doesn't say, and Belichick, well, you know.
<p>
   But the notion he might become the next Raiders coach is not so
far-fetched. For one, the Raiders have managed to nobody's surprise
to be among the last teams to enter the Find-A-Coach pageant. For
two, Parcells and Davis talk relatively often. For three, Belichick
might well be a good coach; it wasn't as though he was overburdened
with talent or resources in Cleveland.
<p>
   In fact, most folks in Cleveland who prefer to dislike him point
to his people skills as a principal problem. Now we don't like to
make assumptions about people we've never met, unless of course
there is a possibility for amusement, but if Belichick is not a
great people guy the Raiders are eminently qualified to live with
that.
<p>
   Besides, if Dick Vermeil can take 15 years off to examine the
darker side of Brent Musburger and still get a job, why are there
flies on Belichick? Well, we're not quite sure. The Raiders aren't
talking (as though they ever do), and Belichick isn't either (as
though he would).
<p>
   So there you have it. Bill Belichick, possibly the new head
coach of your Oakland Raiders. A man with no apparent past or
future, heading into his third Super Bowl.
<p>
   Ah, but what will he say come Monday, when the Packers are no
longer on New England's schedule? ``All my concentration is focused
on our first minicamp,'' he will say. Now what did I tell you about
this guy? He's a total stitch.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1717EST
</TRAILER>
