<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tia-z> A9352 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MATTINGLY-RETIRES </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0957 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BBA-MATTINGLY-RETIRES-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FORMER YANKEE DON MATTINGLY RETIRES FROM BASEBALL (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Bob Bensch through the Princeton Sports Desk &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Rewrites. Adds comment from Mattingly and Yankees owner George
Steinbrenner.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Don Mattingly, the greatest New
York Yankee never to appear in a World Series, retired from
baseball.
<p>
   Mattingly, 35, has not played since 1995 and was plagued by back
problems his final few seasons that cut his production.
<p>
   A free agent after his last season, Mattingly didn't re-sign
with the Yankees and sat out in 1996 as New York won its first
World Series in 18 years.
<p>
   ``I'm proud of everything I've been able to accomplish here with
the Yankees,'' Mattingly said at a press conference at Yankee
Stadium. ``I look back with joy at the opportunities I had and with
no regrets.''
<p>
   He never formally retired, leaving open the possibility to a
return to New York or another major league team. Last season,
Mattingly received contract offers from three or four teams,
although he didn't accept any.
<p>
   ``One of the main words for me has always been loyalty,'' said
Mattingly, who was accompanied by his wife, Kim, and their three
sons. ``One thing I couldn't think of was the thought of myself
playing somewhere else.''
<p>
   He said he originally intended to return in 1997 until a week or
so after Thanksgiving, when he stopped working out.
<p>
   ``When I left it was open ended,'' he said. ``I guess I wasn't
really willing to pay the price to be successful. At that point I
knew it was time to step away and that's what I'm doing today.''
<p>
   A six-time All-Star, Mattingly hit .307 with 222 home runs and
1,099 runs batted in during his 13-year career. He won the 1984
American League batting title with a .343 average, edging out
teammate Dave Winfield on the final day of the season, and was
named the 1985 American League Most Valuable Player after hitting
.324 with 35 HR and 145 RBI.
<p>
   ``We've had greats here with the Yankees, but he's one of the
truly great,'' said Yankees owner George Steinbrenner.
<p>
   Mattingly burst upon the New York baseball scene in his first
full season of 1984. In addition to winning the batting crown, he
led the American League with 207 hits and 44 doubles.
<p>
   He topped those accomplishments the next season by winning the
Most Valuable Player Award, leading the major leagues with 145 RBI
and 48 doubles, and won his first Gold Glove Award.
<p>
   Those two seasons began a six-year stretch in which many
considered him the best player in baseball. From 1984-89, Mattingly
hit a combined .327 with 160 home runs and 684 RBI and was named to
the All-Star team each season.
<p>
   ``I never felt like I was as talented as other players,''
Mattingly said. ``I felt, though, that I was willing to do things
other players weren't willing to do.''
<p>
   He etched his name in the major league record book in 1987 by
belting six grand slams during the season and tied Dale Long's
31-year-old major league mark by hitting home runs in eight
straight games.
<p>
   His back problems began in the 1990 season when he missed 54
games, and his production also began to drop. Although his average
would still hover around .290, his power numbers fell. He averaged
just under 10 home runs and 64 RBI his final six seasons.
<p>
   In 1991, the Yankees named him the 10th captain in team history,
joining the likes of Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig and Thurman Munson. The
team hasn't named a replacement.
<p>
   For all the awards and accolades Mattingly collected, the World
Series eluded him.
<p>
   In his first 11 seasons, the Yankees only finished as high as
second place three times. He looked like he would finally get his
chance in 1994 when the Yankees had the best record in the American
League, although the strike ended the season early and caused the
cancellation of the postseason.
<p>
   Mattingly finally got a taste of postseason play in 1995 when
the Yankees won the first American League wild-card berth. He
shined during a five-game series loss to Seattle, hitting .417 with
one home run and tying for the team lead with six RBI. ]| Mattingly
said he felt that his whole career had been about timing. The
Yankees won their previous world championship in 1978, a year
before he signed with the team, and won their next one the year
after he left the game.
<p>
   ``It was a dual-edge sword from the standpoint of not being
here,'' Mattingly said when asked about the 1996 championship. ``It
was painful, but I was happy for the team.
<p>
   ``I told Kim a week after the series was over and everything
calmed down that I did the right thing and felt good about it.''
<p>
   A complete player, Mattingly was known for his fielding as well
as his hitting.
<p>
   He won nine Gold Glove Awards, most by an American League first
baseman, and led the league in fielding a record seven times.
<p>
   With just 68 errors in 15,462 career chances, his .996 fielding
percentage is the best of any position player in baseball history.
<p>
   While his offense may have suffered from an ailing back toward
the end of his career, his defense didn't. Mattingly set new team
records for fielding percentage for a first baseman in 1993 and
1994 at .998, committing just three errors the first year and just
two the second.
<p>
   Mattingly said he will now turn his attention to his family and
raising horses on his farm in his hometown of Evansville, Indiana.
He also said he would like to give something back to baseball.
<p>
   ``When I was playing, I didn't want to think about anything but
baseball,'' he said. ``I like to be able now to give back,
baseball-wise, to kids through clinics and teach.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1718EST
</TRAILER>
