<DOCID> nyt970122.0438 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=tth-z> A9353 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0868 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CURT FLOOD'S BATTLES WEREN'T FOUGHT FOR FREE LUNACY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ED NOTE: RESENDING TO FIX SPELLING OF LAST NAME OF JULIUS ERVING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURA VECSEY &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Seattle Post-Intelligencer &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SEATTLE  &MD;  In his time, Curt Flood was an original. A Gold Glove
center fielder with the St. Louis Cardinals, he was also a brooder
and a painter and an iconoclast whose active and nervous
intelligence drove him not only to question authority, but to blow
it up.
<p>
   Curt Flood took baseball to the wall.
<p>
   He took unfavorable and costly action against the people who
made up the rules.
<p>
   In 1969, Flood refused to report for duty after the Cardinals
traded him to the Phillies. Instead of accepting his fate, Flood
took his sense of outrage and injustice all the way to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
<p>
   He would not be treated like meat.
<p>
   As a 12-year veteran, he should have some say in what happened
to him.
<p>
   He fought a system that bound Mickey Mantle to the Yankees, Bob
Gibson to the Cardinals and Jackie Robinson to the Dodgers.
<p>
   Flood lost his case. But it is his undying legacy that his fight
enabled others after him to win.
<p>
   But what about this winning?
<p>
   What about the new world order in sports that Curt Flood
invented by calling himself a ``free agent?''
<p>
   We don't have Curt Floods in sports these days. Mostly because
we don't need them, or so it would seem.
<p>
   Today's battles are about the bottom line.
<p>
   Everyone's a star. Everyone's a corporation. Too many players
think they are as big if not bigger than the game, which is a
notion affirmed by their sneaker makers.
<p>
   Gary Payton and Ken Griffey Jr. and Andre Agassi are not only
bound to the NBA, Major League Baseball or the ATP, they are bound
to each other, as ``part of the Nike family.''
<p>
   These guys say these things. And mean it.
<p>
   Twenty-five years ago, Flood did all the dirty work for freedom
and the rights of an individual player to make their own deals,
their best deals.
<p>
   But now, it's 180 degrees wrong the other way.
<p>
   The time line from Curt Flood's righteous and right-on protest
down to Dennis Rodman's latest NBA suspension is filled with other
eruptions and episodes that have radically changed the climate in
which athletes labor.
<p>
   But certainly, a quarter century later, free agency has turned
into free lunacy.
<p>
   Now it's bad as you wanna be.
<p>
   Now it's rich rewards not for substance and convictions, but for
House of Style cameos and fishnet pants and tie-dyed hair that is
only half as mixed up as the stuff inside a Dennis Rodman cranium.
<p>
   Instead of Curt Flood, we get Dennis Rodman as the most
flamboyant symbol of our sporting era  &MD;  with Nike and Converse and
MTV willing to bank their profit margins on a guy who is mistakenly
marketed as the brave one, willing to live out his fantasies in
public.
<p>
   I have a fantasy, too. It's that Nike, Converse and MTV would
cut Rodman loose. Rodman unplugged. For his sake. For ours. So we
can concentrate on other players who are trying to do the right
thing, even though it's hard to figure that out.
<p>
   Sports can give us heroes and role models. Sports can give us
real revolutionaries, not just rebels without a clue.
<p>
   On NBC last Sunday, as the Rodman-less Bulls were getting
hammered by the Rockets, commentator and former NBA great Julius
Erving made a personal plea to Rodman, who was missing game No. 2
of an 11-game (maybe longer) suspension.
<p>
   Erving said one day, when Rodman is done with his career, either
through retirement or exile, he will regret that he never gave
anything back to the game.
<p>
   Erving's plea seemed just as naive as it was earnest.
<p>
   The very idea that Rodman should recognize his responsibility to
give something back to the game seems as far-fetched as his wedding
dress publicity stunts.
<p>
   Rodman, whose free agency landed him a one-year, $10 million
deal with the Bulls this season, is making the Forbes big money
list because he refuses to accept the larger responsibility that
most NBA players, and most athletes, eventually come to accept.
<p>
   Rodman is living proof that humans, unfortunately, need a few
checks and balances to keep things from exploding.
<p>
   ``We all have times of frustration when we want to retaliate,
but we know we can't,'' Michael Jordan said when asked for his take
on Rodman's groin-kicking of a courtside cameraman.
<p>
   Well, this week, when Curt Flood died of cancer, the world lost
a man who fought the good fight for a cause that was worthy of his
anger and frustration and worthy of retaliation.
<p>
   For that, Flood never got the chance to finish what he started.
His .296 career batting average, seven Gold Gloves and three
All-Star appearances had all the makings of a Hall of Fame career.
<p>
   But he traded it to make a stand.
<p>
   Rodman, a gifted athlete who has re-created the art of defense
and rebounding with his tireless effort, is about to trade his for
nothing except the right to be as bad as he wants to be, just
because he thinks he's the boldest sign of our times.
<p>
   Here's hoping history is not as kind to Dennis Rodman as it has
been and will be to Curt Flood.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1718EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0439 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9356 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGACY-REPEAT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1067 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CLINTON-LEGACY-REPEAT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HISTORY MAY RECORD CLINTON AS ANOTHER IKE (REPEAT) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Monroe W. Karmin &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Changes millenium to century in 4th paragraph)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- So it wasn't a great
inaugural speech. So historians don't believe Bill Clinton will
rank as a great president. So what? Clinton, as his second term
begins, stands a good chance of presiding over eight years of peace
and prosperity. What president wouldn't covet that record for his
place in history?
<p>
   ``A lot of presidents would say, 'May God bless me with that
record,''' said Norman Ornstein, a political science scholar at The
American Enterprise Institute, a Washington think tank.
<p>
   Clinton, in interviews, likened himself to Thomas Jefferson and
Theodore Roosevelt, presidents who led the country as it entered
previous centuries. The United States will enter its third century
in 2000, the final year of Clinton's presidency.
<p>
   However, Clinton's stewardship more closely resembles that of
Dwight Eisenhower. He, too, served two terms. He, too, steered the
country down the middle of the road. He, too, presided over peace
and relative prosperity. He, too, was much maligned during his time
in the White House.
<p>
   Yet Eisenhower's reputation is much higher today. If not
regarded as a ``great'' president, he's now rated as well above
average. His ranking has jumped from 22nd in the 1962 poll of
historians conducted by Arthur Schlesinger, the Harvard professor,
to among the top 10 more recently. ``Eisenhower is now seen as
having been a very useful president,'' said Stephen Hess, a
presidential scholar at The Brookings Institution, a Washington
think tank.
<p>
   Clinton could end up with a similar destiny, if the next four
years and history are kind. With luck as well as skill, the
president will have neither an international or domestic crisis to
deal with. There are no war clouds abroad and no recession, or
worse, immediately in sight at home.
<p>
   That benign outlook, strange as it may seem, is enough to
deprive Clinton of greatness. As he, himself, has said in
interviews, greatness tends to be bestowed on those presidents who
are faced with crises; be they George Washington who presided over
the founding of the country, or Abraham Lincoln who was confronted
by the slavery issue and the Civil War, or Franklin Roosevelt, who
had to cope with the Great Depression and World War II.
<p>
   Clinton's place in history, rather, will be determined by his
success, or lack of it, in attaining the goals he has set for his
second term. At the top of the president's agenda is reaching
agreement with congressional Republicans on a plan to balance the
budget by the year 2002.
<p>
   That may not seem to be such a big deal when compared with
winning wars and ending depressions. Yet, it could earn for Clinton
a place in the record books.
<p>
   The current economic expansion will be six years old this
spring. If it endures through Clinton's second term, it will
surpass the expansions of the 1980s and 1960s as the longest of the
post-World War II era. No small achievement.
<p>
   It's true most economists don't see that happening, with the
consensus predicting a recession in 1998 or 1999. Yet many
economists also agree that expansions don't inevitably die of old
age; rather, they come about because of unforeseen foreign crises
or policy mistakes by Clinton or others.
<p>
   In the current situation, most economists agree, one policy
mistake would be for Clinton to abandon his balanced budget goal,
which he so far shows no signs of doing. Abandoning the goal would
increase the pressure on the Federal Reserve to raise interest
rates to contain the inflationary effect of widening deficits.
<p>
   Another policy mistake, obviously, would be for the Fed to wait
too long to move against inflation even if the budget continues on
the road to balance. Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan shows no
inclination toward making that error. He told a congressional
committee this week that there are signs that the nation's tight
labor markets may be beginning to boost workers' pay increases
enough to cause inflation to pick up down the road. If that
happens, he indicated, the central bank will respond by raising
interest rates.
<p>
   Raising rates this year to head off an acceleration in
inflation, of course, would reduce the need to raise rates even
higher later on once inflation builds a head of steam. Early
action, moreover, would give the Fed flexibility to lower rates if
the economy slows too much going into 1998 and thus avert a
recession. If the Fed is skillful, ``we could see the economy
remain strong for quite a while,'' said AEI's Ornstein.
<p>
   For Clinton to make his contribution to the expansion's
longevity, he'll have to ignore the advice of the Schlesinger
historians, now presided over by Arthur Jr. ``Middle-roading may be
fine for campaigning, but it is a sure road to mediocrity in
governing,'' he wrote in a December ranking of presidents in the
New York Times. ``The middle of the road is not the vital center:
it is the dead center. Clinton would be wise to eschew it if he
wants to improve his ratings.''
<p>
   Clinton, however, has no choice but to travel down the middle of
the road; Congress is in Republican hands, after all. The
Republicans failed attempt at confrontation politics a year ago
certainly didn't advance the national agenda. Since his reelection,
the president has talked of the need for political cooperation and
giving voice to America's vital center.
<p>
   He did so again in his inaugural address. Noting that voters had
elected a Republican Congress and a Democratic president, Clinton
said: ``Surely they did not do this to advance the politics of
petty bickering and extreme partisanship they plainly deplore.''
<p>
   This week the president also played his opening card -- a
proposed $138 billion cut in Medicare expenditures over six years
-- in this year's battle of the budget. His formal budget will be
sent to Congress early next month, which will begin the political
painful process of trying to reduce the soaring costs of programs
that distribute benefits to people directly. If the
middle-of-the-road is Eisenhower terrain, then Clinton may find the
journey into history to have a rewarding destination -- a ``peace
and prosperity'' president, like Ike.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1720EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0440 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=ttj-z> A9357 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKER-COACH-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0872 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PACKER-COACH-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SHERM LEWIS SEARCHES FOR RESPECT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN CRUMPACKER &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  You are Sherm Lewis. You are the offensive
coordinator of the Green Bay Packers, have been for five years now.
Your offense led the NFL in scoring this season and produced the
league's most valuable player.
<p>
   You are 54 years old, yet you have coached at only three places
in all that time, at Michigan State, the 49ers and the Packers.
Your imprint is one of constancy in a vagabond profession.
<p>
   You want to rise a rung above your current job and become a head
coach. You know this is a good time to have such a hankering
because there are more openings for head coaching positions than
ever before. Or were. By Monday there will have been 11 openings
around the NFL.
<p>
   Are you considered for any one of them? You are not. You are not
happy, especially now that the openings are closing rapidly.
<p>
   ``If it happens, it happens,'' is your pragmatic reply. ``So
many of them close up before I get a chance to interview. What can
you do?'' You coach the Green Bay offense in Super Bowl XXXI on
Sunday against the New England Patriots is what you do. You hope
the right people notice the man with the trim mustache in the
coaching box at the Louisiana Superdome.
<p>
   ``My main objective is to win the Super Bowl and not get caught
up in this thing,'' you say with little conviction. ``If I win
enough of them, someone is going to recognize me.''
<p>
   Maybe not. When the St. Louis Rams reached into the broadcast
booth and snatched up Dick Vermiel as their new coach, it reduced
the available openings in the NFL to three: New Orleans, Oakland
and the New York Jets.
<p>
   You will not get the Jets' job. That has been promised to Bill
Parcells, the New England coach, as soon as the Super Bowl is over.
<p>
   You probably will not get the New England job. Word is Pete
Carroll, late the 49ers' defensive coordinator, is already putting
a staff together in advance of Parcells' departure.
<p>
   You probably will not get the Oakland job, either. Cold fish
Bill Belichick is the hot candidate for the Raiders as soon as he's
through being the Patriots' assistant head coach.
<p>
   That leaves the Saints, Sherm. A team that has never won a
playoff game. A team that Jim Mora abandoned in midseason in
disgust.
<p>
   ``It's a great opportunity,'' you say. ``You'd like to have any
job in the NFL. I'd just like an opportunity to sit down with
someone and express myself.''
<p>
   You have one problem, Sherm. A seemingly sensible rule is
preventing teams from officially contacting you. Four years ago the
Chicago Bears locked up Dave Wannstedt as their head coach while he
was still a member of Jimmy Johnson's Super Bowl staff in Dallas.
<p>
   Anticipating widespread duplicity, the league instigated a ``no
tampering'' rule in which teams could not officially contact a
coach on another staff until his season was over. Of course, there
is official contact and hey-how's-it-going contact.
<p>
   You know, then, that teams are taking the high ground with you
on this one, waving the rule in your face as if to say, ``Sorry,
Sherm. Rules are rules.'' ``I don't think it's fair,'' you say.
``If someone wanted me bad enough, they'd wait. It's not an excuse.
It's happened for the last 10 years now. If they want you, they'll
find some way to get in touch with you.''
<p>
   Your fight is not a lonely one. You have allies.
<p>
   ``Forget about Sherm Lewis,'' said Ronnie Lott, who was a 49er
when you were on the staff in San Francisco. ``We had 10 openings
this past year. Not one African American was a candidate for a job,
not one African American was hired. It's ludicrous. It's sad. It's
sickening. I'm somewhat appalled.''
<p>
   Oh, yes, when you look in the mirror, you see a face the result
of an African diaspora set in motion nearly 500 years ago. You do
not claim race is a factor in your not getting a head coaching job.
But you wonder, especially when you see Steve Mariucci hired to
coach the 49ers following an intensive search that lasted, oh,
about 20 minutes.
<p>
   You are not happy about that one. Neither is your boss, Packers
coach Mike Holmgren. You both spent years on that staff, working
for Bill Walsh and George Seifert.
<p>
   ``I was a little surprised they didn't wait to maybe talk to
Sherm,'' Holmgren said. ``Sherm Lewis is one of the fine coaches in
this league. I've had coaches on my staff now that are head coaches
in this league ... and there isn't one of those men any better than
Sherm Lewis.''
<p>
   So you continue to coach the Packers' offense while other men
are hired for jobs you would be interested in. You look at the
Super Bowl XXIII ring gaudy on your finger from your days as a San
Francisco assistant and consider one more injustice in life.
Because of your team's success, your professional growth is
stunted.
<p>
   ``If someone was really interested in me, they'd let me know,''
you say. ``I don't believe it would make a big difference between
this week and next.''
<p>
   You are Sherm Lewis and you wonder about the way things work.
Take apart the machine piece by piece and you might not like what
you see.
</TEXT>
