<SLUG> BC-FBC-MOTOR-CITY-BOWL-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0417 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBC-MOTOR-CITY-BOWL-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ORGANIZERS HOPE TO BRING BOWL GAME TO SILVERDOME THIS YEAR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Dan Bollerman &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Pontiac, Michigan, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- An organizing
committee wants to start a college football bowl game to be played
in the Pontiac Silverdome, raising the number of bowls sanctioned
by the NCAA to 19.
<p>
   Organizers of the Motor City Bowl hope to match the champion of
the Mid-American Conference with an at-large team on Dec. 26 at the
80,368-seat home of the NFL's Detroit Lions. The bowl would provide
only the second at-large berth in the bowl system, joining the
Independence Bowl.
<p>
   ``We were interested in getting a MAC team playing in the
Pontiac Silverdome for regional interest,'' said Ken Hoffman, a
representative of the Motor City Bowl Organizing Committee.
<p>
   The MAC champion has played the Big West Conference champion for
the last 16 years in a postseason bowl. The game has been played in
Las Vegas for the last five years, after 11 years as the California
Raisin Bowl.
<p>
   Tom Lessig, the MAC's director of communications, wouldn't
confirm the league's involvement in the game.
<p>
   Each participating team will receive at least $750,000, which is
the NCAA's minimum for bowl accreditation. Hoffman said the money
will be raised through ticket sales, corporate sponsorships,
broadcasting and licensing revenues, like any of the other bowl
games.
<p>
   Hoffman said that the game's title sponsor and television
package are in place, yet wouldn't be revealed until Jan. 30.
<p>
   The game still needs approval of the NCAA's Special Events
Committee and a waiver to be played this year. Approval won't be
granted until the committee meets in late April.
<p>
   The Silverdome tried hosting a bowl once before, yet the Cherry
Bowl failed in 1985 after two years. Hoffman says the Motor City
Bowl organizers have overcome obstacles that hampered the earlier
game. ``There were significant hurdles that the Cherry Bowl had to
overcome that we have taken care of,'' he said. ``There are some
things that we have been able to do.''
<p>
   The Silverdome will lose the Lions by 2005 after a new
70,000-seat domed football stadium is built in downtown Detroit as
part of a complex with a new open-air ballpark for Major League
Baseball's Detroit Tigers.
<p>
   ``That didn't enter into our thinking at all,'' Hoffman said.
``The Pontiac Silverdome certainly fills our need of a place to
play very well.''
</TEXT>
