<SLUG> BC-POLMONEY-WEB-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0363 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-POLMONEY-WEB-COX  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW WEB SITE LETS ANYONE TRACK INFLUENCE OF CAMPAIGN MONEY
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; By ANDREW ALEXANDER &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &QC;  &LR; 
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  Voters will be able to track how campaign funds
influence their representatives in Congress through a
first-of-its-kind Internet site being unveiled Thursday.
<p>
   Created by the non-partisan Center for Responsive Politics, a
campaign finance watchdog group, the site allows users to see how
much money a lawmaker received in political action committee (PAC)
contributions on dozens of issues, many of which are expected to be
debated by the new Congress.
<p>
   The World Wide Web address is: www.crp.org
<p>
   After accessing the site, users can click on a ``Cashing In''
headline that will let them narrow the search for contributions by
issue, state, an individual lawmaker's name or by political party.
<p>
   ``It's customized, so you can ask it to give you all the members
of your state delegation who voted on a particular issue, and it
will tell you how much money each one got,'' said Jay Youngclaus, a
spokesman for the group.
<p>
   ``We hope this will show more people what a large role money
plays in politics,'' he added. ``You'll see that large amounts of
money typically flow to one particular side of an issue, and that's
the side that usually wins.''
<p>
   The group tracked only money from PACs, which have become a
target of reformers who claim they give special-interest groups too
much influence in campaigns. Contributions from single contributors
were not included, Youngclaus said, in part because it is often
difficult to clearly identify an individual as being aligned with a
particular side of an issue.
<p>
   The group's site includes PAC contributions over the past two
years to House members, and PAC contributions for the past six
years for members of the Senate.
<p>
   It shows how the PAC money flowed to lawmakers on heavily
lobbied issues  &MD;  such as federal peanut subsidies or electricity
deregulation  &MD;  during the just-completed 104th Congress. Many of
these issues will be debated again by the new Congress that just
took office.
</TEXT>
