<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9361 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-BRINKER-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0880 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FEA-BRINKER-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BRINKER MAY SEE A FUTURE IN TAKEOUT MEALS: COMPANY SPOTLIGHT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Shannon Stevens &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Repeating for all needing.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Dallas, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- To thrive, a so-called concept
restaurant chain like Brinker International Inc. must do two
things: Jazz up its old restaurants and come up with ideas for new
ones.
<p>
   The Dallas-based company has spent the last few years trying to
turn around its 500 Chili Bar &AMP; Grill stores, a hot chain in the
late '80s and early '90s before diners got bored.
<p>
   Yet Brinker may stand a better chance with the new -- in this
case, a takeout store it calls Eatzi's, which caters to upscale
customers whose tastes range from exotic fare to comfort food. The
store is designed to grab business from supermarkets and other
chains like Boston Chicken Inc. and already shows promise: the
year-old prototype in suburban Dallas has monthly sales of $1
million on twice the expected volume.
<p>
   ``I have seen the future and it is Eatzi's,'' said NatWest
Securities Inc. analyst Damon Brundage.
<p>
   It may take nothing less than a vision of the future to bring
Brinker back. Brinker's earnings growth started slowing in 1994.
Then, in 1996, profit plunged 53 percent to $34 million from $73
million as the company took charges to close several Grady's
American Grill and Spageddies Italian Kitchen, two of Brinker's
newer chains. Investors have soured on the company, whose stock has
tumbled from a high of 33 in early 1994 and recently traded at
about 15.
<p>
   ``The history of Brinker is that a lot of its small, promising
restaurant concepts never live up to their potential,'' said Rajan
Chaudhry, editor of Chain Leader, a restaurant trade publication.
``They reach 15 or 20 restaurants and the wheels start coming
off.''
<p>
   Brinker is betting that Eatzi's is different and will ride a
major industry shift: slow growth for sit-down restaurants, while
the takeout business booms.
<p>
   ``We said to ourselves, `boy are we poorly positioned for an up
and coming trend,'' said Brinker Executive Vice President Lane
Cardwell.
<p>
   Much of Brinker's faith in Eatzi's hangs on the man behind the
idea, Phil Romano. Romano and partner and fellow restaurant-design
guru Rich Melman -- credited with creating some of Chicago's
snazziest restaurants -- own 50 percent of Eatzi's. Brinker owns
the rest.
<p>
   Romano is considered something of a genius in the restaurant
industry, best known as the developer of the Fuddruckers chain of
hamburger restaurants that prospered in the 1980s. Fuddruckers
thrived on a novelty: As customers entered, a glass wall revealed
workers grinding meat for burgers.
<p>
   The Fuddruckers fad didn't age well, though, and its results
have dragged down the earnings of parent Daka International Inc.
<p>
   While the Eatzi's experiment has done well, it still has a long
way to go.
<p>
   ``If they had 100 of them it could be a billion dollar
business,'' said Dean Witter analyst David Adelman. ``Or it could
fall on its face.''
<p>
   The key to Eatzi's isn't just the food, which is cooked to order
and ranges from fresh baked bread to gourmet tossed salads to meat
loaf with mashed potatoes or poached salmon with raspberry sauce
for $5 to $8 a meal. More important, perhaps, Eatzi's is about
atmosphere.
<p>
   Food is cooked in the open, refrigerators are stocked during
business hours and chefs pluck their ingredients off the store
shelves rather than from a refrigerator behind a counter. The
bustle gives the farmers-market-style shop the kind of buzz that
draws customers back for more.
<p>
   ``It's a remarkable concept,'' said Eatzi's regular William
Barker. ``We don't have any kids at home and cooking for two is
sometimes a chore. Our friends do the same thing -- they're middle-
to upper-middle class and willing to pay a little more.''
<p>
   Eatzi's customers are a demographer's dream, with household
income of $35,000 to $55,000 a year and more money than time to
spend.
<p>
   ``It's more of a lifestyle thing than an income thing,''
Cardwell said.
<p>
   There is a hitch. Because it appeals to a limited audience --
mostly single, young and prosperous -- Brinker believes Eatzi's
growth potential has its limits. Cardwell said he thinks the U.S.
can support about 100 stores. That's a far cry from the 1,300
stores operated by No. 1 grocery chain Kroger Co.
<p>
   Finding workers may be another problem. The store has 45 chefs,
each paid a minimum of $8 an hour and a job requirement that plenty
of cranky chefs can't cut: They're supposed to chat up customers,
describing how the meal is being prepared.
<p>
   Another challenge may be finding management with the skills to
run this meld of grocery store and restaurant.
<p>
   ``The execution is higher than a typical Chili's,'' said Marina
Carlson, a portfolio manager at Strong Capital Management, which
held 922,360 Brinker shares as of September.
<p>
   Yet, she thinks that Brinker can roll out Eatzi's ``pretty
broadly across the nation.'' Already the company is considering
stores in Houston and Chicago.
<p>
   It may just work, especially if Brinker duplicates the ambiance
of a relative's crowded kitchen during a holiday with just one
difference: the cash register at the end.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1723EST
</TRAILER>
