<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-BOND-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0315 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-VENEZUELA-BOND-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; VENEZUELA'S PDVSA MAY LIMIT BOND ISSUE TO SMALL INVESTORS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Victoria Cunningham &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Caracas, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Petroleos de Venezuela SA said a
planned 30-billion-bolivar (US$62.89 million) sale of three-year
notes may be limited to small domestic investors if demand is
sufficiently strong.
<p>
   The notes, which will go on sale in late February, will mark the
first time that Venezuela's state oil company has given small
domestic investors the opportunity to invest in its projects.
<p>
   The sale will take place over three weeks, with half of the
issue initially reserved for domestic investors, who will be
allowed to purchase up to 1 million bolivars worth of notes each.
The proportion earmarked for small investors may be increased if
demand merits it.
<p>
   ``Depending on how we see the appetite in the first week, it may
be extended to some $60 million,'' or practically the entire issue,
said Luis Giusti, PDVSA president.
<p>
   Larger domestic private and institutional investors will be
offered the remainder of the notes after the first week. Foreign
investors are excluded, although they may be allowed to buy
subsequent debt instruments or shares.
<p>
   Proceeds from the sale will be used to partially finance the
building of a plastics plant.
<p>
   The notes will have a floating interest rate, paid quarterly.
The coupon will be set between the rates carried by three-month
certificates of deposit and 90-day commercial paper. They will also
have a quarterly option to sell.
<p>
   Co-leaders of the sale are Citibank Mercado de Capitales and the
Valores Vencred SA.
<p>
   PDVSA is selling the notes through a specially created unit, the
Petroleum Investment Fund, or SOFIP. The fund is expected to sell
bonds and shares to finance future oil and petrochemical projects.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1723EST
</TRAILER>
