<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-FUND-SUPERMAR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0298 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MERRILL-FUND-SUPERMARKET-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MERRILL TO OFFER MUTUAL FUND `SUPERMARKET' IN MARCH (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Scott W. Martin &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds that Merrill will offer both load and no-load mutual
funds.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. said it
will start a mutual fund ``supermarket'' in March, in a bid to give
its clients a greater selection of mutual funds to buy.
<p>
   The nation's biggest brokerage firm joins a number of other
mutual fund companies and brokerages in offering a supermarket
product. These typically offer customers the chance to buy a number
of different mutual funds managed by different companies.
<p>
   ``The strategy is to give the client more choices,'' said Arthur
Urciuoli, senior vice president in Merrill's private client group.
<p>
   The Merrill lynch fund supermarket will give customers a choice
of 1,100 different mutual funds, including 110 managed by Merrill
Lynch. The supermarket will offer both load and no-load mutual
funds. Investors don't pay a sales charge when they buy a no-load
fund.
<p>
   Charles Schwab Corp. offered the first fund supermarket in 1992,
called OneSource, which now handles some $39 billion. OneSource's
success spawned several imitations, including products from Quick &AMP;
Reilly Inc., Smith Barney and Fidelity Investments.
<p>
   The move follows Merrill's introduction of a program called
Merrill Lynch Financial Advantage Service, which offers U.S.
clients securities trading, mutual funds and financial planning for
one annual fee.
<p>
   Clients who use the program won't pay brokerage commissions for
a limited number of trades and will get financial advice and price
reductions on other services such as margin loans and mortgages.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1724EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0447 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9364 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EARNS-DEANWITTER-UPDA </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0640 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-DEANWITTER-UPDATE3-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DEAN WITTER 4TH-QTR NET RISES 28% ON ASSET MANAGEMENT (UPDATE3) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Monique Wise &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates with closing stock price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Dean Witter, Discover &AMP; Co.
said fourth-quarter earnings rose 28 percent as rising income from
managing clients' money and from penalties charged to credit card
customers overcame credit card losses.
<p>
   The company, which owns broker Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. and
issues the Discover credit card, said net income rose to $227.8
million, or 68 cents a share, from $178.1 million, or 51 cents, a
year earlier.
<p>
   The earnings beat the average estimate of 65 cents a share of
eight analysts surveyed by Zacks Investment Research Inc. Dean
Witter rose 7/8 to 38 on trading of 880,300 shares, more than the
three-month daily average of 692,300.
<p>
   ``The earnings were very strong,'' said analyst Michael
Freudenstein, who follows financial companies for J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.
``Each of their lines of business performed well.''
<p>
   Net income at Dean Witter Reynolds, the third-largest U.S.
securities firm in terms of brokers, rose 8.8 percent to $126
million from $115.8 million a year earlier, an increase of 5.9
percent from the third quarter.
<p>
   Asset management and administration fees, which increased 16
percent to $299.3 million, led the securities unit's performance.
Investment banking revenue jumped 60 percent to $78.1 million amid
a rally in the stock and bond markets.
<p>
   ``We continued to achieve rapid growth in assets under
management,'' Chairman and Chief Executive Philip J. Purcell said
in a statement.
<p>
   Assets under management and administration rose 13 percent to
$90 billion from the year-ago period. Trading revenue declined 1.9
percent to $108.9 million.
<p>
   Net operating revenue at the securities unit rose 11 percent to
$879 million.
<p>
   In December, Dean Witter announced an agreement to buy Lombard
Securities, an on-line brokerage based in San Francisco.
<p>
   Discover card earnings rose 63 percent to $101.8 million from
$62.3 million a year earlier. The rise came even as the company
increased its provisions for loan losses by 53 percent to $636
million.
<p>
   ``Revenues from their credit card services were very high,''
said analyst Mark Alpert at Alex. Brown &AMP; Sons Inc. ``They priced a
lot of their accounts in terms of annual percentage rates and late
fees, which more than offset the rise in write-offs.''
<p>
   Merchant and cardmember fees, on a managed loan basis, rose 48
percent to a record $563.8 million from a year earlier, boosted by
higher transaction volume.
<p>
   The firm increased the penalties it charges for late payments
and spending over credit limits, a spokeswoman said.
<p>
   The loss, or net charge-off, rate for managed loans in credit
services rose to 6 percent from 4.4 percent in the year-earlier
period.
<p>
   ``Our fourth-quarter results were exceptionally strong given the
industry-wide trend of higher credit card write-offs,'' said
Purcell.
<p>
   Discover net operating revenue rose 14 percent to $735.9
million.
<p>
   For the full year, Dean Witter Discover net income rose 11
percent to $951.4 million, or $2.79 a share, from $856.4 million,
or $2.44 in 1995.
<p>
   Total expenses, excluding interest, increased 9.8 percent to
$1.25 billion, led by a 13 percent rise in payroll costs.
<p>
   Compensation expenses rose 13 percent to $427.1 million at Dean
Witter Reynolds and rose 11 percent to $132.1 million at the credit
card unit.
<p>
   Marketing and business development expenses also contributed to
increased costs, advancing 13 percent to $253.6 million for the
company as a whole. They rose 89 percent to $43 million at the
brokerage unit and rose 5 percent to $210.8 million at the credit
card division.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1725EST
</TRAILER>
