<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DC-AREA-STOCKS-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TEXAS STOCKS: WEAK OILFIELD-SERVICE STOCKS DRAG INDEX LOWER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Daniel Fisher &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Houston, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Texas stocks fell for the third
straight trading day as Cliffs Drilling Co., Energy Ventures Inc.
and other oil-related stocks continued their retreat from recent
highs.
<p>
   The Bloomberg Texas Index fell 1.06 to 163.02, its lowest level
in almost two weeks. The index is a price-weighted list of stocks
in companies with significant operations in Texas that is designed
to reflect the performance of the state's economy.
<p>
   Oil service stocks fell after reporting sharp gains in the first
two weeks of the year, with the decline triggered in part by
falling natural gas prices.
<p>
   ``Nearly every company that has reported earnings so far has met
or exceeded expectations,'' said James Stone, a Schroder Wertheim &AMP;
Co. analyst. ``We don't see any weakening of (industry)
fundamentals here.'' Houston-based Cliffs Drilling fell 5 1/64 to
65, Energy Ventures was down 4 1/8 at 57 7/8, Seitel Inc. fell 3
1/2 to 32 7/8, BJ Services Inc. fell 3 3/8 to 47 5/8, and United
Meridian Corp. fell 2 5/8 to 37 1/8.
<p>
   Texas stocks underperformed the national average, falling 0.64
percent compared with a gain of 0.45 percent for the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 Index, which rose 3.51C to 786.2.
<p>
   Computer-related shares rose after Houston-based Compaq Computer
Corp. reported fourth-quarter earnings far exceeded Wall Street
estimates. Compaq rose 5 to 83 1/2, Irving-based I2 Technologies
Inc. rose 4 3/4 to 41 3/8, and Austin-based Dell Computer Corp.
rose 2 5/8 to 66 3/4.
