   FILM-REVIEW-PREFONTAINE
<p>
   UNDATED  &MD;  ``Prefontaine'' may have wowed the opening-nighters at
the Sundance Film Festival, but when you take it out of movie-nut
territory and plunk it down at the shopping-mall multiplex, it's
just another ``inspiring'' and ``uplifting'' pseudo-documentary
about a gifted grandstander who cashed in too early. Coming from
Steve James, the filmmaker responsible for that excellent
basketball documentary ``Hoop Dreams'' (1994), ``Prefontaine'' is a
singular disappointment. It drags for the most part and is hobbled
by a lead actor (Jared Leto) whose glum inexpressiveness is somehow
supposed to pass for charismatic arrogance. By MICHAEL H. PRICE.
Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category.
