<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-POLL-UPDATE1 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0339 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COMPUTER-POLL-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CISCO, NETSCAPE ARE RATED BEST IN BUYER POLL (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Gerard Meuchner &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds number of survey respondents in third paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Cisco Systems Inc. and Netscape
Communications Corp. received the best reviews from corporate
computer buyers in a survey by Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co.
<p>
   Computer Associates International Inc. and Digital Equipment
Corp. finished last among the 12 hardware and software companies on
which Morgan Stanley sought a ``thumbs up/thumbs down'' performance
appraisal.
<p>
   Cisco, a San Jose, California-based maker of networking
equipment, scored highest, praised by 92 percent of the 50
respondents. Netscape, a Mountain View, California-based maker of
Internet software, won praise from 91 percent of buyers.
<p>
   Islandia, New York-based Computer Associates, a software maker,
and Maynard, Massachusetts-based Digital, the nation's
third-largest computer company, each got a ``thumbs up'' from 28
percent of the respondents. The rest gave them a ``thumbs down.''
<p>
   The results of the survey indicate that corporate buyers want to
do business with fewer computer companies, and with those companies
able to solve computer problems across organizations, said Morgan
Stanley analyst Steven Milunovich. ``Customers want fewer vendors,
and more services and solutions from each,'' Milunovich said.
<p>
   International Business Machines Corp. ranked first among the
companies cited as the best ``solution providers,'' followed by
Microsoft Corp.
<p>
   Corporate buyers cited IBM for its understanding of their needs
and its complete package of products and services, according to the
report.
<p>
   Digital won high marks for its products, yet respondents
criticized its sales force and strategy as lacking focus, the
report said.
<p>
   ``It's hard to get excited about the Digital story when user
apathy offsets the company's outstanding technology,'' Milunovich
said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1727EST
</TRAILER>
