<TEXT>
<p>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
<p>
   Locally heavy rains will douse the Gulf Coast states Thursday as
moist air streaming north from the Gulf of Mexico is forced to rise
over a stalling cold front. A jet stream disturbance pressing east
will augment the lifting of moist air, setting the stage for some
heavy showers and thunderstorms over east Texas. A few of the
storms may reach severe levels, with large hail and tornadoes
possible in spots. Showers and storms will spread into Louisiana
and Mississippi late in the day or at night.
<p>
   Meanwhile, pockets of moderately heavy snow will fall on
west-facing slopes of the Rockies early Thursday as moist Pacific
air is forced to rise up the sloping terrain. Snow will taper off
over the mountains of Utah and western Colorado on Thursday
afternoon.
<p>
   Arctic air will return to northwest New England in the wake of a
low pressure system heading northeast into the Labrador Sea. The
leading edge of Arctic air will be accompanied by a band of snow
showers from the Adirondacks of upstate New York to the Longfellow
Mountains of northern Maine.
<p>
   Broken areas of light snow will spread across portions of the
northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley as relatively mild air
from the south is forced to rise over a cold air dome of air near
the ground.
<p>
   Coastal showers and patchy mountain snows will develop in
western Washington and western Oregon as a jet stream disturbance
from British Columbia interacts with Pacific moisture. Farther
south, clouds will decrease over southern California.
<p>
   FOCUS: Arctic Sunrise
<p>
   At Barrow, Alaska, the relentless darkness of the Arctic night
has ended. The sun rose at 1:25 p.m. Wednesday, after having been
below the horizon since November 18. It set 29 minutes later. Now
the amount of possible sunshine increases at least nine minutes
each day. By May 10, the nation's northernmost town will be in
constant sunshine until late August. This Arctic sunrise is the
beginning of a slow steady process that modifies bitter air masses.
As the rest of the United States reaches a mid-winter ebb, the
brightening Barrow skies are the first true sign of spring.
</TEXT>
