<SLUG> BC-COKE-EU-UPDATE4-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0607 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COKE-EU-UPDATE4-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COKE ENTERPRISES' PURCHASE OF BOTTLER CLEARED BY EU (UPDATE3) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Raphael Minder &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds comment from Virgin in eighth paragraph. Updates with
closing share prices.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Brussels, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The European Commission, as
expected, approved Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc.'s 1.2 billion-pound
($2 billion) purchase of Britain's largest bottler, dismissing
complaints by Virgin Group Ltd. that it would stifle competition.
<p>
   The commission, the executive agency of the European Union, said
it didn't have enough evidence that the purchase by Coca-Cola Co.'s
largest bottler had done anything to change a competitive landscape
in which Coke already has more than 60 percent of the British cola
market.
<p>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises, a separately traded company 44.8 percent
owned by Coke, agreed in June to buy Coca-Cola Schweppes Bottling
Ltd. The joint venture was formed by Coke and Cadbury Schweppes Plc
in 1987, with Coke holding 49 percent.
<p>
   EU officials expressed some reservations about the purchase,
calling it a ``borderline'' antitrust case.
<p>
   ``I can assure you we will continue to monitor closely'' the
purchase's effect on the U.K. beverage industry, said Competition
Commissioner Karel Van Miert. ``We had a lot of concerns but at the
end of the day the conclusion was that we didn't have enough legal
evidence to support that.''
<p>
   The commission said the bottler has agreed not to force
retailers to stock only its colas or to tie rebates to long-term
purchases. That addresses ``at least some of the concerns'' raised
by Richard Branson's Virgin and smaller rivals, it said.
<p>
   The commission is also continuing a separate inquiry into some
licensing arrangements for some Cadbury Schweppes brands.
<p>
   ``They're essentially saying they're going to watch Coke like a
hawk,'' said Nick Cookbridge, Virgin Cola's marketing director.
<p>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises Chief Executive Summerfield Johnston Jr.
said the U.K. bottler would be integrated quickly into its other
operations in Europe once the acquisition is completed in the next
several weeks. After the acquisition, Europe will account for 28
percent of Coca-Cola Enterprises' shipments, up from 5 percent in
1995. It already bottles Coke beverages in the Netherlands, Belgium
and most of France.
<p>
   A company spokeswoman did not rule out more acquisitions.
<p>
   ``We are always interested in contiguous properties or
properties where we can add shareholder value,'' said Laura Asman
of Coca-Cola Enterprises.
<p>
   The Atlanta-based bottler's shares rose 5/8 to 55 1/2.
<p>
   Virgin and other smaller rivals had complained that the purchase
would restrict their access to the U.K. cola market. Virgin said
the market share of its 2-year-old Virgin Cola brand had been more
than halved because of the Coke-Cadbury bottler's dominance of the
market.
<p>
   The bottler distributes all Coca-Cola and Cadbury Schweppes
products in the U.K., from Coke to Cadbury's Dr Pepper and Sunkist
brands. The commission estimates the bottler's share of the U.K.
cola market is triple that of its nearest rival, Britvic Ltd.,
which bottles Pepsi products.
<p>
   American depository receipts of Cadbury rose 1/8 to 33 1/4. The
London-based candy and soft drinks maker has said it will get about
622.5 million pounds ($1.1 billion) from selling its 51 percent
stake in the bottler, halving its net debt and freeing up cash for
investments. The commission's green light was expected after
members of an antitrust advisory committee voted to approve the
purchase earlier this month.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1729EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0454 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9373 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-AIRBUS-ADS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0777 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FEA-AIRBUS-ADS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AIRBUS TV ADS, SEEN BY MILLIONS, APPEAL TO JUST TWO CUSTOMERS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Anthony Effinger &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Repeating for all needing.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Atlanta, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The television commercial touts
the virtues of a fast new model: Lots of leg room, great mileage --
with room for 300 and the ability to fly from New York to Paris
nonstop.
<p>
   Airbus Industrie is betting that out of millions of viewers a
select few will want its A330 jetliner. And at $110 million each, a
few buyers is all the European planemaker needs.
<p>
   The ads are aimed at just two prospects -- Arlington,
Virginia-based USAir Group Inc. and Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines,
both of which are shopping for new jetliners. Airbus says spending
thousands of dollars on TV ads is part of what it takes to beat
archrival Boeing Co.
<p>
   ``It tells the airline that we really want their business,''
said Dave Venz, Airbus's North American vice president for
communications.
<p>
   Venz said the ads work. When Airbus's sales team visited Delta
in December, he said, the Delta people mentioned that they'd seen
the ads on the morning news.
<p>
   The commercials highlight the spaciousness of the A330's
business-class section. In one spot, a diminutive businessman is
squeezed in a middle seat between two giant men, and repeatedly has
to climb over them to get to the aisle. The narrator points out
that this wouldn't happen on an Airbus plane, which has no middle
seats in business class.
<p>
   ``Airbus doesn't expect Joe Blow to get up in the middle of
`Seinfeld' and order an A330,'' said Michael Boyd, president of
Aviation Research Consultants in Golden, Colorado. ``Airbus is
really hoping that the handful of Delta executives who will decide
(which planes to buy) are tuning in.''
<p>
   Buying TV time is new for Airbus, which is trying to woo U.S.
airlines away from Boeing. Delta, the third-largest U.S. carrier,
is considering buying Airbus's A330 or Boeing's 777 or 767 models.
All are large, twin-engine airplanes designed for cross-country or
transatlantic flights.
<p>
   USAir, meanwhile, has tentatively agreed to buy 120 Airbus
jetliners for about $5 billion, which would be one of the biggest
orders ever for Airbus. Airbus, a consortium of manufacturers from
Germany, France, Spain and the U.K., is doing everything it can to
make the order firm.
<p>
   Airbus's TV campaign is unusual because it's aimed at airlines.
While aircraft makers do advertise, they usually do so in business
publications read by decision makers.
<p>
   Boeing, though, has turned to TV ads in the past. For example
during the Persian Gulf War, when air travel plunged, Boeing ran
ads extolling the benefits of flying.
<p>
   Boeing also ran TV ads in the late 1960s, when it introduced its
massive 747. The ads featured the Harlem Globetrotters basketball
team clowning inside its expansive cabin. That ad was designed to
get people accustomed to such an enormous plane.
<p>
   Winning aircraft orders with mass-market advertising doesn't
have a very promising record. British Aerospace, for example, once
posted a huge billboard outside the Texas headquarters of American
Airlines' parent, AMR Corp. The manufacturer didn't get an order.
<p>
   And marketing executives say that TV advertising -- each spot
costs a minimum of $100,000 to produce -- is a costly way to
compete for a contract.
<p>
   ``This isn't a cheap form of advertising,'' said Dave Capano,
media director of Tausche, Martin &AMP; Lonsdorf, an Atlanta
advertising agency.
<p>
   Yet, there are sound reasons to use TV.
<p>
   ``This gets the manufacturer's name out there,'' Capano said.
``If they do win the contract, consumers will know and favor
them.''
<p>
   That can be important to some travelers. UAL Corp.'s United
Airlines says many passengers ask to fly Boeing's new 777, the
first time in recent memory that consumers say they want to travel
on a specific aircraft. That's the kind of cache a jet manufacturer
dreams about in a world where travelers usually hunt for cheap
fares and little else.
<p>
   Airbus wouldn't say how much it spent on the ads, which were
produced by Euro RSCG-WNK-Gosper in London. The ads, which ran last
month in Washington, Atlanta and Pittsburgh, also ran in Europe and
Asia in October and November. Airbus is planning to run more ads in
the U.S. soon.
<p>
   Local 30-second ad spots in the Atlanta market cost $4,000 to
$6,000 and as much as $10,000 for a top-rated show, media experts
in the area say.
<p>
   ``If this is what the public sees,'' said Boyd at Aviation
Research, ``imagine the wining and dining going on behind the
scenes.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1730EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0455 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9375 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-DC-AREA-STOCKS-CLOSE- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0361 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DC-AREA-STOCKS-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; D.C. STOCKS: NATIONSBANK, FIRST VIRGINIA LEAD INDEX HIGHER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Todd Blecher &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Washington. D.C.-area stocks
rose today, led by the shares of NationsBank Corp. and First
Virginia Banks Inc.
<p>
   The Bloomberg Washington Area Stock Index rose 0.91, or 0.5
percent, to 174.63. Of the 186 stocks in the price-weighted index,
67 rose, 55 were unchanged, and 64 fell.
<p>
   So far this year the index has risen 6.5 percent.
<p>
   Created in December 1994 with a value of 100, the index is
designed to measure the Washington area economy by reflecting the
moves of the stocks of Washington's largest publicly-traded
companies.
<p>
   The stock of Charlotte, North Carolina's NationsBank, which
operates an extensive branch network in the Washington area, rose 2
3/4 to 109 1/2, as 1.5 million shares were traded.
<p>
   That stock's three-month average daily volume is 1 million
shares.
<p>
   This morning, the company announced a 2-for-1 stock split, and
Chief Executive Hugh McColl said NationsBank believes its strong
earnings performance will continue.
<p>
   Last week, the company said its fourth-quarter net income rose
24 percent to $632 million, or $2.19 a share, beating the $2.13 a
share consensus estimate from 27 analysts surveyed by Zacks
Investment Research.
<p>
   The stock of Falls Church, Virginia's First Virginia Banks rose
2 5/8 to 52 1/2, on trading of 86,000 shares. The stock's average
daily volume is 26,664 shares.
<p>
   Yesterday, the bank holding company said its fourth-quarter net
income rose 12 percent to $30.8 million, or 94 cents a share, from
$27.6 million, or 81 cents, in 1995's fourth quarter.
<p>
   Among the stocks that fell today was Richmond, Virginia's
Reynolds Metals Co. That stock fell 2 1/8 to 62 3/4 a day after the
stock closed at its 52-week high of 64 7/8.
<p>
   The Washington Area index outperformed the Dow Jones Industrial
Average, which fell 33.87 to 6850.03, while lagging the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500, which rose 3.51 to 786.23, and the Nasdaq Combined
Composite, which rose 11.09 to 1388.06.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1731EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0456 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9378 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-TRADER-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1478 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FEA-TRADER-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; OPTIONS TRADERS WORK AGAINST EXPIRATION DEADLINE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Dylan Ratigan &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Repeating for those needing.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Chicago, Jan. 17 (Bloomberg) -- It's 7 a.m. and for Mercury
Trading's option dealers the next 7 1/2 hours will determine
whether the firm's $121,000 investment is lost or becomes worth
millions of dollars.
<p>
   It's expiration day on the Chicago Board Options Exchange,
world's largest options trading arena, a climax reached the third
Friday of each month in which thousands of stock and index options
are exercised for stock, or expire worthless. The activity creates
a chaos that can make an already volatile U.S. stock market
apoplectic. For Mercury chairman Jon Najarian, a 38-year-old former
Chicago Bears linebacker, this chaos is a way of life.
<p>
   Doug Cliggott, J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.'s chief stock strategist, in
New York, has never traded an option in his life. Still, he keeps
an watchful eye on what's going on in the options market because it
signals what investors are expecting in the months ahead.
<p>
   ``Right now, many people are nervous and they are looking for
insurance,'' said Cliggott, referring to growing demand for options
that guarantee investors a fixed selling price for their
portfolios. He said the options market is useful because it
indicates how apprehensive or optimistic investors are about the
market.
<p>
   Currently, some measures are predicting the most volatile year
for U.S. stocks since 1990. Demand for options to sell the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 at a fixed price, which are known as ``puts'' and
allow an investor to lock in a minimum selling price as insurance
against market drops, is near its highest in 12 months.
<p>
   Options give an investor the right, but not the obligation to
buy or sell a company's stock or an index at a set price before a
certain date. An option price reflects expectations for volatility,
the duration of the contract, its price relative to the price of
its underlying security, interest rates and the expected dividend
from the underlying stock.
<p>
   If the price is rising for an option that expires at the current
price of the underlying security with no expected changes in
interest rates or dividends, it is an indication investors are
expecting bigger market or industry swings. That's what's happening
now.
<p>
   ``People are expecting a choppy market and they are expecting a
market that could spike down,'' said Michael Kelly, co-head of
derivative research at J.P. Morgan. Options to buy and sell the S&AMP;P
500 Index in the months ahead are being priced as if S&AMP;P 500 has a
66 percent chance of swinging almost 18 percent up or down, with a
bias for a decline.
<p>
   ``The skew to the down side is a combination of people that
remember the big crashes and increasing skepticism of a market at
record highs,'' said Najarian, whose pony-tailed head and 210-pound
frame make him look like a balding Steven Segal.
<p>
   Coming out of the longest bull market ever, a swing even half
the size of the one investors are paying for on the S&AMP;P 500 could
be unsettling for people who have come to expect a stock market
that rises with little deviation. The S&AMP;P is up 68 percent since
the end of 1994 and hasn't dropped more than 10 percent since 1990.
<p>
   ``A lot of investors have been spoiled,'' said Richard Jandrain,
director of equities for Banc One Investment Advisors with $39
billion in assets. ``With volatility on the rise it could scare
away some of the money we have seen coming in and hurt the
market.'' Some $730 billion has been invested in U.S. markets
during the past six years with $223 billion coming in 1996 alone.
<p>
   Volatility is a good thing for people like Najarian since the
more the stock market moves, the more investors seek protection
from or look to take advantage of market swings by trading options.
<p>
   For the typical options trader, handling this business produces
an annual income of at least $200,000, and in a good year millions.
The traders are predominantly men in their late 20's and 30's, with
educational backgrounds ranging from high school dropouts, to
Ph.D.'s. Their common tie is a quickness with numbers, an affinity
for risk and an aversion to three-piece suits -- floor attire
ranges from casual and to bizarre.
<p>
   Najarian got his start in 1981 when his sports agent offered him
a job as a runner on the CBOE after he was cut by the Bears after
four pre-season games. He traded for eight years for himself and
others, then started his own firm. It has grown to employ 27
traders on three exchanges.
<p>
   This morning at the daily strategy meeting in Mercury's office
on the 15th floor of the CBOE building, the atmosphere is relaxed
as Najarian reviews the position each of his traders has in their
respective options. The traders, meanwhile, exchange playful verbal
jabs at each other under the watchful eye of a Beavis and Butt-Head
poster.
<p>
   Later, at the opening bell on the exchange floor, Najarian's
Informix trader, Donny Hough, is bouncing up and down on his toes
packed in a crowd of more than 30 traders. The noise is deafening.
<p>
   Hough's are intensely focused on the price screens mounted
overhead. His objective is to sell Informix stock to replace his
expiring options when the shares rise or sell the stocks when it
drops. Today the shares are rising, and Hough is selling. By midday
he has made a $94,000 profit. Yet, he still has $48,000 worth of
options that will be worthless at 3:10 p.m. central time when the
market closes.
<p>
   ``The only people that can read a market like this are
schizophrenics,'' says Najarian, referring to the need to be able
to profit from sharp market upswings and downturns alike. His firm,
Mercury Trading, named for the Roman god of commerce and guardian
of traders, is responsible for making markets in options for 48
companies including Micron Technology Inc., CompUSA Inc. and
Informix Corp.
<p>
   Mercury is one of 21 Designated Primary Market Makers, or DPM's,
on the Chicago Board Options Exchange with responsibility for
maintaining a fair, orderly market on the floor. About 60 percent
of all options traded in the U.S. change hands on the CBOE,
including 93 percent of all U.S. index options.
<p>
   Work as a DPM can be very lucrative, with income ranging from
break-even for a DPM in their first year to take home pay in excess
of $10 million for an established market maker like Najarian.
<p>
   Costs are also high, the latest price for a seat on the CBOE was
$555,000 up from $330,000 two years ago. Seats, which entitle an
individual to trade can also be leased for about $7,500 a month.
Overall, costs exceed $10,000 a month for each trader. Mercury owns
two seats and leases 12 more.
<p>
   Last night computer chip-maker VLSI Technology Inc. reported
less-than-expected fourth-quarter earnings and Mercury's Bill Ray,
who makes a market in the options is frantically exercising his
right to sell the tumbling shares at 22 1/2, capturing $5 in profit
with every trade, or $500,000 so far. What Ray expected to be a
non-event has become his most profitable trade in months. ``I'm
surprised and delighted,'' he said. ``We didn't see this coming.''
<p>
   One indication that Cliggott, Jandrain and other Wall Street
strategists monitor is the put-to-call ratio, or the number of
contracts for ``puts'' which allow an investor to sell a stock or
index at a set price vs. the number of investors buying ``calls,''
or the right to buy at a set price by a set date.
<p>
   Puts are generally purchased as a bet that a security's price
will fall while a call is a bet that it will rise. The ratio
doubled last week as investors bought two puts for every call --
indicating that expectations of a market drop were rising.
<p>
   Some market strategists, including Jandrain, consider a rising
put-to-call ratio to be a bullish sign, viewing it as a contrarian
indicator on the theory that the people buying puts tend to be
smaller investors and are therefore less sophisticated, and more
likely to be wrong.
<p>
   ``The options market has predicted 15 of the last two
recessions,'' Cliggott said. ``But at least it predicts them.''
<p>
   By midday, Najarian's traders have locked in all the profit they
are going take from a rising market and the $121,000 risk has been
reduced to about $6,000. Profits meanwhile are in excess of
$600,000 most of which came compliments of a tumbling VLSI.
<p>
   Last year was the best ever for the equity options market with
199 million contracts changing hands, breaking the record 174
million contracts traded in 1995 -- the first year equity option
volume exceeded the previous record of 164 million contracts in
1987.
<p>
   By the end of trading today, Mercury traders have returned to
their offices to calculate their losses and gains. The tally for
today: a profit of $775,000.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1734EST
</TRAILER>
