<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-VENEZUELA-STOCKS-CLOSE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; VENEZUELAN STOCKS FALL AMID HIGH PRICES AND STRIKES (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Peter Wilson &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates with closing prices.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Caracas, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Venezuelan shares fell for a
second session in light trading amid concern that future corporate
earnings don't justify current stock prices.
<p>
   Investors are also concerned about a possible strike at Cia.
Anonima Nacional Telefonos de Venezuela, the national phone
company.
<p>
   ``There is some concern about the strikes but I think they will
be settled,'' said William Boulton, a trader with Bancaracas Casa
de Bolsa.
<p>
   The Caracas Stock Exchange's general index fell 36.90 points, or
0.6 percent, to 6328.47. The financial index fell 106.14 points, or
1.2 percent, to 8531.24, while the industrial index fell 16.40
points, or 0.3 percent, to 5676.42.
<p>
   Domestic investors sold shares on concern that a December rally
of more than 20 percent pushed prices of some shares to a level
that isn't warranted by their potential future earnings.
<p>
   At CANTV, the national phone company, workers are scheduled to
take a strike vote this afternoon. Workers are demanding a
140-percent raise, while the company is offering 20 percent.
<p>
   Workers are scheduled to vote later this afternoon on whether to
strike. CANTV has had repeated labor disputes since a group led by
GTE Corp. purchased 40 percent of the company in 1991.
<p>
   Benchmark CANTV fell 5 bolivars, or 0.3 percent, to 1,925
bolivars (US$4.04).
<p>
   Twenty-nine stocks fell, eight stocks rose, and 11 stocks closed
unchanged among shares that traded.
<p>
   Banco Provincial fell 0.50 bolivars, or 0.1 percent, to 819.50
bolivars, CA Electricidad de Caracas rose 4.50 bolivars, or 0.9
percent, to 485.50 bolivars, and Mantex SACA fell 0.25 bolivars, or
0.6 percent, to 40.25 bolivars.
<p>
   Also, Mavesa SA fell 0.50 bolivars, or 0.3 percent, to 157
bolivars, Siderurgica Venezolana Sivensa Class A fell 4 bolivars,
or 1.3 percent, to 315 bolivars, and Vencemos Type 1 shares fell 20
bolivars, or 1.6 percent, to 1,230 bolivars.
<p>
   Volume totaled 35.20 million shares worth 2.49 billion bolivars,
below this year's average daily volume of 3.49 billion bolivars.
</TEXT>
