<DOCID> nyt970122.0465 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9394 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EARNS-BEAR-STEARS-UPD </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0530 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-BEAR-STEARS-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BEAR STEARNS COS. FISCAL 2ND-QTR NET UP 68% (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Scott W. Martin &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates with stock close. Adds comments from analyst Sallie
Krawcheck of Sanford Bernstein in fourth paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Bear Stearns Cos. said earnings
in its fiscal second quarter rose 68 percent to a record $176.5
million, led by trading and investment banking.
<p>
   The sixth-biggest U.S. securities firm's net income for the
three months ended Dec. 31 rose to $1.27 a share, from $105.2
million, or 72 cents, in the same period a year earlier.
<p>
   The results exceeded the average forecast of 89 cents a share
from analysts surveyed by IBES International Inc. by more than 40
percent. That sent Bear Stearns shares up 1 7/8, or more than 6
percent, to close at an all-time high of 31 3/4.
<p>
   The stock rose ``as Bear Stearns' good earnings became known and
it was clear that there was nothing one-time in nature in the
results,'' said analyst Sallie Krawcheck, who follows securities
firms for Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. `` The firm was strong
everywhere.''
<p>
   Bear Stearns' earnings come amid a surge in securities firms'
profits as low interest rates and record highs in the stock market
boost trading, underwriting and mergers and acquisitions. Yesterday
Salomon Inc., the world's biggest bond trader, said fourth-quarter
earnings rose 36 percent, while Smith Barney Inc., the
second-biggest broker, reported a 21 percent gain in profits.
<p>
   ``These are the best quarterly results Bear Stearns has ever
had, representing the sixth consecutive quarter in which our return
on common equity has topped 20 percent,'' said Bear Stearns Chief
Executive James Cayne. The firm's return on shareholders' equity, a
key measure of profitability, was 33 percent in the second quarter.
<p>
   Bear Stearns, one of Wall Street's biggest traders of stocks and
bonds, said revenue for the quarter after interest expense rose 37
percent to $940.1 million from $688 million in the year-earlier
period.
<p>
   Trading revenue rose 65 percent to a record $429.2 million.
Trading contributed 46 percent of the firm's net revenue in the
second quarter, versus 43 percent in the same period a year
earlier.
<p>
   Investment banking revenue rose 22 percent to $183 million. Bear
Stearns was the eighth-biggest underwriter of U.S. stocks and bonds
during the quarter, according to Securities Data Co., a Newark, New
Jersey-based firm that tracks the securities industry. Bear Stearns
was the fifth-largest arranger of high-yield debt sales, the most
profitable bond underwriting for Wall Street firms.
<p>
   Brokerage commissions rose 12 percent to $184 million.
<p>
   Bear Stearns' non-interest expense increased 27 percent to $650
million. Compensation as a percentage of net revenue in the quarter
was 49 percent versus 50 percent in the same period a year earlier.
<p>
   For the six months ended Dec. 31, Bear Stearns earned $285.0
million, or $2.02 a share, up 43 percent from $199.0 million, or
$1.36, a year earlier. The firm's return on shareholders' equity
was 27 percent.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1739EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0466 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9396 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SUIT-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0272 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COKE-SUIT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COCA-COLA WINS LEGAL CHALLENGE TO STOCK OPTIONS FOR GOUIZUETA &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By John F. Manser &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Wilmington, Delaware, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Coca-Cola Co.
turned back a court challenge to the soft drink company's granting
of stock options for 1 million shares to Chairman and Chief
Executive Roberto C. Goizueta.
<p>
   Delaware Chancery Court Judge Jack Jacobs dismissed the suit
yesterday, citing incorrect procedure by the plaintiff, shareholder
Melvyn Zupnick.
<p>
   Zupnick claimed that granting the stock options to Goizueta
wasted company assets because the executive was being rewarded for
work he had already been compensated for.
<p>
   Atlanta-based Coca-Cola said the option was a bonus to reward
Goizueta for the $69 billion increase in the company's market value
from 1981 through early 1995.
<p>
   Coke's board approved giving the option in April 1995.
<p>
   Jacobs ruled that before filing suit, Zupnick should have asked
the company's board to take corrective action. Delaware law
requires this step in most cases before allowing a derivative
stockholder's suit.
<p>
   Zupnick argued he was entitled to skip the requirement because
the board's action would not have been approved by a person of
ordinary business judgment.
<p>
   The court disagreed with Zupnick's assessment, however, and
dismissed the case.
<p>
   Executive compensation has been the subject of controversy
recently. Walt Disney Co. shareholders filed suit this month to
stop payment of an estimated $130 million severance package to
former Disney executive Michael Ovitz.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1740EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0467 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=l pri=u sel=ttj-z> A9398 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TV-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1243 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TV-VIOLENCE-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE TV RATINGS GAME &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ROB OWEN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Albany Times Union &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Some groups praise TV, some condemn it, but all take an interest
in the box that changed the world.
<p>
   The most prominent American groups include Viewers for Quality
Television, the Parents Television Council, Entertainment Monitor
magazine, the Catholic Church's TV &AMP; Movie Guide and the American
Family Association. They come to the issue with different
perspectives based on religion, morality and consumer views.
<p>
   The Parents Television Council was formed in 1995 in an effort
to clean up TV. Specifically, it aimed to restore the family hour
(the first hour in prime time), according to executive director
Mark Honig. PTC is a special project of the Media Research Center,
a conservative media watchdog group based in Alexandria, Va., and
had a $700,000 budget in 1996.
<p>
   ``In the past few years what we've seen creeping into the first
hour of prime time is sexual situations and innuendo, promiscuity
and sex outside of marriage and vulgar language that was not on TV
a few years ago or was relegated to later viewing hours,'' Honig
said.
<p>
   PTC publishes an annual Family Guide to Prime Time Television,
which the group hopes will help parents make informed viewing
decisions. The guide rates shows using a traffic light system with
green for family-friendly series, yellow for shows with
adult-oriented themes and red for programs with gratuitous sex,
explicit language and violent content.
<p>
   In the 1996-1997 edition, ``Beverly Hills, 90210,'' ``Cybill,''
``The Drew Carey Show,'' ``Friends'' and ``Seinfeld'' were among
the programs receiving red lights, while ``Walker, Texas Ranger''
(a show decried by many groups for its violence) received a yellow
light.
<p>
   ``At least good always triumphs over evil and there's a positive
lesson from that,'' Honig said of ``Walker,'' but he acknowledged
that some people see violence as more detrimental to young viewers
than sexuality.
<p>
   Viewers for Quality Television is a 12-year-old advocacy group
that lobbies networks on behalf of quality TV shows. VQT doesn't
pick shows that are best for family viewing; rather, the group
defines a show as quality if it ``enriches, challenges, involves
and often confronts ... It rises above entertainment. It dares to
take risks.''
<p>
   With that agenda, VQT supports shows both loved (``Dr. Quinn,
Medicine Woman'') and loathed (``NYPD Blue'') by other
organizations. Other programs endorsed by VQT include ``Dangerous
Minds,'' ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' ``ER,'' ``Frasier,''
``Friends,'' ``Grace Under Fire,'' ``Homicide: Life on the
Street,'' ``Law &AMP; Order,'' ``Mad About You,'' ``Murder One,''
``Party of Five,'' ``Seinfeld,'' ``The X-Files'' and ``Touched By
an Angel.''
<p>
   VQT is supported by member contributions and has a 1997 budget
of $80,000, according to president and founder Dorothy Swanson.
<p>
   Besides specific TV advocacy groups, some organizations have
created publications to address concerns about TV show content. The
Roman Catholic Church has a weekly TV &AMP; Movie Guiden published for
about 10 years and has 120 subscribers (many of them Catholic
schools).
<p>
   ``We don't rate programs,'' said Henry Herx, director of the
office of film and broadcasting for the United States Catholic
Conference. ``We just provide information. We explain what the
story line is and who's in it and how well it's done and what some
might find objectionable for their family.''
<p>
   Most of the space in the TV &AMP; Movie Guide is devoted to film
reviews  &MD;  the group even has a toll-free number parents can call to
hear about movies: (800) 311-4222  &MD;  but the TV information that's
included is written in conventional review form.
<p>
   Of the ABC sitcom ``Spin City,'' Herx wrote: ``As for family
audiences, forget it  &MD;  the spin master shares his bed with a
sleep-in girlfriend and the show's humor is riddled with sexual
references.''
<p>
   The Entertainment Monitor is a commercial publication that has
existed for a little more than a year. The magazine began with a
focus on music, according to publisher Charlie Gilreath, but is now
adding a staff to devote more coverage to TV. The magazine's name
will soon change to the Family Entertainment Review to appeal to
parents seeking guidance.
<p>
   Gilreath said his magazine won't pass judgment on programs;
rather, it will provide general information on show content. He
compared the magazine's descriptions to food labels.
<p>
   ``I don't think we'll get into the number of times someone
utters an expletive,'' Gilreath said. ``We'll just let people know
if a show contains nudity or sexual innuendo, and I think that's
all parents want.'' Gilreath said writing TV show synopses is not
an absolute science.
<p>
   Along with those who seek to promote quality TV and restore the
family hour, there are also groups that urge boycotts of programs
(and the products advertised during them). The most famous of these
protesters is the Rev. Donald Wildmon of Tupelo, Miss., whose
19-year-old American Family Association has led the charge against
``NYPD Blue'' (for language and nudity) and most recently has
promised to protest ``Ellen'' (if she comes out as a lesbian).
<p>
   Wildmon's group is in agreement with many of the other
organizations that the new TV ratings system isn't much help to
parents  &MD;  but for different reasons.
<p>
   In a statement, Wildmon said the TV ratings, because they're
determined by the networks, are ``a self-serving tool. The only
thing this rating system will do is absolve the networks of
responsibility for the content of their programs.''
<p>
   The ratings evaluate programs based on their age appropriateness
and label prime-time shows TV-G (general audiences), TV-PG
(parental guidance suggested), TV-14 (parents strongly cautioned)
and TV-M (mature audiences only).
<p>
   PTC's Mark Honig said the ratings are vague and pointed to
recent episodes of ``Promised Land'' and ``Spin City,'' which both
received a TV-PG rating.
<p>
   ``In terms of language, sex or violence there was nothing
apparent on `Promised Land,' but then I turned on `Spin City' and I
heard the word `ass' twice, `bitch' once and they talked about
downloading nude photos on the Internet,'' Honig said. ``There's a
vast difference between those two shows, but the rating doesn't
tell you why it has that rating.''
<p>
   Albany, N.Y., VQT member Risa Scranton said instead of a rating
she rather have information about a show's content so she can make
a viewing decision herself.
<p>
   ``I would prefer my kids don't see graphic violence or blatant
and gratuitous sex scenes,'' Scranton said. ``Is the rating because
of language? Is it because of violence? I want to know.''
<p>
   The rating system is a precursor to the new V-chip technology,
which will allow parents to program the next generation of
television sets to block out programs they don't want their
children to see. By mid-1998 all new TV sets must have the V-chip.
<p>
   Whatever the future of the TV rating system or technology,
experts say the only way the amount of sex and violence on TV will
be reduced is if viewers stop watching those programs.
<p>
   ``It's easier to shake your finger and say, `This is bad,'''
Gilreath said. ``If you want to change TV, you have to make the
decision to not view things. The world has to get used to the fact
that they're going to have to be active on this issue.''
</TEXT>
