 &UR; BC-FBN-BILLS-HENNING-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BUFFALO BILLS NAME DAN HENNING AS OFFENSIVE COORDINATOR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Bob Bensch &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Orchard Park, New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Buffalo Bills
named former Boston College coach Dan Henning offensive
coordinator.
<p>
   Henning replaces Tom Bresnahan, who was offensive coordinator
and offensive line coach for the past five seasons. Bresnahan will
remain with the team as offensive line coach.
<p>
   He takes over a Buffalo attack that ranked 10th in the AFC in
total yards.
<p>
   Henning resigned after three years at Boston College because of
a gambling scandal at the school this season.
<p>
   He comes to Buffalo with 19 years of NFL coaching experience,
having served as head coach of the Atlanta Falcons (1983-86) and
San Diego Chargers (1989-91). He also was an assistant with the
Washington Redskins when they won Super Bowls XVII and XXII, along
with the Houston Oilers, New York Jets and Miami Dolphins.
</TEXT>
