<SLUG> BC-BOEING-FORECAST-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0537 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BOEING-FORECAST-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BOEING 4TH-QTR PROFIT SEEN HIGHER ON RISING PLANE DELIVERIES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Anthony Effinger &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Seattle, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Boeing Co. is expected to see
earnings jump more than 50 percent in the fourth quarter, bolstered
by increased deliveries of its commercial aircraft.
<p>
   Boeing's deliveries suffered in the fourth quarter of 1995 as a
10-week strike by the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers crippled production.
<p>
   The world's largest maker of commercial jets is expected to earn
97 cents a share in the fourth quarter, up from 63 cents a share in
the year-ago period, according to the average of 14 analysts
surveyed by IBES International Inc.
<p>
   ``A dollar a share isn't unreasonable'' for Boeing in the fourth
quarter, said Wolfgang Demisch, an aerospace analyst at BT
Securities in New York.
<p>
   Boeing is scheduled to report earnings tomorrow morning before
the stock market opens.
<p>
   Analysts based their estimates on Boeing's delivery of 62
aircraft to the world's airlines during the quarter, up from just
36 in fourth-quarter 1995.
<p>
   The deliveries included 10 of Boeing's mammoth 747s, which cost
about $165 million each. Analysts estimate that each 747 sale adds
about 5 cents to Boeing's earnings.
<p>
   Boeing also delivered eight of its new 777s, which deliver far
lower profit because the aircraft is new and still has lots of
development costs that must be paid off. Demisch said sales of the
aircraft probably covers its costs now, and little else.
<p>
   Analysts expect Boeing's earnings to rise from now until at
least 2000 as the torrent of orders it received for commercial
aircraft this year turns into deliveries.
<p>
   Analysts at NatWest Securities Corp. in New York expect Boeing's
deliveries to rise to 365 in 1997 and 445 in 1998, compared with
the 218 Boeing delivered this year.
<p>
   Boeing won orders for 614 aircraft in 1996 as airlines around
the world made plans to replace jetliners and buy new ones to add
to their fleets. That's up from 346 orders in 1995 and just 120 in
1994, when poor profits at the airlines made few willing to splurge
on new aircraft.
<p>
   Seattle-based Boeing will get a modest contribution to earnings
from the defense businesses it bought from Rockwell International
Corp. for $3.2 billion. Boeing completed that purchase on Dec. 8,
making the businesses a subsidiary.
<p>
   Just days later, Boeing agreed to buy rival McDonnell Douglas
Corp. in an all-stock transaction valued at $13.3 billion at the
time. A recent rise in Boeing's stock has made that purchase worth
more than $15 billion to McDonnell shareholders.
<p>
   If the purchase is approved by regulators, Boeing will become
the world's largest aerospace company, competing with Lockheed
Martin Corp. in a wide range of defense and space projects for the
U.S. government.
<p>
   Boeing shares fell 1 5/8 to 112 1/4 today, slipping from the
record high of 114 1/2 reached yesterday when the company said it
scrapped plans to build two larger versions of its 747 jetliner,
already the world's largest. The project was expected to cost $7
billion in research and development.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1742EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
