<STORYID cat=e pri=u sel=taf-z> A9412 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NYCITY-BALLET-REVIEW- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0421 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NYCITY-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DANCE REVIEW: BALANCING CONFECTION WITH `VIENNA WALTZES' &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JENNIFER DUNNING &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  The New York City Ballet presented an extremely
well-balanced program Tuesday night at the New York State Theater.
``The Chairman Dances'' is a colorful, stylized romp through the
score by John Adams that gives the ballet its name. Choreographed
by Peter Martins, the ballet spills two battalions of eight women
across the floor in sidling, sweeping ranks whose momentum matches
that of the music.
<p>
   Dressed in Rouben Ter-Arutunian's fanciful red and purple silk
pajamas and wearing black topknots, the corps women are small
slashes of color moving across a Minimalist canvas. Wendy Whelan,
their leader, looks less glamorous than usual in her bunchy whites.
But ``The Chairman Dances'' is a post-modernist confection that is
not about presence or technique.
<p>
   The program opened with George Balanchine's ``Ballo della
Regina,'' a bit of minor Balanchine classicism that shifts with
distracting abruptness between playful, airborne lyricism and regal
ceremony. The veteran ballerina Merrill Ashley is less buoyant and
driven these days, but it is now possible to see the choreography
and her meticulousness even more clearly in her dancing.
<p>
   Damian Woetzel was her dashing and attentive partner. The
soloists were Rachel Rutherford, Isabel Kimmel, Stacey Calvert and
Jennifer Tinsley.
<p>
   In two role debuts, Ms. Kimmel danced with an engagingly
gangling abandon and Ms. Rutherford with minxlike charm and polish.
<p>
   Balanchine explores a dance form and a culture in his ``Vienna
Waltzes,'' at the same time creating a lavish audience pleaser. The
ballet has lost some of its quieter nuances in the 20 years since
its premiere. There was an inadvertent hint of Mae West in the Gold
and Silver Waltz, danced by Lourdes Lopez, overpowered by her
costume, and Peter Hansen, her very innocent young blond cavalier.
<p>
   And Darci Kistler, partnered by Igor Zelensky, overdramatized
and embellished the exquisite Rosenkavalier waltz, trusting, it
seemed, neither the choreography nor herself to do the job.
<p>
   The performance  &MD;  and the evening as a whole  &MD;  reached a much
higher level of exciting artistry with the exuberant, sharp-edged
classical dancing of Nichol Hlinka and Peter Boal in the
Fruehlingsstimmen. The lead cast was completed by Diana White, Jock
Soto and an enjoyably rowdy Kathleen Tracey and Michael Byars in
the polka.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1742EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0473 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9416 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-LYNCH-UPDATE1 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0669 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MERRILL-LYNCH-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MERRILL OFFERS INVESTMENT SERVICES FOR SINGLE FEE (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Scott W. Martin &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds background on Merrill's mutual fund supermarket and
comments from Merrill Senior Vice President Arthur Urciuoli.
Rewrites.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. said it
began offering all U.S. clients securities trading, mutual funds
and financial planning for a single annual fee.
<p>
   The nation's biggest brokerage firm first offered the new
program, called Merrill Lynch Financial Advantage Service, to some
clients on a trial basis in October.
<p>
   ``Our pilot has been the most successful introduction of a new
service we've ever had.'' said John L. Steffens, head of Merrill's
brokerage unit. Clients participating in the program won't pay
brokerage commissions for a limited number of trades and will get
financial advice and price reductions on other services such as
margin loans and mortgages, the company said.
<p>
   Smith Barney, the nation's second-largest brokerage firm, began
offering a similar service this month. The moves by the two firms
are designed to expand their clients' investment choices as
investors flock to so-called fund supermarkets, which offer the
choice of a variety of mutual funds.
<p>
   Charles Schwab Corp. offered the first fund supermarket in 1992,
called OneSource, which now handles some $39 billion. OneSource's
success has spawned several imitations, including products from
Quick &AMP; Reilly Inc., Smith Barney and Fidelity Investments.
<p>
   Merrill will start a mutual fund supermarket of its own in
March, said Arthur Urciuoli, a senior vice president in Merrill's
private client group, The fund supermarket will give clients a
choice of 1,100 load and no-load mutual funds, including ll0
managed by Merrill.
<p>
   No-load funds don't charge investors sales commissions when they
buy the funds.
<p>
   Clients have put some $150 million in assets into Financial
Advantage since Merrill offered it in 14 offices starting in
October, according to Urciuoli. He said he'd be disappointed if
Financial Advantage doesn't grow to $5 billion in assets by the end
of this year.
<p>
   Merrill doesn't expect to earn any extra money from Financial
Advantage because fees from the program will be offset by lost
brokerage commissions.
<p>
   Still, Financial Advantage will boost Merrill's fee income at a
time when it and many of its Wall Street rivals want to decrease
reliance on volatile trading commissions and underwriting fees,
which rise and fall with swings in the stock and bond markets.
<p>
   ``To the extent our revenues are more predictable, that's a
positive, Urciuoli said.
<p>
   Merrill now covers about 70 percent of its fixed expenses with
fees from asset management, investment banking and other services,
and the firm wants to increase that percentage, Merrill executives
say.
<p>
   Merrill's 13,600 brokers help clients around the world manage
more than $779 billion in assets. Merrill earns fees, as opposed to
brokerage commissions, on about $30 billion of those assets. The
firm expects to more than triple those fee-earning assets in five
years.
<p>
   ``Our fee-based alternatives have nowhere to go but up,'' said
Steffens.
<p>
   Financial Advantage is designed for investors who may trade
stock and bonds infrequently but have several brokerage or mutual
fund accounts and are interested in financial planning.
<p>
   Clients with between $100,000 and $250,000 in Merrill accounts
get 12 commission-free trades a year, an analysis of retirement and
college investments and access to the firm's stock and bond
research for a fee equal to 1.5 percent of assets.
<p>
   As clients keep more money with Merrill, their fees go down and
commission-free trades and financial planning services increase.
Clients with more than $1 million in their Merrill accounts pay a
fee of 1 percent or less and receive between 50 and 75 free trades
and expanded financial planning.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
