<SLUG> BC-COKE-SUIT-CORRECT-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0282 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COKE-SUIT-CORRECT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COCA-COLA WINS LEGAL CHALLENGE TO GOIZUETA'S OPTIONS (CORRECT) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By John F. Manser &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Corrects to fix spelling of Goizueta in headline)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Wilmington, Delaware, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Coca-Cola Co.
turned back a court challenge to the soft drink company's granting
of stock options for 1 million shares to Chairman and Chief
Executive Roberto C. Goizueta.
<p>
   Delaware Chancery Court Judge Jack Jacobs dismissed the suit
yesterday, citing incorrect procedure by the plaintiff, shareholder
Melvyn Zupnick.
<p>
   Zupnick claimed that granting the stock options to Goizueta
wasted company assets because the executive was being rewarded for
work he had already been compensated for.
<p>
   Atlanta-based Coca-Cola said the option was a bonus to reward
Goizueta for the $69 billion increase in the company's market value
from 1981 through early 1995.
<p>
   Coke's board approved giving the option in April 1995.
<p>
   Jacobs ruled that before filing suit, Zupnick should have asked
the company's board to take corrective action. Delaware law
requires this step in most cases before allowing a derivative
stockholder's suit.
<p>
   Zupnick argued he was entitled to skip the requirement because
the board's action would not have been approved by a person of
ordinary business judgment.
<p>
   The court disagreed with Zupnick's assessment, however, and
dismissed the case.
<p>
   Executive compensation has been the subject of controversy
recently. Walt Disney Co. shareholders filed suit this month to
stop payment of an estimated $130 million severance package to
former Disney executive Michael Ovitz.
</TEXT>
