<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=taf-z> A9421 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIA-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1023 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TEN-AUSTRALIA-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SAMPRAS SURVIVES 5-SETTER; IVANISEVIC FALLS TO MUSTER &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBIN FINN &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   MELBOURNE, Australia  &MD;  The evening was pleasantly devoid of
intrusive weather, and 10th-seeded Albert Costa, the Spanish No. 1,
was able to lure Pete Sampras, the world's No. 1, all the way into
a fifth set under the murky clouds Wednesday night in their tense
Australian Open quarterfinal.
<p>
   The occasionally perplexed Sampras lost his serve only once in
the match, but there he was, scampering after drop shots, having
his hair ruffled by passing shots, and spending his second match in
succession locked in long-term combat against a player who
shouldn't have bothered him. At least not this much.
<p>
   But in his most clever maneuver of the night, Sampras sneaked
out to a 3-1 lead in the final set against Costa and held on for a
6-3, 6-7 (5-7), 6-1, 3-6, 6-2 victory that forwarded him into a
semifinal slot here for the fourth time in the last five years.
<p>
   ``These guys are just kind of coming out of the woodwork, and
it's tough to play them; they play with a lot of spin, a lot of
determination, and a lot of heart,'' Sampras said of a new
generation of Spaniards so flexible away from their native red clay
that one of them, 24th-ranked Carlos Moya, has earned a semifinal
assignment against second-seeded Michael Chang.
<p>
   Wednesday night, Sampras put 23 aces past Costa, one of a record
three Spanish men who took advantage of these sluggish hard courts
and reached the Australian quarterfinals, and he also broke his
21-year-old challenger's serve five times. But until Sampras
stepped his aggression up a level in the final set, Costa, now 1-5
in five-setters, showed no signs of backing off.
<p>
   ``For him to play five sets is hard, but it's not really hard,''
Costa said about Sampras, whose five-set resume improved to 24-8.
``He's used to playing like this.''
<p>
   The oppressive 72-hour heat wave had given way to showers during
the day session, so the tournament was able to flaunt its $4
million retractable roof with impunity. But an indoor setting that
should have helped third-seeded Goran Ivanisevic serve with
impunity, didn't.
<p>
   As the swallows trapped in the rafters turned the stadium into a
twittering birdcage, a caged up and cranky Ivanisevic found himself
completely vulnerable to the cat-like attack of fifth-seeded Thomas
Muster of Austria.
<p>
   Muster's emphatic 6-4, 6-2, 6-3 upset of the volatile Ivanisevic
sent the 1995 French Open champion into his first Australian Open
semifinal since 1989. That year a freakish knee injury forced him
to virtually abandon his pursuit of titles on any surface less
forgiving than red clay.
<p>
   So Sampras will get to test his endurance in the semifinals
against Muster, who barely bothered to sit down during the
changeovers in his 1-hour-42-minute throttling of Ivanisevic.
<p>
   ``I don't know if he is normal,'' observed Ivanisevic, who
relishes his rests during changeovers but didn't get to enjoy them
Wednesday. ``I'm sitting on the changeover, and he's already
waiting for me to serve, but that's Thomas, nobody's like Thomas.''
<p>
   The 29-year-old Muster, the oldest but fittest Top 10 player on
the planet, terrorized the Croat with a relentless series of
rock-hard returns that were accompanied by Muster's signature
prehistoric grunts.
<p>
   But Muster's strategy was also enhanced by a double dose of
space-age technology: not only did he use a computer to decipher
Ivanisevic's serve before the match, he used an extended racquet to
bolster his own strokes during it.
<p>
   Muster was still outaced by 16 to three, but he made just 14
unforced errors to Ivanisevic's 54 and said the only drawback about
his computer is that ``it doesn't play for you.''
<p>
   On the women's side, the oldest and youngest players left in
contention prevailed.
<p>
   First, Mary Joe Fernandez, a seasoned two-time finalist at this
Grand Slam, and then 16-year-old Martina Hingis, the fourth and
highest remaining seeded player on the star-starved women's side,
reached the semifinals with straight-set victories. They joined
unseeded Mary Pierce, this event's champion in 1995, and
12th-seeded Amanda Coetzer, a semifinalist last year.
<p>
   Hingis briefly pushed the panic button the other day after
learning that, for the first time in the Open era, a Grand Slam
tournament had lost all three of its top-seeded women before the
quarterfinal round.
<p>
   The development ``made me have a big chance instead of a little
chance,'' said Hingis, who kept her chance of becoming the youngest
Grand Slam champion of this century intact with a 7-5, 6-2
dismissal of eighth-seeded Irina Spirlea of Romania.
<p>
   Hingis, whose previous best showing at a Grand Slam was a
semifinal finish at the 1996 U.S. Open, left herself just two
victories away from becoming the youngest Grand Slam champion since
15-year-old Lottie Dodd won Wimbledon in 1887.
<p>
   In the semifinals, Hingis will face a 10-year veteran in the
25-year-old Fernandez, who advanced by 7-5, 4-0 Wednesday after her
unseeded Belgian opponent, 43rd-ranked Dominque Van Roost,
defaulted because of a strained abdominal muscle. The hard-hitting
Van Roost was already in tears after Fernandez took a 3-0 lead in
the second set, then quit after netting an overhead on the opening
point of the fifth game.
<p>
   ``I may be the oldest one left in the tournament, and I'm
probably the least favorite out of all of them,'' said Fernandez,
who hasn't reached a Grand Slam semifinal since 1993 but reached
the first of her three Slam finals here in 1990. ``In the back of
my mind, I always know that,'' she said, ``so I end up playing
pretty well.''
<p>
   In contrast to Fernandez, who made just 11 unforced errors, Van
Roost committed 43. In further contrast to Fernandez, who split
with the longtime coach Harold Solomon and had contemplated
retirement this year, the 23-year-old Van Roost recently married
her coach and, as a certified late-bloomer, won her second career
title two weeks ago at Hobart, Tasmania. Here, Van Roost knocked
out second-seeded Arantxa Sanchez Vicario.
</TEXT>
