<SLUG> BC-CONNECTICUT-STOCKS-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0346 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CONNECTICUT-STOCKS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CONNECTICUT STOCKS: TRIDENT INTERNATIONAL PULLS INDEX HIGHER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Alvin Powell &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Hartford, Connecticut, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Connecticut stocks
rose to a record, led by shares of Trident International Inc.,
whose stock climbed 24 percent after an Alex. Brown &AMP; Sons Inc.
analyst raised his rating.
<p>
   The Bloomberg Connecticut Index rose 0.26 to a record 153.21,
surpassing yesterday's record of 152.95. The index is a
price-weighted list of 160 Connecticut-based companies' shares
designed to reflect in part the performance of the state's economy.
The index began Dec. 30, 1994 at a base value of 100.
<p>
   Shares of Brookfield-based Trident rose 4 3/8 to 22 1/2 after
Alex. Brown analyst William L. Potter raised his rating on the
maker of industrial ink-jet printing equipment to ``strong buy''
from ``buy.''
<p>
   Trident shares surged 7 1/4, or 48 percent, since the company
said late Monday its fiscal first-quarter net income was $1.74
million, or 24 cents a share, compared with a loss of $405,000, or
28 cents, in the comparable period in 1995.
<p>
   Sales rose 8 percent in the quarter to $6.54 million from $6.05
million, the company said.
<p>
   Prudential Securities analyst Alex Henderson said yesterday the
company could see sustainable 30 percent revenue growth and see
earnings hit $1.00 this fiscal year and $1.35 next year.
<p>
   Shares of insurer Travelers Group Inc. also rose, climbing 2 3/8
to 53 5/8 after the company said it would buy back $1 billion in
stock and increase its dividend 33 percent. Travelers is based in
New York, but has substantial operations in Connecticut.
<p>
   Connecticut-based health maintenance organizations were among
state stocks whose shares fell after the Clinton administration
proposed a plan to reduce Medicare spending, partly with a $46
billion cut in payments to HMOs.
<p>
   Shares of Norwalk-based Oxford Health Plans Inc. fell 1 to 52
3/8. Shares of Trumbull-based Physicians Health Services Inc. fell
1 to 23.
</TEXT>
