<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9427 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CONRAIL-WYSER-PRATTE- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0624 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CONRAIL-WYSER-PRATTE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CONRAIL HOLDER WANTS NORFOLK SOUTHERN VOTING TRUST ON CONRAIL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Greg Groeller &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Norfolk Southern Corp. should
create a voting trust that would try to repeal Conrail Inc.'s
anti-takeover defenses, clearing the way for Norfolk Southern's
$10.32 billion hostile bid for the Philadelphia-based railroad, a
Conrail shareholder said.
<p>
   Wyser-Pratte &AMP; Co., a New York-based investment company that
holds about 385,000 Conrail shares, or 0.4 percent of Conrail's
total, said Conrail shareholders should place their shares in a
voting trust controlled by Norfolk Southern that would vote
collectively on all issues related to Conrail's anti-takeover
provisions.
<p>
   Wyser-Pratte wants the provisions repealed. It has been vocal in
its opposition to CSX Corp.'s planned $9.72 billion cash-and-stock
acquisition for Conrail, saying the offer is too low and coercive
to Conrail shareholders.
<p>
   Guy Wyser-Pratte, president of the investment firm, said
shareholders are upset at Conrail's refusal to talk to Norfolk
Southern, even in the face of a shareholder vote last week that
rejected the CSX-Conrail acquisition under its present terms.
Wyser-Pratte specializes in takeover arbitrage, or investing in
companies that are or may become acquisition candidates.
<p>
   ``By doing nothing more than announcing that they will schedule
another vote, Conrail's board is demonstrating its utter disdain
for shareholders and acting on its belief that shareholders can be
coerced into accepting an inferior offer,'' he said.
<p>
   Last week, Conrail shareholders overwhelmingly rejected a
proposal to exempt Conrail from a Pennsylvania law that forbids a
two-tiered acquisition such as the one CSX has proposed. Conrail
has vowed to call another vote on the issue.
<p>
   Separately, Norfolk Southern today began its promised tender
offer to buy 8.2 million Conrail shares at $115 a piece. That
amount -- about 9.9 percent of the outstanding common shares --is
the maximum Norfolk Southern can buy without tripping Conrail's
``poison pill'' defense against hostile takeovers. The offer
expires at midnight New York time on Feb. 4.
<p>
   CSX also said today that it was extending its own tender offer
for 20.1 percent of Conrail shares to 5 p.m. on Feb. 14. It was
originally scheduled to expire at 5 p.m. today. CSX already owns
19.9 percent of Conrail.
<p>
   Shares of Conrail rose 3 1/4 to 107 1/4, a 52-week high. Shares
of Norfolk Southern rose 1 to 88 1/8, while CSX rose 1 5/8 to 49
1/8.
<p>
   Wyser-Pratte said it will make a proposal on the voting trust to
Norfolk Southern soon.
<p>
   Bob Fort, a Norfolk Southern spokesman, said Norfolk Southern
hasn't received the proposal and declined to comment on it.
<p>
   The voting trust would require at least 50 percent of Conrail's
total outstanding shares to be effective, Wyser-Pratte said. By
placing their shares in the trust, Conrail shareholders wouldn't
give up the right to vote separately on other issues affecting the
merger, Wyser-Pratte said.
<p>
   On Jan. 13, Wyser-Pratte said it will propose an amendment to
Conrail's corporate bylaws that would force the company to call a
special meeting in which shareholders would vote whether to remove
Conrail's ``poison pill'' takeover defenses, which are designed to
make a hostile acquisition prohibitively expensive.
<p>
   Wyser-Pratte also said it will propose that CSX not be allowed
to buy Conrail unless a majority of shareholders not affiliated
with either company vote in favor of the merger. Wyser-Pratte said
it will make the proposals at Conrail's annual shareholders
meeting, which hasn't been scheduled yet.
</TEXT>
