<STORYID cat=e pri=u sel=taf-z> A9432 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TEENS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0437 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TV-TEENS-REVIEW-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; `CLASS OF 2000': WHOLESOME TEEN-AGERS WHO DEFY STEREOTYPES &LR;  &QL; 
(EDS: Broadcast notes appear at the end of the review. Time,
channel are for New York area. Check local listings.) &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By WALTER GOODMAN &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   With his strange slab of hair and his taste for heavy metal,
Steve, who calls himself a ``head banger,'' may seem the sort of
teen-ager you'd just as soon avoid. But in conversation he turns
out to be reflective and, although he might shudder at the word,
sweet.
<p>
   That's applies, too, to the dozen other 14-year-olds you can
meet in ``Class of 2000,'' an upbeat encounter with a generation
that worries the nation.
<p>
   CBS News producers spent four months around Joppatowne High
School in Harford County, Md., last fall talking with freshmen,
parents and teachers. The principal notes that his students come
from high-priced shore homes and from trailer parks; about a
quarter are black, Hispanic or Asian-American. Maybe the producers
chose the most appealing of them; if so, they chose well.
<p>
   There's Suzanne, an honor-roll student determined to become a
cheerleader although she concedes she is quite a few pounds over
the cheerleader image. Tim is worried about his father being out of
work; Kris, who is dyslexic, has to struggle in the classroom, but
football comes naturally to him. Shawn, small, white and good at
schoolwork, is best friends with Brent, tall, black and in special
education. All of them talk sensibly about matters that matter:
parents, sex, drugs, race, religion, music, money, friendship and
death.
<p>
   Mark McEwen delivers the on-camera narration, which, except for
an irrelevant detour to China, keeps the focus on the youngsters.
You can't help liking them.
<p>
   The report finds clues to their apparent wholesomeness in visits
to their homes. Although some of their parents are divorced, and
two girls are being brought up by single mothers, all seem
fortunate in living with adults who pay attention to them.
<p>
   Tim's mother must be speaking for many parents when she says,
``You can raise them so much and give them so many values, and then
you've got to sit back and trust them.'' If there is a lesson in
these heartening and affecting two hours, maybe that is it.
<p>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
<p>
   `CLASS OF 2000'
<p>
   9 p.m. ET Thursday night on CBS
<p>
   (Channel 2 in New York)
<p>
   Written and directed by Maurice Murad. Christopher E. Martin,
co-producer; Stephen J. Dellaplietra, assistant director; Lyne
Bowens, executive producer of the ``Class of 2000'' Project; Linda
Mason, executive producer.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1747EST
</TRAILER>
