<DOCID> nyt970122.0481 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=ttc-z> A9433 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-IMPLANTS-ART </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0775 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DIABETES-IMPLANTS-ART-2Takes-LADN &QL; 
FIRM RESEARCHES DIABETES IMPLANTS &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
(EDITORS: A Macintosh color graphic  &MD;  slugged
DIABETES/insulinimplants &HT;     &MD;  is en route to NYT News Service graphics clients. Call
212-556-4204 for information.) &QL; 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Los Angeles Daily News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WESTLAKE VILLAGE, Calif.  &MD;  Inside a small laboratory, Edward
J.A. Pope wages war on diabetes, one of mankind's most vexing
diseases.
<p>
   Pope's most potent weapon, and one that he developed, is a
``sol-gel'' process not yet found in medical facilities. The
process, for which he has patents pending, produces small,
pale-pink ceramic beads that encase a collection of
insulin-producing beta cells.
<p>
   The goal is simple.
<p>
   The task is daunting.
<p>
   And the testing is in the earliest stages.
<p>
   But the rewards for his company, Matech, could be great.
<p>
   Pope, who earned a Ph.D. in materials science from UCLA, is
trying to develop a new treatment for diabetes that would free
millions of sufferers from the task of giving themselves daily
injections of insulin, which converts blood sugar to energy.
<p>
   The beads, made from a proprietary process that results in the
formation of what he calls ``living ceramics,'' are his magic
bullet.
<p>
   ``We're taking living cells, whether they be bacteria, fungi or
mammal cells, and forming the ceramic around them, while keeping
the cells alive,'' Pope said. ``Nobody has ever done that before.
So in a sense this is a new class of materials.''
<p>
   A $94,000 Small Business Innovative Research Grant from the
National Institutes of Health funded the research's first phase,
during which the treatment kept some laboratory mice that receive
capsule implants diabetes-free for three months.
<p>
   Experts in diabetes research and treatment say it is too early
to say whether Pope will be successful, and they do not want to
raise expectations of people suffering from the disease.
<p>
   ``The public should be aware that is a promising area ... but
(success) is not around the corner. It's going to take a lot of
years to do this,'' said Dr. Seymour Levin, a diabetes specialist
and professor of medicine at UCLA.
<p>
   Levin is also on the board of the Los Angeles chapter of the
American Diabetes Association and is director of the diabetes
program at the West Los Angeles Veterans Administration Medical
Center.
<p>
   ``We've been dreaming about this since the early '70s,'' said
Dr. Gordon Weir, head of the transplant unit at the Joslin Diabetes
Center in Boston. ``We have to be very cautious about accepting
discoveries in mice as being a breakthrough treatment. We don't
know how long this is going to take.''
<p>
   Pope is being assisted in the research by chemist Karen P. Braun
and Dr. Chuck Peterson, a specialist in diabetes and alcoholism. He
agrees that the work must be slow and painstaking.
<p>
   Pope used 15 diabetic mice in the study's first phase. Nine did
not receive any treatment, and six died soon after the onset of
diabetes. Two were given placebos  &MD;  ceramic capsules without the
beta cells  &MD;  and they also died.
<p>
   Four mice received the capsules containing the insulin-producing
cells. Large capsules were implanted in two mice and small capsules
in two.
<p>
   Those with small bead transplants were still alive by the
study's end. And one them was still alive and gaining weight nearly
nine weeks after receiving the implant.
<p>
   The ones that received the large beads were healthy for a while
but then became sick and were euthanized.
<p>
   ``What we wanted to study was whether the diameter of the bead
made a difference. And it does make a big difference, so that's a
very important finding,'' Pope said.
<p>
   The capsules were removed from the euthanized mice, and Pope was
able to verify that they were still producing insulin, although not
enough to overcome the disease.
<p>
   Pope said while waiting for additional health institute funding,
his company will implant small capsules in 10 diabetic mice and
chart the treatment's progress.
<p>
   As the company proceeds with testing, it also plans to try
implanting pig cells that produce insulin in other test mice.
<p>
   It's all part of a lengthy process that could lead to U.S. Food
and Drug Administration approval for human tests in the distant
future.
<p>
   ``It's pretty complicated, and it all depends on what type of
product they are bringing to market and whether it is a variation
of something already out there or a breakthrough process,'' FDA
spokeswoman Sharon Snyder said of the agency's review procedure.
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</TEXT>
