<SLUG> BC-TV-MEDIA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0227 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TV-MEDIA-REVIEW-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; `MEDIA MATTERS': ANOTHER LOOK INSIDE THE PRESS &LR;  &QL; 
(EDS: Broadcast notes appear at the end of the review. Time,
channel are for New York area. Check local listings.) &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By WALTER GOODMAN &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   PBS is broadcasting the second program in a now-and-then series
on the workings and misworkings of the press and television.
<p>
   The first and by far the most incisive segment reports on how
most major news organizations failed to do their own investigations
of last year's dispute over late-term abortions, relying instead on
not always accurate information from the abortion-rights side.
<p>
   Next comes a profile of the ferociously conservative editorial
page of The Wall Street Journal, including an interview with its
editor, Robert Bartley. And the hour ends with a worry-of-the-week
piece on how easily photographs can be manipulated by computers.
<p>
   ``Media Matters'' could do with a touch less sermonizing from
its host and executive editor, Alex Jones, a former reporter for
The New York Times, and from imported experts. But its straight-on,
knowledgeable approach to the contentious issue of how news is
being delivered these days is a welcome addition to the PBS lineup.
<p>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
<p>
   `MEDIA MATTERS'
<p>
   Thursday night on PBS
<p>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 10)
</TEXT>
