<STORYID cat=t pri=u sel=ttj-z> A9436 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAMIC-TRAVEL-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0681 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ISLAMIC-TRAVEL-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDs: For release Sunday Jan. 26) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; A GUIDE TO TRAVELING DURING RAMADAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN FLINN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Fresh off a series of planes from San Francisco, we were waiting
to get our passports stamped at the Cairo airport, standing in a
long line that was going nowhere.
<p>
   All around us, Egyptians in traditional djellabas were shuffling
their feet, checking their watches and exchanging impatient
glances. Suddenly, without warning, a siren sounded and the
Egyptians dropped to the floor.
<p>
   What was going on? An air raid? As I started to crouch down
myself, I saw that the Egyptians were pulling packages of dates and
other food from their robes and tucking hungrily into them. One man
noticed the puzzled look on my face, laughed, gestured at the
impromptu picnic and said, ``Ramadan!''
<p>
   Ramadan, which began nine days ago, is one of the holiest times
of the year for the world's 1.5 billion Muslims, a monthlong
observance marked not by celebration and consumption, but by quiet
devotion and self-sacrifice.
<p>
   Between dawn and sunset, Muslims must abstain from food, drink  &MD; 
including water  &MD;  cigarettes, gum, sex and such frivolous
activities as cursing and gossiping. Most get up long before
sunrise to eat a small meal to sustain them through the day.
<p>
   Traditionally, fasting begins when it grows light enough to
distinguish a black thread from a white one. (These days the time
is a specified period before sunrise, usually an hour to 90
minutes, depending on the latitude.)
<p>
   Fasting continues until the sun dips below the horizon  &MD;  an
event that, at least in the case of the Cairo airport, is announced
by a blaring siren.
<p>
   Muslims believe Ramadan is the month in which God began
revealing the Koran to his prophet Mohammed. Observed during the
ninth month of the Islamic lunar calendar, it moves ahead about 10
days each year. This year the fast began Jan. 10; next year it will
start Jan. 1.
<p>
   There's little pageantry or display associated with it, except
for the last day, when the breaking of the final fast is often
marked by community celebrations called Eid al-fitr.
<p>
   ``Ramadan is a time for developing your inner soul, connecting
with God and developing more sympathy for the unfortunate and the
poor,'' said Ebrahim Nana, a trustee of the Islamic Center of San
Francisco. ``It's not necessarily for show.''
<p>
   Compared to the orgy of commercialism and consumption that
Christmas has become, the inward-looking devotion of Ramadan makes
a fascinating and poignant counterpoint.
<p>
   Traveling through the Islamic world during Ramadan can present
problems for non-Muslim visitors, although not nearly as many as
you'd think. Non-Muslims are not expected to fast, and Muslims
generally don't mind if others eat and drink in their presence.
<p>
   In larger cities that get a lot of international visitors, it's
usually no trouble to find an open restaurant or food store during
daylight hours. But out in the countryside, in more remote towns
and villages, it can sometimes be tricky, if not impossible. Your
best bet is to head to the cafe at the nearest railway station:
Islamic travelers are exempt from fasting, and rail station cafes
are usually open.
<p>
   Slaking certain kinds of thirst can be even more problematic.
Even in downtown Cairo, the bar in our hotel refused to serve
alcohol during Ramadan  &MD;  even after the sun went down.
<p>
   The scarcity of open restaurants can pose a problem for
diabetics, such as my wife, Jeri, who must eat at regular
intervals. In Al Jadida, Morocco, we huddled on a remote corner of
the beach at lunchtime and furtively peeled an orange. Soon we
attracted a large crowd of local youths, who wagged their fingers
at us and made disapproving sounds.
<p>
   It was no use trying to explain that we weren't Muslims, or that
their faith excuses people with legitimate medical needs from
fasting. We hurried back to our hotel, locked the door, drew the
drapes and ate our lunch, feeling slightly guilty.
<p>
   ~~
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1748EST
</TRAILER>
