<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9437 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BRE-X-BARRICK-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0752 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BRE-X-BARRICK-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SOME BRE-X MINERALS HOLDERS SEE BARRICK ACCORD WITHIN 30 DAYS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Paul Brent &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Calgary, Alberta, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Some Bre-X Minerals
Ltd. shareholders said they expect the company and Barrick Gold
Corp. to reach agreement on developing a giant Indonesian gold
deposit within a government-imposed deadline.
<p>
   Bre-X and Barrick submitted a joint development plan to
Indonesian officials on Dec. 16, about three weeks after the
government said Bre-X must sell 75 percent of its holding in the
Busang gold find to Barrick.
<p>
   Indonesian Mines Minister Ida Bagus Sudjana added another demand
in a Jan. 17 letter to the companies, telling them they have a
month to come to terms with Bre-X's local partners, who own 10
percent of Busang.
<p>
   While Bre-X would prefer to hold an auction for any stake in
Busang, ``Barrick has an inside track and will strike a deal
somehow,'' said John Madden of Keystone Investments of Boston,
which holds Bre-X shares.
<p>
   At stake is Bre-X's 90 percent interest in the world's richest
gold find, a field on the island of Borneo that contains at least
57 million ounces of gold and perhaps as much as 100 million
ounces, analysts said.
<p>
   Bre-X shares rose C$0.05 to C$22.65. Barrick shares fell by
C$0.60 to C$35.55.
<p>
   The Indonesia letter is bad news for Placer Dome Inc., analysts
said. Placer Dome, one of the world's top 10 gold producers, last
week attempted to elbow its way into the Busang sweepstakes, making
an unsolicited C$6.7 billion (US$5 billion) bid for Bre-X.
``Unfortunately, Placer is out,'' said Dan Leonard, portfolio
manager with Denver's Invesco Trust Co., which owns 900,000 Bre-X
shares and could benefit if an auction led to a higher price for
Bre-X. ``The Indonesian government is holding a gun to the heads of
Bre-X and Barrick.'' Placer Dome shares fell C$0.70 to C$27.60.
<p>
   The bid by Vancouver, British Columbia-based Placer, which
offered Indonesia a 40 percent interest in Busang, will force
Barrick to increase its offer to Bre-X and Busang's 10 percent
owners PT Askatindo Karya Minerals and PT Amsya Lyna, Leonard said.
<p>
   To be sure, the Indonesia government, ruled by President
Suharto, could still change the rules for any company interested in
Busang.
<p>
   Local businessman Mohammad Hasan, a close friend of President
Suharto, purchased a controlling stake in Bre-X's minority partners
recently. Hasan, who has said he favors an open bidding process,
encouraged Placer Dome to make its bid, a Placer Dome official
said.
<p>
   ``The open auction process is in the works,'' said Greg Chorny
of Aurora, Ontario, who owns 1.5 million Bre-X shares. Chorny, who
says he plans to sue Barrick, said he expects Barrick to be cut out
of the negotiations on Busang.
<p>
   A Barrick spokesman said the company believes it has the support
of the Indonesian government and declined to comment on Hasan or on
Chorny. In the last month, the company said it is better equipped
than any of its potential competitors to finance and operate a gold
mine on the scale of Busang.
<p>
   ``The government wants the most money and they want it developed
as quick as possible,'' said analyst Catherine Gignac of Deacon
Capital Corp. ``The safest bet is with Barrick.''
<p>
   Hasan's influence may yet open the way for an auction involving
Placer and other mining companies, such as Teck Corp. of Vancouver
and Newmont Gold Mining of Denver, Fowler said.
<p>
   Bre-X officials said they will not discuss the new Indonesian
deadline in detail. ``We remain anxious to join forces with local
and foreign partners acceptable to the government of Indonesia,''
David Walsh, chairman of the Calgary-based exploration company,
said in a statement.
<p>
   The Indonesian government hasn't given final approval for
Bre-X's Contract of Work application. The Jan. 17 letter instructs
Bre-X and Barrick to form a new corporate entity and submit an
application for a new Contract of Work.
<p>
   The delay on Busang has caused a backlog in mining applications
and slowed down foreign investment in the resource-rich and
capital-poor country, analysts said.
<p>
   ``The mining business in Indonesia has stopped because of this
long delay,'' said John Eng, analyst with Maison Placements Canada
Inc. ``There are 70-odd contract of work applications that are
currently waiting for final approval. Not only is the government
frustrated but other mining companies are frustrated.''
</TEXT>
