<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=ttc-z> A9438 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-IMPLANTS-2nd </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0382 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DIABETES-IMPLANTS-2ndtake-LADN &QL; 
WESTLAKE VILLAGE, Calif.: review procedure. &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   If Pope's treatment proves suitable for humans, the
ramifications could be huge.
<p>
   Diabetes, a disorder that results in a partial or complete
inability of the body to use its main fuel, glucose, affects about
16 million Americans. Only about half are even aware that they have
the disease.
<p>
   Ignoring the condition can be devastating to the body, since the
disease can gradually damage blood vessels and tissues with
devastating long-term complications. Those complications can
include destruction of the eyes, kidneys and nerves.
<p>
   The disease kills about 400,000 Americans annually.
<p>
   Here is how Pope's process works:
<p>
   The ceramic material and islets containing a collection of
insulin-secreting pancreatic cells, harvested from donor mice, are
mixed and suspended in a special solution at the top of a drip
tower. As the ceramic material moves down through the solution in
the tower, it forms around the cells.
<p>
   By the time it reaches the bottom, the bead has formed.
<p>
   The beads are then implanted into the mice being treated.
<p>
   While the beads look solid to the naked eye, the walls are shot
through with pores large enough for glucose molecules to enter and
trigger the insulin-producing process, much the same way as in a
fully functioning pancreas.
<p>
   Pope says he hopes to make a device that will last at least a
year and be possible to implant just under the skin in humans.
<p>
   Pope has invested about $200,000 of his company's money on the
project and will go to the venture capital market for funds as the
research expands and the tests become more complicated.
<p>
   He has been involved in sol-gel research since 1981 and formed
his Matech materials-technology company in 1989. The company does
materials consulting and develops advanced materials and optical
coatings with special properties.
<p>
   The research into diabetes evolved over time.
<p>
   ``It wasn't a crusade for diabetes. My driving force was to
create a whole new class of engineering materials. That was kind of
my grandiose vision,'' Pope said. ``So I essentially looked at
what's the new frontier for this new class of materials.'' &UR; !end! &LR; 
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1748EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0486 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=taf-z> A9441 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0806 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SKI-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Vt., Calif., Mass.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; `PRIMITIVE BIATHLON' ATTRACTS ENTHUSIASTS IN VERMONT &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; By BARBARA LLOYD &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   A new winter diversion has come to the woods of Vermont. Making
use of cross-country ski trails and a hunter's tool, the sport
encourages the sure-footedness of a snowshoer and the eye of a
rifleman.
<p>
   Organized in the Smugglers' Notch area of Vermont, the event is
being called the Primitive Biathlon. Contestants are limited to
18th century gear: single-barrel muzzleloaders or muskets for their
guns, and wooden frame snowshoes. The muskets fire small lead balls
similar to the kind of ammunition used during the Revolutionary
War. The balls and powder are loaded from the end of the gun barrel
using a mounted ramrod.
<p>
   The snowshoes used are heavier and more ungainly than the short,
lightweight metal varieties so popular today. But the older designs
are meant to fit in with the mountain-man image that makes the
Primitive Biathlon unique. In the Olympics, biathlon competitors
use modern rifles and cross-country skis.
<p>
   ``Most towns have torchlight parades and snowmen,'' said Ray
Saloomey, president of the Smugglers' Notch Area Chamber of
Commerce in Jeffersonville, Vt., and founder of the event. ``I
wanted to come up with something different. Most hunters are bored
stiff at this time of year, and are looking for something to do. So
the idea just kind of evolved.''
<p>
   Twenty-five competitors entered the two-day contest upon its
inception last year. Organizers expect at least that many for the
1997 event this weekend.
<p>
   Michael Burke, who lives a quarter-mile down the road from the
race area, was last year's winner. He said that he won because he
never missed a shot in his 90 minutes of competition.
<p>
   ``It was very icy and rainy last year,'' Burke, 49, said.
``There wasn't enough snow on the day I competed for snowshoes, so
we ran. I'm not a fast runner, so I walked and then trotted. I
controlled my breathing, and I tried to stay focused.''
<p>
   The competition, which is open to all contestants who show up
from 9 a.m. to 2 p.m. Saturday and Sunday, requires each contestant
to set off separately in a race against the clock. Along the route,
laid out on cross-country trails at the Sterling Ridge Inn, the
biathletes encounter three firing ranges.
<p>
   The first two are set in the woods, each with a firing line and
three 8-inch metal gongs at a distance of about 50 yards. Each
competitor is allowed three shots to hit a gong. A misfire, when
the gun fails to go off, is counted as a miss.
<p>
   The last firing range is situated in an open field so that
spectators can watch more easily. The final score is based on total
elapsed time with a five-minute credit for each hit.
<p>
   Burke said that he was so taken with the event last year that he
has invited his brother and his 13-year-old nephew to compete this
year. With about 2 feet of snow on the ground, he expects to be
able to don his snowshoes this time.
<p>
   ``It's a spontaneous thing,'' Burke said. ``It's not so much
winning that's important. It's just a very invigorating thing to do
at a very dark time of the year. It's a good outing.''
<p>
   Winter Sports in the Extreme
<p>
   A winter version of the X Games, the extreme sport competition
staged last summer by ESPN television in Rhode Island, is scheduled
to debut Jan. 30 at the Snow Summit Resort in Big Bear Lake, Calif.
<p>
   The four-day event will feature a bevy of new winter sports for
its television coverage. Included is snowboarding, but with more
daring categories than those approved for Olympic competition.
<p>
   Besides a half-pipe  &MD;  the only Olympic-style discipline  &MD;  the X
Games will stage a boarder X contest with six athletes racing down
the mountain at one time; big air  &MD;  which requires the snowboarder
to leap over a 12-foot jump, and freestyle, races in a snowboard
park setting.
<p>
   Other competitions for the 180 athletes expected at the $200,000
X Games are ice climbing; snow bike racing; shovel racing (on
aerodynamic hybrids of the basic shovel); and a ``duathalon,'' a
combination of snowboarding and dry-land competition.
<p>
   Women's Pro Tour Race Set
<p>
   The Women's Professional Ski Tour plans one of its rare night
races Jan. 25 at Jiminy Peak, Mass. The event, the $25,000 Women's
Pro Ski Bowl, lists the race as the tour's only evening competition
this year in the United States.
<p>
   Among the top Alpine skiers racing will be Julie Parisien, 25, a
former U.S. Olympic skier, who currently is No. 1 on the
professional circuit with 55 points, a five-point lead over Camilla
Lundback of Sweden.
<p>
   The giant slalom race is scheduled to begin at 6 p.m. Saturday;
the slalom event will be at 11 a.m. Sunday. As many as 30 women are
expected to compete.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1749EST
</TRAILER>
