<SLUG> BC-WESTERN-RESOURCES-UPD </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0498 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-WESTERN-RESOURCES-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WESTERN DEBT RATINGS CUT BECAUSE OF HOSTILE BID (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Kerry Dooley &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds closing stock price in last paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Western Resources Inc.'s
ratings on debt and preferred stock were cut by Standard &AMP; Poor's
Corp. because of recent planned and completed acquisitions,
including a $3.5 billion hostile bid for ADT Ltd.
<p>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's lowered its ratings on about $1.3 billion in
senior secured debt one notch to ``BBB+'' from ``A-.'' S&AMP;P also cut
ratings on about $300 million in preferred and preference stock one
notch to ``BBB'' from ``BBB+.''
<p>
   Western could face another ratings cut if it buys ADT, which has
ratings of ``BBB-,'' said Richard Cortwright, a director with the
debt-rating company. Western's ratings have been on watch since
April 15, the day after it made a hostile bid for a neighboring
utility, Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co.
<p>
   ``No matter what, this company won't come out of this with an
`A-' rating,'' Cortwright said. ``We thought it was time we
recognized that.''
<p>
   Western could keep its senior secured rating at ``BBB+'' by
buying Kansas City Power, for which it made a $1.9 billion offer,
Cortwright said.
<p>
   Kansas City Power has a senior secured rating of ``A,'' two
notches above Western's new grade. Western, which operates two
Kansas electricity and natural gas utilities, has said it could
save about $1 billion in 10 years by combining with Kansas City
Power.
<p>
   Although the Kansas City Power board agreed to meet with Western
to discuss the offer, no decision has been made, said Michel
Philipp, a Western spokeswoman.
<p>
   Western is likely to acquire ADT before it purchases Kansas City
Power, even though the ADT board is fighting Western's bid,
Cortwright said. Winning the regulatory approval for a combination
of two electric utilities can take more than a year, he said.
<p>
   Western said it wasn't surprised by the ratings cut because the
company has been expanding into new businesses, Philipp said.
Western, once primarily the parent company of two Kansas utilities,
has expanded into security monitoring to prepare for deregulation
of power sales. The new businesses don't have the guaranteed
returns that utilities long enjoyed, Philipp said.
<p>
   Nor are utilities likely to have those guarantees much longer,
she said. Congress this year is expected to deregulate power sales,
letting consumer choose their power suppliers in much the same way
they currently choose long-distance telephone providers.
<p>
   ``The energy business no longer has a monopoly,'' Philipp said.
More utilities are likely to see their bond ratings fall, she said.
<p>
   S&AMP;P also said Western Resources used too much debt to acquire
monitored security businesses, other than ADT. Western also
prolonged a delay in issuing much-needed common equity, S&AMP;P said.
<p>
   Western rose 1/4 to 31 1/8.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1751EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
