<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9464 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-US-COMMODITIES-CLOSE2 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0974 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-COMMODITIES-CLOSE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. COMMODITIES: COFFEE SOARS ON SUPPLY CONCERN (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Susan Miller &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds final prices, updates indexes in second paragraph)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Coffee jumped to a five-month
high amid concern that a Colombian dockworkers' strike and a
disappointing Brazilian crop would reduce exports from the world's
two top producers.
<p>
   On other markets, gold and soybeans fell. The Commodity Research
Bureau index dropped 0.08 to 240.76, while the energy-weighted
Goldman Sachs Commodity Index gained 0.69 to 209.06.
<p>
   A strike at Colombia's key Pacific port of Buenaventura today
entered its ninth day, delaying shipment of at least 210,000
132-pound bags, said a spokesman for Colombia's Coffee Growers
Federation.
<p>
   At the same time, concern is mounting that Brazil's coffee crop
will fall well short of U.S. Department of Agriculture projections
of 27.0 million bags. Brazilian officials said Monday that the
nation's harvest, normally one-fourth of global supplies, could be
as low as 18 million bags.
<p>
   ``It's difficult to assess the Brazilian crop,'' said Carl
Walker, an analyst at InterAmerican Commodities in Houston. ``That
the prospects for a smaller crop have been advertised is having an
effect on this market,'' he said, while ``the Colombian coffee just
isn't moving.''
<p>
   Coffee for March delivery rose 5.65 cents to $1.353 a pound on
the Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange, the highest price for an active
contract since Aug. 26.
<p>
   While many traders doubt the accuracy of the Brazilian
forecasts, lean supplies leave little cushion for a shortfall.
Exchange-monitored warehouses as of Jan. 20 held 22,363 bags, about
100,000 fewer than a year ago.
<p>
   Speculation that the Association of Coffee Producing Countries,
which represents 70 percent of world coffee output and will meet
tomorrow in Brazil, will agree to reduce exports fueled the rally.
<p>
   ``If they decide to cut exports, prices could go higher, given
that roasters' stock levels are fairly low,'' said Szolt Papp, a
commodity analyst at UBS Ltd. in London.
<p>
   Gold dropped to its lowest price since September 1993 as the
dollar surged against several major currencies, raising the cost to
foreign investors.
<p>
   The dollar climbed to a 47-month high against then yen and a 2
1/2-year high against the deutsche mark, powered by expectations
that industrial nations won't act to halt its rise.
<p>
   Gold prices, suffering from forecasts for muted inflation and
the prospect of central bank sales, are down 4.7 percent so far
this year as investors look for more attractive returns elsewhere.
<p>
   ``Gold has suffered all around the world from asset
relocation,'' said Bridget Fraser, a vice president of
commodity-based derivatives at Bankers Trust in New York. ``The
traditional gold holders are looking for alternative investments --
the outlook for gold isn't great. Prices are going lower.''
<p>
   Gold for February delivery fell $2.10 to $351.70 an ounce on the
New York Mercantile Exchange's Comex division, its lowest closing
price since Sept. 17, 1993.
<p>
   Also, Bema Gold Corp. announced plans to double production at a
mine in northern Chile during the next few years. The Refugio mine
has the potential to produce 500,000 ounces of gold a year,
compared with its target for 1997 of 240,000 ounces.
<p>
   Soybean futures fell amid expectations that recent rain in South
America replenished soil moisture, promising a bumper harvest.
<p>
   As much as 3 inches of rain last weekend fell on the world's
second-largest soybean crop, with the greatest amounts in key
growing areas of southern Brazil. Additional water is on the way.
Weather Services Corp. said scattered rains are likely in southern
Brazil through the weekend, and chances are increasing for showers
or thundershowers early next week.
<p>
   The rains could end concern that dry weather during the past
month would stunt development of the soybean crop, second in size
to the U.S. harvest.
<p>
   ``People don't believe we have a weather problem in South
America,'' said Don Roose, analyst at U.S. Commodities Inc. in West
Des Moines, Iowa. ``We think it's almost back to ideal, and that
has set the market back.''
<p>
   Soybeans for March delivery on the Chicago Board of Trade fell
to $7.405 a bushel, down 6.25 cents.
<p>
   Other commodities settled as follow:
Precious Metals: February Gold down $2.10 to $351.70 an ounce March
Silver up 0.08 cent to $4.723 an ounce April Platinum down $1.70 to
$359.80 an ounce March Palladium up 5 cents to $123.60 an ounce
Livestock: February Live Cattle down 0.475 cent to 65.375 cents a
pound March Feeder Cattle down 0.375 cent at 69.15 cents a pound
February Pork Bellies up 0.225 cent to 75.525 cents a pound
February Hogs down 0.05 cent to 75.35 cents a pound
Grains: March Wheat down 3 cents to $3.7925 a bushel March Corn
down 0.5 cent at $2.705 a bushel March Soybeans down 6.25 cents at
$7.405 a bushel March Oats down 0.75 cent to $1.54 a bushel
Food and Fiber: March Coffee up 5.65 cents to $1.353 a pound March
Sugar unchanged at 10.17 cents a pound March Cocoa down $35 at
$1,290 a metric ton March Cotton up 1.1 cents to 74.10 cents a
pound March Orange Juice up 0.2 cent to 86.85 cents a pound
Energy: March Crude Oil up 2 cents at $24.24 a barrel February
Henry Hub Natural Gas down 0.8 cent to $2.908 for each million
British thermal units February Gasoline up 0.78 cent to 68.22 cents
a gallon February Heating Oil up 0.86 cent to 66.89 cents a gallon
February California-Oregon Border Electricity up 41 cents to $13.64
a megawatt hour February Palo Verde Electricity up 31 cents to
$15.65 a megawatt hour
Others: March Lumber up $8.50 to $425.80 per 1,000 board feet March
Copper up 1.05 cents to $1.073 a pound
</TEXT>
