<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9470 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-US-DOLLAR-UPDATE2-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0858 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-DOLLAR-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DOLLAR RISES ON U.S. ECONOMY, G-7 ACQUIESCENCE (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Dan Weil &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds information about the U.S. economy in third paragraph.
Updates exchange rates, final update.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The dollar jumped to a 47-month
high versus the yen and a 31-month peak against the mark, bolstered
by U.S. economic strength and expectations that leading industrial
nations won't stand in the way of its rise.
<p>
   ``The beat goes on for the dollar,'' said James McGroarty, chief
currency manager of Potomac Babson Inc., a money management firm
whose parent, David L. Babson Inc., manages $13 billion of assets.
Potomac Babson bought dollars at 1.6360 marks today, McGroarty
said. ``We think this move has further to go.''
<p>
   In the past month, the dollar rose 6 percent against the
deutsche mark and 4 percent against the yen, buoyed by reports of
strong job growth and industrial output.
<p>
   It surged to 1.6445 marks today, its highest since June 15,
1994, and to 119.18 yen, its highest since Feb. 19, 1993. It also
climbed to a 32-month peak of 1.4358 Swiss francs.
<p>
   In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 1.6405 marks,
up from 1.6298 marks late yesterday in New York, and at 118.93 yen,
up from 117.99 yen.
<p>
   The U.S. currency got a boost as Russia's parliament voted to
discuss a demand for President Boris Yeltsin's resignation because
of his poor health. Signs of political turmoil in Russia often hurt
the mark because Germany is Russia's largest trading partner and
creditor.
<p>
   Expectations that the U.S. economy will keep outpacing its
rivals, luring global investors, are at the root of the dollar's
recent gains, traders said.
<p>
   ``The U.S. economy is strong enough so that the next move in
interest rates will be up, while Germany's economic recovery is
anemic, and Japan's economy continues to weaken,'' McGroarty said.
<p>
   The economic slump in Japan ``will keep the dollar well
supported,'' said Jeff Berger, director of foreign exchange for
AlliedSignal Inc., an auto-parts maker based in Morristown, New
Jersey. ``We see the dollar strong through the first half of the
year.''
<p>
   Nor do traders expect the world's most powerful central banks to
stand in the dollar's way. The Group of Seven leading industrial
nations ``isn't holding the dollar back,'' said McGroarty of
Potomac Babson. The G-7 are the U.S., Japan, Germany, Britain,
France, Italy and Canada.
<p>
   U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said repeatedly during the
past two weeks that a strong dollar is in the national interest,
making clear the U.S. isn't backing away from its support for the
currency.
<p>
   ``The Treasury secretary has been consistent, and Fed governors
have been talking about the benefits of a strong dollar too,''
McGroarty said.
<p>
   To be sure, Ernst Welteke, a Bundesbank council member, said
today that the dollar is unlikely to rise much further. Yet his
remarks had little effect on the dollar, partly because he also
said the German central bank doesn't plan to sell dollars for marks
to stem its ascent.
<p>
   With Germany's economic recovery still sputtering, the
Bundesbank will likely tolerate a weaker mark, which would boost
German exports by making them cheaper in foreign currency terms,
traders said. Germany's economy grew only 1.4 percent last year.
<p>
   ``Germany's economy is going nowhere fast,'' said Richard Koss,
currency strategist at MFR Inc., a money management and consulting
firm. He predicted the Bundesbank will cut interest rates this
quarter to spark the economy. Lower rates would hurt the mark by
making German deposits and bonds less attractive to global
investors.
<p>
   In Japan, while some officials have warned against an
``excessive'' decline by the yen, they haven't clearly stated that
it has fallen too far.
<p>
   With Japan's economy stagnant, many traders say officials there
favor a weaker yen to boost exports. The economy grew at only a 0.4
percent annualized rate in the third quarter, and its stock market
has plummeted 7 percent so far this year.
<p>
   By comparison, many analysts forecast the U.S. economy grew at a
3.5 percent annualized rate in the fourth quarter -- and stocks
rose to records this week.
<p>
   ``The perception of U.S. economic strength may allow the dollar
to continue higher,'' said Kevin Raphael, manager of foreign
exchange at Rabobank Nederland.
<p>
   He said it could reach 1.68 marks and 120 yen in the next month.
<p>
   Elsewhere, the British pound fell almost 2 percent against the
dollar after the U.K. reported a 0.8 percent drop in December
retail sales. The news quelled speculation that the government will
raise interest rates soon.
<p>
   Sterling fell to $1.6355 in late New York trading from $1.6644
late yesterday in New York. Earlier, it fell to $1.6298, its lowest
since Dec. 5.
<p>
   The dollar rose to 1.4289 Swiss francs from 1.4196 francs
yesterday and to 5.5360 French francs from 5.4960 francs. It gained
to 1,598 Italian lire from 1,582 lire. The Canadian dollar fell to
74.74 U.S. cents from 74.83 cents yesterday.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1755EST
</TRAILER>
