<TEXT>
<p>
   Tokyo, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- The following stories appeared in
major Japanese newspapers this morning:
Front page:
Mazda, Ford Motor Agree to Share Engines to Cut Production Costs
Mazda Motor Corp. and Ford Motor Co. agreed to share engines to cut
production costs. Mazda, which is owned 33.4 percent by Ford, will
make engines for small vehicles while Ford will make all other
engines. Mazda will start making its first such ''world engines''
by 1999. (Nihon Keizai)(For Mazda, see 7261 JP Equity &QR; 
CN; for Ford, see F US Equity &QR;  CN)
Japan to Reduce Red Tape Involving Mergers and Acquisitions
<p>
   A Justice Ministry committee yesterday said the government
should simply administrative regulations to promote corporate
mergers and acquisitions. The advisory committee called for repeal
of a requirement that merged companies report the mergers at a
special shareholders' meeting. The committee also said the
government should lift requirements that the companies individually
report the mergers to their creditors. (Nihon Keizai)
Other news:
Japan Banks to Report Capital Adequacy Ratios Under New Standard
<p>
   Japan's major commercial banks, known as city banks, will
disclose their capital adequacy ratios under a new government
standard when they report their earnings for the half year to
September. The Finance Ministry will compile the new method of
assessing the banks' capital adequacy ratios by the end of this
month. (Nihon Keizai, p.7)
Sony Music Entertainment to Report 39% Rise in Group Net Profit
<p>
   Sony Music Entertainment Inc. is expected to report group net
profit of 14 billion yen ($117.6 million) for this fiscal year
through March 1997, up 39 percent on the year. That's higher than
the company's most recent estimate of 12.8 billion yen. The profit
increase is due to improving earnings of Sony Computer
Entertainment, a subsidiary that makes video game machines. (Nihon
Keizai, p.21)(For Sony Music Entertainment, see 7930 JP Equity &QR; 
CN)
NCR Japan to Report 16% Increase in Current Profit This Year
<p>
   NCR Japan Ltd., a computer company affiliated with NCR Corp. of
the U.S., will likely report current, or pretax, profit of 5.2
billion yen for this fiscal year through December 1997, up 16
percent from an expected current profit for the previous year. The
company's sales are rising thanks to increasing demand for its
computers by financial institutions and distribution companies.
(Nihon Keizai, 21)(For NCR Japan, see 7930 JP Equity &QR;  CN, For NCR,
see
NCR US Equity &QR;  CN)
Story illustration: to graph the stock of the companies mentioned
in the story, type the company tickers and then type Equity &QR;  GP
</TEXT>
