<STORYID cat=w pri=r sel=ttj-z> A9477 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HUD-CUOMO-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0712 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HUD-CUOMO-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GOP PANEL ACCORDS HUD NOMINEE ANDREW CUOMO FAVORABLE TREATMENT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DAN FREEDMAN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Hearst Newspapers &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  The Department of Housing and Urban Development is
not wildly popular with Senate GOP lawmakers, but fortunately for
Andrew Cuomo their attitude does not appear to extend to his
nomination as HUD secretary.
<p>
   Republican senators on the Senate Banking, Housing and Urban
Affairs Committee sang Cuomo's praises Wednesday at a confirmation
hearing, even as they heaped vitriol on the $19.5 billion agency
that 1996 GOP presidential nominee Bob Dole called ``one of the
last bastions of Socialism.''
<p>
   HUD oversees 3,400 public housing authorities, their 1.25
million units providing shelter to three million mainly poor
people. But GOP critics charge many housing programs have failed to
help those in need move out of poverty.
<p>
   ``HUD has failed in many areas and in many instances it has lost
sight of its mission,'' said Sen. Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C., who last
year introduced legislation to abolish the agency.
<p>
   Nevertheless, Faircloth said he had heard many admiring comments
from diverse sources about Cuomo, 39, assistant HUD secretary for
community planning and development, and son of former New York Gov.
Mario Cuomo.
<p>
   ``You certainly have an impressive record and an impressive
group of friends,'' Faircloth told Cuomo, evoking laughter in the
wood-paneled hearing room.
<p>
   Committee chairman Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., told Cuomo he
supported the nomination and no one dissented.
<p>
   If confirmed, Cuomo would succeed departing HUD Secretary Henry
Cisneros, who won praise from committee members for improving the
agency and rethinking the role of government in housing the
nation's poor.
<p>
   Supported at the hearing by his wife Kerry and his mother-in-law
Ethel Kennedy, widow of legendary former senator and attorney
general Robert F. Kennedy, Cuomo attempted to reassure the
Republicans of his moderation.
<p>
   HUD's goal must be ``the development of self-sufficiency, not
the perpetuation of government programs,'' Cuomo said.
Nevertheless, he said, the agency cannot forget the ``millions of
Americans who have not experienced the American dream.''
<p>
   The agency must plan toward ``a future ... in which no person is
left behind and in which no community is forgotten,'' Cuomo said.
<p>
   Under Cisneros, HUD encouraged greater home ownership and
developed partnerships with home-building groups such as Habitat
for Humanity International.
<p>
   HUD, long known as a bloated bureaucracy, also slimmed down,
reducing its payroll from 13,500 employees in 1993 to 10,400 now.
By the year 2000, HUD is to have a workforce of 7,500.
<p>
   The agency accelerated demolition of massive urban housing
projects that Cisneros admitted had failed to relieve the poverty
and social difficulties of the urban poor and minorities who lived
in them.
<p>
   But GOP lawmakers in Congress called for more radical measures,
including repeal of the Housing Act of 1937, the New Deal-era
legislation underlying much of the federal government's involvement
in urban housing. The legislation was sidetracked last year but
Republican senators on Wednesday hinted it could be revived this
year.
<p>
   Cuomo demurred when asked his view on repealing the 1937 law,
saying there were more than 600 references to it in other
legislation and the agency would have to study the possible
aftershocks of such a massive overhaul.
<p>
   D'Amato and other Republicans challenged Cuomo on how HUD would
handle an impending crisis in funding the agency's Section 8 rental
assistance program, which gives rent vouchers to poor tenants in
public housing or subsidies to landlords of private units.
<p>
   According to a chart prepared by the committee staff, the cost
of renewing the rental assistance contracts will rise from $3.6
billion this year to an estimated $16.4 billion by 2002, even as
HUD's $19.5 billion budget will continue to shrink.
<p>
   Cuomo said handling the crunch is a matter of ``making tough
budget choices.''
<p>
   Nevertheless, he said, government has to recognize that failure
to renew at least a portion of the contracts would result in
``displacing families.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1757EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0493 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9478 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINE-STOCKS-CLOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0523 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ARGENTINE-STOCKS-CLOSE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ARGENTINE STOCKS DECLINE AS INVESTORS SWITCH TO BONDS (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Richard Jarvie &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates index levels, number of issues that rose and closed
unchanged, closing prices and movements of Perez Companc, YPF and
Telecom Argentina Stet-France Telecom.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Buenos Aires, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Argentine stocks fell as
investors, encouraged by excess demand at today's government sale
of $2 billion of bonds, sold shares to buy bonds.
<p>
   ``They saw more profit potential in bonds on the back of the
government sale,'' said Maximiliano Goff, an equity markets analyst
at Banco Rio de la Plata.
<p>
   Demand at today's bond sale, the biggest ever by Argentina, was
three times the amount of bonds on offer.
<p>
   The Merval index of the 24 most-traded shares fell 1.03 percent
to 679.47, while the general index slipped 0.8 percent to
19,636.18.
<p>
   Of the 73 issues traded, 22 rose, 37 declined and 14 closed
unchanged. Volume fell to 17.4 million pesos from 23.6 million
pesos yesterday.
<p>
   The biggest loser was oil and gas producer Astra Capsa, down
2.56 percent to 1.9 pesos. Perez Companc SA, another oil and gas
company, fell 1.7 percent to 7.22 pesos. h The country's other
major oil and gas company, YPF SA, fell 0.35 percent to 28 pesos.
<p>
   Among stocks widely traded abroad, telephone company Telefonica
de Argentina SA dropped 1.73 percent to 2.83 pesos. Telecom
Argentina Stet-France Telecom SA, another phone company, fell 0.44
percent to 4.52 pesos.
<p>
   Rising U.S. interest rates also hurt Argentina stock prices.
<p>
   The yield on the benchmark 30-year U.S. Treasury bond rose to
6.82 percent from 6.78 percent yesterday as Wall Street firms
struggled to sell $17.5 billion of two-year notes they bought at
today's Treasury auction and prepared for another auction tomorrow.
<p>
   Rising bond yields can draw investors away from emerging
equities markets like Argentina.
<p>
   ``Stocks felt the lack of support from the strong inflow of
foreign funds that has been a feature in recent weeks,'' said Goff.
<p>
   Only three companies included in the Merval index rose.
<p>
   Pulp and paper company Celulosa Argentina SA rose 1.56 percent
to 0.26 pesos, oil and public services company Sociedad Comercial
del Plata SA gained 1.4 percent to 2.7 pesos and IRSA Inversiones y
Representaciones SA, a real estate company in which hedge fund
manager George Soros is a major shareholder, rose 0.93 percent to
3.23 pesos.
<p>
   Among stocks not included in the Merval index, auto parts
company Mirgor Sacifia soared 10 percent to 20.9 pesos after
winning three contracts to supply vehicle manufacturers with air
conditioning and heating systems.
<p>
   Paint company Colorin Industria de Materiales Sinteticos SA rose
8.33 percent to 1.3 pesos while veterinary drug company Instituto
Rosenbusch SA also rose 8.33 percent to 0.65 pesos.
<p>
   Farm machinery company Agrometal SA rose 7.87 percent to 1.78
pesos on expectations the company's sales will climb as farmers
spend the proceeds of this year's record harvest on new equipment.
</TEXT>
