<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-STOCKS-CLOSE </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0337 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COLOMBIA-STOCKS-CLOSE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COLOMBIAN STOCKS FALL ON RISING U.S. TENSIONS (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By David Scanlan and Andres Salgado &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates with final Bogota and Medellin results.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Bogota, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Colombian stocks fell for a sixth
day amid concern the U.S. would impose trade sanctions to protest
the country's drug trade.
<p>
   ``The tendency is still for prices to fall, and this may
continue a bit more (in coming days),'' said Guillermo Espinosa, a
trader at Correval SA brokerage.
<p>
   The Bogota IBB index fell 23.55 points, or 2.39 percent, to
963.01. Trading volume was 1.79 billion pesos ($1.8 million), down
from the 1996 daily trading average of 2.3 billion pesos. Of the 11
stocks that changed prices, two rose and nine fell.
<p>
   In Medellin, the Ibomed index fell 613.72 points, or 3.9
percent, to 15,103.75. Trading volume was 1.21 billion pesos. Of
the 12 stocks that changed prices, four rose and eight fell.
<p>
   Among movers in Bogota, Bavaria SA fell 8.5 percent to 5,200
pesos. Bancoquia fell 7.9 percent to 2,423 pesos. Cadenalco SA fell
5.6 percent to 850 pesos, and Coltabaco fell 8.4 percent to 3,500
pesos.
<p>
   In Medellin, the main movers included Noel SA, which fell 8.3
percent to 3,483 pesos. Cia. Nacional Chocolates SA fell 8.5
percent to 8,890 pesos, and Exito SA fell 10 percent to 3,056
pesos.
<p>
   Washington is upset with Colombia for imposing light sentences
on two top leaders of the Cali drug cartel. That could lead to
trade sanctions when Washington issues its annual report on the
global drug trade March 1.
<p>
   The six-day stock slump follows 18 days of increases that sent
the Bogota index soaring 26 percent in peso terms.
<p>
   In New York, Banco Ganadero fell 7/8 to 28 1/4 after the bank
reported net income rose 6 percent in 1996 from 1995, below
expectations.
<p>
   In Bogota, the peso was weaker today, closing at 1,030 pesos to
the dollar, compared with 1,023 pesos yesterday.
</TEXT>
