<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9486 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EARNS-BANKS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0638 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-BANKS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. BANKS 4TH-QTR EARNINGS MIXED AS CHARGES SKEW RESULTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Marjorie Shaffer, Joseph A. Giannone and Michael Smith &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan.. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. Bancorp reported higher
fourth-quarter earnings as lending surged, while slow loan growth
and a variety of charges ate into profits at CoreStates Financial
Corp., Comerica Inc. and Great Western Financial Corp..
<p>
   CoreStates net income rose 1.7 percent, and Comerica earnings
fell 43 percent to cover the cost of plans to boost profit by
eliminating 1,890 jobs. U.S. Bancorp profit rose 9 percent, while
Great Western, the second-largest U.S. thrift, said earnings fell
14 percent.
<p>
   The earnings roughly met Wall Street analysts' expectations,
helping send their stocks higher.
<p>
   ``They've come in at exactly what we're looking for,'' said John
Laupheimer, a portfolio manager at Massachusetts Financial
Services, a big bank stock investor.
<p>
   The earnings show how U.S. banks and thrifts are trying to boost
profit by cutting costs and buying competitors. The acquisition of
West One Bancorp allowed U.S. Bancorp to cut expanses, while
CoreStates benefited from the purchase of rival Meridian Bancorp.
<p>
   Like Comerica, Great Western recorded charges tied to a plan to
cut 800 jobs and revamp its lagging mortgage business.
<p>
   Philadelphia-based CoreStates said net income rose to $195.5
million, or 91 cents a share, from $192.1 million or 87 cents a
share. The earnings were slightly below Wall Street's expectations
of 94 cents a share. The stock rose 1 1/8 to 52 5/8.
<p>
   Before charges tied to merger with Meridian, earnings rose 2.8
percent to $201.6 million, or 93 cents a share, from $196.1
million, or 89 cents.
<p>
   Revenue fell 1.3 percent to $761.5 million from $771.9 million.
Net interest income fell 2.0 percent as net interest margin
declined to 5.51 percent form 5.56 percent.
<p>
   Great Western said earnings before charges and gains fell to $85
million, or 58 cents a share, from $98.6 million, or 66 cents, in
the last three months of 1995. After the charges and gains, the
Chatsworth, California- based thrift reported earnings of $5.13
million, or 1 cent a share.
<p>
   The results exceeded analysts' expectations of 56 cents a share,
and Great Western shares rose 5/8 to 32 1/8.
<p>
   Net interest income fell 4.5 percent to $335.0 million, as
revenue from mortgage-backed securities fell. Noninterest income
rose 7.2 percent to $114.1 million, as fees from retail banking
surged
<p>
   Portland, Oregon-based U.S. Bancorp said net income rose to $120
million, or 79 cents per share, from profit from operations of
$110.5 million, or 71 cents, a year earlier. After
acquisition-related charges, net income in the last three months of
1995 was $21.38 million, or 13 cents a share.
<p>
   The earnings met Wall Street's expectations of 79 cents a share,
and U.S. Bancorp shares rose 1/8 to 45 1/4.
<p>
   Total revenue rose 8.5 percent to $515.6 million, as the bank
raised more fees from customers and paid less for funds.
<p>
   Noninterest expenses fell 2.5 percent to $289.9 million, as
employees salaries and benefits were little changed. Before merger
costs, expenses were down 10 percent.
<p>
   Detroit-based Comerica bank took a $90 million charge against
fourth-quarter earnings to pay for job cuts and other restructuring
moves designed to boost revenue, cut costs and avoid being taken
over.
<p>
   Comerica announced the steps as it reported fourth-quarter
profit from operations rose 14 percent to $121 million, or $1.06 a
share -- a penny shy of Wall Street expectations.
<p>
   Comerica shares were unchanged at 56 1/4.
<p>
   Net interest income rose 3.6 percent to $353.3 million, while
noninterest income fell 5.8 percent to $132.4 million.
</TEXT>
