<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9494 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-COHEN-DEFENSE-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0965 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COHEN-DEFENSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. SENATE CONFIRMS COHEN AS SECRETARY OF DEFENSE (UPDATE3) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Dave Ahearn &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds Cohen quotes)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The U.S. Senate confirmed
former Sen. William Cohen as secretary of defense, putting a
Republican in President Bill Clinton's Cabinet.
<p>
   The Senate's 99-to-0 vote to confirm Cohen today came after the
nominee received unanimous support from his former colleagues on
the Senate Armed Services Committee.
<p>
   Clinton's choice of Cohen, a moderate Republican from Maine, for
the top defense post represented as an olive branch to Congress,
which is controlled by Republicans eager to increase spending on
weapons.
<p>
   Cohen, responding to questions from the Armed Services panel,
said the U.S. needs ``to increase procurement spending as rapidly
as possible,'' though that will be difficult given overall budget
constraints. He said replacing aging weapons systems is a top
priority.
<p>
   Earlier today, committee Republicans praised Cohen, with Arizona
Sen. John McCain citing his ``personal and very deep friendship''
with the former senator and Maine Sen. Olympia Snowe calling him
``a powerful and persuasive voice of reason.''
<p>
   And the panel's ranking Democrat, Carl Levin of Michigan,
commended Clinton for ``his willingness to reach across party lines
to select a creative and independent thinker.''
<p>
   Cohen was the second of Clinton's second-term Cabinet nominees
to be confirmed without opposition today. Earlier this afternoon,
senators confirmed Madeline Albright as the first woman secretary
of state.
<p>
   Cohen takes the helm of the Defense Department at a time when
the outcome of this year's round of spending decisions is pretty
much known. Clinton, in his Feb. 6 budget request, likely will seek
$258.8 billion for defense, about $9 billion less that the $268
billion Congress has already recommended. Republicans have the
votes to add several billion dollars of the extra money they seek.
<p>
   Democrats and Republicans agree that the military, after years
of shrinking budgets in the wake of the Cold War's end, now needs
to replace or upgrade aging weapons and other equipment.
<p>
   ``We must not lose sight of the fact,'' Cohen said today, that
the purpose of the military force structure ``is to ensure that our
armed forces can fight and win a nation's wars.''
<p>
   Republican Sen. Dan Coats of Indiana, however, used the Armed
Services panel's confirmation hearing to blast 12 years of defense
spending cuts.
<p>
   ``We must work to cut unnecessary waste from the defense
budget,'' Coats said, ``but I do not believe that haphazard
reduction is appropriate.''
<p>
   Some major decisions on weapons purchases, such as starting to
develop a multi-billion-dollar Joint Strike Fighter, the purchase
of F/A-18 E/F fighters from McDonnell Douglas Corp., and
commissioning of a Seawolf nuclear submarine from General Dynamics
Corp.'s Electric Boat Division at Groton, Connecticut, have been
resolved.
<p>
   Boeing Co. and Lockheed Martin Corp. were chosen in November to
compete for the Joint Strike Fighter, and the program, which could
cost at least $100 billion during the next three decades, is
certain to draw special congressional scrutiny.
<p>
   Cohen endorsed the strike fighter, saying ``joint development
and procurement efforts make a lot of sense'' by eliminating
duplication of weapons among the military branches.
<p>
   Cohen also endorsed Pentagon purchases of anti-missile systems,
both to protect the United States from intercontinental ballistic
attacks -- a national defense system -- and to protect troops
engaged in battles around the world, called Theater Missile
Defense. In the current military budget for the fiscal year ending
Sept. 30, Congress provided $3.5 billion for ballistic missile
defense. Companies working on the missile defense program include
Lockheed Martin Corp., Raytheon Co., General Motors Corp., and
Rockwell International Corp. In addition, Lockheed Martin is
authorized to receive $277.8 million for the Army's Theater
High-Altitude Area Defense System.
<p>
   Cohen said the Persian Gulf War demonstrated the wisdom of
``applying coordinated air power to attack the enemy using
precision munitions and stealth aircraft.'' According to Cohen,
``many of our newest systems performed better than expected'' in
the Gulf War.
<p>
   While Cohen didn't mention specific aircraft used in the Gulf
War, a major stealth fighter is Lockheed Martin's F-117.
<p>
   Smaller Pentagon budgets have shrunk the number of players in
the defense contracting industry, with Raytheon Co. buying General
Motors Corp.'s Hughes defense business for $9.5 billion and Boeing
Co. announcing that it'll buy McDonnell Douglas Corp. for $13.3
billion in stock. That transaction would make Seattle-based Boeing
a pre-eminent defense contractor.
<p>
   Such mergers are ``an inevitable result of the defense (weapons)
procurement budget dropping more than 60 percent in real terms in
the last 10 years,'' Cohen said. While he said he doesn't oppose
consolidation in the industry, he said the Pentagon ``should
continue to monitor this situation carefully.''
<p>
   The Pentagon ``is conducting a thorough review of proposed
mergers and acquisitions in the defense industry'' with the aim of
ensuring that ``adequate price and technical competition is
maintained for major weapons systems procurements,'' he said.
<p>
   While the department ``should not encourage specific
corporations to consolidate,'' Cohen said, the Pentagon may profit
from takeovers ``to the extent that consolidation reduces excess
capacity'' in defense-industry plants, because that could ``make
defense companies more efficient and save the taxpayers money.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1801EST
</TRAILER>
