<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tia-z> A9498 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-FOX-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0324 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-GIANTS-FOX-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GIANTS' COACH FASSEL NAMES JOHN FOX DEFENSIVE COORDINATOR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Michael Buteau &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   East Rutherford, New Jersey, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- New York
Giants head coach Jim Fassel named former Oakland Raiders assistant
John Fox defensive coordinator.
<p>
   Fassel, who has a reputation as an offensive expert, said when
he was hired that picking a defensive coordinator would be a
``critical'' decision.
<p>
   Fox, a seven-year NFL coaching veteran, was the Raiders'
defensive coordinator from 1994-95 before leaving the team prior to
the 1996 campaign. He spent this past season as a consultant with
the St. Louis Rams.
<p>
   Fassel, hired by the Giants last week to replace Dan Reeves,
worked with Fox in 1995 when he was quarterbacks coach for the
Raiders.
<p>
   ``It was important to me that I hire someone that I've had some
experience with and someone who I've seen operate as a
coordinator,'' said Fassel, who served as the Arizona Cardinals
offensive coordinator in 1996 before taking the Giants job.
<p>
   ``John brings with him a wealth of experience and knowledge, and
the right kind of personality that I want in a defensive
coordinator,'' Fassel said.
<p>
   Before joining the Raiders, Fox spent two seasons as the San
Diego Chargers defensive backs coach from 1992-93.
<p>
   He began his NFL coaching career with the Pittsburgh Steelers,
where he worked as the team's secondary coach from 1989 to 1991.
The Steelers had the NFL's top-ranked pass defense in 1990 under
Fox.
<p>
   Fox spent three years as defensive coordinator and secondary
coach at the University of Pittsburgh before moving to the NFL. He
was also coached the secondary at Boise State, Long Beach State,
Utah, Kansas and Iowa State and was an assistant at United States
International University and San Diego State.
<p>
   Terms of Fox's contract with the Giants weren't disclosed.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1802EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0498 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9505 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-US-BONDS-CLOSE2-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1323 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-BONDS-CLOSE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. BONDS FALL AS TRADERS SEEK BUYERS FOR NOTES (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Dave Liedtk &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates prices. Adds information on other markets.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. bonds fell as Wall Street
firms struggled to sell the $17.5 billion of two-year notes they
bought from the Treasury, and prepared for another auction
tomorrow.
<p>
   The Treasury sold its notes at a yield of 5.984 percent, less
than the 6 percent yield traders anticipated just before the sale.
The issue recently yielded 6.01 percent.
<p>
   Wall Street ``paid too much'' for the notes, said Rob McCool, a
trader at First Chicago Capital Markets Inc.
<p>
   The lower-than-expected yield at the sale ``doesn't mean the
auction went well,'' because securities firms can't sell the bonds
for as much as they paid the government for them, said Mark
Sauvigne, a trader at Chase Securities Inc. Making the sale more
difficult is the Treasury's sale of $12.5 billion of five-year
notes tomorrow.
<p>
   The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond, little changed prior to the
1 p.m. Eastern time sale, slumped 5/8 point, or $6.25 per $1,000
bond, pushing its yield up 5 basis points to 6.83 percent, the
highest in nine days.
<p>
   Securities firms had an easier time finding buyers for the $2
billion of 20-year global bonds Argentina sold today, as investors
hungry for higher yields snapped up the securities.
<p>
   The country sold the bonds at a yield of 11.375 percent, or
462.5 basis points more than U.S. government debt. That's better
than the 500 basis point difference underwriters expected less than
a week ago. Global bonds are sold simultaneously around the world
and trade 24-hours a day.
<p>
   Bond investors, faced with low yields and high prices in many
other parts of the world, ``have got to buy high-yield and emerging
markets debt,'' said Carl Ericson, head of $6 billion in taxable
fixed income at Colonial Advisory Services in Boston. Argentina has
``to make hay while the sun shines.''
<p>
   Bond investors failed to take much comfort from a government
report showing a drop in new home starts and a Federal Reserve
study suggesting the economy is still growing with little
inflation. Instead they fretted about demand for all the new
Treasury debt.
<p>
   With all the supply, ``people have got a pretty bearish
viewpoint right now,'' said David Hoffman, who manages $300 million
in bonds at Brandywine Asset Management in Wilmington, Delaware.
<p>
   Wall Street firms often push yields higher before the Treasury
sells debt to try to stir up demand from investors.
<p>
   ``The reaction to the two-year is burdened by the prospect of
more supply coming in the pipeline,'' said Tony Crescenzi, a trader
at Miller Tabak Hirsch &AMP; Co. ``Even with good results, the market
is not trading well off them,'' he said.
<p>
   Traders said comments from Fed Governor Susan Phillips in a
Market News interview hurt bonds earlier in the day. Phillips
suggested that the Fed might not wait for a rise in the core
consumer price index before boosting rates.
<p>
   ``Phillips' comments were extremely bearish. They lend support
to the believers who think that the Fed will still have to
tighten,'' or raise rates, said Todd Speiser, a trader at Aubrey G.
Lanston &AMP; Co.
<p>
   The Fed hasn't changed bank lending rates since January 1996,
when it cut the so-called federal funds target by a quarter of a
percentage point to 5.25 percent. The Fed's policy-making Federal
Open Market Committee next meets on Feb. 4-5.
<p>
   Bonds got only a brief fillip after the government reported a
bigger-than-expected drop in December housing starts.
<p>
   The Commerce Department said housing starts fell by 12.2 percent
in December to an annual rate of 1.329 million. Analysts surveyed
by Bloomberg News on average expected a decline of 2.8 percent. For
the year starts of new houses rose 8.8 percent to 1.474 million,
the highest in eight years.
<p>
   ``By and large the numbers tell me the economy is not going
gangbusters and not falling off a cliff and that's what (Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan) said in his testimony,'' to the Senate
Budget Committee yesterday, said Robert Alley, who manages about
$2.5 billion at AIM Advisors Inc. in Houston.
<p>
   That should help temper concern that the Fed will soon raise
borrowing rates, some investors said.
<p>
   ``The Fed's likely to be on hold,'' said Alley, who's been
buying bonds lately as he receives cash in his fund. ``We're adding
bonds.''
<p>
   The Fed's study of regional economic activity, commonly known as
the beige book, found only ``scattered evidence'' that the robust
U.S. job market is pushing wages higher. It found no signs that
consumer prices are rising at a faster pace, with the exception of
energy prices.
<p>
   ``It more or less confirms the general impression that the
economy has picked up steam and that things are chugging along with
little threat of inflation,'' said Robert McGee, chief economist at
Tokai Bank.
<p>
   The study is based on anecdotal evidence of business conditions
compiled by the Fed's 12 district banks. The report was
inadvertently released ahead of schedule on the Internet.
<p>
   At today's yield of 6.54 percent, U.S. 10-year notes yield 415
basis points more than the 2.39 percent yield on the No. 182
benchmark 10-year Japanese bond, 6 basis points more than a week
ago.
<p>
   U.S. debt now yields 82 basis points more than the 5.72 percent
yield on 10-year German bonds, 6 basis points more than last week.
<p>
   The benchmark five-year U.S. dollar swap spread widened 2 basis
points to 26 basis points. The spread is the difference between the
yield on the benchmark Treasury and the highest rate at which a
``AAA''-rated corporation can sell its fixed-rate bonds, if it
wants to do a swap that leaves it paying no more than the London
interbank offered rate.
<p>
   Corporations use interest-rate and currency swaps to guard
against changes in the value of their outstanding debt and to cut
their borrowing costs. The banks and securities firms that provide
these swaps often buy or sell U.S. Treasuries to hedge the risk of
sudden swings in interest rates.
<p>
   Among the U.S.-based issuers to take advantage of the strong
demand today for corporate debt was Salomon Inc., which sold $500
million of seven-year notes. NationsBank Corp. also $500 million of
securities.
<p>
   More than $3.5 billion in corporate securities were sold.
<p>
   The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey was the largest
issuer in the municipal market, selling $300 million in a two-part
offering. About $900 million in new tax-exempt bonds were priced
today.
<p>
   About $77.4 billion in Treasuries traded through most of the
major bond brokers as of 3:00 p.m. Eastern time, according to
GovPX, Inc., a bond pricing service. That was about 11 percent
below average for a Wednesday in the first quarter of last year,
the service said.
<p>
   The so-called basis, which reflects the difference between the
current 30-year bond and the March futures contract, widened 3 to
at 115/32, or 3 19/32 points.
<p>
   The three-month bill's discount rate was little changed at 5.03
percent, a bond-equivalent yield of 5.16 percent. The six-month
bill's discount rate was also little changed at 5.10 percent, a
bond-equivalent yield of 5.30 percent. The one-year bill's discount
rate rose 1 basis point to 5.29 percent, a bond-equivalent yield of
5.57 percent.
<p>
   The three-year note fell 2/32 to 99 12/32, a yield of 6.12
percent. The five-year note fell 3/32 to 99 07/32, a yield of 6.31
percent. The 10-year note fell 1/4 to 99 21/32, a yield of 6.54
percent.
<p>
   The March Treasury bill contract was unchanged at 94.92, and the
March Eurodollar contract was unchanged at 94.38.
<p>
   The gap between the two, the so-called TED spread, was little
changed at 54 basis points. The TED spread is an indication of
investor confidence in the U.S. financial system.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1805EST
</TRAILER>
