<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9507 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-LABOR-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0210 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-VENEZUELA-LABOR-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; VENEZUELA DRAWING THE LINE ON PUBLIC SALARY HIKES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jake Keaveny &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Caracas, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) Venezuela's government said it will
draw the line for public worker salary raises at 25 percent despite
concern that continuing labor strikes will ignite a chain of
demands for higher raises, officials said.
<p>
   Venezuela has budgeted the increase, setting it to year-ahead
inflation targets, said Finance Minister Luis Raul Matos Azocar.
<p>
   Further increases would derail inflation-fighting efforts, he
said. ``I refuse to play that role, promising workers something
that I don't stand for,'' said Matos Azocar.
<p>
   Public sector doctors got a nearly 200 percent raise Monday by
striking nationwide. Public university professors are striking,
demand a doubling of salaries to match last year's 103 percent
inflation.
<p>
   As a result, other public labor unions may not be satisfied with
25 percent.
<p>
   The government has budgeted 1.2 trillion ($2.5 billion) for the
raises, due in the coming months.
<p>
   More than 800,000 people are employed by the federal government
and another 500,000 by state and city administrations. for a total
of 1.3 billion.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1805EST
</TRAILER>
