<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0243 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FIDELITY-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FIDELITY INVESTMENTS SAYS BOND FUND MANAGER BOB IVES RESIGNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Boston, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Fidelity Investments said bond
fund manager Bob Ives resigned because he doesn't want to relocate
to New Hampshire where the No. 1 U.S. fund group is moving its
fixed-income division in August.
<p>
   Ives, 34, managed more than $1.45 billion in fixed-income
funds,including the $955 million Fidelity Government Securities
Fund. He joined Fidelity in 1991 after graduating with a master's
degree in business from the University of Chicago. He is the 18th
fund manager to leave Fidelity in the past year.
<p>
   Fidelity announced in December that it plans to move its entire
bond and money market investment groups to Merrimack, New
Hampshire, in an effort to reduce costs. Merrimack is 47 miles
north of Boston.
<p>
   Ives is the second Fidelity bond fund manager to announce his
resignation this month. The other is Michael Gray, who managed
almost $10 billion in assets for Fidelity. --Tim Quinson in Boston
(617) 542-3766 through New York newsroom (212) 318-2300 Story
illustration: To chart performance of Fidelity Government
Securities Fund, type FGOVX US Equity &QR;  GP W
Company news: Industry news: 5079Z US Equity &QR;  CN, DES NI FND
Mutual funds
