<DOCID> nyt970122.0501 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tab-z> A9510 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-DYING-WITH-DIGNITY-ED </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0996 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DYING-WITH-DIGNITY-EDITORIAL-ASAHI &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Commentary) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CHOOSING ONE'S OWN DIGNIFIED DEATH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (This 775-word Asahi Shimbun ``separate buy'' editorial is from the
Asahi News Service.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Get your news from Japan and the Pacific Rim straight
from the source  &MD;  the Asahi News Service. Its Monday through Friday
report of news, features and distinctive analysis is culled from
The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's foremost newspaper, renowned for its
integrity and thoroughness (with a daily circulation is 12
million.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased  &MD;  the rate is not
prohibitive  &MD;  from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice  &MD;  into the
``a'' general news and ``k'' commentary news files.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By THE ASAHI SHIMBUN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Asahi News Service &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Dying at home, surrounded by warm memories and familiar faces,
is what many elderly people wish for. They want to leave this world
in a natural and peaceful way, without being forced to live on
unnaturally supported by medical treatment.
<p>
   Their wishes have often been trampled on in this country, with
many people dying in a dreary hospital ward far away from their
homes. Many are subjected to invasive treatments that they have no
wish to undergo.
<p>
   In extreme instances, people have even died because of
negligence at care facilities or through secondary infections
passed on in hospitals.
<p>
   But the situation is gradually changing. Groups examining the
state of home care for the elderly are being established across the
country. The National Council of Social Welfare will soon release a
report that describes special nursing homes that provide care for
the ailing elderly.
<p>
   Amid these changes, a controversy has erupted over an affair at
a nursing home in Kyoto. When an old woman, attached to a feeding
tube because she was severely physically impaired and could no
longer take in the liquid food, her doctor switched the liquid to a
sports drink.
<p>
   Critics question the doctor's judgment in removing a nourishing
liquid and replacing it with a simple sports drink without first
ascertaining the woman's wishes.
<p>
   In some people's view, dying with dignity will only become
possible if the use of artificial respirators and feeding tubes is
stopped. But the matter is not as simple as all that.
<p>
   The way one scholar lived his last months before dying late last
year heralds a new age.
<p>
   When in hospital after being paralyzed on one side of his body
by a stroke, he was unable to swallow food or to speak: the typical
image of a ``vegetable.''
<p>
   But when he finally returned home and was wheeled into his
study, what no one had expected came about. Slowly, he started to
tap keys on his word processor with one finger of his right hand.
On subsequent days, the scholar spent several hours typing each
day.
<p>
   In the summer of 1995, he typed these words:
<p>
   ``I do not want an artificial respirator to be attached to me,
but I would like to know what other people think. I hate the
machine. Please print this part and make arrangements to mail it by
special delivery to Dr. Sato.''
<p>
   Dr. Akira Sato, the man's chief physician, leads a group of
doctors who support home medical care for the elderly.
<p>
   In response to the patient's desires, he sent back a document
that clearly stated that the doctor understood the man did not want
to be hooked to a respirator, outlined the care that would be
provided at the end and pledged that he would do as the scholar
wished.
<p>
   Reading the document letter by letter, the scholar smiled
broadly at the physician's assurances and signed it.
<p>
   Death  &MD;  a peaceful death surrounded by family members  &MD;  came a
year and five months later. Teamwork among the doctor, nurses,
public helpers, and family made a death with dignity possible for
the scholar.
<p>
   At the Sakura-en Special Nursing Home in Yokohama, it is up to
inmates to decide where they want to die. Forty percent choose to
die at Sakura-en. But no one asks them outright about their
decisions.
<p>
   When someone dies at the nursing home, all other patients
assemble for a wake in the dining hall. They talk about their
memories of the deceased as the person's body is laid out for
viewing, surrounded by flowers and with his or her favorite music
playing in the background. Neighborhood children, who often come to
play at the home, join in the ceremonial farewell.
<p>
   After attending the wake, the patients talk about where they
want to die. Listening to their conversations, home officials
arrange for them to die according to their wishes.
<p>
   In other countries where the population is living longer lives,
measures have been established that enable people to die peacefully
and in a manner that meets their wishes.
<p>
   These measures include setting up a system of visiting nurses,
doctors and public helpers that makes it possible for the elderly
to spend their last days at home.
<p>
   Written instructions from the patient concerning the manner of
his or her death (called a ``living will'') and company-sanctioned
paid leave to care for dying family members are other compassionate
advances.
<p>
   It is said that a truly affluent society is one in which
everyone can die a peaceful death. We hope the first steps to
create such a society will be taken this year in Japan.  &LR; 
 &UR; (THIS EDITORIAL WAS PUBLISHED IN THE ASAHI SHIMBUN, JAN. 12,
1997.) &LR; 
 &LR; 
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
 &UR;  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 775-word article from the Asahi News Service, it
must be purchased  &MD;  the rate is not prohibitive  &MD;  from New York
Times Syndicate sales representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-444-0267, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
