<DOCID> nyt970122.0502 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9511 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CME-GLOBEX-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0237 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CME-GLOBEX-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CME TO START TRADING CURRENCIES ON OFF-HOURS ELECTRONIC SYSTEM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Susan Miller &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
Chicago, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
through a new subsidiary, tomorrow will begin trading currency
futures during off hours in hopes of increasing volume when the
trading pits are closed.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The CME, acting through the new Globex Foreign Exchange
Facility, will act as a buyer and seller of currency futures
contracts on the after-hours electronic trading system called
Globex.
<p>
   GFX initially will trade British pounds, German marks, Japanese
yen and Swiss francs.
<p>
   ``There will never be a time when someone who wants to make a
trade won't find a viable and deep bid and offer provided by the
GFX,'' Merc Chairman Jack Sandner said.
<p>
   CME traders will make offsetting transactions in the underlying
market to minimize the exchange's risk.
<p>
   GFX, which will clear trades through a CME clearing member firm,
will post bids and offers between $1 million and $3 million, based
on conditions in the foreign exchange market. Larger trades are
possible, though not guaranteed.
<p>
   Globex, a computer system for off-hours trading, is a joint
venture between the CME, the Marche a Terme International de France
and Reuters Holdings Plc. Reuters competes with Bloomberg News in
providing news and information.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1806EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0503 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=k pri=r sel=tab-z> A9512 </STORYID>
