<STORYID cat=i pri=r sel=tab-z> A9515 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NO-SLIP-ICEBOOTS-JAPA </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0782 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NO-SLIP-ICEBOOTS-JAPAN-ASAHI &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SNOW BOOT TECHNOLOGY IN JAPAN USES HEMP, WALNUT SHELLS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (This curious 550-word ``separate buy'' article is from the Asahi
News Service.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Get your news from Japan and the Pacific Rim straight
from the source  &MD;  the Asahi News Service. Its Monday through Friday
report of news, features and distinctive analysis is culled from
The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's foremost newspaper, renowned for its
integrity and thoroughness (with a daily circulation is 12
million.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased  &MD;  the rate is not
prohibitive  &MD;  from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice  &MD;  into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``i'' international news files.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By KYOTA TSUTSUMI &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Asahi News Service &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   TOKYO  &MD;  In Sapporo, winter boots must do for pedestrians what
winter's snow tires do for cars  &MD;  get a grip on streets slick with
ice.
<p>
   Slippery streets are a perennial winter hazard here,
particularly since 1991, when the national Environment Agency
banned spiked snow tires.
<p>
   The spikes tore up the asphalt surface, creating irritating dust
clouds, but the studless tires that replaced them do a disservice
of their own: they buff the snow and ice to a skating-rink-smooth
sheen known locally as ``mirror burn,'' a worse foe than the
somewhat less treacherous ``ice burn'' or black ice often found on
snowy highways.
<p>
   And so the competition is on to develop a shoe that will not
slip on ice. New footwear appearing this winter features rubber
soles fortified with such novelties as foam rubber, sand, hemp and
walnut shells.
<p>
   Regal Corp., a leading shoe manufacturer, this winter introduced
its ``Corobannsho'' shoe  &MD;  a catchy adaptation of ``korobanai
desho,'' meaning ``you won't fall.''
<p>
   A men's shoe sold only in Hokkaido, Corobannsho has a sole of
notched foam rubber that rakes the treacherous ice surface.
<p>
   Interestingly enough, Corobannsho was the brainchild not of
Regal's product development division but of its Sapporo
salespeople, who knew all about mirror burn firsthand and were
eager to do something about it.
<p>
   Last year the sportswear maker Asics came out with its own
answer to mirror burn: ``Ice Walk'' shoes, whose soles are laced
with sand. Ice Walk footwear comes in both men's and ladies'
styles.
<p>
   Whether the key ingredient is foam rubber or walnut shells,
nonslip shoe technology takes its cue from the earlier competition
to produce the ideal studless tire.
<p>
   The foam rubber that Corobannsho uses, for example, is based on
the principle developed by the tire maker Bridgestone for its
studless tire.
<p>
   The Regal salespeople who devised Corobannsho, in fact, spent a
good deal of time at the library analyzing the literature on
studless tire design. And the walnut shell idea was borrowed from
the studless tire made by Toyo Rubber.
<p>
   Driving the connection home are the posters that stores are
using to push their ice-clutching shoes. They show  &MD;  you guessed it
 &MD;  studless tires. The competition among the various shoe brands
looks rather like a studless tire proxy war.
<p>
   Mirror burn is a perfect example of a solution to one problem
unexpectedly generating another problem. With the dust-causing
spikes now almost entirely replaced by studless tires, skating-rink
streets are turning up all over the city.
<p>
   Just how tough a time of it pedestrians are having is reflected
in recent statistics showing the number of falls resulting in
hospitalization.
<p>
   In the winter of 1990-91, just before the spiked tire ban went
into effect, 375 people had to be taken to hospital by ambulance
after slipping on ice. The next year that figure shot up to 710. In
1995 it was 756.
<p>
   City officials warn against expecting a miracle cure for the
problem.
<p>
   ``Apart from spreading antifreeze or sand, there's not much we
can do,'' says Takao Goto, director of Sapporo snow removal
operations.
<p>
   Though spiked tires are banned, spike-shoe soles are not, and in
fact many shoe brands still feature metal spikes. But, like snow
tires before them, winter shoes are going studless.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
 &UR;  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  &LR;  &QC; 
