<DOCID> nyt970122.0507 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=l pri=u sel=ttj-z> A9516 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TABASCO-SAUCE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0828 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TABASCO-SAUCE-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE WICKED WAYS OF TABASCO SAUCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DOUG BLACKBURN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Albany Times Union &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   You don't have to go to New Orleans to bring the flavor of the
Super Bowl's host city to your party on Sunday.
<p>
   Just grab a small bottle of Tabasco pepper sauce and add
judicious amounts while preparing such traditional buffet dishes as
shrimp or chicken drumsticks. If you do, you'll be using the same
condiment as folks eating their pregame meals on Bourbon Street in
the French Quarter.
<p>
   Before hot sauce became an industry unto itself, with many malls
now featuring a shop that offers only hot sauce, there was Tabasco
pepper sauce by the McIlhenny Company of Avery Island, La. It is,
without a doubt, the zesty precursor to today's burgeoning hot
sauce industry.
<p>
   Nowadays, of course, there are so many hot sauces to choose from
it can be overwhelming to know which sauce to select. At a local
shop, there are more than 300 varieties of hot sauces, salsas and
mustards available.
<p>
   But if you want to pick out just one hot sauce with the piquant
flavor synonymous with New Orleans, try old-fashioned Tabasco
pepper sauce. It is versatile without being overpowering, yet a
little bit goes a long way. After all, how old is that bottle of
Tabasco sauce on your shelf?
<p>
   The McIlhenny Co. is located deep in the heart of Cajun country,
about 45 minutes south of Lafayette near Morgan City. It has been
producing Tabasco pepper sauce for more than 125 years.
<p>
   Avery Island, the company's home and a popular tourist
destination, is one of five small islands that rise above the flat
bayou country of Louisiana's Gulf Coast. The island's perimeter is
made up of deep salt springs, which add richness to the soil and
marshes.
<p>
   Tabasco pepper sauce has made its presence known throughout the
20th century. In 1922, a bottle was shown in a photograph of the
mess table during a halt in the excavation of King Tut's tomb in
Egypt. An intact bottle of Tabasco pepper sauce was recovered from
the 859-foot-long flying aircraft carrier, USS Macon, the largest
airship ever built, which plunged into 1,800 feet of water off
Point Sur, Calif., on Feb. 12, 1935.
<p>
   On several Himalayan climbs, Tabasco pepper sauce reportedly
served as a cherished reward for the Sherpas, the native guides who
have been reported to use an entire bottle at one sitting. And when
astronauts aboard the Skylab space station found their food bland
and uninteresting, NASA sent up Tabasco pepper sauce.
<p>
   To easily spice up your Super Bowl party with the flavor of
Cajun country, try some of the following recipes, all courtesy of
the McIlhenny Co.:
<p>
   (Serves eight)
<p>
    &MD;  Eight pounds pork spare ribs, cut into two-rib portions.
<p>
    &MD;  Two-thirds cup light molasses.
<p>
    &MD;  Three tablespoons balsamic vinegar.
<p>
    &MD;  Three tablespoons prepared mustard.
<p>
    &MD;  Two tablespoons Tabasco pepper sauce.
<p>
   In large saucepan over high heat, heat to boiling the ribs and
enough water to cover. Reduce heat to low; cover and simmer 45
minutes or until ribs are tender. Drain.
<p>
   In medium bowl, combine molasses, balsamic vinegar, mustard and
Tabasco sauce.
<p>
   Preheat broiler. Place ribs on rack in broiling pan; brush with
some sauce. With ribs about seven to nine inches from source of
heat, broil them 15 minutes until heated through, turning ribs
occasionally and brushing often with sauce.
<p>
    &UR; --- &LR; 
<p>
   (Serves eight)
<p>
    &MD;  One-half cup butter or margarine (one stick).
<p>
    &MD;  Two tablespoons Tabasco pepper sauce.
<p>
    &MD;  tablespoon ketchup.
<p>
    &MD;  One teaspoon salt 16 chicken drumsticks (about four pounds).
<p>
    &MD;  One cup bottled blue cheese dressing Preheat broiler.
<p>
   In small saucepan over low heat, melt butter or margarine, then
stir in Tabasco sauce, ketchup and salt.
<p>
   Place chicken drumsticks on rack in broiling pan; brush with
some Tabasco mixture. Broil drumsticks seven to nine inches from
heat source for 10 minutes. Turn and brush with remaining Tabasco
mixture. Broil 10 to 15 minutes longer or until drumsticks are
browned and tender.
<p>
   Serve with blue cheese dressing.
<p>
    &UR; --- &LR; 
<p>
   (Serves eight)
<p>
    &MD;  One 16-ounce can refried beans.
<p>
    &MD;  One tablespoon Tabasco pepper sauce.
<p>
    &MD;  Eight flour tortillas (eight inches round).
<p>
    &MD;  One large red bell pepper, seeded and finely chopped.
<p>
    &MD;  One-quarter cup chopped cilantro or parsley.
<p>
    &MD;  Eight ounces Monterey Jack or cheddar cheese, shredded.
<p>
   Preheat oven to 450. In medium bowl combine refried beans and
Tabasco sauce to mix well. Spread three tablespoons of the mixture
on a flour tortilla to 1/2 inch of edge; sprinkle with some red
pepper, cilantro and shredded cheese. Repeat process with remaining
seven tortillas. Place tortillas on two large cookie sheets.
<p>
   Bake five minutes, or until cheese is melted and tortillas are
golden around the edges. To serve, cut tortillas into wedges.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1807EST
</TRAILER>
