<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0508 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=i pri=r sel=tab-z> A9518 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-KOBE-SURVIVORS-LIMBO- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1188 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-KOBE-SURVIVORS-LIMBO-IHT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Timed for TODAY'S 2nd anniv. of Kobe quake) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; KOBE'S `LOST BAGGAGE' STILL SUFFER TWO YEARS AFTER QUAKE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (This 950-word ``separate buy'' article is from today's edition of
the International Herald Tribune.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders  &MD;  and readers'
horizons  &MD;  the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
 &UR; (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased  &MD;  the rate is
not prohibitive  &MD;  from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice  &MD;  into the
``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news files.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By VELISARIOS KATTOULAS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 International Herald Tribune &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   KOBE, Japan  &MD;  Her face remained calm, but 64-year-old Hisako
Kohashi became animated as she described the life she has led since
an earthquake engulfed her home in fire and she was forced to move
into a tiny room that she shares with her older brother.
<p>
   Her voice filled with sadness, frustration and shame.
<p>
   ``The toughest thing about living in a single room with my
brother is changing into fresh clothes,'' said Mrs. Kohashi, one of
about 70,000 people still living in spartan temporary housing two
years after an earthquake tore through this city west of Tokyo.
<p>
   ``Maybe if I'd taken my clothes off for a living I could undress
in front of him,'' she said. ``But I can't, so when I want to
change I send him to the park to pick up rubbish.''
<p>
   After some 6,300 people died on Jan. 17, 1995, in Japan's worst
earthquake in a half-century, there was tremendous sadness but also
great hope and energy among the 1.5 million residents who survived.
<p>
   The 300,000 who sought shelter in schools, parks, temples and
shrines seemed determined to help one another rebuild their lives,
and great progress has been made.
<p>
   More than 200,000 have repaired their old homes and returned to
them or have moved. After toppling in the earthquake, the city's
main, elevated expressway has been rebuilt and was reopened four
months ago.
<p>
   The volume of goods passing through Kobe's rebuilt port is
approaching full capacity. And the city center, which once
resembled a scene from a war, is brimming with shoppers.
<p>
   But for people like Mrs. Kohashi, who still live in
barracks-like compounds and are old, sick or poor  &MD;  sometimes all
three  &MD;  life is getting harder.
<p>
   After two years, public indifference to their plight has grown
and they have suffered setbacks from officials in their fight for
help.
<p>
   People still living in temporary compounds have become a
distinct underclass, aid volunteers and local journalists say.
<p>
   Like the survivors of the Hiroshima and Nagasaki atomic
bombings, survivors of the Kobe earthquake in temporary housing are
often referred to in derogatory slang.
<p>
   Children from the compounds are called prefabricated kids
(kasetsuko) after the prefabricated buildings in which they live
and the compounds, often isolated, are known as mountains of
discarded old women (ubasuteyama).
<p>
   ``People are just waiting for people stuck in the compounds to
die or disappear,'' said Yoshihiro Tsujiuchi, a Buddhist priest who
distributes food and relief supplies.
<p>
   Since the quake, some 200 people living in temporary housing
have died alone and unnoticed. In a case that caused nationwide
outrage, the death of a man suffering from liver disease went
unnoticed for 10 months.
<p>
   People in temporary housing also feel betrayed by the central
government.
<p>
   After vowing to help survivors rebuild, officials in the
national government stymied plans drawn up in Kobe to have Tokyo
pay between 5 million and 17 million yen to those whose homes were
destroyed.
<p>
   Seiroku Kajiyama, the government spokesman who doubles as
minister in charge of earthquake relief, said last fall that the
government had not yet decided whether to pay compensation.
<p>
   The Finance Ministry has allotted $30 billion to rebuild Kobe's
infrastructure but has strongly resisted paying compensation to
survivors, saying that private charity and personal savings should
suffice.
<p>
   ``The government ought to remember who they are rebuilding this
city for,'' said Mrs. Kohashi's brother, Keiji, 70. ``It's supposed
to be for us. Not for the construction industry.''
<p>
   Perhaps a harsher reality for the victims is the inability of
the Kobe city government to build low-rent public housing at the
pace it promised.
<p>
   A prefectural government survey last year found that 70 percent
of the people in compounds hoped to move into such housing. Last
month, however, officials said people would remain in temporary
compounds until around March 2000, two years longer than the
prefecture originally hoped.
<p>
   This angered the people in the compounds.
<p>
   But Norio Aoki, the city official in charge of a 270 billion yen
project to build 3,000 apartments in Kobe, said the slow pace of
construction was unavoidable because of Japan's development laws.
<p>
   Under them, local officials must first find the landowners,
tenants and subtenants with a stake in any land slated for
development and buy those stakes before construction can begin.
<p>
   ``To be perfectly frank, I've no idea how long it will take to
redevelop this area because there are nearly 2,000 people with a
stake in it,'' Mr. Aoki said.
<p>
   The site, in Kobe's Nagata Ward, is where an estimated 300
people died after gas pipes that ruptured in the earthquake caught
fire.
<p>
   This delay comes as little surprise to Mrs. Kohashi and her
brother. Like many made homeless, the Kohashis would like to move
into public housing.
<p>
   The room they share is barely big enough  &MD;  three meters by three
meters  &MD;  to lay out the foldaway mattresses on which they sleep.
They share a kitchen, bath and toilet with 16 others, mainly the
elderly and ill. The situation is made worse by the paralysis in
Mrs. Kohashi's arm that she suffered nine years ago after a stroke.
<p>
   But when Kobe city recently offered them an apartment in a
suburb, they turned it down. Mrs. Kohashi said the apartment was
too far from her doctor.
<p>
   ``I can't go home,'' she said. ``And I can't stand being here.
But moving to a place that's far from public transport, the shops
and my doctor isn't any good either.
<p>
   ``I guess that to the city of Kobe I'm just a piece of lost
baggage.''
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
 &UR;  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  &LR;  &QC; 
