<DOCID> nyt970122.0511 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tab-z> A9525 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-FENG-SHUI-IHT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0903 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FASHION-FENG-SHUI-IHT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; `FENG SHUI' MEETS MALE FASHION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (This 675-word ``separate buy'' fashion/trend article is from the
International Herald Tribune.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders  &MD;  and readers'
horizons  &MD;  the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
 &UR; (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased  &MD;  the rate is
not prohibitive  &MD;  from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice  &MD;  into the
``i'' international news and ``a'' general/fashion news files.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By SUZY MENKES &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 International Herald Tribune &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   No visible buttons. No fancy details. No blaring status symbols.
Just a pearl-gray suit with a streamlined silhouette that flowed
from wide lapels through soft pants.
<p>
   It was Gucci's feng shui for fashion: purify, simplify and keep
only what counts.
<p>
   Designer Tom Ford, whose taut, sexy, 1970s silhouette has
defined male cool, moved fast forward in Gucci's fall collection.
The once skinny pants had loosened up  &MD;  to the extent that flares
flopped over the signature square-toed boots.
<p>
   The jackets swept across the chest, always with the buttons
concealed in a fly front. Only open shirt cuffs, a sweater artfully
pouched at one hip or a slim belt disturbed the sleek surface.
<p>
   ``It was about a silhouette change  &MD;  that is why I took all the
details off,'' said Ford, whose military epaulettes, top-stitching
and trademark belts have nourished fashion's copyists.
<p>
   But Gucci had not lost an ounce of sex appeal by adding inches
of fabric. It was a smart show in every sense: modern,
forward-looking, clean in its opening cloud-gray colors, rich in
its textures, luxurious in its simplicity.
<p>
   And although it was a fairly dramatic change to a new, looser
shape, there were sly references to Gucci's hippie past in a madcap
patchwork pants, tie-dye velvets and velvet neckties to die for.
They were worn with rich paisley-pattern silk shirts  &MD;  just one
example of simple items that oozed quality and luxury.
<p>
   With his short, sharp velvet coats and his cobweb-fine sweaters,
Ford defined what is modern in menswear: minimalist shapes with no
extraneous details but built-in enrichment through texture, color
and pattern.
<p>
   You want all that con brio? Try a classic shirt in hot-pink silk
with chocolate-brown velvet pants embossed with Gucci's signature
G's. The ever-hip Ford said after his show that he is now moving
from Paris to swinging-again London.
<p>
   Romeo Gigli was first in with the strokeable velvet suit, the
rich Renaissance colors and the narrow-shouldered, slim-trousered
suit. Hey, he owns that fashion territory. Or at least he did, when
the look seemed subversive and revolutionary in contrast to power
suits.
<p>
   Now every menswear collection serves up velvet tailoring, but it
was nice to see Gigli's again  &MD;  the short velvet coats and skinny
pants in succulent mixes of color like lime green and mallard blue,
ruby red and grass green.
<p>
   Textured effects were new, from the furrowed velvet pants to
shadowy patterns like sunlight cast through stained glass.
<p>
   But where Gigli might have played only with his artistic colors
and the sensual surfaces, he piled on the details: braid outlining
lapels and pockets of a raspberry jacket; a pleat opening down the
backbone of an orange coat or twin folds on a Norfolk jacket; plaid
velvet here, club checks there, with even a different pattern for
the brief, curving vest of a three-piece suit. The ensemble of the
show was indigestible, but individual pieces fine.
<p>
   Some collections define what is out. Since Moschino's show
chased after trends, it inevitably hit some misses  &MD;  like techno
plasticized coats that had their brief fashion moment in the early
1990s.
<p>
   Or urban graffiti (think a brick-wall pattern on a jacket and
scribbles in sequins). Or ski-jackets (smothered with photoprints).
Or those wretched hippies (another comeback for psychedelic daisies
and hobo hat).
<p>
   On target were tactile pants in mock pony or moleskin, the
inevitable velvet, and jersey used for supple cardigan jackets.
<p>
   The irony is that classic now looks hip and sophisticated
fabrics seem much cooler than downtown workwear  &MD;  providing that
the proportions of the clothes and the attitude are modern.
<p>
   For Trussardi, classic is just  &MD;  well  &MD;  classic: the elegant
long coat with broad shoulders and lapels; the country suit in
basket-weave tweed; the moleskin pants with gossamer-fine sweater
or ribbed cardigan.
<p>
   Like many Italian houses, it relies on the quality of fabric and
finish, rather than challenging menswear's status quo.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
