<STORYID cat=i pri=r sel=tab-z> A9533 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-TO-BLOW?-INDE </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0721 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ALBANIA-TO-BLOW?-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IS ALBANIA THE NEXT TO EXPLODE? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (This 500-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased  &MD;  the rate is not
prohibitive  &MD;  from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice  &MD;  into the
``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news files.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ANDREW GUMBEL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Independent, London &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   TIRANA, ALBANIA  &MD;  Thousands of Albanians who have lost their
money in failed ``pyramid'' saving schemes thronged into the main
square of the capital, Tirana, for an anti-government rally Sunday,
only to be beaten back by police who lashed out at the crowds with
truncheons and smashed up the stage and sound system being used by
opposition leaders.
<p>
   The incident was the culmination of four days of street protests
in Tirana and other big cities sparked by the latest banking
collapse, and raised the political temperature higher than it has
been since opposition leaders were beaten up in the wake of last
May's rigged general elections.
<p>
   Several demonstrators stumbled away from the rally with bloodied
faces. People closest to the opposition leaders in the center of
Skanderbeg Square were the most roughly handled, as plainclothes
officers swooped in to stop the speeches from beginning.
<p>
   The thousands of uniformed riot police who ringed the area were
less brutal, partly because many in their ranks have lost their
savings too.
<p>
   The pyramid schemes, which have thrived over the past four years
in the absence of a conventional banking system, offer
extraordinarily high rates of interest on hard-currency deposits  &MD; 
more than 10 percent per month  &MD;  but rely on ever more depositors
coming forward to keep going.
<p>
   Hundreds of thousands of Albanians have entrusted their last
assets to them in the hope of getting rich quick, but without
asking themselves how the banks operate and how long they are
likely to survive.
<p>
   President Sali Berisha has great taken pains to dissociate
himself from the schemes in the past few days, but in fact it is
inconceivable that they could have operated without the
government's active approval.
<p>
   In Serbia, where pyramid schemes thrived in 1992-93 before
disappearing overnight, they were a perfect vehicle for
money-laundering and illegal government manipulation of the
people's savings.
<p>
   Like Slobodan Milosevic's Serbia, Albania has a heavily
clientelistic economic structure that is rigorously controlled by
the political leadership.
<p>
   With Serbia's current street revolution very much in the news in
Albania, many of Sunday's demonstrators used the occasion to vent
their fury at the government.
<p>
   ``Down with the dictatorship!'' was a common cry. ``First the
government stole our votes, now it is stealing our money,'' was
another.
<p>
   Albania has effectively been a one-party state since last May's
fraudulent elections. The ruling Democratic Party controls every
institution in the country, and the opposition has refused to take
up the few seats it was grudgingly offered in parliament following
a halfhearted attempt at international mediation.
<p>
   The European Union, in particular, has been reluctant to call
President Berisha to order because it feels it needs him to exert a
stabilizing influence on the Albanian communities in Kosovo and
Macedonia.
<p>
   The diplomatic community is also afraid of a return of the
Socialist Party, heirs to Enver Hoxha's Communists, and has
succeeded in persuading them  &MD;  at least until now  &MD;  to keep a low
profile while they purge their ranks of hard-liners.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
 &UR;  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  -  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 500-word article, it must be purchased  &MD;  the rate
is not prohibitive  &MD;  from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-444-0267, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR; 
