<STORYID cat=i pri=r sel=tab-z> A9535 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-DRY-RIVERS-SYRIA-700&AMP; </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1235 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DRY-RIVERS-SYRIA-700&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SYRIA'S DISAPPEARING RIVERS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (This ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent newspaper in
London.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased  &MD;  the rate is not
prohibitive  &MD;  from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: For those desiring a shorter version, this article
stands in 700 words. A 340-word optional trim follows; total uncut
version is 1,025.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice  &MD;  into the
``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news files.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT FISK &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Independent, London &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   DAMASCUS  &MD;  On Abdul Aziz al-Musri's desk, there is a Koranic
quotation in magnificent Arabic script: ``And tell them that the
water is to be divided between them...''
<p>
   The head of the international water bureau in the Syrian
Ministry of Irrigation keeps a host of other theological
instructions on file, along with historical water agreements
stretching back to 2,360 B.C., via the Iraqi kingdom of Hammurabi
(1792-1750 BC) and four centuries of Ottoman legislation.
<p>
   On al-Musri's wall, a large map appears to show the fruits of
this collected wisdom: most of Syria is colored a dark, verdant
green. But another set of files on al-Musri's desk shows just how
misleading maps can be.
<p>
   For in the far north of his country  &MD;  and it is a problem upon
which al-Musri spends almost every waking hour  &MD;  the color green is
fading away.
<p>
   Four entire rivers, according to the Syrian ministry, have
either dried up because the Turks have diverted the water courses
north of the border, or been contaminated by massive pollution from
Turkey.
<p>
   Al-Musri slides a pen down the mournful list on his desk. ``The
Jaljal River passes through our city of Hassake,'' he said. ``It
has dried up.
<p>
   ``The el-Balih River virtually dried up five years ago when the
Turks began using the underground water in the river's catchment
area in Turkey. In summer now, the Sajar River runs out of water.''
<p>
   Al-Musri knows his job. He speaks fluent Turkish and two years
ago completed a five-year assignment as first secretary at the
Syrian embassy in Ankara.
<p>
   He has visited every Turkish dam on the other side of the
frontier and participated in the major water resource conferences
with Turkey.
<p>
   His pen comes to rest on another river, the Qweik, which once
ran south into the great city of Aleppo. ``It is no more,''
al-Musri says.
<p>
   Not quite. When I visited the area, I found something worse. The
Qweik is now a fast-flowing open sewer, its stench drifting for
miles across the barren fields.
<p>
   In Aleppo itself, the Syrians have been forced to merge the
ancient watercourse, with its underground Roman water tanks and
bridges, into the city's sewage system.
<p>
   ``Just 13 months ago, the Turkish side started releasing
polluted water in some of our joint rivers,'' al-Musri goes on.
``Sewage water and drainage from the lands that carry industrial
pollutants came down the al-Balih Valley and we are still receiving
this dirty water.''
<p>
   And from a battered grey filing cabinet in the corner of the
room comes another file, crammed with statistics of biological
oxygen dissolve (BOD) measurements  &MD;  a system of checking the
purity of water.
<p>
   ``In the normal course of events, there should be only 2
milligrams BOD per liter in a river  &MD;  up to 40 if it is irrigation
water.
<p>
   ``But we've done 300 analyzes in the al-Balih Valley and they
show that BOD reached 500 milligrams per liter. This has polluted
the land  &MD;  it's harmed the health of our farmers and their
families, and contaminated drinking water in the region.''
<p>
   Al-Musri, however, is a technical man. Ask him why the Turks are
polluting the rivers and he replies: ``It's a political question.
From the technical side, we have all the information necessary to
reach a joint agreement.
<p>
   ``The problem today is not so much the amount of water  &MD;  though
that has been a problem on the Euphrates when the Turks were
filling their dams  &MD;  but the quality of the water.''
<p>
   All of which depends, it seems, on the quality of political
relations between Syria and Turkey, a matter upon which al-Musri
did not wish to expand.
<p>
   It is no secret, however, that Turkey's new military agreement
with Israel  &MD;  which allows Israeli pilots to fly in Turkish
airspace along Syria's northern border  &MD;  and Turkey's anger at
Syrian support for Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) separatists who are
waging a brutal campaign in southeast Turkey, have brought
relations between the Syrians and the successors to the old Ottoman
rulers to their lowest point for many years.
 &LR; 
<p>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR; 
<p>
   The PKK leader, Abdullah Ocalan, appears from time to time in
the Syrian-controlled Lebanese Bekaa Valley to issue cease-fire
calls or bloodcurdling threats against his Turkish antagonists.
<p>
   A series of small bombs that exploded in Syrian towns last year
were probably the work of Turkish government agents, and reports of
occasional sniping by Turkish soldiers across the northern border
have been confirmed by a Syrian security source.
<p>
   At one point last year, Syrian armor was moved north after
reports of Turkish troop movements.
<p>
   Publicly, the Syrians do not speak about the lost Syrian lands
around Alexandretta  &MD;  ceded by the French mandate authority in 1939
in the vain hope of persuading Turkey to join the coming Allied
fight against Hitler. But they have not forgotten.
<p>
   And they are ever mindful of that most ancient of rivers that
flows from Turkey, the epic Euphrates whose waters slackened when
Turkey built its dams to the north and are now, according to the
Syrians, in danger of falling again as the Turks establish two new
dams  &MD;  at Biracik and Karkamish  &MD;  for land irrigation.
<p>
   Biracik alone, according to al-Musri, is intended to irrigate
81,670 hectares of land.
<p>
   ``This means it will reduce our share of water in the Euphrates.
Syria and Iraq are ready to sign a final agreement with Turkey to
share the water of the Euphrates in an equitable way according to
international law.
<p>
   ``But the Turkish side, till now, has not reached final
agreement because it would like to have time to finish its planned
projects.''
<p>
   Al-Musri takes the view that already existing legislation
between Turkey, Syria and Iraq  &MD;  especially a 1987 protocol signed
by Turkish prime minister Turgut Ozal  &MD;  form the basis of a final
agreement.
<p>
   The irony, of course, is that the sharing of waters between
Syria and Iraq has long ago been agreed  &MD;  even though Saddam
Hussein remains a visceral enemy of President Hafez Assad of
Syria.
 &LR; 
</TEXT>
