<SLUG> BC-EARNS-GREENPOINT-UPDA </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0434 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-GREENPOINT-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GREENPOINT 4TH-QUARTER EARNINGS RISE 75% (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates to add closing stock price)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- GreenPoint Financial Corp.'s
fourth-quarter net income rose 75 percent as the New York City
thrift increased nationwide mortgages and other lending.
<p>
   GreenPoint's net income rose to $33.9 million, or 81 cents a
share, from $19.4 million, or 42 cents, a year earlier. That beat
the average Wall Street estimate by a penny a share, according to a
Zacks Investment Research survey of 10 analysts.
<p>
   ``This past year was a breakthrough for GreenPoint,'' Chairman
and Chief Executive Thomas Johnson said in a statement. ``We began
to realize the strong financial rewards coming from careful
execution of our business strategy.'' GreenPoint shares fell 1/4 to
54 3/8. The company's net interest income -- the interest it
collected minus the interest it paid -- rose 13 percent to $114.6
million, as GreenPoint's interest expense fell 18 percent.
<p>
   Total loans outstanding rose 25 percent to $7.29 billion, as the
bank booked $735 million in mortgages in the quarter. GreenPoint
specializes in ``low-doc, no-doc'' mortgages, requiring less
documentation from applicants than most banks.
<p>
   The net interest margin, a measure of the gap between the
interest rates the bank pays and receives, widened to 3.82 percent
from 2.96 percent in the same period in 1995.
<p>
   The bank set aside $4.89 million for future loan losses,
compared with a recovery of $2.47 million a year earlier, though
total nonperforming assets fell 11 percent to $384.7 million.
<p>
   Noninterest income, excluding gains from securities sales, fell
15 percent to $10.8 million.
<p>
   Noninterest expense, including writeoffs goodwill related to
past acquisitions, fell 22 percent to $63.3 million, aided by
reduced premiums for federal deposit insurance.
<p>
   Net income for 1996 rose 23 percent to $132.5 million, or $3.02
a share, from $107.5 million, or $2.29, in 1995. --Joseph A.
Giannone in the New York newsroom (212) 318-2346/js
