<SLUG> BC-COMERICA-UPDATE1-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0712 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COMERICA-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMERICA TO CUT 14% OF JOBS, CLOSE BRANCHES (UPDATE3) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Joseph A. Giannone and Michael Smith &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds fourth-quarter net income from today's earnings report in
seventh paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Detroit, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Comerica Inc. said it will cut
1,890 jobs, or 14 percent of its workforce, and close branches to
cut costs, seeking to boost profits and avoid a potential takeover.
<p>
   The Detroit-based bank took a $90 million charge against
fourth-quarter earnings to pay for the job cuts and other
restructuring moves.
<p>
   The bank said its taking other measures to boost revenue by $110
million a year. Comerica needs the changes to convince investors
that the bank -- often cited by analysts as a likely takeover
target -- should remain independent.
<p>
   If Comerica doesn't cut costs, ``someone else will (cut) them
for us,'' said Chairman and Chief Executive Eugene Miller. ``And I
mean being taken over.''
<p>
   Comerica joins Keycorp, First of America Corp., Signet Banking
Corp. and others that are restructuring under pressure from
investors to boost profits. The moves make Comerica less attractive
to acquirers, analysts said, because there's less waste to trim.
<p>
   ``Sounds like they heard footsteps,'' said James Schmidt, a
portfolio manager at John Hancock Funds, which owns 552,800 shares.
<p>
   Comerica announced the steps as it reported that fourth-quarter
profit from operations rose 14 percent to $121 million, or $1.06 a
share -- a penny shy of Wall Street expectations. Net income,
including the $90 million restructuring charge, fell 43 percent to
$61 million, or 52 cents a share, from $107 million, or 92 cents,
in the same period in 1995.
<p>
   Comerica shares were unchanged at 56 1/4 in trading of 452,000
shares, not quite twice its daily average volume.
<p>
   The bank plans to cut jobs in all its businesses, using 1,800
suggestions culled from employees since September. Changes range
from reducing the number of people needed to approve a loan to
saving $1 million a year by using fewer kinds of envelopes. b3 The
bank was advised by Chandrika Tandon's New York-based Tandon
Capital Associates, a consulting firm which built a reputation for
slashing payrolls at other banks.
<p>
   Fleet Financial Corp., Chase Manhattan Corp., Michigan National
Bank, and Midlantic Bancorp all hired Tandon to devise ways to
boost profits at least in part by firing workers.
<p>
   Tandon organized four months of meetings, getting suggestions on
how to save money from 5,000 Comerica employees, ranging from
tellers to Miller. The bank's senior executives then decided which
ideas to implement.
<p>
   Miller said it wasn't difficult convincing his employees to come
up with ideas that may cost them their job in the end. ``We tried
to explain the rationale, that if we're going to grow the company
we have to do these things.''
<p>
   Some investors said banks tend to reduce costs even more than
expected in the long run after they've been
<p>
   ``She's been pretty successful in her plans, most of the banks
have beaten targets,'' said John Laupheimer, who manages a
portfolio of bank stocks for MFS Asset Management Group.
``Efficiency is the name of the game in banking.''
<p>
   Tandon couldn't immediately be reached for comment. In its
earnings report, Comerica said net interest income rose 3.6 percent
to $353.3 million as loans outstanding increased 4.7 percent to an
average of $25.5 billion in the quarter. The net interest margin
widened to 4.61 percent from 4.31 percent.
<p>
   Overall credit quality improved, as the bank reduced by 3
percent to $32 million the amount it set aside for future loan
losses while net write-offs fell 38 percent to $22.3 million.
<p>
   Total noninterest income fell 5.8 percent to $132.4 million,
amid declines in broker fees and revolving credit fees.
<p>
   Noninterest expense rose 24 percent to $356.2 million. Excluding
the restructuring charge, expenses fell 7.7 percent.
<p>
   For full year 1996, net income rose 0.9 percent to $417.2
million, or $3.55 a share, from $413.4 million, or $3.54, in 1995.
<p>
   Comerica, which has $34 billion in assets, operates about 365
branches in Michigan, California, Texas and Florida.
</TEXT>
