<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9539 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERFUND-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0898 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SUPERFUND-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. REPUBLICANS OFFER OLIVE BRANCH ON TOXIC CLEANUPS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Nora Macaluso &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Senate Republicans offered
the Clinton administration and environmental groups an olive branch
today in the form of a draft bill to overhaul Superfund, the
federal program to clean up toxic waste sites.
<p>
   Republican Sens. John Chafee of Rhode Island, the chairman of
the Environment Committee, and Bob Smith of New Hampshire, who
heads the panel's Superfund Subcommittee, proposed a bill to
streamline the program, restructure the way costs are allocated and
to give states more flexibility. Significantly they did not urge
repeal of liability for pollution caused before 1980, a key issue
that stalled legislation last year.
<p>
   The effort to restart negotiations follows years of stalemate,
with all sides agreeing that an overhaul is necessary but without
an agreement on what needs to be done.
<p>
   ``Superfund isn't working,'' Chafee said at a press conference
today. ``Superfund is rapidly becoming an environmental failure
rather than an environmental savior.''
<p>
   Chafee and Smith said they incorporated suggestions from
Democratic lawmakers and Clinton administration officials into the
new bill and welcome further comments. ``We're not saying this is
written in concrete,'' Chafee said.
<p>
   The new bill authorizes $15 million in annual grants to identify
``brownfields'' -- lightly contaminated industrial sites in
industrial or poor neighborhoods, and provides additional grants to
clean up those sites. The idea dovetails with a Clinton
administration plan that would give tax credits and other breaks to
companies that clean up these sites.
<p>
   The bill would give states primary responsibility for Superfund
cleanups. It also would exempt from liability individuals that
disposed of household wastes, and businesses with fewer than 30
employees or less than $3 million in revenue. There's also a
blanket exemption for those involved with municipal solid waste and
sludge, and limits on liability for religious, charitable,
scientific and educational organizations.
<p>
   The bill also would allow states flexibility in determining how
Superfund sites are cleaned up; and require the Environmental
Protection Agency to consider the planned future use of a site when
determining how clean a site must be.
<p>
   Since the Superfund program began in 1980, only 125 of the
approximately 1,300 sites covered by the program have been cleaned
up, according to Smith. At the same time, companies, municipalities
and the government have spent billions of dollars on litigation and
other issues related to the program.
<p>
   ``Superfund has become the classic example of a federal program
awash in red tape, litigation and gold-plated spending,'' Smith
said.
<p>
   Waste-management companies like Thermo TerraTech Inc. are likely
to profit once legislation is passed, regardless of the form it
takes.
<p>
   The Waltham, Massachusetts-based company provides environmental
services to a broad range of companies, and also has a number of
government contracts, said President and Chief Executive John P.
Appleton.
<p>
   Thermo TerraTech's cleanup subsidiary, Thermo Remediation Inc.,
derives about 20 percent of its revenue from Superfund work, said
Appleton.
<p>
   Thermo Remediation's revenue for the year ending in March is
likely to be ``something over $100 million,'' said Appleton, up
from $67 million in the last fiscal year. ``There is a lot of
activity there at the present moment,'' he said.
<p>
   ``I believe that companies have accepted the idea of
environmental stewardship,'' Appleton said. ``They know those
(Superfund) liabilities are not going to go away. They just want to
deal with them in as cost-effective a way as they can.''
<p>
   Appleton said he believes a new Superfund law would allow
companies to have a say in how sites are cleaned up, and would
allow for more of a case-by-case analysis.
<p>
   Thermo Remediation shares closed today at 7, up 1/4. Thermo
Electron shares rose 5/8 to 37 1/2.
<p>
   Insurance companies could also benefit from a law that clarified
their liabilities. The Smith-Chafee bill would cap liabilities in
some instances, but the senators denied that it would ``let
polluters off the hook,'' a charge leveled against last year's
bill.
<p>
   ``The allocation system (in the bill) has really got a lot of
wallop in it,'' Chafee said. Karen Florini, an attorney with the
Environmental Defense Fund, found several flaws in the proposal.
For example, she said, the bill doesn't ensure that ``toxic hot
spots'' will be cleaned up, fails to protect groundwater, and
``rolls back liability for some industrial polluters.''
<p>
   By limiting the number of sites that may be added to the
Superfund program in the future, states could end up footing the
bill for 1,400 to 2,300 additional sites, at a cost of $8.4 billion
to $19.9 billion, she said.
<p>
   The EPA, under Administrator Carol Browner, the EPA has cleaned
up more Superfund sites in three and a half years than it did in
the previous 12 years, according to an agency year-end review. Yet
even though improvements have been made to the program, ``we still
believe legislation is needed,'' said spokeswoman Lauren Mical.
<p>
   Mical said EPA officials are still going over the Smith-Chafee
bill.
</TEXT>
