<DOCID> nyt970122.0524 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=l pri=u sel=taf-z> A9542 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HENRY-GRUNWALD-PROFIL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0600 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HENRY-GRUNWALD-PROFILE-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW YORK: to do.'' &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   As he rose at Time  &MD;  from copy boy in 1944 to writer to senior
editor to assistant managing editor to managing editor (1968 to
1977) to corporate editor to editor in chief (1978 to 1987)  &MD; 
Grunwald loved the high-stakes pressure and heady power of that
business. In his book, he writes: ``I developed an almost physical
connection with news. Certain events, certain ideas for stories,
announced themselves, literally, in my pulse or in the pit of my
stomach.''
<p>
   And Grunwald experienced the Time &AMP; Life Building in midtown
Manhattan as a second home. In his early days as a reporter,
Grunwald writes, the office came to signify his American present, a
respite from his parent's confining ground-floor apartment, which
symbolized his immigrant past.
<p>
   Grunwald also described Time as a graduate school, populated by
eccentric, brilliant tutors who played out their tantrums, love
affairs and vices in full view of one another.
<p>
   They are the sort of characters Grunwald might have created had
he ever succeeded at his first love, writing plays. And he
describes them in the book with a novelist's flare for detail.
About the film critic James Agee: ``otherworldly to the point of
often leaving his paychecks uncashed in his desk drawer.'' The
foreign news editor Whittaker Chambers: ``with a twinkle in his
eyes that somehow did not go with his plain black or gray suits.''
<p>
   To this day, Grunwald said in his apartment, his inability to
succeed as a playwright rankles. But he spoke of it as a skill
that, simply, he was never destined to master. ``It will remain a
regret because theater was a great love of mine as a child, and you
don't easily get over first loves,'' he said. ``Would I change my
life if I could? Should I have quit Time and persevered in writing
plays? No, I really can't say that I would do that.
<p>
   ``It's like wanting to be a ballet dancer when you don't have
the body to be a ballet dancer. And I don't think that is failure
so much as misjudgment.''
<p>
   Grunwald is clearly proud of his work at Time and said he
continues to admire the magazine today. While he concedes that Time
may no longer be the intellectual status symbol it once was  &MD;  a
publication prominently displayed on people's coffee tables  &MD; 
Grunwald said he believes a good news magazine still has an
important role in explaining events. ``We are now surrounded,
enveloped, smothered by information,'' he said. ``Where news used
to be something that was relatively scarce  &MD;  people waited for it  &MD; 
now we are almost in a position of wanting to fight off the news.
<p>
   ``People need some guide through this chaos of information. It
is becoming increasingly difficult to tell the bogus from the real
and the many gradations in between. I would think the news magazine
is the perfect instrument to provide this.''
<p>
   Grunwald thus might be expected to feel nostalgic for the days
of meeting deadlines. But he said he enjoyed the two years he
served as ambassador to Austria after leaving Time Inc.  &MD; 
reacquainting himself with the Vienna of his childhood at a time
when Communism was collapsing. And despite his eye disease,
Grunwald said he has several writing projects in store.
<p>
   ``Yes, I do miss the action,'' he said, his cup of black coffee
now cold. ``I miss the connectedness with events. Writing a book  &MD; 
to use one of the world's oldest cliches  &MD;  is a lonely business
because you don't get any reaction for weeks, months, years.
<p>
   ``So that was a rather unusual experience. But I managed to get
through it.''
</TEXT>
