<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9541 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MICHIGAN-STOCKS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0324 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MICHIGAN-STOCKS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MICHIGAN STOCKS: HERMAN MILLER, COMPUWARE SPUR INDEX'S CLIMB &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Carol Wolf &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
Detroit, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Michigan stocks rose, led by shares
of Herman Miller Inc. and Compuware Corp., reversing yesterday's
decline.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The Michigan Index rose 0.74, or 0.05 percent, to close at
142.06. It lagged the broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index, which
rose 3.51, or 0.45 percent, to 786.23. Herman Miller shares led the
advance, rising 2 13/16 to 60 1/4 after Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. analyst
Pamela Singleton said in a report that the Zeeland-based maker of
office furniture is ``experiencing extremely strong demand'' for
its products. Singleton said she set a target of $70 for the stock.
<p>
   Compuware rose 2 to 60 1/4 after reporting better-than-expected
fiscal third-quarter earnings. Compuware said its profit from
operations for the period ended Dec. 31 rose 43 percent to $32.2
million, or 72 cents a share, from $22.6 million, or 52 cents, a
year earlier.
<p>
   Analysts expected the Farmington Hills-based company to earn 62
cents a share, the average of six analysts surveyed by IBES
International Inc. The software company's stock has risen 13
percent since it unveiled a product last week that will
automatically test new applications.
<p>
   Among decliners, shares in Gelman Sciences Inc., a maker of
medical diagnostic devices, fell 2 5/8 to 29 1/2, while Knape &AMP;
Vogt Manufacturing Co., a maker of storage products and shelving
systems, dropped 1 1/2 to 16 1/2.
<p>
   Among automakers, Chrysler Corp. shares were unchanged at 36,
after rising 1 1/2 yesterday when it reported record
higher-than-expected fourth-quarter profit.
<p>
   General Motors Corp. stock fell 1/8 to 61 7/8, while Ford Motor
Co. shares rose 5/8 to 34 1/4.
<p>
   The Michigan Index has risen 2.7 percent since January, compared
to a 6.1 percent increase in the S&AMP;P 500.
</TEXT>
