<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TRAVELER'S-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TRAVELERS RISES TO RECORD ON BUYBACK, DIVIDEND PLANS (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Ted Hampton &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates share price; adds comment from investor starting in
third paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Travelers Group Inc. said it
would buy back as much as $1 billion of stock and increase its
dividend 33 percent, sending the insurance and financial services
company's shares to an all-time high.
<p>
   Travelers stock rose 2 3/8, or 4.6 percent, to a record 53 5/8
in trading of 2.7 million shares, exceeding its recent daily
trading average of 1.3 million shares.
<p>
   ``They're just doing a great job across the field, and we figure
they're going to continue to outclass their competitors,'' said
Alfred Feinman, a general partner at the New York-based Glickenhaus
&AMP; Co., which owns about 2 million Travelers shares. ``We'll stick
with it.''
<p>
   Today's announcements reflected the expectation Travelers will
keep its profits growing, ``generating enormous amounts of cash
flow,'' Travelers Vice Chairman Jeffrey Lane said. ``The board
feels confident about the future.''
<p>
   The buyback represents as much as 18.6 million shares at today's
price, or about 3 percent of the 639 million shares outstanding.
Repurchases will meet demands of Travelers' employee stock option
and other benefit programs, the company said.
<p>
   Travelers Chairman Sanford Weill yesterday told analysts that
30,000 of the company's 45,000 employees own Travelers shares.
<p>
   The stock-ownership program has won praise among investors. ``
As long as they're willing to put their money on the line, we will
be too,'' said Feinman at Glickenhaus, which acquired its shares 10
years ago in a company called Commercial Credit, now a unit of
Travelers.
<p>
   ``The thing that originally attracted us was that Sanford Weill,
plus the people he brought in, were going to be rewarded by stock
options, not by big fat bonuses,'' Feinman said.
<p>
   In addition, Travelers' said it would increase the company's
quarterly dividend to 15 cents a share from 11.25 cents. It's
payable on Feb. 21 to investors who hold the shares on Feb. 3.
</TEXT>
