<DOCID> nyt970122.0527 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=u sel=taf-z> A9545 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TUCKWELL-MUSIC-ART-NY </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1077 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TUCKWELL-MUSIC-ART-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Md., Australia, Britain) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BARRY TUCKWELL: WITH LITTLE FANFARE, LEADING HORN PLAYER ENDS
CAREER &LR;  &QL; 
(ART ADV: Color photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By JAMES R. OESTREICH &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Those who have lost close track of Barry Tuckwell's illustrious
career over the last decade or two may be surprised to learn that
his final public performances on the horn, Thursday night, Friday
and Saturday, are to take place in Baltimore.
<p>
   With no insult intended to that fair city, it seems an
out-of-the-way place for this ultimate musical cosmopolite to take
his leave.
<p>
   Until, that is, one pursues the 65-year-old Tuckwell to his
home, on the outskirts of Hagerstown, Md.
<p>
   Hagerstown IS out of the way, tucked in the rolling hills
between Pennsylvania and West Virginia some 75 miles northwest of
Baltimore.
<p>
   Tuckwell, whom The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians
describes as ``the leading horn player of his generation,'' was
born in Melbourne, Australia, in 1931, and spent most of his
50-year playing career based in London. He has been an itinerant
soloist and conductor since leaving his positions as principal horn
player and chairman of the board of the London Symphony in 1968, so
American music lovers may not have noticed when he began to
resettle in their midst.
<p>
   The ``catalyst,'' he said, was Walter Lawson, a maker of brass
instruments who played horn in the Baltimore Symphony for 26 years
and now has a shop with his three sons and a daughter-in-law in
nearby Boonsboro.
<p>
   In 1982, in consultation with Lawson and others, Tuckwell
founded the Maryland Symphony, which he still conducts, as a
successor to the bedraggled Potomac Symphony. And he was drawn
increasingly to the area.
<p>
   ``I wanted to live in the country,'' he said last week, sitting
in his living room, which offered a broad view of the spacious
backyard, where squirrels romped in the snow. ``But one thing led
to another.''
<p>
   In Hagerstown, he met Sue Levitan, a former sports reporter for
The Baltimore Sun, who has since become his third wife. He
established permanent residency in the United States in 1992 and
became a U.S. citizen last May. The youngest of his three children,
all born in England, now also lives in Hagerstown along with two
stepdaughters.
<p>
   So yes, Baltimore. Tuckwell is to perform Oliver Knussen's Horn
Concerto and Mozart's Concerto in E flat (K. 447), with the
Baltimore Symphony, conducted by George Cleve at the Joseph
Meyerhoff Symphony Hall.
<p>
   Knussen, an Englishman, composed his terse and charmingly
atmospheric work in 1994, ``as a grateful response to more than 30
years of hearing Barry Tuckwell play,'' he has written. Tuckwell
has since recorded it brilliantly for Deutsche Grammophon, with the
London Sinfonietta, led by Knussen.
<p>
   Mozart's four horn concertos are, of course, standard fare in a
relatively limited field. Tuckwell has played them many times and
recorded them complete on three occasions. Still, they remain fresh
for him, he said, and especially this one, because it constantly
yields up new lessons.
<p>
   ``Yes, it's relatively simple,'' he explained. ``But there is
much more to music than technical challenges. The most important
thing is learning how to turn a phrase, how to make a simple melody
sound interesting.''
<p>
   That was a lesson Tuckwell learned early from a seemingly
unlikely source: recordings of the American jazz trombonist Tommy
Dorsey. ``I played along with his records when I was a kid,'' he
said. ``I'm proud to say I took lessons from Tommy Dorsey.''
<p>
   Matters of balance and structure also emerge starkly in Mozart.
``That's where the real difficulties come in,'' Tuckwell said.
``Throughout my career, each performance has in effect been a
rehearsal for the next. The sad thing is that Saturday evening will
be my last rehearsal.''
<p>
   Tuckwell grew up in a musical family; his father played the
mighty Wurlitzer organ in the local movie palace. After toying with
organ, piano and violin himself, he took up the horn at 13. Within
months, he was filling in with the Melbourne Symphony.
<p>
   He had played most of the major horn concertos by the time he
was 17, and a succession of orchestral positions in Australia and
England led him to the London Symphony in 1955. The rest is a very
rich history.
<p>
   Players of brass instruments live by their lungs, teeth, lips
and facial muscles, and do not always age well. If Tuckwell's
prodigious abilities on the horn have fallen off in any significant
way, however, the loss is not apparent from reviews of his
performances.
<p>
   His decision to retire while still in fine form, he has said,
was motivated less by any sense of decline than by a realization
that his career could hardly get better than it has been in recent
years. The move was made easier by the knowledge that he had
established himself as a conductor with many orchestras and could
continue to perform pretty much at will.
<p>
   The one place where he will not conduct so much after this
season is Hagerstown, for he is resigning his position with the
Maryland Symphony. His relations with the orchestra's board have
soured, he said, partly because the directors declined his offer to
play a farewell recital with internationally renowned friends to
benefit the orchestra, suggesting that it would be too much bother.
He says he will miss the steady contact with the players.
<p>
   ``He has taken an orchestra that played really simple stuff, a
sort of civic symphony, and made it into one that can perform
Mahler's First Symphony and Shostakovich's Fifth very well,'' said
Lawson, the horn maker. ``He's a real conductor. He has left his
imprint here, and the town loves him.''
<p>
   One of the area's logistical assets, Lawson said, is its
proximity to four airports, and Tuckwell will continue to rely on
them. He remains principal guest conductor of the Northern
Sinfonia, in Newcastle-Upon-Tyne, England, as he has been since
1992. And he has numerous engagements lined up around the world.
<p>
   Beyond that, he will relish some free time. ``I have so many
things I want to hear again,'' he said. ``I don't know how many
yards of reel-to-reel tapes I have lined up. I hope they're still
good. I have a lot to do.''
<p>
   ``Besides, I want to play,'' he added, and he didn't mean horn.
</TEXT>
