<DOCID> nyt970122.0532 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=u sel=taf-z> A9550 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-POP-MUSIC-NOTEBOOK-2T </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0717 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-POP-MUSIC-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SOUNDS UNNOTICED LAST YEAR: 10 ALBUMS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; '60s BAND TRYING FOR FAME IN THE '90s &LR;  &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By NEIL STRAUSS &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Though music business sales last year were flat, this had little
to do with the quality of music produced and released. Last year,
independent and international labels released scores of worthy
albums, but many slipped by unnoticed, in large part because these
labels are unable to afford extensive promotion, distribution or
tours for their bands.
<p>
   Listed here are 10 records from 1996 that haven't received much
attention but are worth the extra time it takes to hunt for them,
either through mail order or a local independent record store.
<p>
   Note that, with the increasing frequency at which big labels
sign fledgling bands, a list could just as easily be made of
quality releases by one of the six major labels last year that
received no marketing, promotion or support.
<p>
   `THE SOUL OF CAPE VERDE' (Tinder, 619 Martin Ave., Rohnert Park,
Calif. 94928) Colonization and miscegenation, farming and drought,
emigration and homesickness are among the many elements that
penetrate the sparse, soulful songs of the Cape Verde islands, off
the coast of Senegal, filling the music with a melancholy beauty
lovingly captured on this 19-song compilation.
<p>
   BOWERY ELECTRIC: `BEAT' (Kranky, Box 578743, Chicago 60657) The
release of albums of spacey, droning rock has become a veritable
industry, and of the many great albums that came out this year  &MD; 
from Magnog to Quickspace to Spectrum's collaboration with
Jessamine  &MD;  this was among the best, mixing guitars and drums with
keyboards and electronic effects to create the musical equivalent
of an optical illusion: Is it moving or standing still?
<p>
   ZEN: `DERYA' (Father Yod/Ecstatic Peace, Box 2274, Amherst,
Mass. 01002) Continuing an almost 40-year-old tradition of
innovative rock in Turkey, Zen mixes psychedelic rock, free jazz
and folk melodies and rhythms to come up with 12 challenging and
beguiling improvisations.
<p>
   LOOSE DIAMONDS: `FRESCO FIASCO' (Freedom, Box 650032, Austin,
Texas 78765) This driving Austin roots-rock band unplugs for a
winsome folk-country album on which every tentative strum, every
slightly staggered phrase conveys an emotion that runs as deep as
the music's roots.
<p>
   PRINCE PAUL: `PSYCHOANALYSIS (WHAT IS IT?)' (Wordsound, 129
North 11th Street, Brooklyn, N.Y. 11211) It's hard to realize just
how constrained rappers are by the conventions of the form and the
pressure of their peers and public until hearing an album like
this, on which Prince Paul (formerly associated with De La Soul and
Stetsasonic) unwinds and lets his somewhat puerile mind wander.
<p>
   SUBTROPIC: `HOMEBREW' (Reflective, 759 Harrison, San Francisco
94107) Jake Smith, who records as Subtropic, delivers one of
America's best drum-and-bass albums, approaching the music's
agitated beats with an ear for compositional form and an ability to
speak through rhythm.
<p>
   THE DELGADOS: `DOMESTIQUES' (Chemikal Underground, Box 3609,
Glasgow, Scotland G42 9TP) Reminiscent of their fellow Scots the
Vaselines, the Delgados trade male and female vocals over smart,
infectious songs that mix bubble gum pop, punk rock and occasional
dissonance.
<p>
   `SUSHI 3003' (Bungalow Germany) Taking kitschy cocktail music to
the next level, the 16 modern Japanese bands on this compilation
(several of them side projects of Pizzicato Five) offer variations
on Burt Bacharach, Antonio Carlos Jobim and original melodies using
as many archaic synthesizers, vibraphones, kitten-ish singers and
eccentricities as they can.
<p>
   BETH ORTON: ``TRAILER PARK' (Heavenly, 72 Wardour St., London,
England, W1V 3HP) To find her own timeless muse, Ms. Orton touches
up '60s folk with everything from string sections to trip-hop beats
on a debut album that fuses the lounge-pop of Everything but the
Girl and the soft-spoken introspection of Nick Drake.
<p>
   DUB WAR: `WRONG SIDE OF BEAUTIFUL' (Earache UK) Packing the
political punch of Rage Against the Machine, Dub War, led by a
Welsh Rastafarian, stomps through hardcore punk, dancehall reggae
and rhythm-and-blues ballads with equal proficiency and intensity.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (MORE)
