<DOCID> nyt970122.0533 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=u sel=taf-z> A9551 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-POP-MUSIC-NOTEBOOK-2N </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0566 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-POP-MUSIC-NOTEBOOK-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: and intensity. &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Silver Apples
<p>
   The Knitting Factory in Manhattan was packed Sunday night for
the revival of a band that was never popular in its own time: the
Silver Apples. In the late 1960s, the duo was making cutting-edge
art-pop on homemade electronic instruments. But their record label
marketed them like a pop band, putting them on bills with bubble
gum acts like the 1910 Fruitgum Company.
<p>
   Record-company hype took the band's first album to No. 193 on
the pop charts; its second album didn't even have that nominal
success, and the third and last recording was never even released.
<p>
   But in a testament to the power of mass production, the band's
albums began to take on a life of their own, prized by fans of
German progressive-rock looking for an American equivalent and by
new-music fans as precursors of everything from new wave to techno
to the electro-pop of current bands like Stereolab.
<p>
   But the band's members were completely unaware that they were
turning into legends and pioneers. In an interview before his
performance Sunday, Simeon, the singer, banjo player and
electronics whiz of the Silver Apples, said the tapes of the third
album festered in storage for so long that they were eventually
sold and most likely erased.
<p>
   He said he left the homemade instrument he used on his albums
(known as the Simeon) under a friend's house in Alabama in the
mid-1980s. And he said that he completely lost touch with the
band's other original member, the percussionist Danny Taylor.
<p>
   In 1994, Sony Music even hired a detective to track down the
pair to ask about the missing album. But he was unable to locate
either member.
<p>
   ``Until last year, I thought the Silver Apples were a dead
issue,'' said Simeon, who has been living in Annapolis, Md.,
working as everything from an ice-cream truck driver to a
television news reporter.
<p>
   ``I was pursuing my painting. And one day at an art gallery in
Brooklyn I met a guy named Xian. Recognizing my unusual name, he
asked me if I knew what was going on. So I went around to different
record stores and picked up a bunch of albums that were influenced
by my music. One was an English tribute album to our band. So I
called up the label to thank them, and they promised us the world
if we would create some new music for them.''
<p>
   Simeon tried to find Taylor through the Internet and through
newspaper ads. After failing, he invited Xian (who pronounces his
name Christian) to join his band on electronics.
<p>
   In concert at the Knitting Factory, Simeon and Xian were joined
by an additional keyboardist, a drummer and two very awkward
vocalists. The group mixed Silver Apples songs like
``Oscillations'' with warped electronic versions of '60s classics
like ``In the Midnight Hour.''
<p>
   Since all of them, including Simeon, had to learn the songs from
scratch, they sounded more like a Silver Apples cover band than the
Silver Apples.
<p>
   Now that he's back in the music world, Simeon said he doesn't
plan on leaving again. The Beastie Boys have been talking to him
about reissuing his albums on their Grand Royal label and the
German digital hardcore band Atari Teenage Riot is interested in
collaborating with him.
<p>
   ``I feel like a caged animal that's suddenly been released and
he's running around the zoo terrorizing people,'' he replied.
</TEXT>
