<SLUG> BC-MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0572 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MUTUAL FUNDS: STI STARTS EMERGING MARKETS FUND &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Katherine Burton &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Investors are increasing their
bets in emerging markets funds and so are fund companies.
<p>
   STI Capital Management in Orlando, Florida is one company that
reckons emerging markets will be hot in 1997, so at the end of the
month, it's opening a new fund, STI Emerging Markets Fund.
<p>
   Analysts expect STI will be getting lots more company.
<p>
   ``We've heard a lot of chatter from fund companies'' about
starting emerging markets funds, said Michael Lipper, head of
Lipper Analytical Services Inc. Twenty-eight funds (or new classes
of funds) opened in 1996, according to Lipper, which now follows
116 such funds in its database.
<p>
   This year ``will be an extremely strong year for emerging
markets funds,'' said Gavin Quill, vice president of marketing at
Scudder, Stevens &AMP; Clark in Boston. Scudder's emerging markets
growth fund has pulled in $18 million so far this month, its best
draw yet in its seven-month life. Scudder's Latin American fund has
attracted $41 million, its largest inflow of money in three years.
<p>
   Investors are betting that international markets, and especially
emerging markets, will outperform the U.S. this year. So far in
1997, Russian, Turkish and Hungarian stock markets are the top
performing markets in the world.
<p>
   STI's fund will be managed by Pablo Salas, who also manages the
firm's $18 million institutional emerging markets portfolio, which
returned about 15 percent last year. That compares with 4 percent
for the Morgan Stanley Capital International Emerging Markets Index
and 11.2 percent on average for emerging markets mutual funds,
according to Lipper Analytical.
<p>
   Salas' biggest bet is Brazil, where he has 13 percent of his
portfolio. That includes stakes in power companies Cia. Energetica
de Minas Gerais and Centrais Eletricas de Santa Catarina SA, which
he expects should benefit from government plans to sell state
assets this year.
<p>
   Argentina comprises another 8 percent of the portfolio,
including Banco Frances del Rio de la Plata SA, one of the
country's leading banks. Salas may be unloading that stock soon,
though, because it has already risen almost 50 percent since Sept.
1.
<p>
   Like many international managers, Salas is hunting around the
markets in Korea and Thailand, which tumbled last year, their
benchmark indexes losing 27 percent and 41 percent respectively.
<p>
   ``I see lots of companies selling at less than half the price
they were last year,'' said Salas, who has recently bought two Thai
companies -- Hana Microelectronics Co., a maker of integrates
circuits and printed circuit boards, and K.R. Precision Plc., a
maker of computer components. Salas likes them because their
profits aren't tied to the local economy.
<p>
   Another inexpensive market is South Africa, where Salas has
about 11 percent of his portfolio. ``The valuations are pretty
interesting now,'' he said, considering that Morgan Stanley's South
Africa index fell about 20 percent in dollar terms last year.
<p>
   ``Last year I invested in companies benefiting from a weak
rand,'' said Salas, including Anglo American Coal Corp.; Sasol
Ltd., a producer of liquid fuels and chemicals and Barlow Ltd., a
construction equipment and building materials and retailing
company.
</TEXT>
