<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9556 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-STOCKS-CLOSE-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0298 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PERU-STOCKS-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PERU STOCKS MIXED AS PHONE COMPANY GAINS OFFSET MINING SLUMP &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Carol Salguero &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Lima, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Peruvian stocks were mixed, as
gains by Telefonica del Peru were offset by declining mining
shares.
<p>
   ``Telefonica's prospects for this year are good,'' said Cesar
Beltran, head trader at Coril stock brokerage.
<p>
   Peru's Selective Index rose 2.59 points, or 0.12 percent, to
2,177.98, while the General Index dropped 2.08 points, or 0.14
percent, to 1,520.77.
<p>
   Telefonica said operating profits increased 27 percent in 1996
compared with 1995, raising fourth quarter profit per ADR to $0.477
from $0.373 last year.
<p>
   Telefonica rose 1.08 percent to 5.61 soles, as trading of
26,897,000 soles worth of shares ($10.26 million) accounted for 39
percent of volume.
<p>
   Investors look forward to the publication of the country's 1996
economic results, hoping to confirm the end of a year-long
recession. The government projects first quarter growth of 4
percent. Investors are wary following last year's fluctuating
growth of 2.2 percent for the first 11 months.
<p>
   The government will announce statistics on December's growth and
January's inflation at the beginning of February.
<p>
   Among other widely traded issues, Minsur SA dropped 1.50 percent
to 9.20 soles, while Cia. de Minas Buenaventura SA ``A'' shares
dropped 2.22 percent to 17.60 soles. The company's labor, or
non-voting, share dropped 3.31 percent to 17.50 soles.
<p>
   ``The price drop reflects lower gold prices,'' Beltran said.
<p>
   In the parallel currency market, the closing price for the sol
wasn't immediately available. The sol closed yesterday at
2.617/2.619 soles to the U.S. dollar.
</TEXT>
