<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9563 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FED-PARRY-UPDATE1-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0761 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FED-PARRY-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PARRY SAYS INFLATION MAY RISE AS ECONOMY STRENGTHENS (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Tom Bemis &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds further Parry comments)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   San Francisco, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. inflation may rise in
1997 because employment is high and the economy is showing new
signs of strength, Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco President
Robert Parry said today.
<p>
   ``Inflation could be set to rise in the future,'' Parry said in
the text of a speech to the National Association of Business
Economists in San Francisco. ``Available data on the fourth quarter
have shown considerable strength,'' he said.
<p>
   Parry said this year's strong start means the economy is ``going
to achieve at least its trend rate of growth'' at a rate of between
2 percent and 2.5 percent. At that rate, he said, ``I don't think
one has to be particularly concerned about an acceleration of
inflation.''
<p>
   Still, he said, Fed policymakers must be prepared to quell
inflationary pressures before they actually result in higher
prices.
<p>
   ``If one waits until one sees a problem, however you define it,
then I'm afraid that you're behind the 8-ball quite a bit,'' he
said.
<p>
   Yesterday Parry told reporters he expects the 1997 core rate of
inflation, which excludes volatile energy and food prices, to rise
``a couple of tenths'' to 2.8 percent from 2.6 percent in 1996.
<p>
   Parry's comments today came as newly released figures showed
U.S. housing starts last year rose 8.8 percent to 1.474 million,
the highest level since 1988.
<p>
   The Fed's `beige book'' survey of regional economic data
released today also found ``scattered evidence'' of pressure for
higher wages.
<p>
   U.S. bonds were lower after the U.S. Treasury sold $17.5 billion
of two-year notes today. The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell
1/2, pushing its yield up more than 4 basis points to 6.82 percent.
<p>
   Traders said comments late yesterday from Federal Reserve
Governor Susan Phillips revived concern the Fed may raise interest
rates soon.
<p>
   Phillips suggested in a Market News interview that the Fed might
not wait for a rise in the core consumer price index before
boosting rates.
<p>
   The Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC), the interest
rate-setting body of the central bank, is next scheduled to meet
Feb. 4-5. Parry, who is widely viewed as an inflation hawk, is a
voting member of the FOMC.
<p>
   Yesterday Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told a Senate
hearing that there are few signs of inflation in the economy.
<p>
   ``The economy has retained considerable vigor, with few signs of
the imbalances and inflationary tensions that have disrupted past
expansions,'' Greenspan said. ``By some important measures of price
trends, inflation actually slowed a bit in 1996.''
<p>
   His remarks yesterday helped boost the Dow Jones Industrial
average to a record close of 6877.35. Today, the Dow closed down
33.9 points at 6850. Broader market indices were higher.
<p>
   Fed officials have said tightening job markets are the most
likely threat to price stability in 1997. That's partly because
average hourly earnings rose 6 cents last month, or 0.5 percent,
according to the Labor Department. For all of last year, hourly
earnings climbed 3.8 percent, the biggest gain since a similar 3.8
percent increase in 1990.
<p>
   Last Thursday, Federal Reserve Gov. Laurence Meyer, widely
viewed as an inflation dove, warned the Fed would have to raise
interest rates if unemployment falls much below the current 5.3
percent rate.
<p>
   Greenspan also left open the possibility of an interest rate
increase if the economy grows faster than the 3.0 percent rate he
forecast for 1996. ``Indeed, the recent pickup in some measures of
wages suggests that the transition may already be running its
course,'' the Fed chairman said.
<p>
   Parry reiterated comments he made in a speech yesterday to the
Financial Women's Association that workers who have been more
concerned with keeping their jobs than getting pay raises will
likely begin seeking wage increases this year.
<p>
   ``Even if some workers continue to feel insecure, they still
won't be willing to pass up wage increases forever,'' Parry said
yesterday.
<p>
   He also said a stronger dollar, which makes foreign goods
cheaper by comparison with American products, is unlikely to help
keep inflation down. ``Our inflation rate ultimately depends on our
monetary policy, and not on the existence of foreign competitors,''
Parry said in the text of his speech to the business economists.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1821EST
</TRAILER>
