<DOCID> nyt970122.0538 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=l pri=u sel=taf-z> A9564 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SHODDY-HOUSES-950&AMP;ADD </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1058 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SHODDY-HOUSES-950&AMP;ADD-ART-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHEN WHAT YOU SEE IS ALL YOU GET &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Colo., Conn., Fla.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (kd) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JULIE V. IOVINE &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Preliminary designs for Michael Eisner's multimillion-dollar log
cabin in Aspen, Colo., included stone fireplaces to rival Yosemite
National Park's Ahwahnee Hotel  &MD;  and a retaining wall so thin that
it would have buckled under its own weight.
<p>
   At the Connecticut compound of a retired tennis champion, the
foundation for a new guest house was laid over construction-site
trash, resulting in major cracks and leaks.
<p>
   And the $40 million Long Island house for a billionaire software
developer used an inexpensive Western pine siding that was so
vulnerable to decay that it began to rot while the house was still
under construction.
<p>
   If people with unlimited budgets cannot count on quality
construction, who can?
<p>
   House buyers today want homes of substance, but they may be
trading quality for showy flourishes, building experts say. From
stage-set stairways to nine-foot ceilings, from granite counter
tops to exercise rooms, styling is supplanting substance in houses
that cost more than $300,000, driven by a new-home buying public
that may be unwittingly confusing luxury with quality.
<p>
   ``To many people, crown moldings mean quality,'' said Don
Killoren, the general manager for construction at Celebration,
Fla., the new town development owned by the Walt Disney Co. ``A
detailed railing, for example, may not be sturdier, but the
implication is that it is. And people assume that if that much
thought went into the finishes, the whole thing is more solid,
which may or may not be the case.''
<p>
   Most experts agree with Randy Smith, the president of the
National Association of Home Builders, that building is better than
during the Roaring Eighties, when a lot of fast-track homes were
quickly  &MD;  and poorly  &MD;  constructed. But interviews with more than
30 developers, builders, architects and carpenters  &MD;  from New
England to Florida, from Texas to California  &MD;  painted a less rosy
picture of a hit-or-miss home-building industry in which a modest
Cape Codder in Connecticut may have more nails in place than a
grandiose villa in Florida.
<p>
   Given a lack of enforceable building codes, little
self-monitoring by the industry, pressure to make profits and an
undertrained workforce, houses and their owners are more dependent
than ever on the integrity of individual builders.
<p>
   ``You can have an excellent design, the most expensive
materials, and still end up with poor performance in a house if
there was no quality of assembly,'' said Jonathan Stone, a program
specialist in the United States Energy Department's Office of
Building Systems in Washington. The office is financing research to
investigate ways to improve energy efficiency in houses.
<p>
   ``Fancy, energy-efficient products, such as thermal-pane
windows, don't mean anything if they're badly installed,'' Stone
said.
<p>
   Boyce Thompson, the editor in chief of Builder, a trade journal,
said, ``The industry's largest problem is the lack of skilled
labor, so builders are always looking for ways to decrease the
amount of labor necessary.'' He cited the pervasive use of
prefabricated walls, floors and roofs, now used in more than half
of all new houses, which can reduce construction time by 25 percent
over that of stick-build framing.
<p>
   Many builders say that prefabricated parts, which are
standardized and built to fit, are superior, Thompson said.
``Whenever you can use truss roofs, panelized walls, larger prefab
components and just tilt it up to put the house together, the
better off you are,'' he said. ``You used to have to build stairs
by hand. Now, stairs come in a kit. Fireplace mantles may look
custom, but in reality they come in kits.''
<p>
   But others argue that prebuilt and panelized walls and roofing
systems contribute to the ``dumbing down'' of the construction
site. Chuck Lennon, a former executive director of the Building
Industry Association of South Florida, based in Miami, said:
``Requirements on the job site are not what they used to be. And
the men are working so fast they don't always pay attention to see
if their nails are hitting the wood or not.''
<p>
   He continued: ``When Hurricane Andrew hit, it was shocking to
see how many nails had never touched wood. If you're buying a
house, just make sure you've got a builder who's willing to come
back and fix things later.''
<p>
   The National Association of Home Builders is investigating the
possibility of establishing a nationwide uniform building code.
<p>
   Some experts say that most buyers agonize over the wrong things.
``People just want drop-dead,'' said Tom Kligerman, a Manhattan
architect, who was a project designer for Robert A.M. Stern. ``They
find it boring to spend money on foundations and stud walls. They'd
rather spend it on what they can see.''
<p>
   Stern, famous for the high polish of his luxury homes, said:
``It appears that what sells houses depends on having a tub large
enough for at least two people, and probably more; flashy stairs
that make a racket as if a horse were climbing them, and other
glitzy, totally unnecessary elements, as opposed to spatial or
constructional quality.''
<p>
   A survey of 3,583 potential home buyers, commissioned by the
builders' association and to be released on Sunday at its annual
convention in Houston, indicates that buyers want the kind of
features ``that just a few years ago were reserved for upscale
luxury homes,'' said Smith, the group's president. He rattled tHem
off: nine-foot ceilings, Corian counters, pantries and the newly
trendy ``great room''  &MD;  a gussied-up recreation room that has moved
upstairs and has acquired a fireplace, wet bar and media center.
<p>
   Spencer Goliger, an architect in Palm Beach, Fla., said: ``We're
seeing a lot more faux finishes for that Old World look. People are
not interested in the real dimensions of wood or what it can do,
but just how it looks. So you get plywood that looks like cherry;
moldings made of plastic. People want to capture a certain look as
cheaply as possible.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (MORE)
<p>
   nn
</POSTTEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1821EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0539 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=l pri=u sel=taf-z> A9565 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SHODDY-HOUSES-2NDTAKE </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0949 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SHODDY-HOUSES-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: as possible.'' &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Perhaps we are headed for Disney-style theme parks in our own
homes, with counters that look like nice slabs of granite but are
actually made of the thinnest veneer glued to concrete, where miles
of molding are made of polystyrene, the building block of coffee
cups.
<p>
   ``There's no doubt that people are in the market for quality,''
said Tom Murphy, a custom builder in Miami, whose clients have
included Oprah Winfrey and Sylvester Stallone. ``The big question
is, Are they getting something that's sound or junk with perfume on
it?''
One person who knows is Donald Baerman, part architect, part
sleuth. Based in North Haven, Conn., he teaches a course in
architecture at Yale University and is often hired by architects
and lawyers to sniff out potential design lapses and construction
defects. In his 37 years as a consultant, he has seen it all, from
collapsed roofs to insufficiently supported hot tubs. (It was
Baerman who detected the early design flaw in the Eisner house; the
architects say they do not remember the problem at all.)
<p>
   ``I've seen buildings that cut every corner that can be cut,''
Baerman said one day last month as he toured the site of a new
house in a proliferating development in Mount Kisco, N.Y., within
easy commuting distance of Manhattan. On a day trip organized to
instruct a reporter on what passes for quality in construction
these days, Baerman, a young 65 with furry eyebrows worthy of a
Muppet, was equipped with a Swiss Army knife, a pointer flashlight
and, he said, ``a geezer memory for details.'' As further testament
to his devotion to quality, he wore leather shoes that he had made
himself.
<p>
   The house, a brick veneer, twin-gabled, two-story affair, was
built by Toll Brothers, the development company that is based
outside Philadelphia and was a 1995 winner of the National
Association of Home Builders' quality award.
<p>
   The house, albeit a new sales model, is typical of many in the
region: about 3,500 square feet, with neo-traditional styling,
peaked roofs, a master suite, a chef's kitchen and a base price of
$546,950. The model was fitted with enough optional upgrades  &MD; 
marble in the master bathroom, window wells in the basement  &MD;  to
bring it up to $620,000.
<p>
   ``I look for real defects, not how much swank you can get for
the buck,'' Baerman said. And despite some general gripes about
typical industry practices like putting unyielding brick veneer on
a wood frame that expands and contracts (it could lead to leaks
around doors and windows, ``but then everybody does it,'' he said),
Baerman was pleasantly assured by what he found.
<p>
   Not that the house got off without any complaints. ``Houses
between $300,000 and $1 million are about the same,'' he said. ``To
do it really right is much more expensive, and there are still no
guarantees.''
<p>
   Stepping through mulch chips, he tapped on a shutter.
``Plastic!'' he said. New bricks, he noted, had been stamped with a
fake patina to look handmade, but their uniform lines only
accentuated the artifice.
<p>
   He allowed himself a Ruskinian moment. ``Really good work shows
irregularities,'' he said, ``almost as if it were done by a skilled
laborer with some difficulties.''
<p>
   Surveying the exterior, he focused on the siding, a ``very
low-grade Redcedar, which is neither red nor cedar,'' he said. It
has a horizontal grain that might warp (``Look for vertical grain
siding,'' he advised). Wood siding should be painted on all
surfaces before installation to avoid rot, he said. Pointing out
the proximity to automatic lawn sprinklers, he gave the siding
about two years until the onset of rot should water be trapped on
the underside. (Rob Parahus, a vice president of Toll Brothers,
said the siding had been preprimed by the manufacturer.)
<p>
   After a brief appreciation of the cedar deck, which appeared to
be securely attached to the foundation with bolts (often only the
weight of the deck secures the posts to the ground), Baerman moved
inside and made a beeline for the windows. He sighed. The
vinyl-clad thermopane windows, though efficient, were much uglier
than wooden frames because of snap-in plastic mullions that come
out for easy cleaning but that can also snap off when eager
children grab on to look outdoors. Plastic-coated wire shelving in
all the closets, but especially the one in the front hall, seemed
inexcusable, he said, for such a costly house.
<p>
   In important ways, however, the house stood up well. In the
bathrooms, the tubs were made of cast iron, not steel or plastic.
``When you tap the sides,'' Baerman said, ``look for a sound that
goes `thunk, thunk,' not `ping, ping.' '' In the basement, a steel
girder gave extra support to the floor above, and a beam of
structural fabricated wood reinforced the upstairs kitchen island.
<p>
   Pocketing his flashlight, Baerman made his judgment: ``I've seen
really bad construction, and this is not it. There's nothing
insidious hidden from the eye. I get good vibes, and I always trust
my instincts.''
<p>
   When reached for comment, Parahus said: ``Our houses are built
with today's consumers in mind. And above all, they want
ease-of-maintenance products in their homes. Those snap-in mullions
and vinyl-coated shelves are in demand.''
<p>
   Ever philosophical, and ever snug in his homemade shoes, Baerman
concluded: ``A hundred years ago, it wasn't all that different.
There are good builders and bad ones in every era. Today, there's a
tendency to give people what they can see. And there's nothing
wrong with that as long as people don't forget what really superb
workmanship is about, even if they can't afford it.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1822EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0540 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=u sel=taf-z> A9568 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDANCE-FILM-FESTIVA </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0927 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SUNDANCE-FILM-FESTIVAL-2TAKES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: AT SUNDANCE, FILMS LEAP FROM THE MAINSTREAM &LR;  &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By JANET MASLIN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   PARK CITY, Utah  &MD;  They may be ugly, blind and foul, but they're
among the major attractions at the 1997 Sundance Film Festival. And
when hairless pink mole rats start looking like movie stars, it's
proof that Park City is witnessing Bizarro Sundance this year.
<p>
   This festival, the pre-eminent showcase for American independent
film, hit its high-water mark last year with a phenomenal array of
appealing, accessible features (among them ``Big Night,'' ``Welcome
to the Dollhouse,'' ``Looking for Richard,'' ``Walking and
Talking,'' ``The Whole Wide World'' and ``Citizen Ruth''). And
Sundance is sure to be represented on Oscar night, not only by
``Shine,'' last year's smash hit, but by ``Jerry Maguire,'' which
has the sweet, quirky spirit that so often prevails here.
<p>
   So expectations ran high for another crowd-pleasing festival,
but so far the oddities have prevailed. Aside from those mole rats,
who star with robots, topiary animals and a lion tamer in Errol
Morris' strange and wonderful ``Fast, Cheap and Out of Control,''
some of the outstanding sights here have been a dying masochist, a
mad young woman who enjoys re-enacting President John F. Kennedy's
assassination and a wild woodsman in a Davy Crockett hat.
<p>
   Here's one more oddity: Good-hearted hookers are out of
business. Most of the working girls in movies have secretarial jobs
this year.
<p>
   ``I'm representing a lot of good, interesting films, but if I
were a distributor, I honestly wouldn't know what to do with
them,'' said one publicist who naturally preferred to remain
nameless.
<p>
   ``It's just a down cycle,'' said Bingham Ray of October Films.
<p>
   Michael Barker of Sony Classics, which will distribute Morris'
film, said, ``A lot of the films here don't fit any conventional
idea of what might work in the marketplace.''
<p>
   Speaking of another movie his company will distribute, ``The
Myth of Fingerprints,'' he said, ``I think one of the reasons that
film has been well received here is that everything else is so
warped and strange.''
<p>
   Morris, the director of ``The Thin Blue Line'' and ``A Brief
History of Time,'' certainly represents the bizarre at its best. A
brilliantly idiosyncratic filmmaker with the most appealing aspects
of a mad scientist, he sounded delighted to have made a film that
fits no known category and has been admiringly received as a
metaphysical harbinger of the 21st century.
<p>
   ``This is sort of the sore thumb that sticks out in the middle
of everything,'' he said, looking very pleased about that. Morris
mentioned in passing that when Harvard University once asked him to
teach a course, he suggested doing something on home appliances.
<p>
   ``Fast, Cheap and Out of Control'' interweaves conversations
with four obsessive characters, all somehow seeking philosophical
knowledge in worlds beyond human experience. (This is where the
habits of mole rats come in.)
<p>
   ``They're embracing a world that might actually exclude us,''
said Morris, who cheerfully acknowledged that he shares the
mind-set of his eccentric subjects. ``I think it's more than
fair,'' he said. ``I'm one of them.''
<p>
   However rarefied his thoughts, Morris is not beyond having made
a set of 7-Eleven commercials for a sum greater than the entire
$1.1 million budget of ``The Thin Blue Line.'' After all, nobody
comes to Sundance without at least a passing interest in the
business realities of getting a film off the ground.
<p>
   Tom DiCillo has one of this festival's most hair-raising
hard-luck stories as well as one of its most likable films, the
artfully whimsical ``Box of Moonlight,'' which was five years in
the making and had been repeatedly passed on by the bigger
independent distributors. (Trimark, a lower-profile distributor,
bought it Wednesday.)
<p>
   But DiCillo came here prepared for the worst, even though his
delightful ``Living in Oblivion'' was one of Sundance's biggest
successes two years ago.
<p>
   ``Box of Moonlight,'' with a quixotic magic reminiscent of
Scottish filmmaker Bill Forsyth's ``Local Hero,'' sends a
straight-arrow electrical engineer (played by John Turturro) on a
wild voyage of self-discovery. His companion is a long-haired
renegade played by Sam Rockwell, who is so good in the film that he
has been wandering around Park City hearing the mating cry of the
client-poaching Hollywood agent. (``Are you happy?'' ``Are you
OK?'')
<p>
   ``He's a movie star,'' affirmed Harvey Weinstein of Miramax, who
knows a thing or two about new talent. DiCillo, also good at
spotting star potential, found Rockwell during auditions for his
``Johnny Suede'' but later gave the title role to the equally
unknown Brad Pitt.
<p>
   Rockwell, who has shades of the same Pitt magnetism, faced the
challenge of trying to keep his hair long for years as he waited
for DiCillo to raise enough money to make the film. (Every so often
a role on a police show would interfere.)
<p>
   Meanwhile, DiCillo resisted the suggestion that he cast Jason
Priestley and fumed about financiers and distributors who turned
him down.
<p>
   ``Because this looks like it's happening,'' he said of the sale
to Trimark, ``I feel this extremely odd urge to punch these people.
But if you're going to be in this business, you have to digest
feathers, beaks and gnarly, wrinkled claws. You have to learn to
eat crow.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</TEXT>
