<STORYID cat=e pri=u sel=taf-z> A9570 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDANCE-FILM-FESTIVA </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0524 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SUNDANCE-FILM-FESTIVAL-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PARK CITY, Uta: heat crow.'' &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Well, that's preferable to any of the pursuits seen in ``Sick:
The Life and Death of Bob Flanagan, Supermasochist,'' which is a
major conversation piece here. Sitting through Kirby Dick's raw,
stomach-turning documentary is an unalloyed challenge, but his film
proves as interesting as it is disturbing.
<p>
   Flanagan, a performance artist with tastes that could have made
Robert Mapplethorpe blush, shows off pitch-black humor along with
obscenely mutilated parts of his body. Relating his perversity to
his lifelong struggle with cystic fibrosis, the film offers a
wrenching exploration of crazy courage and pain. Even more
upsetting than its sadomasochistic exhibitionism is the sight of
Flanagan succumbing to torment he can no longer control. A series
of stills documents his death.
<p>
   Like most of the films at this overbooked, jam-packed festival,
``Sick'' isn't likely to generate a consensus. There are dozens of
moderately well received films but no overwhelming favorites yet,
although one thing is clear: Parker Posey is this year's It Girl at
Sundance.
<p>
   In ``Suburbia,'' the understated comedy ``Clockwatchers'' and
the gothic, theatrical ``House of Yes,'' Ms. Posey plays the
brittle, dangerous vamp with star presence and shocking intensity.
She's especially memorable as the main attraction in ``The House of
Yes,'' which is filled with dark secrets and provocative
re-enactments of Kennedy's assassination. Tori Spelling plays
(quite nicely) the role of a simple young woman awed by her
fiance's big house. Bizarro Sundance indeed.
<p>
   Traces of last year's more benign spirit can be found in ``I
Love You . . . Don't Touch Me!,'' a very funny and knowing romantic
comedy directed by Julie Davis. Meeting the 28-year-old Ms. Davis
is cause for a double-take, since she looks and sounds just like
her film's heroine, played by her longtime friend Marla Schaffel.
<p>
   ``The reason I don't get up and introduce the movie beforehand
is that I don't want to confuse anybody,'' said Ms. Davis, who
still has the appealing spontaneity that works so well for her
film. She said that she had thus far earned a grand total of $550
as a director (she otherwise works as a film editor), and that she
burst into tears over the small screen and fuzzy acoustics that are
standard in Park City.
<p>
   Meanwhile, from a different universe, Roland Emmerich and Dean
Devlin are also in town. Thanks to ``Independence Day,'' these two
now represent the last word in independent cinema, which means that
they have started their own production company,
Centropolis-Streamline, to encourage the genre filmmaking they
love. They will be able to make their monster of a new project,
``Godzilla,'' with an absolutely free hand. And they brought their
staff here for skiing, film watching and mingling with other
filmmakers.
<p>
   ``We made friends with Bryan Singer here,'' said Devlin. `` `The
Usual Suspects' is really more of a genre film than you'd think,''
he noted of Singer's film noir.
<p>
   ``You know what?'' said Emmerich. ``This is where it's fun.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1823EST
</TRAILER>
