<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9569 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-US-STOCKS-CLOSE3-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1181 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-STOCKS-CLOSE3-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. STOCKS MIXED AS WEAK PROFIT SHAVES IBM, DJIA (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Roger Madoff and Philip Boroff &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds number of advancing and declining shares in sixth
paragraph, Medaphis activity in 24th paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. stocks were mixed as
disappointing earnings from International Business Machines Corp.
kept the Dow Jones Industrial Average from setting another record.
Rising health and bank shares boosted the broader market.
<p>
   The Dow industrials fell 33.87 to 6850.03, snapping a streak of
four consecutive closing highs. IBM dropped 10 to 158. Had IBM
finished the day unchanged, the 30-stock average would have risen
3.03 points.
<p>
   The benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index rose to a record,
gaining 3.51 to 786.23. Leading the advance were Johnson &AMP; Johnson,
Exxon Corp. and Intel Corp., all of which reported strong earnings
in the past 10 days. The Nasdaq Composite Index jumped 11.09 to an
all-time high of 1388.06.
<p>
   ``We'll have some earnings disappointments,'' and those
companies' shares will suffer, said Kenneth Corba, chief investment
officer at Eagle Asset Management, which oversees $2.7 billion.
Still, ``I don't think the market's overvalued in the context of
all of the positives: You have declining interest rates, corporate
America's become more profitable and more competitive. We're in an
hospitable environment.''
<p>
   Investors pouring money into mutual funds continued to boost
shares. Mutual Fund Trim Tabs, a newsletter that tracks money going
to mutual funds, said assets are pouring in at a $28.4 billion
monthly pace, $500 million short of the record set last January.
<p>
   ``You're having tremendous demand for stocks,'' said Philip
Brown, president of Meridian Investment Co., with $3.7 billion in
equities. ``You have an economy that isn't doing that bad.
Corporate profits aren't declining -- they just aren't going to be
up as much.''
<p>
   Declining shares topped those that advanced by a margin of 1,321
to 1,182 on the New York Stock Exchange. It was the sixth heaviest
trading day ever, with 586 million shares exchanging hands.
<p>
   IBM, which rose 56 percent in the past year, said profit rose 18
percent. A stronger dollar and weak demand in Europe hampered
gains. Net income for the computer maker rose to $3.93 a share, 3
cents below analysts' expectations. Today's 6 percent decline in
IBM shares reduced their value about the same level as three weeks
earlier.
<p>
   Coming on the heels of surprisingly good numbers from Intel and
Microsoft, other computer-industry shares held up amid IBM's
retreat.
<p>
   Oracle Corp. gained 5/8 to 42 3/8. Microsoft Corp. rose 2 3/8 to
97 3/8 and Intel jumped 4 1/16 to 152 1/8, a peak as well.
<p>
   ``I don't think IBM is the bellwether for technology, any more
than General Motors is the bellwether for the U.S. economy,'' said
Sally Anderson, a senior money manager at Kopp Investment Advisors,
which oversees $3.4 billion and holds about $8 million of IBM
stock.
<p>
   ``The economy has become much more diverse,'' Anderson said.
``There have been so many new companies, and they've diluted the
impact of the big ones.''
<p>
   The impact of IBM's disappointment was offset by
better-than-expected profits at the No. 1 maker of personal
computers, Compaq Computer Corp. The Houston-based computer maker
said earnings gained 43 percent, to $1.64 a share, surpassing
expectations by 11 cents. Compaq jumped 5 to 83 1/2.
<p>
   Other PC makers gained. Gateway 2000 Inc., a mail-order computer
retailer, rose 3 1/2 to 62 5/8. Rival Dell Computer Corp. rose 2
5/8 to 66 3/4.
<p>
   Dean Witter Discover &AMP; Co., the brokerage and credit card
issuer, said profit rose 28 percent, topping forecasts. Its shares
gained 7/8 to 38.
<p>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb Co. earnings rose 11 percent to $1.43 a
share, 2 cents above analysts' expectations, according to IBES
International Inc. The shares rose 1 1/2 to 123 1/8.
<p>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson jumped 3 7/8 to a record 57 3/8. The
health-care product company gained 2 1/2 yesterday, after reporting
a 20 percent jump in earnings. Its shares have risen 34 percent in
the past year.
<p>
   Drugmakers rallied as the disappointment from IBM prodded
investors to bid up shares with the ``highest earnings
predictability,'' said Eagle Asset's Corba. Merck &AMP; Co. rose 1 7/8
to 88 3/8, and Pfizer Inc. gained 1 5/8 to 88 1/4.
<p>
   ``The broad market is set up for more disappointments,'' he
said. Travelers Buyback
<p>
   Norand Corp., a maker of mobile computers, surged 13 5/8 to 33
after Western Atlas Inc. said it would pay $261.3 million, or
$33.50 a share in cash, for all of Norand's 7.8 million shares.
Western Atlas fell 2 to 70 1/8.
<p>
   Travelers Group Inc. jumped to a record after saying it would
buy $1 billion in stock and boost its dividend 33 percent to 15
cents a quarter. Shares gained 2 3/8 to 53 5/8.
<p>
   Exxon rose 2 3/8 to a all-time high of 106.
<p>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller shares added 0.33 to a record
307.65, while the broader Wishire 5000 index rose 27.22 to 7594.85.
<p>
   Shares and options of Medaphis Corp., a health-care data
processing company, jumped amid speculation it would be bought out
by HBO &AMP; Co. or National Data Corp. Its stock rose 1 11/16 to 13
1/4 in trading of 7.3 million shares, quadruple its three-month
daily average. Options to buy Medaphis shares at $12.50 each by
Feb. 22 more than doubled to 2 1/4 from 7/8.
<p>
   HBO dropped 3/4 to 62 3/8. National Data was unchanged at 45
5/8.
<p>
   Steris Corp. sank 8 3/4 to 29 1/4 after Bill Sanford, the
company's chairman and chief executive, told the Dow Jones news
service he expects the medical device company to earn 38 cents a
share in the fiscal third quarter, below analysts' average
expectation of 53 cents, according to IBES.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T Corp. said its profit rose to 76 cents a share from 68
cents a year earlier. Analysts expected 80 cents a share, according
to IBES International Inc. The long-distance company's fell 1/2 to
38 7/8.
<p>
   Some companies that beat earnings estimates for last quarter but
fell anyway, as investors expected weakening results down the road.
<p>
   Computer Associates International Inc. retreated 2 3/4 to 43 1/4
after reporting profit rose 25 percent. The company's shares have
fallen 30 percent since Dec. 27, when it warned that software sales
in Europe wouldn't match year-earlier levels.
<p>
   U.S. Robotics slipped 1 3/8 to 72 1/4 after matching profit
forecasts. Concern arose that higher inventory would drag down
future earnings.
<p>
   Gains in stocks were muted as the yield on the 30-year U.S.
Treasury bond rose 5 basis points to 6.83 percent. The yield is
used as a benchmark for corporate borrowing costs, so when it rises
it can hurt companies' bottom lines.
<p>
   Banks continued to rally on the back of yesterday's strong
earnings reports from Citicorp, up 2 5/8 to 114 3/4, and Wells
Fargo &AMP; Co., up 8 3/8 to 297 1/8.
<p>
   Chase Manhattan Corp., which missed Wall Street estimates
yesterday, fell 1/2 to 92 3/8.
</TEXT>
