<SLUG> BC-HKC-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0925 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HKC-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Colo., Wis., N.Y., N.J., Mass., Vt., N.H., R.I., Mich.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COLLEGE HOCKEY NOTEBOOK &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By WILLIAM N. WALLACE &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Jack Riley Scholarship
<p>
   Former players and friends will assemble at West Point, N.Y., on
Saturday to announce the formation of a scholarship fund named
after Jack Riley, who coached the Army teams for 36 years and
served the Military Academy in many other ways.
<p>
   Riley's third son, Rob, now coaches the team, which will play
Yale at the Tate Rink. A small ceremony has been planned between
the second and third periods and Jack Riley will be present.
<p>
   The Jack Riley Scholarship is intended to help a deserving
candidate prepare academically for the Academy by attending the
West Point prep school at Fort Monmouth, N.J., and it will be
administered by the Association of Graduates, the alumni
organization.
<p>
   Riley, an ace at Dartmouth before and after World War II, began
his coaching career at Army in 1950. In the early years, many of
his skaters were football players better at throwing checks than
passing the puck. The advantage he had was the enormous size of the
old Smith rink, which sometimes exhausted the foe's good skaters.
<p>
   Yale is an appropriate opponent for the occasion. Riley once
said he liked every Yale man he had ever met. And how many had he
met? ``Two,'' he replied. One was his 1948 Olympic teammate, Fred
Pearson of West Newbury, Mass., who will be present Saturday.
<p>
   The current Army team (12-9-2) is the best the Academy has had
since leaving the ECAC six years ago, when its officials felt it no
longer could compete. Now playing a mix of Division I and Division
III opponents, Army has tied both Princeton and Cornell, the ECAC
leaders, and boasts an outstanding goalie in Daryl Chamberlain.
<p>
   NCAA Anniversary
<p>
   The National Collegiate Athletic Association's championship
tournament will be played for the 50th time this season, at
Milwaukee on March 27-29, and the milestone will be noted with an
all-star team selected by present and past coaches.
<p>
   A total of 144 players has been nominated. The selection was
limited to those whose teams were good enough to qualify to play in
the tournament.
<p>
   Jack Riley was not nominated but his brothers Bill and Joe,
Dartmouth contemporaries, were named. They played in the first NCAA
tournament, a four-team affair in 1948 at Colorado Springs, where
Michigan defeated Dartmouth, 8-4, to take the crown.
<p>
   Michigan, which has sent teams to 19 tournaments, has the most
players on the ballot, 16, compared with 15 for Boston University,
and 12 for Minnesota. Yet the Golden Gophers have had 23 tournament
teams, the most of any college, and the Terriers have had 22.
<p>
   Hockey East
<p>
   Underdog Boston College managed to tie Boston University twice,
5-5 and 4-4, thanks to the Eagles' best player, Marty Reasoner, and
its fabulous freshman, Jeff Farkas.
<p>
   Reasoner scored two goals in the last five minutes of the third
period to tie the first game and Farkas had two goals and two
assists in the weekend contests.
<p>
   The Eagles did not stop Chris Drury, who scored three times for
a total of seven goals against BC in three games this season. BU
has now played to five ties, a Terrier record, and has a home game
Saturday against Maine, a rival that has won eight of its last 10
matches.
<p>
   ECAC Women
<p>
   The Northeastern coach, Heather Linstad, had her team ready for
the three-day Providence tournament and the Huskies took two steps
forward with 4-3 victories over the host Friars and New Hampshire.
<p>
   These three have long been the dominant teams in women's hockey.
In the finale, however, Concordia of Montreal beat the Huskies,
5-2. Cammi Granato, who played for Providence as a senior four
years ago, continues to skate for Concordia under different
eligibility rules and was the tournament's most valuable performer.
<p>
   Hamilton
<p>
   The euphoria of a rare victory over Middlebury (8-3) did not
last long at Hamilton (10-3). After the tense 3-2 victory on home
ice over the Panthers, the defending Division III national
champions, the Continentals went through the motions the next day
and lost to Norwich, 7-2, ending a nine-game winning streak.
<p>
   Middlebury bounced back to edge Williams, 6-5, on the way home.
The Hamilton-Middlebury series now stands 62-29-2 in favor of the
Panthers. Norwich, picked for 10th place by the coaches in the
preseason poll, is tied for first in ECAC East with Middlebury,
each at 7-1. Then comes St. Anselm, 7-2, and Hamilton, 6-2.
<p>
   Slap Shots
<p>
    &MD;  Princeton, during a two-week break for exams, remains first in
the ECAC, a precarious and peculiar place for the Tigers. Only two
of their eight league victories have come against winning teams and
they return to the ice Jan. 31 with a challenging road test against
second-place Cornell.
<p>
    &MD;  Denver outshot last-place Michigan Tech in a Western
Association match by 49-18 and came out with a 4-4 tie. The hero
had to be Tech's goalie, L.G. Caravaggio, who had 45 saves in 65
minutes of play.
<p>
    &MD;  Goalie Dan Murphy stopped 25 Vermont shots and the leading
scorer Todd White had both goals Saturday night as Clarkson ended
the Catamounts' six-game winning streak in a pivotal 2-1 road
victory between the ECAC's best teams.
<p>
    &MD;  UMass-Lowell beat Yale and Providence defeated Dartmouth on
Tuesday, narrowing the ECAC's season edge over Hockey East, whose
teams have won 6 of the last 8, to 28-16-2.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1824EST
</TRAILER>
