<DOCID> nyt970122.0544 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9576 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CONFIRMATION </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0942 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CONGRESS-CONFIRMATION-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. SENATE CONFIRMS ALBRIGHT, COHEN FOR STATE, DEFENSE POSTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jenny Tomkin &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The U.S. Senate today confirmed
Madeline Albright as the first woman to be U.S. secretary of State
and approved William Cohen as secretary of Defense, putting a
Republican in President Bill Clinton's Cabinet. Albright, who
served as U.S. ambassador to the United Nation's in the first
Clinton administration, was the first appointee to Democrat
Clinton's second-term cabinet to be approved by the
Republican-controlled Senate. Today's 99-0 vote, the first Senate
floor vote this year, came two days after the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee unanimously recommended that she be confirmed.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ``Notwithstanding our differences, Mrs. Albright is a lady who
understands Congress and the important role that it must play in
developing U.S. foreign policy'', said Sen. Jesse Helms, a North
Carolina Republican and chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee.
<p>
   The vote to confirm Cohen, a former senator from Maine, was also
99-to-0. Cohen's former colleagues on the Senate Armed Services
Committee had recommended him unanimously.
<p>
   Senators, who have the right to advise and consent to a
president's Cabinet nominees, also held committee hearings today on
Andrew Cuomo to be secretary of Housing and Urban Development and
Bill Daley to be secretary of Commerce.
<p>
   Cuomo, the son of former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, received a
friendly hearing, and the Senate Banking Committee is likely to
recommend his conformation next week.
<p>
   Daley, a Chicago lawyer and the son of former Chicago mayor
Richard Daley and brother of that city's current mayor, Bill Daley,
faced tougher questioning by the Senate Commerce Committee.
Nevertheless, he is also likely to get Senate approval, perhaps
later this week.
<p>
   At Daley's hearing, Republican senators said the Commerce
Department has become a job haven for people who have helped the
administration politically. Republicans also criticized department
trade missions led by the late Commerce Secretary Ron Brown, which
they said involved fundraising activities for the Democrat Party.
Department programs that fund corporate research and development
also came under the Republican spotlight.
<p>
   Daley agreed to work with the Senate to resolve these issues.
<p>
   Several other Clinton nominees await confirmation, including
Charlene Barshefsky to be U.S. Trade Representative. She has been
acting trade representative since April 1996, when her predecessor,
Mickey Kantor, took over the Commerce Department to replace Brown.
<p>
   Barshefsky faces some opposition because of a 1995 law that
forbids anyone who has worked for a foreign government from being
appointed to the top U.S. trade position. Barshefsky worked briefly
in the early 1980's as an adviser for Canadian lumber interests.
<p>
   The White House asked Congress to exempt Barshefsky on grounds
she took her earlier government position in 1993, before the law
took effect.
<p>
   In spite of the obstacle, Barshefsky is likely to be confirmed
by the Senate before she leaves for Geneva Feb. 12 to attend World
Trade Organization talks to open global telecommunication markets.
<p>
   In the debate on Albright today, Democrats and Republicans alike
praised her, as has much of the U.S. corporate community, which
likes her pro-business positions. She particularly pleased business
leaders at her Jan. 8 confirmation hearing when she told the
Foreign Relations Committee that the U.S. must seek to engage, not
isolate China, the world's most populous nation. Albright testified
that U.S. trade with Asia, particularly China, is high on the
Clinton administration's agenda. ``In Asia,'' she said, ``China is
rapidly emerging as the next great power in our era.'' Mattel Inc.,
and Boeing Co., are among the major U.S. companies with financial
interests in China.
<p>
   Albright also promised to protect U.S. companies and workers in
international trade disputes.
<p>
   ``A principle responsibility of the Department of State is to
see that American companies and workers receive fair treatment and
that inequitable barriers to competition are overcome,'' she told
the Foreign Relations Committee.
<p>
   Clinton's choice of Cohen for the top defense post represented
an olive branch to the Republican-controlled Congress. Republicans
praised Cohen at his confirmation hearing, with Arizona Sen. John
McCain citing his ``personal and very deep friendship.''
<p>
   Cohen takes the helm of the Defense Department as this year's
spending decisions on defense are pretty much settled. Clinton, in
his Feb. 6 budget request, likely will seek $258.8 billion for
defense, about $9 billion less than the $268 billion Congress has
recommended. Republicans have the votes to add several billion
dollars of the extra money they seek.
<p>
   Democrats and Republicans agree that the military, after years
of shrinking budgets in the wake of the Cold War's end, needs to
replace or upgrade aging weapons and other equipment.
<p>
   Some major decisions on weapons purchases, such as on
development of a multi-billion-dollar Joint Strike Fighter, the
purchase of F/A-18 E/F fighters from McDonnell Douglas Corp., and
commissioning of a Seawolf nuclear submarine from General Dynamics
Corp.'s Electric Boat Division at Groton, Connecticut, have been
resolved.
<p>
   Boeing Co. and Lockheed Martin Corp. were chosen in November to
compete for the Joint Strike Fighter, a program that could cost at
least $100 billion during the next three decades.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1825EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
