<DOCID> nyt970122.0545 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=ttj-z> A9577 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-WHITE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0795 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-WHITE-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; REGGIE WHITE IS PART OF THE GREAT PACK TRADITION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  Reggie White is the minister of defense, and the
football field is his pulpit. This week, the world is White's
congregation because he is using Super Bowl XXXI to spread the word
of God to more than 50 countries.
<p>
   White, who might be the best defensive end in NFL history, and
Green Bay teammate Brett Favre share the cover of this week's Time
magazine. In New Orleans, White is like a Pied Piper for the news
media, because reporters, photographers and cameramen follow him
everywhere.
<p>
   ``It's taken me so long to get to the Super Bowl,'' White, 35,
said with a smile. ``If I had never made it, there would have been
a void in my professional life but not in my personal life.''
<p>
   White looks around the room at several hundred media types and
spreads his hands.
<p>
   White, who is a preacher from Tennessee involved in charities in
his home state and Wisconsin, almost has completed the 12th year of
his NFL career and his fourth with Green Bay. He also played two
years in the defunct United States Football League and recently
signed a contract guaranteeing he will finish his career in Green
Bay.
<p>
   ``My championship is to reach the Kingdom of God,'' White said
in a raspy voice. ``I get more excitement seeing lives change for
the benefit of Christ than anything I see on the field.''
<p>
   Another reason White is here is to help the Packers beat New
England and win their first championship in 29 years. To win the
Vince Lombardi Trophy, named after the former Green Bay coach who
won five titles, including the first two Super Bowls, they will
have to overcome Patriots coach Bill Parcells, who has a 5-0 record
in NFC and AFC championship games and Super Bowls.
<p>
   ``Bill's an excellent coach, but I'm mad at him,'' White said,
frowning as if actually angry. ``I want to let him know again that
he cost me two Super Bowl rings. The Giants had a chance to draft
me in the (USFL) supplemental draft (1984), but he took (offensive
tackle) Gary Zimmerman instead. I've tried to make things rough for
him.''
<p>
   When White hears a question he does not expect, he hesitates
before answering and cocks his head to the left. This particular
question involves athletes as role models.
<p>
   ``I think the role-model thing is somewhat overrated,'' he said.
``I think people need to start looking for heroes. But they need to
put stipulations on those heroes. You can be a positive or negative
role model, but a hero is someone with high integrity and high
morality and, to me, one who serves God.''
<p>
   ``You look at guys like (Green Bay safety) Eugene Robinson,
(Green Bay tight end) Keith Jackson and (Washington cornerback)
Darrell Green. Those guys are great fathers and husbands. They're
the guys our young people should want to be like.''
<p>
   Jackson and White were teammates in Philadelphia, where the
Eagles blew three chances to reach the Super Bowl under Buddy Ryan.
As they aged, Jackson and White thought they might never reach the
biggest game of them all.
<p>
   ``After we beat Carolina (NFC Championship Game on Jan. 12),
Reggie was going around the room thanking everybody for helping him
finally get to the Super Bowl,'' said Jackson, one of White's
closest friends.
<p>
   ``We told him we were happy, too, that we didn't do it for
him.''
<p>
   It was White who persuaded Jackson to come to Green Bay in 1995
after the Packers acquired him from Miami. Jackson was going to
retire rather than move to Green Bay.
<p>
   One reason defensive end Sean Jones left the Oilers is because
he wanted to play with White, who preceded him to Green Bay by a
year. With a combined 25 years of NFL experience, White and Jones
are like antique bookends.
<p>
   ``Reggie's impact on this team reaches far beyond football,''
Jones said.
<p>
   ``He stands for so much. He respects the challenges of social
issues, and he doesn't just talk about it. He actually does
something about it.''
<p>
   By his admission, White has been a leader of men since he was a
boy growing up in Knoxville, Tenn.
<p>
   ``I just accept my role,'' he said. ``Leadership qualities are
embedded in all of us. If you want to be a follower, that's all
you'll ever be.
<p>
   It hasn't taken long for White to become a legend in a
football-mad city that worships legends.
<p>
   ``I felt the tradition as soon as I got to Green Bay,'' White
said. ``I opened up a letter one day, and it was from Bart Starr. I
thought, `Oh, my God.' Bart Starr sent me a letter. I talk to guys
like Ray Nitschke, Willie Davis and Herb Adderley. They're a big
part of Packer tradition, and I want to be part of that tradition,
too.''~
</TEXT>
