<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-WESTERN-ATLAS-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WESTERN ATLAS TO BUY NORAND CORP. FOR $261.3 MILLION (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Mary Schlangenstein &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds closing stock activity.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Beverly Hills, California, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Western Atlas
Inc. said it will buy Norand Corp. for $261.3 million in cash to
expand its business that uses mobile computers to track inventory,
billing and other services.
<p>
   Houston-based Western Atlas said it would pay $33.50 for each
Norand share, a 73 percent premium over yesterday's closing price.
Norand stock today rose 13 5/8, or 70 percent, to 33, its highest
since September 1995.
<p>
   Western Atlas, based in Beverly Hills, California, provides
seismic information and well-logging data to companies searching
for oil and natural gas, as well as automation and data collection
systems. Norand makes mobile computers and wireless data
communications networks used to route accounting information and
manage inventory databases.
<p>
   Buying Norand ``will establish Western Atlas as the company with
the broadest technology range and most extensive distribution
network in the industrial automated data collection and mobile
computing solutions industries,'' Alton Brann, Western Atlas
chairman and chief executive, said in a statement.
<p>
   Norand products used by the car rental, automotive and food and
beverage industries will complement the automated-data collection
services of Western Atlas's Intermec unit, Brann said.
<p>
   Norand, based in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, had revenue of $69.4
million in the fiscal year ended Aug. 31. Western Atlas, which
hasn't reported 1996 earnings yet, had 1995 revenue of $2.23
billion, including $957.8 million from its industrial automation
division.
<p>
   Western Atlas shares fell 2 to 70 1/8.
<p>
   Norand's stock was the biggest gainer in U.S. composite trading.
Almost 5.4 million shares traded, more than 108 times its
three-month daily average of 49,578.
</TEXT>
