<SLUG> BC-MARKET-OPTIMISM-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0299 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MARKET-OPTIMISM-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; INVESTMENT ADVISERS GROW MORE OPTIMISTIC ABOUT U.S. STOCKS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Scott Schnipper &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Investment advisers were more
optimistic about the outlook for U.S. stocks last week for the
third time in four weeks.
<p>
   A survey of 140 people by the Investors Intelligence newsletter
found the percentage of advisers who said they were ``bullish,'' or
optimistic about the prospects for stocks, rose to 52 percent from
50.8 percent in the previous survey.
<p>
   The increase in investor optimism coincided with a rally in the
stock market. In the week ended Jan. 17, the Dow Jones Industrial
Average jumped 129.31 points, or 1.93 percent, to a record 6833.19.
<p>
   Some 28.8 percent of investors surveyed last week described
themselves as ``bearish,'' or pessimistic about the outlook for
share prices, down from 31.4 percent the week before.
<p>
   The proportion of advisers who said they foresee a
``correction,'' or a drop in prices of about 10 percent during a
12-month period, rose to 18.2 percent from 17.8 percent a week
before.
<p>
   The combined percentage of advisers who are either outright
bearish or expect a correction in prices fell to 48 percent from
49.2 percent the week before.
<p>
   The increasing optimism may be a bad omen for the market's
future performance, according to contrarian investors, who point
out advisers are more optimistic about stocks only after they have
bought. That means many investors have already finished their
purchases, leaving fewer to drive prices higher. yz A case in
point: Optimism reached 56 percent in the week ended Nov. 29, 1996,
the highest since early 1992. The following week, the Dow
industrials dropped 2.1 percent.
</TEXT>
