 &UR; BC-NORFOK-SOUTHERN-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NORFOLK SOUTHERN FILES SHELF TO SELL $1.25 BLN OF SECURITIES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Miles Weiss &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Norfolk Southern Corp. filed
with the Securities and Exchange Commission to sell as much as
$1.25 billion of securities.
<p>
   Norfolk Southern is currently engaged in a bidding war to
acquire Conrail Inc., and has an offer outstanding to acquire up to
8.2 million Conrail shares for $115 each, or a total of $943
million. Conrail, based in Philadelphia, has agreed to merge with
CSX Corp. at $110 a share.
<p>
   The shelf registration statement that Norfolk Southern filed
today gives the company the flexibility to raise the $1.25 billion
through the sale of debt securities and preferred and common stock.
<p>
   The Norfolk, Virginia, company, parent to the Norfolk Southern
Railway Co., would use the proceeds to repurchase its own common
stock, retire some or all of its short-term debt, and acquire
property, such as locomotives and rolling stock. Norfolk Southern
may also use some of the funds for general corporate purposes, the
SEC filing said.
<p>
   Norfolk Southern may use underwriters to sell the securities,
whose terms will be available in a supplemental prospectus. Company
shares rose 1 today to close at 88 1/8.
</TEXT>
