 &UR; FORD AND MAZDA TO SHARE ENGINES TO CUT COSTS, NIKKEI SAYS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Tak Kumakura and Jackie Kestenbaum &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
Tokyo, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- Ford Motor Co. and Mazda Motor Corp.
agreed to share engines to cut production costs, the Nihon Keizai
newspaper reported. Mazda, which is 33.4 percent owned by Ford,
will make engines for small vehicles while Ford will make all other
auto engines. Mazda will start making its first such ''world
engines'' by 1999, Nikkei said.
</PREAMBLE>
