<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9585 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-FED-FORUM-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0424 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CHICAGO-FED-FORUM-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CHICAGO FED SEES SOME SIGNS OF HIGHER WAGES: BLOOMBERG FORUM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Sandra Jones &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Chicago, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Federal Reserve Bank of
Chicago is seeing the first signs of higher labor costs in the
Midwest in about a year, a Chicago Fed economist said.
<p>
   Companies are willing for the first time in about a year to
raise wages to attract temporary workers, Bob Schnorbus, senior
economist and assistant vice president, told the Bloomberg Forum.
<p>
   ``These are very modest increases, but it seems to be signaling
for the first time that employers themselves are showing some
willingness to pay higher wages in order to get the workers they
need,'' Schnorbus said
<p>
   The Chicago Fed economist's remarks followed the release today
of the Federal Reserve's ``beige book,'' an economic survey based
on reports from the Fed's 12 district banks, including Chicago.
<p>
   The report said it found ``scattered evidence'' of pressures for
higher wages. The beige book will help form the basis for
discussion of interest rate targets at meeting of the Fed's
policy-setting Federal Open Market Committee on Feb. 4 and 5.
<p>
   Temporary-help agencies tend to be sensitive to pressures
building in the labor market, Schnorbus said.
<p>
   ``These are where the marginal decisions are being made and
where we would expect to see the earliest signs of wage pressures
if they are occurring in the economy,'' he said.
<p>
   Further, state agencies are getting more requests from companies
to conduct wage and salary surveys, he said. That could mean that
businesses are beginning to think about increasing starting
salaries or raising existing salaries to retain workers, he said.
<p>
   Fed officials have been keeping a close eye on labor costs.
Their concern is that higher wages could force companies to raise
prices and spark high inflation. Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan told
the Senate Budget Committee yesterday that the era of low wage
gains may be ending.
<p>
   But ``what we're seeing now in an anecdotal sense is a long way
from being translated to real price increases,'' Schnorbus said.
<p>
   Separately, Schnorbus said he views the Midwest as the nation's
strongest regional economy, helped in large part by booming auto
production. U.S. automakers have been manufacturing at record
levels of about 15 million vehicles a year for the past three
years.
<p>
   ``We've been doing much better for a much longer time than other
regions,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1828EST
</TRAILER>
