<DOCID> nyt970122.0558 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9591 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CURRENCY-FOCUS-EXOTIC </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1105 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CURRENCY-FOCUS-EXOTICS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TRADING IN EXOTIC CURRENCIES IS ON THE RISE: CURRENCY FOCUS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Tom Giles &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Name a currency, and chances
are Ricardo Faillace trades it.
<p>
   From his starkly-decorated, expansive office overlooking Park
Avenue on Manhattan's Upper East side, the 40-year-old head of
emerging markets trading at Banque Nationale de Paris bought and
sold some 120 currencies last year, from the Algerian dinar to the
Zambian kwacha. That's up from just 20 or so when he started out
eight years ago.
<p>
   ``Somehow, somewhere, someone is going to need a trade in every
currency,'' he said, poring over the day's relatively light trades
in ``only about 40 currencies.''
<p>
   Faillace isn't alone. More traders and financial institutions
are jumping into the sometimes risky business of buying and selling
the currencies of farthest-flung nations. They're chasing higher
yields and the chance to get a toehold in a growing corner of an
otherwise lackluster foreign exchange market.
<p>
   ``Before, traders were dealing only with major currencies,''
said Faillace. ``Nowadays, they are dealing with places they may
have trouble finding on a map.''
<p>
   Traders and analysts estimate that so-called ``exotic''
currencies account for a bit less than five percent of the $1.2
trillion traded each day in the foreign exchange market. By
century's end, though, they reckon that could swell to more than 20
percent, largely because of rising investment in the developing
world.
<p>
   ``While portfolio managers look for greater returns you're
seeing a global reallocation of assets toward Latin America, East
Europe and Asia,'' said Scott Schultz, an exotics trader at Brown
Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co.
<p>
   In one measure of that change, foreign direct investment in
developing countries rose to $99.7 billion in 1995, up 15 percent
from 1994, according to the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development.
<p>
   Those investments typically require foreigners to trade in
emerging countries' currencies.
<p>
   ``It's a simple matter of supply and demand,'' said Miguel
Perez-Santalla, an exotics trader at Manufacturers &AMP; Traders Trust
Co. ``As more people are doing more business in emerging countries,
they need those countries' currencies.''
<p>
   Also fueling exotics trading is the prospect of European
monetary union, which would ultimately eliminate many of the
world's most widely traded currencies, including the deutsche mark
and the French franc. The single European currency, the euro, is
due to be introduced Jan. 1, 1999.
<p>
   ``If and when Emu succeeds, there's going to be one currency, so
more and more people are going into emerging areas,'' said Donna
Fletcher, manager of Bank of Montreal's specialized currency unit.
``Where else are they going to go with their business? They gotta
go somewhere.''
<p>
   One mark of the growth in exotics trading is the proliferation
of separate trading desks for them even as many banks scale back
their currency operations thanks to mergers, new trading technology
and the advent of relatively stable exchange rates.
<p>
   ABN Amro Bank, Banque Indosuez and Deutsche Morgan Grenfell all
recently opened emerging markets trading desks in London.
<p>
   DMG employs between 30 and 35 exotics traders worldwide, while
Indosuez has 7 in London and ``likely will hire more in the
future,'' said exotics trader Darren Agombar.
<p>
   Though many folks deal in exotics in order to invest in emerging
countries, a growing number are chasing the higher returns they
often provide.
<p>
   The relatively small volume of trading in exotics makes them
riskier than taking a punt on the British pound. ``If you buy the
stuff you might get stuck with it because there's no one else to
buy it,'' said Perez-Santalla.
<p>
   Yet the potential rewards are higher, too, since the spreads
between bid and offer prices are greater. ``When you trade in a
currency like the Trinidadian and Tobagan dollar, you get a much
wider spread simply because the number of players is fewer,'' said
Bank of Montreal's Fletcher.
<p>
   Their spreads can be as much as five times wider than those on
more commonly-traded currencies.
<p>
   Many emerging countries are also making it easier to trade their
currencies. Last June and July, for instance, Russia lifted most
restrictions on trading the ruble. And China late last year
permitted convertibility on the current account, allowing companies
to trade the yuan to meet their import and export needs.
<p>
   Among the currencies in which traders expect volume will swell
are the Mexican peso, the Czech koruna, the Malaysian ringgit and
the yuan.
<p>
   Of course, growing volume will translate into tighter spreads --
and smaller profits. Already, there are several currencies,
including the koruna ``whose spreads are actually narrowing as
their countries are evolving financially, economically, politically
and as they are being traded by more participants,'' Fletcher said.
<p>
   Among the bigger risks inherent in trading exotics are political
unrest, a lack of information and labyrinthine banking regulations,
traders say.
<p>
   Political instability in a country can make investors reluctant
to invest there, damping demand for its currency.
<p>
   ``Right now it's like the Wild West,'' in some parts of the
developing world, said Perez-Santalla. ``There's still a lot of
political unrest. As long as you have that, you won't have
confidence in those countries' currencies.''
<p>
   Even so, a lot of countries experiencing political unrest still
have relatively stable currencies.
<p>
   ``I tend not to pay too much attention to cries of political
instability,'' said Faillace. ``The Russian ruble is still pretty
stable but the government is a mess.''
<p>
   For others, it's the paucity of reliable information that makes
trading in exotics perilous.
<p>
   ``Those countries are a little more esoteric than, say, Germany,
where you have access to a lot of published stuff on interest
rates, for example,'' said Brown Brothers' Scott Schultz. ``And the
information you do have -- who knows whether or not it's correct.''
<p>
   Faillace said that banking regulations also can be hard to
track, and vary from country to country.
<p>
   ``Analyzing banks or an accounting statement in Botswana is not
the same as doing that in Germany or the United States,'' he said.
<p>
   Yet such stumbling blocks don't deter everyone.
<p>
   Faillace could only think of four that he doesn't buy or sell --
the Cuban peso, North Korean won and the Libyan and Iraqi dinars --
and trade in those is illegal.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1831EST
</TRAILER>
