<DOCID> nyt970122.0559 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9592 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-IRAS-UPDATE1-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0445 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SUPER-IRAS-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. LAWMAKERS PROPOSE EXPANSION OF IRAS (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Gerald Burstyn &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds analyst reaction, details in first six paragraphs)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- `Super' individual retirement
accounts will spur Americans to save more money, a bipartisan group
of U.S. Senators and House members said today.
<p>
   The group, which includes Senate Finance Chairman William Roth,
a Republican from Delaware, and Sen. John Breaux, a Democrat from
Louisiana, proposed allowing the tax-sheltered accounts to be used
without penalty for education, small-business startups, first-time
home purchases, and long-term unemployment.
<p>
   Investment analysts said the plan would boost the savings rate
and improve the U.S. economy. ``Expanding the IRA is a win-win
proposition,'' said Robert C. Pozen, general counsel for Fidelity
Investments, the largest U.S. mutual fund company. ``Creating new
tax incentives for IRAs will encourage people to start saving
earlier for retirement and that will raise America's personal
savings rate.''
<p>
   Personal savings rates have fallen by half since 1970, according
to a report compiled by Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., Inc. Today, 4 percent
of disposable income in the U.S. goes to savings. That is less than
half of what the British and Germans save and a third as much of
what the Japanese and French save.
<p>
   ``The expanded IRA may be the single best broad-scale method to
increase savings by middle-class Americans without worsening our
budget deficit,'' said the investment house Dean Witter Discover &AMP;
Co. in a statement.
<p>
   Under the legislation, fully deductible IRAs would be available
to all Americans, regardless of income, by 2001. Currently, only
taxpayers without a pension plan and with incomes that do not
exceed $25,000 -- $40,000 for couples -- can qualify.
<p>
   The bill would also index the contribution limit for inflation;
allow homemakers to contribute $2,000 to an IRA instead of the
current $250; and create an ``IRA Plus Account.''
<p>
   Taxpayers who are ineligible for a regular IRA could put up to
$2,000 annually an IRA Plus account. They would pay taxes on their
contributions but not on the interest they earn. After age 59 1/2,
they would be allowed to withdraw from the account without paying
taxes.
<p>
   A 10 percent penalty would apply for early withdrawals. However,
the penalty would be waived if the withdrawal was used for a
first-time home purchase, educational expenses, or during periods
of unemployment. Taxpayers would be able to convert their current
IRAs into plus accounts without penalty.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1831EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0560 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9596 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SECURITY-CAPITAL-GROU </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0436 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SECURITY-CAPITAL-GROUP-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SECURITY CAPITAL GROUP OFFERS TO SWAP MANAGEMENT COS. FOR STOCK &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Robert Burgess &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Security Capital Group offered
to swap its real estate investment trust management and property
management companies for shares in affiliates Security Capital
Atlantic Inc., Security Capital Pacific Trust and Security Capital
Industrial Trust, the companies said.
<p>
   Security Capital Group officials declined to comment on the
terms of the offer, but analysts estimated a sale could net the
closely held company about $150 million to $210 million in stock,
analysts said.
<p>
   Security Capital Group currently manages the day-to-day
operations and properties of the REITS in exchange for a fee. In
Security Capital Pacific's case, that fee amounts to about $25
million a year, according Everen Securities real estate analyst
James Hoffman.
<p>
   Security Capital Group has about a 57 percent stake in Security
Capital Atlantic, a 46 percent stake in Security Capital Industrial
and a 38 percent stake in Security Capital Pacific.
<p>
   While the REIT industry in recent years has moved away from
hiring outside companies to manage its operations to avoid
potential conflicts of interest, the Security Capital companies
have gone against the trend.
<p>
   ``They are the last of the dinosaurs,'' said Hoffman. ``It
certainly has been a negative against the companies that they are
not self-managed.''
<p>
   Security Capital Atlantic Chairman Constance Moore said the move
makes sense because the three REITs, which all have market
capitalizations of $1 billion or more, are now large enough to run
their own operations efficiently.
<p>
   ``We are of sufficient size to gain economies of scale in our
operations and to let the savings flow to our shareholders,'' she
said.
<p>
   Also, with consolidation in the industry, the companies would be
able to make quicker decisions about buying other companies and
portfolios of properties, she said.
<p>
   Based in Atlanta, Security Capital Atlantic owns and operates
apartment properties in the Southeast. El Paso, Texas-based
Security Capital Pacific is one of the U.S.'s largest apartment
developers, owning about 60,00 units in the Southwest and West.
<p>
   Based in Aurora, Colorado, Security Capital Industrial is one of
the nation's largest owners of industrial and warehouse properties,
controlling a portfolio of more than 85 million square feet of
space.
<p>
   The REITs have set up special committees of independent
directors to evaluate the offer.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1832EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0561 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9598 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-TRADE-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0386 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FARM-TRADE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. FARM LAWMAKERS TOUR CHILE, ARGENTINA IN TRADE MISSION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Roger Runningen &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Six members of the U.S. House
Agriculture Committee left today for a trade mission to Chile and
Argentina amid concern a prospective U.S.-Chile free-trade
agreement may be of little benefit to American agriculture.
<p>
   The delegation, led by Chairman Bob Smith, Republican of Oregon,
said in a statement that lawmakers plan discussions on Chile's
request to become a part of the North American Free Trade
Agreement, and on food safety, trade barriers and liberalized
agricultural trade.
<p>
   U.S. crop subsidies are being phased down over the next six
years, placing an increasing emphasis on U.S. exports for income.
U.S. farmers count of exports for about 33 cents of each dollar in
farm income.
<p>
   ``New markets will be critical to maintaining stable farm
prices,'' Smith said.
<p>
   Among the biggest concerns, committee spokesman Dave Redmond
said, is that Chile currently bans imports of U.S. poultry, beef
and of wheat that's suspected of being infected with Karnal bunt
disease, a harmless fungus.
<p>
   ``The question is `Who gains? Who loses?''' if Chile enters
Nafta, Redmond said.
<p>
   Chile now exports about $11.5 billion in products to the U.S.,
with fish, forestry products and fresh fruits the major
agricultural products.
<p>
   The journey comes as Clinton administration expects Congress to
consider Chile in a new free trade agreement. The White House is
likely to seek ``fast-track'' authority to negotiate a trade deal,
which means Congress must accept or reject any final accord without
changes.
<p>
   Redmond said Chile's ban on major U.S. farm products is a key
concern, and that lawmakers will want to discuss how trade barriers
can be reduced or eliminated.
<p>
   In Argentina, lawmakers want to know how U.S. exports can be
increased, and also will examine the boom in Argentina's wheat
export industry. It's wheat prices have undercut U.S. wheat
shipments in recent months.
<p>
   Smith is accompanied by Rep. Charles Stenholm, Democrat of
Texas; Eva Clayton, Democrat of North Carolina; Thomas Ewing,
Republican of Illinois; and Sam Farr and Cal Dooley, California
Democrats.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
