<p>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Jan. 23. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
<p>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow)  &MD;  In a display of Russia's mounting
restiveness about President Boris Yeltsin's seemingly permanent
absence from the Kremlin, the Parliament votes overwhelmingly for a
resolution to remove Yeltsin from his post because of his poor
health. By Michael Specter.
<p>
   DALEY-CONFIRM (Washington)  &MD;  William Daley tells senators at his
confirmation hearing that as commerce secretary he will impose a
30-day ban on department trade missions and will cut in half the
number of political appointees there. By Richard W. Stevenson.
<p>
   FOOD-LION-ABC (Undated)  &MD;  A federal jury in Greensboro, N.C.,
awards a supermarket chain over $5.5 million in punitive damages
from ABC and two of its employees in a closely watched media case
that focused on the propriety of such widely used TV news
techniques as hidden cameras and undercover reporters. By Barry
Meier.
<p>
   TSONGAS-LEGACY (Lowell, Mass.)  &MD;  When Paul Tsongas died last
weekend, the local newspaper here wrote, ``With his death, Paul
Tsongas's survivors include his wife, his children and a city.''
For the rest of the country, the name Paul Tsongas may only conjure
up vague memories of a man who made a quixotic bid for the
presidency. But for the people of Lowell, who have turned out in
the thousands to pay their respects at his house, Paul Tsongas was
a hero whose legacy will not only be the buildings and the arenas
he helped to build, but the memories of the locals who credit him,
more than anything else, with rescuing the city from the depression
that came with the collapse of the old textile factories. By Sara
Rimer.
<p>
   With photo.
<p>
   And New York metro stories.
<p>
   Reefers:
<p>
   ALBRIGHT-CONFIRM (Washington)  &MD;  Senate confirms Madeleine
Albright as secretary of state. By Stephen Erlanger.
<p>
   CUBA-CANADA (Havana)  &MD;  Canada's foreign minister visits Cuba to
sign joint declarations on human rights and foreign investment; in
Washington, the State Department condemns the visit. By Anthony
DePalma.
<p>
   SIMPSON-SUIT (Santa Monica, Calif.)  &MD;  As jurors sit grim-faced
and two women panelists appear close to tears, a lawyer implores
the jury to make O.J. Simpson pay for the slaying of Ronald
Goldman. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
<p>
   CT-SCHOOL-DESEGREGATION (Hartford, Conn.)  &MD;  A panel established
by Gov. John G. Rowland to address segregation in the state's
schools says the state should require school districts to accept
students from anywhere in Connecticut and should pay more for
school construction projects that bring black and Hispanic students
into mostly white districts.
