<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9605 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EXCO-RULING-UPDATE1-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0489 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EXCO-RULING-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EXCO PLC UNIT WINS $1.15 MLN RULING AGAINST CANTOR (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Betsy Jelisavcic &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds that Cantor filed a hiring suit against a rival today in
paragraphs nine to 11. Adds details about award last year against
PaineWebber in 12th paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Exco Plc won a $1.15 million
ruling against Cantor Fitzgerald &AMP; Co. for payments owed by five
brokers who quit its broker-dealer unit to join Cantor.
<p>
   The ruling was handed down Jan. 8 by New York State Supreme
Judge Leland DeGrasse, but hasn't been widely disseminated. It
follows a $4.6 million verdict Exco won in November against Cantor
for hiring away interest-rate options traders from its Noonan,
Astley &AMP; Pearce unit.
<p>
   Exco's RMJ Securities Corp. unit sued Cantor in 1994 and 1995 to
collect money that five former brokers agreed to pay if they left
the firm before their contracts expired.
<p>
   ``The payout provisions are a reasonable means to provide RMJ
just compensation for its losses upon the contract defendants'
departure,'' DeGrasse said in his ruling.
<p>
   Cantor, which claimed the payments are illegal, is responsible
for the costs because it agreed to take legal responsibility for
the brokers after hiring them, RMJ attorney John Cambria said.
<p>
   Glen Kirwin, a senior broker at RMJ, agreed to pay $100,000 if
he left the firm before December 1996; Louis Spinelli, another
senior broker, agreed to pay $150,000 if he left before January
1997; William Minardi, a managing director, agreed to pay $350,000
if he left before December 1995; Gerald Byrne, a broker, agreed to
pay $200,000 if he left before December 1995; and Mark Colaio, head
of RMJ's government-agency securities desk, agreed to pay $350,000
if he left before August 1996, according to the ruling.
<p>
   Cambria said London-based Exco is seeking additional damages
against Cantor for business it says it lost from the brokers'
departure. RMJ, based in New York, deals in U.S. government
securities.
<p>
   Officials at Cantor weren't immediately available for comment.
<p>
   The two verdicts against Cantor come at a time when brokerages
are trying to fend off high-level defections in the increasingly
competitive securities industry.
<p>
   Cantor itself is a purveyor of such suits. Cantor Fitzgerald
International today sued rival Liberty Brokerage Investment Corp.
and its chairman, Edwin Payne, claiming they illegally hired away
20 of 24 employees responsible for its German and Belgian bond
brokerage business.
<p>
   Last May, PaineWebber inc. was ordered to pay rival Prudential
Securities Inc. $2.5 million for allegedly raiding Prudential's
Gainesville, Florida, brokerage office. A New York Stock Exchange
arbitration panel punished PaineWebber after the company hired
almost all of Prudential's Gainesville brokers and sales assistants
in 1993.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1834EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0566 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9607 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CD-RADIO-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0348 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CD-RADIO-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FCC TO RELEASE AUCTION RULES FOR SATELLITE RADIO LICENSES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Liza McDonald &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Federal regulators are
expected to release -- possibly as soon as tomorrow -- plans to
auction two digital satellite radio licenses to four companies that
have already applied for the rights, agency officials said.
<p>
   The rules for an auction, which would likely be held before the
summer, are being distributed among the agency's four
commissioners. The licenses would give holders the right to beam
digital-quality radio programming to subscribers. Consumers are
expected to use the service primarily in cars and trucks.
<p>
   Companies that have already applied for the licenses and would
be eligible to bid in any such auction include Washington,
D.C.-based CD Radio Inc., New York-based Primosphere, Washington,
D.C.-based Digital Satellite Broadcasting Corp., and Reston,
Virginia-based American Mobile Radio Corp.
<p>
   Each of these companies, except American Mobile Radio,
originally applied for a special pioneer's license that would have
guaranteed them the rights and let them be the first to market.
Each company withdrew its application after an independent
FCC-appointed panel recommended that the agency not award such a
license to any of the three.
<p>
   Now the agency will propose how the two available licenses
should be auctioned. Still unclear is whether the FCC will preclude
the four likely bidders from colluding -- creating two entities --
to avoid having to bid against each other.
<p>
   CD Radio's chairman and chief executive, David Margolese, has
said he's willing and eager to bid for a license at auction, and
doesn't mind if the rules prevent combination among the group.
<p>
   CD Radio was co-founded in 1991 by Margolese and his partner
Robert Briskman, who devised the technology to deliver nationwide
30 channels of compact-disc quality music and 20 channels of news
and information through mini-satellite dishes on roofs of cars and
trucks.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1835EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0567 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9609 </STORYID>
