<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9610 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-UPDATE1-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0451 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FIDELITY-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FIDELITY SAYS BOND FUND MANAGER BOB IVES RESIGNS (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Tim Quinson &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Boston, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Fidelity Investments said bond
fund manager Bob Ives resigned because he doesn't want to relocate
to New Hampshire where the No. 1 U.S. fund group is moving its
fixed-income division.
<p>
   Ives, 34, is the first bond fund manager to announce his
resignation as a result of Fidelity's plan to move its entire bond
and money market investment groups to Merrimack, New Hampshire, in
August. Merrimack is 47 miles north of Boston.
<p>
   ``There will be more defections of senior portfolio managers in
the near future,'' said David O'Leary, president of Alpha Equity
Research Inc. in Portsmouth, New Hampshire, which tracks Fidelity.
<p>
   Fidelity said Ives' decision is nothing more than normal
attrition that's expected with an office relocation. ``As with any
relocation, there are always some individuals who will choose not
to be transferred,'' said Scott Beyerl, a company spokesman.
<p>
   Boston-based Fidelity had 19 portfolio managers in its bond fund
group as of Sept. 30. Since then, at least two managers have
resigned, Ives and Michael Gray.
<p>
   Ives, who managed more than $1.45 billion in fixed-income funds,
including the $955 million Fidelity Government Securities Fund, is
planning to take time off and has not yet decided on what he'll do
next, Fidelity said. Ives will work at Fidelity until the end of
the month, the company said.
<p>
   The announcement of Ives' resignation comes at a bad time for
Fidelity.
<p>
   Fidelity executives, led by J. Gary Burkhead, who's chief of the
firm's fund managers who oversee about $500 billion in assets, are
on a six-city tour that began yesterday in New York.
<p>
   Last night, Burkhead faced numerous questions about manager
defections at Fidelity, as 18 fund managers, including Ives and
Gray, have quit in the past year. Burkhead said Fidelity has the
``depth'' in its money manager ranks weather recent defections by
portfolio managers.
<p>
   Fidelity said today it expects to name new managers for the
funds Ives managed in the next few days.
<p>
   Ives joined Fidelity in 1991 after graduating with a master's
degree in business from the University of Chicago. His most recent
duties included managing the Government Securities Fund, as well as
the Spartan Government Income Fund and the Advisor Government
Investment Fund.
<p>
   The Government Securities Fund returned 2.09 percent last year,
according to the research group Lipper Analytical Services Inc.
which trailed the 2.76 percent return of the Lehman Brothers
Government Bond Index.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1837EST
</TRAILER>
