<DOCID> nyt970122.0569 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=i pri=u sel=taf-z> A9611 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0957 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   RUSSIA'S PARLIAMENT CHALLENGES YELTSIN
<p>
   MOSCOW (NYT)  &MD;  In a confrontational display of its rage at
President Boris Yeltsin's continued absence from the Kremlin, the
Parliament voted overwhelmingly Wednesday evening to support a
resolution to remove Yeltsin from his post because of his poor
health.
<p>
   The 229-63 vote in the Communist-dominated lower house has no
legal force, and it was instantly swamped in a confusing sea of
parliamentary maneuvers that will require a second vote on the
resolution before it is adopted.
<p>
   But after seven troubling months in which the president has been
far too sick to work, the measure reflects the growing sense that
an economically depressed Russia has a leader who may never again
be fully capable of carrying out the strenuous duties of his job.
<p>
   While opposition figures have often called on Yeltsin to be
removed, this was the first time the issue had been put to a vote.
<p>
   SOUTH KOREA'S LABOR CRISIS CONTINUES
<p>
   SEOUL, South Korea (NYT)  &MD;  Opposition parties said Wednesday
that they remained dissatisfied with President Kim Young Sam's
surprise offer to allow revision of controversial labor laws,
suggesting that the national crisis over the legislation may
continue for some time.
<p>
   Kim wants to hold a special session of the National Assembly
next month to resolve the issue, apparently by allowing changes
that would soften the labor code. But opposition parties and labor
unions are sticking to their original demand that the laws be
repealed entirely before the next step  &MD;  hammering out a revision  &MD; 
can take place.
<p>
   Thus the gap between the two sides has been greatly narrowed,
but it still may be too much to bridge for the time being.
<p>
   HOSTAGE TAKERS FIRED WARNING SHOTS IN PERU
<p>
   LIMA, Peru (NYT)  &MD;  Tensions remained high at the Japanese
ambassador's residence here Wednesday, after Marxist guerrillas
holding 73 hostages inside fired shots into the air shortly after
midnight, presumably to scare off police who were conducting
maneuvers outside the compound.
<p>
   The Tupac Amaru rebels have fired shots from automatic weapons
on at least four occasions in recent weeks, saying they were
warning police not to come to close to the residence.
<p>
   But Wednesday morning's gunfire has raised fears that the police
exercises are a harbinger of a government plan to raid the Japanese
residence or that the maneuvers could provoke the guerrillas to
kill some hostages, either by design or accident.
<p>
   ``Fujimori is employing a textbook strategy to dealing with
long-term hostage takers  &MD;  applying psychological pressure,'' said
a Western diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``This is a
fairly dangerous thing to do in this particular situation because
it increases the prospects for bloodshed.''
<p>
   CANADA'S FOREIGN MINISTER MEETS WITH CASTRO
<p>
   HAVANA (NYT)  &MD;  In a brief visit that clearly signaled the sharp
divisions between the United States and Canada over how to deal
with Cuba, Canada's foreign minister dined with President Fidel
Castro and other Cuban officials on Tuesday before signing joint
declarations Wednesday on human rights and foreign investment.
<p>
   In Washington, meanwhile, the State Department condemned the
visit by the highest-ranking Canadian to set foot in Cuba in more
than 20 years.
<p>
   The Canadian official, Lloyd Axworthy, who has been a vocal
critic of U.S. policy toward Cuba and the Clinton administration's
attempt last year to toughen its longstanding economic embargo by
signing the Helms-Burton Act, called the trip the culmination of a
year-long series of meetings between senior Canadian and Cuban
officials. He said it probably signals even closer relations
between the two countries, as Canada tries to play a greater role
in the hemisphere.
<p>
   BRITAIN ANNOUNCES PLANS FOR ANOTHER ROYAL YACHT
<p>
   LONDON (NYT)  &MD;  When the royal yacht Britannia sailed from
Plymouth on Monday on a final Far East tour before its
decommissioning in August, Britons thought they would never see her
costly like again. But, unexpectedly, the government said Wednesday
that a new $100 million ship will be built to replace it and will
enter service in 2002 in time for the queen's golden jubilee.
<p>
   The announcement appeared to put an end to a lengthy debate in
which detractors argued that the vessel was an anachronism. Still,
the government credits Britannia with having provided British
businessmen with an alluring venue for meeting their counterparts
abroad and thereby having secured more than $3 billion worth of
trade for Britain in the past decade.
<p>
   The expectation had been that if there were to be any new royal
vessel, it would have to be paid for by private contributions. But
Michael Portillo, the defense minister, said Wednesday that the
government believed the yacht should be funded by the nation.
<p>
   OLDEST TITANIC SURVIVOR DIES AT 100
<p>
   LONDON (NYT)  &MD;  Edith Haisman, the oldest survivor of the sinking
of the Titanic in 1912, died Monday night at a nursing home in
Southampton, England. She was 100.
<p>
   Karen Kamuda, the vice president of the Titanic Historical
Society, said in a telephone interview from Indian Orchard, Mass.,
that Mrs. Haisman's death left seven of the 705 survivors still
living, three in the United States and two each in Britain and
France.
<p>
   Mrs. Haisman, who was 15-year-old Edith Brown at the time of the
sinking, was the last survivor who was a teen-ager in 1912. The
ones who are still alive ranged in age from 9 weeks to 8 years old
at the time of the disaster, which claimed more than 1,500 lives.
</TEXT>
