<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-DANCE-STRIKE-N </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0266 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HARLEM-DANCE-STRIKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HARLEM DANCE TROUPE, UNITED, GOES ON STRIKE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  The 32 dancers of Dance Theater of Harlem went on
strike Wednesday after unanimously voting down a one-year contract
offer at a meeting Tuesday night at the troupe's headquarters.
<p>
   The American Guild of Musical Artists, the dancers' union, is
filing for arbitration over the company's use of two more
apprentices than the most recent contract allowed and over its use
of ``floaters,'' dancers who are neither apprentices nor union
members.
<p>
   Ballet troupes often use apprentices to augment the corps in
works with large casts.
<p>
   Other issues include wages, work rules and payment for extra
work, seniority compensation and the number of apprentices and
length of apprenticeship. The dancers' contract expired Sept. 30
but had been extended through Tuesday. Negotiations began in
October.
<p>
   A spokesman for Dance Theater, whose headquarters are on West
152nd Street, said that its school and other programs were still
operating and were not affected by the strike.
<p>
   The company's next scheduled appearance is Saturday at the State
University College at Purchase, N.Y., where it is to perform with
the Westchester Philharmonic.
<p>
   Dance Theater is to perform again in New York on Feb. 23 at the
Colden Center at Queens College and March 5 at the World Financial
Center.
<p>
   The company is to perform at the John F. Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts in Washington in mid-April and on national and
European tours through mid-July.
</TEXT>
