<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9614 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SWAP-MARKETS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0927 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SWAP-MARKETS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ASIA SEES GROWING USE OF CREDIT DERIVATIVES: SWAP MARKETS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Kenny Hargrove &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Hong Kong, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Indonesia's May 29, 1997
Parliamentary elections are looming, and bond investors are looking
at new hedging tools to safeguard yields should the nation's
economic policies shift.
<p>
   Winnie Heung, fund manager at BNP Private Banking Asia, which
manages about $300 million in the region, thinks credit derivatives
may help compensate for any losses that might incur due to the
political and economic risks of investing in Asia's younger bond
markets.
<p>
   Though she isn't buying any, she understands how the $40 billion
market in credit derivatives would work for her if she needs them.
To hedge her Indonesia risk, she could buy from a bank a swap
that's tied to an Indonesian government or corporate bond.
<p>
   In return for making a periodic interest payment to the bank,
she'd be compensated if that bond went into default for any reason.
Default would trigger a payment from the bank to her for an amount
equivalent to her bond's losses.
<p>
   ``We've seen a lot of investors using the product for the first
time to see how it works. We think that there's a lot of potential
for more active portfolio hedging,'' said Koh Siew Eng, vice
president of international capital markets at Chase Manhattan Asia
Ltd.
<p>
   The global market for credit derivatives grew to about $40
billion by the middle of 1996 from about $2 billion in 1991 and
could double in size this year, according to CIBC Wood Gundy, the
New York-based investment banking subsidiary of Canadian Imperial
Bank of Commerce.
<p>
   For the moment, these derivatives are being sold only for
default protection. Eventually, they will be used as well to
protect against downgrades in the ratings of bonds and the
resulting price drops, said an official of CIBC Wood Gundy.
<p>
   Credit derivatives coming into their own in Asia is a tribute to
the intersection of an understanding of their value as a hedge
against a range of risks and the growth of computer software and
trained personnel needed to create and monitor them.
<p>
   ``The last six months have really steamed in terms of volume,''
said Jonathan Fox, managing director of international capital
markets at Chase Manhattan Asia Ltd.
<p>
   Credit derivatives allow investors to bet on defaults, changes
in credit ratings, adverse changes in yield spreads, or any other
economic event that could befall an underlying security or index.
Effectively they allow indirect bets on political and economic
risks of companies and countries.
<p>
   Derivatives are contracts whose value is tied to the value of
another asset, such as a stock, bond, commodity, currency or index.
They're used to guard against changes in the value of those assets,
or to make leveraged bets on price and yield changes.
<p>
   ``It's an imperfect way to cover your sovereign or political
risk,'' said Fox. ``But it means that you can do a lot better than
you would otherwise be able to do.''
<p>
   Investors use credit derivatives to provide protection against
the risk that a company or country may not be able to repay its
debts or that its credit rating might deteriorate.
<p>
   These transactions can take the form of both swaps and options.
The most common credit derivative used in Asia is the default swap.
<p>
   An investor who takes out a loan at 50 basis points more than
Libor and earns a Libor plus 85 basis point return on a three year
floating rate note can boost his yields by using credit
derivatives.
<p>
   By buying a default swap from a bank at Libor that pays Libor
plus 50, the investor's returns grow from 35 basis points to 50
basis points. By operating in the synthetic market, rather than the
cash market, the investor does not have to fund the investment.
<p>
   These custom-made hedging products can increase yields and lower
funding costs on bonds and loans at just a fraction of the cost of
buying the actual securities.
<p>
   ``You can get a great deal of leverage through these things,''
said Fox.
<p>
   Daniel Fan, investment manager in the international finance,
planning, and development department of Orix Asia Ltd, a subsidiary
of a Japanese leasing company, uses derivatives based on interest
and foreign exchange rates.
<p>
   While Fan would like to use credit derivatives as a hedging
tool, he said it's difficult to convince Orix to use them because
it's difficult to evaluate non-quantitative risks such as political
change.
<p>
   This makes it difficult for investors to price the risks and
what they're willing to pay for the protection of a credit
derivative.
<p>
   Other fund managers, who buy Asian debt because they believe
that the credit quality of most countries and many companies is
improving as the regional economies grow, see no need for
protection against deteriorating credit quality.
<p>
   Still, as Asia-based businesses expand into the region and
around the world, they'll encounter more risks which could boost
their demand for hedging products, including credit derivatives.
<p>
   This is particularly true for South Korea's globally minded
conglomerates, said Pan.
<p>
   ``Mostly the big corporations because they have a very big
business in the world and also they are exposed to different credit
risks and other types of risks,'' said K. R. Pan, head of financial
engineering for the Korea Development Bank, South Korea's sovereign
borrower.
<p>
   ``They are the frontrunners to those different types of
activities,'' he added.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1839EST
</TRAILER>
