<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9615 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MARVEL-ENTERTAINMENT- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0598 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MARVEL-ENTERTAINMENT-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MARVEL'S BANK LOAN PROVISIONS ARE REJECTED BY JUDGE (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Bob Bauers &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds comment from company in third paragraph, lawyer in fourth
paragraph. Rewrites first two paragraphs.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Wilmington, Delaware, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Marvel
Entertainment Group Inc.'s $100 million credit agreement with Chase
Manhattan Corp. was rejected by a U.S. Bankruptcy Court judge
because of two provisions that would trigger a default.
<p>
   The loan provisions said that Ronald Perelman must retain at
least 51 percent control of Marvel, and that no one can file a
court motion challenging the agreement that lets Toy Biz Inc. make
Marvel-copyrighted products for free.
<p>
   Judge Helen S. Balick extended a $20 million interim credit
facility that already exists, and said she wouldn't approve the
final $100 million facility until the two provisions were fixed. An
outside Marvel spokesman, Michael Freitag, said the company expects
to submit modified provisions by Friday.
<p>
   ``We think this levels the playing field, and we appreciate the
court's evenhanded approach,'' said David Friedman, attorney for
Marvel Holdings Inc. bondholders who had objected to the so-called
debtor-in-possession credit facility.
<p>
   Under the revised credit agreement the company said it will
submit to the court, a default would be triggered if someone other
than Perelman acquired 25 percent control. Also, if the court
struck down the free licensing agreement between Marvel and Toy
Biz, a default would be triggered.
<p>
   In their objection to the $100 million credit facility, the
bondholders said the change of control provision was part of a
improper scheme by Perelman to retain control of the company.
<p>
   The bondholders committee is led by investor Carl Icahn, who
holds about 25 percent of the debt. The bondholders, who are
creditors of the parent company of Entertainment, aren't listed as
creditors in the Marvel Entertainment case.
<p>
   Judge Balick said an alternative, allegedly less expensive
facility proposed by the bondholders would lead to litigation that
would delay the Marvel Entertainment Chapter 11 bankruptcy case,
which in turn could seriously damage the company.
<p>
   The bondholders had offered alternative financing through PPM
America Inc., which had committed $100 million for two years on
behalf of Jackson National Life Insurance Co., a U.S. unit of
Prudential Corp. Plc.
<p>
   Under bankruptcy law, Marvel Entertainment and Perelman have the
exclusive right to propose a reorganization plan unless the court
allows others to file a plan.
<p>
   A consortium of bank lenders, led by Chase, hold some $650
million in secured claims against Marvel Entertainment. The
bondholders have $894 million in claims against three Marvel
Holdings entities, secured by about 80 percent of Marvel
Entertainment's 102 million common shares.
<p>
   Marvel Entertainment filed for Chapter 11 protection on Dec. 27,
proposing a reorganization plan that leaves financier Ronald
Perelman in control.
<p>
   Perelman's reorganization plan calls for his Andrews Group to
pay $365 million for 427 million new shares of Marvel Entertainment
stock with cash or stock of Toy Biz, a profitable toymaker Marvel
is acquiring. Under the plan, Toy Biz would be folded into Marvel
Entertainment.
<p>
   The plan would dilute the current 18.84 percent stake in Marvel
held by public shareholders to 3.63 percent and would dilute the
bondholders' collateral to about 15 percent of the outstanding
shares.
</TEXT>
