<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9617 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HASIMAN-OBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0959 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HASIMAN-OBIT-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Mass., Wash., Conn., Britain, South Africa, Australia) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EDITH HAISMAN, 100, OLDEST SURVIVOR OF TITANIC &LR;  &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By WARREN HOGE &LR;  &QC;  &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   LONDON  &MD;  Edith Haisman, the oldest survivor of the sinking of
the Titanic in 1912, died Monday night at a nursing home in
Southampton, England. She was 100.
<p>
   Titanic Historical Society vice president Karen Kamuda said in a
telephone interview Wednesday from Indian Orchard, Mass., that Mrs.
Haisman's death left seven of the 705 survivors still living  &MD; 
three in the United States and two each in Britain and France.
<p>
   Mrs. Haisman, who was 15-year-old Edith Brown at the time of the
sinking, was the last survivor who was a teen-ager in 1912. The
ones who are still alive ranged in age from 9 weeks to 8 years old
at the time of the disaster, which claimed more than 1,500 lives.
<p>
   She was a guest of honor last August on a pilgrimage cruise to
the spot 400 miles off the Newfoundland coast where the liner, on
its maiden voyage, hit an iceberg on the night of April 14-15,
1912.
<p>
   In 1995 she took part in the opening of a memorial garden at the
National Maritime Museum in Greenwich, London, with a granite
monument commemorating the victims, and in 1993 she appeared in
public in Southampton to receive a gold watch thought to be her
father's from the head of the American company that had salvaged it
from the wreckage.
<p>
   She had last seen the watch protruding from the waistcoat pocket
of her father, Thomas William Solomon Brown, 60, a hotel owner from
Worcester, a suburb of Cape Town, South Africa. He was taking his
wife, Elizabeth, and his daughter Edith to Seattle, where he
intended to open a new hotel.
<p>
   In the hold of the cruise liner were tableware, furnishings and
1,000 rolls of bed linen for the new enterprise.
<p>
   In a series of interviews in her later years and a biography,
``A Lifetime on the Titanic,'' published in 1995, Mrs. Haisman gave
a vivid account of the ship's final moments, although some details
have been called into question.
<p>
   Mrs. Haisman said she remembered that her father was dressed in
an Edwardian dinner jacket, stabbing the cold night air with his
cigar and sipping from a snifter of brandy on the deck of the
listing ship as she and her mother were being winched 70 feet down
into a lifeboat.
<p>
   Mrs. Haisman said that she never forgot the horror of that night
and the loss of her father, and that even in her later years she
suffered nightmares in which she heard the screaming of the
drowning victims in the Atlantic.
<p>
   It was 11:40 p.m. when she recalled being jolted in her
three-berth stateroom. ``Father appeared a few minutes later,'' she
recalled. ``He told us: `You'd better put on your life jackets and
something warm; it's cold on deck. It's just a precaution. We've
struck an iceberg  &MD;  it's nothing much. The steward in the corridor
says it's nothing to worry about.'''
<p>
   They hurried through the corridors, leaving behind in their
haste her mother's jewelry case, 400 gold sovereigns and a roll of
bank notes on top of a bunk. ``We waited for ages on the boat deck
for someone to tell us what to do. The ship's band was playing
ragtime. They played to keep our spirits up. It was so brave of
them. Everybody kept saying: `She's unsinkable. She won't go down.'
<p>
   ``Father kissed us and saw us into Lifeboat 14. Up to 50 people
got in as it swung perilously over the side. One man jumped into
the boat dressed as a woman. As we rowed away from the ship, we
could still hear the band playing, but now it was hymns.'' She
watched the mighty liner go down.
<p>
   ``We were almost six hours in the lifeboat and during that time
we had no water and nothing to eat. I kept wondering if my father
had got off the ship  &MD;  that's all I could think of.''
<p>
   She and her mother were picked up by the Cunard liner Carpathia
and taken to New York, where they left on a train trip to Seattle
to spend time with an aunt of Mrs. Haisman's, who lived there and
had inspired the move to the West Coast. They soon returned to
South Africa, where five years later Edith married Fred Haisman, a
shipbuilder's engineering draftsman from London.
<p>
   Married for 60 years, the couple lived in South Africa,
Australia and Southampton, where Mr. Haisman worked in the
boatyard. They had 10 children.
<p>
   Ms. Kamuda, of the Titanic Historical Society, said Mrs. Haisman
had ``elaborated'' her story over the years, adding details about
what her father was wearing, for example.
<p>
   ``This is not a criticism of Mrs. Haisman,'' Ms. Kamuda said.
``On the contrary, it is only to point out how our memories fail us
as time passes and numerous outside influences shape our lives.''
<p>
   Mrs. Haisman did not share the concern of some survivors and
many curators and historians over efforts to salvage mementos from
the wreck and to raise parts of the ship itself. The 18-carat
pocket watch that she said was her father's had been found in a
purser's black leather portmanteau during a dive in 1987.
<p>
   RMS Titanic of Southport, Conn., the company that exhibits
artifacts from the ship and that has drawn charges of exploiting
the disaster from Ms. Kamuda and others, had the watch attached to
a sterling silver plate inscribed with the words, ``What better use
for scientific technology than to reunite a father with his
child.''
<p>
   The chairman of the company, George Tulloch, presented it to
Mrs. Haisman in Southampton in December 1993.
<p>
   By her bed in the nursing home stood a photograph of her father
in a straw boater, stiff collar and bowtie.
<p>
   Mrs. Haisman was born Oct. 27, 1896. She is survived by four
sons, two daughters and more than 30 grandchildren and
great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1841EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0575 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9618 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CSX-CONRAIL-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0378 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CSX-CONRAIL-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CSX EXTENDS CASH TENDER OFFER FOR CONRAIL SHARES TO FEB. 14 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Greg Groeller &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Richmond, Virginia, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- CSX Corp. said it
extended its tender offer for 20.1 percent of Conrail Inc.'s
shares, hoping to complete the cash portion of its proposed $9.72
billion acquisition.
<p>
   CSX acquired 19.9 percent of Conrail's shares for about $1.96
billion in its first tender offer. CSX said it extended the second
offer to 5 p.m. New York time on Feb. 14. The offer originally
expired at 5 p.m. today.
<p>
   Exercising their rights under Pennsylvania law, Conrail
shareholders last week blocked the acquisition by preventing their
company from accepting two-tiered acquisition bids of the kind CSX
proposes. Conrail and CSX have vowed to call another shareholder
vote on the issue.
<p>
   CSX is committed to buying Conrail at its current offer, CSX
Chairman John Snow said. ``We are confident that Conrail
shareholders will acknowledge that the merger . . . offers them the
most immediate value,'' he said in a statement.
<p>
   Many shareholders, saying CSX's offer is coercive and too low,
favor Norfolk Southern Corp.'s hostile $10.32 billion cash bid for
Conrail.
<p>
   Yet the gap between the bids is narrowing rapidly as the price
of CSX stock rises. CSX shares have risen 18 percent since hitting
a 52-week low of 41 1/4 on Jan. 6, closing today at $49 1/8.
<p>
   If CSX shares rise to $55, the face value both offers will be
worth about $10.3 billion.
<p>
   Earlier today, Norfolk Southern began its promised tender offer
to buy 8.2 million Conrail shares at $115 a piece. That amount --
about 9.9 percent of the outstanding common shares --is the maximum
amount Norfolk Southern can buy without tripping Conrail's ``poison
pill'' defenses.
<p>
   CSX has offered $110 a share in cash for 40 percent of u/Conrail
plus 1.86 shares of CSX common stock and $16 in preferred stock for
the remaining shares.
<p>
   Norfolk Southern's cash offer of $115 a share presumably would
be taxable, while CSX has said the stock portion of its bid is
expected to be a tax-free exchange.
<p>
   Conrail shares rose 3 1/2 to 107 1/2, a 52-week high. Norfolk
Southern rose 1 to 88 1/8.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1841EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0576 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=taf-z> A9621 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-PENALTIES </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0549 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HKN-RANGERS-PENALTIES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; LAX PENALTY KILLING NEARLY KILLED RANGERS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JASON DIAMOS &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  The New York Rangers' problem Tuesday night was not
so much with referee Don Van Massenhoven as it was with their
inability to kill penalties.
<p>
   That has been a seasonlong deficiency for the Rangers, and it
was almost costly to this veteran team again. After they could not
survive two key Edmonton power plays early in the third period, the
Rangers had a one-goal lead turn into a one-goal deficit with time
running down.
<p>
   But Mark Messier, whose criticism of Van Massenhoven sparked a
controversy Jan. 2, snapped a wrist shot from the left circle with
1 minute 41 seconds left in regulation to salvage a 4-4 tie with
the Oilers at Madison Square Garden. The goal was set up by the
rookie Vladimir Vorobiev, who had three assists to go along with
his first National Hockey League goal.
<p>
   Three weeks ago at the Garden, Messier had called Van
Massenhoven a ``disgrace'' after the Rangers' captain had led them
back to a 4-3 victory over the New York Islanders. Messier had also
accused the referee of pursuing a ``personal vendetta'' against the
Rangers that night.
<p>
   So it was interesting having Van Massenhoven watch Messier save
his team from defeat on an evening in which Vorobiev starred
alongside Brian Leetch, who had two goals and two assists.
<p>
   And, while the Rangers' penalty killing continues to be a
concern for Coach Colin Campbell (``We were awful tonight, I don't
care how you cut it,'' said Campbell, who blamed the coaching staff
for the disarray), Vorobiev's play was a nice surprise.
<p>
   With Aleksei Kovalev out for the season as he prepares to have
reconstructive surgery on his right knee, Campbell is giving
Vorobiev a long look at right wing on Messier's line. Barring a
trade, Campbell does not have much choice.
<p>
   And for one night, at least, Vorobiev made the most of the
opportunity in his third NHL game, as Messier's line was on the ice
for each of the Rangers' goals.
<p>
   ``If I had told my friends six years ago that I would be playing
on a line with Mark Messier and Adam Graves, I'd be the
laughingstock in town,'' Vorobiev said through an interpreter.
<p>
   The 24-year-old Vorobiev  &MD;  who, like Kovalev, is a product of
the famed Moscow Dynamo club  &MD;  assisted on both of Leetch's
first-period scores. Vorobiev then broke a 2-2 second-period tie at
13:55, finishing a give-and-go with Leetch to give the Rangers
their only lead, which they took into the final period.
<p>
   ``Vorobiev seemed to fit in well with Mark and Adam,'' Campbell
said. ``For now, he looks like a pretty good find.''
<p>
   But the coach cautioned that it was only one game, and a
wide-open one at that. Messier said it was too quick to pass
judgment after three games. Still, Leetch liked what he saw from
the rookie.
<p>
   ``Usually someone coming up is nervous with the puck,'' Leetch,
an All-Star defenseman, said of Vorobiev. ``But he made some great
plays. He looked awfully confident.''
<p>
   Afterward, Messier said he had no problem with Van Massenhoven
this time, and both said that they did not even talk to each other
about the incident.
<p>
   ``He was good,'' Messier said. ``He reffed a good game.''
</TEXT>
