<SLUG> BC-PREHISTORIC-TOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0121 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PREHISTORIC-TOOLS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; OLDEST-KNOWN TOOLS ARE DESCRIBED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Scientists have published a paper in the journal Nature
describing stone tools made 2.5 million to 2.6 million years ago
that are considered the oldest-known artifacts created by humans or
their direct ancestors.
<p>
   The discovery, which was announced in 1995 at a scientific
meeting, was made in excavations at Gona, Ethiopia, from 1992 to
1994. It included almost 3,000 rounded, fist-size stones and small,
sharp-edged flakes, a finding that pushed the date of the first
tool making back 200,000 years.
<p>
   The principal author of the paper was Dr. Sileshi Semaw, an
Ethiopian paleoanthropologist.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1843EST
</TRAILER>
