<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9624 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FED-GLITCH-UPDATE1-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0584 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FED-GLITCH-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FED INADVERTENTLY RELEASES SURVEY EARLY ON INTERNET (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Laura Cohn and Vincent Del Giudice &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds with background in fifth and 10th-12th paragraphs, analyst
reaction in 8th paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Federal Reserve
inadvertently released its regional survey of economic conditions
almost two hours early today, and officials at the central bank are
still trying to sort out what happened.
<p>
   ``We're even now,'' Fed spokesman Joseph Coyne quipped.
``Everybody has broken an embargo, including me.'' Coyne was caught
by surprise when called by a reporter inquiring about the report's
premature release.
<p>
   The Fed released its regional survey, commonly known as the
beige book, through the central bank's Internet site at 12:10 p.m.
Washington time. That was well ahead of the scheduled 2 p.m.
Washington time release.
<p>
   Coyne said the Fed didn't have an explanation for the early
release of its report. He said the central bank's computer
department is separate from the public affairs office, and he's
looking into it.
<p>
   The Fed observes strict embargoes for its economic reports,
since premature release of the central bank's information could
affect financial markets.
<p>
   One possible explanation for today's glitch is the change in the
release time of the report. Today's release marked the first time
the Fed planned on releasing its regional survey at 2 p.m.
Washington time -- two hours after the previous regular release
time of noon. The Fed said it changed the release time to
accommodate financial markets, without specifying further.
<p>
   The Fed's regional outlook is based on reports from the central
bank's 12 district banks and is published eight times each year. It
will be used to form the basis for discussion on interest rate
targets at the Feb. 4-5 meeting of the Fed's policy-setting Federal
Open Market Committee.
<p>
   Since today's survey confirmed other recent economic reports,
its premature release didn't rattle financial markets, analysts
said. ``Considering it didn't offer anything new about what the
Fed's going to do on interest rates, it was a non-event,'' said
Kevin Flanagan, money market economist at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
in New York.
<p>
   In late New York trading, the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond
fell 1/2 point lower, pushing up its yield 5 basis points to 6.83
percent. The bond slumped as Wall Street firms struggled to sell
$17.5 billion of two-year notes they bought from the Treasury
today.
<p>
   Today's report from the Fed said the economy continues to grow
with low unemployment nudging labor costs higher. While the Fed
found ``scattered evidence'' of pressures for higher wages in its
latest regional economic survey, the central bank still found no
evidence of accelerating consumer prices outside of energy.
<p>
   The report is in line with comments yesterday by Fed Chairman
Alan Greenspan, who said the U.S. economy remains strong with few
signs of immediate inflationary pressures even as an era of low
wage gains may be ending.
<p>
   ``The economy has retained considerable vigor, with few signs of
the imbalances and inflationary tensions that have disrupted past
expansions,'' Greenspan said, in testimony before the Senate Budget
Committee. ``By some important measures of price trends, inflation
actually slowed a bit in 1996.''
<p>
   The Fed's website is located at: www.bog.frb.fed.us.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1844EST
</TRAILER>
