<SLUG> BC-HASBRO-OPTIONS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0622 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HASBRO-OPTIONS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HASBRO OPTION TRADING TARGET OF FORMAL SEC INVESTIGATION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Gerard Meuchner &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Pawtucket, Rhode Island, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Trading in
Hasbro Inc.'s options is the target of a formal investigation by
the Securities and Exchange Commission, whose inquiry may lead them
to company insiders.
<p>
   Dale Carlson, a spokesman for the Pacific Stock Exchange, said a
lawyer representing a person under investigation told the exchange
of the SEC's move to begin a formal action. Hasbro's options trade
on the Pacific exchange, which in May delivered a report to the SEC
detailing what it called suspicious trading in the securities.
<p>
   A formal action means the SEC's board has authorized its
investigators to issue subpoenas or otherwise compel people to
testify about what they know. Typically, SEC investigations are
elevated to formal status after the agency gathers sufficient
evidence during an informal inquiry.
<p>
   Grant Ward, head of enforcement in the Boston office of the SEC,
wouldn't confirm nor deny the existence of a formal action.
<p>
   A spokesman for Hasbro, the maker of Nerf sports toys, Playskool
pre-school toys, and Milton Bradley and Parker Brothers brand board
games, said the company continues to cooperate with the SEC.
<p>
   ``There have been no subpoenas issued at all of Hasbro people,''
said the spokesman, Wayne Charness.
<p>
   The investigation stems from rival Mattel Inc.'s failed bid a
year ago to buy Hasbro, the nation's second-largest toy company.
<p>
   The value of Hasbro's options soared almost 12-fold in the five
days leading up to and following Mattel's public disclosure of its
unsolicited $5.2 billion bid. Investors buy call options when they
expect the underlying stock to rise.
<p>
   The San Francisco-based PSE turned its investigation over to the
SEC in May and asked it to scrutinize trading in 12 accounts. At
the time, the exchange said ``several'' of the 12 people involved
are Rhode Island residents ``who appear to have some connection''
to insiders at Pawtucket, Rhode Island-based Hasbro.
<p>
   The exchange also said in May that none of the 12 individuals
appear to be connected to El Segundo, California-based Mattel.
<p>
   Stock exchanges typically refer cases to the SEC because they
don't have the power to compel individuals to provide information.
<p>
   Mattel announced its offer for Hasbro to the public after the
close of trading on Jan. 24, 1996. On Jan. 26, Hasbro said the SEC
asked the company for unspecified documents. Mattel also said it
was contacted by the SEC.
<p>
   Hasbro officials have said they knew of Mattel's intent as early
as Jan. 15, when Mattel sent its rival an unsigned letter
concerning the bid. A week later, Mattel sent a signed letter to
Hasbro, which the firm's board of directors discussed at a Jan. 23
meeting.
<p>
   Hasbro rejected Mattel because of antitrust considerations, and
Mattel dropped its bid on Feb. 2.
<p>
   Trading in Hasbro's call options began to perk up just before
the Jan. 24 announcement, after weeks during which no transactions
in the securities were made.
<p>
   Hasbro's $30 options that expired in February 1996 began trading
in earnest on Jan. 19, following a five-week period in which the
securities traded on only five days. In the four days prior to
Mattel's Jan. 24 announcement, 286 February $30 call option
contracts traded; only 140 contracts traded in the prior five
weeks. Each option gives the buyer the right to purchase 100 shares
of the underlying stock. The purchase of 100 Hasbro $30 February
call options on Jan. 19 last year would have cost $8,750, plus
commissions. Six days later, they were worth $103,750.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1846EST
</TRAILER>
