<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=taf-z> A9634 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MARVEL-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0362 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MARVEL-BANKRUPTCY-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Del.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IN BLOW TO PERELMAN, COURT REJECTS MARVEL CREDIT TERMS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By FLOYD NORRIS &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Ronald Perelman, the financier who is seeking to maintain
control of the Marvel Entertainment Group in bankruptcy, suffered a
setback Wednesday when a U.S. Bankruptcy Court judge in Delaware
rejected parts of a borrowing agreement that Marvel had negotiated.
But a spokesman for Perelman said the ruling ``is really not a
problem for us.''
<p>
   Judge Helen S. Balick said she would not approve $100 million in
financing from banks led by Chase Manhattan unless two provisions
were changed. Those provisions were intended to insure that
Perelman would not lose control of Marvel and to prevent efforts to
block his planned reorganization of the company.
<p>
   Michael Freitag, a spokesman for Perelman, dismissed the ruling
as unimportant because he said the judge had indicated she would
approve alternate language that would amount to the same thing.
<p>
   One of the provisions the judge rejected would have thrown the
financing loan into default if Perelman's stake in the company fell
below 51 percent. But Freitag said a new provision would be added
that would require default if anyone else obtained a 25 percent
stake.
<p>
   Another provision would have brought on default if anyone
challenged Marvel's license giving Toy Biz the exclusive right to
sell toys based on Marvel characters. But Freitag said a new
provision would be inserted providing for default only if such a
challenge were successful. As part of Perelman's reorganization
plan for Marvel, he intends to have it acquire all of Toy Biz.
<p>
   Marvel, the comic book and sports card company, is 80
percent-owned by companies owned by Perelman. But his shares are
pledged as collateral for junk bonds issued by his companies. The
bondholders are trying to persuade the bankruptcy judge to let them
take control of the shares, and, with control, propose an alternate
reorganization plan.
<p>
   It appears that the substitute proposals, if approved, would
still lead to a default if Perelman lost control of the company to
the bondholders.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1848EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0586 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9635 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-COSTS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0433 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FAA-COSTS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FAA NEEDS BETTER COST ESTIMATING PROCEDURES, AUDITORS SAY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jennifer Thomas &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Federal Aviation
Administration doesn't have in place a reliable cost estimating
process to guide decisions on improving air traffic control,
government auditors say, and hundreds of millions of dollars could
be spent poorly or needlessly.
<p>
   ``Such a situation is unacceptable when making small
investments, but it is especially egregious when making
multimillion- or billion-dollar investments in mission-critical air
traffic control systems,'' Congress's auditing arm, the General
Accounting Office, said in a report today.
<p>
   The absence of reliable estimates of future costs also prevents
Congress from providing adequate funding for system improvements,
the GAO said.
<p>
   The report recommended that the FAA come up with a defined
system for estimating and monitoring costs.
<p>
   Such a system should include a historical database that reflects
cost and schedule estimates and any revisions, a method of
determining what of the current air traffic control software can be
adapted and reused, and a process for dealing with cost and
schedule overruns when they arise, the GAO said.
<p>
   The FAA told auditors that the agency plans to have a cost
accounting system in place by Oct. 1, 1997.
<p>
   The agency began its $34 billion overhaul of the nation's aging
air traffic control in 1982, which is expected to be completed by
the year 2003.
<p>
   Auditors singled out one program -- the Advanced Automation
System -- for particular criticism. The cost of the program, which
involved replacing controllers' work stations at ``en route''
centers that direct traffic between airports with new hardware and
software including radar displays, tripled from $2.5 billion to
$7.6 billion. The program was approximately eight years behind
schedule when the FAA finally scaled back the program in 1994.
<p>
   Loral Corp., acquired by Lockheed Martin Corp. earlier this
year, was the lead contractor on the controversial project.
<p>
   ``Similarly, increases in per-unit costs for five other major
air traffic control projects have ranged from 50 to 511 percent,
and schedule delays have averaged almost four years,'' the GAO said
in the report.
<p>
   Last week, the FAA boasted that a Lockheed Martin-led team
delivered a new air traffic control computer system 10 months ahead
of schedule and $3 million under budget.
<p>
   The agency didn't immediately respond to calls about today's
report.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1848EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0587 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=ttj-z> A9636 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-WAR-STUDY-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0780 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-GULF-WAR-STUDY-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW STUDY RAISES MORE QUESTIONS ABOUT GULF WAR ILLNESS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DON FINLEY &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Antonio Express-News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SAN ANTONIO  &MD;  A new study by San Antonio researchers has found
no link between exposure to toxic substances during the Persian
Gulf War and common complaints of muscle pain and weakness among
veterans.
<p>
   The study adds to a growing body of apparently conflicting
findings in recent weeks, as scientists and government officials
seek answers to the mysterious ailments reported by thousands of
Gulf War vets.
<p>
   ``We looked at the most severe patients, and we found very
little in the way of objective pathology to say that there was a
disorder unique to the Persian Gulf,'' said Dr. Anthony Amato,
former director of the neuromuscular service at Wilford Hall
Medical Center, who headed the study.
<p>
   Muscle pain and weakness are among the more common symptoms
reported by veterans since returning from the Gulf War. Other
symptoms are fatigue, joint pain, headache, memory loss, sleep
disorders, skin rashes and digestive problems.
<p>
   The study, which was published in the current issue of the
journal Neurology, looked at 20 patients with severe muscle pain
and weakness. They were drawn from 263 Gulf veterans from all
service branches seen at Wilford Hall between July 1994 and April
1995.
<p>
   Wilford Hall is a major referral center for active duty
personnel with possible Persian Gulf-related illness.
<p>
   The 20 reported ``the most severe neuromuscular symptoms,'' said
Amato, now with the University of Texas Health Science Center. All
complained of severe weakness or muscle pain lasting six months or
longer that significantly limited their daily activities.
<p>
   The 20 patients  &MD;  15 men and five women, between ages 24 and 50
 &MD;  were enlisted personnel who served in Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the
United Arab Emirates or the Persian Gulf itself on a Navy ship.
<p>
   They underwent a sophisticated battery of tests, including
muscle biopsies, nerve conduction studies and electromyograms, or
EMGs. EMGs record muscle contractions caused by electrical
stimulation.
<p>
   The evaluations showed no evidence of neuromuscular disease in
most of the patients, Amato said. One patient had a slightly
abnormal EMG. Six of the 20 had mildly elevated levels of creatine
kinase, a natural muscle enzyme. And five also had mild,
non-specific abnormalities on muscle biopsies.
<p>
   The researchers said those findings appear unrelated to their
Gulf War duties.
<p>
   But others remain unconvinced. Dr. Claudia Miller, assistant
professor of family practice at the health science center, and a
member of a VA advisory committee on Gulf War illness, said the
problem with Amato's study  &MD;  and similar studies  &MD;  is that no one
really knows what evidence to look for.
<p>
   ``There's a saying: absence of evidence is not evidence of
absence,''' Miller said. ``What we may be dealing with here is
something that's different, that we don't have a marker for yet.''
<p>
   Miller's research is focused on whether Gulf War vets may be
suffering from a disorder known as multiple chemical sensitivity,
which may have caused ``very subtle changes that are not detectable
easily with current methods.''
<p>
   ``There's a big debate in the (medical) community about whether
it's psychosomatic, or whether there is some kind of chemical
imbalance in these disorders that we're just not sophisticated
enough to pick up,'' Amato said.
<p>
   ``I didn't get into that big debate in the (study). Certainly
stress is something that can cause these symptoms,'' Amato added.
<p>
   Amato said some veterans might be experiencing stress-induced
disorders of fibromyalgia or chronic fatigue syndrome. Fibromyalgia
is a disorder characterized by chronic musculoskeletal pain, which
may be a complication of post-traumatic stress disorder.
<p>
   Some 700,000 U.S. troops were deployed to the Persian Gulf for
Operation Desert Shield and Operation Desert Storm.
<p>
   Amato's study comes on the heels of a report to Congress by VA
officials that Gulf War vets who were near an accidental release of
nerve gas in Iraq reported a higher rate of muscle and bone
ailments than those further away.
<p>
   And two weeks ago, the Presidential Advisory Committee on Gulf
War Veterans' Illnesses released its findings. The committee found
no evidence that exposure to chemical weapons caused health
problems for veterans.
<p>
   At the same time, a study by researchers at the University of
Texas Southwestern Medical Center in Dallas suggested that exposure
to certain combinations of chemicals could cause the symptoms
reported by Gulf War vets.
</TEXT>
