<DOCID> nyt970122.0588 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9637 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-YORK-TIMES-UPDATE </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0615 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NEW-YORK-TIMES-UPDATE`1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW YORK TIMES CO. TRUSTS ADD YOUNGER TRUSTEE (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Lynne Marek &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds statement from Arthur Sulzberger Sr. in 3rd paragraph,
adds background throughout and clarifies that single trust became
four trusts in 1990)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The founding family of The
New York Times Co. said today that it had brought a new generation
into the group of septuagenarians that oversee the family's stock
trusts and guide the media empire.
<p>
   Lynn Dolnick, 45, was chosen in December from among 13 fourth
generation heirs to serve as a trustee of four trusts that hold the
family's stock.
<p>
   Filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission today by
family members showed that a 1986 trust agreement was changed last
month so Dolnick could be added to a group of trustees that
includes the company's chairman and chief executive, the
70-year-old Arthur `Punch' Sulzberger Sr., and his three older
sisters. Dolnick is a niece of Sulzberger.
<p>
   ``Lynn's selection represents continuity in the family and is
part of the normal planning and transition that occurs among
generations,'' said the company's top executive in a statement
today.
<p>
   ``It will have no effect on our shareholders or the business
activities of the company. Rather, it's another sign of our
family's continued commitment to the ownership structure of The New
York Times Co.''
<p>
   The choice adds a trustee who works outside the media business
and who has little involvement with the company's day-do-day
operations, which includes publishing The New York Times and The
Boston Globe, as well as operating TV and radio stations.
<p>
   Dolnick works for the National Zoo in Washington, D.C., where
she is chief of the Exhibition Interpretation division, according
to the SEC filing. New York Times spokeswoman Nancy Nielsen said
that Dolnick holds a doctorate degree in molecular biology from
Brandeis University. The new trustee couldn't be reached for
comment on her appointment.
<p>
   Dolnick's mother, Ruth Holmberg, publishes the family's
Chattanooga Times newspaper in Tennessee. Holmberg, one of
Sulzberger's three sisters, also serves as a trustee.
<p>
   Marian Heiskell and Dr. Judith Sulzberger are also trustees and
the three sisters are all members of the company's board of
directors. The Sulzberger family exercises almost full control over
the company by virtue of its non-trading Class B share holdings and
the voting power that accompanies the stock.
<p>
   While the appointment may be part of preparing for the future,
family trust attorney Theodore Wagner points out that the older
trustees could very well be active for many years to come. Iphigene
Ochs Sulzberger -- the mother of the four older trustees -- was
active in directing the company in her late 90s, he said. After she
died in 1990, each of the four children inherited one-quarter of
her holdings and her trust was divided into four trusts, all with
the same four trustees.
<p>
   Despite the family's statement, Steven Barlow, a media analyst
at Smith Barney, said that as the company is passed down from one
generation to the next, family members' allegiance to the company
tends to diminish.
<p>
   ``Every generation that gets further removed from the founding
family is more likely to cause an event to occur if the price of
the stock doesn't increase at a reasonable rate over a period of
time, and it certainly has not over the past 10 years,'' said
Barlow, noting nonetheless that the stock has performed well in the
last couple years.
<p>
   New York Times Class A shares slipped 1/8 to close today at 40
1/2.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1850EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
