<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tia-z> A9642 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-MAYES-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0142 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PACKERS-MAYES-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PACKERS' DERRICK MAYES HURTS RIBS, QUESTIONABLE FOR SUPER BOWL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Scott Soshnick &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New Orleans, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Green Bay Packers reserve
wide receiver Derrick Mayes suffered bruised ribs during practice,
leaving the rookie questionable for the Super Bowl.
<p>
   Mayes, a second-round draft pick out of Notre Dame, was hurt
during punt coverage drills when he collided with teammates. The
Packers were practicing without pads.
<p>
   Green Bay coach Mike Holmgren said Mayes would be able to
practice tomorrow. ``I think he's going to be OK, but right now
he's pretty sore,'' Holmgren said.
<p>
   Mayes caught six passes for 46 yards and two touchdowns during
the regular season. He was inactive for both of the Packers'
playoff games.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1850EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0590 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=taf-z> A9643 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOINSURE-ECONSCENE- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1040 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-AUTOINSURE-ECONSCENE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: N.J., Calif., Conn., Ky., N.Y., Va.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ECONOMIC SCENE: WHITMAN GIVES `AUTO CHOICE' INSURANCE A CHANCE &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By PETER PASSELL &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The proposal from Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey last week
to allow motorists to buy no-frill, no-fault auto insurance that
could pare premiums by as much as one-fourth was a strong
endorsement for a fledgling idea that has been unable to take
flight nationally.
<p>
   The idea is known as auto choice, and the seal of approval from
Whitman, an adroit Republican who undoubtedly has her sights on
bigger things, may finally be the step that helps lift it off the
ground.
<p>
   ``Once people understand auto choice means lower premiums and
better coverage, it's a no-brainer,'' argues Peter Kinzler,
director of the Coalition for Auto Insurance Reform, an ad hoc
group of consumer activists that operates without funds from the
insurance industry.
<p>
   From the perspective of those disturbed by the current, heavily
legalistic system of auto insurance, the Whitman endorsement could
not come at a more opportune time. Next week Kinzler's group, along
with the University of Wisconsin's Auto Compensation Project, is
sponsoring a conference in Washington to highlight the virtues of
auto choice and to publicize the introduction of federal
legislation by Senators Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn., Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., and Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.
<p>
   One reason auto insurance is so expensive is that it costs a
fortune to determine liability in court. Plaintiffs' lawyers
typically take one-third to one-half of any compensation. Moreover,
the ability to sue for intangible losses from pain and suffering
adds even greater costs because the potential for payoffs far
exceeding injury victims' medical bills and lost wages encourages
fraudulent claims. In 1995 Louis Freeh, the FBI director, estimated
that fraud added $200 to the average household's insurance cost.
<p>
   No-fault insurance, requiring insurers to cover their own
clients' economic losses regardless of fault and permitting suits
only when injuries are severe, was supposed to contain this
colossal waste. But in two decades of battles, trial lawyers have
maintained the upper hand by keeping it relatively easy to get to
court in most states.
<p>
   Strict no-fault laws barring all suits against offending drivers
whose behavior is short of criminal would do the trick. But this
approach was recently trounced in California, in no small part
because of opposition from Ralph Nader, who sees no-fault as an
unacceptable interference with every American's right to a day in
court. That's where auto choice fits in.
<p>
   The invention of Jeffrey O'Connell, a law professor at the
University of Virginia, and Michael Horowitz, a fellow at the
Hudson Institute in Washington, auto choice is just what it sounds
like.
<p>
   Those who value the right to sue for pain and suffering could
still buy insurance to do that. Those who do not could save money
by limiting their insurance to no-fault protection covering medical
bills and lost wages.
<p>
   When two drivers who chose the no-fault protection were involved
in an accident, each would look to his own insurer for
compensation. When two drivers who bought pain and suffering
insurance collided, responsibility  &MD;  and compensation  &MD;  would be
settled through the legal system.
<p>
   It gets a bit more complicated if a fully covered ``pain and
suffering'' driver collided with a no-fault driver. In that case,
the fully covered driver would not be able to sue the other for
pain and suffering. Rather, he would look to his own insurer for
such compensation. This may sound odd, O'Connell says, but it is
just the way coverage against ``uninsured motorists'' works today.
<p>
   If everyone chose the no-fault route, the savings would be
enormous. A study by the Rand Corporation, updated to 1996, puts
the figure at $40 billion nationwide, or $220 a vehicle.
<p>
   Auto choice, which was quietly endorsed by President George Bush
in 1992 and Bob Dole in 1996, may be broadening its political base
with the support of moderate Democrats like Lieberman and Moynihan.
What's more, there are signs that Nader-inspired opposition from
consumer groups is crumbling: Stephen Brobeck, executive director
of the Consumer Federation of America, has signed on.
<p>
   But lawyers, who reap tens of billions of dollars annually from
auto injury suits, have plenty of money to feed the campaign
contribution machine. And at least for the moment, there is no
compelling incentive for legislators to bite the hands that feed
them. That's why the New Jersey initiative  &MD;  where 35 cents of the
total premium dollar now goes into compensation for pain and
suffering and lawyers' fees  &MD;  looms so large.
<p>
   The New Jersey plan offers motorists four choices. At one end is
a policy close to business-as-usual, with ``unfettered access'' to
the courts. At the other is $250,000 in true no-fault protection,
which New Jersey's commissioner of insurance estimates would cut
premiums by 20 percent to 25 percent.
<p>
   In between are hybrids that Whitman apparently figured would
help deflate opponents' argument that access to court was a matter
of principle. One option would allow motorists to buy limited
coverage for pain and suffering from their own insurers, reducing
premiums by about 8 percent by eliminating the chance a jury would
issue a multimillion-dollar reward and leaving less to argue about
in court. The other would establish a new, very tough injury
threshold for access to court.
<p>
   Auto choice remains a political long shot. Insurance companies,
which might be expected to be powerful natural allies, are in fact,
largely indifferent because they see little additional profit,
anticipating that competition would force them to lower their
premiums in proportion to their costs.
<p>
   But when seasoned politicians like Whitman take a shot at
mobilizing the discontent of motorists who have insurance premiums
that can easily exceed $2,000, the assumption that trial lawyers
can buy their way out of trouble may not hold forever.
<p>
   ``Who could say no,'' the governor asks, ``to a bill that simply
gives consumers a choice?''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1850EST
