<SLUG> BC-EARNS-AMOCO-UPDATE-BL </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0260 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-AMOCO-UPDATE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AMOCO 4TH-QUARTER PROFIT RISES 55% ON HIGHER PRICES (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Anne Pollak 609 279-4043 and George Stein &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Rewrites. Adds closing stock price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Chicago, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Amoco Corp. said fourth-quarter
earnings rose 55 percent, continuing a pattern among oil companies
of posting bigger profits because of higher oil and natural gas
prices.
<p>
   Amoco said profit from operations rose to $781 million, or $1.56
a share, from $504 million, or $1.02, in 1995.
<p>
   The results beat the average earnings estimate of $1.30 a share
from 22 analysts polled by IBES International Inc. Amoco stock rose
7/8 to 85 7/8.
<p>
   ``Amoco reported the best quarter that we've seen of the big
domestic and international integrated oil companies so far,'' said
Douglas Terreson, an analyst with Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co. ``It will
probably be the best in the end.''
<p>
   Revenue rose to $10.08 billion from $8.09 billion in the
year-ago quarter.
<p>
   A $90 million gain from a reduction in inventory resulted in
fourth-quarter net income of $871 million, or $1.74 a share. A
charge of $380 million relating to the impairment of certain assets
and a gain of $83 million from the sale of the Amoco Motor Club
brought net income in the year-ago quarter to $207 million, or 42
cents.
<p>
   Full-year 1996 profit from operations rose 20 percent to $2.59
billion, or $5.20 a share, from $2.16 billion, or $4.36, in 1995.
Revenue was $36.08 billion, up from $31 billion.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1851EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0596 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=ttd-z> A9649 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWS-2TAKES-SFCHRO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0836 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TV-NEWS-2TAKES-SFCHRON &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; NBC LEARNS THE ABCS OF NEWS &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By JOHN CARMAN &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.1997, San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The television audience is notoriously reluctant to shift its
news loyalty, but just such a glacial swing in viewer preference
may have begun.
<p>
   For four weeks in a row, and six of the past seven, Tom Brokaw
and the ``NBC Nightly News'' have edged out Peter Jennings and
``ABC World News Tonight'' in the Nielsen ratings.
<p>
   ``World News Tonight,'' the ratings leader for eight straight
years, is now in a dead heat with ``Nightly News'' in the
season-to-date ratings.
<p>
   NBC's uptick comes on the heels of a radical alteration in the
format and philosophy of its evening newscast.
<p>
   What's more, a shift in ratings could help spell the end of the
longest period of news anchor stability in TV history. For 14
years, the only change in the network anchor firmament has been
CBS' ill-fated pairing of Dan Rather and Connie Chung as ``Evening
News'' co-anchors.
<p>
   The reasons for NBC's surge are difficult to gauge.
<p>
   ``Pinpointing this,'' says NBC News Vice President Bill
Wheatley, ``is not an exact science.''
<p>
   One possibility is that NBC News sowed the seeds of its current
success with its extensive coverage of the O.J. Simpson trial in
1995. Other parts of the foundation may be the Olympics coverage
last summer on NBC, the additional exposure for NBC News and Brokaw
on the new MSNBC cable channel, and the auxiliary influence of
NBC's winning prime-time programming.
<p>
   Another possibility is the improved performance of NBC- owned
and -affiliated stations, many of which produce local newscasts
leading into the network newscasts. A strong lead-in can be the
best tonic for any TV program.
<p>
   And there is the ``Nightly News'' itself, where changes have
created critics as well as converts.
<p>
   Late last year, NBC cut Brokaw free of the traditional anchor
desk. Since then, he's been standing in front of a large, kinetic
``video wall'' to deliver the nightly newscasts.
<p>
   Andrew Tyndall, who tracks network news trends through a widely
distributed weekly flyer called the Tyndall Report, says removing
Brokaw from the anchor desk and newsroom backdrop has given the
``Nightly News'' an ``MTV or ESPN2'' look, putting Brokaw ``in
virtual space rather than real space.''
<p>
   But the change is far deeper than cosmetic. Tyndall says NBC has
also reduced its story count to as few as five stories a night,
consequently cutting appearances by NBC field correspondents. It
has added regular features such as ``In Their Own Words,'' in which
newsmakers express themselves without the customary journalistic
interpretation.
<p>
   ```In Their Own Words' leaves a viewer thinking he has seen
something not filtered by one of those Armani-suit-wearing, snide
network news reporters,'' a correspondent from another network
said, with a trace of sarcasm, after watching the ``Nightly News.''
<p>
   Also, says Tyndall, NBC has implemented ``a dramatic cutback in
overseas coverage,'' offering only a third as much foreign news as
it did at the start of the decade. Domestic coverage has risen
sharply to fill the void, but not domestic coverage from
Washington, D.C. The old reliance on ``inside the Beltway'' news
from the capital has been curtailed.
<p>
   A look at time allotted to news stories in 1996 demonstrates
Tyndall's point about the shift in emphasis. ABC and CBS each
devoted more than twice as much air time as NBC to the former
Yugoslavia and the introduction of U.S. forces in Bosnia. NBC was
also well behind in its coverage of another important international
story, Israeli-Palestinian relations.
<p>
   Domestically, NBC devoted less time than its competitors to the
national political conventions, the presidential campaign and the
Whitewater investigation.
<p>
   NBC led ABC and CBS in evening news time allotted to the O.J.
Simpson wrongful-death lawsuit, the ValuJet crash in the
Everglades, the bull market on Wall Street and, by far the widest
margin, the Olympic Games in Atlanta.
<p>
   NBC is dialing up the heat not only in its story choices,
Tyndall alleges, but also in its handling of stories.
<p>
   ``It's borderline tabloid,'' he says. ``They get very prickly
when you say `tabloid.' Call them `populist,' and they don't mind
that.''
<p>
   In fact, NBC's Wheatley did reject the ``tabloid'' sobriquet in
a telephone interview this week, and accepted the term
``populist.''
<p>
   NBC is reporting fewer ``process'' stories about the
wheel-turning of the federal government in Washington, he said. And
less foreign news, especially ``second-level'' stories from abroad.
<p>
   ``I think that's true of American journalism in general,''
Wheatley said of the foreign cutbacks. ``But if there's major
foreign news, especially affecting our viewership, we're there.''
<p>
   ``Nightly News'' didn't have a single foreign story in last
Friday's newscast, except for a brief mention of American
balloonist Steve Fossett's troubled attempt to fly over Libya.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
    &UR; (MORE) &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1852EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0597 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=ttd-z> A9650 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWS-2NDTAKE-SFCHR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0604 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TV-NEWS-2NDTAKE-SFCHRON &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; UNDATED: over Libya. &LR;  &HT;     &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The day's lead story, as at many newspapers, was the murder of
Bill Cosby's son. (ABC led with the reprimand and fine imposed on
House Speaker Newt Gingrich.) Brokaw said the murder was ``an
unsolved mystery.'' NBC correspondent George Lewis claimed that the
crime had brought ``emotional turmoil'' to Southern California.
<p>
   Later in the broadcast, NBC aired a ``News in Depth'' feature
about other parents who've coped with the loss of a child. Brokaw
introduced a story about a New Hampshire airplane crash by saying
that ``a small plane ride turned to tragedy today ...'' Still
later, a U.S. flag rippled in the background as Brokaw introduced
an ``American Dream'' segment about the new governors of New
Hampshire and Washington.
<p>
   It can't be said with certainty that cutting back on foreign
news will please viewers; after all, Jennings and ``World News
Tonight'' displayed a special fondness for foreign stories and have
led the pack through the 1990s.
<p>
   But NBC has sprung to life with a sharp departure from the
``headline digest'' style of the 1960s and 1970s. It's also
radically different from the thick analysis on PBS' ``NewsHour,''
where Washington news and foreign developments remain paramount.
<p>
   Some observers see at least a smidgeon of NBC influence in ABC's
switch of its ``American Agenda'' news segment to ``Solutions''
features about ways to solve social problems, and in the addition
of new segments in the ``CBS Evening News.''
<p>
   The battle is for prestige and dollars, but it's waged against
the backdrop of a dwindling audience. In the past decade, the three
network evening newscasts collectively have experienced a 30
percent decrease in ratings.
<p>
   In many cities, the newscasts are on too early for commuting
workers to see them. One network correspondent, who asked not to be
identified, jokes that he's recognized in public only by people
who've seen his stories repeated later on the local news.
<p>
   Also, the evening newscasts tend to be unpopular with younger
viewers, who are increasingly likely to get their news from such
alternate sources as the Internet, radio talk shows and even
late-night entertainment programs on TV.
<p>
   Brokaw, at 56, is enjoying a resurgence among the remaining
viewers for the evening newscasts. He's anchored ``Nightly News''
since 1983. Jennings, now 58, became the solo anchor of ``World
News Tonight'' the same year.
<p>
   The eldest anchor is Rather, who took over for Walter Cronkite
in 1981. Rather is 65, older than Cronkite was when he stepped
down. CBS, which once led the field in ratings, bench strength and
journalistic impact, trails ABC and NBC by more than a full ratings
point.
<p>
   ``CBS Evening News'' is a victim largely of affiliate switches
that have left CBS in partnership with relatively weak UHF
affiliates in some major markets.
<p>
   But as the ``NBC Nightly News'' contests for first place,
proving that viewer preferences are malleable, talk about replacing
Rather at CBS is inevitable.
<p>
   Recent scuttlebutt has centered on Bryant Gumbel, who has left
NBC's ``Today'' program, and Diane Sawyer, whose ABC contract
expires this spring.
<p>
   Within the network news divisions, though, some say the flagship
anchor jobs have lost their allure. Much of the action and many of
the viewers have switched to the prime-time newsmagazines.
<p>
   ``To imagine Ed Bradley moving from `60 Minutes' to anchor the
`CBS Evening News,' that's not a promotion anymore,'' said one
veteran network correspondent.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
    &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1852EST
</TRAILER>
