<SLUG> BC-EARNS-CORESTATES-UPDA </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0355 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-CORESTATES-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CORESTATES FINANCIAL NET UP ON SLOW LOAN GROWTH (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Marjorie Shaffer &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds analyst comment, earnings details, closing stock price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Philadelphia, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- CoreStates Financial
Corp.'s fourth-quarter net income rose 1.8 percent as cost savings
and strong gains internationally failed to offset slow loan growth.
<p>
   The Philadelphia-based bank said net income rose to $195.5
million, or 91 cents a share, from $192.1 million or 87 cents a
share. The earnings were three cents short of Wall Street's
expectations of 94 cents a share, according to a survey of 19
analysts by IBES International Inc.
<p>
   The fourth-quarter figures include costs tied to CoreStates'
merger with Meridian Bancorp last year. Without those costs and
other items, earnings rose 2.8 percent to $201.6 million, or 93
cents a share, from $196.1 million, or 89 cents.
<p>
   The company said strong growth in international fees didn't
offset declines elsewhere due to the competitive market for most
types of commercial lending.
<p>
   Analysts said that slow loan growth and the costs of the
Meridian merger hampered growth in the quarter. However, they said
merger costs were largely taken care of, leading to better earnings
in the future.
<p>
   ``The quarter was a little light, but in the future they are
poised for renewed balanced sheet growth,'' said David Berry, an
analyst at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, Inc.
<p>
   Investors sent CoreStates shares up 1 1/8 to 52 5/8.
<p>
   Net interest income in the fourth quarter fell 2.0 percent to
$543.1 million, as net interest margin declined to 5.51 percent
from 5.56 percent. Non-interest income dipped 0.4 percent to $224.4
million.
<p>
   The bank set aside a little more money for bad loans in the
quarter to $40.0 million from $38.2 million provision, while net
charge-offs, or loan writeoffs, fell to $37.9 million from $54.5
million.
<p>
   For the full year, net income fell 0.9 percent to $649.1
million, or $2.97 a share, from $655.2 million or $2.95, a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
