<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9654 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CAMELOT-TECK-MT.EDON- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0898 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CAMELOT-TECK-MT.EDON-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CAMELOT, TECK CORP. BID A$158 MLN FOR MOUNT EDON (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Jim Pollock &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds closing stock price.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Perth, Australia, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Camelot Resources NL,
an Australian gold mining company, and Canada's Teck Corp., said
they will make a joint A$158 million (US$123 million) takeover bid
for Mount Edon Gold Mines (Australia) Ltd.
<p>
   The bid will be made through Reachwest Pty. Ltd. Reachwest
already holds about 14.2 percent of Mount Edon.
<p>
   The price represents a 48 percent premium to the closing price
of Mount Edon yesterday.
<p>
   ``We like the asset and the exploration potential,'' said Steven
Dean, managing director of Camelot. ``Their regional exploration
position is what interests us.''
<p>
   Analysts say the bid illustrates the attraction of gold assets
in Australia and Papua New Guinea for Canadian companies. It
follows bids by Placer Dome Inc. for Highlands Gold Ltd. and the 25
percent of Placer Pacific Ltd. it doesn't already own, which were
announced last month.
<p>
   ``They are quite willing to come in and pay a 48 percent premium
for gold stocks here,'' said David Kauler, an analyst at ANZ
Securities Ltd. in Melbourne. ``They are far more willing to pay
for gold in the ground than for immediate earnings.''
<p>
   Martin Hickling, who helps manage A$5.7 billion at Colonial
Mutual Investment Management, said there could be more takeovers,
particularly in the smaller Australian gold stocks. ``It's a theme
that you could see continuing,'' he said.
<p>
   Camelot's Dean said Mount Edon has a strong presence in the
Leonora greenstone belt, a group of rocks which is known to contain
gold deposits near Leonora, about 600 kilometers northeast of
Perth.
<p>
   The bid is subject to a number of conditions including
government approval, a minimum acceptance of 90 percent, the cash
price for gold not declining below US$335 an ounce and the
Australian Stock Exchange Gold Index remaining above 1500 points.
The gold price was last quoted at US$351.60 an ounce and the gold
index was at 1732.30 points.
<p>
   ``It's an unsolicited and opportunistic bid,'' said Tony
Brennan, Mount Edon's managing director. ``For the time being,
shareholders should do nothing.''
<p>
   Brennan said Mount Edon's directors were meeting to appoint
advisers later this week.
<p>
   Mount Edon operates the Tarmoola gold mine in Western Australia
state. The mine produced 58,369 ounces of gold in the 12 months to
June 30, 1996.
<p>
   Tarmoola experienced mining problems last year which resulted in
lower gold production. Mount Edon's share price declined from
A$3.49 last February to a low of A$1.35 on Jan.16.
<p>
   Mount Edon's quarterly report for the three months to Dec. 31,
which was released on Jan 17, showed that the production problems
are progressively being overcome. Gold production for the quarter
totaled 38,568 ounces and brought gold output for the six months to
Dec. 31 to 74,416 ounces, 83 percent higher than the previous
corresponding period.
<p>
   ``The results of the December quarter showed a substantial
turnaround,'' Brennan said. ``The December quarter now really
cements the turnaround at the operations.''
<p>
   Teck has given Reachwest a commitment to provide funding to meet
the requirements of the bid for a period of nine months.
<p>
   Within about three months after the close of the bid, Teck and
Camelot are required to make minimum cash contributions to
Reachwest. Camelot must contribute A$40 million to earn a minimum
30 percent interest in Reachwest. Teck must contribute A$93.3
million to earn 70 percent.
<p>
   These funds will be used to repay a substantial part of the
borrowings incurred by Reachwest to finance the bid.
<p>
   Camelot has the right to increase its interest in Reachwest to
50 percent by making further cash payments to Reachwest within six
months of the close of the bid. The cost will be A$1.333 million
for every percentage point interest between 30 percent and 50
percent.
<p>
   Camelot's Dean said Camelot will raise the funds needed to
acquire the minimum 30 percent interest in Reachwest in two
tranches.
<p>
   The first will be through the sale of new Camelot share to Teck
and other investors, at or close to the market price, to raise
about A$7.5 million. Teck will buy sufficient shares to increase
its interest in Camelot to 19.99 percent.
<p>
   A second share sale will raise A$32.5 million and will be made
to existing shareholders, after the successful completion of the
Mount Edon bid. Rights to buy the new shares will be renounceable.
<p>
   Camelot operates the Mount Gibson gold mine in Western Australia
and has an effective 50 percent interest in the Burnside gold mine
through its subsidiary Northern Gold NL.
<p>
   In the year to June 30, Mt Gibson produced 60,248 ounces of
gold. The Burnside project is currently under study. Northern gold
is planning a mine to produce 80,000 ounces of gold a year from the
treatment of 1.5 million metric tons of ore a year.
<p>
   Teck Corp is a major Canadian mining company with a market
capitalization of about C$3.01 billion (US$2.25 billion). It
produces a range of metals and coal from eleven mines in Canada and
one in Chile. It holds cash and money market investments valued at
about C$380 million.
<p>
   Its class A shares rose C$1.75 to C$32 in Toronto.
</TEXT>
