<SLUG> BC-ADS-YU-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0418 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ADS-YU-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SEC FINES CALIFORNIA INVESTMENT ADVISER $150,000 FOR FALSE ADS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Neil Roland &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- A California investment
adviser and the firm he owns were ordered to pay a total of
$150,000 in fines for advertisements that inflated their 1985-1991
results, the Securities and Exchange Commission said today.
<p>
   Norman L. Yu and his Newport Beach, California-based firm,
Norman L. Yu &AMP; Co., agreed to pay the unusually large fine without
admitting or denying the allegations.
<p>
   The SEC accused Yu of distributing advertisements claiming his
accounts gained as much as 23.9 percent in 1990 when in fact they
lost 6.6 percent. These ads claimed his accounts rose 55.9 percent
in 1989 when the actual increase was 38.1 percent, the SEC said.
<p>
   ``In advertising, investment advisers need to be sure they state
their performance accurately and completely,'' said Kelly Bowers,
assistant SEC enforcement director in Los Angeles. Bowers described
the fine as ``a very substantial penalty for investment advisers.''
<p>
   In addition to the fines, Yu and his firm were censured and
prohibited from advertising results for five years until figures
have been audited by an independent certified accountant. The
firm's advertisements also have to be reviewed by someone
acceptable to the SEC.
<p>
   Neither Yu, 65, nor his attorney responded today to requests for
comment about the ads, which ran from 1991 to 1993. His 15-employee
firm had 683 client accounts and $210 million under management in
the early 1990s, according to the SEC.
<p>
   The SEC also alleged Yu failed to keep records that would show
how the firm calculated its performance and prepared no written
policies to prevent the misuse of investment data.
<p>
   ``Yu oversaw all operations,'' the SEC contended. ``Yu
maintained (the firm's) performance materials in his office and
determined which documents should be maintained and preserved, and
which ones should be discarded.''
<p>
   The New York Times reported in 1993 that Yu's advertised returns
vaulted him onto a service that tracks the performance of money
managers. Norm Zadeh, who runs Money Manager Verified Ratings,
published a 1991 report saying that Yu had ``one of the best
records in the world for investing from the long side,'' the
newspaper reported.
<p>
   Zadeh said today that Yu ``deceived'' him, and that he ``blew
the whistle'' to the news media on Yu's activities.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1856EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
