<SLUG> BC-FLEET-SHARES-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0333 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FLEET-SHARES-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; RIGGS NATIONAL SURGES AS MUCH AS 7.8% ON RENEWED TAKEOVER TALK &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Joseph Giannone &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Riggs National Corp. surged
as much as 7.8 percent to a record high as investors bet the
Washington-based bank could be a takeover target.
<p>
   Riggs, which has been the subject of takeover speculation since
July, rose as much as 1 3/8 to 18 7/8 before closing at 18 3/8 a
day after First Maryland Bancorp acquired Pennsylvania-based
Dauphin Deposit Corp.
<p>
   Allied Irish Bank, which has expanded its First Maryland network
throughout Pennsylvania, Maryland and Virginia, said it was eager
to expand in the U.S. -- particularly in the Washington area. For
many investors, that meant Riggs was next, analysts said.
<p>
   ``A lot of people are saying Riggs would be a good match,'' said
Hal Schroeder, a bank analyst at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods.
<p>
   Riggs, with about $5 billion in assets and 57 branches in the
Washington area, fueled takeover talk when it announced it was
putting its RIMCO investment management, trust services and private
banking units into a new division, Riggs &AMP; Co.
<p>
   Investors interpreted the move as a prelude to the bank selling
its branches.
<p>
   A bank spokesman denied any such intentions. ``We think these
changes will add a significant new marketing opportunity for the
benefit of the entire bank,'' the spokesman said.
<p>
   The U.S. banking industry is going through an unprecedented wave
of consolidation, as investors push companies to increase profits,
or else sell to someone who can deliver those profits. Banks make
acquisition to reduce costs and reach more customers.
<p>
   There is a dwindling number of banks of significant size in the
affluent towns of south Maryland and northern Virginia. Another
possible target in the region is Provident Bankshares Corp., a
Baltimore-based bank with about $2.5 billion in assets, Schroeder
said.
</TEXT>
