 &UR; BC-FBN-LIONS-TRESTMAN-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; LIONS NAME FORMER 49ERS ASSISTANT TRESTMAN QUARTERBACKS COACH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Bob Bensch &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Pontiac, Michigan, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Detroit Lions
named former San Francisco 49ers assistant Marc Trestman the team's
new quarterbacks coach.
<p>
   Trestman, 41, directed one of the NFL's most potent attacks over
the past two years as 49ers offensive coordinator. Last season, San
Francisco's Steve Young was the NFL's top-rated quarterback and
Jerry Rice led the league in receptions.
<p>
   In Detroit, he will work with Scott Mitchell, who is expected to
sign a new contract with the Lions shortly. Mitchell was
inconsistent in 1996, throwing 17 touchdowns and 17 interceptions
for 2,917 yards. He enjoyed the finest season of his career in
1995, throwing for 4,338 yards with 32 touchdowns and 12
interceptions.
<p>
   Trestman is leaving San Francisco after the team replaced head
coach George Seifert, who resigned, with Steve Mariucci. In
Detroit, he joins the staff of head coach Bobby Ross, the
replacement for Wayne Fontes, who was fired.
<p>
   A nine-year NFL coaching veteran, Trestman began his career with
the Minnesota Vikings in 1985. He move to the Tampa Bay Buccaneers
as quarterbacks coach in 1987 and went to Cleveland in the same
capacity the next season. He then returned to Minnesota in 1990 for
two seasons.
<p>
   Trestman left coaching from 1992-94 to pursue a career in the
investment banking business before returning to the NFL with the
49ers in 1995.
<p>
   He began his coaching career as a volunteer assistant at the
University of Miami in 1982 while attending law school. While at
Miami he worked with quarterbacks Bernie Kosar and Vinnie
Testaverde.
</TEXT>
