<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BANKAMERICA-OPTIONS-UPDATE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BANKAMERICA OPTIONS SURGE AS INVESTORS BET ON RALLY (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Michael Smith and Dylan Ratigan &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates stock price and option trading.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   San Francisco, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- BankAmerica Corp. options
surged as investors bet the San Francisco bank's stock will rally.
<p>
   ``This is simply somebody looking for an efficient way to invest
in BankAmerica,'' said Harrison Roth, senior options strategist at
Cowen &AMP; Co. in New York.
<p>
   Options giving investors the right, but not the obligation, to
buy BankAmerica shares at 95 in April rose 3 1/2 to 16 1/2 in
trading of 1,510 contracts. That's seven times the daily average.
<p>
   The option, known as a call, rises in value as BankAmerica
shares rise in value. BankAmerica stock rose 2 to 110 in trading of
1.43 million shares.
<p>
   Analysts say BankAmerica's shares will probably rise further as
it buys back its stock, hoping to boost per-share earnings by
reducing the number of shares outstanding.
<p>
   In the fourth quarter, BankAmerica spent roughly $448 million to
buy 4.7 million shares. For the year, the bank bought back 17
million shares, at a cost of roughly $1.3 billion. Last year
BankAmerica shares rose 54 percent.
<p>
   By investing in an option instead of stock, buyers are able to
reduce their initial investment to 16 1/2 a share and still gain if
the stock rises.
<p>
   The disadvantage for option investors is that if they don't use
their option to buy the stock before the third week in April, their
entire investment will be lost. Last week, the bank said
fourth-quarter earnings rose 6 percent, as higher fees from
checking accounts and other services offset sluggish growth in
lending income.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1905EST
</TRAILER>
