<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FEDERAL-EXPRESS-GARY-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FEDERAL EXPRESS FACES BOYCOTT THREAT IN GARY AFTER SERVICE CUT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Deborah Cohen &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Gary, Indiana, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Federal Express Corp.
faces a possible boycott in Gary, Indiana, following the
package-delivery company's decision to reduce service hours in the
city because of courier safety fears.
<p>
   Company representatives met with Gary Mayor Scott King today to
discuss the threatened boycott, a Federal Express spokeswoman said.
<p>
   Federal Express last week moved its pickup deadline in Gary to 4
p.m. from 6 p.m. after company drivers complained their safety was
jeopardized on some routes in the northwest Indiana city,
spokeswoman Shirlee Clark said.
<p>
   ``There were some incidents that our couriers reported to
management,'' said Clark, who declined to give examples of the
complaints or the number of drivers involved. ``The safety of our
employees is of paramount importance to us.''
<p>
   She said regular hours were restored on some routes yesterday.
<p>
   Some area businesses have complained that the scheduling changes
would hamper business and cast the city in a negative light, a Gary
spokeswoman said.
<p>
   Mayor King's office didn't return calls seeking comment.
<p>
   ``We had said all along that we welcomed dialog with the mayor's
office,'' Clark said.
<p>
   She said Memphis, Tennessee-based Federal Express routinely
makes schedule adjustments due to weather or other factors.
</TEXT>
