 &UR; BC-JAPAN-TRADE-SURPLUS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JAPAN'S DECEMBER TRADE SURPLUS SHRANK 20.6% TO 881.5 BLN YEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Ken Belson &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Tokyo, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus
shrank 20.6 percent in December from the same month a year ago to
881.475 billion yen ($7.4 billion), the Finance Ministry said.
<p>
   That's the 24th decline in 25 months.
<p>
   The surplus was smaller than expected. Economists said the
surplus would be 1.055 trillion yen, according to a survey compiled
by Bloomberg Business News. Projections ranged from 970 billion yen
to 1.145 trillion yen.
<p>
   The trade surplus grew 0.2 percent in November compared to a
year earlier. That figure was later revised to a 0.4 percent
decline.
<p>
   Japan's trade surplus with the United States in December rose
7.8 percent to 389.113 billion yen, the ministry said.
<p>
   Global imports to Japan rose 13.4 percent to 3.286 trillion yen,
while exports increased 4.0 percent to 4.168 trillion yen, the
ministry said.
<p>
   For all of 1996, Japan's trade surplus fell 32.4 percent to 6.7
trillion yen. The country's full-year trade surplus with the U.S.
fell 16.5 percent to 3.6 trillion yen.
<p>
   The following is a breakdown of the figures released.
Dec. Change on Dec.'95 bln yen Year (%) bln yen Merchandise Trade
