<SLUG> BC-EARNS-CONRAIL-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0366 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-CONRAIL-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CONRAIL REPORTS 4TH-QTR PROFIT ON MORE TRAFFIC AND LOWER COSTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Greg Groeller &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Philadelphia, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Conrail Inc. said it posted
a fourth-quarter profit, compared with a loss a year ago, on rising
traffic and reduced spending.
<p>
   The railroad, which is the subject of a takeover fight, reported
net income of $147 million, or $1.86 a share, compared with a loss
of $30 million, or 43 cents a share, a year earlier.
<p>
   Revenue fell to $943 million from $951 million.
<p>
   The earnings beat the average estimate of $1.80 a share of 11
analysts surveyed by IBES International Inc.
<p>
   Conrail announced the results after the close of trading. Shares
of Conrail rose 3 1/2 to 107 1/2, a 52-week high.
<p>
   Philadelphia-based Conrail has agreed to be acquired by CSX
Corp. for $9.72 billion in cash and stock. Norfolk Southern Corp.
has made a rival bid of $10.32 billion in cash.
<p>
   ``Despite the potential for distractions resulting from our
proposed merger with CSX, our people clearly focused on controlling
costs, improving safety and maintaining high levels of service to
our customers,'' David LeVan, Conrail's chairman and chief
executive, said in a statement.
<p>
   Earlier today, CSX said it was extending its tender offer for
20.1 percent of Conrail's shares to 5 p.m. on Feb. 14. It was
originally scheduled to expire at 5 p.m. today. CSX already owns
19.9 percent of Conrail.
<p>
   Also today, Norfolk Southern began its promised tender offer to
buy 8.2 million Conrail shares at $115 each. That's the maximum
number of shares Norfolk Southern can buy without triggering
Conrail's ``poison pill'' defense against hostile takeovers.
<p>
   For the quarter, Conrail said its traffic rose 4.7 percent.
LeVan said costs decreased in every major category except fuel.
Compensation and benefits payments fell 8.2 percent; materials and
supplies costs fell 6.1 percent; and insurance costs fell 21.2
percent.
<p>
   For 1996, Conrail's net income rose to $342 million, or $4.25 a
share, from $264 million, or $3.19, in 1995.
<p>
   Revenue rose to $3.7 billion from $3.68 billion.
</TEXT>
