<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=taf-z> A9675 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0666 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COMPAQ-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMPAQ STOCK SOARS AS EARNINGS SURPASS FORECASTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LAWRENCE M. FISHER &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Compaq Computer Corp. reported earnings Wednesday for the fourth
quarter and all of last year that exceeded Wall Street analysts'
estimates, and the company's stock rose sharply.
<p>
   Compaq, the world's largest personal computer company,
attributed the gains in its earnings to greater sales of the more
profitable parts of the company's product line and to internal
changes that have lowered its costs and increased its profit
margins.
<p>
   Compaq shares rose $4.875 Wednesday, to $83.375, on the New York
Stock Exchange. The company's strength in a quarter when many PC
retailers and makers complained of poor consumer sales reflects
strong brand awareness and customer support, analysts said. The
broadening of Compaq's product line, which now includes larger
servers and work stations, also helped to lift the company's
fortunes above those of companies that make only PCs.
<p>
   ``The haves  &MD;  Compaq, IBM, Dell and Hewlett-Packard  &MD;  are
gaining market share at the expense of the have-nots,'' said
Charles R. Wolf, an analyst with CS First Boston.
<p>
   ``Customers in the corporate space are paying much more
attention to quality, brand and support, and are willing pay more
for that,'' he said. ``There's this fundamental shift occurring,
and the companies on the right side of it are reporting superb
results.''
<p>
   For the quarter, Compaq reported earnings of $462 million, or
$1.64 per share, more than five times the $82 million, or 30 cents
a share, reported in the comparable period a year earlier. The
earnings in the fourth quarter of 1995 reflect a one-time charge of
$241 million, or 87 cents a share, related to acquisitions. Sales
grew 15 percent, to $5.42 billion, from the $4.70 billion reported
in the fourth quarter of 1995.
<p>
   Earnings in the fourth quarter of 1996 beat the average estimate
of 34 analysts surveyed by First Call, for earnings of $1.53 a
share.
<p>
   For the year, earnings totaled $1.3 billion on sales of $18.1
billion, up from earnings of $789 million on sales of $14.8
billion.
<p>
   Earl L. Mason, Compaq's senior vice president and chief
financial officer, said in a telephone interview that the company
had not experienced the holiday disappointment reported by some
competitors. ``Our Christmas season was very good,'' he said. ``Our
business increased substantially on the consumer side. Most
importantly, we didn't have a lot of inventory when the Christmas
season ended.''
<p>
   But 85 percent of Compaq's sales are still to the corporate
market, and it was this segment that drove growth in the quarter.
Compaq now sees itself as not just a PC maker but as a computer
systems company, like IBM or Hewlett-Packard, able to fill
corporate needs across a broad spectrum of products, Mason said.
<p>
   The introduction of the company's first work stations, aimed
directly at machines from Sun Microsystems Inc., was particularly
strong, he said.
<p>
   Compaq has also instituted a broad effort to reduce costs and
increase return on capital, which bore fruit in the quarter. The
gross profit margin rose to 24.4 percent from 21.1 percent in the
first quarter of 1996. Mason said he was confident Compaq could
sustain such margins, which the PC industry has not seen in at
least two years.
<p>
   The internal changes also included inventory reduction, Mason
said. ``Taken together,'' he said, ``these operational improvements
lifted our cash balance 436 percent from $745 million in the
previous year to $4 billion.''
<p>
   Wolf of First Boston credits the soft-spoken Mason, who joined
Compaq from Inland Steel Industries just six months ago, as the
architect of these changes.
<p>
   ``The man really understands how to run a business from a
financial perspective,'' he said. ``The return on capital has just
begun to explode. Compaq stock's going to go through $100 like a
knife through warm butter.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1908EST
</TRAILER>
