<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9677 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CONRAIL-SUITORS-MEETI </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0630 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CONRAIL-SUITORS-MEETING-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CONRAIL SUITORS TO MEET FOLLOWING STB CHIEF'S COMMENTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Howard S. Abramson &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The chairmen of CSX Corp. and
Norfolk Southern Corp. agreed to meet in an attempt to reach a
compromise in their contest to acquire Conrail Inc. and dominate
the railroad business in the East.
<p>
   CSX Chairman John Snow and Norfolk Southern chairman David Goode
agreed to meet after a newspaper story quoted the head of the
federal Surface Transportation Board warning that if the railroads
can't reach a compromise, her agency might divide Conrail's routes
between the two other carriers. Conrail Chairman David LeVan is
also expected to attend the meeting.
<p>
   Norfolk Southern has intruded itself into what was intended to
be a friendly takeover of Philadelphia-based Conrail by CSX Corp.,
offering some $10.32 billion in cash, well above CSX's $9.48
billion cash and stock offer.
<p>
   While spokesmen for the three railroads involved in the
acrimonious fight indicated that no hatchets have been buried, the
opening of dialogue may signal the possibility of a peaceful
resolution. Goode proposed the meeting in letters to his
counterparts Tuesday after Linda Morgan, chairwoman of the STB,
stunned the railroad executives with her comments in the Washington
Post Tuesday in which she encouraged the carriers to reach a
compromise, or else.
<p>
   While no official acceptance has yet been communicated, CSX
spokesman Vance Richardson said Snow will attend the proposed
meeting, ``as long as there are no preconditions. We are encouraged
by Mr. Goode's letter. We hope it's not a public relations ploy.''
<p>
   A spokesman for Conrail said LeVan would officially accept the
offer to meet in a letter back to Goode at his Norfolk, Virginia,
headquarters.
<p>
   While Richmond, Virginia-based CSX has won most of the
preliminary court decisions in the battle for Conrail, the water
was muddied last week when Conrail shareholders rejected a bid by
CSX, which is based in Richmond, Virginia, for permission to
acquire an additional 20 percent of Conrail's stock, to bring its
holdings to 40 percent.
<p>
   While Norfolk Southern hailed the vote as a major victory for
its bid, LeVan and Snow said CSX's bid would still go through,
eventually.
<p>
   While not discussing specifics of the case, the STB's Morgan
indicated that the board thought itself compelled to maintain
competition in the East, and implied that the best way might be to
divide Conrail in half. {.7 Her words motivated Goode to write to
his colleagues, and inspired them to accept his offer to meet.
<p>
   ``Her comments sparked the dialogue,'' said Bob Fort, Norfolk
Southern's vice president for public affairs. ``We're pleased,'' he
said, because Morgan's comments were similar to statements Goode
has made about the necessity of maintaining competition after the
merger.
<p>
   CSX's Richardson said Morgan ``sent a clear signal,'' and the
company was responding by agreeing to meet with Goode.
<p>
   CSX and Conrail are expected to file a formal merger application
with the STB by March 1. The STB, which replaced the Interstate
Commerce Commission, normally has three commissioners, but one of
the seats is vacant.
<p>
   A spokesman for Gus Owen, who holds the other STB seat, said the
commissioner ``has no opinion (on the matter,) and will have no
opinion'' until after all the evidence is heard.
<p>
   Morgan today said, ``I'm not ordering anyone to do anything. I'm
not threatening people.''
<p>
   She said she sees government's proper role as ``helping people
resolve their problems'' by encouraging them to seek compromises,
and stepping in only when the public interest requires it to do so.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1911EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
