<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9678 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EARNS-TOSCO-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0438 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-TOSCO-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TOSCO SHARES RISE ON BETTER-THAN-EXPECTED EARNINGS (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By George Stein &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Rewrites.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Stamford, Connecticut, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Tosco Corp.
reported better-than-expected fourth-quarter earnings, though poor
refining and marketing margins cut profits by 11 percent.
<p>
   The company, a refiner and owner of convenience stores, reported
that fourth-quarter net income fell to $30.2 million, or 67 cents a
share, from $33.8 million, or 90 cents a share. The per-share drop
reflects both the drop in profit and a 19 percent increase in the
number of Tosco's outstanding shares.
<p>
   Wall Street expected earnings of 63 cents a share, according to
a consensus of 12 analysts polled by IBES International. Tosco
closed up 3/8 at 91 1/2.
<p>
   ``The earnings were fine,'' said Morgan Stanley analyst Douglas
T. Terreson. ``Our estimate was 65 cents a share so it was slightly
better than expectations.''
<p>
   Thomas D. O'Malley, Tosco's Chairman and Chief Executive
Officer, said in a statement that ``refining and marketing margins
were weak throughout the quarter due to the industry's inability to
pass higher crude oil costs on to the consumer. Cold weather in the
East helped Tosco's Bayway Refinery to a certain degree, but
conditions on the West Coast were weak.''
<p>
   Tosco, the largest operator of convenience stores in the nation,
will be the sixth-largest U.S. refiner after it completes the $1.8
billion purchase of Unocal Corp.'s refineries and gas stations it
announced in November. The company will sell fuel through 5,300 gas
stations and convenience stores nationwide, and be the
third-largest refiner on the West Coast.
<p>
   Tosco issued shares as part of its $750 million acquisition of
the Circle K Corp. convenience store chain in May. Tosco had 44.9
million shares outstanding in the fourth quarter compared with 37.6
million last year.
<p>
   Terreson said Morgan Stanley thinks Tosco's stock has continued
room for growth. ``We have a 110 price target for Tosco by 1997,''
he said.
<p>
   Trading in Tosco stock on the New York Stock Exchange was halted
briefly today following an explosion at a Tosco refinery last
night. After trading resumed, Tosco shares fell as much as 2 to 89
1/8 before recovering
<p>
   ``There were some concerns they would have capacity off the
market for some time,'' Terreson said.
<p>
   The explosion took place yesterday at Tosco's 150,000 barrel a
day Avon refinery in Martinez, California, in the San Francisco Bay
area. The company said one worker was killed and 25 injured.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1913EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
