<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9679 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BANKAMERICA-ROSSI-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0347 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BANKAMERICA-ROSSI-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MICHAEL ROSSI RETIRES AS VICE CHAIRMAN OF BANKAMERICA &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Katherine Burton &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   San Francisco, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Michael E. Rossi, vice
chairman of BankAmerica and a member of the bank's managing
committee said he'll retire from the bank in the second quarter of
this year. ``It's been a great run,'' Rossi, who oversees
BankAmerica's commercial banking and wealth management businesses,
said in a statement. ``I've had the opportunity to be part of the
team that restored BankAmerica to prominence in the 1980s and
achieved considerable success in the 1990s.'' Rossi, 52, plans to
retire from banking. He didn't specify what he'll do after he
leaves the bank.
<p>
   Rossi wasn't in line to become chairman, an analyst said.
<p>
   ``I don't think he was moving up,'' said George Salem, senior
vice president at Gerard Klauer Mattison &AMP; Co. in New York. ``He
was involved in miscellaneous lines of business. I don't consider
it any type of crisis.''
<p>
   Rossi is responsible for commercial business, international
trade banking, commercial real estate services, corporate real
estate and investment management groups and for Bank of America
Illinois.
<p>
   The company hasn't decided ``how to organize going forward,''
said David Coulter, chairman and chief executive. For now, these
units will continue to report to Rossi, he said in a statement.
<p>
   Before becoming vice chairman, Rossi was BankAmerica's chief
credit officer. He began his banking career with Bank of America in
San Francisco in 1966 as a desk officer and assistant cashier for
Mexico.
<p>
   Then he spent 16 years with Citicorp and Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. in
international banking assignments in Latin America and the United
States before rejoining the bank in 1986 as senior vice president
and manager of Latin America Special Assets Group.
<p>
   ``He's done an outstanding job for BankAmerica -- for its
customers and shareholders.'' Said Richard M. Rosenberg,
BankAmerica's recently retired Chairman and CEO.
</TEXT>
