<DOCID> nyt970122.0615 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=tad-z> A9681 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FARMERS-355&AMP;ADD-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0790 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FARMERS-355&AMP;ADD-COX  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; ATTN: Texas, Georgia Editors.
<p>
    &UR; BLACK FARMERS RECOUNT STORIES OF DISCRIMINATION BEFORE PANEL
<p>
    &UR; EDs: With Rick McKay photos, COX4-COX6.
<p>
    &UR; By KIA MORGAN ALLEN &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  Robert Williams Jr. was nearly moved to tears
several times Wednesday, as he recounted how he walks 13 miles each
day to his farm in Rosco, Texas with a .44 Magnum strapped to his
side.
<p>
   He does it because a gunshot shattered the window of his
tractor, just missing the back of his head, and he woke one morning
to find a sign that read: ``Go home Niger--KKK'' posted on his
gate.
<p>
   Williams, one of about two dozen farmers who addressed officials
at a civil rights listening session on Wednesday, said he has
experienced that racism and more at the hands of the U.S.
Department of Agriculture.
<p>
   Testifying before a panel headed by Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman, Williams and other black farmers protested against the
USDA's alleged discriminatory treatment of minority farmers when
applying for loans and other services.
<p>
   The panel, which also consisted of the Civil Rights Action Team
that Glickman formed to address discrimination complaints from
minority farmers, listened as a teary-eyed Williams gave his
testimony and two farmers pulled out the sign with the racially
offensive inscription and paraded it around the room. They rested
it behind Glickman and the panel.
<p>
   Williams, the only black farmer in a predominately white county,
said the scare tactic was made by white farmers jealous of his
productive and profitable cotton field.
<p>
   ``This is a sad day to know that black people still go through
this,'' he said. ``I feel failure in the United States
government.''
<p>
   That statement resonated with the other farmers in a session
characterized by anger, frustration, and outright disdain. Speakers
accused the USDA of conspiring to strip black farmers of their land
and urged them to investigate local USDA units.
<p>
   ``Thousands of blacks have lost farms through ignorance, racism
and prejudice at the hands of the Department of Agriculture,'' said
John Boyd, president of the National Black farmers Association.
<p>
   As Glickman sat looking stern and twiddling a pen at his
fingertips, the session  &MD;  one of 12 heard nationwide  &MD;  was laced
with stories of unjust farm foreclosures, lack of services and loan
programs for minority farmers.
<p>
   (EDs: Optional trim line. Story can end here.)
<p>
   Wednesday's meeting began with control and moderation by
Glickman and his colleagues. However, James Myart(CQ), general
counsel for the National Black Farmers Association took the podium
and took control of the session peppered with criticisms,
finger-pointing and demands.
<p>
   ``I have been eating, drinking, sleeping and crying all of these
farmers concerns,'' he told Glickman. ``I want you to call the
president and meet with him in the Rose Garden and find a
solution.''
<p>
   Case after case was addressed before the panel. One elderly man
pleaded with Glickman and asked for his land back so that he could
be buried on it. Another man said that he could barely survive.
Land that was in his family for 100 years was taken away. He urged
the board to investigate.
<p>
   Agriculture officials said a report on the state of civil rights
enforcement in the USDA will be prepared by mid-February. The
comments from the session will be used in conjunction with the
report.
<p>
   Since the onset of the complaints the USDA has begun interim
measures to deal with the problems. It has halted all pending
foreclosure sales until further review by the department, and an
audit of the civil rights issue will be done by the action team.
They have also asked the inspector general to investigate
complaints of discrimination in farm loans.
<p>
   But these initiatives, Glickman said, are just the tip of the
iceberg. He pledged to end discrimination in both USDA employment
and program participation.
<p>
   ``Under my watch I want this to be the people's department
again,'' he said. ``We will make fundamental and structural
changes.''
<p>
   But the scene was all too familiar for Shirley Sherrod, director
of Southern Cooperatives in Georgia.
<p>
   Sherrod didn't testify but says her father, a farmer, was
murdered by a white farmer in 1965. They didn't prosecute the man
and from that point, she said she made a commitment to work for
change.
<p>
   ``It seems that during the 70s the nation was forced to pretend
discrimination didn't exist. Here we are in the 90s and we're still
trying to do some of what we were trying to do in the 60s,'' she
said.
<p>
   ``In some ways I feel like things haven't changed.''
<p>
    &UR; For clients of The New York Times News Service &LR; 
</TEXT>
