<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9686 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0992 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NATIONAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NATIONAL NEWS IN BRIEF &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SUPERMARKET SUING ABC AWARDED $5.5 MILLION
<p>
   (NYT)  &MD;  A federal jury in Greensboro, N.C., on Wednesday awarded
a national supermarket chain over $5.5 million in punitive damages
from ABC and two of its employees in a closely watched media case
that focused on the propriety of widely used television news
techniques like hidden cameras and undercover reporters.
<p>
   Last month, the same panel ordered ABC to pay $1,400 in actual
damages to Food Lion Inc., the chain, after finding that network
producers had trespassed and committed fraud when researching a
``PrimeTime Live'' segment in 1992 that accused the company of
selling spoiled meat.
<p>
   While Food Lion officials disputed the accuracy of the ABC
report, they did not sue the network for libel. Rather, they
accused ABC of deception by using techniques like having producers
submit fake resumes to get jobs in the meat department of company
stores, and then using hidden cameras to film there.
<p>
   Roone Arledge, the president of ABC News, defended the methods
used by the network to report the segment and said ABC would appeal
the verdict.
<p>
   COHEN CONFIRMED AS DEFENSE SECRETARY
<p>
   WASHINGTON (NYT)  &MD;  The Senate confirmed William Cohen as defense
secretary by a 99-0 vote Wednesday after the former Republican
senator predicted at a good-natured confirmation hearing that he
would sometimes differ with President Clinton on national security
policy.
<p>
   Cohen, the only Republican to serve in the new Cabinet, clung to
positions during the hearing that sometimes differed with
Clinton's. Still, he promised that he would work behind the scenes
and be a good team player. Attempting to balance expressions of
loyalty and independence, Cohen said he would not tinker with the
administration's most basic military doctrine of preparing to fight
for two major regional conflicts simultaneously but he would urge
spending more for procurement of advanced weapons.
<p>
   ATLANTA BOMBS CONTAINED DYNAMITE
<p>
   WASHINGTON (NYT)  &MD;  The federal authorities investigating the
bombing at an abortion clinic near Atlanta last week have concluded
that the two bombs used were each built with 10 to 20 sticks of
dynamite, a powerful high explosive that experts say is unusual in
homemade terrorist devices.
<p>
   In the Jan. 16 attack at the clinic, officials said they had
determined that the design of the second bomb, which detonated
about an hour after law-enforcement officers and news reporters
were drawn to the first blast, differed from the first bomb.
<p>
   The second device, which was packed in a metal, military-style
container that also held three-inch concrete nails, seemed intended
to spew metal fragments over a wide area.
<p>
   So far, no one has claimed responsibility for the bombings and,
although the abortion clinic was a presumed target, investigators
are pursuing other theories, including the possibility that from
the start the attack was aimed at law-enforcement personnel.
<p>
   PIZZERIA UNO DROPS LOW-FAT CLAIM
<p>
   (NYT)  &MD;  One of the nation's leading restaurant chains, Pizzeria
Uno, has conceded that its previous advertisements for thin-crust
pizzas were false and misleading, and has promised the Federal
Trade Commission not to make such claims again.
<p>
   Craig Miller, the president and chief executive officer of Uno
Restaurant Corp., said in a telephone interview that the company
had not thoroughly examined the federal definition of low fat,
which is 3 grams of fat or less per serving.
<p>
   ``This is not something we intentionally did and the FTC
agreed,'' Miller said. ``Low-fat pizza is a pretty strong
statement, and our Thinzettas are not low fat. Only a few of them
qualify.''
<p>
   The consent agreement with the FTC, which the company signed in
October, is not an admission of guilt. The company simply promises
to stop whatever it has been accused of doing.
<p>
   JUDGE RULES PORNOGRAPHY CAN BE SOLD ON MILITARY BASES
<p>
   NEW YORK (NYT)  &MD;  A federal judge in Manhattan ruled Wednesday
that the Department of Defense cannot enforce a law banning the
sale of pornographic movies and videos on military bases because it
violates constitutional protections for free speech.
<p>
   The law, the Military Honor and Decency Act of 1996, forbid
stores and post exchanges on military bases from selling
pornography. Proposed in Congress as a measure to promote ``honor,
commitment and courage'' among soldiers and sailors, the law was
scheduled to take effect at the beginning of this year.
<p>
   But ruling on a challenge filed by the parent company of
Penthouse Magazine, U.S. District Judge Shira Scheindlin said that
the government cannot ban the sale of the material merely because
officials find it offensive.
<p>
   MAGNIFIED PARTICLES TRACKED FROM SUN TO EARTH
<p>
   GREENBELT, Md. (NYT)  &MD;  The sun released a giant cloud of
magnetized particles that researchers were able to monitor in
detail for the first time as it approached and swept past the Earth
this month, scientists said Wednesday.
<p>
   An international group of space scientists said the sun ejected
a pocket of mass from its corona on Jan. 6 that developed into a
giant, tube-shaped magnetic bubble that hit the Earth almost four
days later. The expanding cloud of energized particles triggered a
large storm in the magnetic field, or magnetosphere, surrounding
the planet. The storm brightened the Northern Lights and possibly
knocked out a key communications satellite.
<p>
   Speaking at a briefing here at NASA's Goddard Space Flight
Center, scientists said the mass eruption from the sun was not so
unusual in itself. The unique thing, they said, was that it was
spotted shortly after it occurred on the sun's surface and tracked
by space satellites and Earth stations as it traveled the 93
million miles to the Earth and then passed the planet.
</TEXT>
