<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-SUPER-BOWL-KAN </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0743 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SPRINT-SUPER-BOWL-KAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SPRINT BUILDS A PHONE SYSTEM FOR THE SUPER BOWL -- IN A BIG HURRY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID HAYES &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Kansas City Star &LR;  &QC; 
   (Undated) Think about what it would take to build a telephone
system for a city about the size of Roeland Park, Kan., or
Harrisonville, Mo.  &MD;  from scratch.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   After that, make sure your phone system will work in a place
where someone is using just about every phone just about all the
time. So populate that city with thousands of 16-year-olds.
<p>
   To top it off, do it all in three weeks.
<p>
   That's about the equivalent of what Sprint Corp. has done in New
Orleans, where the company is a sponsor and official long-distance
company for the National Football League and Super Bowl XXXI.
<p>
   Dozens of Sprint employees have been in New Orleans since Jan.
3, where they've been laying cable  &MD;  about 21 miles of telephone
wire  &MD;  and setting up more than 3,000 telephone lines to prepare
for the Green Bay-New England game.
<p>
   ``How we create a telecommunications infrastructure in New
Orleans is similar to how we would create a network for a small
town,'' said Steve Reed, Sprint's national manager of NFL business
development.
<p>
   Sprint and the NFL cut a multimillion-dollar, three-year deal in
April, making the long-distance company an official NFL sponsor and
the league's telecommunications services provider. It also made
Sprint responsible for telephone service to the Super Bowl.
<p>
   That means Sprint is responsible for everything from plain old
telephone service for AFC and NFC officials in New Orleans to
managing the Internet traffic at the official Super Bowl site
(http: &HT;    And, in between, Sprint employees have been setting up a glitzy
``Sprint Stadium'' inside the NFL Experience, an indoor theme park
at the New Orleans convention center for visitors who traveled to
Louisiana for the world's biggest one-day sporting event.
<p>
   There, visitors will walk across an artificial turf playing
field and be greeted by a Jumbotron screen. They'll have a chance
to talk one-on-one  &MD;  during a big-screen teleconference  &MD;  with
players and coaches. They'll be able to surf the Internet and make
phone calls.
<p>
   Although Sprint officials hope that Sprint Stadium wows visitors
to New Orleans, they're hoping that the company's larger presence
in the city will go mostly unnoticed.
<p>
   If it does, that means the thousands of telephone lines worked
OK; the 200 fax machines churned out letters, documents and
statistics sheets as required; and that computers in the NFL's
``virtual headquarters'' in three floors of the Hyatt hotel
downtown were connected seamlessly to the league's offices in New
York and to all 30 football clubs.
<p>
   ``Our purpose is to enable all of these parties to stay in
continuous contact with each other, as well as with the rest of the
world,'' Reed said.
<p>
   It's no small task, and there's a lot riding on the outcome.
<p>
   Sprint officials only have to look back a few months, when
industry-leading AT&AMP;T ran into a series of problems at the Summer
Olympics in Atlanta. What was supposed to be a publicity boon for
AT&AMP;T turned into a public relations mishap when some systems  &MD; 
mostly those involving results sent to the media  &MD;  failed or
provided wrong information.
<p>
   Sprint hopes to avoid such problems by building redundancy into
the telephone system that links six headquarters locations in New
Orleans with the rest of the world. The company built temporary
overhead ``bridges'' to carry phone lines across streets. ``Hot
lines'' have been built to link the NFL Control Center at the
Superdome directly to the playing field.
<p>
   Sprint is bringing translators into the press box to handle
technology problems posed by foreign journalists.
<p>
   Getting that small-city phone network up and running  &MD;  and doing
so in less than three weeks  &MD;  proved to be one of Sprint's greatest
challenges, according to company officials. But the company is
hoping the high-visibility it gets on game day will be worth the
effort.
<p>
   ``Providing the latest technology for Super Bowl XXXI is a
tremendous opportunity for Sprint,'' said Mike Goff, director of
corporate sponsorships.
<p>
   ``Not only does it allow us to play an integral role in making
this event successful for the NFL, but it also allows us to
demonstrate our capabilities as a telecommunications provider to
the world.''
</TEXT>
