<SLUG> BC-YELLOWPAGES-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0462 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-YELLOW PAGES-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Attn.: Minn., Ariz, Fla.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JUDGE FINES PUBLISHER OF LOOK-ALIKE YELLOW PAGES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By PATRICIA WEN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   BOSTON  &MD;  A publisher that posed as the maker of the traditional
Yellow Pages telephone directory, luring many businesses into
paying for what they thought was a listing renewal, has been
ordered to pay a $1 million penalty to the state.
<p>
   AmCan Enterprises, a now-defunct operation based in Miami, and
its owner, Charles Smith, sent mailings that looked like invoices,
had the Yellow Pages and walking-fingers designs and used language
about ``renewal'' fees, said Ernest Sarason, an assistant attorney
general.
<p>
   ``It sends a strong message to scam artists: Stay out of
Massachusetts or prepare to pay a very hefty penalty,'' said
Attorney General Scott Harshbarger.
<p>
   Sarason said the $1 million penalty doubles what the state
sought in its hearings before Suffolk Superior Court Judge Patrick
King. AmCan's attorney, Bruce G. McNeill of Boston, said his client
will appeal.
<p>
   In 1994 alone, 1,300 businesses in Massachusetts signed on for
the directories, which were labeled New England Yellow Pages,
Yellow Pages National Edition and N.E. U.S. Directories. A total of
2.3 million solicitations were sent to Massachusetts businesses
from 1990 to 1994.
<p>
   Nynex business subscribers do not pay extra for one listing in
the Yellow Pages and the white pages. Extra charges only apply if
they seek a larger advertisement in the directories, said Phil
Santoro, a Nynex spokesman.
<p>
   Nine Bay State business owners who complained to the attorney
general's office are now entitled to restitution from the company
for the fees paid, according to the Jan. 10 decision by King.
<p>
   While thousands more also paid AmCan, they do not benefit from
the restitution because they did not initiate contact with the
state to become part of the lawsuit.
<p>
   Aside from the $1 million in penalties, the judge also ordered
AmCan to pay about $26,000 in attorney's fees. The company has also
been sued by authorities in Minnesota, Arizona and Florida for
deceptive advertising, state officials said.
<p>
   McNeill said the company was operating a legitimate business
when it ceased operation a few years ago, unable to sustain the
costs of all the litigation. He said the penalty is excessive, and
the ruling will be appealed on numerous legal grounds.
<p>
   Sarason said the attorney general's office received 75
complaints from different businesses about AmCan, most of whom
caught on before paying fees, prompting the filing of the lawsuit
in 1993. ``It's classic deception,'' said Sarason. ``Everything
they say can be true, but the real effect is to fool you.''
</TEXT>
