<SLUG> BC-KOREA-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0486 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-KOREA-LABOR-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SOUTH KOREAN PRESIDENT FAILS TO PLACATE FOES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (kd) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SEOUL, South Korea  &MD;  Opposition parties said Wednesday that they
remained dissatisfied with President Kim Young-sam's unexpected
offer to allow revision of the contested labor laws, suggesting
that the national crisis over the legislation may continue for some
time.
<p>
   Kim wants to hold a special session of the National Assembly
next month to resolve the issue, apparently by allowing changes
that would soften the labor code. But opposition parties and labor
unions are sticking to their original demand that the laws be
repealed entirely before the next step  &MD;  hammering out a revision  &MD; 
can take place.
<p>
   Thus the gap between the two sides has been greatly narrowed,
but it still may be too much to bridge for the time being.
<p>
   The unions showed that they were unimpressed by going on strike
Wednesday, pursuing a once-a-week national walkout to protest the
labor laws. The unions had been striking daily until a few days
ago, and they say they will resume the general strike next month if
the dispute is not resolved until then.
<p>
   The strike was not hugely disruptive Wednesday, except in the
auto industry, and, as has been the case in the past, the
government said only a small number took part while unions
announced that 140,000 people participated  &MD;  still a modest number
in a country with 12 million workers.
<p>
   The crisis began last month when the ruling party, annoyed that
opposition lawmakers were physically preventing the passage of
legislation, secretly met in a dawn session of the National
Assembly. In seven minutes, without opposition members present,
they passed landmark bills to revise South Korea's labor code and
to give broad new powers to a domestic spy agency that in the past
has been used for political repression.
<p>
   Officials in the ruling party say that the new labor laws  &MD; 
which make it easier for companies to lay off workers and adopt
more flexible patterns of employment  &MD;  are necessary to make the
country competitive in international markets. The security law is
essential, they say, because of the threat of subversion from North
Korea.
<p>
   After Kim agreed to allow revisions of the labor laws, the main
opposition leader, Kim Dae-jung, initially made conciliatory
comments suggesting that there had been ``some advance.'' But after
discussions among themselves, the opposition groups then seemed to
harden their position and reasserted their demand for complete
repeal.
<p>
   ``Any debate in Parliament must be made on the condition that
the law is made null and void,'' Park Sun-sook, of the main
opposition party, the National Congress for New Politics, was
quoted by Reuters as saying Wednesday. For his part, Kim is
insisting that the laws were legally passed and cannot be repealed
in their entirety.
</TEXT>
