<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MIDWEST-COMMODITIES-KAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHEAT FUTURES PRICES CLOSE MIXED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By VICTORIA SIZEMORE LONG &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Kansas City Star &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo.  &MD;  Kansas City and Chicago wheat futures prices
closed mixed Wednesday, partly on weather factors. Chicago corn
futures were little-changed; soybean futures declined.
<p>
   Kansas City Value Line stock-index futures were mixed; Western
Natural Gas futures finished lower across the board as traders
balanced their accounts ahead of the gas storage report late
Wednesday. About 1,200 contracts traded.
<p>
   In wheat, new-crop contracts in Kansas City and Chicago
generally held firm because of recent volatile temperatures. Some
analysts say that current mild conditions have allowed protective
snow cover to melt and are reducing the hardiness of the winter
crop.
<p>
   Corn futures traded steady in nearby contract months amid rumors
of potential business from Asian countries as well as Egypt and
Iraq.
<p>
   Soybean futures finished moderately lower, with pressure coming
primarily from the expiration of the January contracts. Pressure
also came from improved growing conditions in South America, a
major bean competitor of the United States.
<p>
   In the Kansas City Value Line, the stock-index cash settled at a
new high of 706.18, while the March futures contract settled down
60 basis points.
<p>
   The broad market managed to trade firm all day, despite a lower
trend for the Dow industrial average, said Kansas City trader Paul
Dow.
<p>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was dragged down by IBM, whose
earnings were not as robust as other computer industry stocks.
</TEXT>
