<STORYID cat=l pri=r sel=kan-z> A9693 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-SILVA-KAN </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0498 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FOOD-COLUMN-SILVA-KAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JUST A TASTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 The Kansas City Star &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo.  &MD;  If you have a toddler, you're probably
nervously eyeballing that tippy cup. Hmmm, just how many ounces of
juice does this thing hold?
<p>
   ``You never measure. You just pour it in,'' says Kansas City
resident Carrie Larson, the mom of Teddy, 2, and Tommy, 1.
<p>
   But the January issue of Pediatrics, a journal of the American
Pediatric Association, says preschoolers who drink more than 12
ounces of juice a day tend to be shorter and fatter than their
peers.
<p>
   For children a year old and up, 4 ounces of juice a day is
``reasonable,'' according to Lanette Meyer, a clinical dietitian at
Children's Mercy Hospital here. ``That's a surprise to parents
because everyone thinks juice is so nutritious,'' she says.
<p>
   It turns out that the problem with fruit juice is that it tends
to be high in calories. Children who drink too much juice fill
small tummies with juice instead of more nutritious foods.
<p>
   Meyer says infants should not be introduced to juice before the
age of 6 months or they risk developing a ``juice dependency that
is not beneficial.'' And never give your child juice in a bottle;
use a cup instead.
<p>
   Preschoolers who eat the recommended two to three servings of
fresh, canned or dried fruit each day don't actually need any fruit
juice and reap the added benefits of fiber that is not found in
juice. (A serving is one-quarter to one-half cup of fruit.)
<p>
   When Meyer works with overweight children, she often finds that
they drink juice or soft drinks instead of water. ``When you get
into the habit of drinking juice as a thirst quencher, then you get
into large amounts and then you get too many calories,'' she says.
<p>
   So how can parents wean a juice monster?
<p>
   Toddlers like control almost as much as they like juice, so
Larson lets Teddy keep a water bottle by his bedside. Using the
nifty, pop-up spout, he can help himself to a drink throughout the
day. He has never developed a juice habit.
<p>
   Preschoolers also thrive on routine. About the time Lynn Jones
of Leawood, Kan., saw her 2-year-old daughter, Abby, falling into
the juice trap, she decided to impose limits. She offers Abby a
7-ounce cup of half water//half juice in the morning; she gets a
second cup after her nap. ``She fought it at first,'' says Jones,
``but eventually she got used to it.''
<p>
   The popular child-rearing guide What To Expect: The Toddler
Years, by Arlene Eisenberg, Heidi E. Murkoff and Sandee Hathaway,
suggests choosing orange, papaya, pineapple (all rich in vitamin
C), apricot nectar (rich in vitamin A), mango juice or vegetable
juice (rich in both) over apple juice. The guide also advises
choosing 100 percent fruit juice instead of 10 percent fruit-juice
drinks.
<p>
   But Meyer says that while one fruit juice may have more vitamins
than another, they all have comparable calories.
</TEXT>
