<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ROYALYACHT-NY </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0533 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BRITAIN-ROYALYACHT-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IN BRITANNIA'S WAKE, NEW ROYAL YACHT IN 2002 &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By WARREN HOGE &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   LONDON  &MD;  When the royal yacht Britannia sailed from Plymouth on
Monday on a final Far East tour before its decommissioning in
August, Britons thought they would never see her costly like again.
<p>
   But, unexpectedly, the government said Wednesday that a new $100
million ship will be built to replace it and will enter service in
2002 in time for the queen's golden jubilee. The Britannia cost
2,098,000 pounds to build in 1953, equivalent to $52.5 million
today.
<p>
   Wednesday's announcement appeared to put an end to a lengthy
debate in which detractors argued that the vessel was an
anachronism. Lately the queen has used it only once a year, for a
ritual cruise around the Western Isles off Scotland; for more
extended travel, she goes by air.
<p>
   But in her four decades of service the 5,769-ton, 412-foot
Britannia has logged more than a million miles, mostly as a
floating platform for business diplomacy. The government credits
Britannia with having provided British businessmen with an alluring
venue for meeting their counterparts abroad and thereby having
secured more than $3 billion worth of trade for Britain in the last
decade.
<p>
   Aside from its cost, no details of the new royal vessel have
been decided. But officials said the budgeted amount would build a
ship in the same league as the Britannia.
<p>
   The expectation had been that if there were to be any new royal
vessel, it would have to be paid for by private contributions. But
Michael Portillo, the defense minister, said Wednesday that the
government believed the yacht  &MD;  a symbol of ``our crown, our
kingdom and our nation's pride''  &MD;  should be funded by the nation
rather than by sponsorship.
<p>
   The Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, also
reported that the queen had been concerned that a yacht not paid
for by the government would end up with commercial logos on its
funnels ``out of keeping with the ambience of the royal yacht.''
<p>
   Members of both parties in the House of Commons robustly cheered
the announcement Wednesday. Unions welcomed it as ``wonderful
news'' for the nation's slowly recovering shipbuilding industry.
The Britannia was constructed at Clydebank, near Glasgow, in the
same yard that produced the liners Queen Elizabeth I, Queen Mary
and QE2. Michael Forsyth, the head of the Scottish office in Prime
Minister John Major's cabinet, said Wednesday, ``Our fathers built
the old Britannia; this is the chance to show the world that their
skills live on today.''
<p>
   The Britannia's present seven-month tour of the Mediterranean,
Arabian Gulf, Indian Ocean and Far East will take it to Hong Kong,
where it will play a principal ceremonial role in the handover of
the colony to China at the end of June.
<p>
   After her decommissioning, she will not put to sea again, and,
Portillo said Wednesday, she will not be sold. He invited proposals
for a ``suitably prestigious use,'' one that would keep her ``in
excellent condition.'' He added, ``If that cannot be assured it
would be better to see her scrapped than to see her deteriorate.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1922EST
</TRAILER>
