<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=kan-z> A9699 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0595 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BUSINESS GROUP'S AGENDA COULD BE TOO AMBITIOUS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JERRY HEASTER &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Kansas City Star &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Question: What's the difference between the National Federation
of Independent Business and the 105th Congress?
<p>
   Answer: The business group's legislative agenda is substantially
more ambitious.
<p>
   When the country's most aggressive small-business lobbying group
unveiled its goals in six areas last week, the list obviously
focused on concerns shared by business of all sizes. What made
fulfillment of these goals more critical to small businesses,
however, is what can be best described as the coping factor.
<p>
   Whereas troublesome government policies are merely that for big,
resource-rich corporations, they go far beyond troublesome for
small business. The smaller the business, the more troublesome
ill-advised tax and regulatory policies become. The federation's
wish list includes the following:
<p>
   -- Regulation: The goal here is to push Congress to ensure that
regulatory relief laws passed in 1996 are enforced. Other
initiatives include a push for rigorous regulatory cost-benefit
analysis, review of administrative mandates that unduly burden
small business, and liberalization of regulatory compliance
policies.
<p>
   -- Taxes: The federation will seek payroll and capital-gains tax
relief, as well as estate tax reform aimed at ensuring that small
businesses won't have to be sold or liquidated to meet tax
obligations when the owner dies.
<p>
   -- Health care: It will seek expanded opportunities for
participation in health-care coverage cooperatives and allowing the
self-employed full tax deductibility for insurance premiums.
<p>
   -- Legal reforms: Limits on punitive damage awards will be
sought to ameliorate litigation exposure.
<p>
   -- Government mandates: The group will fight attempts to mandate
expanded health-insurance benefits or Family and Medical Leave
provisions.
<p>
   -- Deficit reduction: This includes support for both a
constitutional balanced budget amendment as well as achievement of
a balanced budget without raising taxes.
<p>
   Federation President Jack Faris acknowledged last term's
significant victories but said this session's agenda is critical to
sustaining small business's role as the economy's most dynamic
source of new jobs.
<p>
   His reasoning is sound, of course, but his characterization of
the 105th as a ``small-business friendly'' Congress may miss the
point and thereby explain why the federation agenda will prove too
ambitious.
<p>
   Although the Republicans retained their majority control of both
the House and Senate, there is no sign yet that they plan to use
their power aggressively. The Democrats, conversely, have been
kicking up their heels as if they're in charge.
<p>
   If the GOP does remain timid and the Democrats remain on the
offensive, it will be bad news indeed for small business. Despite
widespread perceptions to the contrary, the Democrats' long reign
transformed them into the party of big business because they were
uninterrupted source of legislative power for so many years. The
GOP's minority status tended to make it the party of small business
almost by default. This anomaly became evident after the GOP took
power and small business priorities got more respect on Capitol
Hill.
<p>
   The Republican majority is no doubt in tune with the small
business agenda as articulated by the National Federation of
Independent Business. The question is whether it can muster the
resolve to do what it was re-elected to do.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1923EST
</TRAILER>
