<SLUG> BC-BEAR-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0643 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BEAR-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BEAR STEARNS CITES EARNINGS OF $176.5 MILLION, UP 68 PERCENT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By PETER TRUELL &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Bear Stearns Cos. on Wednesday became the latest
investment bank to surpass analysts' forecasts.
<p>
   Bolstered by the bull market, Bear Stearns earned $176.5
million, or $1.27 a share, for its fiscal second quarter ended Dec.
31, 1996, an increase of 68 percent from the comparable period a
year earlier. IBES Inc., a research firm, using a consensus of six
analysts' estimates, had forecast per-share earnings of 89 cents.
<p>
   Bear Stearns reported a return on equity of more than 33 percent
for the quarter, significantly above several of its competitors.
Revenues net of interest expense rose 37 percent, to $940.1
million.
<p>
   ``If this isn't good, I don't know what is,'' James E. Cayne,
the company's president and chief executive, said in an interview
at his office Wednesday.
<p>
   Bear Stearns attributed its record earnings to a number of
factors, including a 12.5 percent rise in quarterly commission
revenue to $183.6 million; transactions for its own account that
brought revenues of $429.2 million, a 65 percent increase over the
year-earlier quarter, and investment banking revenues that rose 22
percent, to $183.1 million.
<p>
   The company also held compensation to 48.6 percent of revenues
in the quarter, compared with just over 50 percent a year earlier.
<p>
   On Wall Street, where investment bankers and trader make huge
amounts of money, compensation typically equals about 50 percent of
revenues. Unlike some of its competitors, Bear Stearns has not
suffered many defections to large foreign banks and others trying
to break into Wall Street, executives at the company said
Wednesday.
<p>
   Bear Stearns stock rose $1.875 a share Wednesday to $31.75, on a
mixed day for brokerage firms.
<p>
   ``I think it was an outstanding quarter; the company was firing
on all cylinders,'' said Katrina Blecher, an analyst with Gruntal &AMP;
Company. ``The clear winners were the firm's principal
transactions, which benefited from strength in the fixed-income
market, and their investment banking, and they were still able to
keep their compensation well under control.''
<p>
   December is traditionally a quiet month for business on Wall
Street that pulls down the quarterly revenues of securities firms.
But that was not true in 1996, when securities trading remained
buoyant during the last month of the year.
<p>
   Another securities firm, Dean Witter, Discover &AMP; Co., also
surpassed analysts' earnings forecasts Wednesday.
<p>
   The company reported fourth-quarter earnings of $227.8 million,
an increase of 28 percent from the 1995 period. Per-share earnings
at the brokerage firm and financial services company advanced 33
percent, to 68 cents a share, after being restating for a 2-for-1
stock split. A poll of seven analysts' estimates published by Zacks
Investment Research had predicted 65 cents a share.
<p>
   Dean Witter attributed its good fourth quarter in its securities
business to increased asset management and administration fees,
higher commission revenues from the sale of equity and insurance
products, increased underwriting business and an increase of 180
account executives. In its credit business, merchant and cardmember
fees for the quarter rose 48 percent, to $563.8 million, from the
last three months of 1995.
<p>
   In December 1996, Dean Witter also bought for an undisclosed sum
Lombard Securities Inc., a company that provides on-line brokerage
services.
<p>
   Analysts generally liked Dean Witter's results.
<p>
   ``They were three cents above our estimate for earnings per
share, there were very strong revenues in credit services,'' said
Mark C. Alpert, an analyst with the New York office of Alex. Brown
&AMP; Co. ``Revenues were very strong in the card business.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1923EST
</TRAILER>
