   (Lede story)
<p>
   AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS  &MD;  AT&AMP;T is finally holding on to its customers.
Now, if it can just get more of them to pay their phone bills. AT&AMP;T
said Wednesday that its fourth-quarter income from continuing
operations rose 14.2 percent, to $1.24 billion, helped by a new
flat rate-calling plan that has stanched the flow of customers to
other long-distance carriers. But earnings still fell short of Wall
Street analysts' expectations because of higher costs from unpaid
bills. By Mark Landler.
