<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GROWTH-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0154 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MEXICO-GROWTH-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MEXICO'S ORTIZ ESTIMATES ECONOMY GREW 4.6% OR 4.7% IN 1996 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Eduardo Garcia &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Mexico City, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Mexico's Finance Minister
Guillermo Ortiz estimated the country's economy grew between 4.6
percent or 4.7 percent last year, well above earlier estimates.
<p>
   The government's original growth forecast was for 3 percent,
while analysts predicted growth of 4.3 percent.
<p>
   Ortiz, who made his remarks yesterday in the central city of
Queretaro, said the government will end up with a big fiscal
surplus in 1996 because of higher-than-expected international crude
oil prices.
<p>
   The government plans to use some of the surplus to continue
helping the country's financial system, Mexico's Finance Minister
said.
<p>
   Ortiz also estimated January's inflation rate at about 2 percent
or slightly more.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1932EST
</TRAILER>
