<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tia-z> A9711 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-ASSIGNMENTS- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0292 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BKW-WNBA-ASSIGNMENTS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SIXTEEN PLAYERS ASSIGNED TO TEAMS FOR INAUGURAL WNBA SEASON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Dan Bollerman &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Women's NBA assigned 16
players to its eight teams for its inaugural season, including
Sheryl Swoopes, Rebecca Lobo and Lisa Leslie.
<p>
   The 16, who are the only players who are under contract with the
new league, have combined to win 16 Olympic gold medals, nine NCAA
championships and 16 all-America awards.
<p>
   ``The selection process for the first 16 players was based on
competitive factors, geographic associations and on input from each
of the WNBA teams,'' said WNBA President Val Ackerman.
<p>
   Among those who will be playing in cities near where they played
college ball are Swoopes, a forward from Texas Tech, in Houston;
Lobo, a center-forward from the University of Connecticut, in New
York; and Leslie, a center from USC, in Los Angeles.
<p>
   Also assigned to Los Angeles was guard Penny Toler.
<p>
   Guard Cynthia Cooper will play in Houston. Guard Teresa
Weatherspoon will play for New York, while center Janice Lawrence
Braxton and guard Michelle Edwards have been assigned to Cleveland.
<p>
   Center Vicky Bullett and guard Andrea Stinson will play in
Charlotte, North Carolina, while guard Michele Timms and center
Jennifer Gillom were assigned to Phoenix.
<p>
   Guard Ruthie Bolton-Holifield and forward Bridgette Gordon will
play for Sacramento, California, while center-forward Elena
Baranova and guard Lady Hardmon were assigned to Utah.
<p>
   The league hopes to announce its next 16 signings and team
assignments by late February, while a player draft will be held
April 28. The season starts June 21.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1935EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0635 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=k pri=u sel=taf-z> A9712 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0729 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMMENTARY: PROMISES, PROMISES &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By WILLIAM SAFIRE &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   LONDON  &MD;  When Sen. Rufus Choate in 1856 coined a phrase by
criticizing ``the glittering and sounding generalities'' of the
Declaration of Independence, Ralph Waldo Emerson snapped back with:
``Glittering generalities? They are blazing ubiquities!''
<p>
   That was my chauvinist reaction when The Daily Telegraph,
Britain's liveliest quality newspaper, dismissed President
Clinton's second Inaugural Address as ``banal.''
<p>
   Banal it was not. (That word better describes the plodding poem
read at the ceremony.) Although Clinton's reach for historical
resonance hardly blazed with all-pervasive wisdom, his speech was a
respectable effort, forcefully delivered.
<p>
   In assessing his second inaugural, much depended on how you
participated in the occasion.
<p>
   If you watched as a conservative partisan, you could take
umbrage at his pose of being above the battle. Who is this tricky
triangulator  &MD;  demagogue of Mediscare and rental agent of the
Lincoln bedroom  &MD;  to denounce as ``petty bickering and extreme
partisanship'' congressional disagreement with his outrageous
campaign misrepresentations?
<p>
   If you nitpicked as a writer, you winced at his sentence
fragments, at the awkwardness of shaping a hope into a chapter, and
at the risk of building a speech on the theme of a new ``promised
land''  &MD;  inviting distrust of political promises or derision at
presuming to be a new Moses.
<p>
   But if you let the ceremony wash over you as an American  &MD;  the
monumental setting, the singing of patriotic hymns, the flags, the
oath, the traditional speech  &MD;  you gained an appreciation of what
your president was trying to do.
<p>
   He paid more than the usual obeisance to the black community.
His reminder about the scourge of slavery, his evocation of Martin
Luther King Jr. ``at the other end of this Mall'' and his ``we
shall overcome'' are both payback for monolithic political support
and a genuine expression of one of his few bedrock principles. The
time for affirmative action is out of joint, but for Clinton to
press his strength on race relations is good for the country.
<p>
   He bestraddled the center like a would-be Colossus with ``The
pre-eminent mission of our new government is to give all Americans
an opportunity  &MD;  not a guarantee. ...'' That sentiment was one Newt
Gingrich of the Opportunity Society had to applaud, while
entitlement liberals had to cringe.
<p>
   At the same time, Clinton replied to Ronald Reagan's inaugural
``government is not the solution to our problem'' with an oblique
``government is not the problem and not the solution.''
<p>
   Few can argue with Clinton's welcome call for an assumption of
personal responsibility, unless his simultaneous embrace of ``a new
spirit of community'' turns out to be a euphemism for the continued
assumption of that responsibility by government.
<p>
   His vision of ``a land of new promise''  &MD;  the ``I see an America
where'' construction beloved of American orators  &MD;  is not to be
cynically dismissed. It's a fine farrago of hopes that need to be
expressed by our elected leader as he repeats the informal ``so
help me God'' that George Washington added to the oath set down in
our Constitution.
<p>
   Viewed from across an ocean, the president acting as president
comes across more vividly than when viewed inside our borders or
D.C.'s Beltway. The office seems a bigger part of the man.
<p>
   That's a thought to keep in mind as the second Clinton term
reveals the tawdry secrets of the first. His popularity is at its
peak in the post-election rush of patriotism (I believe the CBS-New
York Times poll, though it was egregiously wrong about the
election), and this may be a good time to lock in profits on
Clinton stock.
<p>
   The investigations may bear bitter fruit; the economy may not
prop up his ratings forever; decision-making will surely move to
the Hill and then to his putative successor. Just as, in Clinton's
stirring inaugural words, our actions at this moment in our
nation's history will ``define our course and our character,'' so
will his reaction to the process of American justice define his
own.
<p>
   I like to think Bill Clinton will preserve, protect and defend
that process, at whatever personal cost, remembering all that he
represented on Inauguration Day.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1936EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0636 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tdt-z> A9713 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PRESS-FOODLION-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1366 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PRESS-FOOD LION-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FALSE TV REPORT BRINGS $5.5M DAMAGES TO ABC &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By PETER S. CANELLOS &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   GREENSBORO, N.C.  &MD;  When two ABC News producers hid cameras in
their deli smocks and went to work at Food Lion supermarkets, they
considered themselves the eyes of the public seeking the inside
story of how the stores prepared meat for sale.
<p>
   They secretly taped employees doctoring allegedly spoiled meat
and, working with ``PrimeTime Live'' anchor Diane Sawyer, compiled
a report that shocked viewers, caused Food Lion's stock to plummet
by $1.7 billion and earned their network some prestigious
journalism awards.
<p>
   But a North Carolina jury Wednesday slapped ABC and its parent
company with more than $5.5 million in punitive damages for having
producers Lynne Dale and Susan Barnett lie on their job
applications to Food Lion.
<p>
   The jury, which labored through five days of deliberations,
finally cast aside ABC's argument that the network was acting in
the public interest, and implicitly endorsed Food Lion's contention
that ``PrimeTime Live'' was an entertainment show, not news,
``juicing the ratings with illegally obtained video,'' according to
Food Lion attorney Tim Barber.
<p>
   The $5.5 million punitive-damage award amounts to less than a
day's earnings for ABC-Capital Cities. But journalism specialists
said the award  &MD;  when combined with the jury's initial ruling that
ABC's reporting methods constituted fraud  &MD;  represents a sharp
rebuke to the news profession.
<p>
   ``I have no doubt news organizations will do fewer undercover
stories and fewer investigations,'' said Sandy Baron, executive
director of the Libel Defense Resource Center. ``In the long run,
the public could be the loser.''
<p>
   Until this case, journalistic pieces were judged by their
accuracy. Food Lion, however, sued ABC on the narrow grounds that
the producers committed fraud by lying to get jobs at Food Lion.
Then, in seeking damages, the supermarket's lawyers inveighed
against what they described as journalism's culture of intrusion,
demanding that ABC be punished for violating Food Lion's privacy.
<p>
   ``They've appointed themselves the ones to judge when to break
the law,'' Barber told the jury. ``Do we want the press to be able
to decide when to break the law?''
<p>
   ABC, for its part, claimed it was acting in a proud journalistic
tradition, dating from Nellie Bly's undercover probe of a mental
hospital in 1888. ABC attorney Bill Jeffress went so far as to say
American journalism ``would not survive'' a high punitive-damage
award, casting the case as a pivotal referendum on the merits of
undercover reporting.
<p>
   Now, with ABC having suffered a multimillion-dollar judgment  &MD; 
the network has said it will appeal  &MD;  media observers are saying
the case, at the least, represents a new benchmark in declining
public regard for the media. But they can only guess at the more
important questions: Will news organizations ever again take the
legal risk of sending reporters undercover? And will the public
really suffer if they don't?
<p>
   Undercover journalism became a force in public life around the
turn of the century, when skepticism about corporate behavior was
rampant.
<p>
   In 1904, when Upton Sinclair posed as a worker in the
slaughterhouses of Chicago and wrote about the fetid conditions
there, he was acclaimed as the voice of average citizens speaking
out against the malefactors of wealth. An admiring President
Theodore Roosevelt dubbed undercover reporters ``muckrakers.''
<p>
   In recent decades, technological advances have spurred a fresh
burst of muckraking, this time on television, with cameras small
enough to be hidden in a reporter's clothing.
<p>
   ABC's ``PrimeTime Live'' went on the air in 1989. In its
relatively low-rated first season, the show broadcast two
undercover pieces. Thereafter, it sharply increased the number of
hidden-camera segments, until they averaged more than 20 per
season. ``PrimeTime Live's'' ratings went up.
<p>
   In 1991, Dale, an ABC producer in Atlanta, learned of
allegations that the nation's fastest-growing grocer, Food Lion,
was mishandling meat in its zeal for profits. The allegation had
been made by the United Food and Commercial Workers of America,
which also attacked the non-union Food Lion for paying low wages.
<p>
   The story appealed to both Sawyer and the heads of ABC's
investigative unit. With their approval, Dale and her associate
producer, Barnett, took a crash course in meat handling and applied
for jobs at Food Lion stores. Once inside, they observed employees
allegedly pouring barbeque sauce over spoiled chicken and sniffing
old rice pudding.
<p>
   Their report was, by the standards of television journalism,
worthy of awards. Former employees appeared on camera to make their
allegations. Hidden-camera footage appeared to back up the former
employees. Sawyer even acknowledged the union dispute. Afterwards,
the Labor Department investigated Food Lion and cited the company
for making some employees work unpaid overtime.
<p>
   Food Lion, however, felt it had been the victim of a televised
mugging, in which innocuous practices got blown up into a sizzling
scandal. Such disputes usually result in libel suits, but Food Lion
claimed that ABC committed fraud by sending its producers
undercover and that the producers then violated their obligations
as Food Lion employees by toting hidden cameras.
<p>
   The judge, N. Carlton Tilley, ruled ABC could not use the truth
of the broadcast as a defense. Thus, the network could only argue
that its producers' falsified resumes weren't technically
fraudulent and that they fulfilled their obligations to Food Lion
even as they cast about for evidence of unhealthy conditions.
<p>
   The North Carolina jury ruled in December that ABC was liable
for fraud. It granted the chain $1,402 in compensatory damages,
representing the salaries and training costs of the two producers.
<p>
   ABC maintained that no further damages were warranted; the
network may have been responsible for the producers lying on their
applications, but not for what they found once inside.
<p>
   An ordained minister who doubled as a professor of journalism
ethics testified on behalf of the network. He told the 12-person
jury, which included four blacks and four senior citizens, about
undercover investigations that revealed the evils of the Ku Klux
Klan, racism in hiring, age discrimination, unclean conditions in
nursing homes and insurance scams that targeted the elderly.
<p>
   Sawyer herself made a much-ballyhooed appearance, as reporters
crowded the courtroom and television vans lined up outside. She
insisted that she only approves hidden-camera reports when they
serve the public.
<p>
   But Food Lion rejected the notion that today's television news
magazines advocate for the public  &MD;  ratings are their
preoccupation, its lawyers claimed. And no longer are journalists
representative of average citizens, they said, a fact seemingly
brought home by Sawyer's testifying, with a shrug, that her ABC
salary totals ``more than $7 million.''
<p>
   ``ABC set up a system where everyone involved in the wrongdoing
gets rewarded,'' said Food Lion's Barber, reading off a list of ABC
salaries.
<p>
   Some journalists are casting the jurors' decision as a death
blow to undercover reporting. ``It's insane,'' said Marcia Rock, a
documentary filmmaker and professor of journalism at New York
University. ``Going undercover has been a useful tactic throughout
the history of the profession.''
<p>
   Meanwhile, under the blue lights and mirrors of a Food Lion meat
counter in Greensboro, shoppers expressed cynicism about
corporations and their cousins in big-time journalism and big-time
food sales. ``I think all the stores are basically the same,'' said
Rita Brown of Greensboro. ``They all try to save a dollar where
they can.''
<p>
   As for news magazines, Brown recalled NBC's infamo U.S. staging
of an explosion of a General Motors truck. ``They're out to get an
audience, to get the money,'' she said. ``If they can make a big
splash, they'll do it anyway they can. They're in it for the bucks,
too.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1937EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0637 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9714 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-JUNK-BONDS-CLOSE-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0965 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-JUNK-BONDS-CLOSE-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JUNK BONDS: ARGENTINA RAISES $2 BILLION IN GLOBAL BOND MARKETS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Malcolm Foster, MaryAnn Busso and Beth Williams &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- Argentina, a junk-rated
borrower, raised $2 billion in the global bond market amid strong
demand for higher-yielding securities.
<p>
   Argentina found ready buyers for its 20-year bonds. The debt
attracted four times as many bids as bond available, according to
J.P. Morgan Securities and Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., which arranged the
sale.
<p>
   The brisk demand suggests that investors are confident that
Argentina, a nation that suffered from economic stagnation and
hyperinflation during much of the 1970s and 1980s, will be able to
pay lenders 20 years from now.
<p>
   ``Argentina is clearly an improving credit,'' said Luis Luis,
principal at Scudder Stevens &AMP; Clark, which put in bids for the
sale and manages $2.0 billion of emerging market debt.
<p>
   Argentina is rated ``B1'' by Moody's Investors Service Inc. and
``BB-'' by Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp.
<p>
   In coming days, junk-rated companies are gearing up to sell morethan $1.5 billion of new debt. Tenet Healthcare Corp. plans to sell
$1.3 billion of debt in a three-part sale of five-year, eight-year
and 10-year notes.
<p>
   CFP Holdings is planning to sell $110 million of senior
guaranteed notes due in 2004, according to KDP Investment Advisors.
Derlan Industries Ltd. is planning to sell $100 million of senior
notes due in 2004, KDP said.
<p>
   Bonds of companies with high ratings in the junk bond class
should outperform their lower-rated brethren later in 1997,
according to Robert Kricheff, head of high-yield research at Credit
Suisse First Boston Corp.
<p>
   Junk bonds -- issues rated below ``Baa3'' by Moody's Investors
Service Inc. or ``BBB-'' by Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. --gained more
than 12 percent in 1996 as investors sought out the juicy yields
they offered when returns on other bonds were slim. Investors were
comfortable owning junk bonds as strengthening corporate profits
resulted in fewer defaults.
<p>
   While that may continue this year, the ``BB''-rated bonds will
probably do best in the second half, Kricheff said.
<p>
   ``Investors should continue to look to enhance yield, but be
wary of a shift to higher-quality in the latter part of the year,''
he said.
<p>
   For instance, companies that in 1993 sold some $7 billion of
bonds without interest payments for the first five years will face
their initial payments on these bonds next year. Preparing for the
payments could put pressure on those with the lowest ratings, and
cause their bonds to lose value relative to benchmark Treasuries.
<p>
   Still, with cash continuing to flow into junk-bond mutual funds,
and with insurance companies and pension funds putting more of
their money into the high-yield market, junk bonds will probably
remain among the best-performing bonds in the first half, Kricheff
said.
<p>
   Strong demand for the high yields offered by junk debt enabled
companies to sell a record $79 billion last year, swelling the junk
bond market to $386.7 billion.
<p>
   Among bonds in the Salomon Brothers indexes, those that pay
interest in cash fell by an average 1 cent per dollar face amount
of bonds; bonds that pay deferred interest rose 3 cents; bonds of
companies in bankruptcy were unchanged.
<p>
   Bonds that pay cash interest rose to 224.94, up from 224.14 at
the beginning of the year. Deferred interest bonds rose to 228.30,
up from 225.79 at the beginning of the year. Bonds of bankrupt
companies were at 201.88, up from 201.71 at the beginning of the
year.
