<p>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Jan. 23. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
<p>
    &UR; TOP &LR; 
<p>
    &UR; Lead story: &LR; 
<p>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow)  &MD;  In a display of Russia's mounting
restiveness about President Boris Yeltsin's seemingly permanent
absence from the Kremlin, the Parliament votes overwhelmingly for a
resolution to remove Yeltsin from his post because of his poor
health. The 229-63 vote in the lower house has no legal force, and
it was instantly swamped in a confusing blizzard of parliamentary
maneuvers that will require a second vote before it is adopted. By
Michael Specter. (We plan to move the story by 8:30 p.m. ET in
``i'' news file.)
<p>
    &UR; Top center story: &LR; 
<p>
   3-column photo reefer to ABORTION-MARCH, story inside.
<p>
    &UR; Off-lead story: &LR; 
<p>
   DALEY-CONFIRM (Washington)  &MD;  President Clinton's nominee for
commerce secretary, William M. Daley, says that if confirmed he
will take steps to depoliticize the department, which Republicans
say has become an outpost of Democratic Party fund-raising. By
Richard W. Stevenson. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news
file.)
<p>
   Reefer to ALBRIGHT-CONFIRM, story and photo inside.
<p>
    &UR; FOLD &LR; 
<p>
   FOOD-LION-ABC (Undated)  &MD;  A federal jury in Greensboro, N.C.,
awards a supermarket chain over $5.5 million in punitive damages
from ABC and two of its employees in a closely watched media case
that focused on the propriety of such widely used TV news
techniques as hidden cameras and undercover reporters. By Barry
Meier. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
<p>
   NY-POLICEUNION-INDICT (New York)  &MD;  In a wide-ranging indictment,
federal authorities charge that top officials of the union that
represents the transit police took kickbacks and engaged in several
other schemes before the force merged with the city police
department. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
<p>
    &UR; BOTTOM &LR; 
<p>
   3-col. photo reefer to inside story:
<p>
   TSONGAS-LEGACY (Lowell, Mass.)  &MD;  When Paul Tsongas died last
weekend, the local newspaper wrote, ``With his death, Paul
Tsongas's survivors include his wife, his children and a city.''
For the people of Lowell, who turned out in the thousands to pay
their respects, Paul Tsongas was a hero who rescued the city from
the depression that came with the collapse of the textile
factories. By Sara Rimer. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a''
news file.)
<p>
   CLINTON-FUNDRAISING (Washington)  &MD;  A longtime adviser to
President Clinton who is a top bank appointee sought last year to
have that institution provide financing for a store franchise to a
woman whose large donations to the Democratic Party have come under
investigation. By Christopher Drew and Jeff Gerth. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
<p>
   Special Report; 2,200 words.
<p>
   NY-SECRET-BENEFACTOR (New York)  &MD;  Over the past 18 years a
billionaire has secretly been giving away his fortune to hospitals,
schools and other beneficiaries who did not even know the identity
of their benefactor, a self-made man born in New Jersey who has
strong ties to Ireland and who did not even take tax deductions. He
revealed his story in an interview. By Judith Miller. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
<p>
    &UR; INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1: &LR; 
<p>
   CUBA-CANADA (Havana)  &MD;  Canada's foreign minister visits Cuba to
sign joint declarations on human rights and foreign investment; in
Washington, the State Department condemns the visit. By Anthony
DePalma. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
<p>
   SIMPSON-SUIT (Santa Monica, Calif.)  &MD;  As jurors sit grim-faced
and two women panelists appear close to tears, a lawyer implores
the jury to make O.J. Simpson pay for the slaying of Ronald
Goldman. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET
in ``a'' news file.)
<p>
   CT-SCHOOL-DESEGREGATION (Hartford, Conn.)  &MD;  A panel established
by Gov. John G. Rowland to address segregation in the state's
schools says the state should require school districts to accept
students from anywhere in Connecticut and should pay more for
school construction projects that bring black and Hispanic students
into mostly white districts. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``a'' news file.)
