<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=tad-z> A9716 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-POLMONEY-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0677 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-POLMONEY-COX  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; PARTY LEADERS RESISTS CLINTON'S FUND-RAISING REFORMS
<p>
    &UR; By ANDREW MOLLISON &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  President Clinton's new voluntary restraints on
fund-raising by the White House and the Democratic National
Committee may not make a deep dent in Washington's campaign money
culture.
<p>
   In addition to promising stricter screening of donors allowed to
attend ``small'' meetings with the president and vice president,
Clinton's voluntary plan to avoid embarrassing campaign abuses
contained three major elements:
<p>
   -- A cap of $100,000 per year on gifts to the DNC from any
donor.
<p>
   -- A ban on gifts from foreign-owned companies and their U.S.
subsidiaries.
<p>
   -- A ban on gifts from non-citizens, even those who are legal,
permanent U.S. residents.
<p>
   Vermont Gov. Howard Dean, chairman of the Democratic Governors
Association, said his group also plans to abide by the DNC
guidelines.
<p>
   Democratic staffers at two of the party's other big
Washington-based committees said that while the guidelines are
likely to be adopted, they are still being reviewed at the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee and the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee.
<p>
   Yet, even if all three end up adopting the DNC guidelines,
loopholes in the plan would still let a single company, its chief
executive officer and the CEO's spouse give more than $1 million a
year to the Democratic party, said Kent Cooper, executive director
of the nonpartisan Center for Responsive Politics.
<p>
   For example, the three donors could each give $100,000 a year to
each of the four Washington-based party committees without
violating the guidelines, Cooper said.
<p>
   ``That's just one of a variety of ways you can split money up,
and wind up giving just as much money as you ever did before there
was a $100,000 cap,'' Cooper said. Giving money directly to one of
the 50 state parties is another way around such limits, he said.
<p>
   Nor will it be easy to distinguish between foreign-owned and
U.S.-owned companies in a global economy, Cooper said.
<p>
   ``The plan may at least be praised as an admission by the White
House and the Democrats that there is a negative publicity value to
accepting large contributions (that) are mind-boggling to the
average person, and are tied to access to the White House and to
Democratic and Republican leaders of Congress and the party,''
Cooper said.
<p>
   ``I don't think Republicans have yet made that initial
concession yet,'' Cooper said, ``but as they go into the Senate
hearings this winter, I think they are going to see the negatives
themselves.''
<p>
   Republicans ranged from scornful to indifferent as they turned
down the president's suggestion that the Republicans join the
Democrats in agreeing to go even further and stop taking any ``soft
money'' gifts from corporate or union treasuries.
<p>
   ``We don't have a problem to solve, since we take only legal
contributions,'' said spokesman Rich Galen of the National
Republican Congressional Committee. ``The Democrats have to alter
their way of doing things because they did take illegal
contributions.''
<p>
   At the National Senate Republican Committee, spokesman Michael
Marr(CQ) dismissed Clinton's plan as ``a gimmick'' designed to
distract the public from the failure of Democrats to abide by
current laws.
<p>
   ``We also think President Clinton is acting in a duplicitous
fashion when he favors limits on soft-money contributions'' but
continues to benefit from dues money spent independently by unions,
Marr said.
<p>
   The Republican National Committee will rely on recommendations
from a task force to be formed from its own members, rather than
advice from a Democratic president, RNC spokeswoman Mary Crawford
said.
<p>
   At the Republican Governors Association, spokeswoman Kirsten
Fedewa(CQ) said her group ``is pleased the Democrats are taking
these steps, in light of their troubles,'' but will continue ``to
follow the lead of the RNC, rather than the DNC.''
<p>
    &UR; For clients of The New York Times News Service &LR; 
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1942EST
</TRAILER>
