<DOCID> nyt970122.0640 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tia-z> A9718 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-PETER-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0376 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-GIANTS-PETER-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GIANTS SIGN FORMER NEBRASKA DEFENSIVE TACKLE CHRISTIAN PETER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Micheal Buteau and Steve Capo &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   East Rutherford, New Jersey, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The New York
Giants signed former University of Nebraska defensive tackle
Christian Peter, giving the troubled former New England Patriots
draft pick a second chance in the NFL.
<p>
   Peter, a 6-foot-3, 304-pounder, was released by New England
three days after the team made him a fifth-round pick in the April
draft, claiming they didn't ``have complete information regarding''
Peter's legal problems while at Nebraska. New England said the
behavior was ``incompatible with our organization's standards of
acceptable conduct.'' Peter was given a 10-day jail sentence in
August and fined $300 for disturbing the peace, and pleaded guilty
in May 1994 to third-degree assault of a former Miss Nebraska,
which resulted in 18 months of probation.
<p>
   In addition, Peter has been arrested for trespassing, public
urination, refusing to comply with the order of a policeman and
third-degree assault for threatening to kill a parking attendant.
<p>
   The Giants, who have been interested in signing Peter since he
was released by the Patriots, said he has put his troubles behind
him.
<p>
   ``We're very pleased that Christian has lived up to the program
that we established in order for us to sign him,'' said Giants
General Manager George Young. ``We feel after giving up a season of
pro football that he understands his situation and will correct the
errors that he made in the past.''
<p>
   The Newark, New Jersey, Star-Ledger reported that Peter has been
going to a rehabilitation program since meeting with Giants'
officials in May.
<p>
   ``I have worked very hard at dealing with the issues in my
life,'' Peter said. ``Those issues are something that I will have
to manage every day for the rest of my life. I understand that, and
I am grateful for the opportunity.''
<p>
   Peter, a native of Locust, New Jersey, was New England's second
pick in the fifth round of the draft after finishing his senior
season with 46 tackles, including 12 solo, and two sacks.
<p>
   Terms of the contract weren't disclosed.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1942EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
