<TEXT>
<p>
   The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, Jan. 23. If
you have any questions, please call Vinton Supplee on the Republic
News Desk at (602) 271-8286.
<p>
   HMOS (Phoenix)  &MD;  The dominance of Health Maintenance
Organizations over the state's insurance business is being
challenged at the state Legislature from an unusual quarter -
conservative Republicans who are normally eager to please big
business. So intent are some GOP lawmakers on regulating insurers
that they have introduced a half-dozen regulatory bills, including
one that would mandate that employers offer alternative health
plans to their employees, and another that establishes a
comprehensive grievance process for patients who are denied
coverage. By KRIS MAYES. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
<p>
   BALLOT (Phoenix)  &MD;  An Arizona state senator wants to give
disaffected voters something to go to the polls for: a third
category on the ballot that reads ``none of the above.'' If ``none
of the above'' gets the most votes, another election would be held,
and the original candidates would be thrown off the ballot. By
MARTIN VAN DER WERF. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
<p>
   GRUNAWALT (Phoenix)  &MD;  The Tysson Gang killer dies at five
minutes after midnight Mountain Time (2 a.m. EST) tonight. By ERIC
MILLER. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
<p>
   VICTIMS (Washington)  &MD;  After 42 rewrites, an amendment to give
victims some constitutional rights to participate in the
prosecution of the accused will make a second pass in the Senate.
Co-sponsors are Arizona U.S. Sen Jon Kyl, a Republican, and U.S.
Sen. Dianne Feinstein of California, a Democrat. By ADRIANNE FLYNN.
Story will move in the ``A'' category.
<p>
   GAMING (Phoenix)  &MD;  The Gila River and Ak-Chin tribes file a
federal suit trying to block the state's attempt to reclassify
gaming machines. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A''
category.
