<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0670 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CLINTON-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CLINTON PUSHES HIGHER GOALS IN EDUCATION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By NANCY MATHIS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NORTHBROOK, Ill.  &MD;  In a push for higher goals in education,
President Clinton called on schools Wednesday to take part in
national standards testing and blasted those who ``hide behind''
the cloak of local control to avoid participating.
<p>
   ``It's selling our kids down the drain, and it's wrong,''
Clinton told hundreds of parents and students gathered at the
Glenbrook North High School gymnasium here. He praised Chicago-area
students, because they participated in recent international math
and science tests.
<p>
   The president chose education as his theme for the first trip of
his second term, an indication, aides said, of the emphasis he will
place on the issue during the next four years and an example of how
he intends to use the ``bully pulpit'' of the presidency.
<p>
   ``To pretend that somehow holding ourselves to these standards
and agreeing that there has to be some uniform way of measuring
them is giving up of local control is just an excuse to avoid being
held accountable, because we're afraid we can't make it,'' Clinton
said.
<p>
   He sharply challenged political and ideological opponents of
national standards and federal assistance in education.
<p>
   ``We can no longer hide behind our love of local control of the
schools and use that as an excuse not to hold ourselves to high
standards. It has nothing to do with local control,'' Clinton said.
``There's no school board in America that controls the content of
algebra.''
<p>
   Clinton said he knows there is resistance to the acceptance of
national standards and national testing. But, he said, it is the
only way students in the United States can be measured against
foreign students and the only way Americans will know if the goal
of excellence has been achieved.
<p>
   ``I have heard all the arguments in the world against this. But
no one has yet made a compelling case to me for how calculus is
different in Chicago from Little Rock, Arkansas., or Cody, Wyoming,
or, for that matter, Germany or Singapore or any other place in the
world,'' Clinton said.
<p>
   Clinton came here to pat the backs of students at Glenbrook
North and in 19 Chicago-area school districts who participated as a
group in the Third International Math and Science Study. The TIMSS
was administered to sample groups of students in 41 countries. The
Chicago-area students participated to test their achievement.
<p>
   The ``First in the World Consortium,'' as the American group
called itself, scored among the top countries in science and in the
second tier in math. Numerous international studies show U.S.
students compare poorly to their foreign counterparts.
<p>
   ``Those who believe there is no role for federal government in
education are simply wrong,'' said West Northfield school
superintendent Paul Kimmelman, whose students participated in
TIMSS. ``There has not been interference, only help and
assistance.''
<p>
   The White House announced that Clinton would seek in his new
budget a 26 percent increase in funding for Goals 2000, the
national education standards project, and nearly a 50 percent
increase for charter schools, which bypass many regulations to set
their own standards.
<p>
   Republicans in Congress have repeatedly tried to eliminate the
Goals 2000 program, maintaining the federal government should not
get involved in a local control issue such as public schools.
<p>
   The president also toured a science class at Stanley Field
Middle School and met in Chicago with Mayor Richard Daley and the
Chicago school board.
<p>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the trek to Illinois is
emblematic of how Clinton will spend his second term.
<p>
   ``We won't be oriented all the time on just what is happening in
Congress or what is happening on legislation. You can tell today
this has got very little to do with action by the federal
government or by the Congress,'' McCurry said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1946EST
</TRAILER>
