<SLUG> BC-BRADLEES-CUTBACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0602 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BRADLEES-CUTBACKS-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BRADLEES TO CUT JOBS, CLOSE N.Y. STORE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRIS REIDY &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Bradlees Inc. said Wednesday it will eliminate 105 jobs at its
Braintree, Mass. headquarters and close a store in New York as part
of a new plan to get the discount department store chain out of
bankruptcy protection.
<p>
   The announcement represents ``the first of several steps we plan
to implement to restore the company to profitability,'' said
Bradlees' chairman Peter Thorner.
<p>
   Bradlees employs roughly 13,000 workers and has eliminated 3,000
jobs since filing for bankruptcy in June 1995. The closing of the
Long Island store will bring Bradlees' store total to 109.
Wednesday, Thorner insisted there will be no further major store
closings or massive layoffs.
<p>
   Thorner spoke a day after a US Bankruptcy Court granted Bradlees
a six-month extension of its time to file a reorganization plan and
shortly after Bradlees renegotiated its lending agreement following
disappointing holiday sales.
<p>
   Nevertheless, Thorner remains upbeat.
<p>
   ``I'm optimistic,'' he said. ``I think we have a lot of
opportunities.''
<p>
   Thorner was promoted to the top job on Christmas Eve when the
board of directors forced the resignation of Mark A. Cohen, who had
come to Bradlees two years earlier.
<p>
   With a department store background, Cohen had upgraded the
merchandise and stocked shelves with more clothing. The plan was to
reposition Bradlees as a sort of retail halfway house between
discounters such as Wal-Mart and department stores such as Macy's.
<p>
   But Thorner said Cohen's strategy resulted in pricing policies
that often made Bradlees nearly as expensive as department stores.
To woo back regulars, Bradlees is reducing prices by ``a notch or
two'' and scaling back promotions, Thorner said.
<p>
   Under Cohen, Bradees became too dependent on one-day promotions,
Thorner said, and customers got into the habit of buying items only
when on sale. Bradlees will now focus on every-day pricing that
offers ``tremendous value,'' he said.
<p>
   New York retail analyst Walter Loeb saw another problem: Cohen
did not execute his strategy uniformly throughout the entire chain.
Some stores were buffed up and stocked with ``fancy'' merchandise,
but others were not, Loeb said.
<p>
   As Cohen upgraded merchandise, he also squabbled with Bradlees'
creditors, a source said. Thorner was promoted partly because of
his success in dealing with creditors when he was a member of a
team that led Ames Department Stores Inc. out of bankruptcy in the
early '90s, the source said.
<p>
   Thorner ``has a certain amount of credibility in the industry
for taking Ames out of bankruptcy,'' noted Terrence McCrary, an
analyst with Auerbach Pollak &AMP; Richardson, who follows Ames.
<p>
   If Cohen is a ``merchant,'' Thorner is an administrator with a
reputation for cutting costs and improving margins, Loeb said. With
a new strategy that puts more emphasis on Bradlees' ``traditional
discount roots,'' Thorner ``has the ability to turn Bradlees
around,'' he said.
<p>
   Still, observers see it as an uphill battle. Some suggest there
are simply too many stores and too few customers in the Northeast
to support a $1.78 billion regional discount chain such as Bradlees
in the face of national juggernaut Wal-Mart.
<p>
   And according to papers filed in Bankruptcy Court, Bradlees lost
$5 million on sales of $155.6 million for the four weeks ended Nov.
30, Bloomberg News reported.
<p>
   ``The big W is not going away,'' said Loeb. ``This is a fight
for survival.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1948EST
</TRAILER>
