<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-335&AMP;A </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0991 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-335&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: S.C., Ill., Va., N.Y., N.J., Conn., Mo., Minn., Mass., Ohio,
Ga.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SURVEY BY FED SEES GROWTH AS `MODERATE' &LR;  &QL; 
(ART ADV: Graphics on indicators and Beige Book report are being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr. &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  Inflation remained subdued despite continued
``moderate'' growth of the economy, the Federal Reserve's periodic
survey of business conditions in all geographic areas showed
Wednesday.
<p>
   The findings, which were presaged Tuesday by comments of Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan, were a further indication that the central
bank was likely to keep interest rates unchanged at its policy
meeting in early February.
<p>
   ``District reports provided scattered evidence of increasing
wage pressures, particularly for skilled workers, but in general
did not indicate significant price pressures other than for energy
items,'' the Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco said,
summarizing the report's findings, which included responses through
the second week of January.
<p>
   The survey, known as the beige book, is a compilation of
anecdotes and research from regional Fed banks that is put together
to help top Fed officials set policy.
<p>
   Employers in the Chicago and Richmond districts appeared to have
the most trouble filling jobs and were being forced to raise pay
accordingly.
<p>
   In the New York district, which includes the entire state plus
northern New Jersey and a small piece of Connecticut, the overall
economy ``has a slightly firmer tone'' than in the preceding
survey, on Dec. 4. Holiday retail sales in the district were among
the best in the nation.
<p>
   Among districts that quantified holiday retail sales, New York
posted growth of 4 to 8 percent compared with 1995 levels, while
sales in Philadelphia rose 5 percent, sales in St. Louis 7 percent
and in Minneapolis zero to 2 percent, the Fed survey reported.
<p>
   It also cited a separate poll of small retailers across New York
state that showed a gain, before inflation, of 4 to 6 percent for
same-store sales, ``with the strongest reports coming from
Manhattan.''
<p>
   Women's and children's apparel and jewelry were the strongest
categories, confirming other appraisals, while electronics and
other big-ticket durable items were generally weak.
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   The survey also cited the New York district, along with Chicago,
as having a ``firming'' of residential real estate prices.
<p>
   Real estate prices advanced 2 to 5 percent during the fourth
quarter, according to real estate agents in New York and New
Jersey, and the tight New York City-area apartment market seems to
have prompted a pickup in construction of new buildings.
<p>
   The pace of permits issued for new apartments more than doubled
that of any of the preceding five years, with the bulk of the
increase coming in the second half of 1996, the Fed's survey said.
Commercial construction was also stronger in the New York district.
<p>
   In a separate government report Wednesday, the Commerce
Department said builders broke ground on single-family homes and
apartment buildings at an annual pace of 1,329,000 in December, a
decline of 12.2 percent from November.
<p>
   Although this decline was about triple the consensus estimate,
analysts cautioned that the seasonal adjustment process was
especially unreliable during the winter months. For all of 1996,
starts climbed 8.8 percent to 1,473,700, the highest total in eight
years.
<p>
   The Fed's survey of its 12 districts, conducted as part of its
preparation for a meeting of its Federal Open Market Committee on
Feb. 4 and Feb. 5, said that, ``Economic growth in December and
early January was moderate in most parts of the country.''
<p>
   The survey also showed that factory activity expanded or held
steady in most areas of the country. Producers of steel and other
metals as well as machine tools, construction materials and capital
equipment registered the biggest gains.
<p>
   Wage pressure was most visible in the bidding for skilled
factory, administrative and technical workers, especially computer
technicians, the Fed reported. ``Signs of increasing wage
pressures'' were reported in Chicago and Richmond characterized
these as ``more evident.'' The Boston, Philadelphia, Cleveland,
Atlanta, St. Louis and San Francisco districts also noted worker
shortages.
<p>
   The job market in Spartanburg, S.C., is so tight, the Richmond
Fed said, that offers of higher pay for temporary employees were
starting to draw workers from low-paying permanent jobs.
<p>
   The Fed mistakenly posted Wednesday's survey on the Internet
nearly two hours before its new official release time of 2 p.m. Bob
Moore, a Fed aide, said, ``We broke our own embargo'' but added
that officials did not yet know whether the error was related to
the fact that until now the beige book was published at noon.
<p>
   Economic announcements such as this one often move the stock and
bond markets, so the releases are carefully timed to prevent some
traders from getting unfair advantages from advance knowledge of
the data. Moore said the Fed had received no complaints from
traders about the early release of the beige book report.
<p>
   The Commerce Department's report also showed that the slump in
new house and apartment construction was most striking in the West,
where starts tumbled 29.2 percent. The Midwest and South declined
7.9 percent and 7.2 percent, respectively, while the Northeast
edged down negligibly but from a pace far below that of any other
region.
<p>
   Permits for new homes moved lower by less than 1 percent, to an
annual pace of 1,410,000, the Commerce Department's report also
showed.
<p>
   Shipment of mobile homes, for which figures lag a month, eased
4.1 percent in November to a rate of 354,000.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1952EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0650 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9733 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-HMOS-REPEAT- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1170 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MEDICARE-HMOS-REPEAT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CLINTON MEDICARE PLAN WOULD SQUEEZE $46 BLN FROM HMOS (REPEAT) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Paul Heldman &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Washington, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Clinton administration
proposal to reduce future Medicare spending relies on a $46 billion
cut in payments to health maintenance organizations over six years
for one third of its savings.
<p>
   HMO stocks, which plunged across the board last week in
anticipation of the administration's curbs on HMO payments, were
mostly lower today.
<p>
   The cuts pose a threat to the business of big Medicare HMOS,
including PacifiCare Health Systems Inc., United Healthcare Corp.,
Oxford Health Plans Inc., and Humana Inc. -- whose shares closed
lower today -- as well as Health Systems International Inc., Aetna
Inc. and others.
<p>
   HMO industry lobbyists said the Clinton proposal could cause
health plans to cut benefits to the elderly. They suggested that
possibility could prompt seniors from big states such as California
and Florida to apply political pressure to scale back the cuts when
the legislation reaches the Republican-led Congress.
<p>
   ``Republicans and the administration have got to know that some
key political areas in (the next) election are areas that would
have payments cut the most,'' said Roy Ramthun, lobbyist for Humana
Inc., the Louisville, Kentucky-based HMO.
<p>
   Shares in PacifiCare, which garners 60 percent of its revenue
from Medicare, closed down 1 1/8 at 76 1/4 on trading of 814,000
shares, compared to three-month average daily trading volume of
456,000 shares.
<p>
   Shares of Oxford closed down 1 at 52 3/8 and United Healthcare
stock finished down 1 at 44 1/4. Humana shares closed down 1/8 at
18 1/4, while Health Systems finished up 1/4 at 25 1/8 and Aetna
was up 1 at 75 7/8.
<p>
   The proposed Medicare HMO cuts may have already been built into
the value of the stocks, which fell last week after word first
leaked that the administration was considering deep cuts.
<p>
   ``You saw HMO stocks take it on the chin at the beginning of
last week,'' said Robert Mains, health industry analyst with Advest
Inc. ``It's built in to some degree, (but) there might be a little
more bloodletting.''
<p>
   In addition, while Republicans and the administration agree that
Medicare is overpaying HMOs and possibly losing the government
money, both sides are hoping HMOs and other insurers will
ultimately play a major role in holding down the program's rising
costs. In fact, the administration included in its Medicare savings
plan a proposal to open Medicare up to more types of managed-care
health plans.
<p>
   ``It doesn't do you much good to run them (the HMOs) out of
business, because then there is no one to manage the care,'' said
John Runningen, analyst with Robinson-Humphrey.
<p>
   Mains also said he is ``skeptical'' that the level of cuts under
consideration will actually be enacted if the Republican-led
Congress and the administration agree on a balanced-budget plan
later this year.
<p>
   ``If managed care is to be one of the ways that Medicare costs
come under control, onerous cuts would strangle the goose that laid
the golden egg pretty quickly,'' he said.
<p>
   Ramthun said that Health and Human Services Secretary Donna
Shalala has tried to calm HMO executives by describing the proposal
as a ``first offer.''
<p>
   Nonetheless, HMOs reacted angrily to the proposal yesterday,
saying health plans may drop out of the Medicare program altogether
if their future payments are cut too deeply.
<p>
   ``The effect of this proposal will be to leave many people with
fewer benefits, larger out-of-pocket costs and perhaps fewer health
plans from which to choose,'' said Don White, spokesman for the
American Association of Health Plans, the nation's largest trade
group for HMOs and other managed-care plans.
<p>
   The administration defended its proposal today. Bruce Vladeck,
the Clinton appointee who runs Medicare, said the Medicare
managed-care program will continue to grow if the administration's
plan is implemented.
<p>
   He noted that Medicare boosted its national payment rates to
HMOs by a total of 16 percent over the last two years while these
same health plans negotiated commercial payment increases in the
low single digits.
<p>
   If the administration's proposed cuts in Medicare HMO payments
are enacted, Vladeck said, senior citizen HMO enrollment will still
continue to grow, although possibly not at the current rate of
80,000 members a month.
<p>
   ``There's still plenty of room in there for new plans to come
into the program and for people to continue to enroll,'' Vladeck
said.
<p>
   Studies show that the government is losing money on Medicare
managed care. ``We see this as a way of eliminating overpayment,''
Vladeck said.
<p>
   The Medicare HMO cuts are part of the Clinton plan presented
yesterday to cut $138 billion in future Medicare spending over six
years to help improve the financial condition of the health
insurance program for the elderly and wipe out federal budget
deficits.
<p>
   The administration has also proposed spending about $9 billion
over six years to add new Medicare benefits. They include new
preventive care coverage such as colorectal cancer screening and
annual mammograms; and up to one week annually of temporary help
for spouses and other family members caring for someone with
Alzheimer's disease.
<p>
   The Medicare HMO cuts are the largest item in the Medicare
proposal. In one concession to the industry, the administration
said it will delay about $8 billion of the $46 billion in proposed
Medicare HMO cuts until the years 2000 through 2003.
<p>
   Those cuts would come from reducing the Medicare HMO base
payment to 90 percent of the cost of senior citizen fee-for-service
care from the current rate of 95 percent. Some HMO lobbyist had
worried the administration would cut the base payment below 90
percent.
<p>
   Other managed-care savings would be achieved by removing from
the Medicare HMO payment rate money that is supposed to be passed
on to hospitals that provide graduate medical education and care to
the poor.
<p>
   That would especially hurt health plans such as Oxford that do
much business in areas where there is a heavy concentration of
teaching hospitals.
<p>
   Hospitals complain that HMOs don't always pass along the
teaching hospital money built into their payments. Today, the
administration said it would set up a six-year $14-billion fund to
compensate teaching hospitals.
<p>
   The administration and Republican lawmakers also want to raise
Medicare HMO rates in low-cost rural areas to make it attractive
for health plans to do business there. Vladeck said 25 percent of
Medicare beneficiaries live in areas where they have no access to
managed care health plans.
<p>
   The money for rural areas will come from squeezing money from
above average HMO payments rates in cities such New York City and
Miami.
<p>
   ``If you're in a (high paying) urban area, it's going to be
triple whammy,'' said Mains.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
