<DOCID> nyt970122.0651 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=tdt-z> A9734 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MONEY-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0838 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CLINTON-MONEY-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GOP DENIES RECEIVING ILLEGAL FOREIGN MONEY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MICHAEL KRANISH &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  One day after President Clinton charged that
Republicans ``raise more foreign money'' than Democrats, White
House officials said Wednesday they could not yet provide
documentation to support Clinton's claim.
<p>
   Republican officials reacted angrily to Clinton's charge, saying
the Republican National Committee had not collected any ``illegal''
foreign money. RNC officials also noted that the Democratic
National Committee has returned $1.5 million, much of it from
foreign sources, because of questions about the legality of the
contributions.
<p>
   White House special counsel Lanny Davis said in an interview
that he could not provide documentation to support Clinton's claim,
but also said a study is under way to determine the extent of
foreign contributions to both parties.
<p>
   ``An effort is underway to determine the total foreign
corporation-based contributions to the Republican Party as well as
the Democratic Party,'' Davis said.
<p>
   Davis noted that Common Cause, the self-styled citizen's lobby,
last year produced a report that said Republicans got more money
from American subsidiaries of foreign corporations than Democrats.
<p>
   But Davis acknowledged the study is incomplete because it looked
only at 16 companies that gave the largest donations to the two
parties. The study did not, for example, look at donations
associated with the Indonesia-based Lippo Group, or a $250,000
contribution to the Democratic Party from a South Korean company
that was later returned.
<p>
   The latest inter-party fingerpointing began when Clinton, in
seeking bipartisan support for a campaign finance reform bill,
lashed out at Republicans. ``They raise more money, they raise more
foreign money, they raise more money in big contributions, and we
take all the heat,'' Clinton charged. ``It's a free ride.''
<p>
   Sen. John McCain, the Arizona Republican who on Tuesday termed
Clinton's charge ``crap,'' issued a warning to both parties. He
said that Republicans and Democrats alike committed fundraising
mistakes that will come to light in congressional hearings
scheduled to start in March.
<p>
   ``We will find out there were transgressions both ethically and
legally on the Republican side'' as well as among Democrats, McCain
said in an interview.
<p>
   DNC spokeswoman Amy Weiss Tobe, meanwhile, said Republicans were
not being truthful when they said they had not returned any foreign
donations. She said the GOP returned a $15,000 donation from a
Canadian in recent months. Asked how that compared to the $1.5
million returned by Democrats, she responded that more improper GOP
donations would be uncovered if ``if the press held them under the
same scrutiny'' as Democrats.
<p>
   Clinton's effort to turn the tables on the GOP is not new.
During the presidential campaign, Clinton tried to counter
questions about alleged improprieties in Democratic fundraising
with a hard-hitting ad. It said, in part: ``Dole and the
Republicans took $2.4 million from foreign interests. Foreign oil,
foreign tobacco, foreign drug companies.'' The Clinton campaign
said the contributions came from U.S. subsidiaries of 16
foreign-companies, including British Petroleum and Brown &AMP;
Williamson  &MD;  both British corporations.
<p>
   To be sure, Republicans have had their share of fundraising
controversies. For example:
<p>
   Massachusetts millionaire Simon C. Fireman and his company,
Aqua-Leisure Industries of Avon, last year were ordered by a
federal court to pay a $6 million fine for making illegal
donations, including $69,000 to the Dole campaign. No similar fine
has been assessed against Democratic contributors.
<p>
   Cuban-born sugar magnate Jose Fanjul was appointed by Dole to be
vice-chairman of Dole's presidential campaign finance committee
even though Fanjul was not a U.S. citizen. Fanjul was a major donor
to the Republican Party and the Dole campaign and he stood to
benefit from Dole's action on sugar policy. Fanjul's donations were
legal because he has U.S. residency status.
<p>
   Still, Clinton's charge that Republicans raised more foreign
money has not been substantiated. There is no simple way to say how
much ``foreign'' money has been raised by either party because
there is no agreement on what constitutes foreign money. While it
is illegal for a foreign citizen or foreign corporation to give
money to the parties, it is legal for a temporary U.S. resident or
a U.S. subsidiary of a foreign company to donate.
<p>
   Clinton appears to have lumped the illegal and legal categories
together, while Republicans say the issue should be which party
raised illegal money.
<p>
   Much of the $1.5 million in returned Democratic contributions
was given back because of questions about whether the funds, mostly
from temporary residents or subsidiaries of foreign companies,
originated from foreign sources which are barred from giving.
</TEXT>
