<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tdt-z> A9738 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-CURE-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0742 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-AIDS-CURE-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TOO SOON TO STOP AIDS TREATMENT, RESEARCHER SAYS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By RICHARD A. KNOX &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  A leading AIDS researcher said Wednesday it will be
at least six months to a year before he will consider stopping
treatment with a cocktail of drugs in some patients to see if the
therapy has eradicated the human immunodeficiency virus, which
causes AIDS.
<p>
   Dr. David Ho, director of the Aaron Diamond AIDS Research Center
in New York City, said last summer he would be ready to do the
crucial drug-cessation experiment in a few patients by the end of
1996. Now, however, he believes it will take considerably longer
for HIV to be eliminated from the bodies of infected individuals.
<p>
   ``We're definitely revising our estimate,'' Ho said at the
opening of a major conference here on AIDS. Recent research has
persuaded him and his colleagues that HIV  &MD;  or rather, viral DNA
that could potentially give rise to more virus particles  &MD;  may lurk
in some cells for three years or even longer.
<p>
   Thus, the researchers ``have never popped the question with our
patients'' about whether they would be willing to discontinue
antiviral drug treatment.
<p>
   Particularly coming from Ho, who has spearheaded the drive to
treat AIDS aggressively, the revised estimate means that people
infected with HIV, their doctors and researchers are in for a long
period of uncertainty about the prospect of eradicating the deadly
infection. Meanwhile, scientists say, patients will have to take
their drugs scrupulously to avoid appearance of dangerous new HIV
strains resistant to the most effective drugs.
<p>
   Even though Ho's group has found no evidence that HIV is
actively reproducing in any of a small group of individuals
followed for up to 18 months on new multidrug treatments, they
cannot be certain that the virus would not reemerge if even a
single infected cell remains hidden away in a lymph node, a corner
of the brain, the testes or some other location.
<p>
   Thus, they believe they must wait until all HIV-infected cells
complete their natural lifespan and are eliminated from the body
before halting HIV-suppressing drugs.
<p>
   One problem is that scientists are uncertain about the lifespan
of these cells; before now, it has not been a question of pressing
scientific interest. In addition, Ho said, ``there is a lot of
individual variation'' in the persistence of HIV-infected cells.
<p>
   Another important factor is that the patients from which many of
Ho's insights are derived represent the best-case scenario of HIV
infection. Twenty of these patients began treatment with the most
potent combinations of anti-HIV drugs within 90 days of being
infected by the virus. By contrast, most HIV-infected individuals
harbor the virus for years before they even know they're infected.
<p>
   Ho's group of acutely infected patients, as they are called,
presumably would be the most likely of any to have the virus
eradicated by aggressive drug treatment. The virus would not have
had as much time to develop drug-resistant variants, and their
immune systems are not as devastated as those of long-infected
patients.
<p>
   However, Ho pointed out that other researchers are seeing
comparably encouraging results in patients with more advanced HIV
disease.
<p>
   Ho's group and other AIDS researchers are studying seminal
fluids and lymph tissue from patients' bowels to see if HIV can be
detected in these samples even when it is undetectable by the most
sensitive tests in blood. ``So far we see no evidence of ongoing
viral replication,'' he said at a press conference. ``We do see
some trapped viral particles.''
<p>
   The absence of active viral replication in seminal fluid does
not suggest that patients on multidrug treatments no longer need to
follow safe-sex precautions, Ho said. Other scientists at this
week's meeting are expected to present data suggesting that semen
does contain HIV particles, even in patients whose blood appears to
contain none.
<p>
   Another new finding from Ho's laboratory is that the immune
system of patients on long-term multidrug treatment is not actively
geared up to fight HIV, as it probably would be if the virus was
actively reproducing.
<p>
   ``It is justified to feel some degree of optimism,'' Ho said,
summing up these recent findings. However, he added, ``the
situation is neither black nor white. It's some shade of gray.''
</TEXT>
