<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0510 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CLINTON-EDUCATION-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CLINTON SEEKS SUPORT FOR EDUCATION INITIATIVE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ANN SCALES &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NORTHBROOK, Ill.  &MD;  Making the first trip of his second term,
President Clinton Wednesday took his bully pulpit to the classroom,
lecturing students and the nation about the importance of
education.
<p>
   In a visit to this affluent Chicago suburb, he praised local
student performance on an international science and math
achievement test and pointed to the exam as a national model.
<p>
   Both the trip and the speech served as symbols, not only of the
president's priorities but also of the way he intends to use his
office, campaigning not for votes but for public support for
government priorities such as education.
<p>
   Later, in Chicago, where many public schools are crumbling, test
scores are low, and class sizes, large, Clinton encouraged Mayor
Richard Daley and school board members to keep up their work on
education reforms, including creating charter schools.
<p>
   Clinton made a similar point during his speech at a packed field
house of 5,000 students, parents, teachers and administrators at
Glenbrook North High School.
<p>
   ``We have the best higher education system in the world; there's
no question about it,'' Clinton said. ``But we do not have the best
system of education in the world from start to finish for all our
children, and we cannot be satisfied until that is exactly what we
have in the United States of America.''
<p>
   Glenbrook North is part of a consortium of 20 school districts
in suburban Chicago that participated in last year's Third
International Math and Science study, which tested and ranked
fourth-, eighth- and 12th-grade students from 41 countries.
<p>
   U.S. students overall faired poorly on the test, with
eighth-graders ranking below average in math and slightly above
average in science when compared to the other countries. But
consortium eighth-graders scored first in science and second in
math, behind Singapore.
<p>
   Clinton, accompanied by Education Secretary Richard Riley, said
he hoped the students' success will ``reverberate all across
America.''
<p>
   The president called for other school districts and states to
adopt the international achievement test as a way to improve
teaching and learning of science and math. ``There is no better
model for what we were trying to do in the entire United States of
America than what you have done here,'' Clinton said.
<p>
   The Education Department has agreed to help as many as 60 states
and school districts participate in the 1997 and 1998 math and
science tests, and to use the results to improve teaching methods.
<p>
   Clinton's new budget, which will be submitted to Congress Feb.
6, will ask for a 26 percent increase in funding for Goals 2000,
his program to raise national education standards, from $491
million to $620 million, White House aides said.
<p>
   In addition, Clinton will propose to nearly double the funding
for charter schools from $51 million to $100 million.
</TEXT>
