<STORYID cat=i pri=u sel=taf-z> A9741 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1062 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PARLIAMENTARY RESOLUTION SEEKS YELTSIN'S REMOVAL &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By MICHAEL SPECTER &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   MOSCOW  &MD;  In a display of Russia's mounting restiveness about
President Boris Yeltsin's seemingly permanent absence from the
Kremlin, the Parliament voted overwhelmingly Wednesday evening for
a resolution to remove Yeltsin from his post because of his poor
health.
<p>
   The 229-63 vote in the Communist-dominated lower house has no
legal force, and it was instantly swamped in a confusing blizzard
of parliamentary maneuvers which will require a second vote on the
resolution before it is adopted.
<p>
   But after seven troubling months in which the president has been
far too sick to work, the measure reflects the growing sense that
an economically depressed Russia has a leader who may never again
be fully capable of carrying out the strenuous duties of his job.
<p>
   ``Either we agree to Russia's collapse as a nation or we try to
do something about it,'' said Viktor Ilyukhin, the Communist
legislator who initiated the resolution calling for Yeltsin, who
has double pneumonia, to be removed from office. ``We can no longer
sit and watch as our government is led by no one.''
<p>
   While opposition figures have often called on Yeltsin to be
removed, this was the first time the issue had been put to a vote.
<p>
   In the middle of the extraordinary debate on Yeltsin's health,
which lasted throughout the day, the president's press service
announced with great fanfare that he had defied his doctors and
traveled to the Kremlin to meet with Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin.
<p>
   But state television failed to broadcast even the usual brief
moment of the two men together Wednesday evening, and most news
shows openly questioned whether Yeltsin, who has not been seen by
the public since Jan. 6, did in fact make the trip.
<p>
   The president has appeared in the Kremlin only a few times since
he was re-elected last July and the country  &MD;  battered by a
depression that has left millions of workers and pensioners without
their salaries and stipends  &MD;  has increasingly viewed him as a
leader who rules in name alone. At first unwilling to exploit his
frailty, the Communists in the legislature have become increasingly
combative in the past month.
<p>
   That may be because recent polls have shown that the tide of
public opinion has turned sharply away from the president and his
administration. On Tuesday, Economics Minister Yevgeny Yasin
acknowledged that the government's economic reform program was not
working.
<p>
   ``One has to say it failed last year,'' he told the Parliament
as they discussed the budget. He said that while inflation dropped,
the ability of private companies to generate profits  &MD;  and pay
their taxes  &MD;  dropped far more precipitously.
<p>
   In November, Yeltsin underwent heart bypass surgery and while
recovering he developed pneumonia that his doctors have described
as ``moderately severe,'' and which they said has left him
``morally and emotionally'' upset.
<p>
   On Tuesday his chief physician said it would take at least two
weeks before the president, who turns 66 next month, could return
to his office. The doctor commented approvingly upon the fact that
the president went out for a short walk with his granddaughter.
<p>
   But Yeltsin was clearly unable to sit in silence as the members
of the national legislature talked about his health the way people
used to talk about Leonid Brezhnev, the doddering Soviet leader who
for years ruled this country despite poor health that left him all
but incapacitated.
<p>
   ``It is not that the vote will force the president to resign,''
said Stepan Kiselyov, a political commentator for the newspaper
Izvestiya. ``That will not happen. But they have shown the general
crisis of state power that becomes more and more obvious each day.
People wonder how bad Yeltsin's disease really is, and they wonder
how much longer we can follow his route from his apartment to the
Kremlin to the hospital and back.''
<p>
   The vote probably will do nothing to calm the country or heal
its visible wounds. If Yeltsin were unable to serve  &MD;  and only he
could make that decision according to the Constitution  &MD;  then
Chernomyrdin would assume his role for up to three months before
calling new elections.
<p>
   It is not clear who would benefit from new elections, however.
Voters are disgusted with the current government and would be
unlikely to support the prime minister if he ran. But they have
also shown their unwillingness to bring Communists back to power.
<p>
   The most popular politician in Russia, Alexander Lebed, is held
in deep suspicion by Communists and liberals alike.
<p>
   Visiting New York on Wednesday, Lebed, while dismissing the
parliamentary vote as ``more political noise,'' repeated his
frequent assertion that Yeltsin is incapable of governing. He said
he suspected that if Yeltsin did step down, Chernomyrdin and the
Communists would protect their vested interests in the status quo
by finding some pretext not to hold elections.
<p>
   Members of most liberal factions in the 450-member Parliament
walked out before Wednesday's vote because they did not want to
take part in what a liberal critic of the administration, Grigory
Yavlinsky, described as a ``political farce and provocation.''
<p>
   Yavlinsky demanded another vote on the entire bill, of which the
resolution was a part. It was a clever move. That vote failed, so
the resolution will have to be reconsidered, probably in a couple
of weeks.
<p>
   Galina Starovoytova, a well-known liberal member of Parliament
who has often been critical of the president, said, ``I would
suggest that this legislative body would be better off preparing a
resolution on the burial of the remains of Lenin. This is a cynical
display that shows this body to be of almost no value at all.''
<p>
   Even if the legislature does pass the resolution in its final
form, it would have no legal basis. Russia's constitution mandates
that the president has immense powers and that the Parliament has
few. The Parliament can tie up legislation  &MD;  and it does. But it
cannot easily prevent Yeltsin from ruling by decree and fiat  &MD; 
which he does.
<p>
   ``This is not government,'' said Yegor Gaidar, the free-market
economist who led Yeltsin's first attempts at reform. ``This is
idiocy. It is time that Russia grew up.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1958EST
</TRAILER>
