<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=tdt-z> A9742 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0980 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SEAN JONES: BRAINS AND BRAWN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BOB RYAN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  I can see how Sean Jones scares people.
<p>
   The Green Bay right defensive end is big, strong, experienced
and, worst of all, in possession of both a very active brain and an
even more active tongue. NFL people like it when their players are
smart enough to learn their assignments but not smart enough to
read the financial pages. Sean Jones owns his own financial
services company.
<p>
   This is a man who during the course of a distinguished 13-year
NFL career has sued both the league and the union. He's an equal
opportunity agitator. He is always secure in himself because he is
one of the few NFL players who knows that the nefarious ``they''
always need him more than he needs them. Sean Jones uses football,
not the other way around.
<p>
   Jones never intended to be a professional football player. After
spurning Cornell (``my mother wanted me to go there'') and Maryland
(``because of the lacrosse program''), he chose to attend
Northeastern because of the co-op program. He did his co-op work at
F.W. Woolworth's. He played his football at Parsons Field before
friends and Jack Grinold. There was never any doubt in his mind
which one was more important.
<p>
   ``I don't even know how the scouts found me, playing against
James Madison, UMass and URI, before, if we were lucky, a whopping
2,300,'' he says.
<p>
   But the scouts started coming around for workouts, and it was
clear to him that pro football was going to be an option. Even
then, he was far from ga-ga about the idea.
<p>
   ``I made up my mind that if I wasn't going to be drafted high, I
didn't even want to try,'' he says. ``I'm not going to sit here and
lie and say I always had an ambition to play pro ball and that this
was some kind of a `Rudy' situation. I just got lucky at the right
time. If I didn't play professional football, I was ready to go to
work.''
<p>
   The Raiders took him in the second round of the 1984 draft. At
training camp things weren't going so well and he figured,
``Woolworth's, here I come.'' Then someone informed him that no
team would give up quickly on a second-round draft pick. ``That's
when I decided I'd better take this job seriously,'' he explains.
<p>
   But at no point did he ever play scared.
<p>
   ``What was the worst that could happen?'' he asks. ``They'd cut
me, and I'd go to work? I'd already been doing that for four
years.''
<p>
   The Raiders gave him an attitude. ``The `Us vs. Them' thing
always stays with you,'' he says. He moved onto Houston, where he
learned conclusively that pure talent without application and order
is a waste.
<p>
   ``I was there six years, and in at least four of them we were
good enough to win the whole thing,'' he maintains. ``What went on
down there was a joke. We were the only AFC team with the
components needed to beat the NFC teams, and we squandered it. It's
not that way there now, but it was back then.''
<p>
   Ten years into his career, he signed with Green Bay. Ever the
pragmatist, he decided that, whatever Green Bay's perceived social
shortcomings for a black player, the football situation was
excellent, and it would be particularly enticing for the ``other''
defensive end; i.e, the one who wasn't Reggie White.
<p>
   ``You'd be playing with a guy who gets triple-teamed all the
time, and you'd get single-teamed?'' he inquires. ``That was a very
selfish motivation.''
<p>
   The black-white thing wasn't going to scare away Jamaican-born
Sean Jones.
<p>
   ``I don't look at simple differences between people as being
racist,'' he says. ``There can be differences without racism. And
let me say this: I was born in Jamaica and I was raised in New
Jersey. I've lived in Boston, Los Angeles and Houston. Green Bay is
the least racist place I've ever lived in.''
<p>
   He applauds the Green Bay organization for creating a pleasant
working circumstance for all of its players. The team imports a
barber from Milwaukee to cut the hair of the African-American
players. The team brings in soul food twice a week.
<p>
   ``I don't believe that every individual player should need to be
personally motivated to play,'' Jones says, ``but an organization
should do what it can to inspire players. Houston did a horrible
job at that, and it's a major reason why they never won a
championship. The people in Green Bay understand.''
<p>
   Long used to being misunderstood by ownership, coaches, media
and even teammates, Jones is classically amused by some of the
things he's been hearing during Super Bowl week. For example,
someone asked him if he considered this game to be a ``showcase''
for his talents.
<p>
   ``People who need to know me know me,'' he says. ``I know when
I've played well and when I haven't played well.''
<p>
   He has a clear understanding of taking the job seriously, as
opposed to taking the game seriously. ``I don't want people to
think football is who I am,'' he says. Jones knows that this is a
game where the end is always one play away, and he is ready for the
next life. Amaroq Financial Services (888-426-2762) is located in
Beverly Hills. He also manages a hedge fund called Daylight
Capital, and he has his own sports apparel company, DSI &AMP;
Associates.
<p>
   But there will be time enough for those ventures in the
offseason. Sean Jones has his mind on a football game to be played
Sunday at 6:18 p.m EDT.
<p>
   ``Getting here is fantastic,'' he says, ``but leaving here
without a ring would be crazy.
<p>
   ``I hope no one misunderstands, but the subject of the ring is
personal. It is important for me to get this ring. Me. Not Reggie
White or anybody else. If you say, `You won it, but only one guy
can get this ring,' I would want that one person to be me.''
<p>
   As I said, Sean Jones scares people.
<p>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1959EST
</TRAILER>
