<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9743 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-WEATHER-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0619 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SPACE-WEATHER-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; RESEARCHERS GET FIRST DETAILED LOOK AT MAGNETIC CLOUD FROM SUN &LR;  &QL; 
(sw) &QL; 
 &UR; By WARREN E. LEARY &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   GREENBELT, Md.  &MD;  The Sun released a giant cloud of magnetized
particles that researchers were able to monitor in detail for the
first time as it approached and swept past Earth this month,
scientists said on Wednesday.
<p>
   An international group of space scientists said that on Jan. 6
the Sun ejected a pocket of mass from its corona that developed
into a giant, tube-shaped magnetic bubble 30 million miles in
diameter that hit Earth almost four days later. The expanding cloud
of energized particles triggered a large storm in the magnetic
field, or magnetosphere, surrounding the planet. The storm
brightened the Northern Lights and possibly knocked out a
communications satellite.
<p>
   Speaking at a briefing here at NASA's Goddard Space Flight
Center, scientists said the mass eruption from the Sun was not so
unusual in itself. What was unusual, they said, was that the
eruption was spotted shortly after it occurred and tracked by space
satellites and Earth stations as it traveled the 93 million miles
to Earth and then passed the planet.
<p>
   ``This is not the first time it ever happened, and it is not the
greatest solar storm ever seen,'' said Dr. Stephen Maran, a NASA
astronomer. ``What it is, is the first time that one of these
events has been captured sort of cradle to grave.''
<p>
   Being able to track this month's event raises hopes of one day
having an early warning system of satellites and ground stations to
detect possibly destructive solar events, the researchers said.
<p>
   Previously, researchers have monitored parts of solar eruptions
and storms at different stages of development, often without
clearly seeing the cause of an observed effect and the evolution of
the phenomenon in between, scientists said.
<p>
   ``Up till now, it's been a little like the fable of three blind
men trying to describe an elephant,'' Maran continued. ``What you
are dealing with here is an elephant millions of miles long,
traveling at a million miles per hour.''
<p>
   What was different about the burst of mass that erupted from the
Sun on Jan. 6 was that the event was recorded as part of the
International Solar Terrestrial Physics Program. This time, more
than 20 satellites operated by the United States, the European
Space Agency, Japan and other nations were in position and
scientists were prepared to observe such an event, researchers
said.
<p>
   Dr. Barbara Thompson, a Goddard scientist, said researchers
attending a workshop on Jan. 7 noticed a solar event in data they
were reviewing that had occurred the day before. The scientists
interpreted the event, noticed by a new United States-European
spacecraft called the Solar and Heliospheric Observatory, or SOHO,
as one that could reach Earth.
<p>
   On Jan. 10, SOHO, which was a million miles from Earth in an
orbit between the gravitational fields of the Sun and Earth,
observed the magnetic event. It was soon picked up by other
satellites closer to Earth, Dr. Thompson said. SOHO measured an
increase of more than 20 percent in the speed of the solar wind
flowing from the Sun, clocking the passing bubble at 962,000 mph.
<p>
   Researchers said there was no proof that the solar storm caused
any damage, but such events can cause disruptions on Earth by
overloading communications and power-generation facilities or
damaging delicate electrical equipment, such as space satellites.
<p>
   Scientists said they did not know if this month's event caused
the failure, early on Jan. 11, of AT&AMP;T's Telstar 401 communications
satellite, but it occurred during magnetic storms above Earth.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 1959EST
</TRAILER>
