<DOCID> nyt970122.0661 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=taf-z> A9744 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CHILDS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0716 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BKN-KNICKS-CHILDS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CHILDS SAYS SOCIALIZING IS NOT PATH TO VICTORY &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By MIKE WISE &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   INDIANAPOLIS  &MD;  Chris Childs considers it a great honor to start
at point guard for the Knicks. He knows with that responsibility
sometimes comes the unenviable chore of letting his teammates know
what he believes to be the truth, even if they do not want to hear
it.
<p>
   Still bothered by an 88-87 loss to Chicago on Tuesday night at
the United Center, the team's floor leader tried to become its
locker-room conscience Wednesday. He never mentioned names, but he
basically said the Knicks need to stop the socializing and shelve
the popularity contests when they step on the floor.
<p>
   It is a refrain that has been echoed by Coach Jeff Van Gundy and
Charles Oakley at different times this season, but Childs tried to
drive it home strongly Wednesday afternoon.
<p>
   He was sitting on a bench at Butler University, where he and the
Knicks' two other point guards, Charlie Ward and Scott Brooks, had
just finished mopping the floor with John Wallace, Walter McCarty
and Dontae Jones, the team's three 6-foot-7-and-over rookies.
Twelve hours after Childs had been jawing with Michael Jordan, he
was talking trash to Jones.
<p>
   He wishes everyone on his team felt this way about every
opponent. Asked why he was so upset after the Knicks nearly pulled
out the victory, Childs replied: ``Just everything. The way we
played down the stretch, the way they played, the way they were
talking, and only a few guys talking back.
<p>
   ``We're just too nice right now. Smiling. Being friendly on the
court. That's not the way to go about it. I didn't like that. Like
I said after the game, when we step between these lines, it's a
war. You have friends, whatever, you can be friends after the game.
Once you come to the arena, 6:30, 6 o'clock whatever, your focus
should just be on our team, us against, you know, the world,
because it's us against everybody in that stadium.''
<p>
   New York has lost three of its last four road games. The Knicks
meet the Pacers on Thursday night at Market Square Arena and
Charlotte on Friday at the Charlotte Coliseum before facing Miami
Sunday at Madison Square Garden. Those games wrap up what Van Gundy
tabbed the most critical stretch for his team thus far in the
regular season, an eight-game, 13-day gauntlet.
<p>
   ``When we step out on the court as a whole  &MD;  it's not an
individual thing, I mean as a team  &MD;  we didn't have that fire and
desire to just go out there and ... us against the world,'' Childs
said, alluding to the Bulls game. ``Because if we did, they got too
many easy layups in transition, without anybody challenging them or
hitting them. When we went to the basket, they were pounding us.''
<p>
   Childs said some of the Knicks ``take that type of approach,''
but not enough of them. ``We have to get back to being nasty, not
dirty. Just being nasty, having that aura when we step out there so
teams fear coming to the basket, teams fear playing against us.''
<p>
   Larry Johnson has been known to fraternize often with opposing
players. On occasion, Patrick Ewing has done the same thing.
Whether that translates to either player going after a loose ball
with the same fervor is better answered by a behavioral
psychologist.
<p>
   As for Allan Houston, well, it is not in his personality profile
to grate on anyone. Asked what the solution was, Childs said:
``Maybe he needs to eat some onions, do something. He's our silent
assassin. He has that inner strength that needs to come out. I
think he's starting to figure out that a guy like Mike, who has
that killer instinct when he's going up against him, he has to have
that same type of mentality. It'll come out of him.''
<p>
   Consequently, a trend of disrespecting the new-look Knicks has
gained impetus in the past few weeks. Charles Barkley said last
week that John Starks is a better shooter than Houston, Scottie
Pippen said after the game on Tuesday night that Anthony Mason gave
them more presence than Johnson.
<p>
   Everyone in the league but David Stern, it seems, has analyzed
them.
<p>
   ``If we would've beat them, you think they would have still
talked?'' Childs said of Pippen's comments. ``Next time we play
them, we'll have to shut them up.''
</TEXT>
