<SLUG> BC-PERU-HOSTAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0619 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PERU-HOSTAGES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GUNFIRE RAISES TENSIONS IN PERU HOSTAGE CRISIS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By CALVIN SIMS &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   LIMA, Peru  &MD;  Tensions remained high at the Japanese ambassador's
residence here Wednesday after guerrillas holding 73 hostages
inside fired shots into the air during the night, presumably to
scare off policemen who were conducting maneuvers outside the
compound.
<p>
   The Tupac Amaru rebels have fired shots from automatic weapons
on at least four occasions in recent weeks, saying they were
warning the police not to come too close to the residence.
<p>
   But the gunfire shortly after midnight has raised fears that the
police exercises are a harbinger of a government plan to raid the
residence or that the maneuvers could provoke the rebels to kill
some hostages.
<p>
   While the government of President Alberto Fujimori has said it
is committed to finding a peaceful resolution to the 36-day-old
hostage crisis, it has undertaken a seemingly contradictory
strategy of taunting the guerrillas in recent weeks.
<p>
   ``Fujimori is employing a textbook strategy to dealing with
long-term hostage takers  &MD;  applying psychological pressure,'' said
a Western diplomat who requested anonymity.
<p>
   ``This is a fairly dangerous thing to do in this particular
situation because it increases the prospects for bloodshed,'' the
diplomat said.
<p>
   A larger-than-usual number of police officers, special military
forces, and SWAT teams were visible Wednesday in the streets
surrounding the Japanese residence.
<p>
   ``All of these new police worry me,'' said Guillermo Sarmiento,
a street vendor who sells ice cream near the residence. ``I think
they are planning an action of some type. But it doesn't make sense
because we've come so far without anyone being killed yet.''
<p>
   In recent days, the police have ordered photographers perched on
roofs near the residence to leave their positions and move behind
newly established police lines several blocks from the residence.
<p>
   The police have also taunted the rebels by throwing debris over
the compound wall and opening and closing wall doors that lead to
the residence's garden.
<p>
   The Tupac Amaru rebels are reportedly heavily armed with
automatic weapons and rocket launchers, and they have placed mines
and booby traps within the compound and the house.
<p>
   An official of Peru's antiterrorism police, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the government had no plans to storm
the residence unless the rebels begin killing hostages.
<p>
   ``Of course, a plan has been devised to take back the residence,
but at this point we have no intention of using it unless we are
forced to,'' the official said.
<p>
   The government's plan to establish a special commission to
negotiate an end to the crisis appears to be stalled. While the
rebels and the government have reportedly agreed to the
commission's makeup, no place or date has been announced for the
first negotiating session. The rebels are asking for the release of
their comrades from Peruvian jails, something the government has
said it will never agree to.
<p>
   Local newspapers reported Wednesday that members of the
International Committee of the Red Cross have begun advising
hostages during their daily visits to the Japanese ambassador's
residence that the crisis could take much longer they had initially
expected. A spokeswoman for the Red Cross declined to comment on
those reports.
<p>
   But the Red Cross acknowledged receiving a donation of 30
mattresses on Tuesday that are expected to be delivered to the
residence. Most of the 73 hostages who are still being held in the
residence  &MD;  out of several hundred taken prisoner Dec. 17  &MD;  sleep
on the floor.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2003EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
