<DOCID> nyt970122.0665 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tdt-z> A9748 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MAMMOGRAM-ACCURACY-BO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0844 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MAMMOGRAM-ACCURACY-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SCIENTISTS SEEK TO RESOLVE MAMMOGRAM TEST CONTROVERSY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By RICHARD SALTUS &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   BETHESDA, Md.  &MD;  In a marathon session, a panel of 13 scientists
worked to hammer out an answer to a health question that vexes
millions of women: Should they start getting screening mammograms
for breast cancer in their 40s, or not until they're 50 or older?
<p>
   The panel, which heard complex and often conflicting evidence
from 32 specialists over a day and a half, is charged with arriving
at a consensus today to help guide doctors and patients through an
issue clouded by confusion and controversy.
<p>
   There's little argument that women 50 and above reduce their
chances of dying from breast cancer by having annual mammograms,
which can detect tumors too small to be felt. What is hotly debated
is the effectiveness of routine mammograms for women in their 40s,
who have a lower risk of breast cancer to begin with and for whom
mammography is less effective.
<p>
   Researchers from Sweden came to the Consensus Development
Conference, convened by the National Institutes of Health, to
present their most recent results from large-scale trials. It was
these findings, which bolster the case that screening can reduce
breast cancer deaths in 40- to 49-year-old women, that prompted the
decision to hold the conference.
<p>
   Earlier data long ago persuaded a number of organizations,
including the American Cancer Society, to recommend screening at
one- or two-year intervals for women in their 40s. But in 1993, the
National Cancer Institute, a branch of the NIH, broke ranks and
withdrew its support for screening this age group, saying there is
too little statistically significant evidence to justify it.
<p>
   Another argument against routinely screening women in their 40s
is that mammograms often detect apparent abnormalities that lead to
further costly, painful and anxiety-provoking tests, including
surgical biopsies, only to determine that the lesion is not a
tumor. The rate of these ``false positives'' is higher among
younger women, according to many studies.
<p>
   The situation has left women and physicians in a quandary.
<p>
   ``I think it's been very disruptive and very confusing to
women,'' said Dr. David Rosenthal, director of health services for
Harvard University and president-elect of the Cancer Society, in a
recent interview. Rosenthal argued that there is now ``strong
evidence'' to support screening for younger women, but he said
``it's going to be damn hard for them (NCI) to back down from this
position.''
<p>
   Beginning at noon Wednesday, the 13 panel members  &MD;  doctors,
statisticians, academic researchers, lay people and activists  &MD; 
went into seclusion to begin sorting through the latest data.
<p>
   The new reports include one from Gothenburg, Sweden, showing a
44 percent decrease in breast cancer deaths among women in their
40s who were screened.
<p>
   Despite this and other data that tended to favor screening, it
was by no means evident which way the panel was leaning. Even the
Swedish researchers said it was an agonizing decision. In that
country, the issue is left up to county health departments, and
counties are about evenly divided on the question, said one
researcher.
<p>
   ``It's a very difficult problem and the balance is about even,''
said Ingvar Andersson, a radiologist from Malmo, Sweden, in an
interview.
<p>
   The strongest evidence on the benefits of screening older women
comes from large-scale trials, in the United States, Canada and
Sweden, that found a 30 percent reduction in breast cancer deaths
among women ages 50 and above. The great majority of breast cancers
occur at older ages, and X-rays of older women's breasts are
generally easier to interpret. In addition, tumors grow more slowly
in older women, so screening has a greater chance of catching them
before the cancer has spread.
<p>
   However, an estimated 33,400 new cases of cancer occurred last
year in women in their 40s  &MD;  about 18 percent of all breast
cancers. More than 5,000 will die of their disease. Still, because
those numbers are relatively small compared to the overall toll of
breast cancer, it has taken many years for clinical trials to
accumulate evidence on effectiveness. In part, however, this is
because earlier studies weren't designed to look at screening in
this age group.
<p>
   The report from Gothenburg showed the largest benefit to date.
Dr. Nils Bjurstam, a radiologist who headed the Gothenburg study,
said that after 12 years of follow-up, during which one group of
women in their 40s was screened five times, there were 44 percent
fewer deaths in that group compared with an unscreened control
group.
<p>
   Noting that the women had mammograms every 18 months, he said,
``I think the benefit would be greater with more frequent
screening.''
<p>
   One of the few points of agreement at the conference was that if
younger women are to be screened, it should be done every year,
because tumors grow faster at younger ages.
</TEXT>
