<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; NO WALLFLOWERS AT THE PARTIE &LR; S
<p>
   Who attended what party the night of the inaugural balls? The
Washington Post has kindly provided rosters for some of more
exclusive events:
<p>
    &MD;  At the Four Seasons Hotel, San Francisco Mayor  &UR; Willie &LR; 
 &UR; Brown &LR;  dined as a guest of L.A. businessman  &UR; Eli Broad &LR; , whose
other guests included singer  &UR; Jessye Norman &LR; ; Ambassador  &UR; Pamela &LR; 
 &UR; Harriman &LR; ; Senators  &UR; Dianne Feinstein &LR;  and  &UR; Barbara Boxer &LR; ;
Massachusetts Democrat Senators  &UR; John Kerry &LR;  and  &UR; Ted Kennedy &LR; ;
artist  &UR; Roy Lichtenstein &LR; ; and Commerce secretary nominee  &UR; Bill &LR; 
 &UR; Daley &LR; .
<p>
    &MD;  Also at the Four Seasons, actor  &UR; Ron Silver &LR;  and consultant
 &UR; Ken Duberstein &LR;  and his wife hosted a soiree that included the
 &UR; Colin Powells &LR; ; House Budget Committee Chairman  &UR; John Kasich &LR;  and
his fiancee; Defense secretary nominee  &UR; Bill Cohen  &LR; and his wife,
TV personality  &UR; Janet Langhart &LR; ; Nebraska Democrat Senator  &UR; Bob &LR; 
 &UR; Kerrey;  &LR; pollster  &UR; Frank Luntz &LR; ; and  &UR; Elaine Kamarck &LR; , adviser to
 &UR; Al Gore &LR; .
<p>
    &MD;  The show-business crowd at a party thrown by lobbyist  &UR; Liz &LR; 
 &UR; Robbins &LR;  included  &UR; Antonio Banderas &LR;  and  &UR; Melanie Griffith &LR;  (both
wearing blue jeans);  &UR; Michael Douglas &LR; ;  &UR; Jimmy Smits &LR; ;  &UR; James &LR; 
 &UR; Naughton &LR; ,  &UR; Kenny G &LR; ;  &UR; Lauren Hutton &LR; ,  &UR; Peter Jennings  &LR; and  &UR; Judy &LR; 
 &UR; Woodruff &LR; .
<p>
    &MD;  In the lobby of the Watergate hotel,  &UR; Stevie Wonder &LR;  began
playing the piano and singing at 2 a.m., and quit two hours later.
<p>
    &UR; BEHIND THE D.C. CURTAIN &LR; 
<p>
    &UR; Bob Barnett &LR;  of the Washington law firm of Williams &AMP; Connelly
is a friend of the loud and powerful, especially when they're
changing jobs. According to the latest GQ, Barnett has lately been
busy exploring the terms of employment opportunities for former
government glitterati  &UR; Lynn Martin &LR; ,  &UR; William Bennett &LR; ,
 &UR; Laura Tyson &LR; ,  &UR; Sam Nunn &LR;  and  &UR; George Stephanopoulos &LR; .
<p>
   Barnett helped Stephanopoulos get a book contract. Also, ``I did
his teaching deal at Columbia University. I've already done his
speaker's deal. I'll also be doing his deal with one of the
networks. ... After the first of the year, I'll add a fifth leg  &MD; 
print media. Possibly a magazine contributing editor.''
<p>
   Barnett also represents about 300 media clients, including
 &UR; Wolf Blitzer &LR; , Judy Woodruff,  &UR; Cokie Roberts &LR; ,  &UR; Andrea Mitchell &LR; 
and  &UR; Sam Donaldson &LR; .
<p>
   ``He's not an agent in the traditional sense,'' said Donaldson
of his lawyer. ``He doesn't hawk you around from network to pillar
to post. ... He's a great lawyer. ... Who wants to sit there and
have (ABC President)  &UR; Roone &LR;  ( &UR; Arledge &LR; ) tell me in a nice way that
I'm lucky to have my job? I shouldn't have to do that!
<p>
   ``I want to jump up and tell Roone that I'm better than
 &UR; Barbara  &LR; and  &UR; Diane  &LR; and  &UR; Peter &LR;  put together! Well, I can't do
that. But Bob can. And he does!''
<p>
    &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR; 
<p>
   ``On TV, they make blurry squares, but a live audience would
suffer.''
<p>
    &MD;  &LR;   &UR; E &LR; , lead singer of the Eels, telling Rolling Stone why they
wore pajamas instead of performing naked in a recent concert.
<p>
    &LR;   &LR;  ``If I were starting life over again, I am inclined to think
that I would go into the advertising business. ... This is because
advertising has come to cover the whole range of human needs and
also because it combines real imagination with a deep study of
human psychology. ... The general raising of the standards of
modern civilization among all groups of people during the past
half-century would have been impossible without the spreading of
the knowledge of higher standards by means of advertising.''
<p>
    &MD;   &UR; Franklin Delano Roosevelt &LR; , quoted in Advertising Age.
<p>
    &UR; YOU CAN STOP HOPPING NOW, FRANK &LR; 
<p>
   The whereabouts of former San Francisco Mayor  &UR; Frank &LR; 
 &UR; Jordan &LR; 's shoe are revealed at last in the latest issue of
Preservation, the magazine of the National Trust for Historic
Preservation.
<p>
   Jordan lost the shoe, says a story about  &UR; Trevor Hailey &LR; 's
``Cruisin' the Castro'' tours, in 1991, hurrying away from a
demonstration in the Castro. Jordan was running for mayor at the
time, and Governor  &UR; Pete Wilson &LR;  had vetoed a bill banning
employment discrimination against gays and lesbians.
<p>
   Candidate Jordan showed up in the Castro hoping to ``court gay
voters,'' as community-based historian  &UR; Gerard Koskovich &LR;  recalls.
``But on his watch as chief, there had been numerous anti-gay
outrages by the San Francisco police, and he was set upon. He left
so fast he ran out of one of his loafers.''
<p>
   The shoe was picked up by a demonstrator who donated it to the
Gay and Lesbian Historical Society. Visitors who want to see it
should ask for an archival box labeled ``Trophies.''
</TEXT>
