<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ISRAEL-MORDECHAI-ART-1000-2TAKES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; YITZHAK MORDECHAI: FORMER GENERAL TAKES ON POPULAR, PROBLEM-SOLVING
ROLE &LR;  &QL; 
(ART ADV: Photo of Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai is being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By SERGE SCHMEMANN &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   TEL AVIV, Israel  &MD;  Nobody would deny that Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai has the least political experience and the least
ideological baggage in the Israeli Cabinet.
<p>
   He is a political rookie, a recently retired general who joined
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's Likud Party only a few months
before the election last spring that brought it back into power.
<p>
   In a government leaning heavily to the right, he is conspicuous
as a moderate, a minister who battled the hawks in the Cabinet for
an agreement on a partial Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank
city of Hebron with the argument, ``Because of some dump in Hebron,
should we set the whole region on fire?''
<p>
   But Mordechai, 52, has emerged from the tumult of the last seven
months as the key problem-solver in the government and as the most
popular member of it.
<p>
   Though largely excluded from the Hebron negotiations at first,
he plunged into the last round, which culminated in a deal last
week, to wrap up the security and civil agreements.
<p>
   While some of his colleagues still bristle at the very sight of
Yasser Arafat, Mordechai had no trouble referring to the
Palestinian leader by his fighting name, Abu Ammar, in private and
in public, or speaking of Palestinian rights as something to be
taken into account.
<p>
   At the same time he has become the government's point man in
dealing with Jewish settlers in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, and
has maintained a measure of credibility with them. Last month,
residents of the Beit El settlement agreed to dismantle an illegal
trailer camp they had set up on a West Bank hilltop, and thus
avoided a confrontation with the army, when they were promised a
meeting with Mordechai.
<p>
   With Israeli-Egyptian ties at a low, Mordechai went to Egypt
last month and, according to Western diplomats there, forged a good
personal bond with President Hosni Mubarak. He will soon travel to
Jordan to meet with King Hussein, and he said he was calling daily
on the leaders of Syria to get down to the negotiating table.
<p>
   Not surprisingly, he has become a favorite of the Clinton
administration, which has been trying to get the Netanyahu
government to move faster on making peace with its neighbors.
<p>
   Public opinion polls have consistently ranked him the most
popular minister in the government, well ahead of Netanyahu. It is
noteworthy that his rating surged to a new high shortly after his
``dump in Hebron'' comment, suggesting that what many Israelis
liked about him was his readiness to cut through the ideology and
get to a deal.
<p>
   All that puts the short and stocky Mordechai squarely in the
classic Israeli mold of the warrior-statesman, men like Yitzhak
Rabin or Moshe Dayan who were trusted to talk of peace because they
had gone through the cauldron of war. Though short on political
experience, his 33 years in the army are still the sort of
background Israelis prefer when it comes to the vital questions of
making deals with the Arabs.
<p>
   Interviewed in his office in the Defense Ministry, Mordechai
told how his experience of battle had molded his attitude toward
peace. He said that during his visit to Egypt in December, he got
together with Defense Minister Mohammed Hussein Tantawi, and soon
the two old soldiers discovered that they had once fought each
other.
<p>
   ``He had commanded an infantry battalion during the Yom Kippur
War in 1973 in the region of the bridgehead on the Suez Canal,''
Mordechai recalled in his limited but adequate English. ``I
commanded the Third Battalion, which attacked his battalion. We
both lost quite a lot of commanders and soldiers. We loved them so
much, and respected them so much, and both of us came to the
conclusion that we have to do all our best not to put our
commanders and units into war and not to lose so many people.''
<p>
   That is the sort of talk that still inspires more confidence
than political slogans, especially from a commander who fought in
all of Israel's modern wars and was renowned for his popularity
with the troops. His simple and practical declarations have been
especially welcome in a government that has often seemed lost
between ideology and hard realities.
<p>
   But Mordechai does not fault the Netanyahu government's
policies. ``To build peace takes a long time,'' he said. ``To
damage it can be done in a very short time. What I am trying to do,
what our government is trying to do in a few months, is to rebuild
the peace process and the negotiations with the Arab leaders and
how we can move forward with the peace process.''
<p>
   In the bitter debates in the Cabinet over Hebron, Mordechai did
not pretend that the agreement guaranteed the security of the
Jewish settlers, or that it would end all strife. His argument was
that it was a risk worth taking for the larger peace it might lead
to.
<p>
   ``We understand that we are putting some of our population in
the Hebron area, and not only there, in a weaker situation,'' he
said. ``I'd like to be honest: the main test of the agreement will
be how all the people play it in the area of Hebron. If all of them
understand that they have to build a new life in the new situation
in the area of Hebron, it can work. If there will be a problem in
the area of Hebron, that can damage all the peace process. That is
one of the reasons we needed time to make the agreement.''
<p>
   His strong advocacy of the 1993 and 1995 agreements that set
Israel on the path of conciliation with the Palestinians has
prompted political satirists to suggest that he might really belong
in the Labor Party, which negotiated the accords with the PLO. But
political analysts argue that it is not Mordechai's dovishness but
his pragmatic approach and his military credibility that really
account for his standing.
<p>
   ``From time to time we will have crises, but we have to more
forward,'' he said. ``Both sides have to be flexible. The
Palestinians have to understand what we can give them and what we
can't give them, not now and not for the future.
<p>
   ``I think we are giving to the Palestinians what no government
ever gave to the Palestinians  &MD;  not the Ottomans, not the Arabs,
not the British, not the French, not anybody. Israel is the first
government, the first power in the Middle East that tried to
support and give quite a lot of rights to the Palestinians. But we
can't allow that there will be a new army in the area of Israel,
and we can't allow that it will be a new power that can change the
situation of Israel.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</TEXT>
