<STORYID cat=i pri=u sel=taf-z> A9752 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MORDECHAI-ART- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0494 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ISRAEL-MORDECHAI-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TEL AVIV, Israel: situation of Israel.'' &LR; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   With Mordechai at the head of the Defense Ministry, which is
responsible for administering those parts of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip that Israel still occupies, the government has moved to lift
many of the restrictions on the Palestinians.
<p>
   The number of Palestinians allowed to work in Israel has been
steadily increased, and the movement of freight trucks in and out
of the Gaza Strip is back to its levels of a year ago, before a
wave of Palestinian suicide bombings prompted an Israeli cutoff of
most traffic with the territories. A road closed for the last two
years in Gaza because it runs near a small Jewish settlement has
been reopened.
<p>
   Mordechai has signaled that he will not automatically slap
severe restrictions on the Palestinians whenever there is tension.
After a young Israeli soldier opened fire on the Arab market in
Hebron on Jan. 1, Mordechai quickly went to Hebron and there met
with Palestinian leaders to find ways of preventing an explosion.
To their surprise, he lifted a curfew after only three hours.
<p>
   The Defense Ministry is also charged with issuing permits for
construction or expansion in the Jewish settlements in the West
Bank, and while the government has come under fire for various
statements and proposals, it has not in fact approved any new
settlements. Mordechai insists that it will not.
<p>
   ``There are government decisions that we are not going to build
new settlements, but the government decided at the same time we
have a right to support the settlements with what they need to
continue their life,'' he said.
<p>
   Mordechai's political emergence has come as something of a
surprise to many Israelis. Though he was courted by both parties
when he retired from the army in October 1995 for his popularity
with the troops and among his fellow Sephardic Jews  &MD;  he is a
Kurdish Jew by birth, the son of a rabbi who brought his family to
Israel from Iraq in 1949  &MD;  he was not regarded as someone destined
for a major political role.
<p>
   But he appears to have learned the ropes quickly. He blocked
Netanyahu's attempt to create a national security council, which
would have pre-empted much of the authority of the defense
minister.
<p>
   And as Netanyahu found himself in crisis after crisis,
Mordechai's steadiness and military experience brought him
increasingly to the fore. He was called on to calm tensions with
Syria after it moved troops closer to the Golan Heights, and then
to restore control after Palestinians rioted over the opening of a
tunnel in Old Jerusalem.
<p>
   Mordechai acknowledged that his plunge into politics was abrupt.
<p>
   ``But now I look forward to moving with our government and the
prime minister into the future,'' he said. ``It will be a lot of
problem in the future, but if all of us are strong enough to
understand what is the end, where we are going, we can achieve the
main goal.''
</TEXT>
