<SLUG> BC-FBN-OILERS-BROWN-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0260 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-OILERS-BROWN-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; OILERS NAME BROWN SECONDARY COACH; RE-SIGN THREE ASSISTANTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Erik Matuszewski &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Houston, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- The Houston Oilers named former
San Diego Chargers assistant Greg Brown their new secondary coach,
the team said.
<p>
   Brown, 39, joins the Oilers after spending two seasons in San
Diego, where he helped the Chargers' secondary improve from 22nd in
the NFL in 1994 to 12th in 1995.
<p>
   Before joining the Chargers, Brown served one season as the
secondary coach for the Atlanta Falcons in 1994, when the team tied
for second in the NFL with 23 interceptions.
<p>
   Brown also spent three seasons (1991-93) as the secondary coach
at the University of Colorado. During his time with the Buffaloes,
he helped tutor two players, Deon Figures and Chris Hudson, who
both went on to win Jim Thorpe Awards as the U.S.'s top collegiate
defensive back.
<p>
   In his first NFL coaching stint, Brown worked three seasons with
the Tampa Bay Buccaneers from 1984-86. He was the defensive
assistant to the Buccaneers' secondary in 1984, the team's quality
control and assistant quarterbacks coach in 1985 and tight ends
coach in 1986.
<p>
   In addition, the Oilers said that assistant coaches Alan Lowry,
Mike Munchak and Russ Purnell will all return for the 1997 season.
<p>
   Lowry will serve as wide receivers coach, Munchak will work one
of the two coaching positions with the offensive line and Purnell
will stay on as the Oilers' special teams coach.
</TEXT>
