<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=taf-z> A9758 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-UPJOHN-MARKETPLACE-NY </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0613 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-UPJOHN-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Mich.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MARKET PLACE: UPJOHN MAY BE BEST VALUE AMONG PHARMACEUTICAL
STOCKS &LR;  &QL; 
(kd) &QL; 
 &UR; By MILT FREUDENHEIM &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Most securities analysts were unhappy with Pharmacia
&AMP; Upjohn even before the surprise resignation this week of John L.
Zabriskie, the American chief executive of the multinational drug
maker. But a few contrarians saw a brighter side.
<p>
   The share price was already one of the cheapest in the
pharmaceutical sector and after Zabriskie quit it got even cheaper,
dropping $2.75, or 7 percent, on Monday and staying flat through
Wednesday, when it closed at $37.375, down $1.125 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
<p>
   ``It's a good value, great for bottom fishers,'' said Mariola
Haggar, an analyst in New York with Deutsche Morgan Grenfell. Ms.
Haggar said that based on projected 1997 profits, the price to
earnings ratio of Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn's stock was 6 percent below
the ratio of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, while drug stocks as a
group were trading at a 20 percent premium to the index.
<p>
   Analysts said the departure of the chief executive would make
little immediate difference to company operations, which are
decentralized and led by strong executives in Kalamazoo, Mich.,
Milan, Italy, and Stockholm.
<p>
   Critics said Zabriskie and his team of senior executives at
company headquarters in London did not push fast enough in knitting
together Upjohn and Pharmacia AB of Sweden in the 14 months since
they merged in November 1995 in a deal valued at $6.9 billion.
<p>
   But Hakan Astrom, a senior vice president, said the company had
cut about $200 million in annual operating costs last year and was
on track to squeeze out $225 million more in 1997, toward its 1998
goal of trimming $500 million.
<p>
   Admittedly looking for a ``silver lining,'' Viren Mehta, a
partner with Mehta &AMP; Isaly, a health care investing firm, projected
three years of annual earnings growth of 17 to 18 percent, from ``a
low base of earnings numbers after a disappointing 1996.''
<p>
   Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn dismayed analysts by twice revising its
profit projections downward last year, most recently in October,
when the company said it had underestimated the adverse effects of
international currency rates. That produced ``a management
credibility issue and concern that management may not be on top of
all parts of the businesses,'' said Robert H. Uhl, an analyst with
Salomon Brothers.
<p>
   He said the stock price would ``remain stuck in the high 30s''
at least for the next three to six months, until problems resulting
from the merger and currency rates were resolved and a new chief
executive named.
<p>
   Sales have been flat but new drug approvals may help. The
company obtained Food and Drug Administration approvals last year
for Xalatan, a treatment for glaucoma, and Camptosar for colon and
rectal cancer, and it introduced Detrusitol, for urinary
incontinence, in Europe. The FDA also recently approved a
nonprescription version of Rogaine, Upjohn's treatment for
baldness. ``The research and development pipeline is beginning to
produce,'' Ms. Haggar said.
<p>
   Scott Shevick, analyst with Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co., classified the
company as ``the ultimate bomb shelter  &MD;  a stock that does not have
a lot of downside.''
<p>
   It will have lower risks than most other drug stocks if the
market sells off, but it will lag in an up market.'' He added:
``Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn has investor sentiment going against it. The
stock is probably going to be dead money for a while, although
there's a possibility that lightning could strike'' in the form of
outsiders attracted by the low price.
</TEXT>
