<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0664 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CREDIT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Argentina) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TREASURY PRICES IN RETREAT AS NOTES ARE AUCTIONED &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT HURTADO &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Treasury prices fell Wednesday, as market
participants wrestled with the first of two note auctions this
week, remarks by Federal Reserve officials and fresh economic data,
f The price of the 30-year Treasury bond fell 15/32 to 95 29/32.
The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the
price rose to 6.82 percent from 6.78 percent on Tuesday.
<p>
   Bond prices were briefly bolstered by a report that showed that
housing starts plunged 12.2 percent in December, a much sharper
than expected decline.
<p>
   ``Housing does appear to be slowing, but at a much more gradual
pace than indicated in today's numbers,'' said Donald Fine, chief
market analyst at Chase Asset Management.
<p>
   Still, he added, ``it may be some time before the current trend
in residential housing can be ascertained because of the continued
impact of the Western floods on the January data, to say nothing of
the subnormal temperatures throughout much of the nation.''
<p>
   The gains in bonds was short-lived, however, as remarks by a Fed
official showed how vulnerable and sensitive the market remains.
<p>
   In an interview Wednesday with the Market News service, Susan
Philips, a Federal Reserve governor, said she might not be willing
to wait for a rise in the ``core'' Consumer Price Index  &MD;  the index
excluding the volatile categories of food and energy  &MD;  before
calling for an increase in interest rates. Some analysts said her
remarks contradicted somewhat the tone of Alan Greenspan, the Fed
chairman, when he spoke before the Senate Budget Committee on
Tuesday.
<p>
   Another report Wednesday, the Federal Reserve's survey of
regional business conditions, known as the Beige book, had little
impact on the Treasury market. The report lacked the numbers to
warrant any inflation concern though it continued to show that wage
pressures are evident for specific skilled workers. Fine of Chase
Asset Management said it did not contain anything more than what
the Fed chairman has already said and merely summerized the last
four weeks of economic data.
<p>
   The Beige book report, however, did have one significant
surprise: it was released inadvertently over the Internet before
its scheduled 2 p.m. release. Traders said the early release might
have influenced the bidding for the new two-year issue, which
caused dealers to pay a higher premium than was expected.
<p>
   The notes were awarded at auction Wednesday at a high yield of
5.984 percent, up from 5.874 percent last month. Analysts said the
bidding was a bit above average and gave the market a brief boost.
<p>
   While the yield on the two's was lower than expected, traders
said it did not necessarily mean the auction was a complete
success, since the higher premium paid by dealers makes it that
more difficult to sell them at an even higher premium. And that
puts a lot of the pressure on the sale of Thursday's five-year note
auction. Some dealers have suggested that the five-year issue may
need a bit more of a concession before the auction takes place.
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   Securities firms said they had an easier time selling the $2
billion of 20-year global bonds by Argentina Wednesday, as
investors eager for higher yields jumped at the issue.
<p>
   The bonds were sold through underwriters led by Merrill Lynch
and J.P. Morgan at a price to yield 11.45 percent, or about 426.5
basis points more than the 6.75 percent Treasury note due on Aug.
15, 2026. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
<p>
   In when-issued trading Wednesday, the new five-year note was
being offered at a price to yield 6.31 percent, up 3 basis points
from the previous day. The Treasury's new inflation indexed
securities being sold next Wednesday were offered at a price to
yield 3.37 percent, up 5 basis points.
</TEXT>
