<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTS-ADS-MEDIA-NY </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0890 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ACCOUNTS-ADS-MEDIA-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Pa., Calif.;, Ill., Ohio) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ADVERTISING: CONSUMER GOODS MAKERS STEP UP AGENCY REVIEWS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By STUART ELLIOTT &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Account activity has been accelerating in the last week across
many consumer product categories. The agency changes and reviews
involve assignments, both domestic and international, with billings
estimated at more than $250 million.
<p>
   One big change was unexpected and came without a review. McNeil
Consumer Product Co., a division of Johnson &AMP; Johnson, moved the
account of its Nicotrol anti-smoking patch, with billings estimated
at $41 million, to the Health Care Connection unit of Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi Advertising in New York from DDB Needham New York.
<p>
   ``This is a complex marketplace, and we are doing some
consolidation of agencies worldwide,'' said Ronald Schmid, a
spokesman for McNeil in Fort Washington, Pa., who confirmed a
report of the change this week in Advertising Age.
<p>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, owned by Cordiant PLC, handles other McNeil
brands like Tylenol. DDB Needham New York, a unit of Omnicom Group,
had handled Nicotrol patches since 1995. A sibling brand, Nicotrol
nasal spray, remains at DDB Needham Toronto.
<p>
   Several offices of Grey Advertising benefited from decisions
made by advertisers in separate reviews.
<p>
   Grey's Los Angeles office was awarded a four-year contract, with
an optional one-year renewal, for the California Lottery. That
account, with billings estimated at $30 million annually, had been
handled by J. Walter Thompson San Francisco.
<p>
   Jeff Alperin, chief executive of Grey's Western division in Los
Angeles, said that decision came after a three-month review that
had been narrowed to Grey; Thompson San Francisco, part of the WPP
Group, and three other finalists: Asher/Gould in Los Angeles; Rogge
Effler &AMP; Partners in Los Angeles, and Young &AMP; Rubicam San
Francisco.
<p>
   And Globalstar LP, a mobile satellite telephone system in New
York that is managed by Loral Space and Communications Ltd., named
Grey's New York office and its sibling shops there as the first
agencies to handle its integrated account. Billings were estimated
at more than $10 million.
<p>
   Jeanette Clonan, a spokeswoman for Loral in New York, said that
Grey and siblings like the GCI Group public relations agency were
awarded the account after a two-month review. She declined to
identify the three other finalists.
<p>
   Offices of two large agencies owned by the Interpublic Group of
Companies and Cordiant were awarded sizable accounts abroad.
<p>
   Boots Healthcare International in Nottingham, England, has
further expanded its relationship with McCann-Erickson Worldwide,
part of Interpublic, by naming that agency to handle its Strepsils
brand of cough and throat lozenges worldwide. The account, with
billings estimated at $30 million, had been handled primarily by
BMP DDB Needham in London, owned by Omnicom.
<p>
   The McCann London office, which handles Nurofen ibuprofen for
Boots, will coordinate the Strepsils account. McCann London was
also named to handle Optrex eyewash for Boots in Britain and other
markets; that account, with billings that were not disclosed, had
also been handled by BMP DDB.
<p>
   And two offices of Nazca S&AMP;S, the Latin American network of the
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi Advertising unit of Cordiant, were awarded two
accounts with combined billings estimated at $25 million.
<p>
   BanCrecer, the fifth-largest Mexican bank, which is part of the
BanCrecer Financial Group in Mexico City, named Nazca S&AMP;S Mexico in
Mexico City to handle its account, which had been at Arellano in
Mexico City.
<p>
   Also, Toyota do Brasil SA in Sao Paulo named F/Nazca S&AMP;S in Sao
Paulo to handle its account, which had been at Fisher Justus in Sao
Paulo. The Nazca network handles Toyota accounts in Argentina,
Puerto Rico and Trinidad.
<p>
   Back in this country, the Hillshire Farm and Kahn's unit of Sara
Lee Corp. named four shops to compete for its account, with
billings estimated at $15 million. Ammirati Puris Lintas in New
York, a unit of Interpublic, handled the account for six years
until the division and the agency agreed to part last week.
<p>
   Kathleen L. Horner, the division's vice president for marketing
in Cincinnati, identified the participants as: D'Arcy Masius Benton
&AMP; Bowles in New York, a unit of MacManus Group; QLM in Princeton,
N.J.; Sive/Young &AMP; Rubicam in Cincinnati, and Euro RSCG Tatham in
Chicago, which is owned by Havas Advertising. A decision is
expected in mid-February, she said.
<p>
   And Autodesk Inc. in San Rafael, Calif., which sells design
software for PC's, began a review for its account, with billings
estimated at $5 million to $10 million. The account had been at
Anderson &AMP; Lembke in San Francisco, a unit of Interpublic.
<p>
   Rick Hooker, managing partner at Pile &AMP; Co. in Boston, a
consulting company handling the review, said Wednesday that seven
agencies had been invited to participate: CKS Partners in San
Francisco, a unit of CKS Group; Euro RSCG Dahlin Smith White in
Salt Lake City, part of Havas Advertising; the FCB Technology Group
of True North Communications in San Francisco; Hodskins Simone &AMP;
Searls in San Francisco; Poppe Tyson in Mountain View, Calif.,
owned by Bozell, Jacobs, Kenyon &AMP; Eckhardt, and Winkler McManus in
San Francisco.
</TEXT>
