<SLUG> BC-FTC-PIZZERIA-UNO-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0419 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FTC-PIZZERIA-UNO-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Mass.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PIZZERIA UNO TO WITHDRAW `LOW-FAT' CLAIMS &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; By MARIAN BURROS &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   One of the nation's leading restaurant chains, Pizzeria Uno, has
conceded that its previous advertisements for low-fat, thin-crust
pizzas were false and misleading, and has promised the Federal
Trade Commission not to make such claims again.
<p>
   Craig Miller, the president and chief executive officer of Uno
Restaurant Corp., said in a telephone interview that the company
had not thoroughly examined the federal definition of low fat as it
relates to its eight varieties of Thinzetta pizzas. ``This is not
something we intentionally did, and the FTC agreed,'' Miller said.
``Low-fat pizza is a pretty strong statement, and our Thinzettas
are not low fat. Only a few of them qualify.''
<p>
   The consent agreement with the FTC, which the company signed in
October, is not an admission of guilt; the company promises to stop
whatever it has been accused of doing.
<p>
   The company, which is based in Massachusetts and has 156 outlets
nationwide, ran a print advertising campaign in 1995 touting its
``low-fat thin-crust pizzas.'' A television commercial broadcast
during the same period referred to ``great tasting, low-fat,
thin-crust pizzas.''
<p>
   The commission said in a complaint filed last October that six
of the thin-crust pizzas, called Thinzettas, did not meet the
federal definition of low fat  &MD;  3 grams of fat per serving  &MD;  since
they contained 14 to 36 grams of fat per serving.
<p>
   ``The consumer needs to be able to rely on food and nutrition
claims,'' said Lee Peeler, the associate director for advertising
practices in the commission's Bureau of Consumer Protection.
``Around 1990, we started giving priority to these claims.''
<p>
   During the 1980s, the commission's enforcement activity dropped
dramatically; states' attorneys general took over much of the work.
Between 1980 and 1990, the commission settled only two cases of
deceptive advertising. Since 1990 the commission has settled 24
cases.
<p>
   In two recent cases, three companies that sell the dietary
supplement chromium picolinate signed consent agreements
acknowledging unsubstantiated claims about the product's ability to
help people lose weight. And Ross Products, a division of Abbott
Laboratories, signed a consent agreement in which it agreed it
would no longer make false and unsubstantiated claims about
doctors' recommendations for Ensure, a nutritional supplement.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2013EST
</TRAILER>
