<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9762 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NYU-RESTAURANT-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0211 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NYU-RESTAURANT-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NYU PLANS REVIVAL OF LUCHOW'S RESTAURANT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Amid a dormitory-building spree that has made it one
of the biggest developers in Greenwich Village, New York University
now finds itself in the position of trying to resurrect a ghost of
New York culture: Luchow's restaurant, the elegant German
restaurant and beer hall that became a cultural icon in the 1890s.
<p>
   NYU plans to build a dorm for 600 undergraduates at East 14th
Street and Irving Place, the site of Luchow's for 100 years,
starting in 1882. With that will be a street-level cafe, with Gay
'90s theme, one floor above a student cafeteria.
<p>
   ``The idea is to re-echo some of the past glory of 14th
Street,'' said Dr. L. Jay Oliva, the university's president. He
said NYU hopes to remind New York that 14th Street, now a cut-rate
shopping district, once was the epicentor of Manhattan cuisine and
clubbish culture, home not only to Luchow's but also to Delmonico's
and the Academy of Music.
<p>
   The cafe, to be called Luchow's if legal permission is obtained,
will include furniture and prints from the old restaurant, if they
can be found. Luchow's moved to midtown in 1982 and closed a few
years later.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2014EST
</TRAILER>
