<DOCID> nyt970122.0678 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=i pri=u sel=taf-z> A9764 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-CANADA-625&AMP;ADD-N </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1343 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CUBA-CANADA-625&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; A TOP CANADIAN VISITS CUBA, NETTLING WASHINGTON &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By ANTHONY DePALMA &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   HAVANA  &MD;  In a brief visit that clearly signaled the sharp
divisions between the United States and Canada over how to deal
with Cuba, Canada's foreign minister dined with President Fidel
Castro and other Cuban officials on Tuesday before signing joint
declarations Wednesday on human rights and foreign investment.
<p>
   In Washington, meanwhile, the State Department criticized the
overnight visit by Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy, the
highest-ranking Canadian to set foot in Cuba in more than 20 years.
<p>
   ``It doesn't make sense to reward a dictator in our hemisphere
who is completely behind the times,'' said the State Department
spokesman, Nicholas Burns, even before Axworthy had arrived in
Havana on Tuesday. ``You reward him by sending your foreign
minister down there, by having visits as usual, by trading. We
think that's wrong.''
<p>
   Wednesday, however, the State Department tempered its response,
with Burns expressing ``the highest personal respect for Minister
Axworthy.'' He reserved critical remarks for Cuba, voicing
skepticism that its government was prepared to take ``systematic
and meaningful steps that would lead to a transition to democratic
rule.''
<p>
   Axworthy, who has been a vocal critic of American policy toward
Cuba and the Clinton administration's attempt last year to toughen
its longstanding economic embargo by signing the Helms-Burton Act,
called the trip the culmination of a yearlong series of meetings
between senior Canadian and Cuban officials. He said it probably
signals even closer relations between the two countries, as Canada
tries to play a greater role in the hemisphere.
<p>
   ``Cuba comes up on our radar scope as a much higher priority
than before,'' Axworthy said in an interview Tuesday. ``Canadians
are discovering a whole new world south of our southern neighbor.''
<p>
   The substance of the visit consisted of a mildly worded joint
statement issued Wednesday before Axworthy's departure saying that
Canada would help Cuba do more to respect human rights, but
containing no mechanism to force the Cuban government to do so. The
countries agreed to cooperate on human rights by preparing seminars
and exchanging human rights experts. The statement also pledged
greater protection for foreign investments.
<p>
   But those declarations were secondary to the imagery of the
visit, which came just just hours after the end of festivities for
President Clinton's second inaugural.
<p>
   Axworthy spent much of the time meeting with Cuban Foreign
Minister Roberto Robaina. Robaina was clearly elated to be host to
the most senior Canadian official to be received in Havana since
Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau in 1976, a visit that was as much an
annoyance to the United States as this trip is now.
<p>
   ``Your country does not share the policy of isolation and
blockade,'' Robaina said to Axworthy at the start of the brief
working session that preceded the state dinner. ``And our country
is grateful for that.''
<p>
   Castro warmly welcomed Axworthy to the ornate Palace of the
Revolution for a formal dinner Tuesday evening of lobster cocktail
and baby lamb chops, topped off by expensive Cuban cigars.
<p>
   Castro also had lunch with the Canadian officials Wednesday
afternoon. Reporters were banned from both meetings, but as the
Cuban leader was leaving the Canadian ambassador's residence he
said that the visit had produced ``better understanding of each
other and lots of good conversation.''
<p>
   ``We talked of many thing, many things, but among friends,''
Castro said in pointed reference to the unwillingness of the United
States to deal directly with Cuba. ``Among friends you can talk
about everything.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   Earlier in the day, Axworthy had been taken by Cuban officials
to an oil-drilling operation in the beach resort of Varadero that
had been taken over recently by a Canadian company, Sherritt
International. A huge American-made Caterpillar motor sat there,
along with several mud pumps that were clearly marked as having
been made in the United States, all in Cuba in violation of the
economic blockade.
<p>
   Cuban Vice President Carlos Lage seemed to best capsulize the
importance of the visit when he said that the presence of the
American equipment at a Canadian project in Cuba showed how
ineffective the U.S. blockade had been.
<p>
   ``Canada is showing that it is possible to be a friend of the
United States and of Cuba too,'' Lage said.
<p>
   Canada and the United States have been at odds over Cuba since
the first days of the Cuban revolution 38 years ago. Washington has
tried to isolate Cuba and Castro diplomatically, while imposing
increasingly restrictive economic blockades.
<p>
   Clinton had shown signs of being willing to negotiate more
directly with Cuba until two Cuban MiGs shot down a pair of unarmed
civilian planes flown by anti-Castro dissidents from Miami in
February 1996. Under pressure from Cuban-Americans, the president
then shifted direction and signed the Helms-Burton Act, which seeks
to punish foreign businessmen, including Canadians, who do business
with Cuba.
<p>
   For its part, Canada never severed its diplomatic and commercial
ties with the island, arguing that close contact, rather than
isolation, would help move Cuba toward democracy.
<p>
   Canada enjoys a substantial and growing trade with Cuba, with
Canadian businesses investing in hotels, restaurants and other
businesses that have been closed to companies from the United
States.
<p>
   Last year, two-way trade between Canada and Cuba exceeded $430
million and was growing by more than 10 percent a year. Canada
sends down machinery, wheat and other products and buys lobsters,
sugar and nickel from Cuba.
<p>
   Canadians are also among the largest groups of tourists to Cuba,
with 156,000 visiting last year, a 10 percent increase over 1995.
<p>
   In addition, Canada provides financial support to several
non-governmental organizations in Cuba, including the Centro Felix
Varela, which lobbies for sustainable development and homosexual
rights, among other issues, but not broader political change.
<p>
   ``If what the U.S. Congress wants is to see changes take place
in Cuba  &MD;  and we support those changes, but go about it in a
different way  &MD;  I can't see what they have to complain about,''
Axworthy said.
<p>
   ``The whole thing is a ruse,'' said Marc Thiessen, a spokesman
for Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee and a sponsor of Helms-Burton. ``If Mr.
Axworthy thinks that coming away with a piece of paper signed by
Castro is going to make one bit of difference, then I have a bridge
I can sell him.``
<p>
   The Helms-Burton Act has created a rift between the United
States and its closest allies while prompting Cuban retaliation.
Earlier this month, Cuba passed tough new measures that would
punish any Americans who filed a suit under the Helms-Burton Act by
excluding them from any future compensation for expropriated
property.
<p>
   On Jan. 3, Clinton delayed for a second six-month period the
part of the act that would have allowed Cuban-Americans to file
such suits against foreign businessmen who have taken over property
once owned by American companies in Cuba.
<p>
   Canada has adopted measures to block the impact of the law. It
also has threatened to bring a complaint against the United States
because the Helms-Burton Act violates the North American Free Trade
Agreement, which guarantees free passage of businessmen in the
United States, Canada and Mexico, the three countries that signed
the agreement.
<p>
   Officials of Sherritt International have been denied entry to
the United States because the company runs a huge nickel-smelting
operation in Cuba that was owned by the American company
Freeport-McMoRan of New Orleans before the 1959 revolution.
<p>
   Axworthy said no decision had yet been made to go forward with
the complaint.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2015EST
</TRAILER>
