<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=taf-z> A9767 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-COHEN-CONFIRM-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0818 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-COHEN-CONFIRM-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Maine, Ariz., Conn., Idaho, Va., W.Va.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GOP'S COHEN CONFIRMED TO RUN DEFENSE DEPARTMENT &LR;  &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By CLIFFORD KRAUSS &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  The Senate confirmed William Cohen as defense
secretary by a 99-0 vote Wednesday after Cohen, the former
Republican senator, predicted at a good-natured confirmation
hearing that he would sometimes differ with President Clinton on
national security policy.
<p>
   Cohen, the only Republican in the new Cabinet, clung to
positions during the hearing that sometimes differed with Clinton's
over the last four years.
<p>
   Addressing the Armed Services Committee on which he served for
18 years, the former senator implicitly criticized the
administration for not establishing a definite ``exit strategy''
for U.S. forces in Bosnia. And he said he would resist any move to
trim the defense budget further.
<p>
   Still, he promised that he would work behind the scenes and be a
good team player. Trying to balance expressions of loyalty and
independence, Cohen said that he would not tinker with the
administration's most basic military doctrine of preparing to fight
for two major regional conflicts simultaneously but that he would
urge spending more for procurement of advanced weapons. He also
announced that he would travel to Europe in the next few weeks to
try to persuade allies of the United States to assume the full
burden of the Bosnia peacekeeping operation by the middle of next
year.
<p>
   ``Uniformity of opinion within an administration is not an
imperative nor even an ideal to be sought,'' he said in his
prepared remarks to the Senate Armed Services Committee. ``If I am
confirmed, I am certain that, on occasion, there will be
differences of views amongst us.''
<p>
   Cohen could hardly have faced a friendlier reception from a
panel he left after deciding not to seek re-election last year. His
Republican colleague from Maine, Sen. Olympia Snowe, noted that
``introducing Bill Cohen to the Armed Services Committee is a
little like introducing Cal Ripkin to the Baltimore Orioles.''
<p>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., teased Cohen about his
long-winded questioning as a senator and his taste for leather
bomber jackets when visiting military bases.
<p>
   Republican members repeatedly praised Clinton during the hearing
for selecting a Republican for what is commonly considered the
second-most-senior Cabinet post.
<p>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said it was ``an act of political
courage by the President to appoint a proven Republican warrior.''
<p>
   Sen. Dirk Kempthorne, R-Idaho, predicted that Clinton and Cohen
would have their share of disputes. ``It will not be easy for
either of you,'' he said, ``but it will be good for the country.''
<p>
   As a senator, Cohen sharply riticized the Clinton
administration's interventions in Haiti and Bosnia, along with the
expansion of the U.S. military mission in Somalia, without gaining
prior approval from Congress. He is taking to the Pentagon four of
his top Senate aides to form a Republican inner circle.
<p>
   Just hours after the hearing, Cohen was confirmed by a unanimous
vote, with only Sen. John D. Rockefeller 4th, D-W.Va., not present
to vote.
<p>
   In his spoken and written responses to questions from the Armed
Services Committee, Cohen gave ample hints of his priorities. He
said he wanted to expand NATO over the next several years to
include several countries of the former Warsaw Pact, but not
without fully consulting with Russia.
<p>
   He urged more spending on developing and acquiring high-tech
weapons systems, even if that means some further reductions in
force size. He said the proliferation of weapons of mass
destruction was the most serious threat the country faces.
<p>
   Cohen also expressed interest in combating international crime
and drug trafficking, two enemies the armed forces have not always
been eager to battle.
<p>
   He said the United States should not only maintain its troop
presence in Asia, but also expand ``our security engagement in the
region.''
<p>
   ``I intend to give new focus to our security relations in the
Asia-Pacific region,'' Cohen said. ``Beyond the near-term threat
from North Korea, our interests are potentially jeopardized by the
danger of instability and rivalry among major regional powers.''
<p>
   He pledged that U.S. servicemen would leave Bosnia in 18 months,
adding, ``we are not going to make an unlimited commitment to that
region.''
<p>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., sought firm assurances that the
administration would not further extend the U.S. military presence
in Bosnia past next spring. ``I really am concerned about a
situation, 18 months from now, where we say `Oh, by the way, our
European friends will not agree to remain if we leave, and we're
going to have to stay longer.' Does that scenario concern you?''
<p>
   Cohen responded, ``It does concern me, Senator McCain.''
</TEXT>
