<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BONDS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0292 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-JAPAN-BONDS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JAPANESE BONDS FALL AS DOLLAR REACHES 47-MONTH HIGH VS YEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Mark Tannenbaum &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Tokyo, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- Japanese bonds fell as the dollar
rose to a 47-month high versus the yen, dimming the allure of
yen-denominated assets.
<p>
   The dollar climbed to 119.32 yen this morning, pushed higher
after by U.S. economic strength and confidence other leading
industrial nations won't block its rise. The dollar last traded for
118.93 yen.
<p>
   ``The rapid pace of the yen's weakening is not positive for
domestic bonds,'' said Shinji Koyama, a manager at Toyo TB
Securities Co.
<p>
   The lead bond futures contract for March delivery was down 0.22
yen to 126 yen. The yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year
government bond rose 2 basis points to 2.41 percent.
<p>
   Shunji Sakami, chief strategist at LTCB Securities Co., said the
impact of the dollar's gains against the yen could be mitigated as
stock prices stabilize.
<p>
   This morning, the Nikkei 225 benchmark stock index was up 53.50
yen, or 0.3 percent, to 18,067 as electronics shares rose on the
stronger dollar.
<p>
   ``If confidence sets in that stocks won't fall much further
through the end of the fiscal year, concern over the need to lock
in returns from bonds will ease,'' he said.
<p>
   Sakami said comments yesterday from Bank of Japan Gov. Yasuo
Matsushita will likely have little impact on bonds this morning.
Matsushita, who was speaking after a gathering this week of the
central bank's branch managers, said the central bank will keep
interest rates low to bolster the economic recovery will
<p>
   The governor also said the economic recovery, while still
moderate, is gaining momentum.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
