<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=tdt-z> A9769 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0880 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMEDY OF THE ABSURD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DAN SHAUGHNESSY &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  Now this was embarrassing.
<p>
   Patriots coach Bill Parcells and owner Bob Kraft, pretending to
like one another, Wednesday put on one of the lamest shows in the
history of Super Bowl week.
<p>
   It was dumb and dumber. A real head-scratcher. Remember Admiral
James Stockdale opening a 1992 vice presidential debate by saying,
``Who am I, why am I here?''? That's what this was like.
<p>
   Football fans no doubt are tired of the ``Parcells is leaving''
topic. Most of the international media was ready to let it die. But
for some reason Kraft thought he could do a little soft-shoe
routine with Bill to diffuse the controversy and convince us that
they're really pals.
<p>
   So they came out with a shtick, like George Steinbrenner and the
late Billy Martin, or Jerry Jones and Jimmy Johnson.
<p>
   It was awful, a real groaner.
<p>
   Parcells spoke first. This is what he said:
<p>
   ``Bob and I thought we would address you kind of jointly here
for a minute and I'll stay on to answer any football questions that
you might have. You know, there's been a little bit, kind of
swirling around here, so my final statement is the same as it has
been  &MD;  Bob and I agreed a long time ago that we would go through
this year and we would discuss the situation about the future when
the season's over. And we're gonna do that as expeditiously as
possible and I also can assure you that it's going to be done in a
very civil and friendly manner. That was our agreement and that's
what we're gonna do as soon as this season's over. OK? Bob has a
little something to say to you.''
<p>
   Kraft moved to the microphone as Parcells stepped back. The
owner said:
<p>
   ``Thank you very much, Bill. I'm glad he set me up this way
because we negotiated all night and I'm happy to announce that Bill
Parcells will be the new manager, he signed a 10-year contract to
be the new manager of our paper and packaging group, Rand-Whitney
and International Forest Products. And because you know he manages
money so well, he also will be the chief executive of our Chestnut
Hill Management.
<p>
   ``It's meant a great deal to me that he's done that and I asked
for his input on our new sideline coach and his recommendation is
that it would be Mickey Corcoran as soon as he gets his knees done.
So it's really great to know that we have that kind of commitment.
<p>
   ``Also, I thanked him for one thing. With everything that has
been stirred up over the last week, three years ago and one day, we
bought the team, and here we are in the Super Bowl. There's a
pretty special karma going on and we're excited about it. And I
thank you for this opportunity.''
<p>
   We kept waiting. Where was the laugh track? Is this how Pat
Whitley and Marjorie Clapprood got started? Did Kraft actually
think this was funny or in any way a display of the close
owner-coach relationship?
<p>
   Kraft walked off the stage. Then Parcells went back to the mike
and actually tried to keep it going. Listen to this knee-slapper
from the Tuna:
<p>
   ``That's the last I'm saying about it. And I also say as the new
manager of  &MD;  what is the that name of that, Bob?  &MD;  my first
managerial decision will be to shut down the most productive plant
in Connecticut because of the high fringe benefit expenses that we
have down there, so we're just going to take the biggest production
plant right out ot play.
<p>
   ``Any football questions?''
<p>
   Whoa. That was it. What we all needed at this point was a
Patriot official to hand out paper bags to put over our heads. No
such luck.
<p>
   ``Which one was the dog and which one was the pony?'' a reporter
wondered aloud.
<p>
   Meanwhile, a Japanese TV crew asked, ``Who is this new coach,
Mickey Corcoran?'' (William ``Mickey'' Corcoran was Parcells' high
school basketball coach.)
<p>
   As Parcells fielded football questions, Kraft walked into the
wings and answered queries from TV crews.
<p>
   ``What was this all about?'' was the theme of the session.
<p>
   ``People have sort of intimated that we don't have a good
personal relationship,'' said Kraft. ``I just don't think that's
true. We've had a lot of fun together. We've had good times
together. Wednesday when we were chatting, and it seemed to get a
little intense, so people thought we didn't have a good time
together, he said, `Come on, why don't you join me at my press
conference tomorrow?' We said we'd do that. We've had fun together.
I don't think I've ever had a real serious argument with him in all
the time he's been here. It's basically an agent- and/or
media-induced topic.''
<p>
   Parcells' version, naturally, is different. He has told friends
that the joint session was Kraft's idea. It's hard to imagine that
the Tuna could have created this scene. But why allow himself to be
part of it?
<p>
   The coach and the owner might as well have been Larry Flynt and
Rev. Jerry Falwell. They could have been JFK and Lyndon Johnson.
<p>
   Frozen smiles and unfunny jokes won't help the situation. Kraft
has to start looking for a new coach. And he might want to hire a
joke writer before he tries another stunt like Wednesday's.
<p>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2024EST
</TRAILER>
