<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=taf-z> A9770 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-CONFIRM-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0771 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ALBRIGHT-CONFIRM-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SENATE CONFIRMS ALBRIGHT AS SECRETARY OF STATE &LR;  &QL; 
(sw) &QL; 
 &UR; By STEVEN ERLANGER &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  Madeleine Albright, who was confirmed on Wednesday
by the Senate as secretary of state by a vote of 99-0, has chosen
two highly experienced government hands for top jobs in the State
Department.
<p>
   Thomas Pickering, 65, the senior professional diplomat in the
Foreign Service, will return after a short retirement to become
under secretary for political affairs, the third-ranking job in the
State Department, Clinton administration officials said. He will
replace Peter Tarnoff.
<p>
   Stuart Eizenstat, 54, a Georgian who ran domestic policy for
President Carter and serves as under secretary of commerce for
international affairs, will become under secretary for economic
affairs in the State Department. He succeeds Joan Spero.
<p>
   Albright, 59, is expected to be sworn in by President Clinton on
Thursday, the first woman to be secretary of state. By choosing
people of such stature for the two appointments, she is understood
to be sending a signal to other government departments that she
intends that the State Department play the leading foreign-policy
role on issues like Mexico, China and Japan, which have had strong
economic components.
<p>
   The Senate vote ``signals a new era of bipartisan foreign
policy, and I can't wait to get started,'' Albright told reporters
at the American Mission to the United Nations in New York, where
she has been serving as American delegate.
<p>
   With Pickering, who had perhaps the most successful career of
any professional diplomat of his generation, Albright is sending an
encouraging message to the Foreign Service officers who are the
backbone of the State Department.
<p>
   Albright's predecessor, Warren Christopher, was sometimes
criticized for letting the Treasury and Commerce Departments, in
particular, take the dominant position in policy formulation toward
Asia and Latin America.
<p>
   Strobe Talbott, the deputy secretary of state, a close friend of
Clinton's and a prime architect of the administration's policy
toward the former Soviet Union and NATO, will remain in his post
for the present. Talbott, who has been managing the parallel task
of NATO expansion and negotiating a document governing NATO's
strategic relationship with Russia, is expected to stay at least
through July, when the alliance will announce its new members at a
Madrid summit conference.
<p>
   Pickering stepped down in November as ambassador to Russia after
more than 30 years with the State Department. He was first named an
ambassador in 1974, when he served in Jordan, and has also been
ambassador to Nigeria, El Salvador, Israel and the United Nations.
<p>
   Pickering returned to Washington to become director of the
Eurasia Foundation, a small, nonprofit organization that works with
the post-Soviet states. He is said to have agonized over leaving
the foundation so quickly, but both Albright and Clinton asked him
to take the new job, which he had sought before his retirement.
<p>
   Eizenstat, who has also served as American envoy to the European
Union, has recently been managing a difficult task: trying to
persuade the European Union, Canada, Mexico and other crucial
American allies to join Washington in isolating Fidel Castro's
Cuba, as called for in the Helms-Burton law, which the president
signed last year.
<p>
   While the European Union still objects to Washington's effort to
place sanctions on European companies and business executives for
otherwise legal trading ties to Cuba, Eizenstat has succeeded in
getting the Europeans to take a more vocal public stance against
Cuban human-rights abuses, enabling Clinton to renew a waiver of
the most contentious part of the law. That section would allow
American citizens to bring suit in American courts against foreign
companies that operate in property expropriated from Americans,
without compensation, when Castro took power nearly 40 years ago.
<p>
   In other important positions, Stanley Roth, who had served as
the Asia director in Clinton's National Security Council before
joining the U.S. Institute of Peace, a federally financed research
institute, is expected to be named assistant secretary for East
Asia, replacing Winston Lord.
<p>
   Albright's chief of staff will be Elaine Shocas, a former
federal prosecutor and counsel to the Senate Judiciary Committee,
who served her in the same job at the United Nations. Her spokesman
there, James Rubin, 36, a former aide to Sen. Joseph Biden Jr.,
D-Del., will become assistant secretary for public affairs.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2025EST
</TRAILER>
