<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9771 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPSON-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0837 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SIMPSON-SUIT-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SIMPSON'S LAWYER ACCUSES PLAINTIFFS OF SEEKING MONEY, NOT JUSTICE &LR;  &QL; 
(sw) &QL; 
 &UR; By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR. &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif.  &MD;  O.J. Simpson's lawyer asserted on
Wednesday that the families of Nicole Brown Simpson and her friend
Ronald Goldman were seeking money, not justice, when they filed
their wrongful-death suit against the former sports and
entertainment personality.
<p>
   ``This isn't a fight for justice but a fight about Mr. Simpson
transferring dollars,'' the lawyer, Robert Baker, said in winding
up his defense of Simpson in the four-month-long civil trial.
<p>
   In any case, Baker went on, the plaintiffs failed to make their
case, especially their promise to demonstrate that Simpson killed
the two in June 1994 in a rage over failure to reconcile with his
former wife.
<p>
   The case is set to go to the jury on Thursday.
<p>
   His final presentation sometimes laconically rambling, sometimes
tightly focused and tinged with emotion, Baker said that in their
effort to wring money from Simpson, the plaintiffs' lawyers had
``twisted'' just about every fact and and every piece of testimony
presented at the trial.
<p>
   ``If you find him not responsible,'' Baker told the jury, ``the
gravy train is over.''
<p>
   In their suit, the plaintiffs left it up to jurors to fix the
amount of money Simpson should pay in recompense should they
conclude that he committed the killings.
<p>
   Baker argued that there was an ``enormous gaping hole'' in the
case as presented by the plaintiffs' legal team, which wound up its
arguments earlier on Wednesday except for brief rebuttal on
Thursday.
<p>
   ``You can't put sympathy, passion and prejudice in your
verdict,'' Baker told the jury soon after the plaintiffs' lawyers
closed their arguments with poetic readings and saddening film and
sound bites of the murder victims.
<p>
   ``You have just been subjected to a ploy for your sympathy,''
Baker warned. ``We have witnessed character assassination. Give me
a break!''
<p>
   The plaintiffs, he said, may have argued emotionally but, he
insisted, had failed to make their case on a motive.
<p>
   ``There was no obsession,'' Baker insisted. ``That's a stretch,
a quantum leap. It's part of an effort by the plaintiffs to
demonize and manufacture a motive.''
<p>
   Then, arguing that Simpson could not have been at the crime
scene at the hour the plaintiffs had placed him, the lawyer offered
a bit of courtroom rhyme of his own.
<p>
   ``I'm no poet,'' he said, ``but obviously if you don't have time
you most certainly can't commit the crime.''
<p>
   Baker also argued that the plaintiffs had chosen to ignore
evidence offered by the defense team that the Los Angeles police
had bungled the Simpson investigation.
<p>
   ``They talk about the results of blood testing,'' he said,
sarcasm rising in his voice. ``We talk about contamination. What
did they do with that blood?''
<p>
   The earlier criminal trial, which ended in Simpson's acquittal
in October 1995, was tried along much the same lines as the civil
case and included occasional offerings of rhyme.
<p>
   Baker argued that police bungling, some of it perhaps
deliberate, had been a critical factor in the criminal case and
should also be a critical factor in the civil trial.
<p>
   ``I didn't hear one word about it from the plaintiffs,'' he
said, ``but it has been in this case from Day One. Police witnesses
have contradicted each other. They have lied from the witness
stand. There is an immense amount wrong with the evidence and
that's not going to go away because they don't want to talk about
it.''
<p>
   Earlier in the day, as the plaintiffs' lawyers ended their
closing arguments  &MD;  except for final, brief rebuttal on Thursday  &MD; 
the lead member of the team, Daniel Petrocelli, argued that
Simpson's guilt could be proved very easily.
<p>
   ``One drop of blood,'' he said, referring to analysis of blood
found at the slaying scene that indicated it had come from Simpson.
<p>
   ``You don't need any more than that,'' Petrocelli went on. ``He
is guilty. He is the killer. And he's got nowhere to run anymore.''
<p>
   Still, he presented more, including a list of some 60 witnesses
and documents that he argued would all have to be found to be
either liars or fakes in order for Simpson to be cleared. ``For him
to be believed,'' he said of Simpson, ``you have to disbelieve all
of it.''
<p>
   Noting that the jury, should it find Simpson guilty, would then
determine how much money he should pay the families of the victims
in recompense, he said:
<p>
   ``There is no amount of money that is ever going to repay for
what has been lost. True justice would be to see Ron Goldman walk
through the doors of this courtroom and to see Nicole Simpson
playing again with her children.''
<p>
   He paused, then turned from the jury and fixed a hard eye on
Simpson.
<p>
   ``But that's not going to happen, not going to happen,''
Petrocelli said, pointing an accusatory finger at Simpson.
<p>
   Simpson stared back, his face an impassive mask.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2026EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0684 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=ttj-z> A9772 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0701 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ASTRONAUT REUNITED WITH WIFE AFTER LONG STAY ON MIR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MARK CARREAU &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Astronaut John Blaha, who Wednesday returned to Earth weakened
from a four-month voyage aboard Russia's Mir space station, got
what he longed for most  &MD;  a speedy reunion with his wife, Brenda.
<p>
   The couple was reunited at NASA's Kennedy Space Center in
Florida shortly after the shuttle Atlantis, with the 54-year-old
veteran astronaut aboard, touched down.
<p>
   ``It was great,'' Brenda Blaha said in a telephone interview
that followed the couple's first face-to-face meeting since his
Sept. 16 liftoff. ``The first thing he did was have me give him a
big smack (kiss).''
<p>
   A former Air Force combat pilot and a veteran of four previous
space missions, Blaha said he was startled by the draining effects
of his stay on Mir. He was too weak to walk or stand without
assistance.
<p>
   ``I'm absolutely stunned by the condition I'm in right now. I
can't believe it,'' Blaha said. ``When (Atlantis) stopped, I
couldn't even raise my leg. It wouldn't even move.''
<p>
   Blaha has admitted in recent days that he suffered a mild period
of depression during the mission and missed his wife terribly.
<p>
   ``I don't even have any plans other than private time with
Brenda,'' Blaha said. ``Cause I missed her. I really missed her.''
<p>
   Blaha's unusually candid assessment of the less glamorous side
of spaceflight was made several hours after Atlantis touched down
at 9:23 a.m. EST. He spoke Wednesday while seated in a recliner as
his wife and daughter, Carolyn, stood nearby. At one point, he
stood briefly with their assistance.
<p>
   Blaha said he would never consider such a long voyage again.
``After one month, I kept longing for things that I loved here (on
Earth). I finally decided I had to forget them. When I did, then I
loved being on the station,'' he said. ``I had to work at
forgetting them, and I had to work at forgetting Brenda. That
shocked me. I didn't expect that kind of thing.''
<p>
   In spite of his travails, Blaha said he felt great physically
while in weightlessness. He formed a strong friendship with Mir
cosmonauts Valeri Korzun and Alexander Kaleri, whom he barely knew
before the mission. The pair replaced the two cosmonauts with whom
Blaha had trained extensively in Russia, after one developed a
heart ailment.
<p>
   Blaha was carried from the shuttle by National Aeronautics and
Space Administration medical personnel. His predecessors on Mir,
Shannon Lucid and Norm Thagard, walked from the shuttle under their
own power.
<p>
   Blaha's crew mates characterized the assistance as something the
veteran astronaut chose rather than required. ``That was totally
John's decision,'' said Atlantis flight engineer John Grunsfeld.
``He wanted the docs to get the best possible data they could. He's
a real trouper. I'm sure he wanted to get up and walk off.''
<p>
   The flight surgeons and scientists who study the range of
changes that occur to space marathoners have urged the fliers to
recline after their return to Earth, until a range of medical tests
can be completed. The cardiovascular, neuro-vestibular, muscle,
skeletal, endocrine and immune systems of astronauts are all
weakened or altered by weightlessness.
<p>
   Space agency researchers, however, say the changes are reversed
as the body slowly readapts to gravity.
<p>
   Atlantis commander Mike Baker, pilot Brent Jett, mission
specialists Marsha Ivins and Jeff Wisoff, Blaha and Grunsfeld spent
their first day back on Earth resting and undergoing routine
medical exams. They were scheduled to return to Houston, where the
space agency planned a brief welcoming ceremony, on Thursday.
<p>
   Brenda Blaha said her husband is strong enough to return to his
Houston-area home during rehabilitation. He can stay at medical
facilities at Johnson Space Center, if he and his flight surgeons
believe he requires closer supervision.
<p>
   After he has regained his strength, Blaha said he and his wife
will be ready for a vacation.
<p>
   ``I know that I definitely want one, but it could be at my
house,'' he joked. ``It doesn't matter where I take it.``
</TEXT>
