<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=taf-z> A9773 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS-ART-525 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1033 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS-ART-525&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AT&AMP;T PROFIT RISES AS BILL PAYMENTS LAG &LR;  &QL; 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By MARK LANDLER &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   AT&AMP;T is finally holding on to its customers. Now, if it can just
get more of them to pay their phone bills.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T said Wednesday that its fourth-quarter income from
continuing operations rose 14.2 percent, to $1.24 billion, helped
by a new flat rate-calling plan that has stanched the flow of
customers to other long-distance carriers. But earnings still fell
short of Wall Street analysts' expectations because of higher costs
from unpaid bills.
<p>
   Excluding special items, the company said its earnings rose to
76 cents a share in the fourth quarter, compared with 68 cents a
share a year earlier. Those results were 3 to 4 cents below the
average forecast of analysts. AT&AMP;T's revenue increased 2.7 percent,
to $13.2 billion.
<p>
   After months of eroding market share and management turmoil, the
stable results were a relief to many analysts who follow AT&AMP;T. But
they noted that the company, the nation's largest long-distance
carrier, still faced a treacherous future, as deregulation opens
its market to competition from the seven regional Bell telephone
companies and GTE.
<p>
   ``Even if they stop the drop in market share of customers, it
doesn't solve their problems in the future,'' said Frank Governali
of CS First Boston.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T's shares declined 50 cents Wednesday, to $38.875, in brisk
New York Stock Exchange trading.
<p>
   The company said it had to budget an extra $200 million in the
fourth quarter to cover unpaid bills, primarily from business
customers. Simon Flannery, a telecommunications analyst at J.P.
Morgan, said the cost of covering these bad debts could total $400
million for all of 1997.
<p>
   AT&AMP;T's chief financial officer, Richard Miller, said the
collection problems stemmed from glitches in the company's billing
systems and from a rise in bankruptcies among its corporate
clients. The onset of competition also makes its harder to collect
bills, he said, because customers could now easily jilt AT&AMP;T for a
rival carrier.
<p>
   ``It used to be the case that if you didn't pay your bill, your
service was canceled and you couldn't live with that,'' Miller
said, ``That threat doesn't work as well anymore.''
<p>
   Like other carriers, AT&AMP;T recently began mailing bills directly
to residential customers in some markets, rather than relying on
the Bell companies and GTE to include AT&AMP;T charges as separate
items on their bills. Other long-distance carriers are also
grappling with collection problems, analysts said, as they take on
direct billing responsibility.
<p>
   An executive at AT&AMP;T said Wednesday that the company's billing
systems were coming under sharp scrutiny from the new president,
John Walter, and from Gail McGovern, whom Walter named in December
to take over the company's giant consumer long-distance business.
<p>
   In addition to the billing problem, a 32.3 percent decline in
revenue at the financial services unit, which consists largely of
the AT&AMP;T Universal Card, hurt the company's quarterly earnings.
Though customer accounts increased to 18.3 million in 1996 from
17.6 million in 1995, AT&AMP;T was hurt by declining use and higher
promotional costs.
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   AT&AMP;T recently named a former banking executive from Citicorp,
Richard Srednicki, to head the credit card division. Miller said he
expected Srednicki to use his marketing skills to attract more card
holders and to stimulate use by current card holders.
<p>
   Miller pointed out that Wednesday's results were restated to
reflect AT&AMP;T's divestiture of its equipment-manufacturing arm, now
Lucent Technologies, and its computer business, NCR. Including
income from discontinued operations and charges related to the
split-up, AT&AMP;T's fourth-quarter net income was $1.62 billion,
compared with a loss of $2.68 billion a year earlier.
<p>
   Analysts, however, spent most of Wednesday scrutinizing the
figures for AT&AMP;T's core long-distance business. And there, the news
was good: Revenue in the so-called wire line business rose 2.9
percent in the fourth quarter, to $11.5 billion. Part of the gain
came from a 5.9 percent rate increase for basic service, which AT&AMP;T
announced the day before Thanksgiving to howls of protest from
consumer advocates.
<p>
   But the volume of long-distance calls also jumped 6 percent  &MD;  a
sign that AT&AMP;T had slowed the exodus of customers to discount
carriers like LCI International and Excel Communications. The
company said it had signed up nearly three million customers for
its One Rate plan, which offers a flat rate of 15 cents a minute
for long-distance calls anywhere in the United States. A majority
of those people were already on other AT&AMP;T calling plans.
<p>
   In a conference call with analysts, Miller sounded a cautious
note about the future. He said AT&AMP;T would keep a tight rein on
expenses for new ventures like its Internet access service,
Worldnet, and would be selective about plunging into new
businesses. ``Some opportunities will have to be deferred,'' he
said, ``Some we will not pursue.''
<p>
   His restrained tone was characteristic of the approach taken by
Walter, who became president of AT&AMP;T in November after a
well-publicized search led by the company's chairman, Robert Allen.
<p>
   Walter has already indicated that AT&AMP;T would throttle back its
expansion into local telephone service. The company is offering
local service to a handful of customers in Sacramento, Calif., and
intends to introduce service in Connecticut, Illinois and Michigan
in the first half of this year. But it no longer plans to roll out
service in all 50 states in 1997.
<p>
   Still, the newly competitive marketplace may make it hard for
AT&AMP;T to hold back too much. Miller noted that AT&AMP;T still planned to
introduce the new type of wireless phone service called personal
communications services this year.
<p>
   And Governali of First Boston noted, ``They don't have the
luxury of saying they're not going to be competitive.''
</TEXT>
