<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CUOMO-CONFIRM-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: N.Y., N.C., Ala.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SENATE PANEL OPENS HEARINGS ON CUOMO NOMINATION &LR;  &QL; 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JERRY GRAY &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  The Senate Banking Committee opened hearings
Wednesday on the nomination of Andrew Cuomo as federal housing
secretary, offering a chorus of bipartisan praise for Cuomo and a
round of criticism against the troubled agency that he has been
picked to lead.
<p>
   ``I am privileged to preside over the confirmation of a native
son of New York,'' said Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., who heads the
committee, ``and I am pleased to support his nomination. The
position of housing and urban development secretary is one of the
toughest positions in government. The new secretary will inherit
serious problems.''
<p>
   For his part, Cuomo said that if confirmed, one of his first
moves would be to reorganize the management and the direction of
the huge agency.
<p>
   ``We must remain committed to our worthwhile goals, but not to
failed means,'' Cuomo said. ``We must be willing to admit that some
programs don't work. We must recognize the roles of government and
the private sector and the partnerships that can be forged.''
<p>
   President Clinton nominated Cuomo, 39, in December to succeed
Henry Cisneros. For the last four years Cuomo has served under
Cisneros as assistant secretary for community planning and
development. Before joining the Clinton administration, Cuomo
headed the New York City Commission on the Homeless and helped
establish and run one of the nation's largest private providers for
transitional housing for the homeless.
<p>
   Cuomo is the son of former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, whose
defeat in 1994 by George Pataki was largely orchestrated by
D'Amato. But there was not a trace of political rancor Wednesday as
D'Amato presided over a hearing that made clear Cuomo would have
little trouble winning approval from the committee when it votes
Tuesday.
<p>
   Even some of HUD's harshest critics, who are members of the
Banking Committee, refrained from any direct attack on Cuomo.
<p>
   ``HUD has become a massive government bureaucracy,'' said one
critic, Sen. Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C., who sponsored legislation in
the 104th Congress to abolish the department. ``In my opinion and
the opinion of many others, HUD has failed; it has lost sight of
its mission.''
<p>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., said, ``HUD has been woefully
mismanaged for too many years,'' and he demanded to know how Cuomo
intended to fix it.
<p>
   Cuomo said: ``HUD's mission cannot be carried out in the future
unless HUD's own house is in good order. I have heard the
committee's concern, and I agree there must be effective management
and financial accountability at HUD.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2028EST
</TRAILER>
