<DOCID> nyt970122.0690 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9779 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-TRADE-SURPLUS-U </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0510 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-JAPAN-TRADE-SURPLUS-UPDATE2-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JAPAN'S DECEMBER TRADE SURPLUS SHRANK 20.6% ON YEAR (UPDATE2) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Ken Belson &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adding economist comments and other details from the report.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Tokyo, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus
shrank 20.6 percent in December from the same month a year ago as
higher oil prices drove up imports, the Finance Ministry said.
<p>
   A senior ministry official said the government expects the
overall trade surplus to shrink more as oil prices rise. He also
said auto exports may continue to rise as the yen weakens against
the dollar.
<p>
   The yen's 8.5 percent decline against the dollar between August
and December led to the third straight monthly increase in Japan's
surplus with the United States. This trend will continue as long as
the yen weakens, economists said.
<p>
   ``The pace of exports to the U.S. will continue because America
has quite robust growth with low inflation,'' said Akio Yoshino,
senior economist at Credit Suisse Asset Management before the
release of the report.
<p>
   Japan's trade surplus with the United States in December rose
7.8 percent to 389.113 billion yen, the ministry said.
<p>
   The smaller-than-expected trade surplus totaled 881.475 billion
yen ($7.4 billion) and has declined for 25 straight months.
Economists said the surplus would be 1.055 trillion yen, according
to a survey compiled by Bloomberg Business News. Projections ranged
from 970 billion yen to 1.145 trillion yen.
<p>
   The trade surplus grew 0.2 percent in November compared to a
year earlier. That figure was later revised to a 0.4 percent
decline.
<p>
   Global imports to Japan rose 13.4 percent to 3.286 trillion yen,
while exports increased 4.0 percent to 4.168 trillion yen, the
ministry said.
<p>
   For all of 1996, Japan's trade surplus fell 32.4 percent to 6.7
trillion yen, the Finance Ministry said. That was fourth straight
yearly decline, and the largest decline in the surplus on record.
<p>
   In yen terms, it was the smallest trade surplus since 1983.
Still, exports and imports both reached record highs. Japan's
exports rose 7.7 percent to 44.734 trillion yen, while imports rose
20.4 percent to 37.990 trillion yen. That was the largest
percentage increase in imports since 1989.
<p>
   The country's full-year trade surplus with the U.S. fell 16.5
percent to 3.6 trillion yen, the second straight yearly decline.
Japan has increased ``reverse imports'' -- goods made at Japanese
factories overseas -- when the yen strengthened against the dollar
in 1994 and 1995. That led to a 21.9 percent increase in imports
from the United States.
<p>
   Japan's surplus with the European Union declined 26.5 percent,
the fourth consecutive decline. Imports of Japanese autos made in
Europe helped reduce the surplus, the government said.
<p>
   Japan's surplus with Asia fell 15.7 percent in 1996, the first
decline in nine years. Weak demand for semiconductors in the region
was the main reason for the decline, the ministry said.
</TEXT>
