<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-PORNOGRAPHY- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0527 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MILITARY-PORNOGRAPHY-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JUDGE VOIDS LAW ON MILITARY BASES' SALE OF SEX MATERIAL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (kd) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN SULLIVAN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  A federal judge in Manhattan ruled Wednesday that the
Defense Department could not enforce a law banning the sale of
sexually explicit magazines and videos on military bases because it
violated Constitutional protections for free speech.
<p>
   The law, the Military Honor and Decency Act of 1996, forbade
stores and post exchanges on military bases to sell or rent sexual
material. Described in Congress as a measure to promote ``honor,
commitment and courage'' among American troops, the law was
scheduled to take effect at the beginning of this year.
<p>
   The judge, Shira A. Scheindlin of Federal District Court, said
the government could not ban the sale of the material merely
because officials found it offensive.
<p>
   ``While the majority of Americans may wish to ban pornography,
in the final analysis, society is better served by protecting our
cherished right to free speech, even at the cost of tolerating
speech that is outrageous, offensive and demeaning,'' Scheindlin
wrote.
<p>
   ``There is no question that the result of permitting such speech
is often unfortunate and unpleasant,'' she wrote. But our
Constitution has effectively protected us for over two centuries
from living in a society where the government intrudes on our
individual rights by deciding what consenting adults can read or
view.''
<p>
   The ruling was in response to a challenge filed by General Media
International, the parent company of Penthouse magazine, and
publishing trade groups. Unless the government files an appeal,
Scheindlin's decision effectively bans the enforcement of the law.
A spokesman for U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White declined to comment on
the decision other than to say that an appeal was under
consideration. The government has 60 days to appeal.
<p>
   Although the decision was primarily based on the First
Amendment, which forbids Congress to make any law abridging freedom
of speech, Scheindlin also said the law was too vague and would
restrict the rights of military personnel. Courts have permitted
this in some areas, but they have required the government to show
that national security interests are served by doing so.
<p>
   ``Citizens do not jettison their constitutional rights simply by
enlisting in the armed forces,'' the judge wrote.
<p>
   Government lawyers had argued that the law would improve the
morale and atmosphere of the armed forces, but the judge's decision
noted that the law would not ban the possession of sexual material
on bases, only its sale.
<p>
   First Amendment experts said the judge's ruling was more an
upholding of traditional court rulings rather than an expansion of
the free speech protections. The courts have long held that the
government has the right to restrict obscene material when it
violates community standards, describes patently offensive sexual
conduct and lacks literary, artistic, political or scientific
value. Yet the plaintiffs and the government lawyers agreed that
the material proposed for banning was not legally obscene.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2031EST
</TRAILER>
