<DOCID> nyt970122.0692 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=taf-z> A9781 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0715 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PATRIOTS RELY ON VETERANS TO ANCHOR OFFENSIVE LINE &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By GERALD ESKENAZI &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  They are two old campaigners who were born in
Miami, but they came here from remarkably different rookie
beginnings. And now they stand side by side to try to stem the best
defense in football.
<p>
   Bruce Armstrong, 32, the left tackle, and William Roberts, 34,
the left guard, find it odd that they are anchoring the Patriots'
line at this stage of their careers. Odder still, they are in a
Super Bowl, and all they have to do is help defeat Green Bay on
Sunday to wind up with a Patriots' championship ring neither
believed possible.
<p>
   They will have to help create an offense that can run as well as
pass to unsettle a veteran Green Bay defense that keeps it simple
and is hard to disrupt. Luckily for Armstrong and Roberts, each has
been around so long that he will not become rattled.
<p>
   The other three members of the offensive line  &MD;  center Dave
Wohlabaugh, right guard Todd Rucci and right tackle Max Lane  &MD; 
total less starting experience than Armstrong's 10 seasons.
<p>
   Armstrong is the senior tenured member of the underdog Patriots.
Incredibly, he has played for as many different owners as coaches  &MD; 
four.
<p>
   ``Every time a new owner changed, you hoped it would be
better,'' said Armstrong on Wednesday, reflecting on the
decade-long optimism that finally paid off.
<p>
   ``Some years it felt very transitory. You had the feeling that
football wasn't primary. But when Bob Kraft came you knew what
happened on the field was most important.''
<p>
   And now comes the Packers' Sean Jones. An intelligent,
two-dimensional defensive right end, Jones will be lined up
opposite Armstrong, who is quarterback Drew Bledsoe's primary
protector.
<p>
   ``Green Bay won't change anything on defense,'' Armstrong said.
``They've got the No. 1 defense in the league. We watched every
game they played because we have the extra week. And what I see is
that it'll be their front seven against our front five. They line
them up the same. Their guys want to beat your guys.''
<p>
   Fred Hoaglin, the Patriots' offensive line coach, tutored
Roberts when both were with the Giants and has overseen Armstrong
here. This is a different operation from Giants' teams, though  &MD; 
especially compared to the one that captured Super Bowl XXV six
years ago. Those Giants had an offense based on ball possession,
with running back Otis Anderson wearing down the opposition on
repeated rushes.
<p>
   Roberts worked hand in glove with Coach Bill Parcells on the
Giants. Of his 13 seasons in the National Football League, Roberts
spent the first 11 with the Giants. He was a key player in their
two Super Bowl victories (1987 and 1991) and became increasingly
frustrated by their decline.
<p>
   ``The core of players that we had, I felt we could have repeated
and three-peated,'' he said.
<p>
   He remembered Giants teams that wore you down, and he remembered
offensive coordinator Ron Erhardt ``getting into a rhythm with the
team and just making the same call after call after call  &MD;  run.''
<p>
   Now, this New England team is in strange territory  &MD;  for both
Roberts and Parcells. There is a quarterback in Bledsoe who has
reached 14,000 yards faster than anyone in NFL history. The Pats
also have a running back, Curtis Martin, who has scored in 15
straight games.
<p>
   ``We have to work harder to keep a drive alive on the
Patriots,'' Roberts said. ``If you pass on first down, then pass on
second down, you have to pass on third down. We have the talent to
be one-dimensional, but you want to be two-dimensional against
Green Bay. They get good pressure from their strong safety, and
then they force you to pass. But when we're two-dimensional, we're
very successful. One-dimensional, we're successful  &MD;  to a point.''
<p>
   Now Roberts, to help create that two-dimensional offense, must
help handle the 325-pound defensive tackle Gilbert Brown, the
biggest player on Super Bowl Sunday. ``Brown will be the biggest,
strongest guy we'll have to face,'' said Hoaglin.
<p>
   The Patriots' offensive coordinator, Ray Perkins, said: ``The
main thing I want our line to know on Sunday is to know what to
do.''
<p>
   He knows there are two players he can count on.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2032EST
</TRAILER>
