<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=taf-z> A9782 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-525&AMP;ADD-N </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0780 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PACKERS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CASTOFF RECEIVERS HAVE FOUND HOME IN GREEN BAY &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; By MIKE FREEMAN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  If you are a wide receiver and your career needs a
pick-me-up, pack those bags and go to Green Bay.
<p>
   Take Andre Rison. He became known as the bad boy who dated
rappers when he was with the Atlanta Falcons and had his house
burned down by a member of the group TLC. On his passing routes he
would zig when he was supposed to zag. Dateline Cleveland: He had
made the Pro Bowl four times as a Falcon, but he was
unceremoniously dumped after one season by the Browns. Dateline
Jacksonville: Rison and Coach Tom Coughlin? That was like Madonna
and Tipper Gore being pals.
<p>
   So he was cut by the Jaguars last November and was claimed off
waivers by the Packers. Offensive coordinator Sherman Lewis said
Rison has been a model citizen and good player.
<p>
   ``I think what got everybody mad at me was that the Browns gave
me such a big contract,'' said Rison, referring to his troubles,
which began in 1995. ``My productivity went down, but they weren't
throwing me the ball. The media didn't have the guts to say that I
wasn't getting the ball.''
<p>
   Then there's Don Beebe. He played in three Super Bowls with the
Buffalo Bills and is probably best known for coming from behind
Leon Lett and knocking the ball out of his hands, a move that
threatened to knock Lett into Super Bowl infamy. But Beebe's career
otherwise was fairly nondescript. Then came the Oct. 14 game
against San Francisco in which he had 11 catches for 220 yards, the
third most receiving yards for a single game in Packers' history.
<p>
   What has been his secret? ``He can take a hit, and he's
extremely fast,'' said Lewis. ``And you know what? I think
defensive backs look at him and say, `Who's this little white guy?
He can't run.' Then by the time they realize how fast he is, it's
too late.''
<p>
   And there is one more piece in this weird Packers receiving
puzzle: Desmond Howard, Mr. Heisman Trophy himself. He was drafted
by the Washington Redskins in 1992, then became known as someone
who couldn't escape off the line, was soft, didn't work hard and
fell asleep in meetings. Now, he is known as a great punt returner
and solid receiver.
<p>
   And no, Howard is not holding back his feelings about the
Redskins. ``Of course, they won't admit they made a mistake in
releasing me,'' said Howard. ``It was a learning experience. It was
politics.''
<p>
   The whispers that followed him after he left Washington amounted
to ``scapegoating. It's covering your back.''
<p>
   So these are the Packers receivers. Combine Rison, Beebe and
Howard with outstanding talent like Antonio Freeman and the injured
Robert Brooks, and you have one of the more interesting  &MD;  and
possibly deep  &MD;  receiving corps in the National Football League.
<p>
   What is interesting about this group is that when one person
goes down with an injury, another seems to step step in. When
Brooks tore the anterior cruciate ligament and patellar tendon in
his right knee against the 49ers, in came Beebe looking like James
Lofton. Freeman joked Wednesday about the plate holding together
his broken forearm, an injury that caused him to miss four games in
the middle of the season. No problem. He was replaced by Terry
Mickens, who finished the year with 18 catches and two touchdowns.
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   Lewis said the Packers did change some things when their lead
receivers started getting hurt. ``It was nothing drastic,'' he
said. ``We dinked and dunked a little more. We went to short passes
and went to the running backs more than normal. We weren't the same
team when those guys got hurt. But let me say this: A lot of guys
stepped up.''
<p>
   Still, the Packers say no one outside Green Bay appreciates what
the receivers have done. ``We still don't get any respect,'' said
Freeman. ``I think we have some terrific receivers, but all we hear
about is Terry Glenn and Ben Coates.'' He was referring to the
Patriots' receivers. ``But that's all right. We just want to win
the game.''
<p>
   Although they do have talent, the main reason why so many of the
Packers' receivers look so good has to do with a guy named Favre.
When the Packers are in the red zone and the team has a quarterback
who can squeeze a football into a tightly compressed area or throw
60 yards on a dime the way Brett Favre can, any receiver will end
up looking good.
<p>
   ``No. 4 is the reason why our receivers always seem to be
stepping it up,'' Freeman said, alluding to the uniform number of
the league's most valuable player. ``He is just awesome at
times.''
</TEXT>
