<DOCID> nyt970122.0694 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=taf-z> A9784 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-MATCHUP-ART </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0608 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-SUPER-MATCHUP-ART-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BIG MISSION FOR PACKER DEFENSE: DEFLATE THE OPPONENT &LR;  &QL; 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By MIKE FREEMAN &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  Green Bay strong safety LeRoy Butler has covered
some of the best tight ends in football  &MD;  Shannon Sharpe, Wesley
Walls, Brent Jones. He must see wide bodies catching passes in his
sleep. Now here comes another tight end who will try to post him
up: the New England Patriots' Ben Coates.
<p>
   ``It's a tough job,'' Butler joked, ``but somebody has to do
it.''
<p>
   In addition to Coates, who is arguably the second-best tight end
in the National Football League behind Sharpe of the Denver
Broncos, the Patriots have the powerful rookie Terry Glenn and the
veteran Shawn Jefferson.
<p>
   The three receivers have combined for 202 catches for 2,585
yards and 19 touchdowns this season.
<p>
   ``They are as good a group of receivers as we've seen all
season,'' said the Packers' defensive coordinator, Fritz Shurmur.
``That bunch knows how to light up the scoreboard.''
<p>
   So how do the Packers keep the Patriots from lighting them up?
Or, at the very least, slowing them down?
<p>
   The Patriots often run what the Packers call an outside flood.
Basically, New England floods about one-third of the field with
three receivers, a scheme that makes it tough for a defense to
cover.
<p>
   Although there are many different variations of the outside
flood, basically Glenn will run a deep straight pattern (a 9
route), Coates will run downfield about 15 yards and then cut
toward the sideline (a 7 route) and one of the running backs will
run a flair route, or short pattern in front of the linebackers.
<p>
   ``They can run a lot of different things out the outside
flood,'' Packers safety Mike Prior said. ``But the main thing is
that from the film we've watched, they confuse a lot of people with
what they do.''
<p>
   If the Packers guess wrong in their coverage, they will be
outnumbered on that side of the field and get burned.
<p>
   ``Our strategy is to keep Drew Bledsoe guessing,'' free safety
Eugene Robinson said. ``We have to keep him moving in the pocket
and wondering what we're doing. If he can just set up in the pocket
and hit all of those receivers, we're dead.''
<p>
   In addition to their downfield game, the Patriots have a strong
running game with Curtis Martin and they use a variety of screen
passes and have been able to get by without using maximum
protection  &MD;  keeping the standard five linemen in to block.
<p>
   Interestingly, though, the Packers say Bledsoe doesn't often
take short drop backs. Most quarterbacks in the league drop back an
average of 3 to 5 yards but Bledsoe drops back an average of 7 to 9
yards.
<p>
   Now comes the Packers and their outstanding defensive line that
is anchored by the defensive ends Reggie White, a future Hall of
Famer, and Sean Jones, a Pro Bowler. There is no way the Patriots
will be able to single pass block them. And how can one person
consistently block the massive 350-pound tackle Gilbert Brown?
<p>
   And the Packers aren't shy about saying they can't be single
blocked.
<p>
   ``I don't think we can be,'' said Green Bay defensive tackle
Santana Dotson. ``I don't recall one game this year where that
happened. If they try to single block us, our job is to take
advantage of that. I hope they don't change what they've been doing
because we'll take advantage of it.''
<p>
   Bold words but the Packers have been able to back up their talk
all season. They only hope that continues on Sunday.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2033EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0695 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=taf-z> A9785 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0763 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: N.Y., Ind.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SPORTS COLUMN: NO STORYBOOK ENDING FOR DON MATTINGLY &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; By HARVEY ARATON &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  An uneasy Don Mattingly said his wife had told him to
speak from the heart, but the retiring New York Yankee, not one to
wear emotions on his pinstriped sleeves, played it diplomatically
safe, never wandering very far off first base.
<p>
   Yes, Mattingly said, the World Series had been a time of great
reflection, some pain, but also of joy for former teammates. He
mentioned Bernie Williams. Derek Jeter. He nodded at the owner,
George Steinbrenner.
<p>
   His partner in life, whose relationship with the former Yankee
first baseman traces its genesis to a bus ride to an American
Legion game in Madisonville, Ky., was unburdened, however, by the
glare of the lights or by a reputation for avoiding controversy
that was sculptured long ago.
<p>
   Kim Mattingly, the daughter of that American Legion team's
coach, didn't mind admitting the anger she felt for her husband
when she would find him in the barn of their Evansville, Ind.,
home, excusing himself from another workout in the weeks following
the World Series that Don Mattingly somehow missed. She had hoped
he would play baseball again.
<p>
   ``Was it internal anger, or did you let him know?'' Kim
Mattingly was asked.
<p>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' she said. ``I've never been one to not express
myself.''
<p>
   It was easier, then, for her to dwell on what everyone knew but
didn't have the heart to acknowledge with anything more than a
brief line of questioning that Don Mattingly would carefully
deflect. Kim Mattingly called the conclusion to her husband's
baseball career, a wrenching October 1995 night in a hideous
Seattle dome, a lousy ending. He was a great player once, and
always was one of the good guys. She would never stop believing
that her man deserved better.
<p>
   ``It seemed like baseball just ended in Seattle for us,'' she
said. ``There just didn't seem to be any closure.''
<p>
   Her bright blue eyes never so much as blinked as she added, ``I
wanted a storybook ending.''
<p>
   That it all happened for the Yankees one year after the
Mattinglys left New York made it difficult to take, she said, and
worse to watch. The long silences at their home as Game 6
progressed, with the Atlanta Braves slip-sliding to what seemed
like their predestined fate, ultimately gave way to waves of
emotion, of sadness, of too many disappointments across 13 years.
<p>
   Kim Mattingly said she walked out of the room in the eighth
inning. Don and their three young sons stayed behind, but she
specifically recalled that the television was turned off soon after
Charlie Hayes had squeezed the final out.
<p>
   ``Before all the commotion on the field,'' she said.
<p>
   So, Kim Mattingly was asked, Don never actually saw the Yankees
celebrate?
<p>
   ``No,'' she said, her eyes again holding their gaze.
<p>
   This was not about blaming anyone, certainly not Steinbrenner
for signing Tino Martinez. But surely there is in this unkind tale
a moral about the loss or lack of continuity that has overwhelmed
pro sports. We always hear much hankering for the days when we
could identify with the players, when they were ``our'' guys, but
the plain truth in the Mattingly case was that history, family and
loyalty were quickly forgotten the season before last in the city's
summer-long outcry for someone, anyone, to drive in 100 runs.
<p>
   Mattingly took that repudiation hard, with good reason, and
probably retreated emotionally when he might have sat down with Joe
Torre, swallowed some pride and worked out a role. Where could he
have played last season? He had played outfield. One year, he
dragged his southpaw glove out to third base for a spell. All I
know is that Yankees seemed to come and go last season as if Yankee
Stadium were a Marriott, and the World Series produced more than a
few heroes with lesser credentials than Mattingly, and less right
to have been there.
<p>
   Kim Mattingly, who married Don in 1979, the year he signed with
the Yankees and reported to Oneonta, N.Y., said she was left with
the feeling of being ``cheated.'' She added that she could only
speak for herself but that probably was the only time all afternoon
she didn't tell the truth.
<p>
   Baseball wives often speak of their husbands' careers as joint
efforts, so on the subject of Don's decision to quit, Kim Mattingly
said, ``Once they had gone to the Series without us, there was no
coming back.''
<p>
   The sad realization had set in. The storybook was closed,
forever.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2034EST
</TRAILER>
