<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9787 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PEOPLE-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0442 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PEOPLE-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HONORS FOR DAVID HAMBURG AND EVELYN LAUDER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; 3 CITED FOR ADVANCING DEMOCRACY IN CHINA &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AWARDS FOR MICHAEL SOVERN AND HIS STUDENT &LR;  &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Organizations everywhere seem to be in a mood for
presenting awards, announcing them or making plans for ceremonies.
The New York Academy of Medicine will pay tribute Thursday night to
Dr. David Hamburg, who in July will step down as the president of
the Carnegie Corp., in New York, and Evelyn Lauder, senior
corporate vice president of Estee Lauder, at its 150th anniversary
celebration at the Museum of Natural History.
<p>
   Hamburg is being honored for bringing critical issues to public
attention, especially those involving the needs of children, and
Mrs. Lauder for her work raising awareness of breast cancer.
<p>
   For Hamburg, the evening will be a family affair. His wife, Dr.
Beatrix Hamburg, president of the W.T. Grant Foundation, is a
member of the academy board. His daughter, Dr. Margaret Hamburg,
the city's health commissioner, was instrumental in helping the
academy establish a center for urban epidemiology. ``It turns out
that the mayor has asked her to represent him at the dinner, so she
will have a formal role in saying a few words for him,'' Hamburg
said.
<p>
   And might she talk about her father? ``I hope so,'' he said. 
<p>
   c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service
<p>
   The Chinese Democracy Education Foundation, a 12-year-old
California organization, announced this week that it would honor
A.M. Rosenthal, a columnist for The New York Times and its former
executive editor. Rosenthal will be given an award for his columns
advocating human rights in China.
<p>
   Also being honored as ``Distinguished Persons for the
Advancement of Democracy in China'' are Chen Ziming, an educator in
China, and Hu Chu-jen, an editor in Hong Kong. The awards will be
presented in May in San Francisco.
<p>
   c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Michael Sovern, former president of Columbia
University and former dean of its law school, will receive
Columbia's highest award, its Medal of Excellence, on Friday along
with one of his students of 40 years ago, Marie Garibaldi, class of
'59 and now a New Jersey Supreme Court justice. The awards will be
presented at the law school's winter luncheon in the Plaza Hotel in
Manhattan.
<p>
   ``The personal pleasure I feel at receiving it is amplified by a
teacher's special joy in seeing a student whom I remember clearly
and for whom I had high hopes realize those hopes,'' said Sovern,
who taught Justice Garibaldi in his evidence class.
</TEXT>
