<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-JAPAN-DOLLAR-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DOLLAR RISES TO 47-MONTH HIGH VS YEN, TRADING AT 119.32 YEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Keiko Kambara &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Tokyo, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- The dollar rose to a 47-month high
of 119.32 yen on expectations investors will keep buying dollars to
invest in the U.S., traders said.
<p>
   ``I think this is rather `the U.S. buying,''' said Shinichi
Yamashita, manager for foreign exchange at Sanwa Bank Ltd. The U.S.
economy and its financial markets are much stronger than Japan's,
he said.
<p>
   The government's announcement that Japan's trade surplus fell
more than expected in December also boosted the dollar, said a
trader at Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi. Japan said its merchandise
trade surplus in December fell 20.6 percent from a year earlier to
881.475 billion yen ($7.4 billion).
<p>
   Economists surveyed by Bloomberg Business News had expected the
trade surplus to fall 5.0 percent. A larger-than-expected decline
in Japan's surplus often helps boost the dollar because it means
fewer dollars in the hands of Japanese exporters to sell for yen to
bring profits home.
<p>
   The dollar rose to its highest level against the yen since Feb.
19, 1993, when it traded for 119.50 yen. It was quoted at 1.6395
marks, compared with 1.6402 marks in New York.
</TEXT>
