<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=taf-z> A9790 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-MARCH-ART-NY </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0837 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ABORTION-MARCH-ART-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MRS. CLINTON AND GORES REITERATE SUPPORT FOR ABORTION RIGHTS &LR;  &QL; 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By JAMES BENNET &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  In a joint show of political force, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and his wife, Tipper, each affirmed
support for abortion rights at a luncheon here Wednesday marking
the 24th anniversary of Roe vs. Wade, the Supreme Court decision
legalizing abortion.
<p>
   Both Gore and Mrs. Clinton also urged the group to work with
opponents of abortion to reduce the need for the procedure. ``I
hope that we will be able to find ways of increasing dialogue and
working together with people of good faith who do not share
extremism as their rallying cry,'' Mrs. Clinton said.
<p>
   It was the first time that Mrs. Clinton and Mrs. Gore had
addressed the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action
League, which held the luncheon, and Mrs. Clinton had not been
expected to attend.
<p>
   It was also the second time in four days the first lady had made
late arrangements to appear at a political event, suggesting she
may be taking a more public role.
<p>
   As Congress prepares for battles over financing family planning
abroad, Mrs. Clinton made clear that efforts supporting abortion
rights were a priority for the administration. She quoted a
conversation with the Brazilian minister of health, who she said
told her during a visit there, `We want to give poor women the same
information and access to family planning that well-to-do women
have always had in this country.''
<p>
   Mrs. Clinton added: ``That should be our goal, not only here but
also in our foreign policy.''
<p>
   Kate Michelman, the president of the abortion rights group, said
the appearance of ``three members of the presidential team'' was an
``extraordinary demonstration of the commitment on the part of the
administration to a woman's right to choose.''
<p>
   But in their own display of political determination across town
Wednesday, thousands of abortion opponents gathered on the Mall at
noon to listen to speeches and then march down Constitution Avenue
to the Supreme Court.
<p>
   Several in the crowd said that they were particularly upset
about Clinton's veto of a bill banning abortions conducted late in
pregnancy in a procedure called ``partial-birth abortion'' by its
foes.
<p>
   ``This march has a special emphasis on partial-birth abortions,
because banning those is a short-term goal that we can
accomplish,'' said Frank Nava, 28, a customer-service
representative for a Virginia home inspection company.
<p>
   Last year's veto was not mentioned during the speeches at the
luncheon, which was held at the Mayflower Hotel.
<p>
   Instead, Gore condemned the violence of some who oppose
abortion, vowing that the government would find those responsible
for bombings in the last week at abortion clinics in Atlanta, and
Tulsa, Okla.
<p>
   ``The American people will not tolerate your cowardly crusade,''
he said. He accused groups that invoke religion to justify violence
of ``an appalling act of hypocrisy.''
<p>
   Gore's commitment to abortion rights was at one point in doubt,
as some in his audience acknowledged. When he was a member of the
House from 1977 to 1984, the National Right to Life Committee, an
anti-abortion group, said he voted 84 percent of the time for
measures of which it approved.
<p>
   But Gore was emphatic in his support for abortion rights
Wednesday. ``How can we say that the government of the United
States of America,'' he said, ``with all of its power, with all of
its resources, with all of its distance and insensitivity to these
fragile and complex circumstances pressing in on that individual
woman  &MD;  how can we say that the government must come in and order
her to do what it has decided is the right thing?''
<p>
   Ms. Michelman, said Gore had ``evolved'' and might serve as a
model for other legislators. ``To his absolute credit, as he is
known to do, he really studied the issue, talked to people,
understood it, became more sensitive to the complex questions,''
she said.
<p>
   Opponents of abortion were not impressed with Wednesday's talk
of making abortion rare, a longstanding pledge of Clinton's.
``That's the sort of rhetoric we've heard from the Clintons,'' said
Douglas Johnson, the legislative director of the National Right to
Life Committee. ``But of course their policies have been to remove
all obstacles to abortion and to expand its use as a method of
birth control, both domestically and overseas.''
<p>
   Hours before the lunch, a tiny explosion occurred about a block
away, near a downtown abortion clinic. Police said they were still
trying to determine who had left the device, which had the force of
a firecracker and scratched the hand of a passerby who picked it
up.
<p>
   They said they had no evidence that it was related to the
commemoration of the Supreme Court decision.
</TEXT>
