<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9791 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CT-SCHOOL-DESEGREGATI </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0687 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CT-SCHOOL-DESEGREGATION-2TAKES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; REPORT URGES SCHOOL CHOICE IN CONNECTICUT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JONATHAN RABINOVITZ &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   HARTFORD, Conn.  &MD;  A panel established by Gov. John G. Rowland to
address segregation in Connecticut's schools said Wednesday that
the state should require school districts to accept students from
anywhere in Connecticut and should pay more for school construction
projects that bring black and Hispanic students into mostly white
districts.
<p>
   In an unusual step, the panel recommended that state assistance
for school construction, typically half the cost of a project, be
linked to the project's effect on racial balance. A project that
improves racial diversity  &MD;  for example, by creating space in a
mostly white district for minority children from neighboring
districts  &MD;  would receive more money. A project that does not help
integrate a school could be penalized.
<p>
   While the report, by the Education Improvement Panel, said such
a test would be applied to every application for state aid for
school construction, it was quiet about what portion of the aid for
any one project should be tied to the estimated effect on racial
balance. Construction could play a major role in making the school
choice provision work, since the panel's recommendations would
allow districts that do not have space to turn away outside
students.
<p>
   Education experts said that they knew of no other state with a
program tying school construction money to desegregation. The issue
had been a difficult one for the panel, with several members saying
that they were wary of going into such uncharted territory.
<p>
   Panel members said they expected the construction-aid and
school-choice recommendations to be hotly debated in the next few
months, as the legislature takes them up.
<p>
   Those provisions were 2 of 15 in the report, which was greeted
by many as the first step toward desegregating the state's schools
and turning around the quality of its urban schools.
<p>
   Rowland praised the panel Wednesday for giving ``us a standard
to follow in the legislature.'' In a 10-minute speech to the panel
this morning, Rowland said, ``I don't want to see any distance
between me and the recommendations at all,'' though he did not
specifically discuss or single out any of the measures.
<p>
   The 22-member panel, which included top legislators, civil
rights leaders and local officials, was created by Rowland in July
after the State Supreme Court ruled that the racial isolation in
the Hartford school system violated the state Constitution.
<p>
   About 95 percent of the students in the Hartford schools are
either black or Hispanic, while almost all of the school districts
in the surrounding 21 towns have a majority of white students.
<p>
   It was the first time that a state high court, using a state
constitution, had ordered a state to develop a desegregation plan
that crossed district lines, encompassing both cities and suburbs.
The decision ran counter to a trend in federal courts, which had
been moving away from ordering desegregation plans across these
district lines.
<p>
   Indeed, Connecticut is considering how to achieve integration as
a host of other states and municipalities have been ordered to
dismantle desegregation plans set in motion by the federal courts
more than a decade ago.
<p>
   Owen M. Fiss, a Yale Law School professor and expert in school
desegregation, said, ``We're basically at a point where school
desegregation efforts have collapsed, and Brown has been emptied of
all its practical meaning, becoming just a symbol.'' Brown vs.
Board of Education was the 1954 case in which the U.S. Supreme
Court found segregated schools unconstitutional.
<p>
   ``These proposals in the panel's report  &MD;  however limited they
may be from the combatants' point of view  &MD;  represent a movement in
a totally different direction than the rest of the nation has
taken,'' Fiss added. ``Connecticut represents a break with the
tradition of following the federal lead on these issues.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
