<DOCID> nyt970122.0700 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9792 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CT-SCHOOL-DESEGREGATI </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0935 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CT-SCHOOL-DESEGREGATION-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HARTFORD, Conn.: these issues.'' &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Many panel members Wednesday played down the choice and school
construction proposals as only 2 measures in a package of 15, and
the panel tried to send a symbolic message about their significance
by voting to move them to the back of the report, instead of at the
beginning.
<p>
   Among the other proposals in the report were recommendations to
increase the numbers of charter and magnet schools; to achieve
universal access to preschool programs for all poor 3- and
4-year-old children by 2000, and to provide additional state aid to
urban school districts for after-school and summer instructional
programs as well as for reading instruction to young students.
<p>
   The report also called for making school districts more
accountable to the state, setting up a system by which the state
could take over school systems that had failed to achieve certain
academic standards that would be determined by the state Education
Department.
<p>
   But the issue that clearly had taken up the most time and that
even Wednesday was debated until the final hour was the provision
that would give students around the state a choice of school
districts.
<p>
   Wednesday, as in previous weeks, that measure was attacked by
critics from across the political spectrum, who disliked it for
very different reasons.
<p>
   ``Many will choose, and few will be called,'' remarked Jerome P.
Brown, a panel member who has been an outspoken proponent for even
more sweeping steps to achieve desegregation, like creating larger
regionwide districts. Under the panel's proposal, school districts
can turn away students if there is no room available, and Brown and
others predicted that there would not be space for out-of-district
students.
<p>
   In turn, some argued that any success of the program would spell
the downfall of urban school systems and divert much-needed
resources away from those schools.
<p>
   The report states that every student leaving a school district
would be accompanied by some of the state funds that would have
otherwise gone to his home district. The state also would put up
additional money for transportation.
<p>
   ``What happens to the children who are left behind?'' asked
State Senator Kevin B. Sullivan, a panel member and the Senate's
top officer, who opposed the school choice plank.
<p>
   Still others argued that parents of black and Hispanic children
did not want to send their children into the suburbs and that most
would not even take that option.
<p>
   ``Choosing suburban schools is not necessarily the choice they
want,'' said Ben F. Andrews Jr., a panel member who is head of the
state NAACP chapter and vice chairman of the national organization.
<p>
   Andrews and four other panel members released their own report
Wednesday that said local school districts should no longer be
financed by municipal property taxes, but rather by the state, a
provision that would equalize funding but likely meet strong
opposition in the legislature.
<p>
   The plaintiffs who brought the case against the state  &MD;  parents
of 17 Hartford and suburban students  &MD;  also weighed in Wednesday,
saying that the panel's report paid insufficient attention to urban
education. They added that it neither sets specific goals for
achieving racial diversity, nor established strong enough
enforcement mechanisms.
<p>
   Still, many of the panel members clearly believed that by tying
the school choice program to state funds for school construction
and increasing the number of magnet and charter schools, they had
come up with a solution that could move the state toward
desegregation.
<p>
   While admitting that it could take a number of years, they said
that it had the potential for positive change, if the legislature
properly financed it.
<p>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
<p>
   A panel of legislators, civil rights leaders, parents and
teachers made a series of recommendations Wednesday to address a
decision last July by the Connecticut Supreme Court that the racial
isolation in the Hartford school system violated the state
Constitution. These are among the recommendations:
<p>
    &MD;  Set up a school choice program that allows students to attend
schools outside their home district and requires districts to
receive outside students if space permits.
<p>
    &MD;  Increase state spending on magnet schools that would attract
students from both city and suburban schools, and encourage them to
open more rapidly.
<p>
    &MD;  Increase the number of Connecticut charter schools and give
preference to charter proposals that reduce racial and economic
segregation.
<p>
    &MD;  Increase state spending for school construction projects that
reduce racial segregation and cut back state spending on projects
that fail to reduce segregation.
<p>
    &MD;  Provide state aid to expand access to preschool programs for
3- and 4-year-olds, starting with the state's largest cities.
<p>
    &MD;  Set up a system that would allow the state to place troubled
school districts on probation and ultimately take them over if no
improvement occurs.
<p>
    &MD;  Increase state aid to city schools for after-school and summer
instructional programs, and for reading instruction for young
students.
<p>
    &MD;  Provide after-school and summer programs for bilingual
students who are not becoming proficient in English. Also, by the
year 2000, provide foreign language instruction in the early
grades.
<p>
    &MD;  Increase state spending for family resource centers, which
provide programs like parent training and preschool child care.
<p>
    &MD;  Expand adult education programs.
</TEXT>
