<STORYID cat=k pri=u sel=taf-z> A9793 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0707 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMMENTARY: INAUGURATION DIARY &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By MAUREEN DOWD &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  Saturday morning, Jan. 18: I rise, ready for
history. I do not feel jaded. I am perfectly prepared to feel
corny. This is a weekend for unblushing patriotism. Barbra
Streisand is not in the Lincoln Bedroom. Dick Morris is not in the
Jefferson bedroom. The United States is the only superpower on
earth. All's right with the world. I can even bear that Michael
Bolton's in town.
<p>
   Bill's and Hillary's first four years were exhausting. The
country's all rolfed out. There were some tawdry moments. But most
Americans seem satisfied that the Clintons have been punished for
cutting all those corners. There was a pounding in the press, and
all those hearings. Perhaps people now look to the presidency for
lurid entertainment as much as moral inspiration. And, as I watch
Al Gore craning from the wings, I can give the Clintons this: They
aren't boring.
<p>
   The inaugural, unfortunately, builds on the themes of the
campaign: bridges, villages, Internet access. But even weighed down
with earnest lectures by family experts and glitzed up with Whoopi
Goldberg (who makes Liza Minnelli look sincere), democracy is
lovely to behold.
<p>
   Saturday night: I go to John McLaughlin's party at the Willard
Hotel. Up or down? Way down. McLaughlin has managed to find the
only white soul band in D.C. Tall Media Analyst William Schneider
looms over Tiny Cabinet Member Donna Shalala to discuss Tarnished
House Speaker Newt Gingrich. ``Three hundred thousand dollars is a
meaningful concept,'' Schneider says.
<p>
   Soignee Conservative Arianna Huffington asks Soigne Conservative
Tony Blankley to film a bit for her Comedy Central gig: ``Let's
find a way to make the Republican Party more compassionate,'' she
says, pointing at me. ``Tony, help her put on her coat. Get her a
drink.''
<p>
   At the Corcoran Gallery's MTV party, as trays of blue martinis
float by, Hillary has an Evita moment at the top of the grand
staircase.
<p>
   I see my personal trainer, and scurry away from the guacamole.
<p>
   Sunday, Jan. 19: Emily's List, the feminist fund-raising group,
has a news conference featuring new Democratic women in Congress. A
reporter asks whether feminists have ignored Paula Jones.
<p>
   The Emily's List spokeswoman cuts off questioning, saying time
has run out.
<p>
   Monday, Jan. 20: I go to the Inaugural Address. Despite the
president's best efforts, it is exciting. Why is he so deadly? Is
it because he speaks in cliches or because he fails to act on his
cliches? He wins the election by trafficking in what Dick Morris
called ``bite-size'' issues. And now he says that ``Nothing big
ever came from being small.''
<p>
   Monday night: After I get tickets to the Arkansas ball, I
realize I have made a fatal mistake. This is a town where you can
never start jockeying for position too early. Everyone is elbowing
into Tennessee.
<p>
   Arkansas has its compensations. A circle of guys in black tie
try to teach me the Arkansas Cheer, which goes, ``Pig  &MD;  soo-eeee!''
<p>
   The Clintons appear on stage at 10:30 p.m., serenaded by Sheryl
Crow singing ``All I wanna do is have some fun.'' But their remarks
sound oddly peevish. Bill harkens back to the dark scandal days of
New Hampshire '92. Hillary tells a story about a woman who called
C-Span to ask if the president was really a Kennedy. ``The woman,''
the first lady says, smiling coolly, ``was spinning out these
extraordinary conspiracy theories that capture the hearts and minds
of too many with too little to do.''
<p>
   ``Nightline'' does a day in the life of Al Gore  &MD;  ``The Vice
President, a Bridge to the Future.'' Ted Koppel asks Gore if he's
running. The tension is unbearable as Koppel waits for a reply. The
reply is even more unbearable. ``My so-called campaign for
president,'' Gore says, ``is a lot like my macarena  &MD;  there's no
visible movement.'' OK, OK, we get it. You're stiff. Stop being so
vain about it.
<p>
   Tuesday, Jan. 21: During the House debate on punishing Newt
Gingrich, Tom DeLay of Texas cries: ``Let's stop this madness.
Let's stop the cannibalism.''
<p>
   Wednesday, Jan. 22: Back to business. Let the madness and
cannibalism begin.
</TEXT>
