<DOCID> nyt970122.0702 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9794 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CORNELL-GIFT-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0599 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CORNELL-GIFT-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ALUMNUS GIVES $20 MILLION TO CORNELL FOR RESEARCH CENTER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   A Cornell University alumnus who amassed a fortune in the
development of computer software is giving his alma mater $20
million toward the construction of laboratories and classrooms to
train the next generation of scientists and engineers.
<p>
   The gift from the alumnus, David A. Duffield, 56, is one of the
largest in the 132-year history of Cornell and is the latest
example of a growing trend in philanthropy, of software and
computer entrepreneurs giving large amounts to education.
<p>
   ``I think we're all maturing,'' said Duffield, the president,
chief executive and chairman of Peoplesoft Inc., of Pleasanton,
Calif., which he founded 10 years ago. ``You get to a point in life
where you sort of wake up to the world and look outside your little
box.''
<p>
   In December, Charles B. Wang, the founder of Computer Associates
International, based in Islandia, N.Y., pledged $20 million to $25
million to create an Asian-American cultural center at the State
University of New York at Stony Brook.
<p>
   In October, Bill Gates, who founded Microsoft Corp. of Redmond,
Wash., with his childhood friend Paul G. Allen, announced his fifth
multimillion dollar gift to a university, $15 million to Harvard
for computer science and engineering programs.
<p>
   Last week, Gates, Allen, Craig McCaw and three brothers from the
family that founded McCaw Cellular Communications gave $30 million
in a challenge grant for education and construction to the Lakeside
School in Seattle, the private school that is their alma mater.
<p>
   Duffield, whose company is a developer of software for
manufacturing, distribution, financial and human resource
management and for higher education, gave $2 million in 1995 to
Cornell for promoting the use of information technology in its
engineering and business schools.
<p>
   He received a bachelor's degree in electric engineering from
Cornell in 1963 and a master's degree in business administration
there in 1964.
<p>
   ``I've made a ton, and you can't take it all with you,'' said
Duffield, whose six children range in age from 4 months to 30
years. ``I don't want to give it all to my kids because they get
all screwed up.''
<p>
   Cornell's president Hunter Rawlings announced Duffield's gift at
the annual Cornell President's Circle Dinner on Wednesday night at
the Rainbow Room in Manhattan. ``We are grateful for his vision and
confidence in Cornell,'' he said in a statement. ``Our students and
faculty will benefit from Dave's generosity for generations to
come.''
<p>
   In an interview, Duffield expressed gratitude toward Cornell.
``I was not one of their better students,'' he said. ``They just
gave me opportunities that maybe I shouldn't have gotten. They
admitted me, for one, whereas other Ivy League universities didn't,
and then offered me a chance to get a business degree when I was
not a fabulous student during my engineering days.''
<p>
   The donation is the lead gift in support of a new center on the
university's campus in Ithaca, N.Y. Initially called the
Engineering Research and Instructional Facility, it will now be
named Duffield Hall. It will house flexible laboratory space and
multimedia classrooms to be used for training at the nanostructure
frontier, involving the understanding of materials at the atomic
and molecular level.
<p>
   Plans for the $40 million center call for construction to begin
in June 1999 and for completion by the end of 2001.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2045EST
</TRAILER>
