<SLUG> BC-GA-CLINIC-BOMB-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0670 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-GA-CLINIC-BOMB-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DYNAMITE WAS USED IN BOMB ATTACK AT ATLANTA CLINIC, OFFICIALS SAY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID JOHNSTON &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  The federal authorities investigating the bombing
at an abortion clinic near Atlanta last week have concluded that
each of the two bombs were built with 10 to 20 sticks of dynamite,
a high explosive that experts say is unusual in homemade terrorist
devices.
<p>
   Amateur bomb-makers, law-enforcement officials said Wednesday,
are more likely to use more readily available black or smokeless
powder in pipe bombs instead of commercial dynamite or
nitroglycerin, which are regulated by the government and require
purchasers to obtain a federal permit to transport it between
states.
<p>
   In the attack at the clinic Jan. 16, officials said the design
of the second bomb, which detonated about an hour after
law-enforcement officers and news reporters were drawn to the first
blast, differed from the first bomb and might have been built to
harm emergency workers.
<p>
   The second device, packed in a metal military-style container
that also held 3-inch concrete nails, appeared to have been
designed to spew metal fragments over a wide area.
<p>
   In contrast, the bomb that exploded at the Olympics in Atlanta
in July, consisted of three lengths of pipe packed with smokeless
powder.
<p>
   The officials said the presence of dynamite, which is
manufactured by a single company in Utah but sold under a variety
of commercial labels, offered some investigative leads to sellers
in the Atlanta area but did not necessarily point to any suspect or
motive for the attack.
<p>
   So far, no one has taken responsibility for the clinic bombing
and, although the abortion clinic was a presumed target,
investigators are pursuing other theories, including the
possibility that the attack was aimed at law enforcement.
<p>
   Investigators have also said both clinic bombs were powerful
devices that could have caused far more serious harm than the six
minor injuries reported. One tore through reinforced concrete and
both left craters several feet deep.
<p>
   The first blast, about 9:30 a.m., caused no injuries but
shattered concrete and blew away pieces of wall and ceiling at the
building housing the clinic. Then as emergency teams converged at
the scene, the second bomb exploded in an adjoining parking lot,
knocking several people to the ground.
<p>
   Officials said more serious injuries were avoided because the
authorities had moved several cars after the first blast to a point
near where the second device exploded. When it detonated, the
vehicles absorbed much of the explosion.
<p>
   Dynamite is seldom used in improvised explosives, said
Christopher Ronay, the president of the Institute of Makers of
Explosives and former chief of the explosives unit at the FBI.
<p>
   Dynamite, Ronay said, is difficult to handle, not easy to buy
and regulated by the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
Legitimate users of dynamite are turning to less unwieldy
alternatives to replace a product that was once widely used in
construction, agriculture, mining and quarrying.
<p>
   Less than 1 percent of domestic bombers use dynamite in their
devices, Ronay said, adding: ``It seldom falls into criminal hands
It is seldom is used in bombs. Most bombs are improvised with
smokeless powder or black powder.''
<p>
   As details of the clinic bombs emerged, a small explosion here
in Washington sent law-enforcement officials racing to an abortion
clinic Wednesday as proponents and opponents of abortion rights
demonstrated on the 24th anniversary of the Supreme Court's
decision establishing a constitutional right to abortion. The
authorities later concluded that the device, a small
military-training fuse, was not directed at the clinic.
<p>
   Officials said Wednesday that they had no evidence that the Jan.
16 bombing near Atlanta was connected to a firebombing at an
abortion clinic in Tulsa, Okla., on Jan. 19. That blast hurt no one
and caused minor damage.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
