<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MATTINGLY-5 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0991 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BBA-YANKS-MATTINGLY-575&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MATTINGLY SAYS FAREWELL, AND SO DOES HIS NUMBER &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; By JACK CURRY &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Don Mattingly's eyes were moist and misty as he stood
behind a podium Wednesday and thanked everyone, from George
Steinbrenner, to his wife and three sons, to the clubhouse security
guards and the groundskeepers at Yankee Stadium. He still looked as
if he could play baseball, but the former Yankee captain said he
did not want to sacrifice for the game anymore.
<p>
   Mattingly explained that during three straight days of batting
practice in November, he convinced himself that he could still
wield a bat with precision. But he decided in early December that
his wrist, elbow and knees ached too much, not to mention his back,
with which he has had chronic problems. He retired his batting
gloves on that day in Evansville, Ind., and he officially retired
from baseball Wednesday.
<p>
   ``I wasn't willing to pay the price it was going to take to be
able to succeed,'' said Mattingly, who revealed Wednesday that he
turned down an offer to join the Baltimore Orioles last July. ``At
that point, I knew it was time to step away.''
<p>
   Steinbrenner presented Mattingly with his No. 23 jersey in a
news conference before 120 reporters at the Stadium Club and
announced that no other Yankee would ever don it. Mattingly's
number will become the 14th retired by the Yankees during a
ceremony at a date to be determined this season.
<p>
   ``I don't believe any player on the New York Yankees was ever as
great as Don Mattingly in every way during my years as an owner,''
said Steinbrenner. ``He was a great athlete and a great player.
Some great athletes are not great human beings and vice versa. This
man combined all of that.''
<p>
   Mattingly, who will be 36 on April 20, retired as a legendary
Yankee, a player who was respected and revered during his 13-year
career.
<p>
   He won a plethora of individual honors, including the American
League Most Valuable Player Award one year and the batting
championship another, but never made it to a World Series. He
laughed about his timing; he was drafted by the Yankees in the 19th
round in 1979, the year after they won the World Series, and he
last played in 1995, the year before they won another championship.
<p>
   ``I wasn't cheated because I chose the road,'' he said. ``Very
honestly, I would do it again. Even if I knew they were going to
win. I know I did the right thing.''
<p>
   There was a possibility Mattingly could have been competing
against the Yankees during their magical sprint to the championship
last season because Jim Krivacs, his agent, confirmed that
Baltimore inquired about Mattingly during the All-Star Game break.
Krivacs said the Orioles ``knew they had a problem in the
clubhouse'' and wanted Mattingly as a designated hitter and a
positive influence. Rebuffed, the Orioles then obtained Eddie
Murray from the Cleveland Indians, who had pursued Mattingly last
spring.
<p>
   ``No, not during midseason,'' said Mattingly, when asked why he
did not seize the opportunity with Baltimore. ``It opened my eyes.
It got me thinking about clubs being interested. But I had made a
commitment to sitting out the season.''
<p>
   After last season, Mattingly set up the parameters of wanting to
play only regularly for a contender close to his Indiana home if he
played at all in 1997. Krivacs said there have been no serious
discussions with any teams during this off-season, and Mattingly
conceded, ``Every time Jim called me, I would tell him I didn't
want to go there.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   Steinbrenner has already implored Mattingly to join the Yankees
as a spring training coach, and he told Krivacs and Ray Schulte,
Mattingly's representatives, that he would love to have Mattingly
as his manager someday. Mattingly said he would not coach or manage
until his sons, who are 5, 9 and 11, are grown.
<p>
   But he added: ``It's something I'd hate to rule out. I want to
stay involved.''
<p>
   With a .307 career batting average and nine Gold Glove Awards,
Mattingly will receive some support for a bust in Cooperstown, N.Y.
But there will be long arguments about his candidacy for the Hall
of Fame.
<p>
   ``It's all been stated,'' Mattingly said. ``It's all out there.
The final arguments have been made. As a player, I am what I am. I
did what I did. I don't know if that puts me in the category or
not.''
<p>
   Steinbrenner said, ``They should close the building if he isn't
in it.''
<p>
   On the flight from Evansville to New York Tuesday night,
Mattingly and his wife, Kim, reminisced about their flight from
Evansville to Oneonta, N.Y. almost 18 years ago. It was Mattingly's
first minor-league assignment with the Yankees.
<p>
   ``To come from where I came from to this point is a long road
for the guy who couldn't run, who couldn't throw and who didn't hit
for power,'' said Mattingly. ``It's a long ride. It's been a great
ride.''
<p>
   INSIDE PITCH:
<p>
   The checkered Yankee career of Scott Kamieniecki also ended
Wednesday when the 32-year-old right-hander agreed to a
minor-league contract with the Baltimore Orioles. Kamieniecki, who
was a free agent after the Yankees did not tender him an offer for
1997, was invited to the Orioles' training camp and will get a
$760,000, one-year salary if he makes the pitching staff. He is
guaranteed $380,000. Kamieniecki, who reached the majors in 1991,
underwent surgery on his right elbow in 1995 and started the 1996
season on the disabled list. He was activated last April and had
five starts before the Yankees optioned him.
<p>
   ``We talked to him about a minor-league contract with the chance
to make the club and make incentives to get him back to a
respectable salary,'' said General Manager Bob Watson of the
Yankees. ``It's my understanding he had assurances he can make
their rotation. But we wouldn't make that guarantee.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2049EST
</TRAILER>
