<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=ttc-z> A9799 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BROWN-LADN </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0770 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BKC-BROWN-LADN &QL; 
RAVELING OWNED BRUINS AT END OF USC TENURE &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
By TIM BROWN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Los Angeles Daily News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   LOS ANGELES  &MD;  In the later years of George Raveling's coaching
career, this was his week. This was his night.
<p>
   Even now, happily employed by Nike, CBS and Fox, and utterly
sickened by some of the maneuvering within his former athletic
department, Raveling can't help but feel the tug of USC versus
UCLA.
<p>
   ``It made any pain that came with coaching at USC worth it,''
Raveling said. ``I kind of lived for the UCLA games.
<p>
   ``And as time moved on, I became more obsessed with beating
UCLA.''
<p>
   On Monday of UCLA week he'd sit at the head of a long table of
reporters at Julie's, lapping soup laced with Tabasco. The
one-liners would start about the God-almighty Bruins and the
pitiful little Trojans, and basketball fans from all over town
would lean in so they could laugh with him.
<p>
   Everyone knew the routine and everyone knew Raveling thought
he'd win again.
<p>
   It did take him some time to figure it out. At USC he lost his
first seven games against the boys in light blue and then won six
of his last nine and five of his last seven, before that
early-morning car wreck talked him out of the profession.
<p>
   Raveling didn't go invited to any Final Fours while at USC and
ended only one season in eight in the national top 10. But he did
find a way to beat UCLA, something of a lost art at Figueroa and
Jefferson.
<p>
   ``It was important to me,'' Raveling said this week. ``Deep down
inside maybe there was some hurt from the losses we took at
Washington State (to John Wooden's UCLA teams). We took some
big-time hind whippings.
<p>
   ``One thing I'll always remember, when we lost to them (former
UCLA athletic director) J.D. Morgan would always come into our
locker room and say, `George, your boys really played well.'''
<p>
   Raveling chuckled and continued with a Jack Nicholson voice that
was supposed to be Morgan's, ``Just once I wanted to go up to him
and say, `J.D., your boys really played well.' Unfortunately, he
retired and died before we beat them.''
<p>
   Damn the luck.
<p>
   Strategically, Raveling said, ``I always felt we were physically
tougher than they were,'' though athletically inferior, so he
trotted out his zone defenses, especially for the Bruins.
<p>
   ``You had to make them play a half-court game,'' he said. ``They
hate to play half-court basketball. You have to make them play long
stretches on defense. You're taking great athletes and making them
stand still and pass the ball. They never had any player movement
against the zone.''
<p>
   His last team, in 1994, defeated UCLA in among the final games
Raveling coached. No big deal.
<p>
   ``There wasn't a (UCLA) game my last four years there I thought
we'd lose,'' he said.
<p>
   Ultimately, the pain from battles with USC athletic director
Mike Garrett and a two-car collision near campus became too severe
to continue. He became a consultant for Nike, primarily in its
grassroots basketball programs. And rather than doing those jumping
jacks on USC's sideline tonight, he'll do the color commentary on
Stanford's, against Washington.
<p>
   Raveling said he won't ever coach again under any circumstance.
He said he holds no bitterness toward USC or about the public
nature of his feud with Garrett.
<p>
   Asked about his relationship with Garrett and how it
deteriorated so, Raveling said, ``Let me just say this, and I don't
want to get particular: There's nothing more dangerous in life than
a person who doesn't know and who doesn't realize he doesn't
know.''
<p>
   His self-evaluation is nearly as cutting.
<p>
   ``I thought I was an average coach,'' he said. ``I probably got
more credit for being a big-time recruiter than I deserved. The
thing I feel best about is I really understood what the real
responsibilities of a coach are. I didn't get myself blinded into
winning at all costs.''
<p>
   That could be a highly rationalized analysis by a coach who lost
more often than he won at USC. Then again, just the other day,
Yamen Sanders, a forward on two of Raveling's USC teams, called for
marital advice. Fact is, former players call all the time.
<p>
   ``I miss him,'' said Stais Boseman, one of three players left
from the Raveling era. ``This is just basketball. Life is a whole
different issue. I wish he was still here. It's sort of like having
a father as a coach. Now, sometimes that's bad and sometimes it's
good.
<p>
   ``He's just a good person to know and a great friend. There are
a lot of false people in the world and he's not one of them.'' &UR; 
</TEXT>
