<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ENVOY-RESIGN-N </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0233 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TAIWAN-ENVOY-RESIGN-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TOP U.S. REPRESENTATIVE IN TAIWAN QUITS AMID PROBE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  James C. Wood Jr., who heads the organization that
represents the United States in Taiwan and is at the center of a
Justice Department inquiry into whether he solicited donations for
the Clinton campaign, has resigned his post, the State Department
said Wednesday.
<p>
   Wood had served as the chairman of the American Institute in
Taiwan since December 1995. The institute was created in 1979 to
carry on unofficial United States relations with Taiwan after the
diplomatic recognition of China.
<p>
   In the fall, the inspector general's office at the State
Department forwarded to the Justice Department allegations that
Wood had urged Taiwanese business executives  &MD;  many of whom carry
dual passports and hold U.S. citizenship  &MD;  to contribute to
President Clinton's re-election effort. That investigation is still
under way.
<p>
   Wood's appointment in 1995 had surprised many in the State
Department, as he had relatively little experience dealing with
China or Taiwan. The post that Wood held is usually filled with
career diplomats with extensive background in the delicate politics
between China and Taiwan, which Beijing regards as a renegade
province. Wood had held several other diplomatic posts, however,
chiefly as a legal adviser.
</TEXT>
