<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9805 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LION-FOX-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0334 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FOOD-LION-FOX-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ABC BLASTS FOX NEWS CHANNEL'S BROADCAST OF `OUTTAKES' &LR;  &QL; 
(Sidebar with FOOD-LION-ABC) &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; By BILL CARTER &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   In an action described as ``outrageously unfair'' by an ABC
executive, the Fox News Channel Wednesday included unused material
or ``outtakes'' from ABC's Food Lion report in its coverage of the
jury decision against ABC.
<p>
   Fox received the outtakes from Food Lion, the supermarket chain
that won $5.5 million in punitive damages from ABC Wednesday.
Presenting several minutes from them in news reports all day,
announcers said that they showed that Food Lion may have had an
even stronger case against the network because the tapes seemed to
show ABC had engaged in unethical practices, like staging evidence
of spoiled meat.
<p>
   Representatives from CBS, NBC and CNN said that their network
had not been offered the material by Food Lion and that, in any
case, it was unlikely they would have chosen to broadcast it,
unless it was presented in full context.
<p>
   Teri Everett, the spokeswoman for ABC News, said the network had
not been informed in advance by Fox that it intended to use the
material supplied by Food Lion.
<p>
   John Moody, the vice president of news for Fox, said he had
asked ABC to have an executive available for comment about an hour
after the first report appeared.
<p>
   David Westin, the president of ABC, said: ``I find it
outrageously unfair that a news organization would proceed that
way. The tape that Food Lion presented is a gross distortion of
what actually occurred.''
<p>
   Moody said that Fox did include an official statement from the
president of ABC News, Roone Arledge. That addressed the jury
award, not the outtakes from Food Lion. But he added that Fox did
bring on the ABC lawyer in the case to present his side on a
program Wednesday evening.
<p>
   Moody said Fox chose to use the outtakes provided by Food Lion
because they illuminated ``a very important aspect of this story.''
</TEXT>
