<SLUG> BC-BIZINSIDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0708 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BIZINSIDER-SFCHRON &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; FINANCIAL COLUMN &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; What's the Real Story Behind Netscape's Perilous Slide? &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Herb Greenberg &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR; 
A month or two ago, when I asked a number of prominent investment
pros which Internet stocks would be worth owning for the long-haul,
the one name that kept coming up was Netscape. They said the real
story was in the business of providing browsers and other software
to businesses, for use on intranets, and that the threat from
Microsoft was overblown. &HT;    Since then, the stock has lost around one-third of its value,
falling another 75 cents yesterday to close at $41.50. The slide
started after several analysts, including one or two big bulls,
began questioning the company's fourth quarter.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   That's noteworthy because in its short life, Netscape has always
beaten analyst estimates by a longshot.
<p>
   Suddenly, it appears, by all accounts, the Mountain View
Internet software maker had to scramble to drum up last-minute
sales just to meet analyst estimates. That's not usually a problem
software companies have in the early years of their lives.
<p>
   How could a company that was supposedly so hot get so cold so
quickly?
<p>
   Or is it really still hot, and are the events of the past few
weeks merely a series of rumors feeding on themselves?
<p>
   I've picked up two stories, both from credible sources. The
first is that midway through December, Netscape realized its sales
were about a quarter below internal expectations, resulting in a
mad dash.
<p>
   The second is that by the middle of December the company thought
it had more than met its goals, so the jubilant sales force took
off for the holidays. A week later they realized that somebody
counted wrong, and some sales had been double-counted and the
company was still well short of its goals.
<p>
   There are even rumors, fairly widespread, that Netscape has lost
a big customer (the name Chrysler has been mentioned) and that it
relied on one or two big transactions to make its sales quota. A
spokeswoman, however, categorically denies that a big customer  &MD; 
she specifically named Chrysler  &MD;  was lost. She adds that ``there
was no deal that was material to the company's results in the
quarter.''
<p>
   Furthermore, regarding what might have gone wrong with the
quarter, she says, ``I don't think people would have gotten that
cocky that they wouldn't try to close business'' by the end of the
quarter  &MD;  even if the company had already met its sales
projections.
<p>
   What does appear to be certain, however, is that the composition
of Netscape's business is changing. Now, instead of just selling
Internet browsers and servers, it's also trying to create broader
software solutions for businesses, adding such features as e-mail
and other tools that allow employees to talk with one another.
Those are markets already dominated by Lotus and Microsoft, and
``Netscape has to displace an incumbent to win,'' says longtime
Netscape bear Bill Smith of Merrill Lynch.
<p>
   Furthermore, last week Smith told his clients that by struggling
to make the fourth quarter, the company may have been forced to
steal business from the first quarter, which traditionally has been
weak for software companies.
<p>
   More details are likely to come out Tuesday, when Netscape
releases earnings. Never has an earnings release, or the subsequent
conference call with analysts, been so important for the company:
Any convincing arguments by execs that everything is hunky-dory
could give investors a reason to think Netscape's stock, at these
prices, is a bargain.
<p>
   Anything else, and, well, Netscape could join the ranks of those
companies whose stocks become damaged goods.
<p>
   Brain Dead
<p>
   An item here yesterday, elaborating on an item from the day
before, mentioned that Data Broadcasting's earnings two years ago
had been inflated because of a one-time ``charge.'' Obviously, that
should have been ``gain.'' Yet another case of my brain and
fingers, up against a tight deadline, disagreeing with one another.
<p>
   Herb Greenberg can be reached online at  &LR; bizinsider(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign &LR; ) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; , and can be read on The Gate at
 &LR; www.sfgate.com/finance &LR; /.
</TEXT>
