<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=taf-z> A9809 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0756 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DOW DROPS 33.87 POINTS; IBM SHARES FALL 6 PERCENT &LR;  &QL; 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID BARBOZA &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Dragged down by a steep decline in the price of IBM
shares, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 33.87 points
Wednesday to close at 6,850.03, ending a run of four consecutive
sessions that set new closing highs.
<p>
   While the blue chips slumped, the Nasdaq composite index surged,
reaching its fourth consecutive closing high on the strength of two
of IBM's technology rivals: Microsoft and Intel. The Nasdaq
composite index of all the market's stocks rose 11.09 points, to
1,388.06.
<p>
   IBM, Intel and Microsoft have all reported strong fourth-quarter
earnings in the last eight days, and all three have warned
investors that their rates of growth may slow in the coming year.
<p>
   But shares of Intel and Microsoft have rallied on the
technology-heavy Nasdaq index since their reports, while IBM's
stock price sputtered Wednesday after it reported its earnings
after the market's close on Tuesday.
<p>
   Analysts said that while Microsoft and Intel warned of slowing
growth in the coming quarters, both companies have strong prospects
for the future. By contrast, IBM's warning means that the company
is forecasting what some analysts consider just average corporate
growth this year.
<p>
   ``IBM is saying their rate of growth is slowing to corporate
averages,'' said James M. Meyer, an analyst at Janney Montgomery
Scott in Philadelphia. ``Microsoft and Intel are slowing to rates
that are well beyond corporate averages. What IBM is saying is a
little less appetizing.''
<p>
   Though IBM's earnings rose 18 percent last quarter from the
corresponding period a year earlier, revenue was up only 6 percent;
some analysts had been looking for a double-digit increase.
<p>
   ``If IBM is going to be characterized as a growth company, I
think it's imperative that you have above-average revenue growth,''
Meyer said. ``Analysts are generally looking for growth of about 15
percent.''
<p>
   Wednesday, IBM's stock suffered all day. The stock fell as many
as 13 points in early trading, before recovering some of its loss
to close down 10 a share, to 158. The drop of roughly 6 percent
accounted for most of the Dow's loss.
<p>
   Meanwhile, shares of Microsoft and Intel have made impressive
gains. Those two companies, along with other big technology stocks
 &MD;  like Dell Computer and Compaq Computer  &MD;  continue to lift broader
market indexes. On the strength of Microsoft and Intel, the Nasdaq
100, an index of Nasdaq's 100 largest stocks, gained 11.79 points,
to 925.52. This year, the Nasdaq 100 is up nearly 12 percent, far
outpacing the Dow's gain of 6.2 percent.
<p>
   Indeed, nearly half the gain of the Nasdaq 100 this year is
attributable to Microsoft and Intel, the index's two largest
stocks. Shares of Microsoft rose 2], to 97], a new high, and Intel
gained 4 1/16, to 152[, also a record high. IBM, Intel and
Microsoft were also three of the four most actively traded stocks
Wednesday, accounting for more than $5 billion worth of shares.
<p>
   Rising stock prices lifted the Dow Jones average close to 6,900
points Tuesday in what has thus far been a roaring January bull
run, but Wednesday the blue-chip index got a lesson in what can
happen when one stock begins to deflate.
<p>
   ``That tells you a little bit about this market,'' said Richard
E. Cripps, an analyst at Legg Mason in Baltimore. ``IBM is a
bellwether stock, and traditionally a stock like that has been able
to affect the whole market. But this market was able to isolate
IBM.''
<p>
   In other words, while IBM's stock sank Wednesday, dozens of
other technology stocks gained. Compaq was up 4~ a share, to 83],
and Dell rose 2|, to 66}.
<p>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks also bucked the Dow
decline, rising 3.51 points, to 786.23, a closing high of its own.
The New York Stock Exchange composite also rose 1.23 points, to
412.80, in a volatile session of trading. Volume on the New York
Stock Exchange was 587.3 million shares; declining issues outpaced
advancers, 1,328 to 1,222.
<p>
   Other issues doing well Wednesday include banking stocks. Shares
of Wells Fargo rose sharply again Wednesday, gaining 8], to 297[.
Shares of the bank holding company rose 9 points Tuesday, after it
said that while its net income slipped last quarter, its operating
profits rose.
</TEXT>
