<SLUG> BC-BOX-WHITAKER-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0221 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BOX-WHITAKER-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOR WHITAKER, TIME TO FOCUS &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   With Oscar De La Hoya waiting in the wings for a big payday in
April, Pernell Whitaker might be expected to take Diobelis Hurtado
lightly for their World Boxing Council welterweight title fight at
the Atlantic City (N.J.) Convention Center Friday night.
<p>
   But Whitaker, who started out as a lightweight, concedes that he
learned a valuable lesson in the first of his two, and only, fights
last year against Wilfredo Rivera. Admittedly unmotivated and
unprepared for that bout last April in the Netherlands Antilles,
Whitaker was lucky to emerge with a split-decision victory.
<p>
   Forewarned and prepared  &MD;  and determined to dispel suspicions
that he might have begun to slip  &MD;  Whitaker clearly outpointed
Rivera in their 12-round rematch five months later.
<p>
   ``I'm not looking ahead to De La Hoya,'' the 33-year-old WBC
champion insisted before his final workout Wednesday at a health
club in Atlantic City. ``This has been one of my best training
camps, and I feel that I'm at the best I've been since 1993. I know
I have to be focused for this one.''
<p>
   Whitaker, 39-1-1 since turning professional in 1994, spent as
much time during and after a news conference talking about De la
Hoya as he did about Hurtado.
</TEXT>
