<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=ttd-z> A9811 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0468 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-INTERNET-SFCHRON &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; $59 Buys Internet for a Lifetime &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR; 
Move over, America Online. &HT;    A San Jose startup,  &LR; bigger.net, is taking on AOL and other
Internet providers by offering unlimited Internet access without
monthly fees.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Beginning today,  &LR; bigger.net says it will charge consumers $59
for unlimited, lifetime use of the Net. It will ask for a $10
annual deposit to maintain users' e-mail addresses.
<p>
   Customers will receive a CD-ROM program of Netscape Navigator
browser software to set up an account, although the service also
works with Microsoft's browser.
<p>
   Unlike AOL's popular service  &MD;  which has mushroomed to 8 million
users  &MD;  the new site does not provide content and will depend
entirely on banner ads for revenue.
<p>
   The ads will appear in a boxed area on users' computer screens,
while they cruise the Net.
<p>
   ``We want to make the Internet available to people who can't
afford subscription fees of $240 to $360 a year,'' said company
chief executive Jeff Fortin. The service will initially be
available in most of San Francisco, San Mateo, Santa Clara, Alameda
and Contra Costa counties. Fortin said the 1-year-old company plans
to launch operations in Los Angeles and San Diego by mid-March and
nationwide throughout 1997.
<p>
   The latest Internet service provider, which employs 18, says it
is the first to eschew the monthly charges that AOL, Microsoft,
AT&AMP;T WorldNet and others have adopted to win customers.
<p>
   While that business model has resulted in millions of consumers
jumping onto the Internet bandwagon, it has created unprecedented
congestion on the Net.
<p>
   AOL, in particular, has been besieged by online traffic. Since
it went to a flat-rate pricing scheme of $19.95 per month on
December 1, its system has buckled under the weight of 1 million
new users.
<p>
   The spike in online use last week prompted AOL chief executive,
Steve Case, to plead with users to cut back their time online
during peak hours.
<p>
   To avoid the same gridlock problems that have bedeviled AOL,
 &LR; bigger.net said it is limiting its capacity to 200,000 people over
the next three months.
<p>
   In addition to Netscape,  &LR; bigger.net says it has enlisted the
help of MFS Worldcom, Bay Networks and Acclaim Technology for
equipment and services.
<p>
   Even with that kind of backing,  &LR; bigger.net faces a ``tremendous
challenge'' of adding customers while building a national network,
according to analysts.
<p>
   ``AOL so far has failed because they're laying the tracks while
the train is running,'' said Allen Weiner, an analyst at Dataquest,
a San Jose market research company.
<p>
   Consumers can order the  &LR; bigger.net service after noon today at
(800) 228-1992.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2055EST
</TRAILER>
