<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=tad-z> A9812 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0899 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BOHLS-COLUMN-COX  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; ATTN: Sports Editors.
<p>
    &UR; COMMENTARY: PATRIOTS' TERRY GLENN, A SURVIVOR, A WINNER
<p>
    &UR; By KIRK BOHLS &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  You notice the eyes first. Terry Glenn stares at
you with his big, brown eyes, and they seem to be sad eyes. Sad but
proud, very proud. Eyes that have seen a life of welfare, a paltry
existence shared with a single- parent mother and a younger
half-sister, a life shattered by the senseless murder of his mother
when he was but 13.
<p>
   Terry Glenn is a survivor. You can see it in his eyes.
<p>
   With his dark mustache and short goatee, this handsome man is as
neatly groomed as his early life was chaotic and ragged. The voice
of the New England Patriots wide receiver never falters as he
traces a life that seemed headed for an end that was more tragic
than magic.
<p>
   He grew up destitute. At times Glenn and his mother, Donetta,
and half- sister, Dorothy, had no electricity or gas in their
Columbus, Ohio, apartment. Through welfare checks, they made ends
meet or at least come close. Glenn never knew his father, has never
heard from him and doesn't want to.
<p>
   One afternoon when he and Dorothy were at an aunt's house, the
police called, saying they had discovered a body in an abandoned
building and were seeking identification. Glenn all but expected
the next call telling him his mother had been beaten to death by an
acquaintance, a man who stalked her for weeks and who now is
serving a sentence of 13 to 40 years.
<p>
   ``I just cried,'' he says softly. ``I started thinking about the
consequences and asking if she was really gone. I was wondering
what would I do. It intensified the hurt I had.''
<p>
   For the next year, Glenn lived in four different homes of
relatives. The relatives who passed him around talked of placing
him in a children's services home. Dorothy moved in with her father
in Akron.
<p>
   ``It was like there was nothing to live for,'' he says. ``It was
so devastating I didn't want to go on. It hurt.''
<p>
   Glenn became friends with June Henley, who also played football,
most recently as a star running back for the Kansas Jayhawks. He
readily accepted the Henley family's offer to put him up one night.
He stayed for eight years. They became his legal guardians.
<p>
   Football remained his other salvation.
<p>
   In all likelihood, his Patriots wouldn't be readying to meet the
Green Bay Packers in Sunday's Super Bowl without Glenn  &MD;  his
quarterback, Drew Bledsoe, said as much  &MD;  and Glenn certainly
wouldn't be a 22-year-old celebrity but for football. He might not
even be alive.
<p>
   Football kept him on the outskirts of trouble in his rough
neighborhood in Columbus when his best friends were immersing
themselves in it.
<p>
   Football got him into Ohio State, where he walked on and became
the nation's most explosive receiver. He played in the same
90,000-seat Ohio Stadium where he used to hawk soda water in the
stands for $30 a tray. At least, that's what he could have made,
except for the fact he never sold more than half that because he
was too occupied watching the games.
<p>
   The game made the 5-foot-11-inch, 184-pound rookie the
first-round pick of the Patriots even though Coach Bill Parcells
was bent on selecting a defensive player.
<p>
   Parcells says Glenn wasn't forced on him by his team's scouting
department, which rated the receiver the highest player on its
draft board. The department spends about $2 million a year making
such evaluations. ``I'm not stupid,'' the coach says. ``I've used
him the best I can.''
<p>
   He also mentally abused him with some denigrating putdowns.
<p>
   ``Bill likes good players,'' Patriots defensive coordinator Al
Groh said. ``In my pre-draft work, I saw a lot of Big Ten
linebackers and a lot of Ohio State games. Every game I'd see one
of those Terry Glenn plays. What are Terry Glenn plays? Bigs ones.
Long ones.''
<p>
   Those plays didn't come as quickly in New England. A pulled
hamstring and Parcells' own impatience prompted the head coach to
refer to Glenn as ``she.'' On Tuesday, Parcells defended the
much-publicized incident and said, ``People in Boston know it was a
joke. I still call him that.''
<p>
   If Parcells was questioning Glenn's toughness and mental makeup,
he was testing the wrong guy. Glenn never blinked, never broke.
Some wonder if his reservoir of tears hadn't been depleted.
Parcells never apologized.
<p>
   ``It didn't bother me at all,'' Glenn says. ``I was more
concerned about getting on the field and not being a bust.''
<p>
   Instead, he busted out in a big way. He caught 90 passes, an NFL
record for rookie wide receivers, for 1,132 yards and six
touchdowns. In two playoff games, Glenn led the Patriots with six
receptions for 102 yards and should be a critical a factor in New
England's chances Sunday night.
<p>
   True to the rest of his life, Glenn did it the hard way and said
he won his coach over with an eight-catch performance against the
New York Giants. That was the regular-season finale.
<p>
   Glenn will soon return to Columbus to spend time with his
8-month-old son, Terry Jr., and also to speak to kids in school who
might be unfocused or unwanted.
<p>
   ``I want other kids to know my story,'' Glenn says. ``Something
good can come out of something bad.''
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (Story Filed By The AMERICAN STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TEXAS.)
<p>
    &UR; For clients of The New York Times News Service &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
