<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tic-z> A9813 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-FRITZ-AZR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0740 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PACKERS-FRITZ-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AGE NOT STOPPING SHURMUR IN HIS SUPER BOWL RUN &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By STEVE SCHOENFELD &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  Green Bay Packers assistant coach Johnny Holland
was telling a story earlier this week about going to New Orleans
International Airport to pick up his son's baby-sitter.
<p>
   ``He is talking about making sure everything goes smoothly, how
his baby-sitter is old, how she's 65,' '' said Packers defensive
coordinator Fritz Shurmur.
<p>
   ``I said, `Timeout, this is a 64-year-old you're talking to.'
<p>
   ``He said, `Yeah, but you're in a 45-year-old body.' ''
<p>
   The subject of age comes up frequently with Shurmur. Nearly
every time he has interviewed for a head coaching job in the past
decade, it's been a contributing factor in not getting the job.
<p>
   Twice the Cardinals interviewed him, once when Joe Bugel got the
job, and again two years ago when Vince Tobin was hired. In
between, he was the team's defensive coordinator from 1991-93.
<p>
   On Tuesday, the St. Louis Rams hired 60-year-old Dick Vermeil, a
move that perplexed Packers offensive coordinator Sherman Lewis,
who also has been passed over for head coaching jobs. ``I threw my
hands in the air,'' Lewis said. ``I couldn't understand the
logic.''
<p>
   Shurmur didn't get upset. He's just happy to be in the Super
Bowl for the first time in his 21 years coaching in the NFL.
<p>
   ``When I got out of (college), I thought I'd coach high school
10 to 12 years and then be a principal,'' Shurmur said. ``I wasn't
on the fast track. I'm a survivor. I've been fortunate. I have
really good health. I still have a lot of energy. I've been blessed
with all that, and I have a wife who has been able to tolerate all
this nonsense.''
<p>
   Shurmur said he won't be upset if he leaves pro football without
getting a head coaching opportunity because ``I'm not motivated by
that.''
<p>
   But he has been motivated to get to the Super Bowl. Four
previous times, he has coached in NFC title games but lost: Twice
with the Los Angeles Rams (1985 and '89) and once with the Packers
('95).
<p>
   ``It became apparent to me in my fourth NFC championship game
that the success was tied to the home field,'' Shurmur said. ``This
is the first time I had the home field. It is important to fight
during the season so you can play that last game on your field.''
<p>
   Shurmur began his NFL coaching career with the Detroit Lions in
1975. In '79, he went to the Patriots, and he became their
defensive coordinator the next year.
<p>
   In 1980, he hired a defensive line coach, Bill Parcells, now
head coach of the Patriots.
<p>
   Parcells said Tuesday he credits Shurmur for ``breaking me into
the league.''
<p>
   ``He was out of football when we hired him,'' Shurmur said.
``The first time I met him, I could tell he was really a bright
guy. He was a quick-minded guy who had a great command of the
game.''
<p>
   Shurmur also is considered a real student of the game. He has
written three books: Coaching Team Defense, The Five Linebacker
Eagle Defense and Coaching Team Defense, second edition.
<p>
   The Packers finished with the NFL's best defense this season,
but he refuses to take the credit.
<p>
   ``I'm coaching in the best place in the world for doing what I
do,'' he said. ``We've got a good chance to win. Ron Wolf (general
manager), Mike Holmgren (head coach) and Bob Harlan (president and
chief executive officer) create a great environment. Everyone in
the state is interested in what we do. It's a small town, and I
have a house on a lake that I can fish. So, there aren't many more
things in life I need.''
<p>
   Shurmur, who also has a houseboat at Lake Havasu, would like one
more thing  &MD;  a victory in Sunday's Super Bowl.
<p>
   ``I'm glad to be here, but if I hadn't gotten to the Super Bowl,
the game wouldn't have owed me anything,'' he said. ``I know a lot
of guys who tried but didn't make it to the Super Bowl. I'm
grateful for the opportunity, and it's hard for me to describe my
feeling after the (NFC title) game, when it hit me we were coming
here to the Super Bowl.''
<p>
   Even if the Packers win Sunday, he knows many still will think
he's too old to become a head coach in the NFL. There have been 10
openings this year, and he hasn't been interviewed for any job.
<p>
   ``People ask my why I'm not higher on the list,'' he said. ``I
say, `Go see the people who make those lists.' ''
</TEXT>
