<SLUG> BC-EARLYRELEASE-TEX-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0930 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARLYRELEASE-TEX-COX  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; ATTN: Texas Editors.
<p>
    &UR; COST OF ENDING EARLY-RELEASE PROGRAM DISPUTED
<p>
    &UR; By MIKE WARD &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   AUSTIN, Texas  &MD;  A proposal to abolish a controversial
early-release program for Texas convicts ran into money trouble
Wednesday, as a House leader predicted it could cost a whopping $2
billion over five years.
<p>
   The previous price tag, according to the proposal's Senate
sponsors, was $400 million.
<p>
   ``There goes the governor's property tax relief, right there,''
House Corrections Committee Chairman Rep. Allen Hightower said.
<p>
   ``We'll fill all the (extra prison) beds we have now. We'll have
inmates backing up in the county jails again,'' said Hightower, a
Huntsville Democrat whose committee oversees prison programs.
``We'll need to build lots and lots of additional beds in the next
five years, another prison construction program like the one we
just finished.''
<p>
   But Sens. John Whitmire and Jerry Patterson, the Senate sponsors
of the proposal, challenged the $2 billion estimate, which
Hightower said he calculated on his own.
<p>
   ``That's horse manure,'' Patterson, R-Pasadena, said of the $2
billion estimate. ``The real issue here is the state budget ... how
any surplus is going to be spent, whether doing away with mandatory
supervision is worth whatever cost there is.''
<p>
   Whitmire, D-Houston and chairman of the Senate Criminal Justice
Committee, system, agreed. ``The bottom line is if we want to do
this, we can make it work,'' he said.
<p>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who has campaigned to abolish the mandatory
supervision program and urged the Legislature last week to
fast-track the change into law, also thinks the cost will be much
less than Hightower estimated, said his press secretary, Karen
Hughes.
<p>
   In fact, Hughes said, Bush plans to include the $42.9 million
cost of abolishing the program for violent- and sex-crime offenders
in his upcoming budget proposal. Because that group of convicts
totals only about 2,714 felons during the next two years, that
could be far less costly than including the 80,745 who otherwise
would be eligible.
<p>
   Under the Whitmire-Patterson bill, automatic release from prison
on so- called mandatory release would abolished for violent- and
sex-crime offenders. They could not be freed early unless parole
officials approved.
<p>
   All other felons who are freed on mandatory supervision could be
subject to that same review, according to Patterson.
<p>
   While mandatory supervision was outlawed for violent offenders
in 1987, and automatic mandatory release was done away with for all
other offenders two years ago, felons who were convicted before
then could still be released automatically.
<p>
   That is what the Whitmire-Patterson bill wants to stop. The
measure is slated for a Senate hearing Feb. 4.
<p>
   When a similar bill was debated two years ago, it faced
opposition over its cost and questions over whether it was
constitutional to change the rules for convicts already sitting in
prison.
<p>
   In the end, the Legislature opted to abolish mandatory release
only for future convicts.
<p>
   Patterson and Whitmire insist they have resolved the legal
questions: The change will alter no one's sentence, they said. It
will require only that before they can be released from prison they
will have to be approved by the parole board.
<p>
   Convicts' sentences will not change, Patterson said. They will
just serve their time inside a prison rather than outside one, on
mandatory release supervised by a parole officer.
<p>
   The cost of abolishing mandatory supervision promises to figure
heavily in the debate on the bill. With limited money available,
and the list of budget demands growing by the day, the Legislature
will have to decide whether to approve it as proposed and cut other
state programs, or scale it back.
<p>
   And for many lawmakers, the last choice may prove the least
acceptable  &MD;  with Bush and crime victims' groups with lots of
political clout pushing for the entire program to be abolished.
<p>
   ``This is an important issue for a lot of people,'' said Rep.
Peggy Hamric, R-Houston, author of a House bill that is similar to
the Whitmire-Patterson measure.
<p>
   Hightower said he intends to closely examine the cost of the
proposals. ``We don't have unlimited money to spend down here,'' he
said.
<p>
   According to a new estimate forwarded Wednesday to Lt. Gov. Bob
Bullock, the Whitmire-Patterson bill could cost $134 million during
the next two years  &MD;  and a total of $412 million in five  &MD;  in
prison operating expenses alone, not including the cost of building
any new prisons.
<p>
   The estimate also shows that abolishing mandatory supervision
for all convicts would create a backlog of 3,642 felons in county
jails by next fall  &MD;  and as many as 14,489 felons by 2001. If
mandatory supervision were abolished only for violent and sex-crime
offenders, there would be no backlog this year but it could reach
4,054 by 1999.
<p>
   Whitmire said he sees no reason there should be any backlog. He
said Texas has enough beds in empty prisons and county jails to
house all those felons in the next few years, and could even send
home the 5,000 out-of-state convicts housed in jails if it needs
that space.
<p>
   ``You have to weigh the costs against what is in the public
good,'' he said. ``And in this case, I think it's for the public
good that these inmates stay inside prison  &MD;  even if it costs us
some money.''
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (Story Filed By The AMERICAN STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TEXAS.)
<p>
    &UR; For clients of The New York Times News Service &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
