<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=ttd-z> A9817 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-JEANS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0479 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-JEANS-SFCHRON &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Clothier Says He's Not Too Small For Levi's Britches &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Steve Rubenstein &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR; 
A barrage of complaints helped persuade Levi Strauss to keep
selling blue jeans to an old-fashioned Illinois store with
crumbling plaster walls that the San Francisco company had found to
be too funky for its britches. &HT;    The store, Rathert Clothing, won its reprieve after Illinois Lt.
Gov. Bub Kustra fired off an impassioned letter to company
headquarters on Battery Street, saying its decision to drop the
store in the town of Red Bud was ``greatly troubling.'' A local
congressman weighed in with a letter, too.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Last month, after sending a crew to videotape conditions at
Rathert Clothing, the 144-year-old company said it would no longer
do business with the 110-year-old store because the company was
seeking more ``high-image retail customers.''
<p>
   The store said it would have to shut down because about 90
percent of its trade is in Levis.
<p>
   Carl Zschiegner, an assistant manager at the store, acknowledged
that Rathert Clothing is in an old building with crumbling plaster,
exposed wiring, leaning shelves and a furnace in the changing room.
<p>
   ``We're not real modern, but we always paid our bills,'' he
said.
<p>
   The store was among two dozen that Levi Strauss and Co., which
got its start in 1853 peddling tough pants to California gold
miners, planned to drop as part of a new program to spiff up its
image. The company said those stores include dry cleaning and
pornography establishments.
<p>
   In its letter to store owner Don Rathert, the company said his
store ``does not provide the type of retail environment that is
consistent with the Levi brands' product positioning.''
<p>
   After a flood of angry calls, faxes and letters, the company
relented.
<p>
   ``We made the decision to work with him and take a look at his
situation,'' said Levi's spokesman Gavin Power. ``We want to talk
with him about his business and the fact that he's so dependent on
our products.''
<p>
   News of the pants cutoff led to big business over the weekend.
The southwestern Illinois store, which usually sells two dozen
pairs of pants a day, sold about 200.
<p>
   Rathert said he has been selling pants so long that ne not only
knows his customers' names but their waist and inseam measurements,
too. The extra business over the weekend was a mixed blessing, he
added.
<p>
   ``There's too many people coming in,'' he said. ``I don't want
that much business. It's hard on the legs, hard on the neck, hard
on the back, hard on the feet.''
<p>
   Rathert Clothing occupies a 140-year-old German colonial style
building on Main Street. There is one aisle, lined on both sides
with wooden tables piled high with jeans.
<p>
   ``We're not fancy; we just sell jeans,'' Rathert said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2058EST
</TRAILER>
