<SLUG> BC-WATER-TEXAS-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0982 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-WATER-TEXAS-COX  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; ATTN: Texas Editors.
<p>
    &UR; WATER BILL DEEMED A TOP PRIORITY FOR LAWMAKERS
<p>
    &UR; EDs: With WATER-BOX; WATER-BROWN.
<p>
    &UR; By RALPH K.M. HAURWITZ &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   AUSTIN, Texas  &MD;  A comprehensive water bill filed Wednesday in
the Texas Senate would require statewide drought planning and
stepped-up conservation but would preserve the traditions of local
control and landowner access to ground water.
<p>
   The measure  &MD;  a moderate reform of state water law rather than
radical surgery  &MD;  would, if enacted, stand as the most important
advance in water policy in 40 years, said Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, an
architect of the bill and the lead-off speaker at a news conference
to unveil it in the Senate chamber.
<p>
   ``This is an opportunity for everyone ... to participate in the
deliberations of what I consider to be the most important bill that
Texas will face this session,'' Bullock said. ``Our very survival
depends on it: water.''
<p>
   Gov. George W. Bush, whose top legislative priority is
property-tax reform, issued a statement applauding Bullock and the
measure's sponsor, Sen. Buster Brown, R-Lake Jackson, for bringing
the issue to the forefront.
<p>
   ``The drought of 1996 highlighted the need for Texas to conserve
water and plan for the future, and I look forward to working with
the Legislature to do so,'' the governor said.
<p>
   The 166-page measure, which was given the symbolically important
designation of Senate Bill 1, emerged from months of closed-door
discussions involving state officials and legislative leaders. No
House version has been filed.
<p>
   The bill would require drought planning at the local, regional
and statewide levels; adoption of conservation measures by cities,
water districts and other suppliers; environmental and economic
studies before water could be transferred from one river basin to
another; and protection of fish, wildlife, bays, estuaries and
in-stream flows when new water rights are granted. In addition,
fines for unsafe dams and levees and for unauthorized water
diversions would be raised sharply.
<p>
   The Legislature last rewrote significant portions of the water
code in 1985. Bullock expressed hope that the issue would not be
shelved as it has been many times since he first joined the
Legislature as a member of the House in 1957.
<p>
   Brown, chairman of the Senate Natural Resources Committee,
pledged that the bill would not die. Citing serious ground water
shortages in parts of Central Texas and critically low surface
supplies in the Rio Grande Valley, Brown said the state is
ill-prepared under current law to manage water properly.
<p>
   ``It is obvious that we must begin to act now to establish a
sound, comprehensive water policy for Texas,'' Brown said. Bullock
said he asked the bill's drafters to be ``bold'' and
``controversial,'' asserting that nothing less than the gross state
product  &MD;  the value of all goods and services  &MD;  depends on an
adequate water supply.
<p>
   However, the measure stops short of revising what could have
been the most contentious issue, the rule of capture. The rule is a
legal principle established by the Texas Supreme Court in 1904 that
allows landowners to pump virtually unlimited quantities of ground
water from beneath their property. The bill also does not establish
a sweeping system of centralized control of water resources, as
recommended in a 1993 report by the state auditor's office.
<p>
   Still, the bill would narrow the scope of the capture rule, by
making it easier to establish ground-water districts and granting
such districts broader powers to regulate spacing of wells and
pumping. The rule of capture would prevail outside such districts.
The omission of the capture rule from the provisions addressed by
the bill reflects the lawmakers' and the governor's strong support
for private property rights.
<p>
   Officials of the state's three main water agencies  &MD;  the Water
Development Board, the Natural Resource Conservation Commission and
the Parks and Wildlife Department  &MD;  said the measure offers
long-overdue relief from antiquated policies.
<p>
   Andrew Sansom, executive director of the Parks and Wildlife
Department, said state water planning historically has glossed over
environmental issues. For example, the reservoir-construction boom
following the record drought of the 1950s reduced natural river
flows for fish and wildlife. Bays and estuaries, which provide
multimillion-dollar fishing industries, depend on adequate flows to
maintain the delicate balance between salt water and fresh water.
<p>
   ``It is time for healthy rivers, lakes and estuaries to be
counted among our highest water-use priorities,'' Sansom said.
<p>
   Other reaction to the bill was somewhat muted, mainly because
few people had read it.
<p>
   ``I'm excited about the issue being put on the front burner,''
said Ken Kramer, director of the Lone Star Chapter of the Sierra
Club, an environmental group. ``The fact that it rates Senate Bill
1, an introduction by Lt. Gov. Bullock and sponsorship by the
chairman of the Senate Natural Resources Committee is a pretty good
sign that something is going to happen this session.''
<p>
   Bill Couch, executive director of the Barton Springs/Edwards
Aquifer Conservation District, a ground-water district in southern
Travis and northern Hays counties, said he was pleased by the
additional authority the bill would provide. For example, smaller
wells currently exempt from regulation would come under his
agency's scrutiny, he said.
<p>
   Bob Stallman, president of the Texas Farm Bureau, the state's
largest agricultural organization, said it was too early to offer
an assessment. The bureau supports local underground water
districts but also supports private property rights, he said.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
