<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-WATER-BOX-COX  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; ATTN: Texas Editors.
<p>
    &UR; HIGHLIGHTS OF SENATE WATER BILL
<p>
    &UR; EDs: With WATER-TEXAS.
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
    &MD;  Preserves the rule of capture, a legal principle dating to
1904 that allows landowners to pump essentially unlimited
quantities of ground water regardless of the effect on stream flow,
spring flow and neighbors' wells.
<p>
    &MD;  At the same time, modifies the scope of the capture rule by
making it easier to establish new ground-water conservation
districts, which can regulate pumping to varying degrees. Also
grants new powers to such districts. The rule of capture would
prevail outside districts.
<p>
    &MD;  Requires the Water Development Board to prepare a
comprehensive state drought plan. Creates a committee with
representatives from various state agencies to oversee drought
response.
<p>
    &MD;  Requires water-management planning by cities, water districts
and other water suppliers and water-rights holders. Such planning
would include conservation to ensure efficient day-to-day use as
well as drought-contingency measures to curb lawn watering and
other nonessential uses during dry spells.
<p>
    &MD;  Mandates regional drought planning. For example, the Lower
Colorado River Authority, the City of Austin and other units of
government in Central Texas would prepare a regional plan in
addition to individual plans.
<p>
    &MD;  Requires the Natural Resource Conservation Commission to hold
public meetings and to conduct a detailed financial and
environmental analysis before approving transfers of water from one
river basin to another.
<p>
    &MD;  Grants the conservation commission authority to issue
citations for unauthorized use of surface water. Also increases the
civil penalty to $10,000 from $1,000 and grants administrative
penalty authority as well to the agency.
<p>
    &MD;  Provides legal recognition of the link between surface water
and ground water. Users of each type and regulatory agencies would
have to consider how ground water use affects surface water, and
vice versa.
<p>
    &MD;  Eases legal roadblocks to reuse of treated waste water for
irrigation and other purposes. Also promotes such reuse.
<p>
    &MD;  Raises to $25,000 a day from $1,000 the civil penalty for
failure to repair or remove an unsafe dam. The penalty for unsafe
levees would rise to $25,000 from $100.
<p>
    &MD;  Expands the consideration given to fish, wildlife and bays.
For example, ground-water districts would have to consider spring
flow and related habitat when authorizing new wells.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (Story Filed By The AMERICAN STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TEXAS.)
<p>
    &UR; For clients of The New York Times News Service &LR; 
