<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tic-z> A9822 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHOENIX-OPEN-AZR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0898 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-GLF-PHOENIX-OPEN-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MICKELSON, WOODS LOOK TO BE FRONT-RUNNERS IN PHOENIX OPEN &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BILL HUFFMAN &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - With apologies to Ernie Els, the two best
young players in the world are camped out this week at the $1.5
million Phoenix Open, which gets under way Thursday and runs
through Sunday at the TPC of Scottsdale.
<p>
   There's no question that Tiger Woods and Phil Mickelson are the
people's choice to hook up in Sunday's final round. Whether that
dream match-up can materialize is anybody's guess, but considering
the past two Opens have ended in a playoff, you never know.
<p>
   For those who have forgotten, Mickelson was the ``next Jack
Nicklaus'' before Woods grabbed the hype last fall when he turned
pro.
<p>
   Since that time, Woods has three victories and has knocked down
some pretty solid foes in playoffs  &MD;  Davis Love III in Las Vegas,
and Tom Lehman, in a one-hole, quick-draw contest at the
season-opening Mercedes Championship.
<p>
   Mickelson hasn't had to work overtime since a year ago, when he
went head to head with Justin Leonard in this tournament,
prevailing on the third playoff hole. It was intense stuff, as
Mickelson 1-putted the last seven greens. Bizarre, too, as the
playoff was held in a circus-like atmosphere with several drunks
serving as ringmasters.
<p>
   Mickelson vs. Woods would be even greater theater. Not
surprisingly, the dynamic duo don't quite see it that way. Neither
do their peers.
<p>
   ``You know, I've been asked that question, and I've thought
about it a lot, and to be honest with you, I don't ever see
rivalries developing as prominent as they used to be with, say,
Arnold (Palmer) and Jack (Nicklaus), or Jack and Tom (Watson), or
now even Greg (Norman) and Nick (Faldo),'' Woods said of the
possibility that he and Mickelson would face off many times in the
future.
<p>
   ``I don't ever see it developing quite like that because there
are so many good (young) players now  &MD;  Ernie Els, Phil, David
Duval, Steve Stricker, Justin Leonard. I mean, it goes on and on.
It's very hard for just two to be singled out.''
<p>
   Mickelson also doesn't know what lies ahead. But you get the
feeling that he's honing his flop shot for a chance at Woods.
<p>
   ``We've never even played in the same group,'' Mickelson said.
``But I think it would be cool to go head to head with him coming
down the stretch on Sunday, because he's such a great competitor.
That would be fun.''
<p>
   Both players' games seem capable of it. Woods was a little wild
during Wednesday's Xerox Siler Pro-Am, perhaps the result of an
evening of playing pool at Stixx &AMP; Jetz.
<p>
   Woods, however, is better than most even on a bad day, and his
tremendous power off the tee is tailor-made for the TPC. The long
hitters have even more of an advantage this week, as the fairways
are soft from recent rains.
<p>
   Mickelson said he's ``a little hesitant to get too high'' about
his game. But he likes the condition of the course, with the rough
up and the greens firm.
<p>
   Still, there's no getting away from the fact that Mickelson and
Woods are the favorites in the 72-hole chase.
<p>
   Mark Brooks, the PGA champ, would agree with that. He even went
as far as to say that Woods and Mickelson are the best two young
players in the game, and he made no apologies to Els.
<p>
   ``There's no question about that,'' Brooks said. ``But the odds
are against them ever developing a rivalry. First of all, they'll
only play in about 12 to 14 events together. Then, you've got 100
guys who can win any week. About the only place you might see (a
rivalry) develop is in the majors.''
<p>
   Mark Calcavecchia, the all-time leading money-winner of Phoenix
Open, and the only two-time champ at the TPC, added this qualifier
about a Mickelson-Woods rivalry.
<p>
   ``I don't think so, unless they get in four sudden-death
playoffs together ,'' said Calcavecchia, who will be paired with
Woods during the first two rounds.
<p>
   Could Mickelson handle Woods, who at this point seems to be a
real tiger in playoffs?
<p>
   ``Oh, sure. Timing is everything, and even though Tiger is
obviously very good, he's got a lot of good breaks,'' Calcavecchia
said. ``Or, looking at it from the other end, nothing has gone
against him (in a playoff).''
<p>
   That certainly was the case in the Mercedes, where Woods watched
Lehman hit a 6-iron into the water on the playoff hole, then, with
the pressure slightly off, stuck a 6-iron to within 8 inches of the
cup.
<p>
   Lehman gets another shot at Woods this week, but he's not
thinking about another head-to-head playoff.
<p>
   ``Well, I'm aching for another shot at playing well,'' said the
Scottsdale pro, who admitted he's struggling a bit. ``But I don't
feel I'm playing against Tiger Woods or Phil Mickelson or Nick
Price or Paul Azinger. You just want to beat up on the golf
course.''
<p>
   Like his peers, Lehman doesn't foresee the Woods-Mickelson
rivalry dominating the future golf scene. It's not the same as when
Nicklaus ruled the world, he added.
<p>
   ``Phil and Tiger both have the potential to have a long time at
the top, where guys are shooting at them. Both have the capability
of being dominant, really dominant players,'' he said. ``Whether
they get into a rivalry or not, that's just chance.''
<p>
   One that many fans are hoping begins with a playoff on Sunday.
</TEXT>
