<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-KENNESAW-GINGRICH-COX &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; STUDENTS AT SPEAKER'S FORMER COLLEGE HOLD MOCK ETHICS VOTE
<p>
    &UR; By MARLON MANUEL &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   MARIETTA, Ga.  &MD;  ``Newt Gingrich''  &MD;  actually a 48-year-old
bespectacled piano teacher playing the role of House speaker  &MD;  was
cleared of three ethics charges Wednesday, once the judge
deciphered what the charges were.
<p>
   The mock verdicts were rendered by an introductory American
government class at Kennesaw State University.
<p>
   Eight ``prosecutors'' and eight ``defenders'' shuffled through
evidence  &MD;  newspaper clippings and Internet documents highlighted
in Day-Glo Yellow  &MD;  in a presentation more like ``The People's
Court'' than Court TV.
<p>
   ``We're not law students,'' said Dale Hartsfield, 39, one of the
Gingrich defenders. Asked if he watched the genuine ethics hearings
on TV, Hartsfield said, ``Who has time? We're college students.''
<p>
   Joe Camillo of Marietta, the faux Gingrich acquitted by the
class, was urged by students to take the role of the Republican
leader. A bulky music major, Camillo dressed in a black suit and
carried a black briefcase.
<p>
   His chief qualification: ``He was the only one with gray hair,''
said political science teacher Kerwin Swint, whose class conducted
the project.
<p>
   Seventy-three students considered whether Gingrich broke tax
laws, lied to Congress and received improper gifts from GOPAC, his
political action committee. (Ethics committee special counsel James
Cole alleged Gingrich violated the tax-exempt status of the
Kennesaw State foundation and interviewed school officials during
the actual investigation of Gingrich.)
<p>
   The class cleared Gingrich on all three counts. The closest vote
was 38-35 on the question of whether he lied to Congress.
<p>
   ``That indicates they paid attention and really thought about
it,'' said Swint, who called the project a ``lesson in democracy.''
<p>
   In a defense that would have made Dick Armey proud, 18-year-old
Nicole Burgess of Acworth labeled the charges a ``political smear
against Gingrich and the Republican Party.''
<p>
   Characterizing herself as a political moderate, Burgess viewed
the project ``as more of a challenge to defend Newt, given all the
press against him.''
<p>
   Camillo said wading through research material was daunting. ``It
shows that it's important to stay plugged in with what's going
on,'' Camillo said. ``You should keep trying to get the facts out.
It's easy to get complacent.''
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (Story Filed by Atlanta, Ga., Newspapers.)
