<DOCID> nyt970122.0728 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=taf-z> A9824 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-DALEY-CONFIRM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0964 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-DALEY-CONFIRM-ART-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMMERCE NOMINEE VOWS TO RID AGENCY OF POLITICS &LR;  &QL; 
(ART ADV: Photo of William Daley has been sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) &QL; 
(sw) &QL; 
 &UR; By RICHARD W. STEVENSON &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  President Clinton's nominee for commerce secretary,
William M. Daley, said on Wednesday that if confirmed he would take
steps to depoliticize the department, which Republicans say has
become an outpost of Democratic Party fundraising.
<p>
   In a clear attempt to defuse any complications for his own
nomination and to suggest that he has a reform-minded agenda as
Republicans prepare for congressional hearings on campaign finance,
Daley said he would eliminate 100 of the 260 politically appointed
jobs within the Commerce Department by the end of the year. He also
said he would suspend all the department's international trade
missions for 30 days while he develops guidelines for choosing
participants to insure that no special consideration goes to big
political donors.
<p>
   ``Let me say without hesitation, as someone who has spent many
years in and around the political process, that there is a place
for politics in public life,'' said Daley, a son of one Chicago
mayor and the brother of another. ``But there is no place for
politics in the Department of Commerce.''
<p>
   Daley's pledge to depoliticize the department came one day after
President Clinton announced new restrictions on Democratic
fundraising, including a ban on donations from non-citizens living
in the United States and from American subsidiaries of foreign
companies.
<p>
   Testifying at the opening of his confirmation hearings before
the Senate Commerce Committee, Daley never mentioned John Huang,
who served for a year and a half in a politically appointed trade
job at the department and then went on to become a senior
Democratic fundraiser. Huang's fund-raising activities are at the
heart of questions about whether the Clinton administration traded
access or influence for political donations.
<p>
   Similarly, Daley did not directly address longstanding
complaints by Republicans and nonpartisan campaign-finance watchdog
groups that Ronald Brown, who served as commerce secretary from
1993 until his death in a plane crash last year, had sometimes
favored Democratic supporters in assembling trade missions to
foreign capitals. Brown's trips often gave those American business
executives who accompanied him access to foreign leaders and
provided them opportunities for new deals.
<p>
   Daley's promise to make the department less partisan won
cautious praise from Republicans on the committee, and he
encountered almost no tough questions on the subject.
<p>
   ``Clearly, Mr. Daley, you have an additional responsibility to
make sure that any taint of politicization or illegal behavior is
eradicated as quickly as possible within your department,'' said
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the Commerce Committee's chairman. ``You
have shared your commitment to me to do that, and I certainly take
you at your word and have every confidence that you will do so.''
<p>
   Indeed, Daley was confronted with little of the partisan rancor
that has surrounded the Commerce Department in recent years, going
back to Republican efforts after the 1994 elections to eliminate
the department.
<p>
   The hearing had gone on for more than two hours before Daley
faced a direct question about whether it would be more efficient to
slim down or to eliminate the department, although he had
repeatedly argued without prompting that it played a critical role
in insuring the competitiveness of American industry.
<p>
   Much of the questioning, in fact, suggested why the department
has proven difficult to shrink, much less eliminate. One after
another, senators of both parties asked about specific programs of
concern to their constituents, from Sen. John Kerrey, D-Mass., who
urged continued efforts to help the fishing industry, to Sen. Ted
Stevens, R-Alaska, who urged him to look into a program that
affects some of his state's most remote islands.
<p>
   Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., said the department had helped finance
successful education and training programs in his state, and he
said Daley should limit his efforts to scale back.
<p>
   ``You can eliminate 100, but don't go too far,'' Ford said.
<p>
   While there are no trade missions scheduled to be led by the
commerce secretary over the next month  &MD;  in fact, there have been
only a handful of secretary-led missions since Brown's death  &MD;  the
30-day ban would affect a host of smaller missions. These are
usually led by political appointees or career officials at the
Commerce Department.
<p>
   Over the next month, according to Commerce Department officials,
such missions were scheduled to Hong Kong, France, Eastern Europe,
Canada, Australia, Argentina, India and Indonesia. They will be
rescheduled, officials say, after Daley completes his review of how
the missions are organized.
<p>
   Suspending the missions was Daley's idea, and it is bound to
ruffle some feathers within the department. Some officials there
view the missions themselves as the embodiment of Brown's legacy at
the department, and the suspension as an implicit criticism of how
they were handled under his tenure.
<p>
   Brown and other Commerce officials from his era always denied
any political favoritism.
<p>
   Mickey Kantor, who succeeded Brown, reduced the overall
employment level at the Commerce Department by about 5 percent,
chiefly through attrition. But he made no overt step to overhaul
the trade mission program.
<p>
   The cut in the number of political appointees at Commerce would
bring the figure more in line with the Treasury Department and
other large Cabinet departments.
</TEXT>
