 &UR; BC-BKN-PACERS-MILLER-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; REGGIE MILLER ENJOYS RIVALRY WITH KNICKS &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   INDIANAPOLIS  &MD;  Yes, he had been serious about entertaining
offers from the New York Knicks. And, yes, he believes the rivalry
still lives.
<p>
   ``The Hatfields and McCoys, all over again,'' Reggie Miller said
Wednesday after the Indiana Pacers prepared for Thursday night's
game at Market Square Arena. ``Both teams don't like one another.
They don't pretend like they like one another, and that's fine with
us.''
<p>
   Miller, who was one of the players New York considered courting
in the off-season, said he understood why the Knicks chose Allan
Houston instead. ``He's a lot younger, and you can understand what
they were going for,'' he said. ``They got two players for the
price of one. My price tag was a little higher than Allan's, where
they couldn't have gone out and got Chris Childs if they got me.''
<p>
   Of the differences between Starks and Houston, he added:
``They're two different players. I think Allan is a better
offensive threat than John, but I think John plays much better
defense than Allan.''
</TEXT>
