<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tad-z> A9826 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-OLDEST-TOOLS-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0548 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-OLDEST-TOOLS-COX  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; HAND-MADE TOOLS THOUGHT TO BE OLDEST FOUND IN ETHIOPIA
<p>
    &UR; By MIKE TONER &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   ATLANTA  &MD;  Among humans' earliest ancestors, ``tool time'' began
more than 2.5 million years ago.
<p>
   Crude stone tools found in an Ethiopian stream bed were
identified Wednesday as the oldest hand-made implements in the
world  &MD;  a discovery that pushes the advent of tool-making, and the
intelligence it required, at least 200,000 years further back in
time.
<p>
   Thousands of stone implements unearthed from ancient sediments
in Ethiopia's Gona River Valley show that early hominids had a
``surprisingly sophisticated'' knowledge of toolmaking, researchers
said Wednesday. They found a wide variety of stone flakes and
larger implements fashioned into a form that could be use for
cutting and chopping.
<p>
   ``These objects have been securely dated between 2.5 and 2.6
million years ago, which makes them the oldest known artifacts from
anywhere in the world,'' said Rutgers University anthropologist
Sileshi Semaw.
<p>
   In a report in the current issue of the journal Nature, Semaw
and J.K.W. Harris, chairman of the Rutgers anthropology department,
say the artifacts are so abundant in the area that subsequent
investigations at the site are likely to unearth even older tools.
<p>
   ``Some researchers think the beginnings of technology go along
with a hominid with an expanded brain,'' Harris said. ``In my 25
years experience in Africa, Gona is the richest site for addressing
questions related to human evolution in the time gap between 3
million and 2 million years ago.''
<p>
   Although the region, which includes Ethiopia's Afar badlands, is
best known as the home of Lucy, the fossil remains of a
small-brained, big-jawed, upright-walking species called
Australopithecus afrarensis, researchers have never found any sign
that Lucy's kin, which roamed the area more than 3 million years
ago, ever evolved tool-making skills.
<p>
   The Rutgers discovery, however, comes on the heels of the
Institute of Human Origins report in November that stone tools  &MD; 
similar in size, shape and function to those reported Wednesday  &MD; 
had been found alongside the remains of the jawbone of one of the
earliest known species of genus Homo. Those tools were dated to 2.3
million years ago.
<p>
   ``Modern human technology had humble beginnings,'' says British
anthropologist Bernard Wood. ``But there is no doubt that these
genuine and remarkably sophisticated artifacts push the onset of
tool manufacture back to at least 2.5 million years.''
<p>
   Before the two most recent discoveries, the earliest evidence of
toolmaking came from excavations in Olduvai Gorge in Tanzania,
where anthropologist Mary Leakey documented similar stone artifacts
that were about 1.8 million years old.
<p>
   The most recent discoveries, however, make it clear that human
ancestors had tools  &MD;  and the intelligence to make them  &MD;  almost a
million years earlier.
<p>
   ``The Gona stone tools are very similar to those from Olduvai
Gorge,'' Semaw said. ``It is amazing to realize that the earliest
human technology went more than a million years with almost no
change at all.''
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (Story Filed by Atlanta, Ga., Newspapers.)
<p>
    &UR; For clients of The New York Times News Service &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
