<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tic-z> A9827 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FAVRE-COMMENTARY- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0673 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-FAVRE-COMMENTARY-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NOSY MEDIA GET COLD FACTS FROM FAVRE &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID CASSTEVENS &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS - Brett Favre was talking about his place in
football history when several members of the national press looked
up from their notepads and exchanged sidelong glances.
<p>
   ``If I had done (sniff) what Bart Starr has done,'' Favre was
saying, `I'd be bigger than Elvis now.''
<p>
   Favre sniffed again.
<p>
   Everyone heard it.
<p>
   It was impossible not to. Favre was speaking into a live
microphone. Each time the Green Bay Packers quarterback paused
between sentences or words and inhaled sharply, like a bloodhound
tracking a fresh scent, the amplified snuffling boomed over the
loud speakers, filling the ornate grand ballroom of the Fairmont
Hotel.
<p>
   Favre's remarks at Wednesday's Super Bowl news conference were
translated into 36 languages and piped to our Armed Forces
overseas. But the longer Favre went on about the Packers' balanced
offense and the importance of staying ``focused''  &MD;  the sports
cliche of the 1990s  &MD;  what the quarterback said seemed to take on
less importance than the tell-tale sniffs, which he used like
commas and periods.
<p>
   Occasionally, Favre lightly touched the back of his hand to his
nostrils. The New York Times looked at USA Today. A Milwaukee
Journal reporter wore a look of growing alarm.
Finally, someone raised a hand and asked the question of the day.
Brett, do you have a cold? &HT;    ``I do have a cold,'' Favre confirmed, sniffing again. The NFL's
Most Valuable Player blamed his condition on the weather change,
the Packers having been transported from 51-below-zero windchill in
Green Bay to 70 degrees in New Orleans.
<p>
   Favre said several teammates also are afflicted. ``We're all
(sniff) on Amoxicillin.'' Amoxicillin is an NFL-approved
antibiotic.
<p>
   It remains to be seen whether ``FAVRE ILL'' headlines will alter
the point spread for Super Bowl XXXI. The Packers probably will
remain 14-point favorites unless their star player develops other
symptom or complications, in which event Favre might show up on
Sunday sporting one of those dilator bandages across his nose.
<p>
   An athlete's ability to perform is influenced in large part on
his or her ability to breath  &MD;  the lone exception being
synchronized swimmers who can hold their breath for weeks.
<p>
   The importance of a healthy intake of oxygen has given rise to a
product fad that appeared at the Super Bowl two years ago. In
Miami, Jerry Rice wore what looked like an elongated butterfly
bandage across the bridge of his schnoz. Teammate Ricky Watters
wore one, too. So did William Floyd. The manufacturer points out
that in Super Bowl XXIX, those three players scored all seven of
the San Francisco 49ers' touchdowns.
<p>
   The bandages are called Breathe Right Nasal Strips. As mentioned
in a previous column, the patches are not to be confused with other
products, such as Breath Assure.
<p>
   Breath Assure is a vial of non-prescription pills that actor
George Kennedy claims cures bad breath. Most Americans had no idea
George suffered from the embarrassment of halitosis, but apparently
he does, or did, until the life-changing day he discovered the
amazing tablets he wholeheartedly endorses on late-night TV.
<p>
   Placed across the sniffer, the Breathe Right bandage pulls up
the outside of one's nose holes, and spreads them. It allows the
nose to draw in more air. Sort of a nasal turbocharger.
According to a press release, seven Packers and five Patriots use
them during games. And get this  &MD;  in the past two Super Bowls, 11
of the 15 touchdowns scored were by players wearing the strips. &HT;    It saddens me to think what a running back like Jim Brown might
have accomplished had this product been available in his day.
<p>
   If Favre is congested on Sunday, he would be crazy not to dilate
the old nasal passages. Maybe he would play better, maybe not. But
like Lombardi said, breathing isn't everything. It's the only
thing.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2101EST
</TRAILER>
