<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0732 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=taf-z> A9828 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0740 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SPORTS COLUMN: OF KINGS AND EMPIRES IN REALMS OF FOOTBALL &LR;  &QL; 
(kd) &QL; 
 &UR; By WILLIAM C. RHODEN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  With the now familiar sea of microphones and
platform full of cameras before them Bob Kraft, the owner of the
New England Patriots, and Bill Parcells, his head coach, Wednesday
appeared before the media to give the serfs and knaves another
day's morsel.
<p>
   For the last two months, these two have waged an intense, public
and amusing feudal war over title and fiefdom. Wednesday, Kraft
stressed once again that he wants Parcells back as coach next
season. But the fundamental issue is ego.
<p>
   Parcells wants full control over the football operation.
Parcells is unhappy with the title ``coach.'' This lowly
description no longer fits his lofty accomplishments: two Super
Bowl championships, possibly a third.
<p>
   At one level, he has a point. If a mediocre neophyte like Steve
Mariucci, hired as the 49ers' head coach after going 6-6 his first
and only season as a head coach at California  &MD;  if he is ``coach,''
then what does that make Parcells? Surely there must be a another,
higher designation.
<p>
   On Tuesday, Dan Reeves, a mere coach with the Giants, was made
head coach and head of football operations for the Atlanta Falcons.
<p>
   Dick Vermeil, who quit the business 14 years ago because of
``burnout,'' was introduced as the St. Louis Rams' new coach and
president of football operations. Jimmy Johnson is the head coach
and general manager of the Dolphins.
<p>
   Bill Walsh, the former San Francisco head coach, is the
modern-day model for the ``Imperial Coach,'' the man who heads up
every phase of the operation. Before that, legendary coaches like
Vince Lombardi and George Halas did everything.
<p>
   Back then, things were simpler,  &MD;  no players played both ways,
didn't wear facemasks and were tied to the team for life. Football
is a more complex place to play these days, and Vermeil should know
that the pressures that forced him to quit 14 years ago have
intensified. Now there are salary caps, free agency, players whose
salaries demand respect from the coach.
<p>
   The conflict for Kraft represents a choice between short-term
gain and constructing a foundation.
<p>
   ``It's hard to be dependent on any one person in any one area,''
Kraft said. Recalling the pitfalls of investing too much in one
person, Kraft recalled Parcells's health problems. ``Each of the
first two years I owned the team, he had a health problem,'' Kraft
said last week. His point was that he will not mortgage the
Patriots' future on one individual.
<p>
   ``If one person is the reason that everything's happening,'' he
said ``then you haven't built anything.''
<p>
   Kraft is fond of telling how, as a season-ticket holder since
1972, he sat on New England's cold aluminum seats as a mere fan. He
has taken an enormous leap  &MD;  from passionate fan on cold seats to
throne as King and owner.
<p>
   Now Parcells wants to be King. Next season he well may King of
the Jets. This could be like being appointed captain of the
Titanic.
<p>
   Think of Reeves in Atlanta and Vermeil in St. Louis, where the
owners were all too happy to relinquish control. Now they can win
either way: If the captain saves the ship the owner takes credit.
If the ship sinks, blame the coach.
<p>
   Thus, this demand to be the Imperial Coach could be seen as
protective layering in a brutal business. In New England, ``coach''
is no longer a fitting distinction for Parcells. Kraft should
declare himself Emperor and make Parcells a King: William of
Foxboro, King of the Patriots.
<p>
   Kraft's problem is simple. Bill Parcells is a genius as a coach.
But he is also like the talented pianist who one day tells the
conductor that he wants to play the clarinet and take over the
Palace orchestra as well.
<p>
   If everything is falling apart as it is in St. Louis and Atlanta
 &MD;  or in ruin as it is for the Jets  &MD;  you let Parcells play whatever
he likes.
<p>
   But organizations like the Giants, the Packers, the 49ers, are
not in ruin. Kraft is confident that the Patriots are not a sinking
ship.
<p>
   For New England fans, the pity is that with Parcells at the
helm, the young Patriots actually have an opportunity to be great
for years to come.
<p>
   But the coach wants to be King; the owner wants to be Emperor.
<p>
   Neither realizes that in the long run the Kingdom and the Empire
are about to be ruined.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2102EST
</TRAILER>
