<DOCID> nyt970122.0733 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tic-z> A9829 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-PHOENIX-WNBA-AZR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0670 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BKW-PHOENIX-WNBA-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WNBA PHOENIX TEAM GETS 2 PLAYERS &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JEFF METCALFE &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   PHOENIX - They still tell stories about the ``Original Sun,''
Dick Van Arsdale.
<p>
   Snatched from the New York Knicks in the 1968 NBA expansion
draft, he scored the team's first basket on a driving layup, was
the Suns' first All-Star, played on their first NBA Finals team,
did TV-radio color commentary for 15 years, was their interim coach
in 1987 and is currently their vice president/director of player
personnel.
<p>
   Michele Timms can only hope for a ride as long and prosperous.
<p>
   She is the ``Original Mercury,'' expected to be the name of the
Phoenix Women's NBA franchise. The league allocation of its first
16 signees Wednesday had few surprises, with most of the eight
teams receiving a small and tall combination.
<p>
   Timms, a 5-foot-7 point guard from Australia, and Jennifer
Gillom, a 6-3 center, are the foundation for Phoenix Coach Cheryl
Miller, whose hiring is a done deal but has not been formally
announced.
<p>
   The next two players will come via an elite draft in about a
month, followed by local and national tryouts/combines and a second
draft of four more players. The final two of 10 roster spots will
be filled by free-agent signings, perhaps with local flavor such as
former Arizona State point guard Ryneldi Becenti.
<p>
   Ticket deposits (252-WNBA) already are being accepted for the
inaugural 28-game season (14 at America West Arena), which begins
June 21.
<p>
   Timms learned of her WNBA assignment while in Slovenia with her
current team, BTV Wuppertal, which last year became the first
German European champion. She will return to Australia in mid-April
and be in Phoenix before the start of training camp May 28.
<p>
   ``It's a relief. Now I can focus on Arizona,'' said Timms, who
admits her knowledge of the state doesn't go much beyond Lute
Olson, the occasional Skins Game, the Suns and the desert.
<p>
   ``This is an unbelievably exciting time and kind of scary in a
way, to think how big women's basketball can become worldwide. You
talk about Steffi Graf and tennis, but there are not enough female
role models.''
<p>
   Phoenix officials expect Timms to be that and the kind of floor
leader who lifted Australia to its first Olympic basketball medal,
male or female.
<p>
   ``She's a spark plug,'' said Bryan Colangelo, Suns general
manager. ``Between her, Jason Kidd, Kevin Johnson and Steve Nash,
we've got a corner on the point-guard market.''
<p>
   Timms' pro career averages (14.1 points, 3.6 rebounds, 3.8
assists, 2.2 steals) reflect her worth. She will turn 32 a week
into the season but said her health has improved since she reached
30.
<p>
   ``I'm the fastest I've ever been,'' said Timms, who scored 27
points in an Olympic semifinal loss to the gold- medal-winning
United States. ``I enjoy the transition style, and my defense is
one of my strengths.''
<p>
   Timms recently played against her new teammate, soon to be
33-year-old Gillom, a 1988 U.S. Olympic gold medalist who is with
the Sporting Flash in Greece.
<p>
   ``She goes to the boards strong, runs well and can put the ball
in the hole,'' Timms said. ``She doesn't stop for one minute.''
<p>
   The overall level of elite talent in the WNBA is extraordinary,
Timms said, even without the seven U.S. Olympians who signed
exclusive contracts with the American Basketball League.
<p>
   The consensus allocation winner is Los Angeles, expected to be
named Stars. It came away with not only 6-5 Lisa Leslie, the
leading U.S. Olympic scorer and second-leading rebounder, but point
guard Penny Toler, currently averaging 28 points and seven assists
in Israel.
<p>
   Sheryl Swoopes, another U.S. Olympic star, was assigned to
Houston but will not be available until August. She is scheduled to
deliver her first child in mid-June. The Houston team, expected to
be named Comets, could be considered for priority in the February
draft because of Swoopes' pregnancy.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2102EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0734 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tic-z> A9831 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-2ND-HALF- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0651 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HKN-COYOTES-2ND-HALF-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COYOTES GET SECOND CHANCE AT SECOND HALF &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BOB MCMANAMAN &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   PHOENIX - Tonight, the Coyotes get a second chance to start the
second half of the NHL season, which is a lucky thing considering
the way they began it before the All-Star break.
<p>
   After going 18-19-4 through their first 41 games, they proceeded
to lose four of their next five, including three that were either
decided in the first minute of overtime or the final minute of
regulation.
<p>
   ``I agree this is a sort of second chance for us,'' right wing
Mike Gartner said. ``All the team in some respect get a fresh start
coming off the All-Star break. Some teams try to continue what they
had going, other teams try to get something going and you could say
we're in the latter category, obviously.''
<p>
   So with a 19-23-4 record and hanging onto a fourth-place tie
with Chicago in the Central Division entering Wednesday's games,
how important is tonight's match-up against the visiting Anaheim
Mighty Ducks and Saturday's game here against the Vancouver
Canucks?
<p>
   Extremely. Especially with a three-game trip right around the
corner at NHL powers Philadelphia, Detroit and Pittsburgh.
<p>
   ``I would say these next two games are as close to being
must-win games, if not must-win games, as you're going to get
during the course of a season,'' Gartner said. ``That's how I
certainly view it. I think we have to win these next two.''
<p>
   Both games are winnable. The Mighty Ducks and Canucks were each
struggling to play .500 hockey in the 10 games leading up to the
break. The Coyotes have lost three straight, but had their third
straight spirited practice Wednesday after not playing for a week,
a good sign entering two games on home ice.
<p>
   But that's been the problem. The Coyotes started the season with
plenty of good signs, from key free-agent additions and trades to a
very friendly home schedule, and the only signs they followed were
ones marked ``dead end.''
<p>
   ``The biggest disappointment in my book is our overall record,''
defenseman Brad McCrimmon said. ``We're a better team than our
record indicates. As for my thoughts involved right now, I'll just
keep to myself.
<p>
   ``We've got to start crossing some roads here in a hurry.''
<p>
   Ditto, said center Jeremy Roenick, who should significantly
increase his point output of 12 goals and 21 assists through 36
games.
<p>
   ``We need as much confidence as possible going into those three
games next week against three of the top teams in the league,''
Roenick said.
<p>
   The continued solid play of captain Keith Tkachuk (29 goals, 52
points) will be imperative. Just as critical will be starting
goalie Nikolai Khabibulin, whose 20 losses are the second-most in
the league behind Toronto's Felix Potvin.
<p>
   ``Nik's going to be crucial,'' Roenick said. ``Anybody will tell
you, in order to go anywhere, you need a goaltender playing good.
If he gets on a streak, we're going to win a lot of games.''
<p>
   Coyotes Coach Don Hay said mental mistakes have been the club's
biggest downfall. They have been most noticeable at the end of
games, when the Coyotes have blown leads and ties, allowing teams
to skate away with an easy two points.
<p>
   ``We need to have pride in the way we're executing, have pride
in the way we're playing the game,'' Hay said. ``The guys have
stuck together and there's good leadership in the dressing room.
<p>
   ``Nobody's pointing fingers and everybody's working hard
together to become a better team.''
<p>
   The players know how important the rest of the season now has
become, Gartner said.
<p>
   ``The next three weeks in particular will in many ways set the
tone for whether we're going to make a good strong run at the tough
teams in our conference,'' Gartner said, ``or whether we'll be
swimming right until the very end.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2105EST
</TRAILER>
