<DOCID> nyt970122.0736 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=w pri=r sel=ttd-z> A9833 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PELOSI-ETHICS-425&AMP;ADD </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0902 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PELOSI-ETHICS-425&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; REP. PELOSI ACCUSES REPUBLICANS OF `SANDBAGGING'' GINGRICH PROBE &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By MARC SANDALOW &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.1997 San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  Only hours after Rep. Nancy Pelosi's six-year
assignment to the House ethics committee came to an end, the San
Francisco Democrat accused Republicans of obstructing the
investigation into Speaker Newt Gingrich and called him ethically
unfit for the job.
<p>
   Pelosi, a Democrat, said that GOP leaders had ``sandbagged'' the
bipartisan inquiry in an effort to conceal evidence that proved
Gingrich had violated tax laws and lied to his colleagues.
<p>
   ``It's clear the Republicans will do anything  &MD;  anything  &MD;  to
protect Newt Gingrich,'' she said.
<p>
   In a lengthy interview with The Chronicle, Pelosi provided an
inside look at the controversial investigation into Gingrich  &MD;  an
inquiry so secret that she once had to ask her husband to leave the
bedroom at 3 a.m. so she could privately conduct business on the
phone.
<p>
   Free to talk now that her committee assignment has ended, Pelosi
said she believes that Gingrich should have been censured, which
would have cost him his job as speaker. She said she went along
with the lighter punishment out of concern that an extended battle
would have torn apart the House.
<p>
   ``He is such a hypocrite,'' Pelosi said. ``I think if a person
loved the House of Representatives, if he loved his party, he would
step aside.''
<p>
   The blunt words from the usually restrained sixth-term Democrat
underscore the partisan rancor that has marked the Gingrich debate
and reveal just how hard it will be for Gingrich to overcome the
ethical misconduct for which he received a reprimand and a $300,000
penalty Tuesday.
<p>
   Gingrich further revealed his ``disdain'' for the ethics
process, Pelosi said, by remaining in his private office as the
House debated his punishment, and then claimed through a
spokeswoman not to have even watched the proceedings on TV.
<p>
   ``You would have thought Newt Gingrich would have been present
at least at some point during the debate,'' she said. ``I think it
was a cowardly act.''
<p>
   Pelosi said the GOP, ``by stall tactics, by sandbagging, they
thwarted the ethics process.''
<p>
   Republicans were so intent on protecting their speaker, Pelosi
said, that they researched family trees and campaign documents of
ethics committee members, hoping to dig up dirt that might weaken
their position.
<p>
   ``They chipped away at their souls'' to save Gingrich, she said.
``Their attitude was they take no prisoners on this.''
<p>
   Pelosi maintained that some Republicans on their committee,
taking their orders from top GOP officials, ``flat-out sandbagged''
the investigation  &MD;  stalling the appointment of a special counsel
to look into the tax violations for which he was ultimately
punished, and refusing to investigate allegations that Gingrich
improperly received $250,000 from his political action committee
known as GOPAC.
<p>
   And they canceled a week's worth of public hearings on the
matter because they were afraid that special James Cole's testimony
would make it clear that Gingrich had intentionally misled the
committee, she said.
<p>
   ``What happened to the soul of the (Republican) party?'' Pelosi
said. ``Don't they know they shouldn't give their highest honor to
a person who has by his own admission brought discredit to the
House of Representatives?''
<p>
   Republicans denied Pelosi's accusation that their leaders
intervened in the ethics investigation.
<p>
   ``There is a very distinct wall between what the committee does
and what the leadership does,'' said Michelle Davis, a spokeswoman
for House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas. ``It was a
bipartisan process and it worked. Clearly there was a group of
Democrats that wanted a harsher punishment, and a group of
Republicans who wanted a lighter one.''
<p>
    
 &UR; STORY CAN END HERE  &MD;  OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &LR; 
  Pelosi revealed that Gingrich knew of the punishment that was in
store for him as far back as December and was aware that if fellow
Republicans learned of the $300,000 fine, it might doom his chances
to be re-elected as speaker.
<p>
   Despite a commitment to keep all aspects of the punishment
secret, Pelosi said, she was stunned to pick up the paper New
Year's Day and learn that two GOP members of the committee had sent
out a letter to Republicans informing them there was no punishment
being considered that would endanger Gingrich's ability to become
speaker.
<p>
   Because GOP rules prevent a member who has been censured from
being named speaker, it in essence tipped members that a lesser
penalty was being considered.
<p>
   Pelosi said she was furious and briefly considered going public
with the $300,000 penalty. Ultimately she decided that such a
battle would ``explode the process,'' and perhaps allow Gingrich to
get off completely.
<p>
   ``We had to keep getting slapped all over the place in order to
get this endgame,'' she said.
<p>
   Gingrich's hold on the GOP was so strong, Pelosi said, that
Democrats were not certain that the House would go along with the
$300,000 penalty until the eve of the Tuesday's vote.
<p>
   ``This can never be a model for future investigations,'' she
said. ``It succeeded despite the actions of the full committee.
It's a shame. It's a disgrace to the House of Representatives.''
<p>
    &LR; 
</TEXT>
