<DOCID> nyt970122.0737 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=w pri=r sel=tth-z> A9834 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MCDERMOTT-INTERVIEW-S </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1359 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-MCDERMOTT-INTERVIEW-SPI &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MCDERMOTT HOPES FOR A MORE PEACEFUL HOUSE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JOEL CONNELLY and CHRISTOPHER HANSON &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Seattle Post-Intelligencer &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  Comparing the embattled House of Representatives
with Bosnia, Rep. Jim McDermott said Wednesday that silence may be
the best solution to the ethics battles that embroiled House
Speaker Newt Gingrich and McDermott as one of Gingrich's chief
investigators.
<p>
   ``We can have a choice. This place is terribly dysfunctional. I
don't want to make it worse. ... And the tenor around here is one
of being tired of war,'' McDermott said in his first in-depth
interview after leaving the Ethics Committee amid a storm of
controversy.
<p>
   McDermott, D-Wash., talked about Congress's flawed ethics
process, ways of fixing it and his own past efforts to leave the
Ethics Committee. But he would not utter a word about the speaker.
Nor would he discuss the firestorm surrounding the tape of an
intercepted Gingrich phone conversation that was turned over to
him.
<p>
   The tape, recorded by Florida couple off an ordinary police
scanner, was leaked to the New York Times and the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, allegedly in violation of federal law.
<p>
   Silence may be golden for McDermott under the circumstances,
because the FBI is probing how the tape was made and how it got
leaked to the newspapers two weeks ago.
<p>
   Republican leaders quickly accused McDermott, who was the senior
Democrat on the Ethics Committee, as the one who leaked the tape.
McDermott has neither confirmed nor denied the charge, but
announced Jan. 14 that he was removing himself from the Gingrich
case.
<p>
   Three days later, the committee voted 7-1 to reprimand Gingrich
and for him to pay $300,000 for misleading the panel and bringing
disfavor upon the House in the probe of how he used tax-exempt
organizations to advance his partisan agenda. The full House
overwhelmingly endorsed this unprecedented penalty on Tuesday.
<p>
   Meanwhile, the McDermott controversy disappeared from the
headlines, but he has not been forgotten by his bitter foes.
<p>
   ``I can assure you a lot of people want to do that, to get a
pound of flesh from Jim,'' said Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash.,
who is close to the House leadership.
<p>
   But Nethercutt indicated that a cease-fire is in the offing and
that Republicans will let the Justice Department investigate the
tape.
<p>
   ``I doubt this will be a public Ethics violation (charge),'' he
said, though about the FBI investigation, he added, ``I am
concerned that Jim is facing some tough problems.''
<p>
   ``I think people are tired of the scandal of the day,'' said
Rep. Linda Smith, R-Wash.
<p>
   McDermott, a fifth-termer from Seattle, has been upbeat and out
and about in the Capitol and finds himself much talked about.
<p>
   He maintained in the interview that he can be just as effective
now as he was before the flap erupted over the tapes. He is one of
the few medical doctors in the House, and suggested that his
background is needed in Medicare reform and efforts to make health
care available to poor children.
<p>
   ``This House operates on the basis of what you know. At least it
used to operate like that. ... Members know what I have to
contribute,'' he said.
<p>
   Despite the professed hopes for political peace, the question
remains: can the House stop being a political killing field and
resume productive legislation?
<p>
   ``Hope springs eternal in the human breast,'' McDermott
responded with a laugh, which he then stifled, adding: ``I'm really
serious. This place is so dysfunctional there must be an end to it.
We must do something about Medicare, for instance, and lobbing
grenades is not the way to get it done.''
<p>
   McDermott said that upon taking power two years ago, the
Republicans tried to run the House like a British-style parliament
in which the majority rams its programs through, with little or no
consultation with the opposition. He likened the modern House to a
battlefield across which the parties had been firing cannon shells.
<p>
   ``We lose the ability to go to the center of the field and talk
about what to do,'' he said.
<p>
   McDermott has known little but war during the eight years he has
served in the House. The Democrats, when they were in the majority,
paid little heed to the desires of the Republicans, and Gingrich
led a Republican insurgency, attacking the Democratic leadership as
corrupt and plotting a Republican takeover.
<p>
   McDermott arrived just in time to see an ethics investigation,
inspired by Gingrich, bring down Democratic House Speaker Jim
Wright.
<p>
   This was followed by the furor over overdrafts in the House
bank, which fell on McDermott's watch as Ethics chairman. And there
was a scandal over misuse of office funds that sent Ways and Means
chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., to federal prison.
<p>
   ``In the eight years I have been here, beginning with Wright,
this place has been like the Balkans. And there is a real desire
for peace on the part of a significant majority,'' McDermott said.
<p>
   ``We want peace and to go back to some kind of thoughtful
process,'' he declared.
<p>
   McDermott acknowledged Wednesday that if he fired off a fresh
barrage at Gingrich it would ``disrupt what is a very delicate
balance.''
<p>
   ``Personally, it was not any good for me,'' he said of his
contentious six-year tenure on the Ethics Committee.
<p>
   He estimated that he had spent 270 hours in the committee room,
some of the time staring at a TV screen in which the House was
debating Medicare  &MD;  the issue that he had come to Congress to
tackle.
<p>
   ``I think there are 207 members in the Democrat Caucus. There
are 202 of them glad they are not on the Ethics Committee,'' he
said.
<p>
   McDermott went twice to House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt
during 1995 and asked to be relieved of his Ethics duties. Gephardt
handed the first letter back. He tore up the second and threw it in
the waste basket, McDermott recalled.
<p>
   The Gingrich investigation had been under way since August 1994.
Gephardt was wary of letting McDermott off the committee because it
would encourage an exodus of Republican members, allowing Gingrich
to hand-pick the Republican half of his own jury.
<p>
   But although he was unable to do that, Gingrich did enjoy close
relationships with the Republican members who were judging him. For
instance, he worked with Ethics chairwoman Nancy Johnson, R-Conn.
Her support helped Gingrich climb the leadership ladder. She, in
turn, had ties to GOPAC, the political action committee that
Gingrich set up to win Republican control of the House.
<p>
   On the Democratic side, McDermott has made no bones about his
antipathy for Gingrich and his agenda.
<p>
   ``If you're looking for somebody pure, there ain't anybody,''
McDermott acknowledged, noting the partisan parity on the panel  &MD; 
five Republicans and five Democrats  &MD;  often makes it difficult to
reach consensus and resolve complaints.
<p>
   One possible reform, he said, would be to provide for a special
counsel to take over cases when the committee drags its feet. If
the panel does not act in 90 days, the counsel would come in.
<p>
   Republican leaders also are toying with a reform of the ethics
process, in which friends will not be forced to judge friends.
<p>
   Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., a member of the Republican
leadership, cited a proposal last year by the bipartisan team of
GOP Rep. David Dreier of California and respected senior Democrat
Lee Hamilton of Indiana, a former chairman of the House Foreign
Affairs Committee.
<p>
   ``They suggested that the Ethics Committee be made less partisan
by putting judges and former (House) members on the committee,''
Dunn said. McDermott also voiced interest in that proposal.
<p>
   Dunn, who herself filed an ethics complaint against Gephardt
last fall, said there had been ``too much partisanship for a lot of
reasons'' in the investigation of Gingrich.
<p>
   She politely declined to talk about McDermott's difficulties.
<p>
   ``It just doesn't serve any purpose to get into negative
discussions of anybody in the (Washington state) delegation,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2106EST
</TRAILER>
