<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tic-z> A9835 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-HIRE-AZR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0554 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-CARDS-HIRE-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JAMIESON READY TO RUN CARDS' OFFENSE &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LEE SHAPPELL &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - During his introductory news conference Wednesday
at the Cardinals complex, Dick Jamieson was handed an old team
publicity photo of himself in which his hair was more abundant and
considerably darker.
<p>
   ``You see what two years with Ricky Watters does to you?'' said
Jamieson, 59, jokingly.
<p>
   For the past two season, Jamieson, new offensive coordinator of
the Cardinals, coached Watters and the Philadelphia Eagles' running
backs in an offense that is rooted in the same West Coast system as
that of the Cardinals.
<p>
   Jamieson might not be the last coach with ties to Coach Vince
Tobin and the Cardinals to rejoin the organization.
<p>
   With New York Giants new Coach Jim Fassel set to hire Cardinals
running backs coach Jim Skipper as Giants offensive coordinator
today, speculatation turned to Johnny Roland as a successor to
Skipper.
<p>
   Roland and Tobin were college teammates at Missouri in the
1960s, and Roland went on to become 1966 NFL offensive rookie of
the year and an all-pro for the Cardinals. For the past two
seasons, Roland was assistant head coach and running backs coach on
Rich Brooks' staff with the St. Louis Rams. Brooks was fired after
the season.
<p>
   Tobin refused to comment on the running backs coach situation
until the Giants make a formal announcement.
<p>
   Jamieson coached with Tobin at Missouri in the early 1970s and
was a Cardinals assistant for six seasons in the 1980s before they
moved to Arizona. In naming Jamieson offensive coordinator, Tobin
said the basic offense and terminology implemented by Fassel, who
held the job last season, will remain the same.
<p>
   Jamieson recalled warmly his first stint with the Cardinals,
when Ottis Anderson carried the ball, Neil Lomax threw it and Roy
Green caught it.
<p>
   ``We had some pretty good players,'' Jamieson said. ``We had as
good a running back as there was in the league at that time, an
all-pro quarterback who was just coming into his prime, and maybe
as good a wide receiver as there was in the league. And we played
pretty good defense on top of it. So my memories are pretty fond.''
<p>
   The Eagles' rushing game, led by the volatile Wattters, has been
among the NFL leaders the past two seasons. Rushing, and offense in
general, have not not been the Cardinals' strong suits, although
they made strides this past season under Fassel's direction.
<p>
   ``Statistics don't really tell the whole story,'' Jamieson said.
``Their average per rush (3.7 yards) was almost as good as ours
(3.8), yet everybody thought we ran the ball extremely well. So
it's all in how you look at it.
<p>
   ``(Cardinals free-agent fullback Larry) Centers is more known
for his receiving ability, but he does good things with the ball
when he carries it. (Leeland) McElroy has got a bright future in
the league. (LeShon) Johnson is like a human bowling ball when he
runs. So those things are in place.''
<p>
   Actually, Centers is not in place. He has been negotiating with
the Cardinals for a new contract since November. He grew close to
Fassel and Skipper. Their exodus might influence whether he stays
or goes. Centers did not return telephone calls on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2106EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0739 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tic-z> A9836 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-OREGONSTA </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0482 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BKC-ARIZONA-OREGON STATE-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UA HOPES HOME TREND MEANS WIN AGAINST OREGON STATE &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By NORM FRAUENHEIM &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   TUCSON, ARIZ. - Welcome to the Pac-10 Conference, where the home
floor is a fortress and everybody else is road kill.
<p>
   That, at least, appears to be the early trend in a basketball
season that leaves little, if any, margin for error for home teams
with any chance at the conference title.
<p>
   ``Any loss at home is devastating,'' Arizona Coach Lute Olson
said.
<p>
   After successive defeats at Southern California and UCLA,
fourth-place Arizona returns to McKale Center tonight with a sense
of urgency against an unlikely opponent. Oregon State (5-9, 1-4
Pac-10) shouldn't be a threat to the Wildcats (10-4, 3-2). After
all, 14 years and a couple of presidents have come and gone since
the Beavers' last victory at Tucson  &MD;  Jan. 29, 1983.
<p>
   But Olson isn't thinking about history these days. No, only the
current state of a very unpredictable conference worries him. He
believes a single loss at home will prove fatal to chances at a
conference championship.
<p>
   ``If you protect your home court and win five out of nine on the
road, you will probably have a share of the title,'' said Olson,
whose No. 11 Wildcats are 7-0 (2-0 in the Pac-10) at home this
season. ``I don't think you can afford to lose at home.
<p>
   ``Anybody who tries to predict the league right now is kidding
themselves. If you drop a couple here or there, it is not like you
are dead and buried. There are others who are going to have to face
the same things.''
<p>
   Proof of Olson's point is Oregon State. Last Saturday, the
Beavers upset Stanford, considered a conference contender, in
Corvallis, Ore. Stanford whipped Pac-10 leader UCLA at home a
couple of weeks ago.
<p>
   Meanwhile, a return home also dictates a return to fundamentals,
Olson said of the Wildcats, whose starting lineup is questionable
because junior guard Miles Simon has the flu.
<p>
   Simon, a starter against UCLA after regaining his academic
eligibility on Jan. 10, was unable to practice Monday and Tuesday.
He did run through some drills on Wednesday, however.
<p>
   ``It's basic things that we need to work on,'' Olson said. ``My
biggest single concern is finishing. We had unbelievable looks to
the basket against UCLA.
<p>
   ``I'm not sure we have played a game where we had more good
looks, open looks than what we had there. The guys have to
finish.''
Briefly
<p>
   The Wildcats have lost two successive games 11 times since the
1983-84 season, Olson's first at Arziona. During that span, Olson
teams have come back to win by an average margin of 19 points after
each time.
<p>
   In Arizona's four losses this season, junior forward Michael
Dickerson is averaging just 12 points. In Arizona's 10 victories,
his scoring average is 25.4 points.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2107EST
</TRAILER>
