<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BKC-ARIZ.ST-OREGON-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ASU LOSSES MOUNT WITH SHOOTING WOES &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BOB COHN &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - It's an old axiom of basketball that if you live
by the jump shot, you die by the jump shot.
<p>
   Lately, Arizona State has been fatally attracted to its outside
shooting.
<p>
   Even with the December addition of 6-foot-8 forward Mike
Batiste, the undersized Sun Devils need to shoot well from outside
to survive. The primary gunners are a trio of guards, junior Jeremy
Veal, sophomore Gee Gervin and freshman Eddie House.
<p>
   Since beating Jackson State on Dec. 20 and pushing its record to
6-2, ASU has lost six of eight games against Division I
competition. During that span:
<p>
   Veal is shooting 43 for 105 (41 percent).
<p>
   Gervin is 18 for 62 (29 percent).
<p>
   House is 32 for 88 (36.3 percent).
<p>
   Veal actually is shooting well from three-point range in those
eight games, 15 for 30, but Gervin and House are a combined 24 for
85 (29.7 percent).
<p>
   And let's not forget Batiste, who isn't shy about hoisting a
few. In the Sun Devils' two defeats in Los Angeles last week,
Batiste made only 8 of 24 shots, many coming from long distance.
<p>
   ``I don't think we're playing as I hoped we would,'' ASU Coach
Bill Frieder said. ``And that's primarily because of our perimeter
shooting. I thought by now we would have a team that could knock
down some threes.''
<p>
   Even Veal has not been consistent in that regard. He made 6 of 8
three-point attempts in the losses to UCLA and Southern California,
but before that was in a slump that prompted Frieder to take him
out of the starting lineup for a game.
<p>
   Veal, a junior, responded. But Gervin and House are different.
Although he is a sophomore, Gervin sat out last season because of
academics and is in his first season of college competition. House
is a freshman.
<p>
   Frieder has stuck with House throughout his difficulties, and he
finally showed some shooting life by making 3 of 6 three-pointers
against USC. But Gervin played only five minutes against the
Trojans.
<p>
   ``You feel like Eddie House is going to be a consistent
shooter,'' Frieder said. ``Whether it's going to be next game, next
week, next month or next season remains to be seen.''
<p>
   Frieder said he limited Gervin against USC because of practice
performance and because ``Southern Cal is very, very athletic, and
I thought Gervin would have problems with their pressure. . . . But
Gervin will be back.''
<p>
   Gervin, the son of NBA Hall of Famer George Gervin, said he
first had a ball in his hand (albeit a tennis ball) at the age of 1
and is prepared to deal with the inevitable slumps.
<p>
   ``I'll get out of it eventually,'' he said.
<p>
   House appears to be getting out of his slump.
<p>
   ``I'm getting open looks,'' he said. ``They're just rimming out.
It's not like I'm missing real bad. Everybody goes through that.
I'll keep working on it and eventually it will keep working itself
out.''
<p>
   As with other problems, Frieder cites lack of manpower as a
primary cause of the shooting woes. ASU has only nine healthy
scholarship players. Batiste's addition was offset by injuries to
Quincy Brewer and Okeme Oziwo, who likely are out for the season.
<p>
   ``We are not getting out of practice situations what you need to
get, just because of a lack of bodies,'' Frieder said.
</TEXT>
