<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9838 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RUSSIA-LEBED-2TAKE </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0688 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-RUSSIA-LEBED-2TAKES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNLIKELY MEETING OF MINDS: LEBED MEETS THE DONALD &LR;  &QL; 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By RACHEL L. SWARNS &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  During his swing through the corridors of America's
business world this week, Alexander Lebed, the retired general who
aspires to be the next president of Russia, hobnobbed with
executives at Du Pont in Delaware and sipped tea with Wall Street
investors at the Harvard Club in Manhattan.
<p>
   And then he dropped in on the man who aspires to be the king of
New York capitalism.
<p>
   Lebed, meet Donald Trump.
<p>
   For almost an hour Wednesday, the two men conferred at Trump
Tower in a meeting that was declared off-limits to the press. What
could be in the works? A five-star hotel and casino smack-dab in
Red Square?
<p>
   Trump said he did indeed discuss his intentions to build
``something major'' in Moscow, maybe a hotel, maybe an apartment
building. And Lebed said he was all for it, with one caveat.
<p>
   ``The highest skyscraper in the world cannot be built next to
the Kremlin,'' Lebed joked. ``We cannot allow anyone spitting from
the roof of the skyscraper on the Kremlin.''
<p>
   But for all his jokes and witticisms, Lebed, 46, described his
mission as a very serious one. For while the ailing Boris Yeltsin
remains president of Russia, the campaign to replace him is already
under way, at home and abroad.
<p>
   And Lebed's visit to the United States has been widely viewed as
an attempt to win the support of American businessmen and to
portray himself as the one man who can lead Russia and pave the way
for investment and democratic reform there.
<p>
   ``He has come around to the idea that in an attempt to run for
the presidency, it's better to have the West in your corner,'' said
Steven Solnick, coordinator of Russian Studies at the Harriman
Institute at Columbia University.
<p>
   ``He may perceive that Yeltsin benefited greatly from support
from the Americans in the last campaign,'' Solnick said. ``Bill
Clinton made a trip to Moscow during the campaign. And the
International Monetary Fund extended loans that enabled the
government to make credible promises to pay wages.''
<p>
   Lebed received none of that support during his bid for the
presidency last year. The retired general, who won the hearts of
many ordinary Russians with his critique of the country's hasty
embrace of the free market, worried many American politicians and
investors with his sometimes autocratic demeanor and crude populist
outbursts.
<p>
   And while his popularity gave him a strong, third-place showing
at the polls and, briefly, a job as national security chief in the
Yeltsin administration, it did not automatically translate into
trust from the West.
<p>
   Lebed, who was dismissed from his post as security chief in
October, took the opportunity provided by an invitation to
President Clinton's inauguration Monday to visit the United States
for the second time in a little more than a month.
<p>
   Sen. William Roth, R-Del., offered the invitation at the behest
of an unnamed businessman from his state. And Lebed used the trip,
from Washington to Delaware and on to New York before heading back
to Russia on Wednesday evening, to reassure American businessmen
that as president he would welcome foreign investment and continue
the democratic process.
<p>
   ``I want to build a free, democratic Russia,'' said Lebed on
Tuesday afternoon in his remarks to the United Nations
Correspondents Association in New York.
<p>
   ``The only thing I kill now are wars,'' he added, describing his
role in brokering peace accords in Chechnya and Moldova.
<p>
   He repeatedly stressed similar themes, saying that the Russian
army should not interfere in politics, that obstacles to foreign
investment should be removed, and that he would not interfere with
NATO expansion into Eastern Europe. ``Russia should take it
calmly,'' he said. ``There should be no hysteria.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</TEXT>
