<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9839 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RUSSIA-LEBED-ART-2 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0741 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-RUSSIA-LEBED-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW YORK: no hysteria.'' &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   But Lebed also insisted that Russia's brand of democracy would
not be transplanted whole from Western soil. Press freedom, he
said, would not extend to the publishing of personal affronts to
national leaders. And free enterprise would not necessarily include
the privatization of the energy, telecommunications and
transportation industries.
<p>
   He left a strong impression on his audience. A bear of a man,
with a craggy face and piercing blue eyes, he sat in a wood-paneled
dining room at the Harvard Club on Wednesday in a charcoal-gray
suit, his big, restless hands alternately tapping the table and
pounding it for emphasis.
<p>
   But even for those who met him, he remained something of an
enigma, especially since he was careful to avoid offering specific
details about how he might manage economic and political change.
<p>
   In one meeting, he declared that he would appoint a panel of
experts aged 30 to 45 to redesign Russia's economic policies,
suggesting that anyone older had been psychologically ruined by the
Soviet experience.
<p>
   ``While he seems to be aware of the difficulties that investors
face,'' said Jack Wirts, the executive vice president of the
Conference Board, a nonprofit business research organization in New
York, ``I don't think he enunciated any different directions that
his government might take.''
<p>
   Still, many of the business people seemed encouraged. A
spokeswoman for John A. Krol, president and chief executive officer
of Du Pont, and Jerry A. Blumberg, Du Pont's executive vice
president, said their hour-long conference with Lebed in Delaware
on Tuesday morning offered a valuable window into the investment
climate in Russia.
<p>
   ``Russia is a key growth market for Du Pont,'' said Kathy Forte,
a spokeswoman for the company.
<p>
   And Trump, who gave the retired general a crystal apple as a
parting gift, said Lebed had ``a lot of wonderful ideas,'' though
he declined to discuss them.
<p>
   ``He invited me to Russia and I accepted,'' Trump said. ``I
thought he was terrific.''
<p>
   For his part, Lebed seemed slightly overwhelmed by New York
City's technology and architecture. During his visit to Trump
Tower, Trump's steel-and-glass palace on Fifth Avenue, he marveled
at the computers on the desks and the automatic lock on the doors.
``Very impressive,'' he said.
<p>
   And he found the city's skyscrapers a bit unnerving.
<p>
   ``It's hard to get used to the huge towering structures,'' he
said.
<p>
   Still, Lebed said the visit had served its purpose.
<p>
   ``I extended the circle of my friends,'' he said, describing the
objectives achieved during his trip. ``We made clearer the routes
and framework for future cooperation. I've received new guarantees
that if I meet certain conditions as president, investments will go
to Russia. If the conditions are civilized, the investments will be
civilized.''
<p>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
<p>
   The Quotable Lebed
<p>
   Alexander Lebed's reputation for blunt speaking comes in part
from his taste for the folksy aphorisms to illustrate a point, put
down an opponent or tout his own achievements. A few examples from
his visit to New York:
<p>
   On his heroes  &MD;  ``I don't have any heroes. Even the sun has
spots.''
<p>
   On Russia's new rich  &MD;  ``I apply a simple test. When I greet a
group of entrepreneurs, I hail them, `Hello, crooks!' If they take
it OK, then they are not hopeless. If they beat their breasts and
deny it, then they are incorrigible.''
<p>
   On his standing with Chechen rebels after negotiating Russia's
withdrawal  &MD;  ``The Chechens put Allah in first place. In second,
they put me.''
<p>
   On Russia's reaction to NATO's expansion  &MD;  ``If the rape is
unavoidable, relax and try to enjoy it.''
<p>
   On investment in Russia  &MD;  ``He who doesn't take risks, doesn't
drink champagne.''
<p>
   On the Russian government ``They're like a dog guarding a
haystack. They can't eat the hay themselves, but they won't let
anyone else eat it either.''
<p>
   On Prime Minister Victor Chernomyrdin  &MD;  ``He's so inarticulate
he needs a translator from Russian into Russian.''
<p>
   On answering questions from a roomful of journalists  &MD;  ``The
paratroopers' principle is: fall from the sky, hit the ground and
start fighting.''
<p>
   On Russia's lurch from one government to another  &MD;  ``There's got
to be a time when you stop stepping on the same rake.''
</TEXT>
