<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9840 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICEUNION-INDICT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1007 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-POLICEUNION-INDICT-280-(2TAKES)-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HEADS OF FORMER TRANSIT POLICE UNION ARE INDICTED &LR;  &QL; 
(With NY-POLICEUNION-ASSESS) &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  In a wide-ranging indictment, federal authorities
charged Wednesday that top officials of the union that represented
the transit police took kickbacks and engaged in several other
schemes before the force merged with the New York City Police
Department in 1995.
<p>
   The racketeering and bribery indictments were immediately seized
on by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who noted that among those indicted
were the chief negotiator for the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association, the union representing the city's 38,000 police
officers.
<p>
   Tuesday, that union rejected the city's last contract offer, a
decision Giuliani said was inextricably linked to legal problems
involving PBA officials and negotiators.
<p>
   While the charges do not implicate PBA officials, they do focus
on a union that merged with the PBA in May 1995, the Transit Police
Benevolent Association, which shared its lawyers with the city
officers' union.
<p>
   Federal prosecutors charged that before the merger, the lawyers
paid bribes to Transit PBA officials to keep the union's work. One
of the lawyers, James J. Lysaght, has been a top strategist for the
PBA in the current contract talks.
<p>
   ``There's no question that today's indictments have had a very
difficult effect on the ability of the city to communicate its
message to the police officers of New York City,'' Giuliani said in
commenting on the indictments.
<p>
   Union officials declined to respond to the mayor's assertion,
but Giuliani's comments underscored the deep rift that has grown
between many police officers and the mayor, who plans to make the
city's record-setting drop in crime a central theme of his
re-election campaign.
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   This year, the mayor will be in the uncomfortable position of
running on his record as a crime fighter while having frayed
relations with the police union and its restive members, who
strongly supported his mayoral bid in 1993.
<p>
   In announcing the indictments of 10 people Wednesday, U.S.
Attorney Mary Jo White said more charges might follow against some
current and former city PBA board members for their part in a
money-laundering scheme.
<p>
   In that scheme, as outlined in Wednesday's indictment, officials
of several police unions essentially lent money to the campaign of
a former Transit PBA president, Ron Reale, so that he could
fraudulently qualify for city matching funds during his
unsuccessful campaign for public advocate in 1993. Reale was among
those indicted Wednesday.
<p>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Andrew Lachow said more than 15
questionable donations to Reale's campaign were made by city,
transit and housing PBA officials, their spouses and their friends,
but it is unclear whether they will face criminal charges.
<p>
   But other investigators, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said the city PBA was now likely to become the focus of
the inquiry because Lysaght and two other lawyers charged
Wednesday, Peter L. Kramer and Richard Hartman, have also had
multimillion-dollar contracts with the city police union for years.
<p>
   Ms. White would not discuss the possibility of indictments
against current PBA officials, saying only, ``We're going to pursue
this case as far as the evidence will take us.''
<p>
   A spokesman for the law firm of Lysaght &AMP; Kramer, which is paid
more than $5 million in public and union money each year to defend
city police officers, said that the lawyers expected to be cleared.
<p>
   ``We at our law firms have acted tirelessly and aggressively on
behalf of police officers for many years,'' the spokesman, Todd
Shapiro, said, ``and given our aggressive efforts, it's not
surprising that we have made certain enemies, nor that these
enemies would target us for this type of attack.''
<p>
   The investigation began two years ago, when top officials of the
transit police union were accused of looting $265,000 from the
union's coffers in the months before the May 1995 merger with the
city PBA.
<p>
   In November two financial officials of the Transit PBA, union
vice president Thomas Zichettello and treasurer Raymond Montero
were charged with using union funds to buy luxury cars for
themselves and their spouses. Montero began cooperating with
federal agents, said law enforcement officials who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
<p>
   They added that Montero described how union officials demanded
cash bribes of more than $300,000 from their lawyers and other
vendors.
<p>
   According to the indictment, which was filed by Michele
Hirschman, head of the Federal Attorney's Public Corruption Unit,
Transit PBA officials paid Lysaght &AMP; Kramer inflated fees for
administering the union's health and welfare benefits fund, annuity
fund and civil legal fund, and then demanded cash kickbacks of more
than $300,000.
<p>
   Zichettello and Montero have both been indicted, and they
pleaded guilty Wednesday to conspiracy and racketeering, Ms. White
said.
<p>
   Transit PBA officials are also charged with demanding similar
kickbacks from the law firm of Barry Agulnick and William Gogel,
two other lawyers who represented transit officers. The two were
also indicted on racketeering charges and Wednesday pleaded guilty.
<p>
   Agulnick and Gogel have also signed co-operation agreements with
federal investigators, according to law enforcement officials who
spoke on the condition of anonymity.
<p>
   The most tantalizing aspects of Wednesday's indictment were the
charges filed against Richard Hartman, a former PBA lawyer who is
one of the most storied figures in local labor politics.
<p>
   Hartman was forced to resign as the lead PBA lawyer in 1988 and
forfeit his law license after he was caught taking $817,000 from
union escrow accounts to support his compulsive gambling habit.
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</TEXT>
