<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9841 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICEUNION-INDICT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0281 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-POLICEUNION-INDICT-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW YORK: gambling habit. &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   During a grand jury proceeding by the Manhattan district
attorney's office in 1988, prosecutors also presented evidence that
Hartman was involved in a kickback scheme and associated with
organized crime figures, according to a letter Armstrong later
filed in court.
<p>
   When Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau agreed to
drop the charges against Hartman in exchange for his forfeiting his
law license, city PBA officials quickly granted him a $2 million
contract as a labor consultant and allowed him to act as the agent
for the members' life insurance plan  &MD;  which generated an
additional $2 million in commissions.
<p>
   Hartman's current lawyer, Stuart London, said his client denied
any wrongdoing. But federal agents charged him Wednesday with
paying a series of bribes to transit police union officials, who
allowed him to act as the life insurance agent for that union's
members.
<p>
   The PBA board met Wednesday, but it was unclear whether the
members made any decision about the law firm's status as the
union's firm. Joseph Mancini, a union spokesman, said that none of
the criminal charges against the lawyers involved its dealings with
the city PBA. ``They have always been professional in their
relations with us,'' he said.
<p>
   The city PBA is a lobbying powerhouse in Albany and has
succeeded in passing several bills through the Legislature despite
Giuliani's determined opposition. Last year, it helped win passage
of a bill that would give a state arbitrator greater powers to
settle the union's grievances and pay disputes with the city.
<p>
   The bill was struck down in court.
</TEXT>
