<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tic-z> A9843 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHOENIX-LYLE-AZR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0662 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-GLF-PHOENIX-LYLE-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; 1988 IS STILL A FINE YEAR FOR LYLE &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN DAVIS &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - When it comes to choosing a bottle of wine,
Sandy Lyle always starts with the year. The selection is an easy
one.
<p>
   First, last and always he picks 1988.
<p>
   ``If I look at the wine list and see '88, I say, `Yes, I'm
familiar with that one,' '' Lyle said Wednesday before his practice
round at the Phoenix Open.
<p>
   To the wine expert, 1988 may not be a prime year. But to the
golf expert, it was vintage Sandy Lyle.
<p>
   That was the year he burst onto the U.S. golf scene, first by
winning the Phoenix Open, then the Greater Greensboro Open,
followed by his only major championship, in The Masters.
<p>
   What even the experts may not realize, however, is that Lyle
hasn't won a PGA event or a major European event since that banner
year. In fact, Lyle hasn't won a tournament anywhere since 1992.
<p>
   ``Just to win again would be nice,'' Lyle said. ``It wouldn't
matter to me if it was a Pro-Am. It would just be nice to be up
there again making a winning speech.''
<p>
   The Scottish golfer wound up seventh on the 1988 PGA money list
with career-high earnings of $726,934. He also won the British
Masters and World Match Play championship.
<p>
   But he played only two more full seasons on the PGA Tour,
instead turning his attention to European events. Disappointed with
the results, and with only two years left on his U.S. exemption,
Lyle now has turned his focus back to the PGA Tour.
<p>
   ``There are two reasons really,'' Lyle said. ``One was to
simplify the travel for my family. The other is to try to get back
to where I was, to get my world ranking back up.''
<p>
   Lyle has fallen to 180th in the Sony World Rankings and hasn't
played in a Ryder Cup or World Cup since 1987.
<p>
   His biggest disappointment has been at the site of his greatest
triumph, The Masters. After winning, he celebrated by adding a
Scottish dish called ``haggis'' to the Champions Dinner menu. For
the unfamiliar, it's a mixture of lungs and heart, mixed with suet,
seasoning and oatmeal and boiled in the stomach of a sheep or cow.
<p>
   But returning to Augusta National has left Lyle with a bad case
of indigestion. He has missed the cut in five of his eight visits
since his victory, with his best finish being a tie for 21st in
1993.
<p>
   ``It's been agonizing ever since I won there,'' he said. ``The
course sets up so well for me, and I feel so comfortable on it. One
thing I'd really like to do, besides winning a tournament, is go
back there and play well.''
<p>
   Lyle, who played in 15 U.S. events last year, said about 90
percent of this golf season will be spent in the United States,
with a handful of majors, such as the British Open and British
Masters, overseas.
<p>
   His 1996 season fell short of his hopes. He finished 168th on
the money list with $94,490, but Lyle saw some reason for optimism.
<p>
   ``I put some new ideas and thought patterns into my game around
the middle of the year and started to feel more comfortable,'' he
said.
<p>
   The biggest change was that he went back to playing a soft
left-to-right fade shot that was so successful in the mid-1980s.
<p>
   Whether that translates into more victories remains to be seen,
but the Phoenix Open may be a good place to start.
<p>
   After all, it launched that banner 1988 season when he went into
the final round at the TPC of Scottsdale trailing Davis Love III by
7 shots. Lyle shot 65 to finish in a tie with Fred Couples and won
on the third playoff hole.
<p>
   Out of his 15 U.S. events last year, his best finish came in the
Phoenix Open, when he tied for 10th, shooting 67 and 66 the last
two days.
<p>
   ``I wouldn't mind that at all, to start out the year by winning
again here,'' Lyle said. ``It would certainly pick my up my
confidence.''
<p>
   It also would call for a plate of haggis. Maybe with a new
vintage of wine .
</TEXT>
