<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHOENIX-WOODS-AZR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0292 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-GLF-PHOENIX-WOODS-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SECURITY TIGHTENS FOR WOODS &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BILL HUFFMAN &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - Security surrounding Tiger Woods was stepped
up significantly for Wednesday's Xerox Silver Pro-Am, and it will
stay tight throughout the rest of Phoenix Open week, according to
the Thunderbirds.
<p>
   The move was necessitated after Tuesday's breakdown, when a
large group of fans seeking autographs nearly attacked Woods on his
way from the 18th green to the clubhouse. One fan poked Woods, 21,
beneath his eye with a program. At the time, only one Scottsdale
police officer was protecting the phenom.
<p>
   On Wednesday, four or five Scottsdale police officers and
several Thunderbirds escorted Woods around the course. In addition,
volunteers were used to cordon off a 6-foot walkway for Woods
between each hole.
<p>
   Greg Mast, the tournament chairman for the Thunderbirds,
downplayed the move, adding that security measures were being taken
for three or four other high-profile groups this week. None,
however, got the restraining-rope treatment that Woods received
Wednesday.
<p>
   ``We're just trying to help him out,'' Mast said. ``The fans
mean well. They want to touch him and tell him, `Way to go, Tiger.'
But sometimes, it gets a little zealous, and he's definitely had
some trouble getting from the clubhouse to the course and back
again.
<p>
   ``We certainly don't want Tiger to get bogged down, and the fans
need to realize that he's not going to able to accommodate all the
requests he's getting for autographs.''
<p>
   The PGA Tour's autograph policy kicks in today, meaning fans can
expect to get a player's autograph only after he completes his
round.
</TEXT>
