<SLUG> BC-TAXES-TEXAS-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0792 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TAXES-TEXAS-COX  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; ATTN: Texas Editors.
<p>
    &UR; BUSH TO PROPOSE SWEEPING BUSINESS TAX
<p>
    &UR; By MICHELE KAY &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   AUSTIN, Texas  &MD;  Gov. George W. Bush's sweeping business tax
proposal in his state-of-the-state address Tuesday will target a
new class of Texas taxpayers  &MD;  among them, thousands of lawyers,
accountants, doctors and even lobbyists.
<p>
   ``It's going to be one of the biggest, most interesting fights
we have had in the Legislature since 1950,'' said Austin lobbyist
George Christian.
<p>
   The business-activity tax  &MD;  expected to be at the core of Bush's
proposal to cut the state's reliance on property taxes to pay for
public schools  &MD;  would replace Texas' franchise tax that only
corporations now pay.
<p>
   Bush wants to expand that base to include any business in Texas
that earns more than $500,000.
<p>
   ``It's going to be the first time legislators hear a sitting
governor say the tax base should be expanded to include all
businesses,'' said Bill Allaway, president of the Texas Taxpayers
and Research Association.
<p>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's communications director, said the governor
believes the tax burden should be shared more evenly.
<p>
   ``We don't believe the current system is fair,'' Hughes said.
``We tax some businesses too much and others not at all.''
<p>
   In order to protect small enterprises, Bush's budget writers
have proposed the $500,000 deduction. As a result, the number of
businesses that pay tax would drop  &MD;  from about 150,000 to 111,000.
But those that pay would have to dig deeper for Bush's proposal to
raise $1.5 billion a year more than Texas now collects with its
franchise tax.
<p>
   The so-called business-activity tax would newly tax professional
firms, some retailers and fast-food franchisees, oil and gas and
real estate partnerships, among others.
<p>
   ``When you suggest bringing in new taxpayers, you're asking for
trouble,'' Christian said. ``The last time that idea came up was in
1991 and it didn't happen. The Senate opposed it and it was
obliterated in the House.''
<p>
   Among businesses now exempt from the franchise tax that would
pay a business activity tax are sports teams, including the Texas
Rangers. Bush is a part-owner of the team.
<p>
   Lobbyists say Bush would not exclude partnerships such as the
Rangers so no one would be able to accuse him of orchestrating a
better deal for himself and his business partners.
<p>
   Bush has said repeatedly since last summer that he wants to
reduce the school taxes paid by residential and commercial property
owners and increase the money the state contributes to public
schools. Bush campaigned two years ago on promises to raise the
state's share of financing schools to 60 percent from 47 percent.
<p>
   The governor has said he hopes his tax plan would bring the
state close to that goal.
<p>
   But he has not been specific. In addition to revealing his tax
plan Tuesday, Bush will submit a budget the next day with
additional details.
<p>
   ``He wants to have his own budget to show there is money in
there for the first $1 billion of the property tax break,'' said
state Rep. Tom Craddick, R-Midland, House Ways and Means Committee
chairman. ``If people say there is no money, he can point to it and
show where he found it.''
<p>
   Bush is expected to suggest cutting school taxes by $3 billion a
year. Property owners now pay close to $10 billion a year.
<p>
   His plan includes raising the homestead exemption to $25,000
from $5,000. Bush's budget writers also have proposed expanding and
increasing the sales tax to collect $900 million more a year. Bush
has said he wants to cut state spending by $1 billion over the next
two years.
<p>
   Lobbyists predict legislators will try to avoid voting on a tax
bill. More likely, they say, legislators would send to voters a
constitutional amendment that would change the tax system.
<p>
   ``The tax plan is going to have to be a dialogue between the
voters of Texas and the governor of Texas,'' said Bill Messer, an
Austin lobbyist. ``It's not going to be driven by lobbyists or
legislators here in Austin.''
<p>
   Legislators and lobbyists believe the verdict on Bush's plan
will be swift.
<p>
   ``It is all going to hinge on people's initial reactions,''
Messer said. ``The issue is either going to be declared dead on
arrival or it's going to move so fast, no one can stop it.''
<p>
   If it survives, Craddick said, Bush may have to call a special
session because the complicated tax issue promises to be too
time-consuming for the regular session.
<p>
   ``Several members have said the question is important enough for
a special session,'' Craddick said.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (Story Filed By The AMERICAN STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TEXAS.)
<p>
    &UR; For clients of The New York Times News Service &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
