<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=tic-z> A9847 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-NEWSOME-A </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0664 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-PACKERS-NEWSOME-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PACKERS' NEWSOME MOTIVATED BY DAYS AS MASON &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By KENT SOMERS &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  Whenever Craig Newsome drives by someone doing
masonry work, he can't help but smile and remember the time when he
felt like his life had hit a block wall.
<p>
   He wasn't much interested in football coming out of high school
in Rialto, Calif., and as a new father, he needed a job. So Newsome
worked as a mason for two years, building block walls.
<p>
   Sunday, he will be the starting left cornerback for the Green
Packers in Super Bowl XXXI. It is a magical story straight out of
some corny sports book for kids, and every time Newsome sees
someone putting mortar to brick, he is reminded of how far he's
come.
<p>
   ``I'm like, `Oh, man, I used to do that,' '' Newsome said. ``I
would hope I would never have to do that again.''
<p>
   That wish is what drives Newsome, who played two seasons at
Arizona State and was a first-round pick by the Packers in 1995.
Ask anyone connected with the Packers about Newsome, and all their
answers invariably contain some reference to his work ethic.
<p>
   ``He learned on the run,'' said Packers defensive coordinator
Fritz Shurmur, who made Newsome a starter from the first day of his
first training camp. ``It wasn't easy for him. People picked on
him. People made some plays over the top of him. But . . . he
practices as hard as anybody I've ever been around. He competes on
every down, and every day he comes off the field a better player
because of it.''
<p>
   That's what Newsome learned laying bricks. You show up on time
every day. Turn in a solid day's work and then you go home. ``I
learned that nothing is free,'' Newsome said.
<p>
   But the biggest thing he learned from building walls is that he
didn't want to spend his life doing it. So he walked on at San
Bernardino (Calif.) Valley Community College, and by the end of his
second year he was one of the most highly recruited junior-college
players in the country.
<p>
   When he entered college, Newsome wanted nothing more out of it
than to find a way to improve life for his family. But when several
major colleges started recruiting him during his sophomore season,
he began to think professional football was a possibility.
<p>
   He signed with ASU, where despite injuries and academic problems
over two seasons, he played well enough to impress pro scouts.
<p>
   ``We really liked his toughness and overall awareness,'' said
Ron Wolf, the Packers general manager. ``Those things have helped
him immeasurably. He's an incredibly tough human being.''
<p>
   Newsome had to be tough to survive his rookie season. He was
penalized several times for holding and interference, and he played
a part in 13 of the 27 passing touchdowns the Packers allowed in
1995.
<p>
   He has made great strides this season. He hasn't been called for
pass interference yet and has given up just three touchdowns.
<p>
   Packers coaches attribute his improvement to having an
additional year of maturity. Newsome, already with the reputation
as one of the most physical corners in the league, has learned what
he can get away with.
<p>
   ``Craig is in your face,'' said safety Eugene Robinson. ``He's
not afraid to challenge you. He will bust you in the mouth,
legally. He gets up in your face and chokes you.''
<p>
   Newsome usually leaves it up to his teammates to speak for him.
He is a shy, private person who goes to great extremes to avoid the
media. He is notorious for showering quickly after practice and
games, leaving before the media enters the locker room. He has been
known to walk out of the shower just as Coach Mike Holmgren begins
his post-game speech. ``A couple of times I've been in there and I
come out with soap in my hair and he (Holmgren) is like, `Craig,
what are you doing?' '' Newsome said. ``I just like to go out there
and play, and when it's over with, I go home and spend time with my
kids.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2112EST
</TRAILER>
