<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tad-z> A9848 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CITADEL-HAZING-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0824 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CITADEL-HAZING-COX  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; NEW VISION FOR CITADEL
<p>
    &UR; By LYN RIDDLE &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   CHARLESTON, S.C.  &MD;  Despite the charges of hazing and abuse
leveled at The Citadel by two of the four women who broke the
gender barrier there, John Grinalds believes establishing a
coeducation program will not be his greatest challenge when he
takes over as president this summer.
<p>
   ``The greatest challenge is to articulate the mission of The
Citadel in terms that make sense to young people and their parents;
to show this is a wonderful laboratory to develop leadership
skills,'' he said in a recent interview. ``Coeducation is going to
go well.''
<p>
   Grinalds, 59, is the headmaster at Woodberry Forest School in
Woodberry Forest, Va. He passed up a promotion to three-star
general in the Marine Corps six years ago to lead the private
preparatory school, which has an enrollment of 368 boys, ages 14 to
18. Two of his sons attended the school near Charlottesville.
<p>
   He said he was asked to apply for the president's job at The
Citadel last May, but did not agree to be considered until
December. He was chosen from a pool of more than 100 applicants.
<p>
   As a boy, Grinalds lived in New York, Alabama and Macon, Ga.,
where he met his wife of nearly 25 years, Norwood. The couple met
when they were 13.
<p>
   ``John likes to say he told me immediately after we met he was
going to marry me, but it took nine years to get around my
mother,'' Mrs. Grinalds said, chuckling. They have four children,
including a daughter, Kate Grinalds, who works for the Alliance
Theater in Atlanta. Mrs. Grinalds' brother, Brown Dennis, is an
Atlanta doctor.
<p>
   Grinalds graduated from West Point in 1959, the first-year
graduates were allowed to become commissioned officers in a service
other than the Army. He chose the Marines and spent a 32-year
career commanding troops in Vietnam and at Marine bases around the
world. In addition, he served as an adviser to the chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff and was a Rhodes Scholar.
<p>
   When he left the service, he was the commanding general of the
Marine Corps Recruit Depot in San Diego, where 23,000 Marines are
trained each year. It may seem a huge leap from Marine Corps
general to headmaster of a school that sends 15 percent of its
graduates to an Ivy League school, but to Grinalds it seemed a
natural progression.
<p>
   ``Much of what I had done was leading young men, and that is
where I had always found my greatest satisfaction,'' he said.
<p>
   Woodberry students describe him as approachable, yet firm.
Before the young men arrive each fall, he learns each one's name
and makes a special point of praising accomplishments. He does not
tolerate dishonesty or discrimination, students said.
<p>
   ``He is an extraordinary leader,'' said Trish Zetterberg, a
longtime friend in Augusta whose two sons graduated from The
Citadel. ``What he requires of everyone else, he requires of
himself.''
<p>
   Zetterberg said she believes Grinalds will bring harmony to the
college.
<p>
   The Citadel has been embroiled in conflict ever since Shannon
Faulkner was admitted under a federal court order three years ago.
<p>
   The school changed its policy last summer after the U.S. Supreme
Court ruled that the all-male admissions policy at the publicly
supported Virginia Military Institute was unconstitutional. Four
women enrolled in August, and a week ago two of them decided not to
return for a second semester, saying they had been abused and
sexually harassed. Kim Messer and Jeanie Mentavlos have reported to
authorities that they were kissed and groped and that male cadets
set their clothes on fire.
<p>
   Eleven cadets have been charged by school officials in the
reported incidents.
<p>
   Grinalds said one of the requests he made when he came to
Charleston for an interview was to meet with the female cadets. He
met with Petra Lovetinska and Nancy Mace, the two women who are not
involved in the dispute. He said he found them ``upbeat and
enthusiastic.''
<p>
   ``I wanted to get the feel of the school and find out what the
situation was,'' he said. ``I expected to find a siege mentality,
but I didn't find that at all.''
<p>
   He also said the cadet leadership was respectful of Lovetinska
and Mace but ``didn't have much to say about the others.''
<p>
   ``The women said don't move too quickly, don't just take
anybody, to look for people who know what they're getting into and
who are coming for the right reasons,'' Grinalds said.
<p>
   He said he is leaving Woodberry, situated on a pristine 1,500-
acre tract in the shadow of the Blue Ridge Mountains, to find new
challenges.
<p>
   He plans to arrive on campus in midsummer and, like the military
man he is, make a reconnaissance. Then he will develop an agenda
for action, moving the tradition-rich institution into the 21st
century.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (Story Filed by Atlanta, Ga., Newspapers.)
<p>
    &UR; For clients of The New York Times News Service &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2112EST
</TRAILER>
