<SLUG> BC-HOPWOOD-CHRON-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0320 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HOPWOOD-CHRON-COX  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; AFFIRMATIVE ACTION: A LOOK BACK
<p>
    &UR; EDs: With AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION.
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   September 1992  &MD;  Cheryl Hopwood and three other white applicants
to the University of Texas law school file suit against UT,
alleging reverse discrimination.
<p>
   April 1993  &MD;  UT changes its law school admission policy,
beginning with the 1995 entering class. The policy, still in
effect, eliminates separate review of applications from minorities.
<p>
   August 1994  &MD;  A U.S. district judge rules that the plaintiffs
were denied their constitutional right to equal protection because
their law school applications were treated differently than those
of minorities. However, Sparks said they didn't prove they would
have been admitted to law school under a system in which all
applicants were judged equally.
<p>
   March 18, 1996  &MD;  The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reverses
Spark's decision, ruling that UT law school discriminated against
whites and others in favor of blacks and Mexican Americans in its
admissions.
<p>
   July 1, 1996  &MD;  The U.S. Supreme Court decision rejects the
state's appeal, letting the 5th Circuit decision stand.
<p>
   Aug. 21, 1996  &MD;  Texas Attorney General Dan Morales issues
guidelines for Texas universities, advising them to use
``race-neutral'' criteria for admissions and awarding scholarships.
<p>
   Jan. 16, 1997  &MD;  University of Houston Chancellor Bill Hobby says
his school will continue to administer certain scholarships to
minorities. He asks Morales for a formal legal opinion on Hopwood,
which would have the force of law.
<p>
   Jan. 21, 1997  &MD;  Morales says he is considering issuing a formal
opinion, which he said would be general and resemble the guidelines
he issued five months earlier.
</TEXT>
