<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=tad-z> A9852 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLEDSOE-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0731 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-BLEDSOE-COX  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; PATS' BLEDSOE FACES JUDGMENT DAY
<p>
    &UR; By LEN PASQUARELLI &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  At least three times a week for four months during
the off season, he practiced the tedious exercise designed to prove
that a quarterback's arm will carry him only as far as his feet
will allow.
<p>
   New England assistant coach Chris Palmer carefully positioned
the big red dots on the grass. And quarterback Drew Bledsoe
simulated his drop-back by trying to step on the dots, like someone
at an Arthur Murray dance studio hoping to transform from awkward
to Astaire.
<p>
   ``After doing it a couple thousand times,'' Palmer recalled
Wednesday, ``he became a great dancer.''
<p>
   Should Bledsoe waltz through Super Bowl XXXI on Sunday evening,
he might even be hailed as a great quarterback. But doubts about
the Patriots passer, a four-year NFL veteran at the tender age of
24, are beginning to overshadow the week's biggest story, an
ongoing spitting match between New England owner Bob Kraft and
coach Bill Parcells.
<p>
   Even in the New England camp, and reportedly as high up in the
organization as Parcells, the suspicion is that the quarterback
with the league's biggest contract isn't ready for the biggest
game. Privately, teammates fear Bledsoe could single-handedly
negate Parcells' meticulous game plan.
<p>
   ``There are a lot of reasons (the Patriots) are underdogs
here,'' said Fox analyst Terry Bradshaw, alluding to a 14 1/2-point
spread that makes New
<p>
   England the third-biggest underdog in Super Bowl history. ``And
one of them is the perception that Drew comes into this game
struggling.''
<p>
   The statistics bolster the perceptions: Over the last four
games, including a pair of playoff victories, Bledsoe has thrown
three touchdown passes and eight interceptions. His passer rating
in that stretch is a puny 58.6.
<p>
   Even in the 28-3 rout of the Pittsburgh Steelers in the Pats'
opening playoff game, Bledsoe was scatter-shot. He followed up a
red-hot start, when he hit his first seven passes for 123 yards, by
completing only seven of 17 attempts for 41 yards over the final
three quarters. In the AFC championship game against Jacksonville,
he never appeared comfortable and several times threw off his back
foot when the Jaguars brought pressure up the middle.
<p>
   Conversely, the first overall selection in the 1993 draft threw
for 25 touchdowns and suffered only 10 interceptions in the first
14 games of the season.
<p>
   Bledsoe, who had a a stellar college career at Washington State,
isn't buying into the theory that the bigger the game the larger
the lump in his throat, but he is aware his detractors feel that's
the case.
<p>
   ``The last month or so, everything has been under the magnifying
glass, . . . and this week it goes under the microscope, so the
pressure is intensified,'' Bledsoe said Wednesday. ``In the big
picture, this isn't a make-or-break game for my career, but it
certainly would dispel some notions if I play well. Or, should I
say, when I play well.''
<p>
   Just when Bledsoe will play well again has become an intriguing
subplot to the Parcells saga. In one of his most frequently used
allegories, Parcells refers to a trapper only being as good as the
number of pelts he brings back from the hunt. ``And Drew is
starting to get some skins,'' Parcells said.
<p>
   In truth, however, Bledsoe and Parcells get under each other's
skins. The quarterback, who conceded earlier in the week that he
``really has no personal (relationship)'' with Parcells, won't shed
many tears if his coach heads off to the New York Jets after
Sunday's game.
<p>
   Said Bledsoe: ``Whatever happens, happens. That's how I feel.''
<p>
   Whatever happens Sunday evening, though, against a Green Bay
defense primed to come after Bledsoe often and early, could
catapult him into the elite grouping of NFL quarterbacks or leave
him stalled in the second tier.
<p>
   During the long off-season tutorials, Palmer, upset that the
6-foot-5 Bledsoe had a league-high 31 attempts knocked down at the
line of scrimmage in '95, set up stepladders as mock pass-rushers.
Reminded of that drill, the quarterbacks coach agreed it has new
symbolism.
<p>
   ``This game,'' Palmer said, ``is the time for Drew to take the
next step up.''
</TEXT>
