<SLUG> BC-CIA-TRUCK-INTRUDER-NY </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0251 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CIA-TRUCK-INTRUDER-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TRUCK SPED THROUGH CIA SECURITY, AGENCY SAYS &LR;  &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID STOUT &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  An emotionally disturbed man sped past the security
checkpoints at the CIA headquarters last month in a pickup truck
that came to rest on the building's front steps, the agency said
Wednesday.
<p>
   The driver, David Crump, 37, was arrested by CIA guards
immediately after the incident, which occurred about 8 p.m. Dec. 23
at the agency's complex in McLean, Va., said Mark Mansfield, a CIA
spokesman.
<p>
   ``It was a breach of physical security,'' Mansfield said of the
episode, which was first reported by CNN Radio. ``It points to the
importance of remaining vigilant.''
<p>
   Mansfield said Crump, who is from McLean, had no criminal record
and no known affiliation with terrorist groups. The CIA spokesman
would give only the barest details of the case, but a federal court
complaint filed in the Eastern District of Virginia accuses Crump
of threatening the life of President Clinton.
<p>
   When asked how an intruder made it to the front steps of an
organization that does not put out a welcome mat, Mansfield said
the truck was traveling at ``extremely high speed,'' so fast that
guards could not activate pop-up metal barriers. He said the CIA
had taken ``significant additional measures'' to prevent a
recurrence.
<p>
   Crump was sent to a federal prison in North Carolina for
psychiatric tests to determine his fitness to stand trial.
</TEXT>
