<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCMAHON-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0614 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-MCMAHON-COX  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
    &UR; THIS TIME, NO MEDIA CIRCUS FOR MCMAHON
<p>
    &UR; By JEFF SCHULTZ &QC; 
<p>
    &UR; c.1997 Cox News Service &LR;  &QC; 
<p>
   NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  Eleven years ago this morning, the phone rang in
Jim McMahon's hotel room. It was a death threat. McMahon didn't
think much of it. He got up, showered, dressed and went downstairs
for breakfast.
<p>
   ``I'm sitting there eating breakfast and (former Chicago general
manager) Jerry Vainisi comes up to me and says, `You really did it
this time, didn't you?' '' McMahon recalled Wednesday. ``I said,
`Did what?' Then (coach Mike) Ditka comes up to me and says, `What
did you say that for?' I said, `What are you talking about?' ''
<p>
   Sunday's Super Bowl will be McMahon's second. The first came in
January of 1986, when he was the starting quarterback for Chicago
in a 46-10 flattening of New England. This time, McMahon mainly
will be watching Brett Favre as the Green Bay Packers face the
Patriots.
<p>
   A lot is different about this week for McMahon. He is near the
end of his career instead of at the peak. Also, no one has
threatened to shoot him.
<p>
   ``The week's not over, yet,'' he said.
<p>
   The Bears' last title is remembered as much for McMahon's antics
(and inaccurately reported antics) as Buddy Ryan's 46 defense and
William Perry's touchdown run. In chronological order, McMahon:
<p>
   EmLeader Wore headbands with anti-NFL messages written on them.
Pete Rozelle, the late commissioner had fined him $5,000 for
wearing an Adidas product, which was in conflict with the league's
marketing deals.
<p>
   EmLeader Mooned a television station's helicopter as it flew
over the Bears' practice field. ``They wanted to see my sore
(rear), so I showed it to them,'' said McMahon, who had been
injected with pain-killers for a sore hip.
<p>
   EmLeader Didn't say anything. A sportscaster on an NBC affiliate
in New Orleans reported a rumor on its 10 p.m. newscast that
McMahon had called the women in New Orleans ``sluts'' and the men
``stupid'' during an interview with a Chicago radio station that
morning.
<p>
   There were only two problems with the report: McMahon didn't do
the interview and he never said it to anybody else, either. The
sportscaster, Buddy Diliberto, who quoted ``a source,'' was
admonished and sent out of town for the rest of the week.
<p>
   ``Big deal,'' McMahon said. ``He got his job back after the
Super Bowl.''
<p>
   The damage had been done. McMahon's history of being slightly
off-center doused his vehement denials of the report. The death
threats continued. A mob of women carrying picket signs chanted in
front of the Bears' hotel. So much for the NFL's proudest moment.
<p>
   ``I was having a nice time here for about three days,'' McMahon
said. ``Then the (stuff) hit the fan.''
<p>
   The circus didn't affect McMahon or the Bears that Sunday. He
threw for 256 yards and ran for two touchdowns, and Chicago posted
what was the most lopsided Super Bowl win in history.
<p>
   It has been a lower-profile McMahon in recent years. The Packers
are his sixth employer in the last eight seasons, after seven years
in Chicago. He hates mop-up duty but has enjoyed his time in Green
Bay.
<p>
   Packers coach Mike Holmgren said, ``He's been a welcome addition
to this team. He does a lot of things to keep me calm during the
game. I tell him, `This really is ironic, you keeping me calm.' But
he's a very bright guy. It's like having the good angel and the bad
angel on your shoulders. I've got McMahon on one side and (receiver
Don) Beebe on the other.''
<p>
   McMahon being the bad angel  &MD;  only not as bad as some thought.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (Story Filed by Atlanta, Ga., Newspapers.)
<p>
    &UR; For clients of The New York Times News Service &LR; 
</POSTTEXT>
