<DOCID> nyt970122.0756 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=taf-z> A9855 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FLYTIER-OUTDOORS-625&AMP; </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0967 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FLYTIER-OUTDOORS-625&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Idaho) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; OUTDOORS: MAKING A PROFESSION OUT OF FLY-TYING &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; By GREG THOMAS &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ST. ANTHONY, Idaho  &MD;  For some people, tying flies might seem a
bit moronic, about as much fun as getting glued to a toilet seat.
<p>
   Could sitting on a stool all winter inspire anything creative?
Could winding feathers around a barbed piece of steel be considered
normal? At least if you were glued to a toilet seat, you could have
a selection of good reading material.
<p>
   For Rene Harrop, one of Idaho's top fly-tiers, however, it's not
only a sentimental winter hobby. Nothing inspires him more than the
hope that he will create a killer fly  &MD;  one that no trout could
refuse. Besides, a well-crafted fly is not only a pile of feathers
and yarn. To the aficionado, it's a work of art. For Harrop and
other professional fly-tiers, that art is also a satisfying way to
make a living.
<p>
   Harrop made the jump from a curious boy chasing barnyard
critters for hackle and fur to a fly-tying professional 27 years
ago. He considers a well-tied fly to be a beautiful creation worth
collecting.
<p>
   Of course, Harrop's best flies won't find their way into any
fancy display cases. You would be more likely to find one stuck in
the bankside brush somewhere. He ties exceptional flies for
fishermen around the country, but his best work is set aside for
special occasions.
<p>
   For personal use that is.
<p>
   ``All of the flies we tie are done right,'' Harrop said. ``When
we started tying professionally in 1967, we set a course for
quality. It's either done right or it's done over  &MD;  there's no
other way to survive. But the flies we save are the very best ones
we produce. Those are the ones we keep for ourselves and fish
with.''
<p>
   Dating back at least 300 years, anglers have attempted to
replicate trout food with feathers. And, with tiny hooks, minuscule
feathers, thread, yarn and glue, the crafty fly-tier can create a
striking imitation of an actual insect. A little work of art  &MD; 
often no larger than your smallest fingernail  &MD;  can turn a
skeptical trout into a taker.
<p>
   When fly-tiers fool that first trout with one of their own
creations, they pass a crucial threshold in an intriguingly
complicated sport.
<p>
   ``Without a doubt, catching that first trout on a fly you tied
is a big event in the evolution of a fly-fisherman,'' Harrop said.
``I haven't talked to anyone who hasn't got a rush out of it.''
<p>
   ``To me, the total package of flyfishing involves fly-tying,''
he said. ``I think that the combination of good angling skills and
the insect observations of a fly-tier will produce a much more
effective fisherman on the stream.''
<p>
   ``You have to understand the living creatures that attach you to
trout,'' he said, warming to his subject. ``If you don't try to
understand them, there's no room for growth. There's always
something new to learn. And that is the appeal.''
<p>
   Although it may not have been a concern two centuries ago,
fly-tying also has an economic incentive.
<p>
   With most flies retailing at $2.50 each, tying your own can save
a creel full of money, especially when you lose one fly after
another on a brushy stream during the height of, say, a brown drake
hatch. Once fledgling professionals make that jump, they realize
that selling flies for profit requires all the attributes of any
successful business.
<p>
   ``First of all, you can't make a lot of money at this craft,''
Harrop said, ``but you can make a living. Based on the simple fact
that there is a shortage of flies right now, an individual who
wants to enter the field could make a business out of it.
<p>
   ``It's the basic human-nature limitations that are the obstacle.
You have to have the discipline to get up in the morning, sit at a
vise and enter a zone that allows you to get through hundreds of
flies at a time. Then you have to get up and do it again the next
day.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   Hundreds of flies? In Harrop's case, it's thousands and
thousands of flies and a good portion of a life spent behind a
vise, tying an imitation of an insect that most of us would simply
flick off our arms and be thankful it didn't bite. But to the
fly-fisherman, there may be nothing prettier in the world than a
tiny mayfly  &MD;  with perfect wings, translucent colors and an evenly
forked tail.
<p>
   Harrop is one of the mayfly's admirers. He realizes the strange
power of an insect that shaped a man's career, his art and his
life-long passion for the rivers of Idaho.
<p>
   ``I think about mayflies a lot, and they have my gratitude,''
said Harrop, who ties at home with his family. ``We've tied a
variety of patterns for people, but it was the mayfly in size 20 or
smaller that established our niche in the industry. There were
never really enough small patterns, and the delicate mayfly
imitations were our way in.''
<p>
   For anyone who has tried to wrap a mass of material around a
size 20 hook, there's no doubt why a hole existed in the market.
Tiny mayfly patterns are a big problem to tie. Consider how tough
it might be to paint a picture on your fingernail and you will
appreciate the difficulties that Harrop and his family face each
day.
<p>
   ``We work in a small room, close together,'' Harrop said. ``We
listen to music and have good conversation. We don't grind our
brains too hard. It's as satisfying as it's ever been to watch a
little box of flies accumulate and see our hearts in them.''
<p>
   For Rene Harrop and other accomplished fly-tiers, their hobby
and their passion will never be a monotonous winter diversion.
Realizing that their creations might one day draw another living
creature from the depths to the surface, in unequivocal deception,
is the apex of their sport.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2115EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0757 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9857 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOSPITALS-225&AMP;ADD- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1093 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-HOSPITALS-225&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NYC SEEKS MORE CONTROL IN CONTRACT TO RUN 2 HOSPITALS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ESTHER B. FEIN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  In an effort to wrest more control from the private
medical centers that staff its public hospitals, New York City
officials said Wednesday that they would seek a new partner for the
city's largest medical-care contract  &MD;  a $100 million deal to run
the Queens and Elmhurst Hospital Centers.
<p>
   City officials have been adamant that they would no longer
accept what they described as decades of paying hundreds of
millions of dollars a year to private institutions to run its
hospitals, with little say over who worked there and how well care
was provided.
<p>
   Since October, the city had been negotiating with Mount Sinai
Medical Center, which has long supplied doctors to Queens and
Elmhurst. But that deal fell through early Wednesday, city
officials said, after they failed to persuade the Mount Sinai
center to give the city more control over running the hospital and
to link productivity and quality of care to what the center would
be paid.
<p>
   ``Historically, affiliation contracts have been monopolized by a
few institutions who have routinely received hundreds of millions
of dollars from us with very little oversight,'' said Dr. Luis R.
Marcos, president of Health and Hospitals Corp., the agency that
runs the city's 11 public hospitals. ``Today, we seek partners that
are accountable, productive and loyal to our public hospitals.''
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   Marcos said that while the city had ``a good track record with
Mount Sinai and would have preferred not to break this
relationship,'' he believed that ``for HHC to face the future we
have to have drastic changes in our relationship with our
affiliates, and perhaps Mount Sinai was not ready for such
change.''
<p>
   Dr. John Rowe, president of Mount Sinai, said that he understood
the colliding needs of the city and his hospital but that he was
not prepared to cede control over staff and faculty decisions to
the city. For example, the city wanted the right to remove the
medical director and other doctors if they failed to meet the
hospital's needs.
<p>
   But he said he would carefully study the city's request for a
new partner and might consider submitting a bid. The contract
between the hospitals agency and Mount Sinai expires at the end of
June, but officials on both sides said it might be extended if the
city cannot complete a new deal by then.
<p>
   The failure of the deal for the Elmhurst and Queens Hospital
Centers has serious implications for both the hospitals corporation
and for Mount Sinai, one of the city's pre-eminent medical
institutions.
<p>
   After 30 years of working with Mount Sinai at its Queens
hospitals, the city must now find a new partner to provide care in
a community that is anxious about the city's commitment to
maintaining hospitals there.
<p>
   Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani has said he would like to turn the two
hospitals and Coney Island Hospital in Brooklyn over to private
hands, but that plan has been mired in lawsuits and community
opposition.
<p>
   And Mount Sinai, which has used the city's hospitals as its base
in Queens, must find a new location in that borough because, as
inpatient stays decline, hospitals increasingly rely on referrals
for specialty care from far-flung networks of affiliates.
<p>
   In addition, with the growing importance of managed health care,
hospitals need to be able to demonstrate that they have contacts
throughout the city and region to provide care to their members.
<p>
   ``This has a serious impact on our health system,'' Rowe said.
``Queens is a borough of two million people. We need a home there.
And if we don't make a presence via our affiliation contract with
HHC, we will do it with somebody else. It means a reorientation of
Mount Sinai's activities from Elmhurst to another community base,
but that is something we are prepared to do.''
<p>
   He added that the two Queens hospitals had also been important
training sites for Mount Sinai medical students. But he said a deal
that Mount Sinai has to merge its hospital and medical school with
New York University would provide alternative outlets for training.
<p>
   Beyond wanting to control which doctors would work in its
hospitals, the city's public hospital system wanted more control
over patient transfers and referrals so it could keep more
business. Now, affiliates like Mount Sinai often transfer patients
requiring specialty care to its own hospital, regardless of whether
another public hospital could provide adequate care.
<p>
   Community leaders in Queens said that though they felt Mount
Sinai provided excellent care, they supported the hospitals
agency's efforts to make affiliates more accountable.
<p>
   ``We're nervous, we're anxious, we're unsettled,'' said Rory
Lancman, chairman of the Queens Hospital Center Community Advisory
Board. ``But we feel HHC is taking a stand, and we support them.''
<p>
   Last year, the hospitals corporation spent around $505 million
in contracts with private institutions to provide medical care at
its hospitals. HHC officials have had mixed success in persuading
their longtime partners to agree to the new terms they are
demanding in the current round of contract negotiations.
<p>
   This month, Columbia University's College of Physicians and
Surgeons agreed to a new contract with the city to run Harlem
Hospital Center, a deal that linked how much the school was paid
with how well doctors met specific health care goals and that gave
the city more control over who worked in the hospital.
<p>
   That agreement marked the first time that one of the major
academic medical centers had agreed to such productivity and
accountability terms in its contract to run a city hospital. City
officials said then that they hoped the deal would set a precedent
for a string of affiliation contracts that were up for renewal.
<p>
   Before concluding the deal with Columbia, the hospitals
corporation had been unsuccessful in getting the Albert Einstein
College of Medicine to agree to similar terms in a contract to run
the Jacobi Medical Center.
<p>
   The Montefiore Medical Center took over that contract and faces
renewal of its $55 million deal next month. New York University
Medical Center also faces negotiations in its $47.3 million
agreement to run the Bellevue Hospital Center, as well as its $6.4
million contract to run the Gouverneur Skilled Nursing Facility,
Diagnostic and Treatment Center.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2116EST
</TRAILER>
