<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9858 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-FIRE-MURDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0793 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NJ-FIRE-MURDERS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BATTLING BLAZE, N.J. FIREFIGHTERS FIND 4 PEOPLE SHOT TO DEATH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ABBY GOODNOUGH &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   MONTCLAIR, N.J.  &MD;  Firefighters rushing to put out a smoky blaze
Wednesday morning forced open a first-floor bedroom door and found
the bodies of a mother and her three young daughters, all shot to
death, the authorities said.
<p>
   The firefighters, responding to a 911 emergency call shortly
after 7 a.m., had broken through a first-floor window to get inside
the home, at 127 North Fullerton Ave., and then forced open the
door to the bedroom, Police Chief Thomas Russo said.
<p>
   The firefighters saw the three children lying on a mattress on
the floor and assumed they were suffering from smoke inhalation,
Russo said. But as the firefighters approached, they realized the
problem was much worse: two of the children had been tied up, he
said, and all three had been shot in the head.
<p>
   The girls' mother, who had also suffered gunshot wounds to the
head, was found lying near the mattress with a gun on her chest,
Russo said. He said that police had not ruled out the possibility
that Ms. Bennett had killed her children and then herself but that
they were considering the crime to be a quadruple homicide pending
autopsy reports and further investigation. As of last night, the
police said they had no suspects in the case.
<p>
   The victims were identified as Delfrances Bennett, 38, and her
children, Adrienne Cheeks, 9, Kristen Cheeks, 7, and Brittney
Bennett, 5.
<p>
   ``We have no suspects,'' Russo said, adding that the authorities
had not determined the cause of the fire, which had been confined
to a hallway just outside the bedroom where the bodies were found.
<p>
   But another law-enforcement official involved in the case, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said the initial evidence pointed
to a murder-suicide. The official said that the bedroom had been
barricaded from the inside, possibly with an old Christmas tree.
<p>
   The official also said that the father of Ms. Bennett's youngest
daughter, who he said lived in Orange, had fallen behind on child
support payments and that investigators had evidence that Ms.
Bennett may have been distressed about that. Investigators had not
uncovered any evidence of domestic violence in the family, the
official said.
<p>
   Russo said that earlier this week, police went to Ms. Bennett's
house in a response to a call. But he would not disclose the nature
of that call.
<p>
   Ms. Bennett had worked as a laboratory technician at Novartis
Pharmaceutical Corp. in East Hanover since October 1995, according
to Harry Rohme, a spokesman for the company. Rohme said her duties
included setting up microscopes and entering data into computers.
<p>
   From 1992 until late last year, Ms. Bennett was also a full-time
student at Montclair State University, said Bob Quarteroni, a
spokesman for the university. He would not say what she had
studied, but several neighbors said she had taken science classes.
<p>
   The three children were all students at Northeast Elementary
School here  &MD;  Adrienne in third grade, Kristen in first grade and
Brittney in kindergarten, the police said. As news of the killings
spread Wednesday morning, the school principal, Terry Trigg-Scales,
went from one classroom to the next, telling all 350 students that
three of their classmates would not be back.
<p>
   Later in the day, school psychologists and nurses also spent
time with the Northeast students, encouraging them to speak about
their memories of the three sisters. One student made a card
inscribed with the words, ``I love you, Adrienne,'' said Andrew
Evangelista, a school counselor. Some asked questions, he said.
Others wept.
<p>
   ``We are all in overdrive, stunned and numb,'' said Dr. William
Librera, the town's superintendent of schools.
<p>
   It was not the first time that children at Northeast Elementary
School had collectively mourned a death, Librera said. Several
years ago, a former principal was killed when a tree fell on her in
the school parking lot, he said.
<p>
   As television crews swarmed to North Fullerton Avenue on
Wednesday morning, residents said the scene was sadly familiar. Two
years ago, a teen-ager who lived in the house next to the Bennetts'
was charged in the shooting of a West Caldwell woman during a
carjacking.
<p>
   Neighbors on Wednesday afternoon described Mrs. Bennett as
soft-spoken and serious, but said that her daughters often played
with other children on the street and were always laughing.
<p>
   ``They were friendly, smiling kids,'' said Maxine Cleare, who
said that she and her son had watched the authorities bring the
children's bodies out of the house. ``I don't know what I'm going
to tell my son.''
</TEXT>
