<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9859 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AIRPORT-RENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0390 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-AIRPORT-RENTS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NYC MAYOR GAINS IN LONG BATTLE ON AIRPORT RENTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By CLIFFORD J. LEVY &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Mayor Rudolph Giuliani won a victory Wednesday in his
long-running battle with the Port Authority over back rent at the
city's two airports when the Federal Aviation Administration partly
reversed an adverse decision it made last fall.
<p>
   In November, the FAA ruled that the mayor had no ground for
seeking at least $220 million of the $500 million that he contends
the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey owes the city in rent
for Kennedy International and La Guardia Airports, which the
authority operates on land it leases from the city.
<p>
   Private arbitrators are trying to settle the dispute between the
mayor and the authority. And with last fall's ruling, the FAA's
chief counsel, Nicholas G. Garaufis, said the decision was binding
on the arbitrators.
<p>
   Giuliani disagreed. His corporation counsel finally sued the FAA
over the matter last week. Wednesday, Garaufis backtracked.
<p>
   In a letter to the city, Garaufis said the ruling was advisory
and not binding on arbitrators. But he said he was not changing the
content of the decision. And agency officials said that although
arbitrators could now legally ignore the ruling, the FAA would be
entitled to sue if its officials believed that the arbitrators'
final judgment violated federal law.
<p>
   The mayor's corporation counsel, Paul Crotty, said the letter
was a concession, giving a new push to the city's claim against the
authority. But Jeffrey S. Green, the authority's general counsel,
played down the letter, saying the aviation agency had not altered
the thrust of its decision.
<p>
   The FAA's original ruling focused on the link between revenue at
the airports and the annual rent. The authority is supposed to pay
the city a percentage of revenues, so the rent varies with the
airports' fortunes.
<p>
   The mayor asserts that when the authority calculates its
revenues, it should include money that it receives from a $3
surcharge that is levied on all airline tickets.
<p>
   But Garaufis countered in his November opinion that the
surcharge should be excluded from the rent formula because
Congress, which authorized it, intended it to be separate from the
airports' general revenue stream.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2118EST
