<DOCID> nyt970122.0761 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tdt-z> A9861 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPSON-CIVIL-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1021 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SIMPSON-CIVIL-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SIMPSON DEFENSE OPENS ATTACK &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ADAM PERTMAN &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif.  &MD;  O.J. Simpson's attorney, retaliating
after the plaintiffs delivered an emotionally wrenching finale to
their case, Wednesday accused his adversaries of manipulating
evidence to ``sandbag'' the defendant.
<p>
   In an often-combative, sometimes-rambling closing argument,
defense counsel Robert Baker took sharp aim at the tactics and
motives of the plaintiffs' lawyers. At the same time, he alleged
that some witnesses had lied or tailored their stories to gain fame
or to harm Simpson.
<p>
   ``We will demonstrate to you that there's an immense amount
wrong with the evidence,'' said Baker, whose client is being sued
for the ``wrongful deaths'' of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ronald
Goldman. Asserting that the victims' families are going after
Simpson for financial gain, Baker added: ``This isn't a fight for
justice, this is a fight for money.''
<p>
   Baker began the defense team's final arguments, which are
expected to conclude today, after a heart-tugging morning
presentation by the plaintiffs' chief counsel, Daniel Petrocelli.
Petrocelli's performance left Goldman's father, Fred, and other
members of the victims' families sobbing; two jurors looking on the
verge of tears; Simpson's sister, Shirley Baker, rubbing her eyes;
and other spectators and reporters crying or trying not to.
<p>
   Petrocelli evoked that outpouring by passionately describing the
loss Fred Goldman had endured, and discussing the relationship
between fathers and sons in general. He pointedly noted that
attorney Baker frequently demonstrates pride in his own son,
Phillip, who is a defense co-counsel in this case.
<p>
   To dramatize his argument, Petrocelli showed a video of Goldman
and his father at a 1993 bat mitzvah party, at which they were
dancing, joking and, finally, laughingly pretending to play guitars
together.
<p>
   With that last scene frozen on an oversized television screen,
the plaintiff's lawyer solemnly read a 16th Century poem:
<p>
   ``My lovely, living boy, my hope, my happiness, my love, my
life, my joy.'' Then he concluded: ``Fred Goldman's lovely, living
boy is no more.''
<p>
   In his response, Baker accused Petrocelli of having
``subjected'' jurors ``to a ploy for your sympathy.'' He asked the
jury to keep in mind one question about the plaintiffs' attorneys:
``Are they attempting to sandbag the defendant?''
<p>
   Baker took hard swings at his courtroom opponents and many of
their witnesses, including personal attacks against some. He
derided a former Playboy model  &MD;  who testified she'd seen Simpson
hit his ex-wife  &MD;  as a publicity hound, and added: ``For me, it
doesn't pay to advertise, so I keep my clothes on.''
<p>
   Baker also criticized the press, which he portrayed as wanting
Simpson to be found liable to keep sensational stories going. ``If
in fact you find him not responsible, ladies and gentlemen, the
gravy train is over,'' he said.
<p>
   Jurors seemed to pay closer attention to Petrocelli than to
Baker, whose style was more more plodding and less concise. One
juror, an elderly black woman, nooded off for a couple of minutes
as the defense attorney spoke.
<p>
   Baker repeatedly charged that his adversaries intentionally
mangled reality in order to harm Simpson and win a monetary
settlement for their clients. Moreover, he mocked the use of poetry
by the plaintiffs' side.
<p>
   Evoking a famous line by Johnnie Cochran, who was Simpson's lead
criminal lawyer  &MD;  ``If the gloves don't fit, you must acquit''  &MD; 
Baker said the plaintiffs had misrepresented Simpson's opportunity
to kill anyone.
<p>
   ``I'm no poet,'' Baker said, ``but obviously if you don't have
time, you most certainly can't commit the crime.''
<p>
   The plaintiffs' closing arguments lasted longer than expected,
so the defense summation didn't begin until Wednesday afternoon. It
should conclude sometime today, followed by a short rebuttal from
Petrocelli, jury instructions and then deliberations beginning late
in the day or early tomorrow.
<p>
   Petrocelli, who began his closing statement Tuesday, Wednesday
continued to pursue a major theme: that Simpson has lied about the
murders so much, so often that his version of events cannot be
trusted on almost any count.
<p>
   While his arguments were framed largely by his final, poignant
display, Petrocelli also employed other techniques to appeal to the
jurors.
<p>
   For instance, Petrocelli presented two displays he said would
clearly demonstrate that Simpson lied consistently.
<p>
   The first huge board was labeled ``Either: Simpson is Lying. Or:
All of These Witnesses and Documents are Lying, Mistaken, or
Faked.'' Below the headline was a list of nearly five dozen
witnesses, documents, writings and other evidence that the
defendant has contradicted or accused of being mistaken.
<p>
   The second display contained 31 photographs of Simpson at a
Sept. 26, 1993, football game wearing Bruno Magli shoes. He has
repeatedly denied ever having owned that type of shoe, which left
prints at the murder scene.
<p>
   Petrocelli drew laughs at one point by likening Simpson's
explanations to a line he said was delivered by Groucho Marx when
the comedian's wife caught him in bed with another woman: ``Who you
gonna believe, me or your lying eyes?''
<p>
   After the closing argument by Petrocelli, who was hired by the
Goldman family, the jury heard briefly from John Kelly, the
attorney for the Brown estate; and from Michael Brewer, who
represents Goldman's mother, Sharon Rufo.
<p>
   Simpson, who was found not guilty of murder last year, is being
sued for unspecified monetary damages by the Brown and Goldman
families. They allege that the former football star is responsible
for the victims' ``wrongful deaths.''
<p>
   Only nine of the 12 jurors must agree on a verdict to find him
liable for the killings. If that happens, a second phase of the
civil jury ensues in which Simpson's finances are presented and the
jury deliberates again about how much they want to award each
plaintiff in financial damages.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2119EST
