<SLUG> BC-ALLEN-OBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0405 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-ALLEN-OBIT-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HERBERT ALLEN, 88, EARLY SPECIALIST IN CORPORATE TAKEOVERS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (kd) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LESLIE EATON &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Herbert Allen Sr., the financier who with his brother
Charles engineered some of the earliest corporate takeovers by Wall
Street firms, died on Saturday at his home in Manhattan. He was 88.
<p>
   Allen, who dropped out of high school to become a stock trader,
soon joined the investment firm his brother founded, Allen &AMP; Co.,
where he was a partner for more than 55 years.
<p>
   He also served for a year as chairman of another concern known
as Allen &AMP; Co., an investment banking firm that has been run by his
son, Herbert A. Allen, since 1965.
<p>
   In recent years, Allen &AMP; Co. has helped put together some of the
biggest deals in the media and entertainment industry, including
Seagram's purchase of MCA Inc. and Sony's purchase of Columbia
Pictures.
<p>
   Long before the 1980s, when the technique became famous, the
Allen brothers specialized in corporate buyouts, in which investors
take over troubled or low-priced companies and try to turn them
around. But the Allens did not have to sell junk bonds to pay for
their purchases, as later ``buyout artists'' did, relying instead
on their own money and that of their partners.
<p>
   Though Allen generally kept a low public profile, in 1956 he
became chairman of Benguet Consolidated, which mined gold and
chrome in the Philippines. Although he had acquired control of
Benguet ``almost by accident'' when he was trading the company's
stock, his son said, Allen fought off a takeover effort by
dissident shareholders in 1962.
<p>
   His other major investments included the diversified Ogden
Corp., of which the Allen brothers' firm owned 80 percent in 1953;
the Syntex Corp., a pharmaceutical company that was at one time
owned by Ogden, and the Irvine Ranch in California, which became
the Irvine Co., the huge real estate and development concern.
<p>
   Allen owned several successful race horses and was also known
for his donations, with his relatives, of millions of dollars to
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center, which named a community
hospital after the family.
<p>
   In addition to his son, Allen's survivors include his wife,
Ethel; two sisters, Evelyn Henry of Arcadia, Calif., and Marjorie
Bisgood of Manhattan; a brother, Harold, of Great Neck; a daughter,
Susan, of Mamaroneck, and eight grandchildren.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2119EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0763 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=tdt-z> A9863 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TUFTS-INSURANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0436 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TUFTS-INSURANCE-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TUFTS HMO TO SELL LIFE INSURANCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEX PHAM &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   BOSTON  &MD;  Tufts Health Plan is expanding its horizons. The
Waltham-based health maintenance organization Wednesday announced
plans to start selling life insurance and other employee benefits
through a partnership with Reliastar Life Insurance Co.
<p>
   The joint marketing agreement also gives Tufts the opportunity
to sell health insurance to about 160,000 Reliastar customers in
New England. About 30,000 of these customers have health insurance
with Reliastar, which plans to gradually transfer them to Tufts.
<p>
   The idea is to offer companies a one-stop-shopping service for a
spectrum of employee benefits, including retirement benefits
administration and health, life and disability insurance. Though
the two companies will jointly market their products, the
businesses will remain separate; each company will receive
commissions for selling the other's products.
<p>
   ``We want to knit together existing products rather than create
our own,'' said Jon Kingsdale, senior vice president of Tufts. ``It
allows us to meet the demands of our customers without losing our
focus on managed medical care.''
<p>
   The announcement is the latest in a series of moves by Tufts to
become a major regional player in the health insurance market. Two
weeks ago, Tufts said it would acquire Prudential's Massachusetts
health insurance business, adding 51,000 members to Tufts' current
625,000 subscribers.
<p>
   Even after the acquisition, Tufts will remain the state's
third-largest HMO after Harvard Pilgrim Health Care and Blue Cross
and Blue Shield of Massachusetts. Blue Cross and Harvard do not
currently offer life insurance or other employee benefits services.
<p>
   While HMOs throughout the country merged and consolidated, Tufts
announced two years ago that it planned to remain independent.
Since then, it has grown rapidly. Between 1994 and 1996, premium
revenues jumped 58 percent to $855 million while membership soared
67 percent.
<p>
   Some of its growth has come from efforts to do business outside
of Massachusetts. Tufts has 14,000 members in New Hampshire and
5,000 in Maine. It plans to enter Rhode Island in April.
<p>
   Reliastar, formerly Northwestern National Life, is based in
Minneapolis and operates nationally, making most of its money from
selling life insurance and administering employee benefits for
other companies. Its parent company, Relia-star Financial Corp.,
also manages mutual funds and has about $2 billion in annual
revenues.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2120EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0764 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9864 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-LOFERSKI-OBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0459 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-LOFERSKI-OBIT-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: R.I., Pa.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JOSEPH J. LOFERSKI, 71, SOLAR CELL PIONEER &LR;  &QL; 
(kd) &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM HILCHEY &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Dr. Joseph J. Loferski, a physicist and pioneer in the
development of modern solar cells, died on Monday in Miriam
Hospital in Providence, R.I. He was 71 and lived in Providence.
<p>
   A spokeswoman for Brown University, where Loferski was an
emeritus professor of engineering, said the cause of death was
cancer.
<p>
   In a four-decade career, Loferski published more than 150
technical papers and contributed chapters to five books. Although
much of his work focused on photovoltaic cells, which convert the
energy in light to electricity, he also wrote and spoke extensively
on the physics of semiconductor materials like silicon.
<p>
   The observation that light could generate an electric current in
an electrolyte solution, known as the photovoltaic effect, was
first reported in 1839.
<p>
   What Loferski and other early researchers into solar cells
demonstrated was that semiconductor devices might one day produce
commercially competitive, pollution-free electricity. Today, solar
cells provide electricity for a variety of items, from portable
calculators to commercial satellites.
<p>
   Joseph J. Loferski was born on Aug. 7, 1925, in Hudson, Pa. In
1948, he earned a bachelor's degree from Scranton University. He
received his master's degree in 1949 and doctorate in 1953 from the
University of Pennsylvania.
<p>
   Upon graduation, he joined RCA Laboratories in Princeton, N.J.,
and, with Dr. Paul Rappaport, now deceased, began researching solar
energy and photovoltaic cells.
<p>
   In 1961, Loferski joined the Brown faculty as an associate
professor of engineering. He served as chairman of the school's
division of engineering from 1968 to 1974, and was associate dean
of the graduate school from 1980 to 1983.
<p>
   He was a consultant for the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, the Departments of Defense and the Navy, as well as
private companies, including RCA and Honeywell. He was also the
co-recipient of six patents in the semiconductor field.
<p>
   Loferski was a fellow of the Institute of Electrical and
Electronic Engineers, which gave him the William R. Cherry Award in
1981.
<p>
   He is survived by his wife of 48 years, the former Sylvia D.
Sweeda; his mother, Mary of Hudson, Pa.; two sisters, Helen
Christman of Selinsgrove, Pa., and Marie Kunec of Falls Church,
Va.; a brother, S. James, of Kitty Hawk, N.C.; four daughters,
Patricia J., of Herndon, Va., Dr. Barbara L., of Providence,
Marianne L. Fleury of Chevy Chase, Md., and Sharon L. Engler of
Philadelphia; two sons, Joseph R. of Blacksburg, Va., and Michael
A. of Monkton, Md., and 10 grandchildren.
</TEXT>
