<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=ttx-z> A9865 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTIONANNIVERSARY-D </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0625 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-ABORTIONANNIVERSARY-DALLAS-TEX &QL; 
SUPPORTERS, FOES MARK `ROE VS. WADE' ANNIVERSARY &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
By JUSTIN BACHMAN &QC; 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   DALLAS  &MD;  Abortion-rights supporters marked the 24th anniversary
of the landmark ``Roe vs. Wade'' decision legalizing abortion with
a Wednesday morning ``celebration of rights'' breakfast.
<p>
   At Dallas City Hall, their opponents applauded ``Jane Roe,''
Dallas resident Norma McCorvey, who defected to the anti-abortion
movement in 1995. A replica of the Liberty Bell was repeatedly rung
to memorialize the millions of fetuses aborted since 1973.
<p>
   For McCorvey, the plaintiff who in 1970 started the legal battle
that led to the Supreme Court decision, ``something just kind of
came over me and I started getting really sad'' shortly before 7
a.m. Wednesday.
<p>
   ``Give her some love,'' said Operation Rescue leader Flip Benham
and the crowd of about 100 erupted in loud applause.
<p>
   The cheers for McCorvey, who never obtained an abortion, were
enthusiastic. So were the hugs that the activists gave her before
and after she read ``Empty Playgrounds,'' a poem she wrote
condemning abortion.
<p>
   ``I sit across from a playground that I visited this eve with a
small child,'' read McCorvey, whose voice faltered at several
points. ``I know of such places where children play. I know that I
am the cause of them not being here today. These playgrounds for
innocent children now dead because of sins I helped do.''
<p>
   McCorvey was the subject of the decision that legalized U.S.
abortions, but she has become the anti-abortion movement's
highest-profile asset since joining two years ago.
<p>
   Earlier, more than 200 abortion-rights activists attended the
seventh annual Greater Dallas Coalition for Reproductive Freedom
breakfast. The coalition is composed of 40 North Texas groups that
support abortion rights.
<p>
   The breakfast at the Grand Kempinski Hotel featured the parents
of Becky Bell, an Indianapolis teen-ager who died in 1988 after
contracting an infection from an illegal abortion.
<p>
   Bell, 17, did not want to upset her parents, so she quietly
sought an illegal abortion to skirt Indiana's notification
requirements, said Judy Shure, the coalition's co-chair.
<p>
   ``Yeah, (abortion) is legal, but if access continues to be
restricted, legality is somewhat irrelevant, isn't it?'' she said.
<p>
   This year, the coalition is renewing its focus on organization,
which pales in comparison to the efforts by anti-abortion groups,
Shure said.
<p>
   ``My perception is that the `antis' have a platform; they've had
25 years to organize; they've got fundraising and networking
capabilities and so forth,'' Shure said.
<p>
   McCorvey, a former abortion clinic worker who is now a full-time
volunteer at Operation Rescue's Dallas headquarters, plans to
publish a memoir this autumn about her change of views.
<p>
   Before she joined the anti-abortion movement, Jan. 22 was not a
particularly eventful date, she said.
<p>
   ``Sometimes I would just mark it as another day,'' McCorvey said
after the rally. ``I normally spent the entire month of January
stoned and drunk ... and trying to see how many Valium I could get
out of people.''
<p>
   Benham said that while abortion remains legal, the fewest women
since 1976 are seeking them.
<p>
   ``We're winning on the streets already,'' said Benham, rattling
off a string of statistics that bolstered his case: 555 fewer
abortion clinics than in 1986, teen pregnancy rates down 2 percent
each year from 1992 through 1995, only 11 percent of medical
schools teaching abortion procedures.
<p>
   ``So you see,'' Benham said, ``everything is going downhill for
them. That's why they want to get us off the street, just to shut
up.''
</TEXT>
