<DOCID> nyt970122.0766 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=i pri=u sel=tdt-z> A9867 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SERBIA-SOCIALISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1719 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SERBIA-SOCIALISTS-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; OUT IN THE SERBIAN COUNTRYSIDE, SOCIALISTS DOMINATE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID FILIPOV &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   VRCIN, Yugoslavia  &MD;  A lock hangs on the door of the lone
supermarket. Middle-aged men loiter on street corners and drink
slivovic plum vodka in Vrcin's bare, shabby eateries. Local
unemployment is over 50 percent, and many of those who do work have
not seen a paycheck in months.
<p>
   If there were ever a place where Serbs should be discontented
with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic's authoritarian 10-year
rule, it would be this run-down working-class town in the hills 12
miles east of Belgrade.
<p>
   But Vrcin has not only avoided the kind of street protests
against Milosevic that have paralyzed the Serbian capital for nine
weeks. Here, people have rallied around their embattled president.
<p>
   ``All those people should go back to their factories, their
jobs,'' said Radovije Nenadovic, a retired truck driver. ``There
should be respect for the law and discipline. Milosevic is the only
one who can give U.S. that. Everyone else would destroy everything.
What is happening in Belgrade is a disaster.''
<p>
   Nenadovic's friend and fellow pensioner, Dobrica Teofilovic,
agreed, saying: ``Our problem is that we have too much democracy
and too much freedom.''
<p>
   The voices of these two men on the street in Vrcin provide a
clue to the mystery of Serbia's political drama: How Milosevic has
been able to largely ignore 65 straight days of high-decibel
protests in Belgrade, and pressure from the international
community, to recognize election victories by his opponents.
<p>
   The answer is that, for better or worse, most Serbs have never
bought into the image of Milosevic as the vampire of the Balkans.
Peasant farmers, pensioners and workers in small towns like Vrcin
still form the majority of Serbia's population and the backbone of
Milosevic's support. There is no sign that they are about to join
the protests by tens of thousands of students and middle-class
intellectuals that broke out in the capital after Milosevic
annulled opposition victories in local elections in Serbia's 14
largest cities.
<p>
   According to a recent poll by the Institute for Social Sciences
in Belgrade, considered a reliable source of sociological data, 51
percent of Serbia's adults disapprove of the protests while only 9
percent approve. The remaining 40 percent refused to give an
opinion or said they were unaware of the protests.
<p>
   Opposition leaders acknowledge that they lack the nationwide
support they need if their quest to topple Europe's last
Communist-era dictator is to succeed.
<p>
   ``What is happening in the streets of Belgrade has created the
impression that we are winning,'' said Zoran Djindjic, a leader of
the opposition coalition, Zajedno. ``The reality is that Milosevic
still has the support of over half the population. It would be a
mistake if this visual image makes U.S. think we have the
majority.''
<p>
   Lost in the commotion over the colorful and witty daily protests
in Belgrade is that Milosevic's Socialist party won a decisive
victory in local elections Nov. 17 in 134 of 189 municipalities
across Serbia. The Socialists also won a landslide in elections to
Yugoslavia's federal parliament, winning over 60 percent of seats.
<p>
   Milosevic's Socialists swept to an easy victory in Vrcin, an
electoral success that belied the economic misery felt by his
supporters.
<p>
   Once a prosperous agricultural center famous for its big houses
and a well-fed population of 10,000, Vrcin  &UR; today &LR;  harvests the
bitter fruit of four years of sanctions imposed on Serbia to punish
Milosevic for instigating the Balkans war, and what economists say
is an even longer record of mismanagement and corruption by the
Serbian leader's Socialist government.
<p>
   But no one interviewed last week in Vrcin saw it that way.
<p>
   ``For the average Serb, Milosevic has been good. He is the best
one to protect U.S. from foreign influences,'' said Zivadin Mitric,
principal of the local elementary school.
<p>
   Such words, heard repeatedly on the streets of Vrcin, in part
reflect the success of the government's information blockade
outside the capital. There is no way for anyone without a shortwave
radio in Vrcin to learn about what is going on in Belgrade.
State-run television, the only readily available source of
information, paints the protesters as a fifth column of
destructive, foreign agents of influence in the rare times it
mentions the rallies at all. When 500,000 people demonstrated in
Belgrade on the Orthodox New Year's eve, it did not make the front
page of leading state-controlled Serbian newspapers.
<p>
   But the mood in Vrcin is more than just a creation of
Milosevic's propaganda machine. Most people in Serbia support the
regime because, as badly as they live, they believe any changes in
the country's socialist system will only make their lives worse.
<p>
   ``The real reason is that people are afraid,'' said Mihajlo
Markovic, a former senior adviser to Milosevic who was purged from
the ruling party in 1994 after a protracted ideological
disagreement with the president's powerful wife, the leader of a
neo-Marxist faction in the government.
<p>
   Markovic said calls by some of Zajedno's leaders for rapid
privatization, loosening of trade restrictions and economic
integration with the rest of Europe are seen as a threat by workers
and collective farmers.
<p>
   ``The reason peasants and workers do not join is that they are
afraid of rapid privatization, they are afraid they will lose their
jobs and pensions,'' he said. ``They look at how people live much
worse in places that have started reforms, like Bulgaria and
Russia, and they figure, `We don't want any part of that.'''
<p>
   Compared with other parts of Eastern Europe, Serbia is a
relatively rich country, where average monthly salaries  &MD;  at $150 a
month  &MD;  are five times the average in Bulgaria. Although annual
inflation is hovering at 100 percent, that is bearable for
Serbians, who remember the height of sanctions in 1993, when it was
common to see prices double several times in a day.
<p>
   Still, with national unemployment at 52 percent and nearly half
of those who do work on forced unpaid leave, it is hard to
understand what keeps voters loyal to the regime. According to
economist Alexandra Posarac, a consultant to the World Bank in
Belgrade, few of the 800,000 Serb workers eligible for unemployment
benefits actually collect the money they are entitled to.
<p>
   Posarac suggests that a different kind of fear keeps Serbs from
joining protests. Small towns are usually built around one or two
large enterprises, whose directors are inevitably members of the
ruling Socialist party, and often members of the government. This
makes it easier for Milosevic's ruling party to control small towns
than urban centers like Belgrade. Factories provide a state-owned
apartment, health care, and medicine and education. Even if
salaries and pensions are late or nonexistent, factories provide
occasional ``food stipends.''
<p>
   ``The state's social safety net is full of holes, but anyone who
wants to have some sense of social security has to stay out of the
streets,'' Posarac said.
<p>
   The pressure to support the regime, or at least keep quiet,
affects many small private traders whose business depends on the
support of state-run firms.
<p>
   ``Local bosses have levers to prevent you from conducting
business,'' said Zoran Obradovic, a butcher who sells meat to
state-owned factories in Vrcin and other localities.
<p>
   Local politicians also have to show loyalty to the directors  &MD; 
which means that even if Zajedno had been allowed its election
victories, the coalition's ability to change things would have
probably been tempered by this dependence.
<p>
   Milosevic's grip on the economy and public opinion seems to have
ensured his survival in the short run. But there is no denying that
the Serbian leader inflicted serious damage on himself by denying
the Zajedno coalition its relatively harmless election successes.
He turned a weak, quarrelsome opposition into a freedom movement
that has humiliated and outwitted his heavy-handed attempts to
muzzle its daily demonstrations.
<p>
   Milosevic could have instead won points as a democrat, by
letting the opposition take control of Belgrade and other
municipalities  &MD;  and their share of the blame for Serbia's economic
ills. Even now, most analysts believe Milosevic could cut his
losses by allowing Zajedno its victories, which would probably end
the daily protests.
<p>
   ``The main reason this is not happening is that Milosevic, like
his predecessors, is bent on absolute power,'' said Ranko Petkovic,
a Belgrade political analyst and former dissident who spent eight
years in prison under Yugoslavia's Communist dictator, Josef Tito,
who ruled until his death in 1980.
<p>
   But unlike Tito, who opened Yugoslavia to foreign investment
despite his iron grip at home, Milosevic's present course is
leading Serbia quickly back down the road of international
isolation from which it only recently emerged with the Dayton
agreements and the lifting of sanctions.
<p>
   Western governments have stated that Serbia will continue to be
denied membership in international financial institutions like the
World Bank until the government implements democratic reform and
recognizes the results of the Nov. 17 poll.
<p>
   ``The basic strategic goal for Yugoslavia, to reintegrate in the
international community, is now on hold,'' Petkovic said. ``There
is no money coming in from abroad. Foreign capital avoids
instability. We were about to begin to live better. Now, that is
not going to happen.''
<p>
   The trouble for Milosevic is where to find the money to keep
paying for the social benefits that preserve his support in the
countryside. Barring that, Milosevic could go looking for an
outside enemy to blame for Serbia's troubles. Whether that means a
crackdown in Belgrade similar to the one in 1991 when Milosevic
sent tanks to crush street demonstrations, or a campaign against
ethnic Albanian separatists in the southern Serbia province of
Kosovo  &MD;  the approach that helped kick off the war in Bosnia and
Croatia  &MD;  many observers fear that is when Serbia's real problems
would begin.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2125EST
</TRAILER>
