<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0767 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9868 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-SECRET-BENE </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0902 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EXCLUSIVE-SECRET-BENEFACTOR-2TAKES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Minn., N.J., N.Y., Ore. pts.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HE GAVE AWAY $600 MILLION, AND NO ONE KNEW &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EXCLUSIVE; 10 p.m. ET EMBARGO) &QL; 
 &LR; (sw) &QL; 
 &UR; By JUDITH MILLER and DAVID CAY JOHNSTON &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Over the last 15 years, a self-made businessman from
New Jersey has given away more than $600 million to hospitals,
universities and other beneficiaries  &MD;  but has done it in such
absolute secrecy that most recipients never learned who their
benefactor was.
<p>
   The donor, Charles Feeney, who made his fortune with a string of
duty-free airport shops, covered his tracks so well that business
magazines for years have estimated his net worth in the billions,
not realizing that he had transferred most of his assets to his two
charitable foundations and is actually worth less than $5 million.
<p>
   After years of secrecy, Feeney agreed this week to discuss his
gifts because the duty-free empire was sold this month to the
company that makes Moet &AMP; Chandon Champagne, and a lawsuit over the
sale would have revealed his anonymous donations.
<p>
   Feeney  &MD;  who has strong ties to Ireland and has made many gifts
there, including personal donations to Sinn Fein, the IRA's
political wing  &MD;  was matter-of-fact in describing why he had given
away his fortune. ``I simply decided I had enough money,'' he said.
``It doesn't drive my life. I'm a what-you-see-is-what-you-get kind
of guy.''
<p>
   While large anonymous donations to charity are not unheard of,
the scope and style of Feeney's giving, and his passion for total
secrecy, are rare, according to independent experts on
philanthropy. ``I've never heard of anything like this,'' said
Thomas Troyer, a senior partner in the law firm of Caplin &AMP;
Drysdale in Washington, who specializes in philanthropic law.
<p>
   Harvey Dale, a New York University tax law professor and
president of Feeney's Atlantic Foundation, who has helped Feeney
orchestrate his gifts since 1982, said: ``He doesn't own a house.
He doesn't own a car. He flies economy. And I think his watch cost
about $15.''
<p>
   It was Dale who helped Feeney set up his foundations, which like
his Duty Free Shoppes chain are based in Bermuda, thus avoiding the
disclosure requirements of private foundations in the United
States.
<p>
   From the Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York to Portland
State University in Oregon, none of the American recipients of
Feeney's largesse knew who their benefactor was. Grants were paid
by cashier's check to conceal the source. In fact, the
beneficiaries never realized that they owed their thanks to a
single giver  &MD;  they were told that the money came from several
generous ``clients'' who wished to remain anonymous.
<p>
   Few of the recipients had ever even met Dale or Joel Fleishman,
the president of Atlantic Philanthropic Services, which actually
gave away the money on behalf of Feeney's two foundations, the
Atlantic Foundation and the Atlantic Trust.
<p>
   Dr. Robert Butler of the Mount Sinai School of Medicine said he
met Feeney in 1990 while making a proposal for funding to an
advisory board that reviewed grant proposals.
<p>
   ``I had no idea that he was the main supporter of what I call
the Anonymous Foundation,'' Butler said, adding that the grant was
made, starting the International Longevity Center at the New York
Academy of Medicine. ``Anonymous giving, giving that is not
dependent on ego, is just really rare.''
<p>
   Feeney said that by giving anonymously, he could go about his
life unhampered by pitches for donations. ``There are people who
want, and rightly deserve, recognition for giving, but in our case
it wasn't important,'' he said.
<p>
   In 1984, when Feeney gave his 38.75 percent interest in the Duty
Free Shoppes chain to the two foundations, even his partner, Robert
Miller, was not told. Now, proceeds from the sale of the chain
earlier this month, along with his other business assets, a total
of $3.5 billion, are owned by the foundations.
<p>
   Feeney's charitable enterprise would rank as the nation's
fourth-largest grant-making foundation if it were based in the
United States, yet the two groups operate with tiny staffs, just 20
professionals in the United States and overseas.
<p>
   Duty-Free Shoppes has sales of more than $3 billion annually,
mostly in liquors and luxury goods, more than the combined sales of
Saks Fifth Avenue and Neiman-Marcus.
<p>
   The foundation's largest single grant was $30 million, according
to Dale, who refused to identify the recipient on grounds that the
information might discourage other donors from supporting it. ``One
reason for keeping gifts anonymous is to avoid what we call this
`crowding out' effect,'' Dale said.
<p>
   Recipients were effusive in their praise for their anonymous
donor's style of giving and what it had enabled them to do. ``This
is operational support, the most valuable kind of assistance,''
said William Nelsen, president of the Citizens' Scholarship
Foundation of America, in St. Peter, Minnesota, which has received
support since 1984, one of the oldest recipients.
<p>
   Nelson said that the group, which mobilizes community groups to
raise money for college student aid, was able to significantly
expand its ``Dollars for Scholars'' program to reach 770 chapters
throughout the country, thanks in large part to Atlantic money,
which he said was more than a million dollars.
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
<p>
   (MORE)
<p>
   nn
</POSTTEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2126EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0768 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9869 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-SECRET-BENE </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0748 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EXCLUSIVE-SECRET-BENEFACTOR-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW YORK: million dollars. &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ``As an organization, we've more than quadrupled in size since
getting support from this anonymous donor,'' Nelsen said.
<p>
   At the College Board, which administers scholastic assessment
tests for college-bound high school seniors, the mystery donor was
always referred to by the name ``anonymous,'' said Dr. Donald
Stewart, president of the College Board.
<p>
   ``Anonymous was most interested in results,'' Stewart said. The
anonymous donor supported ``long-term research to establish whether
we are right, which is crucial for the project's credibility and in
assessing whether schools should adopt the same approach,'' he
said.
<p>
   Several recipients said that once they were invited to apply for
funds their plans were closely examined. ``Ed McMahon did not knock
on my door,'' said Chuck Supple, president of Public Allies, which
places young people in internships with nonprofit organizations.
``These guys really kick the tires.''
<p>
   Judith Ramaley, president of Portland State University called
her first foundation grant last year her ``catalyst,'' financing of
less than one million dollars that enabled the school to publicize
its innovative new curriculum and links to the community, which
have now drawn national attention and the support of other
foundations. ``We were out of cash when they came along,'' she
said. ``They were the trail mix at that key moment on our very
steep hiking path,'' she said.
<p>
   Feeney's contributions in Ireland account for more than half of
Atlantic's international giving and about one-quarter of overall
giving. In addition to Ireland, the foundation supports projects in
South Africa, the former Soviet bloc, Eastern Europe, Israel and
Jordan.
<p>
   There was less secrecy surrounding Feeney's activities in
Ireland. Several Irish university presidents and other
beneficiaries said they had met Feeney several times; they also
knew, they added, that he had a connection to the Atlantic
foundations.
<p>
   Feeney also said he had given substantial personal donations  &MD; 
not from the Atlantic foundations  &MD;  to the Washington office of
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army, which
in 1994 entered into a cease fire with the British that broke down
last February. Public records show that Feeney has contributed some
$280,000  &MD;  making him the group's single largest American donor.
<p>
   Feeney said that his gifts to Sinn Fein had been carefully
monitored to insure that they supported only nonviolent activities,
and that he had continued supporting the Washington office despite
the cease-fire's collapse last February, ``because I'm hopeful that
it will be renewed.''
<p>
   The Atlantic Foundation's board of directors includes several
prominent personalities in the philanthropic and educational
establishment  &MD;  among them, Elizabeth McCormack, a senior adviser
on charitable giving to members of the Rockefeller family and vice
chairman of the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation;
Frank Rhodes, president emeritus of Cornell University, Michael
Sovern, president of the Shubert Foundation and president emeritus
of Columbia University, and Frederick A.O. Schwarz Jr., an attorney
and chairman of the Natural Resources Defense Council. None of them
had disclosed their connection with the Atlantic groups publicly,
nor did they ever discuss Feeney's giving with peers or even their
families, they said in interviews this week.
<p>
   ``This organization has operated on a need-to-know basis,''
Fleishman said.
<p>
   Most recipients  &MD;  a partial list of which was provided by APS  &MD; 
said their only contact was with program officers of the APS, the
for-profit group that selects the grantees, gives out the money,
and evaluates the outcome of what has been given away.
<p>
   Rhodes, the foundation board member and former president of
Cornell, said that the foundation was careful not to use money to
tell recipients what to do or how to do it. ``The danger with
foundations is that sometimes the staff and board come to feel that
they own the money,'' Rhodes said, ``and they micromanage. We have
a motto: noses in, fingers out.''
<p>
   Dale said of the relationship to grant recipients: ``We are
voyeurs. We let good people do good things. We oversee, but we
don't interfere.''
<p>
   And despite his decision finally to disclose his donations,
Feeney is still trying to keep a low profile. He declined this week
to be photographed.
</TEXT>
