<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=taf-z> A9870 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISING-2 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1116 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISING-2TAKES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CLINTON AIDE PUSHED BUSINESS DEAL SOUGHT BY DONOR, FILES SHOW &LR;  &QL; 
(SPECIAL REPORT; 10 p.m. ET EMBARGO) &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER DREW and JEFF GERTH &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  Maria Haley, a longtime aide to President Clinton
who is now an appointee of his at the Export-Import Bank, tried
last year to push through an unusual $6.5 million financing deal
sought by a woman whose large donations to the Democratic Party are
under investigation, interviews and government records show.
<p>
   The proposed deal called for the government bank to help a
company controlled by one of Thailand's wealthiest families finance
a Blockbuster video store franchise in Bangkok.
<p>
   Officials of the bank say the proposal initially ran into stiff
resistance because it seemed to fall outside the mandate of the
institution, whose chief mission is to provide low-cost government
financing to encourage exports and thereby support jobs in America.
<p>
   But Ms. Haley, a former White House official who by then had
become one of the bank's directors, prodded its staff to support
the project, and the deal won approval from one group of bank
officials before collapsing amid unresolved questions about the
franchise's operations.
<p>
   The project was put together in large part by Pauline
Kanchanalak, a Thai businesswoman who attended an important meeting
of Export-Import Bank officials at Ms. Haley's office last summer.
Last year, Mrs. Kanchanalak has said, she and her relatives donated
more than $200,000 to the Democratic Party, most of which was later
returned because of questions about its origins.
<p>
   It is not known whether Ms. Haley was aware of Mrs.
Kanchanalak's donations, and a White House spokesman said the
president was not aware of the Blockbuster deal, which would have
been a small one for the bank.
<p>
   Still, Ms. Haley's effort to push the deal forward is one of the
first signs that some Democratic donors with foreign ties were
seeking more specific help from the government than coffee meetings
and photos with the president. It also illustrates how some donors,
in their efforts to get federal assistance, tapped into a close
network of friends and associates from Clinton's Arkansas days and
zeroed in on agencies involved in promoting international trade.
<p>
   Mrs. Kanchanalak's donations were solicited by John Huang, the
Democratic fund-raiser now at the center of federal inquiries into
questionable donations from Asian and Asian-American business
interests. Huang also arranged for Mrs. Kanchanalak to attend a
White House coffee meeting with Clinton last June 18, a day when
she made $85,000 of the contributions to the party.
<p>
   Records at the Export-Import Bank show that Huang also called
Ms. Haley on June 18. And he called her twice during a crucial week
in August when the fate of the Blockbuster deal was being decided.
Huang and Ms. Haley are friends dating from the mid-1980s in Little
Rock, where they both knew Clinton, who was then governor of
Arkansas.
<p>
   Neither Ms. Haley nor Mrs. Kanchanalak would comment on the
Blockbuster deal, and Huang and his lawyer have declined, since he
came under investigation last fall, to talk about any aspect of his
fund-raising.
<p>
   Asked about the Blockbuster project, David Carter, the
Export-Import Bank's vice president for communications, said that
in order to protect confidential business information of its
applicants, he could not discuss any specific deal.
<p>
   But he did say that the bank had recently undertaken a study of
whether it should get more involved in financing overseas
franchises that might benefit American business, and that ``I am
confident that the bank and Director Haley have acted appropriately
at every turn.''
<p>
   Ms. Haley's telephone and appointment records, obtained by
congressional investigators, show that she was a prime contact for
a small circle of Clinton's former aides, golf buddies and
associates from Little Rock who have tried to use their connections
to make big business deals in Asia. One of them, Mark Grobmyer, an
Arkansas lawyer, met with Ex-Im officials considering the
Blockbuster financing, officials of the bank said.
<p>
   THE LONG ROAD FROM LITTLE ROCK
<p>
   Ms. Haley was one of the first staff members whom Clinton hired
after he became governor of Arkansas in 1979. She later accompanied
him on trade missions to Asia, heading the state's efforts to
attract foreign investment. After Clinton became president in 1993,
she served as a deputy White House personnel director under Bruce
Lindsey. The president nominated her to the Ex-Im Bank's board in
1994.
<p>
   Ms. Haley, 53, a native Filipino, grew up in a prominent
diplomatic family; her brother, Felipe Mabilangan, is the
Philippines' chief delegate to the United Nations.
<p>
   In an interview last fall, she said that as a White House aide
she had tried to help fellow Asian-Americans win federal
appointments. She said she was an old friend of Huang, whom she met
when he worked for a bank in Little Rock, and had helped get him a
job at the Commerce Department, where he was involved in promoting
trade before he joined the Democratic Party's fund-raising staff in
late 1995.
<p>
   Ms. Haley said she also kept in touch with ``old friends from
Arkansas,'' like Grobmyer, after becoming one of the Ex-Im Bank's
five directors. She said she had given them and their clients basic
information on the bank's lending programs.
<p>
   James T. Riady, a wealthy Indonesian businessman who was friends
with Clinton and Ms. Haley in Arkansas, visited her twice at the
bank, once with Huang. She also had contacts with Mark Middleton
and C. Joseph Giroir Jr., both Little Rock lawyers.
<p>
   According to Ms. Haley's appointment records, Giroir visited her
with an Indonesian media executive, Peter Gontha, to discuss
satellite exports last May. She also had dinner in 1995 with
Grobmyer and Steve Bova, an executive of Alltel, a Little Rock
information processing company. Bova said in an interview that
Alltel had hired Grobmyer to help the company ``navigate around how
do we get things like Ex-Im guarantees.''
<p>
   In the interview last fall, Ms. Haley said Grobmyer was
``interested in the Ex-Im Bank'' as a vehicle for developing
business opportunities for possible clients.
<p>
   Grobmyer's office issued a statement Wednesday saying that he
had been aware of the Blockbuster proposal but that he had never
had any financial interest in it. Instead, the statement said, his
attendance at any meetings about the Blockbuster deal ``related to
his interest in the Export-Import Bank's ability to engage in
franchise finance activities.''
</TEXT>
<POSTTEXT>
