<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISING-2 </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1051 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISING-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WASHINGTON: finance activities.'' &LR; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   THE EMERGENCE OF THE THAI COUNCIL
<p>
   Ms. Haley has said it was Grobmyer who introduced her to the
U.S.-Thai Business Council, a private trade-promotion group.
<p>
   The business council was created in 1994 by a group including
Mrs. Kanchanalak, a Thai citizen who lives in Virginia, with the
help of Grobmyer, who is a member. Huang also helped, writing a
memorandum at the Commerce Department noting that ``there are quite
a few members in this proposed council from Arkansas.''
<p>
   In 1994, at the time that Mrs. Kanchanalak was seeking a
government endorsement to give the new council more prestige than
similar rival groups, she donated $32,000 to the Democratic Party.
As a legal resident of the United States, she was entitled to make
political donations.
<p>
   But after the questions about Huang's fund-raising activities
surfaced last fall, the Democratic National Committee returned most
of an additional $200,000 that Mrs. Kanchanalak gave or raised last
year, saying the origin of some of the money was not clearly
documented.
<p>
   One goal of the business council was to familiarize Thai
businessmen, including the group seeking the Blockbuster franchise,
with American trade programs. The Export-Import Bank, an
independent agency, has played an important role in the Clinton
administration's strategy to create high-paying American jobs
through the promotion of trade.
<p>
   According to people familiar with the Blockbuster deal, a Thai
conglomerate, the Sun Tech Group, controlled by one of Thailand's
wealthiest businessmen, Sawasdi Horrungruang, first approached the
Ex-Im Bank in late 1995 or early 1996.
<p>
   Businessmen said the Thais had sought help from the American
bank because financing for American-style franchise rights was hard
to come by in Thailand, and a repayment guarantee from the Ex-Im
Bank would lower the interest rates that the Thais had to pay.
<p>
   One of Sun Tech's subsidiaries had agreed to pay $7.7 million to
the Blockbuster Entertainment Group, a Florida-based division of
Viacom Inc., for the rights to operate more than 100 video rental
stores in Thailand. The deal was to be financed by SunTrust Credit,
a Little Rock unit of a large Florida bank chain.
<p>
   Although business associates estimate that Horrungruang is worth
hundreds of millions of dollars, SunTrust asked the Ex-Im Bank to
insure repayment of 85 percent of the loan, or $6.5 million.
<p>
   The Thai company, with Mrs. Kanchanalak as its agent, argued to
the Ex-Im Bank that this was a valid if novel use of bank
resources, because over time millions of dollars in franchise
royalties would flow back to Blockbuster's American headquarters.
<p>
   But staff officials at the bank, which is best known for
financing huge export sales of Boeing aircraft or Caterpillar
tractors, were highly skeptical, government officials said.
<p>
   While the bank has expanded into a broader array of deals in
recent years, it is required to focus on export sales that do not
qualify for private financing or in which American companies are
competing against financing subsidized by foreign governments.
<p>
   As a result, the video proposal languished for several months at
the bank, while staff officials sought more information about the
Thai investors and how the loan would be repaid, according to
records and officials.
<p>
   Then Ms. Haley, who has generally prodded bank officials to be
more imaginative and who within the bank has been a champion for
small businesses, got involved, bank officials said. And by last
summer the proposal had gained new life.
<p>
   A bank official met with Sun Tech executives in Thailand on July
1 while in Asia on a business trip and later filed a report noting
that the Blockbuster deal could help promote the franchising of
American businesses throughout Asia.
<p>
   Bank officials said Ms. Haley had often inquired about the
status of the video franchise deal, and one official recalled that
at some point she said, ``Let's do it.''
<p>
   Although the bank's directors formally approve all transactions
of more than $10 million, this deal needed the approval of only one
group of senior officials and the bank's loan committee, also made
up of senior officers. But the directors can also meet with
potential bank customers and involve themselves in any issue.
<p>
   Bank officials said Ms. Haley had also been host at a crucial
meeting in her office attended by bank officials and Mrs.
Kanchanalak.
<p>
   As a result of the meeting, the bank took steps to reduce any
risk it would face if it reached any arrangement with the Thais.
One plan was to require Horrungruang to pledge that he would be
personally liable for the loan's repayment before any demands could
be made by the lender against the bank's own guarantee.
<p>
   Records show that last Aug. 13, only a few days after the
meeting in Ms. Haley's office, the first group of senior officials
recommended that the Ex-Im Bank's loan committee approve the deal.
<p>
   Bank records also show that Mrs. Kanchanalak and Huang
frequently made contact with Ms. Haley during the time when Ms.
Haley was giving critical support to the deal.
<p>
   While the records do not reveal what was discussed, they do show
that Mrs. Kanchanalak called Ms. Haley on June 25, met with her on
July 16 and called her on Aug. 13 and Aug. 14.
<p>
   In addition to calling Ms. Haley on June 18, the day of Mrs.
Kanchanalak's meeting with Clinton, Huang also called Ms. Haley on
Aug. 8 and Aug. 12, the records show.
<p>
   The bank loan committee considered giving final approval to the
video deal last August, with Ms. Haley in attendance, according to
bank officials. The committee withheld approval pending further
financial information about the Thai group, but the group decided
that month to drop the effort to get the bank's financing, bank
officials said.
<p>
   Meanwhile, in Bangkok, the Blockbuster deal has gone forward,
without Ex-Im help, and the Thai group has already opened six
stores. Horrungruang said Sun Tech would still be delighted to get
the ``cheap loan'' through Ex-Im. But even though the project's
supporters had argued that financing to buy franchise rights was
unavailable in Thailand, Horrungruang said the company had found
the money it needed there.
</TEXT>
