<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THINGS TURN WACKY ON PLANET PARCELLS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   They got off the elevator together. They shared a podium and
even tried cracking jokes. But the Bill Parcells-Bob Kraft act most
likely played to one of its final audiences.
<p>
   Two people familiar with the plans of both the New England
Patriots' coach and the team's owner indicated Wednesday that the
split between them is irrevocable, and that it is merely a question
of ironing out disputes in the contract before Parcells leaves to
coach elsewhere  &MD;  presumably the Jets.
<p>
   Yet, they made a show of unity Wednesday to diffuse a
controversy that each fears could affect the team only days before
the Super Bowl.
<p>
   Parcells introduced Kraft by saying: ``We will discuss the
situation about the future as expeditiously as possible and I can
also assure you that it's going to be done in a very civil and a
very friendly manner.''
<p>
   Kraft then said, jokingly: ``Bill Parcells will be the new
manager of our paper and packaging group.'' Kraft also made an
obscure reference to Mickey Corcoran, Parcells' old high school
coach and long-time mentor, quipping that he would be the new
Patriots' coach.
<p>
   Joking aside, Kraft, according to one of the people familiar
with the situation, is said to believe that he is due monetary
compensation for releasing Parcells from the fifth and final year
of his contract  &MD;  even though Kraft maintained publicly he did it
in deference to Parcells' concerns about his health.
<p>
   And Parcells is believed to be unable to continue operating in a
system where he will not be given the last word on football
matters. He was hired with those powers in 1993, but that agreement
was with the owner at the time, James Busch Orthwein, who sold the
team a year later to Kraft.
<p>
   Since then, Bobby Grier has been elevated to head of player
personnel and runs the draft.
<p>
   If in fact Parcells leaves New England, a likely successor would
be the team's quarterback coach, Chris Palmer.
<p>
   Eyes and Spies Everywhere
<p>
   This is the price of playing in a small market.
<p>
   Green Bay safety LeRoy Butler says that while he loves the fans
of the city, sometimes they talk a little too much. Butler says
that when he and teammates go out on the town, fans who see them
will call Packers Coach Mike Holmgren and tell him what the players
were doing.
<p>
   Some of the cheeseheads, apparently, double as spies.
<p>
   ``Coach Holmgren is always telling us about certain
situations,'' Butler said. ``He brings up things that I know
someone called him about. But the fans will call him and say, `They
were doing this at this bar.' Then we'll be in meetings, and coach
will say, `Why were you guys doing this?' He knows everything we
do.''
<p>
   Giants Pick Coaches
<p>
   The Giants named John Fox, formerly Oakland's defensive
coordinator, to the same position with them. It is also expected
that the team will soon name Jim Skipper, the former Arizona
running backs coach, as the offensive coordinator.
<p>
   Coach Jim Fassel has also interviewed Larry Mac Duff, the former
University of Arizona defensive coordinator, for the defensive line
coach job. He also interviewed John Dunn, the former San Diego
strength and conditioning coach, to do the same for the Giants. On
Wednesday, Fassel interviewed both Skipper and John Matsko, the
former New Orleans offensive line coach.
<p>
   The Giants also announced that former Nebraska defensive lineman
Christian Peter has signed with the team.
</TEXT>
