<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICEUNION-ASSESS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1086 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-POLICEUNION-ASSESS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ANALYSIS: GIULIANI'S TENSIONS WITH POLICE WILL BE BACKDROP TO
CAMPAIGN &LR;  &QL; 
(With NY-POLICEUNION-INDICT) &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID FIRESTONE &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is never so warm and generous
with his praise as when he is boasting of the achievements of his
Police Department and the dramatic drop in crime it has helped
produce. But for most of his term, the city employees with whom he
has had the coldest relationship has been the 38,000 police
officers who do the crime fighting.
<p>
   Almost all of the other major city unions  &MD;  teachers, teamsters,
municipal workers  &MD;  have swallowed their earlier skepticism of the
Republican mayor and accepted the five-year contracts that fiscal
watchdogs criticized as too generous.
<p>
   The one union that seemed the most enthusiastic about Giuliani's
candidacy was the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, whose members
saw him as far more sympathetic than the rival they despised,
former Mayor David Dinkins.
<p>
   Now, in what may be the singular paradox of the Giuliani era,
this administration's relationship with the PBA may be even more
bitter than was Dinkins', despite the leading role of law
enforcement on Giuliani's agenda.
<p>
   After nearly three years of recriminations, the union's
leadership Tuesday rejected a contract offer from the mayor more
generous than the ones accepted by the other major unions.
<p>
   Thursday, union officials say, police officers at every station
house in the city will begin picketing the best-known law
enforcement mayor the city has had in decades.
<p>
   As contract negotiations head to a binding arbitration process
that seems stacked against the union, the protests are likely to
continue for months, a bizarre backdrop to an election campaign in
which the mayor will run primarily on the city's drop in crime.
<p>
   In part, the breakdown in relations between the mayor and his
police force stems precisely from the high expectations that police
officers had of his administration.
<p>
   Thousands of city police officers live in the suburbs and deeply
resent that their suburban colleagues make 30 to 40 percent more
than they do. Surely a mayor with a law-enforcement background
would finally right that imbalance, many officers believed.
<p>
   ``He asked us to do a job,'' said Officer John Flynn, a union
delegate at the 13th Precinct on East 21st Street in Manhattan,
describing the sense of betrayal expressed by many officers
Wednesday. ``We did the job. They wanted us to go out and make
arrests. We did it. For the first time since the '60s, we blew a
thousand homicides. He always says that we're doing a great job.
But where's the money in our pockets?''
<p>
   But Giuliani was just as interested in cutting spending as he
was in cutting crime, and in 1994, he forced the PBA to accept
essentially the same raise as every other city employee, despite
the union's protests that it should receive special treatment
because the lives of officers were on the line.
<p>
   Almost immediately, the PBA began a strategy to bypass the city
by getting the state Legislature to shift its contract negotiations
to a more generous state arbitration board.
<p>
   The Legislature has a far closer relationship to the union after
years of taking its generous campaign contributions and went along
with the plan, only to see the effort overturned by the state's
highest court last month.
<p>
   It was that strategy that the mayor angrily assailed Wednesday
in lamenting the union's rejection of his contract offer, which
would give the union a raise of almost 16 percent over five years.
<p>
   The architect of that strategy and the union's chief negotiator,
James Lysaght, was indicted Wednesday on federal corruption
charges, a fact that Giuliani took pains to note in a clear sign of
contempt toward the union's leadership.
<p>
   ``The whole thing in Albany never made any sense,'' he said at a
news conference. ``It never made any sense that any mayor, no
matter how supportive you are of the police, no matter how you love
the police and care about the police, is going to let labor
relations slip away from the city and go to Albany.''
<p>
   It also set up the expectation that police officers could
legitimately compare their salaries to those of the suburbs,
because the state board is explicitly allowed to make such a
comparison in arbitrating police salary disputes.
<p>
   By contrast, the city's Board of Collective Bargaining, which
will now decide the contract's fate, can only compare the contract
to other city unions.
<p>
   The mayor argued that New York police salaries could only be
compared with those of other major cities  &MD;  not suburbs  &MD;  and said
his offer would put local salaries above those of other East Coast
cities.
<p>
   Joseph Mancini, a spokesman for the PBA, said the union believed
New York ranks seventh out of the top 10 cities in the country for
police salaries. ``It is meaningless for him to say that in five
years it will give us salaries as good or better than other major
cities when he has no idea where those cities will be in five
years,'' Mancini said.
<p>
   Police officers said they were most upset by having to take two
years of no raises  &MD;  1995 and 1996  &MD;  before the new raise offer
would begin this April. There was also resentment expressed that
newly hired officers would lose 20 minutes a day of ``wash-up
time'' and would have to work an extra 10 days a year.
<p>
   The proposal is the same one made in 1994 by the Citizens Budget
Commission, a fiscal monitoring group, which said the 20 minutes
was wasted every day. By putting officers on the street an extra 10
days a year, the group said, the city could save $50 million
annually. The union hated the idea when it was first proposed, and
the Giuliani administration also dismissed it. But now, the
administration has thrown the proposal back at the union as a means
of paying for a raise 2.5 percent larger than that of other unions.
<p>
   Top union officials were not talking Wednesday, and thus could
not explain their thinking in rejecting the contract. But
administration officials, shaking their heads at the move, think
the union leaders were simply playing to the anger of their
members.
<p>
   When the panel issues its ruling in three to five months, the
union leadership can blame the new contract on the arbitrators, and
step up its oratory against the mayor.
<p>
   When that happens, in the middle of an election campaign,
today's rancor may seem mild by comparison.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2130EST
</TRAILER>
