<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0774 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9875 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MICH-WELFARE-CHIEF </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0807 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-MICH-WELFARE-CHIEF-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GIULIANI'S WELFARE CHIEF TO HEAD SOCIAL SERVICES IN MICHIGAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By VIVIAN S. TOY &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Marva L. Hammons, the head of the sprawling agency
that distributes welfare benefits to nearly a million people in New
York City, is resigning to become head of social services in
Michigan.
<p>
   The departure of Ms. Hammons, one of the few high-ranking black
officials in the Giuliani administration, was not unexpected
because she had been consistently shut out of most important
decisions involving social services and her agency, the Human
Resources Administration.
<p>
   Ms. Hammons was rarely seen at major announcements at City Hall
and was not at Wednesday's news conference when Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani announced her departure and named her replacement, Lilliam
Barrios-Paoli.
<p>
   Ms. Barrios-Paoli is a trusted Giuliani aide who now heads the
Department of Housing Preservation and Development. Ms.
Barrios-Paoli has a reputation as an able administrator who held a
number of management positions in the administrations of Giuliani
and Mayor Edward I. Koch, including a seven-year stint at HRA.
<p>
   Advocates for welfare recipients have sharply criticized Ms.
Hammons, saying she did little to lead an agency that has long been
considered the city's most unmanageable and cumbersome bureaucracy.
<p>
   But in reality, Giuliani and his top aides have directly
overseen many of the agency's new initiatives themselves, including
the city's workfare program, which has put more than 122,000 people
to work cleaning streets and parks in return for their benefits,
and the fingerprint-imaging program to weed out welfare fraud.
<p>
   The mayor congratulated Ms. Hammons on her new appointment
Wednesday and said, ``I want to thank her for the significant
contributions she made to restructuring HRA.''
<p>
   He reserved higher praise for Ms. Barrios-Paoli, saying, ``Her
proven capabilities as a leader, manager and an administrator and
her commitment to city government will be a tremendous asset to the
Human Resources Administration.''
<p>
   Ms. Hammons declined to comment Wednesday but issued a statement
saying she looked forward to her new job and adding, ``I have very
much enjoyed working at HRA and have benefited greatly from the
support I received from Mayor Giuliani and the staff of the
agency.''
<p>
   While Ms. Hammons had receded into the shadows in the Giuliani
administration, John Truscott, a spokesman for Michigan Gov. John
Engler, said, ``She'll have a very high profile in Michigan because
she has the full backing of the governor.''
<p>
   Engler has been in the forefront of welfare reform at a national
level, and has cut the welfare rolls in his own state by more than
140,000, a 46 percent decrease.
<p>
   In her new job, Ms. Hammons will run an agency that administers
cash assistance to about 167,000 people, only a fraction of those
handled by New York's Human Resources Administration. She also will
be taking a pay cut, from $133,000 to $100,000 a year.
<p>
   Ms. Hammons took over HRA in 1994, after managing services for
Denver's 15,000 welfare recipients.
<p>
   During her tenure in New York, the city's social service agency
lost more than 7,500 employees. Much of the staff reduction
occurred when the mayor stripped away the department's
responsibility over child welfare last year and created a new
agency to manage the city's foster-care and child-protection
programs after the highly publicized beating death of 6-year-old
Elisa Izquierdo.
<p>
   The caseload also declined significantly in her tenure. Giuliani
said Wednesday that welfare rolls had been reduced by 220,000 in
the last three years, leaving a caseload of about 940,000.
<p>
   Advocates for the poor said that while some of that decline
could be attributed to an improved economy, the mayor's harsh
policies accounted for the rest of the drop.
<p>
   ``Really bad things happened under her watch, but it's not clear
that she had much to do with any of it,'' said Liz Krueger, of the
Community Food Resource Center, an agency that works with welfare
recipients.
<p>
   Ms. Krueger noted that the new administrator of HRA will have to
deal with enormous upheaval in the next year because of anticipated
federal and state welfare cuts. ``We're coming into a difficult and
extremely volatile period for social services,'' she said. ``We
still have almost two million people living in poverty, and we have
fewer and fewer resources to draw on to meet their basic needs.''
<p>
   Nonprofit organizations that have worked with Ms. Barrios-Paoli
in the 10 months she has run the housing preservation agency
praised her willingness to work with them, but said the department
needed someone with more housing expertise. The mayor has not yet
appointed a successor at the housing agency.
</TEXT>
