<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0576 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BKW-WNBA-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WOMEN'S NBA ALLOCATES THE SUPERSTARS &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; By TARIK EL-BASHIR &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SECAUCUS, N.J.  &MD;  Rebecca Lobo, Lisa Leslie and Sheryl Swoopes
sat patiently as they were questioned, photographed and videotaped
by dozens of New York area reporters Wednesday. Welcome to life as
a professional athlete.
<p>
   All three are members of the 1996 U.S. Olympic team, and now all
three  &MD;  the biggest names in women's basketball  &MD;  are members of
the Women's National Basketball Association, which will begin play
in June.
<p>
   The WNBA, which is owned and operated by the National Basketball
League, Wednesday assigned Lobo, Leslie, Swoopes and 13 other
big-name players to the league's eight charter teams.
<p>
   Among them, the 16 players own 11 gold medals, nine National
Collegiate Athletic Association championships and 16 NCAA
all-America awards.
<p>
   The eight teams, which will play in NBA arenas, were assigned
two players each. The allotments were made according to the
individual player's regional ties and with the aim of ensuring an
even distribution of talent and appeal. Lobo played her collegiate
basketball for Connecticut. Leslie, who played for Southern
California, was assigned to Los Angeles. Swoopes, who played for
Texas Tech, was assigned to Houston.
<p>
   The eight teams, which will be operated by the NBA team in that
city, are divided into two conferences. Charlotte, Cleveland,
Houston and New York make up the Eastern Conference, and Los
Angeles, Phoenix, Sacramento and Utah are in the the Western
Conference.
<p>
   ``I'm just looking forward to that first game, to be in front of
fans again and to play,'' Lobo said. ``I'm excited to be playing in
Madison Square Garden; it's one of the most storied arenas in
sports.''
<p>
   The league expects to announce the allotment of another 16
players as early as next month and will hold a draft for college
seniors on April 20.
<p>
   Although New York is without a coach and without a name, the
team already has a good core of players. In addition to the
6-foot-4-inch Lobo, who led UConn to a perfect record and the NCAA
championship in the 1994-95 season, New York was given Teresa
Weatherspoon, a 5-8 guard who has played professionally overseas.
<p>
   ``Rebecca has done more for women's basketball in the region and
in the nation than anybody,'' said Carol Blazejowski, the league
vice president and general manager of the New York club. ``She is a
great young player with tons of potential, and as for Teresa, if I
were still playing she would be my first pick in the backcourt.''
<p>
   Ackerman said the WNBA does not intend to compete with the
American Basketball League, the women's professional league
currently in season. The main reason is that the ABL plays during
the winter and the WNBA will play for two months in the summer.
That the two leagues will have to compete for the same players also
does not concern Ackerman.
<p>
   ``The ABL players are not available to us contractually, but we
are not bothered by that,'' Ackerman said. ``The good thing about
women's basketball is that the talent pool is very deep.''
<p>
   The one major advantage for the new league is the deep pockets
of the NBA.
<p>
   ``We know it will take more than one or two years,'' Ackerman
said. ``This is a long-term investment. We are very focused on the
quality of the product. From the front office to the coaches to the
player, we want to make this first-class.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2132EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0776 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9877 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JOB-GROWTH-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0891 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-JOB-GROWTH-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. SAYS NEW YORK CITY OUTDID SUBURBS IN '96 JOB GROWTH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By KIRK JOHNSON &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  One of the tenets of economics in America is that
suburbs create more jobs than cities. Last year, New York City
broke that pattern. For the first time since 1980, the city
outshone its entire suburban encirclement of office parks and edge
cities in making new jobs.
<p>
   Of the 70,000 net new private jobs added in the 27-county region
tracked by the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics, 37,000 were in the
five boroughs of New York City  &MD;  a slim majority, but a majority
nonetheless. Over most of the last 17 years, the city has never
come even close to that. Through the boom years for job creation
from 1979 to 1988, for example, New York accounted for only about
one quarter of the one million new jobs created in the region.
<p>
   The changing balance between the growth rates of city and
suburbs is partly because suburban job creation has slowed. ``The
city is driving the growth,'' said John L. Wieting, the New York
regional commissioner for the statistics bureau. ``That's a break
in the historic pattern.''
<p>
   Wieting and other economists said that one year's worth of
numbers, while providing a mirror to the growth that New Yorkers
have already witnessed in places like Times Square and downtown
Brooklyn, do not necessarily suggest the arrival of a long-term
trend. Nor do they point to a dazzling economic boom.
<p>
   New York City's private job base rose only 1.3 percent in the 12
months ending Nov. 30, better than in 1995 but less than in 1994 or
1993, which were both strong years of economic recovery from the
recession of the late 1980s and early 1990s. Growth in the suburban
job base in 1996 slowed even more, rising only 0.8 percent. Both
lagged far behind the national growth rate of 2.4 percent in the
period, according to federal figures.
<p>
   What the New York numbers do suggest  &MD;  especially in some major
areas like retailing and manufacturing, where the city has long
been the weakest link in the regional economic chain  &MD;  is a shift,
at least for now, in the local balance of power.
<p>
   More people were working in New York in October in the retail
trade category, for example  &MD;  nearly 571,000 jobs, up 3,000 in 1996
 &MD;  than in any comparable October since 1990, according to figures
from the New York State Department of Labor.
<p>
   Equally profound is that the city did better, or at least less
badly, than the surrounding counties in holding onto manufacturing
jobs. The city lost manufacturing jobs, as it has nearly every year
since the early 1970s.
<p>
   But in the suburbs, where corporate downsizing and restructuring
continued to be a major force at places like AT&AMP;T, New Jersey's
largest private employer, the hemorrhage was worse. Of the 19,000
manufacturing jobs that disappeared, only 5,000 were in the city.
<p>
   Job growth in areas like motion picture production, on the other
hand, which contributed 6,600 new jobs, indicate larger national
and international changes in which the city stands to benefit
uniquely.
<p>
   An increasing number of internationally produced film projects,
in particular, have found New York to be a convenient halfway point
between Hollywood and Europe for both financing and production,
according to Harold Vogel, an entertainment industry analyst at
Cowan &AMP; Co. A strengthened Canadian dollar also helped, he said, by
making Toronto  &MD;  one of New York's main competitors for urban movie
sets  &MD;  more expensive.
<p>
   There were also indications of internal changes in the city's
economy.
<p>
   The securities industry, buoyed by the bull market for stocks,
fueled much of the city's job creation. But that growth was mostly
in the businesses that serve the needs of Wall Street, like
printers, legal services and accountants, which added 12,500 jobs  &MD; 
making up the single largest component of the job creation.
<p>
   In what may be a portent of a restructuring industry, job growth
in traditional high-paying jobs like brokers increased less than in
previous booming stock years, partly because of labor-saving
technology, according to an analysis by the Federal Reserve Bank of
New York.
<p>
   Another major wrinkle in the city's trajectory is that it
continues to be the center of shrinking public employment, as
state, federal and local governments  &MD;  especially New York City's
government  &MD;  reduce their work forces. The city lost more than
9,000 public jobs in the city in 1996, according to state and
Federal figures.
<p>
   If that public employment deficit is subtracted from the net
growth in private jobs, the city's total growth shrinks to 28,000
jobs, while the rest of the region  &MD;  less affected by government
job cuts  &MD;  still has a growth of 30,000 jobs.
<p>
   Another regional wrinkle indicated in the job creation numbers
is that some parts of the region outside New York are doing better
than others. Long Island, in particular, emerged in 1996 as a
center of suburban job growth, according to Rae D. Rosen, a senior
economist at the Federal Reserve Bank of New York.
<p>
   Ms. Rosen said that Long Island shares some of the same
strengths as New York, with fewer of the city's weaknesses.
<p>
   ``Long Island doesn't have the drag of government layoffs, and
it's adding more retail employment,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2132EST
</TRAILER>
