<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0778 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=ttx-z> A9879 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-MILKPROTEST-TEX </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0654 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-MILKPROTEST-TEX &QL; 
DAIRY FARMERS DUMP MILK TO PROTEST LOW PRICES &QL; 
DUPLICATION ALERT: Story will also move in ``f'' financial
category. &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
By WORTH WREN JR. &QC; 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   FORT WORTH, Texas  &MD;  Protesting dairy farmers dumped one day's
worth of milk production in neighboring Johnson County and other
areas Wednesday to end, they said, unfair pricing practices.
<p>
   A final estimate on how much milk was dumped in Texas won't be
available for several weeks. But one preliminary estimate put the
volume at well over 250,000 gallons, or more than 10 percent of
daily production in the Southwest region.
<p>
   ``Support was greater than we expected,'' said Sulphur Springs
dairy farmer Clint Van Vleet, president of the 250-member Texas
Milk Producers Association.
<p>
   The group was one of the protest sponsors, which also included
some dairy farmers in Wisconsin, New Mexico and Louisiana,
according to Texas dairy farmers.
<p>
   Godley dairy farmers in Johnson County, about 25 miles south of
Fort Worth, said they believe that 39 of the 54 milk producers in
the county dumped one day's production.
<p>
   Van Vleet and the protesters have accused the federal government
and cheese makers of engaging in unfair market manipulation.
<p>
   ``We're not asking for something for nothing,'' said Gary Roden,
who is the partner of his father, Larry Roden, in a Godley dairy
farm. ``We want to just be able to pay our bills and make a
living.''
<p>
   The protesting farmers in Johnson County dumped their milk on
their own farms, mostly into waste water lagoons, Gary Roden said.
<p>
   ``We believe our voice was heard,'' said Roden, remarking on
media interest in the dumping.
<p>
   Many dairy farmers are citing a tight cost-price squeeze from
high feed and other production costs and widely fluctuating milk
prices that they say have fallen below their operating costs.
<p>
   They're blaming the wide price variations since the summer on
unfair trading practices, lack of competition among processors,
rising imports and other government and industry practices.
<p>
   Van Vleet said protesters want the federal government to scrap
the current pricing system, based on cheese prices on the National
Cheese Exchange and tied to a formula administered under the
Federal Milk Marketing Order System.
<p>
   He said the government should initiate a pricing system based on
the national average cost of milk production and require that all
milk move from farms to processors under specific volume contracts.
<p>
   Mid-America Dairymen, based in Springfield, Mo., said the volume
that it lost in the protest was insignificant and created no
shortages for processing customers.
<p>
   Texas was the only state where Mid-America members were
confirmed to have dumped milk, said John Wilson, a cooperative
spokesman.
<p>
   ``Yet we certainly empathize with the dairy farmers and their
tough times on the farm,'' Wilson said.
<p>
   Van Vleet said, ``It shows that dairy farmers know they will
have to take strong measures to change this industry.'' 
<p>
   STORY CAN END HERE
<p>
   North Texas' two dominant milk marketing cooperatives reported
modest protest participation among member farmers in the region.
<p>
   Associated Milk Producers, based in Arlington, lost about 20,000
gallons of milk, or four tanker truckloads, said Sonny Pride, a
cooperative spokesman.
<p>
   About half that volume apparently was dumped in Johnson County,
and the other half in Hopkins County near Sulphur Springs, he said.
<p>
   Pride said the amount dumped was not completely known but that
Associated Milk encountered no supply problems Wednesday. Because
member producers announced dumping plans in advance, the
cooperative made adjustments to deliver sufficient milk to fill
orders, he said.
<p>
   ``Of course, we hate to lose the four loads,'' Pride said.
<p>
   That amounted to an estimated $24,000 net loss to producers, he
said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2134EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0779 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=ttx-z> A9880 </STORYID>
