<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9881 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-ACCIDENT-NY </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0757 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-SCHOOL-ACCIDENT-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GIRL INJURED IN FALL DOWN SCHOOL'S AIR SHAFT &LR;  &QL; 
(bl) &QL; 
 &UR; By MIRTA OJITO &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Trying to hide from a dean who was looking for her
and nine other students who had cut class, a 13-year-old girl fell
two floors down an air shaft at an intermediate school in Jackson
Heights, Queens, Wednesday morning, police officers and school
officials said.
<p>
   The girl, Jennifer Cubillos, was taken to Elmhurst Hospital
Center with multiple cuts to her face and head. She remained in
critical but stable condition Wednesday night in the hospital's
intensive care unit.
<p>
   David Golub, a spokesman for Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew, said
he did not know how Jennifer fell or why she and the others were in
a room that is off-limits to students and protected by two locked
doors. But students who gathered outside the school, IS 145 after
class Wednesday said the small room behind the auditorium is a
favorite hideout for students who skip class. They also said it is
seldom locked.
<p>
   Police and school officials are investigating the case, which so
far has been described as an accident. Golub said there is no
record that a similar accident has ever happened at any school in
the city.
<p>
   ``It was an unfortunate accident,'' Golub said. ``A very, very
rare type of incident.''
<p>
   The incident happened just before 11:30 a.m. Wednesday, when
teachers noticed that some students were missing from third-period
classes. A dean was notified, and she searched for the students,
who were not all in the same class.
<p>
   The dean went to the small room behind the auditorium.
<p>
   ``She had reasons to believe the students might be there,''
Golub said. ``They had done it in the past.''
<p>
   As she unlocked the door, the dean called out the names of the
students and asked them to come out, Golub said. Startled, the
students panicked and scattered, and Jennifer apparently went into
an adjoining room and fell down the shaft.
<p>
   Nobody saw the girl fall, Golub said. When all the students had
come out and they realized she was missing, they looked down the
shaft and saw her body two floors below, sprawled behind the
boiler.
<p>
   The room that Jennifer fled to is used to hold speakers for the
auditorium, and the door inside it leads to the air shaft, which is
protected by an iron rail that, at its highest point, is two and a
half feet high.
<p>
   Patricia Zedalis, chief executive in the school system's
Division of School Facilities, said both the door that leads to the
utility room and the door for the air shaft are locked at all
times, and students know that they are not supposed to be there.
<p>
   However, students told reporters after school that the doors are
usually open. They also said students often use the room to smoke,
cut classes and hang out after school.
<p>
   They also gave a slightly different interpretation of the events
that conflicted with the account of school officials. Jason Wynter,
14, said that a friend who was in the room had told him that
Jennifer fell because she panicked. When the dean approached her
and asked her to come out, Jennifer, who was holding onto a pole in
the rail, let go.
<p>
   The teen-ager also said that even if the doors are locked,
students find ways to get in.
<p>
   Golub said the investigation has not yet revealed how the
students got into the room. He said that doors were checked two
hours before the accident Wednesday morning and they were locked.
In addition, he said, the dean had to use her key to enter the
room.
<p>
   Another way to get in, Golub said, is to use a crawl space that
leads up to the room. The crawl space can be reached from the floor
below, but to reach it one would need to climb 15 feet.
<p>
   Parents gathered outside the school Wednesday said they trusted
the school and despite the incident, were not concerned for the
safety of the children. ``I think this is a good school,'' said
Mailbia Patino, 40. ``I get a lot of academic support.''
<p>
   The school, also known as Joseph Pulitzer Intermediate School,
has a magnet program for communications and technology and is
located at 33-34 80th Street in Jackson Heights. It was built in
1953, and is one of the most overcrowded schools in District 30,
which is the most crowded district in the city.
<p>
   Teachers who spoke on condition of anonymity said part of the
problem is that there are too many children in school and not
enough supervision. The school has a capacity for 1,055 students,
but this year 1,790 registered for classes.
</TEXT>
