<SLUG> BC-WELD-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1078 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-WELD-BUDGET-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WELD OFFERS HIGHER SPENDING IN BUDGET PLAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MICHAEL GRUNWALD &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   BOSTON  &MD;  Buoyed by the economic and fiscal recovery of
Massachusetts, Gov. William F. Weld Wednesday unveiled a
politician's dream budget, featuring deep tax cuts, big spending
hikes and a credibly balanced bottom line.
<p>
   The record-high $18.224 billion budget proposal  &MD;  including
major boosts for education, local aid and human services plus seven
tax cuts  &MD;  completes a remarkable evolution for Weld, who stormed
Beacon Hill as a cost-cutter in 1991. He said Wednesday that, with
unemployment low, revenues high, welfare caseloads down, bond
ratings up and budget-busters in control, the state can now afford
to do more for its residents while taking a smaller bite out of
their incomes.
<p>
   Every year, Weld's budgets have been greeted with criticism and
disdain by Democratic legislators and liberal activists. But this
year, his unusually generous plan won praise from liberals,
conservatives and deficit hawks. Even the Legislature's leaders had
relatively nice things to say about it, although they warned that
Weld's was just the first word in a long process.
<p>
   ``At first blush, this is his best effort yet,'' said House
Speaker Thomas M. Finneran. ``There have been some pretty dismal
ones in the past ... but it sounds like we may be getting on the
same page.''
<p>
   Of course, not all of Weld's 314-page plan was popular. It did
not add much money for higher education or the troubled state park
system. Housing programs were cut. As the Globe reported Wednesday,
Weld's much-hyped bid to downsize state government was mostly
scrapped. Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham said he was
``baffled'' by a lack of money for local school construction, just
a week after Weld made education the centerpiece of his State of
the State address.
<p>
   In general, though, the budget seemed to have something for
everyone, the kind of please-em-all grab bag Weld could have used
in his ill-fated race against Sen. John F. Kerry. Weld said that
after six years of digging out from fiscal disaster, the state is
finally sound enough to look to the 21st century. His budget boosts
overall spending by only 2.9 percent, less than projected
inflation, but its hikes for education, local aid and human
services are higher.
<p>
   ``Six years ago it would have been impossible to fund these new
initiatives, but we've put our house in order,'' Weld said. ``Now
we're going to be able to do an enormous amount to meet these
social needs, and I think we can still afford all these tax cuts
without breaking a sweat.''
<p>
   The Weld recommendations fully fund K-12 education reform,
boosting state spending by $278 million. They hike spending on
early childhood education by 50 percent. They continue to return
Lottery revenues to cities and towns, sending back $55 million
more. They also include more money for water and sewer rate relief,
community policing and domestic violence prevention. There is even
a proposal to make prisoners help pay the costs of their
incarceration.
<p>
   The big departure for Weld was an extra $384 million for human
services, a 5.5 percent increase first reported in Monday's Globe.
That money will help legal immigrants who will lose benefits under
the federal welfare overhaul, frail elders who want to live at
home, mentally retarded adults who have waited years for services,
and thousands of other vulnerable citizens.
<p>
   ``Generally, there are a lot of good-news stories in this
budget. It's certainly a different budget for Weld,'' Birmingham
said.
<p>
   However, Birmingham (D-Chelsea) said Weld shortchanged higher
education, a charge that dogged the governor throughout his Senate
campaign. And human services advocates, while generally delighted
with the budget, were shocked to hear Weld declare that with this
budget he had addressed every unmet social need in the
commonwealth.
<p>
   ``That is staggering,'' said Betsy Wright of the Massachusetts
Human Services Coalition. ``I guess his defeat in the Senate race
put the poor on his radar screen. But now we need to get homeless
families on his radar screen. Now he needs to know 15,000 people
are waiting for adult education.''
<p>
   As usual, tax cuts are likely to be the most controversial part
of Weld's budget. Finneran (D-Mattapan) and Birmingham were
enthusiastic about raising the income tax deduction for dependent
children from $600 to $1,600. But they were cautious about tax
breaks on telecommunications, life insurers, and unearned income.
They said that after cutting deals for Raytheon and mutual funds,
the state's top priority should be working families, not
corporations or rich individuals.
<p>
   The two leaders scoffed at Weld's suggestion that Democratic
legislators are eager to raise taxes, noting that they approved all
15 of Weld's proposed tax cuts, but they said the price tag for
further cuts could be a problem. When fully phased in, Weld's seven
tax cuts could cost $660 million a year.
<p>
   Weld may also face a struggle over policy recommendations. He
wants the Legislature to lift the cap on charter schools. He wants
to abolish county government. He wants state employees to pay more
of their health costs. He wants to speed up a controversial plan to
replace the state's existing job placement and training system and
with ``one-stop career centers.'' And he wants businesses to pay
less to the unemployment insurance trust fund.
<p>
   But the real struggle may lurk years down the road. Right now,
the economy is humming; prosperity is filling state coffers to
overflowing. But the nonpartisan Massachusetts Taxpayers Foundation
warns that times are not quite as good as they seem; a recession
could turn the state's black ink red again.
<p>
   ``This budget is fine, but I'm worried about this sentiment I
hear that the good old days have returned,'' said Michael Widmer,
director of the foundation. ``It's not really backed up by the
numbers. We can definitely afford this now, but the question is
what will happen down the road.''
<p>
   In his budget, Weld proposed at least three new state programs:
one bolstering food pantries, one subsidizing health care for legal
immigrants, and one to bail out school districts facing unexpected
increases in student population. The Legislature is expected to
propose at least one more, a home visiting program for at-risk
parents.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2135EST
</TRAILER>
