<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tth-z> A9883 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOLOGY-WASHINGTON </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1094 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TECHNOLOGY-WASHINGTON-SPI &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TECHNOLOGY-BASED INDUSTRIES PROVIDE ONE-THIRD OF STATE'S JOBS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By WARREN WILSON &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Seattle Post-Intelligencer &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SEATTLE  &MD;  Technology-based industries are responsible for
one-third of all jobs in Washington state and now form a larger
sector than natural resource industries such as agriculture and
forest products, according to a new study by two University of
Washington geographers.
<p>
   Prepared for the Technology Alliance, a non-profit group of
technology business leaders and heads of research institutions, the
study is the first broad-based look at the economic importance of
technology-intensive businesses in Washington.
<p>
   It could become an important point of reference in debates over
state policies regarding education, business regulation and taxes,
research done at state institutions, even roads and bridges.
<p>
   ``It clarifies a phenomenon that's important for us who live in
Washington state to be aware of  &MD;  that we've got an important and
growing sector which needs to be nurtured,'' said attorney William
Gates, chairman of the alliance and father of Microsoft co-founder
Bill Gates.
<p>
   Geography professor Bill Beyers, the study's lead author, called
it ``another piece of evidence'' about the broad changes occurring
in the state's economy.
<p>
   ``We've evolved from a state where natural resource industries
were our economic heart into a more diversified economy,'' Beyers
said. ``Today these parts of our economy are growing fast, and
these are good-paying jobs  &MD;  they're the kind of jobs we talk about
wanting to create.''
<p>
   In the study, Beyers and co-author David Lindahl defined
technology-based industries as those in which at least 10 percent
of employment is related to research and development.
<p>
   They based their categories on Standard Industrial
Classification Codes and National Science Foundation occupation
definitions, to make them comparable across the country and easier
to update in the future.
<p>
   So defined, the technology-based category includes not just the
well-known high-tech categories such as engineering services,
computer services and software but less-obvious fields such as
management and public relations, agricultural chemicals, motor
vehicles and petroleum refining that also have a large research and
development component.
<p>
   It also includes the aerospace industry, which for all its
reliance on steel and aluminum is also technology intensive. More
than 30 percent of its employees are involved in research and
development.
<p>
   Direct employment in technology-based industries in Washington
totals 230,947, the study found. But each of those jobs generates
an average of 2.37 more jobs in services, trade and other
industries, for a total of 778,300 jobs that result directly and
indirectly from technology-based industries.
<p>
   Washington ranks sixth in its relative concentration of those
industries, after the District of Columbia, Massachusetts,
Connecticut, California and Michigan, the study found.
<p>
   Technology-based industries generate $41.8 billion in direct
sales revenue and $74.2 billion when indirect sales are counted.
Direct labor income totals $12 billion, while indirect labor income
adds $13.8 billion more.
<p>
   They contribute disproportionately to the state's economy, the
study found, since 76 percent of their sales are made out of state,
compared to an average of 40 percent for the economy as a whole.
<p>
   And they have grown dramatically over the last two decades, from
93,000 private-sector jobs in 1974 to 220,000 in 1995, plus another
11,000 in the public sector.
<p>
   To a great extent, Gates said, such growth occurs ``inertially''
as businesses develop sophistication and know-how that spins off
into separate ventures  &MD;  a process demonstrated time and again at
the company founded by his son's Redmond-based Microsoft.
<p>
   ``But you need more than that,'' the elder Gates said. ``You
need the external influences  &MD;  things like a first-class
university, first-class research institutions. You need to be sure
you've got the kind of place where professional people want to come
and live.''
<p>
   The University of Washington has been responsible for dozens of
new businesses over the years, many of which have been started
``essentially by accident,'' he said. Now it is becoming more
organized and direct in its efforts to turn laboratory work into
commercial ventures.
<p>
   ``I think that has enormous promise,'' he said. ``When you look
at what's happened by accident, it can be pretty exciting thinking
what might happen if somebody begins to focus deliberate effort on
those kinds of developments.''
<p>
   Several other technology-industry spokesmen echoed Gates' views,
saying the study points up the critical role of the state's
education system in providing both qualified workers and research
advances with commercial potential.
<p>
   ``The biggest issue is really education,'' said Tom Ranken,
executive director of the Washington Biotechnology and Biomedical
Association.
<p>
   ``It was just a few years ago when very few people thought of a
research university as having any impact on pushing the economy
forward . . . they thought of the university as a place to get
qualified workers.
<p>
   ``We've made a lot of progress in the last few years in
recognizing how important research and development, and
university-based resarch, are in developing the economy,'' Ranken
said. ``If we continue (on that track), we'll keep making
progress.''
<p>
   According to Kathy Wilcox, president of the Washington Software
and Digital Media Alliance, the study also is of great value in
promoting Washington state elsewhere in the country.
<p>
   ``When we want to attract businesses . . . we have to get the
rest of the world to know what we have here,'' Wilcox said. The
study allows an ``apples and apples comparison'' that shows ``how
strong we are vis-a-vis other areas of the country.''
<p>
   It also provides ammunition in efforts to make sure legislators
understand the importance of technology-based industries to the
economy, she said.
<p>
   That, in turn, will aid efforts to make sure the state's
research institutions receive the support they need and that the
state's tax and regulatory environment is consistent and fair, she
said.
<p>
   ``It takes everyone,'' she said, ``to embrace that vision and
work cooperatively to make sure the stage is set to continue this
phenomenal growth.
<p>
   ``Absolutely everybody will benefit,'' not just those directly
employed, she said.
</TEXT>
