<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0601 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BUSINESS AT A GLANCE &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   COMPAQ EARNINGS RISE, GIVING SHARES A LIFT
<p>
   Compaq's earnings exceeded Wall Street estimates, and the
company's stock rose sharply. Compaq attributed the earnings gain
to greater sales in the more profitable parts of the company's
product line and to internal changes that have resulted in lower
costs and increased profit margins.
<p>
   CONRAIL, CSX AND NORFOLK MAY MEET
<p>
   In what may be a break in a three-month takeover struggle,
Conrail and its preferred suitor, CSX, said that they would be
willing to meet with the rival bidder, Norfolk Southern, to discuss
the battle.
<p>
   JURY DECIDES AGAINST ABC
<p>
   A jury ruled against ABC and two employees, awarding the Food
Lion supermarket chain more than $5.5 million in punitive damages
in a case that focused on the propriety of gathering TV news with
hidden cameras and undercover reporting.
<p>
   A STRONG QUARTER FOR BEAR STEARNS
<p>
   Quarterly earnings at Bear Stearns rose 68 percent, surpassing
analysts' forecasts, as they have at other investment banks. Dean
Witter reported strong profits, too.
<p>
   USAir PROFIT DOWN 55 PERCENT
<p>
   USAir said that earnings fell 55 percent in the fourth quarter
as it continued to struggle with rising costs.
<p>
   PERELMAN: RULING IS NO PROBLEM
<p>
   Ronald O. Perelman, who is seeking to maintain control of Marvel
Entertainment, suffered a setback when a judge rejected parts of a
borrowing agreement that Marvel had negotiated. But a spokesman for
Perelman said the ruling was not a problem because the judge had
indicated that she would approve alternate language in the
agreement that would amount to the same thing.
<p>
   BOND YIELD MOVES HIGHER
<p>
   Treasury prices fell, with the 30-year bond yield rising to 6.82
percent from 6.78.
<p>
   PHARMACIA STOCK: A BARGAIN?
<p>
   Most securities analysts were unhappy with Pharmacia &AMP;
Upjohn even before the surprise resignation this week of John
Zabriskie, the chief executive. But a few contrarians saw a
brighter side. The share price was already one of the cheapest in
the pharmaceutical sector, and after Zabriskie quit it got even
cheaper.
<p>
   BANK EMPLOYEES RELEASE PRESIDENT
<p>
   Employees protesting a government plan to cut jobs at Credit
Foncier de France released the bank's president and other
executives after six days. But labor organizers pledged to continue
occupying the Paris headquarters until the government scrapped
plans to eliminate the jobs.
<p>
   NEW AGENCY FOR ANTI-SMOKING PATCH
<p>
   Advertising account activity has been accelerating in the last
week. One big change involved a division of Johnson &AMP; Johnson,
which moved the account of the Nicotrol anti-smoking patch, with
billings estimated at $41 million, to the Health Care Connection
unit of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi Advertising in New York from DDB Needham
New York.
<p>
   Pizzeria Uno has conceded that advertisements for ``low-fat''
pizzas were misleading and has promised the FTC not to make such
claims again.
<p>
   NEW YORK CITY JOB GROWTH GAINS
<p>
   Last year, for the first time since 1980, New York City created
more jobs than its suburbs, breaking one of the trends of recent
economic development in America.
<p>
   A BIG DONOR'S ANONYMOUS GIVING
<p>
   Charles Feeney, the founder of the DFS Group chain of duty-free
shops, which was recently sold to LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton,
has secretly donated more than $600 million to hospitals,
universities and other beneficiaries over the last 15 years.
</TEXT>
