<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=kan-z> A9891 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CHIEFS-KAN </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0620 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CHIEFS-KAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; VERMEIL TARGETS THREE ON CHIEFS STAFF &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By KENT PULLIAM &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Kansas City Star &LR;  &QC;  KANSAS CITY, Mo.  &MD;  New St. Louis Rams
coach Dick Vermeil targeted three Chiefs staff members Wednesday as
potential additions to his staff.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   During a telephone news conference with reporters at the Super
Bowl, Vermeil said he would like to hire Lynn Stiles, the Chiefs'
vice president of player personnel, and talk with linebackers coach
John Bunting and former defensive-line coach Carl Hairston.
<p>
   Vermeil, who was officially hired Tuesday, indicated that Stiles
would be his top aide. He was less clear about the positions he
would talk to the two others about  &MD;  though Bunting could be a
candidate as the Rams' defensive coordinator.
<p>
   ``I have talked about bringing Lynn with me as an assistant to
me in my responsibilities,'' Vermeil said. ``I think he will be
coming. I think he is coming.''
<p>
   Carl Peterson, Chiefs president//general manager, said Vermeil
asked permission to talk with Stiles. Hairston was not going to be
retained on the Chiefs' staff. Chiefs Coach Marty Schottenheimer is
interested in retaining Bunting, but his contract expires in
February.
<p>
   ``He (Vermeil) is resurrecting the Philadelphia connection,''
Peterson said, laughing. ``He's moving fast.''
<p>
   Peterson said he would not like to lose Stiles because ``the guy
has the draft in his head right now.'' But if Vermeil offers Stiles
a position that entails more responsibilities than he currently
holds, the league would consider that an advancement, and even
though he is under contract for one more year, he could move.
<p>
   ``All that he (Vermeil) has done is ask for permission to talk
to the guy,'' Peterson said. ``Without any question losing him
before the draft would be difficult. But the other side of it is if
it is something more than a lateral move, you have to look at the
opportunity for career advancement potential for him.''
<p>
   Stiles, reached Wednesday at the Chiefs' offices, said he had
talked with Vermeil twice since Vermeil took the Rams' job. He said
both conversations were brief and more congratulatory in nature.
<p>
   ``My first and foremost obligation is to the Chiefs,'' Stiles
said. ``Unless Carl feels comfortable in me making a move, that's
where I am, and that's what I am.''
<p>
   Stiles was assistant head coach and defensive coordinator for
Vermeil at UCLA in 1974-75. After a two-year stint as head coach at
San Jose State, Stiles rejoined Vermeil with the Eagles as
administrative assistant with coaching responsibilities for the
tight ends and special teams in 1979.
<p>
   In 1982 Stiles became the Eagles' director of player personnel,
replacing Peterson.
<p>
   Like Stiles, Bunting and Hairston both have histories with
Vermeil with the Eagles. Bunting was a starting linebacker for the
Eagles when Vermeil arrived in 1976. Hairston was in Vermeil's
first Eagles draft class in 1976.
<p>
   Bunting is among the candidates Vermeil is considering as a
possible defensive coordinator. Some in the NFL believe Bunting has
head coaching potential.
<p>
   Former Saints coach Jim Mora declined an offer earlier this week
to be the Rams' defensive coordinator//assistant head coach. Mora
was a Rams head coaching candidate.
<p>
   Vermeil, who was in Philadelphia for the conference call, said
he would return to St. Louis today. He planned to interview several
members of the Rams' previous staff. He said he hoped to have his
whole staff in place by today or Friday.
<p>
   Vermeil already has hired Jerry Rhome as his offensive
coordinator, Dick Coury as his receivers coach and Frank Gansz, a
former Chiefs head coach, as his special-teams coach.
</TEXT>
