<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2147EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0791 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9895 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-MALL-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0769 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NJ-MALL-SHOPPING-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: N.Y.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TOWNS COLUMN: TAX-FREE DAYS AREN'T CLOSING THE BORDER &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; By EVELYN NIEVES &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J.  &MD;  Let the record show that in the middle of
New York's tax-free shopping week, even as Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
was urging all good citizens of the metropolis to ``send a message
to Albany'' and shop like they've never shopped before, Myra O.
Sugarman and Dot Singer, Manhattanites both, were deep in the racks
of Anne Klein separates at Filene's Basement in the Newport Center
Mall, which is to say, in New Jersey.
<p>
   ``Oh, so what?'' Ms. Sugarman said. She was nearly embedded in a
crush of blue knit jackets as she struggled vainly to find a size
10 petite.
<p>
   ``Yeah, whaddatheygonnado?'' Ms. Singer said. ``Arrest us?''
<p>
   You never know, considering that the city has added the crime of
taking up more than one seat on the subway to its list of
quality-of-life offenses. (By law, New Yorkers who shop out of
state and bring the goods back home are supposed to pay New York
the difference in sales tax.) And the police would meet their
entire month's quota for quality-of-life tickets if they fined
people for skewing the state's experiment in tax-free clothes
shopping.
<p>
   For here at Newport Center, a Garden State-variety mall by the
Holland Tunnel, Ms. Sugarman and Ms. Singer were far from the only
New Yorkers shopping this crucial week when New York City wants to
show Albany that dropping the sales tax would keep shoppers from
straying across the border. At least the women had an excuse: They
were visiting a friend in the Jersey City Financial Center and had
stopped at the mall on the way home.
<p>
   Doug T. Walker, who lives in New York City's East Village, was
discovered looking at one-pocket T-shirts at the mall Gap. Yes, he
said, sheepishly, there is a Gap around the corner from his
apartment. ``I was just looking,'' he said, gingerly fingering a
black leather belt. He had popped in as he waited to meet his
brother, who lives in Jersey City, he said.
<p>
   ``I came to help buy a 40th-anniversary present for my
parents,'' he said. ``How's that for an excuse?''
<p>
   Better than others. Newport Center, about a 15-minute ride from
Manhattan on the PATH train, counts 25 percent of its customers
from New York City at any given time. (Except Christmas, when cars
pouring in from the Holland Tunnel jam the mall parking garages for
hours.) The lack of a sales tax on clothes and shoes, and only a 3
percent sales tax on other items is the major reason New Yorkers
say they come here. But getting relief from that 8.25 percent tax
hasn't kept these New Yorkers home. The percentage of New Yorkers
at Newport Center remained steady over the weekend, when the mall
had a ``sidewalk sale.''
<p>
   Some stores posted double-digit gains in sales over the same
week last year, said Sarah Liddle, the Newport Center marketing
director. ``It seems the tax-free week hasn't affected us,'' she
said. ``Some of the stores reporting great weekends are apparel
related.''
<p>
   What this says about New York's tax-free shopping experiment is
anyone's guess, especially since Giuliani is crowing over a
shopping frenzy he says has far exceeded expectations.
<p>
   But perhaps for those New Yorkers who have gotten into the mall
habit, the lack of a tax on clothing just can't compete with the
lulling comfort of a climate-controlled Main Street where no one
bumps into you. Especially when Stern's has a sale.
<p>
   ``I find it easy to come here,'' said Sylvia Barash, who lives
in New York City's Greenwich Village. She has taken the PATH to
Newport about half a dozen times, and as an older person she
considers the trip a risk-free adventure in no-pressure shopping.
``It's safe, I think, and pleasant.''
<p>
   Newport Center is an Everymall. It is neither fancy nor
downscale. (The anchors are Stern's, Sears and JC Penney.) It is
neither small nor enormous. (You can walk from one end to the other
in a few minutes, if you don't stop.) It is, in other words, easy
to handle. Which makes it precisely the kind of place New York
business owners worry about.
<p>
   ``There's an advantage to shopping like this, or else why would
so many people do it?'' said Ms. Sugarman, who grew up in Manhattan
(``a long time ago'') and has never lived anywhere else for very
long. ``I like malls. I used to shop Herald Square. Now it's for
the birds. Too crowded.''
<p>
   By the way, she added: ``Put this down: If the tax gets cut,
what are we going to have to do to make up the difference?''
<p>
   ``You got to pay the piper somehow.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2147EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0792 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9896 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DAMATO-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0932 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-DAMATO-LEGIS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; D'AMATO GOES TO ALBANY AND A LAW IS BORN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ALBANY, N.Y.  &MD;  Of all the politicians involved in arranging the
agreement last week to pass legislation providing women longer
hospital stays after mastectomies, the lawmaker most responsible is
a man who has no official role in the state government and in fact
rarely ventures this far north: U.S. Sen. Alfonse D'Amato.
<p>
   By all accounts, New York's junior U.S. senator persuaded
legislative leaders from both parties to work out a deal, providing
yet another example of how D'Amato uses his influence over the
state's political leaders to push issues important to him through
the Legislature.
<p>
   D'Amato's attention to this back-home legislation came as
surveys suggested that his popularity is sagging, particularly
among women. A recent poll found that his approval rating was 41
percent among men and 25 percent among women.
<p>
   Here in Albany, lawmakers in both parties said they thought they
would have passed a mastectomy bill this year, even if D'Amato had
not got involved. But by prodding them along early this month, he
made sure that he would get some of the credit for brokering a deal
on an issue that is of great importance to women, particularly on
Long Island, his political base.
<p>
   The rate of breast cancer on Long Island is among the highest in
the country. That has spawned an emotional debate over whether the
cause of the disease there could be traced to some problem in the
soil, water or air. The high incidence of breast cancer has also
led survivors to organize powerful groups intended to force elected
officials to take action.
<p>
   D'Amato and his aides wasted little time arranging a news
conference last Thursday at which he appeared with Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver, a Democrat, and Senate majority leader Joseph
Bruno, a Republican, to announce that the state's leaders had
agreed on a mastectomy bill.
<p>
   The D'Amato camp handled virtually all the details for the
event. They chose the the date and the site. They drew up a guest
list that included a host of women's groups, several from Long
Island. They issued the press releases announcing the agreement on
D'Amato's Senate letterhead.
<p>
   ``They handled the whole bit,'' said Patricia Lynch, a
spokeswoman for Silver, who is usually in charge of arranging the
speaker's public appearances. ``I think that it was very unique.
But the speaker felt the issue was very important, and that it was
time to put aside partisan differences.''
<p>
   This is not the first time that D'Amato has seized on an issue
in Albany to promote his own political fortunes or those of the
state Republican Party.
<p>
   Last year, the Legislature unanimously approved a bill to set up
a registry to track the use of pesticides, acting only after
D'Amato used his influence to persuade Republican state senators to
support the measure.
<p>
   The registry is intended to help scientists establish links
between pesticides and disease, a major issue on Long Island.
Women's groups like the Huntington Breast Cancer Action Coalition
and 1 in 9 have speculated that extensive spraying of agricultural
chemicals might be a factor in the high rates of breast cancer.
<p>
   But until D'Amato intervened, the Republicans who control the
Senate opposed the registry. They faced pressure from agricultural
lobbyists, who feared that people with cancer and other diseases
would use the information to sue farmers.
<p>
   ``I think he's trying to address not only a low approval rating
but also a wide gender gap,'' said Lee Miringoff, the director of
the Marist Institute for Public Opinion in Poughkeepsie. ``And he's
using his old formula of being a go-to guy who gets things
accomplished. He's getting back to his role as Senator Pothole,
which he has been drifting away from.''
<p>
   But D'Amato's attempts to latch onto popular state issues have
sometimes backfired. Last year, he upset environmentalists and
aides to Gov. George Pataki, his political protege, last year when
he began running television ads featuring himself as a spokesman
for a $1.7 billion bond act to clean up the environment, which the
governor proposed.
<p>
   Many of the bond act's supporters complained that D'Amato's
unpopularity among voters would end up hurting the measure's
chances of approval. In the end, though, voters approved it
overwhelmingly.
<p>
   D'Amato's latest foray into Albany politics started nearly two
weeks ago, when by his own account he phoned Silver and Bruno to
propose a bill that would allow mastectomy patients to stay in the
hospital as long as they and their doctors felt was necessary.
<p>
   D'Amato said he decided to approach legislative leaders here
because he believed that a similar bill he proposed in Washington
would take months to pass. As he recalled it, it didn't take much
persuading to get Bruno and Silver on board. ``They said,
`terrific,' '' he recalled.
<p>
   Then, a D'Amato aide came to Albany to help leaders hammer out
the details of the legislation. The agreement was worked out in
about 10 days, giving potential opponents little time to mobilize a
lobbying campaign.
<p>
   With that done, D'Amato's public relations operation went to
work, issuing a press release on the day of the news conference. In
it, Silver and Bruno thanked the senator for his role. ``I salute
Senator D'Amato for his leadership on this issue,'' Bruno said.
<p>
   Silver provided a slight variation, saying: ``I want to thank
Senator D'Amato for his leadership on this important issue.''
</TEXT>
