<SLUG> BC-CIGNA-SETTLEMENT-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0425 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CIGNA-SETTLEMENT-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CIGNA SETTLEMENT WITH POLICYHOLDERS APPROVED BY U.S. JUDGE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Ted Hampton &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Los Angeles, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- A U.S. judge approved a
settlement in a class-action lawsuit against Connecticut General
Life Insurance, a unit of the Philadelphia-based insurer Cigna
Corp., lawyers for policyholders said.
<p>
   Federal District Court Judge Harry L. Hupp in Los Angeles
approved the settlement on Jan. 13. Plaintiffs claimed the insurer
overcharged and misled them in sales of insurance policies. Cigna
didn't admit wrongdoing in the settlement. A lawyer for the
plaintiffs and a representative of the company disagreed on how
much the settlement could cost. Cigna said it expects to pay out a
maximum of $35 million.
<p>
   Mark Rifkin, an Ardmore, Pennsylvania, attorney representing
plaintiffs, said Cigna could be forced to pay $200 million or more.
``There is absolutely no upward limit to what this could cost the
company,'' he said.
<p>
   ``Any settlement amount at this point is purely speculative,''
because plaintiffs are only now beginning to file for claims under
a dispute-resolution process set up by the settlement, said Cigna
spokesman Ken Ferraro.
<p>
   ``This will not have a material effect on earnings of Cigna or
the earnings of Connecticut General,'' Ferraro said. Cigna stock
closed up 1 5/8 at an a record 151 5/8 in trading of 243,000
shares.
<p>
   Policyholders, beneficiaries and those who paid for coverage
will have until July 12 to submit claims. Most won't receive a cash
settlement, Ferraro said. ``For the vast majority of the people,
we're making a slight adjustment over the lifetime of the policy,''
he said.
<p>
   The case is the result of two lawsuits, one charging that
Connecticut General agents misled customers by promising premiums
would vanish after a certain term and accusing the company of
trying to pass on to policyholders the effects of a 1990 U.S. tax
increase.
<p>
   The settlement on charges of misleading customers will likely
cost the company more per claim than the tax part of the case,
albeit for far fewer claims, Ferraro said.
<p>
   Claims involving the tax, known as the deferred acquisition tax,
will probably account for between two-thirds and three-quarters of
the potential claims in the combined class action lawsuit, Ferraro
said. Costs of compensating such customers will be lower, Ferraro
added.
<p>
   Lawyers for the plaintiffs estimated there could be as many as
128,000 individual claims.
</TEXT>
