<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=tdt-z> A9898 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PIZZA-LOWFAT-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0720 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PIZZA-LOW FAT-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNO NO LONGER HAS `LOW-FAT' PIZZA &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BRUCE MOHL  &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Some are pretty low in fat, some aren't  &MD;  but Pizzeria Uno will
not promote its Thinzettas line of pizzas as ``low-fat'' under an
agreement reached with the Federal Trade Commission Wednesday.
<p>
   The seven-inch, thin-crust pizzas range from relatively lean
vegetarian versions to pepperoni-and-cheese extravaganzas, but most
of them, said the government, had far more fat than the law allows
in a food calling itself low-fat.
<p>
   The FTC concluded the Boston-based chain of 155 restaurants
misled customers two years ago when it ran a two-week print and
television advertising campaign in which the Thinzettas were called
``low-fat.''
<p>
   The settlement doesn't mean that you can't enjoy pizza  &MD;  just
that it's hard to make pizzas that meet the very strict federal
definition of low-fat, with less than 3 grams of fat in a 100-gram
serving (about 3 1/2 ounces).
<p>
   David Schardt, an associate nutritionist with the Center for
Science in the Public Interest in Washington, said most pizzas with
real cheese would flunk the test. But he said that doesn't mean one
or two slices of pizza can't be a healthful meal.
<p>
   Most Americans, though, boost the fat content by piling on meat
toppings and extra cheese, as well as eating too many slices,
Schardt said.
<p>
   The FTC said Wednesday's settlement, which involved no fines or
other disciplinary actions, was its first enforcement action
involving false nutrient claims by a restaurant chain.
<p>
   ``Whether selecting low-fat foods at the grocery store or
restaurants, consumers expect nutrient content claims for products
to be true,'' said Jodie Bernstein, director of the FTC's bureau of
consumer protection.
<p>
   Uno Restaurant Corp. president and chief executive officer Craig
Miller said the ads ran for only a two-week period and did not mean
to imply that all eight Thinzettas pizzas were low fat.
Nevertheless, Miller said, the wording was not as precise as it
should have been.
<p>
   ``We don't fully agree with them, but we weren't going to fight
the FTC,'' Miller said. ``I didn't want to end up in court with
them.''
<p>
   To be labeled low-fat, a food must contain 3 grams or less of
fat per serving or, in the case of a meal-size serving like a
personal pizza, 3 grams of fat or less per 100 grams of food.
<p>
   John T. Dugan, an FTC staff attorney in Boston, said six of the
eight Thinzettas personal pizzas marketed as ``low-fat'' by
Pizzeria Uno contained well in excess of the meal-size standard.
<p>
   Dugan said the terms of the FTC settlement with Pizzeria Uno
prohibited him from discussing the actual fat content or the
ingredients of the Thinzetta pizzas.
<p>
   Miller said Uno's vegetarian-style and barbecue chicken
Thinzettas pizza did qualify as low fat under the federal
definition, but other thin-crust pies with pepperoni, sausage and
cheese did not meet the standard.
<p>
   Miller declined to release information on the fat content of the
Thinzettas pizzas or the chain's more popular deep-dish
Chicago-style pizza, although the fat content of the deep-dish
pizzas sold in supermarkets is listed on the package.
<p>
   Federal dietary guidelines recommend a daily intake of less than
65 grams of fat for someone on a 2,000-calorie diet. The Uno
deep-dish pizza sold in supermarkets contains 15 grams of fat per
4.6-ounce serving, and a single pizza contains five servings.
<p>
   The deep-dish pizza has a buttery crust and uses part-skim
low-moisture mozzarella cheese. By contrast, the thin-crust pizza
uses a fat-free dough and a cheese topping that is 25 percent
part-skim mozzarella and 75 percent mozzarella that is 99 percent
fat free, Miller said.
<p>
   Miller said the Thinzettas pizzas were originally developed to
cater to customers concerned about fat levels. After the FTC raised
questions about the low-fat claims, Miller said all the low-fat
references in the restaurant chain's menu were deleted and no new
ads were run.
<p>
   Starting in May, regulations issued by the US Food and Drug
Administration will require restaurants to disclose nutrient
information in their menus.
<p>
   The FTC settlement agreement with Uno will not take effect until
a 60-day comment period expires.
</TEXT>
