<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0797 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=kan-z> A9902 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-KAN </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0823 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PATRIOTS-KAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NORBORNE, MO., IS SUPER PROUD OF PATRIOTS' MAX LANE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL CORO &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Kansas City Star &LR;  &QC;  NORBORNE, Mo.  &MD;  Head down this town's
main drag, a two-block stretch of bricks called the Business
District, at 85 mph in a neon-pink school bus, and maybe nobody
would notice.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   On a Wednesday morning in Norborne, leafless branches and dead
blades of grass are stirring more than the natives. City Hall and
the public library, housed together in a building smaller than a
QuikTrip, are closed. The lights are off.
<p>
   Only inside Norborne's walls can an outsider discover what a
proud week this is for the 856 people who call this patch of flood
plain home. Their favorite son, Max Lane, will play in Super Bowl
XXXI on Sunday.
<p>
   Most people in the town are more tickled that Lane, New
England's starting right tackle, will play in the Super Bowl than
if the Chiefs had made it. Even Mrs. Whitaker's first-grade class
can rattle off who Lane is, what team he plays for and what number
he wears. And most of the youngsters were not born when Lane donned
the Norborne Pirates' black and gold.
<p>
   Felicia Woods, 8, included a brazen Super Bowl prediction with a
good-luck letter for Lane: ``Max 10, Green Bay 1.''
<p>
   Super Bowl Sunday will be this town's biggest day since the
Soybean Festival in August but probably not bigger. After all, this
is the self-proclaimed ``soybean capital of the world.''
<p>
   ``I'm coming to that Soybean Festival,'' Patriots running back
Dave Meggett said to Lane's parents, Ezell and Lucille, at a game
this year.
<p>
   If Lane, a 1989 graduate of Norborne, had not pulled off a rare
Missouri 1A to Division I football transition and got drafted out
of Navy in the sixth round by New England in 1994, he could have
joined a couple of former Norborne linemen over at Norborne's only
grain elevator.
<p>
   ``He had more initiative and go than anybody I've ever known,''
said Wade Martensmayer, who had just been having a conversation
with Ray Carroll Co. Grain Growers co-workers about how the Navy
must have taken the clumsy out of Lane.
<p>
   Few thought Lane could play college football someday, let alone
start in the NFL. He did well to walk.
<p>
   ``I mean this in a nice way, but he was kind of like a little
puppy that has big feet and hasn't grown into them yet,'' said Ruth
Johnson, the elementary-school secretary. ``He took a lot of
teasing.''
<p>
   He was a head taller than his classmates in junior high and
ever-expanding from that 11-pound, 6-ounce birth weight. Now he's 6
feet 6 and 295 pounds.
<p>
   ``He was our human disposal,'' school cook Marian Kimbrough
said. ``He'd eat all the food the other kids wouldn't.''
<p>
   But dorky size turned into football size, and Lane became the
star of fall Friday nights. In a senior class of 22, Lane was voted
most popular, most likely to succeed, most athletic, hardest
worker, most outgoing, most talented, best personality, best
leader, friendliest and most enthusiastic. Perhaps most daring,
too, for that water-skiing stunt behind a car down the roadside
water pits of Missouri 10.
<p>
   And nothing has changed. Lane is still all that to his hometown
folk, who flock to him for autographs and memories when he comes
home three times a year. He's the same aw-shucks good ol' boy the
Patriots call ``Big Country.''
<p>
   A member of the church choir, he was so tender-hearted that he
was afraid to play football out of fear he would hurt somebody. Yet
when he fell on the stairs in grade school and cut his chin, he
told a teacher, ``I'm OK, it just makes me tougher,'' with tears
rolling down his cheeks.
<p>
   Many residents are planning parties, like the one at the Pine
Street Pub and Laundry, but Norborne's proudest couple is New
Orleans-bound with three of Lane's four siblings. Sister Beth has
to stay home in Augusta, Ga., because she may have a baby just as
Lane is pancaking Reggie White.
<p>
   ``It's pretty exciting to go,'' said Ezell, a retired oil
distributor in a Patriots sweatshirt. ``It's something you don't
expect coming from a small town. You don't have these kinds of
aspirations. There's a small-town syndrome to get over, but he's
pretty determined when it comes to football.
<p>
   ``It hasn't changed him. This is a community where you grow up
and nobody is better than the next person.''
<p>
   Straight across Fifth Street from the Lanes is Kenneth Weymeyer
Field, where Lane was a two-time all-state player. Lucille, whose
family stretches four generations in Norborne, never saw beyond
that humble environment.
<p>
   Now every Sunday, the Lanes fire up the satellite and hustle out
of church clothes to watch the Patriots. They watch it again on
tape to focus on Max, giving them banter for when he calls four
times a week.
<p>
   ``We just thought it was wonderful to see him on TV playing the
Army-Navy game,'' Lucille said. ``I never thought it would go any
farther.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2151EST
</TRAILER>
