<DOCID> nyt970122.0798 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=k pri=u sel=taf-z> A9903 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0456 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EDIT-FUNDRAISING-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EDITORIAL: TOO TIMID TO LEAD &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Jan. 23:
<p>
   Vice President Al Gore, whose Buddhist-temple fund-raiser has
become a national joke, is reported to fear that former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey could win the Democratic presidential
nomination next time by running on a pledge to clean up campaign
finance. That raises the question why Gore does not talk President
Clinton into protecting him by building a strong record on this
issue. Yet Clinton just cannot bring himself to step forward as a
bold leader determined to drive dirty money out of campaigns and to
give up unconditionally the soft money that corporations and
wealthy favor-seekers pump into the national committees of the two
major parties.
<p>
   In place of comprehensive, unilateral reform, Clinton and
officials of the Democratic National Committee have announced some
modest curbs on fund-raising. In a teary voice, the retiring
committee chairman, Don Fowler, said that ``we made mistakes'' in
lapping up millions from foreign contributors. Clinton then said
the committee would not take any more money from citizens of other
nations, a prudent step considering that his campaign fund-raising
is currently under Justice Department investigation.
<p>
   But the president made even this bit of housekeeping seem
grudging by complaining that Democrats take ``all the heat'' for
unseemly fund-raising while Republicans, who ``raise more money in
big contributions,'' get ``a free ride.''
<p>
   Republicans, of course, have not escaped criticism. But it was
not they who were marching Asian contributors through the Oval
Office or who pioneered the artful bending of campaign law to
finance attack ads with soft-money contributions.
<p>
   Clinton announced that the Democrats were going to cut their
soft-money dosage to $100,000 a year from one source. But loopholes
in the self-imposed restriction may mean little real financial loss
for the party. Why not do the right thing and voluntarily forswear
all soft-money donations to the committee? Clinton said he was
ready to give up soft money if the Republicans would do the same.
That is an embarrassing definition of presidential leadership to
come only one day after an inaugural address.
<p>
   Clinton also asked the Republicans to help pass campaign-reform
legislation before the opportunity created by public disgust with
both parties fades away. ``Delay will mean the death of reform one
more time,'' he said, and on that point at least he spoke with real
authority. In the spring of 1993, he and House Speaker Tom Foley
delayed campaign finance legislation, and sure enough, it died.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2152EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0799 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=kan-z> A9904 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERBACKS-KAN </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0856 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SUPER BACKS-KAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BACKS TAKE BACK SEAT ON SUPER BOWL TEAMS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JONATHAN RAND &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Kansas City Star &LR;  &QC;  NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  Only six running backs
have been voted most valuable player of a Super Bowl. Chances are
there won't be a seventh come Sunday.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   For just the second time in seven years, likely Hall of Fame
backs Emmitt Smith or Thurman Thomas won't be in the Super Bowl.
New England's Curtis Martin and Green Bay's Dorsey Levens and Edgar
Bennett will.
<p>
   These backs are secrets almost as well kept as their teams' game
plans, though in the playoffs they've all made a good case for more
work.
<p>
   The Packers' de-emphasis of their backs would make Vince
Lombardi turn over in his grave. You'd think the Patriots'
commitment to the passing game would appall Bill Parcells, except
that he coaches them.
<p>
   The Packers threw 83 times more than they ran in the regular
season and would have run less except they usually had leads to
protect. The Patriots threw 201 more times than they passed and
couldn't have run much less.
<p>
   Parcells once upon a time took the air out of the ball. His New
York Giants ran 39 times and helped control the ball 40 minutes, 33
seconds in a 20-19 Super Bowl victory over the Buffalo Bills six
years ago. Now Parcells puts helium in the ball.
<p>
   ``I wouldn't say neither team can run,'' Parcells said.
<p>
   ``I just think the weapons available have convinced both
coaching staffs that the expedient thing to do sometimes is throw.
I think both will try to use some patterns that in some respects
are similar to a first-down run  &MD;  a short, quick type of thing.''
<p>
   The Packers' commitment to passing is understandable. Coach Mike
Holmgren is a disciple of former 49ers coach Bill Walsh's
ball-control passing, and none of his runners appears to be a
franchise back. But Parcells won two Super Bowls preaching power
football, and Curtis Martin as a rookie gained 1,487 yards in 1995.
He dropped to 1,152 in '96.
<p>
   ``Last year we ran the ball so much, and we were 6-10,'' Martin
pointed out.
<p>
   ``You figure it out right there. I would rather be in this
position than gain 1,500 yards and lose.''
<p>
   This sounds all backwards for the NFL. It's more typical that
high-powered passing teams  &MD;  except, of course, the 49ers  &MD;  can't
become Super Bowl contenders until they learn to run. The
Jacksonville Jaguars, for instance, didn't mount a playoff drive
until Natrone Means' power running began to take some pressure off
Mark Brunell's throwing.
<p>
   But neither Super Bowl team wants to take much pressure off its
quarterback. Green Bay's Brett Favre and New England's Drew Bledsoe
barely take a deep breath to reload.
<p>
   ``Curtis has had a couple of great seasons, and I wouldn't
compare our running game to theirs,'' Levens said. ``But he's in
the same situation as we are because of Bledsoe.''
<p>
   Martin has two 1,000-yard seasons to prove he really can run
when necessary, but Levens and Bennett have mainly a stack of
newspaper clippings claiming what mediocre backs they are.
Actually, Bennett gained 899 regular-season yards and Levens 566,
and each caught 31 passes.
<p>
   ``At the beginning of the year, they said the weak link of the
Packers was the running backs  &MD;  that's why they're not going to the
Super Bowl,'' said Bennett, the starting halfback.
<p>
   ``That was motivation for us the entire season. We wanted to go
out and prove something, and I think we did.''
<p>
   Levens, a fullback who is also used in single-back sets, said:
``I've heard the reason Brett got the MVP (in 1995) was because we
didn't have a running game and he had to do it all by himself. So I
think we tried to prove to everybody that our running backs can
produce.''
<p>
   Packer backs became so desperate for recognition that William
Henderson, the blocking fullback, tried to find a nickname for him,
Levens, Bennett and halfback Travis Jervey.
<p>
   ``William came up with `The Four Horsemen,' '' Levens said,
grinning.
<p>
   ``I don't know if that's going to take off. I think he needs a
marketing assistant.''
<p>
   The best possible marketing for Packers backs has been their
playoff performances. Bennett has rushed for 179 yards and three
touchdowns. Levens has rushed for 134 yards and been the team's top
receiver with seven catches for 133 yards and a touchdown.
<p>
   ``Contrary to what people may believe, I'm not this crazy mad
bomber passing,'' Holmgren said.
<p>
   ``I would like to have a balanced attack and think we have
gotten better the last six weeks at running the ball. Part of that
was the elements. We played a couple of (playoff) games in Green
Bay where it was difficult to throw, and it forced me to call more
runs than maybe I normally would. I would like that to come into
play Sunday, no doubt about that.''
<p>
   Martin, too, has been hot in the playoffs, rushing for 225 yards
and four touchdowns. So could this Super Bowl, though played at
room temperature and on a carpet, showcase the running backs after
all?
<p>
   ``I doubt it,'' Levens said, grinning.
<p>
   ``If Brett's hot and we run the ball 20 times, it would be a
miracle.''
</TEXT>
