<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BONDS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0433 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-JAPAN-BONDS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JAPANESE BONDS FALL AS DOLLAR REACHES 47-MONTH HIGH VERSUS YEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Mark Tannenbaum &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Tokyo, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- Japanese bonds fell as the dollar
rose to a 47-month high versus the yen, further dimming the allure
of yen-denominated assets.
<p>
   The dollar reached as high as 119.32 yen this morning, pushed
higher by U.S. economic strength and confidence other leading
industrial nations won't attempt to block its rise. The dollar last
traded for 119.12 yen.
<p>
   Although the strengthening dollar and rebounding Tokyo stocks
are preventing domestic bonds from rising above recent highs, the
basic trend for bond prices is still up, said Peter Morgan, senior
portfolio manager at Banque Nationale de Paris.
<p>
   ``The bond market is in good shape,'' he said. ``I think that
most domestic market participants are quite constructive'' amid
confidence domestic interest rates will remain low until the
economy's back on track.
<p>
   The lead bond futures contract for March delivery fell 0.22 yen
to 126 yen. The yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year government
bond rose 1.5 basis points to 2.405 percent.
<p>
   The lead futures contract rose as high as 126.34 yen this
morning. Highs for the previous three days were 126.35 yen, 126.38
yen and 126.32 yen, respectively.
<p>
   Prices could fall further by week's end if the contract's
inability to rise through those levels persuades traders to sell
the contract short, Morgan said.
<p>
   The record high for the March contract is 126.55 yen, set on
Dec. 3. For a lead contract, the record high is 126.58 yen, set by
the December contract.
<p>
   Traders and analysts had mixed opinions of how Tokyo share
movements were affecting bonds.
<p>
   This morning, the Nikkei 225 benchmark stock index ended up 6.28
yen, or 0.03 percent, to 18,020.16 as electronics shares rose on
the stronger dollar.
<p>
   Shunji Sakami, chief strategist at LTCB Securities Co., said the
impact of the dollar's gains against the yen could be mitigated as
stocks stabilize.
<p>
   ``If confidence sets in that stocks won't fall much further
through the end of the fiscal year, concern over the need to lock
in returns from bonds will ease,'' he said. Japan's fiscal year
ends March 31.
<p>
   Takeshi Naito, assistant general manager of bond analysis at
Daiwa Securities Co., said that while concern remains that
investors could sell bonds to offset losses in equities, many
financial institutions had probably done so earlier this month,
when the Nikkei 225 sank toward 17,000 yen.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2157EST
</TRAILER>
