<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=tdt-z> A9909 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-GROSSMAN'S-LIQUIDITY- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0463 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-GROSSMAN'S-LIQUIDITY-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GROSSMAN'S SAYS IT MAY SEEK CHAPTER 11 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By CHARLES STEIN &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Grossman's Inc., which has been losing ground to the home
improvement chains for years, Wednesday said it might seek Chapter
11 bankruptcy protection.
<p>
   The Canton, Mass. company said it was experiencing a ``severe
liquidity shortage'' in its Contractors' Warehouse operations, a
group of stores it owns in the Midwest and Far West. A group of
stores that operates in the Northeast, called Mr. 2nd's Bargain
Outlet, is doing somewhat better, according to the company.
<p>
   ``We will make a quick decision on this matter,'' said Steven
Shapiro, a vice president at Grossman's. With the threat of
bankruptcy hanging over the company, vendors could refuse to ship
goods to the stores, say retail analysts.
<p>
   Grossman's operates 10 Mr. 2nd's Bargain Outlet stores in
Massachusetts. The company estimates it has about 150 employees in
the state.
<p>
   Wednesday's news did not come as a great surprise to Wall
Street, which has all but abandoned hope for Grossman's. The
company's stock fell 1/64 to close at 17/64. The stock has been
falling steadily for several days, apparently in anticipation of
bad news.
<p>
   Founded in Quincy, Mass. as a junk business by Louis Grossman
more than 100 years ago, the company reached its peak in 1983 when
it operated 345 stores across the country and its orange delivery
trucks were a familiar part of the landscape.
<p>
   But Grossman's was unprepared to compete with budding national
chains such as Home Depot, which supplied many of the same products
at lower prices.
<p>
   Last March, the company bit the bullet and closed its remaining
60 retail lumber outlets, a move that eliminated 1,600 jobs,
including 500 in Massachusetts. But the parent company continued to
operate the Contractors' Warehouse and Mr. 2nd's chains. As
recently as October, chief executive Robert Swanson sounded upbeat
about the company's chances. ``I am confident that with the
experienced professionals we have, we will keep the company on the
right track,'' he said.
<p>
   That forecast proved too optimistic. Sales have been falling at
Contractors' Warehouse stores. Those stores are responsible for the
bulk of Grossman's sales. More importantly, they were supposed to
be the company's future. ``We expected most of our future growth to
come from them,'' said Shapiro.
<p>
   Grossman's Wednesday said its December comparable store sales
were 4 percent below the levels achieved in December 1995.
Comparable store sales were up 4.7 percent at the 26 stores it
operates in the Northeast.
<p>
   In the 1996's third quarter, Grossman's earned a profit of $1.4
million on sales of $96 million.
</TEXT>
