<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Two days after a 2-year-old Brooklyn boy died with a
blood-alcohol level twice the legal limit defining drunkenness,
city medical examiners began a series of toxicological tests
Wednesday to see if the toddler was killed by alcohol poisoning.
<p>
   The boy, Melquen Blue, was brought to Long Island College
Hospital early Monday morning by his mother, Tarkisha Blue, who
told doctors there that he had fallen out of bed, police said.
Melquen was pronounced dead at 2:15 a.m.
<p>
   His blood alcohol level at death was .27 percent, a worker at
the city's Administration for Children's Services said.
