<SLUG> BC-EARNS-NATIONAL-AUSTRA </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0588 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EARNS-NATIONAL-AUSTRALIA-UPDATE3-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NATIONAL AUSTRALIA BANK 1ST-QTR PROFIT ROSE 13.5% (UPDATE3) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Emma Moody &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Updates with comments from Managing Director Don Argus on
cost-to-income ratios, U.S. bank prices, interest margins and Asian
alliances in second section)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Melbourne, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- National Australia Bank Ltd.
said its net profit rose 13.5 percent to A$582 million (US$451
million) in its first quarter ended Dec. 31.
<p>
   The bank, Australia's most profitable, said revenue rose 8.8
percent to A$3.98 billion.
<p>
   Earnings per share rose 9.7 percent to 39.4 Australian cents.
<p>
   ``Earnings growth was achieved by a combination of cost
containment, strong credit management'' and marketing, said
Managing Director Don Argus.
<p>
   ``The group benefited from continued strength in the performance
of its banking operations in New Zealand, the U.S., the United
Kingdom and the Republic of Ireland.''
<p>
   Apart from its Australian operations, National Australia Bank
owns Bank of New Zealand and controls Scotland's Clydesdale and
Yorkshire banks in England and National Irish Bank in Ireland. It
also owns U.S. regional bank Michigan National Corp.
<p>
   Chairman Bill Irvine said the bank's international spread of
assets puts it in a strong position to ``weather to slow-down'' in
Australian economic activity.
<p>
   ``The Republic of Ireland continues to experience very rapid
growth,'' Chairman Bill Irvine said.
<p>
   ``It now appears that a significant economic upturn is also
under way in the United Kingdom.''
<p>
   Irvine said the economy in Michigan is experiencing ``very
buoyant economic conditions, with record industrial production and
low levels of unemployment.''
<p>
   ``Against that, the New Zealand and Australian economies
continue to experience more difficult and patchy conditions.''
<p>
   National Australia reported a 6.8 percent rise in net profit to
A$2.1 billion in the year ended Sept. 30, 1996. The growth was
driven by the bank's offshore operations.
<p>
   Earning from the Australian operations in the year rose 0.1
percent.
<p>
   Irvine said the bank is seeking additional growth through
``prudent'' acquisitions.
<p>
   ``In the case of the National, our choice is clear,'' Irvine
said. ``We believe it is important to have a spread of assets in
terms of business and geographic locations.''
<p>
   Argus said National Australia bank is seeking alliances with
banks, insurers or other financial institutions in Asia.
<p>
   He said, though, the bank doesn't expect to seek an acquisition
in the U.S. as current bank prices are ``too hot to buy anything.''
<p>
   In the quarter, the bank said non-interest income rose 19.2
percent to A$813 million, group assets rose 11.6 percent to A$184
billion, the bad-debt charge fell 32.8 percent to A$39 million,
while group deposits rose 11.2 percent to A$119.4 billion and its
cost-to-income ratio fell to 53.3 percent from 54.9 percent in the
year-earlier quarter.
<p>
   Argus said the bank intends to reduce the cost ratio further in
the next few years. It is targeting close to 40 percent by 2000, he
said.
<p>
   The National Australia Bank said, though, its interest rate
margins remain under pressure.
<p>
   ``Margins are going to continue to be under pressure,'' Argus
said. ``We are in a competitive game -- I would expect that they
will contract a little bit more yet,'' he said.
<p>
   The company's shares were recently 9 cents higher at A$15.10.
lhH/]w~N{6x7aIizw
</TEXT>
