<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9917 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0480 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-SALES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IN ALBANY, APPROVAL BUT NO ACTION ON ENDING TAX ON CLOTHING &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ALBANY, N.Y.  &MD;  State lawmakers and their aides cautioned
Wednesday against drawing strong conclusions from a sudden apparent
consensus between Gov. George Pataki and the leaders of the
Legislature that the sales tax on most clothing should be
eliminated.
<p>
   Officials noted that the governor and Republican legislators
have made property-tax relief their first priority this year. They
questioned whether the state could take on that expense and absorb
the loss of sales-tax revenue as well.
<p>
   Change in the sales tax has not been a subject of discussion
among Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, a Democrat, and Pataki and
Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, both Republicans. All three
did speak well of the idea on Tuesday when talking to reporters.
Pataki and Bruno offered vaguely supportive statements. But Silver
has long backed eliminating the tax on clothing.
<p>
   The sudden focus on the issue results from the state's
experiment this week with suspending the tax. Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani went to Albany on Tuesday to address legislators about
what the city wants from the state, a closely watched annual event,
and his first request was that the sales tax be ended permanently
before the year is out.
<p>
   Later in the day, reporters asked first Bruno, R-Rensselaer
County, then Pataki, each with Giuliani standing by his side, to
comment on the mayor's request.
<p>
   ``As I've said to the mayor, there isn't a tax cut that I don't
like, so we want to continue to talk about that,'' Bruno said.
<p>
   Pataki said he would ``look over time, as the state's fiscal
condition improves, to getting rid of it,'' but that any reduction
would have to be phased in over a period of years.
<p>
   ``I've got to give it to the mayor,'' said a Democratic Assembly
member, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``He came up here, used
his bully pulpit and forced the issue.''
<p>
   The mayor's comments could not have been better timed, in the
middle of what is, by all reports, a hugely successful experiment
with dropping the sales tax on shoes and items of clothing costing
less than $500.
<p>
   Silver introduced a bill on Tuesday to eliminate the tax, and
said he thought the success of the week-long experiment would
persuade Pataki and Bruno to go along.
<p>
   Eliminating the sales tax on most clothes would erase $600
million a year in state revenues, and even supporters acknowledge
that it would take years for that loss to be recovered.
<p>
   ``The problem with getting rid of the sales tax is it's very
expensive,'' said John McArdle, spokesman for Bruno. ``We have no
problem getting into a bidding war on tax cuts, but from our
standpoint and the governor's standpoint, the priority this year is
the property-tax cuts.''
</TEXT>
