<SLUG> BC-NYC-BUSINES-BRIEFS-NY </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0661 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NYC-BUSINES-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW YORK CITY BUSINESS BRIEFS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Columbus Avenue Base for Soros Institute
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Financier and philanthropist George Soros has leased
two floors of office space, extending the full block along the west
side of Columbus Avenue between 58th and 59th Streets, as a new
base for the Open Society Institute, an organization he founded in
1993.
<p>
   The two floors, totaling 76,250 square feet, are the commercial
base of a 50-story, twin-tower rental apartment complex that is
nearing completion by Manhattan developer Daniel Brodsky.
<p>
   According to Cushman &AMP; Wakefield, the brokerage that represents
Brodsky, the Open Space Institute signed a 15-year lease on the
space for $30 million, and is expected to move into the building
sometime in the spring.
<p>
   Now based at 888 Seventh Ave., the institute is expected to move
all of its 160 New York City employees to the new building.
<p>
   The institute, part of a huge international philanthropic
organization financed by Soros, is engaged in a variety of research
projects and other programs in the United States, Eastern Europe
and Asia, focusing on such areas as criminal justice reform, mental
illness and domestic violence.  &MD;  TOM LUECK
<p>
   Morgan Stanley Rebuts A Racial Bias Lawsuit
<p>
   Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co. chairman Richard B. Fisher and president
John J. Mack have personally sought out senior black executives to
allay concerns following the filing of a racial discrimination
lawsuit against the investment banking company.
<p>
   In addition to sending a memo to the company's 10,000 employees,
``Dick and John made a special effort to speak to the senior people
here and reinforce that we will fight the charges vigorously,''
said Jean Marie McFadden, a company spokeswoman.
<p>
   The lawsuit causing angst inside the 62-year-old firm, at 1585
Broadway, was filed in December by two employees who had earlier
complained about racist jokes being sent around the office via
electronic mail.
<p>
   In their lawsuit, the two employees, Yolanda Owens and Edward
Hutton, said that after they complained about the jokes the company
retaliated by refusing to promote them.
<p>
   Ms. Owens works in the company's computer systems department and
Owens works in facilities maintenance. Both are on voluntary leave,
with full pay and benefits.
<p>
   Morgan Stanley officials do not deny that the e-mail was
circulated, but they have insisted that they disciplined the
employees involved. Ms. McFadden also denied that Ms. Owens and
Hutton were passed over for promotions because they complained
about the incident.  &MD;  BRETT PULLEY
<p>
   A Boom in Tourism
<p>
   Tourism is booming in New York City. According to the latest
estimates, 30.3 billion people visited the city last year, pouring
$13 billion into the local economy.
<p>
   So why is the New York Convention and Visitors Bureau rolling
out a major campaign to lure tourists with discounts at 250 hotels,
restaurants, stores and cultural institutions? Two words: The cold.
<p>
   ``We have now entered the slowest time of the year for the
25,000 tourism-related businesses and their 130,000 employees,''
said Stephen J. Morello, the bureau's president. ``It's not because
we have less to offer but because the weather makes us less
competitive. We can't sit back and let the city sell itself.''
<p>
   Indeed, after the New Year, the hotel occupancy rate dips to
somewhere between 65 percent and 70 percent, compared with last
year's average occupancy rate of 81 percent.
<p>
   Fifteen hotels, from the Days to the Ritz-Carlton New York, are
participating in the campaign called ``New York for a Song,'' by
offering discounts of up to 40 percent.
<p>
   Hotel guests will receive a ``fun pass''  &MD;  a subway Metrocard
with one free fare and a discount at participating restaurants,
stores, theaters and museums. The campaign is scheduled to run
through the end of March.  &MD;  LISA FODERARO
</TEXT>
