<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9923 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-STOCKS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0805 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-JAPAN-STOCKS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JAPANESE STOCKS MIXED; MAJOR ELECTRONICS GAIN ON STRONG DOLLAR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Todd Zaun &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
Tokyo, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- Japanese stocks traded mixed, holding
on to gains yesterday, as a stronger dollar pushed shares of
electronics exporters higher while sending retail and utility
shares lower.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Canon Inc. and Aiwa Corp. led gainers. Tokyo Electric Power Co.
and retailer Ito-Yokado Co. led decliners amid concern the stronger
U.S. currency will raise the cost of imported goods.
<p>
   The benchmark Nikkei 225 stock average rose 6.28, or 0.03
percent, to 18,020.16. The broader Topix index of all first section
shares fell 1.82, or 0.13 percent, to 1,376.80.
<p>
   Investors and analysts' held out hope that deregulation, such as
the possible scrapping of taxes on securities sales, will revive
financial markets.
<p>
   ``We are seeing signs the government is really pushing for
reforms and deregulation,'' said Haruyoshi Mabuchi, chief
strategist at Nikko Research Center, Ltd. ``There's real reason to
be bullish.''
<p>
   The dollar jumped to a 47-month high against the yen. That's
good news for Japanese exporters because a strong dollar makes
their products more competitive overseas and boosts earnings when
converted to yen. In early Asian trading, the dollar rose as high
as 119.32.
<p>
   Canon gained 60 yen to 2,510, Hitachi Ltd. rose 10 yen to 1,040.
Sanyo Electric Co. rose 25 yen to 475 after Nomura Research
Institute raised its rating on the company from ``neutral'' to
``buy,'' citing the company's strategy of focusing on making
electronics components instead of consumer products.
<p>
   Advantest Corp., a maker of semiconductor manufacturing
equipment, rose as much as 120 yen to 6,270.
<p>
   ``The strength of the computer companies in the U.S. will lend
strength to computer-related stocks here,'' said Eiji Azumu,
general manager of the equity trading department at Daiwa
Securities Co.
<p>
   Aiwa's shares rose as much as 180 yen to 2,050. Audio maker Aiwa
Co. earnings for the year are likely to exceed the company's own
forecasts, according to a report by Jardine Fleming Securities Ltd.
<p>
   Mazda Motor Corp. rose 16 yen to 377 after the Nihon Keizai
newspaper said the company and Ford Motor Co. agreed to share
engines to cut production costs. Mazda, which is owned 33.4 percent
by Ford, will make engines for small vehicles while Ford will make
all other engines. Mazda will start making its first such ``world
engines'' by 1999.
<p>
   Elsewhere, shares of Sony Music Entertainment Inc. got a boost
from a report the company's earnings will beat expectations due to
strong sales of the PlayStation video game machines of subsidiary
Sony Computer Entertainment. The stock rose 100 yen to 4,300.
<p>
   ``A continuous higher trending dollar and strength in overseas
computer and high-tech related stocks will continue to give
strength to Japan's high-tech companies and exporters,'' said Dhia
Amir, who sells equity to institutions at Nomura Securities Co.
<p>
   Stocks soared yesterday after Sohei Miyashita, deputy chairman
of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party's tax research committee,
called for repealing the tax levied when investors sell stocks and
bonds
<p>
   Finance Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka sounded cautious about the
proposal, saying at a press conference after the stock market
closed the ministry could only consider eliminating the tax ``in
the whole context of taxation on financial trading.''
<p>
   ``I have heard some members of the LDP's tax council are
proposing the repeal of the tax, but that's the party's idea,'' he
said. The ministry needs to carry out its own study on the plan, he
said.
<p>
   The ministry's cautious stance didn't hurt stocks because
traders and investors are confident the government will have to
eliminate the tax as part of promised deregulation measures,
analysts said.
<p>
   To be sure, some said the weak yen bad news for companies tied
to the domestic economy.
<p>
   A report that car importers will raise prices on some luxury
models shows that the strong dollar is already pushing prices
higher in some areas.
<p>
   Tokyo Electric Power and other utility shares slipped on concern
the yen's weakness would raise the cost of importing fuel. At the
same time, a Ministry of International Trade and Industry official
yesterday called on Japan's power companies to lower rates. Tokyo
Electric stock fell 30 yen to 2,430. Tohoku Electric Power shares
fell 40 yen to 2,190.
<p>
   Retail stocks such as supermarket operator Ito-Yokado Co.
slipped amid lingering concern that a planned consumption tax hike
will weigh on sales, traders said. Ito-Yokado stock fell 230 yen to
5,510. Discount department store operator Jusco Ltd. fell 110 yen
to 3,440. Tokyu Department Store fell 30 yen to 450.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2214EST
</TRAILER>
