<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0814 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9924 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-CONFERENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0793 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-AIDS-CONFERENCE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EXPERIMENT TO SEE IF AIDS CAN BE CURED IS DELAYED A YEAR &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  Dr. David Ho, a leading AIDS scientist, said
Wednesday that he had pushed back by up to a year his plans to do
crucial tests to determine whether infection with the AIDS virus
can be cured in some people.
<p>
   The tests would involve deliberately stopping combination drug
therapy in an infected patient in whom HIV, the virus that causes
AIDS, had not been detected through careful monitoring for at least
two to two and one-half years.
<p>
   Then Ho's team at the Aaron Diamond AIDS Research Center in
Manhattan would test the individual repeatedly to determine if HIV
could be detected again.
<p>
   The theory that the virus can be eliminated from the body is
based on the fact that the cells infected by the virus die after
varying lengths of time. If no HIV is left in the body, then the
cells that replace the old ones should be uninfected.
<p>
   Ho's discussion in Washington seemed much more subdued in tone
than when he and his team spoke at the international AIDS meeting
in Vancouver last July about the possibility of doing the crucial
tests sometime this past fall.
<p>
   Wednesday, Ho said that ``we have never popped the question with
our patients'' to stop therapy to test the theory that AIDS might
be curable. He spoke at a news conference before opening an AIDS
meeting Wednesday night with a talk titled: ``Can HIV Be Eradicated
From an Infected Person?''
<p>
   The answer, Ho said, is ``clearly we don't know.''
<p>
   He also said that ``unequivocally,'' HIV had not been eradicated
from any of the patients in his studies.
<p>
   ``We need to know what happens in the next six months, next
year,'' he said.
<p>
   Ho said his team's first scientific blueprint for the studies
called for addressing the question of stopping therapy a year after
it started.
<p>
   ``However, in the meantime we have learned a great deal and we
need to treat longer,'' he said.
<p>
   He also said his team was reconsidering its original plan to
stop all drugs at the same time. He said the revised timing of
delaying stopping therapy for up to another year particularly
reflected findings obtained since the meeting in Vancouver.
<p>
   Part of the research is intended to define the amount of HIV
replication in the body, how it varies in different organs and
tissues, and how fast HIV and infected cells die.
<p>
   In another part of the research, Ho's team has been treating for
about a 18 months 20 individuals within three months of the date
they were believed to have become infected with HIV.
<p>
   Treatment with a combination of anti-HIV drugs is an initial
step in testing the theory of curability of AIDS.
<p>
   In research conducted in parallel, Ho said his team was ``seeing
very comparable results'' in individuals who had been infected for
much longer periods and who had never taken any anti-HIV drug until
they participated in his study.
<p>
   As part of the research, Ho's team repeatedly uses blood tests
and cultures to try to detect HIV in semen, lymph nodes and lymph
tissue taken in biopsies of the rectum. So far there has been no
evidence of on-going viral replication in the participants' semen
or other tissues, Ho said.
<p>
   He said that the findings should not alter public health
recommendations to practice safe sex.
<p>
   He also said that ``we do find some residual viral particles
trapped in the tissues and we think that that is consistent with
our understanding'' of what happens to HIV in the body.
<p>
   Information based on tests from the participants indicates that
HIV could remain for up to two and one-half years in the areas of
the body that can be tested. But the inability to detect HIV does
not necessarily mean that the virus is absent from the body.
<p>
   It is not known whether HIV can hide in the brain or some other
sanctuary, protected from the combination of drugs, and then
re-infect the body after drug therapy is stopped.
<p>
   The intent of the experiment to see if AIDS can be cured is more
a scientific one than a therapeutic one, Ho said, and it is to
prove the concept that under optimal conditions the virus can be
eradicated from an infected individual.
<p>
   ``You have to take your hat off as a physician and put the hat
of a scientist on,'' said Ho, who is both a medical doctor and a
scientist.
<p>
   He said that the success of combination therapy was something
that virtually all experts considered ``outrageous'' before it was
undertaken. In testing the concept of curing AIDS, he said, ``we
are doing what we are supposed to do as basic researchers.''
<p>
   But Ho said, ``The glare of the media spotlight makes its
difficult for us to do this work.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2216EST
</TRAILER>
