<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0816 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=kan-z> A9926 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-POSNANSKI-KAN </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0901 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-POSNANSKI-KAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FAVRE'S BACKGROUND SUDDENLY POPULAR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JOE POSNANSKI &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Kansas City Star &LR;  &QC;  KILN, Miss.  &MD;  This little town of Kiln
must have been a tough place for Brett Favre to grow up, you know,
with all the reporters hanging around. Heck, half the town wears a
media badge. There are reporters interviewing librarians,
gardeners, shrubs, wood paneling. Mostly, reporters interview
reporters. A young Brett Favre must have had to sidestep ESPN every
time he wanted to eat a sandwich.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ``We've had 50 people over to the house,'' Dad, Irvin Favre,
tells 12 cameras, seven microphones, 23 notepads, six producers and
a tray of bagels. ``I can't get anything done.''
<p>
   Yes sir, this is the ``Explore the Beginnings of Brett Favre Day
Trip,'' a media bus journey through the rustic life and times of
Green Bay Packers quarterback Brett Favre, lunch included. The tour
guarantees insight into Favre, who leads the Packers against the
New England Patriots in Super Bowl XXXI. The package also includes
a Super Bowl pronunciation guide for newcomers to Mississippi.
<p>
   Kiln: pronounced Kill.
<p>
   Favre: pronounced Favre.
<p>
   New Orleans: pronounced N'awlins.
<p>
   New England Patriots: pronounced dead.
<p>
   Then, local knowledge in hand, we headed out to find the real
Brett Favre, who, as you probably know, grew up in Kiln, swam in
swamps, ate live crawdads, killed bears with his bare hands and so
on. We are promised a peek at his rustic American life, complete
with alligators and moonshine and fast cars and dirt roads, a Dukes
of Hazzard reunion tour.
<p>
   They also give out free Brett Favre hats.
<p>
   ``Hey, are you kidding?'' says Mike from the radio show ``Mike
and the Mad Dog.'' ``This bus is going to Hattiesburg, Mississippi?
I don't want to go to Hattiesburg, Mississippi. Hey. Let me out.
I'VE GOT TO GET OUT! HEY!''
<p>
   The bus driver drops off Mike in a nice, rustic field somewhere,
and we are off again, looking for rustic things, like the Kiln Oil
Change and Arcade and also The Rooster, the most popular restaurant
in Kiln, meaning the only restaurant in Kiln, or at least the only
one anyone can find.
<p>
   ``Oh, we're used to crowds,'' explains Lee Lott, owner and
proprietor. ``On Fridays and Saturdays we have entertainment. We
have a piano bar, and we have a singer. Oh, our singer, her name is
Gigi Hines, she's so wonderful and talented. She's black.''
<p>
   Oh, yes, it's quite rustic here in Kiln, among other things, and
Irvin Favre tells the tape recorders, ``So I said, `Well, I'm going
to make my boys quarterbacks,' '' and Bonita Favre tells about the
time the family St. Bernard was munched up by an alligator, and a
family friend tells some story that is supposed to be quite funny
and rustic, only it goes on too long, and he blows the punch line,
and then it's time to leave.
<p>
   We go to the Kiln Public Library, which is significantly larger
than many elevators, and there is a miniature replica of a still.
``Wanted to bring in some local history,'' the librarian says. The
one copy of the Brett Favre biography  &MD;  /{Huck Finn Grows Up/}  &MD;  is
on a shelf. They won't lend it out until after the Super Bowl.
Seven people are on the waiting list.
<p>
   We go to Hattiesburg, home of Southern Mississippi, Brett
Favre's old college. We get a police escort, presumably so we won't
try to escape. We get a nice tour of Hattiesburg, including a
closeup look at the zoo. We get to meet Brett Favre's old coach and
his old assistant coach and the school president and some
fund-raising guy and a bunch of fans and the groundskeeper and the
policemen who provided the escort and a public-relations man from
the hospital that operated on Favre after a car accident and
Favre's old roommate, Chris Ryals.
<p>
   ``Chris, according to Reggie White,'' a television reporter
begins, ``Brett offers many unusual smells and sounds. Can you
explain?''
<p>
   Also, they trot out Lee Roberts, the current Southern Miss
quarterback.
<p>
   ``I've never met Brett Favre,'' he explains. ``I've seen his
face on TV.''
<p>
   Somehow, none of this seems to capture Favre's rustic life or
anything else. Except for a few alligator stories and some good
swamp photo opportunities, Brett Favre remains a mystery. Lunch is
good, though.
<p>
   Then, one old teammate, Greg Reed, sits in a corner. He wears a
UPS jacket. He is on break from work. He also grew up on the Gulf
Coast in Mississippi, and he was a receiver at Southern Miss, a
pretty good one, and he did not know then that Brett Favre would
get that life and he would get this one. Life's that way, though.
There's no time to be bitter.
<p>
   ``I remember the first pass,'' Reed says. ``It was cold, and I
ran about 12 yards, and he threw it. And I turned around and the
ball was coming at me, and I could hear it.''
<p>
   What did it sound like?
<p>
   ``A whistle, maybe,'' he says. ``No, that's not it. I can't
really describe it. I've never heard anything like it. It just sort
of whined, you know? And when I heard that ball, I knew that the
guy was special. You just know.''
<p>
   He laughs a little and looks around at the Brett Favre circus,
and he shakes his head. ``Guess you guys can't get enough of Brett,
huh?'' he asks, and he laughs again and he says that Sunday he will
watch the game in N'awlins. He will keep his ears close to the
television. He will listen for the football.
</TEXT>
