<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-AYALA-WATER-BID-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AYALA, BECHTEL WIN CONTRACT TO RUN MANILA WATER UTILITY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Alex B. Reyes &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Manila, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- Ayala Corp. won one of two
contracts to run Manila's state-owned water utility, ending a
string of losses at big-ticket asset sales for the Philippines'
oldest holding company.
<p>
   Ayala, whose bidding partners are U.S. construction company
Bechtel Group Inc. and Britain's United Utilities Plc., gave the
lowest bid to run half of Metropolitan Waterworks and Sewerage
System's service area where 11 million Filipinos live.
<p>
   The government said a second group, led by Benpres Holdings
Corp. and France's Lyonnaise des Eaux, won the other contract. The
two beat Metro Pacific Corp. and Aboitiz Equity Ventures Inc. in
what the government dubbed as one of the world's biggest water
utility sales.
<p>
   The winners will have to invest a combined $7 billion over the
life of the contract to rehabilitate and expand the water utility's
12,000 kilometers (7,500 miles) of pipes. MWSS, because of leaks
and pilferage, loses more than half the water it pumps.
<p>
   With the win, Ayala will add a new business to its already
formidable portfolio. It controls Ayala Land Inc., the nation's
largest property developer and the most valuable company on the
stock exchange, and Bank of the Philippine Islands, its third
largest bank. It also has telecommunications, electronics, and food
processing units.
</TEXT>
