<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0701 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BRIEFS-ADS-MEDIA-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: N.Y., Ohio, U.K., Australia) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ACCOUNTS AND PEOPLE IN THE ADVERTISING WORLD &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Chief Strategy Officer Quits McCann-Erickson
<p>
   McCann-Erickson Worldwide in New York said Wednesday that Peter
Kim, vice chairman and chief strategic officer, had left the
agency, effective immediately.
<p>
   Susan Irwin, a spokeswoman for McCann, a unit of the Interpublic
Group of Cos., described the surprise resignation of Kim, 37, as
``amicable,'' adding that he had ``decided to pursue other
activities.'' Callers to McCann Wednesday were told by an operator
that Kim ``was no longer with us.''
<p>
   Eric Einhorn, 45, was named to assume Kim's duties, which had
been refocused to concentrate on a McCann brand consulting unit
named the 14th Floor. Einhorn had been executive vice president and
director for the McCann New York strategic review board.
<p>
   Kim joined McCann in 1993 from J. Walter Thompson New York, part
of WPP Group, where he had been executive vice president and U.S.
strategic planning director. He was the second top executive in two
days to abruptly leave a big agency, coming after J. Steve Davis
left as president and chief executive of the New York office of
Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising.
<p>
   TBWA UK to Merge With Simons Palmer
<p>
   TBWA UK, the British operation of TBWA International, and Simons
Palmer Clemmow Johnson, a creatively focused agency in London, said
Wednesday that they would merge by the end of March to form
TBWA/Simons Palmer. Terms were not disclosed.
<p>
   The merged agency, described as the 10th largest in Britain,
will have combined billings estimated at $350 million. TBWA UK is
contributing accounts with billings of $230 million from clients
like Absolut vodka, Nissan and Wonderbra. Simons Palmer brings in
billings of $120 million from clients like Fuji, Nike and Sony.
<p>
   Paul Simons, chairman at Simons Palmer, becomes chief executive
of TBWA/Simons Palmer. And Jonathan Hoare, chairman at TBWA UK,
becomes group chairman of the merged agency. TBWA/Simons Palmer
will be situated in the TBWA UK office in London. TBWA is owned by
Omnicom Group.
<p>
   Ammirati Puris Lintas Announces Revamping
<p>
   Ammirati Puris Lintas, a unit of Interpublic Group of Cos. in
New York, reorganized worldwide management Wednesday by promoting
several executives to new posts and eliminating the title of zone
chairman.
<p>
   Duncan Pollock, chairman for North America and chairman and
chief executive of the New York office, was named president for
North America. Pollock, 53, will assist Martin Puris, chairman,
chief executive and chief creative officer, in running the
worldwide network.
<p>
   Steve Gardner, 43, president of the New York office, was named
to the additional post of multinational client director on the
Compaq Computer account. Terry Rosenquist, 52, zone chairman for
Europe and Africa, who is based in London, was named president for
multinational clients and business development.
<p>
   Also, Max Gosling, 53, zone chairman for Asia/Pacific and the
Mideast, who is based in Sydney, Australia, was named president for
international operations and will relocate to New York. And James
Allman, 45, zone chairman for Latin America and multinational
client director for Johnson &AMP; Johnson in New York, was appointed
multinational client director for Unilever, based in London.
<p>
   Haueter Named Head of Review Board
<p>
   The National Advertising Review Council in New York, the
advertising industry's self-regulation organization, said Wednesday
that Eric D. Haueter, executive director of its National
Advertising Review Board unit since 1990, had been promoted to
chairman. Haueter, 72, succeeds Kenneth Cox, 80, who is retiring.
The council includes members from the American Advertising
Federation, the American Association of Advertising Agencies, the
Association of National Advertisers and the Council of Better
Business Bureaus.
<p>
   Accounts
<p>
    &MD;  Sherwin-Williams diversified brands division, Cleveland, to
Wyse Advertising, Cleveland, to handle the account of its Krylon
paints, which had been inactive. Billings were estimated at $6
million.
</TEXT>
