<SLUG> BC-WHITLOCK-KAN </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0621 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-WHITLOCK-KAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THERE'S A LOT TO LIKE ABOUT PACKERS' BROWN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JASON WHITLOCK &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. 1997 Kansas City Star &LR;  &QC;  NEW ORLEANS  &MD;  Doug Evans says Green Bay
nose tackle Gilbert Brown ``fluctuates'' between 355 and 400
pounds. ``Depending upon whether he's eaten a Gilbert burger or
not,'' adds Evans, a Packer cornerback.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Santana Dotson says he'll never forget the day Brown fell on him
in practice. ``I didn't know if I'd ever see my family again,''
says Dotson, a Packers defensive lineman.
<p>
   Fritz Shurmur says Brown is regarded as the sexiest man over 350
pounds in all of Green Bay. ``He's an acquired taste,'' explains
Shurmur, the Packers defensive coordinator.
<p>
   Fortunately or unfortunately  &MD;  you be the judge  &MD;  Gilbert Brown
is defined by his size. At 6 feet 2 and 350-plus pounds, it's a
rather lengthy definition, but nonetheless it's a rather limiting
one.
<p>
   Brown's size is all that seems to matter here in the Big Easy,
site of Super Bowl XXXI on Sunday. Brown, a former Kansas Jayhawk,
has been here for four days, and all anyone talks to him about is
his weight.
<p>
   No one seems to care that Brown is the heart of the Packers run
defense, that this season, his fourth in the NFL, he established
himself as one of the league's most feared interior tackles, that
the Patriots are probably more concerned with handling Brown than
all-time great Reggie White.
<p>
   Nope. All that matters is Brown's weight.
<p>
   What do you like to eat Gilbert?
<p>
   ``I love my mama's peppered steak and fried chicken. Really,
anything my mama cooks, I love.''
<p>
   How much do you weigh, Gilbert?
<p>
   ``If I told ya, I'd have to kill ya. Let's just say I was 310
pounds in high school, and I don't know when I've seen the 250s  &MD; 
maybe never.''
<p>
   Gilbert, do you mind the questions about your weight?
<p>
   ``It doesn't really bother me. People are amazed at my size, but
it's no big deal to me. My whole family is big.''
<p>
   The questions dragged on and on, until finally those of us who
didn't want to talk or write about Brown's size could see Brown
only in terms of girth.
<p>
   It's difficult to tell where Brown's shoulders end and his neck
begins. His neck is 23 inches round-trip. That's probably bigger
than your thigh. His waist measures 48 inches. He doesn't know his
chest measurement, but a 62 coat fits snugly. He can bench-press
500 pounds.
<p>
   One of his former coaches predicts he'll eat his way out of the
NFL, that Brown will fade quicker than Brown's idol, William ``The
Refrigerator'' Perry, faded from the NFL spotlight.
<p>
   ``Yeah, that's what Coach (John) Teerlinck says,'' Brown said.
``He's still bad-mouthing me, saying I'm going to blow up, eat my
way out of football.''
<p>
   Teerlinck briefly coached Brown in Minnesota, the team that
drafted Brown in the third round of the 1993 draft. The Vikings cut
Brown in training camp. Teerlinck, the Vikings defensive-line
coach, thought Brown was too fat and too slow to play Minnesota's
scheme. The Packers immediately claimed Brown off waivers.
<p>
   ``They never gave me a chance in Minnesota,'' Brown said.
``You've got to give a guy a chance. But that's all right. I'm
happy in Green Bay.''
<p>
   In Wisconsin, Brown is loved. Wisconsin Burger Kings sell the
``Gilbert Meal,'' a hamburger, fries and drink along with a poster
of Brown.
<p>
   ``It's a double Whopper with extra everything and no pickles,''
Brown said. ``It's got about four slices of cheese, extra lettuce,
mayo, mustard and everything. It takes more than two hands to
handle it. You gotta cut it in half to eat it.''
<p>
   It will be interesting to see whether the Patriots can handle
the ``Gilbert Meal'' they'll be forced to swallow Sunday.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2221EST
</TRAILER>
