<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tic-z> A9930 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HMOS-AZR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0758 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HMOS-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GOP BILLS TARGET INSURERS' HOLD ON HMOS &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By KRIS MAYES &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   PHOENIX  &MD;  The influence of health-maintenance organizations over
the state's insurance industry will be challenged in the state
Legislature by an unusual group: conservative Republicans.
<p>
   So intent are some GOP lawmakers on changing the habits of
insurers that they have introduced a half-dozen regulatory bills,
including one that would require employers to offer alternative
health plans, such as chiropractic, to their employees.
<p>
   On Wednesday, Sen. Ann Day, R-Tucson, introduced what many
believe will be the most popular and comprehensive of the bills,
one that would require HMOs to establish clearly understandable
guidelines for their coverage and create an appeals process for
people who are turned down for coverage.
<p>
   ``Health-care plans promise to deliver services, and this bill
is designed to keep them honest,'' Day said.
<p>
   Although Day's bill will likely headline the legislative agenda
on HMOs, a handful of related bills have begun to wend through the
process:
<p>
    &MD; House Bills 2051 and 2441 would require employers with HMOs to
give their employees the option of enrolling in alternative health
plans not available from the HMOs' enrolled physicians.
<p>
    &MD; House Bill 2064 would allow physicians who work for HMOs to
tell patients about any medical treatment they feel is appropriate.
<p>
    &MD;  House Bill 2245 would mandate that insurers provide coverage
for mental illnesses. This measure is being sponsored by Democratic
lawmakers.
<p>
   ``There is a concern out there,'' Day said, because ``health
insurance is a commodity  &MD;  the companies answer to stock markets,
they answer to Wall Street. And anytime you cut costs, it's going
to affect the quality of health care.
<p>
   ``This is the most important protection that consumers can
have.''
<p>
   Rep. Jim Weiers, R-west Phoenix, who sponsored one of the bills
that would give patients more options for treatment, said the rise
of HMOs in the insurance industry has squeezed the number of
choices offered to employees.
<p>
   ``HMOs, rather than the exception, have become the rule in terms
of coverage,'' Weiers said. ``In doing that, there's been a lot of
restrictions placed on personal choice.
<p>
   ``I don't see this as more regulation, it's just opening the
process to personal choice.''
<p>
   HMOs have a strong influence in the insurance industry in
Arizona, with 35 percent of the state's health-insurance business,
or 1.5 million patients.
<p>
   ``We're way ahead of the nation, and it's highly competitive
here,'' said Cathy Eden, executive director of the Arizona
Association of HMOs. ``It's the center of where most of the
innovative ideas are coming from.''
<p>
   During a hearing Tuesday on one of the regulatory bills, Eden
urged lawmakers to remain true to the GOP tradition of limited
government when contemplating the new regulations.
<p>
   ``When you are mandating the point-of-service (optional
treatment) plans, it's similar to mandating the automobile industry
to make a certain kind of car,'' she said.
<p>
   The rash of bills aimed at regulating HMOs has surprised even
some moderate Republicans.
<p>
   Rep. Sue Gerard, R-north-central Phoenix, although a co-sponsor
of the HMO grievance bill with Day, is fighting most of the other
bills.
<p>
   ``I find it fascinating that conservatives are pushing all these
mandates,'' Gerard said. ``I thought we all loved the marketplace
to do things.''
<p>
   Gerard said that the attempts at regulating HMO services are
ironic, given the state's unwillingness to mandate the provision of
insurance to all workers.
<p>
   ``We don't mandate that employers provide insurance to people,
so I can't understand how we can tell companies what they have to
have in the policies they're not required to provide in the first
place,'' Gerard said. ``That doesn't make any sense to me.''
<p>
   The unusual battle between the business community and the
Republican lawmakers that they normally court was visible Tuesday,
when freshman Rep. Debra Brimhall, R-Snowflake, peppered HMO
lobbyist Kevin DeMenna with questions.
<p>
   With some of the state's most powerful industry lobbyists
looking on, Brimhall needled DeMenna on his opposition to the bill
requiring employers to offer optional treatments.
<p>
   ``We're trying to address this problem,'' Brimhall said, ``and
while I understand your concerns, to me, if someone's in the water
drowning, telling them how to swim doesn't help.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2223EST
</TRAILER>
