<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0529 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EDIT-NY-LEGIS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EDITORIAL: THOSE LITTLE LULUS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Jan. 23:
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  New York state voters will be relieved to hear that
the Legislature has settled its lulu crisis. ``Lulu'' is an ancient
New York term that once meant payment in lieu of expenses, but now
refers to prized extra payments that the vast majority of
legislators get for leadership duties.
<p>
   Although the state Legislature is famous for concentrating
authority in a few hands, the monthly payroll boasts more leaders
than the Continental Congress.
<p>
   Gov. George Pataki sent Assembly Democrats into a fury last
month when he refused to reauthorize seven of these stipends, six
of which were supposed to go to Democrats. Rancor over the
reduction in lulus was so intense at the opening of the 1997
session that the governor skipped his traditional-but-futile calls
for bipartisan cooperation and on-time budgets.
<p>
   The Assembly Democrats are very sensitive about lulus because
virtually every other member of the entire Legislature gets a
leadership stipend. Every single member of the state Senate has a
leadership post, from the Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno
($30,000), to the most humble member of the Democratic minority.
<p>
   The recently defeated Sen. Pedro Espada, a Bronx Democrat, for
instance, might have appeared to outsiders as a relatively
unsuccessful and anonymous junior member of the powerless
Democratic caucus. But in the land of the lulus, Espada bore the
proud title of assistant minority whip ($9,500).
<p>
   The Republican Assembly members have little or no impact on what
goes on in a body that is controlled by a Democrat, Speaker Sheldon
Silver. Nevertheless, all but three of them began the year with
leadership posts. Now that the governor has agreed to approve the
seven lapsed stipends, there will be one more job for a Republican
as ranking minority member of the Commission on Food, Farm and
Nutrition ($6,500), and the Assembly Republicans will have 52
chiefs and 2 followers.
<p>
   The plethora of leaders is one of those little ironies of Albany
life, like the fact that the nonpartisan Bill Drafting Commission
includes one commissioner and 100 workers controlled by each
political party. But the humor was lost on Silver when Pataki left
him with 96 members and only 62 leadership stipends to dole out.
<p>
   Democrats believe the governor's resistance to continuing the
lulus was a petty attempt to cause Silver to lose face. Republicans
say it was just an attempt to force the Democrats to act on other
pending bills.
<p>
   Either way, the crisis is over. The Legislature re-approved the
lulus this week, along with some other relatively non-controversial
bills Silver had been sitting on. Pataki has agreed to drop his
objections.
<p>
   That means the Assembly will once again have its $11,000 slot
for a chairman of the Task Force on Demographic Research and
Reapportionment  &MD;  a group that must get some credit for legislative
districts so exquisitely gerrymandered that only one seat in the
150-member Assembly changed parties last year.
</TEXT>
