<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9937 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-BENEFACTOR-PRO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0787 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-SECRET-BENEFACTOR-PROFILE-ART-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: N.J., N.Y.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CHARLES FEENEY: AN ENTREPRENEUR DRIVEN TO REPAY A DEBT TO SOCIETY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (with EXCLUSIVE-SECRET-BENEFACTOR) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic on foundation's recipients is being sent to NYT graphics
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Charles F. Feeney, who secretly gave away a business enterprise
worth billions of dollars, said he never set out to build a
fortune, just to make a good living for his family. But as his
fortune grew, he said, he never forgot that the reason a poor boy
from Elizabeth, N.J., could make it through Cornell University was
the GI Bill and a scholarship in his senior year.
<p>
   In a rare interview this week, he did not mention that to make
ends meet in college he sold sandwiches late at night at fraternity
houses, a touch of the entrepreneurial spirit that later helped him
and a classmate found Duty Free Shoppers Group in 1960 and build it
into the world's largest chain of airport luxury goods stores.
<p>
   Feeney's partner, Robert W. Miller, responded to his wealth in
more conventional ways, adopting a life style famed in global
society circles for its multimillion-dollar, multiday parties.
<p>
   Feeney, meanwhile, started contemplating how to handle his
riches. ``The concept started in the '70s,'' he said in a telephone
interview, ``when I realized that I had made a substantial amount
of money and that the company was generating profits and it
certainly looked as though they would continue to be surplus to my
needs.''
<p>
   Feeney, 65, who favors casual clothes and calls himself a
``shabby dresser,'' said ``money has an attraction for some people,
but nobody can wear two pairs of shoes at one time.''
<p>
   The size of his fortune, he said, revealed only that ``we caught
a wave. We were lucky. We had more luck than we deserved.''
<p>
   As his fortune continued to balloon, he started talking with his
friend Harvey P. Dale, a lawyer, about how to make the best use of
his good fortune and keep his life simple.
<p>
   ``Chuck didn't want his money to crush him,'' Dale said.
<p>
   Feeney started making gifts. One of the first big ones was in
1981 for the 25th reunion of the class of 1956. Cornell University
expected the entire class to donate $250,000; Feeney gave $700,000.
<p>
   ``His gift completely changed fund-raising at Cornell, and so
whatever he has given he has really brought Cornell many times that
amount,'' a classmate said.
<p>
   Soon Feeney retreated from open donations, which invariably
attract requests for more, and three years later Dale created the
structures that allowed Feeney to remain anonymous. All he had to
do was make an irrevocable gift of his assets, now worth $3.5
billion, to his foundations, and do it in Bermuda to avoid
disclosure laws in the United States. So far, the foundations have
given away $610 million, including more than $50 million to
Cornell.
<p>
   One of his biggest gifts to Cornell helps students of modest
means pay down their student loans if they earn good grades, work
and volunteer.
<p>
   Feeney said that he retained enough money to take care of
himself, a sum he said was less than $5 million. He has set up
trusts for his five grown children, he said, ``with enough money
for what they should, and will, need in life.''
<p>
   ``My children are very kind and caring people who have genuine
friends,'' he said. ``People are not close to them because they
have a nicer summer home than someone else but because of who they
are.''
<p>
   Friends say that Feeney has a wicked sense of humor and loves
practical jokes. Soon after the foundations were created, the
trustees gathered in Bermuda, where Dale delivered a stern lecture
about the need for confidentiality. Dale was then summoned from the
room, he said, and when he returned, ``Chuck and the rest of the
trustees were all sitting there wearing those glasses with big
noses and moustaches, showing that they knew about being
anonymous.''
<p>
   Niall O'Dowd, a friend of Feeney who is publisher of The Irish
Voice and Irish America in New York City, said Feeney had told him
he was appalled by ``the competition that the Forbes 400 list
creates by people to get more and more.''
<p>
   ``Chuck thinks that is all wrong that people are looked up to
for how much money they accumulate,'' he said.
<p>
   At Feeney's foundations, the money all comes from him, but he
does not treat it as his own. ``He has one vote, just like every
other director,'' a fellow trustee said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
