<p>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- ABORTION-MARCH-CLR, 1-22
-- On the 24th anniversary of the Supreme Court's decision in Roe
vs. Wade, Hillary Rodham Clinton tells the National Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League on Wednesday that guaranteeing
abortion rights is a priority for the Clinton administration. At
the same time, police officers in riot gear turn out in force
outside the Court, left, in response to thousands of anti-abortion
protesters. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
<p>
   (NYT15) TEL AVIV, Israel -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- ISRAEL-MORDECHAI,
1-22 -- Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai in his office in Tel
Aviv. Mordechai, 52, has emerged from the tumult of the last seven
months as the key problem-solver in the government and as the most
popular member of it. Though largely excluded from the Hebron
negotiations at first, he plunged into the last round, which
culminated in a deal last week, to wrap up the security and civil
agreements. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
<p>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- NY-RUSSIA-LEBED-CLR, 1-22
-- Alexander Lebed, right, is greeted by Donald Trump at his Fifth
Avenue office. Lebed is in New York to court investors, but his
visit to the United States has been widely viewed as an attempt to
win the support of American businessmen and to portray himself as
the one man who can lead Russia and pave the way for investment and
democratic reform there. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
<p>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- ALBRIGHT-CONFIRM-CLR,
1-22 -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, expected to be sworn
in by President Clinton on Thursday, has put two longtime hands in
top jobs at the State Department. Thomas Pickering, 65, will become
under secretary for political affairs, the third-ranking job in the
State Department, replacing Peter Tarnoff. Stuart Eizenstat, 54,
will become under secretary for economic affairs in the State
Department, succeeding Joan Spero. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times
Photo)
<p>
   (NYT12) LOWELL, Mass. -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- TSONGAS-LEGACY-CLR,
1-22 -- During his career, Paul Tsongas, who died on Saturday,
remained loyal to his hometown, Lowell, Mass. His dedication is
rewarded Wednesday at his wake here; thousands arrive to pay their
respects. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
<p>
   (NYT11) HAGERSTOWN, Md. -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- TUCKWELL-MUSIC-CLR,
1-22 -- Barry Tuckwell at home in Hagerstown. Tuckwell, whom The
New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians describes as ``the
leading horn player of his generation,'' was born in Melbourne,
Australia, in 1931, and spent most of his 50-year playing career
based in London. His final public performances on the horn will
take place Thursday, Friday and Saturday in Baltimore. (Marty
Katz/New York Times Photo) *LITE
<p>
   (NYT10) LOS ANGELES -- Jan. 22, 1997 --
HIGHTECH-PRINTS-LADN-CLR, 1-22 -- Muse X Editions' Randall Green,
left, and Charles Leavitt look over some digitally produced prints.
Offering an innovative mix of high-tech and high concept, Muse X
aims to blend the latest in digital technology with the art world's
experimental ideals. ``The realization came at a time when many
fine art figures in L.A. were just beginning to be curious about
computers,'' Green says. (Gus Ruelas/Los Angeles Daily News Photo)
*LITE
<p>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- ECART-FURNITURE, 1-22 --
Andree Putman at the Morgans Hotel. The French interior designer is
leaving Ecart International, the company she founded in 1978 to
reissue classics of early 20th-century furniture design, says
Michel Taurel, development manager of Ecopar, the parent company of
Ecart. ``It's an agreement between her and Ecopar, because, you
know, she is 70- and- something old, and she is actually retiring
from her activities at Ecart,'' says Taurel.(Fred R. Conrad/New
York Times Photo)
<p>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- NY-ANTIQUES-SHOW, 1-22 --
Center, 1933 pencil study of Mona Bismarck, a free spender who
might have savored antiques show fantasias: from far left, pagoda
plaque; ``The Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam''; scrimshaw bureau; Russian
clock; boxer portrait. Just some of the largely unsurprising wares
at the 43rd Winter Antiques Show for the benefit of the East Side
House Settlement, which opened on Jan. 16 and closes Sunday. (David
Corio/New York Times Photo)
<p>
   (NYT7) MOUNT KISCO, N.Y. -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- SHODDY-HOUSES-CLR,
1-22 -- A new four-bedroom twin-gabled house in Mount Kisco is
solidly built but marred by some low-grade materials and mediocre
assembly that critics say is all too common in new construction. If
people with unlimited budgets cannot count on quality construction,
who can? (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
<p>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Jan. 22, 1997 --
HENRY-GRUNWALD-PROFILE-2-CLR, 1-22 -- Henry Grunwald finds time for
Harry. Grunwald, one of Time magazine's most influential editors,
has written a very different book, interweaving descriptions of
public events with personal impressions, pushing himself through an
unfamiliar process of self-disclosure. ``It was not easy,'' he
says. ``There are a great many people to whom conversation is
confession. To me, it isn't really.'' (Suzanne DeChillo/New York
Times Photo)
<p>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Jan. 22, 1997 --
HENRY-GRUNWALD-PROFILE-1-CLR, 1-22 -- When Henry Grunwald (shown
working in his study) ran into Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis at a
party in 1990, he told her he was in the process of researching his
memoir. ``She said, 'Research? Why do you want to do research?' ``
recalls Grunwald, who had his ``One Man's America: A Journalist's
Search for the Heart of His Country,'' published this month. ``
'What I want to know is what Henry Grunwald thinks about in the
bathtub.' `` (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo) *LITE
<p>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT, 1-22 --
Electrical components must be designed and manufactured to handle
current loads without overheating or shorting out, but even the
best components can malfunction if not installed properly. The
government does not regulate manufacturing specifications; instead
manufacturers submit samples of their products to the Underwriters
Laboratories for quality control. Products tested must meet minimum
standards to be approved by the Underwriters. (Edward R.
Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) *LITE
<p>
   (NYT3) PARIS -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- SUB-PARIS-U.S.-DESIGN-STUDENTS,
1-22 -- Two weeks ago, for the first time, 17 American design
students exhibited their work at the Paris furniture show, and by
all accounts they created a sensation. Students and faculty at the
fair: from left, Richard Prisco, Peter Benarcik (leaning on
Precious Box by Bruce Tharp), Julien Egger, Anna Crowley, Dario
Antonioni, Julie Moringello and Thomas Goldstein (seated on his
cafe chair). (Luc Perenom/New York Times Photo)
<p>
   (NYT2) LAS VEGAS -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- CONSUMER-ELECTRONICS-2-CLR,
1-22 -- No longer far-off fantasies, every type of entertainment
and information component was on display at the Consumer
Electronics Show here earlier this month. A Hughes Convergence
Antenna, which speeds up Internet use. (Marty Katz/New York Times
Photo)
<p>
   (NYT1) LAS VEGAS -- Jan. 22, 1997 -- CONSUMER-ELECTRONICS-1-CLR,
1-22 -- No longer far-off fantasies, every type of entertainment
and information component was on display at the Consumer
Electronics Show here earlier this month. From left, a
four-inch-thick Philips television; a stylish Philips P-200 screen
phone, foreground, and an older, squared-off model. (Marty Katz/New
York Times Photo)
<p>
   N.Y. Times News Service
</TEXT>
