<STORYID cat=e pri=r sel=ttd-z> A9942 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PARKER-COMMENT-SFCHRO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0697 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PARKER-COMMENT-SFCHRON &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; BEFORE SHOWBIZ BECAME JUST BIZ, THERE WAS COL. PARKER &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By JOEL SELVIN &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.1997, San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   He was never a colonel and his name wasn't really Parker, but
Col. Tom Parker reigned supreme as rock 'n' roll's first great
impresario, a larger-than-life figure who lived up to his role as
manager of Elvis Presley.
<p>
   Parker, who died Tuesday at age 87 in his Las Vegas home, was an
old-fashioned show business wheeler-dealer capable of pulling out a
pair of dice during complex negotiations with film studio
executives and announcing, ``I'll roll you double or nothing.''
<p>
   He never really outgrew his early career as a carnival barker.
Even when he was managing the most popular artist in show business,
he still enjoyed fleecing suckers.
<p>
   When his client played Lake Tahoe showrooms in the early '70s
and women would snatch scarves off Elvis' neck as he leaned over
the front rows, Parker could be found outside after the show,
hawking identical-looking scarves for five bucks apiece.
<p>
   It wasn't the money  &MD;  he would lose tens of thousands of dollars
the same night at the roulette tables. Parker lived for the chisel.
<p>
   It was said he would make entire deals dependent on the other
party's giving up some personal token, say a prized ashtray, just
to make sure both men knew who got the better of whom.
<p>
   He was the sort of character people told outrageous stories
about, and some were even true. Parker never confirmed or denied
the story that circulated about his carnival attraction, Col.
Parker's Dancing Chickens  &MD;  reputedly nothing more than a cage full
of chickens on hot plates covered with sawdust  &MD;  but he clearly
loved the mystique such tales represented.
<p>
   He understood an antiquated world of show business. He knew tent
shows. He knew exposure. He knew promotion. He made Elvis' record
label, RCA Victor, print up a million pocket-size Elvis calendars
every year, then charged them royalties on the photo.
<p>
   He also masterminded one of the greatest publicity coups in the
history of the music business when he broadcast a 1973 Elvis
Presley concert from Hawaii around the world, for free in every
country of the world except one. In the United States, he let the
networks bid against one another to underwrite the vast venture.
<p>
   He also probably cost Presley millions of dollars in income with
his shortsighted, penny-wise dealings. But when a lawsuit between
the Presley estate and Parker revealed that his management
commissions ran as high as 50 percent, the consensus among industry
insiders was that Parker had earned it. Without his
often-dictatorial, certainly high-handed manipulations of his
client's career, Presley could have disappeared faster than Pat
Boone.
<p>
   In a 1988 book, ``Elvis and the Colonel,'' author Dirk Vellenga
alleged that Parker was actually an undocumented Dutch immigrant
born Andreas van Kuijk and that the reason Presley never accepted
any of the many lucrative offers to tour overseas was that Parker
couldn't obtain a passport.
<p>
   Right after Presley's death in 1977, Parker stayed busy,
continuing to promote and merchandise his client's career. He
remained very close to Presley's father, Vernon, although his
relations with Presley's ex-wife, Priscilla, who came to control
the estate after her former father-in-law's death, were not as
cordial.
<p>
   Soon Parker lost his power with both the estate and Presley's
record label, prowling the halls after hours, his rumpled clothes
and shuffling walk causing people often to mistake him for a
janitor. He split his time between his Palm Springs home and a
hotel suite in Las Vegas.
<p>
   Parker was a controversial man. Hank Snow, the country star
Parker managed before Presley, considered him an unscrupulous fake.
<p>
   But as the show business world changed radically around him, a
revolution he had no small part in creating, Parker remained an
intransigent, old-time hustler, a decidedly different sort of
person from the sharks in suits and ties who understand leveraged
buy-outs and making a fortune in turnaround. He was the anti-Mike
Ovitz.
</TEXT>
