<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SUSPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0368 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-NY-POLICE-SUSPEND-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; LICENSING DIVISION OFFICER IS SUSPENDED &LR;  &QL; 
(th) &QL; 
 &UR; By MICHAEL COOPER &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  The commanding officer of the police department's
licensing division, which is responsible for issuing pistol permits
and gun licenses, was suspended without pay Wednesday after he was
accused of doing favors for friends, police said.
<p>
   Deputy Inspector Henry M. Krantz was charged with violating
police department rules against giving people preferential
treatment, rendering services for private interests and ordering
subordinates to provide preferential treatment, said Deputy
Inspector Michael Collins, a police spokesman.
<p>
   At this point, Krantz only faces internal police department
charges, and the most severe punishment he could face is the loss
of his job. He has not been arrested on any criminal charges,
police said.
<p>
   ``We would have to arrest him if he did it for personal gain,''
Collins said.
<p>
   Krantz, a 30-year veteran of the force, did not respond to calls
to his Westchester County home for comment on the case. Police said
he was suspended as a result of an ongoing investigation into the
licensing division that resulted in seven departmental charges
being filed against him. They did not say what kind of favors he
was accused of doing.
<p>
   The licensing division has been the subject of a federal inquiry
since November, when the bigamy case of a gun dealer raised
allegations of improprieties in the issuance of licenses.
<p>
   The police department's licensing division weighs applications
from New Yorkers who want to own handguns. Under state law, people
must apply to their counties for handgun licenses, and the New York
City Police Department is in charge of issuing pistol permits in
the city's five counties.
<p>
   A high-ranking police official who spoke on the condition of
anonymity speculated that Krantz may have helped ``move friends to
the front of the line'' so they could get quick approval.
<p>
   In addition to being charged with giving preferential treatment
and ordering his subordinates to give preferential treatment, he
was accused of failing to adequately supervise the officers under
his command.
</TEXT>
