<NWORDS> 0177 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-WHOOPI-GOLDBERG-POLICE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: N.J., Md., Del.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHOOPI GOLDBERG DENIES SHE SOUGHT POLICE ESCORT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   TRENTON, N.J.  &MD;  It was a routine morning in Gov. Christie
Whitman's office Tuesday until an excited secretary Mrs. Whitman's
chief spokeswoman, Becky Taylor, that actress Whoopi Goldberg was
on the line.
<p>
   Goldberg was calling to make sure the governor's office knew
that she had not asked for a State Police escort along the New
Jersey Turnpike on Sunday. Goldberg was being driven from New York
City to Washington to participate in pre-inaugural activities that
evening.
<p>
   Fearing she would be late, a member of the inaugural committee
asked the State Police in New Jersey, Delaware and Maryland for
escorts to expedite her trip. The Delaware and Maryland police
obliged. But the New Jersey State Police did not, saying it was not
a public safety matter.
<p>
   ``I called the governor's office to make sure that they stop
saying that I made the request,'' Ms. Goldberg said.
<p>
   END
</TEXT>
