<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0836 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=s pri=r sel=ttc-z> A9948 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WOLF-LADN </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0908 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BKC-WOLF-LADN &QL; 
DUNCAN WAITING TO BE TOP PICK &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
By SCOTT WOLF &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Los Angeles Daily News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   It's the halfway mark of the college basketball season, which
means the nation's top players have taken a focused and
single-minded approach to the remainder of the season.
<p>
   Are they thinking of winning their conference championship?
Nope.
<p>
   Projecting how many victories are necessary to obtain a coveted
bid to the NCAA Tournament? Wrong.
<p>
   What are they pondering?
<p>
   Um, well, it's a simple question really.
<p>
   ``Where will I be drafted?''
<p>
   Most players have only 14 games or so to prove themselves before
the NBA firms up its opinions.
<p>
   If you're Wake Forest's Tim Duncan, none of this matters. He is
the franchise and just marking time until he is the No.1 pick.
<p>
   But others, like USC's Rodrick Rhodes, have seen their stock
drop because of injuries.
<p>
   The rest are jockeying for position. According to NBA scouts and
college basketball analysts, here are the top 10 picks, if the
draft were held today (players with an asterisk are underclassmen):
<p>
   1. &UR; !off! &LR;  Tim Duncan, 6-11 center, Wake Forest.
<p>
   2. &UR; !off! &LR;  Keith Van Horn, 6-9 forward, Utah.
<p>
   3. &UR; !off! &LR;  Ron Mercer, 6-7 forward, Kentucky.
<p>
   4. &UR; !off! &LR;  Paul Pierce, 6-6 forward, Kansas.
<p>
   5. &UR; !off! &LR;  Danny Fortson, 6-7 forward, Cincinnati.
<p>
   6. &UR; !off! &LR;  Alexander Koul, 7-1 center, George Washington.
<p>
   7. &UR; !off! &LR;  Jacque Vaughn, 6-1 guard, Kansas.
<p>
   8. &UR; !off! &LR;  Chauncey Billups, 6-3 guard, Colorado.
<p>
   9. &UR; !off! &LR;  Cory Carr, 6-4 guard, Texas Tech.
<p>
   10. &UR; !off! &LR;  Danya Abrams, 6-7 forward, Boston College.
<p>
   Of course, a January list can undergo wholesale changes by June.
We'd put the Collins twins on this list, but then it would really
be a mock draft.
<p>
    &MD;  &MD;  Kerplunk: How did Oregon collapse so fast in barely three
weeks? The Ducks were flying high at 10-0, ranked in the top 25 and
primed to challenge for the Pac-10 title. Here's one reason:
<p>
   The Ducks played only three games that required stepping onto an
airplane in their first 10.
<p>
   They also played way too many state teams. They defeated Boise
State, Cleveland State, Portland State and San Diego State.
Portland State is in the first year of resurrecting its program and
has won only three games.
<p>
   This helps explain how Oregon got swept in Washington, then lost
both home games to Stanford and Cal.
<p>
    &MD;  &MD;  Good but not great: Kentucky coach Rick Pitino has bemoaned
the lack of elite teams this season and no one could present a
compelling argument otherwise.
<p>
   ``I don't think there are too many great teams,'' Pitino said.
``Kansas is great. I don't know about Cincinnati. They could be.
Wake Forest is great. Outside of that ...
<p>
   ``Kansas has all the answers. With Wake Forest, if they can slow
down the game, they've got all the answers. With the others, can we
have the answers come March? Who's going to improve the most?''
<p>
   Pitino needs to find an answer for losing point guard Derek
Anderson, the Southeastern Conference's leading scorer. He
completely tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his knee against
Auburn last Saturday.
<p>
   A fifth-year senior, Anderson's college career is over.
<p>
    &MD;  &MD;  Bartow Arena: Former UCLA coach Gene Bartow will have the
on-campus facility at Alabama-Birmingham named after him in a
ceremony Saturday. Bartow, who retired after last season after
building the Blazers' program, was chiefly responsible for the
arena, after his teams played downtown for years.
<p>
   Now all that's left is some sort of tribute from UCLA. Just
kidding.
<p>
   !arrow!Local watch:!off! Former Cleveland star Shawn Bankhead is
No.14 Iowa State's second-leading scorer, averaging 11.3 points per
game.
<p>
    &MD;  &MD;  Marquee matchup: While the Martin Luther King Jr. Holiday
Challenge received most of the publicity, Monday's best individual
prep matchup took place at UC Irvine.
<p>
   Woodbridge's 6-foot-11 forward Chris Burgess outdueled Villa
Park's 7-1 center Eric Chenowith. Burgess, who is going to Duke,
had 30 points and four 3-pointers. Chenowith, who will attend
Kansas, had 18 points and six rebounds.
<p>
   Woodbridge defeated Villa Park 71-56.
<p>
    &MD;  &MD;  Pipe dream: Those few die-hard USC basketball fans who exist
have a plan for the Trojans to become a top-25 program, and not
surprisingly, it involves the football team.
<p>
   The theory starts with USC getting a commitment from 6-7 forward
Ryan Humphrey of Oklahoma, considered one of the top tight ends in
the country. Humphrey has narrowed his choices to Kansas, USC and
Michigan.
<p>
   The Trojans would then follow that up with a commitment next
year from Dominguez's 6-4 quarterback, Jason Thomas, who scored 33
points in the Dons' victory over Crenshaw on Monday. Thomas wants
to play both sports in college and is considered exceptional in
football and basketball.
<p>
   Then comes the real coup. Thomas' teammate and close friend
Tayshaun Prince, considered the best junior in the state, joins him
at Troy.
<p>
   Again, it's only a theory.
<p>
    &MD;  &MD;  Here he comes: Oregon State freshman Corey Benjamin of
Fontana is finally living up to his potential after becoming
eligible last month. Benjamin averaged 28.5 points and 5.0 rebounds
in the Beavers' split with the Bay Area schools.
<p>
   The Beavers are relying on freshmen. In their upset of Stanford,
Benjamin had 26 points and fellow freshmen Ron Grady and Carson
Cunningham had 24 and 18.
</TEXT>
