<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PETRON-SHARES-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PETRON SHARES RISE 8.2% ON EARLY DEREGULATION OF OIL INDUSTRY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Chary D. Mercado &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Manila, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- Shares of Petron Corp., the
Philippines largest oil refiner, rose as much as 8.2 percent to
10.50 pesos after President Ramos yesterday ordered full
deregulation of the oil industry by Feb. 8.
<p>
   ``This is news to the market,'' said Gina Dipaling, analyst for
Philippine Asia Equity Securities Inc. ``Full deregulation has been
advanced by a month.''
<p>
   The oil deregulation law stipulates that the government has to
lift all price controls on petroleum products by March this year.
The government advanced the deadline to prevent another deficit in
a state fund used to stabilize consumer fuel prices.
<p>
   With full deregulation, Petron and its rivals - Pilipinas Shell
Petroleum Corp. and Caltex Philippines Inc. - will be free to price
their products.
<p>
   The oil refiners had complained that they were unable to fully
recover costs and maintain profit margins under the present system,
wherein prices are dictated by a formula linked to Singapore
postings.
</TEXT>
