<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-LADN </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0823 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-LADN &QL; 
OAKMONT IS LIKE HOME TO KLEIN &QL; 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL; 
By DAVE SHELBURNE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Los Angeles Daily News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Mother Nature took her shot at Oakmont Country Club two weeks
ago. Next month, the LPGA Tour will have a go at it.
<p>
   Look for Oakmont to survive again.
<p>
   A violent early-January windstorm knocked out 52 trees,
including some nearly 150 years old. But the 68-year-old Glendale,
Calif., course is expected to play as tough as ever when the
$650,000 Los Angeles Women's Championship is held there Feb. 14-16.
<p>
   ``I don't think you'll see very low scores,'' said Emilee Klein,
the former Notre Dame High School star who won back-to-back LPGA
events last year and who grew up playing at Oakmont.
<p>
   ``You'll probably have a couple of girls shoot under par but not
much under par.''
<p>
   Jan Stephenson, who will join Klein in the 144-player field at
the L.A. Women's Championship, can attest to Oakmont's difficulty.
Stephenson called the Glendale course the toughest the LPGA played
in 1985, when her winning total of 2-over par there was highest on
tour that year.
<p>
   During the three years the LPGA played at Oakmont from 1985-87,
only !ital!three!off! players completed a tournament under par
there.
<p>
   ``If you don't really think and use your head, it will eat you
up,'' Klein said. ``I consider it a U.S. Open-type of golf
course.''
<p>
   She said many of the tour players are looking forward to playing
on the 6,413-yard, par-72 hillside layout, where narrow, tree-lined
fairways and fast, difficult greens make any score near par an
accomplishment.
<p>
   ``Everyone is excited to come here,'' Klein said, ``because it
is such a fabulous course. We don't get to play courses like
Oakmont as often as we'd like to.''
<p>
   Klein, who went from Notre Dame to earn NCAA Player of the Year
honors as a sophomore at Arizona State in 1995, said her early
experiences at Oakmont played a large role in her success.
<p>
   ``The greens are tricky, the rough is tough and anyone who plays
the course regularly has to be a better golfer when you get on an
easier course,'' said Klein, who now lives in Florida.
<p>
   ``Oakmont was the main reason I play so well.''
<p>
   Klein's memories of the Glendale course include playing there
every day after school with her father, learning to compete and
visualize.
<p>
   ``When I'd stand on the range there, I'd think I was making the
last shot on 18 or the putt to win the U.S. Open or one of the
majors,'' she said.
<p>
   She got a taste of fulfilling her dream last summer, when she
won the women's British Open one week after shooting a
personal-best 65 in the final round to win the Ping Welch
Championship.
<p>
   ``The first was a great win and I felt really excited,'' Klein
said. ``But the second one meant more because it proved I was here
for real.''
<p>
   She added more proof in the final 1996 tournament, battling
Rookie of the Year Karrie Webb into the last round of the inaugural
LPGA Tour Championship before losing by four strokes.
<p>
   Klein finished the year No.9 on the money list with $463,793 and
could earn more next month at Oakmont, where her local knowledge
should be a big advantage.
<p>
   No matter what, she's going to enjoy the homecoming.
<p>
   ``I've had a lot of really great times at Oakmont,'' she said.
``It was a great place to golf. It's one of the fabulous courses  &MD; 
you really have to think about your game.''
<p>
    &MD;  &MD;  Sorenstam at Oakmont: Two-time defending women's U.S. Open
champion Annika Sorenstam, who started this season by winning the
LPGA Tournament of Champions, will compete in the L.A. Women's
Championship at Oakmont.
<p>
   She is one of several top-20 players who have committed,
including Liselotte Neumann, Val Skinner, Pat Bradley, Rosie Jones,
Patty Sheehan, Meg Mallon and local favorite Klein. Past champions
Stephenson, Chris Johnson ('86) and Jane Geddes ('87) also are
entered.
<p>
    &MD;  &MD;  More wind: The Scholl Canyon driving range, located on a
hilltop in east Glendale, is open for business again after being
knocked out of action for a second straight year by a January
windstorm.
<p>
   Last year, Scholl lost its entire near-60-foot-high, right-side
protective fence when telephone pole-wide supports were snapped
like toothpicks at about four feet high by winds estimated near 100
miles per hour. This year, the course had much of its left-side
fence knocked out during the windstorm that uprooted trees at
nearby Oakmont.
<p>
    &MD;  &MD;  Looking ahead: Stewart Cink and David Berganio, both up from
last year's Nike Tour, made the cut in last week's tour-opening Bob
Hope Chrysler Classic.
<p>
   Cink, winner of last year's Nike Tour championship, tied for
ninth at 21 under par. Berganio, the Alemany High School alumnus
who won two U.S. Public Links titles and placed 16th in last year's
U.S. Open, shot 9-under to finish 66th at the Hope. Both players
have full exemptions for this year's tour.
</TEXT>
