<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-OILERS- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0224 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-OILERS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EMBATTLED ISLANDERS RISE TO THE OCCASION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y.  &MD;  Maybe it was Monday afternoon's after-game
practice. Whatever it was, New York Islanders coach and general
manager Mike Milbury ought to bottle it.
<p>
   Two days after the Islanders played what Milbury called their
worst game of the season, prompting him to punish them with a
44-minute ``conditioning'' skate, the Islanders played one of their
best games Wednesday night, routing the Edmonton Oilers by 8-1
before 10,438 delighted fans at Nassau Coliseum.
<p>
   The victory was just the Islanders' third in their last 15 games
(3-11-1). The eight goals tied the highest total the Islanders have
scored in a game this season, and the margin of victory was their
biggest this year.
<p>
   Derek King scored two goals, and Bryan McCabe, Zigmund Palffy,
Marty McInnis, Derek Armstrong, Paul Kruse and Steve Webb (the
first of Webb's National Hockey League career) had the rest as the
Islanders scored seven unanswered goals in the final 30 minutes 50
seconds of the game.
<p>
   It was a rare outburst, especially for the goaltender Eric
Fichaud, who entered the game with the Islanders averaging just
2.17 goals when he starts (the lowest amount of support for any
goaltender in the NHL.)
<p>
   END
</TEXT>
