<DOCID> nyt970122.0841 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tic-z> A9954 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BALLOT-AZR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0684 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BALLOT-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BILL GIVES BALLOT VOICE FOR `NONE OF THE ABOVE' &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MARTIN VAN DER WERF &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   When Election Day approaches, lots of voters talk of holding
their noses and voting for the candidate who least offends them.
<p>
   The voters write to the newspapers, call the radio stations and
tell their friends, ``They're all crooks anyway. Why vote?''
<p>
   State Sen. Randall Gnant wants to give those disaffected folks a
voice.
<p>
   He wants a new line on the ballot in Arizona elections that
would permit voters to check off ``None of the above.''
<p>
   And if ``None of the above'' wins, another election would be
held. The candidates who ran the first time and were shunned by the
public would be barred from running in the new election.
<p>
   ``You could tell the political parties, `We don't like your
candidates. Try again,' '' Gnant said.
<p>
   Other lawmakers are calling his idea silly and cynical, but
Gnant, a second-term Republican from north Scottsdale, breaks into
a mirthful grin whenever he thinks about it.
<p>
   ``I'm dead serious.''
<p>
   By Gnant's reasoning, the change would prove that the public was
not as disenchanted as pundits seem to think.
<p>
   ``I believe `None of the above' would only win in a minuscule
number of elections,'' Gnant said. ``I think people are less
disenchanted with the process than some of the heated voices would
have us believe.''
<p>
   Voters in Nevada can mark ``None of the above'' on ballots, but
the results are non-binding, said Steve Lilienthal, state policy
director of the Washington, D.C.-based Free Congress Foundation,
which supports ideas that give voters a more direct voice in
decision-making.
<p>
   ``It is sort of a free-market approach to improving campaigns,''
Lilienthal said. ``If people start voting for `None of the above,'
politicians might start taking notice. Just the threat of it might
be incentive enough to change the way campaigns are run, make them
cleaner and more directed to issues.''
<p>
   Of course, there are some who don't see the humor.
<p>
   Sen. Tom Freestone, R-Mesa, said he thinks it would become
another tool for bashing government.
<p>
   ``It cheapens the process,'' Freestone said. ``You put anything
out that is anti-government, and people will vote for it. Then,
they complain that the government isn't there for them.''
<p>
   Lisa Daniel, the state elections director, said she thinks the
embarrassment of losing to ``None of the above'' would discourage
people from running.
<p>
   ``To think that you would work your heart out, raise money, get
a plurality of votes, and then not be able to take office, it seems
like that would be heartbreaking. I don't know who would run for
office.''
<p>
   Then, there would be the cost of holding additional elections. A
statewide election could cost more than $1 million, Daniel said.
<p>
   Also, legislation approved last year allows elections to be held
on only four dates during the year, one day each in March, May,
September and November, so second elections would be difficult to
schedule.
<p>
   None of this discourages Gnant. In fact, he's got more
mischief-making dancing around in his head.
<p>
   He has introduced another bill that would invalidate all
election results in school districts and special taxing districts,
such as irrigation districts, unless the turnout was at least 20
percent.
<p>
   ``That would force them to actually advertise their elections,''
Gnant said. ``There are companies that are paid to consult on how
to keep turnouts low. That is a corruption of the process.''
<p>
   And there is another idea: Gnant would like to set up ballots so
they would list the candidates' names, then have a ``yes'' or
``no'' next to each candidate. The voter would be allowed to mark
only one box.
<p>
   Under this plan, the voter would have to say whether he or she
was voting affirmatively for one candidate or against the candidate
they disliked.
<p>
   ``In theory, someone could be elected with negative votes,''
Gnant said. ``Now wouldn't that send a message? Wouldn't that be
fun?''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2255EST
</TRAILER>
