<DOCID> nyt970122.0842 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tic-z> A9955 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-VICTIM-AZR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0470 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-VICTIM-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SENATE REVISITS VICTIMS-RIGHTS MEASURE &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ADRIANNE FLYNN &QL;  &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  It took 42 rewrites, but Sens. Jon Kyl and Dianne
Feinstein say the victims-rights bill they introduced Tuesday has a
strong chance of becoming an amendment to the Constitution.
<p>
   It's the second time around for the bill. The original,
introduced last April, got as far as a hearing but then expired
without a vote at the end of Congress' session.
<p>
   ``I don't think there was major criticism of the original
bill,'' Kyl, R-Ariz., said at a news conference Wednesday at the
Capitol. ``But when you amend the Constitution, you want to make
sure you have it right.''
<p>
   Only minor changes in wording were made in the many drafts, but
the alterations were designed to stave off criticism from lawmakers
who oppose any change to the Constitution.
<p>
   House sponsorship from Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the respected
chairman of the Judiciary Committee, is likely to enhance its
chances. President Clinton and Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, also support the measure. It would take
affirmative votes from both houses of Congress and ratification by
38 states to be adopted as an amendment.
<p>
   Arizona and 27 other states already have similar constitutional
amendments. Feinstein, a California Democrat, said that although
those laws are individually beneficial, collectively they have
created a patchwork quilt that can be solved only with a
constitutional amendment.
<p>
   ``Victims should have certain rights guaranteed to them under
the Constitution of the United States. What could be wrong with
that?'' Feinstein said. ``The scales of justice today are weighted
too heavily to the rights of the accused.''
<p>
   The bill would guarantee that crime victims be informed of their
rights, of any proceedings in their case and of any escape by the
suspect. They would be assured a right to speak in the case,
granted restitution and guaranteed speedy results.
<p>
   Although the legal language guaranteeing victims' rights may
sound dry, the issue can be an emotional one.
<p>
   In a quiet voice and in tears, Marsha Kight, the mother of
Frankie Merrell, who was killed in the Oklahoma City bombing, told
of the anguish that families faced when a judge ruled that they
could either attend the suspects' trial or testify at sentencing,
but not both. It was a decision they all were forced to make on a
lunch break, she said.
<p>
   ``It would seem that the defendants are the preferred ones, with
all the rights, while the victims are constantly re-victimized by
the judicial system,'' she said. ``There are lessons to be learned
here if we are listening. If not from Oklahoma City, than what?
Who's next? Your child?''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2258EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0843 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9956 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINE-STOCKS-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0391 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-PHILIPPINE-STOCKS-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PHILIPPINE STOCKS RISE AS OIL REFINER PETRON ADVANCES 8% &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Alex B. Reyes &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Manila, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- Philippine stocks rose for the
first time in four days, led by oil refiner Petron Corp., after the
government said it would advance the deregulation of the oil
industry by one month.
<p>
   President Fidel Ramos signed an order freeing the industry from
more than two decades of price controls that often prevented oil
companies from recovering higher costs. The order takes effect Feb.
8.
<p>
   ``We're betting that deregulation will be a major boost for
Petron,'' said Alvin Ang, an analyst at All AsiaCapital and Trust
Corp. ``It's the largest in the market and so far there are no new
companies coming in'' to the deregulated industry.
<p>
   Petron, with a market share of 41 percent, rose as much as 8.25
percent to 10.50 pesos. It has a 5.4 percent weighting in the
benchmark index and was the second most active stock.
<p>
   Ang said Petron's shares could rise to 12 pesos by around March
because the company can start charging more.
<p>
   Petron's advance helped drive the 30-company Philippine Stock
Exchange composite index to as high as 3333.92, up 58.09 points or
1.77 percent from yesterday's close. The all-shares index
comprising 255 issues rose 10.18 points to 1061.69.
<p>
   Ayala Land Inc., the largest property developer, rose as much as
05.0 peso to 31.50. Ayala Land's parent, Ayala Corp., won one of
two concessions to run the country's largest water utility.
<p>
   Ayala's clinching of a 25-year contract to operate the
Metropolitan Waterworks and Sewerage System ends a string of
defeats in bidding for high-profile government asset sales.
<p>
   Bank of the Philippine Islands, the Ayala group's bank, rose as
much as 5 pesos to 175 after announcing that profit in 1996 doubled
to 3.99 billion pesos.
<p>
   Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co. rose as much as 25 pesos
to 1,580 after its U.S.-traded shares rose $1.75 to 59. Some
investors believe that the phone company will be granted increases
in local rates that will offset declining international calling
rates.
<p>
   Philippine Asia Equity Securities Inc. estimates that if PLDT
gets the rate increase, forecasted earnings per share will go up
about 4 percent.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2300EST
</TRAILER>
