<DOCID> nyt970122.0844 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r sel=tic-z> A9957 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-GAMING-AZR </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0382 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-GAMING-AZR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; 2 TRIBES SUE STATE OVER VIDEO-GAMING NUMBERS &QL;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MARK SHAFFER &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 The Arizona Republic &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The Gila River and Ak-Chin Indian communities filed a federal
suit Wednesday against state gaming Director Gary Husk, claiming
the state is overcounting video-gaming machines in their casinos
south of Phoenix.
<p>
   The state's motives, Gila River Gov. Mary Thomas says, are more
sinister than just counting machines.
<p>
   ``It is now obvious that the Arizona Department of Gaming is
determined to try to take over, or worse, end Indian gaming in
Arizona,'' Thomas said.
<p>
   Husk denies that.
<p>
   Central to the dispute are multiplayer gaming devices in which
five machines are joined in one circular pod. In past gaming
compacts with the state, the tribes say, each pod was counted as
one gaming device, but now Husk is counting each machine
individually.
<p>
   By the state's count, Husk said, the Gila River Casino is 36
machines over its maximum of 500 and Harrah's Ak-Chin Casino is
slightly over its ceiling of 475, as agreed to in their compacts
with the state. The Gila River Community also has another, smaller
casino and is allowed a total of 900 gaming devices under its
compact.
<p>
   ``We feel that we are in compliance because the state signed off
on counting each multiplayer device as one,'' said Carol Jackson,
spokeswoman for the Gila River community. ``Why can't the state
admit that it made a mistake?''
<p>
   Jacob Coin, executive director of the Arizona Indian Gaming
Association, agrees.
<p>
   ``When is an agreement with the state an agreement?'' Coin
asked. ``Not only is this a slap in the tribes' face but it once
again says the state cannot be trusted when it comes to its
agreements with tribes.''
<p>
   Husk said he welcomes the lawsuit because ``it's very important
that this fundamental issue of what constitutes a gaming device be
clarified.'' Husk said three other tribes with casinos  &MD;  Fort
McDowell, White Mountain Apache and Quechan  &MD;  had agreed
voluntarily to count each machine as one, regardless of how they
were placed in their gaming buildings.
<p>
   ``Every other state that has gaming counts machines based on the
number of stations. Las Vegas does it for taxing purposes,'' Husk
said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2301EST
</TRAILER>
