<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0847 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=w pri=u sel=tdt-z> A9961 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-SPENDING-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1174 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-FOREIGN-SPENDING-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ADMINISTRATION TO ASK 12 PERCENT CUT IN FOREIGN SPENDING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID L. MARCUS &QC; 
c.1997 The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  President Clinton and his new secretary of state,
Madeleine K. Albright, plan to ask Congress to increase spending on
foreign affairs by about 12 percent, aides said Wednesday. That
would be a dramatic change from the 10 percent cut imposed by
Congress last year.
<p>
   Half of the extra $2.2 billion would be used to pay off the US
debt to the United Nations, an expense that probably will irk
conservatives in Congress. The rest would buy new computers, hire
more diplomats with expertise in trade and other specialities,
repair embassies and expand peacekeeping missions, according to
officials.
<p>
   The decision followed weeks of haggling between the State
Department, where officials have been reeling from cutbacks, and
the president's Office of Management and Budget, which wants to
balance the budget and emphasize spending at home.
<p>
   Clinton wants to take advantage of Congress' bipartisan support
for Albright, who was confirmed Wednesday, and for Bill Richardson,
the former congressman who is expected to be confirmed as
Albright's replacement as UN secretary next week.
<p>
   ``We have to strike while it's hot,'' a State Department
official said. ``We've been cutting back on conducting foreign
affairs at the same time we have become the only superpower in the
world.''
<p>
   The proposed increase in spending on foreign affairs is a
relatively tiny amount for the the federal budget, about the same
amount as the cost of a single Air Force B-2 Stealth bomber. Still,
the administration's determination to expand the foreign budget is
a symbolic victory for internationalists who say the United States
should take a more active role overseas.
<p>
   Last year, a task force sponsored by the Council on Foreign
Relations and the Brookings Institution urged the government to
spend about $3 billion more on foreign affairs. The task force
included prominent Republicans, such as the former national
security adviser, Brent Scowcroft, and former Secretary of State
George P. Shultz.
<p>
   The campaign to persuade a reluctant Congress will start today,
when the newly elected UN secretary general, Kofi Annan, meets
informally with Jesse Helms, the Republican chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee. Annan, a diplomat from Ghana who has
called for UN reform, will later meet other members of the
committee.
<p>
   Tomorrow Annan meets the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott,
whose support the Clinton administration needs as budgets are drawn
up in the next few months.
<p>
   The administration is planning to ask for at least $1 billion
more for foreign affairs and another $1.2 billion to repay the UN
debt, aides to Clinton and former Secretary of State Warren M.
Christopher said.
<p>
   Last year, Congress shot down Clinton's plan to repay the UN
over as many as five years. This time, Clinton will suggest a
relatively small $100 million payment up front. If the UN
reorganizes, trims its bureacracy and disbands several overlapping
agencies, a year later the United States will pay the remainder of
its debt, the aides said.
<p>
   The United States will also seek a change in the formula that
determines how much each country pays to run the UN. The United
States will offer to pay about 23 percent of the total UN budget,
down from the current 25 percent.
<p>
   To please Helms and other critics of foreign affairs programs,
Albright will offer to streamline the State Department and phase
out several agencies, the State Department official said. But while
her predecessor, Christopher, demanded early retirements and
shuttered embassies to save money, Albright will press her
supporters in Congress to spend more, not less.
<p>
   The proposal will probably cause a division in Congress between
hard-liners who dislike the UN and foreign aid and others who want
the United States to be more active. The administration will enlist
moderates such as Richard G. Lugar, the Indiana Republican who
serves on the Foreign Relations Committee, aides said.
<p>
   Albright won over doubters in Washington with her blunt talk at
the UN and her successful effort to block another term for Boutros
Boutros-Ghali of Egypt, the former secretary general who opposed
radical reform. After singing her praises Wednesday, the Senate
voted 99-0 to confirm Albright. William S. Cohen, the Maine
Republican who was confirmed Wednesday as secretary of defense,
also wants more money for diplomacy, officials said.
<p>
   ``It is extraordinary that we have cut back so severely in
foreign affairs and the Congress is talking about increasing
spending on the military by more than what we cut out from foreign
affairs,'' said Joseph S. Nye Jr., dean of the Kennedy School of
Government and a former assistant secretary of defense for
international security affairs.
<p>
   ``It's like cutting away your first line of defense,'' he said.
``Crises avoided are crises that don't cost you.''
<p>
   An administration official added: ``The American people are more
connected to the rest of the world than they used to be, whether
they like it or not.''
<p>
   In many ways, Albright prepared the way for this campaign at her
confirmation hearing on Jan. 8, when she told the Senate that
first-class diplomacy doesn't come ``on the cheap.'' She noted that
the $18.2 billion the United States spends on foreign affairs in
the current fiscal year is only about 1 percent of the federal
budget, but ``That 1 percent may well determine 50 percent of the
history that is written about the era.''
<p>
   Since the Cold War ended, the United States has steadily pruned
its foreign affairs budget. Thirty embassies and consulates have
been shut. The State Department's technology is so bad, Albright
said, that sometimes she could not call Washington from her UN
office. Instead, she had step outside and use a pay phone.
<p>
   Wednesday, a State Department official discussing the budget
proposal pointed to the clunky black-and-white computer monitor on
his desk and sneered, ``Look at this computer!'' Then he flipped
open a staff directory that showed just two people in the State
Department coordinate policy for seven African countries, including
South Africa.
<p>
   But Albright's Congressional hearing offered a glimpse of the
problems that await her as she makes pitches for multilateral
actions abroad. She sat near a large poster of the UN bureacracy
put up by the Foreign Affairs Committee. ``The UN: One Big Mess,''
it said.
<p>
   The proposal to pay off the UN debt will get a very cool
reception from those in Congress who watch budgets, said Charles M.
Lichenstein, a fellow at the conservative Heritage Foundation.
<p>
   ``They are going to say, `What's in it for us?''' said
Lichenstein, who served in the US UN office under President Reagan.
``It's all so nebulous that I scarcely know what it means to clear
up the debt and start afresh. Start afresh to do what?''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2307EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0848 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=u sel=taf-z> A9962 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CONRAIL-DISPUTE-625&AMP;A </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1061 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CONRAIL-DISPUTE-625&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Pa.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OFFICIALS OF THREE RAILROADS TO MEET ON CONRAIL DISPUTE &LR;  &QL; 
(lh) &QL; 
 &UR; By CHARLES V. BAGLI &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   In what may be a breakthrough in the costly three-month-long
battle for Conrail, CSX Corp. and Conrail agreed Wednesday to a
meeting with the Norfolk Southern Corp. to discuss reshaping the
rail freight industry in the East.
<p>
   In a letter to Norfolk Southern, the chairmen of the two
railroads, who had signed a friendly $9.3 billion merger agreement,
said they would hold ``meaningful and candid discussions,'' without
any preconditions. Although the prospect of a meeting represents a
softening in the companies' hard-line stance, analysts were
cautious as to whether a meeting would lead to a negotiated
settlement.
<p>
   Norfolk Southern, which has offered $10.5 billion in a hostile
bid to take over Conrail, had stymied the friendly merger between
CSX and Conrail, at least temporarily, at a special meeting of
Conrail shareholders Friday. Dangling a sweeter offer before
investors, Norfolk persuaded shareholders to reject a measure that
would have allowed CSX to proceed with its merger. But Norfolk,
which plans to purchase 10 percent of Conrail stock, could not go
forward with its own plan for a combination with Conrail.
<p>
   The prize is Conrail's virtual monopoly over rail freight in the
Northeast, which would make either railroad the dominant force east
of the Mississippi River.
<p>
   ``This is a logical progression from the financial contest,
which is not over yet,'' said Scott Flower, a transportation
analyst with Paine Webber. ``There is reason to believe that all
sides would want to negotiate an equitable solution. An
all-or-nothing victory for one side might lead to unintended
consequences before the regulatory bodies.''
<p>
   Any railroad merger would have to be approved by the federal
Surface Transportation Board.
<p>
   News of the letter emerged after the stock market closed.
Earlier, however, investors, who appeared to believe that Norfolk
Southern's higher offer could win out, drove Conrail shares up
$3.50 Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange to close at $107.50.
<p>
   Conrail's share price has climbed more than 50 percent since the
bidding war began last October. Shares of CSX, which had been
losing ground, jumped $1.625 to close at $49.125. Norfolk Southern
closed at $88.125, up $1.
<p>
   The sudden agreement to a three-way meeting represents a shift
in posture for all three railroads, but especially for Conrail and
CSX, which have rebuffed all entreaties from Norfolk Southern. Yet
all three companies also remain committed, at least for now, to
positions that would seem to rule out a possible compromise.
<p>
   Norfolk Southern has pledged to complete a deal for Conrail that
would provide shareholders $115 cash a share, while CSX has stated
publicly that it will not raise its offer again.
<p>
   Conrail, in turn, has fought to remain intact, rather than be
split up between the CSX and Norfolk in some sort of equitable
division. It would appear that one side or another must beat a
public and humiliating retreat for these meetings to have a
meaningful outcome, some analysts said.
<p>
   ``It appears that there is a crack in the hard positions taken
by CSX and Conrail and perhaps a change in attitude,'' Anthony
Hatch, an analyst with NatWest Securities, said. ``But we can't be
sure because it's been a game of feints and deception up until now.
Given the positions they have taken it's hard to see how an
equitable solution can be found without somebody eating crow.''
<p>
   The apparent thaw in relations between the railroad companies
was prompted by comments from Linda Morgan, chairwoman of the
Surface Transportation Board, in an interview in The Washington
Post Tuesday.
<p>
   Ms. Morgan appeared to urge the railroads to devise a solution
that would provide a competitive balance in the East before any
merger proposal comes before her agency.
<p>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
<p>
   In a big merger last year, between the Union Pacific and
Southern Pacific railroads, the board laid down a number of
conditions intended to minimize the loss of competition before it
approved the $5.4 billion merger. The transportation board absorbed
some of the regulatory functions of the Interstate Commerce
Commission, which was eliminated by Congress in 1995.
<p>
   Indeed, in the interview with The Washington Post, Ms. Morgan
pointed to the Union Pacific-Southern Pacific merger.
<p>
   ``I think the STB signaled that it prefers a private market
solution to the problem rather than an unpredictable battle before
the regulatory agency,'' Flower of Paine Webber said. ``They want
something worked out so they can adjust at the margin rather than
making wholesale changes and being the solution.''
<p>
   The letter sent to Norfolk Southern's chairman, David R. Goode,
was in response to a letter from Goode on Tuesday calling for
talks.
<p>
   Norfolk Southern has said that a combined CSX-Conrail company
would control 70 percent of the market in the East, while a Norfolk
combination would ensure a more equitable 60-40 split.
<p>
   CSX and Conrail have repeatedly said they would meet with
Norfolk Southern to discuss track rights and other concessions. But
Norfolk rejected that option as too modest to make a difference.
<p>
   In the past, CSX and Norfolk have held secret negotiations
concerning a more far-reaching solution: buying Conrail and
splitting the railroad between them. But neither company could
figure out how to overcome the strict anti-takeover laws that
protect Conrail in Pennsylvania.
<p>
   A merger of Conrail with either CSX or Norfolk Southern would
create the nation's third-largest freight rail line, behind Union
Pacific and the Burlington Northern Santa Fe.
<p>
   Conrail, meanwhile, Wednesday reported a profit for the fourth
quarter, reversing a loss from a year earlier.
<p>
   The company earned $147 million, or $1.70 a share, compared with
a loss of $30 million, or 43 cents a share, in the quarter a year
earlier. Revenues fell slightly, to $943 million from $951 million.
<p>
   In the quarter a year ago, the company incurred costs of $176
million from disposing of some rail lines. In the most recent
quarter, Conrail reported costs of $10 million stemming from the
proposed merger with CSX.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2315EST
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0849 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9963 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-SECRET-BENE </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0981 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EXCLUSIVE-SECRET-BENEFACTOR-2NDLD-ART-2TAKES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN: Minn., N.J., N.Y., Ore. pts.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (subs for additional information, smoothing) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HE GAVE AWAY $600 MILLION, AND NO ONE KNEW &LR;  &QL; 
(With sidebar, SECRET-BENEFACTOR-PROFILE) &QL; 
(ART ADV: Photo of Charles Feeney is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Graphic on his donations is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) &QL; 
(sw) &QL; 
 &UR; By JUDITH MILLER and DAVID CAY JOHNSTON &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   NEW YORK  &MD;  Over the last 15 years, a self-made entrepreneur from
New Jersey has given away more than $600 million to universities,
medical centers and other beneficiaries  &MD;  but has done it in such
secrecy that most recipients never learned who their benefactor
was.
<p>
   The donor, Charles F. Feeney, 65, who made his fortune with a
string of duty-free airport shops, covered his tracks so well that
business magazines for years have estimated his net worth in the
billions, not realizing that he had transferred most of his assets
to his two charitable foundations and is actually worth less than
$5 million.
<p>
   After years of secrecy, Feeney, who is 65, agreed this week to
discuss his gifts because the duty-free stores were sold this month
to the company that makes Moet &AMP; Chandon Champagne, and a lawsuit
over the sale would have revealed his anonymous donations.
<p>
   Feeney  &MD;  who has strong ties to Ireland and has also made many
gifts there, including personal donations to Sinn Fein, the IRA's
political wing  &MD;  was matter-of-fact in describing why he had given
away his fortune. ``I simply decided I had enough money,'' he said.
``It doesn't drive my life. I'm a what-you-see-is-what-you-get kind
of guy.''
<p>
   Harvey P. Dale, a New York University tax law professor and
president of Feeney's Atlantic Foundation, who has helped Feeney
orchestrate his gifts since 1982, said: ``He doesn't own a house.
He doesn't own a car. He flies economy. And I think his watch cost
about $15.''
<p>
   While large anonymous donations to charity are not unheard of,
the scope and style of Feeney's giving, and his passion for
secrecy, appeared to be unique, according to independent experts on
philanthropy. ``I've never heard of anything like this,'' said
Thomas A. Troyer, a senior partner in the law firm of Caplin &AMP;
Drysdale in Washington, who specializes in philanthropic law.
<p>
   From the Mount Sinai School of Medicine to Portland State
University, none of the American recipients of Feeney's largesse
knew who their benefactor was. Grants were paid by cashier's check
to conceal the source. In fact, the beneficiaries never realized
that they owed their thanks to a single giver  &MD;  they were told that
the money came from several generous ``clients'' who wished to
remain anonymous.
<p>
   Few of the recipients had ever even met Dale or Joel L.
Fleishman, the president of Atlantic Philanthropic Services, which
actually gave away the money on behalf of Feeney's foundations, the
Atlantic Foundation and the Atlantic Trust.
<p>
   Dr. Robert Butler of Mount Sinai School of Medicine said he met
Feeney in 1990 while making a proposal for financing to an advisory
board that reviewed grant proposals.
<p>
   ``I had no idea that he was the main supporter of what I call
the Anonymous Foundation,'' Butler said, adding that the grant was
made, starting the International Longevity Center at the New York
Academy of Medicine. ``Anonymous giving, giving that is not
dependent on ego, is just really rare.''
<p>
   Feeney said that by giving anonymously, he could go about his
life unhampered by pitches for donations. ``There are people who
want, and rightly deserve, recognition for giving, but in our case
it wasn't important,'' he said.
<p>
   It was Dale who helped Feeney set up his foundations, which like
his Duty-Free Shoppes chain are based in Bermuda, avoiding the
disclosure requirements of private foundations in the United
States. Feeney also declined to take a deduction on his personal
income taxes for the money he gave to the foundations, in order to
preserve the secrecy.
<p>
   And Atlantic Philanthropic Services, the New York-based entity
that screens applicants and writes the checks, is set up as a
for-profit company, also to avoid disclosure rules.
<p>
   Feeney gave his entire 38.75 percent interest in the duty-free
chain, known as DFS Group, to the two foundations in 1984 (even his
partner, Robert W. Miller, was not told). Now, the foundations have
received the proceeds from the sale of the controlling interest in
the chain to LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton of France.
<p>
   The chain has sales of more than $3 billion annually, mostly in
liquors and luxury goods, more than the combined sales of Saks
Fifth Avenue and Neiman-Marcus.
<p>
   The sale proceeds, along with other business assets Feeney has
turned over to the foundations, have left the charity with a total
of $3.5 billion, even after the $610 million that has already been
distributed to charities. It would rank as the nation's
fourth-largest grant-making foundation if it were based in the
United States, yet the two groups operate with tiny staffs, just 20
professionals in the United States and overseas.
<p>
   The foundation's largest single grant was $30 million, according
to Dale, who refused to identify the recipient on grounds that the
information might discourage other donors from supporting it. ``One
reason for keeping gifts anonymous is to avoid what we call this
`crowding out' effect,'' Dale said.
<p>
   Recipients were effusive in their praise for their anonymous
donor's style of giving and what it had enabled them to do. ``This
is operational support, the most valuable kind of assistance,''
said William Nelsen, president of the Citizens' Scholarship
Foundation of America, in St. Peter, Minn., which has received
support since 1984.
</TEXT>
