<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9964 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-CALENERGY-FORUM-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0624 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-CALENERGY-FORUM-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CALENERGY MAY SELL POWER TO HOMES (UPDATE1): BLOOMBERG FORUM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Kerry Dooley &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adds details about deregulation and CalEnergy in last nine
paragraphs.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   New York, Jan. 22 (Bloomberg) -- CalEnergy Inc. said it will
sell electricity directly to consumers in the U.S. and Asia in a
few years, challenging local utilities for sales of power to homes
and businesses.
<p>
   CalEnergy isn't the only U.S. power company with plans to find
new customers as deregulation ends monopolies. Atlanta-based
Southern Co. and Western Resources Inc. of Topeka, Kansas, also
intend to expand to new markets.
<p>
   Unlike those utilities, CalEnergy's only business is to build
and run power plants. Until recently, the company has let others
deliver electricity generated at CalEnergy plants.
<p>
   That's changing.
<p>
   ``We want to be able to provide our customers with more
services,'' CalEnergy Chairman and Chief Executive David Sokol told
the Bloomberg Forum.
<p>
   To get experience running a transmission system, CalEnergy made
a successful $1.54 billion hostile bid for Northern Electric Plc.
The U.K. utility's marketing savvy made it attractive to CalEnergy,
which wants to bundle electric power sales with other products,
Sokol said.
<p>
   The Northern acquisition, expected to be completed this year,
will help increase CalEnergy's earnings, analysts said. The Omaha,
Nebraska-based operator of power plants is expected to earn $1.87 a
share in 1997 and $2.47 in 1998, according to three analysts polled
by Zacks Investment Research.
<p>
   CalEnergy yesterday said 1996 net income rose to $92.5 million,
or $1.60 a share, a 48 percent increase from the previous year.
<p>
   CalEnergy intends to keep growing by expanding its holdings and
buying new ones, he said. ``I would expect continued acquisitions
in the future,'' Sokol said.
<p>
   CalEnergy's one of the few companies that can run power plants
as a pure business, seeking to lower operating costs where
possible, Sokol said.
<p>
   Much of the world's electricity comes from government-owned
utilities and publicly traded ones run as highly regulated
monopolies. In the U.S., utilities have made their profits by
negotiating with regulators and getting a guaranteed return on
their investment in power plants and other expenses.
<p>
   ``The more money they spend, the more money they make,'' Sokol
said. ``We're just the opposite.''
<p>
   For that reason, CalEnergy's expects to do well as governments
around the world ease out of the electric industry, Sokol said.
<p>
   Next year, the U.K. will let all consumers choose their own
power suppliers. Some of the largest companies there have seen
their electric bills fall 30 percent already by switching to a less
expensive company, he said.
<p>
   The U.K.'s experience is likely to prompt U.S. regulators to end
monopolies in the U.S., Sokol said. Congress is expected to
consider deregulation this year. Consumers are likely to be able to
choose a power supplier as they now do long-distance telephone
service.
<p>
   If the U.S ends monopolies, Omaha, Nebraska-based CalEnergy
expects to make more sales at home, Sokol said.
<p>
   Although CalEnergy's anxious to see governments get out of the
power industry, its first power plant was built in California's
Mojave Desert for the U.S. Navy. That plant taps into underground
water, heated by the earth's crust, to bring up jets of steam. The
steam spins turbines that create electric power.
<p>
   Today, CalEnergy is one of the world's largest producers of this
geothermal energy with plants in the Philippines and Indonesia. It
also has plants that use new technology to lower air pollution from
coal, Sokol said.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2318EST
</TRAILER>
