<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt970122.0851 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u sel=taf-z> A9965 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-SECRET-BENE </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0784 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-EXCLUSIVE-SECRET-BENEFACTOR-2NDLD-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW YORK: since 1984. &LR;  &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Nelson said that the group, which mobilizes community groups to
raise money for college student aid, was able to significantly
expand its ``Dollars for Scholars'' program to reach 770 chapters
throughout the country, thanks in large part to Atlantic money,
which he said was more than a million dollars.
<p>
   ``As an organization, we've more than quadrupled in size since
getting support from this anonymous donor,'' Nelsen said.
<p>
   At the College Board, which administers scholastic assessment
tests for college-bound high school seniors, the mystery donor was
always referred to by the name ``anonymous,'' said Dr. Donald
Stewart, president of the College Board.
<p>
   ``Anonymous was most interested in results,'' Stewart said. The
anonymous donor supported ``long-term research to establish whether
we are right, which is crucial for the project's credibility and in
assessing whether all schools should adopt the same approach,'' he
said.
<p>
   Several recipients said that once they were invited to apply for
funds their plans were closely examined. ``Ed McMahon did not knock
on my door,'' said Chuck Supple, president of Public Allies, which
places young people in internships with nonprofit organizations.
``These guys really kick the tires.''
<p>
   Judith Ramaley, president of Portland State University, in
Oregon, called her first foundation grant last year her
``catalyst,'' financing of less than one million dollars that
enabled the school to publicize its innovative new curriculum and
links to the community, which have now drawn national attention and
the support of other foundations. ``We were out of cash when they
came along,'' she said. ``They were the trail mix at that key
moment on our very steep hiking path,'' she said.
<p>
   One-fourth of Feeney's contributions have been made abroad, half
of that in Ireland. The foundation also supports projects in South
Africa, the former Soviet bloc, Eastern Europe, Israel and Jordan.
<p>
   There was less secrecy surrounding Feeney's activities in
Ireland. Several Irish university presidents and other
beneficiaries said they had met Feeney several times.
<p>
   Feeney also said he had given substantial personal donations  &MD; 
not from the Atlantic foundations  &MD;  in the last two years to the
Washington office of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish
Republican Army, which in 1994 entered into a cease-fire with the
British that was broken last February. Public records show that
Feeney has contributed some $280,000  &MD;  making him the group's
single largest American donor.
<p>
   While Feeney acknowledged that some would criticize his support
for a group linked to the IRA he said his gifts to Sinn Fein had
been monitored to insure that they supported only nonviolent
activities. He continued supporting the Washington office despite
the cease-fire's collapse last February, he said, ``because I'm
hopeful that it will be renewed.''
<p>
   The Atlantic Foundation's board of directors includes several
prominent personalities in the philanthropic and educational
establishment  &MD;  among them, Elizabeth McCormack, a senior adviser
on charitable giving to members of the Rockefeller family and vice
chairman of the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation;
Frank H.T. Rhodes, president emeritus of Cornell University,
Michael I. Sovern, president of the Shubert Foundation and
president emeritus of Columbia University, and Frederick A.O.
Schwarz Jr., an attorney and chairman of the Natural Resources
Defense Council.
<p>
   None of them had previously disclosed their connection with the
Atlantic groups publicly, nor did they discuss Feeney's giving with
peers or even their families, they said in interviews this week.
``This organization has operated on a need-to-know basis,''
Fleishman said.
<p>
   Most recipients said their only contact was with program
officers of Atlantic Philanthropic Services, which selects the
grantees, gives out the money, and evaluates the outcome of the
gifts.
<p>
   Rhodes, the foundation board member and former president of
Cornell, said that the foundation was careful not to use money to
tell recipients what to do or how to do it. ``The danger with
foundations is that sometimes the staff and board come to feel that
they own the money,'' Rhodes said, ``and they micromanage. We have
a motto: noses in, fingers out.''
<p>
   Dale said of the relationship to grant recipients: ``We are
voyeurs. We let good people do good things. We oversee, but we
don't interfere.''
<p>
   And despite his decision finally to disclose his donations,
Feeney is still trying to keep a low profile. He declined this week
to be photographed.
</TEXT>
