<p>
    &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR; 
<p>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, Jan. 23.
<p>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
<p>
    &UR; INTERNATIONAL  &MD;  (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR; 
<p>
   SPAIN-AUTONOMY (Elche, Spain)  &MD;  The Lady of Elche is Spain's
most famous ancient icon, with its finely chiselled face framed
with an elaborate headdress and necklaces. It represents an Iberian
priestess or princess and is believed to be some 2,500 years old.
When the town of Elche was refused permission to borrow the statue
from Madrid for an anniversary celebration, the dispute became
another skirmish in the perennial tug-of-war over regional
autonomy. A Foreign Journal by Marlise Simons.
<p>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT20) to illustrate story has been sent to NYT
photo clients. Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
<p>
   ASIA-ARMS-SALES (Bangkok, Thailand)  &MD;  Just a few years after
they ended their nuclear arms race, the United States and Russia
are locked in a fierce competition for arms sales to Southeast
Asia, with both countries offering potential purchasers some of the
world's most sophisticated missiles as incentives. By Raymond
Bonner.
<p>
   ISRAEL-MORDECHAI (Tel Aviv, Israel)  &MD;  Nobody would deny that
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai has the least political
experience and the least ideological baggage in the Israeli
Cabinet. But Mordechai, 52, has emerged from the tumult of the last
seven months as the key problem-solver in the government and as the
most popular member of it. By Serge Schmemann.
<p>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT15) of Yitzhak Mordechai has been sent to
NYT photo clients.)
<p>
   CYPRUS-TURKEY (Nicosia, Cyprus)  &MD;  Almost everything about
northern Cyprus  &MD;  its name, its status, the reasons for the 110
miles of barbed wire that divide it from the rest of the island  &MD; 
is a matter of bitter dispute. But little stirs passions on either
side of the nearly 23-year-old buffer zone like the issue of
exactly who lives north of it. By Celestine Bohlen.
<p>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
<p>
    &UR; NATIONAL  &MD;  GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR; 
<p>
   TSONGAS-LEGACY (Lowell, Mass.)  &MD;  When Paul Tsongas died last
weekend, the local newspaper wrote, ``With his death, Paul
Tsongas's survivors include his wife, his children and a city.''
For the people of Lowell, who turned out in the thousands to pay
their respects, Paul Tsongas was a hero who rescued the city from
the depression that came with the collapse of the textile
factories. By Sara Rimer.
<p>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT12) to illustrate story has been sent to NYT
photo clients. Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
<p>
   NY-SECRET-BENEFACTOR (New York)  &MD;  Over the past 18 years a
billionaire has secretly been giving away his fortune to hospitals,
schools and other beneficiaries who did not even know the identity
of their benefactor, a self-made man born in New Jersey who has
strong ties to Ireland and who did not even take tax deductions. He
revealed his story in an interview. By Judith Miller.
<p>
   (ART ADV: Chart of donations has been sent to NYT graphics
clients.)
<p>
   AIDS-CONFERENCE (Washington)  &MD;  Dr. David Ho, a leading AIDS
scientist, said Wednesday that he had pushed back by up to a year
his plans to do crucial tests to determine whether infection with
the AIDS virus can be cured in some people. By Lawrence K. Altman.
<p>
    &UR; WASHINGTON  &MD;  (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR; 
<p>
