<p>
   SHODDY-HOUSES (Undated)  &MD;  Preliminary designs for Michael
Eisner's multimillion-dollar log cabin in Aspen, Colo., included
stone fireplaces to rival Yosemite National Park's Ahwahnee Hotel  &MD; 
and a retaining wall so thin that it would have buckled under its
own weight. At the multimillion-dollar Connecticut home of a tennis
champion, the foundation for a new guest house was laid over
construction-site trash, resulting in major cracks and leaks. And a
$40 million Long Island house for a billionaire software developer
used an inexpensive Western pine siding that was so vulnerable to
decay that it began to rot while the house was still under
construction. If people with unlimited budgets cannot count on
quality construction, who can? By Julie Iovine.
