<p>
   HENRY-GRUNWALD-PROFILE (New York)  &MD;  When Henry Grunwald ran into
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis at a party in 1990, he told her he was
in the process of researching his memoir. ``She said, `Research?
Why do you want to do
research?' '' Grunwald recalled in his soft voice still accented
with German. `` `What I want to know is what Henry Grunwald thinks
about in the bathtub.' '' Seeing the wisdom of this  &MD;  reinforced by
the urging of his family and friends  &MD;  Grunwald wrote a very
different book, interweaving descriptions of public events with
personal impressions, pushing himself through an unfamiliar process
of self-disclosure. ``It was not easy,'' he said. ``I'm not very
easily given to the confessional style. There are a great many
people to whom conversation is confession. To me, it isn't
really.'' By Robin Pogrebin. &HT;    (ART ADV: Photos [NYT5,6) of Henry Grunwald have been sent to
NYT photo clients.)
<p>
   CONSUMER-ELECTRONICS (Undated)  &MD;  For years now, electronics
manufacturers have promised that homes would soon be cocoons
outfitted with every type of entertainment and information
component. No longer far-off fantasies, such devices were on
display at the Consumer Electronics Show here earlier this month.
What's more, many will be on the market in a few months. By David
Elrich.
<p>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT1,2) to illustrate story have been sent to
NYT photo clients.)
<p>
   NY-ANTIQUES-SHOW (New York)  &MD;  Muses have gone out of fashion,
but given the largely unsurprising wares at the 43rd Winter
Antiques Show, the exposition could have used a deity like Mona
Strader Schlesinger Bush Williams von Bismarck de Martini. The
socialite, who died in 1983 at 86, would be the customer of any
dealer's dreams. During her heyday in the 1930s, a $700 million
fortune insured that whatever Mona wanted, Mona got. Too bad this
avaricious sylph, best known as Mona Bismarck, is not around,
checkbook ajar. Clients like her  &MD;  old-fashioned, flaunt-happy
plutocrats  &MD;  would spice up the Winter Antiques Show, a
once-sparkling exhibition that appears to be sliding into a
blancmange. For the benefit of the East Side House Settlement, the
show opened on Jan. 16 and closes Sunday. By Mitchell Owens.
<p>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT8) to illustrate story has been sent to NYT
photo clients.)
<p>
   ECART-FURNITURE (Undated)  &MD;  Andree Putman, the French interior
designer, is leaving Ecart International, the company she founded
in 1978 to re-issue classics of early 20th century furniture
design, said Michel Taurel, development manager of Ecopar, the
parent company of Ecart. Taurel would not say whether or not she
was fired. ``It's an agreement between her and Ecopar,'' he said,
``because you know, she is seventy and something old, and she is
actually retiring from her activities at Ecart.'' Mrs. Putman could
not be reached for comment. By Elaine Louie.
<p>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT9) to illustrate story has been sent to NYT
photo clients.)
<p>
    &UR; NYT News Service &LR; 
