<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIAN-1STLD- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0817 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-TEN-AUSTRALIAN-1STLD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PIERCE CRUISES INTO AUSTRALIAN OPEN FINAL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBIN FINN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   MELBOURNE, Australia  &MD;  She did a nervous little jig Thursday as
she awaited serve, heaved a mighty sigh each time she stepped to
the service line, flashed a dazzling smile of self-mockery after
she failed to serve for the first set at 5-1, and sent an aggrieved
stare toward her coach after her 5-1 lead dwindled to a 5-5
deadlock.
<p>
   Mary Pierce doesn't just play tennis, she performs it, and
Thursday's 7-5, 6-1 performance against 12th-seeded Amanda Coetzer
vaulted the unseeded Pierce into the final of the Australian Open,
the slam where made her breakthrough by winning the title in 1995.
Pierce had won just a single Corel Tour title, and had not been to
a slam final, since she prevailed here two years ago.
<p>
   ``I don't think about when was the last time for this or that,''
said Pierce, ``but the experience helps.''
<p>
   In the women's final Saturday, the 22nd-ranked Pierce hopes to
ferret out some inexperience in Switzerland's 4th-seeded Martina
Hingis, the teenaged phenomenon who became the favorite to capture
her first slam title once the three seeded stars ahead of her here
bowed out.
<p>
   The 16-year-old Hingis launched herself into her first Grand
Slam final with a convincing 6-1, 6-3 demolition of 14th-seeded
Mary Joe Fernandez, a two-time finalist on the cusp of curtailing
her 10-year singles career.
<p>
   ``It was so easy today; I played practically perfect tennis,''
said Hingis, whose control and pace put Fernandez on the defensive
from start to finish.
<p>
   Hingis was realistic about her 0-3 record against Pierce, who in
the past has been able to overpower the teenager from the baseline
with sufficient authority to produce a trio of 6-0 sets.
<p>
   ``It's not going to be easy, I've lost to her every time we've
played: but I'm a better player now,'' said Hingis, whose main
improvement is a less breakable serve.
<p>
   If Hingis, already the Australian Open's youngest semifinalist,
survives another round and pockets this title, she will become the
youngest Grand Slam champion since 15-year-old Lottie Dodd
monopolized Wimbledon in 1887. If Pierce goes full circle and
reclaims the title she earned in 1995, she'll become the first
unseeded woman to claim a Grand Slam since Chris O'Neill won this
tournament in 1978.
<p>
   The last unseeded slam champion was the absent Andre Agassi,
like Pierce an excommunicated disciple of Nick Bollettieri and like
Pierce a champion here in 1995; the Las Vegan zipped through to the
U.S. Open title in 1994, and Pierce has said she wouldn't mind
imitating his act.
<p>
   ``I feel like a different player, a different person,'' said the
22-year-old Pierce, who failed to cope with the attendant pressures
and expectations that followed her victory here and watched her
ranking dip from a career-best of third in the world to 22nd.
<p>
   Last year Pierce played just 32 matches and ended the year on
the sidelines, nursing a wounded shoulder and unable to swing a
racquet for two months.
<p>
   Hingis, by contrast, concluded her 1996 campaign by reaching the
U.S. Open semifinals, winning Oakland, and taking top-ranked Steffi
Graf to five sets at the Chase Championships. Since the Olympics,
only Graf and Jana Novotna have beaten her.
<p>
   But Pierce came into this year's Australian Open, where she was
dethroned in the second round last year by Elena Likhovtseva, with
vindication on her mind and with Sven Groeneveld, the same coach
who shepherded her to her first and only slam crown in 1995, back
on her support squad. She went through a venomous split with her
other mentor from 1995, Bollettieri, after he called her fondness
for sweets a character flaw.
<p>
   Pierce's first order of business was getting revenge on the
13th-seeded Likhovsetva in the opening round, and she ousted two
more seeded contenders before Thursday's bravura handling of
Coetzer, the South African who upset Graf in the Round of 16.
<p>
   After bullying Coetzer off the court in the first six games,
Pierce unraveled as she served for the first set at 5-1, was broken
again on her second try at 5-3, and allowed Coetzer to level things
at 5-5. But after Pierce held for 6-5 with an ace and broke Coetzer
with crosscourt forehand pass, she didn't relinquish control.
<p>
   ``I started off perfectly, then I felt a little bit strange, a
little bit weak,'' said the theatrical Pierce, ``but I just tried
to push myself and gradually I felt better.''
<p>
   MATCH POINTS 
<p>
   Top-ranked PETE SAMPRAS sneaked out to a 3-1 lead in the final
set against 10th-seeded ALBERT COSTA and held on for a 6-3, 6-7
(5-7), 6-1, 3-6, 6-2 victory that forwarded him into a semifinal
slot for the fourth time in five years. Now 24-8 in five-set
matches, Sampras next meets 5th-seeded Muster, a man who thrives on
marathons.
</TEXT>
