<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-TRADE-SURPLUS-U </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0777 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-JAPAN-TRADE-SURPLUS-UPDATE3-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JAPAN'S DECEMBER TRADE SURPLUS SHRANK 20.6% ON YEAR (UPDATE3) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Ken Belson &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adding economist comments in first section, and third section
on Asia.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Tokyo, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus
shrank a larger-than-expected 20.6 percent in December from the
same month a year ago as higher oil prices drove up imports, the
Finance Ministry said.
<p>
   At the same time, Japan's surplus with the United States grew
for the third straight month as the yen declined 8.5 percent
against the dollar between August and December. This trend will
likely continue since U.S. demand is strong.
<p>
   ``The pace of exports to the U.S. will continue because America
has quite robust growth with low inflation,'' said Akio Yoshino,
senior economist at Credit Suisse Asset Management before the
release of the report.
<p>
   Japan's trade surplus with the U.S. in December rose 7.8 percent
to 389.113 billion yen ($3.26 billion), the ministry said. Vehicle
exports rose 8.4 percent in December as Japanese automakers boost
production to meet demand for new models introduced in September. A
senior Finance Ministry official said auto exports may continue to
rise as the yen weakens against the dollar.
<p>
   U.S. officials continue to support a strong dollar even as
Japan's surplus increases.
<p>
   ``A strong dollar is in our national economic self-interest,''
U.S. treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said Tuesday. He added that
the dollar's climb against other major currencies isn't detrimental
to the U.S. trade position. ``The key to (reducing the U.S.) trade
deficit is our competitiveness, not the dollar.''
<p>
   The declines in Japan's trade surplus will end by April as the
yen depreciates further and the price of oil stabilizes, economists
said.
<p>
   ``The declines in Japan's trade surplus will continue through
March as the price of oil continues to increase,'' said Kazutaka
Kirishima, an economist at Sumitomo Mutual Life Research Center.
<p>
   The price of a barrel of Saudi Arabian light oil averaged $22.06
in December, an increase of 33 percent compared to the same time a
year earlier.
<p>
   Market reaction was limited because the trade surplus, which
totaled 881.475 billion yen ($7.4 billion), has declined for 25
straight months.
<p>
   Economists said the surplus would be 1.055 trillion yen,
according to a survey compiled by Bloomberg Business News.
Projections ranged from 970 billion yen to 1.145 trillion yen.
<p>
   Global imports to Japan rose 13.4 percent to 3.286 trillion yen,
while exports increased 4.0 percent to 4.168 trillion yen, the
ministry said.
<p>
   For all 1996, Japan's trade surplus fell 32.4 percent to 6.7
trillion yen, the Finance Ministry said. That was the fourth
straight yearly decline, and the largest decline in the surplus on
record.
<p>
   In yen terms, it was the smallest trade surplus since 1983.
Still, exports and imports both reached record highs. Japan's
exports rose 7.7 percent to 44.734 trillion yen, while imports rose
20.4 percent to 37.990 trillion yen. That was the largest
percentage increase in imports since 1989.
<p>
   The country's full-year trade surplus with the U.S. fell 16.5
percent to 3.6 trillion yen, the second straight yearly decline.
Japan has increased ``reverse imports'' -- goods made at Japanese
factories overseas -- when the yen strengthened against the dollar
in 1994 and 1995. That led to a 21.9 percent increase in imports
from the United States.
<p>
   Japan's surplus with the European Union declined 26.5 percent,
the fourth consecutive decline. Imports of Japanese autos made in
Europe helped reduce the surplus, the government said.
<p>
   Japan's surplus with Asia fell 15.7 percent in 1996, the first
decline in nine years. Weak demand for semiconductors in the region
was the main reason for the decline, the ministry said.
<p>
   At the same time, many Japanese companies are building factories
in Asia to take advantage of lower labor and transportation costs.
That has led to a fall in exports from Japan and an increase in
``reverse imports,'' analysts said.
<p>
   ``A lot of production is done offshore now and that's keeping
the surplus in decline,'' said Dennis Tachiki, a researcher at
Sakura Institute of Research. The surplus has also declined as
Asian manufacturers produce cheaper electronics components.
<p>
   In December, Japan's trade surplus with Asia fell 5.6 percent
compared to a year earlier to 703.1 billion yen. Increasing oil
prices led to the decline as imports of refined oil grew 63.7
percent while natural gas imports grew 56.6 percent.
</TEXT>
