<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=taf-z> A9970 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CAPITALS- </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0801 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-HKN-RANGERS-CAPITALS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; RANGERS EARN AN UTTERLY DIVERTING VICTORY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JOE LAPOINTE &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   LANDOVER, Md.  &MD;  So here is the New York Ranger winning goal,
exactly the way they might have drawn it up on the chalkboard.
<p>
   With the game tied at 3-3 in the final minute Wednesday night,
Wayne Gretzky skates to the New York bench on a line change. At the
doorway, he gets tangled up with Jason Allison of Washington.
<p>
   They grab each other's sticks. Words are exchanged. More players
gather. The scene looks like the entrance to the Lincoln Tunnel at
rush hour. A linesman enters the fray, in the role of traffic cop.
<p>
   While everyone's attention is diverted, the Rangers skate down
the ice, pass the puck around and score  &MD;  Mark Messier to Niklas
Sundstrom to Brian Leetch.
<p>
   The goal, Leetch's second of the night, his fourth in two games
and his 15th of the season, proved to be the winner in a 5-3
victory over the Capitals. Everybody had a hand in it.
<p>
   ``Took my man,'' Gretzky said.
<p>
   Leetch said he wasn't aware of the fracas but he smiled when he
said he was glad it didn't escalate into something that would cause
a whistle to stop play.
<p>
   They could afford to be happy, despite being outplayed most of
the way and losing a three-goal lead.
<p>
   This was the first time this season the Rangers have defeated
the Capitals, after three consecutive defeats. It also was the
first victory for goalie Glenn Healy since Dec. 7. And it raised
the Rangers' record in their Atlantic division to 5-12-4.
<p>
   Because Florida lost to Hartford, the victory put the Rangers
technically into second place in the Atlantic Division, a point
ahead of the Panthers.
<p>
   Leetch, with the hot stick, was asked if he is ``in the zone,''
the way basketball players get.
<p>
   ``No,'' he said. ``I'm just shooting it at the net. I'm as
surprised as anybody. The goalies have seen each and every goal.
<p>
   ``I haven't really picked a spot out. I've kind of throwing it
at the net. They're kind of hitting the goalie and going in or
going in under his glove. It's more good luck than anything.''
<p>
   Leetch also assisted on a goal by Luc Robitaille. The rookie
Vladimir Vorobiev scored the other first-period goal and Adam
Graves scored into the empty net in the dying seconds when
Washington pulled its goalie for an extra attacker. Peter Bondra
scored twice for the Capitals, the second to tie the game at 3-3 at
13 minutes 15 seconds of the third period.
<p>
   The Ranger penalty killing, which allowed 15 goals in the
previous nine games, was perfect in five tries Wednesday night,
including two that overlapped by 50 seconds.
<p>
   Rangers coach Colin Campbell, who sometimes sees the dark lining
in silver clouds, was rather upbeat, about this results and the 4-4
tie with Edmonton on the previous night.
<p>
   ``Three good points in two nights when we were in danger,'' he
said. ``This team sure challenges you in the grit department.''
<p>
   The Rangers played for the second consecutive game without
goalie Mike Richter and right wing Patrick Flatley. And the team's
medical sheet lengthened in the first period when Jeff Beukeboom,
the big, durable defenseman, left with a severe bruise on the
pointing finger of his left hand.
<p>
   The Rangers announced that X-rays of the finger had proven
negative. Campbell said afterward that Beukeboom would probably be
ready for the next game, Saturday afternoon in Pittsburgh.
<p>
   Fortunately, Campbell dressed seven defensemen instead of the
usual six. Richter, with a mild shoulder separation, also could
return Saturday. Flatley has a groin strain and his return is
uncertain.
<p>
   At the opening face-off, the Rangers were the beneficiaries of
two things beyond their control. The first was the absence of
defenseman Mark Tinordi, who usually plays well against them. He is
out for at least a month with a broken ankle bone.
<p>
   The second was the decision of Washington coach Jim Schoenfeld
to start Jim Carey in goal instead of Olaf Kolzig. In their last
visit here, on Jan. 9, Kolzig shut out the Rangers. Cary gave up
two goals on his first three shots and was pulled after the Rangers
took a 3-0 lead in the first 12 minutes.
<p>
   Leetch opened the scoring at 3:53 when his weak shot from high
in the zone found its way behind Carey, who got a piece of it as it
went by.
<p>
   The second, on a two-man power play, was scored by Robitaille,
his 20th. of the season, on a setup from Messier at 10:23. The
Capitals were down a second man because Joe Juneau accidentally
nicked Gretzky's face with a high stick while the Rangers were on
the power play.
<p>
   The Rangers went up by 3-0 at 11:57, on a one-man power play,
when Vorobiev scored his second in two nights on a one-time slap
shot set up by Gretzky.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-97 2331EST
</TRAILER>
