<STORYID cat=s pri=u sel=taf-z> A9973 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0685 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-BKN-NETS-SPURS-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; REEVES AVOIDS TURNOVERS AND EASES PAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (bl) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By SELENA ROBERTS &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;   &QL; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   SAN ANTONIO  &MD;  Khalid Reeves needed a massage and he needed it
now. But it wasn't a good time. Didn't he know that?
<p>
   Reeves was grimacing and wincing with 1 minute, 35 seconds left
as he brought the ball up the court. He pulled up in pain. But a
timeout was all it took as trainer Ted Arzonico managed to rub out
the cramp that bit Reeves' foot.
<p>
   Reeves was up with a bounce, springing onto the floor to finish
a game against the Spurs that he had started, playing at point
guard in place of the injured Robert Pack. That seemed a scary
proposition. After all, Reeves was so turnover prone. But
amazingly, did not have a single turnover, coming up with 7 assists
and 17 points as the New Jersey Nets beat the San Antonio Spurs,
103-95, at the Alamodome.
<p>
   If only they could play San Antonio every day. The Nets' victory
meant a season sweep of the Spurs, sans David Robinson, for the
first time in team history. It took Kendall Gill (32 points) to
bang away at a bigger Sean Elliott, landing a driving layup that
put the Nets ahead, 99-93, with 32 seconds left.
<p>
   And it took a confident Kerry Kittles (23 points) to assert
himself, scoring 10 points in the final five minutes.
<p>
   But none of it would have happened if Reeves had flubbed his
start like he did the last time he started following a Pack injury.
That was a miserable, seven-turnover performance against the
Knicks, Dec. 30.
<p>
   ``No turnovers? That was an accomplishment,'' an understated
Reeves said. ``The last time, I had seven. I was just trying to get
the team going and get everyone into it.''
<p>
   He was into it so much that he came up with a foot cramp. ``I'm
thinking, Oh, no, not now,'' Reeves said. ``But then I knew it
would be OK. It just took a few seconds and I was ready again.''
<p>
   The Nets looked ready from the start, but they let a 10-point
lead early in the second quarter get away from them as Vernon
Maxwell took advantage of the warehouse space that Lloyd Daniels
allowed him. He scored 10 second-quarter points to pull the Spurs
to within one point at the half, the Nets leading, 49-48.
<p>
   They seemed surprised to be ahead, especially after the Spurs
shot 51.4 percent to their 44.7 percent, especially after Dominique
Wilkins had made his return to the team after missing 10 games with
a bruised knee. There was still no Robinson, but the Spurs seemed
healthy enough.
<p>
   They seemed fit to prey on the injury-depleted Nets. But just
the opposite occurred. Reeves played within the offense for the
most part, resisting his urge to shoot as if he were suppressing a
sneeze.
<p>
   It was not easy  &MD;  he clutched to shoot several times and
released on occasion &MD;  but he managed to get the ball to his
teammates without a turnover in the first half, finding Kittles
coming off screens on two nice catch-and-shoot plays.
<p>
   Kittles also made himself available, playing much more
aggressive since a quick benching against Denver for his passive
play. He hit 7 of 10 shots after that. The trend continued against
San Antonio, leading the Nets with 13 first-half points to match
the 13 Maxwell put up.
<p>
   Everything about the game seemed even though the third quarter,
with the two teams going back and forth on the scoreboard. It took
Gill to make the difference. He coolly weaved around a larger
Elliott to come up with 15 points in the third, including a 17-foot
jumper at the buzzer, a shot he grabbed and hurried off a rebound.
<p>
   That play gave the Nets a 76-72 lead to start the fourth, a team
that had committed just three turnovers so far in the game. And
Reeves did not have one of them.
<p>
   REBOUNDS
<p>
   Shawn Bradley, who has been out two weeks with pneumonia, was
cleared to practice by team doctors Wednesday night. He is expected
to join the Nets before they return from their current road trip,
which goes through Houston on Thursday and ends in Dallas on
Saturday. Bradley may need a week of workouts before he is in
playing condition.
</TEXT>
