<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9975 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-AYALA-WATER-BID-UPDAT </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0474 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-AYALA-WATER-BID-UPDATE1-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AYALA-BECHTEL GROUP WINS MANILA WATERWORKS BIDDING (UPDATE1) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Alex B. Reyes and Marc R. Crowe &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
   (Adding information on bids and comments from Ayala, Lyonnaise
officials after sub-heading ``Bidding.'')
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Manila, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- Ayala Corp. won one of two
contracts to run Manila's state-owned water utility, ending a
string of failures to win at big-ticket government auctions. Ayala
and partners -- U.S. construction company Bechtel Group Inc. and
Britain's United Utilities Plc. -- won the right to run the eastern
half of Metropolitan Waterworks and Sewerage System's service area
where 11 million Filipinos live.
<p>
   The government said a second group, led by Benpres Holdings
Corp. and France's Lyonnaise des Eaux, clinched the contract to
operate the western zone.
<p>
   The winners must invest a combined $7 billion over the life of
the contract to rehabilitate and expand the water utility's 12,000
kilometers (7,500 miles) of pipes. MWSS, because of leaks and
pilferage, loses more than half the water it pumps.
<p>
   The winners beat two other groups, led by holding companies
Metro Pacific Corp. and Aboitiz Equity Ventures Inc., in what the
government dubbed as one of the biggest water utility sales.
Generale des Eaux SA, the world's largest water utility, and
Anglian Water Plc. of the U.K. were members of the losing teams.
<p>
   Bids were submitted as a percentage of the current water tariff
of 8.78 pesos (33 cents) per cubic meter, guaranteeing that Manila
residents will see lower water bills.
<p>
   Surprisingly, Ayala's bid of 26.4 percent for the east zone was
less than half of the next closest bid.
<p>
   ``We have to admit that we are quite surprised,'' said Martin
Negre, head of Asian operations for Lyonnaise des Eaux. ``There is
a discrepancy in the order of magnitudes of the bids which will be
interesting to analyze.''
<p>
   Ayala executives said they can turn around the operations of
MWSS faster than the other groups.
<p>
   ``Our bid was based on assumptions we made as to how fast we can
bring down the non-revenue water,'' said Antonio Aquino, vice
president of Ayala Land Inc., the group's property arm. ``I don't
think it should be a reason to worry. We ran our numbers and
checked them again and again.''
<p>
   With the win, Ayala will add a new business to its extensive
portfolio. It controls Ayala Land Inc., the nation's largest
property developer and the most valuable company on the stock
exchange, and Bank of the Philippine Islands, its third largest
bank. It also has telecommunications, electronics, and food
processing units.
<p>
   Ayala owns 60 percent of Manila Water Co. Inc., its vehicle for
undertaking the project. Bechtel owns 20 percent and United
Utilities the balance.
</TEXT>
