<STORYID cat=f pri=r sel=tia-z> A9977 </STORYID>
<SLUG> BC-US-BONDS-ASIA-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> 01-22 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0476 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
 &UR; BC-US-BONDS-ASIA-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. BONDS LITTLE CHANGED IN ASIA AS DOLLAR CLIMBS VERSUS YEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Mark Tannenbaum &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.1997 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC; 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Tokyo, Jan. 23 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. Treasuries were little
changed in Asia as the dollar climbed to a 47-month high versus the
yen amid optimism investors will continue to channel money into
U.S. bonds and stocks.
<p>
   The dollar rose as high as 119.40 yen, its highest since Feb.
19, 1993, up from 118.80 yen this morning. The dollar last traded
for 119.19 yen.
<p>
   ``The dollar's strength isn't having a big impact now, but we'll
have to see what happens in New York-time,'' said Hiroshi Kawakami,
a trader at Hyakujushi Bank, Ltd.
<p>
   A rising dollar can boost the allure of dollar-based assets for
investors who must convert their proceeds into weaker currencies.
<p>
   With Japan's stock market sputtering, and domestic bond yields
not far above record lows, domestic investors will have no choice
but to look overseas for better returns, analysts said.
<p>
   The benchmark 10-year Treasury note last yielded 6.55 percent,
about 410 basis points more than the benchmark 10-year Japanese
government bond. The spread between the two has averaged roughly
380 basis points over the last three months.
<p>
   The 30-year benchmark Treasury bond was up 2/32 from New York,
or about 63 cents per $1,000 bond, to yield 6.82 percent. The
two-year note was yielding 6 percent.
<p>
   Yesterday in New York, bonds fell as Wall Street firms struggled
to sell the $17.5 billion of two-year notes they bought from the
Treasury, and prepared for today's sale of $12.5 billion in 5-year
notes.
<p>
   The Treasury sold its notes at a yield of 5.984 percent, less
than the 6 percent yield traders anticipated just before the sale.
<p>
   Wall Street ``paid too much'' for the notes, said Rob McCool, a
trader at First Chicago Capital Markets Inc.
<p>
   The lower-than-expected yield at the sale ``doesn't mean the
auction went well,'' because securities firms can't sell the bonds
for as much as they paid the government for them, said Mark
Sauvigne, a trader at Chase Securities Inc.
<p>
   In New York, the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond, which was
little changed prior to the 1 p.m. Eastern time sale, slumped 5/8
point, or $6.25 per $1,000 bond, pushing its yield up 5 basis
points to 6.83 percent, the highest in nine days.
<p>
   Traders said comments from Fed Governor Susan Phillips in a
Market News interview hurt bonds earlier in the day. Phillips
suggested the Fed might not wait for a rise in the core consumer
price index before boosting rates.
<p>
   The Fed hasn't changed bank lending rates since January 1996,
when it cut the so-called federal funds target by a quarter of a
percentage point to 5.25 percent. The Fed's policy-making Federal
Open Market Committee next meets on Feb. 4-5.
</TEXT>
